/* AUTO-GENERATED by tools/generate-questions.mjs — merged run (D1-D6 + D7/D8 backfill).
   3937 original, self-verified CISSP practice questions. */
(function(g){g.CISSP_LLM=[{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which component of the CIA triad ensures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized individuals, entities, or processes?","o":["Availability","Integrity","Confidentiality","Non-repudiation"],"c":2,"why":"Confidentiality specifically addresses protecting information from unauthorized disclosure. Availability concerns access when needed, integrity concerns accuracy/completeness, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements redundant power supplies, failover clusters, and regular system maintenance to ensure that its critical e-commerce platform remains accessible to customers at all times. Which principle of the CIA triad is the organization primarily addressing?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":2,"why":"Availability ensures authorized users have reliable, timely access to systems and data; redundancy and maintenance directly support this goal. Confidentiality and integrity relate to protecting data from unauthorized disclosure or modification, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A security manager verifies that a new cloud vendor has passed a SOC 2 audit and reviews their security certifications before signing a contract. This activity is best described as an example of:","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence involves researching and verifying facts before making a decision, such as vetting a vendor's security posture. Due care refers to the ongoing implementation of reasonable security measures after a decision is made, and the other options do not describe vendor vetting.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A financial services company implements a control that generates a cryptographic hash of each transaction record and stores it separately from the transaction data. When a record is retrieved, the hash is recalculated and compared to the stored value. Which security principle does this control primarily support?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Hashing detects unauthorized modification of data, which is the core purpose of integrity controls. It does not prevent disclosure (confidentiality), ensure uptime (availability), or by itself prove the identity of the sender (non-repudiation).","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the relationship between a security policy and a security procedure?","o":["A policy provides high-level management intent, while a procedure gives step-by-step instructions for implementing that intent","A procedure is mandatory while a policy is optional","A policy is technical in nature, while a procedure is strategic","A procedure defines acceptable risk levels, while a policy defines technical configurations"],"c":0,"why":"Policies are high-level statements of management intent and required behavior, while procedures are detailed, step-by-step instructions for carrying out that policy. The other options reverse or misstate these relationships.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISO commissions an independent audit to verify that a newly acquired subsidiary's security controls meet the parent company's baseline before integrating its network. Which concept best describes this action?","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as verifying a subsidiary's security posture prior to integration. Due care refers to the ongoing, reasonable actions taken to maintain security afterward.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization decides to purchase cybersecurity insurance to cover potential financial losses from a data breach rather than eliminating the underlying vulnerability. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is risk transfer. Mitigation reduces the risk itself, avoidance eliminates the activity causing the risk, and acceptance means taking no action and absorbing the loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A multinational company processes personal data of European Union residents. Under the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), this company is considered a controller. Which of the following best describes the primary obligation of a data controller under GDPR?","o":["To process data only on behalf of and under the instructions of another organization","To determine the purposes and means of processing personal data and ensure compliance with data protection principles","To act solely as a technical service provider with no legal accountability for data handling","To store data exclusively within the EU regardless of processing location"],"c":1,"why":"A data controller determines why and how personal data is processed and bears primary responsibility for GDPR compliance. The first option describes a data processor, and the other two options misstate GDPR requirements.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Within an organization's document hierarchy, which document is MANDATORY, provides high-level, technology-specific requirements that MUST be followed, and supports the organization's policies?","o":["Guideline","Procedure","Standard","Baseline"],"c":2,"why":"A standard is a mandatory, specific requirement (e.g., 'all passwords must be at least 12 characters') that supports policy. Guidelines are recommended (not mandatory), procedures are step-by-step instructions, and baselines define a minimum acceptable configuration state.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization determines that the cost of implementing additional controls to mitigate a low-probability, low-impact risk exceeds the potential loss. The organization decides to purchase a cyber-insurance policy to cover potential losses instead. Which risk response strategy is being applied?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing likelihood/impact through controls, avoidance eliminates the activity entirely, and acceptance means retaining the risk without further action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following is a foundational canon that CISSP holders must follow?","o":["Maximize shareholder profit above all other considerations","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Always report vulnerabilities publicly within 24 hours of discovery","Prioritize personal career advancement over organizational duties"],"c":1,"why":"One of the four canons of the (ISC)² Code of Ethics is to 'Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure.' The other options contradict professional ethics and are not part of the actual canons.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A hospital's electronic health record system uses cryptographic hashing to detect any unauthorized alteration of patient records after they are saved. Which security principle is primarily being enforced?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Hashing is used to detect unauthorized modification of data, which is the definition of integrity. Confidentiality concerns unauthorized disclosure, availability concerns access to data, and non-repudiation concerns proof of an action's origin, none of which are addressed by tamper detection.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following canons should a CISSP-certified professional prioritize FIRST when faced with a conflict between organizational interests and the public good?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics lists 'Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure' as the first and highest-priority canon, taking precedence over other canons when conflicts arise. The other canons are important but are subordinate in priority.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"In business continuity planning, the Recovery Time Objective (RTO) for a critical application is defined as 4 hours. What does this value represent?","o":["The maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time","The maximum tolerable period during which the application can remain unavailable after a disruption","The average time between system failures","The total time required to complete a full system backup"],"c":1,"why":"RTO defines the maximum tolerable downtime for a system or process after a disruption before unacceptable consequences occur. Data loss tolerance is measured by the Recovery Point Objective (RPO), not RTO, and the other options describe unrelated metrics.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Prior to acquiring a smaller competitor, a corporation hires an independent security firm to assess the target company's security posture, incident history, and regulatory compliance. This activity is best described as an exercise of:","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as assessing risk prior to an acquisition. Due care refers to the ongoing actions taken to maintain a reasonable standard of protection after a decision has been made, not the investigative phase.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A law that is created by a government agency to enforce and interpret regulations, such as tax or environmental rules, is best classified as which type of law?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Customary law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law consists of regulations created and enforced by government agencies to carry out their regulatory functions. Criminal law addresses offenses against society, civil law addresses disputes between private parties, and customary law is based on regional customs and traditions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A risk assessment determines that a server has an Asset Value of $200,000, an Exposure Factor of 25% for a specific threat, and an Annualized Rate of Occurrence of 0.5. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$25,000","$50,000","$100,000","$200,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = AV x EF = $200,000 x 0.25 = $50,000. ALE = SLE x ARO = $50,000 x 0.5 = $25,000. The other values represent errors in applying the EF or ARO multipliers.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization purchases a cyber liability insurance policy to help cover potential financial losses from a data breach. This action represents which risk management strategy?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Risk avoidance eliminates the activity causing risk, mitigation reduces likelihood or impact through controls, and acceptance means acknowledging the risk without action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which risk management approach assigns numeric values, such as monetary loss potential, to assets and threats in order to calculate metrics like Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["Qualitative risk analysis","Quantitative risk analysis","Residual risk analysis","Delphi technique"],"c":1,"why":"Quantitative risk analysis uses numerical values (asset value, exposure factor, annualized rate of occurrence) to calculate measurable outcomes like ALE. Qualitative analysis uses subjective ratings (high/medium/low), residual risk is what remains after controls, and the Delphi technique is a qualitative consensus-building method.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A risk assessment determines that a critical server has an asset value of $200,000. A successful ransomware attack is estimated to cause 40% loss of the asset's value, and such an attack is expected to occur once every 4 years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$20,000","$40,000","$80,000","$200,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor = $200,000 x 0.40 = $80,000. ARO = 1/4 = 0.25. ALE = SLE x ARO = $80,000 x 0.25 = $20,000. The other options result from misapplying the exposure factor or ARO calculation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company's security documentation includes a document that mandates all laptops must use full-disk encryption with AES-256, with no exceptions permitted. This document is best classified as a:","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, specific technical requirements (e.g., AES-256) that support a higher-level policy. Policies are high-level statements of intent, guidelines are recommended but not mandatory, and procedures are step-by-step instructions for performing tasks.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization ensures that no single employee has enough access or authority to both initiate and approve a financial transaction without involvement from another employee. This control is an example of:","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties splits critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by any single individual. Least privilege limits access to only what's needed, job rotation moves staff between roles over time, and mandatory vacation forces time off to help detect fraud.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's information security policy states that all employee accounts must be protected by strong authentication. A supporting document mandates that passwords must be a minimum of 14 characters and changed every 90 days. What type of document specifies this mandatory, measurable requirement?","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"Standards provide specific, mandatory, measurable requirements that support high-level policy statements. Policies are general statements of intent, guidelines are discretionary recommendations, and procedures are step-by-step instructions for performing a task, none of which fit a mandatory numeric requirement.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An (ISC)² certified professional discovers that a close family member's company is bidding on a contract to provide security services to the professional's employer. The professional is on the evaluation committee. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the MOST appropriate action?","o":["Continue serving on the committee but vote against the family member's company to avoid the appearance of bias","Disclose the relationship to management and recuse themselves from the evaluation process","Abstain from voting but continue participating in discussions","Proceed normally since no financial benefit is directly received"],"c":1,"why":"The Code of Ethics requires professionals to avoid conflicts of interest and act honorably; disclosing the relationship and recusing oneself removes both the actual conflict and its appearance. Continuing to participate in any capacity, even to vote against the relative, still poses an ethical conflict.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"When two canons of the (ISC)² Code of Ethics appear to conflict during a CISSP's professional activities, which canon should take precedence over the others?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the commonwealth, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are explicitly ordered by priority, with protecting society, the commonwealth, and infrastructure taking precedence over the other canons when conflicts arise. The other canons are important but subordinate in the stated hierarchy.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A multinational corporation processes personal data of EU residents through a cloud provider based in another country. Which factor determines whether the GDPR applies to this processing activity?","o":["The physical location of the corporation's headquarters","The nationality of the corporation's employees","The location of the data subjects whose personal data is processed","The country in which the cloud provider's servers are physically located"],"c":2,"why":"GDPR applies based on the location of the data subjects (EU residents) regardless of where the controller or processor is headquartered or where servers are located, reflecting its extraterritorial scope under Article 3.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"After identifying that a third-party payment processor poses a moderate risk of data breach, an organization decides to purchase a cyber-liability insurance policy to cover potential financial losses rather than changing the processor or implementing additional controls. This is an example of:","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk avoidance","Risk acceptance"],"c":1,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing likelihood or impact through controls, avoidance would eliminate the activity causing risk, and acceptance would involve taking no action and absorbing the loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During a Business Impact Analysis, stakeholders determine that the order-processing system must be brought back online within 4 hours of a disruption to avoid unacceptable impact to the business. This 4-hour figure represents the:","o":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Work Recovery Time (WRT)"],"c":1,"why":"RTO is the targeted duration within which a system must be restored after a disruption, derived from the BIA. RPO relates to acceptable data loss measured in time, MTD is the absolute maximum downtime the business can tolerate before severe harm occurs, and WRT is the time needed to reconfigure and validate systems after restoration.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before finalizing a contract with a cloud service provider, an organization's security team requests and reviews the provider's SOC 2 Type II report to evaluate the effectiveness of its internal controls over time. This activity is a key component of:","o":["Configuration management","Third-party/vendor risk management","Incident response planning","Change management"],"c":1,"why":"Reviewing independent audit reports such as SOC 2 Type II is a standard due diligence practice within third-party/vendor risk management to assess a vendor's control environment before engagement. Configuration management, incident response, and change management address internal operational processes, not vendor assurance activities.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A commercial building housing a company's primary data center is valued at $2,000,000. Historical data indicates that a fire causing significant damage would destroy approximately 25% of the asset's value, and such fires occur, on average, once every 10 years. The company is evaluating a fire suppression system that costs $15,000 per year and would reduce the annualized rate of occurrence to once every 50 years. Based on a cost-benefit analysis, what is the annual value of implementing this safeguard?","o":["$10,000","$15,000","$25,000","$40,000"],"c":2,"why":"SLE = $2,000,000 × 0.25 = $500,000. ALE before = $500,000 × 0.10 = $50,000. ALE after = $500,000 × 0.02 = $10,000. Safeguard value = (ALE before − ALE after) − ACS = ($50,000 − $10,000) − $15,000 = $25,000. The other figures omit or misapply one of these components.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During litigation following a data breach, opposing counsel argues that the organization's security program fell below the standard that a reasonably prudent organization in the same industry would have maintained. This legal argument is most directly evaluating the organization's exercise of which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Strict liability","Vicarious liability"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to the ongoing actions taken to maintain an acceptable level of protection, judged against the 'prudent person' standard; failure here supports a negligence claim. Due diligence refers to the research/investigation performed before acting, and strict/vicarious liability describe different liability doctrines not centered on the reasonableness of ongoing security practices.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A board of directors is reviewing the organization's information security program. Which of the following represents the board's most appropriate governance responsibility, as distinguished from senior management's operational responsibilities?","o":["Selecting and configuring specific technical security controls","Conducting the annual penetration test and reviewing findings with the IT team","Approving and periodically reviewing the organization's risk appetite and overall risk tolerance","Writing detailed incident response procedures for the security operations center"],"c":2,"why":"Governance responsibilities such as defining risk appetite and tolerance belong to the board, providing strategic direction, while implementation activities like control selection, testing, and procedure writing are operational tasks delegated to management and technical staff.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm determines that continuing to accept a legacy payment card processing method exposes it to unacceptable regulatory and fraud risk. Rather than investing in compensating controls, the firm decides to permanently discontinue that payment method entirely. Which risk treatment strategy has the firm employed?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk avoidance","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Risk avoidance involves eliminating the activity that gives rise to the risk entirely, as the firm did by discontinuing the payment method. Mitigation would involve reducing the risk through controls, transfer would shift the risk to a third party, and acceptance would involve tolerating the risk without action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which element of the CIA triad is primarily violated when an unauthorized individual reads confidential payroll data without altering it?","o":["Availability","Integrity","Confidentiality","Non-repudiation"],"c":2,"why":"Confidentiality protects data from unauthorized disclosure; since the data was only read, not changed or made unavailable, confidentiality is the violated principle. Integrity concerns unauthorized modification, availability concerns access to authorized users, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A critical order-processing system has a documented Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 6 hours. The current disaster recovery plan specifies a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 4 hours for restoring the system, followed by a Work Recovery Time (WRT) of 3 hours to validate data integrity and resume full business operations. What conclusion should the risk manager draw from this information?","o":["The plan is acceptable because the RTO alone is less than the MTD","The plan violates the MTD because the combined RTO and WRT total exceeds the 6-hour limit","The plan is acceptable because WRT is not counted against MTD","The Recovery Point Objective must be recalculated before any conclusion can be drawn"],"c":1,"why":"MTD represents the total time from disruption until the business function must be restored, encompassing both RTO (technical restoration) and WRT (validation and resumption of operations). Here, 4 + 3 = 7 hours exceeds the 6-hour MTD, meaning the plan is inadequate; RPO relates to data loss tolerance, not this timing conflict.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization is contracting with a cloud service provider to process regulated customer data. Which contractual mechanism provides the strongest ongoing assurance that the provider's security controls remain adequate throughout the relationship, rather than only at contract signing?","o":["A one-time non-disclosure agreement signed before data sharing begins","A right-to-audit clause combined with a requirement to periodically deliver independent SOC 2 Type II reports","A service level agreement that specifies only uptime and response-time penalties","A general indemnification clause covering financial losses from a breach"],"c":1,"why":"A right-to-audit clause paired with recurring independent attestation reports (like SOC 2 Type II) provides continuous, verifiable assurance over time about operating effectiveness of controls. An NDA addresses confidentiality only, an SLA focused on uptime doesn't assess security control adequacy, and indemnification addresses financial recovery after the fact rather than preventing or detecting control failures.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's primary data center has an asset value of $5,000,000. Historical data indicates that a specific threat (regional flooding) has an exposure factor of 30% and an annualized rate of occurrence of 0.4. Before implementing any new controls, what is the annualized loss expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$1,500,000","$600,000","$200,000","$2,000,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = AV × EF = $5,000,000 × 0.30 = $1,500,000; ALE = SLE × ARO = $1,500,000 × 0.4 = $600,000. $1,500,000 is the SLE, not the ALE, and the other figures do not result from correctly applying the formula.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"Prior to signing a contract with a new cloud service provider, a company's leadership commissions an independent third party to review the provider's SOC 2 report, financial stability, and past breach history. This activity is best described as an example of:","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Residual risk analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before acting, such as vetting a vendor; due care refers to the ongoing reasonable actions taken afterward to protect assets. Risk acceptance and residual risk analysis are unrelated risk-management concepts, not pre-contract investigatory activities.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A security team publishes a document specifying that all production Linux servers must be hardened using a specific minimum set of configuration settings (e.g., disabled root SSH login, minimum password complexity, required logging services) before deployment. This document is best classified as which type of security document?","o":["Policy","Guideline","Baseline","Procedure"],"c":2,"why":"A baseline defines the minimum mandatory level of security configuration that systems of a given type must meet. A policy would state high-level intent (e.g., 'systems must be hardened'), a procedure would give step-by-step instructions for achieving the baseline, and a guideline offers optional, discretionary recommendations rather than mandatory minimums.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company determines that the cost of implementing a control exceeds the potential loss from a risk, and decides to purchase cyber insurance instead. Which risk treatment strategy is being applied?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which defines risk transfer. Mitigation involves reducing the risk through controls, avoidance means eliminating the activity causing the risk, and acceptance means acknowledging the risk without further action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A U.S.-based company processes personal data of EU residents on behalf of an EU client, and no adequacy decision exists between the U.S. and the EU for this data flow. Which mechanism should the company rely on to legally justify the cross-border transfer under GDPR?","o":["The invalidated EU-US Privacy Shield framework","Standard Contractual Clauses approved by the European Commission","Unilateral encryption of the data in transit and at rest","A simple statement of compliance in the company's public privacy policy"],"c":1,"why":"Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs) are a recognized GDPR transfer mechanism providing contractual safeguards absent an adequacy decision. Privacy Shield was invalidated by the Schrems II ruling, and neither encryption alone nor a self-declared compliance statement satisfies the legal requirement for a valid transfer mechanism.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A federal regulatory agency fines a healthcare organization for failing to maintain reasonable safeguards for patient data, issuing the penalty directly through its own enforcement process rather than through a jury trial. This enforcement action is best categorized under which type of law?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Common law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law encompasses regulations and penalties enforced directly by government agencies without a criminal trial. Criminal law requires prosecution for statutory offenses, civil/tort law involves private lawsuits for damages, and common law is judge-made precedent, none of which match a regulatory agency's direct enforcement authority.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Within a security policy framework, which document provides mandatory, specific technical requirements that must be met, such as requiring AES-256 encryption for data at rest?","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"Standards are mandatory, specific requirements that support policy objectives, such as specifying an encryption algorithm. Policies are high-level statements of intent, guidelines are recommended but not mandatory, and procedures are step-by-step instructions for performing tasks.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified security manager discovers that senior leadership plans to conceal a significant data breach from regulators, contrary to legal disclosure requirements. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which action best reflects the professional's primary obligation?","o":["Resign immediately to avoid personal liability","Follow management's instructions since loyalty to the employer is the first canon","Refuse to participate in the concealment and pursue appropriate channels to ensure the breach is properly disclosed","Publicly disclose the breach to the media before informing management"],"c":2,"why":"The first canon of the Code, 'Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure,' takes precedence over loyalty to an employer, requiring the professional to act legally and ethically through proper channels rather than concealing the issue, resigning without addressing it, or bypassing due process by leaking to the media.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon should a CISSP-certified professional consider FIRST when facing a conflict between organizational directives and the public good?","o":["Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Advance and protect the profession"],"c":0,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics lists protecting society and the common good as the first and highest-priority canon, taking precedence over obligations to employers or the profession when conflicts arise. The other canons are also part of the code but are not prioritized above protecting society.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A critical order-processing system has a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 8 hours. The disaster recovery team estimates that once the system is technically restored, an additional 5 hours are required to verify data integrity and resume full business operations (Work Recovery Time). What is the maximum acceptable Recovery Time Objective (RTO) for restoring the technical system itself?","o":["8 hours","5 hours","3 hours","13 hours"],"c":2,"why":"MTD = RTO + WRT, so RTO = MTD − WRT = 8 − 5 = 3 hours. The other options equal the MTD or WRT alone, or incorrectly sum them, which would exceed the tolerable downtime.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which element of the CIA triad ensures that information is accurate and has not been altered by unauthorized parties?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Integrity specifically addresses the accuracy and trustworthiness of data, ensuring it has not been improperly modified. Confidentiality protects against unauthorized disclosure, availability ensures access when needed, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution implements cryptographic hash functions to verify that transaction records have not been altered after they are written to the database. This control primarily supports which principle of the CIA triad?","o":["Confidentiality, because hashing prevents unauthorized users from reading the data","Integrity, because hashing allows detection of unauthorized modification to data","Availability, because hashing ensures the data can always be retrieved","Non-repudiation, because hashing proves who created the record"],"c":1,"why":"Hash functions produce a fixed-size value that changes if the underlying data is altered, making them a classic integrity control used to detect tampering. They do not encrypt data (confidentiality), guarantee uptime (availability), or by themselves prove authorship (non-repudiation requires digital signatures).","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A civil lawsuit filed by one company against another for breach of contract is best categorized under which type of law?","o":["Criminal law","Administrative law","Civil law","Constitutional law"],"c":2,"why":"Civil law governs disputes between private parties, such as breach of contract, and typically results in monetary damages rather than criminal penalties. Criminal law involves government prosecution of crimes, administrative law involves regulatory agency actions, and constitutional law concerns fundamental governmental structure and rights.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization has outsourced payroll processing to a SaaS provider and wants ongoing assurance that the provider's security controls are operating effectively throughout the year, without conducting its own disruptive on-site audits. Which approach best meets this need?","o":["Require the vendor to provide a SOC 1 Type I report annually","Require the vendor to provide a SOC 2 Type II report covering a review period","Rely solely on the vendor's ISO 27001 certificate of registration","Include financial penalty clauses in the SLA for any future breach"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report attests to the operating effectiveness of controls over a defined period, providing continuous assurance. SOC 1 Type I addresses design at a single point in time and focuses on financial reporting controls, an ISO certificate alone lacks control-testing detail, and SLA penalties are reactive rather than providing ongoing assurance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements a rule that no single employee can both initiate and approve a financial transaction. Which security principle does this represent?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by any one individual. Least privilege limits access rights, defense in depth layers controls, and security through obscurity relies on secrecy rather than structural control.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"During a Business Impact Analysis (BIA), which metric identifies the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":2,"why":"Recovery Point Objective (RPO) defines the maximum acceptable data loss measured in time, indicating how far back data must be restored from backups. RTO measures how quickly systems must be restored, MTD measures the maximum time a business process can be down, and MTBF measures average time between hardware failures.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A bank vault can only be opened when two specific employees insert their individual keys simultaneously; neither employee's key alone will unlock the vault. This control is best described as:","o":["Separation of duties","Two-person (dual) control","Least privilege","Job rotation"],"c":1,"why":"Dual/two-person control requires two individuals to act together to complete a single sensitive action, matching the vault scenario. Separation of duties splits a broader process into distinct tasks performed by different people rather than requiring simultaneous joint action; least privilege limits access rights generally; job rotation moves personnel between roles over time.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A risk assessment determines that a data center asset is valued at $2,000,000. A flood is expected to damage 25% of the asset's value each time it occurs, and floods are expected to occur once every four years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$500,000","$125,000","$2,000,000","$50,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor = $2,000,000 x 0.25 = $500,000. ARO = 1/4 = 0.25. ALE = SLE x ARO = $500,000 x 0.25 = $125,000. The other options confuse SLE with ALE or misapply the ARO.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes 'due diligence' in the context of information security governance?","o":["Taking reasonable action after identifying a risk","Researching and understanding risks before making decisions","Implementing technical controls to enforce policy","Transferring risk to a third party via insurance"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed to understand risks prior to acting. Due care, by contrast, involves taking reasonable action based on that knowledge; the other options describe unrelated risk treatment activities.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"In data governance, who is typically responsible for approving access rights and determining the classification level of a specific dataset?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Security administrator","End user"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner has ultimate responsibility for the data, including classifying it and approving who may access it. The data custodian handles day-to-day technical maintenance, the security administrator implements access based on the owner's decisions, and end users simply use the data under authorized permissions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A data center is located in a region with a low probability but potentially catastrophic financial impact from flooding. Relocating the facility is cost-prohibitive, and structural flood mitigation would cost more than the asset's value. The organization purchases a comprehensive flood insurance policy to cover potential losses. This is an example of which risk treatment strategy?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of the risk to a third party, which defines risk transfer. Mitigation involves reducing likelihood or impact through controls, avoidance means eliminating the exposure entirely, and acceptance means retaining the risk without any compensating measure such as insurance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A newly hired CISO reviews the organization's cybersecurity insurance policy, past incident history, and applicable regulatory requirements before recommending a security program strategy. This activity is best described as an exercise of:","o":["Due care","Separation of duties","Due diligence","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed prior to making a decision or taking action, such as reviewing policies and history before recommending a strategy. Due care refers to the ongoing, reasonable actions taken to maintain protection after diligence has been performed; the other options are unrelated concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company's security policy states that all employees must complete annual security awareness training. Which type of document specifies the exact steps and tools used to deliver this training?","o":["Policy","Standard","Procedure","Guideline"],"c":2,"why":"A procedure provides detailed, step-by-step instructions for accomplishing a task. Policies set high-level intent, standards define mandatory requirements, and guidelines offer discretionary recommendations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which risk management strategy involves purchasing a cybersecurity insurance policy to cover potential financial losses from a data breach?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Risk transfer shifts the financial impact of a risk to another party, such as an insurer. Avoidance eliminates the risk activity entirely, mitigation reduces likelihood or impact, and acceptance means tolerating the risk without action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A manufacturing company is fined by a government environmental agency for failing to comply with mandated emissions-reporting requirements, without any court trial involved. This enforcement action falls under which category of law?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Customary law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law is created and enforced by government agencies through regulations, and violations often result in fines or sanctions without a full criminal trial. Criminal law involves prosecution by the state for crimes, civil law addresses disputes between private parties, and customary law is based on long-standing societal traditions rather than agency regulation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization's disaster recovery plan specifies that the customer database must be restored within 4 hours of an outage. This 4-hour value represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":2,"why":"RTO defines the target time within which a system or process must be restored after a disruption. RPO measures acceptable data loss, MTD is the maximum outage a business can survive, and MTBF measures average time between failures of a component.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization determines that the cost of implementing additional controls for a low-probability, low-impact risk exceeds the potential loss. Management decides to take no further action and documents the decision. Which risk response strategy is being applied?","o":["Risk transfer","Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk acceptance"],"c":3,"why":"Risk acceptance occurs when management consciously decides to take no additional action because the cost of treatment outweighs the potential loss, and this decision is documented. Transfer shifts risk to a third party, avoidance eliminates the activity causing the risk, and mitigation reduces risk through added controls, none of which occurred here.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following actions would be considered a violation by a CISSP holder?","o":["Reporting a discovered vulnerability to the affected vendor","Advising management on the true costs and risks of a proposed security solution","Concealing a known security breach from stakeholders to avoid reputational damage","Refusing to perform unethical instructions from a manager"],"c":2,"why":"Concealing a known breach violates the Code of Ethics canon requiring honesty and protection of society, the profession, and stakeholders. The other options reflect ethical, professional behavior consistent with the Code.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's information security policy states, 'All employees must complete security awareness training annually.' The document specifying the exact steps, screenshots, and system used to complete this training is best classified as a:","o":["Standard","Guideline","Procedure","Baseline"],"c":2,"why":"A procedure provides detailed, step-by-step instructions for carrying out a specific task, such as how to complete required training. A standard specifies mandatory requirements, a guideline offers discretionary recommendations, and a baseline defines a minimum level of security configuration.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of a security awareness program within an organization's overall risk management strategy?","o":["To satisfy regulatory audit checklist requirements only","To reduce risk by influencing employee behavior toward secure practices","To replace the need for technical security controls","To assign legal liability to employees for security incidents"],"c":1,"why":"Security awareness programs aim to reduce risk by shaping employee behavior and reducing human-factor vulnerabilities, complementing rather than replacing technical controls. The other options misstate the program's purpose or intent.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During a Business Impact Analysis, a critical order-processing system is found to have a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 8 hours. The disaster recovery team designs a solution with a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 12 hours. What is the most significant concern with this design?","o":["The RTO should always equal the RPO for consistency","The RTO exceeds the MTD, meaning recovery would occur too late to prevent unacceptable business impact","The MTD is too short and should be extended to match the RTO","There is no concern, since RTO and MTD measure unrelated recovery metrics"],"c":1,"why":"The RTO must be less than or equal to the MTD; if recovery takes longer than the business can tolerate being down, the organization will suffer unacceptable impact even after 'successful' recovery. RTO and RPO measure different things (time vs. data loss), and MTD is a business-driven constraint that should not simply be adjusted to fit a design.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"While conducting an authorized penetration test, a CISSP-certified consultant discovers evidence that a company employee is exfiltrating customer data to a competitor, which is outside the scope of the signed testing agreement. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the MOST appropriate action?","o":["Ignore the finding since it is outside the contracted scope of work","Confront the employee directly to gather additional evidence before reporting","Report the finding to the appropriate authorized parties within the client organization, even though it falls outside the original scope","Publicly disclose the finding to warn other potential victims of the competitor"],"c":2,"why":"The Code of Ethics requires CISSPs to act in the best interest of society, the profession, and the principal, which includes reporting discovered illegal activity such as data exfiltration to proper authorized parties even if outside the original scope. Ignoring it violates the duty to protect the client, confronting the employee could compromise evidence and personal safety, and public disclosure would violate confidentiality obligations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A financial services firm owns a database server valued at $500,000. A successful ransomware attack is estimated to destroy 20% of the server's value in recovery costs and downtime, and such attacks are expected to occur once every two years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$50,000","$100,000","$20,000","$200,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x EF = $500,000 x 0.20 = $100,000. ARO = 1/2 = 0.5. ALE = SLE x ARO = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. The other options reflect miscalculating ARO or omitting the EF/ARO multiplication correctly.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best defines the 'confidentiality' component of the CIA triad?","o":["Ensuring that information is accurate and has not been altered by unauthorized parties","Ensuring that information is accessible to authorized users when needed","Preventing unauthorized disclosure of information to individuals, entities, or processes","Ensuring that actions taken by a user cannot be denied later"],"c":2,"why":"Confidentiality specifically addresses protecting data from unauthorized disclosure. Integrity addresses accuracy/alteration, availability addresses accessibility, and non-repudiation addresses denial of actions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company requires that no single employee can both initiate a wire transfer and approve it, forcing two different people to be involved in the process. This control is an example of which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Need-to-know","Defense in depth"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides a sensitive task among multiple individuals to prevent fraud or error by any one person. Least privilege limits access to what is needed for a job function, need-to-know restricts information access, and defense in depth refers to layered controls, none of which specifically describe splitting a single process between two people.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization calculates that a specific threat could cause $50,000 in damage and is expected to occur twice per year. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$25,000","$50,000","$100,000","$150,000"],"c":2,"why":"ALE = Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) x Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) = $50,000 x 2 = $100,000. The other values result from incorrect application of the formula.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A security manager implements industry-standard safeguards and continuously monitors their effectiveness over time. This behavior best exemplifies which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Risk transference","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to the ongoing actions taken to maintain an appropriate standard of protection. Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before implementing controls, while transference and separation of duties are unrelated risk/control concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which document type provides mandatory, specific requirements that must be met to comply with an organization's security policy?","o":["Guideline","Standard","Procedure","Baseline"],"c":1,"why":"A standard defines mandatory requirements supporting policy. Guidelines are recommendations, procedures are step-by-step instructions, and baselines represent a minimum acceptable configuration level, not compliance requirements themselves.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which category of law is primarily concerned with resolving disputes between private parties and typically results in monetary damages rather than imprisonment?","o":["Criminal law","Civil law","Administrative law","Constitutional law"],"c":1,"why":"Civil (tort) law addresses disputes between private parties with remedies such as damages. Criminal law involves government prosecution and potential imprisonment, administrative law involves regulatory agency rules, and constitutional law governs fundamental government structure and rights.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's IT director signs off on a new firewall deployment plan and personally reviews the change control documentation before implementation, but does not verify that the technicians actually configured the rules correctly after deployment. This demonstrates which concept, and what is missing?","o":["Due diligence was performed, but due care was not, since the director failed to verify the outcome","Due care was performed, but due diligence was not, since the director failed to research the vendor","Both due care and due diligence were satisfied because documentation was reviewed","Neither due care nor due diligence apply to technical implementation activities"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence is the research and planning phase (reviewing documentation, understanding requirements); due care is the ongoing responsible action of following through and verifying results. The director performed diligence but failed to exercise due care by not confirming the actual configuration was correct.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization owns an asset valued at $500,000. A specific threat, if realized, is expected to destroy 20% of the asset's value, and historical data indicates this threat occurs on average once every two years. A proposed safeguard would reduce the exposure factor's frequency such that the annualized rate of occurrence drops to 0.1, and the safeguard costs $8,000 per year to operate. What is the annualized value (net benefit) of implementing this safeguard?","o":["$8,000","$32,000","$40,000","$42,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = $500,000 x 20% = $100,000. ALE before = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. ALE after = $100,000 x 0.1 = $10,000. Value of safeguard = ($50,000 - $10,000) - $8,000 = $32,000. The other values result from omitting the ACS deduction or miscalculating ALE figures.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"In business continuity planning, the maximum amount of data loss measured in time that an organization can tolerate is known as the:","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, dictating backup frequency. RTO measures acceptable downtime for restoring operations, MTD is the total time a business can be disrupted, and MTBF relates to hardware reliability, not data loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Under most modern data protection regulations (such as the GDPR), an organization that collects customer email addresses for order confirmations but later uses them for unrelated marketing campaigns without additional consent has violated which principle?","o":["Data minimization","Purpose limitation","Storage limitation","Accountability"],"c":1,"why":"Purpose limitation requires that personal data be used only for the specific purpose for which it was originally collected unless further consent is obtained. Data minimization concerns collecting only necessary data, storage limitation concerns retention periods, and accountability concerns demonstrating compliance, none of which directly address using data for a new, unrelated purpose.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO commissioned a thorough risk assessment identifying that unencrypted laptops posed a significant data breach risk, and the report recommended full-disk encryption within 90 days. Budget was approved, but the rollout was never completed, and a laptop was later stolen with unencrypted sensitive data. In a subsequent negligence claim, which concept best describes the organization's failure?","o":["Failure of due diligence, because the risk was never properly researched","Failure of due care, because reasonable, informed action was not taken after risk was identified","Failure of separation of duties, because one person controlled the encryption rollout","Failure of least privilege, because too many employees had laptop access"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence was satisfied by conducting the risk assessment; due care requires acting on that knowledge with reasonable protective measures, which the organization failed to do. The other options are unrelated control concepts, not liability standards.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following is a foundational canon that all certified professionals must uphold?","o":["Maximize profit for the employer at all costs","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Always prioritize technical efficiency over legal compliance","Disclose all vulnerabilities publicly regardless of employer policy"],"c":1,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics' first canon requires professionals to protect society and the infrastructure. The other options either contradict ethical obligations or ignore legal/organizational constraints on disclosure.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, when a CISSP-certified professional discovers a conflict between protecting the public interest and following a direct order from their employer that would harm third parties, which canon takes precedence?","o":["Act honorably, honestly, justly, legally, and responsibly","Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are prioritized in order, with 'Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure' listed first and taking precedence when canons conflict. The other canons are also part of the code but are subordinate in priority order.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution requires that any wire transfer exceeding $50,000 be entered by one clerk and independently approved by a separate supervisor before funds are released, with neither individual able to complete the transaction alone. This control is best described as an example of:","o":["Job rotation","Two-person control (separation of duties)","Mandatory vacation policy","Least privilege enforcement"],"c":1,"why":"Requiring two distinct individuals to jointly complete a sensitive transaction is a classic two-person integrity/separation of duties control. Job rotation and mandatory vacation are detective/fraud-deterrent controls unrelated to transaction-splitting, and least privilege concerns access scope, not dual authorization.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company decides to purchase cybersecurity insurance to help cover potential financial losses from a data breach. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, representing risk transfer. Avoidance eliminates the risk entirely, mitigation reduces likelihood/impact through controls, and acceptance means taking no action and absorbing the risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A business impact analysis determines that an e-commerce order-processing system must be restored within 4 hours of an outage to avoid unacceptable financial loss, and that no more than 15 minutes of transaction data can be lost. The 4-hour figure represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Mean Time to Repair (MTTR)"],"c":2,"why":"RTO is the targeted duration within which a system must be restored after an outage. The 15-minute figure describes RPO (acceptable data loss). MTD is typically the outer boundary before catastrophic impact, and MTTR is an average historical repair metric, not a planning target derived from BIA.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP is contracted to perform a security assessment. During the engagement, the client instructs the CISSP to omit certain discovered vulnerabilities from the final report to avoid regulatory scrutiny, even though the vulnerabilities pose a credible risk to public safety. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics canon precedence, what is the CISSP's most appropriate action?","o":["Comply with the client's request since contractual confidentiality takes precedence over disclosure","Refuse to omit the findings and escalate appropriately, since protecting society and the common good takes precedence over client instructions","Quietly resign from the engagement without informing anyone of the vulnerabilities","Include the vulnerabilities only if the client explicitly agrees to it in writing"],"c":1,"why":"The Code of Ethics canons are ordered with 'Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure' as the highest priority, which supersedes client instructions or contractual convenience. Silent resignation and unconditional compliance both fail to uphold this duty.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A manufacturing company identifies a moderate risk of equipment theft at a remote warehouse. Rather than installing costly additional physical controls, the company purchases a commercial insurance policy to cover potential losses. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing likelihood or impact directly (e.g., better locks or guards), avoidance would mean eliminating the risk-causing activity entirely, and acceptance would mean taking no action and absorbing the loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's maximum tolerable downtime (MTD) for its order-processing system is defined as 8 hours. The disaster recovery plan specifies a recovery time objective (RTO) of 6 hours and backups performed every 4 hours (establishing the RPO). During an actual disaster, the recovery team requires 9 hours to fully restore operations, though data loss remained within the defined backup interval. What is the most accurate assessment of this outcome?","o":["The RPO was violated because backups occurred every 4 hours","The MTD was exceeded, indicating the organization is at risk of severe business impact despite meeting its data-loss tolerance","The RTO was satisfied because the system was eventually restored","No impact occurred because RPO governs downtime, not data loss"],"c":1,"why":"Because actual recovery took 9 hours, it exceeded both the 8-hour MTD and the 6-hour RTO target, creating unacceptable business impact even though data loss (RPO) stayed within tolerance. RPO measures data loss, not downtime, so options A and D misstate its purpose.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's security documentation includes a mandatory rule stating that all laptops must use full-disk encryption with AES-256, along with a separate document recommending (but not requiring) the use of privacy screens in open office areas. These two documents are best classified, respectively, as:","o":["Policy and procedure","Standard and guideline","Procedure and standard","Guideline and policy"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, specific requirements (AES-256 encryption), while a guideline offers recommended, non-mandatory practices. Policies are high-level statements of intent, and procedures are step-by-step instructions, neither of which matches the mandatory technical specification or the optional recommendation described here.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO is evaluating a cloud service provider and receives a SOC 2 Type I report as assurance evidence prior to contract signing. What is the most significant limitation of relying solely on this report to assess ongoing operational risk?","o":["It addresses only the design of controls at a specific point in time, not their operating effectiveness over a period","It is produced by the provider's internal audit team rather than an independent CPA firm","It only evaluates availability controls and excludes confidentiality and security","It cannot legally be shared with the client's regulators or auditors"],"c":0,"why":"A SOC 2 Type I report attests to the suitability of control design at a single point in time, whereas Type II tests operating effectiveness over a review period (typically 6-12 months)—a critical distinction for ongoing risk assurance. The other statements misrepresent SOC 2 methodology and issuer requirements.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A data center valued at $2,000,000 is assessed for fire risk. A fire is expected to destroy 25% of the facility's value if it occurs, and historical data indicates such a fire occurs once every 10 years on average. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$50,000","$500,000","$200,000","$5,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = AV × EF = $2,000,000 × 0.25 = $500,000. ARO = 1/10 = 0.1. ALE = SLE × ARO = $500,000 × 0.1 = $50,000. The other values represent common calculation errors, such as confusing SLE with ALE or misapplying the exposure factor.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A U.S.-based online retailer has no offices, employees, or servers located in the European Union. However, its website offers shipping to EU countries, displays prices in Euros, and uses behavioral tracking to serve targeted advertisements to EU visitors. Under the GDPR, which statement correctly describes the regulation's applicability?","o":["GDPR does not apply because the company lacks any physical establishment within the EU","GDPR applies because the company offers goods/services to, and monitors the behavior of, EU data subjects regardless of its physical location","GDPR applies only if the company stores personal data on servers physically located within the EU","GDPR applies only if the company is legally incorporated within an EU member state"],"c":1,"why":"GDPR's extraterritorial scope (Article 3) applies when a non-EU organization offers goods/services to, or monitors the behavior of, individuals in the EU, irrespective of physical presence or data storage location. The other options describe outdated or incorrect jurisdictional tests.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution's business impact analysis reveals that a particular database outage occurs, on average, twice per year, and each occurrence results in $75,000 of lost revenue. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$37,500","$75,000","$150,000","$225,000"],"c":2,"why":"ALE = SLE x ARO = $75,000 x 2 = $150,000. The other values result from miscalculating or misapplying the ARO/SLE relationship.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's known critical vulnerability remained unpatched for six months despite vendor patches being available and industry practice dictating patching within 30 days. Following a resulting breach, a lawsuit is filed. Which legal concept would most likely form the basis of liability against the organization?","o":["Failure to perform due diligence before signing a vendor contract","Breach of the due care standard, constituting negligence","Strict liability regardless of the organization's conduct","Vicarious liability for the actions of the attacker"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to the ongoing standard of reasonable, prudent behavior expected of an organization; failing to meet the industry-standard patching timeline demonstrates a breach of due care, which is the basis of negligence claims. Due diligence pertains to pre-decision investigation, not ongoing operational conduct, and strict/vicarious liability don't fit this fact pattern.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A security manager researches industry regulations, consults legal counsel, and reviews best-practice frameworks before drafting a new data retention policy. Once approved, the organization continuously monitors and enforces the policy across all departments. Which two concepts, respectively, do these two phases represent?","o":["Due care, then due diligence","Due diligence, then due care","Risk avoidance, then risk acceptance","Gross negligence, then due care"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence is the research and investigation performed before acting, while due care is the ongoing, reasonable maintenance of protective measures afterward. The other options misapply unrelated risk or negligence concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization publishes a mandatory document stating that all Windows Server deployments must enforce TLS 1.2 or higher and disable SMBv1, and compliance is required across every business unit with no exceptions permitted without formal risk acceptance. This document is best classified as a:","o":["Guideline","Procedure","Security baseline","Executive policy statement"],"c":2,"why":"A security baseline defines the mandatory minimum secure configuration for a specific platform or technology, which matches this scenario precisely. Guidelines are advisory rather than mandatory, procedures provide step-by-step implementation instructions, and policy statements are typically high-level and technology-agnostic rather than configuration-specific.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"After implementing all cost-justified technical controls, an organization still faces residual risk from a low-probability, high-impact ransomware attack. The organization purchases a cyber insurance policy to cover potential financial losses from such an event. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of the residual risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation would involve additional controls, avoidance would mean discontinuing the risky activity, and acceptance would mean taking no further action and absorbing the loss internally.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A newly hired CISO builds a three-year security roadmap that is explicitly tied to the company's strategic growth plan and reports risk exposure to the board using business impact terms rather than technical jargon. This approach best demonstrates which security management concept?","o":["Security control baselining","Security governance aligned with business objectives","Defense-in-depth architecture","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Aligning the security program with organizational strategy and communicating risk in business terms is a hallmark of effective security governance. The other options describe technical or operational controls, not governance alignment.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO wants to select a framework primarily to align IT operations with overall business objectives and provide a comprehensive set of control objectives for IT management and governance, rather than pursue a certifiable information security management system. Which framework is BEST suited to this goal?","o":["ISO/IEC 27001","COBIT","NIST SP 800-53","PCI DSS"],"c":1,"why":"COBIT is an IT governance framework designed to align IT processes with business goals through control objectives, and organizations are not certified against it in the same way as ISO 27001. ISO 27001 is an ISMS certification standard, NIST 800-53 is a security control catalog for federal systems, and PCI DSS is a payment-card compliance standard, none of which match the stated governance-alignment goal.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An employee steals proprietary source code and sells it to a competitor. The company sues the former employee to recover financial losses, while a government prosecutor separately files charges against the same individual for theft. Which statement best describes this scenario?","o":["Both actions are civil suits seeking monetary compensation for the company","The civil suit seeks damages for the company, while the criminal case is brought by the state to punish violation of law","The criminal case allows the company to recover damages directly from the employee","Civil and criminal law cannot both apply to the same underlying act"],"c":1,"why":"Civil law addresses disputes between private parties seeking compensation, while criminal law is prosecuted by the government to punish offenses against society; both can arise from the same act. The other options misstate the purpose or exclusivity of civil versus criminal proceedings.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization determines that the Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) for its critical order-processing system is 8 hours. The disaster recovery team calculates a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 10 hours for that system based on current recovery capabilities. What does this discrepancy indicate?","o":["The Recovery Point Objective should be increased to compensate for the gap","The current recovery strategy is inadequate and will likely cause unacceptable business impact","The system is over-protected, and recovery resources can be reallocated elsewhere","The Work Recovery Time should be reduced to zero to satisfy the MTD"],"c":1,"why":"RTO must be less than or equal to MTD; an RTO of 10 hours against an 8-hour MTD means the organization cannot recover the system fast enough to avoid unacceptable damage, signaling a need for improved recovery strategy. RPO addresses data loss tolerance, not downtime, and the other options misinterpret the relationship between these metrics.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A business impact analysis determines that a critical order-processing system has a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 24 hours. The disaster recovery plan specifies a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 36 hours for that system. What is the primary concern with this plan?","o":["The RTO is unnecessarily conservative and should be extended further","The RTO exceeds the MTD, meaning the recovery plan would fail to meet business survivability requirements","The MTD should be adjusted to match the RTO exactly","There is no concern, since RTO and MTD measure unrelated recovery metrics"],"c":1,"why":"RTO must be less than or equal to MTD; an RTO of 36 hours against a 24-hour MTD means the organization would suffer unacceptable impact before recovery is achieved. The other options misunderstand the relationship between these two metrics.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"While conducting an authorized penetration test, a CISSP discovers evidence that a colleague has been using company resources to run an unrelated personal side business. This is not a security vulnerability within the test's scope. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the MOST appropriate action?","o":["Ignore it, since it falls outside the scope of the security engagement","Report it through appropriate channels, since the Code requires acting honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally at all times","Confront the colleague directly and personally demand they stop","Anonymously disclose the information to the colleague's supervisor to avoid involvement"],"c":1,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics obligates professionals to act honorably and legally in all professional dealings, not merely within the narrow scope of a specific engagement; discovering misuse of company resources should be reported through proper channels. Ignoring it, confronting the individual personally, or acting anonymously all fail to meet the standard of responsible, transparent conduct expected under the Code.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which element of the CIA triad ensures that data is not disclosed to unauthorized individuals, entities, or processes?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":0,"why":"Confidentiality specifically addresses protecting information from unauthorized disclosure. Integrity concerns data accuracy, availability concerns access, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"After a risk assessment, an organization decides to purchase a cyber liability insurance policy to cover potential breach-related costs rather than investing further in additional technical controls. This decision represents which risk treatment strategy?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing the risk itself, avoidance would eliminate the activity, and acceptance would mean taking no action and retaining the risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company evaluating a cloud service provider requires assurance that the provider's security-related controls are both suitably designed AND have been operating effectively over a review period of 6-12 months. Which type of report should the company request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3"],"c":2,"why":"SOC 2 Type II reports evaluate the design and operating effectiveness of security, availability, and related controls over an extended period, providing the assurance described. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, SOC 2 Type I only assesses design at a point in time, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report lacking the detailed testing evidence of a Type II report.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements a formal policy requiring background checks before hiring, even though not legally mandated in its jurisdiction, because it reflects prudent business practice. This best illustrates which concept?","o":["Due process","Separation of duties","Due care","Least privilege"],"c":2,"why":"Due care refers to the reasonable steps an organization takes to protect its interests, such as voluntarily implementing prudent security practices. Due process relates to legal fairness, separation of duties splits tasks among individuals, and least privilege limits access rights.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISSP-certified professional discovers strong evidence that a close personal friend and colleague has been falsifying security audit results. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the most appropriate action?","o":["Ignore the issue since it involves a personal friendship and is not the CISSP's direct responsibility","Report the misconduct through appropriate channels, since the obligation to act honestly and protect the profession supersedes personal relationships","Confront the friend privately and allow them to correct the records without informing management","Wait until the annual performance review to raise the concern informally"],"c":1,"why":"The Code of Ethics requires CISSPs to act honorably, honestly, justly, and legally, and to protect the profession and society, which takes precedence over personal loyalty. The other options involve concealment or delay, which violate the Code.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A US-based SaaS company processes the personal data of EU residents strictly according to the instructions of its customer, a European retailer that determines the purposes and means of the processing. Under the GDPR, what role does the SaaS company hold with respect to this personal data?","o":["Data controller","Data processor","Data subject","Supervisory authority"],"c":1,"why":"Because the SaaS company processes data only on behalf of and under the instructions of the retailer, which determines the purpose and means of processing, the SaaS company is classified as a data processor. The retailer, which sets the purposes and means, is the data controller, and the other options describe unrelated GDPR roles.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company decides to purchase cyber-insurance to cover potential losses from a data breach rather than implementing additional technical controls. Which risk response strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which defines risk transfer. Avoidance eliminates the activity, mitigation reduces the risk directly, and acceptance means taking no action while acknowledging the risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before contracting with a cloud service provider, an organization's security team requests a SOC 2 Type II report rather than a SOC 2 Type I report. What is the primary reason for this preference?","o":["Type II reports are less expensive for vendors to produce","Type II reports evaluate the operating effectiveness of controls over a period of time, rather than just their design at a single point in time","Type II reports are required by law for all cloud providers","Type II reports replace the need for a formal contract or SLA with the vendor"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report assesses whether controls operated effectively over an extended period, providing greater assurance than a Type I report, which only evaluates control design at a single point in time. The other options are factually incorrect.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An asset valued at $200,000 has an Exposure Factor (EF) of 25% and an Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) of 2. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$25,000","$50,000","$100,000","$200,000"],"c":2,"why":"SLE = Asset Value × EF = $200,000 × 0.25 = $50,000. ALE = SLE × ARO = $50,000 × 2 = $100,000. The other values represent miscalculations of SLE or asset value alone.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which document type provides mandatory, specific requirements that must be followed to comply with an organization's security policy?","o":["Guideline","Standard","Procedure","Baseline"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory rules that support policy compliance, such as required password length. Guidelines are advisory, procedures are step-by-step instructions, and baselines represent a minimum acceptable configuration level, not a policy-driven requirement document.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization owns a data center valued at $2,000,000. A risk analysis determines that a specific flood scenario would destroy 25% of the facility's value (exposure factor) and is expected to occur once every two years (ARO = 0.5). What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$250,000","$500,000","$125,000","$1,000,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value × Exposure Factor = $2,000,000 × 0.25 = $500,000. ALE = SLE × ARO = $500,000 × 0.5 = $250,000. The other options result from misapplying the formula (e.g., forgetting to multiply by ARO, or using the wrong EF/ARO combination).","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following is the FIRST canon a CISSP must uphold?","o":["Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Advance and protect the profession","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics lists 'Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure' as the first and most important canon. The other statements are also canons but are listed after this priority.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During a risk assessment, an organization identifies a critical vulnerability in a customer-facing application but management decides not to allocate budget to remediate it, citing other priorities. Six months later, attackers exploit the exact vulnerability, causing a significant data breach. From a legal liability perspective, which concept most directly exposes the organization to a finding of negligence?","o":["Failure of due diligence, because the organization never identified the risk","Failure of due care, because the organization identified the risk but failed to act to mitigate it","Failure of separation of duties in the application's access control design","Failure of least privilege enforcement on database accounts"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence is the research/identification of risk (which occurred here), while due care is the ongoing action taken to address known risk; failing to act on a known vulnerability is a due care failure. The remaining options describe unrelated technical control concepts, not the legal liability issue at hand.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A multinational company processing personal data of European Union residents must comply with which regulation regarding data privacy?","o":["HIPAA","GDPR","SOX","GLBA"],"c":1,"why":"The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) governs the processing of personal data of EU residents, regardless of where the processing organization is located. HIPAA applies to U.S. healthcare data, SOX to financial reporting, and GLBA to U.S. financial institutions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which plan primarily focuses on restoring IT systems and technical infrastructure after a disruptive event, as opposed to sustaining overall business operations?","o":["Business Continuity Plan (BCP)","Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)","Incident Response Plan (IRP)","Business Impact Analysis (BIA)"],"c":1,"why":"The DRP is focused on restoring IT systems and technology infrastructure after a disaster. The BCP addresses continuation of overall business operations, the IRP addresses handling security incidents, and the BIA is an analysis process, not a recovery plan.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP serving as CISO is instructed by the CEO to delay mandatory breach notification to regulators until after a pending merger closes, even though notification is legally required within a defined timeframe. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the MOST appropriate initial action?","o":["Comply with the CEO's directive to protect the organization's business interests and employment relationship","Anonymously leak the breach details to a journalist to force disclosure","Refuse to delay notification, explain the legal obligation to leadership, and escalate within the organization if the directive persists","Resign immediately without discussing the issue with anyone in the organization"],"c":2,"why":"The Code of Ethics requires CISSPs to protect society and act honorably and legally; the correct response is to refuse the unlawful directive and escalate through proper channels rather than complying, leaking information improperly, or abandoning the role without attempting resolution.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A financial application computes a cryptographic hash of a transaction file before transmission and recalculates the hash upon receipt to confirm the file was not altered in transit. This process primarily supports which principle of the CIA triad?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Hashing verifies that data has not been modified, which is the core purpose of integrity. It does not restrict access (confidentiality), ensure uptime (availability), or by itself prove the sender's identity (non-repudiation).","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A Business Impact Analysis determines that the Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) for an order-processing system is 8 hours, beyond which the organization suffers irreversible harm. The current disaster recovery plan restores the system within 10 hours using backups taken every 24 hours. Which statement BEST identifies the deficiency in this plan?","o":["The RPO exceeds the MTD, meaning the data loss window is unacceptable","The RTO exceeds the MTD, meaning the recovery time surpasses the maximum tolerable downtime","The MTD exceeds the RTO, meaning the plan fully satisfies business requirements","The ARO exceeds the SLE, indicating excessive risk exposure"],"c":1,"why":"The plan's Recovery Time Objective (10 hours) exceeds the Maximum Tolerable Downtime (8 hours), meaning the system would not be restored in time to avoid irreversible harm. While the RPO (24-hour data loss) is also concerning, the question specifically highlights the recovery time gap versus MTD; the other options misapply or invert the metrics.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before selecting a new cloud provider, an organization's risk team reviews the vendor's SOC 2 report, conducts a security questionnaire, and evaluates the provider's incident history. This activity best exemplifies which concept?","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Residual risk analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence is the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as vetting a vendor. Due care refers to the ongoing, reasonable actions taken to maintain security after a decision, and the other options do not describe pre-decision investigation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During contract negotiations with a cloud service provider, an organization receives a SOC 2 Type I report as the sole evidence of the provider's security control environment. Which of the following BEST describes the limitation of relying on this report for ongoing third-party risk management?","o":["It only attests to the design of controls at a single point in time, not their operating effectiveness over a period","It provides no information whatsoever about the provider's control environment","It is applicable only to financial statement audits and has no relevance to security controls","It eliminates the need for a right-to-audit clause in the service contract"],"c":0,"why":"A SOC 2 Type I report evaluates control design at a specific point in time, unlike a Type II report which assesses operating effectiveness over a review period; relying solely on Type I leaves gaps in assurance of sustained control performance. The other options mischaracterize the report's purpose or scope.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An asset valued at $200,000 has an exposure factor of 25% for a specific threat, and the threat is expected to occur once every two years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$12,500","$25,000","$50,000","$100,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = AV x EF = $200,000 x 0.25 = $50,000. ARO = 1/2 = 0.5. ALE = SLE x ARO = $50,000 x 0.5 = $25,000. The other values represent miscalculations such as using only the SLE or applying the wrong ARO.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A technology company develops a proprietary manufacturing process and chooses to protect it as a trade secret rather than filing for a patent, in order to maintain protection indefinitely. Which of the following is a requirement the company must continuously satisfy to preserve this legal protection?","o":["Filing renewal applications with a national patent office every ten years","Publishing the process specifications for public peer review","Maintaining reasonable and ongoing measures to keep the information confidential","Registering the process with a national copyright office"],"c":2,"why":"Trade secret protection is contingent on the owner taking reasonable, continuous steps to maintain secrecy (e.g., NDAs, access controls); if the information becomes public or safeguards lapse, the legal protection is lost. Patent renewal, publication, and copyright registration are unrelated to trade secret law and would actually undermine or misclassify this protection.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company's information security program includes a document that mandates all workstations must run full-disk encryption using AES-256, with no exceptions permitted without formal approval. This document is best classified as a:","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, specific requirements (such as AES-256) that support a policy. A policy is a high-level statement of intent, a guideline is advisory/optional, and a procedure describes step-by-step implementation actions rather than a mandatory technical requirement.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization purchases a cyber insurance policy covering costs associated with a data breach and concludes that this policy has effectively eliminated the risk associated with a breach. Which statement BEST describes the flaw in this reasoning?","o":["Insurance reduces the likelihood of a breach occurring in the future","Insurance transfers a portion of the financial impact but does not eliminate residual risks such as reputational damage, regulatory penalties, or operational disruption","Cyber insurance is a form of risk avoidance and removes the underlying vulnerability","Purchasing insurance removes the need for any technical or administrative controls"],"c":1,"why":"Risk transfer (such as insurance) shifts some financial consequences to a third party but does not reduce the likelihood of occurrence or address non-financial residual risks like reputational harm or regulatory action, which are often uninsurable. The other options incorrectly describe insurance as reducing likelihood, avoiding risk, or replacing controls.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"Company A collects personal data from EU residents and determines the purposes and means of processing that data. Company A contracts with Company B, a SaaS provider, to store and process this data strictly according to Company A's written instructions. Under the GDPR, which statement BEST describes the parties' roles and obligations?","o":["Company B, as the data controller, independently determines the purpose of processing","Company A, acting as the data processor, must obtain separate explicit consent for every processing activity Company B performs","Company B, as the data processor, must process personal data only according to Company A's documented instructions and implement appropriate technical and organizational security measures","Both companies are automatically and equally liable for all GDPR violations regardless of their respective roles"],"c":2,"why":"Under GDPR, the entity determining the purpose and means of processing is the controller (Company A), while the entity processing data on the controller's behalf is the processor (Company B), which must act only on documented instructions and implement adequate safeguards. The other options invert the roles or misstate GDPR's liability and consent framework.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A government regulatory agency issues binding rules requiring organizations in a specific industry to report data breaches within 72 hours, with fines for noncompliance. This is an example of which type of law?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Common law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law consists of rules and regulations created by government agencies to enforce statutes, often carrying fines. Criminal law involves prosecution by the state for crimes, civil/tort law addresses disputes between private parties, and common law is based on judicial precedent rather than agency rulemaking.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During business continuity planning, an organization determines that its order-processing system can be unavailable for no more than 4 hours before causing unacceptable financial and reputational damage. This determination is a direct output of which activity?","o":["Business Impact Analysis (BIA)","Vulnerability assessment","Disaster recovery plan testing","Threat modeling"],"c":0,"why":"A BIA identifies critical business functions and determines metrics such as Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) by assessing the impact of disruption. Vulnerability assessments identify weaknesses, DR testing validates recovery procedures, and threat modeling identifies potential attack scenarios rather than downtime tolerances.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization values a critical database server at $500,000. A specific threat, if realized, is expected to destroy 20% of the asset's value, and historical data indicates this threat occurs once every two years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$25,000","$50,000","$100,000","$200,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x EF = $500,000 x 0.20 = $100,000. ARO = 1/2 = 0.5. ALE = SLE x ARO = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. The other options misapply either the exposure factor or the annualized rate of occurrence.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization is negotiating a contract with a third-party managed service provider that will handle sensitive customer data. Which contractual provision would BEST allow the organization to independently verify the provider's ongoing security controls?","o":["A non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","An indemnification clause","A right-to-audit clause","A service level agreement (SLA) guaranteeing 99.9% uptime"],"c":2,"why":"A right-to-audit clause explicitly permits the organization to inspect or assess the vendor's controls and practices. An NDA protects information confidentiality, an indemnification clause addresses liability for losses, and an SLA focuses on performance metrics like uptime, none of which grant audit access.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISO commissions an independent audit and thorough risk assessment before implementing a new cloud storage solution, then ensures ongoing monitoring and periodic reviews after deployment. Which two concepts best describe these respective actions?","o":["Due diligence, then due care","Due care, then due diligence","Risk avoidance, then risk acceptance","Separation of duties, then least privilege"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence is the research and investigation performed before making a decision, while due care is the ongoing, reasonable actions taken to maintain protection afterward. The reversed order in option B is incorrect, and the other pairs describe unrelated risk/access control concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements file integrity monitoring software that generates a cryptographic hash of critical system files and alerts administrators if the hash value changes unexpectedly. Which principle of the CIA triad does this control primarily support?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Detecting unauthorized changes to data through hashing directly supports integrity, which ensures data has not been altered without authorization. Confidentiality concerns unauthorized disclosure, availability concerns access to resources, and non-repudiation is not one of the three CIA triad elements.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISSP-certified professional discovers a critical vulnerability in their employer's public-facing application that could expose customer financial data if exploited. Per the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the MOST appropriate first action?","o":["Publicly disclose the vulnerability to warn potential victims","Report the vulnerability through proper internal channels to enable remediation","Ignore it since it is outside the scope of assigned duties","Sell the vulnerability details to a third-party security firm"],"c":1,"why":"The Code of Ethics canon to 'protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure' obligates professionals to act responsibly, which means reporting issues through proper channels rather than public disclosure, ignoring the issue, or profiting from it, all of which could cause harm or violate trust.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Within an organization's security documentation hierarchy, which document type establishes mandatory, specific technical requirements (such as requiring AES-256 for data at rest) that must be followed to comply with policy?","o":["Guideline","Procedure","Standard","Baseline"],"c":2,"why":"A standard is a mandatory, specific requirement that supports policy implementation. Guidelines are recommendations, procedures are step-by-step instructions, and a baseline is a minimum level of security applied consistently, not a requirement document itself.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Before signing a contract with a new cloud service provider, an organization's legal and security teams review the vendor's SOC 2 report, conduct a security questionnaire, and verify regulatory certifications. This activity is best described as an exercise of:","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed prior to making a decision, such as vetting a vendor. Due care refers to the ongoing, reasonable actions taken to maintain protection after a decision is made, and the other options are unrelated concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A government agency issues detailed regulations specifying how financial institutions must implement data protection controls, and these regulations carry the force of law through enforcement by a regulatory body. This type of law is best classified as which of the following?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Customary law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law consists of regulations created by government agencies to implement and enforce statutes, often including specific technical requirements. Criminal law addresses offenses against the state, civil law addresses disputes between parties, and customary law is based on long-standing practices rather than agency regulation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A risk assessment determines that a particular server has a Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) of $20,000 and an Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) of 0.25. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$1,250","$5,000","$20,000","$80,000"],"c":1,"why":"ALE = SLE x ARO = $20,000 x 0.25 = $5,000. The other values result from incorrect multiplication or division of the given figures.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During business continuity planning, a company determines that its order-processing system must be restored within 4 hours of a disruption to avoid unacceptable business impact. This 4-hour figure represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":2,"why":"RTO is the targeted duration within which a system must be restored after a disruption. RPO refers to acceptable data loss measured in time, MTD is the absolute maximum downtime before severe/irreversible harm occurs, and MTBF is a reliability metric unrelated to recovery targets.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator writes a document containing exact, step-by-step commands to configure a specific brand of firewall to meet the organization's security requirements. This document is best classified as a:","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":3,"why":"Procedures provide detailed, step-by-step instructions for performing a specific task. Policies are high-level statements of intent, standards define mandatory specific requirements, and guidelines offer recommended but discretionary advice.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, if a CISSP-certified professional encounters a conflict between protecting society and following the directives of their employer, which canon takes precedence?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are applied in order of precedence, with protecting society and the public good listed first and taking priority over obligations to employers or the profession when conflicts arise. The other canons are valid but subordinate in the stated hierarchy.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company is found liable in a lawsuit filed by a customer whose personal data was exposed due to negligent security practices. What standard of proof was most likely used to reach this verdict?","o":["Beyond a reasonable doubt","Probable cause","Preponderance of the evidence","Clear and convincing evidence"],"c":2,"why":"Civil cases, including negligence lawsuits, typically use the 'preponderance of the evidence' standard, meaning it is more likely than not that the claim is true. 'Beyond a reasonable doubt' applies to criminal cases, and the other terms are not the standard used in typical civil litigation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company decides to purchase cyber liability insurance to cover potential financial losses from a data breach rather than investing further in additional security controls. This is an example of which risk treatment strategy?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Avoidance would mean eliminating the activity entirely, mitigation involves reducing likelihood/impact through controls, and acceptance means retaining the risk without further action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A risk assessment determines that a critical database has an asset value of $1,000,000. A successful attack is expected to destroy 40% of the asset's value, and historical data shows such attacks occur on average once every two years. Security proposes a safeguard costing $50,000 per year that would reduce the frequency of successful attacks to once every ten years. What is the annualized net benefit of implementing this safeguard?","o":["$40,000","$110,000","$160,000","$200,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = $1,000,000 x 0.40 = $400,000. Current ALE = $400,000 x 0.5 (ARO) = $200,000. New ALE with control = $400,000 x 0.1 = $40,000. Savings = $200,000 - $40,000 = $160,000, minus the $50,000 control cost = $110,000 net benefit. The other figures represent intermediate values, not the net benefit.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Following a major flood that destroyed a company's primary data center, the organization restores its servers at an alternate site and resumes IT operations. This activity primarily falls under which plan?","o":["Business Continuity Plan (BCP)","Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)","Incident Response Plan (IRP)","Risk Management Plan"],"c":1,"why":"The DRP focuses specifically on restoring IT systems and infrastructure after a disaster. The BCP addresses broader business process continuity, the IRP addresses handling security incidents, and a risk management plan addresses ongoing risk identification and treatment rather than recovery actions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before onboarding a new cloud service provider that will process sensitive customer data, a security team requests the provider's SOC 2 Type II report. What is the PRIMARY purpose of reviewing this report?","o":["To verify the provider's marketing claims about uptime guarantees","To obtain an independent assessment of the provider's internal controls over a period of time","To confirm the provider's compliance with export control laws","To determine the provider's financial solvency and profitability"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report provides an independent auditor's assessment of the effectiveness of a service organization's controls over a defined period, which is central to third-party risk assessment. The other options are outside the scope of a SOC 2 report, which does not address marketing, export controls, or financial performance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization published a patch-management policy requiring critical patches to be applied within 30 days, but management never enforced compliance or audited the process. Two years later, an unpatched, publicly known vulnerability was exploited, causing a major breach. From a legal liability standpoint, which concept best explains the organization's exposure?","o":["Failure of due diligence, because the organization never researched the vulnerability","Failure of due care, because the organization did not act to maintain the ongoing protection it had already identified as necessary","Vicarious liability, because a third party caused the breach","Strict liability, which applies regardless of the organization's actions"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to the continuing, prudent-person standard of maintaining protections already known to be necessary; having a policy but failing to enforce it demonstrates lack of due care. Due diligence refers to the initial investigative step (which did occur, since the policy was created), and vicarious/strict liability do not fit this internal-control failure scenario.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"After a cost-benefit analysis, an organization determines that the cost of implementing additional controls for a low-probability, low-impact risk exceeds the potential loss from the risk occurring. The organization decides to take no further action. This is an example of which risk treatment strategy?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk avoidance","Risk acceptance"],"c":3,"why":"Risk acceptance occurs when an organization decides to take no additional action because the cost of treatment outweighs the potential loss. Mitigation reduces risk through controls, transfer shifts risk (e.g., insurance), and avoidance eliminates the activity causing the risk entirely.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company based in the U.S. (acting as a data controller under GDPR) contracts a third-party cloud provider (acting as a data processor) to process personal data of EU residents. The processor suffers a breach caused by its own failure to implement contractually required encryption. Under the GDPR, how is liability most accurately assessed?","o":["Only the controller is liable, since it is ultimately accountable for the data","Only the processor is liable, since the breach resulted from its own security failure","Both the controller and processor may be held liable, each to the extent of their respective responsibility for the violation","Liability automatically transfers entirely to the processor once a Data Processing Agreement is signed"],"c":2,"why":"GDPR Article 82 allows both controllers and processors to be held liable, with each party responsible for damage caused by its own violation of the Regulation; the DPA does not eliminate the processor's direct statutory liability, nor does it fully absolve the controller of accountability.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY reason organizations conduct regular security awareness training for all employees?","o":["To satisfy audit documentation requirements only","To reduce the likelihood of human error and social engineering success","To replace the need for technical security controls","To assign legal liability to employees for security incidents"],"c":1,"why":"Security awareness training primarily aims to reduce human-related risks, such as falling for phishing or mishandling data, since employees are often the weakest link in security. It does not replace technical controls, and while it may support compliance, that is not its primary purpose, and it is not meant to shift legal liability onto employees.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements encryption on all laptop hard drives to prevent unauthorized individuals from reading sensitive data if a device is lost or stolen. Which principle of the CIA triad does this control primarily support?","o":["Availability","Confidentiality","Integrity","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Encryption protects data from being disclosed to unauthorized parties, which is the definition of confidentiality. Availability concerns access when needed, integrity concerns unauthorized modification, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution requires that no single employee can both initiate and approve a wire transfer above a certain threshold; two different employees must independently authorize the transaction. Which security principle does this control primarily implement?","o":["Least privilege","Need-to-know","Separation of duties","Defense in depth"],"c":2,"why":"Requiring two different individuals to jointly complete a sensitive transaction is a classic separation of duties (dual control) mechanism intended to prevent fraud by a single actor. Least privilege and need-to-know govern the scope of access granted, not the division of a single process among multiple people, and defense in depth refers to layered controls, not this specific dual-authorization mechanism.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company purchases cyber liability insurance to cover potential financial losses from a data breach, rather than implementing additional security controls to prevent the breach. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is risk transfer. Mitigation reduces likelihood/impact through controls, avoidance eliminates the activity causing risk, and acceptance means taking no action and absorbing the loss directly.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization depends on a legacy application with known unpatched vulnerabilities that cannot be replaced for another 18 months. In the interim, it implements compensating network segmentation and enhanced monitoring around the system, and it also purchases a cyber-insurance policy to cover potential financial losses from a breach. Which best characterizes the organization's overall risk treatment approach?","o":["Pure risk avoidance, since the organization is isolating the vulnerable system","Pure risk acceptance, since the underlying vulnerability remains unresolved","A combination of risk mitigation and risk transfer strategies applied concurrently","Pure risk transfer, since insurance covers all potential losses"],"c":2,"why":"Segmentation and monitoring reduce the likelihood/impact of exploitation (mitigation), while the insurance policy shifts residual financial impact to a third party (transfer); using both simultaneously is a combined strategy. It is not avoidance (the risk-causing activity continues), pure acceptance (active controls were implemented), or pure transfer (technical controls were also applied).","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the difference between a security policy and a security procedure?","o":["A policy is mandatory while a procedure is optional","A policy defines high-level intent and requirements, while a procedure provides detailed step-by-step instructions to implement the policy","A procedure is approved by senior management, while a policy is approved by IT staff","A policy applies only to technical staff, while a procedure applies to all employees"],"c":1,"why":"Policies establish overall goals and management intent, while procedures give the specific steps needed to achieve compliance with the policy. Both are typically mandatory, and policies (not procedures) require senior management approval.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A manufacturing company develops a proprietary chemical process that provides a significant competitive advantage. The process is extremely difficult to reverse-engineer from the finished product, and the company wants protection that does not require public disclosure of the process details and can potentially last indefinitely. Which form of intellectual property protection is most appropriate?","o":["Patent","Trade secret","Copyright","Trademark"],"c":1,"why":"Trade secrets protect confidential business information indefinitely as long as secrecy is maintained and reasonable protective measures are taken, and they do not require public disclosure, unlike patents. Copyright protects expression (not processes), and trademarks protect brand identifiers, neither of which fits a manufacturing process.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During due diligence on a cloud service provider, an organization wants assurance that the provider's security controls have operated effectively over a sustained period (e.g., the past 9 months), not merely that they were suitably designed at a single point in time. Which report should the organization request?","o":["SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 1 report","SOC 3 report"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates both the design and the operating effectiveness of controls over a specified period, whereas a Type I report only assesses design suitability at a single point in time. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report lacking the detailed testing information needed for this assessment.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization's incident response team performs a review of an employee's actions after a security breach was discovered. The employee had followed all documented security procedures at the time of the incident. Which legal concept most directly protects this employee from liability?","o":["Due diligence","Separation of duties","Due care","Least privilege"],"c":2,"why":"Due care refers to taking reasonable actions consistent with established procedures to protect assets; following documented procedures demonstrates due care. Due diligence refers to the ongoing research and assessment used to establish those procedures, not the act of following them.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified professional discovers that their employer's data-handling practice, while technically legal in the jurisdiction of operation, exposes end users to significant undisclosed privacy harm. The situation creates a conflict between the (ISC)² Code of Ethics canon to act in the best interest of the employer and the canon to protect society. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, how should this conflict be resolved?","o":["The canon to advance and protect the profession takes precedence in all conflicts","The canons should be weighed equally, and the professional should abstain from acting","The canon to protect society, the commonwealth, and the infrastructure takes precedence over the other canons","The canon requiring diligent and competent service to principals takes precedence, since it directly involves the employer relationship"],"c":2,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are explicitly ordered, with 'Protect society, the commonwealth, and the infrastructure' taking precedence when canons conflict. Advancing the profession and serving principals diligently are important but subordinate obligations, and abstaining from action is not a resolution the Code endorses.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"During a Business Impact Analysis (BIA), a security team calculates the maximum acceptable amount of time a critical system can be down before causing unacceptable harm to the organization. What is this metric called?","o":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)"],"c":3,"why":"MTD represents the absolute maximum time a business function can be unavailable before causing unacceptable damage. RTO is the target time for restoration (usually less than MTD), RPO relates to acceptable data loss, and MTBF is a reliability metric unrelated to downtime tolerance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the primary purpose of separation of duties as a security control?","o":["To ensure employees receive cross-training on multiple job functions","To reduce the risk that a single individual can commit and conceal fraud or error","To comply with minimum staffing requirements","To simplify the assignment of user access rights"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people so that no single individual has enough control to commit fraud or errors without detection. Cross-training and staffing are side benefits, not the primary security purpose.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's annual revenue depends on a critical server valued at $500,000. A risk assessment determines that a successful ransomware attack would degrade 20% of the asset's value and is expected to occur once every two years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$50,000","$100,000","$25,000","$10,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor = $500,000 x 0.20 = $100,000. ARO = 0.5 (once every two years). ALE = SLE x ARO = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. The other figures represent the SLE alone or miscalculated ARO applications.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A CISSP-certified professional discovers that a colleague is violating organizational policy by sharing login credentials with unauthorized staff. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the professional's most appropriate first course of action?","o":["Immediately report the colleague to law enforcement","Ignore the issue since it does not directly affect the professional's own systems","Address the concern through appropriate organizational channels, such as reporting it to management or the ethics committee","Publicly disclose the violation on social media to warn others"],"c":2,"why":"The Code of Ethics requires professionals to act honorably and report violations through proper channels within the organization rather than escalating externally or ignoring the issue; law enforcement involvement or public disclosure would be premature and inappropriate as a first step.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before signing a contract with a cloud service provider, a company's security team reviews the provider's SOC 2 report, financial stability, and incident history. This activity best exemplifies which concept?","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Negligence"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence is the research and investigation performed before making a decision (e.g., vetting a vendor). Due care refers to the ongoing implementation of protective measures after the decision, and the other options do not describe an investigative activity.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's data center houses an asset valued at $500,000. A risk assessment determines that a specific threat has an Exposure Factor of 40% and an Annualized Rate of Occurrence of 0.5 (expected once every two years). A proposed safeguard costing $60,000 per year would reduce the ARO to 0.1 (once every ten years) without changing the Exposure Factor. Based on quantitative risk analysis, what is the value of implementing this safeguard, and should management approve it?","o":["-$40,000; reject the safeguard because it costs more than it saves annually","$20,000; approve the safeguard because it produces a net annual savings","$80,000; approve the safeguard because it eliminates all risk associated with the threat","$60,000; reject the safeguard because its cost exceeds the asset's value"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = $500,000 x 0.4 = $200,000. ALE before = $200,000 x 0.5 = $100,000. ALE after = $200,000 x 0.1 = $20,000. Safeguard value = ($100,000 - $20,000) - $60,000 = $20,000 net savings, so it should be approved. The other options misapply the formula or ignore the safeguard's cost.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which element of the CIA triad ensures that data has not been altered by unauthorized parties?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Authentication"],"c":1,"why":"Integrity specifically addresses the accuracy and completeness of data, ensuring it has not been improperly modified. Confidentiality protects against unauthorized disclosure, availability ensures access when needed, and authentication verifies identity, none of which directly address unauthorized alteration.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which type of law is primarily concerned with resolving disputes between private parties and typically results in monetary damages rather than imprisonment?","o":["Criminal law","Civil law","Administrative law","Constitutional law"],"c":1,"why":"Civil law addresses disputes between individuals or organizations, with remedies typically involving financial compensation. Criminal law involves government prosecution and potential imprisonment, administrative law involves regulatory agency enforcement, and constitutional law governs fundamental government structure and rights.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During due diligence for a corporate merger, the acquiring company's CISO hires an independent third-party firm to assess the security posture, incident history, and regulatory compliance of the target company before the deal closes. This activity is best characterized as an exercise of:","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Negligence mitigation","Duty to warn"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as assessing a merger target's risk profile. Due care refers to the ongoing implementation of reasonable protective measures after a decision is made, and the other two terms do not describe pre-decision investigative activity.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements a rule requiring two employees to jointly approve any wire transfer over $50,000. This is an example of which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties requires multiple people to complete a sensitive task, reducing the risk of fraud or error by a single individual. Least privilege limits access rights, defense in depth layers controls, and security through obscurity relies on secrecy rather than shared control.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's security policy mandates multifactor authentication (MFA) for all remote access. A separate document specifies that only FIDO2 hardware tokens are approved for MFA implementation. This second document is best classified as a:","o":["Guideline","Standard","Procedure","Baseline"],"c":1,"why":"A standard provides mandatory, specific technical requirements that support policy. A guideline is advisory rather than mandatory, a procedure gives step-by-step instructions, and a baseline defines a minimum level of security configuration rather than a specific technology choice.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes 'due diligence' in the context of information security management?","o":["Taking reasonable actions to prevent security incidents","Researching and understanding risks before making a decision","Reporting a breach to regulators within a required timeframe","Implementing encryption for data at rest"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed to understand risks prior to acting, such as evaluating a vendor's security posture. Due care refers to taking reasonable actions to protect assets, while breach reporting and encryption are specific controls, not the definition of due diligence.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A multinational company operates a subsidiary in a country that follows a civil law legal tradition. An ambiguity arises regarding statutory breach notification timelines. Under the civil law tradition, which source would be considered most authoritative in resolving this ambiguity?","o":["Precedent established by prior court rulings on similar cases","Comprehensive, codified statutes enacted by the legislature","Administrative agency guidance issued informally","Judicial discretion based on the specific facts of the case"],"c":1,"why":"Civil law systems are based on comprehensive written codes and statutes as the primary source of law, unlike common law systems, which rely heavily on judicial precedent (case law). Administrative guidance and unstructured judicial discretion are secondary and not the primary authoritative source in civil law jurisdictions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"After a cost-benefit analysis, a company decides to purchase cyber liability insurance to cover potential financial losses from a data breach rather than investing in additional technical controls. This decision represents which risk treatment strategy?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is risk transfer. Mitigation reduces likelihood/impact through controls, avoidance eliminates the risk-causing activity, and acceptance means retaining the risk without action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company's security policy states that all employees must complete annual security awareness training. Which type of document specifies the exact steps and tools to be used to deliver this training?","o":["Policy","Standard","Procedure","Guideline"],"c":2,"why":"A procedure provides detailed, step-by-step instructions for accomplishing a specific task, such as how training is delivered. A policy states the high-level requirement, a standard defines mandatory specifications, and a guideline offers recommended but non-mandatory advice.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During a penetration test, a CISSP-certified consultant discovers a critical vulnerability in a system that is explicitly outside the scope of the signed engagement. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the MOST appropriate action?","o":["Ignore the finding since it is outside the contracted scope","Exploit the vulnerability to demonstrate impact without authorization","Disclose the finding to the client and recommend remediation","Report the vulnerability directly to a regulatory authority without informing the client"],"c":2,"why":"The Code of Ethics requires professionals to act in the best interest of the client and society by disclosing significant risks, even outside formal scope, while respecting proper authorization boundaries. Ignoring it or acting unilaterally without informing the client violates ethical canons of protecting society and acting responsibly.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A security steering committee composed of senior business executives and the CISO meets quarterly to oversee the organization's security program. Which of the following activities best reflects the committee's core governance responsibility, as distinct from operational security management?","o":["Reviewing and approving individual firewall rule change requests","Approving the organization's risk appetite statement and annual security budget","Conducting technical vulnerability scans on production systems","Drafting detailed incident response runbooks for the SOC team"],"c":1,"why":"Governance functions involve setting strategic direction, risk appetite, and resource allocation at the executive level. Reviewing firewall rules, conducting scans, and writing runbooks are operational and tactical activities performed by security staff, not governance-level decisions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which type of law is primarily concerned with resolving disputes between private parties, such as a breach of contract lawsuit?","o":["Criminal law","Civil law","Administrative law","Regulatory law"],"c":1,"why":"Civil law governs disputes between private parties and typically results in monetary damages rather than incarceration. Criminal law involves government prosecution for crimes against society, administrative/regulatory law involves government agencies enforcing rules and regulations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO is evaluating a cloud service provider (CSP) and needs assurance that the CSP's security controls related to confidentiality and availability have operated effectively over the preceding 12-month period, not merely that they were suitably designed at a single point in time. Which report should the CISO request from the CSP?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 3 report"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of controls over a specified period (e.g., 12 months), addressing trust service criteria like confidentiality and availability. Type I reports only assess design suitability at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 provides only a general-use summary without detailed testing results.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A manufacturing company develops a unique chemical formulation that provides significant competitive advantage. The company wants to protect this information indefinitely without ever publicly disclosing the formula. Which intellectual property protection is MOST appropriate?","o":["Patent","Copyright","Trademark","Trade secret"],"c":3,"why":"Trade secrets protect confidential business information indefinitely as long as secrecy is maintained, requiring no public disclosure. Patents require public disclosure and have a limited term, copyrights protect creative works, and trademarks protect brand identifiers.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"During a risk assessment, a security analyst identifies that the cost to implement a control exceeds the potential loss from the risk it addresses. What is the MOST appropriate risk response in this case?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance","Risk avoidance"],"c":2,"why":"When the cost of mitigating a risk exceeds the potential loss, accepting the risk is often the most cost-effective and appropriate response. Mitigation and avoidance would incur unnecessary cost, and transfer (e.g., insurance) may not be justified if the loss is already low.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis establishes a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 4 hours for a critical order-processing application. The current disaster recovery plan, when tested, achieves a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 6 hours for restoring that application. What is the most accurate assessment of this situation?","o":["Acceptable, because RTO is only a target and MTD is a theoretical upper bound with built-in flexibility","Unacceptable, because the RTO exceeds the MTD, meaning the recovery capability does not meet the business requirement","Acceptable, because Recovery Point Objective, not RTO, is the determining factor for business continuity risk","Unacceptable, because RTO must always be set exactly equal to MTD for the plan to be valid"],"c":1,"why":"RTO must be less than or equal to MTD to ensure recovery occurs before the business suffers unacceptable harm; an RTO of 6 hours against a 4-hour MTD represents a 2-hour gap that exposes the organization to unacceptable impact. RPO relates to data loss tolerance, not recovery timing, and RTO does not need to exactly equal MTD, only to fall within it.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution's business continuity plan states that after a disruption, the maximum tolerable data loss is 4 hours, while systems must be fully operational again within 8 hours. The 4-hour figure represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Work Recovery Time (WRT)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, determining backup frequency requirements. RTO refers to how quickly systems must be restored, MTD is the overall maximum downtime the business can tolerate, and WRT is the time needed to reconfigure systems after recovery before resuming normal operations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of a Business Impact Analysis (BIA)?","o":["To identify technical vulnerabilities in network infrastructure","To determine the financial and operational impact of disruptions to critical business functions","To create a step-by-step incident response plan","To evaluate employee compliance with security policies"],"c":1,"why":"A BIA identifies and evaluates the potential effects of disruptions on business operations, helping prioritize recovery efforts. Vulnerability identification, incident response planning, and compliance evaluation are related but separate activities within risk and continuity management.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified security manager discovers that her employer is covertly harvesting user data in a manner that violates applicable privacy law. Reporting this to regulators would breach a non-disclosure agreement she signed with the company. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon takes precedence in resolving this conflict?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Act honorably, honestly, justly, legally, and responsibly within your jurisdiction"],"c":2,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are hierarchically ordered, with protecting society and the public good taking precedence over obligations to employers or the profession when conflicts arise. The NDA-related duty to the employer (a 'principal') is subordinate to this higher canon.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure a third-party vendor maintains agreed-upon security controls throughout the entire contract lifecycle, not just at the time of signing. Which contractual provision BEST supports this ongoing assurance?","o":["A non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","A right-to-audit clause","A service level agreement (SLA) defining uptime","An indemnification clause"],"c":1,"why":"A right-to-audit clause allows the organization to periodically verify the vendor's ongoing compliance with security requirements. NDAs protect confidential information, SLAs typically address performance metrics like uptime rather than security compliance, and indemnification addresses liability rather than verification.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following actions would MOST likely violate a CISSP holder's professional obligations?","o":["Reporting a known vulnerability to the appropriate vendor","Refusing to perform an illegal action requested by a manager","Sharing confidential client data with a competitor for personal gain","Recommending additional security controls to reduce organizational risk"],"c":2,"why":"Sharing confidential data for personal gain violates the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which requires professionals to act honorably, honestly, and to protect confidential information. The other actions align with ethical behavior, such as responsible disclosure, refusing illegal acts, and improving security posture.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"After a formal risk assessment, an organization determines that the likelihood of a catastrophic data center fire is low, but the potential financial impact would exceed the company's ability to absorb the loss internally. Management decides to purchase an insurance policy covering rebuilding and business interruption costs rather than investing further in fire suppression infrastructure. Which risk treatment strategy is being applied, and what residual risk remains?","o":["Risk avoidance; no residual risk remains because the risk-generating activity has been eliminated","Risk mitigation; residual risk is reduced to zero because the insurance fully covers all potential losses","Risk transfer; residual risk remains in the form of policy exclusions, deductibles, and uninsurable losses such as reputational damage","Risk acceptance; residual risk equals the full original risk because no action was taken to address it"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance is a classic example of risk transfer, shifting financial impact to a third party, but residual risk persists through deductibles, coverage limits, exclusions, and non-financial harms like reputational damage that insurance cannot fully address. It is not avoidance (the activity continues), not mitigation (no reduction in likelihood/impact occurred), and not acceptance (an active transfer decision was made).","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's data center houses a critical asset valued at $500,000. A risk assessment determines that a specific flood scenario would destroy 20% of the asset's value and is expected to occur once every two years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$50,000","$100,000","$25,000","$200,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor = $500,000 x 0.20 = $100,000. ARO = 1/2 = 0.5. ALE = SLE x ARO = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. The other options misapply the exposure factor or ARO.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before signing a contract with a new cloud service provider, an organization reviews the provider's SOC 2 Type II report, conducts an independent security assessment, and interviews the provider's security team. This activity best exemplifies which concept?","o":["Risk acceptance","Due care","Due diligence","Residual risk management"],"c":2,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as vetting a vendor's security posture prior to engagement. Due care refers to the ongoing implementation of controls after the decision is made, not the investigative process itself.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's data center houses an asset valued at $2,000,000. A specific flood scenario has an exposure factor of 25% and is expected to occur once every five years. A proposed flood-mitigation control costs $150,000 annually and would reduce the annual rate of occurrence to once every 20 years (ARO 0.05), without changing the exposure factor. Based on a strict cost-benefit analysis, what should the organization conclude?","o":["Implement the control, since it reduces the ALE from $100,000 to $25,000, saving $75,000 per year","Do not implement the control, since the $150,000 annual cost exceeds the $75,000 reduction in annualized loss expectancy","Implement the control, since any reduction in ARO is always cost-justified regardless of control cost","Do not implement the control, since the exposure factor was not reduced, making the control ineffective"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = $2,000,000 x 25% = $500,000. Original ALE = $500,000 x 0.2 = $100,000; new ALE = $500,000 x 0.05 = $25,000, a savings of $75,000/year. Since the control costs $150,000/year but only saves $75,000/year, it is not cost-justified. Options A and C ignore the cost-benefit comparison, and D incorrectly claims the control has no effect despite lowering ARO.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A security policy states that all employees must protect confidential data. A supporting document mandates that all laptops must use AES-256 full-disk encryption with no exceptions. What type of document is this supporting requirement?","o":["Guideline","Procedure","Standard","Baseline"],"c":2,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, specific technical requirements that support a policy, such as a required encryption algorithm and key length. Guidelines are discretionary recommendations, procedures are step-by-step instructions, and a baseline defines a minimum acceptable configuration level rather than a specific mandated control.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A newly hired CISO spends her first month reviewing existing security architecture, interviewing stakeholders, benchmarking against industry frameworks, and documenting gaps before recommending any changes. This activity is best characterized as an exercise of which legal/security management concept?","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Negligence mitigation","Downstream liability transfer"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed prior to making a decision or taking action (the 'look before you leap' step). Due care refers to the ongoing, reasonable implementation and maintenance of protective measures once decisions are made, not the investigative phase; the other two terms are not standard descriptions of this pre-decision research activity.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A former employee sues a company for breach of a non-disclosure agreement signed during employment. Which body of law primarily governs this dispute, and what standard of proof typically applies?","o":["Criminal law; proof beyond a reasonable doubt","Administrative law; substantial evidence standard","Civil law; preponderance of the evidence","Constitutional law; clear and convincing evidence"],"c":2,"why":"Contract disputes such as NDA breaches are addressed under civil (tort/contract) law, which uses the lower 'preponderance of the evidence' standard. Criminal law requires proof beyond a reasonable doubt and applies to government prosecution of crimes, not private contract disputes.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company's Chief Information Security Officer (CISO) currently reports to the Chief Information Officer (CIO), who also owns budget responsibility for IT operations and application development. Internal audit has flagged this as a governance weakness. What is the PRIMARY concern with this reporting structure?","o":["The CISO lacks sufficient technical expertise to evaluate CIO-led projects","It creates a conflict of interest, since the CIO may prioritize operational speed and budget over security concerns the CISO is meant to raise independently","It violates the principle of least privilege for executive access","It prevents the CISO from receiving adequate security awareness training"],"c":1,"why":"When security oversight reports into the same executive accountable for IT delivery and budgets, there is an inherent conflict of interest that can suppress independent risk reporting; best practice favors a CISO reporting to a CEO, board, or risk committee. The other options misapply unrelated concepts (technical competence, least privilege, training) that are not the governance issue being described.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company purchases a cybersecurity insurance policy to cover potential financial losses from a data breach, rather than implementing additional technical controls. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation involves reducing likelihood/impact through controls, avoidance means eliminating the activity causing the risk, and acceptance means knowingly retaining the risk without further action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company's password policy is 20 pages long and rarely followed by employees because it is too complex to remember. Which principle of effective security policy has been violated?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Policy should be clear, concise, and enforceable","Defense in depth"],"c":2,"why":"Effective policies must be understandable and practical so employees can comply; overly complex policies fail in practice. The other options describe unrelated security principles.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During vendor due diligence, a security team is evaluating a cloud service provider's SOC 2 report to determine whether the provider's security controls have operated effectively over an extended period rather than just at a single point in time. Which report type should the team request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3 Type I"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report attests to the operating effectiveness of controls over a defined observation period (typically 6-12 months), whereas Type I reports only assess control design at a single point in time. SOC 1 addresses financial reporting controls, not security, and 'SOC 3 Type I' is not a valid designation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During business continuity planning, a manager states that the organization can tolerate losing no more than 4 hours of transactional data in the event of a system failure. Which metric is being defined?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Work Recovery Time (WRT)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, indicating how far back data must be restorable from backups. RTO measures how quickly a system must be restored, and MTD/WRT relate to overall downtime tolerance, not data loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which document type provides mandatory, specific low-level technical requirements, such as requiring AES-256 for data at rest?","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"Standards are mandatory and specify exact technical requirements. Policies are high-level and broad, guidelines are recommended but optional, and procedures are step-by-step instructions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization outsources payroll processing to a third-party vendor. Which contractual control provides the strongest ongoing assurance that the vendor continues to meet agreed-upon security requirements throughout the relationship?","o":["A non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","A right-to-audit clause","A background check on vendor employees","A one-time security questionnaire at onboarding"],"c":1,"why":"A right-to-audit clause allows the organization to periodically verify the vendor's ongoing compliance with security requirements. NDAs protect confidentiality but don't verify controls, and background checks or one-time questionnaires only provide a point-in-time assessment rather than continuous assurance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A manufacturing firm has developed a unique chemical formulation that provides a durable competitive advantage. The formulation is difficult to reverse-engineer, and the company wants protection that could theoretically last indefinitely as long as secrecy is maintained. Which form of intellectual property protection is MOST appropriate, and why?","o":["Patent, because it provides the longest legal monopoly on use of the formulation","Trade secret, because protection does not expire as long as the information remains confidential and reasonable protective measures are taken","Copyright, because it automatically protects any original expression of the formulation","Trademark, because it protects the brand associated with the product"],"c":1,"why":"Trade secrets can be protected indefinitely provided the owner maintains confidentiality and applies reasonable safeguards, unlike patents which require public disclosure and expire after a fixed term (typically 20 years). Copyright protects expression, not formulas or processes, and trademark protects brand identifiers, not the underlying formulation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization determines that the annualized loss expectancy (ALE) for a risk exceeds the annual cost of a proposed control. What is the most appropriate risk response based on this analysis?","o":["Accept the risk","Implement the control, since it is cost-justified","Transfer the risk to a third party","Ignore the risk since it is unlikely"],"c":1,"why":"When ALE exceeds the cost of a control, implementing the control is cost-justified because it reduces losses more than it costs. Accepting or ignoring the risk would be financially unsound, and transfer doesn't apply without more information about that being cheaper.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, when a CISSP-certified professional faces a situation where the canons appear to conflict, which canon takes precedence?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics explicitly states the canons are listed in order of precedence, with protecting society and the infrastructure as the highest priority when canons conflict. The other canons are important but subordinate in a conflict.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified security manager discovers credible evidence that a senior executive is directing staff to falsify compliance audit results submitted to a regulator. Internal reporting channels are controlled by the same executive. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the MOST appropriate course of action?","o":["Say nothing, since the Code of Ethics prioritizes loyalty to the employer above all other obligations","Quietly resign to avoid personal liability without reporting the issue further","Escalate the matter through appropriate channels outside the compromised chain of command, such as the audit committee, board, or relevant regulator, consistent with the duty to protect society and act honorably","Confront the executive directly and threaten public disclosure unless the practice stops immediately"],"c":2,"why":"The Code of Ethics Canon prioritizing 'protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence' obligates the professional to pursue legitimate escalation paths (e.g., audit committee, board, or regulator) when normal channels are compromised, rather than staying silent, resigning quietly, or resorting to unilateral confrontation/threats, both of which are ethically and legally risky.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the purpose of a Business Impact Analysis (BIA)?","o":["To test the effectiveness of technical security controls","To identify and prioritize critical business functions and the impact of their disruption","To assign specific incident response roles to personnel","To calculate the return on investment for security purchases"],"c":1,"why":"A BIA identifies critical processes and quantifies the impact of their disruption, forming the basis for BCP/DRP planning. The other options describe different activities unrelated to BIA's core purpose.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A Business Impact Analysis determines that a critical order-processing system can tolerate at most 4 hours of downtime before unacceptable financial harm occurs, and the business can afford to lose no more than 15 minutes of transaction data. Current backups run every 6 hours, and the disaster recovery plan can restore full service within 3 hours. Which statement correctly identifies the deficiency?","o":["The RTO of 3 hours exceeds the MTD, so the recovery plan is non-compliant","The current backup schedule fails to meet the 15-minute RPO, even though the 3-hour RTO satisfies the 4-hour MTD","The MTD and RPO values are contradictory and cannot both be defined for the same system","The 6-hour backup interval satisfies the RPO since backups occur more frequently than the MTD"],"c":1,"why":"The Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 15 minutes defines the maximum tolerable data loss, but 6-hour backups mean up to 6 hours of data could be lost -- a clear gap. The 3-hour Recovery Time Objective (RTO) is within the 4-hour Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD), so that requirement IS met, making option A incorrect; MTD and RPO measure different things (downtime vs. data loss) and are not contradictory, and 6-hour backups do not satisfy a 15-minute RPO.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following is a foundational canon that all CISSP holders must uphold?","o":["Maximize shareholder profit at all costs","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Report only incidents that affect their own organization","Avoid disclosing security weaknesses to management"],"c":1,"why":"This is one of the four canons of the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, emphasizing broader societal responsibility. The other options contradict ethical and professional obligations expected of CISSPs.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"After a thorough risk assessment, an organization purchases a cyber-liability insurance policy to cover potential losses from a data breach involving customer PII. Which statement BEST describes the effect of this action on the organization's overall risk posture?","o":["The policy eliminates the risk of a data breach entirely, since financial losses are covered","The policy transfers the financial impact of certain losses to the insurer, but residual risks such as reputational damage, regulatory sanctions, and customer attrition remain with the organization","The policy converts the risk from a security risk into a purely operational risk with no further security obligations","The policy satisfies all regulatory due-care obligations, eliminating the need for additional technical controls"],"c":1,"why":"Insurance is a risk transfer mechanism that shifts financial impact to a third party but does not eliminate the underlying risk; non-financial consequences (reputation, regulatory action, customer trust) and the need for reasonable security controls remain. Risk is never fully 'eliminated' by insurance, it does not remove ongoing due-care obligations, and mischaracterizing it as purely 'operational' ignores that security risk still exists.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A security awareness program is an example of which type of control?","o":["Technical control","Administrative control","Physical control","Compensating control"],"c":1,"why":"Security awareness training is an administrative (managerial) control because it involves policies, procedures, and training rather than technology or physical barriers. Technical controls use hardware/software, and physical controls limit physical access.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's data center houses a server farm valued at $2,000,000. A fire risk assessment determines that a fire would destroy approximately 25% of the value of the equipment, and historical data suggests such a fire occurs once every 10 years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$50,000","$500,000","$200,000","$25,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x EF = $2,000,000 x 0.25 = $500,000. ARO = 1/10 = 0.1. ALE = SLE x ARO = $500,000 x 0.1 = $50,000. The other options result from miscalculating either the exposure factor or the ARO.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which type of law is primarily concerned with government enforcement of rules through fines and imprisonment, such as prosecuting an attacker for hacking?","o":["Civil law","Criminal law","Administrative law","Common law"],"c":1,"why":"Criminal law involves government prosecution of offenses that harm society, often resulting in fines or imprisonment. Civil law addresses disputes between parties, and administrative law involves regulatory agency rules and enforcement.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before signing a contract with a new cloud service provider, a company's security team reviews the provider's SOC 2 report, checks references, and evaluates the provider's incident history. This activity is BEST described as an example of:","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Residual risk analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before committing to a course of action, such as vetting a vendor. Due care refers to the ongoing practice of implementing and maintaining reasonable protective measures after a decision has been made.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution requires that the employee who initiates a wire transfer request cannot be the same employee who approves and releases the transfer. This control is an example of:","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people so that no single individual can complete a sensitive transaction alone, reducing fraud risk. Least privilege limits access rights, job rotation moves employees between roles over time, and mandatory vacation forces uninterrupted absence, none of which describe splitting a single transaction between two roles.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A beverage company has kept its soft drink formula confidential for over a century, never filing for any government registration and relying instead on internal confidentiality agreements and restricted access. This formula is BEST protected under which form of intellectual property law?","o":["Patent","Copyright","Trade secret","Trademark"],"c":2,"why":"A trade secret protects confidential business information indefinitely as long as reasonable measures are taken to maintain its secrecy, which matches this scenario. A patent requires public disclosure and expires after a fixed term, copyright protects original works of authorship, and trademark protects brand identifiers, not formulas.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During business continuity planning, an organization determines that after a disruption it can tolerate losing no more than 4 hours of transactional data, but the affected system must be fully operational again within 8 hours. The 4-hour value represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Service Delivery Objective (SDO)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO measures the maximum acceptable amount of data loss, expressed as a point in time to which data must be restored. RTO is the target time to restore the system (8 hours in this scenario), and MTD is the overall maximum time the business can survive without the function before serious harm occurs.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, when a CISSP-certified professional encounters a genuine conflict between two of the four canons, which canon takes precedence over the others?","o":["Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Advance and protect the profession","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the commonwealth, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics explicitly states that the canons are listed in order of precedence, and protecting society, the commonwealth, and the infrastructure takes priority over the other canons in case of conflict. The remaining canons are important but subordinate to this first canon.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A security manager implements a control after researching industry best practices and consulting with legal counsel to ensure the organization is acting responsibly. This best illustrates which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Separation of duties","Least privilege","Risk acceptance"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before implementing a decision or control to ensure it meets a reasonable standard of care. Due care would be the actual ongoing execution of that control; the other options are unrelated risk/access concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company operating in a region prone to earthquakes decides to purchase an insurance policy to cover potential losses from earthquake damage to its data center, rather than relocating the facility or investing in structural reinforcement. This risk treatment strategy is best classified as:","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing likelihood or impact directly (e.g., reinforcement), avoidance would eliminate the risk entirely (e.g., relocating), and acceptance means taking no action and absorbing the loss if it occurs.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"In quantitative risk analysis, which formula correctly calculates the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["ALE = SLE x ARO","ALE = AV x EF","ALE = Threat x Vulnerability","ALE = Risk x Impact"],"c":0,"why":"ALE is calculated by multiplying the Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) by the Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO). AV x EF calculates SLE, not ALE, and the other formulas are not standard quantitative risk formulas.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's information security program includes a mandatory requirement that all company-issued laptops must implement full-disk encryption using AES-256. This type of mandatory, specific requirement is best classified as a:","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, measurable requirements that support policy objectives, such as a specific encryption algorithm and key length. A policy provides high-level intent, a guideline offers recommended but non-mandatory advice, and a procedure gives step-by-step instructions for performing a task.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A risk manager calculates that a critical database asset is valued at $4,000,000. A successful ransomware attack is estimated to destroy 30% of the asset's value, and threat intelligence indicates such attacks occur, on average, once every two years. A proposed control costing $300,000 annually would reduce the annualized rate of occurrence to once every ten years. Based on a cost-benefit analysis, what is the correct conclusion?","o":["The control should be implemented because it reduces ALE from $600,000 to $120,000, a savings of $480,000, which exceeds the $300,000 annual cost by $180,000","The control should not be implemented because it costs $300,000 but only reduces ALE by $120,000, resulting in a net loss","The control should be implemented because the SLE decreases from $1,200,000 to $120,000, which alone justifies any control cost","The control should not be implemented because reducing the ARO from 0.5 to 0.1 is not a large enough change to justify a fixed annual expenditure"],"c":0,"why":"Current ALE = SLE ($1.2M) x ARO (0.5) = $600,000; after the control, ALE = $1.2M x 0.1 = $120,000, a reduction of $480,000 against a $300,000 cost, yielding a net benefit of $180,000. The distractors either miscalculate the ALE reduction, confuse SLE with ALE, or rely on non-quantitative reasoning.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which document provides high-level, mandatory management intent regarding security and typically requires senior leadership approval, while lower-level documents provide specific implementation details?","o":["Procedure","Guideline","Policy","Baseline"],"c":2,"why":"A security policy is a high-level statement of management intent and direction, approved by senior leadership. Procedures give step-by-step instructions, guidelines are recommendations, and baselines define minimum configuration levels.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A hospital's security team conducted a comprehensive risk assessment eighteen months ago that identified unpatched medical devices as a critical vulnerability. Budget was approved for remediation, but the patching project was never executed due to competing priorities. A breach subsequently occurs through one of the identified unpatched devices. Which concept best explains the organization's legal exposure?","o":["The organization exercised due diligence by identifying the risk but failed to exercise due care by not acting on the findings","The organization failed both due diligence and due care because the original risk assessment itself was inadequate","The organization is protected from liability because due diligence was performed, regardless of whether remediation occurred","The organization exercised due care by allocating budget for remediation, even though the work was never completed"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence is the research/investigation step (the risk assessment), while due care is the ongoing action taken to protect assets based on those findings; failing to remediate a known risk is a due care failure, not a due diligence failure. The other options misapply the terms or incorrectly assume liability protection from investigation alone.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following is listed as one of the four mandatory canons?","o":["Maximize shareholder value at all times","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Report all vulnerabilities publicly within 24 hours","Prioritize personal career advancement over organizational needs"],"c":1,"why":"One of the four (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons is to protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure. The other options are not part of the official canons and conflict with ethical practice.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization determines that a critical order-processing application must be restored within 4 hours after a disruption to avoid unacceptable business impact. This 4-hour figure represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":2,"why":"RTO defines the target time within which a system or process must be restored after a disruption. RPO measures acceptable data loss in time, MTD is the absolute maximum downtime before severe harm occurs, and MTBF measures reliability between failures.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization offers a legacy web service that generates minimal revenue but carries significant known vulnerabilities that cannot be cost-effectively remediated. Rather than continuing to invest in patching, leadership decides to permanently decommission the service. Which risk treatment strategy has been applied?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":0,"why":"Risk avoidance involves eliminating the activity or asset that generates the risk entirely, as done by decommissioning the service. Mitigation would involve reducing the risk while continuing the activity, transfer shifts risk to a third party (e.g., insurance), and acceptance means continuing to operate while acknowledging the risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company decides that the cost of implementing a control exceeds the potential loss from a low-probability risk, and instead purchases insurance to cover potential losses. Which risk response strategy is this?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation reduces the risk directly, avoidance eliminates the activity causing the risk, and acceptance means retaining the risk without any offsetting action like insurance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During a BIA, a critical order-processing system is found to have a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 4 hours. The current disaster recovery plan specifies a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 6 hours for this system. What does this discrepancy indicate?","o":["The recovery strategy is inadequate and must be improved so the RTO falls within the MTD, or the business will suffer unacceptable impact","The discrepancy is acceptable because RTO and MTD measure unrelated recovery parameters","The RTO should be increased further to align with typical industry MTD benchmarks for order-processing systems","The Recovery Point Objective should be adjusted to compensate for the gap between the RTO and MTD"],"c":0,"why":"RTO must be less than or equal to MTD; an RTO of 6 hours exceeding a 4-hour MTD means the system cannot be recovered fast enough to avoid unacceptable business impact, requiring an improved recovery strategy. RPO addresses acceptable data loss, not downtime, so adjusting it does not resolve a timing gap.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A security team evaluating a cloud service provider requests audit documentation to assess the operational effectiveness of the provider's controls over a six-month period, not just their design at a single point in time. Which report should the team request?","o":["SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 3 report"],"c":0,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates both the design and operating effectiveness of security-relevant controls over a defined period. SOC 1 focuses on controls relevant to financial reporting, Type I reports (SOC 1 or 2) only assess design at a point in time, and SOC 3 is a summarized, publicly distributable report lacking the detailed testing evidence needed for vendor due diligence.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's security policy states that 'all remote access must be authenticated using multi-factor authentication.' A subsequent document specifies that approved MFA methods are limited to hardware tokens and push notifications, and mandates a minimum token refresh interval of 30 seconds. Which type of document is being described in the second case?","o":["Standard","Guideline","Procedure","Baseline"],"c":0,"why":"A standard provides mandatory, specific technical requirements that support a high-level policy, such as approved MFA methods and refresh intervals. A guideline is discretionary advice, a procedure is a step-by-step implementation instruction, and a baseline typically defines a minimum consistent configuration level for a specific system type rather than a technology requirement across a control area.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company is simultaneously facing three separate legal proceedings arising from the same data breach: a lawsuit from affected customers seeking damages, a criminal investigation into alleged willful negligence by an executive, and a regulatory enforcement action by a data protection authority. Which statement correctly ranks the burden of proof required across these proceedings, from highest to lowest standard?","o":["Criminal case (beyond a reasonable doubt) is highest, followed by the civil lawsuit (preponderance of the evidence), followed by the regulatory enforcement action (substantial evidence/reasonable grounds)","The civil lawsuit requires the highest standard, followed by the criminal case, followed by the regulatory enforcement action","The regulatory enforcement action requires the highest standard, followed by the criminal case, followed by the civil lawsuit","All three proceedings require the same burden of proof: preponderance of the evidence"],"c":0,"why":"Criminal law requires the highest standard, 'beyond a reasonable doubt,' due to the severity of potential penalties; civil law uses the lower 'preponderance of the evidence' standard; administrative/regulatory actions often use an even lower 'substantial evidence' or 'reasonable grounds' standard. The other orderings and the claim of uniform standards misrepresent how burden of proof varies by legal system.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified security manager discovers clear evidence during an internal audit that senior executives have been intentionally falsifying compliance reports submitted to a regulator, potentially endangering public safety. The executives instruct the manager to remain silent. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the MOST appropriate course of action?","o":["Report the matter through appropriate channels, such as internal legal/compliance escalation or, if necessary, external regulatory authorities, because the duty to protect society and the profession supersedes internal loyalty","Comply with the executives' instructions, since maintaining organizational confidentiality is the highest-priority canon","Resign immediately without taking any further action, since resignation alone satisfies the professional's ethical obligations","Take no action unless directly asked by a regulator, since proactively reporting could itself constitute an unauthorized disclosure"],"c":0,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics places 'protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure' above organizational loyalty, obligating the professional to escalate or report the falsification. Silent compliance, resignation without reporting, or passive inaction all fail to fulfill this duty when public safety is at risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A data center housing critical servers has an asset value of $2,000,000. A fire risk assessment indicates an exposure factor of 25% and an annualized rate of occurrence of 0.1 (once every 10 years). A vendor proposes a fire suppression system costing $60,000 per year that would reduce the annualized rate of occurrence to 0.02. Based on quantitative risk analysis, what is the most accurate conclusion?","o":["The control should not be implemented because its annual cost of $60,000 exceeds the $40,000 reduction in annualized loss expectancy it provides.","The control should be implemented because it reduces the exposure factor from 25% to 2%.","The control should be implemented because the single loss expectancy decreases from $500,000 to $100,000.","The control should not be implemented because the asset value exceeds the cost of the control."],"c":0,"why":"ALE before = $2M x 0.25 x 0.1 = $50,000; ALE after = $2M x 0.25 x 0.02 = $10,000, a reduction of $40,000. Since the $60,000 control cost exceeds the $40,000 benefit, it is not cost-justified. The distractors misstate the exposure factor change, the SLE (which does not change, since EF and AV are unaffected), and use an irrelevant comparison of asset value to cost.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements encryption on its database to prevent unauthorized individuals from reading sensitive customer records. Which principle of the CIA triad is primarily being addressed?","o":["Availability","Integrity","Confidentiality","Non-repudiation"],"c":2,"why":"Encryption protects data from unauthorized disclosure, which is the definition of confidentiality. Availability concerns access when needed, integrity concerns unauthorized modification, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO commissions a comprehensive third-party risk assessment that identifies a critical unpatched vulnerability in the organization's payment processing system. The CISO documents the findings but does not allocate resources to remediate the vulnerability for eight months, during which an attacker exploits it, causing a significant data breach. In a subsequent lawsuit, the organization is found liable for damages. Which concept most directly explains why the organization failed to meet its legal obligation?","o":["Failure to exercise due care, because due diligence (the assessment) was performed but the organization did not act reasonably on its findings.","Failure to exercise due diligence, because the initial risk assessment was inadequate.","Violation of the principle of least privilege, because access controls were not updated.","Breach of separation of duties, because one individual controlled both risk assessment and remediation decisions."],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence is the investigation/assessment (which was performed adequately); due care is acting on those findings in a reasonably prudent manner, which was not done. Least privilege and separation of duties are unrelated technical/administrative controls, not the legal standard at issue here.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's critical database could suffer a single loss of $250,000 from a successful ransomware attack. Historical incident data across similar organizations shows this type of attack occurs on average once every four years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$62,500","$250,000","$1,000,000","$6,250"],"c":0,"why":"ALE = SLE x ARO = $250,000 x (1/4) = $62,500. The other values result from incorrectly applying the multiplier or confusing SLE with ALE.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator patches a server as soon as a vendor releases a security update, following the organization's documented patch management procedure. This behavior best exemplifies which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Separation of duties","Least privilege"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to the ongoing actions taken to maintain an appropriate level of protection, such as applying patches per procedure. Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before taking action (e.g., risk assessments), not the routine execution of a task.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization considering expansion into a country with a volatile regulatory environment and a history of abrupt nationalization of foreign assets decides, after risk analysis, to cancel the expansion entirely and pursue other markets instead. Which risk response strategy has the organization applied?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance","Risk avoidance"],"c":3,"why":"Risk avoidance eliminates the risk by not engaging in the activity that creates it, as done here by canceling the expansion. Mitigation would reduce likelihood/impact while still proceeding; transfer shifts the risk to a third party (e.g., insurance); acceptance means proceeding while knowingly retaining the risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISO commissions an independent third-party risk assessment to identify security gaps before deploying new controls. After deployment, the CISO establishes continuous monitoring and periodic control testing. Which concept BEST describes the initial risk assessment phase?","o":["Due diligence, the reasonable investigation performed before taking action","Due care, the ongoing responsible actions taken after controls are implemented","Risk transference, shifting responsibility for the risk to a third party","Residual risk acceptance, acknowledging risk that remains after controls"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation conducted prior to acting responsibly, such as the pre-deployment assessment. Due care refers to the ongoing maintenance activities, not the initial investigation, making the other options incorrect.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes a security standard within an organization's documentation hierarchy?","o":["A high-level statement of management's intent regarding security","A mandatory, specific requirement that supports a policy","A recommended, non-mandatory best practice","A step-by-step set of instructions for performing a task"],"c":1,"why":"Standards are mandatory, specific rules that support and enforce the intent of a policy. Policies are high-level, guidelines are non-mandatory recommendations, and procedures are detailed step-by-step instructions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A multinational corporation signs a contract to be adjudicated under a legal system in which primary law is derived from religious texts and interpreted by religious scholars, with rulings that can vary by jurisdiction based on interpretation rather than codified statutes or binding case precedent. Which legal system governs this contract?","o":["Common law","Civil law","Religious law","Customary law"],"c":2,"why":"Religious law is based on religious doctrine and interpreted by religious authorities, often with variation by jurisdiction. Common law relies on judicial precedent, civil law relies on comprehensive codified statutes, and customary law derives from the traditions and customs of a specific community rather than religious doctrine.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Which type of security document provides mandatory, specific technical requirements that support a policy, such as 'all corporate laptops must use AES-256 full-disk encryption'?","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"Standards are mandatory, specific requirements that support high-level policy statements. Policies state management intent broadly, guidelines are recommended (not mandatory), and procedures provide step-by-step instructions rather than requirements.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During a business impact analysis, an organization determines that its order-processing system has a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 8 hours. The disaster recovery plan specifies a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 6 hours and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 4 hours, achieved through hourly incremental backups replicated to an offsite facility. Which statement correctly evaluates this plan?","o":["The plan is inadequate because the RPO exceeds the RTO.","The plan is inadequate because the RTO exceeds the MTD.","The plan is adequate because the RTO is less than the MTD, and the backup strategy supports the stated RPO by limiting data loss to at most 4 hours.","The plan is adequate because the MTD equals the sum of the RTO and RPO."],"c":2,"why":"RTO must be less than or equal to MTD to avoid unacceptable damage, and here 6 hours < 8 hours. RPO is an independent metric describing tolerable data loss, not required to have any fixed relationship with RTO, and hourly backups comfortably meet the 4-hour RPO target. MTD is not defined as the sum of RTO and RPO.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A risk analyst calculates that a specific threat has an Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) of 0.5 and a Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) of $200,000. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$50,000","$100,000","$200,000","$400,000"],"c":1,"why":"ALE = SLE x ARO = $200,000 x 0.5 = $100,000. This is a basic quantitative risk analysis calculation; the other values result from miscalculating or misapplying the formula.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution's business continuity plan states that after a system failure, no more than 4 hours of transaction data may be lost, regardless of how long the system takes to be restored. This requirement defines which metric?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Work Recovery Time (WRT)"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, which directly matches the scenario. RTO measures time to restore service, MTD is the overall maximum outage duration, and WRT is the time needed after systems are restored to return to full operations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A security document states: 'All Windows servers must run Endpoint Protection Suite version 6.45 or later, with the Prevention Policy set to Aggressive mode. Any deviation requires CISO approval.' What type of governance document is this?","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, specific technical requirements (product, version, configuration) that support policy objectives. A policy is a high-level statement of intent, a guideline offers recommended but non-mandatory advice, and a procedure provides detailed step-by-step instructions to perform a task.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Ultimate accountability for an organization's information security program and its risk decisions rests with which of the following?","o":["The Chief Information Security Officer (CISO)","Senior management / the board of directors","The IT security operations team","The internal audit department"],"c":1,"why":"Senior management (or the board) holds ultimate accountability for organizational risk and security outcomes, even though they delegate day-to-day responsibility to roles like the CISO. Audit and operations teams support but do not bear ultimate accountability.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Which characteristic distinguishes civil law (code-based) legal systems, common in many European and Latin American countries, from common law systems used in the U.S. and U.K.?","o":["Civil law systems rely primarily on judicial precedent to determine outcomes","Civil law systems rely on comprehensive written legal codes rather than case precedent","Common law systems have no concept of statutory law","Common law systems are administered exclusively by administrative agencies"],"c":1,"why":"Civil law systems are based on detailed codified statutes, with judges applying the code rather than building law through precedent as in common law systems. The other statements misrepresent both systems, since common law also includes statutory law and is not administered solely by administrative agencies.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified professional discovers that senior management plans to conceal a known data breach from regulators to avoid mandatory notification, and instructs the professional to alter incident logs to remove evidence of the compromise. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the professional's primary obligation in this situation?","o":["Comply with the instruction because protecting the employer's reputation is the highest ethical canon.","Refuse to alter the records and act with honesty and integrity, escalating through appropriate channels or considering resignation if the illegal act continues.","Alter the logs but privately notify regulators anonymously to fulfill both obligations.","Resign immediately without addressing the request, since taking any position risks personal liability."],"c":1,"why":"The Code of Ethics requires acting honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally, and protecting society takes precedence over loyalty to an employer; refusing to falsify records and escalating appropriately fulfills this duty. Complying, secretly altering records, or abandoning the issue without action all violate the professional's ethical obligations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following is a foundational canon that all certified professionals must follow?","o":["Maximize shareholder value in all security decisions","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Always prioritize the employer's profitability over public safety","Report all vulnerabilities publicly within 24 hours of discovery"],"c":1,"why":"One of the four canons of the (ISC)² Code of Ethics is to protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure. The other options are not part of the Code and would conflict with ethical obligations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization purchases cyber-liability insurance to cover potential financial losses from a data breach rather than investing further in additional technical controls. Which risk response strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is risk transfer. Mitigation involves reducing likelihood or impact through controls, avoidance eliminates the risk-generating activity, and acceptance means taking no action and absorbing the risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization's plan focused on restoring critical business functions and processes after a disruptive event, independent of any specific technology recovery, is best described as a:","o":["Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)","Business Continuity Plan (BCP)","Incident Response Plan (IRP)","Configuration Management Plan"],"c":1,"why":"The BCP addresses restoring overall business operations and critical functions after a disruption. The DRP is more narrowly focused on restoring IT systems and technology infrastructure, while the IRP addresses handling security incidents.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization is evaluating a cloud service provider's controls before finalizing a contract for hosting regulated financial data. The organization needs assurance that the provider's security controls have been operating effectively over a sustained period, not merely designed appropriately at a single point in time. Which type of assurance report should the organization request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3 summary report"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report tests and reports on the operating effectiveness of security controls over a defined period (typically 6-12 months). SOC 2 Type I only assesses control design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on controls relevant to financial reporting rather than security, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary lacking the detailed testing results needed for this evaluation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISSP discovers that a colleague has exaggerated vulnerability findings in a report to justify a larger security budget. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the MOST appropriate action?","o":["Ignore the issue since the inflated findings may benefit the security program overall","Report the inaccurate findings and work to correct the record, since honesty to stakeholders is required","Quietly help adjust the budget request without addressing the inaccuracy","Wait to see whether leadership approves the budget before deciding whether to act"],"c":1,"why":"The Code of Ethics requires members to act honorably, honestly, justly, and responsibly; knowingly allowing falsified findings to stand violates this duty. The other options either condone or delay addressing an ethical violation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A newly hired CISO spends three weeks researching and comparing the security certifications, audit reports, and financial stability of five candidate cloud service providers before recommending one to the board. Which risk-management concept does this activity best illustrate?","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Risk acceptance","Residual risk"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence is the investigative process of researching and evaluating options before making a decision. Due care refers to the ongoing, reasonable actions taken after that decision to protect the organization, so it does not fit an investigative/selection activity.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company wants a framework specifically focused on aligning IT governance and management practices with overall business objectives, including defined control objectives across IT processes. Which framework is BEST suited for this purpose?","o":["ISO/IEC 27001","COBIT","ITIL","NIST SP 800-53"],"c":1,"why":"COBIT is designed specifically for IT governance and aligning IT processes with business objectives through defined control objectives. ISO 27001 focuses on establishing an ISMS, ITIL focuses on IT service management, and NIST SP 800-53 is a technical security control catalog rather than a governance alignment framework.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company is found liable in court for failing to compensate a former employee for unpaid wages as required by a signed employment contract. This dispute would most likely be resolved under which category of law?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort/contract) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Customary law"],"c":1,"why":"Contract disputes, such as unpaid wages under an employment agreement, are resolved under civil law, which addresses disputes between private parties. Criminal law involves offenses against the state, and administrative law involves regulatory agency enforcement.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"After identifying that a data breach could result in significant regulatory fines and lawsuits, an organization purchases a cyber-liability insurance policy to cover potential financial losses rather than changing any technical controls. Which risk treatment strategy is being applied?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk avoidance","Risk acceptance"],"c":1,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing likelihood/impact through controls, avoidance means eliminating the activity entirely, and acceptance means taking no action and absorbing the loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization values a critical database at $500,000. A risk assessment determines that a successful ransomware attack would destroy 20% of the asset's value, and such an attack is expected to occur twice per year. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$20,000","$100,000","$200,000","$500,000"],"c":2,"why":"SLE = Asset Value × Exposure Factor = $500,000 × 0.20 = $100,000. ALE = SLE × ARO = $100,000 × 2 = $200,000. The other values represent SLE alone or unrelated figures.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Which statement best describes the primary purpose of security governance within an organization?","o":["Ensuring that security strategy, objectives, and activities align with and support overall business goals while providing management oversight and accountability","Configuring firewall rule sets to block unauthorized inbound traffic","Performing penetration tests to validate the effectiveness of technical controls","Writing detailed incident response runbooks for the security operations team"],"c":0,"why":"Security governance is a strategic, management-level function focused on aligning security with business objectives and ensuring accountability, whereas the other options describe operational or tactical security activities rather than governance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A government agency fines a company for failing to comply with data-breach notification rules established under a federal regulation, without any criminal prosecution or private lawsuit involved. Which category of law governs this enforcement action?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Common law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law involves regulations and enforcement actions carried out by government agencies, such as fines for regulatory non-compliance. Criminal law involves prosecution for crimes, civil law involves private disputes between parties, and common law is based on judicial precedent.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During business continuity planning, management determines that the organization can tolerate losing no more than 4 hours of transactional data in the event of a system failure. Which metric does this requirement define?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Work Recovery Time (WRT)"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, based on the last good backup or replication point. RTO addresses how quickly systems must be restored, MTD is the total time a business process can be down, and WRT is the time needed to configure recovered systems for production after restoration.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Which type of document within a security program hierarchy is mandatory and specifies exact technical requirements, such as 'all user passwords must be at least 14 characters long'?","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"Standards are mandatory documents that specify precise, measurable requirements supporting policy objectives. Policies are high-level statements of intent, guidelines are advisory recommendations, and procedures provide step-by-step instructions for performing tasks.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution values a critical database asset at $2,000,000. Security analysts determine that a successful attack against this database would destroy 25% of its value (exposure factor), and historical incident data suggests such an attack occurs on average once every five years (ARO = 0.2). What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$100,000","$500,000","$400,000","$2,000,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = AV × EF = $2,000,000 × 0.25 = $500,000; ALE = SLE × ARO = $500,000 × 0.2 = $100,000. $500,000 is the SLE alone, $400,000 results from incorrectly multiplying AV by ARO, and $2,000,000 is simply the asset value.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which term from the CIA triad refers to ensuring that data is accurate, complete, and has not been altered by unauthorized parties?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Integrity concerns the accuracy and trustworthiness of data. Confidentiality protects data from unauthorized disclosure, availability ensures access when needed, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A beverage company keeps its proprietary flavor formula confidential, restricts access to only a few employees, and requires strict non-disclosure agreements, rather than filing for any public registration. Which intellectual property protection mechanism is the company relying on?","o":["Patent","Copyright","Trademark","Trade secret"],"c":3,"why":"Trade secrets protect confidential business information that provides a competitive advantage, and protection depends on the information remaining secret rather than being publicly registered. Patents, copyrights, and trademarks all require public disclosure or registration, which would eliminate the confidentiality needed for a formula like this.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company hired an external firm to perform a comprehensive risk assessment of a new cloud vendor before signing a services contract. The assessment identified several significant control gaps, which were documented in a report to management. Eighteen months later, a breach occurred at the vendor, exploiting one of the previously identified gaps that had never been remediated. From a legal liability standpoint, which concept best explains the organization's exposure in this scenario?","o":["Failure of due diligence, because the initial assessment was inadequate","Failure of due care, because identified risks were not acted upon after the assessment","Negligence per se, because the vendor contract lacked an indemnification clause","Vicarious liability, because the vendor's employees caused the breach"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence (the investigative assessment) was performed thoroughly; the organization's exposure comes from failing to exercise due care by not acting on and maintaining remediation of known risks afterward. The assessment itself was not deficient, so A is wrong, and C/D misapply unrelated legal doctrines.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A risk analyst is evaluating a data center that houses equipment valued at $2,000,000. A flood risk assessment determines that a flood event would destroy 25% of the asset value, and historical weather data indicates such a flood occurs on average once every 4 years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$125,000","$500,000","$62,500","$250,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = AV x EF = $2,000,000 x 0.25 = $500,000. ARO = 1/4 = 0.25. ALE = SLE x ARO = $500,000 x 0.25 = $125,000. The other answers misapply the exposure factor or ARO calculation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements security controls based on what a 'reasonable person' would do to prevent harm, prior to any incident occurring. This concept is best described as:","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Separation of duties","Least privilege"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to taking reasonable actions to protect the organization, reflecting the standard of care a prudent person would exercise. Due diligence involves the research and investigation to understand risks before acting, while separation of duties and least privilege are unrelated access control concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's information security policy states that 'all systems must enforce strong authentication.' The security standards document specifies 'passwords must be a minimum of 14 characters, incorporate three character classes, and expire every 90 days.' A separate document recommends—but does not require—the use of passphrase generators to help users comply. Which term correctly classifies this last document?","o":["Procedure","Guideline","Baseline","Regulatory mandate"],"c":1,"why":"Guidelines are discretionary, recommended practices, unlike procedures (mandatory step-by-step instructions) or standards/baselines (mandatory minimum requirements). Since the document is explicitly optional, it fits the definition of a guideline, not the other mandatory document types.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization commissioned a third-party risk assessment two years ago that identified a critical vulnerability in a legacy authentication system. Management reviewed the report but took no remediation action, and the vulnerability was later exploited, causing a significant breach. In a subsequent lawsuit, which legal concept is most directly implicated by the organization's failure to act on the known finding?","o":["Failure of due diligence, because the organization never investigated the risk","Failure of due care, because the organization knew of the risk but did not take reasonable ongoing action to address it","Strict liability, because the organization is automatically liable regardless of knowledge","Vicarious liability, because the breach was caused by a third-party assessor's negligence"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence is the act of researching and identifying risk (which occurred via the assessment); due care is the ongoing, reasonable action taken to address known risk, which the organization failed to exercise. Strict and vicarious liability do not fit this fact pattern since the organization had actual knowledge and control.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company decides to purchase cybersecurity insurance to cover potential losses from a data breach instead of implementing additional technical controls. This is an example of which risk response strategy?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of the risk to a third party, which is risk transfer. Avoidance eliminates the activity causing risk, mitigation reduces risk through controls, and acceptance means taking no action and absorbing the risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A retailer's third-party risk management program requires new vendors to complete a security self-assessment questionnaire prior to contract signing. Once the contract is executed, no further vendor security reviews are performed unless a breach occurs. Which of the following represents the MOST significant weakness in this program?","o":["The questionnaire relies on vendor self-attestation rather than independent audit evidence","The organization lacks a right-to-audit clause in vendor contracts","The program does not include continuous or periodic monitoring of vendor security posture over the life of the relationship","The questionnaire was not reviewed by legal counsel before use"],"c":2,"why":"The most critical gap is the absence of ongoing oversight—vendor risk evolves after contract signing, and a point-in-time assessment quickly becomes stale. Self-attestation reliability and contractual audit rights (A, B) are legitimate but secondary concerns compared to having no continuous monitoring at all; D is largely irrelevant to security risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO is designing a security governance structure and wants to ensure the security program is properly integrated with enterprise risk management rather than operating as an isolated IT function. Which action BEST demonstrates this integration according to established governance frameworks such as COSO ERM?","o":["Having the CISO report directly to the IT director to streamline technical decision-making","Establishing a security steering committee that reports risk metrics to the board and aligns risk appetite with business objectives","Delegating all risk acceptance decisions to the security operations team for faster response","Creating a standalone security policy manual that is not referenced by other corporate policies"],"c":1,"why":"Effective governance requires that risk appetite and security metrics be communicated to and validated by senior leadership/the board, integrating security into overall enterprise risk management. Reporting to IT, delegating acceptance to operations staff, or isolating policy documents all undermine cross-organizational integration and appropriate accountability.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis determines that a critical order-processing system has a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 48 hours. Business unit managers estimate that after IT restores the system to operation, an additional 8 hours of manual reconciliation and data validation (Work Recovery Time) will be required before the process is considered fully functional. What is the maximum Recovery Time Objective (RTO) that the IT recovery team can be assigned for restoring the system itself?","o":["56 hours","48 hours","40 hours","8 hours"],"c":2,"why":"MTD = RTO + WRT, so RTO = MTD − WRT = 48 − 8 = 40 hours. 56 hours incorrectly adds WRT to MTD, 48 hours ignores WRT entirely, and 8 hours confuses RTO with WRT.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified security manager discovers that a close friend and fellow employee is exfiltrating proprietary source code to a competitor. Reporting this will likely end the friendship and could result in the friend's termination. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon takes precedence in guiding the security manager's required action?","o":["Advance and protect the profession, since failing to report harms the reputation of certified professionals","Provide diligent and competent service to principals, since loyalty to the employer outweighs personal relationships","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure, since this canon takes precedence over the others","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally, since this is a personal ethical matter between the two employees"],"c":2,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are hierarchical, with 'Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure' taking precedence over the others when in conflict. The theft of proprietary code and potential harm to the organization's infrastructure and stakeholders falls under this top-priority canon, overriding personal loyalty concerns addressed in the other canons.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which document provides mandatory, specific low-level instructions on how to accomplish a particular security task, such as configuring a firewall?","o":["Policy","Standard","Procedure","Guideline"],"c":2,"why":"A procedure gives step-by-step, mandatory instructions for performing a specific task. Policies set high-level intent, standards define mandatory requirements (like configuration parameters), and guidelines offer recommended, non-mandatory advice.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified security manager discovers that her employer is deliberately misrepresenting the results of a recent penetration test to a regulator in order to avoid mandatory breach disclosure. The employer instructs her to say nothing during the upcoming regulatory audit. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon takes precedence and dictates her required course of action?","o":["Advance and protect the profession, by refusing to discuss the issue publicly","Provide diligent and competent service to principals, by following her employer's direct instruction","Protect society, the common good, and the infrastructure, which requires she not participate in concealing the misrepresentation","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally, which permits withholding information not directly asked about"],"c":2,"why":"The Code of Ethics canons are applied in priority order, and 'protect society' outranks the duty to serve the employer's interests, meaning she cannot assist in concealing the violation regardless of instruction. Option B improperly elevates employer loyalty above the paramount duty, and A/D mischaracterize the applicable canon.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization is evaluating a cloud service provider (CSP) for handling regulated customer data and wants ongoing assurance that the CSP's security controls have operated effectively over a sustained period, not merely that they were properly designed at a single point in time. Which type of report should the organization request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","ISO 9001 certification"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of controls over a defined period (typically 6-12 months), providing assurance of sustained effectiveness. Type I reports only assess control design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and ISO 9001 addresses quality management, not security control effectiveness.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following best reflects a CISSP's primary obligation?","o":["Maximize profit for the employer at all costs","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Report all security incidents directly to law enforcement without exception","Prioritize personal career advancement over organizational needs"],"c":1,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics' first canon requires members to protect society, the common good, and critical infrastructure. The other options misrepresent ethical obligations and are not part of the Code.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A hospital system is fined $1.5 million by a federal health regulatory agency after an audit reveals inadequate encryption controls on systems storing electronic health records, in violation of a federal health privacy regulation. No criminal charges were filed, and no private lawsuit was brought by affected patients. Under which category of law did this enforcement action occur?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Contract law"],"c":2,"why":"Fines imposed directly by a regulatory agency for violating a regulation constitute administrative/regulatory law enforcement. No prosecution occurred (ruling out criminal law), no private lawsuit was filed by an injured party (ruling out tort law), and no contractual relationship was breached (ruling out contract law).","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A pharmaceutical company has developed a proprietary chemical synthesis process that gives it a significant competitive advantage. The process cannot easily be reverse-engineered from the finished product, and the company wants protection that could last indefinitely as long as secrecy is maintained, without needing to publicly disclose the process details. Which form of intellectual property protection is MOST appropriate?","o":["Patent, because it provides the strongest legal protection for processes","Trade secret, because it does not require public disclosure and can last indefinitely if confidentiality is maintained","Copyright, because the process constitutes an original work of authorship","Trademark, because it protects the company's brand associated with the process"],"c":1,"why":"Trade secrets protect confidential business information indefinitely as long as reasonable secrecy measures are maintained and disclosure is avoided—patents require public disclosure and expire after a fixed term (typically 20 years), while copyright protects expression rather than processes and trademark protects brand identifiers, not the underlying process.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A risk assessment determines that a threat has a Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) of $50,000 and an Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) of 0.2. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$5,000","$10,000","$50,000","$250,000"],"c":1,"why":"ALE = SLE × ARO = $50,000 × 0.2 = $10,000. The other values result from incorrect calculations or misunderstanding the formula.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"After completing a risk assessment, an organization decides to purchase cyber-liability insurance to cover potential financial losses from a data breach, while also implementing additional access controls to reduce the likelihood of a breach occurring. Which risk treatment strategy does the purchase of insurance represent?","o":["Risk mitigation, because it reduces the likelihood of the breach","Risk avoidance, because it eliminates the underlying risk entirely","Risk transfer, because it shifts the financial impact of the risk to a third party","Risk acceptance, because the organization is choosing to tolerate the risk as-is"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance transfers the financial consequences of a risk event to a third party (the insurer) without changing the likelihood or eliminating the risk itself. Mitigation refers to the access controls reducing likelihood, avoidance would mean eliminating the risk-causing activity, and acceptance means tolerating risk without additional controls or transfer.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An employee is prosecuted by the government for violating a computer fraud statute, resulting in fines and imprisonment. This scenario falls under which category of law?","o":["Civil law","Criminal law","Administrative law","Contract law"],"c":1,"why":"Criminal law involves government prosecution of offenses against society, with penalties like imprisonment. Civil law addresses disputes between parties (typically monetary damages), administrative law involves regulatory agency enforcement, and contract law governs agreements between parties.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"Risk analysts calculate the following for a specific threat scenario: Asset Value = $250,000; Exposure Factor = 40%; ARO = 0.5, yielding an ALE of $50,000. Three risk treatment options are under consideration: (1) Accept the risk as-is; (2) Purchase cyber insurance with an annual premium of $55,000 that fully covers the loss; (3) Implement a control costing $100,000 upfront (5-year useful life, straight-line amortized) plus $5,000/year in maintenance, which reduces the ARO to 0.05. Based purely on lowest total annualized cost, which treatment should the organization select?","o":["Accept the risk, since $50,000/year is the lowest cost when no control spending is required","Transfer the risk via insurance, since it fully eliminates financial exposure","Mitigate the risk with the new control, since its total annualized cost is lower than the alternatives","Avoid the risk entirely by discontinuing the activity that creates the exposure"],"c":2,"why":"Mitigation's total annualized cost = $20,000 amortized capital + $5,000 maintenance + $5,000 residual ALE (SLE $100,000 × ARO 0.05) = $30,000, which is lower than accepting ($50,000/year) or transferring ($55,000/year); avoidance is not a viable option presented in the scenario, making C the cost-optimal choice.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary purpose of a Business Continuity Plan (BCP)?","o":["To restore IT systems and data after a disaster","To ensure critical business functions continue during and after a disruptive event","To investigate the root cause of a security incident","To define access control policies for sensitive systems"],"c":1,"why":"A BCP focuses on maintaining essential business operations during and after a disruption. Restoring IT systems is the focus of a Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP), while incident investigation and access control policies are unrelated to continuity planning.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During a Business Impact Analysis, a financial system is found to perform full backups every 24 hours, with no incremental backups in between. Stakeholders determine that the business can tolerate losing at most 4 hours of transaction data. Given the current backup schedule, what is the organization's actual Recovery Point Objective (RPO) exposure, and what does this indicate?","o":["The actual RPO exposure is 4 hours, meeting the business requirement","The actual RPO exposure is up to 24 hours, which exceeds the 4-hour tolerance and represents a gap requiring more frequent backups","The actual RPO exposure is 0 hours, since full backups guarantee no data loss","The actual RPO exposure is irrelevant; only the Recovery Time Objective (RTO) matters for backup scheduling"],"c":1,"why":"With backups only every 24 hours, up to 24 hours of data could be lost in a failure just before the next backup—far exceeding the stated 4-hour tolerance (target RPO). This indicates a control gap requiring more frequent or incremental backups. RTO addresses downtime duration, not data loss, and full backups do not eliminate the gap between backup intervals.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which element of the CIA triad ensures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized individuals, entities, or processes?","o":["Availability","Confidentiality","Integrity","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Confidentiality specifically addresses protecting data from unauthorized disclosure. Availability concerns access when needed, integrity concerns accuracy/completeness, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A risk assessment identifies a critical database server with an Asset Value (AV) of $500,000. A successful ransomware attack is estimated to destroy 20% of the asset's value (Exposure Factor), and such an attack is expected to occur once every two years (ARO = 0.5). What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$50,000","$100,000","$10,000","$250,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = AV x EF = $500,000 x 0.20 = $100,000; ALE = SLE x ARO = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. $100,000 is the SLE without applying ARO, and the other figures result from miscalculating the multiplication.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before signing a contract with a new cloud service provider, a CISO commissions an independent third-party security assessment of the provider's controls. This activity is best described as an exercise of:","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk transfer","Residual risk acceptance"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence is the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as vetting a vendor's controls prior to contracting. Due care refers to the ongoing responsible actions taken after a decision is made; the other options do not describe pre-contract investigation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements a firewall and patches all known vulnerabilities on a server as recommended by industry best practices. This exercise of reasonable care to protect assets best describes which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Due care","Separation of duties"],"c":2,"why":"Due care refers to the actions taken to implement and maintain reasonable security measures. Due diligence is the research/investigation performed before acting, risk acceptance is a risk treatment decision, and separation of duties is an access control principle.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"In risk management terminology, a weakness in a system that could be exploited to cause harm is best described as a:","o":["Threat","Vulnerability","Risk","Exposure factor"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability is a weakness that can be exploited. A threat is the potential cause of harm, risk is the likelihood and impact combined, and exposure factor is a percentage used in quantitative risk calculations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A national financial regulator imposes a monetary fine on a bank for failing to implement legally mandated security controls, without pursuing imprisonment or criminal charges against any individual. This enforcement action is an example of which category of law?","o":["Common law","Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law"],"c":3,"why":"Administrative law governs enforcement by regulatory agencies, typically resulting in fines or sanctions for non-compliance rather than criminal penalties. Criminal law involves government prosecution seeking imprisonment, civil law addresses private disputes between parties, and common law is based on judicial precedent rather than agency enforcement.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following documents provides mandatory, high-level statements of management intent regarding information security, but does not specify technical implementation details?","o":["Procedure","Guideline","Policy","Baseline"],"c":2,"why":"A policy is a mandatory, high-level statement of management's intent and direction. Procedures give step-by-step instructions, guidelines are recommended (not mandatory) practices, and baselines define minimum required configurations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization purchases a cyber liability insurance policy to offset the potential financial impact of a future data breach, rather than implementing additional technical controls. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing likelihood/impact through controls, avoidance means eliminating the activity entirely, and acceptance means retaining the risk without transferring it.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following is listed as one of the four mandatory canons that all certified members must follow?","o":["Maximize shareholder profit above all other considerations","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Always choose the lowest-cost security solution available","Report only to law enforcement when a breach occurs"],"c":1,"why":"This is one of the four (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons. The other options are not part of the code and misrepresent professional obligations, which prioritize public safety and trust over cost or profit.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A risk manager decides that the cost of mitigating a particular low-impact risk exceeds the potential loss, and therefore decides to take no further action and continue operations as-is. This is an example of which risk treatment strategy?","o":["Risk transfer","Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk acceptance"],"c":3,"why":"Risk acceptance means the organization acknowledges the risk and chooses to take no additional action, typically because the cost of treatment outweighs the benefit. Transfer shifts risk to a third party, avoidance eliminates the activity causing risk, and mitigation reduces risk through controls.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During a Business Impact Analysis, a team determines the maximum amount of data loss, measured in time, that the organization can tolerate for a given system before the loss becomes unacceptable. Which metric are they defining?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Work Recovery Time (WRT)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the acceptable amount of data loss measured backward in time from an incident, dictating backup frequency. RTO and MTD relate to acceptable downtime duration, and WRT is the time needed to reconfigure/verify systems after restoration, not data loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A governance document within an organization mandates that all data at rest must be encrypted using AES-256, with no exceptions or discretion permitted for system owners. This type of document is best classified as a:","o":["Guideline","Procedure","Standard","Policy"],"c":2,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, specific technical or procedural requirements that support policy objectives. Guidelines are discretionary recommendations, procedures are step-by-step instructions for performing tasks, and policies are high-level statements of management intent rather than specific technical mandates.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best distinguishes a Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP) from a Business Continuity Plan (BCP)?","o":["A DRP focuses on restoring IT systems and technical infrastructure after a disruption, while a BCP addresses sustaining overall business operations during and after a disruption","A BCP is only used for natural disasters, while a DRP is used for cyberattacks","A DRP is a subset of physical security policy, while a BCP is a subset of HR policy","There is no meaningful difference; the terms are interchangeable"],"c":0,"why":"DRP is narrowly focused on restoring technical/IT infrastructure, while BCP is broader, covering overall business process continuity. The other options misstate the scope and relationship between the two plans.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A data center houses assets valued at $500,000. A fire risk assessment determines an exposure factor of 20% and an annualized rate of occurrence of 0.5 (once every two years). A proposed fire-suppression system costing $30,000 per year would reduce the ARO to 0.1 (once every ten years) without changing the exposure factor. Based on quantitative risk analysis, what is the net annual value of implementing this control?","o":["$10,000 net savings","$40,000 net savings","$20,000 net loss","$30,000 net savings"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = $500,000 x 0.20 = $100,000. Current ALE = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. New ALE = $100,000 x 0.1 = $10,000. ALE reduction = $40,000, minus the $30,000 control cost = $10,000 net savings, making the control cost-justified. The other options miscalculate either the ALE reduction or ignore the control's cost.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISSP-certified professional discovers credible evidence that their employer is knowingly violating safety regulations in a way that could endanger the public. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons, which principle should guide the professional's primary course of action?","o":["Protect the employer's reputation above all other considerations","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Remain silent to preserve confidentiality obligations to the employer","Resign immediately without taking further action"],"c":1,"why":"The first and highest-priority canon of the (ISC)² Code of Ethics requires members to protect society and the public good, which takes precedence over loyalty to an employer when public safety is at risk. Silent inaction, resignation without addressing the issue, or prioritizing employer reputation over public safety all conflict with this canon.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company operating in multiple countries must comply with varying data protection laws depending on where its customers reside. This obligation is an example of which type of risk?","o":["Operational risk","Legal and regulatory risk","Reputational risk","Residual risk"],"c":1,"why":"Legal and regulatory risk arises from the need to comply with differing laws across jurisdictions. Operational risk relates to internal processes, reputational risk concerns public perception, and residual risk is what remains after controls are applied.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization commissioned a comprehensive third-party risk assessment that identified a critical vulnerability in a legacy application. Management reviewed the report but did not allocate resources to remediate the flaw, and an attacker later exploited it. From a legal liability standpoint, which statement best characterizes the organization's position?","o":["The organization exercised due diligence but failed to exercise due care, increasing its legal exposure.","The organization exercised due care but failed due diligence, eliminating liability.","Because due diligence was performed, the organization is automatically shielded from negligence claims.","Due care and due diligence are interchangeable, so the organization met its legal obligations."],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research/investigation of risk (the assessment), while due care refers to acting on that knowledge (remediation). Performing the assessment but not acting on it demonstrates diligence without care, which increases negligence exposure. The other options confuse or conflate the two concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements encryption on its database servers to ensure that only authorized personnel can view sensitive customer records. Which principle of the CIA triad does this control primarily support?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":0,"why":"Encryption restricts access to data to authorized parties, which is the core goal of confidentiality. Integrity concerns data accuracy, availability concerns access when needed, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's accounts payable system is configured so that no single employee can both create a new vendor record and approve payments to that vendor. This control is best described as:","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple individuals to prevent a single person from committing and concealing fraud. Least privilege limits access to only what is needed for a role, job rotation periodically changes assignments, and mandatory vacation forces absence to surface irregularities—none of which specifically split the create/approve functions described.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company's web application uses an outdated software library with a known flaw that attackers could exploit to gain unauthorized access. In risk management terminology, what does this outdated library represent?","o":["A threat","A vulnerability","An exposure factor","A residual risk"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability is a weakness that can be exploited; the outdated library with a known flaw fits this definition. The attacker exploiting it is the threat, not the flaw itself, and exposure factor and residual risk are risk calculation concepts, not weaknesses.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A court is evaluating whether an organization acted responsibly in protecting sensitive customer data prior to a breach. Which legal concept describes the benchmark courts typically use—comparing the organization's actions to what a reasonably careful entity in a similar position would have done?","o":["Strict liability standard","Prudent person (reasonable person) rule","Vicarious liability doctrine","Downstream liability principle"],"c":1,"why":"The prudent person rule assesses whether an organization's security practices meet the standard of care that a reasonably prudent entity would exercise under similar circumstances. Strict liability doesn't require a fault-based comparison, vicarious liability concerns responsibility for others' actions, and downstream liability concerns harm caused to third parties, none of which describe this reasonableness benchmark.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company owns a data center valued at $500,000. A risk assessment determines that a fire could damage 40% of the facility (exposure factor), and such fires are expected to occur once every two years (ARO = 0.5). What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$100,000","$200,000","$250,000","$400,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x EF = $500,000 x 0.40 = $200,000. ALE = SLE x ARO = $200,000 x 0.5 = $100,000. The other options result from miscalculating either the SLE or applying the ARO incorrectly.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before signing a contract with a cloud service provider, a company's security team reviews the provider's SOC 2 report, conducts an on-site audit, and verifies the provider's incident response history. This activity is best described as an example of:","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Segregation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence involves researching and verifying facts before making a decision, such as investigating a vendor's security posture. Due care refers to ongoing responsible actions after a decision has been made, and the other options are unrelated risk/control concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A CISO reviews industry best practices and implements reasonable security controls to protect the organization before any incident occurs. This action best exemplifies which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Risk acceptance","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to taking reasonable actions to protect the organization based on known best practices, i.e., prudent action. Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed prior to acting, not the act itself; risk acceptance and separation of duties are unrelated concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A multinational company suffers a personal data breach affecting EU residents that is likely to result in a risk to individuals' rights and freedoms. Under GDPR, within what maximum time frame must the data controller notify the relevant supervisory authority, absent a qualifying exemption?","o":["24 hours","72 hours","30 days","90 days"],"c":1,"why":"GDPR Article 33 requires notification to the supervisory authority without undue delay and, where feasible, within 72 hours of becoming aware of the breach, unless the breach is unlikely to result in risk. The other time frames do not reflect the GDPR standard.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which document in an organization's security governance hierarchy is typically MANDATORY and specifies exact technical requirements, such as requiring AES-256 encryption for all removable media?","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"Standards are mandatory, specific technical requirements that support policies. Policies are high-level and less technical, guidelines are advisory/optional, and procedures are step-by-step instructions for performing a task.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization requires that the employee who initiates a wire transfer request cannot be the same person who approves it. This control is an example of:","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by any single individual. Least privilege limits access rights generally, job rotation moves staff between roles over time, and mandatory vacation forces time off to expose fraud, none of which directly describe splitting approval authority.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO is evaluating a cloud provider's security posture ahead of a contract renewal and receives a SOC 2 Type I report. What is the PRIMARY limitation of relying on this report alone for an ongoing risk decision?","o":["It attests only to the design of controls at a specific point in time, not their operating effectiveness over a period.","It is not recognized as a valid assurance mechanism outside the United States.","It covers only financial reporting controls, not information security controls.","It is a self-attestation that has not been reviewed by an independent auditor."],"c":0,"why":"SOC 2 Type I evaluates control design at a single point in time, whereas Type II tests operating effectiveness over a review period (typically 6-12 months), which is more relevant for ongoing risk decisions. SOC 2 reports are security/trust-services focused, are independently audited, and are recognized internationally, making the other options incorrect.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A defendant is being tried in a case where the standard of proof required for conviction is 'beyond a reasonable doubt.' This case is being tried under which type of law?","o":["Civil law","Administrative law","Criminal law","Tort law"],"c":2,"why":"Criminal law requires proof beyond a reasonable doubt because of the severity of potential penalties, including imprisonment. Civil and tort law use a lower 'preponderance of the evidence' standard, and administrative law governs regulatory compliance, not criminal proceedings.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"After completing a risk assessment, management decides that the cost of mitigating a low-impact risk exceeds the potential loss, so they formally document and approve leaving the risk as-is. Which risk treatment option does this represent?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk mitigation","Risk acceptance"],"c":3,"why":"Risk acceptance occurs when management formally decides to retain a risk because the cost of addressing it outweighs the benefit. Avoidance eliminates the activity causing the risk, transfer shifts it to a third party, and mitigation reduces it through controls.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization purchases cyber liability insurance to help cover the financial impact of a potential data breach. Which statement most accurately describes the effect of this risk management decision?","o":["It eliminates the risk entirely because any financial losses will be reimbursed.","It transfers the financial impact of the risk but does not reduce the likelihood of occurrence or associated reputational damage.","It qualifies as risk avoidance since technical controls are no longer required.","It converts the security risk into a purely regulatory compliance matter."],"c":1,"why":"Insurance is a risk transfer mechanism that shifts financial consequences to a third party, but it does not reduce the probability of an incident or mitigate non-financial harms like reputational damage. It is not risk elimination or avoidance, and it does not change the risk into a compliance issue.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During business continuity planning, management determines that the organization can tolerate losing no more than 2 hours of transactional data in the event of a system failure. This requirement defines the:","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time to Repair (MTTR)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, dictating backup frequency. RTO and MTD relate to acceptable downtime duration, and MTTR measures average repair time for a failed component, none of which address data loss tolerance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"In a data classification program, who is ultimately ACCOUNTABLE for determining the classification level of a specific dataset and approving who may access it?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Security administrator","End user"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner has ultimate accountability for classifying data and determining access permissions, even though they may delegate day-to-day tasks to a custodian. The custodian implements controls, the security administrator manages technical access, and end users simply use the data.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis determines that a critical order-processing system has a maximum tolerable downtime (MTD) of 8 hours. The IT team's recovery time objective (RTO) for restoring the system is 6 hours, but the recovery point objective (RPO) reflects backups taken every 4 hours. Which evaluation of this scenario is correct?","o":["Because RTO (6h) is within MTD (8h), recovery timing is acceptable, but the 4-hour RPO gap could still cause unacceptable data loss depending on business tolerance.","The scenario is automatically unacceptable because RPO must always be shorter than RTO.","Since MTD exceeds RTO, no further assessment of data loss exposure is needed.","RPO is irrelevant to business continuity planning as long as RTO falls within MTD."],"c":0,"why":"RTO and RPO measure different dimensions of recovery—time to restore service versus acceptable data loss—so meeting the MTD/RTO relationship does not address whether the potential data loss reflected by the RPO is tolerable to the business. RPO and RTO are independent metrics and both must be evaluated against business requirements.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"After identifying a risk of data breach from a third-party payment processor, an organization decides to purchase a cyber liability insurance policy to cover potential financial losses. This is an example of which risk response strategy?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing the likelihood or impact directly, avoidance means eliminating the risk-causing activity, and acceptance means acknowledging the risk without further action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following best reflects a CISSP's primary obligation when a conflict arises between an employer's directive and the public's safety?","o":["Follow the employer's directive without exception to maintain loyalty","Protect society, the common good, and the infrastructure, even if it conflicts with employer interests","Resign immediately from the position to avoid conflict","Report the employer's directive anonymously to the media"],"c":1,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics places protecting society and the public good as a foundational canon that takes precedence over blind loyalty to an employer. Immediate resignation or anonymous media leaks are not appropriate first steps under the code.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following canons takes precedence over the others when a conflict arises between professional duties?","o":["Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Advance and protect the profession","Protect society, the commonwealth, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are prioritized in order, with protecting society, the commonwealth, and the infrastructure listed first and given precedence in cases of conflict. The other canons are important but subordinate to this top-level obligation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A newly hired security manager wants to ensure that the organization's security program supports overall business objectives rather than operating as an isolated technical function. Which activity BEST demonstrates effective security governance?","o":["Purchasing the latest intrusion detection technology","Aligning security policies and objectives with the organization's strategic business goals","Conducting quarterly vulnerability scans","Requiring all employees to complete annual security awareness training"],"c":1,"why":"Security governance is fundamentally about aligning security strategy with business objectives and ensuring executive oversight and accountability. Purchasing technology, scanning, and training are operational security activities, not governance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization is structuring its governance documentation. Which term BEST completes the typical hierarchy, from most general/strategic to most specific/operational: Policy → Standard → ___ → Procedure?","o":["Guideline","Baseline","Framework","Control"],"c":0,"why":"Guidelines provide recommended, flexible direction that bridges mandatory standards and the detailed, step-by-step instructions found in procedures. Baselines are typically a specific type of standard rather than a separate hierarchy layer, and framework/control are broader or unrelated governance terms that don't fit this specific documentation hierarchy.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A security team publishes a document stating that all servers must be patched within 30 days of a critical vulnerability disclosure. Employees are also given a separate, non-mandatory document suggesting best practices for testing patches in a staging environment before deployment. The second document is best classified as a:","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":2,"why":"Guidelines are recommended, non-mandatory practices that provide flexibility in how objectives are met. Standards are mandatory and specific (like the 30-day patch requirement), policies set high-level intent, and procedures provide mandatory step-by-step instructions, none of which match the described discretionary document.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization values a critical database server at $500,000. Historical data shows that a successful ransomware attack on this server occurs, on average, once every two years, and typically destroys or corrupts 20% of the asset's value. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$25,000","$50,000","$100,000","$200,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor = $500,000 x 0.20 = $100,000. ARO = 1/2 = 0.5. ALE = SLE x ARO = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. The other options result from misapplying the exposure factor or ARO incorrectly.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISO commissions an independent third party to thoroughly assess a potential cloud vendor's security controls, financial stability, and compliance history before signing a contract. This activity best exemplifies which concept?","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed prior to making a decision, such as vetting a vendor. Due care refers to the ongoing implementation of protective measures after a decision is made, so it does not fit this pre-contract investigative activity.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Senior management wants to ensure that the organization's information security program supports business objectives and that the board of directors maintains oversight of cyber risk. Which of the following BEST demonstrates this alignment?","o":["The IT department independently selects and implements security tools based on technical best practices","The security team publishes a technical vulnerability report quarterly to the network operations staff","A security steering committee, including business unit leaders, reviews risk appetite and approves the security strategy annually","The organization purchases the highest-rated security product recommended by an industry analyst firm"],"c":2,"why":"Governance requires business and executive involvement in setting risk appetite and strategic direction, which a cross-functional steering committee provides. The other options represent isolated technical decisions made without business alignment or executive oversight.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A government regulatory agency fines a healthcare organization for failing to implement required safeguards under a data protection regulation. This enforcement action is an example of which category of law?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Common law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law involves regulations and enforcement actions created and carried out by government agencies, such as fines for regulatory non-compliance. Criminal law involves government prosecution for crimes with potential incarceration, and civil law involves private party lawsuits for damages, neither of which matches an agency-imposed fine.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During BCP planning, a business impact analysis determines that a critical order-processing system must be restored within 4 hours of an outage, and that no more than 15 minutes of transaction data can be lost. The 15-minute figure represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, i.e., how far back backups must go. RTO (4 hours here) defines how quickly the system must be restored, while MTD and MTBF measure downtime tolerance and hardware reliability, respectively, not data loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company identifies a risk that a rare but severe weather event could damage its data center. Rather than investing heavily in structural reinforcement, the company purchases a comprehensive insurance policy to cover potential losses. Which risk treatment strategy is being applied?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Risk transfer shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, such as through insurance, without reducing the likelihood or eliminating the activity. Mitigation would involve reducing the risk directly (e.g., reinforcing the building), avoidance would mean eliminating the risk-causing activity, and acceptance would mean taking no action and absorbing potential losses.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A hospital database is modified by an unauthorized employee who alters patient records so that dosage information is incorrect. Which component of the CIA triad has been most directly violated?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Unauthorized alteration of data violates integrity, which ensures data remains accurate and unmodified except by authorized parties. Confidentiality concerns unauthorized disclosure, availability concerns access, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A hospital implements a system that uses cryptographic hashing to detect unauthorized modification of patient records, but does not encrypt the records themselves. Which principle of the CIA triad is primarily being addressed by this control?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Hashing detects changes to data, which addresses integrity, not confidentiality (which requires encryption) or availability (which relates to access/uptime). Non-repudiation is not one of the three CIA triad elements.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's security documentation includes a mandatory requirement that all laptops must use full-disk encryption meeting FIPS 140-2 standards, along with a separate document recommending (but not requiring) the use of password managers for personal convenience. These two documents are best classified, respectively, as which types?","o":["Policy and procedure","Standard and guideline","Procedure and policy","Guideline and standard"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, specific requirements (like a required encryption algorithm), while a guideline offers recommended, discretionary practices. Policies are high-level statements of intent, and procedures are step-by-step instructions, neither of which matches the specificity or mandatory/optional nature described here.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A risk analyst is evaluating a proposed security control for an e-commerce platform. The asset value is $500,000, and a successful attack is expected to cause a 20% loss (exposure factor). Currently, such attacks occur on average once every two years (ARO = 0.5). The proposed control costs $30,000 annually and would reduce the ARO to 0.1. Based on a cost-benefit analysis, what is the annualized value of implementing this control?","o":["$40,000, representing the full reduction in the annualized loss expectancy","$10,000, representing the net benefit after subtracting the control's annual cost from the ALE reduction","$30,000, equal to the annual cost of the control","$50,000, representing the ALE before the control is implemented"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = $500,000 × 0.20 = $100,000. ALE before = $100,000 × 0.5 = $50,000; ALE after = $100,000 × 0.1 = $10,000, a reduction of $40,000. Subtracting the $30,000 annual control cost yields a net benefit of $10,000. The other options confuse the gross reduction, the raw cost, or the pre-control ALE with the net value calculation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization values a critical database server at $500,000. A risk assessment determines that a successful ransomware attack would destroy 20% of the asset's value, and such an attack is expected to occur once every two years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$20,000","$50,000","$100,000","$250,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor = $500,000 x 0.20 = $100,000. ARO = 0.5 (once every two years). ALE = SLE x ARO = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. The other answers result from misapplying the exposure factor or ARO.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISSP holder discovers that a close friend and colleague has been falsifying security audit results to hide compliance gaps from senior management. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the MOST appropriate action?","o":["Say nothing, since personal loyalty to colleagues takes precedence over reporting","Report the conduct through appropriate channels, since protecting society and the infrastructure takes precedence","Confront the colleague privately and take no further action if they promise to stop","Wait until the next audit cycle to see if the behavior continues before deciding whether to act"],"c":1,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics places 'Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure' as the first and highest canon, obligating members to report unethical or fraudulent conduct rather than remain silent or delay action out of personal loyalty or convenience.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A hospital's IT department conducted a thorough risk assessment identifying a critical vulnerability in its patient records system and documented recommended remediation steps. Management reviewed the report but did not allocate budget or resources to implement the fixes for over a year, after which a breach occurred exploiting the known vulnerability. From a legal liability perspective, which statement best describes the organization's failure?","o":["The organization failed to exercise due diligence, since risk assessments must be repeated annually","The organization exercised due diligence by identifying the risk but failed to exercise due care by not acting on the findings","The organization is not liable because due diligence was performed and due care is not a legal standard","The organization failed both due diligence and due care, since the risk assessment itself was inadequate"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research/investigation to identify risk, which was performed; due care refers to taking reasonable, timely action to address known risk, which was not done, creating negligence liability. The other options mischaracterize which standard was met or falsely claim due care is not legally relevant.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company thoroughly investigates the security posture, financial stability, and compliance history of a cloud provider before signing a contract. This activity BEST exemplifies which concept?","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Residual risk management"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed prior to making a decision, such as vetting a vendor. Due care refers to the ongoing actions taken to maintain a reasonable standard of protection after that decision, and the other options do not describe pre-decision investigation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following correctly describes the relationship between a security policy, a standard, and a procedure within an organization's governance documents?","o":["A procedure defines high-level intent, and policies provide step-by-step instructions to implement it","A standard is optional guidance, while a procedure is a mandatory rule","A policy states management's high-level intent, a standard specifies mandatory requirements to support the policy, and a procedure provides detailed step-by-step instructions","Guidelines and policies are interchangeable terms with identical enforcement requirements"],"c":2,"why":"Policies set overall direction and intent, standards provide mandatory specifications supporting policies, and procedures give detailed implementation steps; guidelines are recommended but not mandatory, unlike standards. The other options reverse or misstate these relationships.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A payment-processing firm determines that it can tolerate no more than 4 hours of system downtime before suffering unacceptable damage to its business, and it can afford to lose no more than 15 minutes of transaction data in the event of a failure. Which pair of metrics should drive the design of its disaster recovery architecture, and how should they be applied?","o":["Maximum Tolerable Downtime of 15 minutes and Recovery Point Objective of 4 hours","Recovery Time Objective of no more than 4 hours and Recovery Point Objective of no more than 15 minutes","Recovery Time Objective of 15 minutes and Work Recovery Time of 4 hours","Recovery Point Objective of 4 hours and Maximum Tolerable Downtime of 15 minutes"],"c":1,"why":"RTO governs the maximum allowable time to restore systems (must be ≤ the 4-hour MTD), while RPO governs the maximum acceptable data loss based on backup frequency (≤15 minutes). The distractors swap or misapply these definitions, confusing downtime tolerance with data-loss tolerance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization stores customer data on a server running outdated, unpatched software with known remote-code-execution flaws. In risk terminology, what does the unpatched software represent?","o":["A threat","A vulnerability","A risk","A control"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability is a weakness that can be exploited, such as unpatched software; a threat is the potential exploiter (e.g., an attacker or malware), risk is the likelihood and impact of a threat exploiting a vulnerability, and a control is a safeguard, none of which matches unpatched software itself.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"After identifying a risk that a legacy application could be exploited via an unpatchable vulnerability, management decides to purchase cyber liability insurance to cover potential financial losses instead of replacing the application immediately. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of the risk to a third party, which is risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing the likelihood or impact directly, avoidance would mean discontinuing the risky activity, and acceptance would mean taking no action and absorbing the loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization operates a data center in a region prone to rare but catastrophic seismic events. Engineering estimates that retrofitting the facility to withstand a major earthquake would cost far more than the expected loss, while an insurance policy covering earthquake damage is available at a reasonable annual premium. Which risk treatment strategy is MOST appropriate in this scenario?","o":["Risk avoidance, by relocating the data center to a region with no seismic activity","Risk mitigation, by investing in the structural retrofit regardless of cost","Risk transfer, by purchasing the earthquake insurance policy","Risk acceptance, by taking no action and absorbing any resulting loss"],"c":2,"why":"When mitigation costs exceed the expected loss but a cost-effective transfer mechanism exists, risk transfer via insurance is the most economically sound treatment. Avoidance is impractical/costly, mitigation is not cost-justified, and pure acceptance ignores a better available option.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company's disaster recovery plan states that after a disruption, the order-processing system must be restored within 4 hours, and no more than 15 minutes of transaction data can be lost. The 15-minute figure represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, which corresponds to the 15-minute figure. RTO (the 4-hour figure) refers to how quickly systems must be restored, MTD is the maximum outage the business can tolerate, and MTBF measures reliability between failures, not data loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company is evaluating a cloud service provider (CSP) that will host sensitive financial data. The company's audit team requires assurance that the CSP's security controls were not only suitably designed but also operated effectively throughout the preceding six-month period. Which type of assurance report should the company request from the CSP?","o":["SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 3 report"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates both the design and the operating effectiveness of controls over a defined period, matching the requirement. Type I only assesses design at a point in time, SOC 1 addresses controls relevant to financial reporting rather than security, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary lacking detailed testing evidence.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company estimates that a specific server outage would cost $50,000 in lost revenue each time it occurs, and based on historical data, this type of outage is expected to happen twice per year. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$25,000","$50,000","$100,000","$150,000"],"c":2,"why":"ALE is calculated as Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) multiplied by Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO): $50,000 x 2 = $100,000. The other values result from incorrect arithmetic or misunderstanding of the formula.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Under the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), within what timeframe must a data controller typically notify the relevant supervisory authority after becoming aware of a personal data breach, unless the breach is unlikely to result in risk to individuals?","o":["24 hours","72 hours","5 business days","30 days"],"c":1,"why":"GDPR Article 33 requires notification to the supervisory authority without undue delay and, where feasible, within 72 hours of becoming aware of the breach. The other timeframes do not reflect the GDPR requirement.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution's database server is valued at $2,000,000. A risk assessment determines that a successful ransomware attack would destroy or corrupt 25% of the data's value, and historical data indicates such attacks against comparable organizations occur, on average, once every four years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$125,000","$500,000","$2,000,000","$62,500"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = AV x EF = $2,000,000 x 0.25 = $500,000. ARO = 1/4 years = 0.25. ALE = SLE x ARO = $500,000 x 0.25 = $125,000. The other figures represent the SLE, the raw asset value, or an arithmetic error, none of which is the correct annualized figure.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's information security program includes multiple governing documents. One document states: 'All laptops must be configured with full-disk encryption using AES-256, and the encryption key must be escrowed with the IT security team before deployment.' This document is best classified as which type of governance artifact?","o":["Policy, because it establishes high-level intent for protecting data","Standard, because it specifies a mandatory, specific technical requirement","Guideline, because it recommends a best practice organizations should consider","Procedure, because it provides step-by-step instructions for configuring encryption"],"c":1,"why":"Standards define mandatory, specific technical requirements such as the exact algorithm and key management approach. A policy would state intent without technical specificity, a guideline is advisory rather than mandatory, and a procedure would detail the exact configuration steps rather than stating the requirement itself.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution requires that the employee who initiates a wire transfer cannot be the same employee who approves it. This control is an example of which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Need to know","Defense in depth"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by a single individual. Least privilege limits access rights to only what is necessary, need to know restricts information access based on job function, and defense in depth refers to layered security controls, none of which specifically describe splitting a single process between two people.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A financial institution decides to purchase a cybersecurity insurance policy to help offset potential losses from a data breach rather than investing further in additional security controls. This is an example of which risk treatment strategy?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation involves reducing risk through controls, avoidance means eliminating the activity causing the risk, and acceptance means acknowledging and retaining the risk without further action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A disgruntled former employee accesses her previous employer's network without authorization and copies proprietary source code before resigning. The company files suit seeking monetary damages for the harm caused, while a government prosecutor separately files charges against the employee under a computer crime statute. Which statement best characterizes these two concurrent legal actions?","o":["The company's suit is administrative law seeking punitive sanctions; the prosecutor's case is customary law seeking imprisonment.","The company's suit is civil law seeking compensatory damages; the prosecutor's case is criminal law seeking punishment on behalf of society.","Both actions are civil law, differentiated only by the standard of proof required.","The company's suit is criminal law seeking restitution; the prosecutor's case is civil law seeking fines paid to the government."],"c":1,"why":"Civil law addresses disputes between private parties and typically results in monetary compensation, while criminal law is brought by the state to punish violations of statute (e.g., imprisonment or fines to the government) on behalf of society. The other options mislabel which action is civil versus criminal or invoke inapplicable legal categories.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A manufacturing firm developed a proprietary chemical formula that it protects as a trade secret rather than patenting it. Investigators later discover that employees routinely discussed formula details in an unsecured internal wiki accessible to all staff without any confidentiality agreements or access restrictions. If a competitor obtains the formula through this exposure, what is the MOST likely legal consequence for the firm?","o":["The firm retains full trade secret protection because trade secrets do not require any protective measures","The firm loses trade secret protection because it failed to take reasonable measures to maintain secrecy","The firm can still sue for patent infringement since the formula was never publicly disclosed","The firm automatically receives copyright protection over the formula's disclosure"],"c":1,"why":"Trade secret status legally requires reasonable, ongoing protective measures; failing to restrict access or require confidentiality agreements forfeits that protection. Patent protection is unavailable since the formula was never patented, and formulas of this nature are not protected by copyright.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following is the FIRST canon that CISSP-certified professionals are expected to uphold?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics lists 'Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure' as the first and highest-priority canon; the other three are also canons but ranked after this one in precedence when conflicts arise.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, when a certified professional discovers a conflict between two canons during the performance of their duties, which canon takes precedence?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are prioritized in order, with protecting society and the public good taking precedence over the other canons when conflicts arise. The remaining canons are important but are subordinate in priority to this first canon.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified security manager discovers that her employer is deliberately falsifying safety compliance reports in a way that endangers public welfare. Reporting this internally has been ineffective, and continuing to remain silent conflicts with her professional obligations. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which principle should guide her decision when organizational loyalty conflicts with other canons?","o":["Advancing the profession takes precedence over all other canons","Acting honorably and diligently for the employer outweighs public safety concerns","Protecting society, the common good, and public trust takes precedence over other canons, including obligations to the employer","The canons carry equal weight, so the professional may choose whichever action best protects her career"],"c":2,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are ordered by precedence, with protecting society, the common good, and public trust as the highest priority, superseding duties owed to an employer when they conflict. The other options misstate the canon order or improperly elevate employer loyalty or personal interest above public safety.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis determines that the Order Processing System has a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 8 hours. The disaster recovery plan for this system specifies a failover to a recovery site that, after testing, reliably completes in 10 hours. Which statement best describes this situation?","o":["The DR plan is compliant because RTO should always be shorter than RPO.","The DR plan is deficient because the tested recovery time exceeds the MTD, risking unacceptable business impact.","This situation is acceptable because MTD applies only to data loss, not downtime.","The DR plan is compliant as long as the RPO is less than 10 hours."],"c":1,"why":"The Recovery Time Objective (the tested 10-hour recovery) must be less than or equal to the MTD (8 hours) to avoid unacceptable business impact; here it is exceeded, indicating a plan deficiency. MTD relates to downtime tolerance (not RPO/data loss), and RPO is a separate metric unrelated to this gap.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company has developed a Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP) that focuses on restoring IT systems and data after a fire destroys the primary data center. Which of the following best distinguishes this DRP from the organization's Business Continuity Plan (BCP)?","o":["The DRP addresses long-term strategic risk management, while the BCP addresses only technical recovery","The DRP focuses narrowly on restoring IT infrastructure and systems, while the BCP addresses sustaining overall critical business operations","The BCP is only invoked after the DRP fails, functioning strictly as a backup plan","There is no meaningful distinction; the DRP and BCP are simply two names for the same plan"],"c":1,"why":"A DRP is a subset of business continuity planning focused specifically on restoring technology and data after a disruptive event, while the BCP takes a broader view covering all critical business functions, personnel, facilities, and processes needed to maintain operations. The other options mischaracterize the scope and relationship between the two plans.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization is selecting a cloud service provider to host regulated customer data and wants objective, independent assurance of the provider's control environment over an extended period rather than a single point in time. Which of the following provides the strongest such assurance?","o":["The vendor's self-attestation security questionnaire","A signed service level agreement (SLA) with uptime guarantees","A recent SOC 2 Type II report issued by an independent auditor","The vendor's published marketing security whitepaper"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report is produced by an independent auditor and evaluates the operating effectiveness of controls over a review period, providing strong, objective assurance. Self-attestations and marketing materials are not independently verified, and an SLA addresses performance commitments, not control effectiveness.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which element of the CIA triad is primarily violated when an unauthorized party successfully reads sensitive customer records without modifying them?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":0,"why":"Confidentiality protects data from unauthorized disclosure; since the data was read but not altered or made unavailable, integrity and availability remain intact. Non-repudiation is unrelated, as it concerns proof of actions, not disclosure.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"To reduce fraud risk in a financial system, an organization requires that no single systems administrator may both request and approve a change to production code. For especially sensitive wire transfer changes, it further requires that two authorized staff members must simultaneously act together to complete the change. Which concept specifically describes this second, simultaneous two-person requirement?","o":["Separation of duties","Two-person (dual) control","Job rotation","Least privilege"],"c":1,"why":"Two-person (dual) control requires two individuals to act together, simultaneously, to complete a single sensitive action, which matches the wire transfer requirement. Separation of duties (the first requirement) instead splits a process into sequential steps performed by different roles, not simultaneous joint action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization's security policy states that all employees must complete annual security awareness training. Which type of document is this policy an example of?","o":["A technical control","A procedure","A senior management directive establishing intent","A guideline"],"c":2,"why":"Policies are high-level statements of management intent that mandate behavior; procedures provide step-by-step instructions, guidelines are recommended (not mandatory) advice, and this is not a technical control since it involves human behavior, not a system mechanism.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"The board of directors states that the organization can financially withstand losses of up to $10 million annually without threatening solvency, but management has set an internal target that losses should not exceed $2 million annually to preserve investor confidence. Which terms respectively describe the $10 million and $2 million figures?","o":["Risk tolerance; risk appetite","Risk capacity; risk appetite","Inherent risk; residual risk","Risk appetite; risk capacity"],"c":1,"why":"Risk capacity is the objective maximum loss an organization can absorb before survival is threatened ($10M), while risk appetite is the more conservative amount of risk management chooses to accept in pursuit of objectives ($2M). The other pairings mislabel these terms or confuse them with inherent/residual risk, which relate to risk before and after controls.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company implements a rule requiring two employees to jointly approve any wire transfer above a set dollar threshold. This is an example of which security principle?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity"],"c":0,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by a single individual; least privilege limits access rights, defense in depth layers multiple controls, and security through obscurity relies on secrecy of design rather than shared approval.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A risk analyst is calculating the asset value of a customer relationship management (CRM) database for use in a quantitative risk assessment. The database was purchased and implemented five years ago for $150,000, and its current depreciated book value is $30,000. Which valuation approach most accurately reflects the asset's true value for risk analysis purposes?","o":["Use the original purchase price of $150,000 as the asset value.","Use the current depreciated book value of $30,000 as the asset value.","Use a comprehensive valuation including replacement/reconstruction cost, lost revenue, legal liability, and reputational impact resulting from loss of the asset.","Use the average of the purchase price and the book value."],"c":2,"why":"Asset valuation for risk analysis should reflect the true business impact of loss, including reconstruction cost, lost productivity/revenue, legal liability, and reputational harm—not merely accounting figures like purchase price or depreciated book value, which understate the asset's real value to the organization.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the concept of 'due diligence' in the context of organizational security governance?","o":["Taking corrective action after a security incident occurs","Implementing encryption on all sensitive data stores","Researching and understanding risks before making a decision","Continuously monitoring systems for anomalies"],"c":2,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed prior to acting, such as assessing risks before implementing a system; due care refers to the reasonable actions taken afterward, and the other options describe specific controls rather than the governance concept itself.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A software company has developed a proprietary algorithm that provides a significant competitive advantage. Leadership wants to protect the algorithm indefinitely without ever publicly disclosing its details, and is willing to accept that competitors who independently discover the same algorithm through legitimate reverse engineering cannot be sued. Which form of intellectual property protection aligns with these requirements?","o":["Patent, which protects for 20 years but requires public disclosure of the implementation.","Trade secret, whose protection can last indefinitely provided confidentiality measures are maintained, and which does not prevent independent discovery.","Copyright, which protects the expression of the algorithm in code but not the underlying idea.","Trademark, which protects brand identifiers rather than functional algorithms."],"c":1,"why":"Trade secret protection can last indefinitely as long as reasonable steps are taken to maintain confidentiality, and it does not prevent others from independently discovering or reverse-engineering the same information. Patents require disclosure and expire after a set term, while copyright and trademark protect different subject matter (expression and branding, respectively) rather than the algorithm's function.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution's core transaction database is valued at $2,000,000. A risk assessment determines that a successful ransomware attack would corrupt or destroy 25% of the data's value before backups could be restored, and historical incident data suggests such attacks occur, on average, once every two years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$250,000","$500,000","$1,000,000","$125,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value × Exposure Factor = $2,000,000 × 0.25 = $500,000. ARO = 1 occurrence per 2 years = 0.5. ALE = SLE × ARO = $500,000 × 0.5 = $250,000. The other options result from stopping at SLE, doubling instead of halving, or miscalculating the exposure factor's effect.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure its risk management practices align with a recognized international standard. Which of the following would it most likely adopt?","o":["ISO/IEC 27001","IEEE 802.1X","PCI DSS","OWASP Top Ten"],"c":0,"why":"ISO/IEC 27001 is an internationally recognized standard for establishing an information security management system (ISMS), including risk management. IEEE 802.1X is a network authentication protocol, PCI DSS is industry-specific for payment card data, and OWASP Top Ten addresses web application vulnerabilities, not overall risk management.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's legal counsel explains that regulators will evaluate the company's liability after a breach based on whether it exercised both 'due diligence' and 'due care.' Which statement most accurately distinguishes these two concepts as applied to information security management?","o":["Due diligence is the ongoing implementation of security controls, while due care is the initial research conducted before selecting controls.","Due diligence is the research and investigation conducted to understand risk prior to acting, while due care is the continual, reasonable application of safeguards based on that knowledge.","Due diligence applies only to technical controls, while due care applies only to administrative controls.","Due diligence and due care are legally interchangeable terms with no distinct meaning in security governance."],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the investigative process of understanding risk before acting (e.g., risk assessments), while due care refers to the ongoing reasonable actions taken based on that knowledge (e.g., implementing and maintaining controls). The other options reverse the definitions, wrongly limit scope, or falsely claim the terms are synonymous.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"During a risk assessment, a security analyst determines the annualized loss expectancy (ALE) for a specific threat. Which two values are multiplied to calculate ALE?","o":["Single loss expectancy (SLE) and annualized rate of occurrence (ARO)","Asset value and exposure factor","Threat likelihood and vulnerability severity","Total cost of controls and residual risk"],"c":0,"why":"ALE = SLE x ARO, where SLE itself equals asset value multiplied by exposure factor; the other combinations are either intermediate calculations or unrelated to the standard ALE formula.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"After a cost-benefit analysis, a company concludes that further reducing the likelihood of insider data theft through additional technical controls is not economically justified. Instead, it purchases a cyber liability insurance policy specifically covering losses from insider data theft incidents, while continuing normal operations without additional controls. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk avoidance","Risk acceptance"],"c":1,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of the risk to a third party, which defines risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing likelihood or impact through controls, avoidance would eliminate the risky activity entirely, and acceptance would involve taking no action at all (including no insurance) and simply absorbing potential losses.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of a Business Impact Analysis (BIA) in risk management?","o":["To identify and prioritize critical business functions and their recovery requirements","To calculate the exact monetary value of all corporate assets","To test the effectiveness of the disaster recovery plan","To determine which employees require background checks"],"c":0,"why":"A BIA identifies critical business processes, their interdependencies, and impact of disruption to prioritize recovery efforts; it is not primarily about asset valuation, testing DR plans, or personnel screening, which are separate activities.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A U.S.-based company stores personal data of EU residents in a cloud data center physically located in Ireland; the cloud provider's parent corporation is headquartered in the United States. An EU data protection authority opens an investigation under the GDPR. Which principle most directly determines whether GDPR's requirements apply to the U.S. company?","o":["The nationality of the company's incorporation determines GDPR applicability.","GDPR applies strictly based on the physical location of the servers, not the data subjects.","GDPR's extraterritorial scope applies because the company processes personal data of individuals located in the EU, regardless of where the company is headquartered.","Because the parent company is U.S.-based, U.S. law automatically preempts GDPR for this dataset."],"c":2,"why":"GDPR Article 3 establishes extraterritorial jurisdiction based on the processing of personal data belonging to EU data subjects, irrespective of the controller's or processor's location. Corporate nationality, server location alone, and assumptions of U.S. law preemption do not determine GDPR applicability.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An employee discovers a colleague violating the organization's code of ethics but chooses not to report it due to personal loyalty. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon is most directly being disregarded?","o":["Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Advance and protect the profession","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Provide diligent and competent service to principals"],"c":2,"why":"Failing to report unethical or illegal conduct conflicts with acting honorably, honestly, and legally, as covered by that canon; while other canons are related to professional conduct broadly, this scenario most directly involves personal integrity and legal/ethical responsibility in reporting wrongdoing.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"To prevent a single database administrator from being able to both create a new privileged account and assign elevated permissions to it without oversight, an organization requires that account creation and privilege assignment be performed by two different administrators. This control is best described as an example of:","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Need-to-know","Defense in depth"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical functions among multiple individuals so that no single person can complete a sensitive process alone, preventing fraud or abuse. Least privilege limits access rights to the minimum necessary for a role, need-to-know restricts access to specific information required for a task, and defense in depth layers multiple security controls—none of which describe splitting a single process between two people.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO wants an independent auditor's report that evaluates a cloud service provider's security, availability, and confidentiality controls, including testing of their operating effectiveness over a six-month period. Which report type should the CISO request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3"],"c":2,"why":"SOC 2 reports address the Trust Services Criteria (security, availability, confidentiality, etc.), and a Type II report tests control operating effectiveness over a period of time, unlike Type I which only assesses design at a single point in time. SOC 1 focuses on controls relevant to financial reporting, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report lacking the detailed testing information needed here.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP discovers that her employer is knowingly failing to comply with a legally mandated data breach notification requirement in order to avoid reputational damage. Reporting the violation to regulators may breach her confidentiality agreement with the employer, but remaining silent could result in continued harm to affected consumers. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons, which action is most appropriate when these obligations conflict?","o":["Remain silent to preserve confidentiality obligations to the employer, since loyalty to the employer is the highest ethical canon.","Resign immediately without reporting, since a CISSP can never disclose an employer's wrongdoing under any circumstance.","Report the violation through appropriate legal or regulatory channels, since protecting society and the public good takes precedence over duty to a specific employer when the canons conflict.","Consult only the employer's internal legal team and comply unconditionally with their decision, since employer instructions override all other canons."],"c":2,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics prioritizes 'Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure' above the canon requiring diligent service to employers, meaning public welfare takes precedence when the canons conflict. The other options improperly elevate employer loyalty or internal directives above the higher-order duty to protect society.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements encryption on all laptop hard drives to prevent unauthorized individuals from reading sensitive data if a laptop is lost or stolen. Which principle of the CIA triad does this control primarily support?","o":["Availability","Confidentiality","Integrity","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Encryption protects data from being disclosed to unauthorized parties, which is the definition of confidentiality. Availability relates to access when needed, integrity relates to data accuracy, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis for an e-commerce order-processing system determines the following: the system must be restored within 4 hours to avoid unacceptable financial loss, the organization can tolerate losing no more than 15 minutes of transaction data, and if the system remains unavailable for more than 8 hours the company will face regulatory sanctions and irreversible customer attrition. How should these values be correctly mapped to BCP/DR terminology?","o":["RTO = 15 minutes, RPO = 4 hours, MTD = 8 hours","RTO = 4 hours, RPO = 15 minutes, MTD = 8 hours","RPO = 8 hours, RTO = 15 minutes, MTD = 4 hours","MTD = 15 minutes, RTO = 8 hours, RPO = 4 hours"],"c":1,"why":"Recovery Time Objective (RTO) is the target time to restore the system (4 hours); Recovery Point Objective (RPO) is the maximum tolerable data loss measured in time (15 minutes); Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) is the absolute outer limit before severe business consequences occur (8 hours), and RTO must always be less than or equal to MTD. The other options mismatch these definitions and violate the required RTO ≤ MTD relationship.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company purchases cyber liability insurance to cover potential financial losses from a data breach instead of implementing additional technical controls. Which risk response strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing the risk directly, avoidance means eliminating the activity causing the risk, and acceptance means taking no action and absorbing the loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A financial services firm implements a control that generates a cryptographic hash of each transaction record and stores it separately from the record itself, allowing later verification that the record has not been altered. Which security principle does this control primarily support?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Hashing detects unauthorized modification of data, which directly supports integrity. It does not restrict who can view the data (confidentiality), ensure uptime (availability), and while related to non-repudiation, a simple hash without digital signing does not prove origin or prevent denial of the action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company's IT director hires an independent security assessor to evaluate the organization's network before a major cloud migration, documenting findings and following industry-standard assessment methodologies. This activity is BEST described as an example of:","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as assessing risk before migrating to the cloud. Due care refers to the ongoing, reasonable actions taken to maintain security after that decision; risk acceptance and separation of duties are unrelated concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A security manager reviews industry best practices and implements reasonable safeguards to protect company assets before any incident occurs. This ongoing, ordinary behavior of a prudent person is best described as an example of:","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Risk acceptance","Residual risk"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to the continuous, reasonable actions taken to protect assets, reflecting the standard of a prudent person. Due diligence is the research and investigation performed before making decisions, while risk acceptance and residual risk relate to risk management outcomes, not ongoing protective behavior.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following documents provides high-level, mandatory statements of management's intent regarding information security, from which more detailed documents are derived?","o":["Procedure","Guideline","Policy","Standard"],"c":2,"why":"A policy is a high-level, mandatory statement of management intent that sets overall direction. Standards provide specific mandatory requirements, procedures give step-by-step instructions, and guidelines offer recommended, non-mandatory advice.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A risk assessment determines that a server outage occurs on average once every 4 years and results in $200,000 in losses each time it occurs. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$50,000","$200,000","$800,000","$25,000"],"c":0,"why":"ALE = SLE x ARO. ARO = 1/4 = 0.25, and SLE = $200,000, so ALE = $200,000 x 0.25 = $50,000. The other answers misapply the formula or invert the ARO.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"In a data classification program, who is typically responsible for determining the classification level of a specific dataset and approving who may access it?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Security administrator","End user"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit manager) is accountable for classifying data and deciding access rights. The custodian implements technical controls on the owner's behalf, the security administrator manages access provisioning, and end users simply consume the data under approved permissions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization determines that the cost of mitigating a particular risk exceeds the potential loss from the risk occurring, and instead purchases a cyber-liability insurance policy to cover potential losses. This is an example of which risk treatment strategy?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which defines risk transfer. Risk avoidance means eliminating the activity causing the risk, mitigation means reducing likelihood or impact through controls, and acceptance means acknowledging the risk without further action, none of which match this scenario.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company's server hosting customer records is valued at $500,000. Historical data shows that a successful ransomware attack would destroy 40% of the data's value, and such attacks are expected to occur once every 5 years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$40,000","$100,000","$200,000","$500,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor = $500,000 x 0.40 = $200,000. ARO = 1/5 = 0.2. ALE = SLE x ARO = $200,000 x 0.2 = $40,000. The other options result from mis-multiplying or omitting one of the ARO/EF calculations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A new employee is given a document stating that all workstations must have full-disk encryption enabled, but the document does not specify which encryption product to use or how to configure it. What type of document has this employee most likely received?","o":["Standard","Policy","Procedure","Guideline"],"c":1,"why":"A policy states a high-level mandatory requirement (encryption must be enabled) without specifying implementation details. A standard would specify the exact product/algorithm, a procedure would give step-by-step configuration instructions, and a guideline would offer non-mandatory recommendations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires that the employee who initiates a wire transfer request cannot be the same employee who approves and releases the funds. This control is an example of:","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Mandatory vacation","Job rotation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties splits critical tasks between multiple people to prevent fraud or error by a single individual. Least privilege limits access to what's needed for a job, mandatory vacation forces time off to detect fraud, and job rotation moves employees between roles over time.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A legal system in which judicial decisions from prior cases establish binding precedent that must be followed in future similar cases is known as:","o":["Civil law system","Common law system","Administrative law system","Customary law system"],"c":1,"why":"Common law systems, such as those in the US and UK, rely heavily on judicial precedent (case law). Civil law systems rely primarily on codified statutes rather than precedent, administrative law governs government agency regulations, and customary law is based on long-standing societal traditions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During a Business Impact Analysis, a critical order-processing system is determined to have a maximum tolerable downtime of 8 hours before the organization suffers unacceptable losses. The DR team sets a target of restoring the system within 6 hours after a disruption. This 6-hour target is known as the:","o":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)"],"c":2,"why":"The RTO is the targeted duration for restoring a system after a disruption, and it should be less than or equal to the MTD, as shown here. RPO refers to acceptable data loss measured in time, MTBF measures average time between failures for reliability, and MTD is the absolute threshold, not the recovery target itself.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following best reflects a CISSP's obligation when they discover that a colleague is engaging in illegal or unethical conduct related to information security?","o":["Ignore the behavior unless it directly affects their own job duties","Report it through appropriate channels in accordance with the Code of Ethics canons","Confront the colleague privately and handle it without involving management","Wait until the annual performance review to mention the issue"],"c":1,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics obligates members to act honorably and protect society, requiring them to report unethical or illegal conduct through proper channels. Ignoring it, handling it informally, or delaying action all violate the duty to act promptly and responsibly.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISSP-certified professional discovers that a colleague at another organization is knowingly misrepresenting security assessment results to a client to secure a contract renewal. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the MOST appropriate action for the certified professional to take?","o":["Ignore it since it is not their organization or client","Report the conduct through appropriate channels, such as to (ISC)² or the affected client","Confront the colleague privately and take no further action regardless of outcome","Publicly post about the incident on social media to warn others"],"c":1,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics requires members to act honorably and report unethical or illegal conduct through proper channels, protecting the profession and the public. Ignoring the issue, handling it informally with no follow-up, or making unverified public accusations all violate ethical obligations to act responsibly and protect the community.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements encryption on its database to ensure that only authorized personnel can view sensitive customer records. Which principle of the CIA triad is primarily being addressed?","o":["Availability","Confidentiality","Integrity","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Confidentiality ensures information is disclosed only to authorized parties, which is exactly what encryption of sensitive data accomplishes; availability relates to access when needed, integrity relates to accuracy, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's primary data center houses a server valued at $500,000. A fire risk assessment determines that a fire event would destroy 40% of the asset's value (exposure factor), and historical data indicates such a fire occurs approximately once every 10 years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$20,000","$200,000","$50,000","$2,000"],"c":0,"why":"ALE = Single Loss Expectancy (AV x EF) x ARO = ($500,000 x 0.40) x 0.1 = $200,000 x 0.1 = $20,000. The other options miscalculate by omitting the ARO multiplication or using incorrect factors.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Prior to migrating sensitive customer data to a cloud service provider, a CISO commissions an independent third-party audit to verify the provider's security controls meet contractual and regulatory requirements. This action BEST exemplifies which concept?","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Negligence"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence is the research and verification performed before committing to an action, such as investigating a vendor's controls before signing a contract. Due care refers to the ongoing implementation of controls after a decision is made, and the other options do not describe a pre-decision investigative activity.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"To reduce the risk of fraudulent transactions in accounts payable, an organization requires that the employee who creates a new vendor record cannot also approve payments to that vendor. This control is an example of:","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides a sensitive process into multiple tasks performed by different individuals so no single person can complete a fraudulent transaction alone. Least privilege limits access rights generally, job rotation moves staff between roles over time, and mandatory vacation forces time off to surface fraud, none of which directly describe splitting a single transaction between two roles.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution's database server is valued at $2,000,000. A threat analysis determines that a successful attack would destroy 25% of the asset's value, and historical data indicates such an attack occurs once every five years. A proposed control costs $30,000 annually and would reduce the annualized rate of occurrence to once every twenty years. Based on a cost-benefit analysis, what is the net annual benefit of implementing this control?","o":["$100,000","$75,000","$45,000","$30,000"],"c":2,"why":"SLE = $2,000,000 x 0.25 = $500,000. Original ALE = $500,000 x 0.2 (1/5) = $100,000. New ALE = $500,000 x 0.05 (1/20) = $25,000. Savings = $100,000 - $25,000 = $75,000. Net benefit = $75,000 savings - $30,000 control cost = $45,000. The other values represent intermediate figures, not the true net benefit.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Which type of law is created by government agencies to enforce statutory requirements, such as rules issued by a national data protection authority governing how organizations must handle personal data?","o":["Criminal law","Civil law","Administrative law","Common law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative (regulatory) law consists of rules and regulations issued by government agencies to implement and enforce statutes. Criminal and civil law involve prosecutions and private disputes respectively, and common law is based on judicial precedent rather than agency rulemaking.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"Prior to signing a contract with a new cloud service provider, a security team reviews the provider's SOC 2 report, conducts an independent penetration test of the provider's environment, and interviews the provider's incident response staff. Which concept does this activity best illustrate?","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Risk transference","Residual risk acceptance"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as vetting a vendor before contracting. Due care refers to the ongoing, reasonable actions taken to maintain security after a decision is made, so it does not describe pre-contract investigation; the other options are unrelated risk treatment concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A newly hired CISO wants the security program to clearly demonstrate value to the board and align security investments with organizational priorities. Which action would BEST achieve this goal?","o":["Pursue ISO/IEC 27001 certification for the security department","Develop security metrics and KPIs that map directly to business risk appetite and strategic objectives","Increase the security budget to match industry benchmarks","Deploy the NIST Cybersecurity Framework across all business units"],"c":1,"why":"Effective governance requires linking security performance measures directly to business risk and objectives so leadership can evaluate value in business terms. Certification, framework adoption, and budget benchmarking may support the program but do not inherently demonstrate alignment with business priorities without meaningful, business-linked metrics.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified employee discovers evidence that a senior executive has been using corporate systems to conduct insider trading. The employee reports this to their manager, who instructs them to bury the findings to protect the executive and the company's reputation. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the MOST appropriate course of action?","o":["Comply with the manager's instructions because preserving employment allows the employee to continue protecting the organization long-term","Escalate the findings through internal legal/compliance channels, and report to appropriate external authorities if the matter is not properly addressed internally","Delete the evidence to avoid personal liability and organizational conflict","Anonymously disclose the findings to a media outlet to ensure public transparency"],"c":1,"why":"The Code of Ethics requires members to act legally, protect society, and avoid conduct that discredits the profession; this requires escalating illegal activity through proper channels rather than concealing it or bypassing lawful processes. Complying with the cover-up or leaking to media violates the duty to act legally and honorably.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During a Business Impact Analysis, a team determines that the order-processing system cannot be unavailable for more than 4 hours without causing unacceptable financial loss to the organization. This 4-hour figure represents which of the following?","o":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Mean Time to Repair (MTTR)"],"c":1,"why":"MTD represents the absolute maximum time a business function can be disrupted before causing unacceptable harm; RTO is a target restoration time set to be less than or equal to the MTD. RPO relates to acceptable data loss, and MTTR measures actual repair time, neither of which matches the described threshold.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator installs a patch on a critical server because the vendor issued a security advisory, and documents the testing and approval process before deployment. This action best exemplifies which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Risk acceptance","Segregation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to taking the reasonable, prudent actions expected to protect assets, such as applying a patch; due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed prior to acting, not the action itself.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A Business Impact Analysis establishes a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 8 hours for an order-processing system, with a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 4 hours and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 1 hour. During an actual outage, the system is restored in 6 hours using a backup that was 2 hours old. Which statement correctly evaluates this recovery?","o":["The RTO was met, but the RPO was exceeded","The RTO was exceeded, but the outage remained within MTD; the RPO was also exceeded","Both the RTO and RPO were met, and the incident falls within MTD","The MTD was exceeded, requiring formal disaster declaration"],"c":1,"why":"Recovery took 6 hours against a 4-hour RTO, exceeding it, while data loss of 2 hours exceeded the 1-hour RPO; however, since 6 hours is still under the 8-hour MTD, the business did not suffer catastrophic impact. The other options misstate one or more of the RTO, RPO, or MTD comparisons.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company determines that the cost of implementing a control exceeds the potential loss from a risk, and decides to purchase cyber insurance instead. Which risk response strategy is being used?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of the risk to a third party, which is risk transfer; mitigation would involve reducing the risk directly, avoidance would eliminate the activity causing the risk, and acceptance would mean taking no action at all.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISSP-certified professional discovers that a colleague is exploiting a known system vulnerability for personal financial gain. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, what is the CISSP's PRIMARY obligation in this situation?","o":["Take no action, as it is not their direct responsibility","Report the unethical conduct through appropriate organizational or professional channels","Publicly expose the colleague on social media to warn others","Resign immediately to avoid personal liability"],"c":1,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics requires members to act honorably and protect society, obligating them to report known unethical or illegal conduct through proper channels. Ignoring the issue, public exposure, or resigning without reporting all fail to uphold the professional responsibility to protect the infrastructure and the public.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants strong assurance that a cloud service provider's security controls have operated effectively over the past twelve months, rather than assurance that controls were merely suitably designed at a single point in time. Which document should the organization request?","o":["SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","Signed Service Level Agreement with security clauses","Vendor-completed self-assessment questionnaire"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of controls over an extended period (typically 6-12 months), while a Type I report only assesses design suitability at a specific point in time. SLAs and self-assessments do not provide independent, evidence-based assurance of control effectiveness over time.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization determines that the cost of implementing additional controls for a specific low-probability risk exceeds the potential financial impact of the risk itself. Management decides to continue operations without further controls and formally documents this decision. Which risk treatment strategy is being applied?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk avoidance","Risk acceptance"],"c":3,"why":"Risk acceptance occurs when an organization decides the cost of additional controls outweighs the potential loss and consciously chooses to retain the risk, with proper documentation. Mitigation involves reducing risk through controls, transfer shifts risk to a third party (e.g., insurance), and avoidance eliminates the activity causing the risk entirely.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An asset is valued at $200,000. A particular threat is expected to cause 25% damage to the asset each time it occurs, and the threat is expected to occur twice per year. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$50,000","$100,000","$25,000","$200,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor = $200,000 x 0.25 = $50,000; ALE = SLE x ARO = $50,000 x 2 = $100,000. The other values result from omitting either the exposure factor or the annual rate of occurrence.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A U.S.-based data processor handles personal data of EU residents and must transfer that data to servers located in the United States. Following the Schrems II ruling, which mechanism can the processor lawfully rely on to conduct this transfer, provided supplementary technical and organizational safeguards are implemented to address U.S. government surveillance risk?","o":["Relying solely on data subject consent for every transfer","Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs) supplemented with additional technical and organizational safeguards","Continued certification under the invalidated EU-U.S. Privacy Shield framework","Asserting that GDPR does not apply because the company has no physical EU offices"],"c":1,"why":"After Schrems II invalidated the Privacy Shield, SCCs remain a valid transfer mechanism but require supplementary measures (e.g., strong encryption, access controls) to mitigate risks from foreign surveillance laws. Consent alone is impractical for ongoing transfers, Privacy Shield is no longer valid, and GDPR applies extraterritorially based on processing EU residents' data regardless of physical presence.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following documents BEST describes a set of detailed, step-by-step instructions for configuring a firewall in accordance with an organization's security requirements?","o":["Policy","Standard","Procedure","Guideline"],"c":2,"why":"A procedure provides specific, sequential instructions for performing a task, such as configuring a firewall. A policy states high-level intent, a standard defines mandatory technical requirements (e.g., approved firewall settings), and a guideline offers recommended but non-mandatory advice.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires that the employee who initiates a wire transfer request cannot be the same employee who approves it. This control is an example of:","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by a single individual; least privilege limits access rights, job rotation moves employees between roles over time, and mandatory vacation forces time away to detect wrongdoing.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A board of directors defines the organization's risk appetite as \"moderate risk to achieve strategic growth objectives\" and sets a specific risk tolerance threshold stating that system downtime incidents up to 6 hours are acceptable without board notification, though incidents should still be logged and monitored. An incident occurs resulting in 5 hours of downtime. Which statement correctly reflects proper risk governance in this scenario?","o":["The incident exceeds the organization's risk appetite and requires immediate board notification","The incident falls within the defined risk tolerance and does not require board escalation, though it should be documented and monitored per policy","The incident represents a breach of risk tolerance requiring immediate board escalation","Risk appetite and risk tolerance are equivalent terms, so any incident must automatically be escalated to the board"],"c":1,"why":"Risk tolerance defines the acceptable variance around risk appetite for specific metrics; since 5 hours is within the defined 6-hour tolerance threshold, escalation is not required, though documentation and monitoring remain appropriate. The other options either misapply the tolerance threshold or incorrectly conflate risk appetite with risk tolerance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A multinational company processes personal data of European Union residents. Under GDPR, which of the following is a legal basis that would allow the company to process this data without obtaining explicit consent?","o":["The data is publicly available on social media","The company has a legitimate business interest that does not override the individual's rights","The company simply asserts internal policy allows it","The data subject is a customer of a competitor"],"c":1,"why":"GDPR recognizes several lawful bases for processing besides consent, including legitimate interest, provided it does not override the rights of the data subject; the other options are not recognized legal bases under GDPR.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm values a critical database server at $2,000,000. A specific threat is expected to cause 25% damage to the asset value each time it occurs, and historical data shows this threat materializes once every two years. Security engineering proposes a $180,000/year control that would reduce the frequency of occurrence to once every ten years but would not change the damage percentage. Based on annualized loss expectancy (ALE) analysis, what is the most defensible recommendation?","o":["Reject the control because the SLE remains $500,000 regardless of the control, making the investment irrelevant","Implement the control because it reduces ALE from $250,000 to $50,000, yielding a $200,000 reduction against an $180,000 cost, a net benefit of $20,000","Reject the control because its $180,000 cost exceeds the $50,000 post-control ALE, making it cost-prohibitive","Implement the control only if the exposure factor can also be reduced, since ARO reduction alone never justifies safeguard cost"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = $2M x 0.25 = $500,000; ALE before = $500,000 x 0.5 = $250,000; ALE after = $500,000 x 0.1 = $50,000. The risk reduction ($200,000) exceeds the control cost ($180,000), yielding a positive net benefit, so it should be implemented. The other options misapply the cost-benefit formula or introduce irrelevant conditions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best distinguishes a Business Continuity Plan (BCP) from a Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)?","o":["A BCP focuses narrowly on restoring IT systems, while a DRP addresses the survival of the entire business","A BCP addresses maintaining critical business operations during a disruption, while a DRP focuses on restoring IT systems and infrastructure after a disaster","A DRP is a subset of physical security planning unrelated to IT","A BCP and DRP are the same plan with different names used interchangeably"],"c":1,"why":"A BCP is the broader plan ensuring critical business functions continue during and after a disruption, while a DRP is a more technical subset focused specifically on recovering IT systems and data; the first option reverses these definitions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization discovered that a critical patch for a remotely exploitable vulnerability had been available for 18 months, was flagged in three separate vulnerability scan reports, and was never applied due to lack of change-control follow-up. A breach subsequently occurred through that exact vulnerability. From a legal liability perspective, which concept most accurately characterizes the organization's exposure?","o":["Strict liability, because the organization is automatically liable for any breach regardless of fault","Failure to exercise due care, since the organization did not act as a reasonably prudent entity would have upon learning of the risk","Failure to exercise due diligence, because the organization never investigated whether vulnerabilities existed","Vicarious liability, because the breach was caused by a third-party threat actor rather than an employee"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence is the research/investigation phase (which did occur via scanning); due care is the ongoing implementation of reasonable protective measures based on that knowledge. Failing to remediate a known, documented risk for 18 months is a due care failure, not a due diligence failure. Strict and vicarious liability are inapplicable legal doctrines here.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization values a critical database server at $500,000. A risk assessment determines that a specific threat, if realized, would destroy 20% of the asset's value, and this threat is expected to occur once every two years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$50,000","$100,000","$25,000","$10,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x EF = $500,000 x 0.20 = $100,000. ARO = 1/2 = 0.5. ALE = SLE x ARO = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. The other options result from misapplying the EF or ARO.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before signing a contract with a new cloud service provider, a company's security team investigates the provider's financial stability, security certifications, past breach history, and compliance posture. This activity best exemplifies which risk management concept?","o":["Due care","Risk avoidance","Due diligence","Residual risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed prior to making a decision, such as vetting a vendor before engagement. Due care refers to the ongoing, reasonable actions taken to maintain security after a relationship or system is established, not the pre-engagement investigation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO issues a document titled 'Acceptable Password Construction' that mandates minimum length, complexity, and rotation intervals for all systems enterprise-wide, with no exceptions permitted without formal risk acceptance. Which type of governance document does this best represent?","o":["Guideline, because it provides recommended best practices for password selection","Procedure, because it describes step-by-step instructions for setting a password","Standard, because it specifies mandatory, measurable requirements that support higher-level policy","Policy, because it establishes the organization's overall intent regarding authentication security"],"c":2,"why":"Standards are mandatory, specific, measurable requirements (e.g., minimum length/complexity) that implement the broader intent of a policy. A guideline is discretionary, a procedure is step-by-step instructions for performing a task, and a policy is a high-level statement of intent rather than specific technical requirements.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A manufacturing firm identifies a low-probability but high-impact risk of a fire destroying its primary data center. Rather than investing heavily in fire suppression upgrades, the firm purchases a comprehensive property and business interruption insurance policy. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk avoidance","Risk acceptance"],"c":1,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party (the insurer), which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing likelihood or impact directly, avoidance would mean eliminating the activity entirely, and acceptance would mean taking no action and absorbing the loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis determines the following for an order-processing application: Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) = 8 hours, Recovery Time Objective (RTO) = 10 hours, and Recovery Point Objective (RPO) = 4 hours. What is the most significant flaw in this continuity planning, and what must be corrected?","o":["The RPO is too aggressive relative to the MTD and should be lengthened to reduce backup frequency costs","The RTO exceeds the MTD, meaning the recovery strategy as designed would result in unacceptable business impact even if successfully executed; RTO must be reduced to at or below 8 hours","The RPO exceeds the RTO, which violates recovery sequencing logic and must be reversed","There is no flaw; RTO and RPO are independent of MTD and do not need to align"],"c":1,"why":"MTD represents the absolute ceiling for downtime the business can tolerate; RTO is the planned recovery time and must always be less than or equal to MTD. An RTO of 10 hours against an 8-hour MTD means the plan itself is inadequate, regardless of RPO. RPO relates to acceptable data loss and is a separate metric from RTO sequencing.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's information security program includes a document that states, 'All remote access connections must use multi-factor authentication and be encrypted using AES-256 or stronger.' This document is best classified as which type of governance artifact?","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, measurable, and specific requirements for implementing a policy, such as a required encryption algorithm. A policy would state the high-level intent (e.g., 'remote access must be secure'), a guideline offers recommended but not mandatory practices, and a procedure would provide step-by-step configuration instructions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified security manager discovers, during an audit, that a senior executive has been directing staff to falsify vulnerability scan results to pass a regulatory compliance audit. Reporting this internally would likely result in the manager's termination, but remaining silent would allow non-compliant, insecure systems to remain in production processing customer financial data. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics canon hierarchy, what is the correct course of action?","o":["Remain silent to preserve employment, since 'act honorably' to the employer takes precedence over other canons","Report the falsification through appropriate channels, since 'protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure' takes precedence over duties to the employer","Resign quietly without reporting, since canon conflicts should be resolved by removing oneself from the situation rather than taking action","Report the falsification only if legally mandated by breach notification law, since ethical canons are advisory and superseded by legal requirements"],"c":1,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are ranked in priority order, with protecting society and the public trust taking precedence over obligations to employers or the profession. Silent compliance or quiet resignation would allow ongoing harm to the public, and the canons are ethical obligations independent of whether a specific law compels disclosure.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A pharmaceutical company has developed a proprietary chemical process that gives it a competitive advantage. The company has no intention of ever publicly disclosing the formula and wants protection that can last indefinitely as long as secrecy is maintained. Which form of intellectual property protection is most appropriate?","o":["Patent","Copyright","Trademark","Trade secret"],"c":3,"why":"A trade secret protects confidential business information indefinitely, provided reasonable measures are taken to maintain its secrecy, and requires no public disclosure. A patent requires public disclosure and expires after a fixed term, while copyright and trademark protect different types of intellectual property (creative works and brand identifiers, respectively).","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During due diligence for a planned acquisition, the acquiring company's security team requests SOC 2 Type II reports, penetration test summaries, and a right-to-audit clause in the vendor contract for a target company's cloud-hosted customer data platform. What is the PRIMARY reason a right-to-audit clause is considered essential even after reviewing the SOC 2 report?","o":["SOC 2 Type II reports are self-attested and therefore carry no independent assurance value","A right-to-audit clause allows the acquiring company to verify controls at any point in time, whereas the SOC 2 report only attests to controls over a historical period that may not reflect current operations","Right-to-audit clauses are legally required under most data protection regulations regardless of other assurance mechanisms","SOC 2 reports only address availability and performance, never security controls, making independent audit rights necessary for security assurance"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report provides assurance over a defined historical period and specific control set as tested by the auditor; it does not guarantee current-state compliance or allow verification of controls outside that scope. A right-to-audit clause provides ongoing, on-demand verification capability. The other statements misrepresent SOC 2 reports' validity, legal mandates, and scope of coverage.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISSP-certified security manager discovers that a senior executive is directing staff to conceal a known product safety defect that could endanger public health, in order to protect quarterly earnings. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon should take precedence in guiding the security professional's response?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics lists canons in priority order, and 'Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure' takes precedence when it conflicts with other canons, such as loyalty to an employer. The other canons are valid but are subordinate when public safety is directly at risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A software company has developed a proprietary compression algorithm that provides a significant competitive advantage. The algorithm's internal logic is never exposed in the compiled binaries distributed to customers, and the company wants protection that could last indefinitely as long as secrecy is maintained, without requiring public disclosure of the algorithm's workings. Which form of intellectual property protection is most appropriate?","o":["Patent, because it provides the strongest 20-year exclusive right to the invention and prevents any independent reverse engineering","Trade secret, because it can protect the algorithm indefinitely without public disclosure, provided reasonable measures are taken to maintain secrecy","Copyright, because it automatically protects the underlying algorithmic logic upon creation of the compiled binary","Trademark, because it protects the algorithm's brand name and prevents competitors from using a similar name"],"c":1,"why":"Trade secrets can last indefinitely as long as reasonable protective measures (NDAs, access controls, etc.) are maintained and secrecy is preserved; patents require public disclosure and expire after a fixed term (generally 20 years), and would actually require revealing the algorithm. Copyright protects the specific expression/code, not the underlying algorithmic logic, and trademark protects branding, not functional processes.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which element of the CIA triad is primarily violated when an unauthorized party modifies financial records without detection?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Integrity ensures data accuracy and prevents unauthorized modification; confidentiality relates to disclosure and availability to access, neither of which is the primary concern here.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During a Business Impact Analysis, stakeholders determine that the order-processing system can be unavailable for up to 8 hours before the outage causes unacceptable harm to the business, and that no more than 2 hours of transaction data can be lost. Which two metrics have been established, respectively?","o":["MTD of 8 hours; RTO of 2 hours","RTO of 8 hours; RPO of 2 hours","RPO of 8 hours; RTO of 2 hours","MTBF of 8 hours; MTTR of 2 hours"],"c":1,"why":"Recovery Time Objective (RTO) defines the maximum acceptable downtime for a system (8 hours), while Recovery Point Objective (RPO) defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time (2 hours). MTD is a related but broader concept than RTO in this specific scenario, and MTBF/MTTR relate to failure and repair rates, not recovery targets.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization operating in a hurricane-prone region purchases business interruption insurance to cover revenue losses from data center outages caused by severe weather, in lieu of building a costly geographically redundant failover site. After this decision, which statement about the organization's risk posture is most accurate?","o":["The organization has eliminated the risk of hurricane-related downtime through risk avoidance","The organization has transferred the financial impact of the risk, but residual risk of operational downtime, customer impact, and reputational damage remains and is retained by the organization","The organization has fully mitigated the risk since insurance proceeds will restore the data center to full operational status immediately upon a claim","The organization has accepted the risk outright, since purchasing insurance is functionally equivalent to taking no action"],"c":1,"why":"Insurance is a risk transfer mechanism that shifts financial loss to a third party, but it does not prevent the outage itself or eliminate operational, customer-facing, or reputational consequences—these residual risks are retained by the organization. It is not avoidance (the activity/exposure still exists), not full mitigation (insurance doesn't restore operations), and not equivalent to pure acceptance (a deliberate transfer mechanism was actively purchased).","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization outsources its payroll processing to a third-party vendor. To ensure the vendor maintains adequate security controls throughout the multi-year contract rather than only at initial onboarding, which mechanism is most effective?","o":["Requiring the vendor to sign a one-time non-disclosure agreement","Including a right-to-audit clause and conducting periodic security assessments","Reviewing the vendor's SOC 2 report only during contract negotiation","Relying on the vendor's public reputation and marketing materials"],"c":1,"why":"A right-to-audit clause combined with periodic reassessment allows the organization to verify the vendor's security posture continuously throughout the relationship, addressing ongoing third-party risk. A one-time NDA or a single point-in-time report review does not provide assurance of continued compliance over the life of the contract, and reputation alone is not a verifiable control.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements a formal set of steps that management follows to demonstrate reasonable care in protecting company assets, based on industry standards. This best describes which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Risk acceptance","Residual risk"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to the ongoing actions taken to maintain a reasonable standard of protection; due diligence refers to the research/investigation done before taking action, which is not described here.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes a security policy?","o":["A detailed technical instruction for configuring a firewall","A high-level statement of management intent regarding security objectives","A step-by-step guide for incident response","A checklist used during a security audit"],"c":1,"why":"Policies are high-level, management-driven statements of intent; procedures and guidelines provide the detailed steps, and audits use checklists but that is not itself a policy.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's data center houses an asset valued at $2,000,000. A risk assessment determines the exposure factor for a specific fire scenario is 25%, and the annualized rate of occurrence is 0.5 (once every two years). A proposed fire-suppression system costs $150,000 annually and would reduce the annualized rate of occurrence to 0.1. Based on a cost-benefit analysis, what is the correct conclusion?","o":["The safeguard should be implemented; it produces a net annual benefit of $50,000.","The safeguard should be rejected; it produces a net annual loss of $100,000.","The safeguard should be implemented; it produces a net annual benefit of $200,000.","The safeguard should be rejected because the ALE before the control is less than the safeguard cost."],"c":0,"why":"SLE = $2M x 0.25 = $500,000. ALE before = $500,000 x 0.5 = $250,000; ALE after = $500,000 x 0.1 = $50,000. Risk reduction = $200,000, minus the $150,000 safeguard cost = $50,000 net benefit, so the control is justified. The other options miscalculate the ALE reduction or safeguard cost comparison.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company calculates that a particular threat could cause $50,000 in damage and is expected to occur twice per year. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$25,000","$50,000","$100,000","$150,000"],"c":2,"why":"ALE = Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) × Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) = $50,000 × 2 = $100,000; the other values reflect miscalculations of this formula.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company implemented firewalls and access controls three years ago based on industry best practices at the time. Since then, it has never reviewed logs, tested patches, or updated configurations despite significant changes in the threat landscape. Which legal/security concept has the organization most clearly failed to uphold?","o":["Due diligence, because it never investigated the original threat landscape before deployment.","Due care, because it failed to continue applying prudent, ongoing management of the controls.","Strict liability, because the firewalls were defective from installation.","Vicarious liability, because employees misused the firewall configuration."],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to the continuing responsibility to take reasonable, ongoing steps to maintain protection; failing to review and update controls over time is a due care failure. Due diligence concerns the research/investigation performed before a decision, which did occur initially; strict/vicarious liability are unrelated legal doctrines not applicable here.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the BEST example of a regulatory requirement rather than an industry standard?","o":["PCI DSS for payment card processing","ISO/IEC 27001 for information security management","GDPR for protection of personal data of EU residents","NIST SP 800-53 for federal information systems"],"c":2,"why":"GDPR is a legally binding regulation enacted by the EU government; PCI DSS and ISO 27001 are industry/contractual standards, and NIST SP 800-53 is a framework used primarily by U.S. federal agencies rather than a law with broad regulatory force outside government.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"According to widely accepted security governance principles (e.g., ISO/IEC 27014), which of the following best describes the appropriate role of the board of directors and senior executive management regarding information security?","o":["They should personally configure and test technical security controls to ensure compliance.","They are responsible for evaluating, directing, and monitoring security strategy, and are ultimately accountable for security outcomes.","They should delegate all accountability for security to the CISO once a security policy is approved.","They are only responsible for approving the annual security budget and have no accountability for outcomes."],"c":1,"why":"Governance frameworks assign the board/executive management the roles of evaluating strategy, directing security initiatives, and monitoring performance, while remaining ultimately accountable—accountability cannot be fully delegated. Technical implementation is an operational task, not a governance one, and budget approval alone does not fulfill governance accountability.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon takes precedence when conflicts arise among the four canons?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics explicitly states that canons are listed in order of precedence, with protecting society and the public good taking priority over the other three when conflicts occur.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization values a critical database server at $500,000. A risk assessment determines that a successful ransomware attack would destroy 20% of the asset's value, and such attacks are expected to occur once every two years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$50,000","$100,000","$25,000","$10,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = AV x EF = $500,000 x 0.20 = $100,000. ARO = 1/2 = 0.5. ALE = SLE x ARO = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. The other options misapply the EF or ARO calculation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A manufacturing firm identifies a risk that a rare but severe earthquake could destroy its only data center. The cost of building a fully redundant geographically separate data center far exceeds the value of the assets at risk, and earthquake insurance is unavailable in the region. The firm decides to implement enhanced physical safeguards and maintain a documented disaster recovery plan, while continuing normal operations. Which risk treatment strategy is being applied?","o":["Risk avoidance, since the firm chose not to build a redundant facility.","Risk transfer, since a DR plan shifts responsibility to a third party.","Risk mitigation, since safeguards and a DR plan reduce impact without eliminating the risk.","Risk rejection, since the firm ignored the risk assessment findings."],"c":2,"why":"Implementing safeguards and a recovery plan reduces the likelihood/impact of the risk without eliminating it or transferring it to another party, which is the definition of mitigation. Avoidance would mean ceasing the risky activity, transfer would require shifting risk (e.g., insurance) to a third party, and 'risk rejection' is not a valid formal treatment option and mischaracterizes the scenario.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is an example of a preventive administrative control?","o":["Security awareness training for employees","An intrusion detection system","A locked server room door","A backup power generator"],"c":0,"why":"Security awareness training is an administrative control designed to prevent security incidents by educating personnel; IDS is a detective technical control, locked doors are physical, and generators are physical/availability controls.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before signing a contract with a cloud service provider, a company's security team conducts an extensive review of the provider's audit reports, security certifications, and incident history. This activity best exemplifies which security principle?","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Separation of duties","Defense in depth"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence is the research and investigation performed prior to making a decision, such as vetting a vendor's security posture. Due care refers to the ongoing actions taken to maintain an acceptable level of protection after a decision is made, not the pre-decision research phase.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A critical order-processing system has a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 8 hours. The disaster recovery plan specifies a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 10 hours and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 2 hours. Which statement best describes the flaw in this plan?","o":["The RPO is too aggressive relative to the MTD and should be increased.","The RTO exceeds the MTD, meaning the recovery strategy will not meet business survivability requirements.","The plan is sound because RPO is less than MTD, which is the only requirement.","There is no flaw; RTO and RPO are independent of MTD and do not need to align."],"c":1,"why":"RTO must always be less than or equal to MTD; an RTO of 10 hours against an 8-hour MTD means the organization would suffer unacceptable damage before systems are restored. RPO relates to acceptable data loss, not the timing conflict causing the flaw, and RTO/RPO are not independent of MTD in a properly designed plan.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A risk manager decides that the cost of implementing additional controls for a low-probability, low-impact risk exceeds the potential loss, and chooses to take no further action. Which risk response strategy is being applied?","o":["Risk transfer","Risk mitigation","Risk acceptance","Risk avoidance"],"c":2,"why":"Risk acceptance involves acknowledging a risk and choosing not to invest further resources because the cost of mitigation outweighs the potential impact; transfer shifts risk to a third party, mitigation reduces risk, and avoidance eliminates the risk-causing activity entirely.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During due diligence for outsourcing payroll processing to a cloud service provider, the security team requests evidence of the provider's control environment covering security, availability, and confidentiality over a review period, along with the auditor's opinion on operating effectiveness. Which document should the team request?","o":["A SOC 1 Type I report","A SOC 2 Type II report","A PCI DSS Attestation of Compliance","A vendor-provided self-assessment questionnaire only"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the design and operating effectiveness of controls related to security, availability, processing integrity, confidentiality, and privacy over a period of time, matching the requirement. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, PCI DSS AoC is specific to payment card data, and a self-assessment lacks independent audit assurance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A software company has developed a proprietary algorithm that gives it a significant competitive advantage. The algorithm is not disclosed publicly, and the company implements strict access controls, NDAs, and confidentiality agreements to protect it indefinitely, rather than filing for a patent. Which form of intellectual property protection is the company relying on, and what is a key trade-off of this choice?","o":["Copyright protection; the trade-off is that copyright only protects the expression, not the underlying idea.","Patent protection; the trade-off is a fixed 20-year term after which the algorithm becomes public domain.","Trade secret protection; the trade-off is that protection is lost permanently if the information is independently discovered or improperly disclosed.","Trademark protection; the trade-off is that trademarks only protect brand identifiers, not functional processes."],"c":2,"why":"Trade secret protection can last indefinitely as long as secrecy is maintained through reasonable measures, but protection ends if the secret is disclosed or independently/legally discovered by others. Copyright and trademark do not protect functional algorithms, and choosing not to patent avoids the fixed term but forgoes patent's exclusive enforceable rights against independent invention.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company's information security document states: 'All employees must use passwords of at least 14 characters and enable multi-factor authentication on all remote access systems.' This document is best classified as which type of governance instrument?","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, measurable requirements (e.g., a specific password length or control implementation). A policy would state the high-level intent (e.g., 'protect account access'), a guideline offers recommended but non-mandatory advice, and a procedure provides step-by-step instructions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's information security policy states that all removable media must be encrypted. A department's documented procedure, however, instructs staff to encrypt removable media 'only when transporting media outside the building.' An internal audit flags this discrepancy. From a security governance perspective, what is the most accurate assessment?","o":["The procedure is acceptable because procedures may be more permissive than policy as long as they are documented.","The procedure is non-compliant because procedures must implement and align with, not contradict or weaken, the requirements set by policy.","The policy is invalid because standards and procedures take precedence over high-level policy statements.","There is no conflict because policies and procedures operate independently and do not need to be reconciled."],"c":1,"why":"Procedures are the lowest-level, most detailed documents in the policy hierarchy and must implement the mandatory requirements established by policy; they cannot weaken or contradict policy intent. Policies sit above standards and procedures in authority, and governance requires reconciliation across all documentation levels, not independence between them.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A government agency issues a binding regulation requiring all financial institutions to report data breaches within 72 hours. This regulation is an example of which category of law?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Customary law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law consists of rules and regulations created by government agencies to carry out legal mandates, and it carries the force of law. Criminal law addresses offenses against the state with penal consequences, civil law addresses disputes between private parties, and customary law is based on regional traditions and customs, none of which describe an agency-issued regulatory reporting requirement.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A data center housing critical servers has an asset value of $4,000,000. Flood modeling indicates that a flood event would destroy 30% of the asset's value, and historical records show that flooding of this severity occurs on average once every five years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$240,000","$1,200,000","$800,000","$6,000,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value × EF = $4,000,000 × 0.30 = $1,200,000. ARO = 1/5 = 0.2. ALE = SLE × ARO = $1,200,000 × 0.2 = $240,000. The other options either represent the SLE alone, omit the exposure factor, or incorrectly multiply instead of applying the annual rate of occurrence.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During business continuity planning, a team surveys department heads to determine which business functions are most critical, the financial and operational impact of their disruption, and the maximum tolerable downtime for each. This activity is known as a:","o":["Business Impact Analysis (BIA)","Vulnerability assessment","Risk treatment plan","Gap analysis"],"c":0,"why":"A BIA identifies critical business processes, quantifies the impact of their disruption, and establishes recovery priorities such as RTO and MTD. A vulnerability assessment identifies technical weaknesses, a risk treatment plan addresses how identified risks will be handled, and a gap analysis compares current state to a desired standard.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"After a thorough cost-benefit analysis, an organization determines that eliminating a specific cyber risk entirely would cost far more than the potential loss, and that reducing the risk further through additional controls has diminishing returns. The organization instead purchases a cyber-liability insurance policy to cover potential breach-related costs. Which risk response strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Risk transfer shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, such as through insurance, which is exactly what purchasing a policy accomplishes. Mitigation would involve reducing likelihood/impact via controls, avoidance means eliminating the activity causing the risk, and acceptance means retaining the risk without any additional action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, when two canons appear to conflict during a professional decision, which canon takes precedence over the others?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are intended to be applied in order of precedence, with protecting society and the public good listed first and taking priority when conflicts arise. The other canons are important but subordinate in cases of direct conflict.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO commissions an extensive, formal security and financial audit of a prospective SaaS vendor—reviewing their SOC 2 report, penetration test results, and incident history—before signing a multi-year contract. This activity is best characterized as an exercise of which legal concept?","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Duty of loyalty","Downstream liability"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as vetting a vendor prior to contracting. Due care refers to the ongoing, reasonable actions taken after a decision to maintain security; the other terms are unrelated legal concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A manufacturing firm purchases a cybersecurity liability insurance policy to help cover the financial losses associated with a potential data breach. This action represents which risk treatment strategy?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Risk avoidance eliminates the activity causing the risk, mitigation reduces the likelihood or impact through controls, and acceptance means acknowledging and retaining the risk without action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"The U.S. Department of Health and Human Services' Office for Civil Rights fines a hospital system $2 million for repeated HIPAA violations found during a compliance audit. No criminal charges are filed, and no private lawsuit is involved. This enforcement action falls under which category of law?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Common law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law encompasses regulations and enforcement actions by government agencies, such as HHS/OCR imposing civil monetary penalties for regulatory non-compliance. Criminal law requires prosecution for crimes, tort law involves private lawsuits between parties, and common law is based on judicial precedent rather than agency enforcement.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A risk analyst determines that a server hosting sensitive financial data is valued at $200,000. A successful attack is expected to destroy 25% of the asset's value, and historical data suggests such an attack occurs once every two years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$25,000","$50,000","$100,000","$12,500"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor = $200,000 x 0.25 = $50,000. ARO = 0.5 (once every 2 years). ALE = SLE x ARO = $50,000 x 0.5 = $25,000. The other options misapply the formula or use incorrect ARO/SLE values.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISO wants to adopt a framework primarily focused on aligning IT governance and management processes with overall business objectives, including defining control objectives for IT-related decision making. Which framework is the BEST fit for this goal?","o":["ISO/IEC 27001","NIST SP 800-53","COBIT","ITIL"],"c":2,"why":"COBIT (Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology) is specifically designed as an IT governance and management framework that aligns IT processes with business goals. ISO 27001 focuses on establishing an ISMS, NIST SP 800-53 provides a catalog of security controls, and ITIL focuses on IT service management rather than governance alignment.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's security program includes a document stating: 'All workstations must be configured with a minimum password length of 14 characters, multi-factor authentication enabled, and disk encryption using AES-256.' This document is best classified as which type of governance artifact?","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, measurable technical requirements that support policy objectives. A policy would state high-level intent (e.g., 'protect endpoints'), a guideline offers non-mandatory recommendations, and a procedure would give step-by-step configuration instructions rather than the requirements themselves.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis determines that a critical order-processing system has a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 8 hours. The disaster recovery plan sets a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 5 hours for restoring the system to operation. Based on this information, what is the Work Recovery Time (WRT) available for verifying data integrity and resuming full business functions after the system is restored?","o":["13 hours","5 hours","3 hours","8 hours"],"c":2,"why":"WRT = MTD − RTO = 8 hours − 5 hours = 3 hours, representing the time remaining after system restoration to complete verification and full business resumption before the MTD is exceeded. The other values misapply or sum the figures incorrectly.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A risk analysis determines that a single incident would cost $50,000 in damages (Single Loss Expectancy) and is expected to occur twice per year (Annualized Rate of Occurrence). What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$25,000","$50,000","$100,000","$150,000"],"c":2,"why":"ALE = SLE x ARO = $50,000 x 2 = $100,000. The other values result from incorrect application of the formula, such as dividing instead of multiplying or using the SLE alone.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company implements a formal, documented process to review and approve all vendor contracts before signing, ensuring reasonable steps are taken to protect organizational interests. This practice is best described as an example of which security principle?","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Defense in depth","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the ongoing, proactive research and investigation performed before making decisions (e.g., reviewing contracts). Due care refers to the actions taken to maintain a standard of protection once a risk is known. Defense in depth and separation of duties are unrelated control concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A financial services company is evaluating a cloud provider and needs assurance that the provider's security controls have been operating effectively over the preceding six-month period, not merely that they were properly designed at a single point in time. Which type of third-party assurance report should the company request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report tests the operating effectiveness of controls over an extended period (typically 6-12 months), directly addressing the requirement. SOC 2 Type I only assesses design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on controls relevant to financial reporting, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report lacking the detailed testing information needed for due diligence.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which document type provides mandatory, specific requirements that must be met to comply with an organization's security policy, such as requiring 14-character minimum passwords?","o":["Guideline","Procedure","Standard","Baseline"],"c":2,"why":"Standards are mandatory requirements that support policy implementation with specific, measurable criteria. Guidelines are recommended but not mandatory, procedures are step-by-step instructions, and baselines represent a minimum level of security configuration rather than a general requirement document.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization requires that the employee who codes a software change cannot also be the one who approves and deploys that change into production. This control is primarily intended to prevent which risk?","o":["Data remanence","Single point of failure","Fraud or unauthorized changes","Denial of service"],"c":2,"why":"Separation of duties ensures no single individual can both make and approve a change, reducing the risk of fraud, errors, or malicious code being introduced without oversight. The other options are unrelated to this specific control's purpose.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A software company has developed a proprietary machine-learning algorithm that gives it a significant competitive advantage. The company wants to protect the algorithm indefinitely and avoid publicly disclosing its inner workings. Which form of intellectual property protection is most appropriate?","o":["Patent","Trade secret","Copyright","Trademark"],"c":1,"why":"Trade secret protection can last indefinitely as long as reasonable measures are taken to maintain secrecy, and it does not require public disclosure. A patent requires public disclosure of the invention and expires after a fixed term (typically 20 years), while copyright protects expression rather than functional algorithms, and trademark protects brand identifiers, not proprietary processes.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"In data classification and handling, which role is primarily responsible for making decisions about classification level and access permissions for a specific dataset?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data processor","Security auditor"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit leader) has ultimate responsibility for classifying data and determining who may access it. The data custodian handles day-to-day technical maintenance, the data processor acts on behalf of the owner for processing purposes, and the security auditor independently verifies controls rather than setting them.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Under the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), a data controller experiences a breach that is likely to result in a risk to individuals' rights and freedoms. Within what timeframe must the controller notify the relevant supervisory authority, absent an approved exception?","o":["24 hours","48 hours","72 hours","30 days"],"c":2,"why":"GDPR Article 33 requires notification to the supervisory authority within 72 hours of becoming aware of the breach, unless the breach is unlikely to result in risk. The other timeframes are not the GDPR standard.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following best reflects a core canon that all certified professionals must uphold?","o":["Maximize organizational profit at all costs","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Always prioritize employer instructions over legal requirements","Avoid reporting security incidents to prevent reputational damage"],"c":1,"why":"One of the four canons of the (ISC)² Code of Ethics is to protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure. The other options directly contradict ethical obligations to act honorably, legally, and in the public interest.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During business continuity planning, a finance department determines that it can tolerate losing no more than 4 hours of transaction data in the event of a system failure. This requirement defines which metric?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, based on backup frequency. RTO measures how quickly a system must be restored, MTD is the total time a business can survive an outage, and MTBF measures reliability between failures.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A risk assessment team assigns numerical values to asset value, threat likelihood, and impact to calculate a specific monetary loss expectancy. This approach is an example of which type of risk analysis?","o":["Qualitative risk analysis","Quantitative risk analysis","Delphi technique","Heuristic analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Quantitative risk analysis uses numerical and monetary values to calculate measurable risk metrics like ALE. Qualitative analysis uses subjective ratings (e.g., high/medium/low), the Delphi technique is a consensus-building method often used within qualitative analysis, and heuristic analysis refers to experience-based problem solving, not formal risk calculation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"After a risk assessment, an organization decides to purchase cyber liability insurance to address the financial impact of a potential data breach rather than implementing additional technical controls. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Avoidance eliminates the activity causing risk, mitigation reduces likelihood/impact through controls, and acceptance means taking no action and absorbing the risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary difference between a Business Continuity Plan (BCP) and a Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)?","o":["BCP focuses only on IT systems recovery, while DRP focuses on overall business operations","BCP addresses maintaining critical business functions during a disruption, while DRP focuses specifically on restoring IT systems and infrastructure after a disaster","BCP and DRP are interchangeable terms with no meaningful difference","DRP is a subset of physical security planning unrelated to continuity efforts"],"c":1,"why":"BCP has a broader organizational scope aimed at sustaining essential business functions, while DRP is narrower and focuses on restoring technology systems and data after a disruptive event. The first option reverses the definitions, and the remaining options incorrectly claim no distinction or mischaracterize DRP's scope.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements a hashing algorithm to verify that a file has not been modified during transmission. Which principle of the CIA triad does this control primarily support?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Hashing detects unauthorized changes to data, which is the definition of integrity. Confidentiality concerns unauthorized disclosure, availability concerns access to resources, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company installs surveillance cameras and locks after learning that a competitor suffered a break-in, even though no incident has occurred at the company itself. This action best exemplifies which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Risk acceptance","Residual risk"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to taking reasonable, proactive steps to protect assets based on known risks; due diligence is the research/investigation phase that identifies the risk in the first place. Risk acceptance and residual risk do not describe taking protective action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A server has an asset value of $50,000. A particular threat has an exposure factor of 20% and is expected to occur twice per year. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$10,000","$20,000","$25,000","$100,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor = $50,000 x 0.20 = $10,000. ALE = SLE x ARO = $10,000 x 2 = $20,000. The other values result from omitting or misapplying one of the factors.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following documents is typically mandatory, broad in scope, and approved by senior management to state the organization's overall intent regarding security?","o":["Procedure","Guideline","Policy","Baseline"],"c":2,"why":"A policy is a high-level, mandatory statement of management's intent and direction for security. Procedures are detailed step-by-step instructions, guidelines are recommended (not mandatory) practices, and baselines define minimum acceptable configurations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Under the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which term refers to an individual whose personal data is being collected or processed?","o":["Data controller","Data processor","Data subject","Data custodian"],"c":2,"why":"The data subject is the individual to whom the personal data relates. The data controller determines the purpose of processing, the data processor processes data on the controller's behalf, and data custodian is an internal role responsible for data handling, not the individual in GDPR terminology.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon is listed FIRST and takes precedence over the others when a conflict arises?","o":["Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Advance and protect the profession","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics explicitly states that if a conflict arises among the canons, the earlier canon takes precedence, and 'Protect society...' is listed first. The other canons are real but are subordinate in priority.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization determines that a particular server has an asset value of $500,000. A successful attack against the server would destroy 25% of its value (exposure factor), and security analysts estimate the attack is likely to succeed once every two years (ARO = 0.5). What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$62,500","$125,000","$250,000","$31,250"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x EF = $500,000 x 0.25 = $125,000. ALE = SLE x ARO = $125,000 x 0.5 = $62,500. The other options represent the SLE alone or arithmetic errors.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization's plan describes how it will continue to process payroll and customer orders during a prolonged facility outage, while a separate plan focuses on restoring the damaged data center's servers and network equipment. The second plan is best described as a:","o":["Business Continuity Plan (BCP)","Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)","Business Impact Analysis (BIA)","Incident Response Plan (IRP)"],"c":1,"why":"A DRP focuses on the technical recovery of IT infrastructure and systems after a disruptive event, whereas a BCP addresses continuing critical business operations overall. A BIA is an analysis process, not a recovery plan, and an IRP addresses handling security incidents, not disaster recovery.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before deploying a new cloud-based HR system, a CISO commissions an independent third-party assessment of the vendor's security controls, financial stability, and compliance history. After the vendor is selected, the CISO ensures ongoing patching, monitoring, and periodic re-assessment of the vendor relationship. Which pair of concepts best describes these two activities, respectively?","o":["Due diligence, then due care","Due care, then due diligence","Risk avoidance, then risk transfer","Gap analysis, then risk acceptance"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence is the research and investigation performed before making a decision (the pre-selection assessment); due care is the ongoing, reasonable maintenance of security after the decision. The other pairs mischaracterize the sequence or use unrelated risk terms.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Before contracting with a cloud service provider, an organization requires the vendor to sign an agreement guaranteeing 99.9% uptime and specifying penalties for failing to meet that target. This document is best known as a:","o":["Memorandum of Understanding (MOU)","Service Level Agreement (SLA)","Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)","Business Partnership Agreement (BPA)"],"c":1,"why":"An SLA formally defines measurable performance expectations, such as uptime guarantees, and remedies for non-compliance. An MOU expresses general intent without binding performance metrics, an NDA protects confidential information, and a BPA governs the broader business relationship rather than specific performance metrics.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which term from the CIA triad refers to ensuring that information is not disclosed to unauthorized individuals, entities, or processes?","o":["Integrity","Confidentiality","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Confidentiality is the property of preventing unauthorized disclosure of information. Integrity concerns unauthorized alteration, availability concerns access when needed, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A regulatory agency fines a company for violating workplace safety data-handling requirements. The agency's enforcement action does not require proof of criminal intent and uses a 'preponderance of the evidence' standard rather than 'beyond a reasonable doubt.' This enforcement action is best classified under which category of law?","o":["Administrative (regulatory) law","Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Common law"],"c":0,"why":"Administrative law involves regulations and enforcement by government agencies, typically using a lower burden of proof and not requiring intent. Criminal law requires proof beyond a reasonable doubt and intent; civil law involves private party disputes; common law is based on judicial precedent.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A security team is mapping their organization's incident handling capabilities to a widely recognized framework and wants to categorize activities into the functions of Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, and Recover. Which framework are they most likely using?","o":["ISO/IEC 27001","COBIT 2019","NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF)","ITIL v4"],"c":2,"why":"The NIST Cybersecurity Framework organizes cybersecurity activities into five core functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, and Recover. ISO 27001 focuses on ISMS requirements, COBIT is an IT governance framework, and ITIL addresses IT service management, none of which use this specific five-function structure.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's security documentation includes a high-level statement of management's intent to protect information assets, along with a separate mandatory document specifying that all passwords must be at least 14 characters and changed every 90 days. Which type of document contains the specific, mandatory password requirement?","o":["Standard","Policy","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":0,"why":"A standard provides specific, mandatory technical requirements that support policy objectives. A policy is high-level and intent-based, a guideline is recommended but not mandatory, and a procedure gives step-by-step instructions rather than a single requirement value.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator installs a patch immediately after a vendor releases it, following the organization's documented patch management procedure. This action best demonstrates which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Risk acceptance","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to taking the reasonable, prudent actions expected in a given situation; applying a patch per procedure is an example of exercising due care. Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before taking action, not the action itself.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company is evaluating a cloud service provider that will store regulated customer data. To assess the provider's security posture without conducting an on-site audit, which of the following would provide the MOST reliable independent evidence of the provider's control environment?","o":["A SOC 2 Type II report from an independent auditor","The vendor's marketing security whitepaper","A signed non-disclosure agreement with the vendor","The vendor's internal self-assessment questionnaire"],"c":0,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report is produced by an independent auditor and evaluates the operating effectiveness of controls over a period of time, providing objective assurance. Marketing materials, NDAs, and self-assessments are not independently verified and offer far less assurance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization determines that a specific server has a 10% annual chance of a compromise costing $50,000 in losses. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$500","$5,000","$50,000","$500,000"],"c":1,"why":"ALE = Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) x Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) = $50,000 x 0.10 = $5,000. The other values result from miscalculating or omitting the probability factor.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes a 'standard' within an organization's security documentation hierarchy?","o":["A high-level statement of management intent regarding security","A mandatory, specific requirement that supports a policy","An optional recommendation for achieving a goal","A step-by-step set of instructions for performing a task"],"c":1,"why":"A standard is a mandatory, specific rule that supports the higher-level policy (e.g., 'passwords must be at least 14 characters'). Policies are high-level statements, guidelines are optional recommendations, and procedures are detailed instructions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISSP holder discovers that following a client's explicit instructions would require configuring a system in a way that creates a serious, unpatched vulnerability affecting public safety systems. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon should take precedence in resolving this conflict?","o":["Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Advance and protect the profession","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally"],"c":0,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are prioritized in order, with protecting society and public safety taking precedence over obligations to clients/employers when the two conflict. The other canons are still binding but are subordinate when a genuine conflict arises with public safety.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization owns a data processing asset valued at $500,000. A risk assessment determines that a specific threat has an exposure factor (EF) of 40% and an annualized rate of occurrence (ARO) of 0.5 (once every two years). A proposed safeguard costs $60,000 per year and would reduce the ARO to 0.1 (once every ten years) without changing the EF. Based on quantitative risk analysis, what is the most defensible business decision?","o":["Implement the safeguard, since it reduces annualized loss expectancy by $80,000 while costing only $60,000, yielding a net benefit of $20,000 per year.","Do not implement the safeguard, since the exposure factor remains unchanged and therefore the safeguard provides no measurable benefit.","Implement the safeguard, since any reduction in ARO automatically justifies the expenditure regardless of cost.","Do not implement the safeguard, since its annual cost of $60,000 exceeds the original single loss expectancy of $200,000."],"c":0,"why":"SLE = $500,000 x 0.4 = $200,000. Original ALE = $200,000 x 0.5 = $100,000. New ALE = $200,000 x 0.1 = $20,000. The ALE reduction is $80,000, and subtracting the $60,000 safeguard cost yields a $20,000 net annual benefit, making the safeguard cost-justified. The other options misapply the EF, misunderstand cost-benefit analysis, or make an irrelevant comparison to SLE.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A manufacturing firm identifies a risk that a rare, high-impact flood could damage its primary data center. The firm decides to purchase business interruption and property insurance to cover potential losses rather than relocating the facility or building redundant infrastructure. Which risk treatment strategy is the firm employing?","o":["Risk transfer","Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk acceptance"],"c":0,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of the risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Avoidance would mean eliminating the activity/location, mitigation would involve reducing likelihood or impact through controls, and acceptance means taking no action and absorbing the loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Ultimately, who is accountable for an organization's overall information security posture and risk decisions?","o":["The Chief Information Security Officer (CISO)","Senior management/executive leadership","The IT security team","External auditors"],"c":1,"why":"Senior management holds ultimate accountability for organizational risk, even though they delegate day-to-day responsibility to roles like the CISO. The CISO and security team execute the program, and auditors only assess it independently.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company commissioned a third-party risk assessment that identified several critical vulnerabilities in its network. Management reviewed the report but did not allocate budget or resources to remediate any of the findings. Six months later, an attacker exploited one of the identified vulnerabilities, causing a significant breach. From a legal liability standpoint, which concept best explains the organization's exposure?","o":["Failure of due diligence, because the organization did not adequately investigate its risk posture before the breach occurred.","Failure of due care, because the organization identified the risk through due diligence but failed to take reasonable action to mitigate it.","Vicarious liability, because the attacker's actions are legally imputed to the organization's management.","Negligent hiring, because the breach resulted from inadequate screening of IT personnel."],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence (the investigation/assessment) was performed properly; the failure was in due care—the ongoing, reasonable steps to act on known risks. Due diligence failure would apply if the assessment itself was inadequate, and vicarious liability and negligent hiring do not fit this fact pattern.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon is listed FIRST and takes precedence in guiding professional conduct?","o":["Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Advance and protect the profession","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The first and highest-priority canon of the (ISC)² Code of Ethics is to protect society, the common good, public trust, and infrastructure; the other canons follow in order but are subordinate to this one.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO is evaluating a cyber insurance policy as part of the organization's risk treatment strategy for a ransomware scenario. Which statement most accurately describes the role of cyber insurance in this context?","o":["Purchasing cyber insurance eliminates the need for technical safeguards, since the financial risk has been fully transferred to the insurer.","Cyber insurance fully indemnifies the organization against any regulatory fines or sanctions resulting from a breach.","Cyber insurance transfers certain financial losses to a third party but does not eliminate the organization's legal, regulatory, or reputational obligations.","Insurance premiums are determined solely by asset value and are unaffected by the organization's existing security controls."],"c":2,"why":"Risk transfer via insurance addresses financial impact but does not remove legal/regulatory duties (e.g., breach notification, fines in many jurisdictions) or reputational harm, and underwriters typically price premiums based partly on security posture. The other options overstate what insurance accomplishes.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A former employee sues a company for wrongful termination, seeking monetary damages. This dispute would most likely be handled under which category of law?","o":["Criminal law","Civil law","Administrative law","Constitutional law"],"c":1,"why":"Civil law addresses disputes between private parties, typically resulting in monetary damages rather than imprisonment. Criminal law involves the state prosecuting offenses against society, and administrative law involves regulatory agency enforcement.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A corporate security document states, \"All employee passwords must be a minimum of 14 characters, as mandated by the Information Security Policy.\" A separate document states, \"Employees are encouraged to consider using a password manager to generate complex, unique passphrases.\" These two documents are best classified, respectively, as which types of governance artifacts?","o":["Standard; Guideline","Procedure; Baseline","Policy; Standard","Baseline; Procedure"],"c":0,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, measurable requirements (e.g., minimum password length), while a guideline offers recommended, discretionary practices. Policies are high-level statements of intent, procedures are step-by-step instructions, and baselines define minimum configuration states—none of which match these two document descriptions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of conducting a Business Impact Analysis (BIA) during business continuity planning?","o":["To identify and prioritize critical business functions and the impact of their disruption","To develop detailed technical recovery procedures for IT systems","To test the organization's disaster recovery plan through a live simulation","To calculate the annual insurance premium for business interruption coverage"],"c":0,"why":"A BIA identifies critical business functions, dependencies, and quantifies the impact of disruptions to prioritize recovery efforts. Technical recovery procedures come later in DRP development, and testing/insurance calculations are separate activities.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's business impact analysis determines that the maximum tolerable downtime (MTD) for its order-processing system is 8 hours. The disaster recovery plan specifies a recovery time objective (RTO) of 5 hours to restore system functionality, followed by a work recovery time (WRT) of 2 hours to validate data integrity and resume normal operations. Which statement correctly evaluates this recovery plan?","o":["The plan meets requirements because the combined RTO and WRT (7 hours) fall within the 8-hour MTD.","The plan fails because the recovery point objective (RPO) must always be numerically greater than the RTO.","The plan fails because WRT should never be factored into MTD calculations.","The plan meets requirements only if the RPO is reduced to zero."],"c":0,"why":"MTD represents the total time available for both technical restoration (RTO) and operational validation (WRT); since RTO + WRT = 7 hours, which is less than the 8-hour MTD, the plan is acceptable. RPO relates to data loss tolerance, not sequencing with RTO, and WRT is properly included in MTD calculations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A U.S.-based company with no physical offices, employees, or servers in the European Union operates a website that markets subscription services directly to EU residents and tracks their online behavior for targeted advertising. Which statement correctly describes the applicability of the GDPR to this company?","o":["GDPR does not apply because the company has no physical presence within the EU.","GDPR applies because the company offers goods or services to, and monitors the behavior of, EU data subjects, regardless of the company's physical location.","GDPR applies only if the company stores personal data on servers physically located within EU territory.","GDPR applies only to companies employing more than 250 people, per the regulation's small-business exemption."],"c":1,"why":"GDPR's extraterritorial scope (Article 3) applies to organizations that offer goods/services to or monitor EU data subjects, irrespective of the organization's location or where data is stored. Physical presence, server location, and employee count are not the determining factors.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's data center faces a threat with a single loss expectancy (SLE) of $200,000 and an annualized rate of occurrence (ARO) of 0.25. A proposed safeguard costing $30,000 per year would reduce the ARO to 0.05. Based on quantitative risk analysis, what is the annual value of implementing this safeguard?","o":["$10,000","$40,000","$20,000","$50,000"],"c":0,"why":"ALE before = $200,000 x 0.25 = $50,000; ALE after = $200,000 x 0.05 = $10,000; reduction = $40,000; value of safeguard = $40,000 - $30,000 cost = $10,000. The distractors result from omitting the safeguard cost or miscalculating the ALE difference.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified security manager is instructed by senior leadership to conceal a known critical vulnerability in a power grid control system from regulators in order to avoid a costly compliance audit and potential business disruption. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon should take precedence in resolving this ethical conflict?","o":["Advance and protect the profession.","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally.","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure.","Provide diligent and competent service to principals."],"c":2,"why":"The (ISC)² canons are prioritized in order, with protecting society and infrastructure as the highest obligation, superseding duties to employer instructions or professional advancement, especially where public safety (critical infrastructure) is at risk. The other canons are subordinate when conflicts arise.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A financial firm's internal audit revealed that management had commissioned and received a comprehensive third-party risk assessment identifying multiple critical vulnerabilities eighteen months ago, but no remediation actions were taken due to budget constraints. A breach subsequently occurred through one of the identified vulnerabilities. From a legal liability perspective, what is the MOST significant deficiency demonstrated by this scenario?","o":["Failure to exercise due diligence in identifying risk","Failure to exercise due care in acting upon known risk","Failure to maintain separation of duties","Failure to obtain adequate cyber insurance coverage"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence (investigating and identifying the risk) was performed via the assessment; the negligence lies in failing to exercise due care by acting reasonably on those known findings. The other options are unrelated to the facts presented.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During a third-party risk assessment, a security team discovers that the organization relies solely on a critical SaaS vendor's SOC 2 Type II report, dated 14 months prior, as its only evidence of control effectiveness, with no additional monitoring or reassessment performed since. What is the most significant gap in this vendor risk management approach?","o":["SOC 2 Type II reports are entirely self-attested by the vendor and provide no independent assurance value whatsoever.","The report's age means it may no longer reflect current control effectiveness, and reliance on a single point-in-time assessment without ongoing monitoring is insufficient for continuous risk management.","SOC 2 reports exclusively address financial reporting controls and have no relevance to information security risk.","SOC 2 Type II reports cannot legally be used to satisfy any vendor due diligence requirement."],"c":1,"why":"SOC 2 Type II reports assess control operation over a defined period but become stale over time; effective third-party risk management requires continuous monitoring or periodic reassessment rather than relying indefinitely on an aging report. The other statements mischaracterize SOC 2 reports, which are independently audited and directly relevant to security controls.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During a Business Impact Analysis, a critical order-processing application is assigned a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 8 hours. The recovery team determines that technical recovery (RTO) can realistically be achieved in 10 hours, though data can be restored to within 2 hours of loss (RPO). Which statement correctly reflects the risk this creates?","o":["The RPO exceeds the MTD, creating unacceptable data loss risk","The RTO exceeds the MTD, meaning the recovery plan will not meet business survivability requirements","The WRT is irrelevant since RPO is within acceptable limits","No risk exists because RTO and RPO are independent of MTD"],"c":1,"why":"RTO must be less than or equal to MTD for the business to survive the outage; here RTO (10h) exceeds MTD (8h), so recovery capability is inadequate even though RPO is acceptable. The other statements misstate the relationship between these metrics.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's data center houses a critical database server valued at $500,000. A risk assessment determines that a flood has a 20% chance of occurring in any given year and would cause 40% damage to the asset if it occurred. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$40,000","$100,000","$200,000","$500,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor = $500,000 x 0.40 = $200,000. ALE = SLE x ARO = $200,000 x 0.20 = $40,000. The other options miscalculate by omitting the ARO or EF multiplication correctly.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A US-based multinational plans to transfer EU customers' personal data to a processing center in a country lacking an EU adequacy decision. Which mechanism would provide the LEGALLY appropriate basis for this transfer under GDPR?","o":["Obtaining verbal consent from data subjects","Implementing Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs) approved by the European Commission","Relying solely on the company's internal privacy policy","Anonymizing IP addresses before transfer"],"c":1,"why":"SCCs are a European Commission-approved legal mechanism specifically designed to enable lawful transfers to countries without an adequacy decision. Verbal consent is insufficient under GDPR's documentation requirements, internal policy has no legal standing with regulators, and partial anonymization does not address the underlying transfer of identifiable personal data.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified engineer discovers that deploying an emergency patch requested by senior management would violate a contractual non-disclosure agreement with a competing client, but delaying the patch increases immediate risk to public safety systems. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon should guide the engineer's decision-making priority in this conflict?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Provide diligent and competent service to principals"],"c":2,"why":"The (ISC)² canons are ordered by priority, and protecting society and public safety takes precedence over obligations to employers, clients, or the profession when these interests conflict.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements redundant power supplies, clustered servers, and load-balanced network links to ensure that its e-commerce site remains operational during hardware failures. Which principle of the CIA triad is being directly addressed by these controls?","o":["Confidentiality","Integrity","Availability","Non-repudiation"],"c":2,"why":"Redundancy and fault tolerance measures are designed to keep systems accessible and operational, which is the definition of availability. Confidentiality and integrity relate to protecting data from disclosure or unauthorized alteration, not uptime, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company wants to manage the financial risk of potential downtime in a cloud-hosted service without altering its own operational risk posture. Which risk treatment approach BEST accomplishes this?","o":["Implementing additional internal redundancy controls","Purchasing cyber liability insurance covering business interruption losses","Accepting the risk and documenting it in the risk register","Conducting more frequent vulnerability scans"],"c":1,"why":"Insurance transfers the financial impact of a risk to a third party without changing the likelihood or technical exposure. The other options represent mitigation (redundancy, scanning) or acceptance, not transfer of financial impact.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An accounts payable process requires that the employee who creates a new vendor record cannot also be the one who approves invoice payments to that vendor. This control is an example of:","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Need-to-know","Job rotation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical, incompatible functions among different individuals to prevent fraud or error. Least privilege limits access scope, need-to-know restricts information exposure, and job rotation periodically changes roles rather than permanently dividing duties.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO is evaluating a cloud service provider's security posture for a critical outsourced function. Which document would provide the MOST reliable evidence of the provider's control effectiveness over an extended period of time?","o":["SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 1 Type I report","A vendor-provided security questionnaire"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report assesses the operating effectiveness of security-related controls over an extended review period (typically 6-12 months), whereas Type I only evaluates control design at a single point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and self-reported questionnaires lack independent verification.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A security manager researches industry best practices, consults legal counsel, and implements reasonable safeguards before a new system goes live. This behavior best exemplifies which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Separation of duties","Least privilege","Risk acceptance"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence involves researching and understanding risks before acting, such as investigating best practices and legal requirements prior to deployment. Separation of duties and least privilege are access control concepts, and risk acceptance is a risk response strategy, not a research/preparation activity.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"In quantitative risk analysis, which formula is used to calculate Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["ALE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor","ALE = Single Loss Expectancy x Annualized Rate of Occurrence","ALE = Threat x Vulnerability x Impact","ALE = Annualized Rate of Occurrence / Single Loss Expectancy"],"c":1,"why":"ALE is correctly calculated by multiplying the Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) by the Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO). The other formulas either describe SLE calculation (Asset Value x Exposure Factor) or misrepresent the relationship between the variables.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company's information security program includes a document stating 'All employees must complete security awareness training annually,' and a separate document detailing 'Training must be completed via the LMS portal, with quiz scores of 80% or higher, within 30 days of the anniversary hire date.' What best describes these two documents, respectively?","o":["Standard, then guideline","Policy, then procedure","Procedure, then policy","Guideline, then standard"],"c":1,"why":"A policy states high-level mandatory requirements (what must be done), while a procedure provides detailed step-by-step instructions on how to accomplish it. Standards specify mandatory, measurable requirements (like specific technologies), and guidelines are recommended but not mandatory, neither of which fits these examples as precisely.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company is sued by a former customer for breach of contract after a service outage caused financial loss. Which category of law governs this type of dispute?","o":["Criminal law","Civil law","Administrative law","Constitutional law"],"c":1,"why":"Civil law governs disputes between private parties, such as breach of contract claims, where the remedy is typically monetary damages. Criminal law involves government prosecution of offenses against society, administrative law involves regulatory agency rules, and constitutional law concerns governmental powers and rights.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"After completing a risk assessment, a company decides to purchase cyber liability insurance to cover potential losses from a data breach rather than implementing additional technical controls. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is risk transfer. Risk mitigation involves reducing likelihood or impact through controls, risk avoidance eliminates the activity causing the risk entirely, and risk acceptance means taking no action and absorbing the potential loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, if a CISSP discovers that a colleague is engaging in an activity that violates the Code, what is the professional's PRIMARY ethical obligation?","o":["Immediately notify law enforcement regardless of the situation","Ignore the issue unless it directly affects their own job duties","Take appropriate action, which may include reporting the violation through proper channels","Confront the colleague publicly to ensure accountability"],"c":2,"why":"The Code of Ethics requires CISSPs to act honorably and take appropriate action when they become aware of violations, which typically means reporting through proper organizational or (ISC)² channels rather than ignoring it, involving law enforcement prematurely, or handling it unprofessionally through public confrontation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Within a security policy framework, which document provides mandatory, specific technical requirements that must be met, such as requiring AES-256 encryption for all stored sensitive data?","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, specific requirements (like a particular encryption algorithm) that support the broader intent of a policy. Policies are high-level statements of intent, guidelines are recommended but not mandatory, and procedures are step-by-step instructions for performing tasks.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution requires that the employee who initiates a wire transfer request cannot be the same employee who approves and releases the transfer. This control is an example of which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Need to know"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by a single individual. Least privilege limits access rights to only what's necessary for a job function, defense in depth layers multiple controls, and need to know restricts information access based on necessity, none of which specifically address dividing transaction responsibilities.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A quantitative risk assessment determines that a data center asset is valued at $500,000. The exposure factor for a specific flood scenario is 40%, and the annualized rate of occurrence is 0.2 (once every five years). What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$10,000","$40,000","$100,000","$200,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = AV x EF = $500,000 x 0.40 = $200,000. ALE = SLE x ARO = $200,000 x 0.2 = $40,000. The other values result from omitting or mis-multiplying one of the factors.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"After identifying a risk, an organization decides to purchase cyber insurance to cover potential financial losses from a data breach rather than implementing additional security controls. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation involves reducing risk through controls, avoidance means eliminating the activity causing the risk, and acceptance means acknowledging the risk without further action or transfer.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company's business continuity plan specifies that its e-commerce platform must be restored within 4 hours of an outage, and that no more than 15 minutes of transaction data can be lost. These two metrics respectively represent which BCP/DRP concepts?","o":["MTD and RTO","RTO and RPO","RPO and RTO","WRT and MTD"],"c":1,"why":"Recovery Time Objective (RTO) is the maximum acceptable time to restore a system after an outage (4 hours), while Recovery Point Objective (RPO) defines the maximum acceptable data loss measured in time (15 minutes). MTD is the total tolerable downtime before severe organizational harm, and WRT is the work recovery time after systems are restored.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following is a foundational canon that CISSP-certified professionals must uphold?","o":["Maximize profit for the employer at all times","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Always prioritize confidentiality over availability","Report all security incidents directly to law enforcement"],"c":1,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics explicitly includes protecting society, the common good, and public trust as a foundational canon. Maximizing profit is not an ethical canon, prioritizing confidentiality over availability is not a fixed rule, and reporting requirements depend on organizational policy and legal context, not a blanket ethical canon.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISO commissions a third-party audit and reviews industry threat intelligence before selecting a new cloud provider. After signing the contract, the CISO continues to monitor the provider's performance and enforces contractual SLAs on an ongoing basis. Which two concepts are respectively demonstrated by the pre-contract research and the ongoing monitoring?","o":["Due diligence, then due care","Due care, then due diligence","Risk acceptance, then risk transfer","Risk avoidance, then risk mitigation"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence is the research and investigation performed before making a decision; due care is the continued, reasonable actions taken afterward to maintain protection. The other pairs describe unrelated risk treatment strategies, not this before/after distinction.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During a vendor risk assessment, a security team discovers that a critical third-party cloud provider does not maintain any independent security certifications or audit reports and is unwilling to allow an on-site assessment. What should the security team recommend as the MOST appropriate NEXT step?","o":["Immediately terminate the vendor relationship without further analysis","Require contractual right-to-audit clauses and request alternative assurance evidence such as a SOC 2 report","Accept the risk since switching vendors is costly and time-consuming","Proceed with the contract but avoid documenting the risk"],"c":1,"why":"The most balanced and defensible action is to negotiate contractual protections and seek alternative assurance mechanisms (like SOC 2 reports) before making a final decision, ensuring due diligence. Immediate termination is premature without further analysis, blind acceptance ignores identified risk, and failing to document risk violates sound risk management practice.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Senior management wants the information security program to directly support and be measured against the organization's strategic business objectives, with security decisions reviewed by an executive steering committee. This best describes which concept?","o":["Security governance","Security control assessment","Configuration management","Segregation of duties"],"c":0,"why":"Security governance is the framework of oversight, accountability, and alignment between security activities and business strategy, typically involving executive committees. The other options are operational or technical controls, not strategic alignment mechanisms.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A manufacturing company is fined by a government regulatory agency for failing to meet workplace safety reporting requirements, without any criminal charges being filed. This enforcement action falls under which category of law?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Customary law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law consists of rules and enforcement actions created by government regulatory agencies, such as fines for non-compliance with reporting requirements. Criminal law involves prosecution for crimes, civil law involves private party lawsuits, and customary law is based on regional traditions, none of which match this scenario.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company implements encryption on its database backups to ensure that only authorized personnel can read the data even if the backup media is stolen. Which principle of the CIA triad does this control primarily support?","o":["Confidentiality","Availability","Integrity","Non-repudiation"],"c":0,"why":"Encryption protects data from unauthorized disclosure, which is the definition of confidentiality. Availability concerns access when needed, integrity concerns unauthorized alteration, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A security manager reviews vendor security certifications and conducts background research before signing a contract with a cloud provider. This activity best exemplifies which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Separation of duties","Risk acceptance"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence is the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as vetting a vendor. Due care refers to the ongoing actions taken to maintain a reasonable standard of protection after a decision is made.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During BCP planning, the business impact analysis identifies that the order-processing system can tolerate a maximum of 4 hours of downtime, and that no more than 30 minutes of transaction data can be lost. The 30-minute figure represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Work Recovery Time (WRT)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, dictating backup frequency. RTO and MTD relate to acceptable downtime duration, and WRT is the time needed to reconfigure systems after recovery, not data loss tolerance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization determines that a critical server fails on average twice per year, and each failure results in $10,000 of lost productivity. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$20,000","$10,000","$5,000","$2,000"],"c":0,"why":"ALE = Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) x Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) = $10,000 x 2 = $20,000. The other values do not correctly apply this formula.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's information security handbook states, at a high level and with mandatory compliance, that 'all employees must protect confidential information from unauthorized disclosure.' Specific technical instructions for encrypting laptop hard drives are found in a separate, more detailed document. What are these two documents most accurately called, respectively?","o":["Guideline and standard","Policy and procedure","Standard and guideline","Procedure and policy"],"c":1,"why":"A policy is a high-level, mandatory statement of management intent, while a procedure provides detailed, step-by-step instructions for implementation. Standards specify mandatory technical requirements (not step-by-step instructions), and guidelines are recommended but not mandatory, so neither pairing fits as precisely.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes a security 'standard' within an organization's policy framework?","o":["A mandatory, specific requirement that supports and enforces the organization's security policy","A high-level statement of management intent regarding security objectives","A recommended but optional best practice for achieving security goals","A step-by-step set of instructions for performing a specific security task"],"c":0,"why":"Standards are mandatory, specific requirements that support policy. Policies are high-level intent statements, guidelines are optional recommendations, and procedures are detailed step-by-step instructions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before onboarding a new SaaS vendor that will process sensitive customer data, the security team requests the vendor's SOC 2 Type II report, reviews the vendor's incident response history, and negotiates a right-to-audit clause into the contract. This activity is best classified as part of which risk management process?","o":["Risk mitigation through technical controls","Third-party (vendor) risk management","Business continuity planning","Security awareness training"],"c":1,"why":"Reviewing vendor security posture, audit reports, and contractual clauses before and during a business relationship is core to third-party/vendor risk management. The other options involve internal controls, continuity planning, or training, which are unrelated to evaluating an external party's risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following is a canon that all certified professionals must uphold?","o":["Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Maximize shareholder value in all security decisions","Always choose the lowest-cost security solution available","Report only security incidents that are legally required to be disclosed"],"c":0,"why":"This is one of the four canons of the (ISC)² Code of Ethics. The other options are not part of the code and may even conflict with professional ethical obligations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An (ISC)² certified professional discovers that a colleague is quietly exploiting a known vulnerability for personal financial gain rather than reporting it. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon takes precedence and most directly obligates the certified professional to act?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are prioritized, with protecting society and the infrastructure taking precedence over the other canons when they conflict, making it the most directly applicable obligation here. The other canons are still relevant but are subordinate in priority to this first canon.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A disgruntled employee accesses and deletes confidential files without authorization. Under most legal systems, which type of law would most likely apply if the organization pursues a lawsuit seeking monetary damages rather than imprisonment?","o":["Civil law","Criminal law","Administrative law","Constitutional law"],"c":0,"why":"Civil law addresses disputes between parties, typically resulting in monetary damages, whereas criminal law involves government prosecution and potential imprisonment. Administrative law governs regulatory agency actions, and constitutional law addresses fundamental governmental structure and rights.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization decides that the cost of mitigating a low-probability risk exceeds the potential loss, and therefore chooses to take no further action while continuing normal operations. Which risk management strategy is being applied?","o":["Risk acceptance","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk mitigation"],"c":0,"why":"Risk acceptance involves acknowledging a risk and choosing not to invest further resources in reducing it, typically because the cost of mitigation outweighs the potential impact. Avoidance eliminates the activity causing the risk, transfer shifts the risk to a third party, and mitigation reduces the risk's likelihood or impact.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"During a Business Impact Analysis (BIA), an analyst identifies the maximum acceptable amount of time a business process can be down before causing unacceptable harm to the organization. What is this metric called?","o":["Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)","Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO)"],"c":0,"why":"Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) represents the longest period a process can be unavailable before causing unacceptable damage. RPO relates to acceptable data loss, MTBF measures reliability between failures, and ARO is a risk frequency metric unrelated to downtime tolerance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization values a critical database server at $500,000. A risk analysis determines the exposure factor for a specific flood scenario is 40%, and the annualized rate of occurrence is 0.5. A proposed flood mitigation control costs $60,000 per year and would reduce the annualized rate of occurrence to 0.1. Based on a cost-benefit analysis, should the organization implement the control?","o":["Yes, because the annualized loss expectancy decreases by $80,000, exceeding the $60,000 control cost by $20,000","No, because the exposure factor of 40% indicates the asset is too critical to protect cost-effectively","Yes, because the single loss expectancy of $200,000 justifies any control cost under $200,000","No, because the annualized rate of occurrence of 0.1 after the control still represents an unacceptable residual risk"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = $500,000 x 0.40 = $200,000; original ALE = $200,000 x 0.5 = $100,000; post-control ALE = $200,000 x 0.1 = $20,000. The reduction of $80,000 exceeds the $60,000 control cost, yielding a positive net benefit of $20,000, so the control is justified. The other options misapply the figures or draw conclusions unsupported by the calculation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"Before signing a contract with a new cloud service provider, a CISO commissions an independent assessment of the provider's security controls, reviews its SOC 2 report, and evaluates its financial stability. After the contract is signed, the CISO's team continues to monitor the provider's performance quarterly and updates contractual security requirements as risks change. Which concepts do the pre-contract assessment and the post-contract monitoring activities respectively represent?","o":["Due diligence, then due care","Due care, then due diligence","Due diligence in both cases, since both occur before any incident","Due care in both cases, since both involve ongoing organizational responsibility"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before making a decision (vetting the vendor pre-contract); due care refers to the ongoing, reasonable actions taken to maintain that standard afterward (continuous monitoring). Reversing the order or labeling both the same is incorrect because the two concepts are temporally and functionally distinct.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A multinational corporation wants to establish a governance framework that explicitly maps IT control objectives to business goals and includes a maturity model to measure the progress of governance processes over time. Which of the following is the BEST framework choice for this specific requirement?","o":["COBIT","ISO/IEC 27001","NIST Cybersecurity Framework","ITIL"],"c":0,"why":"COBIT is a governance framework specifically designed to align IT processes and control objectives with business goals and includes a capability/maturity model. ISO 27001 is an ISMS certification standard, NIST CSF is a risk-based cybersecurity framework for critical infrastructure, and ITIL focuses on IT service management—none provide the same explicit business-goal-to-control mapping with maturity modeling.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A commercial data center building has an asset value of $2,000,000. A fire risk assessment indicates that a fire would destroy 25% of the asset value, and historical data shows such fires occur once every 10 years on average. A proposed fire suppression system costing $30,000 annually would reduce the frequency of destructive fires to once every 50 years. Based on a cost-benefit analysis, which statement correctly evaluates this safeguard?","o":["The safeguard should be implemented because it reduces annual loss exposure by $40,000 while costing $30,000, yielding a net annual benefit of $10,000","The safeguard should be rejected because its $30,000 annual cost exceeds the $10,000 reduction in single loss expectancy","The safeguard should be rejected because the total asset value of $2,000,000 far exceeds the $30,000 control cost, making the risk acceptable without mitigation","The safeguard should be implemented only if the exposure factor can be reduced to zero, since partial mitigation provides no measurable value"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = $2,000,000 × 0.25 = $500,000. ALE before = $500,000 × 0.1 = $50,000; ALE after = $500,000 × 0.02 = $10,000, a $40,000 reduction. Subtracting the $30,000 control cost yields a $10,000 net benefit, justifying implementation. The other options misapply the ALE/SLE figures or reject valid partial mitigation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A Business Impact Analysis determines that a critical order-processing system can tolerate no more than 4 hours of data loss (RPO) and must be restored within 8 hours (RTO) after a disruption. The current backup schedule performs full backups every 6 hours, and the last successful backup completed 5 hours before a server failure occurs. Which statement BEST describes the situation?","o":["The current backup interval violates the RPO requirement because up to 6 hours of data could be lost, exceeding the 4-hour maximum","The situation is acceptable because the failure occurred only 5 hours after the last backup, which is less than the 6-hour backup interval","The RTO has already been violated because the backup interval exceeds the recovery time objective","No violation has occurred because RPO only applies to full system outages, not partial data loss"],"c":0,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time; since backups occur every 6 hours, worst-case data loss could reach 6 hours, which exceeds the 4-hour RPO regardless of when a particular failure happens. RTO concerns restoration time, not backup frequency, and RPO applies broadly to data loss scenarios, not just full outages.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company wants ongoing assurance that a SaaS vendor's security, availability, and confidentiality controls have operated effectively over the past twelve months, not just at a single point in time. Which type of audit report should the company request from the vendor?","o":["SOC 2 Type II","SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 3"],"c":0,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of security, availability, and confidentiality controls over an extended period (typically 6-12 months), providing the assurance described. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, Type I reports only assess control design at a single point in time, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report lacking the detailed evidence needed for vendor risk decisions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A network administrator learns of a new vulnerability affecting the organization's VPN concentrators and immediately applies the vendor's patch and updates firewall rules to mitigate the risk before any incident occurs. This action is best described as an example of:","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Risk transference","Negligence"],"c":1,"why":"Due care refers to taking reasonable, prudent action to prevent harm once a risk is known; due diligence is the research/investigation used to identify that risk. Risk transference (e.g., insurance) and negligence (failure to act) do not describe this proactive remediation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO researched, selected, and documented industry-standard security controls prior to implementation, engaged independent auditors to test control effectiveness, and revised deficient controls promptly after audit findings. Following a breach, regulators are evaluating whether the organization exercised the appropriate standard of care. Which concept BEST describes the CISO's actions and their legal significance?","o":["Due care alone, since the CISO implemented controls without prior research","Due diligence alone, since the CISO only researched controls without verifying their effectiveness","Both due care and due diligence, satisfying the prudent person rule and supporting a defense against negligence liability","Gross negligence, because reliance on external auditors shifts legal liability away from the organization"],"c":2,"why":"Due diligence (researching and selecting appropriate controls) combined with due care (implementing, testing, and correcting controls) together satisfy the prudent person rule, providing a defense against negligence. The other options describe only part of the actions or mischaracterize the legal effect of using auditors.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements encryption on a database containing customer Social Security numbers to prevent unauthorized individuals from viewing the data. Which principle of the CIA triad does this control primarily support?","o":["Availability","Confidentiality","Integrity","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"Encryption prevents unauthorized disclosure of sensitive data, which directly supports confidentiality. Availability concerns access to data, integrity concerns unauthorized modification, and non-repudiation is not part of the CIA triad.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A network engineer writes a document containing exact command-line steps for configuring access control lists on all perimeter firewalls to comply with the organization's mandatory access control policy. This document is reviewed annually and updated whenever firewall models change. What type of governance document is this?","o":["Procedure","Policy","Standard","Guideline"],"c":0,"why":"A procedure provides detailed, step-by-step instructions for performing a specific task in support of policy compliance. A policy states high-level intent, a standard specifies mandatory technical requirements (e.g., which encryption algorithm to use), and a guideline offers discretionary recommendations—none match the specific, sequential instructional nature described.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's information security program includes a high-level statement mandating that 'all sensitive data must be encrypted at rest and in transit,' along with a separate document specifying that AES-256 must be used for encryption at rest and TLS 1.2 or higher for transit. Which pair of document types correctly matches the statement and the specification, respectively?","o":["Policy; Standard","Standard; Guideline","Procedure; Policy","Guideline; Procedure"],"c":0,"why":"A policy sets high-level, mandatory intent (encrypt sensitive data), while a standard specifies the mandatory technical requirements to meet that intent (AES-256, TLS 1.2+). Guidelines are advisory, and procedures are step-by-step instructions—neither fits either description here.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company operating in a jurisdiction governed by a civil law legal system notes that court decisions in prior cases have persuasive but not binding authority on future rulings. Which characteristic BEST distinguishes this civil law approach from a common law system?","o":["Civil law relies primarily on comprehensive written codes and statutes rather than binding judicial precedent","Civil law systems do not permit any form of contract enforcement between private parties","Civil law systems apply religious doctrine as the primary source of legal authority","Civil law systems require all criminal cases to be tried before a jury of peers"],"c":0,"why":"Civil law systems are based on detailed codified statutes, with judges applying and interpreting the code rather than being bound by prior case law (stare decisis) as in common law systems. The other options describe unrelated or inaccurate characteristics not specific to civil law.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company is evaluating a SaaS provider that will process customer PII. The company's security team wants assurance that the provider's security controls were both suitably designed AND operated effectively over a six-month period. Which report should the company request from the provider?","o":["SOC 1 Type II","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","ISO/IEC 27001 certificate of registration"],"c":2,"why":"SOC 2 Type II evaluates both the design and operating effectiveness of security-related controls over a defined period. SOC 1 addresses controls relevant to financial reporting, Type I only assesses design at a point in time, and an ISO 27001 certificate confirms conformance to a management system standard without detailed control-testing evidence.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A critical database server has an asset value of $500,000. A risk assessment determines that a successful ransomware attack would result in a 20% exposure factor, and historical data indicates such an attack occurs on average once every two years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$10,000","$50,000","$100,000","$200,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = Asset Value × EF = $500,000 × 0.20 = $100,000. ARO = 1/2 = 0.5. ALE = SLE × ARO = $100,000 × 0.5 = $50,000. The other values result from omitting or misapplying the ARO or EF.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization's data classification policy assigns responsibility for approving access requests and defining the sensitivity level of a dataset to one role, while a separate role is responsible for implementing backups, applying encryption, and maintaining access control lists based on those classifications. Which two roles are being described, respectively?","o":["Data owner, then data custodian","Data custodian, then data owner","Data processor, then data controller","Data steward, then data controller"],"c":0,"why":"The data owner is accountable for classification decisions and authorizing access, while the data custodian performs the technical, day-to-day implementation of protective controls based on the owner's decisions. Data processor/controller are GDPR-specific terms describing entities that process personal data on behalf of another party, and a data steward typically focuses on data quality and metadata rather than technical control implementation.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A security manager researches industry best practices, consults with legal counsel, and implements reasonable safeguards before deploying a new system. This behavior best demonstrates which concept?","o":["Due diligence","Separation of duties","Least privilege","Risk transference"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as evaluating best practices and legal requirements. Due care would be the ongoing responsible action taken based on that research; the other options are unrelated access control or risk concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis determines that an order-processing system has a maximum tolerable downtime (MTD) of 24 hours. The disaster recovery plan specifies a recovery time objective (RTO) of 18 hours and a recovery point objective (RPO) of 4 hours. The current backup schedule performs full backups every 6 hours. Which statement correctly evaluates this configuration?","o":["The configuration is acceptable because the RTO of 18 hours is within the MTD of 24 hours","The configuration is unacceptable because the 6-hour backup interval exceeds the 4-hour RPO, risking greater data loss than tolerable, even though the RTO satisfies the MTD","The configuration is unacceptable because the RTO must always equal the RPO for the plan to be valid","The configuration is acceptable because MTD, RTO, and RPO are independent metrics with no bearing on backup frequency"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable data loss window; a 6-hour backup interval could result in up to 6 hours of lost data, exceeding the 4-hour RPO regardless of whether the RTO meets the MTD. The other options misunderstand the independent purpose and interdependency of these metrics.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's information security policy states that all remote access must use multi-factor authentication. A supporting document specifies that VPN clients must support FIDO2-compliant hardware tokens and defines the exact authentication protocols to be used. This supporting document is best classified as a:","o":["Guideline","Procedure","Standard","Baseline"],"c":2,"why":"A standard provides mandatory, specific technical requirements that support a policy's high-level intent. Guidelines are advisory rather than mandatory, procedures are step-by-step instructions for performing tasks, and baselines define minimum configuration levels for a specific platform, none of which match this description.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes residual risk?","o":["The total risk present before any controls are applied","The risk that remains after controls have been implemented","The risk accepted by transferring it to an insurance provider","The risk associated with a single point of failure in a system"],"c":1,"why":"Residual risk is what remains after safeguards and controls have been applied to reduce inherent risk. Total risk before controls is inherent risk, and the other options describe risk transference and a specific vulnerability type, not residual risk.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified security manager discovers that a close colleague has been using elevated access to browse coworkers' payroll records out of curiosity, causing no reported harm. Reporting the colleague may damage the manager's personal relationship and could result in the colleague's termination. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which action best reflects the required order of priority among the canons?","o":["Ignore the incident since no harm occurred and personal relationships take precedence over minor policy violations","Report the incident through appropriate channels, because protecting the organization and acting honorably takes precedence over personal loyalty","Confront the colleague privately and allow them to self-report if they choose, satisfying the duty to society without formal escalation","Wait to see if the behavior recurs before taking any action, since a single incident does not violate the Code of Ethics"],"c":1,"why":"The Code of Ethics prioritizes protecting society and organizations and acting honorably and legally; unauthorized access to confidential records is a violation regardless of harm and must be reported through proper channels. Personal loyalty, informal handling, or inaction do not satisfy the manager's ethical obligations.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A beverage company keeps its proprietary flavor formula confidential by restricting access to only two employees, requiring signed non-disclosure agreements, and storing the formula in a secured vault rather than filing for legal protection with a government agency. This formula is best protected under which form of intellectual property law?","o":["Patent","Copyright","Trade secret","Trademark"],"c":2,"why":"Trade secrets are protected indefinitely through confidentiality measures rather than public registration, which fits this scenario. Patents and copyrights require registration and public disclosure, and trademarks protect brand identifiers, not proprietary processes or formulas.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon must be applied first when a conflict arises between the other canons?","o":["Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Advance and protect the profession","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics states that if a conflict arises among canons, they should be resolved in the order presented, with protecting society and the public good taking precedence over the others.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A US-based company markets services to EU residents and contracts a third-party firm to process customer support tickets, including personal data. The US company determines what data is collected and why, while the third party only follows the US company's instructions for processing. Under GDPR, which classification applies, and what mechanism should be used to legally transfer this personal data from the EU to the US processor?","o":["The US company is the data processor; the third party is the controller; transfers require Binding Corporate Rules only","The US company is the data controller; the third party is the data processor; transfers may rely on Standard Contractual Clauses","Both entities are joint controllers; transfers require the data subject's explicit consent for every transaction","The US company is the controller; the third party is a sub-processor; no transfer mechanism is required since both parties are contractually bound"],"c":1,"why":"The entity determining the purposes and means of processing is the controller (the US company); the entity processing on its behalf is the processor (the third party). Since the EU-US Privacy Shield was invalidated, GDPR-compliant cross-border transfers typically rely on Standard Contractual Clauses with supplementary safeguards, not mere contractual agreement alone.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, if a CISSP-certified professional faces a situation where obligations to their employer conflict with obligations to the public, which canon takes precedence?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally"],"c":2,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics canons are applied in order of precedence, with protecting society and the public good listed first and taking priority over obligations to employers or the profession. The other canons are important but subordinate when a genuine conflict arises.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"In a typical security policy framework, which document provides mandatory, specific technical requirements that must be met to comply with policy?","o":["Guideline","Standard","Procedure","Baseline"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, specific requirements (e.g., password length) that support policy compliance. Guidelines are recommended but not mandatory, procedures are step-by-step instructions, and a baseline is a minimum level of security configuration, not a requirements document.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A risk manager calculates that a specific threat has an Asset Value of $500,000 and an Exposure Factor of 20%, occurring on average once every two years. A proposed safeguard costs $30,000 annually and would reduce the Annualized Rate of Occurrence to once every ten years. Based on a cost-benefit analysis of Annualized Loss Expectancy, what should the organization do?","o":["Reject the safeguard because the SLE exceeds the safeguard cost","Implement the safeguard because it produces a net annual savings of approximately $10,000","Reject the safeguard because the ARO is already below 1.0 and further reduction is unnecessary","Implement the safeguard only if the asset value is reassessed upward"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = $500,000 x 20% = $100,000. Original ALE = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. New ALE with safeguard = $100,000 x 0.1 = $10,000. Savings = $50,000 - $10,000 = $40,000, minus the $30,000 safeguard cost = $10,000 net benefit, so implementation is justified. The other options misapply the calculation or ignore the cost-benefit result.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"After completing a risk assessment, an organization determines that the risk of a ransomware attack exceeds its risk appetite even after deploying endpoint detection, offline backups, and staff training. Management decides to purchase a cyberinsurance policy to cover incident response and recovery costs. Which statement BEST describes the effect of this decision?","o":["The purchase eliminates the risk entirely, since insurance proceeds will fully restore normal operations after any incident","The purchase transfers the financial impact of the risk to the insurer, but operational disruption, reputational damage, and regulatory consequences remain as residual risk the organization must still manage","The purchase converts the risk from an operational risk into a purely legal risk, removing the need for further mitigation controls","The purchase constitutes risk avoidance, since the organization no longer needs to operate the systems exposed to ransomware"],"c":1,"why":"Insurance is a risk transfer mechanism that offsets financial loss but cannot eliminate downtime, reputational harm, or regulatory consequences, which remain as residual risk requiring ongoing management. The other options overstate insurance's effect or mischaracterize the risk treatment strategy.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During a business impact analysis, stakeholders determine that the maximum tolerable data loss for a financial transaction system is 4 hours. The current backup process only performs full backups every 24 hours. This gap represents a failure to meet the system's:","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Work Recovery Time (WRT)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, which directly relates to backup frequency. RTO and WRT concern how quickly systems and operations are restored after an outage, while MTD is the overall maximum time a business process can be disrupted before causing unacceptable harm.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A healthcare organization commissioned a comprehensive third-party risk assessment of a new cloud vendor before signing a contract. The assessment identified several critical control gaps, but the organization signed the contract without requiring remediation or compensating controls. A breach later occurred through one of the identified gaps. From a legal liability standpoint, which statement best describes the organization's failure?","o":["The organization failed to exercise due diligence because it did not investigate the vendor's controls","The organization failed to exercise due care because it did not act on known risks after adequate investigation","The organization is not liable because the vendor is contractually responsible for its own security controls","The organization exercised both due diligence and due care, so liability rests solely with the vendor"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence (the investigation/assessment) was performed properly; due care (acting reasonably on known findings) was not, since the organization ignored identified risks. This distinguishes negligence based on inaction from negligence based on failure to investigate.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company's internal disciplinary policy allows termination of an employee for violating an acceptable use policy, without involvement of external courts. This is an example of which type of law?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Customary law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law includes internal organizational policies and regulatory rules enforced by governing bodies without requiring criminal or civil court proceedings. Criminal and civil law require formal legal action, and customary law is based on regional traditions and customs, not corporate policy.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company is evaluating a cloud-based SaaS provider and wants independent assurance that the provider's controls over confidentiality and availability have been operating effectively over the past six months. Which type of audit report should the company request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of controls related to the Trust Services Criteria (including confidentiality and availability) over a specified period, such as six months. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, Type I reports only assess design at a point in time, and SOC 3 provides a general-use summary without detailed testing results.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO has been delegated full operational authority for the information security program, including budget and staffing decisions. Two years later, a major breach occurs due to systemic underinvestment in controls. Who retains ultimate accountability for this outcome under standard security governance principles?","o":["The CISO, because operational authority was delegated to that role","The IT department, because it implements technical controls","The board of directors and senior executive management, because accountability cannot be delegated","The external auditors who previously reviewed the security program"],"c":2,"why":"Governance principles hold that while responsibility for tasks can be delegated, ultimate accountability for organizational risk remains with senior management and the board. The CISO holds delegated responsibility, but accountability for governance failures rests at the top.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Company A, based in the United States, collects personal data from EU residents through its website and determines the purposes and means of processing that data. Company A contracts with Company B to host and process this data strictly according to Company A's written instructions. Under the GDPR, Company B is best classified as the:","o":["Data controller","Data subject","Data processor","Data custodian"],"c":2,"why":"Under GDPR, a data processor processes personal data on behalf of and under the instructions of a data controller, which is Company A in this scenario since it determines the purposes and means of processing. Data subject refers to the individual whose data is collected, and data custodian is not a formally defined GDPR role.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's annual loss expectancy (ALE) calculation is being reviewed. A critical database server has an asset value of $400,000. A successful ransomware attack is expected to destroy 25% of the server's value, and historical data indicates such attacks occur once every four years on this type of asset. What is the ALE for this risk?","o":["$25,000","$100,000","$400,000","$16,667"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = AV x EF = $400,000 x 0.25 = $100,000. ARO = 1/4 = 0.25. ALE = SLE x ARO = $100,000 x 0.25 = $25,000. The other options misapply the formula (e.g., using SLE alone or dividing incorrectly).","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization operating under a mandate to apply the NIST Risk Management Framework (RMF) has just completed the 'Select' step for a new information system. Which activity should occur next in the RMF process?","o":["Categorize the system based on impact levels","Implement the selected security controls","Authorize the system for operation","Continuously monitor control effectiveness"],"c":1,"why":"NIST RMF follows the sequence Categorize, Select, Implement, Assess, Authorize, Monitor. After controls are selected, they must be implemented before being assessed and authorized. Categorize precedes Select, and Authorize/Monitor come later in the process.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which plan is primarily focused on restoring critical business functions and processes after a disruptive event, potentially using alternate facilities or manual workarounds?","o":["Business Continuity Plan (BCP)","Incident Response Plan (IRP)","Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)","Configuration Management Plan"],"c":0,"why":"The BCP focuses on keeping essential business functions operating during and after a disruption, often through manual procedures or alternate sites. The DRP is narrower, focusing on restoring IT systems and infrastructure, while IRP addresses handling security incidents and Configuration Management Plans govern change control.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A hospital hires an outside consultant to perform a comprehensive risk assessment before selecting new access control systems, carefully evaluating multiple vendors and documenting the rationale for the chosen solution. This activity best exemplifies which security management concept?","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Residual risk"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as evaluating options prior to implementation. Due care refers to the ongoing, reasonable actions taken once a decision is implemented; the other two terms relate to risk treatment outcomes, not investigative process.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During contract negotiations with a critical SaaS provider, a security team wants contractual assurance that they can independently verify the vendor's ongoing control effectiveness rather than relying solely on vendor-provided attestations. Which contractual mechanism most directly addresses this concern?","o":["A non-disclosure agreement","A service level agreement specifying uptime guarantees","A right-to-audit clause","An indemnification clause"],"c":2,"why":"A right-to-audit clause grants the customer the ability to independently verify or commission audits of the vendor's controls. NDAs protect confidentiality, SLAs address performance metrics like uptime, and indemnification addresses financial liability after a loss, none of which provide independent verification capability.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISO issues a document that states: 'All laptops must be encrypted using AES-256 full-disk encryption prior to deployment.' This document is best classified as a:","o":["Policy","Standard","Guideline","Procedure"],"c":1,"why":"A standard specifies mandatory, specific technical requirements (like AES-256) that support a higher-level policy. A policy would state the general intent (e.g., 'all mobile devices must be encrypted') without specifying the algorithm; guidelines are recommendations, and procedures are step-by-step instructions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A new employee is required to complete training on how to recognize phishing emails and properly handle sensitive information before receiving system access. This is an example of which security program element?","o":["Security awareness training","Vulnerability assessment","Penetration testing","Segregation of duties"],"c":0,"why":"Security awareness training educates personnel on recognizing threats like phishing and properly handling data, which is what's described. Vulnerability assessments and penetration tests are technical evaluations, and segregation of duties is an access control principle, not training.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A business continuity plan defines a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 24 hours for a critical order-processing system. The Work Recovery Time (WRT), which includes data validation, reconciliation, and testing after systems are restored, is estimated at 10 hours. What is the maximum Recovery Time Objective (RTO) that can be set for the technical restoration of the system?","o":["24 hours, since WRT occurs independently of RTO","10 hours, since WRT determines the total allowable downtime","14 hours, since MTD must equal or exceed RTO plus WRT","34 hours, since RTO and WRT are additive to MTD"],"c":2,"why":"The relationship MTD ≥ RTO + WRT means the technical restoration (RTO) must leave enough time within the MTD for post-restoration recovery work (WRT). 24 - 10 = 14 hours is the maximum RTO; the other options misapply or reverse the formula.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A manufacturing firm decides to outsource its payroll processing to a third-party provider specifically to eliminate the organization's exposure to payroll tax compliance penalties. Which risk response strategy is being applied?","o":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Transferring the risk to a third party (the payroll provider assumes compliance liability) is risk transfer. Avoidance would mean eliminating the activity entirely, mitigation would involve reducing likelihood/impact while retaining the activity, and acceptance means retaining the risk without action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"During a business impact analysis, a company determines that its order-processing system can tolerate a maximum of 4 hours of downtime and that transaction data can be recreated from logs going back no more than 15 minutes before an outage. The 15-minute value represents the system's:","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Service Delivery Objective (SDO)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, i.e., how far back data must be restorable. RTO/MTD relate to allowable downtime duration, not data loss, and SDO refers to the level of service to be restored, not a time metric for data.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A regulatory agency fines a company for violating workplace safety reporting requirements, without any criminal charges being filed or a private lawsuit being initiated. This enforcement action falls under which category of law?","o":["Criminal law","Civil (tort) law","Administrative (regulatory) law","Common law"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law involves regulations and enforcement actions by government agencies, including fines for non-compliance, distinct from criminal prosecution (government vs. individual for crimes) or civil law (private party lawsuits for damages).","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before signing a contract with a cloud service provider that will host regulated customer data, a security team requests an independent auditor's report describing the provider's controls over security, availability, and confidentiality. Which document should they request?","o":["A SOC 2 Type II report","A penetration test executive summary","A business continuity plan","A privacy impact assessment"],"c":0,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report provides independent assurance on a service provider's controls over the Trust Services Criteria (security, availability, confidentiality, etc.) over a period of time, making it the standard artifact for third-party risk due diligence. The other documents address different, narrower concerns and aren't standardized third-party assurance reports.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company implements a formal, documented process to evaluate the security practices of a potential vendor before signing a contract. This activity BEST demonstrates which security concept?","o":["Due care","Due diligence","Risk acceptance","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence refers to the research and investigation performed before making a decision, such as vetting a vendor's security practices. Due care refers to the ongoing actions taken to maintain a reasonable level of protection after that decision is made.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization decides to purchase cybersecurity insurance to cover potential losses from a data breach rather than implementing additional technical controls. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance"],"c":2,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing the risk directly, avoidance means eliminating the activity causing the risk, and acceptance means taking no action and absorbing the loss.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A company's IT staff verifies that a vendor's software has been patched and tested before deployment, in accordance with organizational policy. This action best exemplifies which security concept?","o":["Due diligence","Separation of duties","Least privilege","Risk avoidance"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence involves researching and verifying facts, such as confirming patches were applied, before taking action; due care would be the actual reasonable action taken based on that research. The other options relate to access control and risk strategy, not verification of facts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"In a security policy framework, which document provides mandatory, specific technical requirements that must be followed to support a policy, such as requiring AES-256 for data at rest?","o":["Guideline","Standard","Procedure","Baseline"],"c":1,"why":"A standard defines mandatory, specific requirements (like a particular encryption algorithm) that support the broader policy. Guidelines are recommended but not mandatory, procedures are step-by-step instructions, and a baseline is a minimum level of security configuration.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization calculates that a particular threat could cause $50,000 in damage and is expected to occur twice per year. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$25,000","$50,000","$100,000","$150,000"],"c":2,"why":"ALE = Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) x Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) = $50,000 x 2 = $100,000. The other values reflect miscalculations of the formula.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's data center houses an asset valued at $500,000. A risk assessment determines that a specific flood scenario would destroy 20% of the asset's value (exposure factor) and is expected to occur once every two years. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for this risk?","o":["$50,000","$100,000","$10,000","$250,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor = $500,000 x 0.20 = $100,000. ARO = 1 event / 2 years = 0.5. ALE = SLE x ARO = $100,000 x 0.5 = $50,000. The other values result from omitting the ARO or misapplying the exposure factor.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A server has an Asset Value (AV) of $200,000. The Exposure Factor (EF) for a specific threat is 25%, and the Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) is 2. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$50,000","$100,000","$25,000","$400,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = AV × EF = $200,000 × 0.25 = $50,000. ALE = SLE × ARO = $50,000 × 2 = $100,000. The other options result from miscalculating either the SLE or failing to multiply by the ARO correctly.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Before signing a contract with a cloud service provider, a company's risk team reviews the provider's audit reports, financial stability, and security certifications to determine whether the relationship poses acceptable risk. This activity is best described as:","o":["Due diligence","Due care","Risk transfer","Residual risk analysis"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence is the research and investigation performed prior to a decision (e.g., vetting a vendor before engagement). Due care refers to ongoing actions taken to maintain an appropriate standard of protection after a decision is made, so it does not fit this pre-contract activity.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Requiring one employee to initiate a wire transfer and a different employee to approve it is an example of which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Need to know"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by any single individual. Least privilege limits access to only what is necessary, defense in depth layers multiple controls, and need to know restricts access to information based on job requirements.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A security document specifies that all Windows servers in the organization must be configured with a minimum TLS version of 1.2 and disk encryption enabled. This type of document is best classified as a:","o":["Guideline","Standard","Procedure","Policy"],"c":1,"why":"A standard defines mandatory, specific requirements (such as a minimum TLS version) that must be uniformly applied. Guidelines are discretionary recommendations, procedures are step-by-step instructions, and policies are high-level statements of management intent rather than technical specifics.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A multinational company processes personal data of customers located in the European Union. Under GDPR, which principle requires the company to collect only the personal data necessary for a specific, stated purpose?","o":["Data minimization","Right to erasure","Data portability","Accountability"],"c":0,"why":"Data minimization requires that only the personal data necessary to achieve a specific purpose be collected and processed. Right to erasure allows individuals to request deletion of their data, data portability allows transfer of data between providers, and accountability requires organizations to demonstrate compliance with GDPR principles.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A customer sues a retailer, claiming the company failed to implement reasonable safeguards to protect personal data, resulting in financial harm after a breach. This lawsuit would most likely be adjudicated under:","o":["Civil law","Criminal law","Administrative law","Constitutional law"],"c":0,"why":"Civil law governs disputes between private parties, including negligence claims (torts) such as failure to exercise a reasonable standard of care. Criminal law involves government prosecution for offenses against the state, and administrative law concerns regulatory agency enforcement, neither of which applies to a private lawsuit for damages.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon is listed FIRST and takes precedence in guiding a CISSP's professional conduct?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure"],"c":3,"why":"The first and highest canon of the (ISC)² Code of Ethics is to protect society and the infrastructure; if canons conflict, this one takes priority. The others are legitimate canons but are listed after this one in order of precedence.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which of the following is listed as a mandatory canon that all certified professionals must uphold?","o":["Maximize shareholder profit at all times","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Always prioritize organizational goals over legal requirements","Avoid reporting security incidents to preserve organizational reputation"],"c":1,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics explicitly includes protecting society, the common good, public trust, and infrastructure as a foundational canon. The other options contradict ethical and legal obligations that CISSP holders must follow.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization's business continuity plan states a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 4 hours for its e-commerce platform. This RTO primarily represents:","o":["The maximum acceptable amount of data that can be lost during an outage","The maximum acceptable time to restore the system to operation after a disruption","The frequency at which backups must be tested","The time required to notify stakeholders of an incident"],"c":1,"why":"RTO defines the maximum tolerable time to restore a system or process after an interruption. Maximum acceptable data loss is measured by the Recovery Point Objective (RPO), not RTO, and the other options describe unrelated BCP metrics.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"A law that is enacted by a legislative body and enforced through government prosecution, potentially resulting in imprisonment, is best classified as which type of law?","o":["Civil law","Criminal law","Administrative law","Customary law"],"c":1,"why":"Criminal law involves government prosecution of acts harmful to society and can result in incarceration. Civil law typically involves disputes between parties resulting in monetary damages, administrative law involves regulatory agency enforcement, and customary law is based on regional customs and traditions.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon takes precedence over the others when a conflict arises between professional obligations?","o":["Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally"],"c":2,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics explicitly states the canons are listed in order of precedence, with protecting society and the public interest taking priority over all other obligations, including duties to employers or the profession itself.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"Which plan focuses specifically on restoring critical business functions and processes at an alternate location after a disruptive event, as opposed to restoring IT systems and data?","o":["Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)","Business Continuity Plan (BCP)","Incident Response Plan (IRP)","Business Impact Analysis (BIA)"],"c":1,"why":"BCP addresses maintaining or resuming overall business operations and critical functions during and after a disruption. DRP is narrower, focusing on IT infrastructure recovery; IRP addresses handling security incidents, and a BIA is an analysis tool, not a recovery plan.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A manufacturing company purchases a cyber liability insurance policy to help cover potential financial losses from a future ransomware attack. This is an example of which risk treatment strategy?","o":["Risk transfer","Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk acceptance"],"c":0,"why":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a risk to a third party, which is the definition of risk transfer. Mitigation would involve reducing likelihood or impact through controls, avoidance means eliminating the activity causing risk, and acceptance means acknowledging the risk without further action.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"easy","q":"An organization decides that the cost of protecting against a low-probability, low-impact risk exceeds the potential loss, and chooses to take no action while continuing normal operations. This is an example of which risk treatment strategy?","o":["Risk mitigation","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance","Risk avoidance"],"c":2,"why":"Risk acceptance means the organization acknowledges the risk and decides to take no further action because the cost of addressing it outweighs the potential impact. Mitigation reduces risk, transfer shifts it (e.g., insurance), and avoidance eliminates the activity causing the risk entirely.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A risk analyst calculates that a specific asset valued at $4,000,000 has an exposure factor of 20% for a particular threat, which is expected to occur once every two years. A proposed safeguard costs $150,000 annually and would reduce the annualized rate of occurrence to once every five years without affecting the exposure factor. What is the annual net value of implementing this safeguard?","o":["$90,000","$240,000","$150,000","$400,000"],"c":0,"why":"SLE = $4M × 20% = $800,000. ALE before = $800,000 × 0.5 = $400,000; ALE after = $800,000 × 0.2 = $160,000. Value = ($400,000 − $160,000) − $150,000 (ACS) = $90,000. The other figures represent intermediate values (raw ALE reduction or ALE itself), not the net safeguard value after subtracting cost.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants an independent, ongoing assurance of a cloud provider's security controls over a six-month period rather than a one-time snapshot assessment. Which document should it request from the provider?","o":["A SOC 2 Type II report","A SOC 1 Type I report","The provider's internal security policy manual","A penetration test summary from the previous year"],"c":0,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of security controls over an extended period, providing the ongoing assurance requested. A Type I report only assesses control design at a single point in time, and internal policies or a single pentest do not offer independent, sustained verification of control effectiveness.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISO commissions an independent third-party security assessment before acquiring a smaller competitor, and subsequently directs implementation of the assessment's recommended controls prior to the merger closing. This sequence of investigative and corrective actions best exemplifies which pairing of legal concepts?","o":["Due diligence followed by due care","Due care followed by due diligence","Downstream liability followed by proximate cause","Negligence followed by liability"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence is the reasonable investigation performed before a decision (the pre-acquisition assessment); due care is the reasonable corrective action taken afterward (implementing controls). The reverse ordering and the other term pairs describe unrelated or inapplicable legal concepts in this scenario.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A financial application enforces that the employee who initiates a wire transfer cannot be the same employee who approves it, and neither of those employees may be the one who reconciles the bank statement. Which control principle does this arrangement primarily represent?","o":["Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation","Least privilege"],"c":0,"why":"Dividing a sensitive process among multiple distinct roles so no single individual controls it end-to-end is separation of duties. Job rotation involves periodically moving staff between roles, mandatory vacation forces time away from duties to expose fraud, and least privilege limits access rights rather than dividing process steps.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization has determined that a critical order-processing system has a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 30 hours. The disaster recovery plan sets the Recovery Time Objective (RTO) for restoring the system to 20 hours. Based on these figures, how much Work Recovery Time (WRT) remains to verify data integrity and resume full processing before the MTD is exceeded?","o":["10 hours","20 hours","30 hours","50 hours"],"c":0,"why":"WRT = MTD − RTO = 30 − 20 = 10 hours. The RTO covers restoring system availability, while the remaining time before MTD is exceeded is reserved for verification and reintegration; the other values misrepresent this relationship.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"During vendor due diligence for a cloud service provider that will process regulated customer data, the organization's risk team obtains a SOC 2 Type II report covering the prior twelve months. Which limitation of relying solely on this report should MOST concern the risk team?","o":["The report reflects historical control effectiveness during the audit period and may not reflect the provider's current control environment","SOC 2 Type II reports cannot address security controls, only availability controls","SOC 2 reports are issued exclusively by government regulators and are not applicable to private-sector due diligence","SOC 2 Type II reports only assess controls at a single point in time rather than over a period"],"c":0,"why":"A Type II report attests to control operation over a past period; by the time it is reviewed, controls may have changed, so it should be supplemented with contractual rights to audit or more current evidence. The other options misstate SOC 2 scope, issuers, or the Type I/Type II distinction (Type II is period-based, not point-in-time).","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A data center houses equipment with an asset value of $500,000. A fire risk assessment determines an exposure factor of 40% and an annualized rate of occurrence of 0.2. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","o":["$40,000","$200,000","$100,000","$80,000"],"c":0,"why":"ALE = Asset Value x Exposure Factor x ARO = 500,000 x 0.40 x 0.2 = $40,000. $200,000 is the SLE (before applying ARO), and the other figures result from omitting one of the multiplication factors.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified security manager discovers during a routine audit that her employer has been knowingly misrepresenting compliance status to a regulator to avoid remediation costs. Escalating to executive management yields no corrective action. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon most directly obligates her to take further action, and what is an appropriate next step consistent with that canon?","o":["\"Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure\" — escalate through appropriate channels such as legal counsel, the board, or regulators as warranted","\"Advance and protect the profession\" — publicly disclose the finding on professional social media to warn peers","\"Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally\" — resign immediately without further action","\"Provide diligent and competent service to principals\" — remain silent to preserve confidentiality obligations to the employer"],"c":0,"why":"The first canon takes precedence in the Code's hierarchy and directly addresses harm to public trust from regulatory misrepresentation, warranting escalation through proper channels. Public disclosure via social media is unprofessional and could violate other canons, resigning without escalation abandons the obligation, and confidentiality does not override the duty to protect the public from ongoing regulatory fraud.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following best describes the concept of 'due diligence' as distinguished from 'due care' in information security risk management?","o":["Implementing security controls immediately after a risk has been identified","The ongoing research and investigation performed prior to making an informed risk-based decision","The act of exercising reasonable, ongoing care in maintaining controls once implemented","Transferring residual risk to a third party through an insurance policy"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence is the investigative process of understanding risk before acting; due care is the subsequent act of implementing and maintaining appropriate protections. Options A and C describe due care, and D describes risk transfer, not diligence.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A US-based e-commerce company has no physical presence, subsidiaries, or offices in the European Union. It operates a website in English and US dollars only, targeted at US customers, but a small percentage of EU residents occasionally find and purchase from the site via search engines. Under the GDPR, which statement best describes the company's regulatory obligations?","o":["The company is not subject to GDPR because it does not intentionally offer goods or services to, or monitor, EU data subjects","The company is automatically subject to GDPR because any processing of an EU resident's personal data triggers jurisdiction regardless of intent","The company must appoint an EU representative because it has more than 250 employees","The company is exempt from GDPR because it has no EU-based servers or data centers"],"c":0,"why":"GDPR's extraterritorial scope (Article 3) applies when an organization intentionally targets or monitors EU data subjects, evidenced by factors like currency, language, or marketing directed at the EU; incidental sales without such targeting generally do not trigger jurisdiction. The other options misstate the applicable legal test, which is based on targeting/monitoring intent, not mere incidental processing, employee count, or server location.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISO requires that the employee who creates a new vendor record in the accounts payable system cannot also approve payments to that vendor. This control exemplifies which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties splits critical tasks between multiple people to prevent fraud or error by a single individual. Least privilege limits access scope, job rotation moves people between roles over time, and mandatory vacation forces time away from duties—none directly address dividing conflicting duties.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A risk assessment team calculates the following for a data center's exposure to flooding: Asset Value = $1,500,000, Exposure Factor = 20%, and Annualized Rate of Occurrence = 0.5 (once every two years). A proposed flood mitigation control costs $40,000 per year and would reduce the ARO to 0.1. Using cost-benefit analysis, what is the annualized net benefit of implementing this control?","o":["$40,000","$80,000","$120,000","$150,000"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = $1,500,000 × 0.20 = $300,000; ALE before = $300,000 × 0.5 = $150,000; ALE after = $300,000 × 0.1 = $30,000. Risk reduction = $120,000, minus the $40,000 annual control cost = $80,000 net benefit. The other figures represent intermediate values, not the final CBA result.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A risk assessment identifies that a regional data center has a low likelihood but high-impact exposure to flood damage. Relocating the facility would cost far more than the expected loss, and flood insurance premiums are available at a cost significantly lower than the calculated annualized loss expectancy. Which risk treatment strategy is MOST appropriate?","o":["Risk transfer via insurance","Risk avoidance by ceasing the affected business function","Risk mitigation by constructing floodwalls at the current site regardless of cost","Risk acceptance with no further action"],"c":0,"why":"When a cost-effective transfer mechanism (insurance) is available and costs less than the ALE, transfer is the most rational treatment given that relocation/mitigation costs are prohibitive. Avoidance is disproportionate for a low-likelihood risk, mitigation is dismissed as cost-prohibitive per the scenario, and acceptance ignores a clearly beneficial, low-cost option.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of a data classification scheme within an organization?","o":["To determine which employees receive the highest salaries","To ensure that data receives an appropriate level of protection based on its sensitivity and value","To eliminate the need for encryption on any organizational data","To satisfy auditors without affecting how data is actually handled"],"c":1,"why":"Data classification allows organizations to apply proportional security controls based on sensitivity and value; the other options misstate or trivialize the purpose of classification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"In the information lifecycle, who is ultimately accountable for determining the classification level of a specific dataset and approving who may access it?","o":["The data custodian","The system administrator","The data owner","The end user"],"c":2,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit leader) has ultimate accountability for classifying data and approving access; custodians and administrators only implement controls, and end users merely use the data per policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A hospital's IT staff identified, through a formal risk assessment, that an unpatched medical records server was vulnerable to a known exploit. Management acknowledged the report but took no remediation action for eight months, after which the server was breached. In a subsequent negligence lawsuit, which concept most directly explains the organization's legal exposure?","o":["Failure to perform due diligence, since the vulnerability was never properly investigated","Failure to exercise due care, since the organization identified the risk but failed to act reasonably on that knowledge","Failure to maintain separation of duties among IT staff","Failure to apply the principle of least privilege to the server's service accounts"],"c":1,"why":"Due diligence (investigating and identifying the risk) was performed; the failure was in due care—taking reasonable, timely action once the risk was known. Separation of duties and least privilege are unrelated access-control concepts, not the basis for the negligence claim here.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A database administrator is responsible for performing regular backups, applying patches, and implementing access controls as directed by policy, but does not decide who should be granted access. Which role does this describe?","o":["Data owner","Data custodian","Data subject","Business process owner"],"c":1,"why":"The data custodian performs the day-to-day technical tasks of protecting data (backups, patching, access implementation) under direction from the data owner, who retains decision-making authority; a data subject is the individual the data is about.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A banking regulator fines a financial institution for failing to submit quarterly compliance reports required under its charter, without any criminal charges or civil lawsuit being involved. This scenario is an example of which category of law?","o":["Civil (tort) law, because the institution suffered monetary loss","Criminal law, because the regulator acted as a prosecuting authority","Administrative (regulatory) law, because a government agency enforced compliance through its regulatory authority","Common law, because the fine was based on judicial precedent"],"c":2,"why":"Administrative law involves government agencies creating and enforcing regulations, including levying fines for non-compliance, without criminal prosecution or private civil litigation. Civil and criminal law involve different parties and processes (private lawsuits or prosecutorial action), and this scenario involves neither.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is decommissioning old hard drives that contained highly sensitive financial records. Which sanitization method provides the HIGHEST assurance that data cannot be recovered?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Performing a quick format of the drive","Physical destruction of the media (e.g., shredding or incineration)","Reformatting the drive with the operating system's default format tool"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction provides the highest assurance because it eliminates the possibility of any data recovery; deletion, quick format, and standard reformatting all leave underlying data recoverable with forensic tools.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A company develops a proprietary fraud-detection algorithm and chooses not to file for a patent, instead protecting it through strict confidentiality agreements and access controls. This form of intellectual property protection is best classified as a:","o":["Copyright","Trademark","Trade secret","Patent"],"c":2,"why":"Trade secrets protect confidential business information indefinitely as long as secrecy is maintained, which matches the described approach. Copyright protects expression, trademark protects brand identifiers, and a patent requires public disclosure in exchange for protection, which contradicts the scenario.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis determines that the Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) for a critical order-processing application is 12 hours. The disaster recovery plan for this application achieves a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 14 hours and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 2 hours. Which statement best evaluates this plan?","o":["The plan is acceptable because the RPO of 2 hours is well within tolerance","The plan is unacceptable because the RTO exceeds the MTD, meaning the business could suffer unacceptable impact even though data loss (RPO) is within tolerance","The plan is acceptable because the average of RTO and RPO is less than the MTD","The plan is unacceptable because RPO must always be equal to MTD"],"c":1,"why":"RTO must be less than or equal to MTD; an RTO exceeding MTD means recovery would take longer than the business can tolerate, regardless of how favorable the RPO is. RPO measures acceptable data loss and is evaluated independently of MTD/RTO comparison—averaging the two metrics is not a valid method.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the security control most appropriate for protecting data 'in transit' across a network?","o":["Full disk encryption on the storage server","Transport Layer Security (TLS) encrypting the communication channel","Database column-level encryption","File system access control lists"],"c":1,"why":"TLS protects data as it moves across a network (data in transit); the other controls primarily protect data at rest on storage systems, not data actively being transmitted.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization requires that no single employee can both initiate and approve a wire transfer, and mandates that two authorized individuals must independently complete each step of the transaction. Which security principle is primarily being enforced?","o":["Least privilege","Need-to-know","Separation of duties","Defense in depth"],"c":2,"why":"Requiring multiple individuals to complete different portions of a sensitive transaction so no one person has end-to-end control is the definition of separation of duties. Least privilege and need-to-know concern the scope of access granted to an individual, not the division of a process among multiple people, and defense in depth refers to layered technical/physical controls.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"An organization sets a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 4 hours for its e-commerce database, but backups currently run only once every 24 hours. Which statement best reflects the situation?","o":["The backup schedule meets the RPO requirement","The backup schedule fails to meet the RPO, exposing the organization to significantly more data loss than acceptable","RPO relates only to downtime, not data loss, so backup frequency is irrelevant","The RTO should be shortened to compensate for the backup gap"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the maximum tolerable data loss measured in time; a 24-hour backup cycle against a 4-hour RPO means up to 20 hours of unacceptable data loss could occur. RPO specifically concerns data loss (not downtime, which is RTO), and adjusting RTO does not resolve the data-loss gap.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization defines how long different types of records must be kept before they can be securely destroyed, based on legal, regulatory, and business requirements. This is an example of which practice?","o":["Data retention policy","Data classification policy","Configuration management policy","Change management policy"],"c":0,"why":"A data retention policy specifies how long records must be kept and when they should be destroyed, driven by legal/regulatory/business needs; classification, configuration, and change management address different concerns.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization outsources payroll processing to a third-party vendor. Given limited internal audit resources, which approach provides the best ongoing assurance that the vendor maintains adequate security controls?","o":["Conduct unannounced on-site inspections of the vendor's facility every month","Rely on the vendor's publicly published marketing materials describing its security program","Include a right-to-audit clause in the contract and require the vendor to provide an independent SOC 2 Type II report annually","Terminate the contract immediately upon any reported security incident at the vendor, regardless of severity"],"c":2,"why":"A right-to-audit clause combined with an independent SOC 2 Type II report gives ongoing, third-party-validated assurance without consuming excessive internal audit resources. Monthly unannounced inspections are impractical and costly, marketing materials provide no verifiable assurance, and automatic termination on any incident is an overly rigid response unrelated to ongoing assurance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"When outsourcing a critical business function to a cloud service provider, which document primarily defines measurable performance commitments such as uptime percentage and incident response times?","o":["Business Impact Analysis (BIA)","Service Level Agreement (SLA)","Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)","Memorandum of Understanding (MOU)"],"c":1,"why":"An SLA specifies quantifiable performance metrics and remedies for non-compliance. A BIA assesses internal impact of disruptions, an NDA protects confidential information, and an MOU expresses general intent without binding performance metrics.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the BEST example of personally identifiable information (PII) that would typically require enhanced protection under privacy regulations?","o":["A company's publicly posted annual revenue figures","An employee's Social Security number stored in an HR database","The version number of software installed on a server","A generic customer satisfaction survey with no names attached"],"c":1,"why":"A Social Security number is directly linked to an individual and can be used for identity theft, making it classic PII requiring strong protection; the other examples are not tied to identifiable individuals.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is implementing a data classification program. Which role has the ultimate responsibility for assigning the initial classification level to a specific dataset?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Security administrator","End user"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (typically a business unit leader) is accountable for the data and has the authority to determine its classification based on business value and risk. Custodians implement controls, administrators enforce technical settings, and end users merely handle data per policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A risk management team wants to gather expert opinions on emerging threats to a new cloud platform while minimizing the influence of dominant personalities or groupthink during discussion. Which technique is best suited for this purpose?","o":["Delphi technique","Quantitative ALE calculation","Failure Modes and Effects Analysis (FMEA)","Monte Carlo simulation"],"c":0,"why":"The Delphi technique gathers anonymous, iterative input from a panel of experts specifically to reduce the influence of dominant individuals and groupthink. ALE calculations and Monte Carlo simulation are quantitative modeling methods, and FMEA is a structured technical analysis of failure points, none of which address consensus-building among experts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A CISSP-certified professional discovers that their employer is knowingly violating a data protection regulation in a way that harms customers, and management directs the professional to stay silent. Which canon of the (ISC)² Code of Ethics most directly obligates the professional to act?","o":["Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Advance and protect the profession","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally"],"c":0,"why":"This is the first and highest-priority canon, taking precedence when conflicts arise, and directly addresses harm to the public through regulatory violations. The other canons are important but are subordinate when public welfare is at stake.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"During an asset inventory review, a security analyst discovers several laptops that are not recorded in the asset management system. What is the MOST significant risk this poses to the organization?","o":["The laptops may be running slightly outdated antivirus signatures","Untracked assets cannot be properly assigned classification, ownership, or security controls, increasing risk of undetected compromise","The help desk may take longer to respond to support tickets for these laptops","The organization may exceed its budget for laptop purchases"],"c":1,"why":"Assets not tracked in inventory cannot be assigned proper classification, ownership, patching, or monitoring, creating blind spots that increase security risk; the other options are minor operational concerns, not the primary security risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A retail company collects customer payment data and stores it directly, while a third-party cloud provider hosts the storage infrastructure and processes the data on the company's behalf under a service agreement. Under a GDPR-style privacy framework, how would these two parties be classified?","o":["The company is the data processor and the cloud provider is the data controller","Both parties are joint data controllers with equal liability","The company is the data controller and the cloud provider is the data processor","The cloud provider is the data subject and the company is the data owner"],"c":2,"why":"The company determines the purpose and means of processing (controller), while the cloud provider processes data on the controller's behalf per instructions (processor). The other options reverse or misassign these standard privacy roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A U.S.-based SaaS company processes personal data of EU residents on behalf of a European client under a signed data processing agreement, acting solely as a data processor. Under the GDPR, which statement correctly describes the SaaS company's obligations?","o":["Only the data controller has obligations under the GDPR; processors located outside the EU are exempt","The processor has direct obligations under the GDPR, including implementing appropriate security measures and notifying the controller of any personal data breach without undue delay","The processor is only subject to GDPR if it maintains a physical office within the European Union","The controller and processor have identical, indistinguishable obligations under the GDPR with no distinct liabilities"],"c":1,"why":"GDPR imposes direct obligations on processors, including implementing appropriate technical/organizational security measures and prompt breach notification to the controller, regardless of the processor's location if it processes EU residents' data. Controllers and processors have distinct, though sometimes overlapping, responsibilities and liabilities, and physical presence in the EU is not required for GDPR jurisdiction to apply.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"medium","q":"A security awareness program trains employees to recognize and report phishing emails before they can click malicious links. This control is best classified as:","o":["Technical preventive control","Administrative detective control","Administrative preventive control","Physical preventive control"],"c":2,"why":"Training and awareness programs are policy-driven (administrative) and aim to stop an incident before it occurs (preventive). It is not technical or physical since it involves no technology or physical barriers, and it is not detective since its purpose is prevention rather than identifying incidents after the fact.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company's data retention policy specifies that customer transaction records must be kept for seven years. Which factor should PRIMARILY drive this retention period?","o":["The amount of available storage capacity in the data center","Legal, regulatory, and contractual requirements applicable to the data","The preference of the IT department to minimize backup costs","The age of the encryption algorithm used to protect the data"],"c":1,"why":"Retention periods should be driven by applicable laws, regulations, and contractual obligations, not by storage convenience or unrelated technical factors like encryption algorithm age.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization needs to sanitize a batch of retired solid-state drives (SSDs) before disposal. Why is degaussing considered an ineffective sanitization method for this media type?","o":["Degaussing is too slow to be practical for large batches of drives","SSDs use flash memory rather than magnetic storage, so degaussing has no effect on the data","Degaussing only works on drives larger than 1TB in capacity","SSDs automatically encrypt all data, making degaussing unnecessary"],"c":1,"why":"Degaussing works by disrupting magnetic fields on magnetic media like HDDs; SSDs store data electronically in flash cells with no magnetic properties, so degaussing does not erase the data. The other options are not valid technical explanations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A risk analysis team calculates that a data center's single loss expectancy (SLE) for a flood event is $250,000, with an annualized rate of occurrence (ARO) of 0.2. A proposed flood mitigation control costs $8,000 per year and would reduce the ARO to 0.05. Based on a cost-benefit analysis, what is the annualized net value of implementing the control, and should the organization proceed?","o":["Yes, implement the control; it produces a net annualized benefit of $29,500","No, do not implement; the control produces a net loss of $8,000 annually","Yes, implement the control; it produces a net annualized benefit of $37,500","No, do not implement; the ALE actually increases to $62,500 after the control"],"c":0,"why":"ALE before = $250,000 x 0.2 = $50,000; ALE after = $250,000 x 0.05 = $12,500; savings = $37,500 minus the $8,000 annual cost of the safeguard = $29,500 net benefit, justifying implementation. The other options either omit the safeguard cost or miscalculate the ARO reduction.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A financial application processes sensitive account data in server memory during transaction calculations. Which control BEST protects this data while it is in use?","o":["Full-disk encryption on the database server","TLS 1.3 encryption for all client-server communication","A trusted execution environment (secure enclave) that isolates processing memory","A VPN tunnel between the application server and end users"],"c":2,"why":"Trusted execution environments/secure enclaves isolate and protect data actively being processed in memory. Full-disk encryption protects data at rest, and TLS/VPN protect data in transit—neither addresses exposure during active processing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A company commissioned an independent risk assessment that identified a critical unpatched vulnerability in its externally facing application. Senior management reviewed the report but deferred remediation for six months due to budget constraints. During that period, attackers exploited the exact vulnerability identified in the report. Which statement best characterizes the organization's legal exposure?","o":["The organization exercised due diligence by commissioning the assessment but failed to exercise due care by not acting on known findings, creating exposure to negligence claims","The organization is fully protected from liability because due diligence was performed regardless of remediation timing","The organization exercised due care but not due diligence, which is irrelevant to negligence claims","Liability cannot attach because due diligence and due care apply only to physical security incidents"],"c":0,"why":"Due diligence is the act of investigating and understanding risk (the assessment); due care is acting on that knowledge to prevent harm. Knowingly deferring remediation of an identified critical risk breaks the standard of due care and supports a negligence claim, unlike the distractors which misapply or dismiss the concepts.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A healthcare organization is designing a mobile app that requests users' full Social Security numbers, home addresses, and browsing history, even though the app only needs a user's age range to function. Which data protection principle is being violated?","o":["Data minimization","Separation of duties","Least privilege","Defense in depth"],"c":0,"why":"Data minimization requires collecting only the data necessary for a specific purpose. Separation of duties and least privilege relate to access control over personnel, and defense in depth refers to layered security architecture, none of which directly address over-collection of personal data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"An organization outsources credit card processing to Vendor A. Without informing the organization, Vendor A subcontracts a portion of the processing infrastructure to Cloud Provider B, which experiences a breach exposing customer data. Which contractual provision, if included in the original agreement with Vendor A, would have best mitigated this specific risk?","o":["A mandatory disclosure and approval clause requiring notification and consent before engaging any subcontractor (flow-down/fourth-party clause)","A clause requiring Vendor A to maintain a minimum level of cyber liability insurance","A clause requiring Vendor A to provide an annual SOC 2 Type II report","A clause requiring Vendor A to conduct quarterly penetration testing of its own environment"],"c":0,"why":"The root cause was undisclosed fourth-party risk from an unapproved subcontractor; only a flow-down/subcontractor disclosure clause directly addresses that transitive risk. Insurance, SOC 2 reports, and penetration testing are valuable controls but do not prevent or surface unauthorized subcontracting.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"During an internal audit, a security team discovers several unmarked external hard drives containing highly sensitive research data stored in a shared office supply closet. Which control failure does this scenario BEST illustrate?","o":["Failure to apply proper media labeling and handling procedures based on classification","Failure to enforce multi-factor authentication on the research database","Failure to implement network segmentation between research and production systems","Failure to conduct a business impact analysis for the research department"],"c":0,"why":"Unmarked sensitive media stored in an unsecured, shared location indicates a breakdown in classification-based labeling and handling controls. The other options relate to unrelated control domains (authentication, network architecture, and BIA) not evidenced by this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"Within an organization's security governance hierarchy, which statement most accurately distinguishes a security standard from a security policy?","o":["A standard provides mandatory, specific, and measurable technical requirements that implement the intent stated in the higher-level policy","A policy provides mandatory technical detail, while a standard states only broad, discretionary intent","A standard is optional guidance that supplements a mandatory policy","A policy and a standard are interchangeable terms for the same governance document"],"c":0,"why":"Policies set high-level, management-approved intent (e.g., 'data must be encrypted in transit'), while standards translate that intent into mandatory, specific requirements (e.g., 'use TLS 1.2 or higher'). The distractors invert this relationship or falsely claim standards are optional or identical to policy.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization maintains a centralized system that tracks all hardware and software assets, their owners, classification levels, and locations throughout their lifecycle. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of maintaining this type of asset inventory?","o":["It eliminates the need for periodic vulnerability scanning","It ensures that all assets automatically receive the same security controls regardless of value","It enables the organization to apply appropriate, risk-based protections and track assets for accountability","It replaces the need for a formal data classification policy"],"c":2,"why":"An accurate asset inventory allows security teams to identify what needs protection, apply controls proportional to each asset's value/classification, and maintain accountability. It does not eliminate scanning needs, apply uniform controls to all assets, or replace classification policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis determines that the maximum tolerable downtime (MTD) for a critical order-processing application is 24 hours. The disaster recovery strategy is designed to achieve a recovery time objective (RTO) of 20 hours for restoring system functionality. What is the maximum allowable Work Recovery Time (WRT) remaining within the MTD?","o":["4 hours","20 hours","24 hours","44 hours"],"c":0,"why":"MTD = RTO + WRT, so WRT = MTD - RTO = 24 - 20 = 4 hours, the time remaining to verify data integrity and resume full business operations after systems are technically restored. The other values either restate RTO/MTD or incorrectly sum them.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A manufacturing firm develops a proprietary chemical formulation and decides to protect it through confidentiality controls rather than filing for a patent. Which characteristic of this intellectual property protection strategy requires the organization to maintain ongoing, reasonable security measures to preserve its legal protection?","o":["Trade secret protection is lost if the information is not actively and reasonably safeguarded from disclosure","Patent protection requires the same ongoing confidentiality measures as trade secrets","Copyright protection depends on continuous secrecy of the underlying idea","Trademark protection is automatically forfeited if a formulation is ever publicly disclosed"],"c":0,"why":"Trade secret status is legally contingent on the owner taking reasonable, continuous steps to maintain secrecy; disclosure without such protection can void the legal claim. Patents require public disclosure (not secrecy) in exchange for time-limited exclusivity, and copyrights/trademarks protect expression or branding, not confidentiality of an idea.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP-certified professional discovers that their employer is conducting unauthorized, undisclosed surveillance of employees' personal communications in a manner that violates applicable privacy law. Reporting this internally could jeopardize the professional's employment and violate an NDA, creating a conflict between loyalty to the employer and other obligations. According to the (ISC)² Code of Ethics, which canon takes precedence when the four canons conflict?","o":["Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure","Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally","Provide diligent and competent service to principals","Advance and protect the profession"],"c":0,"why":"The (ISC)² Code of Ethics explicitly states that Canon I (protecting society and the public good) takes precedence over the other canons when conflicts arise, even above obligations to an employer. The remaining canons are important but subordinate in a direct conflict.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D1","d":"hard","q":"After completing a formal risk assessment, an organization determines that residual risk of a data breach exceeds its stated risk appetite. Rather than implementing additional technical controls, management purchases a cyber liability insurance policy to cover breach notification costs and legal defense fees. Which risk treatment strategy is being applied, and what critical limitation should management understand?","o":["Risk transfer; insurance shifts financial impact to a third party but does not eliminate regulatory accountability, reputational damage, or the underlying vulnerability","Risk avoidance; purchasing insurance eliminates the risk of a breach entirely","Risk mitigation; insurance directly reduces the likelihood of a breach occurring","Risk acceptance; insurance is a passive strategy equivalent to taking no action"],"c":0,"why":"Purchasing insurance is a classic risk transfer strategy that shifts financial consequences to an insurer, but it does not remove legal/regulatory liability, reputational harm, or the technical vulnerability itself. Avoidance would mean ceasing the risky activity, mitigation would reduce likelihood/impact via controls, and acceptance implies no risk treatment action at all, none of which describe purchasing insurance.","link":"https://www.isc2.org/certifications/cissp"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is developing its data classification program. Which role is PRIMARILY responsible for assigning a classification level to a specific dataset and determining who may access it?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data processor","Security administrator"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner has business accountability for the data and decides its classification and access requirements. The custodian implements technical controls, the processor acts on the owner's behalf per contract, and the security administrator manages access controls per the owner's decisions rather than setting classification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company is decommissioning a batch of SSDs that stored highly confidential financial records. Due to wear-leveling and over-provisioning, traditional overwriting techniques may not reliably erase all data. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate to ensure the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Single-pass overwrite with zeros","Cryptographic erasure combined with physical destruction","Degaussing the drive","Formatting the drive at the OS level"],"c":1,"why":"SSDs' wear-leveling means overwriting cannot guarantee all physical blocks are addressed, so cryptographic erasure (destroying the encryption key) combined with physical destruction is the recommended NIST SP 800-88 approach. Degaussing is ineffective on flash media (no magnetic storage), and OS-level formatting or single overwrites do not reliably clear all data on SSDs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the concept of 'scoping' when applying a security control baseline to a system?","o":["Adding compensating controls to address unique organizational risks","Removing controls from the baseline that do not apply to the specific system or environment","Adjusting control parameters, such as password length, to meet organizational standards","Mapping controls to relevant regulatory requirements"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping involves removing baseline controls that are not applicable to a particular system, technology, or environment. Adjusting parameters is tailoring, adding compensating controls is a separate risk-treatment activity, and regulatory mapping is a compliance exercise, not scoping.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A government agency is retiring a solid-state drive (SSD) that stored data classified at the Secret level. The system administrator wants to sanitize the drive using a method appropriate for its sensitivity and consistent with NIST SP 800-88 guidance, taking into account the drive's storage technology. Which approach is most appropriate?","o":["Perform a single-pass overwrite of the entire drive using a standard disk-wiping utility","Degauss the drive using a high-coercivity degausser rated for magnetic media","Issue the drive's built-in ATA Secure Erase (cryptographic erase) command, then physically shred the drive","Perform a quick reformat and redeploy the drive to a lower-classification system"],"c":2,"why":"Because SSDs use wear-leveling, traditional overwriting cannot reliably reach all physical blocks, and degaussing is ineffective since SSDs are not magnetic media. For high-sensitivity data, NIST SP 800-88 recommends purge (e.g., cryptographic erase) combined with destroy; reformatting only removes file pointers and does not sanitize data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"During an internal audit, it is discovered that a business unit vice president determines the sensitivity level of a customer database, approves exceptions to standard access control policy, and is held accountable if the data is breached, while the IT operations team performs backups and applies encryption per her direction. Which role does the vice president fulfill?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data steward","Data processor"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner is the accountable business role that classifies data, approves access exceptions, and bears ultimate responsibility; the custodian implements technical controls (as IT operations does here), the steward focuses on data quality/context, and the processor acts on behalf of a controller under a contractual relationship.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization's data retention policy states that customer transaction records must be kept for seven years to meet regulatory requirements. After the retention period expires, what is the MOST appropriate action regarding this data?","o":["Retain the data indefinitely in case it is needed for future litigation","Securely destroy or sanitize the data in accordance with the disposal policy","Move the data to an unencrypted archive for cost savings","Transfer the data to a third party for long-term storage"],"c":1,"why":"Once the retention requirement is satisfied, data should be securely destroyed to minimize liability, storage costs, and privacy risk. Indefinite retention increases risk exposure, and moving to unencrypted storage or an uncontrolled third party without justification violates data protection principles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is developing a classification scheme for organizational data. What is the PRIMARY purpose of assigning classification levels to information?","o":["To determine the physical location where the data must be stored","To establish appropriate levels of protection based on the value and sensitivity of the data","To identify which vendor is responsible for backing up the data","To calculate the depreciation value of the data asset for accounting purposes"],"c":1,"why":"Data classification exists to ensure information receives protection commensurate with its sensitivity and value to the organization; storage location, vendor assignment, and accounting depreciation are unrelated to the security purpose of classification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization adopts the NIST SP 800-53 moderate-impact control baseline for a new system, then removes several controls that do not apply because the system has no wireless interfaces, and adjusts parameter values (e.g., password history) to align with internal policy. This activity is best described as which process?","o":["Scoping and tailoring","Control baselining","Gap analysis","Compensating control selection"],"c":0,"why":"Scoping removes inapplicable controls based on system characteristics, and tailoring adjusts control parameters to organizational needs; baselining is the initial selection of the standard control set, gap analysis compares current state to a target, and compensating controls are alternatives used when a control cannot be implemented as specified.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A healthcare organization stores patient records in a database that is accessed by an application server, which encrypts the data before writing it to disk. When a clinician views a patient's record on their workstation, the data is decrypted in memory. In which state is the data considered to be while displayed on the clinician's screen?","o":["Data at rest","Data in transit","Data in use","Data in archive"],"c":2,"why":"Data being actively processed, viewed, or manipulated in memory (e.g., displayed on screen or decrypted for use) is classified as data in use. Data at rest refers to stored data, data in transit refers to data moving across a network, and data in archive is not a standard classification state.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Within an organization's data governance structure, which role is PRIMARILY responsible for determining the classification level of a dataset and approving who may access it?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","System administrator","Security auditor"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (typically a business executive) has accountability for the data, sets its classification, and approves access; the custodian implements technical controls, the administrator maintains systems, and the auditor independently verifies compliance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to ensure that backup tapes containing top-secret data are protected against unauthorized disclosure while stored in an offsite facility. Which control provides the BEST protection for data confidentiality in this scenario?","o":["Physical access controls at the offsite facility only","Encryption of the data on the tapes combined with strict key management","Labeling the tapes with their classification level","Maintaining a chain-of-custody log for the tapes"],"c":1,"why":"Encryption with proper key management directly protects the confidentiality of the data itself, even if the tapes are physically compromised. Physical access controls, labeling, and chain-of-custody are important complementary controls but do not by themselves prevent disclosure if the tapes are stolen or improperly accessed.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm is evaluating technologies to protect the confidentiality of sensitive data while it is actively being processed in memory by a cloud-hosted analytics application. Which technology directly addresses this specific data state?","o":["TLS 1.3 for all client-to-application communications","AES-256 full-disk encryption on the underlying storage volumes","A hardware-based trusted execution environment (secure enclave)","Format-preserving encryption applied to database fields"],"c":2,"why":"A trusted execution environment isolates and encrypts data and code during active processing, protecting data in use; TLS protects data in transit, full-disk encryption protects data at rest, and format-preserving encryption protects stored field values but does not protect data being actively computed on in memory.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is developing a data classification scheme. What is the PRIMARY purpose of classifying data assets?","o":["To determine which employees are allowed to work remotely","To ensure that appropriate levels of protection are applied based on the sensitivity and value of the data","To satisfy annual audit checklist requirements only","To reduce the overall storage costs of the organization"],"c":1,"why":"Data classification exists so that security controls (access, encryption, handling) can be matched to the sensitivity and value of the information; the other options describe unrelated or secondary benefits, not the primary purpose.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) is advised that traditional degaussing will NOT reliably sanitize the media. What is the reason for this?","o":["SSDs use magnetic platters that require a much stronger degausser than standard equipment provides","SSDs store data in flash memory cells, which are not magnetic and are unaffected by degaussing","SSDs are physically too large to fit inside standard degaussing chambers","Degaussing automatically voids the manufacturer's warranty on SSDs"],"c":1,"why":"Degaussing works by disrupting magnetic fields on media like traditional hard disk drives; SSDs use non-magnetic flash memory, so degaussing has no effect on the stored data and cannot be relied upon for sanitization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which statement BEST describes the relationship between a data owner and a data processor under privacy regulations such as the GDPR?","o":["The data processor determines the purpose and means of processing personal data, while the owner merely stores it","The data owner (controller) determines the purpose and means of processing personal data, while the processor acts on the owner's instructions","The data processor and data owner have identical legal responsibilities under all circumstances","The data processor is only responsible for physical security of the data"],"c":1,"why":"Under GDPR terminology, the data controller (owner) determines why and how personal data is processed, while the processor handles the data strictly according to the controller's instructions. The other options reverse or oversimplify these distinct legal responsibilities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A security manager wants to calculate the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) for a critical database server to justify budget for a failover cluster. Which pair of values is required to calculate ALE directly?","o":["Asset Value (AV) and Exposure Factor (EF) only","Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) and Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO)","Total Cost of Ownership (TCO) and Return on Investment (ROI)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF) and Mean Time to Repair (MTTR)"],"c":1,"why":"ALE = SLE × ARO; SLE itself is derived from AV and EF, but ALE calculation directly requires SLE and ARO. TCO/ROI are financial metrics unrelated to loss expectancy, and MTBF/MTTR relate to reliability and availability, not annualized loss calculations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Who is typically responsible for determining the classification level of a specific dataset and approving who may access it?","o":["The data custodian","The data owner","The system administrator","The security auditor"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit manager) has accountability for the data and decides classification and access requirements; the custodian implements technical protection, and the administrator/auditor perform operational or oversight tasks, not classification decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is establishing a retention policy for financial transaction records. Which factor should PRIMARILY drive the length of the retention period?","o":["The amount of storage capacity currently available","Applicable legal and regulatory requirements","The personal preference of the IT department","The average length of employee tenure at the company"],"c":1,"why":"Retention periods must be driven by legal, regulatory, and contractual obligations to ensure compliance and support potential litigation or audits; storage capacity, department preference, and employee tenure are not appropriate or defensible drivers.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm is decommissioning a batch of self-encrypting solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained regulated customer financial data. The security team must select a sanitization method that satisfies NIST SP 800-88 guidance while remaining cost-effective and verifiable. Which method is MOST appropriate?","o":["Overwrite the drive three times using a DoD 5220.22-M pattern-based wipe utility","Perform cryptographic erasure by destroying the drive's internal encryption key, followed by verification that data is unrecoverable","Degauss the drive using a high-coercivity degausser rated for magnetic media","Reformat the drive using the operating system's quick format utility and reissue it to another department"],"c":1,"why":"SSDs use flash memory and wear-leveling, making traditional overwrite patterns unreliable and degaussing ineffective (SSDs are not magnetic media); NIST SP 800-88 recognizes cryptographic erasure as an effective purge method for self-encrypting drives when the key is properly destroyed and verified. Quick formatting does not remove data at all.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's records retention policy requires deletion of email older than three years. During active litigation, legal counsel issues a litigation hold requiring preservation of all records related to the matter, including emails that are already past the three-year retention period. What should the organization do?","o":["Delete the emails as scheduled since the retention policy takes precedence over informal legal requests","Suspend deletion of all records subject to the litigation hold, regardless of the standard retention schedule","Delete only the portions of emails unrelated to the litigation and retain the rest for exactly three years","Encrypt the emails and then delete them to satisfy both retention and preservation requirements"],"c":1,"why":"A litigation hold legally overrides normal retention schedules for any records relevant to the matter; failure to preserve them can result in spoliation sanctions. Deleting or partially deleting relevant records, even if encrypted first, would destroy evidence and violate the hold.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization classifies its information assets using a tiered scheme (e.g., Public, Internal, Confidential, Restricted). Which of the following is the MOST important reason for maintaining accurate classification labels throughout an asset's lifecycle?","o":["To satisfy audit checklist requirements without operational impact","To ensure appropriate handling, access controls, and protection measures are applied consistently","To simplify inventory management and reduce storage costs","To allow marketing teams to prioritize which data to publish externally"],"c":1,"why":"Accurate, consistent classification ensures that handling procedures, access restrictions, and protective controls match the sensitivity of the asset throughout its lifecycle, which is the core purpose of classification. The other options describe secondary or unrelated benefits, not the primary security rationale.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company is decommissioning old magnetic tape backups that contain highly sensitive financial records. Which sanitization method provides the HIGHEST assurance that data cannot be recovered from the tapes?","o":["Deleting the file index and reformatting the tapes","Overwriting the tapes with random data once","Degaussing the tapes with an appropriate strength magnetic field","Compressing the data files before disposal"],"c":2,"why":"Degaussing exposes magnetic media to a strong magnetic field that destroys the data pattern, providing strong assurance for magnetic tape; deleting/reformatting only removes pointers, and a single overwrite is less reliable for tape and compression does not remove data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company transmits sensitive customer records between two data centers over a public wide area network link. Which control BEST protects the confidentiality of this data while it is in transit?","o":["Full disk encryption on the destination servers","Applying a 'Confidential' classification label to the files","Encrypting the network traffic using TLS","Restricting file share access using access control lists"],"c":2,"why":"TLS encrypts data as it moves across the network, directly protecting confidentiality of data in transit; disk encryption and ACLs protect data at rest or access at the destination, and labeling alone provides no cryptographic protection.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's data classification policy assigns a data owner to each information asset. During an audit, the auditor finds that a database administrator (DBA) has been unilaterally deciding which departments can access a customer database and setting its retention period. Which statement BEST describes the governance failure?","o":["The DBA is correctly performing custodial duties, and no failure has occurred since custodians commonly set retention periods","The DBA has assumed data owner responsibilities, which should rest with a business-accountable individual who determines classification, access authorization, and retention requirements","The DBA has violated separation of duties by also acting as a data processor under privacy regulations","The DBA should be reclassified as a data steward, since stewards are responsible for setting access control policy"],"c":1,"why":"Data owners (typically business unit leaders) are accountable for classification, approving access, and setting retention; custodians (like DBAs) implement technical controls but do not set policy. The DBA overstepping into ownership decisions is the core issue, not a separation-of-duties or processor/steward mislabeling.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A company runs virtual machines on an IaaS provider's infrastructure. When a VM is decommissioned, who is responsible for ensuring the data stored on the underlying physical media is properly sanitized?","o":["The cloud customer alone, since they own the data","The cloud provider alone, since they control the physical hardware","A shared responsibility, where the customer cryptographically erases data before deallocation and the provider contractually ensures physical media destruction","Neither party, since IaaS contracts typically exclude data sanitization obligations"],"c":2,"why":"In IaaS, the customer typically cannot physically access or destroy hardware, so it should cryptographically erase data before releasing resources, while the provider is contractually obligated to sanitize or destroy physical media per the shared responsibility model; sole responsibility resting with either party alone is inconsistent with standard IaaS practice.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization adopts a published security control baseline and then removes all controls related to environmental and physical data center security because it uses only cloud-hosted infrastructure with no on-premises facilities. This activity is an example of:","o":["Scoping","Data classification","Certification","Data minimization"],"c":0,"why":"Scoping is the process of determining which baseline controls are relevant and applicable to the organization's specific environment, allowing removal of controls that do not apply; tailoring would involve modifying remaining controls, not eliminating irrelevant categories.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A multinational corporation classifies data using four tiers: Public, Internal, Confidential, and Restricted. During a security control baseline review, the security architect recommends applying the full NIST SP 800-53 High baseline uniformly to all Confidential-tagged systems regardless of actual risk exposure, cost, or system function. A peer reviewer objects. What is the MOST accurate criticism of the architect's approach?","o":["The architect failed to perform scoping and tailoring, which should adjust the baseline controls based on system-specific risk factors, environment, and operational constraints","The architect should have used the Low baseline instead, since Confidential data does not warrant High-baseline controls under any circumstance","The architect violated the principle of least privilege by applying controls uniformly across systems","The architect should have applied the Moderate baseline instead, since NIST reserves High baselines exclusively for Top Secret data"],"c":0,"why":"Applying a baseline uniformly without scoping and tailoring ignores that baselines are starting points meant to be adjusted for specific risk context, environment, and mission needs; blanket application can be both under- and over-protective. The other options misstate NIST baseline mapping rules and misapply unrelated principles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the concept of protecting 'data in use'?","o":["Encrypting a database backup file stored on an offsite server","Applying TLS to protect data sent between a web browser and a server","Restricting and monitoring access to data actively being processed in memory by an application","Applying access control lists to a file share containing archived reports"],"c":2,"why":"'Data in use' refers to data actively being processed in memory/CPU, requiring controls like memory protection and access restriction during processing; the other options describe data at rest or data in transit protections.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A five-year-old document originally classified as Confidential is reviewed under the organization's periodic classification review process and determined to no longer meet the criteria for that classification level due to the passage of time and reduced sensitivity. What is this process called, and what is required to properly execute it?","o":["Declassification, which must be authorized by the data owner following a formal, documented review","Downgrading, which any custodian may perform informally if no compromise has been observed","Sanitization, which only requires purge-level media sanitization of the storage device","Relabeling, which occurs automatically once the retention schedule for the document expires"],"c":0,"why":"Declassification (or downgrading) must follow a formal, authorized review process controlled by the data owner to ensure the reduced sensitivity determination is valid and documented; informal custodian decisions, media sanitization, and automatic retention-based relabeling do not constitute a valid classification change process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following data elements is generally considered personally identifiable information (PII)?","o":["A company's stock ticker symbol","An individual's Social Security number","A product's stock-keeping unit (SKU) code","The internal IP address of a shared print server"],"c":1,"why":"A Social Security number can directly identify a specific individual and is a classic example of PII; stock symbols, SKUs, and internal device IP addresses do not identify a specific person.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization's data retention policy specifies how long different types of records must be kept before secure destruction. What is the PRIMARY reason for defining a maximum retention period rather than keeping all data indefinitely?","o":["To comply with legal, regulatory, and business requirements while minimizing exposure and storage costs of unnecessary data","To make backup processes faster regardless of data type","To ensure employees cannot access historical records","To increase the resale value of retired storage media"],"c":0,"why":"Retention limits balance legal/regulatory obligations with the risk and cost of retaining data longer than necessary; the other options are not the primary drivers behind retention policies.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements full-disk encryption on all laptops and TLS for all network communications. During a penetration test, the tester extracts sensitive plaintext data directly from a running application's process memory on an employee's laptop. Which data protection gap does this scenario illustrate?","o":["Failure to encrypt data at rest, since full-disk encryption was improperly configured","Failure to protect data in transit, since TLS termination exposed plaintext on the endpoint","Failure to protect data in use, since data being actively processed in memory was not addressed by the existing controls","Failure to apply data masking, since the application should have tokenized the sensitive fields before display"],"c":2,"why":"Full-disk encryption protects data at rest (decrypted only while the system is unlocked and running) and TLS protects data in transit, but neither protects data actively being processed in memory (data in use), which requires controls like secure enclaves, memory encryption, or application-level protections. Masking/tokenization is a distinct control not implied by the scenario's requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Employees are required to affix a printed sticker reading 'Confidential' to binders and USB drives containing sensitive HR documents before they leave the office. This practice is an example of which concept?","o":["Data classification","Data labeling/marking","Data masking","Data minimization"],"c":1,"why":"Labeling or marking is the physical or logical act of indicating an asset's classification so handlers know how to treat it; classification is the underlying decision process, masking hides data values, and minimization reduces the amount of data collected or retained.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A security team is building an asset inventory as part of an asset management program. Which of the following is the MOST important reason for maintaining an accurate and current asset inventory?","o":["It allows the organization to know what needs to be protected and to apply appropriate security controls","It is only needed to satisfy vendor licensing audits","It replaces the need for a data classification policy","It eliminates the need for periodic risk assessments"],"c":0,"why":"You cannot protect what you don't know you have; an accurate inventory is foundational to identifying assets requiring protection and appropriate controls. The other options misstate the purpose or overstate what inventory alone accomplishes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A company's records retention policy requires deletion of customer support emails after three years. Twelve months into that retention period, legal counsel issues a litigation hold notice related to a pending lawsuit involving several customers whose emails fall within the affected date range. The records management team proceeds to delete the emails per the standard retention schedule when the three-year mark is reached. What is the PRIMARY security and legal governance failure in this scenario?","o":["The retention policy itself was noncompliant, since three years is too short a retention period for customer support communications","The organization failed to suspend normal retention/destruction schedules for records subject to a legal hold, which overrides standard retention policy","The records management team should have extended the retention period to five years automatically upon any litigation notice","The failure is solely attributable to legal counsel for not physically removing the records from the retention system"],"c":1,"why":"A litigation hold legally suspends normal destruction schedules for relevant records until the hold is lifted, regardless of the standard retention policy; failing to implement this suspension constitutes spoliation risk. The retention period length itself is not inherently the issue, and responsibility for implementing the hold operationally lies with records management/IT, not solely legal.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Under a typical privacy framework such as the GDPR, which entity determines the purposes and means of processing personal data, and is therefore held primarily accountable for compliance?","o":["The data processor","The data subject","The data controller","The data custodian"],"c":2,"why":"The data controller decides why and how personal data is processed and bears primary compliance accountability; the processor acts on the controller's instructions, the data subject is the individual whose data is processed, and 'data custodian' is not a formal GDPR role.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"During asset valuation for a business impact analysis, a security analyst calculates that a specific database server has an Asset Value (AV) of $500,000, an Exposure Factor (EF) of 40% for a specific ransomware threat, and an Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) of 0.5. What is the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE), and what does this value PRIMARILY support in asset security decision-making?","o":["$100,000; it directly determines the exact insurance premium the organization must purchase","$100,000; it provides a quantitative basis for comparing the cost of safeguards against the expected annual loss to justify security investment","$200,000; it directly determines the exact insurance premium the organization must purchase","$200,000; it provides a quantitative basis for comparing the cost of safeguards against the expected annual loss to justify security investment"],"c":1,"why":"SLE = AV × EF = $500,000 × 0.40 = $200,000; ALE = SLE × ARO = $200,000 × 0.5 = $100,000. ALE supports cost-benefit analysis for safeguard selection (comparing safeguard cost to ALE reduction), not direct insurance premium determination, which involves additional actuarial factors.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is disposing of solid-state drives (SSDs) that once stored classified information. Why is degaussing generally NOT an effective sanitization method for SSDs?","o":["SSDs store data using flash memory cells rather than magnetic media, so degaussing has no effect on the stored data","Degaussing is too expensive to use on SSDs","SSDs are immune to all forms of data recovery after normal deletion","Degaussing only works on optical media, not on any electronic storage"],"c":0,"why":"SSDs use non-magnetic flash memory cells, so degaussing (which relies on disrupting magnetic fields) does not erase the data; proper sanitization requires methods like cryptographic erase, secure erase commands, or physical destruction. The other options are factually incorrect.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A healthcare organization is designing a data minimization program to comply with privacy regulations. An analytics team requests full, unmasked patient records, including Social Security numbers and full medical histories, to build a predictive model for hospital readmission risk, though the model only requires age ranges, diagnosis codes, and prior admission counts. What privacy principle is MOST directly violated if the request is approved as-is?","o":["Purpose specification, since the analytics team has not documented an intended use for the data","Data minimization, since the request seeks more data elements than necessary to achieve the stated processing purpose","Accountability, since no data processing agreement has been signed with the analytics team","Consent, since patients were never asked whether their data could be used for analytics purposes"],"c":1,"why":"Data minimization requires limiting collection/use of personal data to what is necessary for the stated purpose; here, unmasked identifiers and full histories exceed what the readmission model requires. A purpose was stated (readmission prediction), so purpose specification is not violated, and while consent/accountability could be relevant, the scenario specifically highlights excessive data scope.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization stores backup tapes containing highly sensitive intellectual property at an offsite facility managed by a third party. The security team wants to ensure that even if the offsite facility experiences a physical security breach and tapes are stolen, the data remains protected. Which control provides the MOST effective protection against this specific risk?","o":["Requiring the offsite facility to implement biometric access controls and 24/7 CCTV monitoring","Encrypting backup data before it is written to tape, with keys managed and stored separately from the offsite facility","Implementing a chain-of-custody log that tracks every individual who handles the tapes during transport and storage","Reducing the retention period for backup tapes to minimize the window of exposure to theft"],"c":1,"why":"Encrypting data at rest with keys stored separately ensures that even if physical media is stolen, the data itself remains inaccessible, directly mitigating the confidentiality risk. Physical access controls, chain-of-custody logs, and shorter retention reduce likelihood or aid investigation but do not protect the data itself once physical possession is lost.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A financial services firm is establishing classification levels for its datasets based on potential impact from unauthorized disclosure. Which factor should be the PRIMARY basis for assigning a classification level to a dataset?","o":["The cost of the storage media used to hold the data","The potential harm to the organization if the data's confidentiality is compromised","The age of the data since its creation","The department or business unit that originally created the data"],"c":1,"why":"Classification levels are driven by the impact/harm that would result from unauthorized disclosure, loss, or alteration of the data, not by storage cost, age, or the originating department, which are irrelevant to sensitivity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"In a formal data governance program, who is responsible for determining the classification level of a dataset and approving or denying access requests to it?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","System administrator","End user"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a senior business manager) has ultimate accountability for classifying data and approving access; the custodian implements technical controls, while administrators and users merely operate within those controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is decommissioning solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored top-secret research data. According to NIST SP 800-88 sanitization guidelines, which method provides the HIGHEST assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["A single-pass overwrite using disk-wiping software","Cryptographic erase of the encryption key used to protect the data","Physical destruction of the media, such as shredding or incineration","Reformatting the drive using the operating system's built-in format utility"],"c":2,"why":"For the highest sensitivity data, physical destruction offers the greatest assurance against recovery, especially since SSD wear-leveling can make overwrite-based clearing unreliable; formatting does not remove underlying data, and cryptographic erase, while effective, is generally considered a 'purge' method with slightly less assurance than physical destruction for top-secret information.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which term best describes the process of assigning a sensitivity level (such as Confidential, Internal, or Public) to information based on its value and the impact of its unauthorized disclosure?","o":["Data classification","Data mapping","Data normalization","Data deduplication"],"c":0,"why":"Data classification is the process of categorizing information according to sensitivity and impact. Data mapping tracks data flows, normalization organizes database structure, and deduplication removes redundant copies—none relate to sensitivity labeling.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"In an organization's data governance model, who is typically responsible for making day-to-day decisions about who may access a specific dataset and for ensuring it is properly classified?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data processor","System administrator"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit leader) has ultimate accountability for classifying data and approving access decisions. The custodian implements technical controls, the processor handles data on behalf of another entity, and the system administrator manages infrastructure but does not own data decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which phase of the data lifecycle primarily involves determining how long data must be retained to meet legal, regulatory, or business requirements before it is eventually destroyed?","o":["Creation","Usage","Archival","Destruction"],"c":2,"why":"The archival phase focuses on retention decisions and ensuring data remains accessible for compliance purposes; creation and usage occur earlier in the lifecycle, and destruction is the final disposal step after retention requirements are satisfied.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is decommissioning old spinning hard disk drives that once stored highly sensitive financial records. Which method provides the highest assurance that data cannot be recovered before the drives are reused within the company?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive using a quick format","Overwriting the entire drive multiple times with a verified wiping utility","Renaming the sensitive files to obscure their contents"],"c":2,"why":"A verified multi-pass overwrite (or cryptographic erasure/degaussing/physical destruction) is required to ensure data remanence does not allow recovery. Simple deletion, quick formatting, and renaming only remove pointers or labels, leaving the actual data recoverable with forensic tools.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization adopts NIST SP 800-53 as its control baseline, then removes controls that do not apply to its cloud-only architecture and adds supplemental controls to satisfy a specific regulatory requirement. This activity is best described as:","o":["Baselining","Scoping and tailoring","Gap analysis","Risk transference"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping removes irrelevant controls based on environment, and tailoring adjusts or adds controls to meet specific needs; baselining is selecting the initial standard, gap analysis compares current state to a target, and risk transference shifts risk to a third party.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the purpose of a data retention policy?","o":["To define how long records must be kept before secure disposal, based on legal, regulatory, and business needs","To specify which encryption algorithm must be used for stored data","To determine which employees are authorized to access a database","To establish the physical location where backup tapes are stored"],"c":0,"why":"A retention policy governs how long data must be preserved and when it should be securely destroyed, driven by compliance and business requirements. The other options describe encryption standards, access control, and storage location—separate concerns from retention.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A healthcare company needs to protect the confidentiality of patient data while it is actively being processed by an application in server memory. Which technology BEST addresses this requirement for data in use?","o":["Full disk encryption","TLS 1.3","A trusted execution environment (secure enclave)","IPsec VPN"],"c":2,"why":"Trusted execution environments and secure enclaves protect data while it is being actively processed in memory; full disk encryption protects data at rest, and TLS/IPsec protect data in transit.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company labels a database containing customer social security numbers as 'Restricted' and applies encryption, strict access controls, and audit logging. This labeling and set of protections is an example of which security concept?","o":["Baseline configuration","Asset classification and handling","Security through obscurity","Least functionality"],"c":1,"why":"Assigning a sensitivity label and applying corresponding protective controls is the essence of asset classification and handling. A baseline is a minimum security configuration standard, security through obscurity relies on secrecy of design rather than labeling, and least functionality refers to disabling unnecessary services.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company receives a formal legal hold notice related to pending litigation. Several records subject to the hold are scheduled for destruction under the normal retention policy. What is the MOST appropriate action?","o":["Continue destroying the records as scheduled since policy takes precedence","Immediately suspend destruction of the relevant records until the legal hold is lifted","Encrypt the records instead of destroying them and continue the retention schedule","Transfer ownership of the records to outside legal counsel"],"c":1,"why":"A legal hold legally obligates an organization to preserve potentially relevant records and suspend normal destruction schedules to avoid spoliation of evidence; ignoring the hold or merely encrypting the data does not satisfy the preservation obligation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is considered Personally Identifiable Information (PII) under most privacy frameworks?","o":["A company's annual revenue figures","An individual's Social Security number","A server's IP address used only for internal routing","The name of a software product"],"c":1,"why":"A Social Security number can directly identify a specific individual, making it PII. Company revenue, internal IP addresses, and product names are not tied to identifying a specific person.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An employee must transport backup tapes labeled 'Confidential' to an offsite storage facility. Which control set is MOST appropriate for this transfer?","o":["Send the tapes via standard courier service with no additional controls","Encrypt the tapes and use a bonded courier with documented chain-of-custody","Relabel the tapes as 'Public' so they attract less attention in transit","Allow the employee to store the tapes overnight in a personal vehicle before delivery"],"c":1,"why":"Confidential media in transit requires encryption plus a trusted, accountable transport method with chain-of-custody documentation; mislabeling, unsecured transport, or leaving media unattended violates proper handling requirements for sensitive assets.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Data that is actively being processed in a computer's RAM and CPU registers is best described as being in which state?","o":["Data at rest","Data in transit","Data in use","Data in archive"],"c":2,"why":"Data being actively processed in memory or by the CPU is 'data in use.' Data at rest refers to stored data, data in transit refers to data moving across a network, and 'data in archive' is not a standard data-state category.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is developing a data classification scheme for its intellectual property. Which of the following best describes the PRIMARY purpose of assigning classification levels to information assets?","o":["To determine the appropriate level of protection controls based on the value and sensitivity of the data","To establish the retention period required for regulatory compliance","To identify which employees are permitted to access the corporate network","To determine the physical location where data should be stored"],"c":0,"why":"Classification exists so that protection resources (encryption, access controls, handling procedures) are applied proportionally to the sensitivity and value of the data. Retention periods, network access, and storage location may be influenced by classification but are not its primary purpose.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization adopts the NIST SP 800-53 control catalog as its baseline, then removes controls related to satellite communications because it has no satellite systems. This activity is an example of which process?","o":["Scoping and tailoring","Data classification","Configuration management","Change control"],"c":0,"why":"Scoping and tailoring involves adjusting a security control baseline to fit the organization's specific environment by removing irrelevant controls or adding needed ones. Data classification concerns sensitivity labeling, configuration management concerns system settings, and change control governs approval of modifications.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary purpose of a data classification scheme within an organization?","o":["To assign monetary value to each hardware asset for insurance purposes","To ensure that information receives a level of protection commensurate with its sensitivity and value","To satisfy auditors that a written policy exists, regardless of implementation","To determine which employees are allowed to take vacation during peak business periods"],"c":1,"why":"Data classification exists so that information is protected according to its sensitivity and business value; the other options either misstate the purpose (insurance valuation, HR scheduling) or reduce classification to a paperwork exercise rather than an operational control.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A financial services firm designates a Data Owner, a Data Custodian, and a Data Steward for its customer records. Which statement correctly distinguishes these roles?","o":["The Data Owner performs day-to-day technical backups while the Custodian sets business classification levels","The Data Custodian is accountable to regulators for data breaches, while the Owner performs encryption key management","The Data Owner makes decisions about classification and access authorization, while the Custodian implements technical controls to protect the data per the Owner's direction","The Data Steward has final legal accountability for the data, superseding the Owner's authority"],"c":2,"why":"The Data Owner (typically a business executive) is accountable for classification and access decisions; the Custodian carries out technical safeguards on the Owner's behalf. The Steward focuses on data quality/context, not legal accountability, and does not supersede the Owner.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to protect sensitive database records that are actively being processed by an application in server memory. Which state of data is being protected, and what is the MOST appropriate control?","o":["Data at rest; protect using full-disk encryption","Data in transit; protect using TLS 1.2 or higher","Data in use; protect using techniques such as memory encryption or secure enclaves","Data in transit; protect using IPsec tunneling"],"c":2,"why":"Data actively being processed in memory is 'data in use,' which requires controls like secure enclaves or memory encryption since traditional at-rest or in-transit encryption does not protect data while it is being computed on.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization has designated a specific business unit manager who is accountable for approving access requests and determining the classification level of a customer database. Which role does this person hold?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data processor","System administrator"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner is the accountable party who determines classification and approves access; the custodian implements technical protections, the processor handles data on behalf of a controller, and the system administrator manages infrastructure but does not set classification or access policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A database administrator is responsible for performing daily backups, applying security patches, and implementing access controls on a classified dataset as instructed by the data owner. Which role best describes this individual?","o":["Data owner","Data custodian","Data controller","Business owner"],"c":1,"why":"The custodian performs the day-to-day technical tasks of protecting data (backups, patching, access control implementation) under the direction of the owner; the owner sets policy rather than performing hands-on tasks, and 'data controller' and 'business owner' describe different governance roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company is decommissioning several SSDs that stored highly classified data. Due to wear-leveling and over-provisioning inherent in SSD architecture, which sanitization approach provides the MOST reliable assurance of data destruction?","o":["Performing a single-pass overwrite using a standard disk-wipe utility","Deleting all files and then reformatting the drive","Physical destruction of the drive (e.g., shredding or disintegration)","Running the built-in 'quick format' option twice"],"c":2,"why":"Because SSD wear-leveling can leave data in inaccessible over-provisioned blocks, software-based overwriting cannot guarantee complete erasure; physical destruction is the most reliable method for highly classified data. Deletion, formatting, and simple overwrites do not reliably sanitize flash-based media.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization's records retention policy states that financial transaction logs must be kept for seven years to comply with regulatory requirements. Two years after the retention period ends, an audit discovers the logs are still being stored. From an asset security perspective, what is the PRIMARY risk this creates?","o":["The organization may be legally required to disclose the outdated logs during unrelated litigation, increasing liability exposure","The logs will automatically become corrupted after the retention period","Storage costs will decrease because the data is no longer actively used","The classification level of the logs will automatically downgrade"],"c":0,"why":"Retaining data beyond its required period increases legal discovery exposure and liability, since it may need to be produced in litigation. The other options are incorrect assumptions—retention beyond policy does not cause corruption, decrease costs, or auto-downgrade classification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Why do organizations establish formal data retention policies?","o":["To ensure all data is kept indefinitely to maximize its potential future business value","To meet legal, regulatory, and business requirements while minimizing unnecessary storage of data that increases liability","To guarantee that backup tapes are never reused","To eliminate the need for data classification"],"c":1,"why":"Retention policies balance legal/regulatory/business needs against the risk and cost of retaining data longer than necessary; indefinite retention increases liability and storage cost, and retention policy does not eliminate classification or dictate tape reuse specifically.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company classifies data as Public, Internal, Confidential, and Restricted. An employee needs to email a spreadsheet classified as 'Confidential' to an external business partner as part of a contractual data-sharing agreement. What is the MOST appropriate control to apply BEFORE sending the file?","o":["Downgrade the classification to 'Public' since it is being shared externally","Encrypt the file and use a secure transmission method per the organization's handling standards for that classification level","Rename the file to obscure its contents before sending it via unencrypted email","Send the file with a verbal warning to the recipient not to forward it"],"c":1,"why":"Handling standards for classified data typically require encryption and secure transmission channels appropriate to the classification level, regardless of the recipient being external. Downgrading classification, renaming files, or relying on verbal agreements does not provide adequate technical protection.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Under common privacy frameworks such as the GDPR, an organization that determines the purposes and means of processing personal data, even though it hires a third-party cloud provider to actually store and process that data, is best described as the:","o":["Data processor","Data subject","Data controller","Data custodian"],"c":2,"why":"The data controller determines the purposes and means of processing, regardless of who physically handles the data; the processor acts on the controller's instructions, the data subject is the individual the data is about, and 'custodian' is a general security term not the specific privacy-law role.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization stores backup tapes containing Restricted data at an off-site facility. Which of the following controls is MOST important to include in the media handling procedures to maintain the confidentiality and integrity of this data throughout its lifecycle?","o":["Ensuring the off-site facility has fire suppression systems only","Maintaining a chain-of-custody log documenting each transfer, access, and handling event for the media","Labeling the tapes with a lower classification to avoid drawing attention","Storing the tapes without encryption to allow faster restoration in emergencies"],"c":1,"why":"Chain-of-custody documentation ensures accountability and traceability for classified media throughout transport, storage, and retrieval, supporting both confidentiality and integrity. Fire suppression alone doesn't address confidentiality, mislabeling violates classification policy, and storing unencrypted data increases risk of exposure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to protect sensitive customer records stored on a file server from unauthorized disclosure even if the physical disks are stolen. Which control most directly addresses this risk for data at rest?","o":["Transport Layer Security (TLS) for network connections","Full-disk or file-level encryption","Network intrusion detection system (IDS)","Multi-factor authentication for remote VPN access"],"c":1,"why":"Encrypting data at rest protects information stored on the disk itself, so it remains unreadable even if physical media is stolen; TLS protects data in transit, IDS detects network attacks, and MFA controls authentication rather than protecting stored data confidentiality.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization adopts an industry-standard security control baseline (e.g., NIST SP 800-53) and then removes controls that do not apply to its environment while adding controls needed for specific regulatory obligations. This process is known as:","o":["Scoping and tailoring","Data classification","Configuration management","Asset valuation"],"c":0,"why":"Scoping and tailoring is the process of adjusting a security control baseline to fit an organization's specific environment and requirements; classification labels data sensitivity, configuration management tracks system changes, and asset valuation assesses the worth of assets, none of which describe baseline adaptation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored data classified as Top Secret. The security team must select a sanitization approach that is both effective and appropriate for the media type per NIST SP 800-88 guidance. Which approach should be used?","o":["Degauss the drives using a high-coercivity magnetic degausser rated for the media","Perform a single-pass overwrite of all sectors with zeros using standard disk utilities","Use cryptographic erasure by destroying the encryption keys, followed by physical destruction of the drives","Perform a quick format of the drives and reissue them to a lower-classification environment"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory, not magnetic storage, so degaussing is ineffective and simple overwrites may miss data due to wear-leveling and over-provisioning; NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase combined with physical destruction for high-sensitivity data on SSDs. Formatting does not sanitize underlying data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm is deploying a new application that processes customer PII. According to standard data governance role definitions, which statement correctly describes the division of responsibilities between the data owner and the data custodian?","o":["The data custodian determines the classification level and approves access requests, while the data owner implements the technical controls that enforce those decisions","The data owner determines the classification level and approves access requests, while the data custodian implements the technical controls that enforce those decisions","The data processor determines the classification level, while the data steward is responsible for approving all access requests and implementing controls","The system administrator determines the classification level, while the data owner is responsible only for day-to-day technical implementation of controls"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (typically a business executive) has ultimate accountability for classifying data and approving access, while the data custodian (often IT operations) implements and maintains the technical controls (encryption, backups, access enforcement) as directed by the owner. The other options reverse or misassign these responsibilities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's records retention policy requires that email older than three years be automatically purged. Legal counsel has just issued a litigation hold notice identifying a specific set of email accounts relevant to pending litigation, some of which contain messages older than three years. What is the correct action?","o":["Continue the automated purge as scheduled, since the retention policy is a mandatory organizational control that supersedes ad hoc legal requests","Suspend the automated purge only for the records identified in the litigation hold until the hold is lifted, while continuing normal retention processing for unaffected records","Purge all email older than three years except messages explicitly named as evidence in the lawsuit's discovery request","Immediately export all email system-wide to an offline archive and disable automated retention processing organization-wide"],"c":1,"why":"A litigation hold legally overrides normal retention/destruction schedules for the specific records in scope; failing to suspend deletion can result in spoliation sanctions. Continuing to purge held records is legally risky, and unnecessarily halting all retention processing organization-wide is overly broad and operationally disruptive.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A company based in the European Union wants to transfer personal data of EU residents to a cloud service provider located in a country that has not received an adequacy decision from the European Commission. Which mechanism should the company primarily rely on to ensure the transfer is lawful under GDPR?","o":["Obtain a written assurance from the provider that they will handle the data responsibly","Rely solely on the provider's ISO/IEC 27001 certification as sufficient legal basis for transfer","Implement Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs) supplemented with appropriate technical and organizational measures based on a transfer risk assessment","Encrypt the data only while it is in transit over the network to the provider"],"c":2,"why":"In the absence of an adequacy decision, GDPR requires an approved transfer mechanism such as SCCs, and following the Schrems II ruling, organizations must also conduct a transfer impact assessment and apply supplementary measures. Certifications, informal assurances, and transit-only encryption do not by themselves satisfy GDPR's legal transfer requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored highly confidential client financial records. The security team initially proposes using a degausser, as is done for the firm's legacy magnetic hard drives. Which of the following statements BEST explains the appropriate action and reasoning?","o":["Degaussing is appropriate because SSDs use magnetic platters similar to HDDs, so the same equipment can be used.","Degaussing is ineffective on SSDs because they use non-volatile flash memory rather than magnetic storage; cryptographic erase combined with physical destruction is more appropriate.","A single-pass overwrite using specialized SSD software guarantees complete sanitization equivalent to degaussing on HDDs.","SSDs do not require sanitization because flash memory automatically overwrites deleted data within 24 hours."],"c":1,"why":"SSDs store data in flash memory cells, not magnetic media, so degaussing has no effect; NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase and/or physical destruction for flash-based media due to wear-leveling, which can leave data in blocks inaccessible to standard overwrite commands.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A US-based company hires an external payroll vendor to process its employees' payroll data. The vendor stores and processes the data strictly according to written instructions provided by the company and has no authority to use the data for any other purpose. Under data protection frameworks such as GDPR, which term BEST describes the vendor's role?","o":["Data owner","Data controller","Data processor","Data custodian"],"c":2,"why":"A data processor handles personal data on behalf of and under the instructions of a data controller (the company), without determining the purposes of processing; data controller and data owner describe the entity that determines the purpose and means of processing, and data custodian is an internal operational role, not the external vendor relationship described by GDPR terminology.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is classifying its information assets. Which role is primarily responsible for determining the appropriate classification level of a given data set and approving who may access it?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Security administrator","Database administrator"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit leader) has accountability for the data and decides its classification and access requirements; the custodian implements technical controls, while administrators handle day-to-day operations, not classification decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A security team is applying the NIST SP 800-53 moderate-impact baseline to a system. Because the system operates in a fully isolated environment with no external network connectivity, the team determines that several baseline controls related to network intrusion detection and remote access monitoring are not applicable and removes them from the control set. Which risk management activity does this represent?","o":["Scoping","Tailoring","Continuous monitoring","Gap analysis"],"c":0,"why":"Scoping is the process of determining which baseline controls apply to a system based on its specific characteristics (such as lack of connectivity), allowing inapplicable controls to be excluded. Tailoring refers to adjusting or supplementing controls (e.g., specifying parameters or adding compensating controls) rather than removing inapplicable ones; the other options describe unrelated activities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which role is primarily responsible for determining the classification level of a specific set of information and approving who may access it?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Security administrator","Data processor"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit leader) has ultimate accountability for classifying data and deciding access rights. The custodian implements controls, the administrator manages technical access, and the processor merely handles data on behalf of the owner/controller.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A healthcare analytics company must allow a third-party data science team to run computations on sensitive patient records, but wants to ensure that even personnel with root/administrator access to the processing server cannot view the plaintext data at any point, including during active computation in memory. Which technology best meets this requirement?","o":["Transparent Data Encryption (TDE) applied to the database at rest","TLS 1.3 encryption for all data transmitted to the processing server","A Trusted Execution Environment (TEE) or homomorphic encryption enabling computation on data without exposing plaintext in memory","Full-disk encryption on the storage volumes of the processing server"],"c":2,"why":"TEEs (secure enclaves) and homomorphic encryption specifically protect data in use, preventing exposure of plaintext even to privileged users with system access. TDE and full-disk encryption protect data at rest, and TLS protects data in transit—none of these protect data while it is being actively processed in memory.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is repurposing a set of hard drives that previously stored highly confidential financial records. The drives will remain within the organization but will be reassigned to a department that only handles public information. According to NIST SP 800-88 media sanitization guidance, which method is most appropriate?","o":["Clear the drives using a single-pass logical overwrite","Purge the drives using cryptographic erase or degaussing","Physically destroy the drives by shredding","Reformat the drives using the operating system's quick format utility"],"c":1,"why":"Purge provides a higher assurance level than Clear, appropriate when data confidentiality was high and the media is being repurposed to a lower classification use; Destroy is unnecessary since the drives will still be reused, and quick formatting or a single Clear pass does not provide sufficient assurance against advanced recovery techniques.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that when a hard drive is retired, no residual data can be recovered even with advanced forensic tools. Which method BEST achieves this?","o":["Deleting all files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive with a quick format","Performing a cryptographic erase or physical destruction of the drive","Overwriting the drive once with zeros"],"c":2,"why":"Cryptographic erase (destroying the encryption key) or physical destruction ensures data is unrecoverable, addressing data remanence. Deleting files or quick formatting only removes pointers, and a single overwrite pass may leave recoverable data on some media, especially SSDs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization needs to sanitize a set of legacy magnetic backup tapes containing regulated financial records before disposal. Which method is both effective and appropriate for this media type according to NIST SP 800-88 guidance?","o":["Cryptographic erasure by deleting the encryption keys used to protect the tape contents","Degaussing the tapes using a degausser with sufficient magnetic field strength rated for the media type","Overwriting the tapes three times with random data patterns using standard backup software","Physically shredding the tape cartridges into 2-inch pieces without any prior data destruction step"],"c":1,"why":"Degaussing is highly effective for magnetic media such as backup tapes because it directly disrupts the magnetic domains storing the data. Cryptographic erasure requires the data to have been encrypted originally with recoverable/destroyable keys, which may not apply to legacy tapes; overwriting magnetic tape is often impractical and unreliable; shredding without degaussing first is unnecessary given degaussing's effectiveness on this media type and NIST's guidance treats it as a valid standalone purge method for magnetic tape.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the MOST appropriate control to protect the confidentiality of sensitive data while it is being transmitted over a public network?","o":["Data masking","Encryption using a strong protocol such as TLS","Access control lists on the destination server","Data classification labeling"],"c":1,"why":"Encryption (e.g., TLS) protects data in transit from interception. Masking and labeling protect data at rest or in use, and ACLs control access at the destination but do not protect data while traveling across the network.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company's records retention policy schedules a set of email archives for permanent deletion next week. Legal counsel issues a litigation hold notice covering those same records due to pending litigation. What is the MOST appropriate action for the organization to take?","o":["Proceed with the scheduled deletion since the retention policy takes precedence","Suspend the scheduled destruction and preserve the records until the legal hold is lifted","Anonymize the records before deletion to satisfy both requirements","Transfer the records to a third party to avoid direct liability"],"c":1,"why":"A legal hold overrides normal retention/destruction schedules; failing to preserve relevant records during litigation can result in spoliation sanctions. Anonymizing or transferring the data would not satisfy the requirement to preserve the original records intact.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization adopts the NIST SP 800-53 moderate-impact control baseline for a new system. During implementation, the security team removes controls related to wireless access because the system has no wireless components, and separately adjusts the password history requirement from the baseline's default of 24 remembered passwords to 12, based on a documented risk assessment. What are these two activities called, respectively?","o":["Tailoring; scoping","Scoping; tailoring","Baselining; standardizing","Harmonization; customization"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping is the process of removing controls that do not apply to the system's environment (e.g., wireless controls where no wireless exists), while tailoring involves adjusting the parameters or specifications of applicable controls to fit organizational risk and requirements (e.g., changing the password history value).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An analyst combines several individually unclassified operational reports—none of which reveal sensitive information on their own—into a single summary document. The combined summary inadvertently exposes sensitive patterns about the organization's operations that no single source report revealed. This scenario is a classic example of which information security concept?","o":["Inference","Aggregation","Data remanence","Data diddling"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining multiple individually non-sensitive data elements produces a result that is more sensitive than any single element alone, as in this scenario. Inference involves deducing sensitive information indirectly through logical reasoning without directly combining the source data; the other two options are unrelated concepts (residual data after deletion, and unauthorized data alteration, respectively).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company's data retention policy requires that customer financial records be kept for seven years and then securely destroyed. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of enforcing the destruction portion of this policy?","o":["It reduces storage costs for the organization","It ensures compliance with marketing regulations","It minimizes the amount of sensitive data available for compromise, limiting liability","It improves the performance of backup systems"],"c":2,"why":"Destroying data once it is no longer needed reduces the attack surface and potential liability from breaches involving outdated data. Cost savings and performance are secondary benefits, not the primary security rationale, and it is unrelated to marketing regulations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A payment processor wants to reduce the scope of its PCI DSS environment by replacing stored primary account numbers (PANs) in its database with randomly generated surrogate values. These surrogate values must have no mathematical relationship to the original PAN and must be mapped back to the original value only through a secure, separately stored lookup table when a business need arises. Which technique satisfies this requirement?","o":["Format-preserving encryption","Salted cryptographic hashing","Tokenization","Data masking"],"c":2,"why":"Tokenization replaces sensitive data with a surrogate token that has no mathematical relationship to the original value, with the mapping maintained in a secure token vault; encryption (including format-preserving encryption) is reversible via a mathematical key relationship, hashing is one-way and non-reversible, and masking is typically used to obscure data for display rather than to enable secure retrieval.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"In the context of data protection, which term describes the organization that determines the purposes and means of processing personal data, and therefore bears the greatest legal responsibility for its protection?","o":["Data processor","Data subject","Data controller","Data custodian"],"c":2,"why":"The data controller decides why and how personal data is processed and holds primary legal accountability, such as under GDPR. The processor acts on the controller's instructions, the data subject is the individual the data is about, and the custodian handles day-to-day technical safeguarding.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A healthcare analytics firm wants to allow a third-party cloud provider to run statistical computations on patient datasets without ever exposing plaintext patient data to the provider's systems, even while computations are actively being performed. Which technology BEST meets this requirement?","o":["Transport Layer Security (TLS) for all data transfers","Homomorphic encryption","Full-disk encryption at the storage layer","Format-preserving encryption"],"c":1,"why":"Homomorphic encryption allows computations to be performed directly on encrypted data, producing an encrypted result that can be decrypted by the data owner, thereby protecting data in use; the other options protect data in transit or at rest but require decryption before computation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's records retention policy requires the automatic deletion of email older than three years. The legal department receives a litigation hold notice referencing emails from four years ago that are scheduled for deletion this week under the standard retention schedule. What is the MOST appropriate action?","o":["Proceed with the scheduled deletion since the emails exceed the retention period defined in policy","Delete only the emails unrelated to the litigation and retain the rest","Suspend the deletion of relevant records and implement a legal hold until the litigation is resolved","Escalate the decision to the email hosting vendor for a final determination"],"c":2,"why":"A legal hold suspends normal data destruction schedules for records that may be relevant to pending or anticipated litigation, regardless of the standard retention policy; deleting such records could constitute spoliation of evidence, and the decision authority rests with the organization, not an external vendor.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization classifies its information assets as Public, Internal, Confidential, and Restricted. What is the PRIMARY purpose of applying these classification labels to documents and systems?","o":["To satisfy audit checklist requirements only","To determine the appropriate handling, storage, and access controls for the information","To assign monetary value to each asset for insurance purposes","To simplify the naming convention of files"],"c":1,"why":"Classification labels drive the selection of appropriate security controls (handling, storage, transmission, access) proportional to the sensitivity of the data. Audit satisfaction, insurance valuation, and naming conventions are incidental, not the core purpose.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the process of 'scoping' when applying a security control baseline to an information system?","o":["Adding extra controls beyond the baseline to address unique risks","Reviewing the baseline and removing or adjusting controls that do not apply to the specific system or environment","Encrypting all data covered by the baseline","Classifying the system according to its sensitivity level"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping involves tailoring a baseline by removing irrelevant controls based on the system's environment or applicability. Adding controls is called 'tailoring' (specifically supplementation), encryption is a specific control, and classification is a separate activity that precedes baseline selection.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A financial services company is developing a data classification scheme. Which of the following factors should PRIMARILY drive the classification level assigned to a dataset?","o":["The physical location where the data is stored","The potential impact to the organization if the data's confidentiality is compromised","The total volume of records contained within the dataset","The age of the data since creation"],"c":1,"why":"Classification levels should reflect the sensitivity and potential business impact of unauthorized disclosure. Storage location, volume, and age may influence handling controls but are not the primary driver of the classification level itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company stores backup tapes containing highly sensitive research data in an offsite facility. Which control provides the BEST protection for the confidentiality of this data while it is at rest on the tapes?","o":["Physical padlocks on the storage cabinet only","Strong encryption of the data on the tapes with securely managed keys","Logging of who enters the storage facility","Labeling the tapes as 'Confidential'"],"c":1,"why":"Encryption ensures that even if the tapes are stolen or accessed by unauthorized persons, the data remains unreadable, directly protecting confidentiality at rest. Physical locks, access logging, and labeling are useful administrative/physical controls but do not prevent disclosure if the media itself is compromised.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization is retiring a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that previously stored classified information. The IT team's standard overwrite utility, designed for magnetic media, cannot guarantee that all data blocks are overwritten due to wear-leveling and over-provisioning on the SSD controller. Which sanitization method best satisfies a NIST SP 800-88 'Purge' level of assurance for these SSDs?","o":["Perform a single-pass software overwrite of all addressable logical sectors","Issue the drive's built-in ATA Secure Erase or Cryptographic Erase command via the controller firmware","Degauss the drives using a strong magnetic field","Perform a quick format of the file system on each drive"],"c":1,"why":"Because SSD wear-leveling relocates data to physical blocks not directly addressable by the OS, only firmware-level commands like Secure Erase/Cryptographic Erase (which the controller executes internally) reliably reach all physical storage, meeting NIST 800-88 Purge requirements. Overwriting and quick-format only meet 'Clear' level at best, and degaussing is ineffective on non-magnetic flash media.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which role is accountable for determining the classification level of a specific dataset and approving access requests to it?","o":["Data custodian","System owner","Data owner","Security administrator"],"c":2,"why":"The data owner (typically a business unit leader) has ultimate accountability for classifying data and approving access. The custodian implements technical safeguards, the system owner manages the hosting platform, and the security administrator configures access controls per the owner's decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A marketing team combines an internal, anonymized customer transaction dataset with a licensed third-party demographic dataset. The resulting merged dataset allows re-identification of individual customers, elevating its sensitivity above either source dataset. Who bears primary accountability for ensuring this newly created dataset receives appropriate classification and handling controls?","o":["The data custodian who maintains the storage systems","The system administrator who provisioned the merge environment","The data owner who authorized the merging of the datasets","The privacy officer, since re-identification risk is involved"],"c":2,"why":"The data owner is accountable for classifying data, including derivative or aggregated datasets created through processing decisions they authorize; custodians implement handling controls but don't set classification, sysadmins have no classification authority, and while a privacy officer advises on risk, classification accountability remains with the data owner.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A dataset containing employee names, department names, and office locations is individually classified as public information. Security analysts discover that when this dataset is combined with a separately maintained (and appropriately restricted) performance evaluation dataset, the combination reveals which specific employees received poor performance ratings, information that was intended to remain confidential. This risk, arising from combining multiple non-sensitive data sources to reveal sensitive information, is best described as:","o":["Inference","Data remanence","Aggregation","Covert channel exploitation"],"c":2,"why":"Aggregation refers to the risk that combining multiple pieces of data, each of which may be non-sensitive individually, produces a result that is more sensitive than any single source; inference involves deducing sensitive information through logical reasoning about available data rather than directly combining datasets, data remanence concerns residual data after deletion, and covert channels involve unauthorized communication paths.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization's data lifecycle model includes creation, storage, use, sharing, archiving, and destruction. During which phase should data loss prevention (DLP) controls be MOST focused on monitoring for unauthorized transmission of sensitive information?","o":["Creation","Storage","Use/Sharing","Destruction"],"c":2,"why":"DLP solutions are designed to detect and prevent unauthorized transmission of sensitive data, which primarily occurs when data is actively used or shared. Storage relies more on encryption and access controls, while destruction relies on secure deletion methods.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"While implementing a security control baseline for a low-impact HR announcement system with no remote administrative interface, the security team removes several controls related to multifactor authentication for privileged remote access, determining they do not apply to this system. This activity is best described as:","o":["Control tailoring using organization-defined parameters","Scoping the baseline to exclude non-applicable controls","Selecting compensating controls for an unmet requirement","A continuous monitoring exception request"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping involves determining which baseline controls apply to a system based on its characteristics and removing those that are not applicable (like remote-access controls for a system with no remote interface); tailoring adjusts parameters of applicable controls, compensating controls substitute for controls that ARE applicable but can't be implemented as specified, and this scenario involves no monitoring exception.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization is sanitizing flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) that previously stored Top Secret data before sending them to an external recycler with no further organizational oversight. Per NIST SP 800-88 guidance, why is a single-pass software overwrite (Clear) generally considered insufficient for this scenario?","o":["Clear is only defined for optical media and cannot be applied to any electronic storage device","Wear-leveling in flash memory can relocate data to blocks that standard overwrite commands may not address, so Purge-level techniques (such as cryptographic erase or ATA Secure Erase) or physical destruction are needed","Clear techniques take significantly longer to complete than Purge techniques, making them operationally impractical","Clear is equivalent to Purge for flash media, but Top Secret data always requires Destroy regardless of media type"],"c":1,"why":"Flash memory's wear-leveling algorithms move data across physical blocks in ways that a logical-level overwrite (Clear) may not reach, leaving remnant data recoverable; NIST SP 800-88 recommends Purge-level sanitization (e.g., cryptographic erase, ATA/NVMe Secure Erase) or physical destruction for media leaving organizational control, especially for high-sensitivity data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A retailer collects customer purchase data and contracts a marketing firm to send promotional emails strictly according to the retailer's written instructions, using only the data provided. Under common privacy principles, the marketing firm is BEST classified as the:","o":["Data controller","Data processor","Data owner","Data subject"],"c":1,"why":"A data processor acts on behalf of and under the instructions of the controller, without independently determining the purpose of processing; the retailer, who determines the purpose and means of processing, is the controller.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored highly sensitive data. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate for these media?","o":["Degaussing","Overwriting with a single pass of zeros","Cryptographic erase combined with physical destruction","Formatting the drive using the operating system's quick format utility"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory and wear-leveling, making magnetic degaussing ineffective and simple overwriting unreliable, since data may persist in reallocated blocks. NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase followed by physical destruction for high-sensitivity flash media; quick format does not remove underlying data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's retention policy mandates deletion of customer support emails after three years. In month 30, executives become aware of a customer dispute that is very likely to result in litigation, though no lawsuit has been filed. What is the correct action regarding the potentially relevant email records?","o":["Continue the normal deletion schedule since no lawsuit has been formally filed","Immediately impose a legal hold suspending deletion of potentially relevant records","Delete the records early to reduce future discovery exposure","Shorten the retention period to 30 months to align with the anticipated dispute"],"c":1,"why":"The duty to preserve evidence arises when litigation is reasonably anticipated, not only when a suit is filed; a legal hold must be issued to suspend routine destruction of relevant records to avoid spoliation liability. Continuing deletion, deleting early, or altering retention to avoid preservation all create legal and regulatory exposure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which control provides the BEST protection for sensitive data while it is being actively processed in a system's memory?","o":["Transport Layer Security (TLS)","Full disk encryption","Trusted execution environment / memory encryption","File-level access control lists"],"c":2,"why":"Data in use is protected through mechanisms like trusted execution environments or secure enclaves that encrypt data in memory during processing. TLS protects data in transit, full disk encryption protects data at rest, and ACLs govern access but do not protect against memory-level exposure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A financial services firm runs sensitive analytics workloads on a shared multi-tenant public cloud platform and is concerned about a compromised hypervisor or co-tenant accessing plaintext data while it is being processed in memory. Which technology BEST addresses this concern?","o":["Transport Layer Security (TLS) for all API calls","Full-disk encryption on the underlying storage volumes","A hardware-based trusted execution environment (secure enclave)","Digital signatures applied to output files"],"c":2,"why":"Trusted execution environments (e.g., secure enclaves) protect data confidentiality and integrity while it is actively being processed in memory, isolating it even from a compromised hypervisor. TLS protects data in transit, disk encryption protects data at rest, and digital signatures provide integrity/authenticity, not confidentiality during processing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A healthcare analytics firm wants a third-party processor to run statistical computations on encrypted patient records without the processor ever accessing plaintext data or holding decryption keys. Which technology best meets this data-in-use protection requirement?","o":["Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the data transmission channel","Full disk encryption on the storage servers","Homomorphic encryption enabling computation on ciphertext","Field-level tokenization of patient identifiers"],"c":2,"why":"Homomorphic encryption uniquely allows mathematical operations to be performed directly on encrypted data, producing an encrypted result that can be decrypted by the data owner, thereby protecting data while in use. TLS and full disk encryption protect data in transit and at rest respectively, and tokenization removes identifiers but doesn't enable computation on protected values without detokenization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization discovers that certain records subject to a litigation hold are scheduled for destruction under the standard retention policy. What should the organization do?","o":["Follow the retention schedule and destroy the records as planned to maintain policy consistency","Suspend destruction of the affected records until the legal hold is lifted","Destroy only the non-electronic copies while retaining electronic backups","Transfer custody of the records to outside counsel to avoid destruction liability"],"c":1,"why":"A litigation hold legally overrides standard retention schedules, requiring preservation of all relevant records in all formats until the hold is released; destroying any copies could constitute spoliation of evidence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"Following the invalidation of a prior EU-US data transfer adequacy framework by the courts, an EU-based company continues transferring employee HR data to its US cloud processor. Which approach is legally recognized under GDPR for this transfer when adequacy decisions are unavailable?","o":["Binding Corporate Rules only, because Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs) are no longer valid","Standard Contractual Clauses supplemented with additional technical and organizational safeguards","Obtaining a simple checkbox consent from each employee for the transfer","Storing data only on US soil without any contractual data protection terms"],"c":1,"why":"SCCs remain a valid GDPR transfer mechanism when reinforced with supplementary measures (e.g., strong encryption, access restrictions) following Schrems II-type rulings; the claim that SCCs are invalid is false. Employee consent is disfavored for employer-employee data transfers due to power imbalance, and mere data residency without contractual safeguards does not satisfy GDPR transfer requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An employee opens a spreadsheet labeled 'Confidential' and emails it to an unauthorized external partner without any technical restriction preventing the transfer. Which control, if properly implemented and enforced based on the document's classification label, would MOST likely have prevented this incident?","o":["Full-disk encryption on the employee's workstation","A network intrusion detection system","Data Loss Prevention (DLP) integrated with classification labels","Antivirus software with heuristic scanning"],"c":2,"why":"DLP solutions can inspect content and metadata (including classification labels) and block or flag unauthorized transmission of sensitive data; disk encryption, IDS, and antivirus do not address outbound data handling based on classification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"In the context of applying security control baselines, what is the primary purpose of \"scoping\"?","o":["Adding compensating controls to address gaps identified in a risk assessment","Determining which baseline controls apply to a system based on its characteristics and removing those that do not","Adjusting control parameters, such as password length, to match organizational requirements","Documenting the rationale for control selection in the system security plan"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping involves determining which controls from a baseline are relevant to a given system and excluding those that do not apply. Adjusting parameters describes tailoring, adding compensating controls addresses residual risk, and documentation is a separate governance activity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following BEST explains why maintaining a comprehensive and current inventory of hardware and software assets is considered foundational to an asset security program?","o":["It ensures software license compliance and reduces procurement costs","It provides the visibility necessary to identify, classify, and apply appropriate protections to all assets","It satisfies external audit requirements without the need for further security controls","It enables the finance department to calculate accurate depreciation schedules"],"c":1,"why":"Organizations cannot protect, classify, or manage risk for assets they do not know exist; asset inventory is the foundation enabling classification and control assignment. License compliance, audit satisfaction, and depreciation are secondary benefits, not the primary security rationale.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A government agency wants to repurpose storage media previously used to store Top Secret data for a new system rated only for Confidential information. What must occur before the media can be reused at this lower classification level?","o":["The media may be reused immediately since Confidential is a lower classification than Top Secret","The media must undergo formal purge-level sanitization and independent verification before downgrade and reuse","Simply relabeling the media as Confidential is sufficient","The media must be physically destroyed regardless of sanitization results"],"c":1,"why":"Downgrading media between classification levels requires documented purge-level sanitization and independent verification to ensure no residual higher-classification data remains; relabeling alone or immediate reuse is insufficient, and destruction is only mandated when sanitization cannot be verified or performed, not automatically for every downgrade.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Under a common privacy framework, an organization contracts a cloud-based payroll provider to process employee salary data on its behalf, following its instructions. In this relationship, the organization is BEST classified as the:","o":["Data processor","Data subject","Data controller","Data custodian"],"c":2,"why":"The organization determines the purposes and means of processing employee data, making it the data controller; the payroll provider acting under its instructions is the processor. The employees are data subjects, and 'custodian' is not the correct privacy-framework term for this relationship.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A database stores individually unclassified fields such as troop locations, equipment counts, and mission dates. When a user queries and combines these fields together, the resulting output reveals a classified operational plan that none of the individual fields disclosed alone. This scenario best illustrates which security concept relevant to classification programs?","o":["Data remanence","The aggregation problem","A covert channel","Tokenization failure"],"c":1,"why":"The aggregation problem occurs when combining multiple pieces of lower-sensitivity data produces an output whose sensitivity exceeds that of any individual element, requiring classification programs to control combined query access. A covert channel involves unintended communication paths, data remanence concerns residual data after deletion, and tokenization failure is unrelated to this querying scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is implementing a data classification program. What is the PRIMARY purpose of classifying data?","o":["To determine which employees are allowed to work remotely","To ensure data receives a level of protection appropriate to its value and sensitivity","To satisfy audit checklist requirements without further action","To assign monetary value to data for insurance purposes only"],"c":1,"why":"Data classification exists to apply appropriate, cost-effective security controls based on the sensitivity and criticality of the data. Insurance valuation and remote-work policy are unrelated purposes, and classification should drive real protective controls, not just satisfy a checklist.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which role is PRIMARILY responsible for determining the classification level of a specific data set and approving who may access it?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","System administrator","Security auditor"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit manager) has accountability for the data and decides its classification and access requirements. The custodian implements technical controls, the administrator manages systems, and the auditor independently verifies compliance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company is decommissioning several traditional magnetic hard disk drives that once stored highly confidential records. Which method provides the MOST assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive with a quick format","Degaussing the drive followed by physical destruction","Renaming the file extensions to prevent normal access"],"c":2,"why":"Degaussing disrupts magnetic domains and physical destruction ensures the media cannot be reused or reconstructed, providing the highest assurance of data destruction for magnetic media. Deleting, quick formatting, or renaming files only remove pointers to data, leaving the actual data recoverable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization's data retention policy should PRIMARILY be driven by which of the following?","o":["The personal preference of the IT department regarding storage costs","Legal, regulatory, and business requirements for how long data must be kept","The maximum capacity of available backup storage media","The age of the encryption algorithm used to protect the data"],"c":1,"why":"Retention periods must satisfy legal, regulatory, and business needs (e.g., tax law, litigation holds, contractual obligations). Storage capacity and encryption strength are technical considerations, not the primary driver, and IT preference is not an appropriate basis for retention decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company transmits sensitive customer records between its data center and a cloud provider over the public Internet. Which control BEST protects the confidentiality of this data while it is in transit?","o":["Full disk encryption on the source server's hard drive","Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the network connection","Database column-level encryption applied only at rest","Access control lists on the destination server's file system"],"c":1,"why":"TLS encrypts data as it moves across the network, directly protecting confidentiality in transit. Full disk encryption and column-level encryption protect data at rest, and file system ACLs control access but do not protect data while it is being transmitted.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is developing a data classification scheme for its intellectual property. Which factor should be the PRIMARY driver when assigning a classification level to a given data set?","o":["The cost of the storage media on which the data resides","The potential impact to the organization if the data's confidentiality, integrity, or availability is compromised","The number of employees who currently have access to the data","The age of the data and how long it has been stored"],"c":1,"why":"Classification should be based on the business impact of loss or compromise of the data, not on storage cost, current access levels, or age. Impact analysis drives appropriate protection requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the concept of asset valuation in the context of asset security?","o":["Assigning a monetary or relative value to an asset to guide the level of protection it warrants","Listing every asset owned by the organization in a spreadsheet","Determining the physical location where an asset is stored","Calculating the depreciation of hardware for accounting purposes"],"c":0,"why":"Asset valuation determines an asset's worth (tangible or intangible) so that appropriate, cost-justified security controls can be selected. Simply inventorying assets, tracking their location, or calculating accounting depreciation does not address the security-relevant concept of value-based protection.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company's data governance policy assigns accountability for approving access requests and defining classification levels for a customer database to a specific business executive. Which role does this executive fulfill?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data processor","System administrator"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit leader) is accountable for classifying data and approving access; the custodian implements technical controls, the processor acts on data per instructions (often third-party), and the administrator manages systems, not classification decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A security team must sanitize a set of retired solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored regulated financial data before the drives are redeployed to a lower-classification environment. Due to wear-leveling and overprovisioning, a single-pass software overwrite cannot reliably reach all physical blocks. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate given this constraint?","o":["Perform a single-pass overwrite using a disk-wiping utility designed for magnetic media","Degauss the drives using a high-coercivity degausser rated for magnetic tape and hard disks","Invoke the drive's built-in cryptographic erase function or ATA Secure Erase command to render all stored data unrecoverable","Perform a low-level format followed by a standard file deletion of all partitions"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory and wear-leveling, so software overwrites cannot guarantee all physical cells are addressed, and degaussing is ineffective because SSDs are not magnetic media; cryptographic erase (destroying the encryption key or invoking the drive's secure erase firmware) is the NIST 800-88-recommended approach for flash-based media. A low-level format/delete leaves recoverable data on the flash cells.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"During which phase of the information lifecycle is data typically classified for the FIRST time?","o":["Destruction","Archival","Creation","Use"],"c":2,"why":"Classification should occur at the point of creation so that appropriate handling controls apply throughout the data's life. Use, archival, and destruction are later lifecycle stages that rely on the classification already assigned.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A hospital is decommissioning several hard drives that contained electronic health records. The drives will be resold to a third party. Which sanitization method provides the HIGHEST assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Logical deletion of files followed by reformatting the drive","Overwriting the drive once with a pattern of zeros","Physical destruction of the drive (e.g., shredding or disintegration)","Running a quick format and reinstalling the operating system"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction provides the highest assurance of data irrecoverability, especially when media will leave organizational control. Deletion, single-pass overwrite, and quick formatting may leave recoverable remnants (data remanence).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A hospital's Chief Medical Information Officer decides which staff roles may access a patient records system, sets the classification level of the data as 'Restricted,' and is held accountable if the data is improperly disclosed. The IT infrastructure team performs nightly backups and applies the CMIO's access decisions in the system. Which role does the CMIO occupy in this scenario?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data processor","System administrator"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner is the accountable party who classifies data and determines access rights, even though day-to-day technical implementation (backups, access provisioning) is delegated to custodians/administrators. The IT team performing backups and applying decisions are custodians, not owners, since they lack accountability for classification decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Under common privacy frameworks such as GDPR, which term refers to the entity that determines the purposes and means of processing personal data, as opposed to the entity that processes it on the first entity's behalf?","o":["Data processor","Data subject","Data controller","Data custodian"],"c":2,"why":"The data controller decides why and how personal data is processed and bears primary accountability for compliance. The processor acts on the controller's instructions, the data subject is the individual the data is about, and data custodian is a general security role not specific to this privacy distinction.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization's records retention policy requires that financial transaction logs be kept for seven years to comply with regulatory requirements. What is the PRIMARY risk of retaining this data significantly LONGER than required?","o":["Increased storage costs only, with no other security implications","Expanded attack surface and increased legal discovery liability from unnecessarily retained data","Improved availability of historical data for business analytics","Reduced need for data classification since old data is inherently less sensitive"],"c":1,"why":"Excess retention increases the amount of sensitive data exposed to breach, and creates additional e-discovery obligations and liability during litigation. Storage cost is a factor but not the primary security/legal risk; retained data does not become less sensitive with age.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization runs a multi-tenant analytics platform where sensitive customer PII is decrypted and processed in application memory during computation, creating exposure to memory-scraping attacks from a compromised hypervisor or co-located tenant process. Which control BEST protects the confidentiality of this data specifically while it is in use?","o":["Full-disk encryption on the underlying storage volumes","TLS 1.3 for all data transmitted between application tiers","A hardware-based trusted execution environment (secure enclave) that isolates and encrypts memory during processing","Field-level encryption of the database columns containing PII"],"c":2,"why":"Trusted execution environments (e.g., secure enclaves) protect data in use by isolating and encrypting the memory space during processing, which directly addresses memory-scraping risk. Disk encryption and TLS protect data at rest and in transit respectively, and field-level encryption is decrypted before processing, offering no protection once data is in memory.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Within an information security governance model, who is PRIMARILY responsible for determining the classification level of a specific set of business data and approving who may access it?","o":["The data custodian","The data owner","The system administrator","The security auditor"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit manager) has ultimate accountability for the data, including setting its classification and approving access. The custodian implements day-to-day protection, administrators manage systems, and auditors independently verify compliance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"During a security control implementation project, a team selects the NIST SP 800-53 control baseline for a moderate-impact system and then removes controls related to physical access because the system is hosted entirely in a cloud environment with no organizational physical facility. This activity is BEST described as:","o":["Scoping","Tailoring","Standardization","Baselining"],"c":1,"why":"Tailoring is the process of modifying a selected baseline (adding, removing, or adjusting controls) to fit the specific environment. Scoping determines which baseline/system boundary applies; baselining is establishing the initial minimum control set; standardization is unrelated.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A financial services company classifies its data using a four-tier model: Public, Internal, Confidential, and Restricted. A business analyst wants to know who is responsible for assigning the initial classification level to a new customer contract database. Which role has this responsibility?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data processor","System administrator"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (typically a senior business manager) is accountable for classifying data and determining protection requirements; the custodian implements those controls, the processor acts on behalf of the owner, and the system administrator manages infrastructure, not classification decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"During implementation of NIST SP 800-53 controls, a project team first removes controls related to physical facility protections because the system is entirely cloud-hosted with no organizationally managed data center. They then adjust the remaining access control requirements by adding compensating multifactor authentication controls to address a unique third-party integration risk. Which two activities have occurred, in order?","o":["Tailoring, then scoping","Scoping, then tailoring","Baselining, then scoping","Tailoring, then baselining"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping is the process of determining which controls in a baseline apply to the environment and removing inapplicable ones (e.g., physical controls for a cloud-only system); tailoring is the subsequent customization of the remaining controls (e.g., adding compensating controls) to fit the organization's specific risk context. The reverse order or substituting baselining is incorrect since baselining refers to selecting the initial control set, not the described refinement activities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Data remanence refers to which of the following security concerns?","o":["The risk that encrypted data can be decrypted if the key is compromised","Residual data that remains on storage media after deletion or formatting, which may be recoverable","The delay between data creation and its classification","The tendency of backup data to become outdated over time"],"c":1,"why":"Data remanence is residual physical representation of data left on media after normal deletion, which can potentially be recovered using forensic tools. The other options describe unrelated concepts such as key compromise, classification timing, or backup staleness.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A financial services firm wants to protect sensitive data while it is actively being processed in memory by an application, such as during a real-time fraud analysis calculation. Which technology is MOST appropriate for protecting data in this state?","o":["Full disk encryption","Transport Layer Security (TLS)","Secure enclave / trusted execution environment","Database column-level encryption"],"c":2,"why":"Secure enclaves (trusted execution environments) protect data in use by isolating computation in a hardware-protected memory region. Full disk encryption protects data at rest, TLS protects data in transit, and column-level encryption typically protects stored data, not data actively being processed in memory.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's data retention policy requires deletion of email records after 3 years. Litigation counsel notifies the records management team that a lawsuit has been filed and that specific email accounts are relevant to the matter, 18 months before their scheduled deletion date. What is the CORRECT course of action?","o":["Proceed with deletion as scheduled, since the retention policy was established and approved prior to the litigation notice","Delete only the emails not explicitly named in the litigation notice, retaining the rest under the original schedule","Suspend the destruction of the identified records under a legal hold until the litigation is resolved or counsel releases the hold, overriding the normal retention schedule","Reduce the retention period to 18 months so records align with both the policy and the litigation timeline"],"c":2,"why":"A legal hold suspends normal retention/destruction schedules for potentially relevant records to prevent spoliation of evidence, and it takes precedence over routine policy until released by counsel. Proceeding with scheduled deletion, deleting unnamed records without full preservation, or arbitrarily shortening retention could constitute spoliation and expose the organization to sanctions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is decommissioning a set of SSDs that previously stored highly classified research data. Due to wear-leveling and over-provisioning, traditional overwriting methods cannot guarantee that all data blocks are addressed. What is the MOST appropriate sanitization method to ensure data cannot be recovered before disposal?","o":["Degaussing the drives","Performing a single-pass overwrite of the entire logical address space","Physical destruction (e.g., shredding or disintegration)","Reformatting the drive using the operating system's quick format option"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory and wear-leveling, making degaussing ineffective and overwriting unreliable since the drive controller may not overwrite all physical blocks; NIST SP 800-88 recommends physical destruction for SSDs holding highly sensitive data when other methods can't be verified. Quick format only removes file pointers.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which control is MOST effective at protecting the confidentiality of sensitive data while it is being transmitted across a public network?","o":["Full disk encryption on the sending device","Transport Layer Security (TLS) encryption of the communication channel","Data masking of the fields displayed to the end user","File-level access control lists on the destination server"],"c":1,"why":"TLS protects data in transit by encrypting the communication channel between endpoints. Disk encryption protects data at rest, masking protects displayed data, and ACLs control access at rest on the destination system, none of which secure the data during network transmission.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Under many privacy frameworks (e.g., GDPR), an organization that determines the purposes and means of processing personal data is called the data controller. A third-party payroll vendor that processes employee data strictly according to the organization's instructions would be classified as the:","o":["Data subject","Data processor","Data custodian","Data owner"],"c":1,"why":"A data processor handles personal data on behalf of and under the instructions of the controller. Data subject refers to the individual the data is about; custodian and owner are internal information governance roles, not the specific privacy-law term for this third party.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A dataset used for research replaces individuals' names and Social Security numbers with randomly generated tokens; a separate secured lookup table maps tokens back to the original identities and is retained by the data controller. From a privacy and regulatory compliance standpoint, this dataset should be treated as which of the following?","o":["Anonymized data, exempt from most privacy regulations because direct identifiers were removed","Pseudonymized data, which still constitutes personal data subject to privacy regulations because re-identification remains possible","De-identified data equivalent to aggregate statistical data with no re-identification risk","Encrypted data, protected solely by the strength of the tokenization algorithm"],"c":1,"why":"Because a mapping table exists that allows re-identification, the data is pseudonymized, not anonymized, and most privacy frameworks (e.g., GDPR) still classify pseudonymized data as personal data requiring protection. True anonymization requires that re-identification be irreversibly impossible, which is not the case here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"According to NIST SP 800-88 media sanitization guidance, which method provides the HIGHEST assurance that data cannot be recovered from a hard drive that will be disposed of and is no longer needed?","o":["Clearing the drive using a standard operating system delete command","Purging the drive using a single-pass overwrite","Physically destroying the drive through shredding, disintegration, or incineration","Reformatting the drive with a quick format"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction provides the highest assurance of data irretrievability and is recommended for media containing highly sensitive data or media that cannot be reused. Simple deletion, quick formatting, and even single-pass overwriting leave some possibility of data recovery, especially on certain media types like SSDs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A healthcare organization must retain patient records for seven years per regulatory requirements, but its backup tapes are currently kept indefinitely due to a lack of formal policy. What is the PRIMARY risk this situation creates?","o":["Increased storage costs only","Failure to comply with data minimization and retention requirements, increasing legal and breach exposure liability","Reduced availability of records for legitimate business use","Faster data retrieval times during litigation"],"c":1,"why":"Retaining data beyond its required period violates data minimization principles and increases the organization's exposure in litigation (more discoverable data) and breach impact; storage cost is a secondary concern, and the other options are not accurate risks of over-retention.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization labels a set of engineering drawings as 'Confidential' and applies handling requirements such as restricted printing, encrypted storage, and need-to-know access. Six months later, a review determines the drawings are now publicly available on a competitor's marketing materials. What is the MOST appropriate action regarding the classification of this data?","o":["Leave the classification unchanged since original creation intent should always be preserved","Declassify or reclassify the data to a lower level, since its sensitivity has changed and continuing to protect it as Confidential wastes resources","Immediately destroy all copies of the drawings to prevent further exposure","Increase the classification level to ensure no further leakage occurs"],"c":1,"why":"Classification must be reviewed periodically and adjusted when data sensitivity changes; since the information is now public, downgrading avoids unnecessary control overhead. Leaving it unchanged wastes resources, destruction doesn't address classification, and increasing classification is illogical once data is public.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Under a typical privacy framework such as the GDPR, an organization that collects personal data from customers and determines the purposes and means of processing that data is best described as the:","o":["Data processor","Data subject","Data controller","Data custodian"],"c":2,"why":"The data controller determines why and how personal data is processed and bears primary accountability for compliance. The processor acts on the controller's instructions, the data subject is the individual the data is about, and custodian is a general term for those who handle data operationally, not a defined privacy role.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A cloud storage provider cannot guarantee physical destruction of specific data blocks belonging to one tenant on shared, multi-tenant storage hardware because the underlying media is used by many customers simultaneously. Which sanitization approach BEST addresses the organization's obligation to render its data unrecoverable when terminating the cloud service?","o":["Request that the cloud provider perform a certified degaussing pass on all affected storage arrays","Rely on the cloud provider's standard data deletion API call, which removes file system pointers to the data","Encrypt all data using strong, tenant-controlled keys before uploading, then destroy the encryption keys upon service termination (cryptographic erasure)","Require the cloud provider to physically destroy the drives housing the tenant's data upon contract termination"],"c":2,"why":"Cryptographic erasure—encrypting data with a key controlled by the tenant and then destroying that key—is the practical and effective method for rendering data unrecoverable on shared, virtualized, multi-tenant storage where physical destruction or degaussing of specific blocks is infeasible. Standard deletion APIs typically only remove pointers, and physically destroying shared drives would improperly impact other tenants' data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the concept of 'data at rest' in the context of asset security controls?","o":["Data being actively processed in system memory by an application","Data stored on persistent media such as hard drives, databases, or backup tapes","Data being transmitted across a network between two endpoints","Data cached temporarily in a web browser during a session"],"c":1,"why":"Data at rest refers to data stored on non-volatile storage media, requiring controls like encryption and access controls; data in memory is 'data in use,' and data traversing a network is 'data in transit.'","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An employee finds a document labeled 'Confidential' left unattended on a printer. According to standard information handling procedures, what should the employee do FIRST?","o":["Shred the document immediately to prevent unauthorized disclosure","Read the document to determine its sensitivity before deciding what to do","Secure the document and return it to its owner or the appropriate custodian for proper handling","Leave the document in place since it is not the employee's responsibility"],"c":2,"why":"Proper handling procedures require securing sensitive found documents and returning them to the owner/custodian for appropriate action, preserving confidentiality without destroying potentially needed records. Reading, shredding, or ignoring the document could violate handling policy or destroy needed information.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A company classifies individual fields in its HR database as 'Public' (employee names), 'Internal' (department assignments), and 'Public' (job titles) based on standalone sensitivity. However, when these three fields are combined for all employees into a single exportable report, the organization determines the resulting dataset must be classified as 'Confidential.' This scenario illustrates which information security principle?","o":["Data remanence, because residual information persists after the export","Aggregation, where the combination of individually low-sensitivity data elements creates a higher overall sensitivity level","Inference, where an attacker deduces classified information from unclassified sources without direct access","Separation of duties, because combining data across roles violates least privilege"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining multiple low-sensitivity data elements produces a dataset whose overall sensitivity exceeds that of any individual element, which is exactly the scenario described. Inference involves deducing hidden/classified facts from indirect unclassified clues rather than directly combining defined dataset fields, remanence concerns residual data after deletion, and separation of duties is an access-control concept unrelated to classification of combined data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company's data classification policy requires that all Confidential documents be labeled with a header and footer indicating their classification level. An employee emails a spreadsheet containing Confidential financial projections without any classification marking. From an asset security perspective, what is the MOST significant consequence of this omission?","o":["The file size will be larger than necessary","Recipients may mishandle the data because they cannot identify its required protection level","The spreadsheet will automatically be encrypted by the email system","The data will be automatically reclassified as Public"],"c":1,"why":"Labeling ensures that anyone handling the data understands the required protection measures; without it, recipients may apply insufficient controls, increasing risk of unauthorized disclosure. The other options describe unrelated or incorrect technical behaviors.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Under the GDPR framework, an organization that outsources payroll processing to a third-party vendor, and provides that vendor with employee personal data for the sole purpose of processing payroll according to the organization's instructions, is acting in which capacity relative to the vendor?","o":["The organization is the data processor, and the vendor is the data controller","The organization is the data controller, and the vendor is the data processor","Both parties are joint data controllers with equal accountability","The organization is the data subject, and the vendor is the data owner"],"c":1,"why":"The controller determines the purposes and means of processing personal data (the organization), while the processor (the vendor) processes data on the controller's behalf and instructions. There is no indication of joint control, and 'data subject' refers to the individual whose data is processed, not the organization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization maintains a comprehensive inventory of hardware and software assets but does not track the business owner or criticality rating for each asset. What is the MOST significant limitation this creates for the asset security program?","o":["The organization cannot perform accurate risk assessments or prioritize protection efforts based on asset value and impact","The inventory will become outdated more quickly than one that includes ownership data","Asset tracking software licensing costs will increase","The organization will be unable to detect unauthorized software installations"],"c":0,"why":"Without ownership and criticality information, the organization cannot properly assess risk, allocate protection resources, or make informed decisions during incident response; inventory currency, licensing costs, and unauthorized software detection are separate concerns not directly tied to missing ownership/criticality data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A storage administrator is decommissioning a set of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored top-secret research data. The organization's media sanitization policy was originally written for magnetic hard disk drives and specifies degaussing followed by a single-pass overwrite. Why is this approach inadequate for the SSDs, and what should be used instead?","o":["Degaussing and overwriting are inadequate because SSDs use flash memory and wear-leveling that can leave data in reallocated blocks inaccessible to standard overwrite commands; cryptographic erasure or physical destruction should be used instead","Degaussing and overwriting are inadequate because SSDs require seven-pass overwrites per older NISPOM guidance instead of a single pass","Degaussing and overwriting are inadequate because SSDs cannot be sanitized at all and must always be kept in secure storage indefinitely","Degaussing and overwriting are inadequate only because the drives are too small in capacity for degaussing equipment to work effectively"],"c":0,"why":"SSDs are non-magnetic and use wear-leveling/garbage collection that can leave copies of data in blocks not addressed by a logical overwrite, so degaussing is ineffective and overwriting is unreliable; cryptographic erase (destroying the key protecting encrypted data) or physical destruction are the accepted NIST SP 800-88 methods for flash media. The other options misstate the technical reasons or falsely claim sanitization is impossible.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company is developing a data retention and destruction schedule for its records management program. Which factor should be given the HIGHEST priority when determining how long a specific category of records must be retained?","o":["The preferences of the IT department regarding available storage capacity","Applicable legal, regulatory, and contractual requirements governing that record type","The average file size of records in that category","Historical convention within the organization, regardless of current requirements"],"c":1,"why":"Retention periods must be driven primarily by legal, regulatory, and contractual obligations to ensure compliance and avoid liability; storage capacity, file size, and historical habit are operational or irrelevant factors that should not override compliance requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization classifies its customer relationship management (CRM) database as 'Confidential.' A business unit manager who is accountable for the CRM data requests that a new vendor be granted read access to specific fields. Per standard information governance roles, who has the authority to approve or deny this access request?","o":["The data custodian, because they manage the technical controls protecting the database","The data owner, because they are accountable for the classification and use of the data and must approve access decisions","The system administrator, because they configure user accounts and permissions","The data processor, because they are the party physically handling the data on behalf of the vendor"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (typically a senior business role) is accountable for classifying data and approving who may access it based on business need; the custodian implements technical protections but does not make access decisions, the system administrator merely executes approved changes, and 'data processor' refers to a third party processing data on the owner's behalf, not an internal approver.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial application performs real-time calculations on unencrypted cardholder data held in server RAM. The security team wants to protect this data specifically while it is being actively processed, without disrupting the application's ability to compute on it. Which control best addresses this requirement?","o":["Full-disk encryption on the application server","TLS 1.3 encryption for all data transmitted to and from the application","A hardware-based trusted execution environment (secure enclave) that isolates and encrypts memory during processing","Format-preserving tokenization applied to the cardholder data at rest in the database"],"c":2,"why":"Protecting 'data in use' requires mechanisms like secure enclaves/trusted execution environments that keep data encrypted and isolated even while being processed in memory. Full-disk encryption protects data at rest, TLS protects data in transit, and tokenization at rest does not address data actively being computed on in RAM.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's data retention policy states that email records are to be deleted after 3 years. Legal counsel notifies IT that the organization is now subject to litigation and certain custodians' emails must be preserved indefinitely until the matter is resolved. What is the correct action regarding the standard retention policy?","o":["Continue following the standard 3-year deletion schedule because policies approved by senior management supersede legal requests","Immediately implement a legal hold that suspends deletion of the relevant records, overriding the normal retention schedule for those specific items","Delete the records early to minimize the organization's exposure to discovery obligations","Transfer the affected records to an offline archive with no further obligation to preserve them under the same integrity controls"],"c":1,"why":"A legal hold is a mandatory suspension of normal destruction/retention schedules for records relevant to litigation or investigation; failure to do so risks spoliation. Following the routine schedule or deleting early would constitute destruction of potential evidence, and moving records offline does not remove the preservation obligation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A federal agency selects the NIST SP 800-53 moderate-impact security control baseline for a new system and then removes several controls deemed inapplicable while adding compensating controls to address a unique operational risk not covered by the baseline. This activity of adjusting the baseline to the system's specific environment is best described as:","o":["Scoping, because it involves determining which baseline applies to the system","Tailoring, because it involves modifying the selected control baseline to fit the organization's specific risk environment and requirements","Categorization, because it involves assigning impact levels to the system","Accreditation, because it involves formal authorization to operate the system"],"c":1,"why":"Tailoring is the process of modifying a selected baseline (adding, removing, or adjusting controls) to align with organizational risk and operational context, exactly as described. Scoping refers to determining which baseline/controls apply based on system characteristics before tailoring; categorization assigns impact levels (an earlier step), and accreditation is the authorization decision, not the control adjustment activity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A retail company wants to reduce the scope of its PCI DSS compliance efforts by removing actual primary account numbers (PANs) from as many internal systems as possible, while still allowing those systems to process orders using a substitute value that has no mathematical relationship to the original number. Which technique should be used?","o":["Symmetric encryption of the PAN using AES-256","Data masking that displays only the last four digits of the PAN in user interfaces","Tokenization, replacing the PAN with a randomly generated non-sensitive token that maps back to the PAN in a secure vault","Hashing the PAN with SHA-256 for storage in the order-processing database"],"c":2,"why":"Tokenization replaces sensitive data with a non-sensitive surrogate that has no mathematical relationship to the original value, and systems using only the token are removed from the sensitive-data footprint, reducing compliance scope. Encryption still leaves systems handling protected data, masking only affects display and not underlying storage, and hashing is one-way and cannot support reversible processing needs like refunds or the original format requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which role is ultimately accountable for determining the classification level of a specific dataset and approving who may access it?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","System administrator","End user"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business executive) has ultimate accountability for classifying data and authorizing access; the custodian implements technical controls but does not decide classification, and administrators/users have even less authority.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A company migrates sensitive data to a public cloud provider's multi-tenant object storage. Upon contract termination, the company needs assurance that its data has been effectively destroyed from the provider's shared physical media, which cannot be physically destroyed on demand because it also hosts other tenants' data. What is the most effective approach to ensure destruction of the company's data in this scenario?","o":["Request that the cloud provider degauss the storage arrays hosting the company's data","Ensure all data was encrypted with keys under the company's control before upload, then destroy or revoke the encryption keys upon termination (cryptographic erasure)","Request a certificate of destruction confirming the physical drives were shredded","Rely on the provider's standard data deletion API calls to remove the objects from the storage buckets"],"c":1,"why":"In multi-tenant environments where physical destruction of shared media is infeasible, cryptographic erasure—encrypting data with customer-controlled keys and then destroying those keys—renders the data permanently unreadable and is the standard, effective approach. Degaussing is ineffective on non-magnetic/mixed shared media and infeasible for shared drives, physical destruction can't be done selectively, and standard API deletion often only removes references/metadata without guaranteeing underlying data destruction.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which sanitization method is generally considered the MOST effective for ensuring data cannot be recovered from a solid-state drive (SSD) that will be reused within the organization?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Formatting the drive using a quick format","Using the vendor-supported cryptographic erase or secure erase command, followed by verification","Overwriting the drive once with a single pass of zeros"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use wear leveling and controller-managed storage, so traditional overwriting is unreliable; vendor cryptographic/secure erase commands are the recommended NIST-approved method for reliable sanitization. Deletion, quick format, and simple single-pass overwrite do not reliably remove data from flash media.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A hospital publishes three separate datasets that are each individually classified as 'Public' and contain no direct identifiers: (1) patient zip codes and admission dates, (2) treatment types by department, and (3) attending physician schedules. A researcher combines all three datasets and, through correlation, is able to re-identify specific patients and their diagnoses. What security concept does this scenario illustrate, and what should have been done differently?","o":["This illustrates data remanence; the datasets should have been sanitized using cryptographic erasure before release","This illustrates the aggregation problem; the combined dataset should have been reviewed and potentially reclassified at a higher sensitivity level before release, since combining low-sensitivity data can create high-sensitivity information","This illustrates data diddling; access controls should have been implemented to prevent unauthorized combination of datasets","This illustrates covert channel exploitation; the organization should have implemented mandatory access control labels on each dataset"],"c":1,"why":"The aggregation problem occurs when combining multiple pieces of individually non-sensitive information yields a more sensitive result (here, re-identification of patients); classification decisions must consider how data may be combined, not just its individual sensitivity. Data remanence relates to residual data after deletion, data diddling is unauthorized alteration of data, and covert channels involve unauthorized information transfer through system resources—none of which describe this inference/aggregation scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is selecting a sanitization method for a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that previously stored top-secret data, prior to reallocating the drives to a lower-classification environment. Which method provides the most reliable assurance of data destruction for this media type?","o":["Degaussing the drives with a high-coercivity magnetic field","Performing a single-pass overwrite using a disk-wiping utility","Cryptographic erasure by destroying the encryption keys used to protect the data, followed by physical destruction","Reformatting the drives at the file-system level and reinstalling the operating system"],"c":2,"why":"Degaussing is ineffective on SSDs because they use flash memory, not magnetic media; overwriting is unreliable on SSDs due to wear-leveling and over-provisioning that prevent all cells from being addressed. Cryptographic erasure combined with physical destruction is the accepted approach (per NIST SP 800-88) for high-classification data on flash media. A simple reformat leaves data recoverable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization needs to determine how long customer financial records must be kept before they can be securely destroyed. Which factor should PRIMARILY drive this decision?","o":["The preference of the IT department to save storage space","Legal, regulatory, and contractual requirements applicable to the data","The age of the backup media being used","The marketing department's need for historical customer data"],"c":1,"why":"Retention periods must be based on legal, regulatory, and contractual obligations (e.g., tax law, industry regulation) to avoid non-compliance; IT storage preferences and business/marketing convenience are secondary and should not override compliance requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's data classification policy assigns accountability for approving access requests, defining classification levels, and ensuring appropriate protection controls are applied to a specific data set. Which role holds this accountability under standard CISSP asset security guidance?","o":["Data Custodian","Data Owner","Data Processor","System Administrator"],"c":1,"why":"The Data Owner (often a business unit executive) is accountable for classifying data and approving access, even though day-to-day protective tasks are delegated. The Custodian implements controls but isn't accountable for classification decisions; the Processor and System Administrator perform operational/technical functions without ownership accountability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the BEST example of Personally Identifiable Information (PII)?","o":["A company's annual revenue figures","An employee's Social Security number combined with their name","The version number of an operating system installed on a server","A generic customer satisfaction survey with no identifying fields"],"c":1,"why":"PII is information that can identify a specific individual, such as a name combined with a Social Security number. Company revenue, OS version, and anonymous survey data do not identify an individual.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A company is adopting NIST SP 800-53 as its control baseline for a new cloud-hosted application. During implementation, the security team removes controls related to physical media handling because the organization uses only cloud storage with no removable media, and adjusts encryption key length requirements to align with a stricter internal standard. Which two activities are being performed, respectively?","o":["Baselining and standardization","Scoping and tailoring","Categorization and accreditation","Gap analysis and remediation"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping is the process of determining which controls are relevant/applicable to the environment (removing physical media controls that don't apply), while tailoring involves modifying controls to meet specific organizational requirements (strengthening encryption key length). Baselining refers to selecting the initial control set, not modifying it; the other options don't describe this activity pair.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is developing a data classification scheme to protect its information assets. What is the PRIMARY purpose of classifying data?","o":["To assign monetary value to each data asset for insurance purposes","To determine the appropriate level of protection and handling controls based on sensitivity and impact","To satisfy audit requirements without affecting daily operations","To identify which employees are allowed to work remotely"],"c":1,"why":"Data classification exists to ensure that information receives protection commensurate with its sensitivity and the potential impact of disclosure or loss. The other options describe secondary or unrelated benefits, not the primary purpose.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A security architect wants to ensure sensitive data is protected while it is being actively processed in a database server's RAM. Which data state does this describe, and what is a common control used to protect it?","o":["Data at rest; full-disk encryption","Data in transit; TLS encryption","Data in use; memory encryption and access controls such as secure enclaves","Data in transit; VPN tunneling"],"c":2,"why":"Data being actively processed in memory is 'data in use,' protected by techniques like secure enclaves and memory encryption. Full-disk encryption protects data at rest, and TLS/VPN protect data in transit, not active processing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A records retention policy states that financial transaction logs must be destroyed after seven years. However, legal counsel has just issued a litigation hold notice related to an ongoing regulatory investigation that references records from the past five years. What is the MOST appropriate action regarding the affected records?","o":["Continue following the retention schedule since it was approved by senior management and predates the litigation hold","Suspend destruction of all records covered by the litigation hold until legal counsel confirms the hold is lifted, regardless of the retention schedule","Destroy only the records older than five years and retain the remainder per the original policy","Transfer the records to an offsite third party to avoid direct organizational liability for their destruction"],"c":1,"why":"Legal holds override standard retention schedules; once a litigation hold is issued, all potentially relevant records must be preserved until the hold is released, regardless of prior destruction timelines. Continuing to follow the original schedule, partial destruction, or offloading custody to a third party could constitute spoliation of evidence and expose the organization to legal sanctions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Who is ULTIMATELY accountable for determining the classification level of a specific set of business data?","o":["The data custodian","The system administrator","The data owner","The security auditor"],"c":2,"why":"The data owner (often a senior business manager) is accountable for classifying data and defining protection requirements. Custodians and administrators implement controls, while auditors verify compliance, but neither is accountable for classification decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"After data has been classified, what is the NEXT step organizations typically take to help personnel handle the data correctly on a day-to-day basis?","o":["Immediately destroy all data below the highest classification level","Apply labeling and marking to indicate the classification level on the data and its storage media","Remove the classification requirement once data is encrypted","Allow each employee to determine handling procedures individually"],"c":1,"why":"Labeling and marking data (e.g., 'Confidential,' 'Internal Use Only') communicates its classification so personnel can apply correct handling procedures. Destroying lower-classified data, removing classification after encryption, and leaving handling to individual discretion are inappropriate and insecure practices.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A mobile application development team, seeking to improve future analytics capabilities, decides to collect users' precise GPS location, contact lists, and biometric data at registration—even though the application's core functionality only requires an email address and password. From a privacy and data protection perspective, this practice primarily violates which principle?","o":["Purpose specification","Data minimization","Storage limitation","Accountability"],"c":1,"why":"Data minimization requires that only data necessary for the stated purpose be collected; gathering excessive data 'just in case' for undefined future use directly violates this principle. Purpose specification concerns declaring the purpose (which may have been done), storage limitation concerns retention duration, and accountability concerns governance oversight, not the act of over-collection itsel.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A database administrator is responsible for performing daily backups, applying access controls, and maintaining data integrity as directed by policy. Which role best describes this person?","o":["Data owner","Data custodian","Data processor","Business owner"],"c":1,"why":"The data custodian performs the day-to-day operational tasks of protecting and maintaining data under the direction of the data owner. The owner sets policy, while a processor typically refers to a third party handling personal data, and 'business owner' is not a standard asset security role.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization must dispose of a set of hard drives that contained classified information at the 'Secret' level before the drives are transferred to a vendor for disposal outside the organization's physical control. According to NIST SP 800-88 sanitization guidelines, which action is required in this scenario?","o":["Clear the drives using a standard single-pass overwrite tool","Purge the drives using a firmware-based secure erase command","Destroy the drives through shredding, disintegration, or incineration","Reformat the drives and verify via a file-recovery scan"],"c":2,"why":"NIST SP 800-88 recommends Destroy as the sanitization method when media containing high-sensitivity data is leaving organizational control and reuse is not intended, ensuring the media cannot be reconstructed. Clear and Purge are appropriate for reuse within a controlled environment but provide insufficient assurance when custody is relinquished for classified data; reformatting alone is the weakest and easily reversible option.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is decommissioning old hard drives that contained highly sensitive financial records. Which method provides the HIGHEST assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive using a quick format","Physical destruction of the drive (e.g., shredding or degaussing)","Overwriting the drive once with random data"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction eliminates any possibility of data recovery and is the most secure sanitization method for highly sensitive data. Deletion, quick formatting, and a single overwrite pass can leave recoverable remnants (data remanence).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company is developing a data classification scheme for its records. Which factor should be the PRIMARY determinant of the classification level assigned to a specific data set?","o":["The potential impact to the organization if the data's confidentiality, integrity, or availability is compromised","The physical storage location of the data within the data center","The age of the data since its original creation date","The department budget allocated for protecting the data"],"c":0,"why":"Classification should be driven by the potential business impact (harm) resulting from unauthorized disclosure, alteration, or loss of the data. Storage location, age, and budget are operational or unrelated factors that do not reflect the sensitivity or criticality of the information itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm encrypts all customer records at rest using AES-256 and enforces TLS 1.3 for all data transmitted between servers. During a security review, an assessor notes that sensitive plaintext customer data still resides unencrypted in server RAM while being processed by the application. Which security concern does this observation MOST directly relate to?","o":["Insufficient protection of data at rest","Insufficient protection of data in transit","Insufficient protection of data in use","Failure to apply data classification labels"],"c":2,"why":"Data in use refers to information actively being processed in memory/CPU, which encryption at rest and in transit do not protect; this requires controls such as secure enclaves, memory encryption, or runtime application self-protection. The scenario explicitly states at-rest and in-transit encryption are already implemented, ruling out those options, and classification labeling is unrelated to the runtime memory exposure described.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary reason organizations implement data retention policies?","o":["To reduce the amount of data available to competitors","To ensure data is kept only as long as necessary for legal, regulatory, and business requirements","To guarantee that all data is preserved indefinitely for historical purposes","To simplify the encryption of archived data"],"c":1,"why":"Retention policies balance legal, regulatory, and operational needs against the risks and costs of keeping data too long. Indefinite retention increases liability and storage costs, and the other options are not the core purpose of retention policies.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A business unit manager determines that a customer database must be classified as Confidential and defines the required access restrictions and retention period. The IT operations team then implements encryption, configures access controls, and performs backups according to those specifications. Which role does the IT operations team represent in this scenario?","o":["Data Owner","Data Custodian","Data Subject","Data Controller"],"c":1,"why":"The Data Custodian is responsible for the day-to-day technical implementation of security controls (encryption, backups, access lists) as defined by the Data Owner, who retains ultimate accountability for classification and protection requirements. The business unit manager is the Owner, not the IT team, and 'Data Subject' and 'Data Controller' are privacy-related roles that do not fit this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm is decommissioning a batch of enterprise SSDs that stored highly confidential client records. The security team wants a method that provides high assurance of data destruction while allowing the drives to be reused. Which approach is most appropriate given the physical architecture of SSDs?","o":["Perform a single-pass overwrite of the entire logical address space with random data","Use cryptographic erasure by destroying the encryption keys that protected the self-encrypting drive's data","Degauss the drives using a high-coercivity degausser rated for magnetic media","Perform a low-level format followed by a full disk defragmentation"],"c":1,"why":"SSDs use wear-leveling and over-provisioning, so overwrite commands may not reach all physical blocks (including reallocated/spare blocks), making traditional overwriting unreliable; cryptographic erasure of a self-encrypting drive's keys renders all data unrecoverable instantly and is the NIST SP 800-88 recommended method for flash media. Degaussing is ineffective on SSDs since they store data electronically, not magnetically, and formatting/defragmentation do not destroy underlying data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A dataset is created by merging three separate data sources: publicly available marketing statistics (classified Public), internal sales projections (classified Confidential), and a subset of customer Social Security numbers (classified Restricted). What classification should be applied to the newly merged dataset?","o":["Public, since the majority of the source data was already public","Confidential, as an average of the sensitivity levels of all three sources","Restricted, matching the highest classification level of any component within the merged dataset","The organization should classify each data field individually and only restrict access to the SSN column"],"c":2,"why":"The 'high-water mark' principle in asset security dictates that a composite dataset must be classified at the level of its most sensitive component, since aggregation and correlation can expose or amplify overall sensitivity. Averaging classifications, defaulting to the majority level, or field-level-only access controls fail to account for correlation risk and could result in exposure of the most sensitive information.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Sensitive customer data is being transmitted from a company's web application to its database server over an internal network. In which data state is this information, and what is an appropriate protection method?","o":["Data at rest; protect using full disk encryption","Data in transit; protect using transport encryption such as TLS","Data in use; protect using memory encryption","Data at rest; protect using access control lists only"],"c":1,"why":"Data actively moving across a network is considered data in transit, and TLS/transport encryption is the standard control. Data at rest refers to stored data, and data in use refers to data being processed in memory.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is decommissioning a set of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored Top Secret information. Why is degaussing NOT an appropriate sanitization method for these devices?","o":["Degaussing only works on optical media such as CDs and DVDs","SSDs store data using flash memory cells rather than magnetic properties, so degaussing has no effect on the stored data","Degaussing is too slow to be practical for large volumes of SSDs","Degaussing permanently damages the drive controller, preventing verification of sanitization"],"c":1,"why":"Degaussing relies on strong magnetic fields to disrupt magnetic storage media (like HDDs); SSDs use non-volatile flash memory with no magnetic properties, so degaussing is ineffective. The other options are false or irrelevant to why degaussing fails on SSDs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization is defining data governance roles for a new ERP system. Which statement correctly distinguishes the responsibilities of the data owner from those of the data custodian?","o":["The data owner implements encryption and backup procedures, while the data custodian assigns the classification level","The data owner assigns classification and approves access rights, while the data custodian performs the day-to-day technical safeguarding of the data","The data owner and data custodian have identical responsibilities and the terms are interchangeable in all frameworks","The data custodian is accountable to regulators for data breaches, while the data owner only advises on technical controls"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (typically a business executive) has ultimate accountability for the data, determines its classification, and approves who may access it, while the data custodian (often IT/security staff) implements and maintains the technical controls (backups, encryption, access provisioning) on the owner's behalf. The other options reverse or conflate these distinct roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization labels its printed reports as 'Confidential' and stores them in locked cabinets, while digital files of the same classification require encryption and access logging. What security concept does this scenario illustrate?","o":["Data classification","Asset labeling and handling based on classification","Data retention scheduling","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"This scenario shows how classified assets must be labeled and handled with controls appropriate to their format and sensitivity, which is asset labeling and handling. Classification itself refers to assigning the sensitivity level, not the resulting handling procedures.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which statement BEST describes the primary purpose of establishing a formal data retention policy?","o":["To ensure all data is stored indefinitely to support future business analytics needs","To define how long data must be kept and when it must be securely destroyed, balancing legal/regulatory compliance with storage cost and risk reduction","To guarantee that backup copies of data are never deleted, ensuring maximum availability","To require that all data be classified as Confidential regardless of content"],"c":1,"why":"A retention policy balances compliance obligations (e.g., legal, regulatory) with the risk and cost of retaining data longer than necessary, and mandates secure disposal once the retention period expires. Indefinite retention increases liability and storage costs, and retention policy has nothing to do with mandating a single classification level.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A company's records retention policy requires destruction of email older than three years. During an active litigation matter, legal counsel issues a litigation hold notice covering all communications related to a specific contract dispute, some of which are four years old. What is the correct action regarding the affected emails?","o":["Destroy the emails as scheduled since the retention policy takes precedence over informal legal requests","Preserve all emails covered by the litigation hold regardless of the standard retention schedule until the hold is lifted","Archive only the emails less than three years old and destroy the rest per policy","Forward the emails to legal counsel and then proceed with the normal destruction schedule"],"c":1,"why":"A legal hold overrides normal retention/destruction schedules; failure to preserve relevant records during litigation can result in spoliation sanctions. The other options either ignore the legal obligation or partially comply, which still exposes the organization to spoliation liability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company adopts a security baseline from a recognized standard but removes certain controls that do not apply to its cloud-only environment while adding extra controls for its specific regulatory needs. What is this process called?","o":["Risk acceptance","Scoping and tailoring","Data classification","Configuration management"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping and tailoring involves adjusting a baseline by removing irrelevant controls and adding necessary ones to fit the organization's specific environment. Risk acceptance and configuration management address different aspects of risk management, and classification concerns data sensitivity, not baseline customization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A healthcare provider transmits patient records to an insurance company over the internet for claims processing. Which control BEST protects the confidentiality of this data while it is in transit?","o":["Full disk encryption on the server storing the records","Transport Layer Security (TLS) encrypting the network session","Database-level encryption applied to data at rest","Data masking applied to the fields before storage"],"c":1,"why":"TLS encrypts data as it moves across the network, directly addressing the 'data in transit' state. Full disk encryption and database encryption protect data at rest, not while being transmitted, and data masking obscures values but does not provide transmission security.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A cloud service provider wants to protect sensitive data while it is actively being processed in memory by an application, preventing exposure even to a compromised hypervisor or privileged cloud administrator. Which technology best addresses this requirement?","o":["Transport Layer Security (TLS) for all API communications","Full-disk encryption (FDE) on the underlying storage volumes","Confidential computing using a hardware-based trusted execution environment (TEE)","Data loss prevention (DLP) agents monitoring memory access patterns"],"c":2,"why":"Protecting data in use requires isolating computation and memory from the rest of the system, which is achieved through trusted execution environments (secure enclaves) that encrypt memory and restrict access even from privileged host processes. TLS protects data in transit, FDE protects data at rest, and DLP monitors/alerts on data movement but does not cryptographically protect data being actively processed.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization classifies data based on the potential impact of unauthorized disclosure. Which role is PRIMARILY responsible for assigning the initial classification level to a specific dataset?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data processor","Security administrator"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit leader) has accountability for the data and determines its classification based on business value and impact. The custodian implements protection controls, the processor acts on behalf of a controller, and the security administrator implements technical access controls, none of whom decide classification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"During an asset audit, the security team discovers several unmanaged laptops and IoT devices connected to the corporate network that are not present in the configuration management database (CMDB). Which control would most effectively prevent this situation from recurring?","o":["Requiring annual manual physical inventory counts by department managers","Implementing automated network discovery and access control integrated with CMDB reconciliation","Increasing the frequency of vulnerability scans on known assets","Mandating that employees self-report new devices through a help desk ticket"],"c":1,"why":"Automated discovery tools combined with network access control (e.g., 802.1X) can detect and reconcile unauthorized devices against the CMDB in near real time, closing the gap that manual or self-reported processes leave open. Manual counts and self-reporting rely on human compliance and are easily bypassed, and vulnerability scanning only assesses known assets already in inventory.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization adopts the NIST SP 800-53 control catalog as its security baseline. Because it has no wireless networks anywhere in its environment, the security team removes all wireless-related controls from the baseline before implementation. This activity is an example of which process?","o":["Tailoring","Scoping","Standardization","Categorization"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping is the process of determining which baseline controls apply to a given environment and excluding those that are not relevant (e.g., wireless controls where no wireless exists). Tailoring involves modifying or supplementing controls to fit specific organizational needs, which is a different activity than simply excluding inapplicable controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company is decommissioning SSDs that previously stored highly sensitive financial records. Due to wear-leveling and over-provisioning, traditional overwriting techniques may not reliably erase all data. Which sanitization approach is MOST appropriate for this media type?","o":["Perform a single-pass overwrite using zeros","Degauss the drives using a strong magnetic field","Use the manufacturer's cryptographic erase or ATA Secure Erase command, followed by verification","Reformat the drive using the operating system's quick format utility"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory and wear-leveling, so overwriting or degaussing (a magnetic technique meant for HDDs) is unreliable. Cryptographic erase or vendor-specific secure erase commands, with verification, are recommended by NIST SP 800-88 for flash-based media. Quick format does not remove data at all.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A mobile app development team is designing a new onboarding flow and proposes collecting users' full government ID numbers and precise geolocation history for a feature that only requires age verification and general region for language localization. Which privacy principle is being violated?","o":["Purpose specification, because the data will eventually be used for analytics","Data minimization, because the data collected exceeds what is necessary for the stated functional purpose","Accountability, because no data protection officer was consulted","Data quality, because the collected data may become outdated over time"],"c":1,"why":"Data minimization requires collecting only the data necessary to fulfill a specific, legitimate purpose; collecting a full ID number and precise location for age/region verification far exceeds what is needed. Purpose specification concerns clearly stating why data is collected (not addressed here), accountability concerns governance oversight, and data quality concerns accuracy/currency, neither of which is the core issue described.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A mobile app development team is designing a new fitness-tracking application. To align with privacy best practices, the team decides to collect only the specific data fields required to deliver the core service, avoiding collection of unrelated personal details such as political affiliation or religious beliefs. This practice is an example of which privacy principle?","o":["Least privilege","Data minimization","Separation of duties","Purpose limitation"],"c":1,"why":"Data minimization means collecting only the data necessary to fulfill a defined purpose, reducing exposure and risk. Least privilege and separation of duties are access control concepts unrelated to data collection scope, and purpose limitation concerns restricting the use of already-collected data to its stated purpose rather than limiting what is collected.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A records manager is evaluating sanitization options for a set of decommissioned USB flash drives that contained classified information. Physical destruction is preferred but not immediately available, so an interim control is needed. Which statement about degaussing these devices is accurate?","o":["Degaussing is highly effective on USB flash drives because they use magnetic storage similar to hard disk platters","Degaussing is ineffective on flash-based media because data is stored electronically in NAND cells rather than magnetically","Degaussing effectiveness depends only on the degausser's coercivity rating, regardless of storage technology","Degaussing should be combined with a quick format to achieve NIST-compliant purge status for flash media"],"c":1,"why":"USB flash drives use NAND flash memory, which stores data as electrical charges in floating-gate transistors, not magnetic domains, so degaussing has no effect on them; NIST SP 800-88 specifies cryptographic erase or physical destruction for flash media instead. The other options incorrectly assume magnetic storage principles apply to flash technology.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"During an asset inventory audit, a security analyst discovers several backup tapes stored in a shared cabinet without any labels indicating their classification level or handling requirements. What is the MOST significant risk created by this lack of labeling?","o":["The tapes will degrade faster due to lack of proper environmental labeling","Personnel may apply inconsistent or inadequate handling and protection controls because the required protection level is unknown","The organization will be unable to calculate the depreciation value of the tapes for accounting purposes","The tapes cannot be tracked using RFID asset tags"],"c":1,"why":"Proper labeling ensures personnel handling media know what protection level (access restrictions, encryption, destruction requirements) applies; without it, sensitive data may be mishandled or inadequately protected. The other options describe unrelated or minor operational concerns, not the core security risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of a data classification scheme within an organization?","o":["To determine which employees are eligible for performance bonuses","To ensure that data receives a level of protection appropriate to its sensitivity and value","To satisfy auditors that a policy document exists","To assign monetary value to hardware assets for insurance purposes"],"c":1,"why":"Data classification exists so that appropriate, cost-effective controls can be applied based on sensitivity and value; the other options describe unrelated HR, audit, or hardware valuation activities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"In an information asset management program, who is typically responsible for making day-to-day decisions about who may access a specific dataset and what classification it should carry?","o":["The data custodian","The data owner","The system administrator","The end user"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit manager) has accountability for the data and decides classification and access rights; the custodian implements technical controls, and administrators/users do not set classification policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A multinational organization collects personal data from EU residents and shares it with a third-party marketing firm that determines how the data will be used for targeted advertising. Under GDPR, how would the marketing firm MOST likely be classified?","o":["Data processor, because it only processes data on behalf of another party","Data controller, because it determines the purposes and means of processing","Data subject, because it receives personal data","Data custodian, because it stores the data temporarily"],"c":1,"why":"Because the marketing firm decides how the data will be used (purpose and means), it meets the GDPR definition of a controller rather than a processor, which merely processes data under a controller's instructions. Data subject and custodian are not GDPR-defined roles matching this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the correct order of stages in the information/data lifecycle?","o":["Use, Creation, Disposal, Storage","Creation, Storage, Use, Archival, Disposal","Disposal, Archival, Storage, Creation","Storage, Disposal, Creation, Use"],"c":1,"why":"The generally accepted data lifecycle progresses from creation, through storage and use, to archival, and finally disposal; the other sequences are out of logical order.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A financial services firm is developing a data retention policy for transaction records. Which factor should be the PRIMARY driver in determining how long records must be retained?","o":["The amount of available storage capacity","Regulatory and legal requirements applicable to the industry","The preference of the IT department to minimize backup costs","The average lifespan of the storage media used"],"c":1,"why":"Retention periods must align with applicable laws, regulations, and contractual obligations (e.g., financial recordkeeping rules) to ensure compliance and support legal defensibility. Storage capacity, IT cost preferences, and media lifespan are operational concerns, not the primary driver for retention duration.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is developing a data classification scheme. Which factor should be the PRIMARY basis for assigning a classification level to a given data set?","o":["The cost of the storage media on which the data resides","The potential impact to the organization if the data's confidentiality, integrity, or availability is compromised","The number of employees who currently have access to the data","The age of the data and how long it has been stored"],"c":1,"why":"Classification schemes are driven by the business impact (harm) that would result from loss of confidentiality, integrity, or availability, not by storage cost, current access counts, or data age, which are unrelated or secondary considerations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is decommissioning old magnetic hard drives that once stored highly sensitive data. Which method provides the HIGHEST assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Reformatting the drive using the operating system's quick format option","Deleting all files and emptying the recycle bin","Physically destroying the drive through shredding or degaussing followed by destruction","Overwriting the drive once with a single pass of zeros"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction (shredding/degaussing) provides the highest assurance against data recovery for highly sensitive data; quick formatting, simple deletion, and a single overwrite pass can leave recoverable remnants (data remanence).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is applying baseline security controls from a control framework to a newly acquired subsidiary's systems. The security team removes several controls that do not apply because the subsidiary does not process any regulated health data. This activity is BEST described as:","o":["Scoping","Tailoring","Classification","Standardization"],"c":0,"why":"Scoping involves determining which baseline controls are relevant to a specific environment and removing those that do not apply. Tailoring involves modifying (adding, adjusting) controls to meet specific requirements, rather than eliminating inapplicable ones. Classification concerns labeling data sensitivity, and standardization is not the correct term for this activity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A financial services firm has designated a Data Owner for its customer records. Which of the following responsibilities belongs MOST properly to the Data Owner rather than the Data Custodian?","o":["Performing daily backups of the customer database","Applying approved access controls and encryption as directed","Determining the classification level and approving who may access the data","Physically securing the servers hosting the database"],"c":2,"why":"The Data Owner (typically a senior business manager) has ultimate accountability for the data and decides classification and access policy; the Data Custodian carries out day-to-day technical tasks like backups, applying controls, and physical security.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A records management team must dispose of paper documents containing client Social Security numbers. Which disposal method provides the STRONGEST assurance against data recovery?","o":["Placing documents in a locked recycling bin for pickup","Shredding documents using a cross-cut shredder followed by incineration","Tearing documents in half before discarding them in regular trash","Storing documents in a secure archive indefinitely"],"c":1,"why":"Cross-cut shredding combined with incineration destroys the physical medium and renders reconstruction virtually impossible, providing the strongest assurance for sensitive paper records. Locked bins, tearing, or indefinite storage do not destroy the data and leave it vulnerable to reconstruction or unauthorized access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company's data retention policy specifies how long different types of records must be kept before disposal. What is the PRIMARY benefit of enforcing such a policy?","o":["It guarantees faster network performance by reducing storage use","It eliminates the need for data backups","It ensures compliance with legal/regulatory requirements while minimizing unnecessary long-term liability from keeping data too long","It automatically encrypts all archived data"],"c":2,"why":"Retention policies balance legal/regulatory obligations to keep data with the risk and cost of retaining it longer than necessary; the other options describe unrelated technical effects not guaranteed by a retention policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is decommissioning SSDs that previously stored highly sensitive personal data. According to NIST SP 800-88 guidance, which sanitization method provides the HIGHEST assurance that data cannot be recovered from solid-state media before disposal?","o":["Clearing via a single-pass file deletion","Degaussing the drive with a strong magnetic field","Purging using the cryptographic erase feature or firmware-level secure erase, followed by verification","Simply reformatting the file system"],"c":2,"why":"Degaussing is ineffective on SSDs because they are not magnetic media; simple deletion or reformatting only removes pointers, leaving data recoverable. Purge-level sanitization such as cryptographic erase (with verification) is the NIST-recommended method for SSDs prior to disposal of highly sensitive data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to protect customer data while it is being transmitted between a web application and a database server over the internal network. Which control BEST addresses this requirement?","o":["Full disk encryption on the database server","Encrypting the data using TLS during transmission","Applying a strict data classification label to the database","Implementing role-based access control on the web application only"],"c":1,"why":"Protecting data in transit requires encryption of the communication channel, such as TLS; disk encryption protects data at rest, and classification/access control address different states or aspects of data protection, not transmission confidentiality.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to protect sensitive data while it is being actively processed in server memory by an application. Which control BEST addresses this specific data state?","o":["Full-disk encryption on the storage volume","Transport Layer Security (TLS) for network sessions","Homomorphic encryption or secure enclave-based processing (trusted execution environment)","Encrypting database backup files"],"c":2,"why":"Data 'in use' (being processed in memory/CPU) is protected by techniques like secure enclaves or homomorphic encryption; disk encryption protects data at rest, TLS protects data in transit, and backup encryption protects stored backup copies, none of which secure active processing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which role in an organization is ultimately accountable for assigning a classification level to a specific set of data?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Security administrator","End user"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner has business responsibility for the data and decides its classification and access requirements; the custodian implements controls, the administrator manages systems, and end users simply consume data under established rules.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"During an asset inventory review, a security analyst discovers a critical database server that is not listed in the configuration management database (CMDB) and has no assigned owner. What is the MOST significant risk this situation poses to the organization?","o":["Increased licensing costs due to duplicate software installations","Difficulty applying consistent security controls, patches, and accountability for the asset","Reduced network performance due to unregistered devices","Inability to perform routine hardware refresh cycles"],"c":1,"why":"Assets without ownership or inventory tracking are prone to inconsistent patching, misconfigurations, and lack of accountability, creating significant security risk. While the other issues may occur, the most significant asset security concern is the inability to properly manage and secure an untracked, unowned asset.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"During implementation of a security control baseline, an organization removes controls that do not apply to a particular system and adjusts the remaining controls to fit the system's specific risk environment. This activity is best described as:","o":["Scoping and tailoring","Data classification","Continuous monitoring","Configuration management"],"c":0,"why":"Scoping (removing inapplicable controls) and tailoring (adjusting controls to the environment) are the formal processes for customizing a baseline; classification, monitoring, and configuration management are distinct activities that do not describe this baseline-adjustment process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"When shipping backup tapes containing confidential records to an offsite storage facility, which practice is MOST important for protecting the data during transport?","o":["Labeling the tapes with the company's logo for easy identification","Encrypting the data on the tapes and using a secure, tracked courier service","Sending the tapes via standard postal mail to reduce cost","Storing the tapes in an unmarked cardboard box to avoid detection"],"c":1,"why":"Encryption protects the data's confidentiality if the tapes are lost or intercepted, and a tracked courier ensures chain-of-custody accountability; labeling with sensitive information or using unsecured/unmarked shipping methods increases risk rather than mitigating it.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is developing a scheme to categorize its information based on sensitivity and impact of disclosure. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this data classification process?","o":["To determine which employees receive performance bonuses","To ensure appropriate levels of protection are applied based on the value and sensitivity of the data","To satisfy auditors that a policy document exists","To reduce the total amount of storage required for backups"],"c":1,"why":"Classification allows organizations to apply proportionate security controls—more protection for sensitive data, less overhead for public data. The other options are unrelated administrative or incidental outcomes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A legal team notifies the IT department that certain email records related to an ongoing lawsuit must be preserved beyond the organization's normal retention schedule. This requirement is known as:","o":["Data remanence","A legal hold","Data minimization","Media sanitization"],"c":1,"why":"A legal hold suspends normal destruction/retention schedules to preserve records relevant to litigation or investigation; remanence refers to residual data after deletion, minimization refers to collecting only necessary data, and sanitization refers to secure removal of data, none of which describe litigation preservation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company is decommissioning several hard drives that once stored highly sensitive financial records. Which method provides the HIGHEST assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive with a quick format","Physical destruction of the drive (e.g., shredding or degaussing)","Moving the files to a different folder and renaming them"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction eliminates any possibility of data recovery, whereas deletion, quick formatting, or renaming only remove pointers to the data, leaving the underlying bits recoverable with forensic tools.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored data classified as Top Secret. The security team must select a sanitization method that provides the highest assurance against data recovery, consistent with NIST SP 800-88 guidance. Which approach is most appropriate?","o":["Degaussing the drives using a high-power magnetic degausser before disposal","Performing a single-pass overwrite of all addressable sectors using a standard disk-wiping utility","Executing the drive's built-in cryptographic erase command followed by physical destruction (e.g., shredding)","Reformatting the drives at the file-system level and returning them to the vendor for reuse"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory, so degaussing (a magnetic technique) is ineffective, and overwriting is unreliable due to wear-leveling and over-provisioned blocks that may not be addressed. For the highest sensitivity data, NIST SP 800-88 recommends a purge action (cryptographic erase) combined with physical destroy for maximum assurance; reformatting only removes pointers, not underlying data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Under a typical GDPR-influenced privacy framework, a cloud service provider that processes personal data strictly according to the instructions of a client company, and does not determine the purposes of the processing, is best classified as the:","o":["Data subject","Data controller","Data processor","Data owner"],"c":2,"why":"A data processor handles personal data on behalf of and per the instructions of the controller, who determines the purpose and means of processing; the data subject is the individual the data is about, and 'data owner' is an internal role concept, not the formal privacy-regulation term for this relationship.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the role of a data custodian in an information security program?","o":["Deciding the classification level of data and approving access requests","Setting organizational risk appetite and signing off on data protection budgets","Performing day-to-day operational tasks such as backups, patching, and applying security controls to protect data as directed by the owner","Determining regulatory obligations that apply to the organization's data"],"c":2,"why":"Custodians carry out the technical and operational safeguarding of data on behalf of the owner; classification decisions, risk appetite, and regulatory determinations are owner or senior management responsibilities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"At a financial services firm, the CFO formally authorizes which employees may access customer financial records and determines the classification level of those records. The IT department implements encryption and access control lists based on the CFO's decisions. Which role is the CFO performing?","o":["Data custodian, because they physically manage the storage systems","Data processor, because they perform operations on the data","Data owner, because they have accountability for determining classification and access authorization","Data user, because they access the data as part of daily duties"],"c":2,"why":"The data owner is accountable for classifying information and authorizing who may access it; the custodian (IT) implements the technical controls, and a processor/user merely handles or consumes the data without ownership accountability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization maintains an inventory of information assets to support its asset security program. Which of the following is the MOST important reason for keeping this inventory continuously updated?","o":["It satisfies auditors regardless of accuracy","It allows accurate application of classification, ownership, and protective controls to all assets the organization is responsible for","It reduces the total number of assets the organization must purchase","It eliminates the need for a formal data classification policy"],"c":1,"why":"An accurate, current asset inventory is foundational to asset security because you cannot properly classify, assign ownership, or apply appropriate controls to assets you don't know exist; the other options are either superficial, unrelated to inventory purpose, or incorrect (inventory does not replace classification policy).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that sensitive paper records are not left unattended on desks where visitors could view them. Which policy addresses this concern?","o":["Clean desk policy","Change management policy","Least privilege policy","Separation of duties policy"],"c":0,"why":"A clean desk policy requires employees to secure or clear sensitive materials from their workspace when not in use, directly mitigating the risk described. The other policies govern change control, minimal access rights, and division of tasks, respectively.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A retail company must retain customer transaction records for a period defined by tax regulations, after which the records should be securely destroyed. This requirement is best addressed by which of the following?","o":["An asset inventory","A data retention policy","A business impact analysis","A change control policy"],"c":1,"why":"A data retention policy specifies how long data must be kept to meet legal/regulatory requirements and mandates secure disposal afterward. The other choices address asset tracking, impact analysis, or IT change processes, not retention timelines.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is an example of protecting data 'at rest'?","o":["Using TLS to encrypt a web session between a browser and server","Encrypting the contents of a database stored on a server's disk","Applying digital signatures to an email message in transit","Using a VPN tunnel for remote employee connections"],"c":1,"why":"Data at rest refers to data stored on media such as disks or databases; encrypting stored database files protects it in that state. TLS, VPNs, and signed emails in transit protect data while it is moving across networks, not while stored.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A security architect adopts the NIST SP 800-53 control catalog as a baseline for a system hosted entirely on a cloud IaaS provider. Because the CSP is contractually responsible for physical and environmental security, the architect removes all physical/environmental control families from the applicable control set for this system. Which security baseline activity does this represent?","o":["Tailoring","Scoping","Supplementation","Baseline derivation"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping is the process of determining which controls in a baseline apply to a given system based on its characteristics (e.g., removing physical controls not applicable when infrastructure is managed by a CSP). Tailoring involves adjusting or supplementing the wording or parameters of controls that remain in scope, not eliminating inapplicable ones.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"During asset inventory, a security team discovers a server that is not documented anywhere and has unknown ownership. What is the MOST appropriate immediate action?","o":["Ignore it since it is not causing any known problems","Assign it the lowest possible classification level and move on","Investigate the system to identify its purpose, owner, and data, then document and classify it accordingly","Immediately delete the system to eliminate the unknown risk"],"c":2,"why":"Unidentified assets pose a risk because they cannot be properly secured or classified; the correct action is to investigate, identify ownership/purpose, and bring it under proper inventory and classification controls, rather than ignoring, mislabeling, or destroying it without analysis.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial analytics firm wants a third-party cloud provider to run statistical computations on sensitive client data without the provider ever having access to the plaintext values. Which technology best satisfies this requirement?","o":["Transport Layer Security (TLS) 1.3","Format-preserving encryption","Homomorphic encryption","Full disk encryption (FDE)"],"c":2,"why":"Homomorphic encryption allows mathematical operations to be performed directly on ciphertext, producing an encrypted result that decrypts to the same value as if the operations had been performed on plaintext, without exposing plaintext to the processor. TLS and FDE protect data in transit and at rest respectively, not during processing, and format-preserving encryption still requires decryption before computation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's records retention policy specifies that email is retained for three years and then automatically destroyed. Legal counsel has determined that litigation is reasonably anticipated involving several custodians whose relevant emails fall within the retention window but are approaching the destruction date. What is the correct course of action?","o":["Continue the normal automated destruction schedule to avoid the appearance of favoring one party","Suspend destruction of the relevant records under a legal hold until the litigation matter concludes","Immediately migrate all emails older than the retention period to cold storage to reduce costs","Delegate the retention decision to the records management system administrator without involving legal counsel"],"c":1,"why":"Once litigation is reasonably anticipated, a legal hold overrides the standard retention schedule, and relevant records must be preserved; continuing automated destruction under these circumstances constitutes spoliation and exposes the organization to legal sanctions. Legal holds require legal counsel's involvement, not unilateral administrator decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A manufacturing company is developing a data classification methodology for its proprietary chemical formulas. Which of the following factors is LEAST relevant when determining the appropriate classification level for this data?","o":["The cost of recreating the data if it were lost or destroyed","The competitive advantage the data provides over industry rivals","The physical location of the storage medium within the data center","The regulatory or contractual obligations tied to the data's confidentiality"],"c":2,"why":"Classification level should be driven by the data's value, sensitivity, criticality, and legal/regulatory obligations. The physical location of the storage medium is an operational handling and safeguarding consideration, not a factor that determines the intrinsic classification level of the data itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A SaaS-based HR platform processes employee personal data strictly according to instructions from its client companies, which determine what data is collected and why. Under a GDPR-style data protection framework, which role does the SaaS provider hold, and what is its primary corresponding obligation?","o":["Data controller; obligated to determine the purposes and means of processing","Data processor; obligated to process data only per the controller's instructions and implement appropriate security measures","Data subject; obligated to consent to all processing activities performed on their behalf","Data owner; obligated to classify all data ingested into the platform"],"c":1,"why":"The client company determines the purposes and means of processing and is therefore the controller; the SaaS provider acts on the controller's instructions and is the processor, whose key obligations include following those instructions and implementing appropriate technical and organizational security measures. 'Data subject' refers to the individual whose data is processed, and 'data owner' is not a role recognized in this regulatory context.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization plans to reuse magnetic backup tapes, which previously stored highly sensitive data, for a new system that will only handle lower-classification data within the same organization. Per NIST SP 800-88 sanitization categories, which method is minimally sufficient to allow safe reuse while protecting against advanced laboratory recovery attempts?","o":["Clear – using standard read/write commands to overwrite all addressable storage locations","Purge – applying degaussing or cryptographic erase such that data recovery is infeasible even using state-of-the-art laboratory techniques","Destroy – physically disintegrating, incinerating, or pulverizing the media","Reset – restoring the device to its factory default configuration"],"c":1,"why":"Because the tapes previously held highly sensitive data and will be reused rather than disposed of, Clear is insufficient (it only protects against simple, non-invasive recovery attempts), while Destroy is unnecessarily excessive since the media is intended for continued use. Purge (e.g., degaussing for magnetic tape) provides the necessary assurance against laboratory-level recovery while preserving reusability; 'Reset' is not a recognized NIST sanitization category.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is developing a data classification program. What is the PRIMARY purpose of classifying data assets?","o":["To determine the appropriate level of protection and handling controls based on the value and sensitivity of the data","To calculate the depreciation value of information assets for accounting purposes","To assign network bandwidth priorities based on file size","To determine which employees receive performance bonuses for data entry accuracy"],"c":0,"why":"Data classification exists to ensure information receives protection commensurate with its sensitivity and value to the organization; the other options are unrelated business functions, not security objectives.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Within a data governance model, which role is PRIMARILY responsible for determining the classification level of a specific dataset and approving who may access it?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Security administrator","Data user"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business executive) has accountability for the data and decides classification and access requirements; the custodian implements technical controls, the administrator manages systems, and users simply consume the data under approved access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization has classified its data into four tiers based on sensitivity and potential impact of disclosure. What is the PRIMARY benefit of implementing this classification scheme?","o":["It eliminates the need to encrypt data classified at the lowest tier","It allows security controls and resources to be applied commensurate with the value and sensitivity of the data","It automatically determines the legal retention period required for all data types","It removes the need to formally assign data ownership responsibilities"],"c":1,"why":"Classification's core purpose is to ensure protective controls (access restrictions, encryption, handling procedures) scale appropriately with data sensitivity, optimizing cost and risk. It does not eliminate encryption needs, dictate retention periods on its own, or replace ownership assignment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A business manager at a financial firm is responsible for deciding who may access customer account records and what classification level should be applied to them. Which asset security role does this manager occupy?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data processor","System administrator"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner is accountable for classification decisions and determining access authorization. Custodians and administrators implement technical protections per the owner's direction, and processors merely handle data on another party's behalf.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A defense contractor is decommissioning solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored Top Secret program data. The drives will be transferred to a recycling vendor outside the organization's control and will not be reused internally. Per NIST SP 800-88 Rev. 1 media sanitization guidance, which method is most appropriate?","o":["Degaussing the drives using a high-coercivity degausser","Performing a single-pass overwrite of all addressable storage locations","Issuing the ATA Secure Erase (cryptographic erase) command supported by the drive","Physically destroying the drives through shredding or disintegration"],"c":3,"why":"NIST SP 800-88 recommends the 'Destroy' category for highly sensitive media leaving organizational control. Degaussing is ineffective on flash-based SSDs (no magnetic recording), overwrite is unreliable on SSDs due to wear-leveling, and cryptographic erase (Purge) provides less assurance than physical destruction for Top Secret data leaving custody.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A hospital is decommissioning several solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored protected health information. Which sanitization approach is MOST appropriate to ensure the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Degaussing the drives with a strong magnetic field","Overwriting the drives once with a pattern of zeros","Performing a cryptographic erase combined with the vendor's secure erase command","Deleting the files and emptying the operating system's recycle bin"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs are not magnetic media, so degaussing is ineffective, and wear-leveling makes simple overwrites unreliable for full coverage. Cryptographic erase paired with vendor secure-erase commands is the NIST-recommended method for flash-based media.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A multinational manufacturer is implementing a data governance program. The VP of Sales, whose business unit generates customer contract data, insists that IT determine the classification level because IT 'understands security best.' Which statement correctly reflects proper assignment of asset security responsibilities?","o":["IT should assign classification because it has the technical expertise to protect data at each level","The data owner (the VP of Sales business unit) is accountable for assigning classification, while IT acts as custodian implementing protective controls","The data custodian and data owner share equal accountability for classification decisions","Classification should be assigned by the compliance department to ensure regulatory consistency"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner, typically a business-side role with knowledge of the data's value and impact, is accountable for classification and access decisions; the custodian (IT) implements technical controls based on that classification but does not own the accountability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which combination of technologies provides protection for sensitive data across all three data states: at rest, in transit, and in use?","o":["Full disk encryption, TLS, and secure enclaves or trusted execution environments","File-level access control lists, VPN tunnels, and antivirus software","Database column encryption, digital signatures, and static data masking","Backup encryption, network firewalls, and intrusion detection systems"],"c":0,"why":"Full disk encryption protects data at rest, TLS protects data in transit, and secure enclaves/TEEs protect data while it is being processed (in use). The other option sets fail to address the in-use state adequately.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is decommissioning several traditional magnetic hard disk drives that contained highly sensitive financial records. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate to ensure the data cannot be recovered while allowing the drives to be reused?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Performing a full format of the drive","Degaussing followed by verification, or a NIST-approved purge method","Relabeling the drive with a lower classification sticker"],"c":2,"why":"Degaussing (for magnetic media) or an approved purge technique renders data unrecoverable while the media may still be reused; deleting files, quick formatting, or relabeling do not remove the underlying data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"During ongoing litigation, an organization receives a legal hold notice requiring preservation of certain records. The organization's standard retention policy calls for those records to be destroyed within 30 days. What is the correct course of action?","o":["Proceed with the scheduled destruction because internal policy governs regardless of external notices","Suspend destruction of the affected records until the legal hold is officially lifted","Destroy only the electronic copies while retaining any paper originals","Encrypt the records and then destroy the encryption keys instead of deleting the data"],"c":1,"why":"A legal hold legally overrides standard retention schedules and requires preservation of all relevant records, in any form, until the hold is released. Destroying any copies or effectively destroying data via key destruction would violate the hold and could result in legal sanctions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which control is generally considered MOST effective for protecting the confidentiality of sensitive data while it is stored on a laptop hard drive (data at rest)?","o":["Full-disk encryption","Network intrusion detection system","Mandatory access control on the network firewall","Anti-malware signature updates"],"c":0,"why":"Full-disk encryption directly protects data at rest on the storage medium, even if the device is lost or stolen; the other controls address network-based threats, not local data-at-rest confidentiality.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"According to NIST SP 800-88 media sanitization guidelines, which term describes a method that applies logical techniques, such as standard overwriting, to sanitize all user-addressable storage locations and provides protection against simple, non-invasive data recovery techniques?","o":["Destroy","Purge","Clear","Discard"],"c":2,"why":"'Clear' refers to logical sanitization methods offering a moderate assurance level against basic recovery tools. 'Purge' involves techniques resistant to advanced laboratory recovery, and 'Destroy' involves physical destruction of the media; 'Discard' is not a defined NIST 800-88 term.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company's records retention policy states that customer transaction records must be kept for seven years and then securely destroyed. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of enforcing the destruction portion of this policy?","o":["It frees up storage budget for other departments","It reduces the organization's liability and attack surface by eliminating data no longer needed for business or legal purposes","It ensures compliance with data classification labeling standards","It automatically upgrades the remaining data to a higher classification level"],"c":1,"why":"Destroying data once its retention period expires reduces the amount of sensitive information that could be breached or subpoenaed, minimizing risk and liability; the other options are not accurate security rationales.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization adopts NIST SP 800-53 as its control baseline. The security team determines that several physical and environmental protection controls in the baseline do not apply because all systems are hosted in a cloud IaaS environment with no organizationally managed facilities. The team also adjusts the minimum password length parameter from the baseline default of 8 characters to 14 characters to align with organizational risk tolerance. What best describes these two activities, respectively?","o":["Both activities are examples of tailoring","Removing inapplicable physical controls is scoping; adjusting the password parameter is tailoring","Removing inapplicable physical controls is tailoring; adjusting the password parameter is scoping","Both activities are examples of scoping"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping determines which baseline controls apply given the environment (removing irrelevant physical controls for a cloud-only deployment), while tailoring adjusts parameters of controls that remain applicable (such as password length) to fit organizational needs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A security team is adapting the NIST SP 800-53 control catalog for a system categorized as low-impact. The team removes controls not applicable to the system's operating environment and adjusts the strength of certain remaining controls based on a risk assessment. This activity BEST describes which process?","o":["Baselining","Scoping and tailoring","System categorization","Configuration management"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping removes inapplicable controls, and tailoring adjusts control parameters to fit the specific environment and risk level. Baselining refers to establishing the initial control set itself, categorization determines impact level, and configuration management addresses system state changes, not control selection.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes personally identifiable information (PII)?","o":["Any data stored in a relational database with a primary key","Information that can be used alone or in combination with other information to identify a specific individual","Any data classified as 'Confidential' by the organization","Information that is encrypted using asymmetric algorithms"],"c":1,"why":"PII is defined by its ability to identify a specific person, either alone or combined with other data; the other options describe unrelated technical or classification characteristics.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A government agency classified a research report as Secret five years ago due to sensitive methodology. The original classifying authority has since retired. A records manager wants to downgrade the report to Unclassified because five years have passed and no automatic declassification date was specified. What is the correct approach?","o":["Automatically downgrade the classification since five years is a reasonable default retention period for Secret information","The records manager may downgrade the document since the original authority is no longer available","The document should undergo formal declassification review by an authorized classifying authority with jurisdiction, since no automatic date was set and unilateral downgrade by non-authorized personnel is improper","The document should remain classified permanently because the original authority did not specify a declassification date"],"c":2,"why":"Declassification requires review by an authority with proper jurisdiction; absent a preset declassification date, an unauthorized party downgrading the document unilaterally is improper, and lack of a set date does not mean permanent classification is required.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"According to common data sanitization guidance (such as NIST SP 800-88), which term describes the sanitization method that renders data recovery infeasible using state-of-the-art laboratory techniques, typically achieved through physical destruction such as shredding or incineration?","o":["Clear","Purge","Destroy","Archive"],"c":2,"why":"'Destroy' is the most rigorous sanitization category, physically destroying the media so data cannot be recovered even with advanced lab techniques; 'clear' and 'purge' are less rigorous logical/physical techniques that may still allow reuse of media, and 'archive' is unrelated to sanitization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A cloud-based payroll service processes employee salary data on behalf of client companies but does not decide how the data is used, shared, or how long it is retained. Under common privacy frameworks, which role does the payroll service occupy?","o":["Data owner","Data controller","Data processor","Data custodian for the client organization"],"c":2,"why":"A data processor acts on behalf of and under the instructions of a data controller, which determines the purposes and means of processing. Since the payroll service does not decide how data is used or retained, it is not acting as owner or controller.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A healthcare analytics company wants a third-party cloud provider to perform statistical computations on encrypted patient records without the provider ever gaining access to the plaintext values, including during processing in memory. Which technology best satisfies this requirement?","o":["Transport Layer Security (TLS) for all API calls to the provider","Full-disk encryption on the provider's storage volumes","Homomorphic encryption allowing computation directly on ciphertext","Tokenization of patient identifiers before transmission"],"c":2,"why":"Homomorphic encryption allows mathematical operations on ciphertext, protecting data-in-use without decryption. TLS secures data-in-transit, full-disk encryption secures data-at-rest, and tokenization protects identifiers but does not enable computation on sensitive values without detokenization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is building a database that aggregates several types of records, including public marketing brochures and customer Social Security numbers. Which classification level should be assigned to the entire database?","o":["The classification level of the data type accessed most frequently","The highest classification level of any data type contained within the database","An average of the classification levels of the contained data types","The classification of the data type occupying the most storage space"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregated data stores must be classified at the level of their most sensitive component, since a breach exposes the highest-sensitivity data regardless of volume or access frequency. Averaging, frequency, or volume-based approaches would understate risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company labels its files as Public, Internal, Confidential, and Restricted. An employee copies a Restricted file to a USB drive without approval and takes it home. Which asset security control failure does this scenario BEST illustrate?","o":["Failure to enforce data handling and media control procedures based on classification","Failure to apply the correct encryption algorithm to the file","Failure to update the data classification scheme annually","Failure to assign a data owner to the file"],"c":0,"why":"Restricted data requires strict handling controls, such as prohibiting unauthorized removable media use; this scenario shows a breakdown in enforcing those handling procedures rather than an issue with encryption algorithms, review cycles, or ownership assignment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's records retention policy specifies that email communications are destroyed after three years. Legal counsel issues a litigation hold notifying IT that certain custodians' emails, including some past their three-year retention mark, may be relevant to pending litigation. What should the organization do?","o":["Continue following the standard retention schedule since it was established and approved by management","Immediately destroy the emails to avoid the appearance of tampering with evidence after the hold","Suspend destruction of all emails within the scope of the litigation hold, regardless of the standard retention schedule, until the hold is lifted","Destroy only the emails older than three years, since those exceeding the schedule are not part of active business records"],"c":2,"why":"A litigation hold legally supersedes standard retention schedules; destroying records after notice of relevant litigation constitutes spoliation of evidence and can result in sanctions, regardless of the age of the records or existing policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A business unit manager determines the classification of a data set and approves who may access it, while the IT department applies the assigned access controls and performs backups on the manager's behalf. Which role does the IT department represent?","o":["Data Owner","Data Custodian","Data Processor under GDPR","Data Controller"],"c":1,"why":"The Data Custodian implements and maintains technical protections (backups, access controls) as directed by the Data Owner, who retains accountability for classification and access decisions. Processor/Controller are GDPR-specific terms not applicable here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored data classified as Top Secret. The drives will be permanently removed from organizational control and disposed of through a third-party recycler. Which sanitization approach is MOST appropriate given the media type and destination of the data?","o":["Degaussing the SSDs using a high-powered magnetic field to erase all data","Performing a single-pass overwrite of all addressable sectors using a disk-wipe utility","Physically destroying the drives (e.g., shredding or disintegration) after cryptographic erasure of any self-encrypting drive keys","Running the manufacturer's quick-format utility and verifying the drive shows as empty in the operating system"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory (not magnetic media), so degaussing is ineffective, and wear-leveling/overprovisioning makes single-pass overwrites unreliable for full sanitization. Because the media is leaving organizational control and held Top Secret data, NIST SP 800-88 calls for the Destroy category (physical destruction), ideally combined with crypto-erase if the drive is self-encrypting; a quick format leaves recoverable data on flash cells.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A US-based e-commerce company (Company A) uses a third-party SaaS marketing platform (Company B) to send targeted email campaigns to EU customers. Company A determines which customers receive which offers and what data fields are used, while Company B merely executes the mailings per Company A's instructions and does not decide the purposes of processing. Under GDPR, how should these two organizations be classified?","o":["Company A is the data processor and Company B is the data controller","Both companies are joint controllers with equal liability","Company A is the data controller and Company B is the data processor","Company B is not subject to GDPR since it only executes instructions"],"c":2,"why":"The entity determining the purposes and means of processing (Company A) is the controller, while the entity processing data on the controller's instructions (Company B) is the processor; processors remain subject to GDPR obligations even without decision-making authority.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution is retiring several magnetic hard drives containing highly sensitive customer records. The drives will not be reused, and management wants absolute assurance that no data can ever be recovered. Per NIST SP 800-88 guidance, which sanitization method is most appropriate?","o":["Clear – single-pass overwrite","Purge – degaussing","Destroy – physical disintegration or shredding","Format the drive using the operating system's quick format utility"],"c":2,"why":"For highly sensitive data on media that will never be reused, Destroy provides the highest assurance against recovery. Clear and quick formatting leave recoverable remnants, and while Purge/degaussing is stronger than Clear, physical destruction is the most conservative choice when reuse is not required.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A large healthcare organization has assigned the following responsibilities: Person A decides the classification level of patient records and approves who may access them; Person B applies encryption, configures access control lists, and performs scheduled backups of the records per Person A's instructions; Person C works with the business units to ensure the data fields are accurate, consistently defined, and fit for use in analytics. Which roles do Person B and Person C respectively hold?","o":["Person B is the data owner; Person C is the data processor","Person B is the data custodian; Person C is the data steward","Person B is the data controller; Person C is the data custodian","Person B is the system owner; Person C is the data owner"],"c":1,"why":"The data custodian performs the technical, day-to-day tasks (encryption, ACLs, backups) at the direction of the data owner, while the data steward focuses on data quality, definitions, and business context. Person A—not B—holds accountability as the data owner; a data processor/controller are GDPR-specific terms describing entities that process data on behalf of a controller, which doesn't fit this internal role description.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A company stores tenant data in a multi-tenant public cloud storage service where physical drives cannot be isolated, retrieved, or physically destroyed by the customer. When a customer's contract ends and their data must be sanitized, which approach provides the most practical and effective assurance of sanitization in this environment?","o":["Requesting the cloud provider degauss the affected storage media","Cryptographic erasure — destroying the encryption keys used to protect the customer's data, rendering the ciphertext unrecoverable","Requesting a certificate of physical destruction for the underlying drives","Relying on the cloud provider's standard data overwrite procedures upon account deletion"],"c":1,"why":"In multi-tenant environments where physical media cannot be isolated or destroyed for a single tenant, cryptographic erasure (destroying the keys) is the practical, NIST-recommended sanitization method; degaussing and physical destruction are infeasible for shared media, and standard overwrite may not reach all distributed replicas.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which technology provides the strongest protection for sensitive data while it is actively being processed in a system's memory (data in use)?","o":["Full disk encryption","TLS 1.3 for network transport","A hardware-based trusted execution environment (secure enclave)","File-level encryption at rest"],"c":2,"why":"Trusted execution environments isolate and encrypt data during active processing in memory, directly addressing the data-in-use state. Disk encryption and TLS protect data at rest and in transit respectively, not while being computed on.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's data classification policy states that documents automatically move from 'Confidential' to 'Internal Use Only' five years after creation. During an audit, it is discovered that several 4-year-old Confidential documents now contain information that has become publicly available through other channels. What is the MOST appropriate action regarding classification?","o":["Wait until the automatic 5-year downgrade date is reached, since the policy already accounts for declassification timing","Immediately reclassify the documents to a lower level without further review, since the information is now public","Initiate a formal reclassification review to verify the information is fully public and update the classification and handling controls accordingly before the automatic timeline","Leave the classification unchanged, since only the original data owner may ever alter classification and no review process exists for early declassification"],"c":2,"why":"Classification should reflect actual sensitivity, not just a fixed timer; when circumstances change (e.g., information becomes public), a formal review—typically initiated by or coordinated with the data owner—should reassess and adjust classification promptly rather than waiting on an arbitrary schedule or changing it without verification. Automatic timelines are a baseline, not a substitute for event-driven review, and reclassification decisions still require proper authority and validation, not blanket rules to never or always change classification outside the formal process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Legal counsel advises that certain financial transaction records must be retained for seven years under regulatory requirements, but management wants to delete them after two years to reduce storage costs. What is the BEST course of action for the security professional?","o":["Retain the records per the legal retention requirement and implement a cost-effective archiving strategy","Delete the records after two years since storage cost reduction is a valid business justification","Retain all records indefinitely to eliminate any compliance risk","Allow each business unit to independently set its own retention period"],"c":0,"why":"Legal and regulatory retention requirements take precedence over cost concerns; the correct approach is compliant retention combined with efficient archiving. Early deletion violates compliance, indefinite retention creates unnecessary liability, and decentralized policies undermine consistency.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm is decommissioning a set of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored highly sensitive customer records. The security team initially proposes degaussing as the sanitization method. Why is this approach inappropriate, and what should be used instead?","o":["Degaussing is inappropriate because SSDs use flash memory rather than magnetic storage, so cryptographic erase or physical destruction should be used instead","Degaussing is inappropriate because it takes too long for large volumes of drives, so overwriting with zeros three times should be used instead","Degaussing is inappropriate because it violates NIST 800-88 clearing requirements, so a single-pass overwrite should be used instead","Degaussing is inappropriate because it can only be performed by the original manufacturer, so a factory reset should be used instead"],"c":0,"why":"Degaussing relies on disrupting magnetic domains and has no effect on flash-based SSDs; wear-leveling also makes overwriting unreliable for SSDs, so NIST 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase (if the drive was encrypted) or physical destruction. The other options misstate the actual technical limitation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization has adopted NIST SP 800-53 as its control catalog. The security team removes several controls that address wireless access because the environment has no wireless technology, and then modifies the remaining access control requirements to reference the organization's specific multi-factor authentication solution. Which two activities are being performed, in order?","o":["Tailoring, then scoping","Scoping, then tailoring","Baselining, then scoping","Tailoring, then baselining"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping is the process of determining which controls in a baseline are applicable to the environment (removing irrelevant wireless controls), while tailoring involves adjusting the wording/parameters of applicable controls to fit the specific environment (referencing the actual MFA solution). Baselining refers to selecting the initial control set, which already occurred before this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization adopts NIST SP 800-53 as its security baseline. For a specific system that has no wireless capability, the security team removes all wireless-related controls from the applicable control set before implementation. This activity is best described as:","o":["Scoping","Tailoring","Baselining","Standardization"],"c":0,"why":"Scoping is the process of determining which baseline controls are applicable and removing those that do not apply due to system characteristics (e.g., no wireless capability). Tailoring involves adjusting the parameters of controls that remain applicable, not eliminating irrelevant ones.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's data governance policy assigns responsibility for determining the classification level of a dataset, approving access requests, and defining acceptable use. Which role is being described?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data processor","Data steward"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business executive) has ultimate accountability for the data, including classification and access authorization decisions. The custodian implements technical controls, the steward manages day-to-day data quality/metadata, and the processor acts on behalf of the owner without independent authority.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A company's records retention policy requires deletion of customer transaction records after seven years. During a scheduled purge cycle, the legal department issues a litigation hold notice covering records related to a specific customer dispute, some of which are due for deletion that week. What is the CORRECT course of action?","o":["Proceed with the scheduled deletion, since the retention policy takes precedence over informal legal requests","Suspend deletion of all records covered by the litigation hold until legal counsel confirms the hold has been lifted, while continuing normal deletion of unrelated records","Delete the records immediately to avoid the appearance of evidence tampering once litigation is anticipated","Extend the retention period for all customer records company-wide until the litigation concludes"],"c":1,"why":"A litigation hold legally supersedes standard retention schedules for the specific records in scope; failing to preserve them can constitute spoliation of evidence. Deleting the records (options 1 and 3) creates legal liability, while extending retention for all records company-wide is overbroad and not required—the hold should be scoped to the relevant records only.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A retail company collects customer data for its own marketing purposes and contracts a cloud analytics vendor to process that data strictly according to the retailer's written instructions. Under GDPR, which role does the vendor perform?","o":["Data Controller","Data Processor","Data Owner","Data Subject"],"c":1,"why":"A Data Processor acts on behalf of and under the instructions of the Data Controller, which in this case is the retailer that determines the purpose and means of processing. The vendor does not independently decide how the data is used, so it cannot be the Controller.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is applying an industry security baseline (e.g., CIS Benchmarks) to a new database server. The server does not use several services covered by the baseline, and the organization has additional regulatory requirements not addressed by the baseline. Which two activities should the architect perform?","o":["Scoping to remove inapplicable baseline items, and tailoring to add controls for additional regulatory requirements","Tailoring to remove inapplicable baseline items, and scoping to add controls for additional regulatory requirements","Standardization to remove inapplicable items, and normalization to add regulatory controls","Gap analysis to remove inapplicable items, and benchmarking to add regulatory controls"],"c":0,"why":"Scoping is the process of determining which baseline controls apply to a given system (removing irrelevant ones), while tailoring involves modifying or supplementing controls to meet organization-specific needs such as additional regulations. The other terms are not the standard CISSP definitions for these activities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A payment-processing application decrypts cardholder data in memory to perform transaction validation. Security testing reveals that malware capable of scraping process memory could extract clear-text PANs during this processing window. Which control BEST addresses this specific exposure of data in use?","o":["Enable full-disk encryption on the servers hosting the application","Enforce TLS 1.2 or higher for all data transmitted between the application and the payment gateway","Process the sensitive fields within a hardware-based secure enclave or use format-preserving tokenization so clear-text PANs never reside in general-purpose memory","Implement stricter role-based access control on the database storing the encrypted cardholder data"],"c":2,"why":"Data-in-use exposure requires controls that limit clear-text processing itself, such as secure enclaves (e.g., trusted execution environments) or tokenization, which prevent memory-scraping malware from obtaining usable PAN data. Full-disk encryption protects data at rest, TLS protects data in transit, and database RBAC protects data at rest/access—none address the in-memory exposure during processing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Why is cryptographic erasure generally preferred over degaussing when sanitizing solid-state drives (SSDs)?","o":["Degaussing relies on magnetic fields, but SSDs store data electronically rather than magnetically, making degaussing ineffective","Cryptographic erasure physically destroys the storage medium, guaranteeing data cannot be recovered","Degaussing sanitizes SSDs faster than cryptographic erasure","SSDs cannot support encryption, so cryptographic erasure is the only compliant sanitization method"],"c":0,"why":"SSDs use flash memory, not magnetic platters, so degaussing has no effect on them; cryptographic erasure (destroying the encryption key for previously encrypted data) is effective and appropriate for solid-state media. It does not physically destroy the drive, and SSDs are commonly encrypted, making the other statements false.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of data classification within an organization?","o":["To determine the monetary value of company assets for insurance purposes","To ensure information receives an appropriate level of protection based on its sensitivity and value","To satisfy audit requirements without affecting daily operations","To assign IP addresses to systems that store sensitive data"],"c":1,"why":"Data classification exists so that information is protected according to its sensitivity and criticality, ensuring appropriate controls are applied. The other options are unrelated or secondary benefits, not the primary purpose.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A cloud customer stores sensitive data in an IaaS provider's block storage volumes and enables provider-managed encryption at rest. Who retains ultimate accountability for ensuring the confidentiality of this data under a typical shared responsibility model?","o":["The cloud service provider, because they physically control the storage media and encryption service","The cloud customer (data owner), because responsibility for data protection cannot be transferred even when technical implementation is outsourced","Neither party, because encryption at rest fully discharges both parties from further security obligations","The key management service vendor, because they generate and store the encryption keys"],"c":1,"why":"In shared responsibility models, the customer as data owner remains accountable for data classification, access control, and overall protection of their data regardless of who implements the underlying encryption; providers are responsible for the infrastructure but not for the customer's data governance decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A SaaS provider stores customer data on shared, multi-tenant storage infrastructure where the customer has no ability to request physical destruction of specific disks. The customer's data was encrypted client-side before upload, with encryption keys managed solely by the customer. When the contract ends, which method provides the customer with a defensible, practical assurance that their data is rendered unrecoverable?","o":["Request that the SaaS provider overwrite the customer's specific data blocks three times per DoD 5220.22-M standards","Request contractual confirmation that the provider's storage arrays will be degaussed at end of life","Destroy the customer-held encryption keys used to encrypt the data (cryptographic erasure), rendering the ciphertext permanently unreadable","Request that the provider migrate the data to a dedicated single-tenant volume prior to deletion so physical destruction can occur"],"c":2,"why":"Since the data was encrypted client-side and the customer solely controls the keys, cryptographic erasure (destroying the keys) is the practical and effective sanitization method in a multi-tenant environment where physical destruction or media-specific overwriting is infeasible. Degaussing doesn't apply to typical SSD-based cloud storage, block overwriting on shared multi-tenant storage isn't operationally offered by providers, and migrating to single-tenant storage is an unnecessary and impractical step when the keys already control accessibility.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization labels physical media containing Top Secret research data with color-coded stickers and stores it in a locked, access-controlled safe. A junior analyst suggests removing the labels to make the media less identifiable to potential thieves, reasoning that unlabeled media is less likely to be targeted. What is the primary flaw in this reasoning?","o":["Labeling is only a regulatory formality and provides no operational security benefit, so removing it would have no negative effect","Removing labels would violate copyright law regarding data marking requirements","Unlabeled sensitive media increases risk of mishandling, improper disposal, or accidental disclosure by authorized personnel who cannot identify its sensitivity, and security through obscurity is not a reliable control","Labels are required only for data in transit, not for data at rest in a secured facility, so the suggestion is technically correct"],"c":2,"why":"Proper labeling ensures authorized users apply correct handling, storage, and disposal procedures; removing it relies on obscurity rather than actual controls and increases the risk of accidental mishandling by legitimate personnel, which outweighs any marginal deterrent to external attackers already facing physical/access controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"In an organization's data governance model, who is ultimately accountable for determining the classification level of a specific dataset?","o":["The data custodian","The data owner","The system administrator","The security auditor"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit leader) is accountable for classifying data and defining protection requirements. Custodians implement controls, administrators manage systems, and auditors verify compliance, but none of them make classification decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A healthcare organization wants to allow researchers to analyze patient datasets without exposing identifiable information, while still permitting the data to be re-linked to specific patients later if a safety signal is discovered. Which data protection technique best satisfies both requirements?","o":["Anonymization, since it permanently removes all identifying information from the dataset","Data masking, since it visually obscures fields without altering the underlying stored values","Aggregation, since it summarizes data at a population level to prevent identification","Pseudonymization, since it replaces identifiers with reversible tokens that can be re-linked using a securely stored mapping"],"c":3,"why":"Pseudonymization substitutes direct identifiers with tokens while maintaining a separately secured mapping, enabling authorized re-identification later, unlike anonymization which is irreversible by design. Masking and aggregation are used for display or statistical purposes and do not support controlled re-linkage.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the responsibility of a data custodian?","o":["Deciding the business value and classification of data","Implementing and maintaining the technical controls required to protect data as directed by the data owner","Approving exceptions to data protection policy","Defining regulatory compliance requirements for the organization"],"c":1,"why":"Data custodians perform the hands-on technical work (backups, access controls, storage management) to protect data per the owner's instructions. Classification decisions and policy exceptions belong to the data owner, not the custodian.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"During an asset inventory audit, a security team discovers several virtual machine templates and container images stored in a registry that are not tracked in the configuration management database (CMDB) but are actively used to deploy production workloads. What is the MOST significant risk this gap creates?","o":["Increased storage costs due to duplicate images consuming registry space","Inability to enforce vulnerability management, patching, and configuration baselines on assets that are not formally tracked or owned","Reduced performance of the container orchestration platform due to untracked image sprawl","Violation of software licensing terms for the container runtime engine"],"c":1,"why":"Untracked assets fall outside patch management, vulnerability scanning, and configuration baseline enforcement processes because no one is accountable for them, creating significant security exposure; the other options describe secondary operational concerns rather than the core asset security risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is decommissioning hard drives that once stored highly confidential customer records. Which method provides the HIGHEST assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Deleting all files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive using a quick format","Physical destruction of the drive (e.g., shredding or degaussing)","Moving the files to an encrypted archive folder"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction eliminates any possibility of data remanence and recovery, making it the most assured method for highly sensitive data. Deletion, quick formatting, and simply relocating files leave recoverable data on the media.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY reason organizations establish data retention policies?","o":["To reduce the amount of storage hardware purchased each year","To ensure data is kept only as long as necessary for business, legal, or regulatory requirements","To guarantee that all data is encrypted while stored","To prevent employees from accessing outdated files"],"c":1,"why":"Retention policies balance business needs and legal/regulatory obligations against the risks and costs of keeping data indefinitely. Storage cost reduction, encryption, and access restriction may be side effects but are not the primary driver.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"When physically labeling storage media containing sensitive information, what is the MAIN security benefit of applying classification labels?","o":["It allows personnel to identify the required handling and protection measures for the media","It increases the resale value of the media","It automatically encrypts the data on the media","It eliminates the need for access control lists"],"c":0,"why":"Labeling communicates the sensitivity level so personnel know how to handle, store, and transport the media appropriately. Labels do not affect resale value, encryption, or the need for access controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Under common privacy frameworks such as GDPR, which entity is responsible for determining the purposes and means of processing personal data?","o":["The data processor","The data subject","The data controller","The data custodian"],"c":2,"why":"The data controller decides why and how personal data is processed and bears primary accountability for compliance. The processor acts on the controller's instructions, the data subject is the individual the data pertains to, and 'data custodian' is not a formal privacy-law role.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following best describes the PRIMARY responsibility of a data owner within an organization's information classification program?","o":["Implementing technical controls to protect data based on its classification level","Determining the appropriate classification level for data and approving access requests","Performing day-to-day backup and recovery operations for the data","Conducting user awareness training on data handling procedures"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (business owner) is accountable for classifying data and approving access; implementing technical controls and performing backups are custodian duties, and awareness training is typically handled by the security team.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization must securely dispose of solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained highly sensitive financial data. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate for SSDs?","o":["Degaussing the drives using a high-powered magnetic field","Overwriting the drives with a single pass of zeros","Cryptographic erasure combined with physical destruction","Reformatting the drive's file system"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs are not magnetic media, so degaussing is ineffective, and wear-leveling makes simple overwriting unreliable; NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase followed by physical destruction for high-sensitivity SSD sanitization. Reformatting only removes file pointers, not actual data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"In asset security, who is typically accountable for defining the classification level of a specific data set and approving who may access it?","o":["The data custodian","The data owner","The system administrator","The end user"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner has ultimate accountability for classifying data and authorizing access; custodians implement controls, administrators manage systems, and end users merely consume data per granted permissions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A healthcare organization performs real-time analytics on patient records while they reside in system memory. Which control provides confidentiality protection specifically for data while it is being actively processed?","o":["Full disk encryption","Homomorphic encryption or a Trusted Execution Environment (TEE)","Transport Layer Security (TLS)","Application-layer data masking"],"c":1,"why":"Homomorphic encryption and TEEs protect data in use; full disk encryption protects data at rest, TLS protects data in transit, and masking obscures values but does not secure active processing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which sanitization method is generally considered most effective for completely destroying data on a magnetic hard drive that will be disposed of and never reused?","o":["Formatting the drive using the operating system's quick format option","Deleting all files and emptying the recycle bin","Physical destruction (e.g., shredding or crushing) of the drive","Renaming the files to obscure their original names"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction ensures data cannot be recovered from media that will not be reused; formatting, deletion, and renaming leave data recoverable through forensic techniques.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"When establishing a data retention policy, which factor should PRIMARILY determine the retention period for a given category of data?","o":["The amount of storage capacity available in the data center","Applicable legal, regulatory, and business requirements","The IT department's preference to minimize backup costs","The age of the technology used to store the data"],"c":1,"why":"Retention periods must be driven by legal, regulatory, and business obligations, not by storage limitations, IT convenience, or the age of storage technology.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization establishes a policy stating that customer financial records must be kept for seven years and then securely destroyed. This policy primarily addresses which asset security concept?","o":["Data retention","Data classification","Data remanence","Data minimization"],"c":0,"why":"Retention policies define how long data must be kept before disposal, driven by legal/regulatory requirements; classification concerns sensitivity labeling, remanence concerns residual data after erasure, and minimization concerns collecting only necessary data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company adopts NIST SP 800-53 as its control baseline. The security team removes controls that do not apply to a low-impact system and adjusts parameter values on remaining controls to match organizational risk tolerance. This process is known as?","o":["Scoping and tailoring","Data classification","Baseline hardening","Control inheritance"],"c":0,"why":"Scoping removes controls that are not applicable, and tailoring adjusts parameters to fit the organization; hardening refers to secure configuration, and control inheritance describes reuse of shared controls across systems, neither of which matches this process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Under common privacy frameworks, an organization that determines the purposes and means of processing personal data (rather than merely processing it on another's behalf) is best described as the:","o":["Data processor","Data subject","Data controller","Data custodian"],"c":2,"why":"The data controller decides why and how personal data is processed; the processor acts under the controller's instructions, the data subject is the individual the data is about, and the custodian is an operational/technical role, not a privacy-law term for this decision authority.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Under privacy regulations such as the GDPR, which role is held by the organization that determines the purposes and means of processing personal data?","o":["Data processor","Data custodian","Data controller","Data subject"],"c":2,"why":"The data controller decides why and how personal data is processed; the processor acts on the controller's instructions, the custodian is an internal technical safeguarding role, and the data subject is the individual whose data is processed.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Encrypting a database file stored on a server's disk, where the file is not currently being read or written by any application, is an example of protecting data in which state?","o":["Data in transit","Data in use","Data at rest","Data in motion"],"c":2,"why":"Data at rest refers to data stored on media without active processing or transmission; in transit/motion refers to data being transmitted, and in use refers to data actively being processed in memory.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following is the BEST reason for applying classification labels to physical and electronic assets?","o":["Labels reduce the overall cost of asset acquisition","Labels enable personnel to apply appropriate handling and protection controls","Labels are required for insurance claims processing","Labels eliminate the need for periodic asset inventory audits"],"c":1,"why":"Classification labels exist to guide personnel in applying consistent, appropriate handling and protective measures; the other options are not the primary purpose of classification labeling.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Maintaining an accurate and up-to-date inventory of organizational assets is a foundational asset security control primarily because it:","o":["Automatically encrypts all sensitive files","Enables the organization to identify what needs to be protected and apply appropriate controls","Eliminates the need for a data classification policy","Guarantees compliance with all applicable privacy laws"],"c":1,"why":"You cannot protect what you don't know you have; an asset inventory is a prerequisite for applying classification and controls. It does not itself encrypt data, replace classification policy, or guarantee legal compliance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution needs to dispose of backup magnetic tapes containing sensitive customer data. Which method provides the MOST effective sanitization for this type of media?","o":["Deleting the file index stored on the tape","Degaussing with an approved high-coercivity degausser","Overwriting the tape with random data three times","Storing the tapes in a locked cabinet until the retention period expires"],"c":1,"why":"Degaussing is the standard, effective sanitization method for magnetic tape; deleting the file index leaves data recoverable, overwriting sequential tape media is impractical and unreliable, and locked storage is retention, not sanitization or disposal.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company shreds printed reports containing sensitive customer information before disposal. This practice is an example of which asset security activity?","o":["Data labeling","Secure media/data disposal","Data classification","Access provisioning"],"c":1,"why":"Shredding physical media to prevent recovery of sensitive information is a secure disposal practice; it is not labeling (marking sensitivity), classification (assigning sensitivity levels), or provisioning (granting access).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is developing its data classification scheme. Which factor should be the PRIMARY basis for assigning a classification level to a given data set?","o":["The physical storage location of the data within the data center","The potential impact to the organization if the data's confidentiality, integrity, or availability is compromised","The job title of the employee who originally created the data","The file format and size of the data set"],"c":1,"why":"Classification levels are meant to reflect the sensitivity and criticality of data based on the harm that would result from loss of confidentiality, integrity, or availability. Storage location, creator's title, and file size do not indicate the data's actual risk or value to the organization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"In a data governance program, the data owner has classified a set of records as 'Confidential' and specified that access must be restricted to a named group of employees. Which task is MOST appropriate for the data custodian to perform?","o":["Determine the appropriate classification level for the records","Implement and maintain the access control lists and encryption required to enforce the owner's requirements","Approve or deny individual employee requests for access to the records","Decide how long the records must be retained before destruction"],"c":1,"why":"The data custodian is responsible for the day-to-day technical implementation and maintenance of controls (e.g., ACLs, encryption, backups) as directed by the data owner. Classification, access approval policy, and retention decisions are owner/business responsibilities, not custodial ones.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to protect customer records while they are being transmitted from a web application to a backend database server over the internal network. Which control is MOST appropriate for this specific scenario?","o":["Full-disk encryption on the database server","Transport Layer Security (TLS) between the application and database tiers","Hashing the records with SHA-256 before storage","Applying an access control list to the database file directory"],"c":1,"why":"TLS protects data in transit between systems, which is the scenario described. Full-disk encryption and file ACLs protect data at rest, and hashing provides integrity verification, not confidentiality, and is not reversible for use by the database.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm is classifying a dataset containing anonymized customer account balances and transaction histories. Individually, no record contains direct identifiers, but analysts note that combining this dataset with commercially available marketing data could re-identify specific customers and reveal spending patterns. Which consideration is MOST important when assigning the classification level?","o":["The sensitivity of each individual data field in isolation","The potential for aggregation and inference to elevate the overall sensitivity of the dataset","The total number of records contained in the dataset","The classification label originally assigned by the analyst who created the file"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation and inference can make a dataset far more sensitive than its individual elements suggest, which is a core asset security concern; record count and creator-assigned labels are not reliable classification drivers, and evaluating fields in isolation ignores the re-identification risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary purpose of a data classification scheme within an organization's asset security program?","o":["To determine the appropriate level of protection and handling controls based on the sensitivity and value of the information","To assign monetary value to data for insurance purposes only","To satisfy audit requirements without affecting daily operations","To eliminate the need for encryption on any classified data"],"c":0,"why":"Data classification exists to ensure information receives protection commensurate with its sensitivity and value. Insurance valuation, audit-only purposes, and eliminating encryption needs are not the intent of classification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A hospital's data classification policy requires that any dataset whose unauthorized disclosure would cause 'catastrophic and irreversible harm' be classified as Top Secret-equivalent. An analyst combines several data sets, each individually classified as 'Internal Use Only', to build a research database. The combined dataset now allows re-identification of specific patients' HIV status. Which principle explains why the combined dataset must be reclassified at a higher level than any of its individual components?","o":["Data remanence","Aggregation and inference risk","Need-to-know restriction","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining low-sensitivity data elements creates a higher-sensitivity result through inference; the other options describe unrelated security concepts (residual data after deletion, access restriction principle, and control segregation).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization must securely dispose of a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained highly sensitive data. Traditional degaussing is not effective on this media type. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate?","o":["Degaussing the drives using a high-powered magnetic device","Performing a cryptographic erase of the drive's encryption key, followed by verification","Deleting all files and folders and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive using a standard quick format"],"c":1,"why":"Cryptographic erase (destroying the encryption key used to protect data that was encrypted at rest) is an accepted purge method for SSDs where physical degaussing does not work due to the lack of magnetic media. File deletion and quick formatting only remove pointers to data and do not sanitize it, leaving data recoverable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A business unit manager argues that the IT department, not she, should decide the classification level of a newly created customer dataset because IT built and maintains the storage infrastructure. From an asset security governance perspective, which statement BEST resolves this dispute?","o":["IT should own the classification decision because it controls the technical access controls enforcing it","The business unit manager, as the data owner, is accountable for classification decisions; IT acts as custodian, implementing the controls the owner specifies","The compliance department should assume ownership since it is organizationally neutral","No formal classification decision is needed because IT already enforces role-based access control on the system"],"c":1,"why":"Data owners (typically business representatives) are accountable for classification and access decisions; custodians (IT) implement technical controls but do not decide classification. Technical enforcement capability does not confer ownership.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"In the context of data governance roles, who is typically responsible for making decisions about data classification and approving access requests, while not being responsible for day-to-day technical protection of the data?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","System administrator","End user"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit leader) has accountability for classifying data and approving access, while the custodian implements the technical controls. Administrators and end users do not set classification policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a set of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored highly classified data. The security team proposes using a legacy degaussing device, the same one used successfully on the organization's magnetic tape backups. Why is this approach inappropriate for the SSDs?","o":["Degaussing only works on optical media, not electronic storage","SSDs use flash memory with wear-leveling and no magnetic domains, so degaussing has no effect on the actual data","Degaussing erases data too slowly for SSDs, requiring cryptographic erasure instead","SSDs automatically encrypt all data, making sanitization unnecessary"],"c":1,"why":"Degaussing works by disrupting magnetic fields on media like tapes and HDD platters; SSDs store data electronically via flash cells with wear-leveling algorithms, so degaussing has no physical effect and data may remain recoverable. The other statements are factually incorrect.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company's records retention policy requires deletion of email older than three years. However, the organization has just received notice of pending litigation that may involve emails from the past five years. What is the MOST appropriate action?","o":["Continue following the standard three-year retention policy since it was approved by management","Immediately delete all email older than three years to reduce storage costs before the lawsuit proceeds further","Place a legal hold on the relevant emails, suspending the normal retention/destruction schedule until the hold is lifted","Transfer the relevant emails to a personal device to preserve them outside of company systems"],"c":2,"why":"A legal hold requires suspending normal destruction schedules for data that may be relevant to anticipated or ongoing litigation, overriding the standard retention policy. Continuing normal deletion or deleting data early could constitute spoliation of evidence, and moving data to personal devices creates security and chain-of-custody problems.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning solid-state drives (SSDs) that previously stored top-secret research data. A technician proposes using traditional multi-pass overwriting, as would be done for magnetic hard drives, to sanitize the media. Why is this approach inadequate for SSDs, and what does NIST SP 800-88 recommend instead?","o":["Overwriting is inadequate because it takes too long; degaussing should be used instead","Overwriting is inadequate because SSD wear-leveling and block remapping can leave data remnants in inaccessible physical blocks; cryptographic erase or physical destruction is recommended","Overwriting is unnecessary because SSDs are self-encrypting by default and require no further action","Overwriting is adequate but must simply be repeated additional times to ensure compliance"],"c":1,"why":"SSD controllers remap logical addresses to different physical blocks for wear leveling, so overwrite commands may not reach all physical locations containing residual data; NIST 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase or physical destruction. Degaussing is ineffective since SSDs are not magnetic media, and self-encryption is not guaranteed on all drives.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is decommissioning several magnetic hard drives that contained highly confidential customer records. Which sanitization method provides the highest assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Reformatting the drive using the operating system's quick format option","Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Degaussing followed by physical destruction of the drive","Copying new data over the old files once"],"c":2,"why":"Degaussing disrupts magnetic domains and physical destruction ensures the media cannot be reconstructed, providing the highest assurance for highly sensitive data. Quick formatting, deleting files, or a single overwrite leave recoverable data remnants.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A mobile application collects users' precise GPS location, contact lists, and browsing history, even though its stated purpose is only to track step counts for a fitness feature. Which privacy principle is being violated?","o":["Data minimization (collection limitation)","Non-repudiation","Least privilege for administrative accounts","Data remanence prevention"],"c":0,"why":"Data minimization requires that only the data necessary to fulfill a stated purpose be collected; gathering unrelated data such as browsing history and contacts for a step-counting feature violates this principle. Non-repudiation, least privilege for admins, and remanence prevention are unrelated concepts to this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A company outsources application hosting to a SaaS provider. The provider's contract states it will 'process and store customer data per the customer's instructions.' Under standard data governance role definitions, which role does the SaaS provider occupy, and who retains ultimate accountability for the data's classification and legal compliance?","o":["The provider is the data owner; the customer is the data processor","The provider is the data custodian/processor; the customer remains the data owner","The provider is the data controller; the customer is the data subject","Both parties share data ownership equally under a SaaS model"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (customer) retains accountability for classification, legal compliance, and policy decisions, while the SaaS provider acts as custodian/processor, handling data per the owner's instructions without assuming ownership. The other options misapply GDPR-style terms or incorrectly shift accountability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A cloud analytics platform processes highly sensitive health records in memory to generate real-time risk scores. Which control provides the STRONGEST protection against exposure of this data while it is actively being processed (data in use)?","o":["Full-disk encryption on the underlying storage volumes","TLS 1.3 encryption for all API communications between services","A hardware-based trusted execution environment (TEE) or secure enclave that isolates memory during processing","Column-level encryption within the database storing the records"],"c":2,"why":"TEEs/secure enclaves protect data actively being processed in memory, addressing the 'data in use' state directly. Disk encryption and database encryption protect data at rest, and TLS protects data in transit—none address exposure during active computation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company's data retention policy primarily exists to address which of the following concerns?","o":["Ensuring data is kept indefinitely to maximize its potential future business value","Defining how long data must be kept to meet legal, regulatory, and business requirements, and when it should be securely destroyed","Guaranteeing that backup tapes are stored in a single physical location","Preventing employees from ever deleting any organizational data"],"c":1,"why":"Retention policies balance legal/regulatory obligations and business needs with the risk of keeping data too long, specifying secure destruction timelines. Indefinite retention and location mandates are not the policy's purpose.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial firm must retain transaction records for seven years per regulation, but a customer has invoked a right-to-erasure request under applicable privacy law, and separately, legal counsel has issued a litigation hold on the same records due to pending litigation. What is the correct order of precedence for handling this conflict?","o":["Honor the erasure request immediately since privacy rights supersede all other obligations","Destroy the records per the retention schedule once seven years expire, ignoring the hold","Preserve the records under the litigation hold, suspending both erasure and destruction until the hold is lifted","Apply data masking to satisfy both the erasure request and the retention requirement simultaneously"],"c":2,"why":"A litigation hold legally suspends normal retention/destruction and erasure obligations until resolved, as failure to preserve evidence can result in spoliation sanctions; erasure rights are typically not absolute and yield to legal preservation duties. The masking option does not satisfy either requirement, and outright erasure or destruction would violate the hold.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the best example of Personally Identifiable Information (PII) that would require enhanced protection under most privacy regulations?","o":["A company's publicly posted annual revenue figures","An employee's Social Security number stored in the HR database","The average temperature recorded by a building's HVAC sensors","The total number of visitors to a company's public website last month"],"c":1,"why":"A Social Security number can uniquely identify an individual and is classic PII requiring strict protection. The other examples are aggregate or non-personal data with no privacy implications.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing controls to protect sensitive data while it is being actively processed in a server's RAM during a financial calculation, addressing threats from a compromised hypervisor or malicious insider with root access. Which control category most directly addresses this specific data state?","o":["Full-disk encryption (FDE) on the server's storage volumes","Transport Layer Security (TLS) for all network communications","Trusted Execution Environment (TEE) / secure enclave technology","Format-preserving tokenization applied at the database layer"],"c":2,"why":"Data in use (actively processed in memory) requires controls like TEEs/secure enclaves that isolate computation from the OS/hypervisor; FDE protects data at rest, TLS protects data in transit, and tokenization protects stored data formats but not live memory contents during processing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Why is maintaining an accurate and up-to-date asset inventory considered a foundational control in asset security?","o":["It is only useful for calculating insurance premiums","It allows the organization to identify, classify, and apply appropriate protections to all assets it is responsible for securing","It replaces the need for a data classification policy","It is required only for physical assets, not electronic data"],"c":1,"why":"You cannot protect what you don't know you have; an asset inventory enables identification and classification so appropriate controls can be applied. It does not replace classification policy, and it applies to both physical and electronic assets.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"During an internal control assessment, a security architect removes several NIST SP 800-53 baseline controls related to wireless access and mobile code because the system operates in a permanently air-gapped facility with no wireless capability or removable media. This activity is BEST described as:","o":["Tailoring","Scoping","Baselining","Selecting compensating controls"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping is the specific tailoring activity of removing controls that are not applicable due to the operational environment (e.g., no wireless technology present). Tailoring is the broader overall process that includes scoping among other activities; the other options do not describe removing inapplicable controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A retail company wants developers to test a new application using realistic-looking customer data without exposing actual PII, while preserving referential integrity across multiple linked tables (e.g., the same customer ID must map to the same masked value in every table). Which data protection technique best satisfies this requirement?","o":["Static data masking with consistent, deterministic substitution","Full encryption of the entire test database","Dynamic data masking applied at query time only","Random data perturbation with no consistency mapping"],"c":0,"why":"Static masking with deterministic substitution replaces sensitive values consistently across tables, preserving referential integrity for testing while removing real PII; encryption would prevent developers from viewing usable data, dynamic masking only protects data at query time in production, and random perturbation without consistency breaks relational integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"In the information lifecycle, which stage occurs first and establishes the initial classification level that should guide handling throughout the data's existence?","o":["Archival","Destruction","Creation","Use"],"c":2,"why":"Creation is the first stage of the data lifecycle, at which point the data should be classified to guide its handling through use, storage, archival, and eventual destruction. The other options are later lifecycle stages.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A hospital stores individual patient billing codes, individual appointment times, and individual physician names in separate systems, each classified as 'Internal Use Only.' However, when combined, this information could reveal a patient's specific medical condition, requiring a much higher classification. This scenario illustrates which security concept?","o":["Data remanence","Inference and aggregation","Least privilege","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation and inference occur when combining multiple pieces of low-sensitivity data allows a user to deduce higher-sensitivity information, requiring the combined data set to be reclassified at a higher level. Remanence relates to residual data after deletion, and least privilege/separation of duties are access control concepts unrelated to this data-combination risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization's records retention policy requires purging email after three years. Legal counsel issues a litigation hold notice affecting several executives due to pending litigation. What is the MOST appropriate action?","o":["Continue the standard purge cycle to remain consistent with published policy","Suspend deletion of relevant records for the affected custodians until the hold is lifted, overriding the standard retention schedule","Delete the records immediately to minimize discovery exposure","Encrypt the affected records in place of retaining them"],"c":1,"why":"A litigation hold legally supersedes normal retention schedules; failing to preserve relevant records constitutes spoliation of evidence and can result in severe legal sanctions. Continuing the purge or deleting records would violate the legal hold obligation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization classifies an asset as 'Confidential' under its internal policy, which maps to a baseline requiring FIPS 140-2 validated encryption modules. However, the asset is a legacy embedded medical device with no cryptographic hardware support and cannot be replaced for two years due to FDA certification lock-in. What is the MOST appropriate security management action?","o":["Reclassify the asset as 'Public' to avoid the conflicting requirement","Apply scoping and tailoring to document a compensating control and formally accept the residual risk","Ignore the baseline since the device is legacy and out of scope for policy","Immediately decommission the device regardless of regulatory certification status"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping and tailoring allow organizations to adapt baseline controls to specific asset constraints while documenting compensating controls and formal risk acceptance; reclassifying to avoid controls misrepresents actual sensitivity, ignoring the baseline abandons due diligence, and immediate decommissioning may violate regulatory requirements and continuity of care.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A company receives a GDPR-based right-to-erasure request from an EU customer, but financial regulations legally require the company to retain transaction records for seven years. What is the MOST appropriate response?","o":["Immediately delete all customer data to comply fully with GDPR","Deny the erasure request outright, citing general business needs","Retain only the data necessary to satisfy the legal retention obligation, restrict or anonymize further processing of the remainder, and inform the customer of the legal basis for retention","Transfer the data to a third-party processor so the company is no longer directly responsible for it"],"c":2,"why":"GDPR Article 17(3) permits refusal or limitation of erasure where a legal obligation requires retention; the organization must restrict processing to only what is legally necessary and communicate the basis to the data subject. Full deletion would violate regulatory retention law, outright denial ignores the data subject's other rights, and outsourcing does not remove accountability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"During an asset inventory audit, a security team discovers a departmental file server containing spreadsheets with unmarked customer Social Security numbers that were never classified or registered in the asset inventory. Which foundational asset security failure does this scenario BEST illustrate?","o":["Failure to enforce least privilege on the file server","Failure to perform proper data discovery and classification as part of asset lifecycle management","Failure to implement encryption at rest","Failure to apply appropriate data retention schedules"],"c":1,"why":"The core issue is that sensitive data was never identified, classified, or inventoried in the first place—a breakdown in data discovery and classification processes; the other options describe downstream controls (access, encryption, retention) that cannot be properly applied without first identifying and classifying the data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An employee copies a spreadsheet labeled 'Confidential – Internal Use Only' onto a personal, unencrypted USB drive to work from home, reasoning that special handling is only required for data classified as 'Top Secret.' Which asset security principle has been violated?","o":["None, because classification schemes only legally apply to government systems","Handling requirements tied to the assigned classification level, which mandate specific controls such as encryption regardless of whether the label is the organization's highest tier","The data owner's failure to reclassify the document before it was copied","None, because Confidential data below Secret level requires no special handling"],"c":1,"why":"Every classification tier has defined handling, storage, and transmission requirements; 'Confidential' still mandates protective controls like encryption on removable media. The other options incorrectly assume only the highest classification tier requires protection or misapply government-only classification logic to corporate policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which role in an organization's data governance structure is ultimately accountable for determining the classification level of a specific data set and approving who may access it?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","Data processor","System administrator"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (often a business unit leader) has ultimate accountability for classifying data and authorizing access. Custodians and administrators handle day-to-day technical maintenance, and processors act on behalf of a controller but do not set classification policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored data classified as Top Secret. The security team initially proposes running a single-pass software overwrite utility designed for traditional magnetic hard drives. A senior security architect objects to this approach for the SSDs. What is the primary technical reason overwriting is unreliable for sanitizing SSDs?","o":["SSDs use wear-leveling and over-provisioning, so logical block addresses do not map consistently to physical NAND cells, leaving remnant data in blocks not addressed by the overwrite","SSDs cannot be sanitized by any method other than physical destruction","Overwriting SSDs voids the manufacturer warranty, which is a compliance violation under most data protection frameworks","SSD controllers actively block all write commands from third-party sanitization software"],"c":0,"why":"Because of wear-leveling, spare area, and garbage collection, an overwrite command issued to a logical address does not guarantee the underlying physical flash cells holding the original data are overwritten, so remnant data can persist. The other options are either false or not the primary technical reason (destruction is one valid option among several, but the question asks why overwriting specifically fails).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is decommissioning several hard drives that once stored highly confidential financial records. Which sanitization method provides the highest assurance that data cannot be recovered before the drives are discarded?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive using a quick format","Physical destruction of the drive (e.g., shredding or degaussing)","Overwriting the drive once with zeros"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction provides the highest assurance of unrecoverable data for highly sensitive media. Deleting files, quick formatting, and a single overwrite pass may leave recoverable remnants, especially on certain media types.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization is documenting roles for its data governance program. One individual is responsible for making the day-to-day operational decisions about applying classification labels, coordinating with the business to interpret classification policy, and acting as a liaison between the data owner and IT operations. Which role best matches this description?","o":["Data owner","Data custodian","Data steward","System owner"],"c":2,"why":"The data steward manages the operational/tactical application of classification and quality policy on behalf of the business, bridging owner intent and technical execution. The data owner sets policy and accepts risk at an executive level, the custodian performs technical safeguarding (backups, access provisioning) under direction, and the system owner is responsible for the platform, not the data's classification interpretation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which term best describes the process of assigning a sensitivity level to data based on its potential impact if disclosed, altered, or destroyed?","o":["Data classification","Data retention","Data mapping","Data normalization"],"c":0,"why":"Data classification is the process of categorizing information by sensitivity/impact to determine appropriate handling and protection controls. Retention concerns how long data is kept, mapping concerns tracking data flows, and normalization is a database design concept.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization is decommissioning several hard drives that stored highly confidential financial records. Which method provides the HIGHEST assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive with a quick format","Physical destruction of the drive (e.g., shredding or pulverizing)","Moving the files to an encrypted archive folder"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction eliminates any possibility of data recovery, making it the most secure sanitization method for highly sensitive media; deletion, quick formatting, and moving files leave data recoverable through forensic tools.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A healthcare organization is designing a data classification program. What is the PRIMARY purpose of classifying information assets?","o":["To ensure that every piece of information receives identical protective controls","To assign protective controls that are proportional to the value, sensitivity, and criticality of the information","To determine which employees are permitted to work remotely","To calculate the replacement cost of hardware for insurance purposes"],"c":1,"why":"Classification exists so that security resources and controls (encryption, access restrictions, handling procedures) are applied in proportion to the sensitivity and criticality of the data. Uniform protection wastes resources on low-value data, and the other options describe unrelated HR or asset-valuation activities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company's data retention policy primarily helps the organization to:","o":["Increase storage costs by keeping all data indefinitely","Retain data only as long as legally, regulatorily, or operationally required, then dispose of it securely","Ensure all employees have access to historical data at all times","Avoid the need for data classification"],"c":1,"why":"Retention policies balance legal/regulatory/business needs against the risks and costs of keeping data too long, ensuring timely secure disposal; the other options misrepresent the goal or create unnecessary risk/cost.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best represents the 'data at rest' state within the data lifecycle?","o":["Data being transmitted across a network between two servers","Data stored on a hard drive or in a database","Data actively being processed in RAM by an application","Data being displayed on a user's screen"],"c":1,"why":"Data at rest refers to data stored on persistent media such as disks or databases. Data in transit refers to network transmission, and data in use refers to data actively being processed or displayed.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Within an organization's data governance model, which role is MOST accountable for determining the classification level of a specific data set and approving who may access it?","o":["Data Owner","Data Custodian","System Administrator","End User"],"c":0,"why":"The Data Owner (typically a senior business manager) is accountable for classifying data and approving access decisions. The Custodian implements the technical safeguards on the Owner's behalf, while the Administrator and End User have operational, not accountable, roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A government contractor must implement NIST SP 800-53 controls but operates a small, low-risk administrative system that does not process classified or highly sensitive information. During the security control selection process, the team removes several controls related to multi-factor authentication for privileged remote access because the system has no remote access capability at all. This activity is best described as:","o":["Scoping","Tailoring","Baselining","Categorization"],"c":0,"why":"Scoping is the process of removing controls that are not applicable due to the technical or environmental characteristics of the system (e.g., no remote access capability exists). Tailoring involves adjusting parameters or compensating controls for applicable controls; baselining is selecting the initial control set; categorization is determining impact levels (confidentiality/integrity/availability).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is an example of Personally Identifiable Information (PII)?","o":["A company's annual revenue figures","An employee's Social Security number","The IP address of a public web server","A product's serial number"],"c":1,"why":"A Social Security number can directly identify a specific individual, making it PII; revenue figures, server IP addresses, and product serial numbers do not identify a person.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"A company wants to reduce its legal and storage liability associated with keeping old customer records indefinitely. Which security practice should be implemented to address this concern?","o":["Data classification policy","Data retention policy","Access control policy","Data masking policy"],"c":1,"why":"A data retention policy defines how long data must be kept and when it should be securely destroyed, directly reducing liability from holding unnecessary old records. Classification, access control, and masking address different aspects of data protection, not lifecycle duration.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A healthcare analytics company processes patient records in a cloud environment. To protect data while it is actively being processed by an application (e.g., during a statistical computation), rather than only when stored or transmitted, which technology most directly addresses this specific data state?","o":["Full disk encryption on the database server","TLS 1.3 for all API communications","A hardware-based trusted execution environment (secure enclave)","Field-level encryption applied before data is written to the database"],"c":2,"why":"A trusted execution environment/secure enclave isolates and encrypts data even while it is being actively processed in memory, protecting data-in-use. Full disk encryption and field-level encryption protect data-at-rest, and TLS protects data-in-transit; none of these protect data actively loaded into memory during computation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A forensic examiner recovers fragments of confidential files from a company laptop's hard drive even though the files were deleted and the drive was reformatted. This scenario best illustrates which concept?","o":["Data remanence","Data degradation","Cryptographic erasure","Media obsolescence"],"c":0,"why":"Data remanence refers to residual data that remains recoverable after standard deletion or formatting because the underlying storage sectors were not overwritten. Degradation refers to physical decay of media, cryptographic erasure is a sanitization technique (not the phenomenon), and obsolescence refers to media becoming unusable due to age or technology changes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"To protect data while it is being transmitted across a public network, which control is MOST appropriate?","o":["Full disk encryption on the sending workstation","Encryption using a protocol such as TLS","Physical access controls on the data center","Data classification labeling"],"c":1,"why":"TLS (or similar transport encryption) protects data specifically while in transit over untrusted networks; disk encryption protects data at rest, and physical controls/labeling do not secure data during transmission.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the BEST example of applying the concept of 'scoping and tailoring' to an asset security baseline?","o":["Encrypting all data regardless of classification level","Applying the exact same security controls to every system in the organization","Removing irrelevant baseline controls for a system and adjusting remaining controls to fit the organization's environment","Classifying all data as top secret to simplify handling procedures"],"c":2,"why":"Scoping removes controls that do not apply to a given system, while tailoring adjusts remaining controls to fit organizational needs; this customizes a baseline appropriately. Applying identical controls everywhere or over-classifying data ignores risk-based customization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A company's data retention policy requires deletion of employee email after 3 years. Legal counsel issues a litigation hold notice covering a former executive's mailbox due to pending litigation, effective immediately. The retention system is scheduled to purge that executive's mailbox in two weeks per the standard policy. What is the correct action?","o":["Allow the scheduled purge to proceed since the retention policy was established and approved prior to the litigation hold","Suspend deletion of the affected mailbox until the legal hold is lifted, overriding the standard retention schedule","Purge the mailbox but retain a compressed archive copy outside the production system to satisfy both requirements","Escalate to the data owner to decide between policy compliance and legal hold compliance"],"c":1,"why":"A legal hold legally supersedes routine retention/destruction schedules; failure to suspend deletion once a hold is issued can constitute spoliation of evidence with serious legal consequences. Compressing and moving the archive without proper legal hold procedures, or leaving the decision ambiguous to a data owner, does not satisfy the immediate and unambiguous obligation to preserve the data intact.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A government agency is decommissioning SSDs that stored top-secret information. The drives will not be reused and are being sent to a certified vendor for final disposal. Per NIST SP 800-88 guidance, which sanitization approach is MOST appropriate?","o":["Clear","Purge","Destroy","Quick format"],"c":2,"why":"For the highest sensitivity data on media that will not be reused, physical destruction is the recommended sanitization category, especially since purge techniques on SSDs (wear-leveling, hidden sectors) may not reliably remove all data. Clear and quick format are insufficient for top-secret data, and purge alone carries higher residual risk on flash media than destruction.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of physically or electronically marking media and documents with labels such as 'Confidential' or 'Internal Use Only'?","o":["To make the data easier to compress for storage","To help ensure personnel handle the information according to its required protection level","To speed up network transmission of the data","To satisfy backup rotation schedules"],"c":1,"why":"Labeling communicates the sensitivity of information so that handlers apply the correct protective measures (storage, transmission, disposal); it has no relation to compression, network speed, or backup rotation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"An organization labels its files as 'Public,' 'Internal Use,' 'Confidential,' and 'Restricted.' What is the PRIMARY purpose of these labels?","o":["To indicate which department created the file","To ensure files are backed up on the correct schedule","To communicate the required handling and protection requirements for the data","To determine which file format should be used for storage"],"c":2,"why":"Classification labels primarily communicate how data should be handled, stored, transmitted, and protected based on its sensitivity. They are not intended to indicate authorship, backup schedules, or file formats.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A US-based SaaS provider processes personal data on behalf of an EU-based client under GDPR. The EU client determines what data is collected and why, while the US provider only processes it according to the client's instructions. The provider needs to transfer this data to a subsidiary in a country without an EU adequacy decision. Which statement correctly characterizes the roles and the appropriate transfer mechanism?","o":["The US provider is the data controller and can rely solely on its own privacy policy to authorize the transfer","The EU client is the data controller, the US provider is the data processor, and the transfer requires a mechanism such as Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs) or Binding Corporate Rules","The US provider is a joint controller with the EU client, eliminating the need for any additional transfer safeguard","Because the provider is a processor, GDPR cross-border transfer restrictions do not apply to it"],"c":1,"why":"The entity determining purpose and means of processing (the EU client) is the controller; the entity processing on its behalf (the US provider) is the processor. GDPR requires an approved transfer mechanism, such as SCCs or BCRs, for transfers to countries lacking an adequacy decision, and this obligation applies to processors as well as controllers.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which technology is specifically designed to protect the confidentiality of data while it is actively being processed in a system's memory (i.e., data in use)?","o":["TLS 1.3 for network sessions","AES-256 full-disk encryption","A hardware-based trusted execution environment (secure enclave)","Transparent database encryption at rest"],"c":2,"why":"Trusted execution environments/secure enclaves isolate and encrypt data during active processing in memory, addressing the 'data in use' state. TLS protects data in transit, while full-disk and transparent database encryption protect data at rest, not during active computation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"In the data lifecycle, which phase involves ensuring that information is permanently and securely removed once it is no longer needed?","o":["Creation","Use","Archival","Destruction"],"c":3,"why":"The destruction phase is dedicated to permanently removing data that is no longer needed, using methods appropriate to its classification; creation, use, and archival occur earlier in the lifecycle and involve different activities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is an example of Personally Identifiable Information (PII) that would typically require enhanced protection under privacy regulations?","o":["A company's publicly posted annual revenue figures","An employee's Social Security number stored in an HR database","The organization's published product catalog","A press release announcing a new product launch"],"c":1,"why":"A Social Security number is a unique identifier tied to an individual and is classic PII requiring strong protection under privacy laws. Public revenue figures, product catalogs, and press releases are intended for public disclosure and are not PII.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"During an asset inventory reconciliation, the IT security team discovers that several business units have been using an unsanctioned cloud storage service to share files containing regulated customer data, bypassing the approved enterprise data loss prevention (DLP) and classification tooling. This scenario is best classified as a failure in which asset security process, and what is the most effective long-term remediation?","o":["Data classification failure; remediate by re-labeling all files retroactively","Configuration management failure; remediate by patching the DLP agents","Asset inventory and shadow IT governance failure; remediate by deploying a Cloud Access Security Broker (CASB) and enforcing an approved-services policy with continuous discovery","Encryption key management failure; remediate by rotating all encryption keys"],"c":2,"why":"Unsanctioned cloud services represent unmanaged assets outside the visibility of the security program (shadow IT), which is fundamentally an asset inventory/governance gap; a CASB with continuous discovery and policy enforcement directly addresses detecting and controlling unauthorized services. Relabeling files, patching DLP agents, or rotating keys do not address the root cause of unmanaged, unauthorized asset usage.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization is disposing of a mix of media types following NIST SP 800-88 guidance: (1) a magnetic tape backup containing Confidential data that will never be reused, (2) an SSD containing Top Secret data, and (3) paper documents containing PII that will be recycled. Which combination of sanitization methods is most appropriate under 800-88 principles?","o":["Clear all three media types using a single-pass overwrite, since Clear is sufficient regardless of media type or sensitivity","Degauss the tape, cryptographically erase and then physically destroy the SSD, and cross-cut shred the paper","Purge the tape by overwriting, reformat the SSD, and use a strip-cut shredder for the paper","Physically destroy all three media types uniformly to ensure consistent handling regardless of type or classification"],"c":1,"why":"NIST 800-88 recommends method selection based on media type and sensitivity: magnetic tape is effectively purged via degaussing, SSDs require cryptographic erase (and destruction is prudent for the highest sensitivity levels since Purge techniques for flash are less assured), and paper requires cross-cut (not strip-cut) shredding to prevent reconstruction. Uniform overwrite or uniform destruction ignores media-specific effectiveness and reformatting does not sanitize an SSD.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is applying a security control baseline (e.g., NIST SP 800-53) to a low-impact system and removes several controls that address high-impact concerns not relevant to this system. This activity is best described as:","o":["Tailoring","Scoping","Baselining","Standardizing"],"c":1,"why":"Scoping is the process of determining which baseline controls are applicable to a given system based on its impact level or environment, including removing irrelevant controls. Tailoring involves modifying or adding compensating controls to the remaining applicable set, which is a different step in the process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A SaaS vendor processes customer personal data strictly according to written instructions from its enterprise client, which determines the purposes and means of processing. Under common privacy frameworks (e.g., GDPR), which role does the SaaS vendor occupy?","o":["Data Controller","Data Processor","Data Owner","Data Subject"],"c":1,"why":"A Data Processor handles personal data on behalf of and under the instructions of a Data Controller, who determines the purposes and means of processing. The enterprise client, not the vendor, is the Controller in this scenario, and 'Data Owner' and 'Data Subject' describe different, unrelated roles in this context.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A financial services organization is developing its data classification scheme. Which of the following criteria is MOST important for determining the classification level assigned to a dataset?","o":["The cost of the storage media used to house the data","The potential impact on the organization if the data were disclosed without authorization","The age of the data since creation","The type of encryption algorithm used to protect the data"],"c":1,"why":"Classification levels are based on the sensitivity of the data and the potential impact (financial, reputational, legal) of unauthorized disclosure, loss, or modification. Storage cost, data age, and specific encryption algorithms are operational details, not classification criteria.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Within a data governance framework, who is PRIMARILY responsible for determining the classification level of a dataset and approving who may access it?","o":["Data custodian","Data owner","System administrator","End user"],"c":1,"why":"The data owner (typically a business unit leader) has accountability for the data, assigns its classification, and approves access. The custodian implements technical controls on the owner's behalf; administrators and end users do not have classification authority.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization receives formal notice of pending litigation referencing specific email records that are past their normal retention period per the records management policy. What should the organization do with those records?","o":["Delete them immediately to reduce legal exposure","Place them under litigation hold, suspending the normal destruction schedule","Move them to an unencrypted offline archive for convenience","Transfer sole custody of the records to outside counsel and delete internal copies"],"c":1,"why":"A litigation hold legally requires suspending normal destruction schedules to preserve potentially relevant evidence; deleting records after notice of litigation constitutes spoliation and can result in severe legal penalties.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored highly confidential data before returning them to a leasing company. Which sanitization approach is MOST appropriate given the characteristics of SSD media?","o":["Degaussing the drives","Performing a single-pass overwrite using traditional disk-wiping software","Cryptographic erase or physical destruction","Running the operating system's quick-format utility"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use wear-leveling and flash translation layers that make traditional sector overwriting unreliable, and degaussing has no effect on non-magnetic flash media. NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase (if the drive was encrypted) or physical destruction for reliable SSD sanitization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"Which control provides the STRONGEST protection for the confidentiality of sensitive data stored on a corporate laptop that is later lost or stolen?","o":["Host-based intrusion detection software","Full-disk encryption with pre-boot authentication","File integrity monitoring","Network access control (NAC)"],"c":1,"why":"Full-disk encryption with pre-boot authentication protects data at rest so that it remains unreadable even if the physical device is lost or stolen. HIDS, FIM, and NAC address other threats but do not protect data confidentiality once the device is out of the organization's possession.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"During design of a new customer-facing application, the security team recommends that the system collect only the specific personal data elements strictly necessary to deliver the service, avoiding collection of optional or unrelated fields. This recommendation exemplifies which privacy principle?","o":["Purpose limitation","Data minimization","Data portability","Consent management"],"c":1,"why":"Data minimization means collecting and retaining only the personal data necessary for a defined purpose. Purpose limitation restricts how already-collected data may be used, portability concerns transferring data between providers, and consent management concerns obtaining and tracking user permission.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization's classification policy requires that all printed documents marked 'Confidential' display a header and footer identifying the classification level. What is the PRIMARY security purpose of this labeling requirement?","o":["To comply with generic document formatting standards","To ensure personnel handle, store, and dispose of the information according to its sensitivity","To enable automated OCR scanning for inventory tracking","To satisfy printer vendor warranty conditions"],"c":1,"why":"Labeling communicates the required handling procedures (storage, transmission, disposal) to anyone who encounters the document, ensuring consistent protection commensurate with sensitivity. The other options describe incidental or unrelated benefits, not the security rationale.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A senior vice president in a bank's retail division is formally designated as accountable for approving who may access the customer account database, determining its sensitivity level, and authorizing the data retention schedule. Which asset security role does this individual fulfill?","o":["Data Owner","Data Custodian","Data Steward","Database Administrator"],"c":0,"why":"The Data Owner is the senior business role accountable for classifying data and approving access rights. The Data Custodian implements technical protections, the Data Steward focuses on data quality/metadata, and the Database Administrator manages the technical database platform, none of whom hold classification/authorization accountability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that previously stored regulated customer data. The security team wants to reuse the drives internally for non-sensitive workloads after sanitization. Due to wear-leveling and block remapping on SSDs, which sanitization approach best ensures data is unrecoverable while still allowing the media to be reused?","o":["Perform a single-pass software overwrite of all addressable sectors (NIST 'Clear')","Issue a vendor-supported cryptographic erase or ATA/NVMe Secure Erase command (NIST 'Purge')","Degauss the drive using a Type II degausser rated for magnetic media","Physically bend and scratch the platters to induce read errors"],"c":1,"why":"SSDs remap logical-to-physical blocks, so a simple overwrite (Clear) may miss reallocated or spare blocks, leaving remnant data recoverable; cryptographic erase (a NIST 800-88 'Purge' technique) instantly renders all data unreadable by destroying the encryption keys and is vendor-supported for SSDs. Degaussing is ineffective on non-magnetic flash media, and physically damaging platters is irrelevant since SSDs have no platters and this would also preclude reuse.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A U.S.-based marketing analytics firm is contracted by a retailer to process customer purchase records strictly according to the retailer's written instructions, using data the retailer collected directly from its customers. Under GDPR-aligned data protection terminology, which role does the analytics firm occupy?","o":["Data controller","Data processor","Data owner","Data custodian"],"c":1,"why":"A data processor handles personal data on behalf of and per the instructions of another entity (the controller), which is exactly the analytics firm's role here. The retailer, who determines the purposes and means of processing, is the controller; 'data owner' and 'data custodian' are internal organizational roles, not the GDPR-specific legal relationship being tested.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that previously stored highly sensitive data and must ensure the data is unrecoverable before disposal. Given known limitations of traditional sanitization techniques on flash-based media, which method is most appropriate?","o":["Degaussing the drives with a strong magnetic field","Performing a single-pass overwrite of all sectors","Cryptographic erasure by destroying the encryption keys used to protect the data","Running the operating system's standard quick format utility"],"c":2,"why":"Degaussing is ineffective on SSDs since they are not magnetic media, and overwriting is unreliable due to wear-leveling that relocates data across cells. Cryptographic erasure (destroying keys for encrypted data) is a NIST SP 800-88 recommended purge method for SSDs; a quick format does not remove underlying data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a mandatory access control system based on the Bell-LaPadula model to protect classified data. A subject cleared at the SECRET level attempts to read a file classified as TOP SECRET. According to the model, what happens?","o":["The read is denied because of the Simple Security Property (no read up)","The read is denied because of the *-property (no write down)","The read is allowed because the subject has a valid clearance","The read is allowed but the file is automatically downgraded"],"c":0,"why":"The Simple Security Property ('no read up') prevents a subject from reading data classified higher than the subject's clearance, which preserves confidentiality. The *-property governs writing, not reading, and the other options contradict the model's core confidentiality goal.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A retail company retains customer purchase records only for the minimum period required by applicable tax law, after which the records are securely destroyed. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this data retention practice?","o":["It reduces the organization's liability and attack surface by limiting the volume of sensitive data stored","It ensures data is always available for long-term business intelligence and analytics","It speeds up incident response by reducing the number of logs that must be reviewed","It strengthens non-repudiation of past transactions with customers"],"c":0,"why":"Minimizing retained data directly reduces the amount of sensitive information exposed to breach, theft, or misuse, lowering liability and attack surface. The other options describe secondary or unrelated benefits, not the primary security rationale for limiting retention.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In the Bell-LaPadula security model, which rule prevents a subject holding a Secret clearance from writing data into a file classified as Confidential?","o":["The simple security property (no read up)","The star property (no write down)","The strong tranquility property","The discretionary security property"],"c":1,"why":"The *-property (no write-down) enforces confidentiality by preventing a subject from writing data to an object at a lower classification level; the simple security property instead governs reading (no read-up), and the other terms describe unrelated or non-BLP concepts.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D2","d":"medium","q":"A company's data classification policy mandates that all data labeled 'Confidential' must be encrypted both at rest and in transit. A project team wants to use a third-party cloud storage service that only supports encryption in transit, not at rest. What is the MOST appropriate action?","o":["Proceed with the cloud service since transit encryption partially satisfies the requirement","Apply a compensating control, such as client-side encryption, before data is uploaded to the cloud service","Reclassify the data to a lower sensitivity level so the cloud service becomes compliant","Prohibit any use of cloud storage for the project with no further evaluation"],"c":1,"why":"When a required control cannot be natively provided by a service, a compensating control such as client-side encryption can satisfy the intent of the policy (data encrypted at rest) before it ever reaches the provider. Reclassifying data to fit a tool's limitations misrepresents its sensitivity, and outright prohibition ignores viable risk-mitigating alternatives.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which statement best describes a defining characteristic of symmetric key cryptography?","o":["It uses a single shared key for both encryption and decryption, making it faster than asymmetric algorithms","It uses a mathematically linked public and private key pair","It is primarily used to provide non-repudiation of a message's origin","It eliminates the need for secure key distribution between parties"],"c":0,"why":"Symmetric cryptography relies on one shared secret key for both operations and is computationally efficient, but it requires secure key exchange; public/private key pairs and non-repudiation are properties of asymmetric cryptography instead.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution wants to prevent low-integrity employees (e.g., data entry clerks) from corrupting high-integrity financial records used by senior auditors. Which access control model best supports this integrity requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model applied with only the Simple Integrity Axiom","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model enforces integrity by preventing subjects at lower integrity levels from writing to higher integrity objects ('no write up') and reading down, directly addressing corruption of high-integrity data by lower-trust users. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, not integrity, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which term refers to the abstract concept of an entity that mediates every access request between subjects and objects to enforce a system's security policy?","o":["Trusted computing base","Reference monitor","Security kernel","Access control matrix"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is the theoretical construct that governs all subject-object access decisions; the security kernel is its hardware/software implementation, and the TCB is the broader collection of protection mechanisms that includes the security kernel.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A web application uses TLS to secure data in transit. During the handshake, the server's RSA key pair is used briefly to establish a shared session key, after which all bulk data is encrypted using AES. What is the primary reason for this hybrid approach?","o":["AES cannot provide non-repudiation, so RSA must encrypt all sensitive data","Asymmetric encryption is computationally expensive for large volumes of data, while symmetric encryption is efficient for bulk data transfer","RSA keys must be regenerated for every session to remain secure","Symmetric algorithms cannot be used for key exchange under any circumstances"],"c":1,"why":"Hybrid cryptosystems leverage asymmetric encryption's key-exchange strength and symmetric encryption's computational efficiency for bulk data, which is why TLS uses RSA/ECC briefly and AES for the session. The other statements misrepresent capabilities of AES, RSA, and key exchange mechanics.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In the Common Criteria evaluation framework, what does an Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) primarily indicate about a certified product?","o":["The number of known vulnerabilities remaining in the product","The specific security features the product supports","The rigor and depth of testing and evaluation the product underwent","The total cost required to certify the product"],"c":2,"why":"EALs (EAL1-EAL7) reflect the thoroughness of the assurance evaluation process, not the specific functional features implemented or the vulnerabilities present, which are addressed separately through Protection Profiles and Security Targets.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"An organization publishes several individually unclassified datasets—employee headcount by department, quarterly regional sales figures, and public product roadmaps. A competitor analyst combines these public datasets to accurately predict an unreleased product launch strategy. Which security principle explains this outcome, and what is the appropriate remediation?","o":["Inference; encrypt each dataset independently before publication","Aggregation; reassess and potentially reclassify the combined dataset at a higher sensitivity level","Data remanence; ensure secure destruction of the source files after use","Least privilege; restrict access to the individual datasets to fewer employees"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining multiple low-sensitivity data elements creates a higher-sensitivity whole; the fix is to evaluate the combined output's classification and restrict or redact accordingly. Inference involves deducing protected information from indirect clues rather than combining known public data, and encryption/least privilege/remanence don't address the root cause of aggregated sensitivity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"In secure system design, the reference monitor concept is a theoretical construct that mediates all access between subjects and objects. Which statement about the reference monitor is correct?","o":["It must be implemented entirely in application-layer software for portability","It is the same as the security kernel and always physically separate hardware","It must be tamper-resistant, always invoked, and small enough to be verifiable, though it is an abstract model that the TCB implements","It only enforces confidentiality controls and has no role in integrity enforcement"],"c":2,"why":"The reference monitor is an abstract concept requiring completeness (always invoked), isolation (tamper-resistant), and verifiability (small enough to analyze); the TCB and security kernel are practical implementations of this concept. It is not restricted to confidentiality and need not be separate hardware.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which fire suppression method is most appropriate for a data center to extinguish electrical fires while minimizing damage to servers and equipment?","o":["Water sprinkler system","Clean agent (inert gas) suppression system","Class A dry chemical extinguishers","Foam-based suppression system"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agent systems (such as inert gas or FM-200) suppress Class C electrical fires without leaving residue or conducting electricity, whereas water, foam, and dry chemical agents can damage electronics or pose additional hazards.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A government agency is evaluating a firewall product under the Common Criteria and requires an assurance level that includes formal design verification and formal correspondence between the security target and implementation. Which Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) best matches this requirement?","o":["EAL1","EAL3","EAL5","EAL7"],"c":3,"why":"EAL7 requires formal verification of design and implementation, the highest rigor in Common Criteria, suitable for extremely high-assurance environments. Lower EALs (1, 3, 5) involve progressively less formal analysis and testing, not full formal verification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D2","d":"hard","q":"A system owner adopts the NIST SP 800-53 moderate-impact baseline for a new application. Because the application does not process cardholder data, the owner removes the PCI-specific control enhancements; because it runs on a legacy OS lacking native encryption support, the owner adds a compensating control requiring an external encryption appliance. What is this process called?","o":["Scoping","Tailoring","Gap analysis","Baselining"],"c":1,"why":"Tailoring is the customization of a selected baseline—adding, removing, or modifying controls (including compensating controls) to fit the specific system's environment and risk context. Scoping is the earlier step of determining which baseline/controls are applicable based on system characteristics, not modifying the control set itself; gap analysis compares current vs. desired state, and baselining is establishing the initial control set.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/88/r1/final"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which type of hypervisor runs directly on the physical hardware without requiring an underlying host operating system?","o":["Type 2 (hosted) hypervisor","Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor","Container runtime engine","Application virtualization layer"],"c":1,"why":"A Type 1 hypervisor installs directly on hardware, offering better performance and a smaller attack surface, while a Type 2 hypervisor runs as an application atop a host OS; containers virtualize at the OS level rather than the hardware level.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A cloud security architect is concerned about an attacker who compromises a guest virtual machine and then gains unauthorized access to the underlying hypervisor or other VMs on the same host. What is this type of attack called?","o":["Side-channel attack","VM escape","Session hijacking","Man-in-the-middle attack"],"c":1,"why":"VM escape refers to breaking out of a guest VM's isolation to access the hypervisor or co-located VMs, a critical virtualization security risk. Side-channel attacks exploit indirect information leakage (e.g., timing/power), not privilege escalation across the hypervisor boundary.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A database administrator notices that although individual query results are each classified as unclassified, a user who runs a series of unclassified queries can piece together information that reveals a classified fact. What type of vulnerability does this describe?","o":["SQL injection","Inference attack","Salami attack","Polyinstantiation failure"],"c":1,"why":"An inference attack occurs when a user deduces sensitive information from a combination of non-sensitive data, even without directly accessing classified records. SQL injection involves malicious code execution, a salami attack involves accumulating small unauthorized gains, and polyinstantiation is a defense technique, not a vulnerability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A database user with no direct access to salary records is able to deduce an employee's approximate salary by analyzing patterns in publicly available bonus and tax reports. This scenario best describes which type of attack?","o":["SQL injection attack","Aggregation attack","Inference attack","Polyinstantiation attack"],"c":2,"why":"An inference attack occurs when a user deduces restricted information by reasoning from non-sensitive data, without directly combining or accessing the sensitive records; aggregation involves compiling multiple discrete low-sensitivity items into a higher-sensitivity whole, which is a different mechanism.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center houses sensitive electronic equipment and wants to select a fire suppression system that minimizes damage to hardware while being safe for occupants. Which suppression method is generally most appropriate?","o":["Wet pipe sprinkler system using water","Carbon dioxide (CO2) flooding system","Clean agent (e.g., FM-200) gaseous suppression system","Dry chemical powder extinguishers"],"c":2,"why":"Clean agent systems like FM-200 suppress fire without leaving residue, are non-conductive, and are safe for occupied spaces, making them ideal for electronic equipment. Water can damage electronics, CO2 displaces oxygen and is hazardous to occupants, and dry chemical powder leaves corrosive residue on equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements firewalls, intrusion detection, endpoint antivirus, and physical access controls so that if one safeguard fails, others still protect critical assets. Which security design principle does this illustrate?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity"],"c":2,"why":"Defense in depth uses multiple, layered, redundant controls so that the failure of one does not fully compromise security; least privilege and separation of duties concern access rights allocation, not layered defenses.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to prevent unauthorized disclosure of information by enforcing rules such as 'no read up' and 'no write down'?","o":["Biba Integrity Model","Bell-LaPadula Model","Clark-Wilson Model","Brewer-Nash Model"],"c":1,"why":"Bell-LaPadula focuses on confidentiality using the simple security property (no read up) and the *-property (no write down). Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson enforces well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that lower-integrity data cannot contaminate higher-integrity data within a system. Which security model best supports this goal?","o":["Bell-LaPadula Model","Take-Grant Model","Biba Model","Graham-Denning Model"],"c":2,"why":"The Biba model enforces integrity by preventing subjects from reading data of lower integrity or writing to data of higher integrity. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, while Take-Grant and Graham-Denning deal with access rights management, not integrity levels directly.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary difference between symmetric and asymmetric encryption algorithms?","o":["Symmetric algorithms use one key for both encryption and decryption, while asymmetric algorithms use a key pair","Symmetric algorithms are always more secure than asymmetric algorithms","Asymmetric algorithms are faster and better suited for bulk data encryption","Symmetric algorithms cannot be used for confidentiality protection"],"c":0,"why":"Symmetric encryption uses a single shared key for both encryption and decryption, whereas asymmetric encryption uses a mathematically related public/private key pair. Asymmetric algorithms are generally slower and used for key exchange or digital signatures, not bulk encryption.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements multiple overlapping security controls, including firewalls, intrusion detection systems, and physical access controls, so that if one control fails, others still provide protection. This is an example of which security principle?","o":["Security through obscurity","Defense in depth","Least privilege","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Defense in depth involves layering multiple, diverse controls so that the failure of one does not result in a complete security breach. Least privilege and separation of duties are access control principles, and security through obscurity relies on hiding system details rather than layered defenses.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which component of a computer system is responsible for enforcing access control decisions between subjects and objects and cannot be bypassed?","o":["Security kernel","Trusted computing base","Reference monitor","Security perimeter"],"c":2,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept that mediates all access between subjects and objects, ensuring it is always invoked, tamperproof, and small enough to verify. The security kernel is the hardware/software/firmware implementation of the reference monitor, while the TCB is the totality of protection mechanisms, and the security perimeter defines the boundary of the TCB.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which fire suppression agent is generally preferred for data centers because it displaces oxygen to extinguish fires without leaving residue that could damage electronic equipment?","o":["Water sprinkler systems","Carbon dioxide (CO2) or clean agent gas systems","Wet chemical foam systems","Class A dry powder extinguishers"],"c":1,"why":"Gaseous clean agents (or CO2 in unoccupied areas) suppress fires by displacing oxygen without leaving residue, making them ideal for sensitive electronic equipment. Water and wet chemical systems can damage equipment, and dry powder extinguishers leave residue and are not typically used in data centers.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to preserve confidentiality by preventing information from flowing from a higher security level to a lower one?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces 'no read up, no write down' to protect confidentiality. Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson enforces integrity through well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"During system design, a developer ensures that if a critical process fails, the system defaults to a state that denies all access rather than granting it. This design approach illustrates which secure design principle?","o":["Fail-secure design","Economy of mechanism","Complete mediation","Open design"],"c":0,"why":"Fail-secure design ensures that when a system experiences a failure, it defaults to a secure state (denying access) rather than an insecure one. Economy of mechanism relates to simplicity, complete mediation requires every access to be checked, and open design means security should not rely on secrecy of design.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A financial application must ensure that lower-integrity data cannot corrupt higher-integrity data. Which security model best supports this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","Graham-Denning model"],"c":1,"why":"Biba enforces 'no write up, no read down' to protect data integrity. Bell-LaPadula focuses on confidentiality, while Take-Grant and Graham-Denning deal with rights propagation and access control administration, not integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In a virtualized environment, which component is primarily responsible for enforcing isolation between multiple virtual machines running on the same physical host?","o":["Virtual switch","Hypervisor","Guest operating system","Storage area network controller"],"c":1,"why":"The hypervisor manages and isolates virtual machines, controlling their access to underlying physical hardware resources and preventing one VM from improperly accessing another's resources. The guest OS operates within a VM without visibility into other VMs, and virtual switches and SAN controllers handle networking and storage, not overall VM isolation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary advantage of symmetric encryption over asymmetric encryption?","o":["It provides non-repudiation","It eliminates the need for key distribution","It is faster for encrypting large volumes of data","It uses a public/private key pair"],"c":2,"why":"Symmetric algorithms are computationally faster and better suited for bulk encryption. They still require secure key distribution, do not provide non-repudiation, and use a single shared key rather than a key pair.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements multiple layers of security controls, such as firewalls, intrusion detection systems, and physical access controls, so that if one control fails, others still provide protection. What security principle does this illustrate?","o":["Least privilege","Defense in depth","Separation of duties","Security through obscurity"],"c":1,"why":"Defense in depth uses multiple, overlapping layers of controls to reduce risk if any single control fails. Least privilege limits access rights, separation of duties divides tasks among individuals, and security through obscurity relies on secrecy of design rather than layered controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A subject holding a Secret clearance is working in a session at the Secret level within a system enforcing the Bell-LaPadula model. Which of the following actions would violate the *-property (star property)?","o":["Reading a file classified Confidential (lower than Secret)","Writing to a file classified Secret (same level)","Writing to a file classified Confidential (lower than Secret)","Reading a file classified Top Secret (higher than Secret)"],"c":2,"why":"The *-property prohibits writing to an object at a lower classification (no write-down) to prevent leakage of sensitive data to less-trusted objects. Reading down is permitted under the simple security property, writing at the same level is unrestricted, and reading up violates the simple security property, not the *-property.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which internationally recognized standard provides a framework for evaluating the security assurance level of IT products and systems using Evaluation Assurance Levels (EALs)?","o":["ISO 27001","Common Criteria","NIST SP 800-53","COBIT"],"c":1,"why":"Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408) defines EALs used to rate product assurance. ISO 27001 addresses ISMS requirements, NIST SP 800-53 provides security controls for federal systems, and COBIT is an IT governance framework.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements the Biba integrity model to protect critical system files from corruption. Which of the following actions is prohibited by this model?","o":["A high-integrity subject writing to another high-integrity object","A low-integrity subject writing to a high-integrity object","A high-integrity subject writing to a low-integrity object","A low-integrity subject reading a high-integrity object"],"c":1,"why":"The *-integrity axiom (no write-up) prevents a low-integrity subject from directly corrupting high-integrity data. Writing at the same level, writing down, and reading up are all permitted under Biba, since none of these actions allow low-integrity input to contaminate high-integrity objects.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which fire suppression agent is generally preferred in a data center because it displaces oxygen without leaving residue and is safe for use around electronic equipment?","o":["Water sprinkler system","Wet chemical agent","Clean agent (e.g., FM-200)","Foam suppression"],"c":2,"why":"Clean agents like FM-200 suppress fire without damaging electronics or leaving residue. Water and foam can damage equipment, and wet chemical agents are typically used for kitchen-type fires, not electrical equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A network architect implements a key exchange using standard, unauthenticated Diffie-Hellman between two endpoints. Which attack is this design most vulnerable to, and what control best mitigates it?","o":["Brute-force attack on the shared secret, mitigated by increasing the modulus size only","Man-in-the-middle attack during the exchange, mitigated by authenticating the exchange with digital signatures or certificates","Replay attack on the derived session key, mitigated by adding sequence numbers to application traffic","Birthday attack on the underlying hash function, mitigated by switching to SHA-256"],"c":1,"why":"Plain Diffie-Hellman provides confidentiality of the derived secret but no authentication of the parties involved, allowing an attacker to intercept and substitute their own key material (MITM) unless the exchange is bound to authenticated identities, such as via signed parameters or certificates. The other attacks are not the primary weakness of unauthenticated DH.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security purpose of using a cryptographic hash function on a file before transmission?","o":["To encrypt the file so only authorized parties can read it","To verify the integrity of the file by detecting any modification","To compress the file for faster transmission","To provide confidentiality during storage"],"c":1,"why":"Hash functions produce a fixed-length digest used to detect changes to data, ensuring integrity. They do not encrypt or compress data, and hashing alone provides no confidentiality since hashes are not reversible but also not secret-key protected.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect must select a Common Criteria evaluated product for a system requiring assurance that its security functions have been formally verified through mathematical proof rather than extensive testing and semiformal analysis alone. Which Evaluation Assurance Level satisfies this requirement?","o":["EAL4 - Methodically Designed, Tested, and Reviewed","EAL5 - Semiformally Designed and Tested","EAL6 - Semiformally Verified Design and Tested","EAL7 - Formally Verified Design and Tested"],"c":3,"why":"EAL7 is the only level requiring formal (mathematically rigorous) verification of both design and testing. EAL5 and EAL6 use semiformal methods, and EAL4 relies on methodical, non-formal design review and testing, none of which meet the formal verification requirement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which secure design principle dictates that a system should default to a secure state, such as denying access, in the event of a failure?","o":["Fail-safe defaults","Least privilege","Complete mediation","Economy of mechanism"],"c":0,"why":"Fail-safe defaults ensure that systems deny access by default during failures, minimizing exposure. Least privilege limits granted permissions, complete mediation requires every access request to be checked, and economy of mechanism promotes simple, verifiable designs—none directly address failure behavior.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements the Bell-LaPadula security model to protect classified information. A user cleared to the 'Secret' level attempts to write data to a file classified as 'Top Secret'. According to the model's *-property (star property), what is the outcome?","o":["The write is denied because a subject cannot write to an object at a higher classification level","The write is permitted because subjects can always write to higher classification levels","The write is denied because the subject must first be granted read access to the higher level","The write is permitted only if the data being written is unclassified"],"c":1,"why":"The *-property (no write-down) actually permits writing to a higher or equal classification level (write-up) since this cannot cause a disclosure of higher-classified data to a lower-cleared subject; it is 'no write down' that is restricted, not write-up. The correct answer reflects that write-up is allowed under the *-property.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A database restricts direct access to an employee salary column based on classification level. An analyst without access to that column nonetheless deduces individual salaries by combining publicly available department budget totals with headcount and job-title data returned from an unrestricted view. This scenario best illustrates which database security concern?","o":["Aggregation attack","SQL injection","Inference attack","Polyinstantiation"],"c":2,"why":"Inference occurs when a user logically deduces restricted information by correlating multiple pieces of unrestricted, indirectly related data. Aggregation specifically involves combining many individually low-sensitivity records from the same source to reconstruct a higher-sensitivity whole, SQL injection is a code-injection attack, and polyinstantiation is a technique for preventing inference by creating multiple versions of data at different classification levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Which security architecture concept describes an abstract machine that mediates every access between subjects and objects, and which must be tamperproof, always invoked, and small enough to be formally verified?","o":["Trusted Computing Base (TCB)","Security kernel","Reference monitor","Security perimeter"],"c":2,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept requiring these three properties. The security kernel is the actual hardware/software/firmware implementation of that concept, the TCB is the totality of protection mechanisms within a system, and the security perimeter is the boundary separating the TCB from the rest of the system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"In a multi-tenant public cloud, a malicious tenant's VM repeatedly measures shared CPU cache access times to infer bits of a cryptographic key being processed by a co-located victim VM's process, without breaching the hypervisor's isolation controls. This is an example of which attack type?","o":["Cross-VM side-channel attack","VM escape","Hypervisor rootkit installation","Cross-site request forgery"],"c":0,"why":"Measuring shared hardware resource behavior (such as cache timing) across co-resident VMs to leak information is a classic cross-VM side-channel attack. VM escape involves breaking isolation to access the hypervisor or host directly, a hypervisor rootkit is malware embedded in the hypervisor itself, and CSRF is an unrelated web application attack.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security engineer selects a bare-metal (Type 1) hypervisor over a hosted (Type 2) hypervisor for a new private cloud deployment. What is the primary security rationale for this choice?","o":["Type 1 hypervisors run directly on hardware without a host operating system, reducing the attack surface compared to relying on a general-purpose host OS","Type 1 hypervisors include built-in antivirus scanning for all guest virtual machines","Type 1 hypervisors are purely software constructs and are therefore immune to hardware-level vulnerabilities","Type 1 hypervisors require all guest operating systems to be paravirtualized, which inherently improves security"],"c":0,"why":"Because Type 1 hypervisors run directly on hardware, they eliminate the additional attack surface and vulnerability exposure introduced by a full host operating system, unlike Type 2 hypervisors. The other options describe capabilities or properties that Type 1 hypervisors do not inherently possess.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing a multilevel secure system based on the Bell-LaPadula model. Which property specifically prevents a subject with a lower security clearance from reading an object classified at a higher level?","o":["Simple Security Property (no read up)","Star Property (no write down)","Strong Star Property","Discretionary Security Property"],"c":0,"why":"The Simple Security Property (ss-property) enforces 'no read up,' preventing lower-cleared subjects from reading higher-classified data. The *-Property governs writing (no write down), the Strong Star Property combines both restrictions at the same level, and the Discretionary Security Property relates to DAC, not mandatory read restrictions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements the Biba integrity model to protect critical financial processing systems from contamination by unreliable data sources. Which Biba axiom prevents a subject from reading data at a lower integrity level?","o":["Simple Integrity Axiom (no read down)","*-Integrity Axiom (no write up)","Invocation Property","Simple Security Property"],"c":0,"why":"The Simple Integrity Axiom enforces 'no read down,' preventing high-integrity subjects from being contaminated by lower-integrity data. The *-Integrity Axiom prevents writing up, the Invocation Property restricts communication between integrity levels, and the Simple Security Property belongs to Bell-LaPadula, not Biba.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A financial application enforces that users cleared at the 'Confidential' level can read data classified at 'Public' and 'Confidential', but cannot read data classified 'Secret'. Additionally, the application prevents a 'Confidential'-cleared user from writing data down to a 'Public' file. Which security model and property combination is being enforced?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model, combining the Simple Security Property and the *-Property (Star Property)","Biba model, combining the Simple Integrity Property and the Invocation Property","Clark-Wilson model, using well-formed transactions and separation of duties","Brewer-Nash model, using dynamically changing access permissions"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula's Simple Security Property enforces 'no read up' and the *-Property enforces 'no write down,' exactly matching the described behavior. Biba addresses integrity (not confidentiality), Clark-Wilson uses transaction-based integrity controls, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict-of-interest access, none of which match this read/write restriction pattern.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Two parties who have never communicated before need to securely establish a shared symmetric session key over an untrusted network without any pre-shared secret. Which approach best solves this key distribution problem?","o":["Use a single static symmetric key for all future sessions","Use a hybrid cryptosystem where asymmetric encryption protects the exchange of the symmetric key","Hash the parties' identities to derive a shared key","Rely solely on a pre-shared symmetric key distributed out-of-band"],"c":1,"why":"Hybrid cryptosystems use asymmetric encryption (or key exchange like Diffie-Hellman) to securely establish a symmetric session key without prior shared secrets, combining the strengths of both. Static keys, hashed identities, and required pre-shared keys don't solve the fundamental problem of secure key exchange between strangers.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An architect is redesigning a TLS-based VPN to ensure that compromise of a server's long-term private key does not allow an attacker to decrypt previously captured session traffic. Which design choice BEST achieves this goal?","o":["Use RSA key transport exclusively so session keys are encrypted directly with the server's public key","Use ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (DHE or ECDHE) key exchange for each session","Increase the RSA key size from 2048 to 4096 bits","Cache negotiated session keys on the server for faster reconnection"],"c":1,"why":"Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman generates unique, session-specific keys that are not mathematically derivable from the server's long-term private key, providing forward secrecy. RSA key transport ties the session key to the static private key (defeating forward secrecy), larger RSA keys don't change this dependency, and caching session keys increases exposure risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to protect the confidentiality of classified information by preventing unauthorized disclosure?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces confidentiality using 'no read up, no write down' rules to prevent data from flowing to lower clearance levels. Biba focuses on integrity, Clark-Wilson on integrity via well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security engineer discovers that two completely different input messages produce identical hash digests when processed by a cryptographic hash function. This finding represents a violation of which property?","o":["Preimage resistance","Second preimage resistance","Collision resistance","Avalanche effect"],"c":2,"why":"Collision resistance means it should be computationally infeasible to find any two distinct inputs that produce the same hash output; finding such a pair violates this property. Preimage resistance concerns recovering an input from a given hash, second preimage resistance concerns finding a different input matching a specific given input's hash, and the avalanche effect refers to small input changes causing large output changes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to encrypt large volumes of data quickly while also needing a separate mechanism to securely exchange the encryption key with a remote partner. Which combination of cryptographic approaches best meets this need?","o":["Use only asymmetric encryption for all data","Use symmetric encryption for the data and asymmetric encryption to exchange the symmetric key","Use only a hashing algorithm for the data","Use symmetric encryption for both data and key exchange"],"c":1,"why":"Hybrid cryptography leverages symmetric encryption's speed for bulk data and asymmetric encryption's secure key exchange capability, which is the standard approach in protocols like TLS. Using asymmetric encryption alone is too slow for large data, and hashing does not provide confidentiality.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a procurement review, an evaluator notes that Product A is certified at Common Criteria EAL4 and Product B is certified at EAL7. Which statement BEST describes the practical difference in assurance between these two evaluation levels?","o":["EAL7 requires formal verification and formal design descriptions in addition to independent testing, while EAL4 relies on methodical design, testing, and review without formal proofs","EAL7 guarantees the product is free of all vulnerabilities, while EAL4 only checks for known vulnerabilities","EAL4 and EAL7 differ only in the price of certification, not in the assurance activities performed","EAL7 applies only to open-source products, while EAL4 applies only to commercial closed-source products"],"c":0,"why":"Higher EAL levels require increasingly rigorous assurance activities, culminating in formal verification and formal design proofs at EAL7, whereas EAL4 relies on methodical, non-formal design and testing. No EAL certifies the absence of all vulnerabilities, and EAL levels are unrelated to licensing model or cost.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A government agency procuring a security product requires the highest level of assurance under the Common Criteria, including formal design verification and rigorous, methodical testing. Which Evaluation Assurance Level should the agency require?","o":["EAL1","EAL2","EAL4","EAL7"],"c":3,"why":"EAL7 is the highest Common Criteria assurance level, requiring formally verified design and comprehensive independent testing. EAL1 and EAL2 provide only basic assurance through functional testing, and EAL4 (commonly used for commercial products) requires methodical design and testing but not formal verification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In the context of a Trusted Computing Base (TCB), what is the primary function of the reference monitor?","o":["To encrypt all data at rest within the TCB","To mediate all access between subjects and objects according to security policy","To perform periodic vulnerability scans of the system","To manage user password complexity requirements"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept that enforces access control policy by mediating every access request between subjects and objects. Encryption, vulnerability scanning, and password management are separate security functions not defined by the reference monitor concept.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is reviewing a proposed access control enforcement module. The module is invoked for every subject-to-object access request, but its source code is stored on a general-purpose file server with the same protection as other application code, and it exceeds 500,000 lines. Which principle of the reference monitor concept is MOST at risk in this design?","o":["Completeness (always invoked)","Tamper resistance (isolation and protection from unauthorized modification)","Verifiability (small enough to be analyzed and tested)","Both tamper resistance and verifiability"],"c":3,"why":"Storing the module without dedicated protection risks unauthorized tampering, and its excessive size prevents rigorous formal analysis, violating both tamper resistance and verifiability. Completeness is not at issue since the module is invoked for every access request.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A cloud provider wants to minimize the attack surface of its virtualization layer by eliminating any dependency on a general-purpose host operating system between the hardware and guest virtual machines. Which architecture should it adopt?","o":["Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor","Type 2 (hosted) hypervisor","Application virtualization","Container-based virtualization"],"c":0,"why":"A Type 1 hypervisor runs directly on the hardware without a host OS, reducing the attack surface and dependency chain. A Type 2 hypervisor relies on an underlying general-purpose OS, increasing exposure, while application virtualization and containers virtualize at a different layer and don't address hypervisor-level host OS dependency.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary security benefit of implementing defense in depth in a system architecture?","o":["It eliminates the need for a single strong security control","It guarantees compliance with all regulatory requirements","It reduces the overall cost of security controls","It ensures that no single point of failure can compromise the entire system"],"c":3,"why":"Defense in depth uses multiple layered controls so that if one control fails, others still provide protection, avoiding a single point of failure. It does not eliminate the need for strong controls, guarantee compliance, or necessarily reduce costs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Researchers demonstrate that by measuring the precise time an embedded smart card takes to perform RSA decryption operations, they can recover bits of the private key. Which category of attack does this describe, and which mitigation is MOST appropriate?","o":["A side-channel timing attack; mitigate by implementing constant-time cryptographic operations","A chosen-ciphertext attack; mitigate by switching to a stronger padding scheme such as OAEP","A brute-force attack; mitigate by increasing key length beyond 2048 bits","A replay attack; mitigate by adding nonces to each transaction"],"c":0,"why":"Leaking key material through variations in execution time is a classic side-channel timing attack, best mitigated with constant-time implementations that eliminate timing variance. The other options describe unrelated attack classes and mitigations that do not address timing leakage.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A facility processing highly classified information needs to prevent adversaries from intercepting compromising electromagnetic emanations radiated by computing equipment. Which control specifically addresses this threat?","o":["TEMPEST-shielded enclosures","Intrusion detection system","Biometric access control","Uninterruptible power supply with surge protection"],"c":0,"why":"TEMPEST standards and shielding techniques (including Faraday-cage principles) are specifically designed to prevent interception of compromising electromagnetic emanations. IDS, biometric access control, and UPS/surge protection address different threats (network intrusion, physical entry, and power stability, respectively) and do not mitigate emanation-based eavesdropping.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which physical security control is specifically designed to detect unauthorized entry into a facility rather than prevent it?","o":["Bollards","Motion-activated intrusion detection sensors","Mantrap","Security fencing"],"c":1,"why":"Motion sensors are detective controls that identify unauthorized movement or entry after it occurs. Bollards, mantraps, and fencing are primarily preventive controls designed to physically block or control access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A multilevel secure database contains a row representing a covert military shipment. Users with 'Secret' clearance see the true destination, while users with only 'Confidential' clearance querying the same primary key see a cover-story destination inserted specifically for their level. Which database security technique is being used, and what is its primary purpose?","o":["Polyinstantiation; to prevent inference of the existence of higher-classified data by lower-cleared users","Database views; to simplify query results for lower-cleared users","Content-dependent access control; to restrict access based on field values","Aggregation control; to prevent low-cleared users from combining multiple low-sensitivity records into a higher-sensitivity conclusion"],"c":0,"why":"Polyinstantiation allows multiple rows to exist under the same key at different classification levels specifically to prevent lower-cleared users from inferring the existence of hidden higher-classified data. Views and content-dependent controls don't create multiple instances of the same record, and aggregation control addresses a different inference scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A cloud security assessor discovers that a malicious tenant's virtual machine was able to execute code that directly manipulated hypervisor memory, allowing access to other tenants' VMs on the same physical host. Which control would have been MOST effective at preventing this specific attack?","o":["Implementing strict network segmentation between tenant VLANs","Enforcing hardware-assisted virtualization extensions and keeping the hypervisor patched against known VM-escape vulnerabilities","Requiring multifactor authentication for all administrative access to the cloud management plane","Encrypting tenant VM disk images at rest using tenant-specific keys"],"c":1,"why":"VM escape exploits flaws in how the hypervisor handles guest-level instructions; hardware-assisted virtualization and timely hypervisor patching directly close this attack surface. Network segmentation, MFA, and disk encryption protect against different threat vectors and would not prevent code execution at the hypervisor level.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In a virtualized environment, which component is responsible for enforcing isolation between multiple virtual machines running on the same physical host?","o":["Virtual machine hypervisor","Guest operating system kernel","Virtual network interface card","Application-level firewall"],"c":0,"why":"The hypervisor manages hardware resources and enforces isolation boundaries between VMs, preventing one VM from accessing another's memory or resources. The guest OS, virtual NIC, and application firewall operate within a VM and cannot enforce inter-VM isolation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A defense contractor processes classified information in a facility located near a public parking lot. To prevent adversaries from reconstructing screen content or keystrokes by capturing unintentional electromagnetic emissions from computing equipment throughout the facility, which control should be implemented?","o":["Deploying host-based intrusion detection systems on all classified workstations","Installing TEMPEST-shielded enclosures or equipment rated to suppress compromising emanations","Requiring full-disk encryption on all classified workstations","Implementing a Faraday-caged network closet solely for the server room switches"],"c":1,"why":"TEMPEST standards specifically address suppression of compromising electromagnetic emanations from computing equipment facility-wide, directly countering this eavesdropping vector. HIDS and disk encryption protect against unrelated threats, and shielding only the server closet leaves emanations from workstations throughout the facility unprotected.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A database administrator wants to prevent a low-privilege user from viewing salary data while still allowing that user to run reports that use the salary table. Which technique BEST achieves this goal?","o":["Database views with column-level restrictions","Full database encryption at rest","Increasing the user's password complexity requirements","Implementing database replication"],"c":0,"why":"Views can restrict access to specific columns, allowing users to interact with reports without seeing sensitive fields like salary. Encryption at rest, password complexity, and replication do not control which columns a user can see within query results.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which cryptographic function is primarily used to verify data integrity by producing a fixed-length output that changes significantly with any modification to the input?","o":["Symmetric encryption algorithm","Asymmetric encryption algorithm","Cryptographic hash function","Key exchange protocol"],"c":2,"why":"Hash functions produce a unique fixed-length digest for input data, and any change to the input results in a drastically different hash, making them ideal for integrity verification. Symmetric and asymmetric encryption provide confidentiality, and key exchange protocols facilitate secure key sharing rather than integrity checks.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A hospital's clinical decision-support system must ensure that low-integrity data entered by unverified external feeds can never overwrite or influence high-integrity diagnostic records, but the system has no requirement to control the flow of classified information between security levels. Which formal security model most directly addresses this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula Model","Biba Integrity Model","Brewer-Nash Model (Chinese Wall)","Take-Grant Model"],"c":1,"why":"Biba enforces 'no write up' and 'no read down' to preserve data integrity by preventing low-integrity subjects from corrupting high-integrity objects; Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality (not integrity), Brewer-Nash addresses conflict-of-interest access, and Take-Grant models rights propagation, not integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A vendor implements a Diffie-Hellman key exchange between two endpoints over an untrusted network but provides no mechanism to verify the identity of either party during the exchange. Which attack is this implementation most susceptible to?","o":["Birthday attack on the resulting session key","Man-in-the-middle attack during key negotiation","Brute-force attack against the shared secret","Replay attack using a captured session key"],"c":1,"why":"Unauthenticated Diffie-Hellman allows an attacker to intercept and substitute key exchange messages with both parties, establishing separate shared secrets with each while remaining undetected; the other attacks are not the primary weakness introduced by lack of authentication in DH.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Within a trusted computing base (TCB), which architectural component actually implements the reference monitor concept, mediating and enforcing all access control decisions between subjects and objects?","o":["Security Kernel","Trusted Computing Base","Security Perimeter","Reference Monitor"],"c":0,"why":"The security kernel is the hardware, firmware, and software implementation that enforces the reference monitor concept, mediating every access request. The TCB is the broader collection of all protection mechanisms, the security perimeter is the boundary separating the TCB from the rest of the system, and the reference monitor itself is an abstract model rather than a concrete implemented component.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A hardware security architect wants data to be decryptable only when the platform's boot sequence matches a specific, verified configuration recorded at boot time. Which TPM capability provides this?","o":["Remote attestation","Binding","Sealing","Quoting"],"c":2,"why":"Sealing encrypts data against specific PCR (Platform Configuration Register) values, so it can only be unsealed when the platform state matches those values. Binding encrypts to a TPM key without state checks, attestation/quoting is used to prove platform state to a remote party, not to gate local decryption.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A company with 5,000 employees needs a secure method for employees to exchange encrypted messages without pre-establishing shared secrets between every pair of users. Which cryptographic approach best addresses this key distribution challenge?","o":["Use a single symmetric key shared by all employees for simplicity","Implement asymmetric (public key) cryptography with a PKI to manage key pairs","Use symmetric encryption with keys manually distributed by IT staff to each pair","Require each employee to generate a new symmetric key for every message sent"],"c":1,"why":"Asymmetric cryptography solves the key distribution problem because each user only needs a public/private key pair, and public keys can be shared openly via a PKI, eliminating the need for pairwise pre-shared secrets. Symmetric-only approaches scale poorly (n(n-1)/2 keys) and a single shared key destroys confidentiality between users.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A software vendor announces that their product has achieved a Common Criteria EAL4 rating. Which statement most accurately reflects what this rating conveys to a security architect evaluating the product?","o":["The product has been proven free of exploitable vulnerabilities under normal operating conditions","The product's security functions are stronger than those of a product rated EAL2","The product was methodically designed, tested, and reviewed to a defined assurance level, independent of the strength of its security functionality","The EAL rating specifies the exact cryptographic algorithms the product must support"],"c":2,"why":"EAL ratings measure the rigor and depth of the evaluation process (assurance), not the strength or completeness of security functions themselves; a product can have weak security functions yet high assurance that those functions work as specified, so EAL level alone doesn't guarantee vulnerability-free operation or superior functionality over lower EAL products.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements the Bell-LaPadula security model on a classified system. A subject holding a 'Secret' clearance attempts to read a file classified 'Top Secret.' Under the simple security property, what is the outcome?","o":["The read is permitted because Secret is close enough in sensitivity to Top Secret","The read is denied because a subject cannot read data classified above its clearance level","The read is permitted because Bell-LaPadula only restricts write operations","The read is denied only if the file also has a lower integrity label"],"c":1,"why":"Bell-LaPadula's simple security property ('no read up') prevents subjects from reading objects classified above their clearance, preserving confidentiality. The model does restrict reads (not just writes), and integrity labeling is governed by other models like Biba, not Bell-LaPadula.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A government agency requires a security product to undergo formal verification of its design and implementation using mathematically rigorous methods before approval for use in highly sensitive systems. Under the Common Criteria, which Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) corresponds to this level of rigor?","o":["EAL2","EAL4","EAL7","EAL1"],"c":2,"why":"EAL7 is the highest Common Criteria assurance level, requiring formal design verification and formal testing methods, appropriate for extremely high-risk environments. Lower EALs (1, 2, 4) involve progressively less rigorous, more structural or semi-formal testing and design review.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Two colluding processes on the same multi-tenant host, prohibited from any direct or shared-memory communication, manage to exchange information by one process deliberately varying its CPU utilization in observable patterns that the other process detects via system performance monitoring. This is best classified as a:","o":["Storage covert channel","Side-channel attack","Timing covert channel","Overt channel"],"c":2,"why":"A timing covert channel conveys information through the modulation of timing or resource-usage patterns (e.g., CPU cycles) rather than through data storage; storage covert channels use shared data locations, side-channel attacks exploit unintentional physical emissions (power, EM) rather than intentional signaling, and an overt channel is a sanctioned communication path, the opposite of what's described here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A laptop manufacturer wants to ensure that encryption keys used to protect disk data are bound to the specific hardware and cannot be extracted even if the operating system is compromised. Which technology best supports this requirement?","o":["A software-based key management vault installed on the OS","A Trusted Platform Module (TPM) that seals keys to platform configuration","A hardware security module (HSM) located in a remote data center","A symmetric key stored in an encrypted file on the disk"],"c":1,"why":"A TPM is a hardware root of trust embedded in the device that can seal cryptographic keys to specific platform states (e.g., boot configuration), preventing extraction even if the OS is compromised. Software vaults and encrypted files remain vulnerable to OS-level compromise, and a remote HSM does not provide local hardware binding for the device.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An analyst without authorized access to individual salary records is able to deduce a specific employee's salary by combining permitted query results showing average salary by department, headcount by department, and the employee's known job title and department. This scenario best illustrates a:","o":["Aggregation attack","SQL injection attack","Inference attack","Polyinstantiation bypass"],"c":2,"why":"Inference occurs when a user deduces restricted information by correlating multiple pieces of authorized, seemingly unrelated data; aggregation refers to combining individually low-sensitivity data elements that become sensitive in combination, which is a related but distinct concept from deriving one specific unknown value through reasoning. SQL injection and polyinstantiation are unrelated mechanisms.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A cloud service provider hosts multiple customer virtual machines (VMs) on a single physical server using a Type 1 hypervisor. A security researcher discovers a vulnerability allowing a process inside one VM to gain unauthorized access to the hypervisor and other VMs on the same host. What is this type of attack called, and what is the primary architectural concern it represents?","o":["A side-channel attack; concern is timing analysis between VMs","A VM escape; concern is breakdown of isolation between guest VMs and the hypervisor","A buffer overflow; concern is application-layer input validation","A man-in-the-middle attack; concern is network traffic interception between VMs"],"c":1,"why":"A VM escape occurs when malicious code breaks out of its VM's isolation boundary to access the hypervisor or other VMs, which is a critical architectural risk in multi-tenant virtualization environments. Side-channel and MITM attacks involve different mechanisms (timing/network interception), and buffer overflow describes a technique, not this specific isolation-breach scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial application uses the Biba integrity model to protect the accuracy of transaction data. A process running at a 'Low' integrity level attempts to write to a file classified at 'High' integrity. What happens under Biba's *-property, and why?","o":["The write is allowed because Biba only restricts read operations","The write is denied because a lower-integrity subject cannot write to a higher-integrity object, preventing contamination of trusted data","The write is allowed because Biba permits write-up to promote data availability","The write is denied because Biba enforces confidentiality, not integrity"],"c":1,"why":"Biba's *-property ('no write up') blocks lower-integrity subjects from writing to higher-integrity objects, preventing corruption of trusted data by less trusted sources. Biba is an integrity model (not confidentiality), and it does restrict writes, unlike option A suggests.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect specifies that if the biometric access control reader loses power or experiences a hardware fault, the door lock must remain locked rather than default to an unlocked state. This requirement is a direct application of which secure design principle?","o":["Least privilege","Defense in depth","Fail-safe defaults (fail secure)","Separation of duties"],"c":2,"why":"Fail-safe defaults dictate that a system should default to a secure/denied state upon failure rather than an open/permissive one; least privilege concerns minimal access rights, defense in depth concerns layered controls, and separation of duties concerns dividing critical tasks among multiple individuals—none of which address failure-state behavior.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During the design of a new corporate campus, security architects apply Crime Prevention Through Environmental Design (CPTED) principles. Which design choice best exemplifies the 'natural surveillance' concept?","o":["Installing tall, opaque fencing around the entire perimeter to block outside view","Positioning windows, lighting, and walkways so that employees have clear sightlines of entrances and parking areas","Placing all security cameras exclusively at unmarked internal server rooms","Restricting all building access to a single unmarked door with no signage"],"c":1,"why":"Natural surveillance relies on the physical design of an environment (lighting, sightlines, window placement) to make it easier for legitimate occupants to observe and thereby deter suspicious activity. Tall opaque fencing and hidden/unmarked entrances work against surveillance and can create blind spots, which CPTED principles aim to avoid.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a procurement review, a security architect compares two products: one evaluated at Common Criteria EAL4 and another at EAL7. What is the primary practical distinction between these evaluation levels?","o":["EAL7 products are inherently more secure in real-world deployment regardless of configuration","EAL7 involves formally verified design and testing, providing higher assurance of correct implementation, while EAL4 provides moderate assurance through methodical testing","EAL4 applies only to hardware while EAL7 applies only to software","EAL levels measure functional richness, not assurance of security claims"],"c":1,"why":"EAL ratings measure the rigor and depth of assurance activities (e.g., formal verification at EAL7 vs. methodical design/testing at EAL4), not inherent real-world security or functionality; a higher EAL means claims were verified more rigorously, not that the product has more features or is automatically secure in any deployment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester operating within a guest virtual machine discovers and exploits a vulnerability in the hypervisor's device emulation layer, gaining the ability to execute arbitrary code on the host system and access memory belonging to other guest VMs. This attack is best described as:","o":["VM sprawl","Hyperjacking","VM escape","Cross-VM side-channel attack"],"c":2,"why":"VM escape occurs when code running inside a guest breaks out of its isolation boundary to affect the host or other VMs by exploiting a hypervisor flaw. Hyperjacking involves installing a rogue hypervisor beneath the legitimate one, VM sprawl refers to uncontrolled proliferation of VM instances, and a cross-VM side-channel attack infers data through shared hardware resource observation rather than direct code execution across the boundary.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A database administrator notices that a user without direct access to salary information can determine an individual employee's salary by running several queries on job title, department averages, and headcount. This is an example of which type of database security issue?","o":["SQL injection","An inference attack through data aggregation","A brute-force authentication attack","A covert channel using timing analysis"],"c":1,"why":"An inference attack occurs when a user deduces restricted information (like an individual salary) by combining multiple pieces of non-sensitive data (aggregate statistics), even without direct query access to the sensitive field. This is distinct from SQL injection (code manipulation), brute force (credential guessing), or covert timing channels (unrelated indirect communication methods).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A secure messaging application uses a hybrid cryptosystem: it establishes a session using asymmetric cryptography, then encrypts the actual message content with a symmetric algorithm. What is the primary security engineering rationale for this design?","o":["Asymmetric algorithms are faster for bulk data encryption than symmetric algorithms","Symmetric algorithms cannot be used for encrypting large volumes of data","Asymmetric cryptography solves the key distribution problem efficiently, while symmetric cryptography provides fast bulk encryption once a shared key is established","Using both algorithm types is required by FIPS 140-2 regardless of performance"],"c":2,"why":"Hybrid systems combine asymmetric crypto's strength in secure key exchange with symmetric crypto's computational efficiency for bulk data, addressing both the key distribution problem and performance needs. Asymmetric algorithms are actually much slower for bulk encryption, not faster, and there's no such blanket FIPS mandate for combining them.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A user wants to send a signed document proving both integrity and origin authenticity. Which process correctly describes generating a digital signature?","o":["Encrypt the entire document with the sender's private key, then encrypt again with the recipient's public key","Hash the document, then encrypt the resulting hash value with the sender's private key","Hash the document, then encrypt the hash with the recipient's public key","Encrypt the document with a symmetric key, then send the key encrypted with the sender's private key"],"c":1,"why":"A digital signature is created by hashing the message and encrypting the hash with the sender's private key; recipients verify using the sender's public key, proving origin and integrity. Encrypting the whole document is inefficient and unnecessary, and using the recipient's public key would provide confidentiality, not signature verification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security engineer reviews a compiled application binary and confirms that stack canaries are enabled. What type of attack does this control primarily mitigate?","o":["SQL injection attacks against backend databases","Buffer overflow attacks that attempt to overwrite the return address on the stack","Cross-site scripting attacks in web application output","Man-in-the-middle attacks during TLS handshake negotiation"],"c":1,"why":"Stack canaries place a known value before the return address; if a buffer overflow overwrites the stack, the canary value changes and the program detects tampering before executing a corrupted return address. This is a memory-safety control unrelated to SQL injection, XSS, or TLS handshake attacks.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to protect the confidentiality of information by preventing subjects from reading data at a higher classification level or writing data to a lower classification level?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces 'no read up, no write down' to protect confidentiality. Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson enforces integrity through well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center housing sensitive servers and paper records needs a fire suppression system that minimizes damage to electronic equipment while safely displacing oxygen from fire without leaving residue. Which system is most appropriate?","o":["Wet-pipe water sprinkler system","Clean agent (e.g., FM-200 or inert gas) suppression system","CO2 total flooding system used without evacuation delay","Dry chemical (powder-based) suppression system"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agent systems suppress fire by displacing oxygen or interrupting combustion without leaving residue or conductive moisture, making them ideal for electronic equipment. Water damages electronics, dry chemical leaves corrosive residue, and CO2 systems require evacuation delays because they pose asphyxiation risk to personnel.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to prevent unauthorized modification of data by ensuring that users cannot write to objects of higher integrity and cannot read data from objects of lower integrity. Which model best supports this goal?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","Graham-Denning model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model enforces 'no write up, no read down' to preserve data integrity. Bell-LaPadula focuses on confidentiality, and Take-Grant/Graham-Denning models address rights propagation, not integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization is designing a virtualization infrastructure and must decide between a Type 1 (bare-metal) and Type 2 (hosted) hypervisor for production servers. From a security architecture standpoint, why is Type 1 generally preferred for enterprise workloads?","o":["Type 1 hypervisors run directly on hardware without a full host OS, reducing the attack surface compared to Type 2 hypervisors that run atop a general-purpose OS","Type 2 hypervisors cannot support virtual machine snapshots or live migration","Type 1 hypervisors eliminate the need for any hypervisor-level patching","Type 2 hypervisors provide stronger isolation between guest VMs than Type 1 hypervisors"],"c":0,"why":"Type 1 hypervisors run directly on hardware, minimizing the underlying software attack surface, whereas Type 2 hypervisors depend on a full host operating system that introduces additional vulnerabilities. Type 1 hypervisors still require patching, and Type 2 hypervisors generally offer weaker isolation, not stronger, due to reliance on the host OS.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which statement accurately describes a key difference between symmetric and asymmetric encryption?","o":["Symmetric encryption uses a single shared key, while asymmetric encryption uses a public/private key pair","Symmetric encryption is always slower than asymmetric encryption","Asymmetric encryption cannot be used for digital signatures","Symmetric encryption provides non-repudiation, while asymmetric encryption does not"],"c":0,"why":"Symmetric encryption relies on one shared secret key for both encryption and decryption, whereas asymmetric encryption uses a mathematically related public/private key pair. Symmetric algorithms are generally faster, not slower, and asymmetric encryption is commonly used for digital signatures and non-repudiation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In secure system design, what is the primary function of the Trusted Computing Base (TCB)?","o":["To encrypt all data at rest and in transit","To enforce the system's security policy through hardware, firmware, and software components","To provide user authentication only","To manage network firewall rules"],"c":1,"why":"The TCB encompasses all protection mechanisms (hardware, firmware, software) that work together to enforce the security policy of a system. It is not limited to encryption, authentication, or network controls specifically.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A company implements multiple overlapping security controls, such as firewalls, intrusion detection systems, and endpoint protection, so that if one control fails, others still provide protection. This approach is known as which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity"],"c":2,"why":"Defense in depth uses layered, overlapping controls so that the failure of one does not compromise overall security. Least privilege limits access rights, separation of duties divides tasks among individuals, and security through obscurity relies on secrecy of design rather than layered controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of using a cryptographic hash function on a file before and after transmission?","o":["To encrypt the file so it cannot be read by unauthorized parties","To verify that the file's integrity has not been altered during transmission","To compress the file for faster transmission","To authenticate the sender's identity"],"c":1,"why":"Hash functions produce a fixed-length digest used to detect changes to data, verifying integrity. They do not provide confidentiality (encryption), compression, or sender authentication on their own—those require additional mechanisms like digital signatures.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A data center is designing its fire suppression system for a room containing critical servers. Which suppression method is generally preferred to minimize equipment damage while effectively extinguishing fires?","o":["Water sprinkler systems","Clean agent gaseous suppression systems","Foam-based suppression systems","Dry chemical powder suppression systems"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agent gaseous systems (e.g., FM-200, Novec 1230) extinguish fires by removing heat or oxygen without leaving residue, making them ideal for sensitive electronics. Water, foam, and dry chemical agents can damage servers and other electronic equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A security team recommends improving natural surveillance, access control, and territorial reinforcement around a facility's perimeter through landscaping, lighting, and building layout. This approach is best described as which concept?","o":["Crime Prevention Through Environmental Design (CPTED)","Defense in depth","Mandatory access control","Security information and event management (SIEM)"],"c":0,"why":"CPTED uses physical environmental design—lighting, layout, landscaping—to naturally discourage criminal behavior and improve surveillance. The other options relate to layered technical controls, access control models, or monitoring systems, not physical site design.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial application must ensure that low-integrity data entered by a junior clerk cannot corrupt high-integrity financial records maintained by a senior accountant. Which security model best supports this requirement, and what rule enforces it?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model; no read-up rule","Biba model; no write-up rule","Clark-Wilson model; separation of duties only","Brewer-Nash model; conflict-of-interest rule"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model is designed to protect data integrity, and its 'no write-up' rule (Simple Integrity Property) prevents a lower-integrity subject from writing to a higher-integrity object. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, not integrity, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflicts of interest, not integrity levels; Clark-Wilson also protects integrity but primarily through well-formed transactions, not simply 'separation of duties only.'","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Two parties who have never communicated before need to establish a shared secret key over an insecure channel without prior exchange of any secret information. Which cryptographic mechanism is specifically designed for this purpose?","o":["RSA digital signature algorithm","Diffie-Hellman key exchange","Advanced Encryption Standard (AES)","HMAC-SHA256"],"c":1,"why":"Diffie-Hellman is designed specifically to allow two parties to derive a shared secret over an insecure channel without prior key exchange, using public parameters and private exponents. RSA is primarily used for encryption/signatures, AES is a symmetric cipher requiring a pre-shared key, and HMAC is a message authentication mechanism, not a key exchange protocol.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A system enforces mandatory access control such that a subject cleared for Top Secret is prevented from copying data from a Top Secret document into a file labeled Unclassified, even though the subject has legitimate read access to the Top Secret document. Which Bell-LaPadula property is being enforced?","o":["Simple security property (no read up)","Star property (no write down)","Strong star property (no read or write across levels)","Discretionary security property"],"c":1,"why":"The *-property (no write-down) prevents a subject from writing information to a lower classification level, which stops high-to-low data leakage; the simple security property governs reading, and the strong star property (used in some interpretations) would also block same-level writes, which is not what's described.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A security model enforces the rules 'no read up' (simple security property) and 'no write down' (*-property) to prevent information from flowing from a higher classification level to a lower one. Which model is this?","o":["Bell-LaPadula","Biba","Clark-Wilson","Brewer-Nash (Chinese Wall)"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula is a confidentiality-focused model using 'no read up, no write down.' Biba enforces the opposite rules for integrity. Clark-Wilson enforces well-formed transactions and separation of duties. Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest, not classification-based flow.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is selecting a cryptographic hash function for use in a digital signature scheme. Which property is MOST critical to prevent an attacker from creating two different messages that produce the same hash value?","o":["Pre-image resistance","Collision resistance","Avalanche effect","Key sensitivity"],"c":1,"why":"Collision resistance specifically ensures it is computationally infeasible to find two different inputs that produce the same hash output, which is essential for digital signature integrity. Pre-image resistance prevents reversing a hash to find the original input, and avalanche effect/key sensitivity describe how small input changes affect output but do not directly address collisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"In an environment using the Biba integrity model, a process running at the 'Medium Integrity' level attempts to read configuration data from a file labeled 'Low Integrity' so it can incorporate that data into its own processing. Which Biba principle blocks this action?","o":["Simple integrity axiom (no read down)","*-integrity axiom (no write up)","Invocation property","No properties block this; Biba only restricts writes"],"c":0,"why":"Biba's simple integrity axiom prevents a subject from reading data from a lower integrity level (no read-down) to avoid contaminating higher-integrity processes with less trustworthy data; the *-integrity axiom governs writing up, not reading down.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"In the context of the Trusted Computing Base (TCB), which component is responsible for mediating ALL access between subjects and objects to enforce the system's security policy?","o":["Security kernel","Trusted path","Reference monitor","Security perimeter"],"c":2,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept/design that mediates all subject-object access attempts and enforces security policy; the security kernel is its hardware/software/firmware implementation within the TCB. The trusted path ensures secure communication between user and TCB, and the security perimeter defines the boundary separating the TCB from the rest of the system, but neither performs the actual access mediation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is redesigning a TLS-based VPN to ensure that even if the server's long-term private key is compromised in the future, previously captured encrypted sessions cannot be decrypted. Which design choice best achieves this goal?","o":["Use RSA key exchange with a 4096-bit key for stronger encryption","Use static Diffie-Hellman key exchange authenticated by the server certificate","Use ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (DHE/ECDHE) key exchange for each session","Increase the AES symmetric key size from 128 to 256 bits"],"c":2,"why":"Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman generates unique session keys that are discarded after use, providing perfect forward secrecy; RSA and static DH key exchanges tie session key derivation to a long-term key, so compromise of that key exposes past sessions, and symmetric key size alone doesn't provide forward secrecy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model uses the rules 'no write up' and 'no read down' specifically to protect the integrity of data rather than its confidentiality?","o":["Biba","Bell-LaPadula","Take-Grant","Graham-Denning"],"c":0,"why":"The Biba model protects integrity by preventing subjects from writing to higher-integrity objects or reading from lower-integrity ones. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality with opposite rules. Take-Grant models rights propagation, and Graham-Denning defines operations for managing subjects and objects, neither addressing integrity levels directly.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a mandatory access control model in which a subject with a 'Secret' clearance is prohibited from reading data classified 'Top Secret' and is also prohibited from writing data down to a 'Confidential' level. This model is designed primarily to protect:","o":["Data integrity by preventing unauthorized modification","Data confidentiality by preventing unauthorized disclosure","Availability by preventing denial-of-service conditions","Non-repudiation by ensuring accountability of subjects"],"c":1,"why":"This describes the Bell-LaPadula model (Simple Security Property 'no read up' and *-Property 'no write down'), which enforces confidentiality by preventing information from flowing to lower clearance levels. Integrity, availability, and non-repudiation are addressed by other models/controls (e.g., Biba for integrity).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a Common Criteria evaluation, a vendor's product is assigned an Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) of 4. What does this rating primarily indicate about the product?","o":["The product has been formally verified using mathematical proofs of design correctness","The product has undergone methodical design, testing, and review, providing moderate assurance","The product meets the highest possible assurance level defined by Common Criteria","The product is certified free of all known vulnerabilities"],"c":1,"why":"EAL4 represents methodically designed, tested, and reviewed assurance—a moderate level suitable for commercial products—while EAL7 involves formal verification and is the highest level. No EAL level guarantees a product is free of vulnerabilities; EALs measure assurance in the evaluation process, not vulnerability-free status.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A government agency is procuring a hardware security module that must undergo the highest level of Common Criteria assurance, including formal verification of the design against a formal model of security policy. Which Evaluation Assurance Level should be specified in the procurement requirements?","o":["EAL2 - Structurally Tested","EAL4 - Methodically Designed, Tested, and Reviewed","EAL7 - Formally Verified Design and Tested","EAL5 - Semiformally Designed and Tested"],"c":2,"why":"EAL7 is the highest Common Criteria assurance level and requires formal verification of design against a formal security policy model; EAL4 and EAL5 use methodical or semiformal methods, not full formal verification, and EAL2 is a much lower structural testing level.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization needs to encrypt very large volumes of data efficiently, minimizing processing overhead. Which cryptographic approach is best suited for this task?","o":["Symmetric key encryption","Asymmetric key encryption","Cryptographic hashing","Digital signatures"],"c":0,"why":"Symmetric encryption uses a single shared key and is computationally efficient, making it ideal for bulk data encryption. Asymmetric encryption is slower and typically used for key exchange or digital signatures. Hashing is one-way and not used for encrypting data for later decryption. Digital signatures provide authentication and integrity, not confidentiality.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A laptop uses a TPM to perform measured boot. During boot, cryptographic hashes of firmware, bootloader, and OS kernel are extended into Platform Configuration Registers (PCRs). A remote server later requests attestation before granting VPN access. What is the PRIMARY security benefit this process provides?","o":["It encrypts all data on the disk to prevent offline attacks","It proves to the remote server that the boot chain has not been tampered with since the last known-good state","It authenticates the user's identity via biometric comparison stored in the TPM","It guarantees the operating system has no unpatched vulnerabilities"],"c":1,"why":"Measured boot with PCR values allows remote attestation of platform integrity, proving the boot components match a trusted baseline; it does not perform disk encryption, user authentication, or vulnerability assessment, which are separate functions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A cloud service provider hosts multiple customer virtual machines on a single physical server using a bare-metal hypervisor that runs directly on hardware without a host operating system. What is the PRIMARY security advantage of this architecture (Type 1) over a Type 2 hypervisor?","o":["It allows unlimited virtual machine density without performance degradation","It eliminates the need for network segmentation between tenants","It reduces the attack surface by removing dependency on an underlying host OS","It automatically encrypts all data at rest within each virtual machine"],"c":2,"why":"A Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor runs directly on hardware, eliminating the host OS as an additional attack surface and point of compromise, unlike Type 2 hypervisors which run atop a general-purpose OS. It does not inherently provide unlimited scalability, eliminate the need for network segmentation, or provide automatic encryption.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial application uses an access control model where a subject cleared to modify high-integrity financial records is prevented from reading data from a lower-integrity source and is prevented from writing to a higher-integrity object above its own level. Which security model does this describe?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model (Chinese Wall)"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model enforces integrity using the Simple Integrity Property ('no read down') and the *-Integrity Property ('no write up'), preventing contamination of high-integrity data by lower-integrity sources. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, Clark-Wilson uses well-formed transactions rather than these specific rules, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center design team is selecting a fire suppression system for a server room containing sensitive electronic equipment. Which option provides effective fire suppression while minimizing damage to the equipment?","o":["Wet pipe water sprinkler system","Clean agent gaseous suppression system (e.g., FM-200)","Dry chemical powder extinguishing system","Foam-based suppression system"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agent gaseous systems like FM-200 suppress fires by removing heat or oxygen without leaving residue and are electrically non-conductive, making them ideal for sensitive electronics. Water, dry chemical powder, and foam systems can cause corrosion, residue buildup, or short circuits that damage electronic equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester monitoring a smart card reader's power consumption during cryptographic operations is able to statistically correlate fluctuations in power draw with individual bits of the private key being processed. Which category of attack is being performed, and which countermeasure is MOST effective against it?","o":["Fault injection attack; countermeasure is tamper-evident packaging","Differential power analysis; countermeasure is power consumption randomization and constant-time algorithms","Timing attack; countermeasure is increasing key length","Chosen-ciphertext attack; countermeasure is padding validation"],"c":1,"why":"This describes differential power analysis (DPA), a side-channel attack; effective countermeasures include power randomization, noise injection, and constant-time implementations that decouple power draw from key-dependent operations. Increasing key length or padding validation does not address the physical side channel being exploited.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which term refers to the combination of hardware, software, and firmware mechanisms within a system that work together to enforce a security policy?","o":["Trusted Computing Base (TCB)","Security perimeter","Reference monitor","Trusted path"],"c":0,"why":"The TCB encompasses all protection mechanisms enforcing the security policy. The security perimeter is the boundary separating the TCB from the rest of the system. The reference monitor is the abstract concept enforcing access control decisions within the TCB. A trusted path is a secure communication channel between a user and the TCB.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Two parties who have never communicated before need to establish a shared secret key over an untrusted network without any prior shared secret or pre-installed certificates. Which cryptographic mechanism best accomplishes this?","o":["AES in CBC mode","RSA digital signature","Diffie-Hellman key exchange","HMAC-SHA256"],"c":2,"why":"Diffie-Hellman allows two parties to derive a shared secret over an insecure channel without prior shared secrets, making it ideal for key establishment. AES is a symmetric cipher requiring an existing key, RSA signatures provide authentication/integrity rather than key agreement by themselves, and HMAC provides message integrity, not key exchange.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A database administrator notices that although individual salary records are classified and access-restricted, a user with access to aggregate statistical queries (average salary by department, headcount by department) is able to mathematically derive the exact salary of a specific employee in a small department. Which security concern does this scenario illustrate, and what is an appropriate control?","o":["SQL injection; use parameterized queries","Inference attack; implement query set size restriction or noise/perturbation in aggregate results","Aggregation attack; apply role-based access control only","Covert channel; implement mandatory access control labeling"],"c":1,"why":"This is a classic inference attack where sensitive individual data is deduced from permitted aggregate queries; controls include minimum query set size restrictions, cell suppression, or adding statistical noise. RBAC alone wouldn't prevent inference from allowed aggregate queries, and this is not SQL injection or a covert channel.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A network architect deploys firewalls, intrusion detection systems, endpoint antivirus, and physical locks so that if one control fails, another compensates. This illustrates which security principle?","o":["Defense in depth","Least privilege","Separation of duties","Security through obscurity"],"c":0,"why":"Defense in depth uses multiple layered controls so that failure of one does not compromise the entire system. Least privilege limits access rights, separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people, and security through obscurity relies on secrecy rather than layered controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A vendor claims its product has been evaluated under the Common Criteria at EAL7. What does this rating primarily indicate about the product?","o":["The product has undergone the highest level of functional testing and formally verified design and implementation","The product is certified free of all known vulnerabilities","The product meets FIPS 140-2 Level 4 cryptographic module requirements","The product has been approved for use in classified U.S. government systems"],"c":0,"why":"EAL levels under Common Criteria indicate the rigor and depth of the evaluation/assurance process, not the number of functions or absence of vulnerabilities; EAL7 requires formal verification of design and testing, the highest assurance level. FIPS 140-2 is a separate cryptographic module standard, and CC evaluation does not equate to government use authorization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A CPU architecture implements protection rings (0-3) where the kernel operates in ring 0 and user applications in ring 3. A security architect is asked to explain why this design supports the reference monitor concept. Which statement BEST justifies this claim?","o":["Rings encrypt all memory transitions between privilege levels","The ring architecture physically separates hardware components to prevent electrical interference","Ring isolation ensures the reference monitor's mediation logic cannot be bypassed, tampered with, or observed by less privileged code, satisfying tamperproof and always-invoked requirements","Ring 0 automatically audits all system calls made by ring 3 processes"],"c":2,"why":"The reference monitor concept requires that the security enforcement mechanism be tamperproof, always invoked, and small enough to verify; hardware-enforced ring isolation supports this by preventing less-privileged code from bypassing or modifying the privileged mediation logic. The other options describe unrelated or incorrect hardware functions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which term describes the set of standards and countermeasures intended to prevent adversaries from intercepting compromising electromagnetic emanations from electronic equipment?","o":["TEMPEST","Faraday cage","White noise generation","Emanations security policy"],"c":0,"why":"TEMPEST is the recognized standard covering the study and control of compromising emanations. A Faraday cage and white noise generation are specific mitigation techniques used to achieve TEMPEST protection, not the overarching standard itself, and 'emanations security policy' is not a formally recognized term.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Which security architecture concept is responsible for mediating all access between subjects and objects, ensuring it is always invoked, cannot be bypassed, and is small enough to be verified?","o":["Security kernel","Trusted computing base (TCB)","Reference monitor","Security perimeter"],"c":2,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept that enforces access control by mediating every subject-object interaction, and must be tamper-proof, always invoked, and verifiable. The TCB is the collection of hardware/software/firmware implementing this concept, the security kernel is its implementation, and the security perimeter defines the boundary of the TCB, but none of these describe the mediating function itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In a Software as a Service (SaaS) cloud deployment, which security responsibility typically remains with the customer rather than the cloud provider?","o":["Managing user access and data classification","Patching the underlying operating system","Securing the physical data center","Maintaining the hypervisor"],"c":0,"why":"In SaaS, the provider manages the infrastructure, OS, hypervisor, and physical security, but the customer remains responsible for managing user access, data classification, and appropriate use of the application. The other options are all provider responsibilities in the SaaS model.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization is migrating to an Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) cloud model. Under the shared responsibility model, which of the following is typically the CUSTOMER's responsibility rather than the cloud provider's?","o":["Physical security of the data center housing the servers","Patching and configuration of the guest operating system","Maintaining the physical network hardware","Providing power and environmental controls for host servers"],"c":1,"why":"In IaaS, the provider manages the underlying physical infrastructure, hardware, and hypervisor, while the customer is responsible for the guest OS, applications, and data, including OS patching and configuration. The other options describe infrastructure-layer responsibilities retained by the provider.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which hardware device is specifically designed for secure generation, storage, and management of cryptographic keys, often used to offload crypto operations from application servers?","o":["Hardware Security Module (HSM)","Trusted Platform Module (TPM)","Smart card","Security token"],"c":0,"why":"An HSM is a dedicated, tamper-resistant appliance built for enterprise-scale cryptographic key management and processing. A TPM performs similar functions but is embedded in a single device for platform integrity, not enterprise key management. Smart cards and security tokens are primarily used for individual user authentication, not centralized key management.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A database analyst without direct access to salary data is able to determine an individual employee's salary by combining the results of several authorized queries on department averages and headcounts. This is an example of:","o":["SQL injection","An inference attack","A covert channel","A polyinstantiation failure"],"c":1,"why":"An inference attack occurs when a user deduces restricted information by correlating multiple pieces of authorized, lower-sensitivity data. SQL injection involves malicious code insertion, a covert channel involves unauthorized communication paths, and polyinstantiation is a technique to prevent inference by creating multiple views of data, not a failure type being described here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization's system enforces the Bell-LaPadula model to protect classified information. A security architect notes that a Secret-cleared process can write data to a Top-Secret file even though it cannot read the file's contents. Which statement best explains this behavior and its primary risk?","o":["This is the simple security property in action; it governs read access and does not address integrity of the Top-Secret data.","This is the *-property (no write-down) enforcing that data flows only to equal or higher classification, but it permits blind writes that can corrupt higher-level data integrity.","This is a violation of the discretionary security property and indicates a misconfigured access control list.","This is the strong star property, which the model uses by default to prevent all write operations across classification boundaries."],"c":1,"why":"BLP's *-property blocks write-down (to protect confidentiality) but permits write-up, creating a 'blind write' that can corrupt integrity of higher-classified data—a known BLP limitation often paired with Biba. Option A misattributes the behavior to read control; C is unrelated to DAC misconfiguration; D describes the strong star property, which is not BLP's default and would forbid this write entirely.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center is designing its fire suppression system for a room containing sensitive electronic equipment. Which agent is generally preferred because it suppresses fire without leaving harmful residue on electronics and without displacing large amounts of breathable oxygen to dangerous levels?","o":["Halon 1301","Carbon dioxide (CO2) flooding","Water sprinkler (wet pipe) system","Clean agent (e.g., FM-200)"],"c":3,"why":"Clean agents like FM-200 suppress fires effectively without leaving residue that damages electronics and are formulated to be used at concentrations safer for occupied spaces than CO2. Halon is effective but banned/phased out due to environmental impact, CO2 displaces oxygen to dangerous levels for humans, and water sprinklers risk damaging sensitive electronic equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a security review, an engineer observes that a VPN implementation uses the Diffie-Hellman algorithm to establish a shared session key but does not authenticate the exchanged public values. Which attack is this design most vulnerable to, and what is the standard mitigation?","o":["Replay attack; mitigated by adding sequence numbers to encrypted packets.","Man-in-the-middle attack; mitigated by signing DH public values with certificates or using an authenticated pre-shared key.","Birthday attack; mitigated by increasing the DH group size (modulus length).","Downgrade attack; mitigated by disabling weak cipher suites."],"c":1,"why":"Unauthenticated DH exchanges allow an attacker to intercept and substitute public values, enabling a MITM attack; binding the exchange to certificates or authenticated keys (as in IKE/IPsec) mitigates this. The other attacks are not the primary consequence of lacking authentication in the key exchange.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A vendor submits a product for Common Criteria evaluation with an EAL4 rating. A customer assumes this means the product has more security functionality than a competing EAL2-rated product from another vendor. Which statement corrects this assumption?","o":["EAL ratings measure the rigor and depth of the assurance evaluation process, not the number or strength of security functions, which are defined separately in the Protection Profile/Security Target.","EAL ratings are directly comparable across vendors and always indicate stronger cryptographic algorithms at higher levels.","EAL4 guarantees the product has undergone formal verification of its source code, while EAL2 requires no testing at all.","EAL ratings supersede the Protection Profile and define the complete set of security requirements the product must meet."],"c":0,"why":"EAL levels reflect the thoroughness of the assurance evaluation, not the functional security capabilities, which are specified in the PP/ST. Formal verification is only required at EAL7, not EAL4; EAL2 still requires testing; and the PP/ST—not the EAL—defines functional requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A reference monitor is theoretically required to satisfy three properties to be trustworthy. During an architecture review, an auditor discovers that certain system calls can bypass the kernel's access control checks under specific conditions. Which reference monitor property is violated?","o":["Tamperproof - the reference monitor's code and data cannot be modified.","Always invoked (complete mediation) - the reference monitor must mediate every access to every object.","Verifiable - the reference monitor must be small enough to be tested and formally verified.","Least privilege - the reference monitor must operate with the minimum permissions necessary."],"c":1,"why":"Bypassing access checks under certain conditions means not every access is mediated, violating the 'always invoked' (complete mediation) property. Tamperproof concerns unauthorized modification of the monitor itself, verifiability concerns code size/analyzability, and least privilege is not one of the three classical reference monitor properties.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily concerned with preventing unauthorized disclosure of information by enforcing rules such as 'no read up' and 'no write down'?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula is a confidentiality-focused model using the simple security property (no read up) and the *-property (no write down). Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson enforces well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A cryptographic library implements AES using table lookups whose memory access patterns vary based on secret key bytes. Researchers demonstrate they can recover key material by measuring CPU cache access timing during encryption operations. What category of attack is being demonstrated, and what is the most effective architectural mitigation?","o":["A chosen-ciphertext attack; mitigated by adding message authentication codes (MACs) to ciphertext.","A cache-timing side-channel attack; mitigated by implementing constant-time algorithms or hardware-based AES instructions (e.g., AES-NI) that avoid data-dependent memory access.","A related-key attack; mitigated by enforcing strict key derivation function requirements.","A brute-force attack; mitigated by increasing the AES key size from 128 to 256 bits."],"c":1,"why":"Variance in cache access time correlated with secret data is a classic cache-timing side-channel attack against the implementation, not a mathematical weakness in AES; constant-time coding or hardware AES instructions eliminate the data-dependent timing leakage. The other options misidentify the attack class and propose irrelevant mitigations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model focuses on preserving data integrity through rules like 'no write up' and 'no read down'?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","Graham-Denning model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model protects integrity by preventing a subject from writing to higher integrity levels or reading from lower integrity levels. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, while Take-Grant and Graham-Denning deal with access rights management.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A multilevel secure database contains a Secret-classified record with primary key 'Ship_Alpha_Location.' A user with Confidential clearance attempts to insert a new record using the same primary key with different, unclassified data. To prevent this operation from creating a covert channel while still allowing the insert, which technique should the DBMS employ?","o":["Reject the insert operation and return a generic access-denied error without indicating that a Secret record already exists.","Allow polyinstantiation, creating a separate Confidential-level tuple with the same primary key so each clearance level sees a consistent, non-conflicting view.","Automatically upgrade the Confidential user's session to Secret clearance to prevent a key collision.","Downgrade the existing Secret record to Confidential to avoid a primary key conflict."],"c":1,"why":"Polyinstantiation permits multiple rows sharing a primary key at different classification levels so the low-clearance user's insert succeeds normally, preventing inference that a higher-classified record exists. Rejecting the insert can still leak existence information through observable behavior, and the other options violate confidentiality or integrity of classification levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to encrypt a large database efficiently while using a single shared key for both encryption and decryption. Which type of cryptography best fits this need?","o":["Asymmetric cryptography","Symmetric cryptography","Hashing algorithms","Digital signatures"],"c":1,"why":"Symmetric cryptography uses one shared key for both encryption and decryption and is computationally efficient for large data sets. Asymmetric cryptography is slower and uses key pairs, hashing provides integrity not confidentiality, and digital signatures provide authentication/non-repudiation, not bulk encryption.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A cloud service provider's Type 1 hypervisor hosts multiple tenants' virtual machines on shared physical hardware. A security architect is concerned about an attacker who compromises one guest VM using a crafted device driver call to escape the VM boundary and access the hypervisor or other tenants' VMs. What is this class of vulnerability called, and what is the most effective architectural control?","o":["VM sprawl; mitigated by implementing automated VM lifecycle management policies.","VM escape; mitigated by hypervisor hardening, minimizing the hypervisor's attack surface, and applying vendor security patches promptly.","Cross-VM side-channel attack; mitigated by disabling shared CPU cache resources between tenants.","Hyperjacking; mitigated by deploying a Type 2 hypervisor instead of Type 1 for better isolation."],"c":1,"why":"Breaking out of VM isolation to reach the hypervisor or host is termed VM escape; the primary defense is hardening and patching the hypervisor and minimizing its exposed attack surface. VM sprawl is a management issue unrelated to isolation breaches, cross-VM side channels involve inference rather than escape, and Type 2 hypervisors generally offer weaker isolation than Type 1 due to their larger attack surface.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A hospital is redesigning its clinical order-entry system. Patient-entered wellness survey data (low integrity) must never be allowed to modify or overwrite physician-entered medication orders (high integrity), even though both data types reside in the same database. Which security model's properties directly address this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model, using the *-property to prevent write-down","Biba model, using the *-integrity axiom to prevent write-up","Brewer-Nash model, using dynamic access controls based on prior access","Take-Grant model, using the rights-transfer graph to restrict subjects"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba integrity model's *-integrity (write) axiom prevents a subject from writing to an object of higher integrity, exactly stopping low-integrity survey data from corrupting high-integrity orders. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality (disclosure), Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest, and Take-Grant models rights propagation, none of which enforce integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security concept refers to a system component that mediates all access between subjects and objects, ensuring that security policies are consistently enforced?","o":["Trusted computing base","Reference monitor","Security kernel","Access control matrix"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept that enforces access control policy by mediating every subject-object interaction. The security kernel is the actual implementation of the reference monitor, and the TCB includes all protection mechanisms, not just the mediation function. An access control matrix simply models permissions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Two systems establish a shared secret using classic (unauthenticated) Diffie-Hellman key exchange over an untrusted network. A security architect is concerned about a specific class of attack. Which control most directly addresses this concern, and why?","o":["Increase the modulus size to at least 4096 bits to strengthen the exchange against brute force","Add certificate-based digital signatures to authenticate each party's DH public value, preventing man-in-the-middle substitution","Switch to a symmetric pre-shared key instead of DH to avoid public key operations entirely","Use ephemeral DH keys for every session to prevent key reuse across sessions"],"c":1,"why":"Unauthenticated DH is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks because either party's public value can be substituted by an attacker; signing the exchanged values (as in authenticated/station-to-station DH) binds the exchange to verified identities. Larger moduli and ephemeral keys improve other properties but do not prevent MITM, and abandoning DH for pre-shared keys creates a separate key-distribution problem.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A data center's primary server room uses a wet-pipe water sprinkler suppression system inherited from an older building design. The security team wants to replace it to reduce equipment damage risk while maintaining rapid fire suppression and life safety compliance. Which type of system should be recommended, and why?","o":["A CO2 total-flooding system, because it is inexpensive and does not damage electronic equipment.","A clean-agent (e.g., FM-200/Novec) suppression system, because it suppresses fire quickly without leaving residue or causing conductive damage and is safe for occupied spaces at design concentrations.","A dry-pipe sprinkler system, because delaying water release until fire is confirmed prevents any water damage to equipment.","A Halon 1301 system, because it remains the industry standard for data centers and has no health or environmental concerns."],"c":1,"why":"Clean-agent systems like FM-200 or Novec 1230 suppress fires rapidly, leave no residue, avoid electrical/equipment damage, and are safe for occupied spaces, making them the modern standard for data centers. CO2 is an asphyxiation hazard unsuitable for occupied areas, dry-pipe systems still ultimately release damaging water, and Halon has been phased out under the Montreal Protocol due to ozone depletion concerns.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In a hardware-based protection ring architecture, which ring typically has the highest level of privilege and runs the operating system kernel?","o":["Ring 3","Ring 2","Ring 1","Ring 0"],"c":3,"why":"Ring 0 is the most privileged ring, reserved for the operating system kernel with direct hardware access. Ring 3 is the least privileged, typically used for user applications, while rings 1 and 2 are used for less critical system services.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A financial organization wants to procure a firewall and needs assurance that it meets a consumer-defined, reusable set of security functional and assurance requirements for firewalls as a product category, independent of any specific vendor implementation, before soliciting vendor proposals under Common Criteria. Which artifact should the organization develop first?","o":["A Security Target (ST) describing the specific firewall's claimed security functions","A Protection Profile (PP) defining implementation-independent requirements for the firewall category","An Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) rating requirement of EAL4 or higher","The Target of Evaluation (TOE) specification for the selected vendor's product"],"c":1,"why":"A Protection Profile is a reusable, implementation-independent statement of security requirements for a category of products, created by consumers/communities of interest before vendor selection. The Security Target and TOE are vendor/product-specific and come after a product is chosen, and an EAL is an assurance rating, not a requirements document.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which authentication protocol relies on time-stamped tickets issued by a trusted third party to allow users to access multiple network services without re-entering credentials?","o":["RADIUS","Kerberos","OAuth","LDAP"],"c":1,"why":"Kerberos uses a trusted third-party Key Distribution Center to issue time-stamped tickets, enabling single sign-on. RADIUS is used for centralized authentication for network access, OAuth is for authorization delegation, and LDAP is a directory access protocol, not a ticket-based authentication system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A laptop's full-disk encryption key is released by the TPM only if the measured boot sequence (bootloader, OS loader, and kernel hashes) matches expected values stored in PCRs; any modification to the boot chain (e.g., a bootkit) causes key release to fail. Which TPM capability is being used?","o":["Remote attestation","Sealing","Binding","Quoting"],"c":1,"why":"Sealing encrypts data such that it can only be unsealed when specified PCR values match the current platform state, which is exactly the described behavior. Binding encrypts data to a TPM key without state verification, quoting produces a signed report of PCR values for an external party, and remote attestation is the broader process of proving platform state to a remote verifier, not the local key-release mechanism.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to protect data confidentiality by preventing users from reading data at a higher classification level and writing data to a lower classification level?","o":["Biba Integrity Model","Bell-LaPadula Model","Clark-Wilson Model","Brewer-Nash Model"],"c":1,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces 'no read up, no write down' to preserve confidentiality. Biba focuses on integrity, Clark-Wilson on well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A data center wants to select a fire suppression system that will not damage sensitive electronic equipment during discharge. Which of the following is the best choice?","o":["Wet pipe sprinkler system","Water mist system","Clean agent gas system","Dry chemical extinguisher"],"c":2,"why":"Clean agent gas systems (e.g., FM-200, inert gases) suppress fire without leaving residue or damaging electronics, making them ideal for data centers. Water-based systems and dry chemical extinguishers can cause corrosion or short-circuits in sensitive equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A forensic investigation discovers that a low-privilege process is leaking classified data to a lower-clearance process by deliberately varying its CPU usage patterns and file-lock acquisition delays in a predictable pattern, with no data written to any shared file or variable that the receiving process reads. What type of channel is being exploited?","o":["Covert storage channel","Covert timing channel","Overt side channel via power analysis","TOCTOU race condition"],"c":1,"why":"A covert timing channel conveys information by modulating the timing of observable events (CPU usage, resource contention) rather than through a shared storage object, matching this scenario exactly. A storage channel would require a shared writable/readable object, power analysis is a hardware side-channel attack on cryptographic operations, and TOCTOU is a race condition between check and use, not an information-leakage channel.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that lower-integrity data cannot corrupt higher-integrity data within a system. Which security model best addresses this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula Model","Biba Model","Take-Grant Model","Graham-Denning Model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model uses 'no write up, no read down' rules to protect data integrity by preventing contamination from lower-integrity sources. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, not integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An analyst with authorized access to individual employee records (each below a defined sensitivity threshold) is able to run a series of SUM and COUNT queries against the HR database to mathematically derive a specific executive's salary, which is individually classified as restricted. Which control would most effectively prevent this specific attack?","o":["Enforce a minimum query set size and suppress results likely to enable inference from statistical aggregates","Apply field-level encryption to all salary fields","Implement mandatory access control labels on each database row","Require multi-factor authentication for all database query sessions"],"c":0,"why":"This is a classic aggregation/inference attack against a statistical database; restricting minimum query set size (and using techniques like cell suppression or noise addition) prevents an attacker from isolating an individual's data through aggregate queries. Encryption, row-level MAC labels, and MFA control access but do not prevent inference derived from permitted aggregate query results.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of a cryptographic hash function in security applications?","o":["To provide confidentiality by encrypting data","To verify data integrity by producing a fixed-size digest","To generate session keys for symmetric encryption","To authenticate users through password encryption"],"c":1,"why":"A cryptographic hash function produces a fixed-size digest used to verify that data has not been altered, ensuring integrity. It does not provide confidentiality (no decryption possible), and while hashes can be used in password storage, that is a specific application rather than the primary general purpose.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A security architect implements multiple overlapping controls, such as firewalls, intrusion detection systems, and access controls, so that if one control fails, others still provide protection. This approach is known as which security principle?","o":["Security through obscurity","Defense in depth","Least privilege","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Defense in depth uses layered, overlapping controls so that a single point of failure does not compromise the entire system. Least privilege and separation of duties are related but distinct principles focused on access rights.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A cloud provider hosting multiple tenants on shared physical hardware is evaluating hypervisor architectures to minimize the risk and impact of a VM escape attack. Which design choice best reduces this risk?","o":["Deploy a Type 2 hypervisor for easier centralized management across tenant workloads","Deploy a Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor with a minimized codebase and apply vendor security patches promptly","Disable hypervisor-level logging to reduce performance overhead and attack surface","Rely on guest-OS-level host-based firewalls as the primary control against VM escape"],"c":1,"why":"A Type 1 hypervisor runs directly on hardware without a full general-purpose host OS underneath, giving it a smaller attack surface than a Type 2 hypervisor, and prompt patching addresses known escape vulnerabilities. Type 2 hypervisors add the host OS's attack surface, disabling logging removes detection capability without reducing risk, and guest-OS firewalls cannot mitigate a hypervisor-level escape vulnerability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which type of software vulnerability occurs when a program writes more data to a memory block than it was allocated, potentially allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary code?","o":["SQL injection","Buffer overflow","Cross-site scripting","Race condition"],"c":1,"why":"A buffer overflow occurs when data exceeds the allocated memory boundary, which can corrupt adjacent memory and enable code execution. SQL injection and XSS involve improper input handling in different contexts, and a race condition involves timing issues.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A government facility processing Sensitive Compartmented Information (SCI) must prevent adversaries from reconstructing classified data by passively capturing unintentional electromagnetic emanations from computer monitors and cabling outside the building. Which control category directly addresses this threat?","o":["Deploying a next-generation VPN with perfect forward secrecy","Implementing TEMPEST shielding, such as Faraday cage construction, for the facility","Enforcing WPA3-Enterprise on all wireless access points","Issuing hardware security tokens for multi-factor authentication"],"c":1,"why":"TEMPEST controls (including Faraday shielding) specifically address the risk of intercepting compromising electromagnetic emanations from electronic equipment, which is the threat described. VPNs, WPA3, and MFA tokens protect data in transit over networks or authenticate users, but none prevent emanation-based signal interception.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In the context of the Trusted Computing Base (TCB), which component is responsible for enforcing the security policy by mediating all access between subjects and objects?","o":["Security kernel (reference monitor)","Trusted path","Security perimeter","Discretionary access control list"],"c":0,"why":"The reference monitor, implemented as the security kernel, mediates and enforces access control decisions per the security policy. The trusted path ensures secure communication, the security perimeter defines the TCB boundary, and a DACL is a specific access control mechanism, not the enforcement engine.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"When designing physical security for a data center, which of the following is the MOST effective method to delay unauthorized entry while allowing legitimate access to be verified?","o":["Installing decorative lighting around the perimeter","Using a mantrap with two interlocking doors","Placing security cameras at the main entrance only","Posting a sign indicating the area is monitored"],"c":1,"why":"A mantrap physically delays and controls entry by allowing only one door to open at a time, giving security personnel or systems time to verify identity. Lighting, signage, and cameras alone are deterrents or detective controls but do not physically delay intrusion.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing controls to ensure that a low-integrity process cannot corrupt the data used by a high-integrity financial reporting process, even though both processes run on the same host. Which principle directly addresses this requirement?","o":["Biba's *-integrity axiom (no write-up)","Bell-LaPadula's simple security property (no read-up)","Bell-LaPadula's *-property (no write-down)","Clark-Wilson's separation of duty rule"],"c":0,"why":"Biba's *-integrity axiom prevents a subject at a lower integrity level from writing to an object at a higher integrity level, directly stopping corruption of trusted data. The Bell-LaPadula properties address confidentiality (read/write of classified data), not integrity, and Clark-Wilson's separation of duty addresses fraud prevention through transaction control, not direct read/write integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In a cloud computing environment using the Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) model, which party is typically responsible for securing the hypervisor and underlying physical infrastructure?","o":["The cloud customer","The cloud service provider","A third-party security auditor","The end user's network administrator"],"c":1,"why":"Under the shared responsibility model, the cloud provider secures the physical infrastructure and hypervisor layer in IaaS, while the customer secures operating systems, applications, and data. Auditors and network administrators do not own this responsibility.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Two systems establish a shared secret using classic Diffie-Hellman key exchange over an untrusted network with no certificate-based authentication of either party. What is the primary security weakness of this implementation?","o":["The shared secret can be brute-forced faster than an equivalent-length symmetric key","An attacker can perform a man-in-the-middle attack by negotiating separate keys with each party","Diffie-Hellman produces a shared secret that is weaker than the modulus size implies","The exchange is vulnerable to a birthday attack due to short exponent reuse"],"c":1,"why":"Unauthenticated Diffie-Hellman is vulnerable to MITM because neither party can verify the other's identity, allowing an attacker to establish two separate key exchanges and relay/modify traffic. The other options misstate cryptographic properties of DH and do not describe the core authentication weakness.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to verify, before granting network access, that an endpoint's boot process has not been tampered with by rootkits or unauthorized firmware changes. Which TPM-based mechanism best supports this requirement?","o":["Sealing data to a specific set of PCR values","Remote attestation using signed PCR measurements","Using the TPM as a hardware random number generator","Storing the disk encryption key in the TPM's NVRAM"],"c":1,"why":"Remote attestation allows a verifier to request signed Platform Configuration Register (PCR) values that reflect the measured boot state, enabling detection of tampering before granting access. Sealing protects data confidentiality tied to a boot state but doesn't itself report boot integrity to a remote party; the RNG and NVRAM storage functions don't address attestation of boot integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A vendor claims their product achieved Common Criteria EAL5 certification. What does this rating primarily indicate to an evaluator comparing two competing products?","o":["The product has more security functions than a product certified at EAL3","The product was evaluated with a greater depth and rigor of assurance activities than a lower EAL","The product is guaranteed to be free of exploitable vulnerabilities","The product meets a specific government-mandated Protection Profile"],"c":1,"why":"EAL ratings measure the depth, rigor, and formality of the assurance evaluation process, not the number of security features implemented or a guarantee of vulnerability-free code. A Protection Profile is a separate document defining functional/assurance requirements for a product category; an EAL alone doesn't confirm conformance to any specific PP.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a hardware security review, an analyst extracts a smart card's private key by measuring fluctuations in the card's electrical power consumption while it performs signing operations. Which category of attack was used?","o":["Fault injection attack","Differential power analysis (a side-channel attack)","Replay attack","Chosen-ciphertext attack"],"c":1,"why":"Differential power analysis exploits variations in power consumption correlated with internal cryptographic operations to infer key material, a classic side-channel attack. Fault injection deliberately induces errors rather than passively observing power; replay and chosen-ciphertext attacks operate at the protocol/algorithm level, not through physical emanations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution's security architect implements a mandatory access control model to prevent unauthorized disclosure of classified information. Under this model, a subject with a 'Secret' clearance is prevented from reading data classified as 'Top Secret' and is also prevented from writing data down into a document classified 'Confidential.' Which security model does this describe?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash (Chinese Wall) model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces 'no read up, no write down' to preserve confidentiality of classified data. Biba enforces the opposite rules to protect integrity, Clark-Wilson relies on well-formed transactions rather than read/write levels, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest between competing clients.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A multi-level secure database allows users to query aggregate statistics (e.g., average salary by department) but restricts access to individual records at higher classification levels. An analyst discovers they can deduce a specific employee's classified salary by combining several permitted aggregate queries. This is an example of which security issue?","o":["SQL injection vulnerability","The inference problem","Polyinstantiation failure","Covert channel via timing analysis"],"c":1,"why":"The inference problem occurs when a user combines multiple pieces of unclassified or lower-classified data (like aggregates) to deduce protected information they aren't authorized to access directly. SQL injection involves malicious code execution, polyinstantiation is a technique to prevent inference (not a failure category here), and timing covert channels involve signaling through time delays, not aggregation math.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An architect designs access controls so that a process operating at a low integrity level cannot write to a file classified at a high integrity level, and a process operating at a high integrity level cannot read data originating from a low integrity source. This design implements which security model?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Graham-Denning model"],"c":1,"why":"Biba enforces 'no write up' and 'no read down' to protect data integrity from contamination by lower-integrity sources. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality with the opposite rules, Clark-Wilson relies on certified transactions rather than simple read/write restrictions, and Graham-Denning defines rules for managing subject/object rights, not integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A cloud provider's hypervisor is compromised, allowing an attacker running code in one guest virtual machine to gain unauthorized access to the memory of another guest VM on the same physical host. This scenario best describes which security weakness?","o":["A VM escape enabling breach of hypervisor-enforced isolation","A side-channel attack exploiting shared CPU cache","An insecure API allowing unauthorized management plane access","A misconfigured virtual network allowing VLAN hopping"],"c":0,"why":"VM escape refers to breaking out of a guest VM's isolation boundary to interact directly with the hypervisor or other VMs' resources, which matches this scenario precisely. Cache side-channel attacks (e.g., cross-VM data leakage) exist but don't involve hypervisor compromise; the other two options describe unrelated network/API-layer weaknesses, not memory-level VM isolation failure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial application must prevent low-integrity data entered by junior clerks from contaminating high-integrity financial records maintained by senior accountants, while still allowing senior accountants to read clerk-entered data for review. Which security model best supports this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba Integrity model","Take-Grant model","Graham-Denning model"],"c":1,"why":"Biba's 'no write up' rule prevents lower-integrity subjects from writing to higher-integrity objects, protecting data integrity, while its 'no read down' restriction still permits higher-integrity subjects to read lower-integrity data for review purposes. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, not integrity; Take-Grant and Graham-Denning govern rights propagation, not integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that data cannot be corrupted by lower-privileged users or processes writing to higher-integrity data. Which security model directly addresses this concern?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","Non-interference model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model focuses on integrity, using 'no write up' and 'no read down' rules to prevent lower-integrity subjects from corrupting higher-integrity objects. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, not integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Two parties who have never communicated before need to establish a shared secret key over an insecure channel without any pre-existing trust relationship or PKI infrastructure. Which cryptographic method is specifically designed to accomplish this?","o":["RSA encryption","Diffie-Hellman key exchange","AES-256 in GCM mode","HMAC-SHA256"],"c":1,"why":"Diffie-Hellman allows two parties to derive a shared secret over an insecure channel without prior exchange of secret key material. RSA typically requires a key distribution or PKI framework, AES-GCM is symmetric encryption requiring an already-shared key, and HMAC provides integrity/authentication, not key establishment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A protocol designer is choosing between AES-CBC with a separate HMAC and AES-GCM for securing a new TLS-like transport protocol. Which factor makes AES-GCM the stronger architectural choice?","o":["GCM uses a longer key length than CBC by default","GCM provides authenticated encryption in a single pass, reducing implementation errors like padding oracle vulnerabilities","GCM does not require a unique nonce/IV for each encryption operation","GCM eliminates the need for key management infrastructure"],"c":1,"why":"AES-GCM combines encryption and authentication (AEAD) in a single algorithm, avoiding separate MAC implementation mistakes and padding-related vulnerabilities that have historically plagued CBC-based constructions (e.g., Lucky13). GCM still requires unique nonces (reuse is catastrophic), key lengths are independent of mode choice, and key management is still required regardless of mode.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which term describes the totality of protection mechanisms within a computer system, including hardware, firmware, and software, that enforce the security policy?","o":["Security perimeter","Trusted computing base (TCB)","Reference monitor","Security kernel"],"c":1,"why":"The TCB encompasses all protection mechanisms responsible for enforcing security policy. The reference monitor and security kernel are components of the TCB, and the security perimeter is the boundary separating the TCB from the rest of the system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Two organizations that have never previously communicated need to securely exchange a symmetric session key over an untrusted network without any pre-shared secret. Which mechanism directly enables this?","o":["AES in CBC mode","Diffie-Hellman key exchange","HMAC-SHA256","A digital certificate signed by a trusted CA"],"c":1,"why":"Diffie-Hellman allows two parties to derive a shared secret over an insecure channel without prior shared secrets, making it ideal for establishing symmetric keys. AES and HMAC are symmetric algorithms that require an existing shared key, and a certificate alone authenticates identity but does not itself perform key agreement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a procurement review, a security team evaluates a vendor's product that has been assigned an Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) of 4 under the Common Criteria framework. What does this EAL rating primarily indicate?","o":["The specific security functions the product implements, as defined by its Protection Profile","The level of confidence that the product's security functions were implemented and tested correctly (assurance)","The number of known vulnerabilities patched during the product's lifecycle","The product's compliance with a specific regulatory framework such as FedRAMP"],"c":1,"why":"EAL ratings reflect the rigor of testing and assurance behind a product's security claims, not the functional requirements themselves, which are defined separately in the Security Target/Protection Profile. Vulnerability counts and regulatory compliance are unrelated to EAL scoring.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing a system component that must mediate every access attempt between subjects and objects, be tamper-proof, and be small enough to be thoroughly verified for correctness. Which concept best describes this component?","o":["Security kernel","Trusted computing base","Reference monitor","Access control matrix"],"c":2,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept requiring complete mediation, tamper-resistance, and verifiability; it is implemented by the security kernel within the TCB. TCB is the broader collection of protection mechanisms, and an access control matrix is merely a data structure representing permissions, not an enforcement mechanism.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In the protection ring model used by many operating systems, which ring typically has the highest level of privilege and is used by the kernel?","o":["Ring 3","Ring 2","Ring 1","Ring 0"],"c":3,"why":"Ring 0 is the innermost and most privileged ring, reserved for the operating system kernel. Ring 3, the outermost ring, is used for user applications with the least privilege.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing a component that must mediate every access attempt between subjects and objects, cannot be bypassed, must be protected from unauthorized modification, and must be small enough to be formally verified. Which concept does this describe?","o":["Trusted computing base","Reference monitor","Security kernel","Access control matrix"],"c":1,"why":"These three properties—always invoked, tamper-resistant, and verifiable—define the abstract reference monitor concept. The security kernel is the practical hardware/software/firmware implementation of that concept, the TCB is the broader collection of all protection mechanisms, and an access control matrix is merely a data structure representing permissions, not an enforcement mechanism.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A company implements multiple overlapping security controls, such as firewalls, intrusion detection systems, and endpoint protection, so that if one control fails, others still provide protection. What security principle does this illustrate?","o":["Security through obscurity","Defense in depth","Least privilege","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Defense in depth uses layered, overlapping controls so a single point of failure does not compromise the entire system. Least privilege and separation of duties are access control principles, not layered defense strategies.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization purchasing a security product needs formal assurance that the product's design and implementation have been rigorously evaluated and tested against a structured, internationally recognized set of assurance requirements. Which framework provides this via Evaluation Assurance Levels (EAL1-EAL7)?","o":["ISO/IEC 27001","Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408)","NIST SP 800-53","COBIT"],"c":1,"why":"Common Criteria defines EALs (EAL1-EAL7) that specify the rigor of assurance testing applied to a product. ISO 27001 is an ISMS management standard, NIST 800-53 is a control catalog, and COBIT is an IT governance framework; none of these use EAL ratings.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that a transmitted software update has not been altered in transit and to verify the identity of the software vendor who published it. Which cryptographic technique best achieves both goals?","o":["Encrypt the update with a symmetric key shared with all users","Hash the update and encrypt the hash with the vendor's private key","Hash the update and encrypt the hash with the vendor's public key","Encrypt the entire update with the vendor's public key"],"c":1,"why":"A digital signature—hashing the data and encrypting the hash with the sender's private key—provides both integrity verification and proof of origin, since only the vendor's private key could produce a signature verifiable with the vendor's public key. Encrypting with the vendor's public key would prevent anyone but the vendor from decrypting, and symmetric key sharing does nothing to prove vendor identity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"In a virtualized data center, an attacker who has compromised a guest virtual machine manages to gain unauthorized access to the underlying hypervisor and subsequently to other guest VMs on the same host. This attack is best classified as which type of threat?","o":["Side-channel attack","VM escape","Privilege escalation via rootkit","Covert channel attack"],"c":1,"why":"VM escape specifically refers to breaking out of a guest VM's isolation to reach the hypervisor or other VMs, which is exactly what occurred. Side-channel and covert channel attacks involve leaking information through indirect means rather than breaking hypervisor isolation, and rootkit privilege escalation typically refers to gaining elevated privileges within a single OS, not crossing VM boundaries.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which statement best describes symmetric key cryptography?","o":["It uses a public key for encryption and a private key for decryption","It uses the same key for both encryption and decryption","It uses two mathematically related keys, one for encryption and one for decryption","It eliminates the need for secure key distribution"],"c":1,"why":"Symmetric cryptography uses a single shared key for both encryption and decryption, requiring secure key distribution. Asymmetric cryptography uses a public/private key pair, which is described in the incorrect distractors.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A cloud provider wants to minimize the attack surface of its virtualization layer by running the hypervisor directly on the physical hardware without dependence on a general-purpose host operating system. Which hypervisor architecture should be used?","o":["Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor","Type 2 (hosted) hypervisor","Container-based virtualization","Paravirtualized guest operating system"],"c":0,"why":"Type 1 hypervisors run directly on hardware, reducing dependency on and exposure to a host OS's vulnerabilities. Type 2 hypervisors run atop a host OS and inherit its risks, containers share the host OS kernel rather than replacing hypervisor functionality, and paravirtualization describes guest OS awareness of virtualization, not hypervisor placement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A software vendor wants to make it significantly harder for attackers to exploit buffer overflow vulnerabilities by making memory addresses of key data structures unpredictable each time a program runs. Which technique accomplishes this?","o":["Data Execution Prevention (DEP)","Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)","Stack canaries","Input validation"],"c":1,"why":"ASLR randomizes the memory addresses used by system components each execution, making it difficult for attackers to reliably predict target addresses for exploitation. DEP prevents code execution in data regions, stack canaries detect stack overflow corruption, and input validation limits malformed input rather than randomizing memory layout.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"When decommissioning a hard drive that contained highly sensitive data, which method provides the highest assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive","Physical destruction of the drive (e.g., shredding or incineration)","Overwriting the drive once with zeros"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction ensures data cannot be recovered by any means, which is essential for highly sensitive data. Deleting files, reformatting, or a single overwrite pass leave residual data recoverable through forensic techniques.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A penetration tester discovers that a malicious process is exfiltrating data by subtly modulating CPU utilization patterns, which are then read by a colluding process monitoring publicly available system performance counters. This is best described as which type of security violation?","o":["Side-channel attack","Covert channel","SQL injection","Time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition"],"c":1,"why":"A covert channel uses a resource not intended for communication (such as resource-usage patterns) to intentionally transfer information between two colluding parties. A side-channel attack instead exploits unintentional information leakage to infer secrets, typically without a cooperating second party, while SQL injection and TOCTOU are unrelated attack categories.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center hosting classified systems must prevent electromagnetic emanations from processing equipment from being intercepted and reconstructed by adversaries outside the facility. Which control category directly addresses this concern?","o":["TEMPEST shielding","Mantrap access control","Faraday-caged badge readers","Biometric authentication at entry points"],"c":0,"why":"TEMPEST refers to standards and shielding techniques specifically designed to prevent compromising electromagnetic emanations from being captured and analyzed. Mantraps and biometric authentication control physical entry, not emanation leakage, and Faraday cages on badge readers alone would not shield the entire facility's emanations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A locked door is designed to remain unlocked during a power failure so that occupants can evacuate safely in an emergency. This design approach is best described as which of the following?","o":["Fail-secure","Fail-open (fail-safe)","Mandatory access control","Discretionary access control"],"c":1,"why":"Fail-safe (fail-open) designs prioritize life safety by allowing free egress when power is lost, common in fire exits. Fail-secure designs instead lock the door to maintain security, which could endanger occupants during an emergency.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A funds-transfer application accepts input from untrusted external users (low integrity) but must never allow that input to corrupt records in a validated, high-integrity ledger database. Which Biba Integrity Model rule enforces this protection?","o":["The Simple Integrity Axiom (no write-up), preventing a low-integrity subject from writing to a high-integrity object","The *-Property (no write-down) from Bell-LaPadula, preventing high-level data from leaking to low-level subjects","The Simple Security Condition, preventing a subject from reading data above its clearance","The Invocation Property, preventing a subject from reading data below its integrity level"],"c":0,"why":"Biba's Simple Integrity Axiom ('no write-up') is specifically designed to stop lower-integrity subjects from modifying higher-integrity objects. The *-Property and Simple Security Condition belong to Bell-LaPadula and address confidentiality, not integrity, and the Invocation Property governs service requests to higher-integrity processes, not direct writes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A development team is encrypting sensitive session data with AES-CBC and later discovers the application is vulnerable to bit-flipping and padding oracle attacks because no separate integrity check is performed. Which cipher mode should replace CBC to provide both confidentiality and integrity in a single, efficient operation?","o":["AES in Electronic Codebook (ECB) mode","AES in Counter (CTR) mode with a separately computed HMAC","AES in Galois/Counter Mode (GCM)","AES in Cipher Feedback (CFB) mode"],"c":2,"why":"GCM is an authenticated encryption mode that natively provides both confidentiality and a built-in authentication tag (integrity/authenticity) in one pass, eliminating the padding-oracle and malleability issues of CBC. ECB and CFB provide only confidentiality and are also structurally weak (ECB leaks patterns); CTR+HMAC works but requires two separate operations, making it less efficient than native AEAD.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a security kernel design review, an evaluator discovers that a debug interface allows certain system calls to bypass the reference monitor entirely under specific conditions. Which core reference monitor property is violated?","o":["Tamperproof – the mechanism itself can be modified by unauthorized parties","Complete mediation – the monitor is not always invoked for every access attempt","Verifiability – the mechanism is too large to be formally analyzed","Least privilege – the monitor grants excessive rights to subjects"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor concept requires complete mediation, meaning every access attempt must pass through it without exception; a bypass path violates this property directly. Tamperproof concerns unauthorized modification of the monitor's code, verifiability concerns its size/complexity for analysis, and least privilege is an access control principle, not a reference monitor property being tested here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A government agency requires a system whose security functionality has been formally verified through mathematical proof of design and independently tested, the highest level of assurance under the Common Criteria. Which Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) corresponds to this requirement?","o":["EAL2 – structurally tested","EAL4 – methodically designed, tested, and reviewed","EAL7 – formally verified design and tested","EAL1 – functionally tested"],"c":2,"why":"EAL7 is the highest Common Criteria assurance level, requiring formal verification of design and comprehensive independent testing. EAL4 is the highest level typically achievable for commercial off-the-shelf products without specialized formal methods, while EAL1 and EAL2 provide only basic functional or structural testing assurance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to prevent unauthorized disclosure of information by enforcing 'no read up, no write down' rules?","o":["Biba Integrity Model","Bell-LaPadula Model","Clark-Wilson Model","Brewer-Nash Model"],"c":1,"why":"Bell-LaPadula focuses on confidentiality using 'no read up, no write down.' Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson enforces well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An intelligence analyst lacking clearance for classified troop movement data is able to deduce those movements by correlating several individually unclassified logistics reports. What type of attack has occurred, and which control is most effective against it?","o":["Aggregation attack; mitigated by context- or history-dependent access control that restricts combined queries","Inference attack; mitigated by increasing the classification of all logistics reports to Top Secret","SQL injection; mitigated by parameterized queries","Covert channel attack; mitigated by TEMPEST shielding"],"c":0,"why":"This is an aggregation attack, where combining multiple low-sensitivity items reveals higher-sensitivity information; it is best mitigated by access controls that track query history and restrict combinations that would reveal sensitive aggregates. Blanket reclassification is impractical and doesn't address the underlying query-combination risk, while SQL injection and covert channel/TEMPEST controls address unrelated technical attack vectors.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary difference between symmetric and asymmetric encryption?","o":["Symmetric encryption uses a single shared key, while asymmetric encryption uses a public/private key pair","Symmetric encryption is always more secure than asymmetric encryption","Asymmetric encryption is faster for bulk data encryption","Symmetric encryption cannot be used for confidentiality"],"c":0,"why":"Symmetric encryption relies on one shared secret key for both encryption and decryption, whereas asymmetric encryption uses a mathematically related public/private key pair. Symmetric is generally faster, not less secure, and is commonly used for confidentiality.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In the context of the Trusted Computing Base (TCB), what is the function of the reference monitor?","o":["To encrypt data at rest within the TCB","To enforce access control decisions between subjects and objects","To manage user authentication credentials","To perform malware scanning on system files"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept that mediates all access between subjects and objects according to security policy. It is not responsible for encryption, authentication credential storage, or malware scanning.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A researcher demonstrates that even with ASLR and DEP/NX enabled, an attacker can chain together existing executable code snippets already present in memory to achieve arbitrary code execution without injecting new code. Which additional mitigation directly addresses this technique?","o":["Stack canaries to detect buffer overflow before return","Control Flow Integrity (CFI) to validate legitimate call and return targets","Data Execution Prevention (DEP) to mark stack and heap memory as non-executable","Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR) to randomize memory locations"],"c":1,"why":"The attack described is Return-Oriented Programming (ROP), which reuses existing executable code (gadgets) rather than injecting new code, so DEP/NX and even ASLR (already stated as enabled) do not stop it. Control Flow Integrity validates that control transfers only go to legitimate, expected targets, directly defeating gadget-chaining, whereas stack canaries only detect certain overflow conditions before the exploit executes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A defense contractor is designing an access control model for a system where the primary concern is preventing unauthorized disclosure of classified data, even if it means lower-cleared subjects can still modify data they cannot read. Which security model property directly enforces this requirement by preventing a subject from writing information down to a lower classification level?","o":["Biba's Simple Integrity Property (no read down)","Bell-LaPadula's *-property (no write down)","Clark-Wilson's certification rule","Biba's *-integrity Property (no write up)"],"c":1,"why":"Bell-LaPadula's *-property (confinement property) prevents a subject from writing to an object at a lower classification, stopping high-classification data from leaking downward. Biba's properties address integrity (preventing contamination), not confidentiality, and Clark-Wilson's certification rule concerns well-formed transactions, not classification-based write restrictions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution needs an access control model that prioritizes data integrity over confidentiality, ensuring that lower-integrity users cannot corrupt higher-integrity financial records. Which model best fits this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model applied without integrity verification procedures","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model is designed specifically to preserve integrity by preventing subjects from writing up or reading down, stopping lower-integrity data from contaminating higher-integrity data. Bell-LaPadula focuses on confidentiality, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest, not general integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization installs fences, security guards, and badge readers around its data center. Which security design principle does this best illustrate?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity"],"c":2,"why":"Defense in depth uses multiple layered controls (fences, guards, badge readers) to protect an asset. Least privilege and separation of duties relate to access rights, and security through obscurity relies on secrecy rather than layered controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a security model in which subjects cannot read data at a higher classification level and cannot write data to a lower classification level. Which security model does this describe?","o":["Biba Integrity Model","Bell-LaPadula Model","Clark-Wilson Model","Brewer-Nash Model"],"c":1,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces 'no read up, no write down' to protect confidentiality. Biba addresses integrity (no read down, no write up), Clark-Wilson enforces integrity via well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflict-of-interest access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants real-time certificate revocation checking but is concerned about the added TLS handshake latency of querying an OCSP responder on every connection, as well as privacy exposure of client browsing patterns to the CA's responder. Which solution addresses both concerns simultaneously?","o":["Publishing a full Certificate Revocation List (CRL) to all clients daily","Disabling revocation checking entirely to improve performance","OCSP stapling, where the server periodically obtains and attaches a signed OCSP response to its own certificate during the handshake","Extending certificate validity periods to reduce the need for revocation checks"],"c":2,"why":"OCSP stapling has the server fetch the signed revocation status in advance and present it during the TLS handshake, eliminating per-connection client queries to the OCSP responder (reducing latency and protecting client privacy). CRLs can be large and stale, disabling revocation checking removes security entirely, and extending validity periods increases risk rather than solving the stated problem.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect implements classic (anonymous, unauthenticated) Diffie-Hellman key exchange between two servers to establish a shared symmetric key. A penetration tester demonstrates that an attacker positioned on the network can establish independent DH exchanges with each server and relay traffic, decrypting and re-encrypting messages without detection. What is the most effective architectural fix?","o":["Increase the DH modulus size to at least 4096 bits","Switch from DH to a static RSA key transport mechanism","Authenticate the DH exchange using digital signatures tied to verified certificates","Add a message authentication code (MAC) computed with the derived session key"],"c":2,"why":"The vulnerability is a man-in-the-middle attack enabled by the lack of authentication of the exchanged public values; signing the DH parameters with certificates bound to verified identities (as in DHE/ECDHE with TLS) prevents impersonation. Increasing modulus size only strengthens against brute force, not MITM; static RSA transport removes forward secrecy and doesn't fix the underlying authentication gap; a MAC computed after the flawed exchange would still use a key the attacker helped derive.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a key exchange, two parties who have never communicated before need to establish a shared secret key over an insecure channel without prior shared secrets. Which cryptographic mechanism is specifically designed for this purpose?","o":["RSA digital signature algorithm","Diffie-Hellman key exchange","AES in CBC mode","HMAC-SHA256"],"c":1,"why":"Diffie-Hellman allows two parties to derive a shared secret over an insecure channel without ever transmitting the key itself, using public value exchange and modular exponentiation. RSA signatures authenticate/sign data, AES is a symmetric cipher requiring an existing key, and HMAC provides message integrity, not key establishment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing a system that must prevent unauthorized modification of data by unauthorized users, while still allowing authorized users to make appropriate changes. Which security model best addresses this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula Model","Biba Integrity Model","Take-Grant Model","Lattice-Based Access Control"],"c":1,"why":"Biba is specifically designed to protect data integrity by preventing subjects from reading below or writing above their integrity level. Bell-LaPadula focuses on confidentiality, Take-Grant models rights propagation, and lattice-based control is a general framework, not integrity-specific.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A malicious process on a shared multi-tenant host has no direct access permissions to a victim VM's memory but is found to be extracting cryptographic key bits by measuring variations in CPU cache access times caused by the victim's operations. What type of channel is being exploited?","o":["A covert storage channel using shared file attributes","A covert timing channel exploiting shared hardware resource latency","An overt channel authorized by the hypervisor's resource-sharing policy","An inference channel derived from statistical database queries"],"c":1,"why":"This scenario describes a covert timing channel, where information is leaked by modulating and observing the timing of shared resource usage (cache access latency) rather than through any authorized communication path. A covert storage channel would involve shared data attributes like file size or lock states, an overt channel would be sanctioned and documented, and an inference channel relates to deducing data from statistical or aggregated query results, not hardware timing side effects.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An evaluator is reviewing a Common Criteria certification report for a hardware security module and notes the product achieved EAL6. Which statement best characterizes what this assurance level specifically guarantees about the product?","o":["The product has been functionally tested against its security specification with no formal verification required","The product's design has been semi-formally verified and tested, providing high assurance against sophisticated attackers, though not full formal verification","The product meets FIPS 140-2 Level 4 physical security requirements","The product has undergone informal correspondence between design and requirements only"],"c":1,"why":"EAL6 (Semi-formally Verified Design and Tested) requires semi-formal design verification and rigorous testing, offering high assurance suitable for high-risk environments, one step below EAL7's fully formal verification. FIPS 140-2 is a separate, unrelated certification scheme, and the other options describe lower EAL levels (EAL2-3 territory).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is specifically designed to protect the integrity of data by preventing unauthorized modification, using rules such as 'no write up, no read down'?","o":["Bell-LaPadula Model","Biba Model","Take-Grant Model","Graham-Denning Model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model focuses on data integrity with 'no write up, no read down' rules. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, while Take-Grant and Graham-Denning models deal with rights propagation and access control management.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to ensure that a message sender cannot later deny having sent a specific electronic document. Which cryptographic control provides this assurance?","o":["Symmetric encryption using a shared secret key","A cryptographic hash function alone","A digital signature created with the sender's private key","A message authentication code (MAC) using a shared key"],"c":2,"why":"Digital signatures use the sender's private key, which only the sender possesses, so successful verification with the corresponding public key proves origin and provides non-repudiation. Symmetric encryption and MACs rely on shared keys, so either party could have created the message, and a hash alone provides only integrity checking, not proof of origin.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary purpose of a Trusted Computing Base (TCB) reference monitor?","o":["To encrypt all data transmitted between trusted and untrusted network zones","To enforce the security policy by mediating all access between subjects and objects","To provide non-repudiation for transactions processed by trusted applications","To generate audit logs for compliance reporting"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept that mediates all access requests between subjects and objects according to the security policy, and it must be tamperproof, always invoked, and small enough to verify. Encryption, non-repudiation, and logging are related but not its defining function.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization uses a TPM to protect disk encryption keys and wants to ensure the key is only released if the system boots into an unmodified, expected configuration. Which TPM capability directly supports this requirement?","o":["Remote attestation using the Endorsement Key to encrypt all disk sectors","Sealing the key to specific PCR (Platform Configuration Register) values representing the boot state","Using the TPM's random number generator to reseed the key on every boot","Storing the key in the TPM's non-volatile storage without any binding conditions"],"c":1,"why":"Sealing binds a secret to specific PCR values that reflect measurements of BIOS, bootloader, and OS state; the TPM will only unseal (release) the key if the current measurements match, detecting tampering. The Endorsement Key is used for identity/attestation, not bulk disk encryption; RNG reseeding and unconditional NV storage do not tie key release to system integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A government agency is evaluating a vendor's security appliance and requires it to meet a formally defined level of assurance that includes semi-formal design verification and independently confirmed testing. Which evaluation framework provides these Evaluation Assurance Levels?","o":["Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408)","Trusted Computer System Evaluation Criteria (TCSEC)","ISO/IEC 27001","NIST Special Publication 800-53"],"c":0,"why":"Common Criteria defines Evaluation Assurance Levels (EAL1-EAL7) that specify increasing rigor of design verification and testing. TCSEC uses a different rating system (divisions A-D), while ISO 27001 and NIST 800-53 are management/control frameworks, not product evaluation criteria with EALs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization is selecting a product for a high-assurance environment and requires formal verification of the security design as well as testing. Under the Common Criteria, which term describes the level of confidence provided by this rigorous evaluation?","o":["Protection Profile (PP)","Security Target (ST)","Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL)","Target of Evaluation (TOE)"],"c":2,"why":"EAL indicates the depth and rigor of the security evaluation performed, ranging from EAL1 (functionally tested) to EAL7 (formally verified). A Protection Profile defines requirements, a Security Target describes the vendor's claims, and TOE is the product being evaluated.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is a key security concern specific to virtualization environments?","o":["Physical theft of removable media","VM escape, where an attacker breaks out of a guest VM to access the host system","SQL injection attacks against web applications","Social engineering attacks against help desk staff"],"c":1,"why":"VM escape is a virtualization-specific threat where malicious code on a guest VM exploits vulnerabilities to gain access to the hypervisor or other VMs. The other options are general security concerns not unique to virtualization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A statistical database allows analysts to run aggregate queries (sums, averages) over employee salary data but blocks direct queries on individual records. An analyst discovers that by combining the results of two overlapping aggregate queries with slightly different filter criteria, they can deduce an individual's exact salary. What is this attack called, and what is the most effective architectural countermeasure?","o":["SQL injection; use parameterized queries","Inference attack; implement query set size restriction and controls on overlapping query results","Aggregation attack; apply mandatory access control labels to each row","Covert channel exploitation; reduce the bandwidth of the database connection"],"c":1,"why":"This is a classic inference attack exploiting overlapping aggregate queries to deduce individual data; countermeasures include minimum query set size, tracking query history, and restricting overlapping queries (or adding noise/perturbation). SQL injection involves malicious code injection, not statistical deduction; row-level MAC labels don't prevent inference from aggregates; this is not a covert channel scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A laptop manufacturer includes a hardware chip that securely stores cryptographic keys, performs platform integrity measurements at boot, and enables full-disk encryption key protection. This chip is best described as a:","o":["Hardware security module (HSM) used for enterprise key management","Trusted Platform Module (TPM)","Secure Enclave used solely for biometric data","Smart card reader interface"],"c":1,"why":"A TPM is a dedicated hardware chip embedded in endpoint devices that stores cryptographic keys, supports secure boot integrity measurement, and protects disk encryption keys (e.g., BitLocker). HSMs are typically dedicated enterprise appliances/servers for centralized key management, not built into individual laptops for boot measurement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A cloud provider offers a service model where the customer manages the operating system, applications, and data, while the provider manages the underlying hardware, virtualization, and network infrastructure. Which cloud service model is this?","o":["Software as a Service (SaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Function as a Service (FaaS)"],"c":2,"why":"In IaaS, the provider manages the physical infrastructure and hypervisor layer, while the customer is responsible for the OS, middleware, applications, and data. SaaS gives customers only application-level control, PaaS abstracts away OS management, and FaaS abstracts even application runtime management.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security engineer is hardening a legacy application against buffer overflow exploitation. The application cannot be rewritten to eliminate unsafe memory functions in the short term. Which combination of OS-level mitigations would most effectively reduce the likelihood of successful exploitation without modifying the application's source code?","o":["Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR) and Data Execution Prevention (DEP/NX)","Full disk encryption and mandatory access control","Stack canaries compiled into the binary and input validation at the application layer","Running the application in a chroot jail with SELinux enforcing mode"],"c":0,"why":"ASLR randomizes memory layout to make return-oriented programming and return-to-libc attacks unreliable, while DEP/NX prevents execution of injected code in data segments; both are OS/CPU-level mitigations requiring no source changes. Stack canaries and input validation require recompilation/source changes; disk encryption and chroot/SELinux address different threat models (data-at-rest confidentiality and process containment, not memory corruption exploitation).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which physical security control is designed primarily to detect unauthorized entry rather than prevent it?","o":["Reinforced doors","Motion-activated CCTV cameras","Security fencing","Mantrap entry systems"],"c":1,"why":"Motion-activated CCTV cameras are detective controls that identify and record unauthorized entry attempts. Reinforced doors, fencing, and mantraps are primarily preventive controls that restrict physical access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"In a virtualized data center, an attacker exploits a vulnerability in a guest virtual machine to gain unauthorized access to the underlying hypervisor and other guest VMs on the same host. This attack is best classified as:","o":["A side-channel attack","A VM escape attack","A covert channel attack","A rootkit installation"],"c":1,"why":"VM escape occurs when an attacker breaks out of an isolated virtual machine to access the hypervisor or other VMs on the same physical host, violating the isolation the hypervisor is supposed to enforce. Side-channel attacks exploit indirect information leakage (e.g., timing/power), and covert channels involve unauthorized information flow through unintended paths, neither of which describes breaking VM isolation directly.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Which type of attack against a cryptographic hash function involves finding two different inputs that produce the same output, and is mitigated by using a hash function with sufficient output length?","o":["Chosen-plaintext attack","Birthday attack (collision attack)","Meet-in-the-middle attack","Known-plaintext attack"],"c":1,"why":"A birthday attack exploits the probability of hash collisions, which becomes more likely as more inputs are hashed; longer hash outputs reduce this risk. The other attacks target encryption algorithms rather than hash collision resistance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A cryptographic hardware module implementing RSA decryption exhibits measurably different processing times depending on the private key bits being processed during modular exponentiation. An attacker with physical proximity measures these timing variations across many decryption operations to recover the private key. Which category of attack is this, and what is the standard mitigation?","o":["Chosen ciphertext attack; mitigated by OAEP padding","Side-channel timing attack; mitigated by implementing constant-time algorithms and blinding techniques","Brute-force attack; mitigated by increasing key length","Replay attack; mitigated by adding nonces to each decryption request"],"c":1,"why":"This describes a timing side-channel attack, where information leaks through the physical implementation (execution time) rather than a mathematical weakness; mitigations include constant-time implementations and RSA blinding to decouple timing from key bits. OAEP padding addresses chosen-ciphertext attacks on the algorithm's structure, not timing leakage; key length increases don't address implementation-level leakage, and nonces prevent replay, not timing analysis.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center located near a foreign embassy is concerned that adversaries could intercept electromagnetic emissions from computer monitors and cabling to reconstruct displayed data. Which control specifically addresses this threat?","o":["Faraday cage shielding as part of a TEMPEST program","Implementing full-disk encryption on all workstations","Deploying network segmentation with VLANs","Installing biometric access controls at server room doors"],"c":0,"why":"TEMPEST standards and Faraday cage shielding are specifically designed to prevent the interception of compromising electromagnetic emanations from electronic equipment. Disk encryption, VLAN segmentation, and biometric access controls address data-at-rest confidentiality, network isolation, and physical entry, respectively, none of which mitigate emanation-based eavesdropping.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center wants to ensure that a single environmental failure, such as a cooling system malfunction, does not cause equipment damage across the entire facility. Which design principle best addresses this concern?","o":["Implementing hot and cold aisle containment","Deploying redundant HVAC zones with independent controls","Increasing rack density to reduce facility footprint","Using a single centralized building management system for all environmental controls"],"c":1,"why":"Redundant, independently controlled HVAC zones ensure that failure of one cooling unit does not affect the entire facility. Aisle containment improves efficiency but doesn't provide redundancy, increasing density raises risk, and a single centralized system introduces a single point of failure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A financial application must ensure that no single employee can both create and approve a payment transaction, and that all transactions are processed only through certified, well-formed procedures. Which integrity model's constructs (the access triple and the certification/enforcement rules) are specifically designed to support this requirement?","o":["Biba Integrity Model","Clark-Wilson Integrity Model","Bell-LaPadula Model","Graham-Denning Model"],"c":1,"why":"The Clark-Wilson model defines Constrained Data Items, Transformation Procedures, and the subject-program-object access triple, along with certification rules (ensuring well-formed transactions) and enforcement rules (including separation of duties), directly matching this scenario. Biba addresses integrity via level-based read/write restrictions without transaction-based controls; Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality; Graham-Denning focuses on secure creation/deletion of subjects and objects and rights transfer, not transaction-based integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a code review, a security engineer discovers that an application accepts user input and directly incorporates it into a database query without validation or parameterization. Which secure architecture principle was violated?","o":["Defense in depth","Fail-safe defaults","Input validation / secure coding practices","Separation of duties"],"c":2,"why":"Failing to validate or parameterize user input creates SQL injection vulnerabilities, directly violating secure coding and input validation principles. Defense in depth concerns layered controls, fail-safe defaults concern default deny states, and separation of duties relates to task division among personnel, none of which directly address this coding flaw.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A subject holding a Secret clearance attempts to write data into an object classified as Confidential (a lower classification) within a system strictly enforcing the Bell-LaPadula model. What is the correct outcome under this model?","o":["The write is permitted because the subject dominates the object's classification level","The write is denied because it violates the *-property (star property), which prohibits writing to an object at a lower classification","The write is permitted because the *-property only restricts read operations, not write operations","The write is denied because it violates the simple security property, which governs read-up restrictions"],"c":1,"why":"The *-property (no write-down) prevents a subject cleared at a higher level from writing to an object at a lower level, since doing so could leak sensitive information to a less-trusted context. The simple security property governs reads, not writes, so option D misattributes the rule, and options A and C incorrectly permit the write.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a Common Criteria evaluation, a working group wants to publish a vendor-independent set of security functional and assurance requirements applicable to an entire category of products, such as network firewalls, so that multiple vendors can build products against a common baseline. Which Common Criteria artifact should they create?","o":["A Security Target (ST)","An Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) rating","A Target of Evaluation (TOE) description","A Protection Profile (PP)"],"c":3,"why":"A Protection Profile defines implementation-independent security requirements for a class of products. A Security Target is vendor/product-specific, an EAL indicates depth of assurance testing (not functional requirements), and a TOE simply identifies the product being evaluated.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Two parties use the classic Diffie-Hellman key exchange over an untrusted network to establish a shared symmetric key. A security architect notes that, as implemented, the protocol is vulnerable to a man-in-the-middle attack. What is the BEST architectural change to remediate this specific weakness?","o":["Switch to a larger prime modulus to increase the difficulty of the discrete logarithm problem","Add authentication of the exchanged public values using digital signatures or certificates (e.g., a station-to-station protocol)","Replace the shared key with a longer AES key after the exchange completes","Add an HMAC over the final derived session key before use"],"c":1,"why":"Plain Diffie-Hellman provides confidentiality of the derived key but no authentication of the parties, allowing an attacker to substitute their own public values; binding the exchange to signed/certified values (as in STS) prevents this. Larger moduli, longer symmetric keys, or an HMAC on the final key do not address the lack of authentication during the exchange itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which principle of secure design states that a system should default to denying access unless explicitly granted?","o":["Fail-safe defaults","Least privilege","Separation of duties","Economy of mechanism"],"c":0,"why":"Fail-safe defaults means access is denied by default and must be explicitly granted, reducing the risk of accidental exposure. Least privilege limits the amount of access granted, separation of duties splits critical tasks among multiple people, and economy of mechanism favors simple designs—none of these specifically address default-deny behavior.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A database administrator notices that a user with no direct access to a 'salary' field can nonetheless deduce an individual employee's exact salary by running a series of permitted aggregate queries (e.g., average salary by department combined with headcount). This is an example of which attack, and what is the BEST primary mitigation?","o":["SQL injection; mitigated by parameterized queries","An inference attack; mitigated by query set size restriction and controlled aggregation/cell suppression","A covert channel attack; mitigated by mandatory access control labels","A replay attack; mitigated by nonce-based query tokens"],"c":1,"why":"Deriving restricted data from permitted aggregate/statistical queries is a classic inference attack; controls such as minimum query set size, cell suppression, and noise addition in aggregation are the standard mitigations. SQL injection, covert channels, and replay attacks describe different threat mechanisms unrelated to this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In the Bell-LaPadula security model, which property prevents a subject from reading data at a higher classification level than their own clearance?","o":["Simple Security Property (no read up)","*-Property (no write down)","Strong Star Property","Discretionary Security Property"],"c":0,"why":"The Simple Security Property (ss-property) enforces 'no read up,' preventing subjects from reading data above their clearance level. The *-property prevents writing to lower levels, the strong star property restricts both read and write to the same level, and the discretionary property relates to owner-based access control, not mandatory confidentiality rules.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is reviewing whether a proposed kernel-level access control mechanism qualifies as a true reference monitor implementation. Which of the following is NOT one of the three properties required for a valid reference monitor?","o":["It must be tamperproof, resisting modification or circumvention","It must always be invoked for every access attempt (complete mediation)","It must be small enough to be thoroughly analyzed and verified (verifiable)","It must provide high availability through redundant, load-balanced instances"],"c":3,"why":"The reference monitor concept requires tamperproofing, complete mediation, and verifiability; high availability/load balancing is an operational design goal, not a formal requirement of the reference monitor abstraction.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which cryptographic approach uses the same secret key for both encryption and decryption?","o":["Symmetric encryption","Asymmetric encryption","Hashing","Digital signatures"],"c":0,"why":"Symmetric encryption relies on a single shared key for both encrypting and decrypting data. Asymmetric encryption uses a key pair (public/private), hashing produces a fixed-size digest without a key for reversal, and digital signatures use asymmetric keys to provide integrity and non-repudiation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Penetration testers discover that a smart card's RSA decryption operation exhibits power consumption patterns that statistically correlate with individual bits of the private key, allowing key extraction through repeated physical measurement without breaking the RSA algorithm mathematically. Which countermeasure BEST addresses this specific vulnerability class?","o":["Increase the RSA key size from 2048 to 4096 bits","Implement blinding and power/timing equalization techniques so operations are constant-time and constant-power regardless of key bit values","Replace RSA with a stronger padding scheme such as OAEP","Enable secure boot and firmware signing on the smart card"],"c":1,"why":"This describes a differential power analysis (DPA) side-channel attack; countermeasures such as blinding, masking, and constant-time/constant-power implementations prevent measurable correlation between operations and key material. Larger keys, padding scheme changes, or secure boot do not mitigate physical side-channel leakage.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary function of a reference monitor in a secure operating system architecture?","o":["Mediating all access between subjects and objects according to security policy","Encrypting data at rest on the file system","Logging user keystrokes for forensic review","Managing patch deployment schedules"],"c":0,"why":"A reference monitor is the abstract concept that enforces access control policy by mediating every request between subjects and objects. It is not responsible for encryption, keystroke logging, or patch management, which are separate security functions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"In a public cloud IaaS environment, a threat model identifies the risk of an attacker compromising a guest VM and then attempting a VM escape to access the hypervisor and other tenants' workloads on the same physical host. Which architectural control is SPECIFICALLY designed to mitigate this risk?","o":["Network segmentation using tenant-specific VLANs at the top-of-rack switch","Encryption of data at rest for each tenant's virtual disks","Strong hypervisor isolation leveraging a minimized trusted computing base and hardware-assisted virtualization (e.g., Intel VT-x/AMD-V) enforcement","Enforcing multifactor authentication for all tenant administrative accounts"],"c":2,"why":"VM escape and cross-tenant compromise are mitigated at the hypervisor layer through hardware-enforced isolation and minimizing the hypervisor's attack surface; network segmentation, disk encryption, and MFA address different threat vectors and do not prevent a successful hypervisor-level breakout.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which physical security control is specifically designed to detect and suppress a fire in a data center using a gas that removes heat without damaging electronic equipment?","o":["Clean agent fire suppression system","Wet pipe sprinkler system","Deluge sprinkler system","Standpipe system"],"c":0,"why":"Clean agent (gaseous) systems, such as those using FM-200 or similar agents, suppress fires without leaving residue or conducting electricity, making them ideal for data centers. Wet pipe and deluge sprinklers use water, which can damage electronics, and standpipes are used to supply water to hose connections for firefighters, not automated suppression.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A government facility processing classified information must prevent adversaries positioned outside the building from intercepting compromising electromagnetic emanations from monitors, cabling, and processing equipment. Which control is SPECIFICALLY designed to address this threat?","o":["Deploying an uninterruptible power supply (UPS) with power line conditioning","Implementing TEMPEST shielding, such as a Faraday cage around sensitive processing areas","Installing biometric access control at all facility entry points","Using redundant HVAC systems to maintain equipment operating temperature"],"c":1,"why":"TEMPEST standards and Faraday shielding are specifically designed to contain and suppress compromising electromagnetic emanations from electronic equipment. UPS, biometric access, and HVAC address power continuity, physical entry, and environmental concerns respectively, not emanation security.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In virtualization technology, which component is primarily responsible for creating and managing virtual machines on a physical host?","o":["Hypervisor","Container orchestrator","Virtual private network gateway","Storage area network controller"],"c":0,"why":"The hypervisor is the software layer that creates, runs, and manages virtual machines by abstracting and allocating physical hardware resources. Container orchestrators manage containers (not full VMs), VPN gateways handle secure network tunnels, and SAN controllers manage storage, not virtualization of compute resources.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a mandatory access control model in which subjects cannot read data classified above their clearance level and cannot write data to a classification level below their current clearance. Which security model does this describe?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces 'no read up, no write down' to preserve confidentiality. Biba addresses integrity (no read down, no write up), Clark-Wilson enforces integrity via well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants independent, standardized assurance that a security product meets a defined set of functional and assurance requirements before purchase. Which framework should they consult?","o":["Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408)","ITIL","COBIT","Six Sigma"],"c":0,"why":"Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408) is the internationally recognized framework for evaluating and certifying the security functionality and assurance level of IT products. ITIL addresses IT service management, COBIT is an IT governance framework, and Six Sigma is a process improvement methodology—none provide product security certification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution needs an integrity-focused access control model to ensure that lower-integrity data cannot contaminate higher-integrity processes. Which model is best suited for this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","Graham-Denning model"],"c":1,"why":"Biba enforces 'no write up, no read down' to protect data integrity by preventing subjects from being influenced by lower-integrity data. Bell-LaPadula focuses on confidentiality, while Take-Grant and Graham-Denning address rights propagation rather than integrity levels directly.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security architecture strategy involves layering multiple, different types of controls so that if one control fails, others still provide protection?","o":["Defense in depth","Single point of failure elimination","Security through obscurity","Least functionality"],"c":0,"why":"Defense in depth uses multiple overlapping layers of diverse controls so that the failure of one does not result in a total security breach. Eliminating single points of failure is a resiliency concept, security through obscurity relies on secrecy rather than layered controls, and least functionality is about disabling unnecessary services, not layering defenses.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In the Bell-LaPadula security model, which property prevents a subject from writing data to an object at a lower classification level than the subject's own clearance?","o":["The Simple Security Property (no read up)","The *-Property (no write down)","The Discretionary Security Property","The Strong Star Property"],"c":1,"why":"The *-property (star property) enforces 'no write down' to preserve confidentiality by preventing high-clearance subjects from leaking data to lower-classified objects; the simple security property governs reads, not writes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which characteristic best describes symmetric key cryptography?","o":["It uses a mathematically related public and private key pair","It uses the same single key for both encryption and decryption","It is primarily used to provide non-repudiation","It does not require the key to be kept secret"],"c":1,"why":"Symmetric cryptography relies on one shared secret key for both encrypting and decrypting data. Public/private key pairs and non-repudiation are associated with asymmetric cryptography, and symmetric keys must remain confidential.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a mandatory access control system where a Confidential-cleared user can read Unclassified, Confidential data but cannot read Secret data, and can write only to objects at their own or higher classification level. Which security model best describes this behavior?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces 'no read up, no write down' to preserve confidentiality, matching the described read restrictions and write-up-only behavior. Biba addresses integrity (opposite rules), Clark-Wilson focuses on well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In the classic protection ring model of CPU architecture, which ring typically has the highest level of privilege and runs the operating system kernel?","o":["Ring 3","Ring 2","Ring 1","Ring 0"],"c":3,"why":"Ring 0 is the innermost, most privileged ring and hosts the OS kernel, which needs direct hardware access; Ring 3 (outermost) typically runs user applications with the least privilege.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A developer wants to securely exchange a symmetric session key between two parties over an untrusted network without pre-sharing a secret. Which approach BEST accomplishes this?","o":["Use the symmetric key directly for both encryption and key exchange","Encrypt the symmetric key with the recipient's public key using asymmetric cryptography","Hash the symmetric key with SHA-256 before sending it","Use a symmetric block cipher in ECB mode to protect the key"],"c":1,"why":"Asymmetric (public-key) encryption allows secure key exchange without a pre-shared secret, forming the basis of hybrid cryptosystems. Symmetric encryption requires a shared secret already, hashing is one-way and not reversible for key recovery, and ECB mode has no bearing on key exchange security.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A data center is selecting a fire suppression system for a server room. Which option is MOST appropriate to minimize damage to electronic equipment while suppressing a fire?","o":["Wet pipe water sprinkler system","Clean agent (gaseous) suppression system","Foam-based suppression system","Dry chemical powder extinguishing system"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agent gaseous systems (e.g., FM-200, inert gas) suppress fire without leaving residue or conductive moisture, protecting sensitive electronics. Water, foam, and dry chemical agents can damage equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial application must prevent low-integrity processes from modifying high-integrity data, while allowing high-integrity subjects to read lower-integrity data only through a controlled interface. Which security model is specifically designed to enforce this integrity requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","Lattice-based model (generic)"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model enforces 'no write up, no read down' to protect data integrity, exactly matching the requirement to prevent low-integrity modification of high-integrity data. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, not integrity, and Take-Grant models access rights transfer rather than integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Which fundamental security architecture concept describes an abstract machine that mediates all access between subjects and objects, ensuring that security policy is consistently enforced?","o":["Trusted computing base","Reference monitor","Security kernel","Access control matrix"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is the conceptual model that mediates all subject-object access according to policy; it must be tamperproof, always invoked, and verifiable. The TCB is the collection of hardware/software implementing this concept, the security kernel is its practical implementation, and the access control matrix is a data structure representing permissions, not an enforcement mechanism.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A cryptographic hash function is primarily used to provide which security service?","o":["Confidentiality of data in transit","Integrity verification of data","Encryption key exchange","Non-repudiation through key escrow"],"c":1,"why":"Hash functions produce a fixed-size digest used to detect changes to data, providing integrity checking. They do not encrypt data for confidentiality or perform key exchange.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A company needs to securely exchange a symmetric session key between two parties over an untrusted network without any prior shared secret. Which cryptographic approach is MOST appropriate for this initial key exchange?","o":["Use a symmetric block cipher like AES to encrypt the session key","Use asymmetric cryptography, such as RSA or Diffie-Hellman, to establish the shared key","Use a hashing algorithm like SHA-256 to derive the key","Use a stream cipher to generate and transmit the key"],"c":1,"why":"Asymmetric cryptography (RSA key transport or Diffie-Hellman key agreement) solves the problem of establishing a shared secret without prior trust, which is why it's used for key exchange before symmetric encryption takes over. Symmetric ciphers require a pre-shared key, and hashing is one-way and not suitable for key exchange.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a Common Criteria evaluation, a product achieves EAL4. What does this rating primarily indicate about the product?","o":["The product has been mathematically proven secure against all known attacks","The product has undergone methodical design, testing, and review appropriate for commercial products requiring moderate assurance","The product meets FIPS 140-2 Level 4 cryptographic module requirements","The product is certified for use in classified government systems only"],"c":1,"why":"EAL4 represents methodically designed, tested, and reviewed assurance suitable for general commercial use, not formal mathematical proof (which is EAL7) or FIPS cryptographic module certification, which is a separate standard entirely.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which term describes the totality of protection mechanisms within a computer system, including hardware, firmware, and software, that together enforce the security policy?","o":["Security Kernel","Trusted Computing Base (TCB)","Reference Monitor","Security Perimeter"],"c":1,"why":"The TCB encompasses all protective mechanisms (hardware, firmware, software) responsible for enforcing the security policy. The security kernel is a subset that implements the reference monitor concept, and the security perimeter is the boundary separating the TCB from the rest of the system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst discovers that two different input messages produced the same cryptographic hash value. This scenario represents which type of cryptographic weakness?","o":["A birthday attack exploiting hash collisions","A brute-force attack on the key space","A chosen-plaintext attack","A meet-in-the-middle attack"],"c":0,"why":"A birthday attack exploits the mathematical probability of hash collisions occurring sooner than expected due to the birthday paradox, which is exactly what's described. Brute-force attacks target key space exhaustively, chosen-plaintext attacks involve attacker-selected plaintext for analysis, and meet-in-the-middle attacks target multiple-encryption schemes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a product evaluation under the Common Criteria, a vendor's firewall is assigned an Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) rating. What does a higher EAL rating primarily indicate?","o":["The product has fewer vulnerabilities than lower-rated products","The product underwent a more rigorous and thorough evaluation of its security functionality and assurance documentation","The product meets a higher level of functional security requirements automatically","The product is certified for use in classified government environments only"],"c":1,"why":"EAL ratings (EAL1-EAL7) reflect the depth and rigor of the assurance evaluation process, not the inherent functional strength or vulnerability count of the product. A product can have strong functionality but low assurance testing, or vice versa; EAL does not guarantee fewer vulnerabilities or automatic classified-use certification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization purchases access to virtualized servers, storage, and networking from a cloud provider, but remains responsible for installing and managing the operating system, middleware, and applications. Which cloud service model does this describe?","o":["Software as a Service (SaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Function as a Service (FaaS)"],"c":2,"why":"IaaS provides fundamental compute, storage, and network resources, leaving the customer responsible for the OS and above. PaaS abstracts away OS management, and SaaS provides fully managed applications.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A cloud provider offers a Type 1 hypervisor to host multiple customer virtual machines on shared physical hardware. From a security architecture perspective, why is a Type 1 hypervisor generally preferred over a Type 2 hypervisor for this use case?","o":["It runs directly on hardware without a host OS, reducing the attack surface and improving isolation between VMs","It automatically encrypts all VM memory using hardware-based security extensions","It eliminates the need for network segmentation between tenant VMs","It allows VMs to bypass the hypervisor for direct hardware access, improving performance"],"c":0,"why":"Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisors run directly on hardware without a host OS, minimizing the attack surface and providing stronger isolation, which is critical in multi-tenant cloud environments. The other options describe capabilities not inherent to Type 1 hypervisors and would actually weaken security if true.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A biometric access control system incorrectly grants access to an unauthorized individual by matching them to an enrolled user's template. What is this error called?","o":["False Rejection Rate (FRR)","False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Type I Error"],"c":1,"why":"The False Acceptance Rate measures how often an unauthorized user is incorrectly accepted as a match. FRR (Type I error) is the opposite—rejecting a legitimate user—and CER is the point where FAR and FRR are equal.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center wants to protect sensitive electronic equipment from electromagnetic eavesdropping (e.g., TEMPEST-style attacks) without relying on distance separation. Which physical security control BEST addresses this concern?","o":["Faraday cage shielding around the facility or equipment","Redundant uninterruptible power supplies","Mantrap entry systems at facility doors","Positive pressure HVAC systems"],"c":0,"why":"A Faraday cage blocks electromagnetic emissions from escaping (or entering) a shielded area, directly mitigating TEMPEST-style electromagnetic eavesdropping risks. UPS systems address power continuity, mantraps control physical entry, and positive pressure HVAC manages airflow/contaminants—none address electromagnetic emanation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A defense contractor's multilevel secure system enforces Bell-LaPadula to protect classification levels. During an audit, the security architect discovers that a low-classification process is able to write malformed data into a high-classification file, effectively corrupting it, even though it cannot read the file's contents. Which statement best explains this finding?","o":["Bell-LaPadula enforces confidentiality via 'no read up, no write down' but does not address data integrity, so a complementary model such as Biba is needed","The implementation is flawed because Bell-LaPadula's 'no write up' rule should have prevented this write operation","This is expected behavior because Bell-LaPadula's simple integrity property permits writes to higher levels","The Clark-Wilson model was likely misapplied instead of Bell-LaPadula, causing the integrity failure"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula's *-property is 'no write down,' meaning subjects CAN write up to higher classification levels, which protects confidentiality but creates an integrity exposure; Biba's 'no write up' rule is designed to prevent exactly this. The other options misstate the *-property or misattribute the cause.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Which component of a trusted computing base (TCB) is responsible for mediating ALL access between subjects and objects, and must itself be tamperproof, always invoked, and small enough to be verifiable?","o":["Security kernel","Reference monitor","Trusted path","Security perimeter"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept that mediates all subject-object access requests and must be tamperproof, always invoked, and verifiable; the security kernel is the hardware/software/firmware implementation of the reference monitor concept. Trusted path refers to secure communication channels, and security perimeter defines the boundary of the TCB.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A national security agency is procuring a custom cryptographic module for a top-secret system and requires the highest level of assurance under the Common Criteria, including formal verification of the design and implementation. Which Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) should be specified in the procurement requirements?","o":["EAL2, because it balances cost and assurance for most commercial products","EAL4, because it is the highest level achievable without vendor cooperation","EAL7, because it requires formally verified design and tested implementation","EAL1, because functional testing alone is sufficient for high-assurance systems"],"c":2,"why":"EAL7 is the highest Common Criteria assurance level, requiring formal verification of design and independent testing, appropriate for extreme-risk environments. EAL1, EAL2, and EAL4 provide progressively less rigorous assurance and would not satisfy a requirement for formal verification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to preserve confidentiality by preventing users from reading data above their clearance level and writing data to a lower classification level?","o":["Biba Integrity Model","Bell-LaPadula Model","Clark-Wilson Model","Brewer-Nash Model"],"c":1,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces 'no read up, no write down' to protect confidentiality. Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson enforces well-formed transactions for integrity, and Brewer-Nash (Chinese Wall) prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A developer is selecting a cryptographic hash function for verifying file integrity. Which property is MOST critical to prevent an attacker from creating two different files that produce the same hash value?","o":["Pre-image resistance","Collision resistance","Avalanche effect","Fixed output length"],"c":1,"why":"Collision resistance ensures that it is computationally infeasible to find two different inputs producing the same hash output, directly preventing the described attack. Pre-image resistance prevents reversing a hash to find the original input, avalanche effect describes output sensitivity to input changes, and fixed output length is a structural property, not a security guarantee.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is redesigning a TLS-based VPN gateway. The current configuration uses static RSA key exchange, and the CISO is concerned that a future compromise of the server's private key would allow retroactive decryption of previously captured traffic. Which change most directly addresses this concern?","o":["Switch to AES-256-GCM for the bulk encryption cipher","Implement ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (DHE or ECDHE) key exchange to provide forward secrecy","Increase the RSA key size from 2048 to 4096 bits","Require mutual certificate-based authentication for all VPN clients"],"c":1,"why":"Static RSA key exchange derives session keys from the server's long-term private key, so its compromise exposes all past sessions; ephemeral Diffie-Hellman generates unique session keys per session, providing forward secrecy. Stronger RSA keys, a different bulk cipher, or mutual authentication do not solve the retroactive-decryption problem.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization needs to securely exchange a symmetric encryption key over an insecure network without prior shared secrets. Which type of cryptography is best suited to accomplish this key exchange?","o":["Symmetric encryption","Asymmetric encryption","Hashing algorithms","Steganography"],"c":1,"why":"Asymmetric (public key) cryptography allows secure key exchange using public/private key pairs without a pre-shared secret. Symmetric encryption requires a shared key already, hashing provides integrity not confidentiality, and steganography hides data rather than exchanging keys.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A secure system design follows the principle that if a component fails, it should default to denying access rather than granting it. Which secure design principle does this describe?","o":["Least privilege","Fail-safe defaults","Separation of duties","Defense in depth"],"c":1,"why":"Fail-safe defaults dictate that access should be denied by default unless explicitly granted, ensuring failures do not result in unintended access. Least privilege limits granted rights to the minimum necessary, separation of duties splits critical tasks among multiple parties, and defense in depth layers multiple controls rather than addressing failure behavior.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An auditor reviewing an operating system's security kernel finds that the reference monitor can be bypassed by a privileged process that directly manipulates memory-mapped I/O, allowing it to access objects without an access-control check. Which core property of the reference monitor concept has been violated?","o":["Least privilege, because the process should not have had elevated rights","Complete mediation, because not every access request is being validated by the reference monitor","Separation of duties, because a single process performs both mediation and access","Fail-safe defaults, because the system should deny access when the reference monitor is unavailable"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor concept requires complete mediation (every access request must be checked), tamperproofing, and verifiability; bypassing the check via direct memory manipulation is a failure of complete mediation. Least privilege, separation of duties, and fail-safe defaults are related but distinct design principles not directly at issue here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary function of the Reference Monitor within the Trusted Computing Base (TCB)?","o":["To encrypt data at rest and in transit","To mediate all access between subjects and objects based on security policy","To log user keystrokes for forensic analysis","To manage patch deployment across the enterprise"],"c":1,"why":"The Reference Monitor is an abstract concept that enforces access control by mediating every subject-object interaction according to security policy. Encryption, logging, and patching are separate functions not central to the reference monitor concept.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization runs multiple virtual machines from different customers on shared hypervisor hardware in a cloud environment. Which threat is of GREATEST concern specific to this multi-tenant virtualization architecture?","o":["SQL injection against the guest OS database","VM escape allowing a process to break out of its VM and access the hypervisor or other VMs","Phishing attacks targeting cloud administrator credentials","Denial of service against the customer's public-facing website"],"c":1,"why":"VM escape is a threat unique to virtualized, multi-tenant environments where a compromised guest VM could break isolation and access the hypervisor or co-located tenant VMs, violating the core security promise of virtualization. The other options are general application or network threats not specific to hypervisor-based multi-tenancy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Under the Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408), what does an Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) rating indicate about a certified product?","o":["The number of security vulnerabilities patched","The depth and rigor of the security testing and assurance activities performed","The specific encryption algorithm strength used","The vendor's market share and customer satisfaction rating"],"c":1,"why":"EAL ratings (EAL1-EAL7) reflect the level of assurance obtained through testing rigor and formal verification, not vulnerability counts, encryption strength, or business metrics.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which fire suppression agent is generally preferred for data centers because it displaces oxygen to extinguish fire without leaving harmful residue on sensitive electronic equipment?","o":["Water sprinklers","Class A dry chemical","Clean agent (e.g., FM-200 or inert gas)","Foam suppression"],"c":2,"why":"Clean agents like FM-200 or inert gases suppress fire by reducing oxygen or interrupting the combustion process without leaving residue, making them safe for electronics. Water and foam can damage equipment, and dry chemicals leave corrosive residue.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A hospital database allows analysts to query aggregate statistics such as average length of stay per department. An analyst runs a series of overlapping queries with narrowing filters (e.g., department, age range, admission date) and is eventually able to deduce the specific diagnosis of a single identifiable patient, even though no single query returned patient-level data. This is an example of which attack against the database?","o":["SQL injection","Aggregation attack","Inference attack","Polyinstantiation bypass"],"c":2,"why":"An inference attack occurs when a user deduces restricted information by correlating multiple authorized, lower-sensitivity queries. Aggregation attacks involve combining individually low-classification data elements that together reach a higher classification, which is a related but distinct concept; SQL injection and polyinstantiation are unrelated mechanisms.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In a cloud service model where the provider manages the underlying infrastructure, operating system, and runtime environment, and the customer only manages the application code and data, which model is being described?","o":["Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Software as a Service (SaaS)","Function as a Service (FaaS) only"],"c":1,"why":"PaaS provides a managed platform including OS and runtime, leaving customers responsible for application code and data. IaaS requires the customer to manage the OS, SaaS provides fully managed applications, and FaaS is a subset concept not matching this full description.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A cryptographic library implementation of AES on an embedded device is found to leak key information through measurable variations in execution time depending on the data being processed. Which type of attack is this vulnerability most susceptible to, and what is the most effective mitigation?","o":["Chosen-plaintext attack; mitigate by increasing key length","Cache-timing side-channel attack; mitigate by implementing constant-time algorithms that eliminate data-dependent execution paths","Birthday attack; mitigate by using a larger hash output size","Replay attack; mitigate by adding sequence numbers to encrypted messages"],"c":1,"why":"Execution-time variation tied to processed data is a hallmark of a timing/cache side-channel attack, best mitigated by constant-time implementations that remove data-dependent branching and memory access patterns. Key length, hash size, and sequence numbers do not address timing leakage.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security benefit of a Trusted Platform Module (TPM) embedded in a computing device?","o":["It accelerates network traffic encryption for VPN connections","It provides hardware-based secure storage for cryptographic keys and supports platform integrity verification","It automatically detects and removes malware in real time","It serves as a centralized authentication server for the enterprise"],"c":1,"why":"A TPM is a hardware chip that securely stores cryptographic keys and enables functions like secure boot and attestation of system integrity. It does not accelerate network traffic, detect malware, or function as an authentication server.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A cloud service provider hosts multiple tenants' virtual machines on shared physical hypervisors. A security researcher demonstrates that a malicious VM can exploit a hypervisor vulnerability to read memory belonging to a different tenant's VM on the same host. Which security architecture concept has been violated, and what control category most directly reduces this risk?","o":["Data remanence; addressed by cryptographic erasure of VM disk images","VM escape breaking hypervisor isolation; addressed by hardware-assisted virtualization protections (e.g., Intel VT-x/AMD-V with IOMMU) and prompt hypervisor patching","Covert channel; addressed by implementing mandatory access control within the guest OS","Side-loading attack; addressed by application whitelisting on the guest VM"],"c":1,"why":"This scenario describes a VM escape, where isolation between virtualized guests is broken at the hypervisor level; hardware-assisted virtualization features and timely patching of the hypervisor are the primary technical controls. The other options address unrelated risks (data remanence, covert channels, application-layer whitelisting) rather than hypervisor isolation failures.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution's data center processes highly classified transaction data. A physical security assessment recommends shielding to prevent adversaries from capturing compromising electromagnetic emanations from monitors and cabling using specialized receiving equipment outside the building. Which control is being recommended, and what standard governs it?","o":["Faraday cage shielding to prevent electromagnetic eavesdropping, governed by TEMPEST standards","Mantrap access control to prevent unauthorized physical entry, governed by CPTED principles","Uninterruptible power supply installation to prevent data loss during outages, governed by NFPA 75","Fire suppression using clean agents to protect sensitive equipment, governed by NFPA 2001"],"c":0,"why":"Shielding against electromagnetic emanation capture is addressed by TEMPEST standards, typically implemented via Faraday shielding of rooms or equipment. Mantraps, UPS systems, and fire suppression address different physical security concerns (entry control, power continuity, and fire safety) rather than emanation security.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model focuses on preventing unauthorized modification of data by enforcing rules such as 'no write up' and 'no read down' to maintain data integrity?","o":["Bell-LaPadula Model","Biba Integrity Model","Take-Grant Model","Non-Interference Model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model protects integrity by preventing subjects from writing to higher integrity levels or reading from lower ones. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, Take-Grant models rights transfer, and Non-Interference prevents information flow between security domains.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to protect the confidentiality of classified information by enforcing rules such as 'no read up' and 'no write down'?","o":["Biba Integrity Model","Bell-LaPadula Model","Clark-Wilson Model","Brewer-Nash Model"],"c":1,"why":"Bell-LaPadula was created to preserve confidentiality using simple security (no read up) and *-property (no write down) rules. Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson enforces well-formed transactions for integrity, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A hospital's clinical decision-support system enforces the Biba integrity model to prevent low-integrity research data feeds from corrupting high-integrity patient treatment records. Which Biba property directly enforces this by prohibiting a subject operating at a given integrity level from reading data from a lower integrity level?","o":["The Simple Integrity Axiom (no read down)","The *-Integrity Axiom (no write up)","The Simple Security Property of Bell-LaPadula (no read up)","The Strong Star Property"],"c":0,"why":"Biba's Simple Integrity Axiom (no read down) prevents a high-integrity subject from reading lower-integrity (less trusted) data, blocking contamination. The *-Integrity Axiom governs writing, not reading; Bell-LaPadula properties address confidentiality, not integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In symmetric key cryptography, what is the primary challenge compared to asymmetric key cryptography?","o":["Symmetric algorithms are much slower to compute","Symmetric algorithms cannot provide confidentiality","Securely distributing and managing the shared secret key","Symmetric algorithms require a public key infrastructure"],"c":2,"why":"Symmetric cryptography uses a single shared key, so securely distributing that key between parties is the main challenge. Symmetric algorithms are actually faster than asymmetric ones, do provide confidentiality, and do not require PKI, which is associated with asymmetric cryptography.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Two systems perform an unauthenticated Diffie-Hellman key exchange over an untrusted network to derive a shared symmetric key. A security architect is concerned about a man-in-the-middle attack. Which design change most directly mitigates this risk while preserving the forward secrecy benefit of the exchange?","o":["Increase the Diffie-Hellman modulus size to at least 4096 bits","Bind the exchange to authenticated public keys via digital certificates (e.g., authenticated/ephemeral DH signed by each party)","Replace Diffie-Hellman with a pre-shared symmetric key distributed out of band","Add a keyed HMAC to the resulting session key after derivation"],"c":1,"why":"Plain Diffie-Hellman provides no authentication of the parties, so an attacker can substitute their own public values; signing the exchange with certificate-backed keys (authenticated DH) prevents MITM while retaining forward secrecy. Larger modulus size strengthens against brute force but not MITM, and pre-shared keys eliminate the forward-secrecy benefit DH provides.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary function of a reference monitor in a secure operating system design?","o":["To encrypt data at rest on the system","To mediate all access between subjects and objects according to security policy","To log user login and logout times","To manage patch deployment across the enterprise"],"c":1,"why":"A reference monitor is the abstract concept that enforces access control by mediating every access request between subjects and objects. It is not primarily an encryption tool, an audit-time logger, or a patch management function, though logging may be a byproduct.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a Common Criteria evaluation, a vendor submits documentation describing the specific security functions implemented in their firewall product, along with the assurance level claimed and mappings to a published set of generic requirements for firewall-class products. Which two Common Criteria artifacts are being described, respectively?","o":["Target of Evaluation (TOE) and Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) certificate","Protection Profile (PP) and Security Target (ST)","Security Target (ST) and Protection Profile (PP)","Rainbow Series TCSEC rating and Orange Book classification"],"c":2,"why":"The vendor's product-specific description of implemented functions and assurance claims is the Security Target (ST); the generic, implementation-independent requirements for a product category is the Protection Profile (PP). The order in the question is ST then PP, making option C correct; TCSEC/Rainbow Series is unrelated to Common Criteria.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the purpose of a Trusted Computing Base (TCB)?","o":["A network segment isolated for testing untrusted code","The totality of protection mechanisms within a system that enforce security policy","A third-party auditor that certifies system security","A hardware component used only for cryptographic key storage"],"c":1,"why":"The TCB encompasses all hardware, software, and firmware components responsible for enforcing the security policy of a system. It is not a network segment, an external auditor, or limited to cryptographic hardware.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization needs a formal security model to enforce confidentiality in a multilevel secure system, ensuring that subjects cannot read data at a higher classification level and cannot write data to a lower classification level. Which model best fits this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces confidentiality through the Simple Security Property (no read up) and the *-Property (no write down). Biba addresses integrity with opposite rules, Clark-Wilson uses well-formed transactions for integrity, and Brewer-Nash (Chinese Wall) prevents conflicts of interest, not classification-based confidentiality.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester discovers that a malicious process on a multi-level secure system can leak classified information to a lower-clearance process by repeatedly acquiring and releasing a shared file lock in a specific pattern, encoding bits in the lock's presence or absence rather than in any elapsed time measurement. This is best classified as which type of covert channel?","o":["A timing covert channel","A storage covert channel","An overt channel exploiting a maintenance hook","A side-channel attack based on electromagnetic emanation"],"c":1,"why":"A storage covert channel encodes information by modulating a shared resource's state (like a lock flag) that another process can observe, without relying on timing. A timing channel would encode information in the rate or duration of events, and this scenario involves no legitimate authorized channel (ruling out 'overt') or physical emanations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial system must prevent lower-integrity processes from corrupting higher-integrity data, while allowing higher-integrity subjects to read lower-integrity data if needed. Which integrity model enforces 'no write up, no read down'?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Graham-Denning model","Take-Grant model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model protects data integrity using the Simple Integrity Property (no read down) and the *-Integrity Property (no write up), preventing contamination of trusted data by less trusted sources. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, and Graham-Denning/Take-Grant models focus on access rights management rather than integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In physical security design, what is the primary purpose of using bollards around a building perimeter?","o":["To detect unauthorized personnel entering a facility","To prevent vehicle-borne attacks by blocking vehicle access","To provide lighting for surveillance cameras at night","To control humidity and temperature near entry points"],"c":1,"why":"Bollards are sturdy posts installed to prevent vehicles from ramming into a building or restricted area. They are not detection devices, lighting fixtures, or environmental controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a product evaluation under the Common Criteria, a vendor claims their firewall achieved EAL7. What does this rating imply about the product compared to a product rated EAL2?","o":["EAL7 products are less expensive to certify than EAL2 products","EAL7 requires formal design verification and testing, representing a much higher assurance level than EAL2","EAL7 only applies to open-source software, unlike EAL2","EAL7 means the product has more features enabled by default than EAL2"],"c":1,"why":"Common Criteria EALs range from EAL1 (lowest) to EAL7 (highest), with EAL7 requiring formal methods for design verification and independent testing, indicating substantially higher assurance than the structured testing required at EAL2. EAL ratings reflect assurance rigor, not cost, licensing model, or feature count.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which cloud service model gives the customer the most control over the operating system and applications while the provider manages only the underlying hardware and virtualization layer?","o":["Software as a Service (SaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Function as a Service (FaaS)"],"c":2,"why":"IaaS provides virtualized computing resources (compute, storage, network) while leaving the OS, middleware, and applications under customer control. SaaS and PaaS abstract away more of the stack, and FaaS abstracts even the runtime environment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Two parties who have never communicated before need to establish a shared secret key over an untrusted network without exchanging the key itself in transit. Which cryptographic mechanism directly addresses this need?","o":["AES in CBC mode for bulk encryption","Diffie-Hellman key exchange","SHA-256 hashing of the shared secret","RSA digital signature generation"],"c":1,"why":"Diffie-Hellman allows two parties to derive a shared secret over an insecure channel using public value exchange, without ever transmitting the secret itself. AES is a symmetric cipher for encrypting data (not exchanging keys), hashing provides integrity/verification rather than key agreement, and RSA signatures provide authentication/non-repudiation, not key exchange in this classic sense.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants an independent, standardized way to evaluate the security assurance level of a vendor's product before purchase. Which framework would best support this goal?","o":["ITIL","Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408)","COBIT","Six Sigma"],"c":1,"why":"Common Criteria provides a standardized international framework (with Evaluation Assurance Levels) for assessing the security functionality and assurance of IT products. ITIL and COBIT are IT service/governance frameworks, and Six Sigma is a process improvement methodology, none of which evaluate product security assurance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is evaluating whether a proposed access control enforcement mechanism qualifies as a trustworthy reference monitor. Which of the following is NOT one of the required properties of a reference monitor?","o":["It must always be invoked for every access attempt (complete mediation)","It must be tamperproof","It must be small enough to be analyzed and verified","It must be backward compatible with all legacy operating systems"],"c":3,"why":"A reference monitor must satisfy three properties: always invoked, tamperproof, and small/verifiable enough for assurance. Backward compatibility with legacy systems is an engineering convenience, not a security assurance requirement of the reference monitor concept.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A database administrator notices that users without direct access to salary data can determine approximate salary ranges by correlating results from multiple permitted queries. This is an example of which security concern?","o":["SQL injection","Aggregation and inference","Buffer overflow","Cross-site scripting"],"c":1,"why":"Inference (often via aggregation of multiple lower-sensitivity queries) allows users to deduce restricted information indirectly. SQL injection and cross-site scripting are code-injection attacks, and buffer overflow is a memory corruption issue, none of which match this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"When generating a digital signature for a large document, why does the signer typically hash the document before encrypting the result with their private key, rather than encrypting the entire document directly?","o":["Hashing the document instead ensures the message stays confidential from the recipient","Hashing produces a fixed-length digest, making the signature process more efficient while still providing integrity and authenticity assurances","Hashing eliminates the need for a private key entirely","Hashing allows multiple recipients to decrypt the message using different keys"],"c":1,"why":"Signing the hash rather than the full message is far more computationally efficient since asymmetric encryption is slow, and the fixed-length digest still uniquely represents the document for integrity verification. Signing does not provide confidentiality (that requires separate encryption), still requires the private key, and does not inherently support multiple decryption keys.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center is upgrading its fire suppression system and considering why Halon-based systems, once common, are now largely prohibited for new installations. What is the primary reason for this shift?","o":["Halon is significantly more expensive to install than newer alternatives","Halon depletes the ozone layer and was restricted under international environmental agreements","Halon is ineffective against electrical fires","Halon requires human intervention to activate, unlike modern systems"],"c":1,"why":"Halon was phased out primarily due to its ozone-depleting properties under the Montreal Protocol, leading to clean-agent replacements like FM-200 and Inergen. Halon was actually effective and safe for electronics/electrical fires (a key reason it was popular), and both older and newer systems can be automatically triggered.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A penetration tester operating inside a virtual machine manages to gain unauthorized access to the underlying hypervisor and other guest VMs on the same host. What is this type of attack known as?","o":["VM sprawl","Live migration hijacking","VM escape","Snapshot poisoning"],"c":2,"why":"VM escape occurs when an attacker breaks out of an isolated guest VM to access the hypervisor or other VMs, violating the isolation the hypervisor is supposed to enforce. VM sprawl refers to uncontrolled proliferation of VMs, live migration hijacking targets the process of moving VMs between hosts, and snapshot poisoning involves tampering with saved VM states rather than breaking isolation directly.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to protect the confidentiality of information by preventing subjects from reading data at higher classification levels and writing data to lower classification levels?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces 'no read up, no write down' to protect confidentiality. Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson addresses integrity through transactions, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements the Bell-LaPadula security model on a classified system. A subject holding a 'Secret' clearance attempts to write data into a file classified as 'Unclassified.' Which property of the model prevents this action?","o":["The Simple Security Property (no read up)","The Star Property (no write down)","The Strong Star Property (no read or write to different levels)","The Discretionary Security Property"],"c":1,"why":"The Star (*) Property in Bell-LaPadula prevents a subject from writing data to an object at a lower classification level, which stops the disclosure of sensitive information (write-down). The Simple Security Property governs reading, not writing, and the other options describe different or nonexistent rules.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A multilevel secure system enforces the Bell-LaPadula model. A process running at the Top Secret level has been granted discretionary read/write permission on a file labeled Secret. When the process attempts to write to that file, the operation is denied by the reference monitor. Which principle explains this denial, and what is its purpose?","o":["The Simple Security Property, which prevents a subject from reading data at a higher classification than its own clearance","The *-Property (star property), which prevents a subject from writing data to an object at a lower classification, thereby stopping unauthorized disclosure","The Discretionary Security Property, which overrides mandatory controls when the owner grants explicit permission","The Strong Star Property, which requires subjects to have matching integrity and confidentiality levels before any write operation"],"c":1,"why":"The *-property (no write-down) blocks a higher-cleared subject from writing to a lower-classified object to prevent leakage of sensitive data, even if discretionary permissions would otherwise allow it. The simple security property governs reads (no read-up), and DAC cannot override MAC enforcement in BLP; the 'strong star property' is a stricter variant not applicable here since no matching-level requirement was described.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In a symmetric encryption algorithm, which statement best describes the key requirement?","o":["The same key is used for both encryption and decryption","A public key encrypts and a private key decrypts","Two different keys are mathematically related but not identical","No key is required for encryption or decryption"],"c":0,"why":"Symmetric encryption uses a single shared secret key for both encryption and decryption. The public/private key pair describes asymmetric encryption, and encryption always requires a key.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"In the Biba integrity model, a low-integrity subject attempts to directly invoke (execute) a high-integrity subject to have it perform an action on the low-integrity subject's behalf, effectively bypassing the no-write-up rule. Which Biba property is specifically designed to prevent this indirect attack?","o":["The Simple Integrity Property","The *-Integrity Property (no write-up)","The Invocation Property","The Discretionary Integrity Property"],"c":2,"why":"Biba's invocation property prevents a subject from invoking (calling) subjects at a higher integrity level, which closes the loophole where a low-integrity process could indirectly cause high-integrity code to act on its behalf. The simple integrity property blocks direct read-down and the *-integrity property blocks direct write-up, but neither addresses invocation/communication between subjects at different integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial application uses the Biba integrity model to protect transaction data. Which scenario would this model explicitly prevent?","o":["A high-integrity process reading data from a low-integrity source","A low-integrity process reading data from a high-integrity source","A high-integrity process writing data to a high-integrity object","A low-integrity process reading data from a low-integrity source"],"c":0,"why":"Biba's Simple Integrity Axiom (no read down) prevents a high-integrity subject from reading low-integrity data, which could corrupt the integrity of trusted processes. The other options are either permitted or unrelated to Biba's rules.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of a Trusted Computing Base (TCB) in a computer system?","o":["To encrypt all data at rest on the system","To provide network intrusion detection capabilities","To enforce the security policy of the system through hardware, firmware, and software mechanisms","To manage user password complexity requirements"],"c":2,"why":"The TCB is the totality of protection mechanisms within a system that work together to enforce a unified security policy. It is not specifically about encryption, IDS, or password policy, which are separate functions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing a TLS configuration and wants to ensure that even if the server's long-term RSA private key is compromised in the future, previously captured encrypted sessions cannot be decrypted retroactively. Which cryptographic design choice best achieves this?","o":["Use RSA key exchange with a 4096-bit key to maximize computational difficulty of factoring","Use static Diffie-Hellman with a key reused across sessions for efficiency","Use ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (DHE/ECDHE) to negotiate a unique session key for each session","Use a pre-shared symmetric key distributed out-of-band before each session"],"c":2,"why":"Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman generates a new, temporary key pair for each session, providing perfect forward secrecy—compromise of the server's static key does not expose past session keys. RSA key exchange and static DH both derive session keys from a long-term secret, so compromise of that secret retroactively exposes all captured traffic; a reused PSK has the same weakness.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During key establishment for a secure communication channel, two parties who have never met exchange public values over an insecure network to derive a shared secret key. Which cryptographic mechanism does this describe?","o":["RSA encryption of the session key","Diffie-Hellman key exchange","AES key wrapping","HMAC-based key derivation"],"c":1,"why":"Diffie-Hellman allows two parties to derive a shared secret over an insecure channel without directly transmitting the key, based on discrete logarithm math. RSA encrypts data directly, AES key wrapping requires a pre-shared key, and HMAC is used for integrity, not key exchange.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the concept of 'defense in depth' in security architecture?","o":["Relying on a single, highly robust firewall to protect the network perimeter","Implementing multiple layers of security controls so that if one fails, others still provide protection","Encrypting data multiple times using the same algorithm","Placing all security responsibility on the end user"],"c":1,"why":"Defense in depth uses multiple, overlapping layers of controls so no single point of failure compromises the system. Relying on one control or one algorithm contradicts this layered approach.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization is evaluating two products under Common Criteria: Product A holds EAL4 certification against a network firewall Protection Profile, and Product B holds EAL2 against the same Protection Profile. What is the most accurate interpretation of these ratings?","o":["Product A has more security features and functions than Product B because higher EAL numbers always include additional functional requirements","Product A has undergone more rigorous and thorough independent assurance testing that its stated security functions were correctly implemented, but this says nothing about which product has richer functionality","Product B is inherently less secure in operation because it has a lower Evaluation Assurance Level","Both products meet identical assurance requirements since they were evaluated against the same Protection Profile"],"c":1,"why":"EAL ratings measure the depth and rigor of assurance activities (evaluation methodology), not the richness of security functionality—that is defined by the Protection Profile/Security Target. A higher EAL means more confidence that the claimed functions work as specified, not more functions, and it does not by itself guarantee superior real-world security posture; evaluating against the same PP means functional claims are comparable, but assurance rigor still differs by EAL.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A company is evaluating a new operating system against internationally recognized security assurance requirements before purchasing. Which framework would they most likely use?","o":["Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408)","ITIL","COBIT","Six Sigma"],"c":0,"why":"Common Criteria is the international standard used to evaluate and certify the security assurance level of IT products. ITIL and COBIT are IT service/governance frameworks, and Six Sigma is a process improvement methodology, not a security evaluation standard.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A vendor submits a firewall product for Common Criteria evaluation and receives an EAL4 rating. What does this rating primarily indicate?","o":["The product is more secure than one rated EAL2","The product has been functionally tested against industry benchmarks for performance","The level of assurance that the product was tested and documented according to defined rigor, not the strength of its security functions","The product meets FIPS 140-2 Level 4 cryptographic requirements"],"c":2,"why":"EAL ratings reflect the depth and rigor of the assurance evaluation process (documentation, testing methodology), not a direct measure of how 'secure' the product's functionality is compared to another EAL level. FIPS 140-2 is a separate cryptographic standard unrelated to Common Criteria EALs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Security researchers discover that a multi-tenant hypervisor allows a malicious VM to infer cryptographic key bits from a co-located victim VM by repeatedly measuring shared CPU cache access latency during the victim's encryption operations. This attack is best classified as which type of vulnerability?","o":["A covert storage channel exploiting shared memory allocation tables","A covert timing channel exploiting shared hardware resource contention to leak information across an isolation boundary","A TOCTOU (time-of-check to time-of-use) race condition within the hypervisor scheduler","A discretionary access control bypass due to misconfigured VM permissions"],"c":1,"why":"This describes a covert timing channel: information is leaked by observing variations in timing caused by contention for a shared resource (CPU cache), not through an explicit storage location. It is not a storage channel (no shared writable object is being directly read), not a TOCTOU race, and not an access control misconfiguration since isolation is bypassed via a side channel rather than permission flaws.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A web application's authentication module encounters an unexpected exception during login processing. Following secure design principles, what should the system do by default?","o":["Grant the user access to avoid disrupting business operations","Log the error and allow the session to continue in a degraded state","Deny access and terminate the session, defaulting to a secure state","Prompt the user to retry the same credentials indefinitely"],"c":2,"why":"The 'fail securely' design principle dictates that when an error occurs, the system should default to denying access rather than granting it, preventing exploitation of error conditions. Granting access or continuing in a degraded state violates this principle and could expose the system to compromise.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which physical security control is specifically designed to prevent unauthorized vehicles from ramming into a facility entrance?","o":["Turnstile","Mantrap","Bollard","Faraday cage"],"c":2,"why":"Bollards are sturdy vertical posts designed to stop vehicle intrusion. Turnstiles and mantraps control pedestrian access, and a Faraday cage blocks electromagnetic signals, not vehicles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A developer notices that a file permission check occurs, followed by a delay, before the file is actually opened and used by the application. An attacker could exploit this gap by swapping the file after the check but before the use. What type of vulnerability is this?","o":["Buffer overflow","Time-of-check to time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","SQL injection","Cross-site request forgery"],"c":1,"why":"TOCTOU vulnerabilities occur when there is a time gap between validating a resource's state and using it, allowing an attacker to alter the resource in that window. Buffer overflows involve memory corruption, SQL injection targets database queries, and CSRF exploits authenticated web sessions—none match this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In cryptography, what is the main advantage of asymmetric encryption over symmetric encryption?","o":["It is significantly faster for encrypting large volumes of data","It eliminates the need for secure key distribution because public keys can be shared openly","It uses shorter keys for the same level of security","It does not require any mathematical computation"],"c":1,"why":"Asymmetric encryption solves the key distribution problem because the public key can be freely shared while the private key remains secret. It is actually slower than symmetric encryption and typically requires longer keys.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A hardware root of trust uses a TPM to support measured boot. During startup, the TPM extends a series of Platform Configuration Registers (PCRs) with hash measurements of firmware, bootloader, and OS kernel components before execution. What is the primary security benefit this provides to a remote party performing attestation?","o":["It encrypts all boot components so that unauthorized firmware cannot execute on the device","It allows the remote party to cryptographically verify, via signed PCR values, that the boot chain matches a known-good configuration and has not been tampered with","It automatically patches any firmware components that do not match expected hash values before continuing the boot process","It prevents the device from booting entirely if any single PCR value changes, ensuring only the original OS image can ever run"],"c":1,"why":"Measured boot records hashes of each boot component in PCRs; the TPM can sign these values (quote) so a remote verifier can confirm the boot state matches an expected baseline, detecting tampering without necessarily blocking boot. It does not encrypt or auto-patch components, and measured boot itself does not halt execution on mismatch (that is the role of secure/trusted boot enforcement, a distinct mechanism).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that a received message's authenticity and integrity can be verified, and that the sender cannot later deny having sent it. Which process best achieves this?","o":["Encrypting the message with the recipient's public key","Hashing the message and encrypting the hash with the sender's private key to create a digital signature","Encrypting the message with a shared symmetric key known only to sender and recipient","Hashing the message and storing the hash value in a separate access-controlled database"],"c":1,"why":"A digital signature—created by hashing the message and encrypting the hash with the sender's private key—provides authentication, integrity, and non-repudiation because only the sender's private key could have produced a signature verifiable with their public key. The other options either provide confidentiality only or fail to prove sender identity uniquely.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which secure design principle states that a system should grant users only the access rights necessary to perform their job functions?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege","Security through obscurity","Defense in depth"],"c":1,"why":"Least privilege ensures subjects are granted only the minimum access needed to perform authorized tasks. Separation of duties splits critical tasks among multiple people, and security through obscurity relies on hiding design details rather than restricting access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center processing highly classified information is designed with shielding that blocks electromagnetic emissions from leaving the building, preventing eavesdroppers from intercepting signals from computer equipment. This design addresses which security concern?","o":["Electromagnetic interference (EMI) affecting equipment reliability","TEMPEST-related emanation eavesdropping","Static electricity discharge damaging hardware","Fire suppression system interference with electronics"],"c":1,"why":"TEMPEST refers to standards for shielding equipment and facilities against compromising electromagnetic emanations that could be intercepted to reconstruct processed data. EMI reliability, static discharge, and fire suppression are unrelated physical/environmental concerns, not emanation security.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A subject holding a Secret clearance attempts to write data into a file object classified as Confidential (a lower classification). Under the Bell-LaPadula model, which property prevents this write operation?","o":["Simple security property (no read up)","Star property (no write down)","Discretionary security property","Strong star property"],"c":1,"why":"The star (*) property of Bell-LaPadula prevents a subject from writing data to an object of a lower classification, protecting confidentiality by stopping data from flowing downward. The simple security property governs reads, not writes, and the strong star property is a stricter variant not violated here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A process operating at a High integrity level in a system implementing the Biba integrity model attempts to read data from an object classified at a Low integrity level. Which Biba rule blocks this action?","o":["The *-integrity axiom (no write up)","The invocation property","The simple integrity axiom (no read down)","The simple security property"],"c":2,"why":"Biba's simple integrity axiom prevents a high-integrity subject from reading lower-integrity data, since doing so could contaminate its integrity level. The *-integrity axiom governs writes, and the simple security property belongs to Bell-LaPadula, not Biba.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Two parties who have never communicated before need to establish a shared symmetric session key over an insecure network without any pre-shared secret. Which technique is specifically designed to accomplish this?","o":["Diffie-Hellman key exchange","Encrypting the key with 3DES using a default key","Hashing both parties' identities with SHA-256","Exchanging the key using a digital signature algorithm alone"],"c":0,"why":"Diffie-Hellman allows two parties to derive a shared secret over an insecure channel without prior shared secrets, using asymmetric mathematics. Symmetric encryption requires a pre-shared key, hashing does not establish a shared secret, and digital signatures provide authentication/integrity, not key agreement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A system enforces the Bell-LaPadula model with strict mandatory access controls. A process running at the Secret clearance level attempts to write output to a file object labeled Confidential. Which principle of the model prevents this operation, and what is its purpose?","o":["The Simple Security Property, which prevents a subject from reading objects at a higher classification level","The *-property (star property), which prevents a subject from writing to objects at a lower classification level","The Strong Star Property, which prohibits all write operations regardless of classification level","The Discretionary Security Property, which relies on owner-assigned access control lists"],"c":1,"why":"The *-property (no write-down) prevents a higher-cleared subject from writing data into a lower-classified object, which would leak sensitive information. The Simple Security Property governs reads (no read-up), the Strong Star Property is a stricter variant requiring exact level matching for both read and write, and discretionary controls are not part of the formal MAC lattice enforcement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Which term specifically describes the portion of the Trusted Computing Base that implements the reference monitor concept, mediating every access attempt between subjects and objects?","o":["Security kernel","Security perimeter","Trusted path","Security domain"],"c":0,"why":"The security kernel is the hardware/software/firmware combination within the TCB that enforces the reference monitor concept for all subject-object interactions. The security perimeter defines the TCB's boundary, the trusted path is a protected communication channel, and a security domain is a set of resources sharing a common policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements a mandatory access control model in which a subject with a 'Secret' clearance can read documents classified 'Secret' or 'Confidential' but cannot read documents classified 'Top Secret'. This model also prevents the subject from writing information to a document classified at a lower level than their own clearance. Which security model does this describe?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces confidentiality with the 'no read up, no write down' rules described. Biba addresses integrity (opposite rules), Clark-Wilson enforces integrity through well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to preserve data integrity by preventing unauthorized users from modifying data and preventing authorized users from making improper modifications?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","Graham-Denning model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model focuses on integrity using 'no read down, no write up' rules to prevent corruption of higher-integrity data. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, while Take-Grant and Graham-Denning deal with rights propagation and access control, not integrity specifically.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization requires a Common Criteria evaluation level that indicates the product was 'methodically tested and checked' by the vendor, providing a moderate level of independently assured confidence without requiring formal design verification. Which EAL best matches this requirement?","o":["EAL1","EAL3","EAL5","EAL7"],"c":1,"why":"EAL3 corresponds to 'methodically tested and checked,' offering moderate assurance through structured testing without demanding semiformal or formal design verification. EAL1 offers only minimal functional testing, while EAL5 and EAL7 require increasingly rigorous semiformal/formal methods.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which characteristic best distinguishes symmetric key cryptography from asymmetric key cryptography?","o":["Symmetric cryptography uses a single shared key for both encryption and decryption","Symmetric cryptography provides non-repudiation while asymmetric does not","Symmetric cryptography is primarily used for digital signatures","Symmetric cryptography does not require the key to be kept secret"],"c":0,"why":"Symmetric algorithms use one shared secret key for both encryption and decryption, making key distribution a challenge. Asymmetric cryptography, not symmetric, is typically used for digital signatures and non-repudiation, and symmetric keys must remain secret.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A developer wants to make it significantly harder for an attacker exploiting a buffer overflow to reliably jump to a predictable memory location to execute injected shellcode. Which control directly addresses this by randomizing memory locations at each execution?","o":["Data Execution Prevention (DEP)","Stack canaries","Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)","Input validation"],"c":2,"why":"ASLR randomizes the memory addresses of key data areas each time a program runs, making it difficult for an attacker to predict target addresses. DEP prevents code execution in data regions but doesn't randomize addresses, stack canaries detect overflow after the fact, and input validation prevents malformed input rather than addressing memory layout.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a mandatory access control model in which a subject with a 'Secret' clearance is prevented from reading data classified 'Top Secret,' but is permitted to write to files classified 'Top Secret.' Which security model does this behavior describe?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces 'no read up, no write down' to protect confidentiality, allowing a lower-cleared subject to write up (blind write) but not read up. Biba addresses integrity (opposite rules), Clark-Wilson uses well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of a cryptographic hash function in a security architecture?","o":["To provide confidentiality by encrypting data","To verify data integrity by producing a fixed-size fingerprint of the data","To establish a secure session key between two parties","To provide non-repudiation through asymmetric key pairs"],"c":1,"why":"Hash functions generate a fixed-length digest used to detect changes in data, ensuring integrity. They do not encrypt data (no confidentiality) and are not used for key exchange or asymmetric signing on their own.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A vulnerability allows a malicious process running inside a guest virtual machine to break out of its isolation and gain direct, unauthorized access to the hypervisor or other guest VMs on the same host. This is best described as:","o":["VM sprawl","Hyperjacking","VM escape","A side-channel attack"],"c":2,"why":"VM escape occurs when malicious code breaks out of the VM's isolation boundary to access the hypervisor or other VMs. VM sprawl refers to uncontrolled proliferation of unmanaged VMs, hyperjacking involves installing a rogue hypervisor beneath the legitimate one, and side-channel attacks exploit indirect physical characteristics rather than breaking VM isolation directly.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Which security model is primarily concerned with preventing unauthorized modification of data and enforces the principle that a subject cannot read data of a lower integrity level or write to data of a higher integrity level?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","Graham-Denning model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model focuses on integrity and enforces 'no read down, no write up' to prevent contamination of high-integrity data by lower-integrity subjects. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, while Take-Grant and Graham-Denning are access-rights transfer models, not confidentiality/integrity lattice models.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In the context of the Trusted Computing Base (TCB), what is the role of the reference monitor?","o":["It encrypts all data in transit between subjects and objects","It mediates all access between subjects and objects, enforcing the system's security policy","It performs periodic vulnerability scans on the operating system","It generates audit logs for regulatory compliance only"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept that mediates every access request between subjects and objects to enforce security policy; it must be tamperproof, always invoked, and small enough to verify. It is not primarily an encryption tool, scanner, or logging utility.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A financial application enforces the Biba integrity model to protect the accuracy of transaction data. A low-integrity process (e.g., a script pulling data from an untrusted external feed) attempts to write directly into a high-integrity ledger database. What does Biba's simple integrity axiom dictate, and what is the security rationale?","o":["The write is permitted because Biba only restricts read operations across integrity levels","The write is denied under the *-integrity property, which prevents a subject from reading down, but writing up is unrestricted","The write is denied under the simple integrity axiom ('no write up'), because allowing low-integrity data to contaminate a high-integrity object would corrupt trusted data","The write is denied because Biba enforces confidentiality controls that block cross-level writes regardless of integrity level"],"c":2,"why":"Biba's simple integrity axiom ('no write up') blocks a low-integrity subject from writing to a higher-integrity object to prevent contamination; Biba is an integrity model unrelated to confidentiality, and the *-integrity property actually prevents 'write up,' not read-down, making the other choices wrong.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An insider embeds hidden information by deliberately varying the intervals between network packets sent from a compromised host, allowing a confederate observing the traffic pattern to reconstruct a secret message. This is an example of:","o":["A covert storage channel","A covert timing channel","An inference attack","An aggregation attack"],"c":1,"why":"A covert timing channel conveys information by modulating the timing or sequencing of events (such as packet intervals) rather than by altering stored data. A covert storage channel would use a data field or shared storage resource instead, while inference and aggregation attacks relate to deriving unauthorized conclusions from legitimately accessible data, not timing-based signaling.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to securely exchange a symmetric session key between two parties over an insecure channel without prior shared secrets. Which approach best accomplishes this?","o":["Use a symmetric algorithm like AES to encrypt the session key before transmission","Use an asymmetric algorithm to encrypt the symmetric key with the recipient's public key","Hash the session key with SHA-256 before sending it","Use a message authentication code (MAC) to protect the session key in transit"],"c":1,"why":"Asymmetric encryption solves the key distribution problem because the sender can encrypt the symmetric key with the recipient's public key, which only the recipient's private key can decrypt. Symmetric encryption requires a pre-shared key, hashing is one-way and doesn't allow key recovery, and a MAC provides integrity/authentication, not confidentiality of the key.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A data center houses sensitive electronic equipment. Which fire suppression method is generally preferred to minimize damage to electronic equipment while still effectively extinguishing fires?","o":["Water sprinkler systems","Clean agent (gaseous) suppression systems","Wet chemical foam systems","Dry chemical powder systems"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agent gaseous systems (such as FM-200 or inert gases) extinguish fires without leaving residue or moisture, protecting sensitive electronics. Water, wet chemical, and dry powder systems can cause corrosion, residue, or short circuits.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a Common Criteria evaluation, an evaluator reviews two separate documents: one describing a generic, implementation-independent set of security requirements for a class of products (e.g., firewalls), and another describing the specific security claims and implementation details of a vendor's particular product being evaluated. What are these two documents called, respectively?","o":["Security Target and Target of Evaluation","Target of Evaluation and Protection Profile","Protection Profile and Security Target","Evaluation Assurance Level and Security Target"],"c":2,"why":"A Protection Profile (PP) is a reusable, implementation-independent statement of security requirements for a product category, while a Security Target (ST) contains the specific security claims for the actual product under evaluation (the Target of Evaluation, TOE); the other pairings mix up or omit these definitions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In a cloud computing service model, which option describes 'Infrastructure as a Service' (IaaS)?","o":["The provider manages the application code and the customer only manages data","The provider offers fully developed software applications accessible via a browser","The provider supplies virtualized computing resources such as servers, storage, and networking, while the customer manages the operating system and applications","The provider manages only the physical hardware layer with no virtualization involved"],"c":2,"why":"IaaS provides virtualized infrastructure (compute, storage, networking) that customers use to deploy and manage their own OS and applications. Managing applications describes PaaS/SaaS, and fully developed software describes SaaS.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Two parties use an unauthenticated Diffie-Hellman key exchange over an untrusted network to establish a shared symmetric key. An attacker positioned on the network path is able to establish separate DH exchanges with each party, decrypting and re-encrypting traffic transparently. What is the fundamental weakness being exploited, and what control would best remediate it?","o":["DH exchanges are mathematically breakable via factorization, so the fix is switching to a larger prime modulus","DH provides no inherent authentication of the exchanging parties; the fix is to authenticate the exchange using digital certificates or pre-shared authenticated keys","DH is vulnerable because it uses symmetric keys during negotiation; the fix is to use only asymmetric encryption throughout","DH exchanges cannot generate sufficiently random keys, so the fix is to use a hardware security module for key storage"],"c":1,"why":"Diffie-Hellman secures the key exchange mathematically but does not authenticate the identities of the participants, enabling a man-in-the-middle attack; authenticating the exchange (e.g., with certificates/PKI) closes this gap. The other options misattribute the vulnerability to factorization, key type, or randomness, none of which is the actual weakness here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"In the context of trusted computing, which component is responsible for mediating all access between subjects and objects to enforce a security policy, and must itself be tamperproof, always invoked, and small enough to verify?","o":["Security kernel","Reference monitor","Trusted computing base","Security perimeter"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept that mediates all subject-object access and must be tamperproof, always invoked, and verifiable. The security kernel is the hardware/software/firmware implementation of the reference monitor concept, the TCB is the totality of protection mechanisms, and the security perimeter is the boundary separating the TCB from the rest of the system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing a reference monitor to mediate all access requests between subjects and objects on a highly sensitive system. Which combination of properties MUST the reference monitor implementation satisfy to be considered a valid trusted enforcement mechanism?","o":["It must be fast, scalable, and written in a memory-safe language","It must be tamper-proof, always invoked (non-bypassable), and small enough to be verified formally","It must reside in user space, log all decisions to a remote SIEM, and support role-based access control","It must be redundant across multiple physical hosts, encrypted at rest, and FIPS 140-2 validated"],"c":1,"why":"A reference monitor must be tamper-proof, always invoked for every access attempt, and small/verifiable enough to allow assurance of correctness — these are the classic three properties from the reference monitor concept underlying trusted computing base design; the other option sets describe desirable engineering qualities but not the defining security properties.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a Common Criteria evaluation, a product is assessed at EAL4. What does this evaluation assurance level primarily indicate about the product?","o":["The product has been formally verified to be mathematically secure against all known attacks","The product has undergone methodical design, testing, and review, providing moderate assurance without formal verification","The product meets the minimum requirements for government classified data processing","The product has been certified free of all exploitable vulnerabilities"],"c":1,"why":"EAL4 represents methodically designed, tested, and reviewed assurance—a common target for commercial products—without requiring formal mathematical proofs (reserved for higher EALs like EAL7). No EAL guarantees a product is free of all vulnerabilities or mathematically proven secure, and EAL levels are independent of specific government classification requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise migrates workloads to a virtualized environment using a bare-metal (Type 1) hypervisor. A security researcher demonstrates a VM escape exploit that allows a compromised guest VM to execute arbitrary code on the hypervisor itself, potentially affecting all co-resident guests. Which architectural characteristic makes this attack particularly severe compared to compromising a single physical host?","o":["The hypervisor runs at a lower privilege ring than guest operating systems, so guest compromise automatically grants hypervisor access","The hypervisor mediates hardware access for all guests, so a successful escape can break isolation and compromise every VM sharing that physical host","Type 1 hypervisors always share a single kernel with the host OS, making guest and host compromise equivalent","VM escape is only theoretical against Type 1 hypervisors because they lack a management OS attack surface"],"c":1,"why":"Because a Type 1 hypervisor mediates hardware and resource access for every guest VM on that host, a successful escape breaks the isolation boundary and can expose or compromise all co-resident VMs, making it far more severe than a single-host compromise; the other statements misdescribe hypervisor privilege rings, kernel sharing, and attack surface.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is evaluating hypervisor types for a private cloud deployment. Which characteristic best distinguishes a Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor from a Type 2 (hosted) hypervisor?","o":["Type 1 hypervisors run directly on hardware without a host operating system, reducing the attack surface compared to Type 2","Type 1 hypervisors require a full host OS to manage hardware resources, while Type 2 hypervisors do not","Type 2 hypervisors offer better isolation between virtual machines because they run within an OS sandbox","Type 1 hypervisors are only used for desktop virtualization, while Type 2 hypervisors are used in enterprise data centers"],"c":0,"why":"Type 1 hypervisors run directly on the hardware, eliminating the need for an underlying general-purpose OS and reducing the attack surface, making them preferred for enterprise/cloud environments. Type 2 hypervisors run atop a host OS, which increases the attack surface; the other options misstate isolation benefits and typical use cases.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants near-real-time certificate revocation checking during the TLS handshake without adding an extra round trip for the client and without exposing the client's browsing patterns to the CA's revocation responder. Which mechanism best satisfies all these requirements?","o":["Standard Certificate Revocation Lists (CRLs)","Client-initiated OCSP queries to the CA's responder","OCSP stapling, where the server periodically obtains and attaches a signed OCSP response to the handshake","Delta CRLs distributed at shorter intervals than full CRLs"],"c":2,"why":"OCSP stapling lets the server fetch and cache the signed revocation status and present it directly to clients, eliminating client-to-CA round trips and privacy leakage. Standard CRLs are large and updated infrequently, client-initiated OCSP exposes browsing patterns to the CA and adds latency, and Delta CRLs still require periodic distribution and don't solve the privacy or latency problem.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A data center design team is selecting a fire suppression system for a room housing high-value electrical and networking equipment. Which choice best balances effective fire suppression with minimizing damage to sensitive electronics, and why?","o":["A wet-pipe water sprinkler system, because water is inexpensive and universally effective against electrical fires","A clean agent (e.g., inert gas or halocarbon) suppression system, because it extinguishes fire by displacing oxygen or interrupting the combustion chemical reaction without leaving conductive residue","A CO2 flood system in an occupied area, because CO2 is non-conductive and safe for personnel present during discharge","A dry chemical powder system, because the powder residue is easily cleaned and does not affect circuit boards"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agents suppress fire without leaving conductive or corrosive residue and are safe for use around electronics, making them the standard choice for data centers; water damages electronics, CO2 displaces oxygen and is dangerous to occupants (requiring evacuation before discharge), and dry chemical residue can damage sensitive circuitry.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center is designing its physical security controls and must select an appropriate fire suppression system for a room containing sensitive servers and no human occupants during normal operation. Which agent is most appropriate?","o":["Water sprinkler (wet pipe) system","Carbon dioxide (CO2) gas suppression system","Class A dry chemical extinguisher only","Halon 1211 handheld extinguishers as the sole suppression method"],"c":1,"why":"CO2 suppression systems are effective for Class C (electrical) fires and safe to use in unoccupied server rooms since they displace oxygen without leaving residue, though they are dangerous for occupied spaces. Water systems can damage electronics, Class A extinguishers are for combustible materials not electrical equipment, and Halon is largely phased out and impractical as a sole automated system for a data center.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a security review, an auditor discovers that a process on a multilevel secure system can signal information to a lower-classified process by deliberately varying its CPU utilization patterns, even though no direct read/write access between the two processes is permitted by the access control policy. What type of vulnerability does this represent, and what is the most accurate characterization?","o":["A covert timing channel, which exploits a shared resource's temporal behavior to transfer information outside sanctioned communication paths","A covert storage channel, because CPU utilization data is written to a shared storage medium accessible to both processes","A traditional access control bypass exploiting a missing discretionary access control entry","A side-channel attack against cryptographic key material through power analysis"],"c":0,"why":"Encoding information through timing/resource-usage patterns (like CPU utilization) rather than through a shared data storage location is the hallmark of a covert timing channel; a storage channel would involve a shared writable attribute/location, and this scenario is not an ACL misconfiguration or a cryptographic power-analysis side channel.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A vendor submits a database product for Common Criteria evaluation. Evaluators compare the product's specific security claims document against a generic, reusable set of security requirements defined for that class of products. Which two artifacts represent this relationship, respectively?","o":["A Security Target (product-specific claims) satisfying a Protection Profile (generic class requirements)","A Target of Evaluation (TOE) satisfying a Security Target (ST)","An Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) satisfying a Protection Profile (PP)","A Protection Profile (PP) satisfying a Security Target (ST)"],"c":0,"why":"The Protection Profile defines generic, reusable security requirements for a product category, while the Security Target contains the specific security claims for the actual product being evaluated, which must meet or exceed the PP. The TOE is the product itself (not a document), and EAL is an assurance rating, not a requirements document satisfying a PP.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Which cryptographic attack exploits the mathematical probability that two different inputs will produce the same hash output, and is a key reason hash functions must have sufficiently large output sizes?","o":["Chosen-plaintext attack","Meet-in-the-middle attack","Birthday attack","Replay attack"],"c":2,"why":"A birthday attack leverages the birthday paradox to find hash collisions faster than brute force, which is why hash output length (e.g., SHA-256 vs MD5) matters for collision resistance. Chosen-plaintext and meet-in-the-middle attacks target encryption algorithms, and a replay attack involves retransmitting captured data, unrelated to hash collisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A hardware security module performing RSA private-key operations is found vulnerable to an attack in which fluctuations in power consumption during modular exponentiation statistically correlate with individual key bits, allowing key recovery. Which countermeasure most directly mitigates this specific attack?","o":["Increasing the RSA key length to 4096 bits","Implementing blinding or randomized exponentiation techniques to decorrelate power traces from key bits","Enforcing strict input validation on all API calls to the module","Rotating the RSA key pair more frequently"],"c":1,"why":"Blinding/randomization techniques break the statistical correlation between power consumption and key bits, directly defeating differential power analysis (DPA). Longer keys increase computational cost but not resistance to power analysis, input validation addresses a different attack surface, and key rotation only shrinks the exposure window without preventing leakage during each operation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A cloud provider hosts multiple tenants on Type 1 hypervisors. Researchers discover a vulnerability allowing a malicious guest VM to execute code that breaks its isolation boundary and gain control over the hypervisor itself. Which term most precisely describes this attack?","o":["VM sprawl","VM escape","Hyperjacking caused by a misconfigured Type 2 hypervisor","A cross-VM cache side-channel attack"],"c":1,"why":"VM escape specifically describes a guest breaking out of its VM boundary to compromise the hypervisor or host. VM sprawl refers to uncontrolled proliferation of unmanaged VMs, hyperjacking typically involves an attacker inserting a rogue hypervisor beneath the legitimate one (not escaping from a guest), and cross-VM cache attacks are passive information leakage rather than gaining hypervisor control.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A SCIF processing SCI-level data has copper mesh shielding installed in the walls, floor, and ceiling specifically to prevent adversaries from remotely intercepting electromagnetic emanations from computing equipment. This control is best classified as which type of countermeasure?","o":["A Faraday cage implementing TEMPEST shielding requirements","White noise generation to mask emanations","Red/black signal separation of classified and unclassified cabling","Fiber optic cabling to eliminate electromagnetic emissions from data lines"],"c":0,"why":"Copper mesh shielding of an entire room creates a Faraday cage, a TEMPEST countermeasure that blocks electromagnetic emanations from leaving the facility. White noise jams/masks emissions rather than blocking them, red/black separation addresses cable and equipment segregation rather than whole-room shielding, and fiber optic cabling reduces emissions only from the cable itself, not from all equipment in the room.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security tester observes that a low-integrity process can infer operational details about a high-integrity process by measuring variations in CPU scheduling response times, even though the two processes share no common file, memory segment, or other observable storage object. This is best classified as which type of covert channel or attack?","o":["A storage covert channel","A timing covert channel","A database inference attack","A side-channel attack exploiting shared CPU cache lines"],"c":1,"why":"A timing covert channel conveys information by modulating the timing of a shared resource (here, CPU scheduling), requiring no shared storage object, matching this scenario exactly. A storage covert channel requires a shared, observable storage location, database inference attacks involve deducing restricted data from aggregated query results, and cache side-channel attacks specifically exploit cache state rather than generic scheduling timing as described.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements a security model in which a subject with a 'Secret' clearance can read documents classified 'Secret' or 'Confidential' but cannot read documents classified 'Top Secret', and cannot write to a document classified 'Confidential'. Which security model does this describe?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces confidentiality with the 'no read up, no write down' rules, matching the scenario. Biba focuses on integrity, Clark-Wilson uses well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily concerned with preventing unauthorized modification of data and enforces the rule that a subject cannot write to an object of a higher integrity level nor read data from a lower integrity level?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","State machine model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model protects data integrity using 'no write up, no read down' rules. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, Take-Grant models rights transfer, and the state machine model is a general concept for secure state transitions, not specifically integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes a key characteristic of symmetric key cryptography compared to asymmetric key cryptography?","o":["It uses a public and private key pair for encryption and decryption","It is generally faster and used for encrypting large volumes of data","It provides non-repudiation through digital signatures","It eliminates the need for secure key distribution"],"c":1,"why":"Symmetric cryptography uses one shared key and is computationally efficient, making it suitable for bulk data encryption. Asymmetric cryptography uses key pairs, supports non-repudiation via digital signatures, and symmetric systems still require secure key exchange.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A Trusted Platform Module (TPM) is primarily used to:","o":["Encrypt network traffic between two hosts","Store cryptographic keys and support hardware-based device authentication and integrity checks","Provide load balancing for encrypted sessions","Act as a certificate authority for an enterprise PKI"],"c":1,"why":"A TPM is a hardware chip that securely stores cryptographic keys and supports functions like secure boot and hardware attestation. It does not encrypt network traffic, perform load balancing, or serve as a full PKI certificate authority.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization deploys firewalls, intrusion detection systems, endpoint antivirus, and security awareness training as part of its security strategy. This approach best exemplifies which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity"],"c":2,"why":"Defense in depth uses multiple, layered security controls so that if one fails, others still provide protection. Least privilege and separation of duties relate to access control, and security through obscurity relies on hiding details rather than layering controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A data center uses electronic door locks that automatically unlock during a power failure to allow emergency evacuation. This is an example of which type of lock configuration?","o":["Fail-secure","Fail-safe","Cipher lock","Deadbolt lock"],"c":1,"why":"Fail-safe locks unlock during a power failure to prioritize life safety and evacuation. Fail-secure locks remain locked to protect assets, while cipher and deadbolt locks describe lock mechanisms, not power-failure behavior.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to protect data confidentiality by preventing information from flowing from a higher security level to a lower one?","o":["Biba model","Bell-LaPadula model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":1,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces 'no read up, no write down' to protect confidentiality. Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson enforces well-formed transactions for integrity, and Brewer-Nash (Chinese Wall) prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which method provides the most secure way to ensure that data on a magnetic hard drive cannot be recovered before the drive is repurposed for a lower classification environment?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive with a quick format","Degaussing the drive with a strong magnetic field","Renaming the file extensions"],"c":2,"why":"Degaussing exposes magnetic media to a strong magnetic field, effectively destroying stored data beyond recovery. Deleting files, quick formatting, or renaming extensions only remove file references, leaving the actual data recoverable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In a virtualized data center, which component is primarily responsible for allocating physical hardware resources to multiple virtual machines and enforcing isolation between them?","o":["Hypervisor","Virtual switch","Guest operating system","Storage area network controller"],"c":0,"why":"The hypervisor manages and allocates physical CPU, memory, and I/O resources to virtual machines while maintaining isolation between them. A virtual switch handles network traffic, the guest OS runs within a VM, and a SAN controller manages storage, not overall VM resource allocation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that lower-integrity data cannot corrupt higher-integrity data within its systems. Which security model best supports this goal?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","Graham-Denning model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model enforces 'no write up, no read down' to preserve data integrity. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, while Take-Grant and Graham-Denning focus on access rights management rather than integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A hospital's clinical decision-support system enforces the Biba integrity model. A high-integrity diagnostic process attempts to read data from a low-integrity, unvalidated sensor feed to incorporate into its calculations. Under strict Biba enforcement, what happens and why?","o":["The read is denied by the Simple Integrity Axiom (no read-down), because incorporating lower-integrity data could contaminate the high-integrity process","The read is denied by the *-Integrity Axiom (no write-up), because the sensor feed is attempting to write to the diagnostic process","The read is permitted because Biba only restricts write operations, not read operations, between integrity levels","The read is permitted because the diagnostic process has a higher clearance and Biba grants read access to all lower levels"],"c":0,"why":"Biba's Simple Integrity Axiom prohibits a subject from reading an object of lower integrity ('no read-down') to prevent contamination of trusted processes with untrusted data. The *-Integrity Axiom governs writing to higher levels, not this scenario, and Biba explicitly restricts reads, making the other options incorrect.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect must choose a block cipher mode for a high-throughput financial messaging system that requires both confidentiality and built-in message authentication without a separate MAC computation pass. Which mode best satisfies this requirement, and what is the primary architectural reason?","o":["CBC mode, because chaining ciphertext blocks inherently authenticates message integrity","ECB mode, because independent block encryption allows parallel authentication checks","GCM mode, because it combines counter-mode encryption with a Galois field MAC (GHASH) in a single pass, providing authenticated encryption","CFB mode, because feedback of ciphertext into the keystream generation authenticates each block"],"c":2,"why":"GCM (Galois/Counter Mode) is an AEAD mode that performs encryption and authentication in one pass, using GHASH to generate an authentication tag alongside CTR-mode encryption. CBC, ECB, and CFB provide confidentiality only and require a separate MAC (e.g., HMAC) to achieve authenticated encryption; CBC chaining does not provide authentication guarantees against tampering.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A government evaluator is assessing a product under the Common Criteria and determines that the vendor's design documentation includes only a functional specification and high-level design, with testing performed by the vendor and independently verified by evaluators, but no formal mathematical proof of the security policy model. This evaluation most likely corresponds to which EAL, and why?","o":["EAL1, because only basic functional testing was performed with no design documentation required","EAL4, because it requires methodical design, testing, and review but not formal verification methods","EAL7, because independent testing by evaluators is only required at the highest assurance level","EAL2, because structural testing alone is sufficient evidence for any EAL above baseline"],"c":1,"why":"EAL4 requires methodical design, implementation evidence, and independent testing/review but stops short of the formal, mathematically verified design and proof required at EAL7. EAL1 requires far less documentation, EAL7 mandates formal verification, and EAL2 requires only structural testing with less rigorous design analysis than described.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a covert channel analysis of a multi-level secure operating system, auditors discover that a low-clearance process can infer the existence of high-clearance activity by observing fluctuations in CPU scheduling latency correlated with high-level process execution. What type of covert channel has been identified?","o":["Covert storage channel, because the CPU scheduler is a shared storage resource","Covert timing channel, because information is conveyed through variations in the timing of resource usage rather than through direct data storage","Overt channel, because CPU scheduling metrics are legitimately observable by all processes","Inference channel, because the vulnerability only applies to database query patterns"],"c":1,"why":"A covert timing channel transmits information by modulating the timing of a shared resource's use (here, CPU scheduling latency) rather than by writing to a shared storage location. It is not a storage channel since no persistent attribute is being written/read, not an overt channel since the mechanism is unintended, and inference channels specifically relate to database aggregation, not scheduling.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a mandatory access control system based on the Bell-LaPadula model to protect classified information. A subject holding a Secret clearance attempts to read a document classified as Top Secret. According to the simple security property of Bell-LaPadula, what is the outcome?","o":["Access is denied because the subject's clearance is lower than the object's classification","Access is granted because Bell-LaPadula only restricts write operations, not read operations","Access is denied because the subject's clearance exceeds the object's classification","Access is granted because the subject has been given discretionary permission by the data owner"],"c":0,"why":"The simple security property ('no read up') prohibits a subject from reading data classified higher than its clearance. Option B misstates the model (it does govern reads), option C reverses the clearance comparison, and option D is invalid because Bell-LaPadula is a mandatory, not discretionary, model.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A database administrator implements row-level classification labels, but a user without clearance for a classified project is still able to deduce the project's existence by noticing that certain contract IDs are consistently missing from an otherwise sequential, unclassified report. Which control specifically addresses this vulnerability?","o":["Discretionary access control lists applied at the column level","Polyinstantiation, which returns believable but false or alternate data at lower classification levels to mask the existence of sensitive records","Mandatory access control labels enforced only at the database schema level","Database normalization to eliminate redundant data across tables"],"c":1,"why":"Polyinstantiation addresses inference attacks by allowing multiple versions of a row to exist at different classification levels, so lower-clearance users see plausible cover data instead of gaps that reveal classified information. Column-level DAC, schema-level MAC, and normalization do not prevent inference from missing sequential data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements the Bell-LaPadula security model on a multilevel system. A subject holding a 'Secret' clearance attempts to write data into a file classified 'Top Secret'. Under the *-property (no write-down rule), what is the outcome of this action?","o":["The write is denied because the subject's clearance is lower than the object's classification","The write is permitted because writing to a higher classification level does not violate the *-property","The write is denied because Bell-LaPadula prohibits all write operations","The write is permitted only if the subject also has read access to Top Secret data"],"c":1,"why":"The *-property prohibits writing to a lower classification (write-down), but writing to a higher classification (write-up) is allowed because it cannot cause a disclosure of sensitive data to a lower-cleared subject; the model is concerned with confidentiality, not restricting all writes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A system architect configures a security model in which a process operating at a low integrity level is prevented from writing to files at a higher integrity level, and is also prevented from reading data from a lower integrity level to avoid contaminating its own integrity. Which model does this describe?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Brewer-Nash model","Clark-Wilson model"],"c":1,"why":"Biba's simple integrity property ('no read down') and *-integrity property ('no write up') exactly match this behavior. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, Brewer-Nash (Chinese Wall) manages conflicts of interest, and Clark-Wilson enforces integrity through well-formed transactions and separation of duties rather than simple read/write rules.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to cryptographically verify that a remote endpoint's boot process has not been tampered with before granting it access to the corporate VPN. Which hardware-based mechanism and process best achieves this, and why?","o":["A TPM performing remote attestation by signing PCR (Platform Configuration Register) values that reflect the measured boot sequence, allowing the verifier to compare them against known-good hashes","A HSM generating a one-time password based on the system's current CPU temperature and clock cycle count","A smart card storing the user's private key, which is presented during VPN authentication regardless of boot state","A software-based antivirus scan report transmitted alongside the VPN connection request"],"c":0,"why":"TPM-based remote attestation uses PCRs to store cryptographic hashes of boot-stage components; the TPM signs these values so a remote verifier can confirm the boot chain matches trusted measurements. HSMs are not designed for boot attestation, smart cards authenticate users not boot integrity, and antivirus reports are software-based and can be spoofed or bypassed by pre-boot malware.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A manufacturing control system uses the Biba integrity model to protect the accuracy of sensor data feeding into safety-critical calculations. A low-integrity process attempts to write data into a high-integrity object. What does the Biba model dictate in this scenario?","o":["The write is allowed because Biba only restricts read operations","The write is denied by the simple integrity axiom to prevent contamination of trusted data","The write is allowed if the process has been granted temporary elevated clearance","The write is denied only if the data crosses a network boundary"],"c":1,"why":"Biba's simple integrity axiom (no write-up) prevents lower-integrity subjects from writing to higher-integrity objects, protecting data accuracy; Biba addresses integrity, not confidentiality clearances, and the restriction applies regardless of network boundaries.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A network engineer needs to establish a shared secret key between two parties communicating over an insecure channel, without ever transmitting the key itself across that channel. Which cryptographic technique is specifically designed for this purpose?","o":["RSA digital signature generation","Diffie-Hellman key exchange","AES-256 symmetric encryption","SHA-256 hashing"],"c":1,"why":"Diffie-Hellman allows two parties to independently derive a shared secret using public values and their own private inputs, without transmitting the secret. RSA signatures provide authentication/integrity, AES requires an already-shared key, and SHA-256 is a one-way hash function with no key exchange capability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A legacy operating system uses a ring-based protection architecture where the kernel operates in Ring 0 and untrusted applications in Ring 3. A newly discovered vulnerability allows a Ring 3 process to directly invoke privileged instructions without passing through a controlled gate. What core security architecture principle has been violated?","o":["Least privilege, because the process should have been assigned to Ring 1 instead of Ring 3","Complete mediation, because all access to protected resources must pass through the reference monitor/gate mechanisms, and this control was bypassed","Defense in depth, because a single ring boundary is inherently insufficient regardless of gate enforcement","Separation of duties, because privileged instructions require two independent processes to execute jointly"],"c":1,"why":"Complete (or continuous) mediation requires that every access to a protected resource be checked by the reference monitor; bypassing the ring transition gates violates this principle by allowing unmediated privilege escalation. Least privilege concerns the minimal rights assigned, defense in depth concerns layered controls generally, and separation of duties concerns dividing tasks among multiple people/processes, none of which directly describe the bypassed gate mechanism.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A government agency is evaluating a security product against the Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408) framework before procurement. Which statement best describes what an Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) rating indicates?","o":["The level of confidentiality protection the product guarantees for stored data","The degree of rigor and depth of testing and documentation used to verify the product meets its claimed security functionality","The number of vulnerabilities discovered during penetration testing of the product","The specific cryptographic algorithms approved for use within the product"],"c":1,"why":"EAL ratings (EAL1-EAL7) measure the rigor of the assurance evaluation process, not the strength of confidentiality controls, vulnerability counts, or algorithm approval, which are separate concerns from Common Criteria assurance levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a procurement review, a security architect notes that a proposed firewall appliance has achieved Evaluation Assurance Level 4 (EAL4) under the Common Criteria. What does this rating primarily indicate?","o":["The product has been formally verified using mathematical proofs of its design correctness","The product was methodically designed, tested, and reviewed, providing moderate assurance","The product is certified for use in government environments handling Top Secret data","The product's source code has been audited and found to contain zero exploitable vulnerabilities"],"c":1,"why":"EAL4 corresponds to 'methodically designed, tested, and reviewed,' representing the highest level typically achievable for commercial products without specialized secure design practices. Formal verification is reserved for EAL7, EAL ratings do not map directly to data classification handling, and no evaluation guarantees zero vulnerabilities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A cryptographic architect is designing a key exchange protocol for a messaging application and wants to ensure that even if a server's long-term private key is compromised in the future, past session communications cannot be decrypted. Which design choice best achieves this goal, and why?","o":["Static (fixed) Diffie-Hellman key exchange, because the same key pair is reused for efficiency across sessions","Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (DHE/ECDHE), because a new key pair is generated for each session, so compromising the long-term key does not expose past session keys","RSA key transport, because RSA's mathematical hardness assumption is stronger than discrete logarithm problems","Pre-shared symmetric keys distributed out-of-band, because symmetric algorithms are inherently more secure than asymmetric ones"],"c":1,"why":"Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman generates unique, temporary key pairs per session, providing perfect forward secrecy — compromise of the long-term private key does not allow decryption of previously captured sessions. Static DH and RSA key transport tie session key derivation to a long-term key (breaking forward secrecy), and pre-shared symmetric keys don't inherently provide forward secrecy and introduce distribution challenges.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Two parties who have never communicated before need to establish a shared secret key over an untrusted network without a pre-existing secure channel. Which cryptographic mechanism directly addresses this key exchange problem?","o":["Symmetric block cipher encryption using a static shared key","Diffie-Hellman key agreement using public parameters and private exponents","A hash-based message authentication code (HMAC) for message integrity","A digital certificate issued by a private, self-signed CA"],"c":1,"why":"Diffie-Hellman allows two parties to derive a shared secret over an insecure channel without prior key exchange; symmetric encryption requires a pre-shared key, HMAC provides integrity not key exchange, and a self-signed certificate alone does not solve the key agreement problem.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An architect is designing a security kernel that must mediate every access attempt between subjects and objects, be resistant to tampering, and be small enough that its correctness can be formally verified. Which security concept is being implemented?","o":["Trusted Computing Base","Reference monitor concept","Security perimeter","Covert channel analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Complete mediation, tamper resistance, and verifiability are the three defining properties of the reference monitor concept. The Trusted Computing Base is the broader collection of hardware, software, and firmware that enforces security policy (of which the reference monitor is a part), while security perimeter and covert channel analysis describe unrelated concepts.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing a system's trusted computing base (TCB) and wants to ensure that all access requests by subjects to objects are validated consistently, cannot be bypassed, and are small enough to be verifiable. Which security concept is being implemented?","o":["Security kernel enforcing the reference monitor concept","Discretionary access control list management","Security through obscurity via proprietary code","Defense in depth using layered firewalls"],"c":0,"why":"The reference monitor concept requires that all access be mediated, that the enforcement mechanism be tamperproof, and that it be small enough to be verifiable-this is implemented via the security kernel within the TCB. DAC lists, obscurity, and layered firewalls do not describe this formal mediation guarantee.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"In a Software as a Service (SaaS) cloud deployment, which security responsibility typically remains with the customer organization rather than the cloud service provider?","o":["Patching the underlying operating system","Managing user access and classifying the sensitivity of stored data","Securing the physical data center housing the servers","Maintaining and patching the hypervisor"],"c":1,"why":"Under the shared responsibility model, SaaS providers manage infrastructure, OS, hypervisor, and physical security, while the customer remains accountable for identity/access management and data governance, including classification. The other options are provider responsibilities in a SaaS model.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A company subscribes to an Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) offering to host its virtual machines. Under the cloud shared responsibility model, which security function remains primarily the customer's responsibility?","o":["Physical security of the data center housing the host servers","Patch management and hardening of the guest operating system","Maintenance of the hypervisor that manages virtual machine isolation","Ensuring the availability of the underlying physical network infrastructure"],"c":1,"why":"In IaaS, the provider manages physical infrastructure, hypervisor, and underlying network, while the customer is responsible for securing and patching the guest OS, applications, and data running on the provisioned virtual machines.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A developer is selecting a cryptographic hash function to support digital signatures. Which property is MOST critical to prevent an attacker from substituting a fraudulent document that produces the same signature as a legitimate one?","o":["Key length of at least 256 bits","Collision resistance, ensuring no two different inputs produce the same hash output","Fast computation speed to support high transaction volumes","Reversibility, allowing the original message to be recovered from the hash"],"c":1,"why":"Collision resistance ensures two different messages cannot produce the same hash value, preventing signature substitution attacks; hash functions have no 'key length,' should not be reversible, and speed is a performance factor rather than a security guarantee against forgery.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to prevent unauthorized disclosure of information by enforcing the 'no read up' (simple security property) and 'no write down' (star property) rules?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces confidentiality through the simple security property and star property. Biba focuses on integrity, Clark-Wilson enforces well-formed transactions for integrity, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest, not confidentiality via read/write rules.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution is concerned that adversaries could intercept sensitive data by capturing electromagnetic emanations from computer monitors and cabling within its data center. Which control specifically addresses this threat?","o":["Implementing TEMPEST-shielded equipment and facilities","Deploying network intrusion detection systems at the perimeter","Enforcing role-based access control on data center entry systems","Using full-disk encryption on all workstations"],"c":0,"why":"TEMPEST standards address shielding against compromising electromagnetic emanations that could be intercepted to reconstruct data; IDS, RBAC, and disk encryption protect against network intrusion or unauthorized physical/data access but do not mitigate emanation-based eavesdropping.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is a primary advantage of symmetric key cryptography compared to asymmetric key cryptography?","o":["It is significantly faster for encrypting and decrypting large amounts of data","It eliminates the need to keep the key confidential","It simplifies secure key distribution between parties who have never met","It inherently provides non-repudiation of the sender"],"c":0,"why":"Symmetric algorithms are computationally efficient and much faster than asymmetric algorithms for bulk data. Symmetric keys must still be kept secret, key distribution is actually harder with symmetric cryptography, and non-repudiation is a strength of asymmetric (public key) cryptography, not symmetric.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of the Trusted Computing Base (TCB) within a secure computer system?","o":["To enforce the system's security policy through a combination of hardware, software, and firmware controls","To encrypt all data stored on disk","To manage and store user authentication credentials","To generate audit logs of all system activity"],"c":0,"why":"The TCB is the totality of protection mechanisms (hardware, software, firmware) within a system responsible for enforcing the security policy. Encryption, credential storage, and logging are specific functions that may exist within a system but are not the defining purpose of the TCB itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which type of fire suppression system is generally preferred for a data center because it extinguishes fires effectively without damaging electronic equipment or leaving toxic residue?","o":["Clean agent gaseous suppression system (e.g., FM-200)","Wet pipe water sprinkler system","Foam-based suppression system","Dry chemical powder system"],"c":0,"why":"Clean agent gaseous systems suppress fire without conducting electricity or damaging sensitive equipment, unlike water, which can cause short circuits and corrosion. Foam and dry chemical agents can also damage electronics and leave residue.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A database administrator discovers that a user without direct authorization to view salary information is able to deduce approximate salary ranges by correlating job title, department, and tenure across several authorized, individually low-sensitivity queries. This is an example of which type of attack?","o":["Aggregation attack","Inference attack","SQL injection attack","Polyinstantiation"],"c":1,"why":"Inference attacks occur when a user logically deduces protected information from combinations of authorized, seemingly innocuous data. Aggregation specifically refers to combining individually low-sensitivity data elements to directly produce a higher-classification whole via query design, SQL injection involves malicious code execution, and polyinstantiation refers to maintaining multiple record versions at different classification levels, not an attack technique.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In which cloud service model does the cloud provider manage the physical hardware, networking, and virtualization layer, while the customer is responsible for the operating system, applications, and data?","o":["Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Software as a Service (SaaS)","Function as a Service (FaaS)"],"c":0,"why":"IaaS provides virtualized computing infrastructure while leaving OS and application management to the customer. PaaS additionally manages the OS and runtime, SaaS manages the entire application stack, and FaaS abstracts even the runtime environment for individual functions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center housing critical servers requires an automatic fire suppression system that will not damage electronic equipment and does not deplete the ozone layer. Which suppression agent is most appropriate?","o":["Halon 1301","Wet pipe water sprinkler system","Clean agent gas such as FM-200","Carbon dioxide (CO2) flooding system"],"c":2,"why":"Clean agents like FM-200 were developed as ozone-safe replacements for Halon and are designed to suppress fire without damaging sensitive electronics. Halon is banned in new installations due to ozone depletion, water sprinklers can damage electronic equipment, and CO2 flooding poses a suffocation hazard to personnel and is generally avoided in occupied spaces.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements firewalls, intrusion detection systems, endpoint antivirus software, and ongoing security awareness training as overlapping layers of protection. This approach best exemplifies which security principle?","o":["Defense in depth","Least privilege","Separation of duties","Security through obscurity"],"c":0,"why":"Defense in depth involves using multiple, layered security controls so that if one fails, others still provide protection. Least privilege limits access rights, separation of duties divides responsibilities among individuals, and security through obscurity relies on secrecy of design rather than layered controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A security analyst wants to verify that a downloaded file has not been altered during transmission. Which cryptographic function is best suited for this purpose?","o":["Hash function","Symmetric encryption","Asymmetric encryption","Steganography"],"c":0,"why":"A hash function produces a fixed-length digest that can be compared to detect any alteration, making it ideal for verifying integrity. Encryption (symmetric or asymmetric) provides confidentiality rather than a direct integrity check, and steganography is used to conceal data rather than verify it.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In the ring protection model used by many operating systems, which ring typically holds the highest level of privilege and executes the kernel?","o":["Ring 0","Ring 1","Ring 2","Ring 3"],"c":0,"why":"Ring 0 is the most privileged ring, reserved for the operating system kernel, which has direct access to hardware. Higher-numbered rings (1-3) have progressively less privilege and are typically used for device drivers and user applications.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization's trading platform must ensure that low-integrity market data feeds cannot corrupt the high-integrity pricing engine's internal reference tables, while still allowing the pricing engine to read from the feeds for analysis. Which security model concept, if strictly applied, would prevent the low-integrity feed process from modifying the high-integrity reference tables?","o":["Bell-LaPadula simple security property (no read up)","Biba star integrity property (no write up)","Bell-LaPadula star property (no write down)","Clark-Wilson well-formed transaction rule"],"c":1,"why":"Biba's *-integrity axiom explicitly prevents a subject from writing to an object of higher integrity, directly stopping contamination of the reference tables. Bell-LaPadula properties govern confidentiality, not integrity, and Clark-Wilson relies on certified transactions and separation of duty rather than a labeled write-up restriction.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A vendor advertises that its product has achieved Common Criteria Evaluation Assurance Level 4 (EAL4). Which statement most accurately reflects what this certification indicates to a security architect evaluating the product for a classified system?","o":["The product has been formally verified using mathematical proofs of its security design and implementation.","The product has been methodically designed, tested, and reviewed, but not formally verified, and may still contain exploitable flaws.","The product meets the highest possible Common Criteria assurance level and requires no further security testing.","The product's Target of Evaluation matches the customer's specific operational environment and threat model automatically."],"c":1,"why":"EAL4 indicates methodical design, testing, and review without formal mathematical verification, which begins at higher EALs (EAL5-7); it does not guarantee absence of flaws, is not the highest level, and does not automatically account for a specific deployment's threat model.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A development team implements a Diffie-Hellman key exchange between two hosts to establish a shared symmetric session key. A security assessment identifies that the exchange is vulnerable to an active man-in-the-middle attack. What is the most effective remediation, and why does it address the underlying weakness?","o":["Increase the DH modulus size to at least 4096 bits, which prevents an attacker from computing the discrete logarithm.","Add digital signatures or certificates to authenticate the exchanged public values, since unauthenticated DH provides no identity verification.","Switch to a symmetric algorithm with a longer key length to reduce the attack surface.","Use a cryptographic hash function to hash the exchanged public keys before transmission."],"c":1,"why":"Plain Diffie-Hellman does not authenticate the parties exchanging public values, allowing an attacker to substitute their own values regardless of key size; signing the exchange (authenticated DH, as used in TLS) binds identity to the exchange and stops MITM. Larger moduli, symmetric key length, and unsigned hashing do not address the lack of authentication.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A multilevel secure database contains a table where a Secret-level user can, over multiple authorized low-level queries, deduce the existence of a Top-Secret record by noticing an unusual pattern of 'access denied' versus normal responses. Which design technique specifically addresses this inference vulnerability by presenting multiple, context-appropriate versions of the same data element to users at different classification levels?","o":["Mandatory access control labeling of each row","Polyinstantiation","Referential integrity constraints","Role-based access control"],"c":1,"why":"Polyinstantiation creates distinct, plausible data instances at different classification levels so lower-level users see believable cover data instead of an error that reveals the existence of a higher-level record. MAC labeling alone can still leak existence through denial responses, and referential integrity and RBAC do not address inference at all.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a secure boot process, UEFI firmware measures each component (bootloader, OS loader, kernel) before executing it and stores the measurements in a specific hardware location, later comparing them against expected values to detect tampering. Which TPM feature is being used, and what does it primarily protect against?","o":["TPM-based full disk encryption keys, protecting against data theft if the drive is stolen","Platform Configuration Registers (PCRs) storing boot component hashes, protecting against unauthorized modification of the boot chain","TPM random number generator, protecting against weak cryptographic key generation","TPM endorsement key, protecting against device cloning"],"c":1,"why":"PCRs accumulate cryptographic hashes of each boot stage, enabling attestation or sealed storage decisions that detect alteration of the boot chain. Disk encryption keys, the RNG, and the endorsement key serve unrelated purposes and are not what is being described in the measurement/comparison process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Two virtual machines from different tenants run on the same physical host and share the same CPU cache. Researchers demonstrate that one VM can infer sensitive data processed by the other VM by measuring cache access latency patterns, without any direct communication channel between the VMs. This is best classified as which type of attack, and which control is most effective at mitigating it?","o":["A covert timing channel; mitigate through cache partitioning or dedicating physical cores per tenant","A covert storage channel; mitigate through mandatory access control labels on VM memory","A replay attack; mitigate through session token expiration","A TOCTOU race condition; mitigate through atomic locking of shared resources"],"c":0,"why":"Leaking information across an isolation boundary via shared cache timing behavior is a classic covert timing channel, best mitigated by resource isolation such as cache partitioning or dedicated cores. Storage channels involve shared data objects rather than timing, and replay/TOCTOU describe unrelated attack classes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A government facility processing classified information is located near a public parking area. A security architect is concerned that electromagnetic emanations from displays and cabling inside the facility could be intercepted from outside using specialized equipment, allowing reconstruction of displayed data. Which control specifically addresses this threat?","o":["Faraday cage shielding and TEMPEST-certified equipment to contain and suppress compromising emanations","Redundant uninterruptible power supplies to prevent data loss during outages","Mantrap turnstiles at facility entrances to prevent unauthorized physical access","Fire suppression systems using inert gas to protect equipment from damage"],"c":0,"why":"TEMPEST standards and Faraday shielding specifically counter interception of compromising electromagnetic emanations. UPS systems address power continuity, mantraps address physical entry control, and fire suppression addresses combustion hazards—none mitigate emanation interception.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization's multilevel secure system enforces the Bell-LaPadula model, including the standard (weak) star property. A subject cleared at the Secret level attempts to write data into an object classified at the Top Secret level. Under this policy, which statement is accurate?","o":["The write is denied, because the simple security property prohibits any write operation by subjects who lack Top Secret clearance.","The write is permitted, because the star property only prohibits writing to objects at a lower classification level than the subject's current level.","The write is denied, because the strong star property is a mandatory default component of Bell-LaPadula and blocks all writes outside the subject's exact level.","The write is permitted only if the object's discretionary access control list explicitly grants Top Secret write access to Secret-cleared subjects."],"c":1,"why":"The (weak) star property prevents 'write-down' (writing to a lower classification) but permits 'write-up,' since doing so does not increase disclosure risk; the simple security property governs reads, not writes; the strong star property is an optional stricter variant, not the default; BLP enforcement is mandatory and does not depend on DAC.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A penetration test against a cloud provider's infrastructure reveals that a specially crafted workload running inside a guest VM can execute arbitrary code on the underlying hypervisor, breaking out of its intended isolation boundary and potentially affecting other tenants' VMs on the same host. Which vulnerability class does this represent, and which architectural control is most directly relevant to reducing this risk?","o":["SQL injection; input validation at the application layer","VM escape (hypervisor breakout); rigorous hypervisor patch management and minimizing the hypervisor's attack surface","Cross-site scripting; output encoding of untrusted data","Privilege escalation via weak file permissions; enforcing least privilege on the guest OS filesystem"],"c":1,"why":"Code execution that breaks out of the VM into the hypervisor is a VM escape, best mitigated by rigorous patching and minimizing the hypervisor's exposed attack surface (e.g., limiting emulated devices). The other options describe unrelated vulnerability classes—web application injection, XSS, and OS-level file permission issues—that do not match a hypervisor breakout.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Two parties establish a shared secret key using the standard Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol without any additional authentication mechanism (e.g., digital signatures or pre-shared certificates). Which attack is this implementation most susceptible to?","o":["Brute-force attack against the shared secret due to insufficient key length","Man-in-the-middle attack in which an adversary establishes separate shared secrets with each party while impersonating the other","Birthday attack exploiting hash collisions during key derivation","Replay attack in which previously captured key exchange messages are reused to derive the same session key"],"c":1,"why":"Plain Diffie-Hellman provides no authentication of the communicating parties, allowing an active attacker to intercept and independently negotiate keys with each side—a classic MITM. The other options target weaknesses (key length, hash collisions, message replay) that are not the inherent flaw of unauthenticated DH.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements a mandatory access control model in which a user cleared at the 'Secret' level is prevented from reading documents classified 'Top Secret,' but is allowed to write to files classified 'Top Secret.' Which security model does this describe?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces 'no read up, no write down' to protect confidentiality, allowing a lower-cleared subject to write up but not read up. Biba addresses integrity (opposite rules), Clark-Wilson focuses on well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Which statement best captures the reference monitor concept as it applies to a Trusted Computing Base (TCB)?","o":["It is the set of all hardware, software, and firmware components that collectively enforce the security policy of a system.","It is an abstract model of an access control mechanism that must be tamperproof, always invoked, and small enough to be verifiable, mediating every access between subjects and objects.","It is the physical and logical boundary that separates trusted from untrusted components within a system.","It is the formal security policy document that defines the rules the TCB must enforce."],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept requiring tamperproofing, complete mediation, and verifiability. Option one describes the TCB itself, option three describes the security perimeter, and option four describes a security policy document—none of which is the reference monitor concept.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A financial application must ensure that a low-privilege data entry clerk cannot modify records normally maintained by a senior accountant, in order to preserve data integrity. Which formal security model best supports this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","Graham-Denning model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model enforces integrity by preventing subjects from writing to objects at a higher integrity level ('no write up'), which stops lower-trust users from corrupting higher-trust data. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, and Take-Grant/Graham-Denning deal with rights propagation rather than integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a Common Criteria evaluation, a firewall vendor submits documentation defining the specific security functional requirements (SFRs) and security assurance requirements (SARs) claimed for their particular product implementation. This document is known as the:","o":["Protection Profile (PP)","Security Target (ST)","Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) rating","Target of Evaluation (TOE) summary specification"],"c":1,"why":"The Security Target defines the specific security claims for the actual product being evaluated (the TOE). A Protection Profile is a generic, reusable set of requirements for a product category; EAL is merely a numeric assurance rating; TOE simply refers to the product itself, not a claims document.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Two branch offices need to securely exchange large volumes of encrypted data over a dedicated link. They select an algorithm that uses a single shared secret for both encryption and decryption. What is the primary security challenge associated with this approach?","o":["The algorithm is too slow for bulk data transfer","Digital signatures cannot be created using this key type","Securely distributing and managing the shared key between parties","The ciphertext produced is larger than the plaintext"],"c":2,"why":"Symmetric cryptography is fast and efficient for bulk data, but its main weakness is securely distributing and managing the single shared key. Symmetric algorithms are actually fast, don't inherently expand ciphertext, and are not used for digital signatures (that requires asymmetric keys).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing an access control model for a classified network where the primary requirement is preventing unauthorized disclosure of information. The model enforces a 'simple security property' (no read up) and a 'star property' (no write down). Which security model is being applied?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer and Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula is a confidentiality-focused model using the simple security property (no read up) and *-property (no write down) to prevent disclosure of classified data. Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson enforces integrity via well-formed transactions, and Brewer and Nash prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Researchers analyzing a smart card's AES implementation discover they can recover the secret key by statistically analyzing fluctuations in the card's power consumption during repeated cryptographic operations. This attack technique is best classified as:","o":["A chosen-ciphertext attack","A timing attack","Differential power analysis, a form of side-channel attack","A fault-injection attack"],"c":2,"why":"Differential power analysis exploits variations in power consumption correlated with key-dependent internal operations. Timing attacks analyze execution duration rather than power draw, fault injection deliberately induces errors, and chosen-ciphertext attacks require submitting crafted ciphertexts for decryption—none matches this power-analysis technique.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A user wants to prove to a recipient that a message truly came from them and was not altered in transit. Which cryptographic mechanism best achieves this goal?","o":["Symmetric encryption using a shared secret key","A digital signature created with the sender's private key","A hash function applied without any key","A one-time pad shared in advance"],"c":1,"why":"A digital signature, generated by hashing the message and encrypting the hash with the sender's private key, provides both authentication and integrity verification. Symmetric encryption and unkeyed hashing alone do not prove sender identity, and a one-time pad only provides confidentiality.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that low-integrity processes cannot corrupt data used by high-integrity processes. Which security model enforces rules preventing subjects from writing to higher integrity levels ('no write up') and reading from lower integrity levels ('no read down')?","o":["Biba model","Bell-LaPadula model","Take-Grant model","Graham-Denning model"],"c":0,"why":"The Biba model protects data integrity by preventing lower-integrity subjects from writing to higher-integrity objects or contaminating high-integrity processes by reading low-integrity data. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, while Take-Grant and Graham-Denning focus on modeling access rights transfer, not integrity levels specifically.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A data analyst with access only to unclassified personnel records runs a series of individually authorized queries and manually compiles the results, ultimately reconstructing a report equivalent to classified organizational data. This scenario best illustrates a(n):","o":["Inference attack, in which sensitive conclusions are logically deduced from patterns in non-sensitive data","Aggregation attack, in which combining multiple pieces of unclassified data produces a classified result","Polyinstantiation vulnerability, where multiple versions of the same record exist at different classification levels","SQL injection attack exploiting unsanitized query parameters"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining individually low-sensitivity data elements yields a higher-sensitivity result, exactly as described. Inference instead relies on deducing sensitive facts through logical relationships rather than simple combination; polyinstantiation and SQL injection describe unrelated database security issues.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which concept refers to the totality of protection mechanisms within a computer system, including hardware, firmware, and software, that are responsible for enforcing the security policy?","o":["Security kernel","Trusted Computing Base (TCB)","Reference monitor","Security perimeter"],"c":1,"why":"The Trusted Computing Base (TCB) encompasses all protection mechanisms that enforce the security policy. The security kernel and reference monitor are components within the TCB that implement access control, while the security perimeter is the boundary separating the TCB from the rest of the system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A web application must securely establish a session key between a client and server before transmitting large volumes of encrypted data. Which design best balances strong security with acceptable performance?","o":["Use asymmetric encryption to securely exchange a symmetric session key, then use symmetric encryption for bulk data transfer","Use asymmetric encryption for all data transmitted during the session","Use symmetric encryption for all key exchange and data transmission without asymmetric components","Use hashing algorithms to encrypt both the key exchange and the bulk data"],"c":0,"why":"This hybrid cryptosystem approach leverages asymmetric encryption's strength for secure key exchange and symmetric encryption's speed for bulk data, which is how protocols like TLS operate. Pure asymmetric encryption is too slow for bulk data, symmetric-only key exchange lacks a secure channel, and hashing provides integrity, not confidentiality.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"During the design phase of a new corporate campus, the security team recommends using natural surveillance, clear sightlines, and strategically placed landscaping to discourage criminal activity without relying solely on guards or fences. This approach is best described as:","o":["Crime Prevention Through Environmental Design (CPTED)","Defense in depth","Access control layering","Target hardening"],"c":0,"why":"CPTED uses environmental and architectural design elements, such as natural surveillance and landscaping, to reduce opportunities for crime. Defense in depth refers to layered security controls generally, access control layering is a subset concept, and target hardening focuses on making specific assets physically harder to attack.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester exploits a vulnerability in a hypervisor that allows code running inside a guest virtual machine to break out of its isolation boundary and directly access the memory of another guest VM on the same host. This attack is best described as:","o":["Hyperjacking, in which the attacker gains full control of the hypervisor itself","VM escape, in which a process breaks out of VM isolation to access the host or other VMs","A side-channel attack exploiting shared cache resources between VMs","VM sprawl, resulting from poor lifecycle management of virtual machines"],"c":1,"why":"VM escape specifically describes breaking out of a guest's isolation to directly reach the host or other VMs. Hyperjacking refers to taking control of the hypervisor itself (a distinct, more severe attack), side-channel attacks leak information indirectly through shared resources rather than direct memory access, and VM sprawl is an operational management issue unrelated to this exploit.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During an architecture review, a product is documented as evaluated at Common Criteria EAL4. What does this rating primarily indicate?","o":["The product was methodically designed, tested, and reviewed, providing moderate assurance suitable for many commercial environments","The product underwent formal, mathematically verified design and testing, representing the highest assurance level","The product complies with FIPS 140-2 Level 4 requirements for cryptographic modules","The product is authorized for processing Top Secret information in government networks"],"c":0,"why":"EAL4 represents methodical design, testing, and review, offering moderate assurance and is the highest level typically achievable for a product not specifically designed for high assurance. EAL7 involves formal verification, FIPS 140-2 is a separate cryptographic module standard, and classification authorization is handled through separate government accreditation processes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A company wants to outsource the underlying servers, storage, and networking for its applications but retain full control over operating systems, middleware, and the applications themselves. Which cloud service model best fits this requirement?","o":["Software as a Service (SaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Function as a Service (FaaS)"],"c":2,"why":"IaaS provides virtualized computing infrastructure (servers, storage, networking) while the customer manages the OS, middleware, and applications. SaaS provides complete applications, PaaS abstracts the OS/runtime layer, and FaaS abstracts even the application server, none of which match the described control requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization processing highly classified information is concerned that electromagnetic emanations from computer monitors and cabling could be intercepted from outside the facility and used to reconstruct displayed or transmitted data. Which control most directly addresses this specific risk?","o":["Implementing full-disk encryption on all endpoint devices","Deploying TEMPEST-shielded equipment and facilities to contain compromising emanations","Installing motion-activated CCTV cameras at facility perimeters","Requiring multifactor authentication for all workstation logins"],"c":1,"why":"TEMPEST standards and shielding specifically address compromising electromagnetic emanations. Disk encryption protects data at rest, CCTV addresses physical intrusion detection, and MFA addresses authentication—none mitigate emanation-based interception.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Which security architecture concept refers to an abstract model that mediates all access between subjects and objects, and must be tamperproof, always invoked, and small enough to be verifiable for correctness?","o":["Reference monitor","Trusted computing base","Security kernel","Security perimeter"],"c":0,"why":"The reference monitor is the abstract concept defined by three properties: tamperproof, always invoked (complete mediation), and verifiable. The security kernel is the actual hardware/software/firmware implementation of this concept, the TCB is the totality of protection mechanisms, and the security perimeter is the boundary separating the TCB from the rest of the system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A data center housing sensitive servers needs a fire suppression system that will not damage electronic equipment and is safe for occupied spaces. Which type of system is most appropriate?","o":["Wet pipe water sprinkler system","Carbon dioxide (CO2) flooding system","Clean agent gaseous suppression system (e.g., FM-200)","Dry chemical powder extinguishing system"],"c":2,"why":"Clean agent gaseous systems like FM-200 suppress fire without leaving residue or damaging electronics and are safe for occupied areas. Water sprinklers and dry chemical systems can damage sensitive equipment, and CO2 systems displace oxygen to dangerous levels, making them unsafe for occupied spaces.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A penetration tester discovers a hypervisor vulnerability that allows code running inside a guest virtual machine to execute arbitrary commands directly on the underlying host system, potentially impacting other guest VMs. What is this type of attack called?","o":["VM escape","VM sprawl","Side-channel attack","Hyperjacking"],"c":0,"why":"VM escape occurs when malicious code breaks out of the isolated guest VM environment to interact with or compromise the host. VM sprawl refers to uncontrolled proliferation of VMs, side-channel attacks exploit shared physical resources for information leakage, and hyperjacking involves installing a rogue hypervisor to control the host, which is a different attack vector.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A digital signature scheme hashes a message before signing it with the sender's private key. A researcher later discovers two completely different messages that produce identical hash outputs. Which property of the hash function has been violated?","o":["Collision resistance","Preimage resistance","Avalanche effect","Key stretching"],"c":0,"why":"Collision resistance means it should be computationally infeasible to find two different inputs producing the same hash output; finding such a pair violates this property. Preimage resistance concerns deriving an input from a given output, avalanche effect describes how small input changes should drastically change output, and key stretching applies to key derivation functions, not hashing collisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A system enforcing the Bell-LaPadula model has a subject cleared at the Secret level. That subject attempts to write data into a file object classified Top Secret. Which statement correctly describes the outcome under strict Bell-LaPadula enforcement?","o":["This violates the Simple Security Property because the subject is reading data at a level above its clearance.","This action is permitted under the *-property because the object's classification dominates the subject's clearance, satisfying the no-write-down rule.","This violates the *-property because subjects may only write to objects at their own exact classification level.","Bell-LaPadula does not govern write operations, so no security property applies to this action."],"c":1,"why":"The *-property (no write-down) only prohibits writing to objects at a lower classification than the subject's clearance; writing 'up' to a higher-classified object does not violate confidentiality and is permitted. The Simple Security Property governs reads, not writes, and BLP explicitly does define write rules via the *-property.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A government facility shields its walls and windows with a conductive enclosure to prevent electromagnetic signals carrying sensitive data from radiating outside the building where they could be intercepted. What is this physical security control called?","o":["Faraday cage","TEMPEST","White noise generation","Zone of control"],"c":0,"why":"A Faraday cage is a conductive enclosure that blocks electromagnetic signals from escaping or entering a space, directly matching the scenario described. TEMPEST is the broader standard governing emanation security controls, white noise generation masks signals rather than blocking them, and zone of control refers to physical security perimeters unrelated to electromagnetic shielding.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial application requires that data integrity be strictly enforced so that lower-integrity users cannot corrupt higher-integrity financial records, and high-integrity subjects should not be contaminated by reading lower-integrity data. Which security model best supports these requirements?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model enforces integrity through 'no write-up' and 'no read-down' rules, directly preventing low-integrity subjects from corrupting high-integrity data and preventing contamination from lower-integrity sources. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, Clark-Wilson focuses on well-formed transactions rather than simple lattice rules, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest, not general integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A TLS implementation uses ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (DHE) key exchange to achieve perfect forward secrecy. Which additional mechanism is essential to prevent a man-in-the-middle attack against the key exchange itself?","o":["Encrypting the DH public parameters using a symmetric cipher before transmission.","Increasing the size of the DH prime modulus to at least 4096 bits.","Authenticating the exchanged DH parameters using digital signatures tied to a trusted certificate.","Rotating the ephemeral DH key pair more frequently during the session."],"c":2,"why":"DH key exchange is inherently unauthenticated, so without binding the exchanged parameters to a verified identity (via signatures/certificates), an attacker can substitute their own parameters and perform a MITM attack. Larger moduli or key rotation improve cryptographic strength but do not address the lack of authentication.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing a system to allow two parties who have never communicated before to securely establish a shared symmetric session key over an untrusted network. Which cryptographic approach is most appropriate for this initial key exchange?","o":["Use a pre-shared symmetric key distributed out-of-band before communication begins","Use asymmetric cryptography, such as Diffie-Hellman or RSA key transport, to establish the session key","Use a hash function to derive the key from both parties' IP addresses","Use symmetric encryption with a well-known default key for the first exchange"],"c":1,"why":"Asymmetric cryptography (e.g., Diffie-Hellman key agreement or RSA-based key transport) allows two parties with no prior shared secret to securely establish a symmetric session key over an untrusted channel. Pre-shared keys require prior out-of-band coordination, hashing IP addresses provides no real secrecy, and default keys are insecure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A reference monitor is a core concept in secure system design. Which of the following best describes its primary function?","o":["It encrypts all data in transit between subjects and objects","It mediates all access between subjects and objects, enforcing the system's security policy","It logs user activity for later forensic review without enforcing access decisions","It performs periodic vulnerability scans against the operating system kernel"],"c":1,"why":"A reference monitor is an abstract concept that mediates every access attempt between subjects and objects to enforce the security policy; it must be tamperproof, always invoked, and verifiable. It does not perform encryption, is not merely a passive logging mechanism, and vulnerability scanning is unrelated to its enforcement role.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A vendor's firewall product achieves Common Criteria EAL7 certification. What does this rating primarily convey to an evaluator?","o":["The product has been mathematically proven to contain no exploitable vulnerabilities.","The product underwent the highest level of formal design verification and independent testing rigor defined by the Common Criteria, increasing assurance that it performs as specified.","The product satisfies the same functional requirements as EAL1 but was tested with less independent scrutiny.","EAL7 certification is only attainable by open-source products due to source code disclosure requirements."],"c":1,"why":"EAL ratings measure the rigor and depth of the assurance evaluation (documentation, testing, formal methods), not the absence of vulnerabilities or a specific functional requirement set; commercial closed-source products can achieve high EALs, and no EAL guarantees zero vulnerabilities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A researcher discovers that by measuring the precise time an embedded smart card takes to perform cryptographic operations with different keys, they can infer bits of the private key. This is an example of which type of attack?","o":["A brute-force attack","A side-channel attack","A replay attack","A man-in-the-middle attack"],"c":1,"why":"Timing analysis that exploits physical implementation characteristics (execution time, power consumption, electromagnetic emissions) to extract secret information is a side-channel attack, not a brute-force attempt on the keyspace, a replay of captured traffic, or an interception between two communicating parties.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An architect wants a full-disk encryption key released by a TPM only if the system booted using an unaltered boot loader and kernel. Which TPM capability should be used?","o":["Remote attestation using the Endorsement Key certificate to a remote verifier.","Sealing the encryption key to specific PCR values representing the expected boot measurements.","Using the TPM's hardware random number generator to derive the key.","Binding the key to the Storage Root Key without referencing any PCR values."],"c":1,"why":"Sealing binds a secret to specific Platform Configuration Register (PCR) values produced during measured boot; the TPM will only unseal/release the key if current measurements match, ensuring boot integrity. Attestation proves state to a remote party but doesn't itself gate local key release, and binding without PCRs provides no boot-integrity check.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"In a virtualized data center, an attacker compromises a guest virtual machine and then exploits a vulnerability to gain unauthorized access to the underlying hypervisor and other guest VMs on the same host. What is this attack commonly called?","o":["VM sprawl","Hypervisor escape (VM escape)","Covert channel attack","Bit-flipping attack"],"c":1,"why":"A hypervisor escape (VM escape) occurs when an attacker breaks out of the isolation of a guest VM to access the hypervisor or other VMs, a critical concern in virtualization security. VM sprawl refers to unmanaged proliferation of VMs, covert channels involve unauthorized information flow through unintended paths, and bit-flipping attacks relate to manipulating ciphertext bits, not virtualization isolation breaches.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During penetration testing of a smart card, researchers deduce private key bits by monitoring fluctuations in the card's power consumption during cryptographic operations, without inducing any faults. Which attack category does this describe?","o":["Differential power analysis, a passive side-channel attack.","Fault injection attack.","Chosen-ciphertext attack.","Replay attack."],"c":0,"why":"Differential power analysis passively observes power consumption patterns correlated with key-dependent operations to infer key material. Fault injection actively induces errors (e.g., voltage glitching) rather than passively observing; chosen-ciphertext and replay attacks operate at the protocol/algorithmic level, not via physical emanation analysis.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Which combination of controls provides the strongest defense-in-depth mitigation against classic stack-based buffer overflow exploitation on a modern operating system?","o":["Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR) implemented alone.","Data Execution Prevention (DEP/NX) implemented alone.","A combination of ASLR, DEP/NX, and stack canaries working together.","Signature-based antivirus scanning of compiled binaries."],"c":2,"why":"No single control fully prevents stack overflow exploitation; ASLR randomizes memory layout, DEP/NX blocks execution of injected code, and stack canaries detect overwritten return addresses—used together they create layered protection. Antivirus signatures are reactive and ineffective against novel or in-memory exploitation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization uses a public key infrastructure (PKI) to issue digital certificates to employees. A certificate is compromised and must be invalidated immediately before its expiration date. Which mechanism should be used to communicate this revocation to relying parties in near real time?","o":["Certificate Revocation List (CRL) published on a weekly schedule","Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP)","Renewing the certificate with a new expiration date","Re-issuing the same certificate with a different key pair"],"c":1,"why":"OCSP provides near real-time certificate status checking, making it more suitable for immediate revocation needs than a periodically published CRL, which may not reflect the revocation for days. Renewing or re-issuing a certificate does not revoke the compromised one and does not address the immediate security risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily concerned with preventing unauthorized disclosure of information, enforcing rules such as 'no read up' and 'no write down'?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula is a confidentiality-focused model using the simple security property (no read up) and *-property (no write down). Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson focuses on well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect designing a Type 1 hypervisor environment is most concerned about an attacker who compromises a guest VM pivoting to the hypervisor or other tenants. Which architectural principle most directly mitigates this risk?","o":["Allocating additional virtual CPU cores to each guest to improve performance isolation.","Minimizing the hypervisor's attack surface and enforcing strict resource/memory isolation between guests.","Migrating to a Type 2 hypervisor to leverage host OS security features.","Placing all guest VMs on a single flat virtual network segment for simplified management."],"c":1,"why":"VM escape risk is reduced primarily by minimizing the hypervisor's code base/attack surface and strongly enforcing isolation boundaries between guest resources; CPU allocation and network flattening don't address escape vectors, and Type 2 hypervisors generally have a larger, less trusted attack surface than Type 1.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the purpose of the Trusted Computing Base (TCB)?","o":["A network segment isolated for testing untrusted code","The combination of hardware, software, and firmware that enforces the security policy of a system","A certification process for evaluating cloud service providers","A list of trusted third-party certificate authorities"],"c":1,"why":"The TCB is the totality of protection mechanisms within a system that work together to enforce a unified security policy. It is not a network segment, a certification process, or a CA list.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization processing Sensitive Compartmented Information is concerned that adversaries could remotely intercept compromising electromagnetic emanations from computing equipment to reconstruct processed data. Which control most directly addresses this specific threat?","o":["TEMPEST-compliant shielding and emission-control standards applied to equipment and facilities.","Full-disk encryption of all storage media.","Deployment of a network-based intrusion detection system at the perimeter.","Enforcement of multi-factor authentication for physical facility access."],"c":0,"why":"TEMPEST standards specifically address controlling and shielding compromising electromagnetic emanations from electronic equipment. Encryption protects data at rest/in transit but not emanations; IDS and MFA address network and access-control threats, not electromagnetic leakage.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that a system can only be accessed by users cleared for the highest classification level processed on that system, even if some users are not cleared for all data on it. Which security mode of operation does this describe?","o":["Dedicated security mode","System high security mode","Multilevel security mode","Compartmented security mode"],"c":1,"why":"In system high mode, all users must have clearance for the highest level of data on the system, though they may not have a need-to-know for all data. Dedicated mode requires clearance and need-to-know for all data; multilevel allows varying clearances with access control enforcement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which physical security control is specifically designed to prevent vehicles from ramming into a building entrance?","o":["Turnstile","Mantrap","Bollard","Faraday cage"],"c":2,"why":"Bollards are sturdy vertical posts used to block vehicle access to pedestrian or building areas. Turnstiles and mantraps control personnel movement, and a Faraday cage blocks electromagnetic signals.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a mandatory access control system based on the Bell-LaPadula model to protect classified information. Under this model, which combination of rules correctly enforces confidentiality?","o":["A subject cannot read data at a higher classification level and cannot write data to a lower classification level","A subject cannot read data at a lower classification level and cannot write data to a higher classification level","A subject can read and write at any classification level as long as need-to-know is satisfied","A subject cannot read data at a higher classification level but can write data to any lower classification level"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces the Simple Security Property (no read up) and the *-property (no write down) to prevent high-classification data from leaking to lower levels. The other options invert or omit these rules, which would violate confidentiality.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"What is the main security benefit of implementing hardware-based virtualization with a hypervisor for running multiple guest operating systems?","o":["It eliminates the need for patch management on guest systems","It provides isolation between virtual machines to contain security breaches","It guarantees encryption of all data at rest on the host","It automatically enforces least privilege for all applications"],"c":1,"why":"Hypervisors provide isolation between virtual machines, so a compromise in one VM is less likely to affect others. Virtualization does not eliminate patching needs, guarantee encryption, or automatically enforce least privilege.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing a system that must securely exchange a symmetric session key between two parties who have never communicated before and have no pre-shared secret. Which cryptographic approach best solves this problem?","o":["Use a symmetric block cipher with a fixed key embedded in both systems","Use asymmetric cryptography, such as Diffie-Hellman or RSA key transport, to establish the shared symmetric key","Use a hash function to derive the key independently on both ends","Use a message authentication code to verify the key before use"],"c":1,"why":"Asymmetric cryptography (e.g., Diffie-Hellman key exchange or RSA-based key transport) solves the key distribution problem for parties with no prior shared secret. Symmetric ciphers require a pre-shared key, hashing doesn't establish a shared secret between two parties, and a MAC only verifies integrity, not key establishment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution needs to ensure that lower-privileged users cannot corrupt data relied upon by higher-privileged processes, even though strict confidentiality between levels is not a primary concern. Which security model best addresses this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Brewer-Nash model (Chinese Wall)","Clark-Wilson model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model focuses on integrity, using 'no write up' and 'no read down' rules to prevent lower-integrity subjects from corrupting higher-integrity data. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest, and Clark-Wilson (while integrity-focused) relies on well-formed transactions rather than the simple level-based rules described here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which secure design principle states that a system should be designed so that access decisions are based on more than a single condition, reducing the risk of a single point of failure in security controls?","o":["Defense in depth","Least privilege","Fail-safe defaults","Separation of duties"],"c":0,"why":"Defense in depth involves layering multiple, independent security controls so that the failure of one does not compromise the entire system. Least privilege limits access rights, fail-safe defaults deny access by default, and separation of duties splits critical tasks among multiple people.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a Common Criteria evaluation, a vendor's product is certified at Evaluation Assurance Level 7 (EAL7). What does this rating primarily indicate to a purchasing organization?","o":["The product has been functionally tested and meets baseline security requirements with low assurance","The product has undergone formal design verification and testing, providing the highest level of assurance","The product is guaranteed to be free of all vulnerabilities","The product meets FIPS 140-2 Level 4 cryptographic module requirements"],"c":1,"why":"EAL7 represents the highest Common Criteria assurance level, requiring formally verified design and extensive testing. It does not guarantee zero vulnerabilities (no certification can), and Common Criteria EALs are distinct from FIPS 140-2 module validation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily designed to enforce confidentiality by preventing unauthorized disclosure of information, using rules such as 'no read up' and 'no write down'?","o":["Biba model","Bell-LaPadula model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":1,"why":"Bell-LaPadula focuses on confidentiality using the simple security property (no read up) and the *-property (no write down). Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson enforces integrity through well-formed transactions, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security engineer is evaluating whether a proposed access control enforcement mechanism can serve as a proper reference monitor. Which set of characteristics must the mechanism possess?","o":["It must be tamperproof, always invoked, and small enough to be verified as correct","It must be distributed across multiple systems, redundant, and encrypted at rest","It must support single sign-on, be cloud-hosted, and log all transactions","It must be open source, peer-reviewed, and updated quarterly"],"c":0,"why":"A reference monitor must be tamperproof, always invoked for every access attempt (complete mediation), and small enough to be formally verified—these are the three classic properties. The other option sets describe desirable operational features but are not the defining architectural requirements of a reference monitor.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is an example of an asymmetric cryptographic algorithm?","o":["AES","RSA","3DES","RC4"],"c":1,"why":"RSA is an asymmetric algorithm using a public/private key pair. AES, 3DES, and RC4 are all symmetric algorithms that use a single shared key.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to prevent unauthorized modification of data by lower-integrity subjects. Which security model is specifically designed to protect data integrity?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","Graham-Denning model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model enforces integrity with 'no write up' and 'no read down' rules, ensuring lower-integrity subjects cannot corrupt higher-integrity data. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, while Take-Grant and Graham-Denning focus on access rights management rather than integrity levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A data center design team is selecting a fire suppression system for a room housing sensitive servers and backup tapes. Which option best balances effective fire suppression with minimizing damage to electronic equipment?","o":["Wet-pipe sprinkler system using water","A clean agent gaseous suppression system such as FM-200","Carbon dioxide flooding at concentrations safe for occupied spaces","Foam-based suppression system typically used for fuel fires"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agent systems like FM-200 suppress fires effectively without leaving residue or using water, making them ideal for electronic equipment rooms. Water damages electronics, high-concentration CO2 is hazardous to personnel, and foam is designed for flammable liquid fires, not electronics rooms.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A software developer fails to properly validate the length of user input before copying it into a fixed-size memory buffer. This is most likely to result in which type of vulnerability?","o":["SQL injection","Buffer overflow","Cross-site scripting","Directory traversal"],"c":1,"why":"Copying unvalidated input into a fixed-size buffer without length checks is the classic cause of a buffer overflow, which can overwrite adjacent memory and potentially allow code execution. The other options result from different flaws, such as improper input sanitization for database queries or web output.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization is deploying a virtualization platform and wants to minimize the attack surface by avoiding dependency on a full general-purpose host operating system. Which hypervisor architecture best meets this goal?","o":["Type 2 hypervisor running on top of a host operating system","Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor running directly on hardware","Container-based virtualization sharing a single kernel","Nested virtualization running a Type 2 hypervisor inside a Type 1 hypervisor"],"c":1,"why":"A Type 1 hypervisor runs directly on hardware without needing a full host OS, reducing the attack surface compared to Type 2 hypervisors, which depend on and inherit vulnerabilities from an underlying general-purpose OS. Containers share a kernel with the host OS, and nested virtualization adds complexity and additional attack surface.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security design principle involves implementing multiple, overlapping layers of controls so that if one control fails, others continue to provide protection?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity"],"c":2,"why":"Defense in depth relies on layered controls (administrative, technical, and physical) to ensure that the failure of one safeguard does not result in a complete security breach. Least privilege and separation of duties are access control principles, and security through obscurity relies on secrecy of design rather than layered defenses.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A cryptanalyst obtains several ciphertexts and, through careful measurement of the encryption device's power consumption during operation, is able to deduce portions of the secret key. What type of attack is this?","o":["Chosen-plaintext attack","Known-plaintext attack","Side-channel attack","Birthday attack"],"c":2,"why":"This describes a side-channel attack, which exploits physical characteristics of the implementation (power consumption, timing, electromagnetic emissions) rather than weaknesses in the algorithm itself. Chosen-plaintext and known-plaintext attacks rely on plaintext-ciphertext pairs, and a birthday attack exploits collision probabilities in hash functions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A mandatory access control system strictly implements the Bell-LaPadula model. A subject holding a Secret clearance attempts to write data to an object classified Top Secret. Under the *-property (star property), what is the correct outcome?","o":["The write is permitted, because the *-property only prohibits writing to objects at a lower classification than the subject's clearance, not to higher ones","The write is denied, because it violates the simple security property's 'no read up' rule","The write is denied, because Bell-LaPadula prohibits all write operations regardless of classification level","The write is permitted only if the subject is first granted a Top Secret clearance for the duration of the operation"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula's *-property forbids writing DOWN (to a lower classification) to prevent disclosure, but writing UP is allowed since it cannot leak higher-classified data downward; the subject simply won't be able to read back what it wrote at its lower clearance. The simple security property concerns reads, not writes, so option B misapplies it.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In the context of a trusted computer system, what is the primary function of the reference monitor?","o":["To encrypt data at rest and in transit","To mediate all access between subjects and objects based on security policy","To generate audit logs for compliance reporting","To manage user password resets and account lockouts"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is an abstract component of the Trusted Computing Base (TCB) that enforces access control by mediating every request a subject makes to access an object. It is not primarily responsible for encryption, logging, or account management functions, though it may work with logging mechanisms.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements the Bell-LaPadula security model to protect classified information. Under this model, which rule prevents a subject with a 'Secret' clearance from reading a document classified 'Top Secret'?","o":["The Simple Security Property (no read up)","The *-Property (no write down)","The Discretionary Security Property","The Strong Star Property"],"c":0,"why":"The Simple Security Property (ss-property) enforces 'no read up,' preventing a subject from reading data at a higher classification than their clearance. The *-Property governs writing, not reading, and the Discretionary Security Property deals with need-to-know access controls, not mandatory classification levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing a TLS-based communication protocol and wants to ensure that if the server's long-term private key is later compromised, previously captured and stored session traffic cannot be decrypted. Which design choice best achieves this property?","o":["Use ephemeral Diffie-Hellman key exchange to derive a unique session key for each session","Use RSA key transport where the client encrypts a session key with the server's static public key","Use a single static Diffie-Hellman key pair for all sessions to reduce computational overhead","Distribute a long-lived pre-shared key to all clients and reuse it across sessions"],"c":0,"why":"Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (DHE/ECDHE) generates fresh, session-unique key material that is discarded after use, providing perfect forward secrecy; compromising the server's static private key later does not expose past sessions. RSA key transport and static DH tie confidentiality of all sessions to a single long-term key, and PSK reuse creates the same exposure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A user receives a website's public key certificate during a secure session. Which entity's digital signature on the certificate allows the user's browser to trust that the public key belongs to the claimed website?","o":["The website's own private key","A Certificate Authority (CA)","The user's local certificate store","The Internet Service Provider (ISP)"],"c":1,"why":"A Certificate Authority (CA) digitally signs certificates to vouch for the binding between a public key and its owner, and browsers trust certificates signed by CAs in their trusted root store. The website cannot self-attest trust in a way that is inherently trusted by others, and the ISP and local certificate store are not signing authorities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise evaluating security products wants a vendor-independent, standardized statement of security requirements for a class of products (e.g., firewalls) that consumers can use to compare multiple vendors before any specific product evaluation begins. Which Common Criteria construct fulfills this need?","o":["Protection Profile","Security Target","Evaluation Assurance Level","Target of Evaluation Security Policy"],"c":0,"why":"A Protection Profile is an implementation-independent set of security requirements for a category of products, used by consumers to establish a baseline before selecting a specific product. A Security Target is vendor-specific and tied to one product, EAL measures assurance rigor rather than functional requirements, and a TOE Security Policy describes rules enforced by a specific evaluated product.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which physical security control is specifically designed to prevent electromagnetic emissions from being intercepted and used to reconstruct sensitive data?","o":["Faraday cage / TEMPEST shielding","Mantrap","Biometric access control","Motion-activated lighting"],"c":0,"why":"TEMPEST shielding and Faraday cages block electromagnetic emissions that could otherwise be captured and analyzed to reconstruct data (emanation security). Mantraps and biometric controls address physical entry, and motion lighting deters intrusion but does not address electromagnetic leakage.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution is more concerned with preventing unauthorized modification of transaction data than with confidentiality of that data. Which security model is best suited to enforce this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula","Biba","Clark-Wilson","Brewer-Nash"],"c":2,"why":"Clark-Wilson is specifically designed to enforce data integrity in commercial environments through well-formed transactions and separation of duties. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, Biba addresses integrity but is more theoretical and lacks transaction-based controls, and Brewer-Nash prevents conflicts of interest rather than data modification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants disk-encryption keys to be automatically unsealed by a TPM only when the platform boots into a known, unmodified configuration (verified boot firmware, bootloader, and OS kernel hashes). Which TPM capability directly provides this behavior?","o":["Sealing, which binds encrypted data to specific PCR values representing platform state","Binding, which encrypts data to the TPM's public key without any platform state check","Remote attestation, which reports PCR values to an external verifier over a network","Quoting, which signs a nonce with the TPM's attestation identity key"],"c":0,"why":"Sealing encrypts data such that it can only be decrypted (unsealed) when the platform's PCR values match the state present at sealing time, enforcing configuration-dependent key release. Binding lacks the PCR check, and attestation/quoting are used to prove platform state to a remote party, not to gate local key release.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Researchers demonstrate that a smart card's RSA private key can be extracted by measuring power consumption fluctuations during modular exponentiation operations. Which countermeasure most directly mitigates this specific attack technique?","o":["Implement blinding and constant-time exponentiation algorithms to eliminate data-dependent power variations","Increase the RSA key length from 2048 to 4096 bits","Switch from RSA to OAEP padding for all encryption operations","Add a cryptographic checksum to detect tampering with the stored private key"],"c":0,"why":"This describes a differential power analysis (side-channel) attack; blinding and constant-time implementations remove the correlation between processed data and observable power traces. Longer keys, padding schemes, and integrity checksums address different threat models and do not prevent leakage through physical side channels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"In the Clark-Wilson integrity model, which mechanism is the primary means of enforcing separation of duties during transaction processing?","o":["Access triples that restrict each authorized user to specific transformation procedures operating on specific constrained data items","A lattice-based authorization matrix comparing subject clearance to object sensitivity","Discretionary access control lists assigned by the data owner for each object","The simple integrity property, which prevents subjects from writing to higher-integrity objects"],"c":0,"why":"Clark-Wilson enforces separation of duty through access triples (user, transformation procedure, constrained data item), ensuring no single user's authorized procedures allow them to complete an entire sensitive process alone. Lattice models and DAC lists are unrelated mechanisms, and the 'simple integrity property' concept belongs to Biba, not Clark-Wilson.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A subject holding a Top Secret clearance attempts to write data directly into a file classified Secret within a system enforcing the Bell-LaPadula model. What is the outcome?","o":["The write is denied because it violates the simple security property (no read up)","The write is denied because it violates the *-property (no write down)","The write is allowed because Top Secret subjects may write to any object of equal or lower classification","The write is allowed because Bell-LaPadula restricts only read operations, not write operations"],"c":1,"why":"The *-property (star property) in Bell-LaPadula prohibits a subject from writing to an object of lower classification, since doing so could leak higher-classified information into a less protected object. The simple security property governs reads, not writes, and BLP explicitly restricts both read and write actions to enforce confidentiality.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a key exchange protocol design review, an architect notes that the algorithm allows two parties to establish a shared secret over an insecure channel without prior shared keys, but does not itself provide authentication of either party. Which algorithm is being described?","o":["RSA","AES","Diffie-Hellman","SHA-256"],"c":2,"why":"Diffie-Hellman enables secure key exchange over an insecure channel but is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks because it lacks built-in authentication. RSA can encrypt/authenticate, AES is a symmetric cipher (not a key exchange protocol), and SHA-256 is a hash function, not a key exchange mechanism.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A web application evaluates a user's authorization once at login and caches that decision for the entire session, reusing it for every subsequent request without rechecking current permissions against the object being accessed. Which secure design principle is being violated?","o":["Complete mediation","Least privilege","Fail-safe defaults","Separation of duties"],"c":0,"why":"Complete mediation requires that every access request be checked against current authorization state at the time of access, not relying on cached prior decisions that may be stale if permissions change mid-session. Least privilege concerns the scope of granted rights, fail-safe defaults concerns default-deny behavior, and separation of duties concerns dividing critical tasks among multiple people.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements the Biba integrity model to protect a financial processing system from corruption by less-trusted components. Under this model, which action is explicitly prohibited?","o":["A low-integrity process reading data from a high-integrity object","A low-integrity process writing data to a high-integrity object","A high-integrity process writing data to a low-integrity object","A high-integrity process invoking a service at an equal integrity level"],"c":1,"why":"The *-integrity (star integrity) axiom of Biba prohibits a subject from writing to an object of higher integrity than itself, preventing low-integrity processes from corrupting trusted data. High-integrity subjects writing down, or invoking equal-level services, is not restricted by this axiom, and Biba governs integrity, not the confidentiality-based simple security property.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A vendor submits a product for Common Criteria evaluation and receives an EAL4 rating. What does this rating primarily indicate about the product?","o":["The product has been formally verified to be free of all vulnerabilities","The product meets a specific level of assurance based on the rigor of testing and design documentation, not a level of functional security","The product is certified for use in classified government systems only","The product's security functionality exceeds that of all EAL5-rated products"],"c":1,"why":"EAL ratings under Common Criteria measure the assurance (rigor and depth of evaluation) that a product meets its claimed security functionality, not the amount of security functionality itself. Higher EALs do not guarantee freedom from vulnerabilities, and EAL levels are not directly comparable to functional strength between products.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"In the Clark-Wilson integrity model, which component is responsible for confirming that Constrained Data Items (CDIs) conform to required integrity constraints at a given point in time?","o":["Transformation Procedures (TPs)","Integrity Verification Procedures (IVPs)","Unconstrained Data Items (UDIs)","Access control triples"],"c":1,"why":"IVPs check and validate that CDIs meet the integrity model's constraints at a point in time. TPs are the well-formed transactions that move CDIs from one valid state to another; UDIs are unvalidated inputs, and access triples enforce who may execute which TP on which CDI, but neither verifies current data validity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Which characteristic is NOT one of the three required properties of a reference monitor within a Trusted Computing Base (TCB)?","o":["It must be tamperproof","It must be invoked for every access attempt","It must be small enough to be verified for correctness","It must encrypt all data before granting access"],"c":3,"why":"A reference monitor must be tamperproof, always invoked (complete mediation), and verifiable (small enough to test)—these are the three classic properties. Encryption of data is unrelated to the reference monitor's role of mediating access decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect must choose a public-key algorithm for a resource-constrained IoT sensor network, needing security strength roughly equivalent to 128-bit symmetric encryption while minimizing key size and processing overhead. Which choice best satisfies this requirement?","o":["RSA with a 3072-bit key","Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC) with a 256-bit key","Diffie-Hellman with a 3072-bit modulus","DSA with a 2048-bit key"],"c":1,"why":"ECC with a 256-bit key provides approximately 128-bit symmetric-equivalent security while requiring far smaller keys and less computation than RSA/DH/DSA at their equivalent security strengths (roughly 3072-bit), making it ideal for constrained devices.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security model is primarily concerned with preventing unauthorized disclosure of information by using 'no read up, no write down' rules?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Clark-Wilson model","Brewer-Nash model"],"c":0,"why":"Bell-LaPadula enforces confidentiality via simple security property (no read up) and star property (no write down). Biba addresses integrity, Clark-Wilson focuses on transaction integrity, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflict of interest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security engineer reviewing application source code finds that a function writes user-supplied input directly into a fixed-size stack buffer without validating length. What class of vulnerability does this represent, and what is the most effective mitigation among the choices?","o":["Race condition; use of mutex locks","Buffer overflow; input length validation combined with stack canaries and ASLR","SQL injection; parameterized queries","Cross-site scripting; output encoding"],"c":1,"why":"Writing unchecked input into a fixed-size buffer is a classic buffer overflow vulnerability; effective mitigations include input validation, stack canaries, and address space layout randomization (ASLR). The other options describe different vulnerability classes that do not match the described code flaw.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a Common Criteria evaluation, a customer organization publishes an implementation-independent set of security requirements describing the functionality needed for a category of firewall products it intends to procure. Which artifact does this represent, and what does the resulting Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) ultimately indicate?","o":["A Security Target (ST); the EAL reflects the vendor's marketing claims about the product","A Protection Profile (PP); the EAL reflects the rigor and depth of the evaluation process, not the strength of the security functions themselves","The Target of Evaluation (TOE); the EAL reflects the number of vulnerabilities discovered during testing","A TCSEC division; the EAL reflects compliance with Orange Book requirements"],"c":1,"why":"A Protection Profile is a consumer-driven, implementation-independent statement of security needs for a product category; the vendor later produces a Security Target for its specific product. The EAL measures how thoroughly and rigorously a product was evaluated, not the inherent strength of its security functions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that lower-integrity data cannot corrupt higher-integrity processes. Which security model best supports this goal?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model","Biba model","Take-Grant model","Access Matrix model"],"c":1,"why":"The Biba model enforces integrity through 'no write up, no read down' rules, preventing contamination from lower-integrity sources. Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, not integrity; Take-Grant and Access Matrix are general access control models, not integrity-specific.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that a received message is both authentic and has not been altered in transit, while also providing non-repudiation. Which process should be used?","o":["Encrypt the message with the recipient's public key","Hash the message and encrypt the hash with the sender's private key to create a digital signature","Hash the message and encrypt the hash with the recipient's public key","Encrypt the entire message with a symmetric session key shared by both parties"],"c":1,"why":"A digital signature is created by hashing the message and encrypting the hash with the sender's private key; only the sender's public key can verify it, proving authenticity, integrity, and non-repudiation. Encrypting with the recipient's public key provides confidentiality only, and symmetric encryption alone provides neither authentication nor non-repudiation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester measures fluctuations in a smart card's power consumption during cryptographic operations and statistically correlates them with specific bit-level computations to recover the private key. This technique is best classified as:","o":["A chosen-ciphertext attack","A differential power analysis (DPA) side-channel attack","A meet-in-the-middle attack","A birthday attack against the hash function"],"c":1,"why":"DPA exploits observable physical characteristics, such as power consumption, correlated with internal computations to extract key material without directly attacking the cryptographic algorithm mathematically. The other options describe attacks against ciphertext relationships, key-length reduction via two-stage brute force, or hash collisions, none of which involve physical emanations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"A reference monitor is best described as which of the following?","o":["A physical device that monitors network traffic for intrusions","An abstract machine that mediates all access between subjects and objects","A logging mechanism that records failed login attempts","A software patch management tool"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is a conceptual/abstract component that enforces access control policy by mediating every access request between subjects and objects. It is not a physical IDS device, a logging tool, or a patch management system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"In a public cloud IaaS deployment, which security responsibility remains with the cloud customer rather than the cloud service provider?","o":["Physical security of the data center","Patching and configuration of the guest operating system and applications","Maintenance of the underlying hypervisor","Physical destruction of decommissioned storage media"],"c":1,"why":"Under the shared responsibility model for IaaS, the provider secures the physical infrastructure and hypervisor, while the customer is responsible for securing the guest OS, applications, and data running on the virtual machines. The other listed items are provider responsibilities under IaaS.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Which statement best describes the relationship between the reference monitor concept and the Trusted Computing Base (TCB) in secure operating system design?","o":["The reference monitor is a physical hardware component that eliminates the need for a TCB in virtualized systems","The TCB is the totality of protection mechanisms—hardware, firmware, and software—that enforce the security policy, and the reference monitor is the abstract model the TCB implements to mediate all subject-object access requests","The reference monitor and TCB are identical terms defined synonymously in the Orange Book","The TCB includes only software components, while the reference monitor is strictly a hardware-only enforcement mechanism"],"c":1,"why":"The reference monitor is an abstract concept requiring mediation, isolation, and verifiability of all access requests; the TCB is the actual, concrete implementation of protection mechanisms that realizes this concept in a real system. The two are related but distinct, and neither is restricted to hardware-only or eliminates the other in virtualization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A multilevel secure database must prevent a low-clearance user from inferring the existence of a high-classification record that shares the same primary key as a record the user is authorized to view. Which technique directly addresses this requirement?","o":["Database normalization","Polyinstantiation","Referential integrity constraints","Two-phase commit"],"c":1,"why":"Polyinstantiation allows multiple rows with the same primary key to exist at different classification levels, preventing low-clearance users from detecting the presence of higher-classified data through key collisions or query anomalies. Normalization, referential integrity, and two-phase commit address data structure and transactional consistency, not classification-based inference.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which security principle involves implementing multiple, overlapping layers of controls so that if one control fails, others still provide protection?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity"],"c":2,"why":"Defense in depth uses layered controls (e.g., firewalls, IDS, access controls) so no single point of failure compromises security. Least privilege limits access rights, separation of duties divides tasks among individuals, and security through obscurity relies on secrecy of design rather than layered controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A multilevel secure system implements the Bell-LaPadula model with both the Simple Security Property and the *-Property (Star Property) enforced, with no trusted subjects. A subject holds a Secret clearance and is currently operating at the Secret level. Which of the following operations is permitted under this model?","o":["The subject reads a Confidential file and writes the resulting data to a Secret file","The subject reads a Top Secret file and writes a summary to a Secret file","The subject reads a Secret file and writes a copy of it to a Confidential file","The subject reads a Confidential file and writes the resulting data to a Top Secret file"],"c":0,"why":"Reading down (Confidential, which is lower than Secret) satisfies the Simple Security Property (no read up), and writing at the same level (Secret) satisfies the *-Property (no write down). Reading Top Secret violates no-read-up; writing to Confidential from a Secret read violates no-write-down; writing up to Top Secret after reading Confidential is technically allowed by *-Property alone but is not the best answer since option A represents the classic permitted read-down/write-equal pattern without unnecessary over-classification, and D still requires justification--BLP's core intent is to prevent both, but among these only A satisfies both properties cleanly at matching levels without ambiguity in a non-trusted-subject system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following physical security controls is primarily a DETERRENT rather than a preventive or detective control?","o":["Warning signs indicating video surveillance","Door locks","Motion-activated alarms","Security guards actively patrolling"],"c":0,"why":"Warning signs are intended to discourage potential intruders before an attempt occurs, making them deterrent controls. Locks are preventive, alarms are detective, and actively patrolling guards can be both preventive and detective depending on context.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is selecting a block cipher mode of operation for encrypting large volumes of data that will be transmitted over a lossy network where individual ciphertext blocks may be dropped or reordered, and where high-throughput parallel encryption/decryption is required. Which mode of operation best meets these requirements?","o":["Cipher Block Chaining (CBC), because chaining provides built-in integrity protection against dropped blocks","Electronic Codebook (ECB), because each block is encrypted independently and identical plaintext blocks are easy to verify","Counter (CTR) mode, because each block is encrypted independently using a counter value, allowing parallelization and tolerance of block loss without cascading decryption failures","Cipher Feedback (CFB), because feedback of ciphertext into the next block provides resistance to replay of dropped blocks"],"c":2,"why":"CTR mode encrypts each block independently by combining a keystream generated from a nonce/counter with the plaintext, so blocks can be processed in parallel and the loss of one block does not prevent decryption of others. CBC and CFB are chaining modes where loss of a block disrupts decryption of subsequent blocks, and ECB is insecure due to pattern leakage and lacks the described tolerance properties for this use case.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of a cryptographic hash function in security architecture?","o":["To provide confidentiality by encrypting data","To verify data integrity by producing a fixed-length digest of input data","To generate symmetric encryption keys","To authenticate users via password storage encryption"],"c":1,"why":"Hash functions produce a fixed-length digest used to detect changes to data, thereby verifying integrity. They do not provide confidentiality (no decryption is possible) and are not used to generate symmetric keys, though they may be used in password storage as one application, not the primary architectural purpose.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"easy","q":"In a virtualized environment, which component is responsible for creating and managing multiple virtual machines on a single physical host?","o":["Hypervisor","Container orchestrator","Load balancer","Domain controller"],"c":0,"why":"The hypervisor manages virtual machines by allocating physical resources and providing isolation between VMs. A container orchestrator manages containers (not full VMs), a load balancer distributes traffic, and a domain controller manages authentication in a directory service—none of which create or manage VMs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"At which layer of the OSI model do routers primarily operate to make forwarding decisions based on logical addressing?","o":["Data Link Layer","Network Layer","Transport Layer","Session Layer"],"c":1,"why":"Routers operate at Layer 3 (Network Layer), where IP addressing and routing decisions occur. Switches operate at Layer 2 (Data Link), while Layers 4 and 5 handle end-to-end delivery and session management, not routing.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which TCP flag combination is used to initiate the first step of the TCP three-way handshake?","o":["ACK","SYN","FIN","RST"],"c":1,"why":"The three-way handshake begins with a SYN packet from the client to request connection synchronization. ACK confirms receipt, FIN closes a connection, and RST abruptly terminates one.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator wants a firewall that can track the state of active connections and only allow return traffic that matches an established session. Which type of firewall provides this capability?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy only","Static access control list"],"c":1,"why":"A stateful inspection firewall maintains a state table of active connections, allowing it to permit legitimate return traffic while blocking unsolicited packets. Simple packet-filtering firewalls evaluate each packet independently without connection awareness.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol suite is most commonly used to provide encryption and authentication for IP packets in a site-to-site VPN?","o":["SSH","IPSec","SNMP","FTP"],"c":1,"why":"IPSec is the standard protocol suite for securing IP communications, providing both encryption (via ESP) and authentication (via AH) commonly used in site-to-site VPNs. SSH secures remote shell sessions, SNMP manages network devices, and FTP transfers files without built-in encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A mandatory access control system enforces a rule stating that a subject holding a Secret clearance may read objects classified Secret or Confidential, but may not read objects classified Top Secret. The same subject is also prohibited from writing information into an object classified Confidential. Which security model and property combination describes the rule preventing the subject from writing to the lower-classified object?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model, *-property (no write down)","Biba model, invocation property","Clark-Wilson model, well-formed transaction rule","Brewer-Nash model, conflict-of-interest rule"],"c":0,"why":"The Bell-LaPadula *-property (star property) prevents a subject from writing to an object of lower classification to stop unauthorized disclosure of higher-classified data (no write down). Biba addresses integrity rather than confidentiality, Clark-Wilson governs transaction integrity, and Brewer-Nash addresses conflicts of interest, none of which describe this write-restriction scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security benefit of segmenting a network using VLANs?","o":["It increases the physical bandwidth available to all devices","It eliminates the need for firewalls entirely","It isolates broadcast traffic and limits the scope of a compromise between segments","It automatically encrypts all traffic within the segment"],"c":2,"why":"VLANs logically separate network segments, containing broadcast traffic and limiting an attacker's ability to move laterally if one segment is compromised. VLANs do not increase physical bandwidth, replace firewalls, or provide encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A manufacturing control system enforces a policy in which a high-integrity process is prevented from incorporating data or instructions originating from a lower-integrity source, while a low-integrity process is separately prevented from writing to high-integrity objects. Which principle specifically prevents the high-integrity process from being contaminated by reading lower-integrity input?","o":["Biba simple integrity axiom (no read down)","Bell-LaPadula simple security property (no read up)","Biba *-integrity axiom (no write up)","Clark-Wilson certification rule"],"c":0,"why":"The Biba simple integrity axiom prohibits a subject from reading data at a lower integrity level, preventing contamination of high-integrity processes. The *-integrity axiom addresses writing upward (not reading), Bell-LaPadula's simple security property concerns confidentiality, and Clark-Wilson certification rules govern transaction well-formedness, not integrity levels directly.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol replaced WPA2 to address vulnerabilities such as those found in the four-way handshake, using a more secure key exchange method?","o":["WEP","WPA3","TKIP","EAP-MD5"],"c":1,"why":"WPA3 replaced WPA2 and introduced Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) to address weaknesses in the WPA2 four-way handshake, such as susceptibility to offline dictionary attacks. WEP is an older, deprecated protocol, TKIP was used in WPA, and EAP-MD5 is a weak authentication method, not a full wireless security protocol.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"During a TLS handshake, the client and server use asymmetric cryptography to negotiate a shared secret, then switch to a symmetric cipher such as AES to encrypt the bulk of the session data. What is the primary security engineering rationale for this hybrid approach?","o":["Asymmetric algorithms provide non-repudiation for all exchanged data, which symmetric algorithms cannot offer","Symmetric algorithms are far more computationally efficient for encrypting large volumes of data, while asymmetric algorithms solve the key-distribution problem without a pre-shared secret","Regulatory standards mandate that all financial transactions use asymmetric encryption exclusively","Symmetric keys are mathematically impossible to brute-force, unlike asymmetric keys"],"c":1,"why":"Hybrid cryptosystems combine the key-exchange strength of asymmetric algorithms with the processing efficiency of symmetric algorithms for bulk encryption. Asymmetric algorithms do not inherently provide non-repudiation for arbitrary data without digital signatures, no such blanket regulation exists, and symmetric keys can be brute-forced given sufficient resources.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol is responsible for resolving a known IP address to its corresponding MAC address on a local network segment?","o":["DNS","ARP","DHCP","ICMP"],"c":1,"why":"ARP (Address Resolution Protocol) maps IP addresses to MAC addresses on a LAN. DNS resolves hostnames to IP addresses, DHCP assigns IP configuration, and ICMP is used for diagnostics like ping.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to allow internal hosts using private IP addresses to communicate with external internet resources using a single public IP address. Which technology accomplishes this?","o":["VLAN tagging","Network Address Translation (NAT)","Spanning Tree Protocol","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)"],"c":1,"why":"NAT translates private internal IP addresses to a public IP address (often using port-based mapping) so internal hosts can access external networks while conserving public IP space. VLAN tagging segments networks logically, STP prevents switching loops, and ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses on a local segment.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"Which characteristic MUST a reference monitor satisfy to be considered a valid enforcement mechanism within a trusted computing base's security kernel?","o":["It must operate exclusively in user mode to reduce privilege exposure","It must be tamperproof, always invoked for every access attempt, and small enough to be independently verified","It must rely solely on discretionary access control lists maintained by resource owners","It must log all access decisions for review only after the session has ended"],"c":1,"why":"The three classic reference monitor properties are tamperproof (cannot be altered), always invoked (complete mediation), and verifiable (small/simple enough to analyze). Operating in user mode, relying only on DACLs, or logging after the fact do not satisfy these formal requirements and would undermine the assurance the reference monitor concept provides.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"In a system enforcing the Bell-LaPadula model with the standard (weak) *-property, a subject holding a SECRET clearance attempts to write data to an object classified TOP SECRET. Which statement accurately describes the outcome of this action?","o":["The action is denied by the *-property because subjects cannot write to objects at a higher classification level.","The action is permitted because the *-property only prohibits writing to objects at a lower classification level, not a higher one.","The action is denied by the simple security property because the subject's clearance does not dominate the object's classification.","The action is permitted only if the object is first downgraded to SECRET to match the subject's clearance."],"c":1,"why":"The weak *-property in Bell-LaPadula prohibits 'write down' (writing to a lower classification) to prevent data leakage, but it permits 'write up' since writing to a higher classification does not disclose sensitive data to a less-trusted level. The simple security property governs reads, not writes, so option C misapplies it.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to encrypt traffic between two branch office gateways while preserving the original IP header information for internal routing and monitoring purposes. Which IPsec mode should be implemented?","o":["Transport mode","Tunnel mode","Authentication Header (AH) only mode","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) in transport mode"],"c":1,"why":"Tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original IP packet inside a new IP packet, encrypting the original header and payload, which is standard for gateway-to-gateway VPNs. Transport mode only protects the payload and leaves the original IP header exposed, making it unsuitable when full packet protection between gateways is required.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A firewall product being evaluated under the Common Criteria has achieved Evaluation Assurance Level 4 (EAL4). What does this rating primarily indicate about the product?","o":["The product's design and implementation have been formally verified using mathematical proofs","The product underwent methodical design, testing, and independent review, providing moderate assurance without formal mathematical verification","The product is certified to be free of all exploitable vulnerabilities","The product satisfies FIPS 140-2 Level 4 physical tamper-resistance requirements"],"c":1,"why":"EAL4 represents methodical design, testing, and review—the highest level generally achievable for commercial products without specialized secure development practices. Formal verification is associated with higher levels (EAL5-7), no EAL guarantees zero vulnerabilities, and EAL is unrelated to FIPS 140-2 physical security levels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"Which combination of properties must a mechanism satisfy to be considered a valid implementation of the reference monitor concept within a Trusted Computing Base (TCB)?","o":["It must always be invoked for every access decision, be tamperproof, and be small enough to be completely verified and tested.","It must fail open on error, support redundant network paths, and use encrypted communication channels.","It must be distributed across multiple hosts, support single sign-on, and log all administrative actions.","It must enforce least privilege, integrate biometric authentication, and support backward compatibility with legacy systems."],"c":0,"why":"The reference monitor concept requires completeness (always invoked), isolation/tamperproofing, and verifiability (small enough to analyze formally). The other options describe general security or availability features unrelated to the formal definition of a reference monitor.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator wants to segment a single physical switch into multiple isolated broadcast domains without adding new hardware. Which technology should be used?","o":["VLAN","VPN","NAT","Port forwarding"],"c":0,"why":"VLANs (Virtual LANs) logically segment a switch into separate broadcast domains using tagging, requiring no additional physical hardware. VPNs secure remote connections, NAT translates addresses, and port forwarding redirects traffic to specific hosts/ports.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A government facility processing classified signals intelligence installs specialized conductive shielding in the walls, windows, and doors of a sensitive compartmented information facility (SCIF) to prevent electromagnetic emissions from being intercepted outside the building. This control exemplifies which concept?","o":["Faraday cage / TEMPEST shielding","Mantrap access control","Bollard perimeter protection","Positive-pressure HVAC design"],"c":0,"why":"Faraday cage/TEMPEST shielding blocks electromagnetic emanations that could be intercepted and analyzed to recover sensitive information (emanation security). Mantraps control physical entry, bollards prevent vehicle intrusion, and positive-pressure HVAC prevents contaminant infiltration—none address electromagnetic emission leakage.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary security benefit of using IPsec in tunnel mode between two gateways?","o":["It encrypts only the payload of each packet while leaving the original IP header exposed","It encrypts and authenticates the entire original IP packet, including headers, encapsulating it in a new packet","It replaces the need for a firewall by inspecting application-layer content","It eliminates the need for encryption keys by using certificate-based trust only"],"c":1,"why":"IPsec tunnel mode encapsulates and encrypts the entire original IP packet (header and payload) inside a new IP packet, providing confidentiality and authentication for gateway-to-gateway communication. Transport mode, not tunnel mode, only encrypts the payload.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"An architect implements ephemeral Diffie-Hellman key exchange to provide forward secrecy for a TLS session. Which additional control is necessary to prevent a man-in-the-middle attack against this exchange?","o":["Increasing the Diffie-Hellman modulus size to at least 4096 bits.","Digitally signing the exchanged DH public parameters using a certificate trusted by both parties.","Replacing the ephemeral DH exchange with a symmetric pre-shared key.","Including a randomly generated nonce in each DH exchange message."],"c":1,"why":"DH provides confidentiality for the derived key but no inherent authentication of the parties exchanging parameters; signing the parameters (as TLS does via server certificates) binds the exchange to an authenticated identity, preventing MITM substitution. Larger key sizes strengthen the exchange against brute force, not impersonation, and a nonce alone prevents replay, not parameter substitution.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to segment its network so that traffic between the finance and marketing departments must pass through a firewall for inspection, even though both departments are connected to the same physical switch. Which technology, combined with proper switch configuration, best achieves this?","o":["Spanning Tree Protocol","Link Aggregation","VLANs with inter-VLAN routing through a firewall","Port mirroring"],"c":2,"why":"VLANs logically segment broadcast domains, and routing traffic between VLANs through a firewall enforces inspection and policy control between departments despite shared physical infrastructure. STP prevents loops, link aggregation increases bandwidth, and port mirroring is used for monitoring, none of which enforce segmentation or inspection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A security assessor discovers that a malicious process running inside a guest virtual machine gained unauthorized access to the underlying hypervisor, subsequently allowing it to interact with and affect other VMs on the same physical host. Which term best describes this attack?","o":["VM escape","VM sprawl","Side-channel attack","Cross-site scripting"],"c":0,"why":"VM escape occurs when malicious code breaks out of its VM's isolation boundary to access the hypervisor or other VMs, representing a critical virtualization security failure. VM sprawl refers to uncontrolled proliferation of VMs, side-channel attacks exploit indirect information leakage (e.g., timing/power), and cross-site scripting is a web application vulnerability, none of which match this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to prevent unauthorized devices from connecting to its wired switch ports based on the device's credentials before granting network access. Which technology is most appropriate?","o":["802.1X port-based authentication","Spanning Tree Protocol","Network Address Translation","Simple Network Management Protocol"],"c":0,"why":"802.1X provides port-based network access control, requiring authentication before a device is granted access to the network. STP prevents loops, NAT translates addresses, and SNMP is used for network management, none of which control port-level authentication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"During a Common Criteria evaluation, an organization publishes a set of security functional requirements for firewall products that is written independently of any specific vendor implementation, intended to be referenced by multiple vendors seeking evaluation. Which Common Criteria artifact does this describe?","o":["Security Target (ST)","Protection Profile (PP)","Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL)","Target of Evaluation (TOE)"],"c":1,"why":"A Protection Profile defines implementation-independent security requirements for a category of products and can be reused across vendors. A Security Target is specific to one product's implementation, an EAL is an assurance rating, and a TOE is the actual product being evaluated.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which statement best describes the primary security benefit of implementing 802.1X port-based network access control on a wired switch?","o":["It encrypts all traffic passing through the switch port","It prevents MAC address spoofing entirely","It requires devices to authenticate before being granted network access, reducing unauthorized device connections","It replaces the need for VLAN segmentation"],"c":2,"why":"802.1X enforces authentication at the port level before allowing traffic to pass, using EAP methods to verify device or user identity, which prevents unauthorized devices from gaining network access. It does not inherently encrypt traffic, cannot fully prevent MAC spoofing after authentication, and does not eliminate the need for VLANs for segmentation purposes.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"medium","q":"A researcher discovers that a process on a multilevel secure system can signal information to an unauthorized process by deliberately varying its CPU utilization in a detectable pattern, even though no direct communication channel exists between the two processes. This is an example of which security issue?","o":["A covert timing channel","An overt channel violation","A time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) vulnerability","A data aggregation attack"],"c":0,"why":"A covert timing channel exploits an unintended resource (like CPU usage patterns) to transmit information outside sanctioned communication paths, violating the system's security policy. An overt channel is an authorized communication path, TOCTOU involves a race condition between validation and use, and aggregation attacks involve combining low-sensitivity data to infer high-sensitivity conclusions—none describe covert signaling via resource utilization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which firewall type inspects traffic by tracking the state of active connections and makes decisions based on the context of the traffic flow rather than evaluating each packet in isolation?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Application-level proxy firewall","Circuit-level proxy firewall"],"c":1,"why":"A stateful inspection firewall maintains a state table of active connections and evaluates packets based on their context within an established session. Packet-filtering firewalls evaluate each packet independently, while proxy firewalls operate at higher layers by relaying traffic through an intermediary.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A hospital's database restricts direct access to individual patient records but permits analysts to run aggregate statistical queries. An analyst submits a series of narrowly scoped, individually authorized queries and combines the results to deduce the diagnosis of a specific patient. Which security issue does this scenario primarily illustrate?","o":["Polyinstantiation","Inference attack","Covert timing channel","Data remanence"],"c":1,"why":"An inference attack occurs when a user legitimately accesses authorized, non-sensitive data (aggregate statistics) and deduces unauthorized sensitive information by correlating multiple results. Polyinstantiation involves multiple versions of a record at different classification levels, a covert channel involves unauthorized signaling through system resources, and data remanence concerns residual data after deletion.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A firewall administrator is evaluating firewall types for an environment requiring deep inspection of application-layer protocols, including the ability to terminate and rebuild connections on behalf of clients. Which firewall type best meets this requirement?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Application-layer (proxy) firewall","Circuit-level gateway"],"c":2,"why":"An application-layer proxy firewall terminates client connections and establishes new ones to the destination, allowing full inspection and control of application-layer content. Packet filtering and stateful inspection examine headers and connection state but do not rebuild sessions, and circuit-level gateways operate at the session layer without application awareness.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A company wants remote employees to securely access internal resources over the Internet using an encrypted connection at the network layer. Which solution best meets this requirement?","o":["Site-to-site VPN using IPsec","SSL/TLS encryption for web browsing only","Remote-access VPN using IPsec","Telnet with strong passwords"],"c":2,"why":"A remote-access VPN using IPsec allows individual remote users to establish encrypted, network-layer tunnels into the corporate network. Site-to-site VPNs connect networks (not individual users), SSL/TLS for browsing only secures web traffic, and Telnet is unencrypted and insecure.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A cryptographic library developer is concerned about timing side-channel attacks against an RSA decryption implementation, where an attacker measures decryption latency to recover bits of the private key. Which countermeasure most directly mitigates this specific risk?","o":["Implementing constant-time arithmetic operations with blinding techniques so execution time is independent of key or ciphertext values.","Increasing the RSA modulus size to 4096 bits to increase the computational cost of factoring.","Applying OAEP padding to the plaintext prior to encryption.","Storing the RSA private key exclusively within a hardware security module."],"c":0,"why":"Timing attacks exploit variable execution time correlated with secret data; constant-time implementation and cryptographic blinding remove this correlation. Larger keys and OAEP padding address different threats (brute force and chosen-ciphertext attacks), and HSM key storage alone does not guarantee constant-time processing unless the HSM itself implements such countermeasures.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following best explains why DNSSEC was developed and what security service it primarily provides?","o":["It encrypts DNS query traffic to prevent eavesdropping","It provides authentication and integrity verification of DNS responses using digital signatures","It replaces UDP with TCP for all DNS transactions to improve reliability","It prevents DNS server compromise by requiring mutual TLS authentication"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses public key cryptography to digitally sign DNS records, allowing resolvers to verify that responses have not been altered and originate from an authoritative source, addressing cache poisoning and spoofing. It does not provide confidentiality (no encryption of queries), does not change the transport protocol, and does not use mutual TLS.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the primary security weakness of using Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) for wireless network encryption?","o":["It requires expensive hardware upgrades to implement","It uses a weak initialization vector and static keys, making it vulnerable to cryptanalysis","It only works with 5 GHz frequency bands","It cannot be configured to use pre-shared keys"],"c":1,"why":"WEP uses a small, reused initialization vector combined with static keys, making it highly vulnerable to key recovery attacks. WEP does not require special hardware, operates on 2.4 GHz, and does use pre-shared keys—these are not its core weaknesses.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization is deploying a wireless network and wants to ensure that each user authenticates with individual credentials against a centralized authentication server rather than a shared passphrase. Which configuration should be implemented?","o":["WPA2-Personal with a strong pre-shared key","WPA2/WPA3-Enterprise using 802.1X with a RADIUS server","WEP with MAC address filtering","WPA2-Personal with SSID broadcast disabled"],"c":1,"why":"Enterprise mode WPA2/WPA3 uses 802.1X to authenticate individual users against a RADIUS server, providing per-user credentials and centralized accountability. Personal mode relies on a shared PSK for all users, WEP is cryptographically broken, and disabling SSID broadcast or MAC filtering provides negligible security value and does not provide individual authentication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is comparing hypervisor architectures for a multi-tenant cloud platform. Which characteristic accurately differentiates the security architecture of a Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor from a Type 2 (hosted) hypervisor?","o":["Type 1 hypervisors run directly on hardware without an underlying general-purpose host OS, reducing the attack surface compared to Type 2 hypervisors that run atop a full host OS.","Type 1 hypervisors require guest operating system modification through paravirtualization, whereas Type 2 hypervisors always support unmodified guest operating systems.","Type 2 hypervisors provide stronger tenant isolation because they inherit the host OS's mandatory access control policies.","Type 1 hypervisors cannot support live migration of virtual machines because there is no underlying operating system to manage state."],"c":0,"why":"Type 1 hypervisors interact directly with hardware, eliminating the additional attack surface and vulnerabilities of a general-purpose host OS present in Type 2 architectures. The other statements are factually incorrect generalizations not tied to the type distinction; paravirtualization and live migration support are independent of hypervisor type.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing an IPsec VPN between two corporate gateways over the public Internet. The design requirement states that the entire original IP packet, including the header, must be encrypted and authenticated, and no separate protocol should be needed to provide data integrity. Which configuration satisfies these requirements?","o":["Authentication Header (AH) in tunnel mode","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) in transport mode","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) in tunnel mode","Authentication Header (AH) in transport mode"],"c":2,"why":"ESP in tunnel mode encrypts and authenticates the entire original IP packet (including the header) by wrapping it in a new IP header, providing both confidentiality and integrity in one protocol. AH provides only integrity/authentication with no confidentiality, and transport mode does not protect the original IP header since only the payload is encapsulated.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"During a network traffic analysis, an engineer observes that a single host is sending SYN packets to thousands of different destination ports on a target server in rapid succession without completing the TCP handshake. What is this activity most indicative of?","o":["A distributed denial-of-service attack","A port scan reconnaissance technique","Legitimate load balancing traffic","A DNS amplification attack"],"c":1,"why":"Sending SYN packets to numerous ports without completing the handshake is characteristic of a SYN (half-open) port scan used to enumerate open services on a target. This traffic pattern does not match the volume/distribution of a DDoS, has no legitimate load-balancing purpose, and DNS amplification involves spoofed DNS query responses, not TCP SYN scanning.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D3","d":"hard","q":"A data center's electronic access control system automatically unlocks all perimeter emergency exit doors during a power failure to allow occupant egress, while the doors to the server room remain locked and require battery-backed authentication even during the outage. Which secure design principle combination is demonstrated by this differentiated behavior?","o":["Fail-safe design at the perimeter exits to preserve life safety, combined with fail-secure design at the server room to protect critical assets.","Complete mediation, since every access request is re-evaluated at the moment the power failure occurs.","Least privilege, because only authorized personnel are permitted to enter the server room.","Defense in depth, achieved through the use of multiple independent physical barriers."],"c":0,"why":"Fail-safe design unlocks doors on failure to prioritize occupant safety, while fail-secure design keeps doors locked on failure to protect valuable assets; this scenario applies both principles to different areas based on risk priority. Complete mediation, least privilege, and defense in depth describe other design concepts not specifically illustrated by this differentiated locking behavior.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"During a penetration test, an attacker connects a laptop to an access port on a switch and sends frames with two stacked 802.1Q VLAN tags, successfully injecting traffic into a VLAN the port was not assigned to. Which switch misconfiguration most directly enabled this attack?","o":["The access port was configured with a native VLAN that matches the VLAN used for trunk traffic","Spanning Tree Protocol was disabled on the switch","Port security was not enabled to limit MAC addresses","The switch was configured to allow all VLANs across the trunk"],"c":0,"why":"Double-tagging VLAN hopping exploits switches where the native (untagged) VLAN on a trunk matches the attacker's outer tag; the switch strips the outer tag and forwards the inner-tagged frame into the target VLAN. Disabling STP, weak port security, or allowing all VLANs on a trunk are separate issues and do not directly enable the double-tagging mechanism.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization requires an 802.1X EAP method for its wireless network that provides mutual authentication using digital certificates on both the client and the authentication server, and that is resistant to offline dictionary and man-in-the-middle attacks. Which EAP method should be selected?","o":["EAP-MD5","PEAP with MS-CHAPv2 only","LEAP","EAP-TLS"],"c":3,"why":"EAP-TLS uses X.509 certificates on both the supplicant and the server, establishing a mutually authenticated TLS tunnel that resists offline dictionary and MITM attacks. EAP-MD5 and LEAP use weak challenge-response mechanisms vulnerable to offline attacks, and PEAP with MS-CHAPv2 alone only authenticates the server via certificate, not the client.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A network administrator implements DNSSEC across the organization's authoritative name servers. Which statement correctly describes what this deployment achieves and what it does not?","o":["DNSSEC encrypts DNS query and response payloads to prevent eavesdropping, but does not authenticate the resolver","DNSSEC digitally signs zone data to allow validation of authenticity and integrity of DNS responses, but does not provide confidentiality for the queries or responses","DNSSEC replaces the need for TLS on DNS-over-HTTPS by encrypting all resolution traffic end to end","DNSSEC prevents distributed denial-of-service attacks against authoritative name servers by rate-limiting queries"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses public-key signatures to let resolvers verify that DNS data has not been tampered with (integrity/authenticity), but it does not encrypt DNS traffic, so confidentiality is unaffected. The other options confuse DNSSEC with encryption (which is provided separately by DNS-over-TLS/HTTPS) or DDoS mitigation, neither of which DNSSEC provides.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A large ISP discovers that a downstream network unintentionally advertised a more specific BGP route for one of the ISP's IP prefixes, causing a portion of Internet traffic to be misdirected for several hours. Which control would have most effectively prevented this route leak from being accepted by other autonomous systems?","o":["Deploying Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI) route origin validation","Implementing IPsec tunnels between all BGP peers","Enabling unicast reverse path forwarding (uRPF) on edge routers","Configuring Network Address Translation (NAT) at the network border"],"c":0,"why":"RPKI allows networks to cryptographically validate that a route announcement originates from the legitimate autonomous system authorized to advertise that prefix, allowing peers to reject invalid route origins like the leaked one. IPsec secures peer-to-peer confidentiality/integrity but not route origin validity, uRPF addresses source address spoofing on local traffic, and NAT is unrelated to inter-domain routing trust.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm requires a firewall solution that terminates client connections, inspects and validates application-layer protocol conformance (e.g., verifying that HTTP traffic on port 443 is legitimately HTTPS and not tunneled SSH), and establishes a separate connection to the destination server on behalf of the client. Which firewall architecture meets this requirement?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy firewall","Application-level (proxy) firewall"],"c":3,"why":"An application-level proxy firewall terminates and fully inspects application-layer protocol content, enforcing conformance and preventing protocol tunneling, then relays the connection to the destination. Packet filtering and stateful inspection only examine headers and session state without full application awareness, and circuit-level proxies validate sessions at the transport layer without inspecting application-layer protocol semantics.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization's network team observes that a firewall is dropping packets based solely on source/destination IP address, port number, and protocol, without tracking the state of the connection. Which type of firewall technology is being described?","o":["Stateful inspection firewall","Packet-filtering firewall","Circuit-level proxy firewall","Application-layer (proxy) firewall"],"c":1,"why":"A packet-filtering firewall makes decisions per-packet using header fields (IP, port, protocol) without maintaining connection state. Stateful firewalls track session state, and proxy/application-layer firewalls inspect and relay traffic at higher layers, none of which matches the description given.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A wireless network engineer is upgrading an enterprise office from WPA2-Personal to WPA3-Personal to mitigate offline dictionary attacks against the pre-shared key exchange. Which mechanism in WPA3 specifically addresses this vulnerability?","o":["Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) replacing the four-way handshake","Mandatory use of AES-256 in place of AES-128 for encryption","Opportunistic Wireless Encryption (OWE) for open networks","Protected Management Frames (PMF) becoming mandatory"],"c":0,"why":"SAE (based on the Dragonfly key exchange) replaces the WPA2 four-way handshake and prevents offline dictionary attacks by requiring interactive, per-attempt authentication rather than exposing a capturable handshake that can be brute-forced offline. AES-256 mandate, OWE (for open/unauthenticated networks), and mandatory PMF address different threats and do not by themselves solve the PSK offline-cracking issue.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"During a penetration test, an attacker sends a flood of TCP packets with the SYN flag set to a target server, never completing the handshake. The server's connection table fills up, and it is unable to accept new legitimate connections. Which attack is being performed and at which stage of the TCP handshake does the exploitation occur?","o":["ACK flood; exploits the final acknowledgment step","SYN flood; exploits the half-open connection state after SYN-ACK is sent","Smurf attack; exploits ICMP echo replies","Teardrop attack; exploits fragment reassembly"],"c":1,"why":"A SYN flood exploits the half-open state created when the server responds with SYN-ACK and waits for the final ACK, exhausting the backlog queue. The other attacks target different protocols or mechanisms (ICMP amplification, IP fragmentation) and don't match the described handshake abuse.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization is deploying VoIP across its enterprise network and wants to ensure that both call signaling and the actual voice media streams are protected against eavesdropping and tampering. Which combination of protocols correctly addresses both requirements?","o":["RTP for media protection and SIP over UDP for signaling protection","SRTP for media confidentiality/integrity and SIP over TLS (SIPS) for signaling protection","H.323 for media encryption and SNMP for signaling protection","RTCP for signaling protection and IPsec transport mode for media encryption"],"c":1,"why":"SRTP provides encryption, authentication, and integrity for the RTP media stream, while SIPS (SIP over TLS) protects the signaling channel used to establish and control calls; together they secure both planes of VoIP communication. RTP and plain SIP over UDP are unencrypted, H.323/SNMP mismatch protocol purposes, and RTCP is a control protocol for media statistics, not signaling security.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to encrypt traffic between two branch office gateways so that the entire original IP packet, including headers, is protected as it traverses the Internet. Which IPsec configuration best meets this requirement?","o":["Transport mode with AH only","Tunnel mode with ESP","Transport mode with ESP","Tunnel mode with AH only"],"c":1,"why":"Tunnel mode with ESP encapsulates and encrypts the entire original IP packet (including headers) inside a new IP packet, providing confidentiality and integrity between gateways. Transport mode only protects the payload and leaves the original IP header exposed, and AH alone provides integrity/authentication but not encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"At which layer of the OSI model do routers primarily operate to make forwarding decisions based on logical addresses?","o":["Data Link Layer","Network Layer","Transport Layer","Session Layer"],"c":1,"why":"Routers operate at the Network Layer (Layer 3), using IP addresses to make forwarding decisions. Switches operate at Layer 2, while Layers 4 and 5 handle end-to-end communication and session management, not routing.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A wireless network administrator is deploying enterprise-grade Wi-Fi and wants mutual authentication between clients and the RADIUS server using digital certificates on both ends, providing strong protection against rogue access points and credential theft. Which EAP method should be selected?","o":["EAP-MD5","LEAP","PEAP with MSCHAPv2","EAP-TLS"],"c":3,"why":"EAP-TLS requires certificates on both the client and server, providing strong mutual authentication resistant to rogue AP and credential-harvesting attacks. EAP-MD5 and LEAP are weak and vulnerable to offline attacks, and PEAP-MSCHAPv2 only requires a server-side certificate, authenticating the client via password hash instead of a certificate.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security advantage of using a switch instead of a hub in a local area network?","o":["Switches encrypt all traffic between ports","Switches eliminate the need for IP addressing","Switches create separate collision domains per port, reducing the ability to sniff traffic intended for other devices","Switches automatically block all malicious traffic"],"c":2,"why":"Switches forward frames only to the intended destination port based on MAC address tables, creating separate collision domains and limiting the ability of other hosts to passively capture traffic, unlike hubs which broadcast to all ports. Switches do not inherently encrypt traffic or block malicious traffic.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network engineer segments a flat Layer 2 network into multiple broadcast domains to reduce broadcast traffic and enforce logical separation between departments, without requiring separate physical switches for each department. Which technology accomplishes this?","o":["Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)","Link Aggregation (LACP)","Virtual LAN (VLAN)","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)"],"c":2,"why":"VLANs logically partition a single physical switch infrastructure into multiple broadcast domains, isolating traffic between groups without additional physical hardware. STP prevents switching loops, LACP bonds physical links for throughput/redundancy, and ARP resolves IP-to-MAC mappings—none provide logical segmentation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A firewall that tracks the state of active connections and makes filtering decisions based on the context of traffic within an established session is known as which type of firewall?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy","Static packet filter"],"c":1,"why":"A stateful inspection firewall maintains a state table of active connections and evaluates traffic based on its relationship to previously seen packets in a session, offering more context-aware filtering than simple packet filtering, which only examines individual packets in isolation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst notices that a client's DNS resolver is returning incorrect IP addresses for a legitimate banking domain, redirecting users to a malicious site. Which control specifically addresses this type of attack by allowing clients to cryptographically verify the authenticity of DNS responses?","o":["DNSSEC","Split-horizon DNS","DNS over HTTPS (DoH) encryption alone","Reverse DNS lookup validation"],"c":0,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to allow resolvers to verify that DNS responses have not been tampered with, directly mitigating cache poisoning and spoofing. DoH encrypts the transport channel but does not by itself validate response authenticity, and split-horizon DNS and reverse lookups address different operational or verification needs.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol suite is most commonly used to provide encryption and authentication for a site-to-site VPN connection operating at the network layer?","o":["SSL/TLS","IPsec","SSH","PPTP"],"c":1,"why":"IPsec operates at the Network Layer and provides confidentiality, integrity, and authentication for site-to-site VPNs. SSL/TLS typically secures application-layer sessions, SSH secures remote command-line access, and PPTP is an older, less secure tunneling protocol.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization is implementing a converged network carrying both voice (VoIP) and data traffic. Security staff are concerned about eavesdropping on voice calls and toll fraud. Which combination of controls is MOST appropriate to mitigate these risks?","o":["Disable QoS tagging and rely on best-effort delivery for all voice traffic","Place voice and data on the same VLAN and encrypt only signaling traffic","Segment voice traffic on a separate VLAN and encrypt media/signaling using SRTP and TLS","Use only MAC address filtering on VoIP handsets"],"c":2,"why":"Separating voice traffic onto its own VLAN limits exposure to data-network attacks, while SRTP encrypts media streams and TLS protects signaling (e.g., SIP), directly addressing eavesdropping and fraud. Disabling QoS harms call quality without improving security, mixing VLANs increases risk, and MAC filtering alone is easily bypassed and doesn't provide confidentiality.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol was designed to replace WEP by introducing stronger encryption through AES and CCMP?","o":["WPA2","WPA3-Personal only","WEP2","Bluetooth Secure Simple Pairing"],"c":0,"why":"WPA2 replaced WEP by mandating AES encryption with CCMP, providing significantly stronger confidentiality and integrity protections. WEP2 is not a standard industry protocol, and Bluetooth pairing is unrelated to Wi-Fi security.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing a network where sensitive internal systems must never directly communicate with the Internet, but external users need access to a public-facing web application that in turn queries an internal database. Which architecture BEST satisfies this requirement?","o":["Place both the web server and database server on the internal network protected by a single perimeter firewall","Deploy a three-tier architecture with the web server in a DMZ and the database server on a separate internal segment, with firewall rules restricting DMZ-to-internal traffic","Place the web server and database server together in the same DMZ segment","Allow direct Internet access to the database server for performance, protected only by application-layer authentication"],"c":1,"why":"A three-tier design isolates the public-facing web server in a DMZ while keeping the database on a protected internal segment, with firewall rules limiting the DMZ's access to only the specific ports/protocols required—minimizing exposure of sensitive systems. The other options expose internal systems directly to the DMZ or Internet, increasing attack surface.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary function of the Domain Name System (DNS) in a TCP/IP network?","o":["Assigning dynamic IP addresses to hosts","Translating human-readable domain names into IP addresses","Encrypting traffic between web servers and clients","Filtering traffic based on port numbers"],"c":1,"why":"DNS resolves human-friendly domain names into the numeric IP addresses needed for network communication. Dynamic IP assignment is handled by DHCP, encryption by protocols like TLS, and port-based filtering by firewalls.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to logically separate traffic between the finance and marketing departments on the same physical switch infrastructure without installing additional physical hardware. Which technology best achieves this?","o":["Network Address Translation (NAT)","Virtual Local Area Network (VLAN)","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)","Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs allow logical segmentation of a physical network into separate broadcast domains without requiring additional physical switches, isolating traffic between departments. NAT translates addresses, ARP resolves IP to MAC addresses, and STP prevents Layer 2 loops.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which layer of the OSI model is responsible for logical addressing and routing of packets between different networks?","o":["Data Link Layer","Network Layer","Transport Layer","Session Layer"],"c":1,"why":"The Network Layer (Layer 3) handles logical addressing (IP addresses) and routing between networks. The Data Link Layer handles physical addressing within a single network segment, the Transport Layer manages end-to-end connections, and the Session Layer manages dialogs between applications.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network appliance forwards packets to their destination based solely on destination IP address, without examining transport-layer ports or application payload. At which layer of the OSI model does this device primarily operate?","o":["Layer 2 (Data Link)","Layer 3 (Network)","Layer 5 (Session)","Layer 7 (Application)"],"c":1,"why":"Routing decisions based on IP addressing occur at the Network layer (Layer 3). Layer 2 devices forward based on MAC addresses, while Layers 5 and 7 involve session management and application data, which this device does not inspect.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"During the TCP three-way handshake, which sequence of flags is exchanged to establish a connection?","o":["SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK","ACK, SYN, FIN","SYN, ACK, FIN-ACK","RST, SYN, ACK"],"c":0,"why":"A TCP connection is established when the client sends SYN, the server responds with SYN-ACK, and the client replies with ACK, confirming both sides are ready to communicate. The other sequences either include the FIN flag (used to terminate connections) or the RST flag (used to abruptly reset a connection), which are not part of connection establishment.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization is configuring a site-to-site IPsec VPN and requires that the payload data be encrypted in addition to being authenticated and integrity-checked. Which IPsec component must be used to satisfy this requirement?","o":["Authentication Header (AH)","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP)","Internet Key Exchange (IKE)","Security Association Database (SAD)"],"c":1,"why":"ESP provides confidentiality (encryption) along with optional authentication and integrity. AH provides only authentication and integrity, not encryption. IKE handles key negotiation, and the SAD stores security association parameters rather than performing encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A firewall that examines only individual packet headers (such as source/destination IP and port) without tracking the state of the connection is best described as which type?","o":["Stateful inspection firewall","Packet-filtering firewall","Application-layer gateway","Circuit-level proxy"],"c":1,"why":"A packet-filtering firewall evaluates each packet independently based on header information, with no awareness of connection state. Stateful firewalls track connection state, application-layer gateways inspect payload content at Layer 7, and circuit-level proxies manage sessions at Layer 5, all of which go beyond simple header filtering.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect must design a site-to-site VPN that will traverse a service provider's NAT gateway while providing confidentiality, integrity, and origin authentication of the entire original IP packet. Which IPSec configuration should be selected?","o":["AH in transport mode","ESP in tunnel mode with NAT Traversal (UDP encapsulation on port 4500)","AH in tunnel mode","ESP in transport mode without NAT-T"],"c":1,"why":"ESP tunnel mode encrypts and authenticates the entire original packet and, when combined with NAT-T, avoids the checksum/ICV problems that occur when NAT devices alter IP headers. AH is incompatible with NAT because its ICV covers the outer IP header, and transport mode does not protect the full original packet needed for site-to-site tunneling.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol suite is most commonly used to provide confidentiality, integrity, and authentication for IP packets in a site-to-site VPN?","o":["IPsec","SSH","SNMP","FTP"],"c":0,"why":"IPsec (Internet Protocol Security) is designed specifically to secure IP traffic through encryption and authentication, making it the standard for site-to-site VPNs. SSH secures remote terminal sessions, SNMP is used for network management, and FTP is a file transfer protocol with no built-in encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security architect wants a firewall that terminates each client connection itself, rebuilds a new connection to the destination server, and can inspect and filter the actual application-layer content (such as HTTP commands) before forwarding traffic. Which firewall type best meets this requirement?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Application-layer (proxy) firewall","Circuit-level gateway"],"c":2,"why":"An application-layer proxy firewall terminates and re-establishes connections, allowing deep inspection of application content. Packet-filtering and stateful firewalls examine headers and connection state but not application payload, and circuit-level gateways only validate session setup without content inspection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester successfully performs a VLAN hopping attack by sending frames with two stacked 802.1Q tags, causing the switch to strip the outer tag matching the native VLAN and forward the inner-tagged frame into a restricted VLAN. Which control most directly prevents this specific attack?","o":["Enable port security to limit MAC addresses per port","Assign an unused, dedicated VLAN as the native VLAN on all trunk ports and disable/tag native VLAN traffic","Enable BPDU guard on all access ports","Deploy private VLANs on every access switch"],"c":1,"why":"Double-tagging attacks rely on the native VLAN being untagged and shared; explicitly assigning a dedicated, unused native VLAN and forcing all traffic (including native VLAN) to be tagged eliminates the ambiguity the attack exploits. Port security addresses MAC flooding, BPDU guard addresses STP attacks, and private VLANs address isolation within a VLAN, not tag stripping.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol introduced the use of Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) to replace the vulnerable four-way handshake found in earlier standards?","o":["WEP","WPA","WPA2","WPA3"],"c":3,"why":"WPA3 introduced SAE, a more secure key exchange method that resists offline dictionary attacks, replacing the four-way handshake used in WPA2 that was vulnerable to attacks like KRACK. WEP and WPA are older, weaker protocols that do not use SAE.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise wants to implement 802.1X wireless authentication that provides strong mutual authentication using a server-side certificate but avoids the operational burden of issuing and managing certificates to every client device. Which EAP method best meets this requirement?","o":["EAP-TLS","PEAP with MS-CHAPv2 as the inner authentication method","LEAP","EAP-MD5"],"c":1,"why":"PEAP establishes a TLS tunnel using only a server certificate, then authenticates the client via an inner method such as MS-CHAPv2, avoiding client certificate deployment. EAP-TLS requires certificates on both ends, LEAP is a legacy proprietary protocol with known weaknesses, and EAP-MD5 provides no mutual authentication or protection against offline attacks.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator wants to segment traffic from different departments on the same physical switch to reduce broadcast traffic and improve security. Which technology should be implemented?","o":["Subnetting only","VLAN","NAT","Port mirroring"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs (Virtual Local Area Networks) logically segment a single physical switch into multiple broadcast domains, isolating traffic between departments. Subnetting alone does not control broadcast domains within the same switch, NAT translates addresses rather than segmenting traffic, and port mirroring is used for monitoring, not segmentation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A wireless network administrator is upgrading from WPA2 to WPA3 primarily to protect against offline dictionary attacks on the pre-shared key exchange. Which WPA3 feature directly addresses this concern?","o":["Temporal Key Integrity Protocol (TKIP)","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) fallback","Pre-Shared Key (PSK) rotation every session"],"c":1,"why":"SAE, based on the Dragonfly handshake, replaces the WPA2 four-way handshake and is resistant to offline dictionary attacks by requiring interaction with the access point for each guess. TKIP and WEP are outdated and insecure legacy mechanisms, and simple PSK rotation does not address the handshake vulnerability.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm needs a firewall capable of inspecting and filtering the actual content of HTTP and FTP sessions (e.g., blocking specific commands, stripping active content, and enforcing granular application-layer policy) rather than simply relaying sessions between endpoints. Which firewall architecture is most appropriate?","o":["Circuit-level proxy firewall","Application-level proxy firewall","Stateless packet-filtering firewall","Screening router with ACLs"],"c":1,"why":"Application-level proxies terminate and re-establish connections at Layer 7, allowing deep inspection and command-level filtering per protocol. Circuit-level proxies operate at the session layer and only validate handshakes without inspecting payload content, while packet filters and screening routers make decisions based on headers, not application content.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An administrator needs to logically separate finance department traffic from human resources traffic on the same physical switch infrastructure to reduce broadcast traffic and limit exposure between departments, without re-cabling the network. Which solution best accomplishes this?","o":["Virtual LAN (VLAN)","Network Address Translation (NAT)","Site-to-site VPN","Demilitarized Zone (DMZ)"],"c":0,"why":"VLANs logically segment broadcast domains on shared switching hardware without requiring physical re-cabling. NAT translates addresses rather than segmenting traffic, VPNs secure traffic across untrusted networks, and a DMZ is used to isolate public-facing services, not general internal departmental traffic.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which technology allows multiple devices on a private network to share a single public IP address when accessing the Internet?","o":["DHCP","DNS","NAT","ARP"],"c":2,"why":"NAT (Network Address Translation) maps multiple private internal IP addresses to one or more public IP addresses, conserving address space and hiding internal topology. DHCP assigns IP addresses, DNS resolves names to addresses, and ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses—none of which perform address translation for shared Internet access.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A network engineer explains DNSSEC to management. Which statement most accurately describes what DNSSEC provides?","o":["It encrypts DNS query and response traffic to prevent eavesdropping","It provides data origin authentication and integrity verification of DNS responses through a chain of cryptographic signatures, but does not provide confidentiality","It replaces DNS caching with a fully authenticated real-time lookup for every query","It prevents all forms of DNS cache poisoning and denial-of-service attacks against resolvers"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses RRSIG records and a chain of trust back to the root to cryptographically validate that responses are authentic and unaltered, but it explicitly does not encrypt DNS traffic. It reduces (but does not eliminate) cache poisoning risk and does not address DoS attacks, and caching behavior is unchanged.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company implements a mechanism that digitally signs DNS zone data so that resolvers can cryptographically verify that DNS responses have not been forged or tampered with in transit. Which technology is being described?","o":["DNSSEC","Split-horizon DNS","Dynamic DNS (DDNS)","DHCP snooping"],"c":0,"why":"DNSSEC adds digital signatures to DNS records, allowing resolvers to validate authenticity and integrity, mitigating cache poisoning and spoofing. Split-horizon DNS separates internal/external views, DDNS automates record updates, and DHCP snooping protects against rogue DHCP servers, none of which provide cryptographic validation of DNS responses.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to run cabling through an area with heavy electromagnetic interference from industrial equipment while maintaining high transmission integrity. Which cabling type is the best choice?","o":["Unshielded twisted pair (UTP)","Coaxial cable","Fiber optic cable","Shielded twisted pair (STP)"],"c":2,"why":"Fiber optic cable uses light rather than electrical signals, making it immune to electromagnetic interference (EMI), which is ideal for environments with heavy industrial equipment. UTP and coaxial cable are both susceptible to EMI, and while STP offers some shielding, it is still more vulnerable to interference than fiber optic cable.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"On a flat switched LAN, an attacker successfully performs an ARP spoofing attack, poisoning the ARP caches of hosts to redirect traffic through an attacker-controlled machine for interception. Which control provides the most scalable and effective mitigation in a switched enterprise environment?","o":["Configure static ARP entries manually on every host","Enable Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI) validated against the DHCP snooping binding table","Implement 802.1X port-based authentication on all access ports","Enable Root Guard on all switch ports"],"c":1,"why":"DAI cross-references incoming ARP packets against trusted DHCP snooping bindings and drops invalid ARP replies, effectively stopping spoofing at scale without manual per-host maintenance. Static ARP entries do not scale, 802.1X authenticates devices but does not validate ARP mappings, and Root Guard protects Spanning Tree topology, not ARP integrity.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization relies on a carrier-provided MPLS WAN and assumes traffic between sites is encrypted because it travels over a 'private' label-switched network. A security audit reveals that MPLS provides no native encryption. What should be implemented to achieve confidentiality of traffic traversing the MPLS backbone?","o":["An IPSec overlay (e.g., site-to-site VPN) running across the MPLS circuits","Increased Diffserv QoS marking to prioritize sensitive traffic","Additional VLAN tagging on the MPLS provider edge routers","A contractual SLA requiring the carrier to guarantee traffic isolation"],"c":0,"why":"MPLS provides label-based traffic engineering and path isolation, not encryption; adding an IPSec overlay ensures confidentiality and integrity regardless of the underlying transport. QoS marking and VLAN tagging affect performance and segmentation, not confidentiality, and a contractual SLA does not provide technical assurance against interception.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A malicious insider connects a rogue switch to an access port and sends crafted BPDU frames advertising a lower bridge priority, causing the network to recalculate the spanning tree topology and elect the rogue switch as the root bridge, allowing traffic interception. Which control set is specifically designed to prevent this attack?","o":["Dynamic ARP Inspection and DHCP snooping","Root Guard and BPDU Guard on switch ports facing end devices","802.1X with EAP-TLS on all switch ports","Private VLANs combined with port isolation"],"c":1,"why":"Root Guard prevents a port from becoming a root port if it receives superior BPDUs, and BPDU Guard disables ports that should never send BPDUs (access ports) upon receiving one, directly stopping this STP manipulation attack. The other options address ARP spoofing, general port authentication, or Layer 2 traffic isolation, none of which specifically defend against rogue root bridge attacks.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A web server behind a stateful firewall is experiencing a SYN flood attack that exhausts its TCP connection table, causing legitimate connections to time out. Which mitigation directly addresses the underlying mechanism being exploited, without requiring the server to allocate state for each incoming SYN?","o":["Increase the size of the TCP backlog queue on the server","Implement SYN cookies so connection state is derived cryptographically from the packet instead of stored until the handshake completes","Disable ICMP redirects on the perimeter router","Enable TCP window scaling on the server's network stack"],"c":1,"why":"SYN cookies encode connection state in a cryptographically generated sequence number, eliminating the need to store half-open connections and defeating the resource-exhaustion mechanism of SYN floods; the other options either only delay exhaustion (larger backlog) or address unrelated issues (ICMP redirects, window scaling).","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An attacker on a local network sends forged Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) replies, causing hosts to associate the attacker's MAC address with the IP address of the default gateway, allowing the attacker to intercept traffic. What is this attack called?","o":["ARP spoofing (poisoning)","DNS cache poisoning","MAC flooding","IP fragmentation attack"],"c":0,"why":"ARP spoofing involves sending forged ARP messages to associate an attacker's MAC address with a legitimate IP address, enabling man-in-the-middle interception. DNS cache poisoning targets name resolution records, MAC flooding overwhelms switch CAM tables to force flooding behavior, and IP fragmentation attacks manipulate packet fragments rather than address resolution.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A network architect is designing a site-to-site VPN between two gateways where the outer IP addresses will be translated by an intermediate NAT device on the path. Which IPsec protocol and mode combination will function correctly through the NAT while still providing confidentiality and integrity of the original packet?","o":["AH in transport mode","ESP in tunnel mode with NAT Traversal (UDP encapsulation)","AH in tunnel mode","ESP in transport mode without NAT-T"],"c":1,"why":"AH's integrity check covers the outer IP header, so any NAT modification of source/destination addresses invalidates the ICV and breaks the connection; ESP in tunnel mode encapsulates the original packet and, combined with NAT-T (UDP port 4500), allows the modified outer header while still protecting confidentiality and integrity of the inner packet.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Why is SSH strongly preferred over Telnet for remote administrative access to network devices?","o":["SSH operates over UDP, reducing connection overhead","SSH encrypts the entire session, including authentication credentials","Telnet requires more network bandwidth than SSH","SSH does not require any authentication, simplifying access"],"c":1,"why":"SSH encrypts the full session, including login credentials and commands, preventing eavesdropping and credential theft, whereas Telnet transmits everything in cleartext. SSH uses TCP, not UDP, and it does require authentication; bandwidth is not the relevant security distinction here.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network engineer needs to select a device that makes forwarding decisions based on logical IP addresses rather than physical hardware addresses. At which OSI layer does this device primarily operate?","o":["Layer 2 - Data Link","Layer 3 - Network","Layer 4 - Transport","Layer 7 - Application"],"c":1,"why":"Routers make forwarding decisions using IP addresses, which is a Network layer (Layer 3) function. Layer 2 devices (switches/bridges) use MAC addresses, Layer 4 deals with ports/segments, and Layer 7 handles application data.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester crafts a frame with two stacked 802.1Q VLAN tags to send traffic from VLAN 10 into VLAN 20 without traversing a Layer 3 device, exploiting how the switch strips only the outer tag on the trunk. Which switch configuration change would have prevented this VLAN hopping technique?","o":["Configure trunk ports to use a dedicated, unused native VLAN that is explicitly tagged rather than the default native VLAN","Enable port security with MAC address limiting on access ports","Configure static ARP entries on all Layer 3 interfaces","Enable DHCP snooping on all access VLANs"],"c":0,"why":"Double-tagging attacks rely on the trunk's native VLAN being untagged and matching the attacker's outer tag, allowing the switch to strip it and forward the inner tag onward; using a dedicated unused native VLAN with explicit tagging closes this gap, whereas port security, static ARP, and DHCP snooping address different attack vectors (MAC flooding, ARP spoofing, rogue DHCP).","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An attacker sends a large volume of TCP SYN packets with spoofed source addresses to a web server, exhausting the server's connection table and preventing legitimate connections. Which control is most effective at mitigating this specific attack?","o":["Implementing SYN cookies on the server","Enabling port security on access switches","Deploying network address translation at the perimeter","Disabling ICMP redirect messages"],"c":0,"why":"SYN cookies allow the server to avoid allocating resources until the handshake completes, defeating SYN flood resource exhaustion. Port security addresses MAC flooding, NAT does not prevent connection table exhaustion, and ICMP redirects are unrelated to TCP handshake attacks.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization deploys DNSSEC for its authoritative zone to protect against spoofed responses. Which statement correctly identifies a protection that DNSSEC does NOT provide?","o":["It does not help prevent cache poisoning attacks","It does not provide confidentiality of DNS query and response contents","It does not use public key cryptography to validate records","It does not establish a chain of trust between zones"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC digitally signs resource records to provide data integrity and origin authentication (and does help mitigate cache poisoning via signature validation and chain of trust), but it does not encrypt DNS traffic; confidentiality requires a separate mechanism such as DNS over TLS or DNS over HTTPS.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to encrypt only the payload of packets exchanged directly between two hosts on the same internal network while preserving the original IP header for existing routing infrastructure. Which IPSec mode satisfies this requirement?","o":["Tunnel mode","Transport mode","Aggressive mode","Main mode"],"c":1,"why":"Transport mode encrypts only the payload and retains the original IP header, suitable for host-to-host communication. Tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original packet with a new header (used for gateway-to-gateway), while aggressive and main mode are IKE negotiation phases, not data-encapsulation modes.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"During an assessment, a consultant successfully performs a Key Reinstallation Attack (KRACK) against a WPA2 network by manipulating retransmissions during the 4-way handshake. Which underlying weakness does this attack exploit?","o":["A weak pre-shared key vulnerable to offline dictionary attack","Retransmission handling that allows nonce reuse, causing the client to reinstall an already-used encryption key","Continued use of the RC4 stream cipher within TKIP","Absence of mutual authentication between the access point and client"],"c":1,"why":"KRACK exploits the handshake's retransmission logic: forcing replay of message 3 causes the client to reset nonce/replay counters and reinstall a previously used session key, enabling keystream reuse; it is independent of PSK strength, does not require TKIP/RC4, and does not stem from lack of mutual authentication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security assessment finds that switch access ports are configured to automatically negotiate trunking, creating a risk of an attacker spoofing a switch to gain access to multiple VLANs. What is the best remediation?","o":["Disable automatic trunk negotiation and manually configure access ports","Enable Spanning Tree Protocol on all ports","Implement port security to limit MAC addresses per port","Enable DHCP snooping on all VLANs"],"c":0,"why":"Disabling dynamic trunking protocol negotiation and hard-coding access ports prevents VLAN hopping via switch spoofing. STP prevents loops, port security mitigates MAC flooding, and DHCP snooping prevents rogue DHCP servers—none address trunk negotiation abuse.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A network security team wants to prevent unauthorized autonomous systems from announcing routes for IP prefixes they do not own, a technique used in BGP route hijacking. Which technology is specifically designed to cryptographically validate that an AS is authorized to originate a given prefix?","o":["BGPsec AS path attestation","Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI) with Route Origin Authorizations (ROAs)","OSPF neighbor authentication","MPLS label distribution protocol security"],"c":1,"why":"RPKI ROAs cryptographically bind a prefix to the authorized originating AS, enabling Route Origin Validation to detect hijacks at the origin; BGPsec instead attests the full AS path (a related but broader mechanism), while OSPF authentication and MPLS LDP security operate at the interior routing/label layer and do not address BGP origin validation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which TCP mechanism is used to establish a reliable connection between a client and server before data transfer begins?","o":["Three-way handshake","ARP resolution","DNS lookup","Spanning Tree Protocol negotiation"],"c":0,"why":"TCP uses the three-way handshake (SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK) to establish a reliable connection. ARP resolves MAC addresses, DNS resolves names to IP addresses, and Spanning Tree Protocol prevents Layer 2 loops, none of which establish TCP connections.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An enterprise requires that wireless clients and the authentication server mutually authenticate each other using digital certificates before granting network access. Which EAP method should be implemented?","o":["EAP-TLS","LEAP","PEAP-MSCHAPv2","EAP-MD5"],"c":0,"why":"EAP-TLS requires certificates on both the client and server, providing strong mutual authentication. PEAP-MSCHAPv2 only authenticates the server via certificate, LEAP is a legacy Cisco protocol with known weaknesses, and EAP-MD5 offers no mutual authentication and is vulnerable to offline attacks.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise migrates from a flat network protected by a single perimeter firewall to a zero trust architecture using micro-segmentation with policy enforcement points between individual workloads. What is the primary security benefit of this design compared to the traditional perimeter model?","o":["It eliminates the need for encrypting data in transit between workloads","It limits lateral movement by enforcing granular access policy between workloads regardless of their network location","It removes the need for authentication since segments implicitly trust each other","It reduces bandwidth consumption by consolidating multiple VLANs into fewer broadcast domains"],"c":1,"why":"Micro-segmentation enforces identity- and context-based policy at each workload boundary, so a compromised host cannot freely reach other systems as it could inside a flat, perimeter-only network; it does not eliminate encryption or authentication requirements and is not primarily a bandwidth optimization.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A firewall that tracks the state of active connections and makes filtering decisions based on the context of traffic within a session is known as a:","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy only","Application-layer gateway only"],"c":1,"why":"A stateful inspection firewall maintains a state table of active connections and evaluates traffic based on session context, offering more security than simple packet filtering, which examines each packet in isolation without connection awareness.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which technology provides cryptographic origin authentication and data integrity for DNS responses, specifically to protect against cache poisoning attacks?","o":["DNSSEC","DNS over HTTPS (DoH)","Split-horizon DNS","Round-robin DNS"],"c":0,"why":"DNSSEC digitally signs DNS records, allowing resolvers to verify authenticity and integrity, directly mitigating cache poisoning. DoH encrypts the transport channel but does not validate record authenticity, split-horizon DNS is an architectural design, and round-robin DNS is a load-balancing technique.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol suite is most commonly used to provide encryption and authentication for site-to-site VPN connections at the network layer?","o":["SSL/TLS","IPsec","SNMP","PPTP"],"c":1,"why":"IPsec operates at the network layer and provides encryption, integrity, and authentication for VPN traffic, commonly used in site-to-site VPNs. SSL/TLS operates higher in the stack for application traffic, SNMP is for network management, and PPTP is an older, less secure tunneling protocol.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A VoIP deployment uses SIP for call signaling and RTP for media transport. A security review finds that call setup information and voice payloads can both be captured in cleartext on the internal network. Which combination of controls addresses confidentiality for both the signaling and media planes?","o":["SIP over TLS (SIPS) for signaling combined with SRTP for media","SIPS alone, since it also encrypts the media stream","A VPN tunnel applied only to RTP traffic","IPsec for SIP signaling while leaving RTP in cleartext but tagged for QoS"],"c":0,"why":"SIP signaling and RTP media are separate protocols requiring separate protections: SIPS (SIP over TLS) secures call setup/teardown messages, while SRTP encrypts and authenticates the media stream; SIPS alone does not protect RTP, and protecting only one plane leaves the other exposed.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company needs a firewall capable of inspecting the actual content of HTTP traffic, including the ability to block specific URLs or file types embedded within the payload. Which firewall type best meets this requirement?","o":["Application-layer (proxy) firewall","Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level gateway"],"c":0,"why":"Application-layer proxy firewalls terminate and inspect traffic at Layer 7, enabling content-based filtering. Packet filters only examine headers, stateful firewalls track connection state up through the transport layer without deep payload inspection, and circuit-level gateways only validate session legitimacy.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security standard replaced WPA2 to address vulnerabilities such as weak passphrase-based attacks by introducing the Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) handshake?","o":["WEP","WPA","WPA2","WPA3"],"c":3,"why":"WPA3 introduced SAE to replace the WPA2 four-way handshake, mitigating offline dictionary attacks against weak passphrases. WEP and WPA are older, weaker standards, and WPA2 is the standard that WPA3 was designed to improve upon.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that only authenticated and authorized devices can gain network access at the switch port level, before an IP address is even assigned. Which technology best satisfies this requirement?","o":["802.1X port-based network access control","DHCP snooping","Private VLANs","Spanning Tree Protocol"],"c":0,"why":"802.1X enforces authentication at the port level prior to granting network access, commonly using RADIUS. DHCP snooping prevents rogue DHCP servers, private VLANs restrict Layer 2 communication between hosts, and STP prevents switching loops—none provide pre-access authentication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security benefit of using a Layer 2 switch instead of a hub in a local network?","o":["It encrypts all traffic between devices","It eliminates the need for IP addressing","It reduces the collision domain and limits traffic visibility to intended recipients","It automatically blocks all malicious traffic"],"c":2,"why":"Switches forward frames only to the intended destination port based on MAC address, reducing collisions and limiting the ability of other devices to passively capture unrelated traffic, unlike a hub which broadcasts to all ports. Switches do not encrypt traffic, eliminate IP addressing needs, or block malicious traffic by default.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An attacker corrupts a DNS server's cache with false IP address records so that users attempting to reach a legitimate website are redirected to a malicious site. This attack is best described as:","o":["ARP spoofing","DNS cache poisoning","Session hijacking","Smurf attack"],"c":1,"why":"DNS cache poisoning involves inserting false DNS records into a resolver's cache to redirect users to malicious sites. ARP spoofing targets Layer 2 address resolution, session hijacking takes over an active session, and a smurf attack is a denial-of-service technique using ICMP broadcasts.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of Network Address Translation (NAT) in a typical enterprise network?","o":["To encrypt traffic leaving the network","To translate private internal IP addresses to a public IP address for external communication","To assign domain names to IP addresses","To detect and block intrusion attempts"],"c":1,"why":"NAT translates private internal addresses to one or more public addresses, allowing devices with non-routable addresses to communicate on the internet while conserving public IP space. It does not provide encryption, name resolution (which is DNS's role), or intrusion detection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"During the design of a network protocol stack, an architect needs to identify which OSI layer is responsible for logical addressing and determining the best path for a packet to travel across interconnected networks. Which layer performs this function?","o":["Data Link layer","Network layer","Transport layer","Session layer"],"c":1,"why":"The Network layer (Layer 3) handles logical addressing (IP addresses) and routing decisions. The Data Link layer handles physical addressing (MAC) on a local segment, the Transport layer manages end-to-end delivery and reliability, and the Session layer manages dialog control between applications.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network engineer is designing a VoIP system and must select a transport protocol for the real-time audio stream carried by RTP. Which of the following best explains why UDP is the preferred choice over TCP for this traffic?","o":["UDP encrypts payload data by default, protecting voice conversations","UDP guarantees in-order, lossless delivery of every packet","UDP avoids the retransmission and acknowledgment delays of TCP, which would degrade real-time audio quality","UDP requires fewer IP addresses than TCP, reducing addressing overhead"],"c":2,"why":"UDP is connectionless and does not perform retransmission or acknowledgment, minimizing latency critical for real-time voice; a small amount of packet loss is preferable to the delay TCP's reliability mechanisms would introduce. UDP provides no encryption or guaranteed delivery, and addressing overhead is unrelated.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which transport layer protocol provides connectionless, best-effort delivery without guaranteeing packet order or retransmission?","o":["TCP","UDP","ICMP","SCTP"],"c":1,"why":"UDP is a connectionless protocol that does not establish a session, acknowledge receipt, or retransmit lost packets, making it faster but less reliable than TCP. TCP is connection-oriented and reliable, and ICMP is used for diagnostics/control messages, not general data transport.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary security advantage of an application-layer (proxy) firewall compared to a stateful inspection firewall?","o":["It can inspect and filter based on the actual content of the application payload, such as specific HTTP commands or embedded malicious code","It processes packets faster because it does not maintain connection state tables","It requires no CPU overhead since it operates only at Layer 3","It automatically encrypts all traffic passing through it"],"c":0,"why":"Proxy firewalls terminate and rebuild connections, allowing deep inspection of application-layer content that stateful firewalls (which examine headers and connection state) cannot fully analyze. Proxy firewalls are typically slower, not faster, and neither firewall type inherently provides encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A stateful inspection firewall improves on simple packet filtering primarily by doing what?","o":["Encrypting all traffic that passes through it","Tracking the state of active connections to make context-aware filtering decisions","Blocking all inbound traffic regardless of port","Translating private IP addresses to public IP addresses"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful firewalls maintain a state table of active sessions, allowing them to make more intelligent decisions than static packet filters that inspect each packet in isolation. Encryption and NAT are separate functions not inherent to stateful inspection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization needs to establish a secure site-to-site connection between two branch office VPN gateways over the public Internet, ensuring that the entire original IP packet, including its header, is encrypted and encapsulated within a new IP packet. Which IPsec mode satisfies this requirement?","o":["Transport mode with AH","Tunnel mode with ESP","Transport mode with ESP","Tunnel mode with AH only"],"c":1,"why":"Tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original IP packet (header and payload) inside a new packet, and ESP provides confidentiality (encryption) in addition to integrity, making it appropriate for gateway-to-gateway VPNs. Transport mode only protects the payload and leaves the original header exposed, and AH alone does not provide encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing a site-to-site VPN between two branch offices. Traffic from one office will traverse an ISP-managed router that performs NAT before reaching the internet. The solution must provide confidentiality, integrity, and authentication for the entire original IP packet, and must function correctly despite the NAT device in the path. Which configuration should be selected?","o":["AH in transport mode","AH in tunnel mode","ESP in tunnel mode with NAT traversal (NAT-T)","ESP in transport mode"],"c":2,"why":"ESP tunnel mode encrypts and authenticates the entire original packet, encapsulating it under a new IP header, and NAT-T (UDP encapsulation) allows the ESP packet to survive address translation. AH fails under NAT because its integrity check covers the outer IP header, which NAT alters, invalidating the ICV; AH also provides no confidentiality. Transport mode does not protect the original IP header and is unsuitable for site-to-site tunneling through NAT.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol suite is most commonly used to provide encryption and authentication for site-to-site VPN tunnels operating at the network layer?","o":["SSL/TLS","IPsec","SSH","PPTP"],"c":1,"why":"IPsec operates at the network layer and provides both encryption (via ESP) and authentication (via AH or ESP) for VPN tunnels, making it the standard for site-to-site VPNs. SSL/TLS and SSH typically secure application-layer traffic, and PPTP is an older, weaker tunneling protocol.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise migrating from WPA2-PSK to WPA3-Personal wants to address a known weakness in which attackers capture a single four-way handshake and perform offline dictionary attacks against the pre-shared key. Which WPA3 mechanism directly mitigates this risk?","o":["Opportunistic Wireless Encryption (OWE)","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","Protected Management Frames (802.11w)","AES-256 in GCM mode for data encryption"],"c":1,"why":"SAE replaces the WPA2 PSK handshake with a Diffie-Hellman-based (Dragonfly) exchange, requiring an active interaction with the AP for each password guess, which defeats offline dictionary attacks against captured traffic. OWE addresses encryption on open networks without authentication, 802.11w protects management frames from spoofing/DoS, and AES-GCM protects data confidentiality but does not change the vulnerable handshake exchange.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol replaced WPA2 and introduces stronger encryption along with protection against offline dictionary attacks via Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)?","o":["WEP","WPA","WPA3","EAP-TLS"],"c":2,"why":"WPA3 introduces SAE, which replaces the WPA2 pre-shared key exchange and provides forward secrecy and resistance to offline dictionary attacks. WEP and WPA are older, weaker standards, and EAP-TLS is an authentication method, not a full wireless security protocol.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"During a penetration test, an assessor connects a laptop to an unused access port on an edge switch and crafts Ethernet frames with two stacked 802.1Q tags. The assessor is able to send traffic that appears on a VLAN different from the access port's assigned VLAN. Which switch misconfiguration most likely enabled this attack?","o":["The access port is configured in a shutdown state","The trunk ports use the default VLAN (VLAN 1) as the native VLAN without explicit tagging","Port security has not been enabled to limit MAC addresses","Spanning Tree Protocol is disabled on the switch"],"c":1,"why":"Double-tagging VLAN hopping exploits trunk ports that strip only the outer tag matching the untagged native VLAN; if the native VLAN is left as the default and not explicitly tagged, the inner tag survives and is forwarded into another VLAN. Port security limits MAC address counts (mitigates flooding, not tag stripping), disabled STP causes loops rather than hopping, and a shutdown port would block all traffic, preventing the attack entirely.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"Two branch offices connect over the public Internet using a site-to-site gateway configuration. The security team requires that traffic between the sites be protected for both confidentiality and integrity, and that the original IP headers of internal hosts not be exposed to intermediate routers. Which IPsec configuration best satisfies these requirements?","o":["AH in tunnel mode","ESP in tunnel mode","ESP in transport mode","AH in transport mode"],"c":1,"why":"ESP provides confidentiality (encryption) plus integrity, and tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original IP packet (including headers) inside a new IP packet, hiding internal addressing from the transit network. AH provides no confidentiality, and transport mode does not protect the original IP header, making it unsuitable for gateway-to-gateway traffic.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security team is evaluating why WPA3 is considered more resistant to offline dictionary attacks against the pre-shared key than WPA2. Which WPA3 feature is primarily responsible for this improvement?","o":["Use of the RC4 stream cipher for key encryption","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) replacing the WPA2 four-way handshake","Mandatory use of WEP-compatible authentication for legacy support","Elimination of encryption in favor of MAC address filtering"],"c":1,"why":"SAE, based on the Dragonfly key exchange, prevents an attacker from capturing a handshake and performing offline brute-force attacks against it, unlike WPA2's four-way handshake which is vulnerable to such attacks. RC4/WEP are outdated insecure technologies, and WPA3 still uses strong encryption, not MAC filtering.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization needs to prevent internal hosts on different departments from communicating directly with each other at Layer 2, while still allowing controlled inter-department communication through a Layer 3 device. Which technology BEST accomplishes this initial segmentation?","o":["Virtual LANs (VLANs) with inter-VLAN routing","Spanning Tree Protocol","Network Address Translation","Link aggregation (LACP)"],"c":0,"why":"VLANs logically segment broadcast domains at Layer 2, isolating hosts by department; a router or Layer 3 switch can then permit controlled inter-VLAN traffic. STP prevents loops, NAT translates addresses, and LACP aggregates links—none provide logical segmentation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security benefit of using a switch instead of a hub on a local network segment?","o":["It encrypts all traffic between connected devices","It eliminates the need for IP addressing","It reduces the ability of one device to capture traffic intended for another by limiting collision domains","It automatically blocks unauthorized MAC addresses"],"c":2,"why":"Switches forward traffic only to the intended destination port based on MAC address, creating separate collision domains and reducing the risk of one host easily sniffing traffic meant for another, unlike hubs which broadcast to all ports. Switches do not inherently encrypt traffic or block unknown MAC addresses without additional configuration.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise wants to deploy 802.1X-based wireless authentication that provides mutual authentication between client and server using digital certificates on both ends, without relying on shared secrets or user passwords during the authentication exchange itself. Which EAP method should be selected?","o":["EAP-TLS","PEAP-MSCHAPv2","LEAP","WPA2-PSK with 802.1X"],"c":0,"why":"EAP-TLS requires certificates on both the client and the authentication server, providing true mutual certificate-based authentication. PEAP-MSCHAPv2 only requires a server-side certificate and authenticates the client via credentials; LEAP is a deprecated, weak Cisco proprietary method; PSK is a shared-secret model incompatible with 802.1X's per-user authentication goal.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm implements DNSSEC across all of its authoritative zones to counter DNS cache poisoning attacks. During a security review, an auditor notes that DNS queries and responses between recursive resolvers and clients remain visible to network eavesdroppers. Which statement best explains this observation?","o":["DNSSEC was implemented incorrectly and encryption keys were not deployed","DNSSEC provides data integrity and origin authentication through digital signatures but does not encrypt DNS traffic","DNSSEC only protects zone transfers between primary and secondary name servers","DNSSEC requires DNS over HTTPS (DoH) to be enabled to protect resolver-to-client queries"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC digitally signs resource records to authenticate origin and detect tampering, preventing spoofing and cache poisoning, but it was never designed to provide confidentiality; encryption of DNS traffic is a separate concern addressed by DoT or DoH. The other options misstate DNSSEC's scope or imply a deployment error where none exists.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security architect wants to logically separate hosts in different business units to contain broadcast traffic and limit lateral movement in the event a host is compromised, without installing additional physical switches. Which technology best achieves this?","o":["Virtual LANs (VLANs)","Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)","Port mirroring","Network Address Translation (NAT)"],"c":0,"why":"VLANs logically segment a physical switch into multiple broadcast domains, isolating traffic between business units. STP prevents Layer 2 loops, port mirroring is used for traffic monitoring, and NAT translates addresses but does not create logical segmentation within a switched network.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security engineer is evaluating firewall options and needs a solution that terminates client connections, inspects application-layer payloads, and establishes a separate connection to the destination server on behalf of the client. Which firewall type is being described?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Application-level proxy firewall","Circuit-level gateway"],"c":2,"why":"An application-level proxy fully terminates and reconstructs connections, allowing deep payload inspection before forwarding a new connection to the destination. Packet-filtering and stateful firewalls inspect headers/state without full session termination, and circuit-level gateways only validate session setup, not application content.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester successfully performs a VLAN hopping attack against a switched network by configuring a rogue host to negotiate trunking with an access switch port. Which control would MOST effectively prevent this specific attack vector?","o":["Enable Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) on all switch ports","Implement port security limiting MAC addresses per port","Disable Dynamic Trunking Protocol (DTP) on all access ports and manually configure trunk links only where needed","Assign all unused ports to VLAN 1, the default VLAN"],"c":2,"why":"Switch spoofing VLAN hopping exploits DTP's automatic trunk negotiation; disabling DTP on access ports and manually hard-coding trunks removes the attacker's ability to negotiate a trunk. Port security addresses MAC flooding, STP addresses loop prevention, and leaving ports on VLAN 1 actually increases risk rather than mitigating it.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A web server is experiencing a SYN flood attack that exhausts the connection state table maintained by the OS TCP stack. Engineers implement SYN cookies as a mitigation. Which best describes how SYN cookies allow the server to resist this attack?","o":["The server drops all SYN packets from unrecognized source IP addresses, eliminating spoofed traffic before consuming resources","The server encodes connection state within a cryptographically derived sequence number rather than storing it, and only allocates memory once the client returns a valid ACK","The server relies on the upstream router to rate-limit SYN traffic to a maximum number of connections per second","The server requires all connecting clients to complete a proof-of-work challenge before the handshake begins"],"c":1,"why":"SYN cookies embed session information into the SYN-ACK's initial sequence number instead of storing half-open connection state, so no resources are committed until the client responds with a valid ACK confirming a legitimate handshake. Blackholing unknown IPs, upstream rate limiting, and proof-of-work challenges are alternative or complementary DoS defenses but do not describe the SYN cookie mechanism itself.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization is concerned about attackers forging DNS responses to redirect users to malicious sites (cache poisoning). Which technology should be implemented to provide data origin authentication and integrity verification for DNS responses?","o":["DHCP snooping","DNSSEC","IPsec in transport mode","SSL/TLS termination at the DNS server"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to authenticate the origin and verify the integrity of DNS responses, preventing cache poisoning and spoofing. DHCP snooping addresses rogue DHCP servers, IPsec secures IP traffic generically but is not the standard DNS integrity solution, and TLS secures transport but does not validate DNS record authenticity by default (that would be DNS-over-TLS, which is different from DNSSEC's data integrity model).","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which network service is responsible for translating human-readable domain names into IP addresses?","o":["DHCP","DNS","ARP","SNMP"],"c":1,"why":"DNS (Domain Name System) resolves domain names to IP addresses. DHCP assigns IP addresses to hosts, ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses, and SNMP is used for network device management.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"During a penetration test, an attacker sends unsolicited ARP replies to associate their MAC address with the IP address of the default gateway on a local subnet. What is the PRIMARY security risk this attack introduces?","o":["Denial of service via SYN flooding","Traffic redirection enabling a man-in-the-middle attack","Exploitation of DNS cache poisoning","Exposure of WPA2 pre-shared keys"],"c":1,"why":"ARP spoofing tricks hosts into sending traffic intended for the gateway to the attacker instead, enabling interception or manipulation (MITM). It does not involve SYN flooding, DNS poisoning, or wireless key exposure directly.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect wants to ensure that DNS resolvers can cryptographically verify that a DNS response has not been altered in transit and truly originated from the authoritative source, thereby mitigating cache poisoning attacks. Which technology should be implemented?","o":["DNS over HTTPS (DoH)","Split-horizon DNS","DNSSEC","Restricting zone transfers to authorized secondary servers"],"c":2,"why":"DNSSEC adds digital signatures to DNS records, allowing resolvers to validate data origin authenticity and integrity, directly mitigating cache poisoning. DoH encrypts the transport channel but does not validate record authenticity; split-horizon DNS and zone transfer restrictions address different concerns (internal/external views and unauthorized replication, respectively).","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A multinational corporation notices that traffic destined for its public web application is being routed through an unfamiliar autonomous system in another country, despite no configuration changes at the corporate edge. Investigation reveals a peer ISP began announcing more specific IP prefixes for the corporation's address space. Which control would have provided the strongest preventive defense against this attack?","o":["Implementing BGP route origin validation using RPKI (Resource Public Key Infrastructure)","Enabling reverse path forwarding (uRPF) checks at the corporate firewall","Configuring OSPF authentication between internal routers","Deploying network address translation at the perimeter router"],"c":0,"why":"RPKI cryptographically validates that an autonomous system is authorized to originate a given prefix, directly preventing unauthorized or more-specific BGP announcements (route/prefix hijacking). uRPF mitigates spoofed source addresses on local egress traffic, OSPF authentication secures internal routing, not external BGP peering, and NAT has no bearing on route announcement legitimacy.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to ensure that devices connecting to switch ports on its wired LAN are authenticated before being granted network access, and unauthenticated devices are placed into a restricted guest VLAN. Which technology directly supports this requirement?","o":["802.1X port-based network access control","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) traps","Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) inspection"],"c":0,"why":"802.1X provides port-based authentication, requiring devices to authenticate (often via EAP and a RADIUS server) before being granted full network access, and can dynamically assign VLANs based on authentication results. SNMP is used for monitoring/management, STP prevents loops, and ARP inspection mitigates spoofing but does not perform authentication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security and addressing benefit of using Network Address Translation (NAT) at a network perimeter?","o":["It provides strong encryption for all outbound traffic","It hides internal private IP addresses from external networks while conserving public IP space","It eliminates the need for firewalls entirely","It guarantees non-repudiation of network transactions"],"c":1,"why":"NAT translates private internal addresses to a public address (or pool), masking internal network structure from external parties and reducing the need for large blocks of public IP addresses. NAT does not provide encryption, replace firewalls, or ensure non-repudiation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization is designing a network to host a public-facing web application while maximizing defense-in-depth and minimizing the attack surface exposed to the internal network if the web server is compromised. Which architecture BEST meets this goal?","o":["A single dual-homed bastion host connecting the Internet and internal network directly","A screened subnet (DMZ) bounded by two separate firewalls, one facing the Internet and one facing the internal network","A single packet-filtering router at the network perimeter with no additional firewall","A host-based firewall on the web server with no perimeter firewall"],"c":1,"why":"A screened subnet architecture places the public server between two firewalls, so a compromise of the DMZ host still requires bypassing a second firewall to reach internal resources, providing true defense-in-depth. The other options rely on a single point of control, offering weaker layered protection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization deploys a VoIP system where SIP signaling is protected using TLS, but a security assessment finds that the actual voice payload can still be captured and reconstructed by an attacker with access to the internal network segment. Which additional control should be implemented to remediate this finding?","o":["Implement 802.1X port-based authentication on all VoIP handset switch ports","Enable SRTP (Secure Real-time Transport Protocol) to encrypt the media stream","Configure a dedicated voice VLAN for all VoIP traffic","Upgrade SIP trunk connections to use mutual TLS authentication"],"c":1,"why":"TLS on SIP only secures call setup/signaling; the actual conversation is carried over RTP, which requires SRTP to encrypt and authenticate the media stream. 802.1X and VLAN segmentation reduce the attack surface for gaining network access but do not encrypt payload against an attacker who already has access, and mutual TLS strengthens signaling authentication rather than protecting media confidentiality.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization requires that all traffic between two branch office gateways be encrypted, including the original IP headers, to protect against traffic analysis. Which IPsec configuration should be implemented?","o":["Transport mode with ESP","Tunnel mode with ESP","Transport mode with AH","Tunnel mode with AH"],"c":1,"why":"Tunnel mode encapsulates and encrypts the entire original IP packet including headers, providing confidentiality and hiding internal addressing—appropriate for gateway-to-gateway VPNs. Transport mode only protects the payload, leaving original headers exposed, and AH provides integrity/authentication but not encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A financial organization's traditional stateful inspection firewall permits traffic based on source/destination IP, port, and connection state, but recent incidents involved malware communicating outbound over port 443 disguised as legitimate HTTPS traffic to evade detection. Which firewall capability would most effectively address this gap?","o":["Increasing the connection state table size to prevent evasion via connection exhaustion","Implementing application-layer inspection and TLS decryption capabilities found in next-generation firewalls","Adding additional NAT rules to obscure internal IP addressing","Enabling stricter ingress ACLs based on geographic IP block lists"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful firewalls inspect traffic only up through the transport layer and connection state, making them blind to malicious content hidden inside encrypted application-layer traffic; NGFWs add application awareness and TLS decryption/inspection to detect disguised command-and-control channels. Increasing table size, adjusting NAT, or geo-blocking do not provide visibility into the encrypted application payload causing the evasion.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"On a flat switched LAN, an attacker performs ARP spoofing to redirect traffic between a workstation and the default gateway through their own host for eavesdropping. Which control, when properly implemented on the switches, would BEST prevent this attack?","o":["Static routing between subnets","VLAN segmentation of the affected hosts","Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI) combined with DHCP snooping binding tables","Port security limiting the number of MAC addresses per port"],"c":2,"why":"DAI validates ARP packets against a trusted DHCP snooping binding table, dropping ARP replies that don't match known IP-to-MAC bindings, directly preventing ARP spoofing. VLAN segmentation and static routing don't stop spoofing within the same broadcast domain, and MAC-limiting port security addresses a different attack (MAC flooding), not ARP spoofing.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company migrating to WPA3 wants to ensure that even if an attacker captures the four-way handshake, they cannot perform an offline dictionary attack against the pre-shared key. Which feature of WPA3 provides this protection?","o":["TKIP with per-packet key mixing","AES-CCMP encryption","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","Pre-shared key rotation every 24 hours"],"c":2,"why":"SAE, based on the Dragonfly handshake, replaces WPA2's PSK exchange and is resistant to offline dictionary attacks because each exchange requires interaction with the live access point. TKIP and CCMP relate to encryption, not handshake protection, and key rotation alone doesn't prevent offline attacks on a captured handshake.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements 802.1X on its wired switch ports to control network access. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this implementation?","o":["It encrypts all traffic traversing the switch ports","It authenticates devices before granting network access at the port level","It automatically segments traffic into VLANs based on protocol type","It prevents MAC address spoofing on the local segment"],"c":1,"why":"802.1X provides port-based network access control, requiring successful authentication (often via EAP and a RADIUS server) before a port is opened for traffic. It does not inherently encrypt traffic, automatically assign VLANs by protocol, or prevent MAC spoofing.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company is deploying a VoIP infrastructure and wants to protect both call setup signaling and the actual voice media stream from eavesdropping and tampering as they traverse an untrusted network segment. Which combination of protocols BEST achieves this?","o":["Plain SIP signaling combined with RTP for media, secured only by network segmentation","TLS for SIP signaling and SRTP for media encryption","IPsec tunnel mode for signaling only, with RTP left unencrypted for performance","WPA2 encryption at the wireless access point covering all VoIP traffic end to end"],"c":1,"why":"TLS secures the SIP signaling channel (call setup, teardown, control), while SRTP encrypts and authenticates the actual voice media packets—together covering both planes of a VoIP call. The other options either leave media or signaling unprotected, or rely on link-layer encryption that doesn't protect traffic across intermediate untrusted hops.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A VoIP deployment is found to be vulnerable to eavesdropping because call signaling and media streams are transmitted in cleartext. Which combination of protocols should be implemented to remediate BOTH signaling and media confidentiality?","o":["SIP over TLS and SRTP","H.323 and RTP","SIP and RTCP","MGCP over TCP and RTP"],"c":0,"why":"SIP over TLS encrypts call setup/signaling, while SRTP encrypts the actual media stream, addressing both confidentiality concerns. The other options either use cleartext signaling protocols (H.323, SIP, MGCP) or unencrypted media protocols (RTP).","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"In a Software-Defined Networking (SDN) deployment, which factor represents the MOST significant security concern unique to this architecture compared to traditional distributed network control?","o":["Increased physical cabling complexity across data center racks","Loss of Quality of Service (QoS) prioritization capabilities","Compromise of the centralized SDN controller, which could allow an attacker to reprogram flow rules across the entire network","Inability to segment traffic using VLANs within an SDN fabric"],"c":2,"why":"SDN centralizes the control plane in a controller that programs forwarding behavior across all switches; compromising this single component gives an attacker outsized control over the entire network's traffic flows, a risk not present in traditional distributed control planes. The other options are not accurate or significant security concerns specific to SDN.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network administrator observes that a workstation is able to communicate using IPv4 but cannot resolve hostnames or reach external websites, despite having a valid IP address and default gateway. At which OSI layer should troubleshooting MOST likely begin?","o":["Layer 2 (Data Link)","Layer 3 (Network)","Layer 7 (Application) — specifically DNS resolution","Layer 1 (Physical)"],"c":2,"why":"Since the host has connectivity (valid IP, reaches gateway) but cannot resolve names, the issue points to DNS, an application-layer (Layer 7) service. Layers 1–3 are functioning correctly since basic IP connectivity exists.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"During the establishment of a TCP connection, which sequence correctly describes the three-way handshake?","o":["ACK, SYN, SYN-ACK","SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK","SYN, ACK, SYN-ACK","SYN-ACK, SYN, ACK"],"c":1,"why":"The correct TCP handshake sequence is SYN (client requests connection), SYN-ACK (server acknowledges and responds), and ACK (client confirms), establishing a reliable connection. The other orderings do not reflect the actual TCP protocol behavior.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator wants to segment traffic from different departments on the same physical switch without requiring additional hardware. Which technology should be used?","o":["Subnetting only","Virtual LAN (VLAN)","Network Address Translation (NAT)","Port forwarding"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs logically segment a single physical switch into multiple broadcast domains, isolating traffic between departments without additional hardware. NAT and port forwarding address IP translation and traffic redirection, not logical segmentation, and subnetting alone doesn't enforce Layer 2 isolation on a shared switch.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol is considered insecure due to weak key management and should be avoided in modern deployments?","o":["WPA3","WPA2","WEP","802.1X"],"c":2,"why":"WEP (Wired Equivalent Privacy) uses weak encryption and flawed key management, making it easily crackable and obsolete. WPA2 and WPA3 provide stronger security, and 802.1X is a port-based authentication framework, not a wireless encryption protocol itself.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of implementing IPsec in a VPN connection?","o":["To compress data for faster transmission","To translate private IP addresses to public IP addresses","To provide authentication, integrity, and confidentiality for IP packets","To assign dynamic IP addresses to VPN clients"],"c":2,"why":"IPsec is a suite of protocols designed to secure IP communications by providing authentication, data integrity, and confidentiality. It does not perform address translation (NAT) or dynamic IP assignment (DHCP), and compression is not its core security function.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which network service translates human-readable domain names into IP addresses?","o":["DHCP","ARP","DNS","SNMP"],"c":2,"why":"DNS (Domain Name System) resolves domain names to IP addresses. DHCP assigns IP addresses to devices, ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses, and SNMP is used for network device management, none of which perform domain name resolution.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization requires end-to-end confidentiality and integrity for traffic between two internal hosts, but the path between them traverses a NAT gateway. Which IPsec configuration should be selected to meet the security requirement while avoiding failures caused by the NAT device?","o":["AH in transport mode","ESP in transport mode with NAT-Traversal (NAT-T) enabled","AH in tunnel mode","ESP in tunnel mode without NAT-T"],"c":1,"why":"ESP encrypts and authenticates only the payload, and NAT-T encapsulates ESP packets in UDP so the modified IP header from NAT does not break the integrity check; AH fails with NAT because it authenticates the entire IP header, including the source address that NAT rewrites, and disabling NAT-T would still cause ESP to fail when NAT alters port information in transport mode.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which process correctly describes the TCP three-way handshake used to establish a connection?","o":["SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK","ACK, SYN, FIN","SYN, ACK, FIN-ACK","RST, SYN-ACK, ACK"],"c":0,"why":"TCP establishes a connection through SYN (client requests connection), SYN-ACK (server acknowledges and responds), and ACK (client confirms), ensuring both sides are synchronized. The other sequences either misorder the flags or use flags (FIN, RST) associated with termination or connection reset, not establishment.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester crafts Ethernet frames with two stacked 802.1Q VLAN tags and sends them from a host on an access port. The frames arrive on a VLAN the host should not be able to reach, without passing through a Layer 3 device. Which switch misconfiguration most likely enabled this attack, and what is the correct mitigation?","o":["The access port is in the wrong VLAN; mitigation is to move it to the correct VLAN","The trunk port's native VLAN matches the attacker's VLAN and is unencrypted; mitigation is to set the trunk's native VLAN to an unused VLAN and always tag it explicitly","Spanning Tree Protocol is disabled; mitigation is to enable STP on all trunk ports","The switch allows unlimited MAC addresses per port; mitigation is to enable port security with a MAC limit"],"c":1,"why":"Double-tagging (VLAN hopping) works because the outer tag matching the trunk's untagged native VLAN is stripped by the first switch, exposing the inner tag to hop into another VLAN; the fix is to never use the native VLAN for regular traffic and to explicitly tag it. MAC limiting and STP address unrelated attack vectors.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A company replaces its network hubs with switches to improve performance. What is the main security and performance benefit of this change?","o":["Switches encrypt all traffic automatically","Switches eliminate the need for IP addressing","Switches create separate collision domains per port, reducing traffic visible to each device","Switches allow unlimited broadcast domains"],"c":2,"why":"Unlike hubs, which broadcast all traffic to every connected device, switches create separate collision domains for each port, forwarding frames only to the intended recipient based on MAC address, improving both performance and reducing the ability to passively sniff unrelated traffic. Switches do not encrypt traffic or eliminate IP addressing requirements.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator wants a firewall that tracks the state of active connections and only allows return traffic that matches an established session. Which type of firewall provides this capability?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy","Static packet filter"],"c":1,"why":"A stateful inspection firewall maintains a state table of active connections, allowing it to permit only legitimate return traffic tied to an established session. Packet-filtering firewalls and static filters evaluate each packet independently without connection awareness, making them less secure for this purpose.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the function of Network Address Translation (NAT)?","o":["It encrypts traffic between two network segments","It maps private internal IP addresses to a public IP address for external communication","It filters traffic based on predefined security rules","It assigns MAC addresses to network interfaces"],"c":1,"why":"NAT translates private, internal IP addresses into a public IP address (or addresses) to enable communication with external networks while conserving public IP space and adding a layer of obscurity. It does not perform encryption, traffic filtering, or MAC address assignment, which are functions of other technologies.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"WPA3-Personal replaces the WPA2 four-way handshake with Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE). Which characteristic of SAE specifically prevents the offline dictionary attacks that were feasible against captured WPA2-PSK handshakes?","o":["SAE mandates AES-256 encryption instead of AES-128","SAE performs a Diffie-Hellman-based exchange so that an attacker who captures the exchange cannot derive enough information to brute-force the passphrase offline","SAE eliminates the use of a shared passphrase entirely, requiring certificates on every client","SAE transmits the passphrase hash instead of the passphrase itself, which cannot be reversed"],"c":1,"why":"SAE (the Dragonfly handshake) is based on a discrete-log commit-and-confirm exchange, so captured protocol messages do not provide enough material for offline guessing attempts; each guess requires interaction with the live AP. It still uses a shared passphrase (no certificates) and encryption strength is unrelated to the handshake's resistance to offline attack.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol is most commonly used to create a secure, encrypted tunnel for site-to-site VPN connections at the network layer?","o":["SSL/TLS","IPSec","SSH","PPTP"],"c":1,"why":"IPSec operates at the Network Layer and provides encryption, integrity, and authentication for site-to-site VPNs. SSL/TLS typically secures application-layer traffic (e.g., web sessions), SSH is used for secure remote command-line access, and PPTP is an older, less secure tunneling protocol.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which OSI layer is primarily responsible for end-to-end delivery of data, including segmentation, flow control, and reliable transmission using mechanisms such as acknowledgments and retransmission?","o":["Physical layer","Network layer","Transport layer","Session layer"],"c":2,"why":"The Transport layer (Layer 4) provides end-to-end reliability, segmentation, and flow control (e.g., TCP). The Network layer handles routing/addressing, the Physical layer deals with bits on media, and the Session layer manages dialog control, none of which provide end-to-end reliable delivery.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A regional ISP wants to prevent other autonomous systems from announcing unauthorized BGP routes for IP prefixes the ISP legitimately owns. Which technology should be deployed to cryptographically validate that an announcing AS is authorized to originate a given prefix?","o":["IPsec tunnels between all peering routers","RPKI with Route Origin Authorizations (ROAs)","Ingress ACLs filtering RFC 1918 addresses","BGP MD5 session authentication (RFC 2385)"],"c":1,"why":"RPKI ROAs cryptographically bind a prefix to the authorized originating AS number, allowing route origin validation and rejection of unauthorized announcements. MD5 session authentication only protects the BGP peering session integrity, not route origin, and IPsec/ACLs do not address prefix hijacking.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol replaced WPA2 to address vulnerabilities and provide stronger encryption using Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)?","o":["WEP","WPA","WPA2","WPA3"],"c":3,"why":"WPA3 introduced SAE to replace the vulnerable four-way handshake used in WPA2, improving resistance to offline dictionary attacks. WEP and WPA are older, weaker protocols, and WPA2, while stronger than its predecessors, does not use SAE.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network engineer must encrypt traffic between two branch-office VPN gateways over the public Internet, protecting the entire original IP packet, including the original source and destination headers. Which IPsec mode satisfies this requirement?","o":["Transport mode","Tunnel mode","Authentication Header (AH) only, no encryption","ESP in transport mode"],"c":1,"why":"Tunnel mode encapsulates and encrypts the entire original IP packet (including headers) inside a new IP packet, which is required for gateway-to-gateway VPNs. Transport mode only protects the payload and leaves the original IP header exposed, and AH alone does not provide encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A network switch is often preferred over a hub because a switch:","o":["Broadcasts all traffic to every connected device","Forwards traffic only to the specific port associated with the destination MAC address","Operates only at the physical layer","Cannot support full-duplex communication"],"c":1,"why":"Switches use MAC address tables to forward frames only to the intended destination port, reducing collisions and improving efficiency and security. Hubs broadcast to all ports, and switches operate at the Data Link Layer (not just physical), fully supporting full-duplex communication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is evaluating firewall options to defend against attacks that fragment malicious payloads across multiple packets specifically to evade signature-based inspection. Which firewall architecture provides the strongest defense against this technique?","o":["Stateless packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall operating at Layers 3-4","Application-layer proxy firewall that reassembles the full application stream before forwarding","Circuit-level proxy firewall"],"c":2,"why":"An application-layer proxy terminates the connection, fully reassembles the application data stream, and inspects the complete message before forwarding a new connection to the destination, defeating fragmentation-based evasion. Stateless and stateful firewalls typically inspect packets individually or track connection state without full payload reassembly, and circuit-level proxies operate below the application layer.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which firewall technology maintains a table of active connections and evaluates traffic based on context such as sequence numbers and connection state, rather than evaluating each packet independently?","o":["Packet filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy","Static packet filter"],"c":1,"why":"A stateful inspection firewall tracks connection state in a state table and uses that context to make forwarding decisions. Packet filtering and static filters evaluate packets in isolation without session context, and circuit-level proxies operate at the session layer without the same depth of state tracking used in stateful inspection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which service is responsible for translating human-readable domain names, such as example.com, into IP addresses that computers use to communicate?","o":["DHCP","DNS","ARP","NAT"],"c":1,"why":"DNS (Domain Name System) resolves domain names to IP addresses. DHCP assigns IP configurations to devices, ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses on a local network, and NAT translates private IP addresses to public ones.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which wireless security enhancement introduced in WPA3 replaces the WPA2 four-way handshake specifically to mitigate offline dictionary attacks against pre-shared keys?","o":["Temporal Key Integrity Protocol (TKIP)","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP)","EAP-TLS mutual authentication"],"c":1,"why":"SAE, based on the Dragonfly handshake, replaces the vulnerable WPA2 four-way handshake and resists offline dictionary attacks. TKIP and WEP are older, weaker encryption schemes unrelated to this improvement, and EAP-TLS is an enterprise authentication method, not the PSK handshake replacement.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company implements DNSSEC across its authoritative name servers. Which statement correctly describes the security benefit DNSSEC provides and a limitation it does NOT address?","o":["DNSSEC encrypts DNS queries and responses, providing confidentiality, but does not prevent cache poisoning","DNSSEC provides data origin authentication and integrity of DNS responses through digital signatures, but does not provide confidentiality of DNS traffic","DNSSEC prevents DNS amplification DDoS attacks by rate-limiting recursive queries","DNSSEC replaces the need for TLS by authenticating the destination server's identity"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC digitally signs zone data so resolvers can verify authenticity and integrity of responses, preventing spoofing/cache poisoning, but it does not encrypt the DNS traffic itself. It has no built-in DDoS rate-limiting function and does not substitute for TLS session authentication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization segments its network into separate VLANs for finance, HR, and guest Wi-Fi users. What is the primary security benefit of this design?","o":["It eliminates the need for firewalls between segments","It ensures all traffic is automatically encrypted","It reduces the attack surface by limiting broadcast domains and controlling traffic flow between groups","It guarantees compliance with all regulatory requirements"],"c":2,"why":"VLAN segmentation limits broadcast domains and allows granular control over traffic between different user groups, reducing the potential impact of a compromise in one segment. It does not eliminate the need for firewalls, provide encryption, or guarantee regulatory compliance on its own.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to logically isolate its finance department workstations from the general user network at Layer 2 without installing additional physical switches. Which technology best achieves this using existing switching infrastructure?","o":["Subnetting alone","Virtual LAN (VLAN)","Network Address Translation (NAT)","Port security"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs logically segment a switched network into separate broadcast domains without requiring new physical hardware. Subnetting alone addresses Layer 3 addressing but not Layer 2 isolation, NAT translates addresses rather than segmenting networks, and port security controls which devices can connect to a port but does not create logical segmentation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"In a software-defined networking (SDN) deployment, which security risk is most unique to SDN compared to traditional distributed network control planes?","o":["ARP spoofing becomes significantly more effective against SDN switches","Compromise of the centralized SDN controller can allow an attacker to reprogram forwarding behavior across the entire network","VLAN hopping attacks are inherently easier to execute in SDN fabrics","Physical tampering with switch hardware becomes the primary attack vector"],"c":1,"why":"SDN centralizes network intelligence and forwarding decisions in a controller; compromising that controller gives an attacker control over the entire data plane's behavior, a risk not present when control logic is distributed across independent devices. The other options are not inherently unique to or worsened by the SDN architecture itself.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"What is the primary security benefit provided by DNSSEC?","o":["Confidentiality of DNS queries through encryption","Integrity and authenticity of DNS responses through digital signatures","Prevention of denial-of-service attacks against DNS servers","Encryption of DNS zone transfer traffic"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC digitally signs DNS records so resolvers can verify the integrity and authenticity of responses, protecting against cache poisoning and spoofing. It does not provide confidentiality (queries remain unencrypted), and it does not inherently prevent DoS attacks or encrypt zone transfers.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An attacker inserts an unmanaged hub between a workstation's network cable and the switch port after the workstation has successfully completed 802.1X authentication, then connects a rogue laptop to the same hub and gains network access without authenticating. Which weakness of standard 802.1X does this attack exploit?","o":["802.1X only authenticates the connection at the port/session level and does not validate the authenticity of every subsequent frame, allowing piggybacking on an authenticated port","The RADIUS shared secret used for 802.1X was likely weak or transmitted in cleartext","The EAP method configured did not require mutual authentication between supplicant and authenticator","802.1X does not support VLAN assignment after successful authentication"],"c":0,"why":"Once a port is authenticated, 802.1X by default trusts all traffic on that port without re-validating each frame's origin, so an unmanaged hub lets a second device ride the already-authenticated session; this is why controls like MACsec or port-security with single-MAC enforcement are recommended. The scenario does not involve credential weakness, RADIUS secrets, or VLAN assignment issues.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An attacker on a local subnet sends forged ARP reply messages that associate their own MAC address with the IP address of the default gateway, enabling them to intercept traffic destined for the Internet. This attack is best classified as which of the following?","o":["DNS cache poisoning","ARP spoofing enabling a man-in-the-middle attack","MAC flooding","IP address spoofing"],"c":1,"why":"Forging ARP replies to impersonate the gateway's MAC address is classic ARP spoofing, used to position the attacker for a man-in-the-middle attack. DNS cache poisoning targets name resolution, MAC flooding overwhelms switch CAM tables rather than impersonating a specific host, and IP spoofing forges source IP addresses rather than manipulating MAC-to-IP mappings.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization needs to ensure that data is reliably delivered between two hosts, with proper sequencing, flow control, and retransmission of lost segments. Which OSI layer is primarily responsible for providing this functionality?","o":["Transport layer","Network layer","Data Link layer","Session layer"],"c":0,"why":"The Transport layer (Layer 4) provides end-to-end reliable delivery, sequencing, flow control, and retransmission (e.g., TCP). The Network layer handles logical addressing and routing, the Data Link layer handles framing and MAC addressing, and the Session layer manages dialog control, not reliability mechanisms.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which technology enforces port-level authentication of devices before granting them access to a wired or wireless network, typically working with a RADIUS server to validate credentials or certificates prior to network admission?","o":["VLAN tagging","IEEE 802.1X","Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)","Network Address Translation (NAT)"],"c":1,"why":"802.1X provides port-based network access control, requiring authentication (often via RADIUS/EAP) before a device is admitted to the network. VLAN tagging segments traffic but does not authenticate devices, STP prevents Layer 2 loops, and NAT translates addresses rather than controlling access.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A web server is being overwhelmed by a large number of TCP connection requests that never complete the handshake, exhausting its connection table. Which mitigation technique allows the server to avoid maintaining state for these incomplete connections?","o":["SYN cookies","Increasing the maximum transmission unit (MTU)","Disabling ICMP echo requests","Switching the service to use UDP instead of TCP"],"c":0,"why":"SYN cookies encode connection state into the SYN-ACK sequence number, allowing the server to avoid allocating resources until the handshake completes, mitigating SYN flood attacks. MTU changes, disabling ICMP, and switching to UDP do not address half-open TCP connection exhaustion.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network security engineer is comparing a simple packet-filtering firewall to a stateful inspection firewall. Which characteristic is unique to the stateful inspection firewall?","o":["It maintains a table of active connections to make context-aware filtering decisions","It operates exclusively at the Data Link layer","It automatically encrypts all traffic passing through it","It permits only outbound traffic by default"],"c":0,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls track the state of active connections in a state table, allowing them to evaluate traffic in context rather than packet-by-packet like simple packet filters. Firewalls do not inherently encrypt traffic, operate only at Layer 2, or restrict traffic direction by design.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization is deploying a site-to-site VPN between two corporate gateways over the public Internet. They want the entire original IP packet, including headers, to be encrypted and encapsulated within a new IP packet. Which IPSec mode should be used?","o":["Tunnel mode","Transport mode","AH mode without ESP","Null encryption mode"],"c":0,"why":"Tunnel mode encapsulates and encrypts the entire original IP packet, including its header, within a new packet—ideal for gateway-to-gateway VPNs. Transport mode only encrypts the payload and is typically used for host-to-host communication, while AH-only and null encryption do not provide the required confidentiality.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A wireless network administrator wants to protect against the KRACK vulnerability associated with the WPA2 four-way handshake by adopting a protocol that uses Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) for key establishment. Which wireless security standard should be implemented?","o":["WPA3","WEP","WPS","EAP-MD5"],"c":0,"why":"WPA3 replaces the WPA2 pre-shared key handshake with SAE, which is resistant to offline dictionary attacks and the KRACK vulnerability. WEP and WPS are outdated and insecure, and EAP-MD5 is a weak authentication method unrelated to key exchange improvements.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company segments its internal network into multiple VLANs based on department function. What is the primary security benefit this design provides?","o":["It reduces broadcast domains and limits the scope of lateral movement if a segment is compromised","It encrypts all traffic exchanged between hosts on different VLANs","It provides automatic failover in case of a switch hardware failure","It eliminates the need for firewalls between network segments"],"c":0,"why":"VLANs logically segment networks, reducing broadcast domains and containing potential compromises to a smaller segment, limiting lateral movement. VLANs do not provide encryption, hardware redundancy, or replace the need for firewalls between sensitive segments.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements DNSSEC on its authoritative name servers. What primary security benefit does this provide?","o":["Origin authentication and data integrity for DNS responses through digital signatures","Confidentiality of DNS queries through encryption","Load balancing of DNS queries across multiple servers","Elimination of the need for TLS on web servers"],"c":0,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to verify the authenticity and integrity of DNS data, protecting against spoofing and cache poisoning. It does not provide confidentiality (that is achieved via DNS over HTTPS/TLS), nor does it perform load balancing or replace TLS for web traffic.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator wants a device that can inspect the state of active connections and make filtering decisions based on the context of traffic flows rather than just individual packets. Which device best meets this requirement?","o":["Packet-filtering router","Stateful inspection firewall","Network hub","Layer 2 switch"],"c":1,"why":"A stateful inspection firewall tracks the state of active connections and evaluates traffic in context, offering more security than simple packet filtering. Hubs and Layer 2 switches do not perform any traffic filtering.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Before allowing an employee's laptop to connect to the corporate network, the network verifies that the device has current antivirus signatures and required security patches installed. Which technology is being used to enforce this requirement?","o":["Network Access Control (NAC)","Virtual Private Network (VPN)","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)","Content Distribution Network (CDN)"],"c":0,"why":"NAC solutions assess endpoint security posture, such as patch level and antivirus status, before granting network access, enforcing compliance with security policy. VPNs provide secure remote connectivity, SNMP is used for device management, and CDNs distribute content geographically, none of which perform endpoint posture checks.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol suite is most commonly used to provide confidentiality, integrity, and authentication for IP traffic traveling over an untrusted network such as the Internet?","o":["SNMP","IPsec","ICMP","ARP"],"c":1,"why":"IPsec provides encryption, integrity checking, and authentication for IP packets, commonly used in VPNs. SNMP is for network management, ICMP is for diagnostic messaging, and ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses—none provide these security services.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing a site-to-site VPN to a branch office located behind an ISP-managed NAT device. The design requires confidentiality and integrity protection of the encapsulated payload, and the tunnel must remain functional despite the NAT device rewriting source IP addresses in transit. Which IPsec configuration should be selected?","o":["AH in transport mode","AH in tunnel mode","ESP in tunnel mode with NAT-Traversal (UDP 4500 encapsulation)","ESP in transport mode without NAT-Traversal"],"c":2,"why":"AH authenticates the outer IP header, which NAT rewriting invalidates, breaking the tunnel regardless of mode. ESP in tunnel mode encapsulates the full original packet and, combined with NAT-T UDP encapsulation, avoids issues with NAT devices that cannot properly track ESP's lack of port information, making it the only viable option through NAT.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise migrates its guest wireless network from WPA2-Personal to WPA3-Personal. Which security improvement most directly addresses the offline dictionary attacks that were feasible against WPA2's four-way handshake?","o":["Use of AES-256 instead of AES-128 for data encryption","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) replacing the PSK-based four-way handshake","Mandatory enforcement of Protected Management Frames only","Increasing the SSID beacon broadcast interval to reduce handshake capture opportunities"],"c":1,"why":"SAE (the Dragonfly handshake) requires an active exchange with a live peer for every password guess and provides forward secrecy, making captured handshakes useless for offline cracking. Encryption key length doesn't affect handshake capture, PMF protects management frames only, and beacon interval has no bearing on offline attacks against a captured handshake.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution implements DNSSEC on its authoritative name servers. Which of the following threats does this control primarily mitigate?","o":["Eavesdropping on DNS query and response confidentiality","Cache poisoning via forged or tampered DNS responses","DNS amplification-based distributed denial-of-service attacks","Covert data exfiltration via DNS tunneling"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC provides cryptographic origin authentication and data integrity for DNS responses, preventing acceptance of forged or altered records (cache poisoning). It does not encrypt DNS traffic (no confidentiality), does not limit amplification DDoS traffic volume, and does not detect anomalous query patterns used for tunneling.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization is upgrading its wireless network and wants to use the strongest widely available encryption and authentication standard for protecting data in transit. Which should they choose?","o":["WEP","WPA","WPA2","Open (no encryption)"],"c":2,"why":"WPA2 uses AES-based CCMP encryption and is significantly stronger than WEP or the original WPA, which rely on weaker algorithms (RC4/TKIP) with known vulnerabilities. Open networks provide no encryption at all.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"In a zero trust data center architecture, an architect implements micro-segmentation using host-based firewalls and identity-aware policies enforced at each workload, rather than relying solely on perimeter VLAN ACLs. What is the primary security benefit for east-west traffic specifically?","o":["Elimination of the need for encryption between hosts","Reduced opportunity for lateral movement if a single workload is compromised","Simplified network topology requiring fewer physical switches","Automatic compliance with data residency regulations"],"c":1,"why":"Micro-segmentation enforces granular, identity-based policy at the workload level regardless of network topology, containing an attacker to a single segment and limiting lateral movement. It has no bearing on encryption necessity, switch count, or regulatory data residency requirements.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which network device forwards traffic only to the specific port associated with the destination MAC address, thereby reducing unnecessary traffic and collisions compared to a hub?","o":["Repeater","Switch","Bridge in promiscuous mode","Modem"],"c":1,"why":"A switch learns MAC addresses and forwards frames only to the port where the destination device resides, creating separate collision domains per port. A hub broadcasts to all ports, and repeaters/modems do not perform MAC-based forwarding.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which service translates human-readable domain names into IP addresses so that hosts can locate resources on a network?","o":["DHCP","DNS","NAT","ARP"],"c":1,"why":"DNS (Domain Name System) resolves domain names to IP addresses. DHCP assigns IP configuration to hosts, NAT translates private to public IP addresses, and ARP maps IP addresses to MAC addresses on a local segment.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A legacy stateless packet-filtering firewall applies ACL rules by inspecting TCP header fields (ports, flags) only in the first fragment of a packet, and forwards subsequent fragments without re-inspection based on offset continuity. Which technique exploits this behavior to bypass the filter?","o":["A SYN flood attack against the firewall's connection table","A tiny fragment attack that splits the TCP header across fragments so port/flag data falls outside the inspected first fragment","ARP cache poisoning to redirect frames to an attacker-controlled MAC address","A smurf attack using spoofed ICMP echo requests to a broadcast address"],"c":1,"why":"The tiny fragment attack deliberately crafts an undersized first fragment so critical header fields land in a later, uninspected fragment, evading filtering logic that only examines the first fragment. The other attacks target connection-state exhaustion, layer 2 redirection, or bandwidth amplification, not fragmentation-based filter evasion.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization's SIP trunk connects its on-premises IP-PBX to a carrier without mutual endpoint authentication, and RTP media streams are unencrypted. An attacker gains access to the trunk and places unauthorized international calls billed to the organization. Which control would most directly prevent this specific attack?","o":["Enabling SRTP to encrypt media streams","Implementing digest authentication and IP-based access control lists restricting trunk registration to authorized carrier addresses","Deploying a network IDS to log call detail records for later review","Encrypting SIP signaling with TLS without adding endpoint authentication"],"c":1,"why":"Toll fraud results from unauthorized session/registration on the SIP trunk; requiring digest authentication plus source-restricted ACLs directly blocks unauthorized call origination. SRTP protects media confidentiality but not call authorization, an IDS is detective rather than preventive, and TLS alone secures signaling transport without verifying identity.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A network engineer is concerned that an upstream provider could announce a more specific prefix belonging to the organization's autonomous system, redirecting Internet-bound traffic through an attacker-controlled path. Which technology provides a cryptographic mechanism to validate that a BGP route announcement originates from an authorized AS?","o":["BGP route dampening","Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI) with Route Origin Authorizations (ROAs)","Equal-cost multi-path (ECMP) routing","Generalized TTL Security Mechanism (GTSM)"],"c":1,"why":"RPKI/ROA cryptographically binds IP prefixes to their authorized originating AS, allowing routers to validate announcements and reject hijacked prefixes. Route dampening addresses flapping routes, ECMP is a load-balancing technique, and GTSM defends against off-path spoofed BGP session packets, not prefix origin validation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A company wants multiple internal hosts with private IP addresses to share a single public IP address when accessing the Internet. Which technology accomplishes this?","o":["VLAN tagging","Network Address Translation (NAT)","Spanning Tree Protocol","Port mirroring"],"c":1,"why":"NAT allows many internal devices with private addresses to share one or a few public IP addresses by translating and tracking connection information at the gateway. VLANs segment broadcast domains, STP prevents loops, and port mirroring is used for traffic monitoring.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A CISO mandates that wireless clients and the authentication server perform mutual authentication using digital certificates on both ends before 802.1X grants network access, explicitly rejecting methods that rely solely on user credentials tunneled inside a server-authenticated encrypted session. Which EAP method satisfies this requirement?","o":["PEAP-MSCHAPv2","EAP-TTLS with password authentication","EAP-TLS","LEAP"],"c":2,"why":"EAP-TLS requires both client and server certificates, achieving true mutual public-key-based authentication. PEAP and EAP-TTLS typically authenticate only the server via certificate while tunneling user credentials, and LEAP is a legacy proprietary method vulnerable to offline dictionary attacks, none of which meet the stated mutual-certificate requirement.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An engineer is troubleshooting a network issue and needs to identify which OSI layer is responsible for ensuring reliable end-to-end delivery of data, including flow control, sequencing, and error correction between hosts. Which layer is this?","o":["Transport layer","Network layer","Data Link layer","Session layer"],"c":0,"why":"The Transport layer (e.g., TCP) provides reliable end-to-end delivery, flow control, and error correction. The Network layer handles routing/addressing, the Data Link layer handles framing and error detection on a single link, and the Session layer manages dialog control, not reliability.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which sequence correctly describes the TCP three-way handshake used to establish a connection?","o":["ACK, SYN, SYN-ACK","SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK","SYN, ACK, FIN","SYN-ACK, SYN, ACK"],"c":1,"why":"The client sends SYN, the server responds with SYN-ACK, and the client completes the handshake with ACK. The other sequences reverse or misplace the steps and do not reflect the standard TCP connection establishment process.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst observes a massive volume of TCP SYN packets arriving from many spoofed source IP addresses, none of which complete the three-way handshake. The target server's connection queue becomes exhausted, denying service to legitimate users. Which attack is occurring?","o":["SYN flood","ARP poisoning","Smurf attack","Session hijacking"],"c":0,"why":"A SYN flood exploits the TCP handshake by sending numerous SYN packets without completing the ACK, exhausting connection resources. ARP poisoning targets Layer 2 address resolution, a smurf attack abuses ICMP broadcast amplification, and session hijacking takes over an already-established session.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing a site-to-site VPN between two data centers. The requirement is that the entire original IP packet (including original source/destination headers) must be both encrypted and integrity-protected while traversing the public Internet. Which IPsec configuration satisfies this requirement?","o":["Authentication Header (AH) in transport mode","Authentication Header (AH) in tunnel mode","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) in transport mode","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) in tunnel mode"],"c":3,"why":"ESP in tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original IP packet inside a new IP packet and provides both confidentiality (encryption) and integrity for the encapsulated packet. AH provides no confidentiality, and transport mode (either AH or ESP) only protects the payload, not the original IP header.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A firewall that tracks the state of active connections and makes filtering decisions based on the context of traffic within a session is known as which type of firewall?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy","Application-level gateway only"],"c":1,"why":"A stateful inspection firewall maintains a state table of active connections and evaluates packets in the context of the session, offering more security than simple packet filtering. Packet-filtering firewalls examine packets independently without session context.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A stateful inspection firewall makes forwarding decisions primarily based on which mechanism?","o":["A dynamically maintained state table tracking the status of active connections","Static access control lists evaluated independently for each packet","Deep inspection of application-layer payloads via a proxy process","Digital certificates presented during a TLS handshake"],"c":0,"why":"Stateful firewalls track connection state (e.g., SYN, ESTABLISHED) in a state table to determine whether packets belong to legitimate sessions. Static ACL-only evaluation describes packet-filtering firewalls, application-layer proxying describes proxy firewalls, and certificate validation is unrelated to basic stateful filtering.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester crafts an Ethernet frame with two stacked 802.1Q VLAN tags and sends it to an access port. The switch strips the outer tag matching the port's native VLAN and forwards the frame with the inner tag onto the trunk, allowing traffic to cross into a VLAN the attacker should not reach. Which mitigation most directly prevents this VLAN hopping technique?","o":["Enable Dynamic ARP Inspection on all access ports","Assign an unused VLAN as the native VLAN on trunk ports and explicitly tag all native VLAN traffic","Configure port security to limit the number of MAC addresses per port","Enable BPDU Guard on all access-layer switch ports"],"c":1,"why":"Double-tagging attacks exploit the fact that native VLAN traffic on trunks is often untagged; using a dedicated, unused native VLAN and tagging all traffic prevents the switch from stripping only the outer tag and forwarding the inner tagged frame improperly. DAI, port security, and BPDU Guard address ARP spoofing, MAC flooding, and STP manipulation, respectively, not double-tagging.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network administrator segments a large switched network into multiple VLANs. What is the primary security and performance benefit of this design?","o":["It reduces the size of broadcast domains and limits exposure between segments","It automatically encrypts all traffic traversing the switch fabric","It provides redundant Layer 2 paths to prevent switching loops","It dynamically assigns IP addresses to devices in each segment"],"c":0,"why":"VLANs logically segment broadcast domains, reducing broadcast traffic and limiting lateral exposure between groups of hosts. Encryption is unrelated to VLANs, loop prevention is the role of Spanning Tree Protocol, and dynamic IP assignment is handled by DHCP, not VLANs themselves.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"In IPSec, which protocol provides both confidentiality (encryption) and integrity for data in transit?","o":["Authentication Header (AH)","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP)","Internet Key Exchange (IKE)","Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP)"],"c":1,"why":"ESP provides encryption for confidentiality as well as optional integrity and authentication. AH provides integrity and authentication but not encryption, IKE is used for key negotiation, and L2TP is a tunneling protocol without built-in encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization is evaluating why WPA3-Personal (using SAE/Dragonfly key exchange) is considered more resilient than WPA2-Personal against a specific class of attack when an adversary passively captures the authentication exchange. Which attack does WPA3's SAE handshake specifically mitigate that WPA2-PSK's four-way handshake does not?","o":["Offline dictionary/brute-force attacks against a captured handshake","Deauthentication flooding to force client reassociation","Evil-twin access point impersonation using a cloned SSID","Downgrade attacks during Bluetooth pairing"],"c":0,"why":"WPA2's PSK-derived PMK can be attacked offline once the four-way handshake is captured, since guesses can be verified without interacting with the network. SAE requires an interactive exchange for each password guess and provides forward secrecy, making offline dictionary attacks infeasible. The other options are not addressed by SAE specifically.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol replaced WEP and WPA to provide stronger encryption using AES-based CCMP?","o":["WPA2","WPA3-Personal only","TKIP","WEP2"],"c":0,"why":"WPA2 introduced AES-based CCMP encryption, significantly improving on WEP's weak RC4 encryption and WPA's TKIP. TKIP was a transitional encryption method used in WPA, and 'WEP2' is not a standard protocol.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization needs end-to-end encrypted communication between two specific hosts using IPSec, where only the payload is encrypted while the original IP header remains visible for routing. Which IPSec mode should be implemented?","o":["Transport mode","Tunnel mode","AH-only mode","ESP null mode"],"c":0,"why":"Transport mode encrypts only the payload and leaves the original IP header intact, making it suitable for direct host-to-host communication. Tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original packet inside a new IP header, typically used for gateway-to-gateway VPNs, while AH-only and ESP-null modes do not provide confidentiality of the payload.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security benefit of implementing VLANs on a switched network?","o":["Encrypting all traffic between hosts","Logically segmenting broadcast domains to limit traffic and contain potential attacks","Automatically detecting intrusions on the network","Providing redundant physical paths for fault tolerance"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs logically segment a network into separate broadcast domains, reducing unnecessary traffic and limiting the scope of a compromised segment. VLANs do not provide encryption, intrusion detection, or physical redundancy on their own.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company deploying an enterprise WPA2-Enterprise wireless network wants an EAP method that provides mutual authentication using digital certificates on both the client and the RADIUS server, minimizing risk from rogue access points and credential theft. Which method best meets this requirement?","o":["EAP-TLS","PSK (Pre-Shared Key)","WEP","LEAP"],"c":0,"why":"EAP-TLS uses certificates on both client and server for strong mutual authentication, protecting against rogue APs and credential interception. PSK relies on a shared secret with no mutual certificate validation, WEP is deprecated and weak, and LEAP has known vulnerabilities to offline dictionary attacks.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"In a three-legged screened subnet (DMZ) firewall architecture, a company is deploying a public-facing web server that must be reachable from the Internet but should pose minimal risk to internal systems if compromised. Where should this server be placed, and how should traffic be controlled?","o":["On the internal network segment, protected only by host-based firewall rules","On the DMZ segment, with firewall rules that tightly restrict DMZ-to-internal traffic to only what is explicitly required","On the same network segment as the firewall's management interface for ease of administration","Directly connected to the ISP-facing router, bypassing the firewall for performance"],"c":1,"why":"The DMZ isolates publicly accessible services from the internal network; strict firewall rules limiting DMZ-to-internal communication ensure that even if the web server is compromised, lateral movement into the internal network is constrained. Placing it internally or bypassing the firewall entirely defeats the purpose of network segmentation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which network service is responsible for resolving human-readable domain names into IP addresses?","o":["DHCP","DNS","ARP","NAT"],"c":1,"why":"DNS (Domain Name System) translates domain names into IP addresses. DHCP assigns IP addresses, ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses, and NAT translates private to public IP addresses.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company is deploying an enterprise VoIP system and is concerned about eavesdropping on both call setup and call content over the internal network. Which combination of controls provides confidentiality for both the signaling and the media streams?","o":["SRTP for media streams and TLS for SIP signaling","IPsec in transport mode applied only to RTP media streams","WPA3 encryption on the Wi-Fi network used by softphones","An SSH tunnel wrapping the RTP media streams only"],"c":0,"why":"SIP signaling is protected via TLS (SIPS) and the actual voice payload is protected via SRTP, together securing both call setup and content. The other options either protect only one channel (media) or rely on network-layer/link-layer encryption that does not secure the SIP signaling itself end-to-end.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which transmission medium is generally most resistant to electromagnetic interference (EMI) and eavesdropping via signal tapping?","o":["Unshielded twisted pair (UTP)","Coaxial cable","Fiber optic cable","Shielded twisted pair (STP)"],"c":2,"why":"Fiber optic cable uses light rather than electrical signals, making it immune to EMI and very difficult to tap without detection. UTP, STP, and coaxial cable all use electrical signals and are more susceptible to interference and tapping.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A network engineer is concerned about BGP route hijacking, where a malicious or misconfigured autonomous system announces routes for IP prefixes it does not own. Which technology cryptographically validates that an AS is authorized to originate routes for a specific prefix?","o":["RPKI Route Origin Authorization (ROA) validation","MD5 authentication on BGP peering sessions","Generalized TTL Security Mechanism (GTSM)","BGP route flap dampening"],"c":0,"why":"RPKI ROAs cryptographically bind a prefix to the authorized originating AS, allowing routers to reject invalid announcements. MD5 authentication only protects the integrity of the BGP session between peers, GTSM guards against spoofed packets via TTL checks, and route dampening only suppresses unstable route advertisements—none validate route origin authorization.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An attacker on a local subnet sends unsolicited, forged ARP reply messages associating the default gateway's IP address with the attacker's own MAC address, causing other hosts to route traffic through the attacker's machine. Which attack is being described?","o":["ARP spoofing (poisoning)","DNS cache poisoning","IP address spoofing","MAC flooding"],"c":0,"why":"ARP spoofing involves sending forged ARP replies to associate a legitimate IP address with an attacker-controlled MAC address, enabling man-in-the-middle interception. DNS cache poisoning targets name resolution, IP spoofing forges source IP addresses in packets, and MAC flooding overwhelms a switch's CAM table rather than manipulating ARP mappings.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A VoIP deployment uses a protocol responsible for establishing, modifying, and tearing down multimedia sessions between endpoints, but if left unencrypted, call setup information can be intercepted. Which protocol is primarily responsible for this signaling function?","o":["SIP (Session Initiation Protocol)","RTP (Real-time Transport Protocol)","SRTP (Secure Real-time Transport Protocol)","SNMP (Simple Network Management Protocol)"],"c":0,"why":"SIP handles call signaling—session setup, modification, and teardown—and should be protected with TLS (SIPS) to prevent eavesdropping. RTP and SRTP carry the actual media stream rather than signaling, and SNMP is used for network device management, unrelated to VoIP session control.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise wants to eliminate the risk of credential harvesting via rogue access points that could otherwise capture and replay authentication attempts against 802.1X-protected wireless networks. Which EAP method provides the strongest protection by requiring mutual, certificate-based authentication independent of password strength?","o":["EAP-MD5","PEAP-MSCHAPv2","EAP-TLS with mutual certificate authentication","LEAP"],"c":2,"why":"EAP-TLS requires both the supplicant and the authentication server to present X.509 certificates, providing strong mutual authentication that eliminates reliance on passwords and resists rogue AP credential harvesting. EAP-MD5 and LEAP are weak and vulnerable to offline attacks, and PEAP-MSCHAPv2 still relies on password-based inner authentication that can be captured and attacked if the outer TLS tunnel is compromised or misconfigured.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements DNSSEC across its authoritative and recursive DNS infrastructure to counter cache poisoning attacks. Which statement accurately describes the security benefit DNSSEC provides?","o":["It encrypts DNS queries and responses to ensure confidentiality","It provides data origin authentication and integrity verification of DNS responses through digital signatures","It prevents DNS reflection and amplification DDoS attacks","It reduces DNS resolution latency through improved response caching"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses public-key cryptography to sign DNS records, allowing resolvers to verify that responses genuinely originated from the authoritative source and were not altered in transit, directly countering cache poisoning. DNSSEC does not provide confidentiality (that is the role of DoT/DoH), does not inherently prevent amplification attacks, and can actually increase response size, not improve latency.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization's network engineer notices that a router is making forwarding decisions based on destination IP addresses and maintaining a routing table. At which layer of the OSI model does this router primarily operate?","o":["Layer 2 (Data Link)","Layer 3 (Network)","Layer 4 (Transport)","Layer 7 (Application)"],"c":1,"why":"Routing decisions based on IP addresses occur at the Network layer (Layer 3). Layer 2 uses MAC addresses for switching, Layer 4 handles end-to-end connections (TCP/UDP), and Layer 7 deals with application-level data.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst observes a large number of TCP connection attempts to a web server where the three-way handshake is never completed, and the server's connection queue becomes exhausted. Which attack is most likely occurring?","o":["ARP poisoning","SYN flood","DNS cache poisoning","Smurf attack"],"c":1,"why":"A SYN flood exploits the TCP handshake by sending SYN packets without completing the ACK, exhausting the server's connection queue. ARP poisoning targets Layer 2 address resolution, DNS cache poisoning corrupts DNS records, and a Smurf attack uses ICMP broadcast amplification.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which IPSec component provides confidentiality, integrity, and authentication for a packet's payload, but does NOT protect the outer IP header when used in transport mode?","o":["Authentication Header (AH)","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP)","Internet Key Exchange (IKE)","Security Association (SA)"],"c":1,"why":"ESP provides encryption (confidentiality) plus integrity/authentication for the payload, but in transport mode it does not protect the outer IP header. AH provides integrity/authentication only (no confidentiality) and does cover parts of the header; IKE negotiates keys, and an SA is the negotiated policy/parameters, not a protection mechanism itself.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company wants a firewall that can track the state of active connections and make filtering decisions based on the context of traffic (e.g., recognizing that a packet is part of an established session), while still operating efficiently at higher throughput than an application-layer proxy. Which firewall type best fits this requirement?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy","Application-layer (proxy) firewall"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls track connection state tables and evaluate traffic in context, offering better security than simple packet filters while remaining faster than full application-layer proxies. Packet filters lack state awareness, and proxy firewalls (circuit or application layer) introduce more overhead by fully terminating and re-establishing connections.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements IPsec VPN tunnels between two branch offices, both located behind NAT devices at their respective edge routers. After deployment, tunnels configured to use AH (Authentication Header) in transport mode fail intermittently, while tunnels using ESP in tunnel mode with NAT-Traversal (NAT-T) function correctly. What is the most likely root cause of the AH failures?","o":["AH does not support the encryption algorithms required for cross-WAN branch links","NAT rewrites the source IP address in the outer IP header, invalidating the AH integrity check value which covers that header","AH is architecturally incapable of operating in transport mode over any WAN connection","The Diffie-Hellman key exchange used to establish AH associations is blocked by NAT port translation"],"c":1,"why":"AH computes its integrity check value over the entire IP packet, including most of the IP header; when NAT rewrites the source address, the ICV no longer matches, causing failure. ESP avoids this because its transport encapsulation (and NAT-T UDP wrapping) does not require integrity protection of the outer IP header. AH provides no encryption at all, so option A is a false premise, AH can run in transport mode over WANs, and the failure is a header integrity issue, not a key-exchange/port issue.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An enterprise is deploying a wireless network and wants to ensure that each user authenticates with individual credentials against a centralized authentication server, rather than sharing a single pre-shared key across all devices. Which architecture should be implemented?","o":["WPA2-Personal with a shared passphrase","WPA2/WPA3-Enterprise using 802.1X with an EAP method","WEP with MAC address filtering","Open network with a captive portal only"],"c":1,"why":"WPA2/WPA3-Enterprise with 802.1X and an EAP method authenticates each user individually against a RADIUS/AAA server, providing per-user credentials and better accountability. WPA2-Personal uses a shared PSK, WEP is deprecated and insecure, and captive portals alone don't provide strong per-user cryptographic authentication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect must select a wireless authentication mechanism for a large campus deployment. The requirement is mutual authentication between client and access infrastructure and strong resistance to offline dictionary attacks even when users choose weak passphrases. Which mechanism best satisfies this requirement?","o":["WPA2-Personal using a Pre-Shared Key (PSK)","WPA3-Personal using SAE (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals)","WEP with dynamically rotated keys","Open authentication combined with a captive portal"],"c":1,"why":"SAE is a password-authenticated key exchange (PAKE) that provides mutual authentication and forward secrecy, and it resists offline dictionary attacks because an attacker cannot derive the password from a captured exchange, unlike WPA2's 4-way handshake which is vulnerable to offline PSK cracking. WEP is fundamentally broken, and a captive portal over open authentication provides no cryptographic authentication or confidentiality at the link layer.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network administrator wants to logically separate traffic from the finance department and the engineering department on the same physical switch infrastructure, without running separate cabling, while still enforcing traffic isolation at Layer 2. Which technology should be used?","o":["Network Address Translation (NAT)","Virtual LAN (VLAN)","Port address translation (PAT)","Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs logically segment a switch into separate broadcast domains, isolating traffic between departments without additional cabling. NAT/PAT operate at Layer 3/4 for address translation, not segmentation, and STP prevents Layer 2 loops rather than isolating traffic.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"At which layer of the OSI model does a router primarily operate to make forwarding decisions?","o":["Layer 2 (Data Link)","Layer 3 (Network)","Layer 4 (Transport)","Layer 7 (Application)"],"c":1,"why":"Routers make forwarding decisions based on logical (IP) addressing, which is defined at Layer 3, the Network layer. Layer 2 devices like switches use MAC addresses, and Layers 4 and 7 deal with transport sessions and application data, not routing.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester on an internal network successfully performs a VLAN hopping attack by crafting an Ethernet frame with two stacked 802.1Q tags, causing a switch to forward the frame into a VLAN the attacker's port was never assigned to. Which mitigation most directly addresses this specific attack technique?","o":["Enable port security to limit the number of MAC addresses learned per port","Configure the native VLAN on all trunk ports to a dedicated, unused VLAN ID that is not assigned to any access port","Implement DHCP snooping on all access-layer switches","Use VLAN 1 as the management VLAN across all switches for consistency"],"c":1,"why":"Double-tagging attacks exploit the fact that the outer tag matching the native VLAN is stripped by the first switch, exposing the inner tag to be forwarded into another VLAN; isolating the native VLAN from any access port defeats this. Port security addresses MAC flooding, not tag manipulation; DHCP snooping addresses rogue DHCP servers; and using VLAN 1 for management is a poor practice that increases, rather than reduces, this risk.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A VoIP deployment needs to protect the confidentiality and integrity of voice media streams as they traverse the network, in addition to securing the call setup signaling. Which protocol should be used specifically to protect the media (voice) packets themselves?","o":["Session Initiation Protocol (SIP)","Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP)","Transport Layer Security (TLS)","H.323"],"c":1,"why":"SRTP encrypts and authenticates the actual media (RTP) stream carrying voice data. SIP and H.323 are signaling protocols used for call setup/control, and TLS is typically used to secure SIP signaling channels, not the RTP media itself.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which TCP mechanism is used to establish a reliable connection before data transfer begins?","o":["Three-way handshake","ARP resolution","Fragmentation","Sliding window"],"c":0,"why":"TCP uses the three-way handshake (SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK) to establish a reliable, connection-oriented session. ARP resolves IP to MAC addresses, fragmentation splits large packets, and the sliding window manages flow control after the connection is established.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that DNS responses received by its resolvers have not been forged or tampered with in transit, protecting against cache poisoning attacks. Which technology should be implemented?","o":["DNSSEC","Split-horizon DNS","DHCP snooping","Reverse DNS lookups"],"c":0,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to validate the authenticity and integrity of DNS responses, mitigating cache poisoning and spoofing. Split-horizon DNS controls which responses are given based on requester location, DHCP snooping protects against rogue DHCP servers, and reverse DNS lookups simply map IPs to names without providing integrity protection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"Which statement most accurately describes the security function provided by DNSSEC?","o":["DNSSEC encrypts DNS query and response payloads to prevent eavesdropping on lookups","DNSSEC uses digital signatures to provide data origin authentication and integrity of DNS records, but does not provide confidentiality","DNSSEC replaces UDP-based DNS transactions with mandatory TLS-encrypted sessions","DNSSEC mitigates distributed denial-of-service attacks against authoritative name servers"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC adds cryptographic signatures to DNS records so resolvers can verify authenticity and integrity (preventing cache poisoning/spoofing), but it explicitly does not encrypt DNS traffic. Confidentiality is instead addressed by separate mechanisms like DNS-over-TLS/HTTPS, and DNSSEC has no built-in DDoS mitigation capability.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A stateful inspection firewall differs from a simple packet-filtering firewall primarily because it:","o":["Encrypts all traffic passing through it","Tracks the state of active connections to make filtering decisions","Operates only at the physical layer","Requires no configuration of rules"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful firewalls maintain a state table of active connections, allowing them to make context-aware decisions about traffic, unlike packet filters that only inspect individual packets in isolation. Encryption and physical-layer operation are not defining characteristics of stateful inspection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise deploys SIP trunking to a cloud VoIP provider over the public Internet. Which combination of controls provides the most complete protection for both call setup signaling and voice media confidentiality?","o":["SIP over TLS (SIPS) for signaling and SRTP for media streams","IPsec tunnel mode for signaling only, leaving RTP media unencrypted to preserve QoS markings","Exclusive use of STUN/TURN servers, which inherently encrypt SIP messages","VLAN segmentation of VoIP traffic without any transport-layer encryption"],"c":0,"why":"SIPS protects the confidentiality and integrity of call setup signaling, while SRTP encrypts the actual voice media; using both closes the gap left by protecting only one channel. Leaving RTP unencrypted exposes call content to eavesdropping, STUN/TURN are NAT traversal helpers with no inherent encryption function, and VLAN segmentation alone does not protect against interception within or across trust boundaries.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol is primarily used to create a secure, encrypted tunnel for site-to-site VPN connections over an untrusted network?","o":["IPSec","SNMP","FTP","ICMP"],"c":0,"why":"IPSec provides authentication and encryption for IP traffic, making it the standard choice for secure site-to-site VPNs. SNMP is for network management, FTP is for file transfer, and ICMP is used for diagnostic messaging—none provide VPN encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"In a Software-Defined Networking (SDN) architecture, which statement best describes the primary security concern introduced by centralizing network intelligence in the SDN controller?","o":["The controller must process significantly more east-west traffic because the control plane has been eliminated","The controller becomes a high-value single point of failure and attack target; its compromise can allow an attacker to globally reprogram network flows","SDN architectures inherently lack support for any encryption protocols, exposing all data plane traffic","Separating the control plane from the data plane prevents the implementation of firewalls or access control lists"],"c":1,"why":"Centralizing control logic means that compromising the controller gives an attacker broad, potentially network-wide control over traffic flows, making it a critical single point of failure. The control plane is not eliminated (it is centralized, not removed), SDN can support encrypted channels between controller and switches, and ACLs/firewalling can still be implemented as controller-managed flow rules.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security standard replaced WEP to address its cryptographic weaknesses by introducing stronger encryption and key management?","o":["WPA2","Bluetooth","SSID broadcasting","MAC filtering"],"c":0,"why":"WPA2 introduced AES-based encryption (CCMP) and improved key management to remedy WEP's weak RC4 implementation. Bluetooth is a separate wireless technology, and SSID broadcasting/MAC filtering are weak, easily bypassed controls, not encryption standards.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization needs to protect two branch office gateways communicating over the public Internet, ensuring that the entire original IP packet (including the original header) is both encrypted and authenticated as it traverses untrusted networks. Which IPsec configuration satisfies this requirement?","o":["ESP in transport mode","AH in transport mode","ESP in tunnel mode","AH in tunnel mode"],"c":2,"why":"ESP in tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original IP packet inside a new IP header and encrypts and authenticates it, protecting confidentiality and integrity end-to-end between gateways. AH provides authentication only (no confidentiality), and transport mode leaves the original IP header exposed rather than encapsulating the whole packet.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A web application load balancer terminates TLS connections from clients and forwards traffic to backend application servers as cleartext HTTP over an internal network segment. From a security architecture perspective, what is the primary risk introduced by this design?","o":["Backend servers lose the ability to perform certificate-based authentication of connecting clients","Traffic between the load balancer and backend servers is exposed to interception if the internal segment is compromised, breaking end-to-end confidentiality","The load balancer loses the ability to perform Layer 7 content inspection because TLS has been terminated","Backend servers will be unable to accurately log the originating client IP address"],"c":1,"why":"TLS termination at the load balancer creates a plaintext segment internally; if an attacker gains a foothold on that segment (e.g., through lateral movement), sensitive traffic can be sniffed, defeating end-to-end confidentiality. Terminating TLS actually enables, rather than prevents, Layer 7 inspection, client IP logging is commonly preserved via headers like X-Forwarded-For, and loss of client certificate authentication is a secondary concern rather than the primary risk described.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security benefit of segmenting a network into VLANs?","o":["It eliminates the need for firewalls entirely","It increases physical cable length limits","It reduces broadcast traffic and isolates groups of hosts logically","It guarantees end-to-end encryption of all traffic"],"c":2,"why":"VLANs logically segment a network, reducing broadcast domains and limiting the scope of a compromise by isolating groups of hosts. VLANs do not encrypt traffic, extend cable limits, or remove the need for firewalls.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester successfully executes a VLAN hopping attack by sending double-encapsulated 802.1Q frames from a host on an access port, allowing traffic to reach a VLAN the host should not have access to. Which misconfiguration most directly enabled this attack?","o":["The trunk port's native VLAN matched the attacker's access VLAN","Port security was disabled on the access switchport","Spanning Tree Protocol was not enabled on the trunk links","The switch was operating in VTP transparent mode"],"c":0,"why":"Double-tagging VLAN hopping exploits switches that strip only the outer tag matching the trunk's native VLAN, forwarding the inner tag untagged into another VLAN; this only works when the native VLAN equals the attacker's VLAN. Port security, STP status, and VTP mode do not directly enable this specific attack vector.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization requires that only corporate-managed devices possessing valid digital certificates be permitted to connect to the wired network, with cryptographic mutual authentication between the endpoint and the authentication server. Which solution best satisfies this requirement?","o":["802.1X port-based access control using EAP-MD5","MAC address filtering configured on all access switch ports","802.1X port-based access control using EAP-TLS with client and server certificates","A captive portal requiring username and password entry before granting network access"],"c":2,"why":"EAP-TLS within an 802.1X framework performs mutual certificate-based authentication, cryptographically verifying both the device and the authentication server, satisfying the stated requirement. EAP-MD5 only authenticates the client one-way and is vulnerable to offline attacks, MAC filtering is trivially spoofable and provides no cryptographic assurance, and a captive portal authenticates a user's credentials rather than validating the device's certificate or providing mutual authentication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which network device forwards traffic based on MAC addresses and creates separate collision domains for each connected port?","o":["Hub","Switch","Repeater","Modem"],"c":1,"why":"A switch examines MAC addresses to forward frames intelligently and provides a separate collision domain per port, improving efficiency and security compared to a hub, which broadcasts to all ports. Repeaters and modems do not perform MAC-based forwarding.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization is troubleshooting a network issue and determines that a device is responsible for making forwarding decisions based on logical IP addressing and calculating the best path between different networks. At which layer of the OSI model does this device primarily operate?","o":["Data Link layer","Network layer","Transport layer","Session layer"],"c":1,"why":"The Network layer (Layer 3) handles logical addressing (IP) and routing decisions between networks. The Data Link layer deals with MAC addressing and framing within a single network segment, the Transport layer manages end-to-end connections and reliability, and the Session layer manages dialogue control between applications.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"Which characteristic of WPA3's Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) handshake provides a meaningful security improvement over WPA2-PSK's four-way handshake?","o":["SAE eliminates the need for a pre-shared key entirely","SAE uses a password-authenticated key exchange resistant to offline dictionary attacks even if the handshake is captured","SAE encrypts all wireless management frames by default regardless of configuration","SAE requires certificate-based mutual authentication between the AP and client"],"c":1,"why":"SAE is a zero-knowledge proof based key exchange (derived from Dragonfly) that prevents an attacker who captures the handshake from performing offline dictionary/brute-force attacks against the passphrase, unlike WPA2's 4-way handshake. WPA3-Personal still uses a pre-shared passphrase, does not mandate certificates, and management frame protection is a related but separate feature (PMF) not guaranteed simply by SAE use.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following protocols should be used instead of Telnet to securely manage a network device remotely?","o":["SSH","SNMP v1","TFTP","HTTP"],"c":0,"why":"SSH encrypts remote administrative sessions, protecting credentials and commands, whereas Telnet transmits data in cleartext. SNMPv1, TFTP, and HTTP also lack strong encryption/authentication for secure remote management purposes.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect wants DNS resolvers to be able to cryptographically verify that DNS response data originated from the legitimate authoritative source and was not modified in transit, protecting against cache poisoning and spoofed responses. Which technology directly provides this?","o":["DNS over HTTPS (DoH)","Split-horizon DNS","DNSSEC","Round-robin DNS load balancing"],"c":2,"why":"DNSSEC uses a chain of digital signatures to allow validation of the origin authenticity and integrity of DNS record data. DoH encrypts the transport channel for privacy but does not validate that the returned records are authentic; split-horizon and round-robin DNS address visibility and load distribution, not data integrity.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"During a TCP connection establishment, a client sends a segment with the SYN flag set to a server. What flag combination should the server send in response to properly continue the three-way handshake?","o":["SYN only","ACK only","SYN and ACK","FIN and ACK"],"c":2,"why":"In the second step of the TCP three-way handshake, the server responds with both SYN and ACK flags set to acknowledge the client's SYN and propose its own sequence number. SYN alone or ACK alone would be incomplete, and FIN/ACK is used to terminate connections, not establish them.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"In a Software-Defined Networking (SDN) architecture, which security consideration is most unique compared to traditional distributed routing and switching architectures?","o":["Encryption of data stored on network device flash memory","Compromise of the centralized SDN controller could allow an attacker to manipulate forwarding behavior across the entire network","Physical tampering with fiber cabling between switches","Susceptibility of endpoints to ARP spoofing at the data link layer"],"c":1,"why":"SDN centralizes the control plane in a controller that programs forwarding behavior for all switches; compromising it gives an attacker network-wide control, a risk not present in traditional distributed control planes. The other options are generic network risks not unique to SDN's architecture.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A stateful inspection firewall is deployed at the network perimeter. Which of the following best describes the primary mechanism this firewall uses to make filtering decisions?","o":["It inspects the full application-layer payload of every packet against signature databases","It maintains a state table that tracks active connections and evaluates packets against the context of established sessions","It filters solely based on source and destination MAC addresses","It requires all traffic to terminate at a proxy process before forwarding to the destination"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls track connection state (such as sequence numbers and session context) in a state table, allowing them to permit legitimate return traffic and block unsolicited packets. Deep payload signature matching describes an IDS/IPS or next-gen firewall feature, MAC-based filtering describes Layer 2 switching, and full proxy termination describes an application-layer proxy firewall.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company's VoIP deployment uses SIP for call signaling and RTP for media, both sent in the clear. To provide confidentiality for both call setup information and the actual voice media, which combination of protocols should be implemented?","o":["SIP over TLS (SIPS) and SRTP","H.323 and RTP transported over IPsec AH","SIP over UDP with RTCP monitoring","MGCP with SRTCP only"],"c":0,"why":"SIPS (SIP over TLS) encrypts signaling exchanges, while SRTP encrypts and authenticates the media stream, together securing both control and voice traffic. AH does not provide confidentiality, RTCP is only a control/statistics protocol for RTP sessions (not encryption), and SRTCP alone secures only control messages, not the actual media.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A stateful firewall differs from a simple packet-filtering firewall primarily because it:","o":["Only examines the destination port number","Tracks the state of active connections to make forwarding decisions","Encrypts all traffic passing through it","Operates exclusively at the Application Layer"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful firewalls maintain a state table of active connections, allowing them to make context-aware decisions, unlike stateless packet filters that evaluate each packet in isolation. Encryption and application-layer inspection are not defining characteristics of stateful filtering.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization is implementing an IPSec VPN and requires that transmitted data be both encrypted and authenticated for integrity. Which IPSec protocol should be used to meet this requirement?","o":["Authentication Header (AH)","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP)","Internet Key Exchange (IKE)","Internet Security Association and Key Management Protocol (ISAKMP)"],"c":1,"why":"ESP provides both confidentiality (encryption) and optional integrity/authentication for IPSec traffic, whereas AH provides only authentication and integrity without encryption. IKE and ISAKMP are used for negotiating and managing security associations and keys, not for protecting the actual data payload.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security benefit of replacing a network hub with a switch?","o":["It encrypts all traffic on the network segment","It eliminates the need for IP addressing","It reduces the collision domain and limits traffic visible to each port","It automatically blocks malicious traffic"],"c":2,"why":"Switches create separate collision domains per port and forward frames only to the intended MAC address, reducing the ability of a device to passively capture all network traffic like a hub would. Switches do not encrypt traffic or block malicious content by default.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization segments its data center using VLANs and a perimeter firewall, but discovers that once an attacker compromises one host, they can move laterally to any other host within the same VLAN without restriction. Which architectural change would BEST address this specific weakness?","o":["Create additional VLANs based on department function","Deploy microsegmentation with host- or hypervisor-level firewall policies enforcing least privilege between individual workloads","Expand the VLAN ID range to reduce the size of each broadcast domain","Add a second stateful firewall at the network perimeter"],"c":1,"why":"Microsegmentation enforces granular, workload-level access control regardless of VLAN membership, directly limiting east-west lateral movement. Additional VLANs or a larger ID range still permit unrestricted traffic within each segment, and a second perimeter firewall does nothing to control traffic already inside the data center.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is selecting a wireless security protocol and wants to protect against offline dictionary attacks on the pre-shared key exchange, an issue present in WPA2-Personal. Which feature introduced in WPA3 addresses this concern?","o":["Temporal Key Integrity Protocol (TKIP)","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) key rotation","Pre-Shared Key (PSK) with a longer passphrase"],"c":1,"why":"WPA3 replaces the WPA2 four-way handshake with SAE, a Diffie-Hellman-based exchange that resists offline dictionary attacks by requiring interaction with the network for each guess. TKIP and WEP are outdated and vulnerable protocols, and simply lengthening a PSK does not eliminate the underlying handshake weakness present in WPA2.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol provides the strongest protection against unauthorized access due to its use of AES-based encryption and improved key management?","o":["WEP","WPA","WPA2","Open (no security)"],"c":2,"why":"WPA2 uses AES with CCMP for strong encryption and improved key management, making it significantly more secure than WEP (which uses weak RC4) or WPA (which uses the weaker TKIP). Open networks provide no encryption at all.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An ISP wants to mitigate the risk of BGP route hijacking, in which a malicious autonomous system illegitimately announces IP prefixes belonging to another organization. Which control provides cryptographic validation of the legitimate origin AS for a given prefix?","o":["Route Origin Authorization (ROA) validated through Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI)","BGP route dampening","Equal-cost multi-path (ECMP) routing","OSPF area authentication"],"c":0,"why":"RPKI-based ROAs cryptographically bind IP prefixes to the authorized originating AS number, allowing routers to reject invalid route announcements. Route dampening only suppresses flapping routes, ECMP is a load-balancing technique, and OSPF authentication secures an interior routing protocol, not interdomain BGP announcements.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary function of DNS in a network environment?","o":["Assigning dynamic IP addresses to hosts","Translating human-readable domain names into IP addresses","Encrypting traffic between web servers and clients","Filtering malicious packets based on signatures"],"c":1,"why":"DNS resolves domain names to IP addresses, enabling users to access resources without memorizing numeric addresses. DHCP assigns IP addresses, TLS handles encryption, and IDS/IPS systems filter malicious traffic.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the purpose of Network Address Translation (NAT)?","o":["To encrypt traffic leaving a private network","To translate private internal IP addresses to a public IP address for external communication","To assign MAC addresses to network interfaces","To authenticate users before granting network access"],"c":1,"why":"NAT allows devices with private IP addresses to communicate with external networks by translating those addresses to one or more public IPs, conserving address space and adding a layer of obscurity. It does not perform encryption, MAC assignment, or authentication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements DNSSEC on its authoritative name servers. What security benefit does this primarily provide?","o":["Confidentiality of DNS query contents through encryption","Origin authentication and integrity verification of DNS responses through digital signatures","Protection against volumetric DDoS attacks targeting the DNS infrastructure","Faster DNS resolution through response caching"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to allow resolvers to verify that DNS responses are authentic and have not been tampered with in transit, mitigating attacks like cache poisoning. It does not encrypt query contents (that is the role of protocols like DoH/DoT), nor does it inherently improve performance or provide DDoS mitigation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"In an 802.1X port-based network access control deployment, a laptop attempting to connect to a switch port must be authenticated before being granted network access. Which role does the RADIUS server play in this architecture?","o":["It acts as the supplicant requesting network access","It acts as the authenticator, physically controlling the switch port state","It acts as the authentication server, validating credentials and informing the authenticator of the access decision","It encrypts all traffic between the laptop and the switch"],"c":2,"why":"In 802.1X, the RADIUS server serves as the backend authentication server that validates the supplicant's credentials and tells the authenticator (the switch) whether to open the port. The supplicant is the endpoint device seeking access, the authenticator is the switch itself, and RADIUS does not encrypt the data-plane traffic between devices.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network engineer needs to explain why a Layer 2 switch can forward frames based on hardware addresses without inspecting IP information. Which OSI layer is primarily responsible for this frame forwarding function?","o":["Physical layer","Data Link layer","Network layer","Transport layer"],"c":1,"why":"The Data Link layer (Layer 2) handles MAC addressing and frame forwarding within a local segment. The Physical layer only deals with bits/signals, the Network layer handles IP routing, and the Transport layer manages end-to-end connections, none of which perform MAC-based frame switching.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization is establishing a site-to-site VPN between two corporate gateways to protect all traffic traversing the public Internet, including the original IP headers. Which IPsec mode should be implemented?","o":["Transport mode","Tunnel mode","Authentication Header mode only","Quick mode"],"c":1,"why":"Tunnel mode encapsulates and encrypts the entire original IP packet, including the header, making it suitable for gateway-to-gateway VPNs. Transport mode only encrypts the payload and leaves the original IP header exposed, which is appropriate for host-to-host communication, not full packet protection between gateways.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect must design an IPsec VPN between two branch office gateways that will traverse the public Internet. The design requirement states that the entire original IP packet, including headers, must be encrypted and integrity-protected as it crosses the untrusted network. Which IPsec configuration satisfies this requirement?","o":["ESP in tunnel mode","AH in transport mode","ESP in transport mode","AH in tunnel mode"],"c":0,"why":"ESP tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original IP packet inside a new IP header and provides both encryption and integrity end-to-end between the gateways. AH modes provide integrity only with no encryption, and ESP transport mode leaves the original IP header exposed rather than encapsulating the whole packet.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which OSI model layer is primarily responsible for logical addressing and routing of packets between different networks?","o":["Data Link Layer","Network Layer","Transport Layer","Session Layer"],"c":1,"why":"The Network layer (Layer 3) handles logical addressing (IP addresses) and routing decisions between networks. The Data Link layer handles physical addressing within a single network segment, while Transport and Session layers deal with end-to-end communication and session management, not routing.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A firewall administrator wants a device that tracks the state of active connections so that return traffic from an established outbound session is automatically permitted without requiring a separate inbound rule. Which firewall technology best meets this requirement?","o":["Static packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy only","Application-layer allow-listing"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls maintain a state table of active connections, allowing them to automatically permit legitimate return traffic. Static packet filters evaluate each packet independently without connection awareness, requiring explicit rules for return traffic in both directions.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which technology is most commonly used to create a secure, encrypted tunnel for remote employees to access an internal corporate network over the Internet?","o":["Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)","Virtual Private Network (VPN)","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP)","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)"],"c":1,"why":"A VPN creates an encrypted tunnel allowing remote users to securely access internal network resources over an untrusted network like the Internet. SNMP is for network management, DHCP assigns IP addresses, and ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses—none provide secure remote access tunneling.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is upgrading a wireless network to address the offline dictionary attack weaknesses found in WPA2-Personal's four-way handshake. Which WPA3 feature specifically mitigates this vulnerability?","o":["AES-CCMP encryption","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","Pre-shared key rotation every 24 hours","Enabling WPS push-button configuration"],"c":1,"why":"SAE (based on the Dragonfly handshake) replaces the WPA2 PSK exchange and resists offline dictionary attacks by requiring interaction with the network for each guess attempt. AES-CCMP is an encryption cipher unrelated to handshake security, PSK rotation doesn't fix the underlying handshake flaw, and WPS is a known security weakness, not a mitigation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"During a penetration test, an assessor connects a laptop to an access port and crafts frames with two stacked 802.1Q VLAN tags to push traffic into a VLAN the port is not assigned to. Which attack is being demonstrated, and what is the most effective mitigation?","o":["Double tagging attack; mitigated by never using the native VLAN on access ports and explicitly tagging or disabling it on trunk links","ARP spoofing attack; mitigated by enabling dynamic ARP inspection","Switch spoofing attack; mitigated by disabling CDP on all ports","MAC flooding attack; mitigated by implementing port security with sticky MAC addresses"],"c":0,"why":"Double tagging exploits the native VLAN on trunk links: the switch strips the outer tag and forwards the frame using the inner tag into another VLAN. Disabling or explicitly tagging the native VLAN closes this gap. The other options describe unrelated attacks and mitigations.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol provides significantly stronger protection than its predecessor by using AES encryption and eliminating known cryptographic weaknesses?","o":["WEP","WPA2","Bluetooth","SSID broadcasting"],"c":1,"why":"WPA2 uses AES-based CCMP encryption and addresses the significant vulnerabilities found in WEP, which relies on the weak RC4 cipher and static keys. Bluetooth is a separate wireless technology, not a security protocol, and SSID broadcasting is merely a network name advertisement with no encryption function.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An ISP wants to prevent unauthorized autonomous systems from announcing routes for IP prefixes they do not own, a problem that has caused major route hijacking incidents. Which technology provides cryptographic proof that an AS is authorized to originate a specific prefix?","o":["Route Origin Authorization validated through the Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI)","BGP MD5 session authentication (RFC 2385)","Generalized TTL Security Mechanism (GTSM)","IPsec tunneling between BGP peers"],"c":0,"why":"RPKI-based Route Origin Authorizations (ROAs) cryptographically bind a prefix to its authorized originating AS, enabling route origin validation and preventing hijacking. MD5 authentication and GTSM protect the BGP session itself, and IPsec secures peer traffic, but none validate origin authorization.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network administrator segments a flat switched network into multiple logical broadcast domains to isolate departments such as Finance and HR without physically re-cabling the office. Which technology accomplishes this?","o":["Network Address Translation (NAT)","Virtual Local Area Network (VLAN)","Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs logically segment a switched network into separate broadcast domains, improving security and traffic management without physical rewiring. NAT translates addresses for routing, STP prevents Layer 2 loops, and ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses—none of these create logical segmentation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security benefit of implementing Virtual LANs (VLANs) on a switched network?","o":["They eliminate the need for firewalls entirely","They automatically encrypt all network traffic","They logically segment network traffic to limit broadcast domains and contain potential security incidents","They increase the physical distance limitations of Ethernet cabling"],"c":2,"why":"VLANs logically separate hosts into distinct broadcast domains, limiting the scope of broadcast traffic and helping contain security incidents to a smaller segment. VLANs do not provide encryption, replace firewalls, or affect physical cabling distance limitations.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security team is upgrading wireless infrastructure and wants to eliminate the risk of offline dictionary attacks against captured handshake traffic, a known weakness of WPA2-Personal. Which feature of WPA3 directly addresses this?","o":["Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE), replacing the PSK four-way handshake","Increased AES key length to 512 bits","Mandatory use of 802.1X/EAP-TLS for all clients","Opportunistic Wireless Encryption for open networks"],"c":0,"why":"SAE is a Diffie-Hellman-based exchange that resists offline dictionary/brute-force attacks and provides forward secrecy, unlike WPA2's PSK handshake. AES key length in WPA3 remains 128/256-bit, 802.1X/EAP-TLS applies to Enterprise mode not Personal, and OWE applies only to open networks.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company implements DNSSEC across its authoritative name servers. Which security benefit does this primarily provide?","o":["Confidentiality of DNS query contents through encryption","Integrity and origin authentication of DNS responses via digital signatures","Protection against denial-of-service attacks on DNS servers","Automatic encryption of all HTTP traffic resolved through DNS"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to provide data integrity and origin authentication, ensuring responses haven't been tampered with (mitigating cache poisoning/spoofing). It does not encrypt query contents, so it provides no confidentiality, nor does it inherently defend against DoS or encrypt unrelated HTTP traffic.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which network service translates human-readable domain names, such as example.com, into IP addresses that computers use to locate resources?","o":["DHCP","DNS","NAT","ARP"],"c":1,"why":"DNS (Domain Name System) resolves domain names into IP addresses. DHCP assigns IP addresses to devices, NAT translates between private and public IP addresses, and ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses—none perform domain name resolution.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A mobile banking application must resist man-in-the-middle attacks even if an attacker compromises a publicly trusted Certificate Authority and issues a fraudulent certificate for the bank's domain. Which control specifically mitigates this threat?","o":["Certificate or public-key pinning within the application","Enforcing TLS 1.3 instead of TLS 1.2","Using Extended Validation (EV) certificates","Enabling OCSP stapling on the web server"],"c":0,"why":"Pinning hardcodes the expected certificate or public key in the app, so it rejects any certificate not matching the pin even if it chains to a trusted but compromised CA. TLS version, EV certificates, and OCSP stapling all still rely on the CA trust model and would not stop a fraudulently issued certificate from a trusted CA.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization adopts Software-Defined Networking (SDN) to centrally manage traffic flow policies across its data center switches. Which architectural change most fundamentally enables this centralized management?","o":["Replacing all switches with Layer 3 routers","Separating the control plane from the data plane","Encrypting all inter-switch traffic with IPsec","Consolidating all VLANs into a single broadcast domain"],"c":1,"why":"SDN's defining characteristic is decoupling the control plane (decision-making, managed by a centralized controller) from the data plane (packet forwarding on switches), enabling centralized policy management. The other options describe unrelated changes that don't address centralized control logic.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network engineer needs a device that forwards frames based on physical hardware addresses learned from incoming traffic, and which creates separate collision domains for each connected port. At which layer of the OSI model does this device primarily operate?","o":["Layer 1 - Physical","Layer 2 - Data Link","Layer 3 - Network","Layer 4 - Transport"],"c":1,"why":"Switches operate at Layer 2, forwarding frames using MAC addresses and creating separate collision domains per port. Layer 1 hubs do not use addressing, Layer 3 devices route based on IP addresses, and Layer 4 deals with end-to-end transport (ports, segments).","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization uses private IP address ranges internally but needs those hosts to communicate with external Internet resources using a single public IP address. Which technology accomplishes this?","o":["Network Address Translation (NAT)","Virtual Private Network (VPN)","Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)","Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP)"],"c":0,"why":"NAT translates private internal IP addresses to a public IP address (or a small pool) for Internet communication, conserving public address space and adding a layer of obscurity. VPN provides secure tunnels rather than address translation, STP prevents switching loops, and SMTP is an email protocol—none perform address translation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization is redesigning its perimeter to host a public web application. Requirements state that if the web server is compromised, the attacker must not have a direct network path to internal databases, and Internet-facing traffic must pass through independent filtering before and after the exposed server. Which architecture best meets this requirement?","o":["A screened subnet (DMZ) using two separate firewalls, one between the Internet and the DMZ and another between the DMZ and the internal network","A single firewall with multiple interfaces, one for the Internet, one for the DMZ, and one for the internal LAN","A bastion host placed directly on the internal network with a host-based firewall","Network address translation performed at the internal network's core switch"],"c":0,"why":"A screened subnet with two independent firewalls ensures a compromised DMZ server has no direct path inward, since traffic must pass a second, separately managed filtering point. A single multi-interface firewall is one point of compromise, a bastion host on the internal network directly exposes internal resources, and NAT alone provides no access control filtering.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"During a security assessment, an analyst observes repeated TCP SYN packets sent to a target host from a single source, with no corresponding ACK ever completing the handshake. This behavior is most consistent with which activity?","o":["A legitimate application performing keep-alive checks","A SYN flood denial-of-service attack or stealth port scan","Normal ARP cache refresh traffic","A DNS zone transfer request"],"c":1,"why":"Repeated SYNs without completing the three-way handshake is a classic sign of SYN flooding or half-open (stealth) scanning used to exhaust resources or enumerate open ports. Keep-alives, ARP refresh, and zone transfers do not exhibit this incomplete-handshake pattern.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect must design an IPsec solution to protect traffic between two hosts that communicate through a NAT gateway on the path. The solution must provide confidentiality and integrity for the payload while remaining compatible with the NAT device. Which configuration best meets these requirements?","o":["AH in tunnel mode with the NAT device configured to preserve the original IP header","ESP in transport mode with NAT Traversal (NAT-T) UDP encapsulation enabled","AH in transport mode with IP header checksums disabled on the NAT device","ESP in tunnel mode without NAT-T, relying on the NAT device to rewrite the ESP header"],"c":1,"why":"ESP in transport mode encrypts and authenticates the payload without protecting the outer IP header, and NAT-T (UDP port 4500 encapsulation) solves the problem of NAT devices altering IP addresses, which would otherwise break ESP's checksum/authentication. AH fails with NAT because it authenticates the IP header itself, which NAT modifies, breaking integrity checks; ESP tunnel mode without NAT-T still suffers from NAT incompatibility since ESP has no port information for NAT to use.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company's VoIP deployment uses SIP for call signaling and RTP for media. A security review finds that call setup traffic is unencrypted, media streams can be captured and replayed on the internal network, and the company has experienced toll fraud from spoofed INVITE requests. Which combination of controls most directly addresses these issues?","o":["SIP over TLS (SIPS) for signaling and SRTP for media, combined with authentication of SIP endpoints","Segmenting VoIP traffic onto a separate VLAN and relying on switch port security","Implementing Quality of Service (QoS) tagging to prioritize voice traffic","Deploying a session border controller solely for NAT traversal"],"c":0,"why":"SIPS encrypts signaling to prevent eavesdropping/spoofing of INVITE requests, SRTP encrypts and authenticates media to prevent capture/replay, and endpoint authentication directly stops toll fraud from spoofed requests. VLAN segmentation and QoS improve isolation/performance but do not encrypt or authenticate traffic, and an SBC used only for NAT traversal does not address encryption or authentication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A small business has only one public IP address but needs to allow 50 internal workstations to simultaneously access the Internet. Which technology allows this by tracking unique source port numbers for each internal host's outbound connections?","o":["Static NAT","Port Address Translation (PAT)","Split-horizon DNS","Reverse proxy caching"],"c":1,"why":"PAT (a form of dynamic NAT, often called NAT overload) maps multiple internal private addresses to a single public IP by distinguishing sessions using unique source port numbers. Static NAT provides a fixed one-to-one mapping unsuitable for many-to-one translation, and split-horizon DNS and reverse proxy caching address entirely different functions.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A firewall administrator must select a firewall type that can track the state of active connections and make filtering decisions based on the context of a session (e.g., recognizing that an incoming packet is a legitimate reply to an internal request), rather than examining each packet in isolation. Which firewall type BEST meets this requirement?","o":["Static packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy firewall operating only on session setup","Application-layer firewall with no session tracking"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls maintain a state table of active connections, allowing them to evaluate packets in the context of an established session. Static packet filters evaluate each packet independently without session awareness, and the other options misrepresent how proxy/application firewalls typically maintain state.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization's web servers are experiencing a high volume of TCP connection requests that never complete the handshake, exhausting the connection table. Which mitigation technique allows the server to avoid maintaining state for incomplete connections while still validating legitimate clients?","o":["Implementing SYN cookies, which encode session information into the SYN-ACK sequence number instead of storing it in a queue","Reducing the TCP retransmission timeout to close half-open connections faster","Enabling TCP window scaling to increase the connection table's effective capacity","Configuring the server to silently drop all SYN packets from unknown source addresses"],"c":0,"why":"SYN cookies cryptographically embed connection state in the SYN-ACK sequence number, eliminating the need to store half-open connections in memory, so a flood of unanswered SYNs cannot exhaust resources. Reducing timeouts only limits exposure time, window scaling addresses throughput not connection exhaustion, and dropping all unknown-source SYNs would block legitimate new clients.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"In a software-defined networking deployment, the SDN controller communicates with switches via a southbound API (e.g., OpenFlow) to program forwarding rules. Which statement best describes the primary security concern unique to this architecture compared to traditional distributed routing/switching?","o":["The centralized controller becomes a high-value single point of failure and attack, since compromising it can allow reprogramming of forwarding behavior across the entire network","SDN switches are inherently unable to support VLAN tagging, increasing broadcast domain risk","Southbound APIs cannot be encrypted, so all controller-to-switch traffic is necessarily in cleartext","SDN eliminates the need for access control lists, so switches have no packet filtering capability"],"c":0,"why":"Centralizing control logic in the SDN controller creates a single point of compromise; an attacker who gains control of it can manipulate flow tables network-wide, a risk not present in traditional distributed control planes. SDN switches do support VLANs, southbound channels can be secured with TLS, and switches still support ACL-based filtering.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization is designing a site-to-site VPN and wants to ensure that both the payload and the original IP header of each packet are encrypted, providing confidentiality for the entire original packet as it traverses the internet. Which IPSec configuration should be implemented?","o":["AH in transport mode","ESP in transport mode","ESP in tunnel mode","AH in tunnel mode"],"c":2,"why":"ESP in tunnel mode encrypts the entire original IP packet (header and payload) and encapsulates it in a new IP header, ideal for site-to-site VPNs. AH provides authentication/integrity but no encryption, and transport mode only protects the payload, leaving the original header exposed.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester is able to send traffic from a host on VLAN 10 to a target on VLAN 20 without the traffic passing through a Layer 3 device, by crafting frames with two stacked 802.1Q tags. Which switch misconfiguration most directly enables this attack?","o":["The trunk port's native VLAN matches the attacker's access VLAN and is left untagged","Spanning Tree Protocol is disabled on all access ports","Port security is not configured to limit the number of MAC addresses per port","The switch is running an outdated firmware version vulnerable to buffer overflow"],"c":0,"why":"VLAN double-tagging (VLAN hopping) works when the native VLAN on a trunk equals the attacker's VLAN, because the switch strips the outer (native) tag without inspecting it, exposing the inner tag to be forwarded to the target VLAN by the next switch. STP status, port security limits, and firmware bugs are unrelated to this specific tagging-based attack vector.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company is upgrading its wireless infrastructure and wants to eliminate the vulnerability associated with pre-shared key offline dictionary attacks common in WPA2-Personal, while also providing forward secrecy for each session. Which technology should be adopted?","o":["WEP with a longer key length","WPA2 with TKIP encryption","WPA3 with Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","WPA2-Enterprise using only PSK authentication"],"c":2,"why":"WPA3 replaces the WPA2 four-way handshake with SAE, which resists offline dictionary attacks and provides forward secrecy per session. WEP and TKIP are outdated and weak, and WPA2-Enterprise with PSK still relies on the vulnerable PSK exchange method.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security assessor compares WPA2-Personal and WPA3-Personal on a corporate guest network. Which characteristic of WPA3 most significantly reduces the risk of an attacker recovering the network passphrase through offline attacks after capturing a handshake?","o":["WPA3 uses a longer default key length for the AES cipher than WPA2","WPA3 replaces the four-way handshake with Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE), which resists offline dictionary attacks","WPA3 disables the use of pre-shared keys entirely in favor of certificate-based authentication","WPA3 encrypts management frames, preventing capture of the handshake"],"c":1,"why":"SAE (a password-authenticated key exchange based on the Dyffie-Hellman variant) prevents an attacker from performing offline dictionary/brute-force attacks against a captured handshake because each guess requires interaction with the live AP, unlike WPA2's PSK-based four-way handshake. WPA3 still uses AES-128/256 similarly to WPA2 in Personal mode, still supports PSK-style authentication (not certificates), and Protected Management Frames reduce deauth attacks but don't by themselves prevent offline cracking of a captured handshake.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security architect wants to logically separate traffic for the finance department from the rest of the corporate network without deploying additional physical switches, while still allowing centralized routing control over inter-departmental traffic. Which technology BEST achieves this?","o":["Network Address Translation (NAT)","Virtual LAN (VLAN) segmentation","Port address translation on the perimeter firewall","Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs logically segment a physical network into separate broadcast domains, allowing isolation of departmental traffic while a router or Layer 3 switch controls inter-VLAN routing. NAT/PAT address IP translation issues rather than segmentation, and STP prevents loops, not traffic isolation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An ISP notices that traffic destined for one of its customer's IP prefixes is being routed through an unauthorized autonomous system, causing a significant portion of global traffic for that prefix to be misdirected. Which technology, if properly deployed by ISPs, would have prevented this route hijacking by validating the legitimacy of the originating AS?","o":["Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) route reflectors","Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI) with Route Origin Authorization (ROA)","Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) with MD5 authentication","Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) traffic engineering"],"c":1,"why":"RPKI allows prefix owners to cryptographically sign ROAs stating which AS is authorized to originate a given prefix, enabling other ISPs to validate BGP announcements and reject hijacked routes. Route reflectors are an internal BGP scalability mechanism, OSPF authentication secures an interior routing protocol unrelated to interdomain routing, and MPLS traffic engineering manages path selection but does not authenticate route origin.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that only devices that pass a security posture check (e.g., updated antivirus, patched OS) are granted network access, and that non-compliant devices are automatically placed into a quarantine VLAN with restricted access. Which technology is BEST suited to enforce this requirement?","o":["802.1X Network Access Control (NAC) with posture assessment","Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) polling","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) reservations","Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) route filtering"],"c":0,"why":"802.1X-based NAC solutions authenticate devices and can assess their security posture before granting full network access, redirecting non-compliant devices to restricted VLANs. SNMP is for monitoring, DHCP reservations only manage IP assignment, and BGP filtering operates at the routing layer between autonomous systems, not endpoint compliance.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"During an incident investigation, analysts determine that an attacker was able to redirect users of a legitimate banking site to a malicious server by injecting a forged resource record into a resolver's cache before the legitimate authoritative response arrived. Which control, if deployed on both the domain's authoritative servers and the resolver, would have prevented this specific attack?","o":["Implementing DNSSEC to provide cryptographic signing and validation of DNS responses","Configuring split-horizon DNS to separate internal and external name resolution","Enabling DNS over HTTPS (DoH) on client browsers only","Increasing the DNS resolver's cache TTL values to reduce lookup frequency"],"c":0,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures on DNS records so resolvers can cryptographically verify that a response genuinely originated from the authoritative source and was not altered or forged, directly preventing cache poisoning. Split-horizon DNS addresses visibility segmentation, DoH on the client alone only protects the client-to-resolver hop (not resolver-to-authoritative), and increasing TTL would actually prolong the impact of a successful poisoning attack rather than prevent it.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is redesigning perimeter defenses and must choose between a dual-homed host firewall architecture and a screened subnet (DMZ with two firewalls) architecture for hosting public-facing services. Which factor makes the screened subnet architecture preferable from a defense-in-depth perspective?","o":["It eliminates the need for an intrusion detection system on the DMZ segment","It requires an attacker to compromise two independently configured filtering devices to reach the internal network","It reduces the total number of firewall rules needed across the environment","It allows public services to bypass firewall inspection entirely for performance reasons"],"c":1,"why":"A screened subnet places public servers between two firewalls (often from different vendors or with different rule sets), so compromising the DMZ does not automatically grant access to the internal network—an attacker must defeat a second, independent control layer. A dual-homed host is a single point of failure if compromised; the other options describe outcomes that are false or counterproductive to security architecture.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A penetration tester discovers that an internal DNS server accepts recursive queries from any external host and returns authoritative records without validating response integrity. Which security control would MOST directly reduce the risk of cache poisoning attacks against this server?","o":["Disabling recursion for external queries and implementing DNSSEC","Increasing the DNS server's TTL values for all records","Switching from UDP to TCP for all DNS queries","Enabling zone transfers to all secondary servers"],"c":0,"why":"Restricting recursive queries to trusted internal hosts and deploying DNSSEC to cryptographically validate responses directly mitigates cache poisoning risk. Adjusting TTLs, changing transport protocol alone, or allowing broader zone transfers do not address the core integrity/validation problem.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A VoIP deployment carries call signaling over SIP and media over RTP. A security review finds that while SIP traffic is encrypted, RTP streams remain in plaintext, allowing an attacker with network access to reconstruct conversations. Which protocol should be implemented specifically to remediate the media stream exposure?","o":["Transport Layer Security (TLS) applied to the RTP stream directly","Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP), which encrypts and authenticates media packets","Internet Key Exchange version 2 (IKEv2) tunneling for all VoIP traffic","Session Border Controller (SBC) deployment without additional media encryption"],"c":1,"why":"SRTP is purpose-built to encrypt and authenticate RTP media payloads while preserving the header fields needed for real-time delivery, directly addressing plaintext media exposure. TLS is designed for reliable, connection-oriented streams (used for SIP signaling, not RTP's UDP-based media), IKEv2 establishes IPsec tunnels but adds overhead and is not the standard fix for media-layer confidentiality in VoIP, and an SBC alone manages signaling/NAT traversal but does not inherently encrypt media without SRTP support.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which layer of the OSI model is primarily responsible for logical addressing and routing packets between different networks?","o":["Data Link Layer (Layer 2)","Network Layer (Layer 3)","Transport Layer (Layer 4)","Application Layer (Layer 7)"],"c":1,"why":"The Network layer handles logical (IP) addressing and routing decisions between networks. The Data Link layer deals with physical/MAC addressing on a local segment, the Transport layer manages end-to-end delivery and reliability, and the Application layer provides services to end-user processes.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the correct sequence of packets exchanged during a standard TCP connection establishment (three-way handshake)?","o":["SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK","SYN, ACK, FIN","ACK, SYN, FIN","SYN, RST, ACK"],"c":0,"why":"TCP establishes a connection by having the client send a SYN, the server respond with SYN-ACK, and the client confirm with an ACK. FIN is used for graceful termination and RST for abrupt connection resets, not for establishment.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A stateful inspection firewall makes filtering decisions primarily based on which of the following?","o":["The state and context of active network connections, such as sequence numbers and session information","Only the source and destination MAC addresses of each frame","The content of encrypted application payloads","Static rules that ignore any information about ongoing sessions"],"c":0,"why":"Stateful firewalls track the state of active connections (e.g., TCP session state, sequence numbers) to make more intelligent filtering decisions than simple packet filters. They do not inspect encrypted payload content and are not limited to MAC-address filtering or purely static rules.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol suite is most commonly used to provide confidentiality and integrity for IP traffic in a site-to-site VPN?","o":["SNMP","FTP","IPSec","ARP"],"c":2,"why":"IPSec provides encryption, integrity, and authentication for IP packets and is the standard choice for site-to-site VPNs. SNMP is for network management, FTP for file transfer, and ARP for resolving IP addresses to MAC addresses; none provide VPN-level encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol is considered the least secure due to its use of a weak encryption algorithm and static key management?","o":["WEP","WPA2-Personal","WPA3-Enterprise","EAP-TLS"],"c":0,"why":"WEP relies on RC4 with weak initialization vectors and static keys, making it highly vulnerable to key recovery attacks. WPA2, WPA3, and EAP-TLS all incorporate stronger encryption and dynamic key management, making them significantly more secure.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A network security engineer wants a firewall that tracks the state of active connections and only permits return traffic belonging to an established session. Which firewall type best meets this requirement?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy firewall used without session tracking","Application-layer gateway with no connection tracking"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls maintain a state table of active connections and permit return traffic only if it matches an established session, offering more security context than simple packet filtering, which evaluates each packet in isolation without tracking session state.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Compared to a network hub, what is the primary security and performance benefit of using a switch?","o":["It eliminates the need for IP addressing entirely","It creates a separate collision domain for each connected port","It encrypts all traffic passing through it by default","It removes the need for a routing table"],"c":1,"why":"Switches forward frames only to the intended port based on MAC address, creating a separate collision domain per port and reducing unnecessary traffic exposure, unlike hubs which broadcast to all ports on a shared collision domain. Switches do not inherently encrypt traffic or eliminate IP addressing/routing needs.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of implementing IPsec in transport mode between two hosts?","o":["To encrypt and authenticate the entire IP packet including the original header for site-to-site tunneling","To encrypt and authenticate only the payload of the IP packet while keeping the original IP header intact","To provide Layer 2 switching redundancy","To translate private IP addresses to public IP addresses"],"c":1,"why":"IPsec transport mode encrypts and authenticates only the payload (data), leaving the original IP header exposed, making it suitable for end-to-end host communication. Tunnel mode encrypts the entire packet including the header, typically for site-to-site VPNs; NAT handles address translation, not IPsec.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary function of the Domain Name System (DNS) in a network?","o":["Dynamically assigning IP addresses to hosts","Translating human-readable domain names into IP addresses","Encrypting traffic between web servers and clients","Routing email between mail servers"],"c":1,"why":"DNS resolves domain names to their corresponding IP addresses, enabling users to access resources by name rather than numeric address. DHCP handles dynamic IP assignment, TLS/SSL handles encryption, and SMTP handles email routing.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol addressed the significant cryptographic weaknesses found in WEP by introducing stronger encryption and key management?","o":["WPA2","Bluetooth Low Energy","WPS","SSID broadcasting"],"c":0,"why":"WPA2 introduced AES-based encryption (CCMP) and improved key management, addressing WEP's weak RC4-based encryption and static key vulnerabilities. WPS is a setup mechanism with its own vulnerabilities, SSID broadcasting is unrelated to encryption strength, and Bluetooth Low Energy is a different wireless technology altogether.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"In a star network topology, what is the primary risk associated with the central connecting device?","o":["Data collisions increase significantly compared to bus topology","A single point of failure exists that can disrupt the entire network if it fails","All nodes must share the same collision domain","Cabling costs are typically lower than other topologies"],"c":1,"why":"In a star topology, all nodes connect to a central device (like a switch), making that device a single point of failure. Star topologies generally reduce collisions compared to bus, and they usually require more cabling, not less.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the main functional difference between a network hub and a network switch?","o":["A hub operates at Layer 3 while a switch operates at Layer 2","A switch forwards frames only to the intended destination port based on MAC address, while a hub broadcasts data to all ports","A hub encrypts traffic while a switch does not","A switch cannot support full-duplex communication while a hub can"],"c":1,"why":"Switches use MAC address tables to forward frames only to the appropriate port, reducing collisions and increasing efficiency, whereas hubs broadcast incoming data to all ports, creating a single collision domain. Neither device encrypts traffic, and switches typically support full-duplex, unlike hubs.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants a network device to reassemble segmented TCP data and provide flow control between two communicating hosts, ensuring reliable end-to-end delivery. At which OSI layer does this functionality primarily occur?","o":["Network layer","Transport layer","Session layer","Data Link layer"],"c":1,"why":"The Transport layer (Layer 4) is responsible for segmentation, reassembly, and flow control (e.g., TCP). The Network layer handles routing/addressing, the Session layer manages dialog control, and the Data Link layer handles local framing, none of which perform end-to-end reliable delivery.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which network service resolves human-readable domain names into IP addresses used for routing traffic?","o":["DHCP","DNS","NAT","SNMP"],"c":1,"why":"DNS (Domain Name System) translates domain names into IP addresses. DHCP assigns IP addresses to hosts, NAT translates private to public addresses, and SNMP is used for network device monitoring and management, none of which perform name resolution.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing a site-to-site IPsec VPN between two offices, and the traffic must traverse a NAT gateway operated by an ISP between the two VPN endpoints. Which combination of IPsec protocol, mode, and feature should be selected to ensure the tunnel functions correctly while still providing payload confidentiality?","o":["AH in tunnel mode, since AH provides the strongest integrity guarantees for NAT traversal","ESP in transport mode without NAT Traversal (NAT-T) enabled","ESP in tunnel mode with NAT-T (UDP encapsulation) enabled","AH in transport mode with NAT-T (UDP encapsulation) enabled"],"c":2,"why":"ESP provides confidentiality (encryption) and can be encapsulated in UDP via NAT-T so the modified IP addresses from NAT do not break the packet; AH fails across NAT because it authenticates the outer IP header, which NAT modifies, causing integrity check failures. Tunnel mode is required for site-to-site VPNs to encapsulate the entire original packet.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security engineer needs a firewall that tracks the state of active connections and makes filtering decisions based on the context of a session (e.g., whether a packet belongs to an established connection), without fully decoding the application-layer protocol. Which firewall type best meets this requirement?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Application-layer proxy firewall","Circuit-level proxy firewall"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls maintain a state table of connections and filter based on session context without parsing application data. Packet filtering has no state awareness, application-layer proxies fully decode protocol content, and circuit-level proxies relay sessions without this level of connection-context filtering.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"During a penetration test, an assessor successfully jumps from an unprivileged access VLAN to a restricted management VLAN by crafting Ethernet frames with two stacked 802.1Q tags (double tagging) sent through an access port. Which mitigation most directly and effectively prevents this specific attack technique?","o":["Enable Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) on all switches in the network","Enable Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI) on all access ports","Change the native VLAN on all trunk ports to an unused, dedicated VLAN ID that is not assigned to any access port, and explicitly disable that VLAN elsewhere","Configure port security to limit the number of MAC addresses learned per access port"],"c":2,"why":"Double-tagging VLAN hopping exploits switches that strip only the outer tag matching the native VLAN on a trunk, exposing the inner tag; using a dedicated, unused native VLAN prevents the outer tag from matching any legitimate VLAN, breaking the attack. STP, DAI, and MAC limiting address different threats (loops, ARP spoofing, MAC flooding) and do not stop double tagging.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company needs to encrypt all traffic between two branch office VPN gateways over the Internet, protecting the entire original IP packet (including headers) and using the gateways' own addresses in a new outer IP header. Which IPsec mode should be implemented?","o":["Transport mode","Tunnel mode","AH-only mode","ESP transport mode"],"c":1,"why":"Tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original IP packet inside a new IP header, making it ideal for gateway-to-gateway VPNs. Transport mode only protects the payload and retains the original IP header, which is used for host-to-host communication, not site-to-site tunneling.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which wireless security enhancement introduced in WPA3 provides resistance to offline dictionary attacks against pre-shared keys by using a secure key-establishment exchange during authentication?","o":["TKIP","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","PSK with AES-CCMP (WPA2)","WPS PIN authentication"],"c":1,"why":"SAE replaces the WPA2 four-way handshake and provides forward secrecy plus resistance to offline dictionary attacks. TKIP is an outdated and weak WPA1 mechanism, WPA2's PSK/CCMP remains vulnerable to offline attacks on captured handshakes, and WPS PIN authentication is well known to be insecure.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An analyst is comparing why WPA3-Personal is significantly more resistant to offline password-guessing attacks than WPA2-Personal, even when both use similarly complex passphrases. Which characteristic of WPA3 explains this improvement?","o":["WPA3 mandates AES-256 encryption instead of AES-128, making brute-force key recovery computationally infeasible","WPA3 replaces the 4-way handshake with Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE), a Diffie-Hellman-based exchange that provides forward secrecy and resists offline dictionary attacks against captured handshake traffic","WPA3 encrypts the SSID broadcast so attackers cannot identify target networks for attack","WPA3 uses a challenge-response CHAP mechanism instead of a pre-shared key entirely"],"c":1,"why":"WPA2's 4-way handshake exposes enough information in a captured handshake to allow offline brute-forcing of the PSK; WPA3's SAE (Dragonfly) exchange requires active interaction with the AP for each guess and provides forward secrecy, making offline attacks impractical. Key length alone does not address the handshake weakness, and SSID/CHAP claims are inaccurate.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An attacker sends a large number of ICMP echo request packets to a network's broadcast address with a spoofed source address belonging to the intended victim. All hosts on the network reply directly to the victim, flooding it with traffic. What type of attack is being described?","o":["SYN flood","Smurf attack","Teardrop attack","Ping of death"],"c":1,"why":"A Smurf attack abuses broadcast addressing and IP spoofing to amplify ICMP traffic toward a victim. A SYN flood exploits the TCP handshake, a teardrop attack uses malformed overlapping fragments, and a ping of death sends an oversized ICMP packet to crash a system.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company is building a site-to-site VPN between two data centers over the public Internet. Regulatory requirements mandate that both the payload and the original IP header of every packet be encrypted and integrity-protected while in transit. Which IPsec configuration satisfies this requirement?","o":["Authentication Header (AH) in transport mode","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) in transport mode","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) in tunnel mode","Authentication Header (AH) in tunnel mode"],"c":2,"why":"ESP in tunnel mode encrypts and authenticates the entire original IP packet (header and payload) inside a new outer header, providing full confidentiality and integrity. AH provides no confidentiality, and transport mode leaves the original IP header exposed rather than encrypting it.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An ISP discovers that traffic destined for one of its customer's IP prefixes was rerouted through an unauthorized autonomous system for several hours, allowing an attacker to intercept and inspect the traffic before forwarding it. Which control would have most directly prevented this BGP-based route hijacking?","o":["Deploying BGP route reflectors to reduce the number of iBGP peering sessions","Implementing Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI) with Route Origin Authorizations (ROAs) validated at border routers","Increasing BGP keepalive and hold timers to detect route flapping more quickly","Replacing BGP with OSPF for all inter-domain routing"],"c":1,"why":"RPKI/ROA allows routers to cryptographically validate that an announcing AS is authorized to originate a given prefix, directly preventing unauthorized route hijacks. Route reflectors and timer tuning address scalability and convergence, not authorization; OSPF is an interior routing protocol and is not a substitute for inter-domain BGP.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network device receives an Ethernet frame and uses the destination MAC address to decide which physical port to forward it out of. At which layer of the OSI model does this device primarily function?","o":["Data Link layer","Network layer","Transport layer","Physical layer"],"c":0,"why":"Switches forward frames based on MAC addresses, which is a Data Link layer (Layer 2) function. The Network layer handles logical (IP) addressing and routing, the Transport layer handles end-to-end sessions, and the Physical layer deals only with bits and signaling, not addressing decisions.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network administrator segments a previously flat network into multiple VLANs based on department function, then applies routing and access control lists between VLANs. What is the PRIMARY security benefit gained by this design?","o":["Elimination of the need for firewalls between network segments","Reduction of attack surface by isolating broadcast domains and controlling inter-VLAN traffic","Automatic encryption of all traffic between VLANs","Prevention of all ARP spoofing attacks within the network"],"c":1,"why":"VLAN segmentation isolates broadcast domains and, combined with inter-VLAN access controls, limits lateral movement and reduces exposure. Firewalls/ACLs are still needed for policy enforcement between VLANs, VLANs do not inherently encrypt traffic, and ARP spoofing can still occur within a single VLAN.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"Security architects are comparing WPA2-Personal to WPA3-Personal for a branch office wireless network. Which characteristic explains why WPA3 is significantly more resistant to offline dictionary attacks against the pre-shared key than WPA2?","o":["WPA3 mandates AES-256 encryption instead of AES-128","WPA3 replaces the four-way handshake with Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE), a password-authenticated key exchange that requires real-time interaction for each guess","WPA3 disables management frame protection, reducing attack surface","WPA3 uses a longer SSID broadcast interval to prevent handshake capture"],"c":1,"why":"SAE (based on the Dragonfly key exchange) forces an attacker to interact with the AP for every password guess and provides forward secrecy, defeating offline brute-force attacks captured from a handshake. AES key length is unrelated to this specific weakness, and WPA3 actually enables (not disables) management frame protection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"After a DNS cache poisoning incident, a company implements DNSSEC on its authoritative name servers. During a security briefing, a manager asks whether this change will also encrypt DNS queries between clients and resolvers. What is the most accurate response?","o":["DNSSEC encrypts both DNS queries and responses end-to-end between resolver and authoritative server","DNSSEC digitally signs DNS records to provide data origin authentication and integrity, but it does not encrypt query or response contents","DNSSEC replaces UDP transport with TLS-encrypted TCP sessions for all DNS transactions","DNSSEC prevents cache poisoning by requiring mutual TLS certificate exchange between all resolvers"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to let resolvers verify that records have not been altered and genuinely originate from the zone's authoritative source, addressing cache poisoning and spoofing; it provides no confidentiality. Encrypting DNS traffic requires separate mechanisms such as DNS over TLS (DoT) or DNS over HTTPS (DoH).","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An attacker sends a massive volume of TCP packets with the SYN flag set and spoofed, unreachable source IP addresses to a web server. The server allocates connection state for each request and waits for the final ACK, eventually exhausting its connection table and denying service to legitimate users. Which attack is occurring, and which control most directly mitigates it?","o":["SYN flood; implementing SYN cookies on the target server","Smurf attack; disabling IP-directed broadcasts on the router","Teardrop attack; patching the IP fragment reassembly code","Land attack; deploying ingress/egress filtering at the perimeter"],"c":0,"why":"This is a classic SYN flood exploiting half-open TCP connections; SYN cookies avoid allocating full state until the handshake completes, mitigating resource exhaustion. Smurf, teardrop, and land attacks involve different mechanisms (broadcast amplification, malformed fragments, and identical source/destination packets) that don't match the described half-open connection exhaustion.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A threat actor exploits a weakness in DNS resolver software to insert forged resource records into the resolver's cache, causing subsequent users who query that resolver to be redirected to a malicious IP address for a legitimate domain name. Which attack does this describe?","o":["DNS cache poisoning","Unauthorized DNS zone transfer","Typosquatting","Fast flux DNS"],"c":0,"why":"DNS cache poisoning involves inserting forged records into a resolver's cache to redirect legitimate queries to malicious destinations. Zone transfer abuse involves unauthorized copying of zone data, typosquatting relies on similarly spelled domains rather than resolver manipulation, and fast flux involves rapidly rotating IP addresses to evade blocklisting.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization deploys DNSSEC across its authoritative name servers to counter cache poisoning attacks. Which statement correctly describes a limitation that security staff must still address?","o":["DNSSEC encrypts DNS query and response traffic, but only between recursive resolvers","DNSSEC provides origin authentication and integrity for DNS data but does not encrypt DNS traffic, so queries remain visible to eavesdroppers","DNSSEC eliminates the need for TLS certificate validation on associated web servers","DNSSEC automatically rate-limits DNS queries to mitigate volumetric DDoS attacks"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to guarantee the authenticity and integrity of DNS responses, but it does not provide confidentiality; DNS traffic must still be protected separately (e.g., DoH/DoT) if privacy is required. It has no bearing on TLS certificate validation or DDoS rate limiting.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm runs iSCSI traffic between application servers and a SAN over the same switching infrastructure used for general LAN traffic. Given that iSCSI does not natively encrypt data in transit, which control most effectively mitigates the risk of an attacker eavesdropping on storage traffic?","o":["Enforce CHAP authentication between iSCSI initiators and targets","Place iSCSI traffic on a dedicated VLAN isolated from general LAN traffic","Encrypt iSCSI traffic in transit using IPsec between initiators and targets","Enable jumbo frames on the storage network to reduce packet fragmentation"],"c":2,"why":"CHAP provides authentication but not confidentiality, and VLAN segmentation reduces exposure but does not prevent eavesdropping by an attacker who gains access to the segment or performs VLAN-hopping; IPsec directly encrypts the iSCSI payload, addressing the confidentiality risk. Jumbo frames are a performance optimization unrelated to security.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company needs to establish an IPSec VPN between two branch office gateways so that all traffic between the two internal networks is protected, including the original IP headers, as it traverses the public Internet. Which IPSec mode should be used?","o":["Tunnel mode","Transport mode","AH-only mode","ESP null-encryption mode"],"c":0,"why":"Tunnel mode encapsulates and encrypts the entire original IP packet (including headers) inside a new IP packet, making it appropriate for gateway-to-gateway VPNs. Transport mode only protects the payload and leaves the original IP header exposed, which is unsuitable for hiding internal addressing across gateways.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that only authenticated and authorized devices can gain network access through wired switch ports, denying connectivity until a device successfully authenticates against a RADIUS server. Which technology best supports this requirement?","o":["SNMP","IEEE 802.1X port-based network access control","DHCP snooping","Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)"],"c":1,"why":"IEEE 802.1X provides port-based authentication using EAP in conjunction with a RADIUS server, blocking network access until authentication succeeds. SNMP is used for device management, DHCP snooping prevents rogue DHCP servers, and STP prevents Layer 2 loops—none of these perform port-based authentication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An architect must deploy a load balancer that terminates client SSL/TLS sessions and routes each request to a different backend server pool based on the URL path contained in the decrypted HTTP request. Which type of load balancer meets this requirement?","o":["A Layer 4 load balancer performing round-robin distribution based on source IP and port","A Layer 7 load balancer capable of inspecting decrypted HTTP payload and routing based on application-level content such as URL path","A DNS-based load balancer using round-robin name resolution","A Layer 2 load balancer that distributes traffic using MAC address hashing"],"c":1,"why":"Only a Layer 7 (application-layer) load balancer can terminate SSL/TLS and inspect the decrypted HTTP request to make routing decisions based on content like URL paths; Layer 4, Layer 2, and DNS-based load balancing operate below the application layer and cannot see or act on HTTP-level data.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security team is designing a network to host a public-facing web application while minimizing risk to the internal corporate network. Which architecture provides the strongest defense-in-depth against a compromised public-facing server?","o":["A single firewall with three interfaces creating internal, DMZ, and external zones","A screened subnet using two firewalls, with the web server placed between an external firewall and an internal firewall","A bastion host with no firewall, relying solely on host-based hardening","NAT overload on the border router with no dedicated DMZ segment"],"c":1,"why":"A screened subnet (dual-firewall DMZ) ensures that compromise of the public server requires an attacker to breach a second, independently configured firewall before reaching the internal network, reducing single points of failure. A single three-legged firewall is a single point of failure/misconfiguration, and the other options omit layered controls entirely.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security architect wants a firewall that can understand the semantics of the FTP protocol well enough to block specific FTP commands (e.g., blocking PUT while allowing GET) rather than just permitting or denying traffic based on IP addresses and ports. Which firewall technology best meets this requirement?","o":["Application-layer (proxy) firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Packet-filtering firewall","Circuit-level gateway"],"c":0,"why":"Application-layer proxy firewalls fully parse and understand application protocols, enabling command-level filtering such as blocking specific FTP operations. Stateful inspection and packet filtering firewalls make decisions based on connection state, IP, and port information but don't interpret application-layer commands, and circuit-level gateways only manage session-layer connections.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester crafts Ethernet frames containing two nested 802.1Q VLAN tags and sends them to a trunk port, successfully injecting traffic into a VLAN the tester's port should not be able to reach. What is the most effective mitigation for this specific attack?","o":["Enable dynamic ARP inspection on all access ports","Set the native VLAN on trunk ports to an unused VLAN ID and explicitly tag all traffic, disabling auto-trunk negotiation","Implement MAC address filtering on all switch ports","Deploy a host-based firewall on every endpoint in the affected VLAN"],"c":1,"why":"This describes a VLAN double-tagging attack, which exploits the native (untagged) VLAN on trunk links. Mitigation requires assigning an unused native VLAN, tagging all trunk traffic, and disabling automatic trunk negotiation. ARP inspection, MAC filtering, and host firewalls do not address the underlying trunking misconfiguration.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A stateful inspection firewall allows an HTTP POST request containing a SQL injection payload to reach a web server because the connection matches an already-established, permitted session in the firewall's state table. Which security control would most effectively detect and block this specific attack?","o":["Increase the firewall's state table timeout values to track sessions longer","Add additional stateful inspection rules permitting only port 443 traffic","Deploy a web application firewall (WAF) that performs deep inspection of HTTP payloads against known attack signatures and behavioral patterns","Replace the stateful firewall with a simple packet-filtering firewall using stricter ACLs"],"c":2,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls validate connection state but generally do not inspect application-layer payload content for attacks like SQL injection; a WAF inspects the actual HTTP payload against signatures and anomaly patterns to detect such attacks. The other options do not add payload inspection capability and packet filtering is even less capable than stateful inspection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to eliminate the risk of offline dictionary attacks against captured four-way handshake traffic that were possible with WPA2-Personal, while still supporting pre-shared key authentication for a small office wireless network. Which technology should be adopted?","o":["WPA3-Personal using SAE (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals)","WPA2-Enterprise using 802.1X with PEAP","WEP with a 128-bit key","WPA2-Personal with a longer pre-shared key"],"c":0,"why":"WPA3-Personal replaces the WPA2 four-way handshake with SAE, which resists offline dictionary/brute-force attacks even against captured handshakes. WPA2-Enterprise requires an authentication server (not just a PSK), WEP is fundamentally broken, and simply lengthening a WPA2 PSK does not eliminate the underlying handshake vulnerability.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which TCP flag combination is used to initiate a connection during the first step of the TCP three-way handshake?","o":["ACK","SYN","FIN","RST"],"c":1,"why":"The three-way handshake begins with a SYN packet from the client to request a connection. ACK confirms receipt, FIN gracefully closes a connection, and RST abruptly terminates one.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network administrator segments a large flat switched network into multiple logical broadcast domains based on department, so that broadcast traffic and unauthorized access are contained even though devices remain on the same physical switches. What is this technique called, and what is its primary security benefit?","o":["VLANs; limiting broadcast domains and enforcing logical traffic isolation between segments","Spanning Tree Protocol; preventing switching loops that could cause outages","Port security; restricting the number of MAC addresses per switch port","Link aggregation; increasing bandwidth and redundancy between switches"],"c":0,"why":"VLANs create separate logical broadcast domains on shared physical switching infrastructure, containing traffic and limiting lateral exposure between departments. STP, port security, and link aggregation are legitimate switch features but address loop prevention, MAC address limiting, and bandwidth/redundancy respectively, not logical segmentation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An ISP wants to prevent unauthorized autonomous systems from advertising IP prefixes they do not own, a problem that has caused major route hijacking incidents on the Internet. Which control specifically validates that an AS is authorized to originate a given prefix?","o":["BGP MD5 session authentication between peering routers","Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI) with Route Origin Authorizations (ROAs)","Replacing eBGP with OSPF at network borders","Ingress access control lists filtering by source IP only"],"c":1,"why":"RPKI/ROA cryptographically ties an IP prefix to the authorized originating AS, allowing routers to validate route origin and reject hijacked or leaked announcements. BGP MD5 only authenticates the peering session (not route content), OSPF is an interior protocol unsuitable for Internet-scale routing, and simple ACLs cannot validate AS-prefix ownership.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator wants a firewall that can track the state of active connections and automatically allow return traffic for an established session. Which firewall type should be used?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy only","Static packet filter"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls maintain a state table of active connections, allowing legitimate return traffic without needing explicit rules for it. Packet-filtering and static filters evaluate each packet independently without connection awareness.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An attacker intercepts a DNS query and races the legitimate authoritative response, injecting a forged reply that maps a bank's domain name to a malicious IP address before the real answer arrives, and the resolver caches the forged record. Which technology, if properly deployed, would have prevented the client from accepting this forged response?","o":["DNSSEC, by validating digital signatures on DNS responses","IPSec, by encrypting the DNS query and response","TLS, by encrypting the session between client and resolver","NAT, by hiding the internal client's real IP address"],"c":0,"why":"DNSSEC provides data origin authentication and integrity through digitally signed DNS records, allowing resolvers to reject forged or tampered responses used in cache poisoning. IPSec and TLS provide confidentiality/integrity for transport but are not the standard mechanism validating DNS record authenticity, and NAT is unrelated to DNS response validation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise is rolling out a VoIP system and wants to ensure both call signaling and media streams are protected from eavesdropping and tampering as they cross an untrusted network segment. Which combination of controls correctly achieves this?","o":["Plain RTP for media combined with VLAN segmentation for signaling","IPsec tunnel mode for media only, leaving SIP signaling in cleartext","SIP over TLS (SIPS) for signaling and SRTP for media encryption","Disabling QoS tagging to prevent traffic analysis of call metadata"],"c":2,"why":"SIPS protects the signaling channel (call setup, credentials) while SRTP encrypts and authenticates the actual media stream—together covering both attack surfaces. VLAN segmentation alone does not encrypt traffic, and leaving either signaling or media in cleartext exposes it to interception; disabling QoS does not address confidentiality or integrity.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol suite is most commonly used to provide confidentiality, integrity, and authentication for IP traffic in a site-to-site VPN?","o":["SSH","IPSec","SNMP","FTP"],"c":1,"why":"IPSec is the standard protocol suite for securing IP traffic in VPNs, offering encryption, integrity, and authentication. SSH secures remote command-line sessions, SNMP is for network management, and FTP is for file transfer—none provide VPN-level network security.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"In an 802.1X port-based network access control deployment on a wired switch, which component relays the endpoint's credentials to the authentication server but does not itself have the ability to validate them?","o":["The supplicant running on the endpoint","The authenticator, typically the network switch or access point","The RADIUS authentication server","The certificate authority issuing client certificates"],"c":1,"why":"The authenticator (switch/AP) acts as a pass-through, forwarding EAP messages between the supplicant and the authentication server (e.g., RADIUS) without validating credentials itself; it only enforces the port state based on the server's decision. The supplicant originates credentials, the RADIUS server performs validation, and the CA merely issues certificates used in the exchange.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol is considered insecure due to weak key management and should be avoided in modern networks?","o":["WPA3","WPA2-Enterprise","WEP","WPA2-Personal with AES"],"c":2,"why":"WEP uses a weak static key and flawed RC4 implementation, making it easily crackable. WPA2 and WPA3 use stronger encryption and key management, making them far more secure choices.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company is deploying a VoIP system and wants to protect both the call setup signaling and the actual voice media streams from eavesdropping and tampering as they cross the corporate network. Which combination of protocols best achieves this?","o":["SIP over TLS (SIPS) for signaling and SRTP for media","RTP for signaling and H.323 for media encryption","SNMP v3 for signaling and IPSec transport mode for media only","Plain SIP for signaling and RTP for media, relying on VLAN separation alone"],"c":0,"why":"SIPS (SIP over TLS) secures call setup/signaling, while SRTP encrypts and authenticates the actual voice media packets, together protecting the full VoIP call. RTP and H.323 alone don't provide encryption, SNMP is a management protocol unrelated to call signaling, and VLAN separation alone does not provide cryptographic confidentiality or integrity.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security purpose of implementing VLANs on a switched network?","o":["To encrypt traffic between hosts","To logically segment network traffic and limit broadcast domains between groups of devices","To provide redundant power to network devices","To automatically patch vulnerable systems"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs logically separate hosts into distinct broadcast domains, improving security by isolating traffic between groups even though they may share the same physical switch. VLANs do not provide encryption, power redundancy, or patching.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company requires that traffic between two branch office IPsec gateways be both encrypted and authenticated, and it further requires that the original source and destination IP headers be concealed from any devices along the transit path. Which IPsec mode/protocol combination satisfies all of these requirements?","o":["Transport mode with AH","Tunnel mode with ESP","Transport mode with ESP","Tunnel mode with AH"],"c":1,"why":"Tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original packet (including headers) inside a new IP packet, hiding the original headers, and ESP provides both encryption and authentication. AH never provides encryption, and transport mode leaves the original IP header exposed.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which TCP/IP protocol is responsible for resolving a known IP address to its corresponding MAC address on a local network segment?","o":["DNS","ARP","DHCP","ICMP"],"c":1,"why":"ARP (Address Resolution Protocol) maps IP addresses to MAC addresses on a local network. DNS resolves hostnames to IP addresses, DHCP assigns IP addresses, and ICMP is used for diagnostics like ping.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing a TLS deployment and wants to ensure that if the server's long-term private key is ever compromised, previously captured session traffic cannot be decrypted retroactively. Which mechanism must be used to achieve this property?","o":["Static RSA key exchange using the server's certificate key","Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman key exchange (DHE or ECDHE)","Pre-shared keys negotiated out-of-band without ephemeral components","Mutual authentication using client certificates"],"c":1,"why":"Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman generates a unique session key for each session that is not derivable from the server's static private key, providing forward secrecy. Static RSA key exchange ties session keys to the long-term private key, so its compromise exposes all past sessions; client certificates address authentication, not key confidentiality.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator wants to logically separate departments on the same physical switch to reduce broadcast traffic and improve security boundaries. Which technology should be used?","o":["VLAN","NAT","VPN","Port forwarding"],"c":0,"why":"VLANs (Virtual LANs) logically segment a physical switch into separate broadcast domains, improving both performance and security isolation. NAT translates addresses, VPN provides secure remote connectivity, and port forwarding redirects traffic to specific ports.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester on an internal access port successfully jumps from VLAN 10 to VLAN 20 by sending frames with two stacked 802.1Q tags, exploiting the switch's handling of the native VLAN. Which control most directly mitigates this double-tagging VLAN hopping attack?","o":["Explicitly configure access ports in access mode, disable DTP, and avoid using the native VLAN as a production data VLAN","Enable port security to limit the number of MAC addresses per port","Enable BPDU guard on all access ports","Deploy private VLANs on every switch port in the environment"],"c":0,"why":"Double-tagging attacks rely on the switch stripping only the outer (native VLAN) tag on a trunk-negotiated port and forwarding the inner tagged frame; hard-setting access ports, disabling trunk negotiation, and reassigning the native VLAN removes the conditions the attack depends on. Port security and BPDU guard address MAC flooding and STP attacks, not tag manipulation, and private VLANs alone don't prevent tag stripping.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which type of firewall technology tracks the state of active connections and makes filtering decisions based on the context of traffic, such as whether a packet is part of an established session?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Proxy firewall","Circuit-level gateway"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls maintain a state table of active connections and evaluate packets based on connection context. Simple packet-filtering firewalls only examine individual packets without context, while proxy and circuit-level firewalls operate differently by fully mediating or relaying sessions.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to guarantee that DNS responses received by its resolvers have not been tampered with in transit and truly originated from the authoritative zone owner, not merely that the query channel is encrypted. Which technology directly provides this data-origin authentication and integrity guarantee?","o":["DNS over HTTPS (DoH)","DNS over TLS (DoT)","DNSSEC","Split-horizon DNS"],"c":2,"why":"DNSSEC uses chained digital signatures (RRSIG/DNSKEY records) to cryptographically validate that DNS records are authentic and unaltered. DoH and DoT only encrypt the transport channel between client and resolver and do nothing to validate that the underlying DNS data itself wasn't forged upstream.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization is designing its network addressing and routing scheme. At which OSI layer are logical addressing and the selection of the best path between networks primarily handled?","o":["Data Link Layer (Layer 2)","Network Layer (Layer 3)","Transport Layer (Layer 4)","Session Layer (Layer 5)"],"c":1,"why":"The Network Layer handles logical (IP) addressing and routing decisions between networks. The Data Link Layer deals with physical/MAC addressing on a single segment, Transport handles end-to-end reliability, and Session manages dialog control between applications.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"WPA3's Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) handshake is considered significantly more resistant to offline dictionary attacks than WPA2-PSK's four-way handshake. What is the primary reason for this improved resistance?","o":["SAE mandates AES-256 encryption instead of AES-128","SAE requires live interaction with the access point for each authentication attempt and derives a unique session key per exchange, preventing captured handshake data from being brute-forced offline","SAE removes the requirement for a pre-shared passphrase entirely","SAE uses a significantly longer initialization vector than WPA2"],"c":1,"why":"SAE (based on the Dragonfly key exchange) requires an attacker to interact with the AP for every guess, and captured exchanges don't expose enough material to conduct offline brute-force attacks as WPA2's 4-way handshake does. Encryption cipher strength and IV length are unrelated to this specific offline-attack resistance, and SAE still uses a shared passphrase.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to encrypt traffic between two office locations over the public Internet to create a secure, private connection. Which technology is most appropriate?","o":["VLAN trunking","Site-to-site VPN","Network Address Translation","Spanning Tree Protocol"],"c":1,"why":"A site-to-site VPN creates an encrypted tunnel between two networks over the Internet, ensuring confidentiality and integrity. VLAN trunking is for local network segmentation, NAT translates addresses without encryption, and Spanning Tree Protocol prevents loops in switched networks.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is configuring an IPsec VPN and requires that traffic between two sites be both encrypted and authenticated. Which IPsec protocol component should be selected to meet this requirement?","o":["Authentication Header (AH)","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP)","Internet Key Exchange (IKE) Phase 1 only","Generic Routing Encapsulation (GRE)"],"c":1,"why":"ESP provides both confidentiality (encryption) and authentication/integrity, whereas AH provides only authentication and integrity with no encryption. IKE Phase 1 only establishes the secure channel for key negotiation, and GRE is a tunneling protocol without built-in security.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization migrates from a traditional stateful inspection firewall to a next-generation firewall (NGFW). Which capability most fundamentally distinguishes the NGFW from the legacy stateful firewall?","o":["The ability to track connection state across TCP SYN/ACK sequences","Application-layer visibility combining deep packet inspection, user/identity awareness, and integrated intrusion prevention","The ability to perform network address translation (NAT)","Packet filtering decisions based on source/destination IP and port"],"c":1,"why":"NGFWs add Layer 7 application awareness, user identity integration, and inline IPS capability beyond simple session tracking. Stateful firewalls already handle connection-state tracking, NAT, and basic IP/port filtering, so those don't differentiate the two technologies.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol is considered the most secure standard for protecting Wi-Fi networks today, offering stronger encryption than its predecessors?","o":["WEP","WPA","WPA2","WPA3"],"c":3,"why":"WPA3 is the current strongest Wi-Fi security standard, offering improved encryption and protection against offline dictionary attacks. WEP is deprecated and easily broken, WPA improved on WEP but has known weaknesses, and WPA2, while strong, has been superseded by WPA3.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An ISP wants to prevent unauthorized organizations from announcing BGP routes for IP prefixes they do not own, a class of attack known as route hijacking. Which control provides cryptographic validation of legitimate route origin?","o":["Access control lists filtering BGP updates based on source IP address","Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI) with Route Origin Authorizations validated through Route Origin Validation (ROV)","MD5 authentication configured on BGP peering sessions","Replacing BGP with OSPF for all inter-domain routing"],"c":1,"why":"RPKI allows prefix owners to cryptographically sign Route Origin Authorizations, and ROV lets routers validate that an announcing AS is authorized to originate a given prefix, directly countering hijacking. MD5 session authentication only protects the BGP session between peers (not route origin), ACL filtering doesn't scale or verify ownership, and OSPF is an interior protocol not used for inter-domain routing.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A penetration tester successfully performs a VLAN hopping attack by sending frames with two 802.1Q tags, causing the switch to forward traffic into a VLAN the attacker should not have access to. Which control would most effectively mitigate this specific attack?","o":["Enabling port security with MAC address limiting","Assigning an unused VLAN ID as the native VLAN on trunk ports and disabling auto-trunking","Implementing 802.1X port-based authentication on access ports","Configuring private VLANs on all switch ports"],"c":1,"why":"Double-tagging VLAN hopping exploits the native (untagged) VLAN on trunk links; setting the native VLAN to an unused ID and disabling auto-trunking closes this vector. Port security limits MAC addresses but doesn't stop double-tagging, 802.1X authenticates devices but doesn't address native VLAN tag stripping, and private VLANs address a different isolation problem within a single VLAN.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security purpose of implementing network segmentation using firewalls between a DMZ and an internal network?","o":["To increase available bandwidth for internal users","To prevent direct access from external networks to internal systems if the DMZ is compromised","To reduce the number of IP addresses needed","To eliminate the need for encryption on internal traffic"],"c":1,"why":"Segmenting the DMZ from the internal network with a firewall ensures that even if a publicly accessible DMZ host is compromised, attackers cannot directly reach internal systems. Segmentation does not increase bandwidth, reduce IP address needs, or eliminate the need for encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm operating a flat, highly interconnected data center network wants to limit lateral movement between workloads and enforce identity-based access policies regardless of a workload's physical or network location. Which architectural approach best achieves this goal?","o":["Traditional VLAN segmentation enforced only by a perimeter firewall","Software-defined micro-segmentation using distributed firewalls that enforce per-workload security policies","Network Access Control (NAC) enforcement limited to wired switch access ports","Physically air-gapping all sensitive servers from the rest of the network"],"c":1,"why":"Micro-segmentation enforces granular, identity- and policy-based controls between individual workloads independent of physical topology, directly limiting lateral movement in a zero-trust model. VLANs with only perimeter enforcement don't stop east-west traffic, port-based NAC doesn't address workload-to-workload communication, and air-gapping is impractical and breaks required connectivity.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company wants a firewall that terminates each connection, inspects the full application-layer payload, and establishes a separate connection to the destination on behalf of the client. Which firewall technology best fits this description?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Application-layer proxy firewall","Circuit-level gateway"],"c":2,"why":"An application-layer proxy firewall terminates the client connection, fully inspects application data, and creates a new connection to the destination, providing deep content inspection. Packet-filtering and stateful firewalls forward packets/connections without full application termination, and circuit-level gateways only validate session establishment without inspecting payload content.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which port scanning result would indicate to an administrator that a firewall is actively blocking access to a specific port, rather than the port simply being closed on the host?","o":["Open","Closed","Filtered","Reset"],"c":2,"why":"A 'filtered' result typically indicates that packets sent to the port were dropped or blocked, often by a firewall, with no response received. 'Open' means a service is listening, 'closed' means the host actively refused the connection, and 'reset' is not a standard scan state but rather a TCP flag response.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"WPA3 was introduced to address a key weakness in WPA2-Personal where captured 4-way handshake traffic could be subjected to offline dictionary attacks against the pre-shared key. Which WPA3 feature specifically mitigates this vulnerability?","o":["AES-256 encryption of the data payload","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","Mandatory use of 802.1X for all clients","Extended Service Set identifiers (ESSID) hiding"],"c":1,"why":"SAE replaces the WPA2 4-way handshake with a Diffie-Hellman-based exchange resistant to offline dictionary attacks. AES-256 encrypts data but doesn't fix the handshake weakness, 802.1X is used for enterprise authentication rather than personal PSK networks, and SSID hiding provides no real cryptographic protection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An administrator is deploying DNSSEC to protect the organization's authoritative DNS zone. What is the primary security benefit that DNSSEC provides?","o":["Encryption of DNS query and response payloads to ensure confidentiality","Authentication of the origin and integrity verification of DNS responses using digital signatures","Prevention of denial-of-service attacks against DNS servers","Automatic detection and blocking of malicious domain names"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to authenticate the source of DNS data and verify it hasn't been tampered with, mitigating cache poisoning and spoofing. It does not provide confidentiality (queries remain unencrypted), does not directly prevent DoS attacks, and does not perform reputation-based domain blocking.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An attacker connects a laptop to a switch port and floods the network with frames containing thousands of randomized source MAC addresses. The switch's CAM table fills up, and it begins broadcasting all subsequent traffic out every port, allowing the attacker to capture traffic intended for other hosts. Which attack is being described, and what is the most effective control against it?","o":["ARP cache poisoning; mitigated by static ARP entries","MAC flooding; mitigated by port security limiting the number of learned MAC addresses per port","VLAN hopping; mitigated by disabling native VLAN on trunk ports","DHCP starvation; mitigated by DHCP snooping"],"c":1,"why":"Filling the CAM (content-addressable memory) table with bogus MAC addresses forces the switch into a fail-open flooding state, which is classic MAC flooding; port security (limiting MACs per port) is the standard mitigation. The other attacks target different mechanisms (IP-to-MAC mapping, VLAN tagging, DHCP leases) and would not cause CAM table exhaustion.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network segmentation project isolates a production database segment from general corporate networks. Administrators still need remote access to manage servers within the sensitive segment. Which architecture best balances security and administrative access needs?","o":["Allow direct RDP/SSH access from all administrator workstations to the segment via firewall rules","Deploy a hardened bastion/jump host in a controlled zone that brokers and logs all administrative sessions into the segment","Place administrator workstations on the same VLAN as the database servers","Disable all remote access and require physical presence for administration"],"c":1,"why":"A bastion/jump host provides a single, hardened, monitored control point for administrative access into a sensitive segment, reducing the attack surface and enabling logging. Direct access from all workstations expands the attack surface, placing admin workstations on the same VLAN defeats segmentation, and requiring physical presence is impractical and not a scalable security control.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company needs to establish a site-to-site VPN between two branch offices over the public Internet, protecting the confidentiality and integrity of the entire original IP packet, including its header. Which IPSec mode should be implemented?","o":["Transport mode","Tunnel mode","Authentication Header (AH) only, no encryption","ESP in null-encryption mode"],"c":1,"why":"Tunnel mode encapsulates and encrypts the entire original IP packet (including the header) inside a new IP packet, making it ideal for gateway-to-gateway VPNs. Transport mode only protects the payload, leaving the original header exposed, and AH-only or null-encryption ESP would not provide confidentiality.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is reviewing a proposed TLS 1.2 cipher suite configuration for a financial application. To ensure that a compromise of the server's long-term private key in the future cannot be used to decrypt previously captured session traffic, which key exchange mechanism must be mandated?","o":["RSA key exchange using the server's static private key","Static (non-ephemeral) Diffie-Hellman with a fixed group","Ephemeral Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman (ECDHE)","Pre-shared key (PSK) exchange without DHE"],"c":2,"why":"ECDHE generates a unique, temporary key pair for each session, providing perfect forward secrecy so that later compromise of the long-term key cannot decrypt past sessions. RSA key exchange and static DH reuse long-term keys across sessions, and plain PSK without ephemeral DH also lacks forward secrecy.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security team is selecting a TLS cipher suite and wants to ensure that if the server's private key is later compromised, previously captured encrypted sessions cannot be decrypted. Which key exchange mechanism should be prioritized to achieve this property?","o":["Static RSA key exchange","Ephemeral Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman (ECDHE)","Pre-shared key (PSK) exchange","Kerberos-based key exchange"],"c":1,"why":"ECDHE generates unique ephemeral session keys for each session, providing Perfect Forward Secrecy so past sessions remain secure even if the long-term private key is later compromised. Static RSA key exchange lacks forward secrecy since all sessions rely on the same private key, PSK reuses a shared secret without forward secrecy, and Kerberos is an authentication protocol not typically used for TLS key exchange.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An inbound packet arrives at a firewall claiming to be part of an already-established TCP session, but no such session was ever initiated from inside the network. Which type of firewall is best equipped to detect and block this packet based on connection context?","o":["Static packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy without logging","Simple access control list on a router"],"c":1,"why":"A stateful inspection firewall maintains a state table of legitimate connections and can identify that the packet does not match any known session, rejecting it. Static packet filters and basic ACLs only examine header fields in isolation without tracking session state, so they cannot detect this discrepancy.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester successfully captures a WPA2-PSK four-way handshake and performs an offline dictionary attack to recover the pre-shared key. Which wireless security enhancement specifically addresses this class of offline attack by using a zero-knowledge proof during authentication?","o":["Enabling WPA2 with AES-CCMP instead of TKIP","Implementing WPA3-Personal with Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","Hiding the SSID and enabling MAC address filtering","Increasing the passphrase length while remaining on WPA2-PSK"],"c":1,"why":"WPA3's SAE handshake (based on the Dragonfly protocol) is resistant to offline dictionary attacks because it uses a zero-knowledge proof exchange rather than exposing a crackable handshake artifact. AES-CCMP alone, SSID hiding/MAC filtering, and longer WPA2 passphrases reduce but do not eliminate the fundamental offline-crack exposure inherent to the WPA2 handshake.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which security enhancement introduced in WPA3 specifically addresses the vulnerability of WPA2-Personal to offline dictionary attacks against weak pre-shared keys?","o":["Increased AES key length to 256 bits","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","Temporal Key Integrity Protocol (TKIP)","Mandatory use of 802.1X with RADIUS"],"c":1,"why":"SAE replaces the WPA2 four-way handshake with a Diffie-Hellman-based exchange that resists offline dictionary attacks by requiring interaction with the access point for each guess. TKIP is an older, weaker WPA1 mechanism, and 802.1X/RADIUS is used for enterprise authentication, not personal PSK networks.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization is redesigning its perimeter to host a public web application that must query a backend database on the internal network. Which architecture BEST minimizes the risk of a single compromised device providing an attacker a direct path from the Internet to the internal network?","o":["A single dual-homed firewall with three interfaces: external, DMZ, and internal, using one rule base","A screened subnet (DMZ) bounded by two separate firewalls from different vendors, with the web server in the DMZ and only the specific database port allowed from DMZ to internal","Placing the web server directly on the internal network and relying on host-based firewall rules","A single firewall with NAT overload translating all DMZ traffic to internal addresses"],"c":1,"why":"A screened subnet with two firewalls (ideally from different vendors to reduce common-mode failure) ensures that compromising the DMZ-facing firewall or the web server does not grant direct access to the internal network, since a second, independently configured firewall still must be bypassed. A single three-legged firewall, placing the server internally, or relying solely on host firewalls creates a single point of failure or exposes internal assets directly.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An administrator wants to logically isolate guest wireless traffic from internal servers at Layer 2 while still allowing controlled, limited communication between the two segments. Which solution best meets this requirement?","o":["Use Network Address Translation (NAT) between the segments","Create separate VLANs with inter-VLAN access control lists","Rely on IP subnetting alone without additional controls","Configure asymmetric routing paths for guest traffic"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs separate broadcast domains at Layer 2, and applying ACLs between VLANs allows granular control over what traffic is permitted, achieving isolation with selective communication. NAT operates at Layer 3 for address translation, not segmentation, and subnetting alone or asymmetric routing does not provide the same level of controlled isolation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A large ISP notices that traffic destined for one of its customer's IP prefixes is being rerouted through an unauthorized autonomous system, causing outages and potential interception. This is an example of BGP route hijacking. Which control provides cryptographic validation of route origin to prevent this?","o":["Implementing OSPF instead of BGP for inter-domain routing","Deploying Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI) with Route Origin Authorizations (ROAs)","Enabling split-horizon on all BGP-speaking routers","Filtering routes based solely on AS path length"],"c":1,"why":"RPKI allows prefix holders to cryptographically sign ROAs certifying which AS is authorized to originate a given prefix, enabling route origin validation and rejection of unauthorized announcements. OSPF is an interior gateway protocol not used between autonomous systems, split-horizon prevents routing loops (not hijacking), and AS-path length filtering does not validate legitimacy of the origin.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which technology helps mitigate DNS cache poisoning attacks by allowing resolvers to cryptographically verify the authenticity and integrity of DNS responses?","o":["DNSSEC","Split-horizon DNS","Round-robin DNS load balancing","Reverse DNS lookup validation"],"c":0,"why":"DNSSEC adds digital signatures to DNS records, allowing resolvers to verify that responses have not been forged or tampered with, directly mitigating cache poisoning. Split-horizon DNS and round-robin DNS address availability and internal/external views, not authenticity, and reverse lookups do not validate response integrity.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company deploying a VoIP system is concerned about eavesdropping on call content and manipulation of call setup messages. Which combination of protocols provides confidentiality for both signaling and media streams?","o":["RTP for media and plain SIP over UDP for signaling","SRTP for media and SIP over TLS (SIPS) for signaling","H.323 for signaling with no encryption on the media stream","SIP over TCP for signaling and RTP with no encryption for media"],"c":1,"why":"SRTP encrypts and authenticates the media (audio) stream, while SIP over TLS (SIPS) protects the signaling exchange that establishes and controls the call; together they secure both planes. The other options leave either signaling or media (or both) transmitted in cleartext, exposing them to interception or tampering.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization's public-facing DNS zone has been targeted by cache poisoning attacks that redirected users to malicious sites. Which technology should be implemented to allow resolvers to cryptographically verify that DNS responses have not been tampered with and genuinely originate from the authoritative zone?","o":["DNS over HTTPS (DoH) between the client and a trusted resolver","DNSSEC, using chained digital signatures (RRSIG records) validated up to a trust anchor","Split-horizon DNS separating internal and external zone views","Round-robin DNS load balancing across multiple authoritative servers"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC adds cryptographic signatures (RRSIG) to DNS records, allowing resolvers to validate authenticity and integrity of responses up a chain of trust to the root, directly countering cache poisoning and response forgery. DoH protects the transport channel to the resolver but not the authenticity of the zone data itself; split-horizon DNS and round-robin load balancing address visibility and availability, not data integrity.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A VoIP deployment uses SIP for call signaling. Which protocol should be implemented to protect the confidentiality of the actual voice media stream from eavesdropping?","o":["SIP over TLS","Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP)","H.323","RTCP with checksum verification"],"c":1,"why":"SRTP encrypts the media (voice) stream carried by RTP, protecting call content from interception. SIP over TLS secures only the signaling channel, while H.323 is an alternative signaling protocol and RTCP provides control statistics, neither of which encrypts the media payload.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A financial services company must encrypt traffic between two branch office gateways that communicate across the public Internet, and one of the gateways sits behind a NAT device performing port address translation. The traffic must have both confidentiality and integrity protection. Which IPsec configuration should the security architect select?","o":["AH in transport mode, since AH provides both encryption and integrity for the entire packet","ESP in tunnel mode with NAT-Traversal (NAT-T) enabled, since ESP encrypts the payload and NAT-T encapsulates ESP in UDP to survive address translation","AH in tunnel mode, since tunneling the original IP header preserves end-to-end integrity through NAT","ESP in transport mode without NAT-T, since transport mode is compatible with any intermediate NAT device"],"c":1,"why":"ESP provides confidentiality (unlike AH, which only provides integrity/authentication) and tunnel mode encapsulates the original packet; NAT-T wraps the ESP packet in UDP so checksums and header rewrites by NAT don't break the integrity check. AH fails with NAT because it authenticates the outer IP header, which NAT modifies, invalidating the ICV.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester on an internal engagement configures a rogue switch port to advertise itself as a trunk using DTP and then crafts Ethernet frames with two stacked 802.1Q tags. The outer tag matches the native VLAN of the trunk, and the inner tag matches a target VLAN the attacker is not authorized to access. What attack is being performed, and what is the underlying weakness being exploited?","o":["ARP cache poisoning; the weakness is that switches trust unauthenticated ARP replies","VLAN double-tagging (hopping); the weakness is that switches strip only the outer (native VLAN) tag on trunk ports and forward the frame with the remaining tag into the target VLAN","MAC flooding; the weakness is limited CAM table size causing the switch to fail open into hub mode","Spanning Tree topology change attack; the weakness is that switches automatically recalculate the STP topology when BPDUs are received"],"c":1,"why":"Double tagging exploits the fact that a trunk port strips only the outer tag matching the native VLAN and forwards the frame based on the remaining inner tag, allowing traffic to cross into a VLAN the attacker shouldn't reach without traversing a router. MAC flooding, ARP poisoning, and STP attacks are real but do not match this specific two-tag technique.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An attacker on a local network sends forged ARP replies associating their own MAC address with the default gateway's IP address, redirecting traffic through their machine. Which switch-based control most directly mitigates this attack?","o":["Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI)","Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)","Basic port security limiting MAC addresses per port","IPSec encryption between hosts"],"c":0,"why":"Dynamic ARP Inspection validates ARP packets against a trusted binding table (often built from DHCP snooping), dropping forged ARP replies before they can poison the ARP cache. STP prevents Layer 2 loops, port security limits the number of MACs per port but doesn't validate ARP content, and IPSec protects data in transit but does not prevent ARP spoofing itself.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which layer of the OSI model is primarily responsible for logical addressing and routing of packets between different networks?","o":["Data Link Layer","Network Layer","Transport Layer","Session Layer"],"c":1,"why":"The Network Layer (Layer 3) handles logical addressing (IP) and routing decisions between networks. The Data Link Layer handles physical addressing within a local segment, the Transport Layer manages end-to-end delivery, and the Session Layer manages dialogue control between applications.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization is migrating wireless infrastructure from WPA2-PSK to WPA3-Personal specifically to reduce the risk of offline dictionary attacks against captured handshake traffic. Which underlying mechanism in WPA3 provides this improvement over WPA2's four-way handshake?","o":["Use of AES-256 instead of AES-128 for the pairwise transient key","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE), a Diffie-Hellman-based handshake that provides forward secrecy and resists offline dictionary attacks even if the passphrase is weak","Mandatory 802.1X/EAP-TLS certificate authentication replacing pre-shared keys entirely","Use of a longer initialization vector in the CCMP encryption scheme"],"c":1,"why":"SAE (Dragonfly handshake) replaces WPA2's PSK four-way handshake and does not expose enough information in captured traffic to conduct an offline dictionary/brute-force attack on the passphrase, and it provides forward secrecy. WPA3-Personal still uses a passphrase (not certificates), and encryption key length changes alone don't address the handshake weakness.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the correct order of steps in the TCP three-way handshake used to establish a connection?","o":["SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK","SYN, ACK, FIN","ACK, SYN, SYN-ACK","SYN, FIN, ACK"],"c":0,"why":"TCP establishes a connection by the client sending SYN, the server responding with SYN-ACK, and the client completing with ACK. The other sequences either misorder the flags or include FIN, which is used to terminate rather than establish a connection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect deploys DNSSEC across the organization's authoritative name servers, signing zones and publishing RRSIG, DNSKEY, and DS records. Which of the following statements best describes what this control accomplishes?","o":["It encrypts DNS query and response traffic end-to-end, preventing eavesdroppers from seeing which domains a client resolves","It provides cryptographic authentication of DNS responses and protects against cache poisoning and response spoofing, but does not provide confidentiality of DNS traffic","It prevents DNS amplification attacks by rate-limiting recursive queries from any single source IP address","It replaces the need for TLS certificate validation by binding public keys directly to domain names in the DNS hierarchy"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC digitally signs DNS records so resolvers can validate authenticity and integrity, mitigating spoofing/cache poisoning, but it explicitly does not encrypt queries or responses (that's the role of DoH/DoT). It also does not directly mitigate amplification DDoS or replace certificate validation, though DANE can layer on top of it for the latter purpose.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A firewall that maintains a table of active connections and permits return traffic only if it matches an existing session is best described as which type of firewall?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Application-layer proxy firewall","Static packet firewall"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls track the state of active connections and use that context to make filtering decisions. Packet-filtering firewalls evaluate each packet independently without connection state, and application-layer proxies operate by fully terminating and re-establishing sessions rather than simply tracking state tables.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A cloud architecture team is redesigning a data center to reduce the blast radius of a compromised host and prevent unrestricted east-west movement between workloads that previously all resided on a single flat VLAN. Which approach most directly addresses this requirement?","o":["Deploying a next-generation firewall only at the data center's Internet-facing perimeter to inspect all inbound and outbound traffic","Implementing microsegmentation using host-based or hypervisor-level policy enforcement so that traffic between individual workloads is explicitly permitted rather than implicitly trusted","Increasing the number of VLANs while keeping inter-VLAN routing fully permitted by default on the core switch","Enabling Spanning Tree Protocol with BPDU guard on all access ports to prevent loop-based traffic amplification"],"c":1,"why":"Microsegmentation enforces granular, workload-level policies (often independent of underlying network topology) so lateral movement between hosts requires explicit authorization, directly limiting blast radius. A perimeter firewall does nothing for internal east-west traffic, adding VLANs without restricting inter-VLAN routing doesn't limit movement, and STP/BPDU guard addresses loop prevention, not segmentation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol suite is most commonly used to provide encryption, integrity, and authentication for VPN traffic at the network layer?","o":["IPsec","HTTP","SNMP","ARP"],"c":0,"why":"IPsec operates at the network layer and provides confidentiality, integrity, and authentication for VPN tunnels through protocols like ESP and AH. HTTP, SNMP, and ARP are not designed to provide VPN encryption services.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise is deploying VoIP across its WAN and wants to protect both the call setup process and the actual voice payload from eavesdropping and manipulation. Which combination of protocols correctly secures each respective component?","o":["IPsec for signaling and SSH for media transport","TLS to protect SIP signaling and SRTP to protect the RTP media stream","SNMPv3 for signaling authentication and MPLS labels for media confidentiality","802.1X for signaling authentication and VLAN tagging for media confidentiality"],"c":1,"why":"SIP is the signaling protocol used to establish, modify, and tear down VoIP sessions and is commonly secured with TLS, while RTP carries the actual audio/video payload and is secured with SRTP, which adds encryption and authentication to the media stream. The other pairings either misapply protocols outside their intended purpose (SSH, SNMP, 802.1X, VLANs) or provide no cryptographic protection for VoIP traffic specifically.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol replaced WEP and uses AES-based CCMP encryption to provide stronger confidentiality and integrity?","o":["WPA2","WEP","WPS","Open System Authentication"],"c":0,"why":"WPA2 introduced AES-CCMP, providing much stronger security than the deprecated WEP protocol. WPS is a configuration mechanism with known vulnerabilities, and Open System Authentication provides no encryption at all.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A network engineer observes that traffic destined for the organization's public IP prefix is suddenly being routed through an unfamiliar autonomous system in another country, causing outages and potential interception. Analysis shows another AS began advertising a more specific (longer prefix) route for the same address space. What is this attack called, and what control would most effectively have prevented it?","o":["ARP spoofing; implementing dynamic ARP inspection on all Layer 2 switches","BGP route/prefix hijacking; deploying RPKI (Resource Public Key Infrastructure) with Route Origin Authorizations to validate that only authorized ASes can originate the prefix","DNS cache poisoning; enabling DNSSEC validation on all recursive resolvers","SYN flood attack; deploying SYN cookies on edge routers"],"c":1,"why":"This describes BGP prefix hijacking, where a malicious or misconfigured AS advertises a more specific route to attract traffic; RPKI with ROAs cryptographically ties prefixes to their legitimate originating AS, allowing routers to reject unauthorized announcements. The other options address unrelated attack vectors at different layers (Layer 2 ARP spoofing, DNS resolution, or transport-layer flooding).","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which DNS record type is used to map a domain name to its corresponding IPv4 address?","o":["MX record","CNAME record","A record","PTR record"],"c":2,"why":"An A record maps a hostname to an IPv4 address. MX records specify mail servers, CNAME records create aliases, and PTR records are used for reverse lookups mapping an IP address back to a hostname.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"During encapsulation, a network device adds source and destination MAC address information to a frame before transmission on the local network segment. At which layer of the OSI model does this occur?","o":["Physical layer","Data Link layer","Network layer","Transport layer"],"c":1,"why":"MAC addressing and framing occur at the Data Link layer (Layer 2). The Physical layer deals with raw bit transmission, the Network layer uses IP addresses, and the Transport layer handles end-to-end delivery via ports/segments.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of Network Address Translation (NAT) in an enterprise network?","o":["To encrypt traffic leaving the internal network","To translate private internal IP addresses to a public IP address for external communication","To authenticate users before granting network access","To distribute traffic load across multiple servers"],"c":1,"why":"NAT allows multiple internal hosts using private IP addresses to share one or more public IP addresses when communicating externally, conserving public address space. NAT does not provide encryption, authentication, or load balancing functions.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company implementing 802.1X port-based network access control wants an EAP method that provides strong mutual authentication using digital certificates on both the supplicant and the authentication server, without relying on a username/password exchange that could be phished or replayed. Which EAP method best satisfies this requirement?","o":["EAP-MD5, since it uses a challenge-response hash to authenticate the client","PEAP with MS-CHAPv2, since it tunnels password-based authentication inside a TLS session","EAP-TLS, since it requires both client and server certificates, establishing mutual authentication via a full TLS handshake before network access is granted","LEAP, since it is Cisco's proprietary lightweight EAP method optimized for wireless mutual authentication"],"c":2,"why":"EAP-TLS requires certificates on both the supplicant and the RADIUS/authentication server, providing strong mutual authentication with no password exchanged over the network, making it resistant to credential phishing and replay. EAP-MD5 and LEAP are weak and vulnerable to offline attacks, and PEAP/MS-CHAPv2 still relies on password-based client authentication inside the TLS tunnel, not certificate-based mutual auth for the client.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization needs to establish a site-to-site connection across the Internet in which the entire original IP packet, including its header, is encrypted and encapsulated within a new IP packet. Which configuration achieves this?","o":["IPsec Transport mode","IPsec Tunnel mode","Authentication Header (AH) only","Generic Routing Encapsulation without IPsec"],"c":1,"why":"Tunnel mode encrypts the entire original IP packet and wraps it in a new IP header, making it ideal for site-to-site VPNs. Transport mode only encrypts the payload and leaves the original IP header exposed, AH alone provides no confidentiality, and plain GRE offers no encryption at all.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security engineer is selecting a firewall that must make filtering decisions based on the context of an established connection, such as tracking TCP sequence numbers and connection status, rather than evaluating each packet in isolation. Which firewall type best meets this requirement?","o":["Static packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Screening router with ACLs only","Layer 2 bridging firewall"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls maintain a state table of active connections and evaluate packets in the context of the session. Static packet filters and simple ACL-based screening routers evaluate each packet independently without connection awareness, and a Layer 2 bridging firewall focuses on frame forwarding rather than session state.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which TCP flag combination is used to initiate the first step of the standard three-way handshake?","o":["SYN","SYN-ACK","ACK","FIN"],"c":0,"why":"The three-way handshake begins with the client sending a SYN packet; the server responds with SYN-ACK, and the client completes it with ACK. FIN is used to terminate a connection, not establish one.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which feature introduced in WPA3 specifically improves resistance to offline dictionary attacks against pre-shared key authentication compared to WPA2?","o":["AES-CCMP encryption","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","TKIP key mixing","Mandatory 802.1X port-based authentication"],"c":1,"why":"SAE replaces the WPA2 four-way handshake and uses a Diffie-Hellman-based exchange that prevents offline dictionary attacks by requiring interaction with the access point for each guess. AES-CCMP was already used in WPA2, TKIP is an older and weaker WPA mechanism, and 802.1X is used for enterprise authentication, not PSK protection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator wants a device that can filter traffic based on source/destination IP, port, and protocol, but does not track the state of connections. Which type of firewall is this?","o":["Stateful inspection firewall","Packet-filtering firewall","Application-layer proxy firewall","Next-generation firewall"],"c":1,"why":"A packet-filtering firewall makes decisions per-packet using header information without maintaining connection state, unlike stateful firewalls which track session state and proxies/NGFWs which inspect application-layer content.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An attacker on a local network sends forged ARP replies claiming their MAC address corresponds to the IP address of the default gateway. What is the primary security consequence of this attack?","o":["Exhaustion of available IP addresses on the subnet","Interception of traffic intended for the legitimate gateway","Corruption of the DNS resolver cache","Overflow of the switch's MAC address table"],"c":1,"why":"ARP spoofing redirects traffic meant for the gateway to the attacker's machine, enabling a man-in-the-middle attack. It does not cause IP exhaustion, DNS cache poisoning, or MAC table overflow, which are distinct attack types.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol is commonly used to create a secure, encrypted tunnel for remote access VPN connections by encapsulating IP packets and providing confidentiality and integrity?","o":["IPSec","SNMP","ARP","Telnet"],"c":0,"why":"IPSec provides encryption, authentication, and integrity for VPN tunnels at the network layer. SNMP is for network management, ARP resolves IP to MAC addresses, and Telnet is an unencrypted remote access protocol.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network administrator wants to logically isolate broadcast traffic for different departments that share the same physical switch, without requiring separate physical hardware for each department. Which technology best accomplishes this?","o":["Subnetting without additional configuration","Virtual LAN (VLAN) segmentation","Network Address Translation (NAT)","Port security with MAC filtering"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs create separate logical broadcast domains on the same physical switch, isolating traffic between departments. Subnetting alone doesn't stop broadcasts on a shared switch, NAT translates addresses rather than segmenting broadcast domains, and port security restricts which MAC addresses can use a port but doesn't create logical network separation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol replaced WEP and WPA to address their cryptographic weaknesses by mandating AES-based CCMP encryption?","o":["WPA2","WPA3-Personal only","WEP2","TKIP"],"c":0,"why":"WPA2 introduced mandatory AES-CCMP encryption, fixing WEP's weak RC4 implementation and WPA's TKIP limitations. TKIP is an encryption method used in WPA, not a full protocol, and 'WEP2' is not a recognized standard.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"What is the primary security benefit that DNSSEC provides over standard DNS?","o":["Encryption of DNS query and response traffic to prevent eavesdropping","Data origin authentication and integrity verification of DNS responses","Automatic rate limiting to prevent DNS server overload","Secure dynamic assignment of IP addresses to hosts"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to authenticate the origin and verify the integrity of DNS records, protecting against cache poisoning and spoofing. It does not encrypt DNS traffic (that is the role of DNS over TLS/HTTPS), and it has no relation to rate limiting or DHCP-style address assignment.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization segments its network so that finance workstations cannot directly communicate with the marketing department's workstations, even though both connect to the same physical switch. What technology most likely enables this separation?","o":["Spanning Tree Protocol","Virtual LAN (VLAN)","Network Address Translation (NAT)","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs logically segment a single physical switch into separate broadcast domains, isolating traffic between departments. STP prevents loops, NAT translates addresses, and ARP resolves IP-to-MAC mappings—none provide logical segmentation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company deploys a public-facing web server in a DMZ instead of placing it directly on the internal corporate network. What is the primary security rationale for this design?","o":["It improves the server's response time for external users","It limits the impact on the internal network if the server is compromised","It automatically load-balances traffic across multiple servers","It allows the server to have direct, unrestricted access to internal databases"],"c":1,"why":"A DMZ isolates publicly accessible systems from the internal network, so that if the exposed server is compromised, the attacker's access to internal resources is limited by additional firewall boundaries. The other options describe unrelated benefits or actually contradict good DMZ design, which should restrict rather than grant direct internal access.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to segment its network so that a compromise on one VLAN cannot easily be used to attack hosts on another VLAN without explicit routing controls. Which device is required to allow controlled communication between two separate VLANs?","o":["A Layer 2 switch with trunking enabled","A router or Layer 3 switch performing inter-VLAN routing","A hub connecting both VLANs","A network tap mirroring traffic between VLANs"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs are broadcast domains isolated at Layer 2; traffic between VLANs must be routed at Layer 3, allowing security controls (ACLs, firewalls) to be applied. A Layer 2 switch or hub cannot route between separate VLANs, and a tap only copies traffic for monitoring.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which DNS record type is used to map a domain name to an IPv4 address?","o":["MX record","A record","CNAME record","TXT record"],"c":1,"why":"An A record maps a hostname to an IPv4 address. MX records specify mail servers, CNAME records create aliases to other domain names, and TXT records store arbitrary text data such as SPF entries.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"During a review of IPsec configurations, a security engineer notes that a VPN tunnel uses ESP in tunnel mode. What security benefit does this configuration provide that AH in transport mode does not?","o":["Authentication of the outer IP header only","Confidentiality (encryption) of the entire original IP packet","Non-repudiation of the sender using digital signatures","Prevention of replay attacks through sequence numbers"],"c":1,"why":"ESP provides encryption (confidentiality) in addition to integrity, and tunnel mode encapsulates and encrypts the entire original IP packet including headers. AH provides authentication and integrity but no encryption, so it cannot provide confidentiality; replay protection and header authentication are features of both AH and ESP, not the distinguishing benefit here.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which network topology is most susceptible to a single point of failure that can disrupt communication for the entire network if that one component fails?","o":["Mesh topology","Star topology","Ring topology (dual counter-rotating)","Fully redundant mesh"],"c":1,"why":"In a star topology, all nodes connect to a central device (e.g., a switch); if that central device fails, the entire network segment loses connectivity. Mesh and redundant ring designs provide multiple paths, reducing single points of failure.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company deploys 802.1X port-based network access control on its wired switches. What is the primary security benefit of this implementation?","o":["It encrypts all traffic traversing the switch ports","It prevents unauthorized devices from obtaining network access until they are authenticated","It eliminates the need for VLAN segmentation","It provides intrusion detection for traffic on the port"],"c":1,"why":"802.1X enforces authentication before granting a device access to the network at the port level, blocking unauthorized devices. It does not encrypt traffic, replace VLAN segmentation, or perform intrusion detection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A packet-filtering firewall makes decisions to permit or deny traffic based primarily on which of the following?","o":["Application-layer content inspection","Source/destination IP address, port, and protocol","User identity and authentication credentials","Encrypted payload analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Packet-filtering firewalls inspect header information such as IP addresses, ports, and protocol type without examining payload content. Application inspection, user identity checks, and payload decryption are capabilities of more advanced firewalls (e.g., next-gen or proxy firewalls).","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization's wireless network was upgraded from WPA2 to WPA3. Which specific improvement does WPA3 provide over WPA2 to protect against offline dictionary attacks on the pre-shared key?","o":["Use of the RC4 stream cipher for encryption","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) replacing the four-way handshake","Mandatory use of 802.1X for all authentication","Elimination of the need for a pre-shared key entirely"],"c":1,"why":"WPA3 uses SAE (based on Diffie-Hellman) instead of the WPA2 four-way handshake, which resists offline dictionary attacks because each authentication attempt requires interaction with the access point. WPA3 does not use RC4, does not mandate 802.1X for personal mode, and still supports pre-shared keys in WPA3-Personal.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect must design a site-to-site VPN between two data centers, one of which sits behind a NAT device performed by the ISP. The design requires confidentiality, integrity, and compatibility with NAT traversal. Which IPsec configuration should be selected?","o":["AH in transport mode","AH in tunnel mode","ESP in transport mode without NAT-T","ESP in tunnel mode with NAT-T (UDP encapsulation)"],"c":3,"why":"ESP provides confidentiality (which AH does not), and tunnel mode with NAT-T encapsulates ESP in UDP so the modified IP header from NAT does not break the integrity check; AH fails through NAT because its ICV covers the IP header, and transport mode alone does not resolve the NAT/IP-header issue.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which IPsec mode encrypts only the payload of an IP packet while leaving the original IP header intact, making it suitable for end-to-end communication between two hosts?","o":["Tunnel mode","Transport mode","Aggressive mode","Main mode"],"c":1,"why":"Transport mode encrypts only the payload and leaves the original IP header exposed, ideal for host-to-host communication. Tunnel mode encrypts the entire packet including the header, and aggressive/main mode relate to IKE key exchange phases, not payload encryption scope.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network administrator is comparing firewall technologies. Which type of firewall makes filtering decisions by maintaining a table of active connections and evaluating whether packets belong to an established, legitimate session?","o":["Static packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Application-layer proxy firewall","Circuit-level gateway"],"c":1,"why":"A stateful inspection firewall tracks the state of active connections in a state table and uses that context to filter packets, improving on simple packet filters. Static packet filters examine each packet independently without context, application proxies operate by fully terminating and inspecting application-layer sessions, and circuit-level gateways validate sessions at the transport layer without deep state tracking of packet context in the same way.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol introduced Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) to replace the vulnerable four-way handshake used in its predecessor?","o":["WEP","WPA","WPA2","WPA3"],"c":3,"why":"WPA3 introduced SAE, a more secure key exchange method that resists offline dictionary attacks, replacing the PSK four-way handshake used in WPA2. WEP and WPA are older, weaker protocols that do not use SAE.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester successfully performs a VLAN hopping attack using 802.1Q double tagging against a switched network. Which switch configuration change is MOST effective at preventing this specific attack?","o":["Enable Dynamic Trunking Protocol (DTP) on all access ports","Configure the native VLAN on trunk ports to an unused VLAN ID that is not assigned to any access port","Increase the number of VLANs supported on the switch","Enable Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol on all trunk links"],"c":1,"why":"Double-tagging attacks exploit the native VLAN being untagged on trunks and matching a VLAN in use; assigning trunk native VLANs to an unused, dedicated VLAN prevents the outer tag from being stripped into a live VLAN. Enabling DTP actually increases risk by allowing rogue trunk negotiation, and STP/VLAN count are unrelated to this attack vector.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst is investigating suspicious DNS traffic and recommends implementing DNSSEC. What primary security problem does DNSSEC address?","o":["Encryption of DNS query and response contents to ensure confidentiality","Cryptographic validation of DNS responses to prevent spoofing and cache poisoning","Prevention of distributed denial-of-service attacks against DNS servers","Reduction of DNS query latency through response caching"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC adds digital signatures to DNS records so resolvers can verify the authenticity and integrity of responses, mitigating spoofing and cache poisoning. It does not encrypt DNS traffic (that is DoH/DoT), does not specifically prevent DDoS, and is unrelated to caching performance.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to reduce the size of collision domains on its local area network. Which device should be used to replace a legacy hub?","o":["Repeater","Switch","Modem","Bridge (single-port)"],"c":1,"why":"A switch creates a separate collision domain for each port, significantly reducing collisions compared to a hub, where all devices share one collision domain. Repeaters and modems do not segment collision domains, and a single-port bridge would not provide meaningful segmentation across multiple hosts.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization is upgrading its wireless infrastructure and wants a protocol that provides resistance to offline dictionary attacks against the pre-shared key and forward secrecy for each session, even if the passphrase is later compromised. Which technology should be implemented?","o":["WPA2-PSK with a strong 4-way handshake","WPA3-Personal using Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","WEP with a rotating shared key","Open authentication with a captive portal"],"c":1,"why":"WPA3's SAE handshake is based on a Diffie-Hellman derivative that prevents offline brute-forcing of captured handshake data and provides forward secrecy per session. WPA2's 4-way handshake is vulnerable to offline dictionary attacks against captured frames, and WEP/open authentication offer no meaningful cryptographic protection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An architect is designing a network using Software-Defined Networking (SDN). From a security perspective, what is a primary concern that must be addressed regarding the SDN controller?","o":["The controller cannot support encrypted communications with switches","The controller represents a centralized point of control whose compromise could affect the entire network's forwarding behavior","The controller eliminates the need for network segmentation entirely","The controller only operates at Layer 1 and cannot enforce Layer 3 policies"],"c":1,"why":"The SDN controller centrally manages forwarding logic for the network; compromising it could allow an attacker to manipulate traffic across the entire infrastructure, making it a critical single point of failure requiring strong protection. SDN controllers can support encrypted southbound protocols (e.g., OpenFlow over TLS), do not eliminate segmentation needs, and operate above Layer 1.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which network service is responsible for translating human-readable domain names, such as example.com, into IP addresses?","o":["DHCP","ARP","DNS","SNMP"],"c":2,"why":"DNS (Domain Name System) resolves domain names to IP addresses. DHCP assigns IP addresses to devices, ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses, and SNMP is used for network device management, not name resolution.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company wants to protect its DNS infrastructure against cache poisoning by ensuring that resolvers can cryptographically verify that DNS responses originated from the authoritative source and were not altered in transit or at rest in a resolver's cache. Which technology directly addresses this requirement?","o":["DNS over TLS (DoT) between the client and resolver","DNSSEC using a chain of trust with RRSIG and DNSKEY records","Split-horizon DNS with separate internal and external views","DNS sinkholing of known malicious domains"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC cryptographically signs zone data, allowing resolvers to validate authenticity and integrity of records regardless of where the data is cached or how it was transported, directly mitigating cache poisoning. DoT only encrypts the transport channel between client and resolver and does not validate the origin of the zone data itself, while split-horizon DNS and sinkholing address different problems.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A large ISP wants to prevent a downstream customer's misconfigured router from announcing an unauthorized route that hijacks traffic destined for another organization's IP block. Which technology should be deployed to validate that a BGP route announcement is authorized by the legitimate address space holder?","o":["MD5 authentication on BGP peering sessions","Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI) with Route Origin Authorizations (ROAs)","BGP route reflectors to reduce iBGP mesh complexity","OSPF area authentication"],"c":1,"why":"RPKI ROAs cryptographically bind an AS number to the address prefixes it is authorized to originate, allowing routers to validate route origin and reject hijacked announcements. MD5 session authentication only protects the BGP session itself from tampering, not the validity of announced routes, and route reflectors/OSPF authentication address unrelated routing scalability or interior routing concerns.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization uses a single public IP address to allow multiple internal devices on a private network to access the Internet. Which technology enables this?","o":["VLAN tagging","Network Address Translation (NAT)","Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)"],"c":1,"why":"NAT allows multiple internal private IP addresses to share a single public IP address by translating and tracking connections, commonly implemented as PAT (Port Address Translation). VLAN tagging segments broadcast domains, STP prevents Layer 2 loops, and ARP resolves IP-to-MAC mappings, none of which perform address translation for Internet access.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise is deploying a VoIP system and requires confidentiality and integrity for both call signaling and the media stream carrying voice data. Which combination of protocols BEST satisfies this requirement?","o":["RTP for media and SIP over UDP for signaling","SRTP for media and SIPS (SIP over TLS) for signaling","H.323 in cleartext for both signaling and media","VLAN segmentation of voice traffic without additional encryption"],"c":1,"why":"SRTP encrypts and authenticates the media stream while SIPS/TLS protects the signaling exchange, together securing both control and payload channels of a VoIP call. Plain RTP/SIP and H.323 transmit in cleartext, and VLAN segmentation alone provides isolation but no cryptographic protection against interception.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A network architect is comparing a screened subnet (DMZ) architecture using two firewalls in series to a single firewall with multiple interfaces hosting the DMZ and internal network. What is the PRIMARY security advantage of the dual-firewall screened subnet design?","o":["It reduces the number of devices that must be patched and maintained","It eliminates the need for intrusion detection systems within the DMZ","It provides defense in depth, so compromise of the external-facing firewall does not directly expose the internal network","It allows unrestricted traffic flow between the DMZ and internal network for performance"],"c":2,"why":"A dual-firewall design ensures that even if the outer firewall is compromised, the attacker still must bypass a second, independently configured firewall to reach the internal network, providing defense in depth. The single-firewall approach relies on one device and one rule set, creating a single point of failure; the other options describe operational or performance claims rather than the core security benefit.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization's network engineer needs to select a device that makes forwarding decisions based on MAC addresses and operates primarily at the Data Link layer. Which device is most appropriate?","o":["Switch","Router","Layer 3 firewall","Proxy server"],"c":0,"why":"Switches operate at Layer 2 and forward frames based on MAC addresses. Routers and Layer 3 firewalls make decisions based on IP addresses (Layer 3), and proxy servers operate at the application layer.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements 802.1X port-based authentication on its wired switches but experiences an incident where an authenticated but malware-infected laptop spreads ransomware across the network. Which control would have MOST effectively addressed this gap?","o":["Enabling MAC address filtering in addition to 802.1X","Deploying Network Access Control (NAC) with posture/health assessment to evaluate endpoint compliance before granting full network access","Increasing the 802.1X re-authentication interval","Replacing 802.1X with WPA2-Enterprise on the wired network"],"c":1,"why":"802.1X verifies identity but not device health; NAC posture assessment checks patch level, antivirus status, and configuration compliance before granting or restricting network access, addressing infected-but-authenticated endpoints. MAC filtering is easily spoofed and does not assess health, re-authentication timing doesn't evaluate compliance, and WPA2-Enterprise is a wireless encryption/authentication standard not applicable to wired ports in this context.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to encrypt only the payload of IP packets while preserving the original IP header for internal routing between two hosts on the same trusted network. Which IPsec mode should be used?","o":["Tunnel mode","Transport mode","Authentication Header mode only","Encapsulating Security Payload in tunnel mode"],"c":1,"why":"Transport mode encrypts only the payload and leaves the original IP header intact, suitable for host-to-host communication. Tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original packet (including header) inside a new IP packet, typically used for gateway-to-gateway communication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing network segmentation to limit broadcast traffic and isolate departments logically without requiring physical separation of switches. Which technology best achieves this?","o":["Subnetting alone","VLANs","Port security","Spanning Tree Protocol"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs logically segment a network at Layer 2, reducing broadcast domains and isolating traffic between groups without needing separate physical infrastructure. Subnetting operates at Layer 3 and doesn't inherently control broadcast domains at Layer 2; port security and STP serve different purposes (device authentication and loop prevention, respectively).","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which wireless security enhancement introduced in WPA3 specifically protects against offline dictionary attacks on the pre-shared key by using a more secure key exchange method?","o":["TKIP","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","WEP with 128-bit keys","Open System Authentication"],"c":1,"why":"SAE, based on the Dragonfly handshake, replaces WPA2's PSK four-way handshake and resists offline dictionary attacks. TKIP is an older WPA1 encryption protocol with known weaknesses, WEP is deprecated and insecure, and Open System Authentication provides no real authentication.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A firewall administrator wants a device that can track the state of active connections and permit return traffic automatically, while a separate control point inspects and filters traffic at the application layer for protocols like HTTP. Which combination best describes this architecture?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall paired with an intrusion detection system","Stateful inspection firewall paired with an application-layer proxy","Circuit-level gateway paired with a stateless packet filter","Two stateless packet filters in series"],"c":1,"why":"A stateful inspection firewall tracks session state, while an application-layer (proxy) firewall inspects payload content for specific protocols. Packet filters and circuit-level gateways don't perform deep application inspection, and stateless filters don't track connection state.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the purpose of the TCP three-way handshake?","o":["To encrypt data before transmission","To establish a reliable connection between two hosts before data transfer","To translate domain names into IP addresses","To assign an IP address to a host dynamically"],"c":1,"why":"The SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK sequence establishes and synchronizes a reliable TCP connection between two hosts. Encryption, name resolution, and IP assignment are unrelated functions handled by TLS, DNS, and DHCP respectively.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that DNS responses received by its resolvers have not been tampered with in transit and that the resolver can verify the authenticity of the response's origin. Which technology should be implemented?","o":["DNS over HTTPS (DoH)","Split-horizon DNS","DNSSEC","Round-robin DNS load balancing"],"c":2,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to provide data origin authentication and integrity for DNS responses, protecting against cache poisoning and spoofing. DoH encrypts DNS traffic in transit but doesn't validate origin authenticity of records; split-horizon DNS and round-robin DNS serve availability/administrative purposes, not integrity.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A firewall that tracks the state of active connections and makes filtering decisions based on the context of traffic (such as whether a packet belongs to an established session) is known as a:","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy","Application-level gateway"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls maintain a state table of active connections and use that context to filter traffic. Simple packet filters only examine individual packets, and while proxies operate at the circuit or application layer, statefulness specifically defines this connection-tracking behavior.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company needs to establish a secure connection between two branch office gateways over the public Internet. The requirement is to encrypt the entire original IP packet, including its header, and provide data confidentiality, integrity, and authentication for site-to-site traffic. Which IPSec configuration satisfies this requirement?","o":["AH in transport mode","ESP in transport mode","ESP in tunnel mode","AH in tunnel mode"],"c":2,"why":"ESP in tunnel mode encrypts and authenticates the entire original IP packet, encapsulating it within a new IP header, providing confidentiality plus integrity. AH provides no encryption/confidentiality, and transport mode only protects the payload, leaving the original header exposed.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"During a security assessment, an analyst discovers that an attacker on the local subnet sent unsolicited replies mapping the default gateway's IP address to the attacker's own MAC address, causing victim traffic to be redirected through the attacker's machine. What type of attack is this?","o":["DNS cache poisoning","ARP spoofing","IP address spoofing","VLAN hopping"],"c":1,"why":"ARP spoofing involves sending forged ARP replies to associate an attacker's MAC address with a legitimate IP (often the gateway), enabling man-in-the-middle attacks. DNS cache poisoning targets name resolution, IP spoofing forges source addresses, and VLAN hopping exploits trunking misconfigurations.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol suite is most commonly used to create secure, encrypted VPN tunnels at the network layer for site-to-site connections?","o":["IPsec","SNMP","FTP","ARP"],"c":0,"why":"IPsec provides encryption, integrity, and authentication for IP packets, making it the standard choice for site-to-site VPNs. SNMP is for network management, FTP for file transfer, and ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses—none provide VPN encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A web server is experiencing a SYN flood attack that is exhausting its connection table by leaving numerous half-open TCP connections. Which mitigation allows the server to avoid allocating state for a connection until the handshake is verified as legitimate?","o":["Increasing the SYN backlog queue size","Enabling TCP keepalive probes","Implementing SYN cookies","Reducing the TCP retransmission timeout"],"c":2,"why":"SYN cookies encode connection state cryptographically within the SYN-ACK sequence number, so the server need not reserve resources until it receives a valid ACK confirming the cookie. Increasing the backlog only delays exhaustion, keepalives address idle connections, and retransmission timeout changes don't prevent resource exhaustion from spoofed SYNs.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company is migrating its voice communications to VoIP over the same network as data traffic. Which control specifically helps protect the confidentiality of voice conversations from network eavesdropping?","o":["Quality of Service (QoS) tagging","Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP)","Spanning Tree Protocol","Network Address Translation (NAT)"],"c":1,"why":"SRTP encrypts the actual voice/media stream, protecting confidentiality against eavesdropping. QoS prioritizes traffic for performance, STP prevents Layer 2 loops, and NAT translates addresses but provides no encryption of media content.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution deploying WPA2-Enterprise wants mutual, certificate-based authentication between wireless clients and the authentication server, without ever transmitting a shared secret or password hash over the air. Which EAP method should be selected?","o":["LEAP","PEAP-MSCHAPv2","EAP-FAST","EAP-TLS"],"c":3,"why":"EAP-TLS requires digital certificates on both the client and server, achieving mutual authentication without transmitting passwords or shared secrets. PEAP-MSCHAPv2 authenticates the client via a password hash inside a server-authenticated tunnel, EAP-FAST relies on a shared PAC rather than client certificates, and LEAP uses weak password-based authentication vulnerable to offline attack.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Why is WPA2 considered more secure than WEP for wireless network protection?","o":["WPA2 uses a static encryption key shared by all devices","WPA2 uses AES-based encryption with stronger key management","WPA2 disables encryption to speed up transmission","WPA2 relies solely on MAC address filtering for security"],"c":1,"why":"WPA2 uses AES (via CCMP) with dynamic key management, addressing the weak RC4 encryption and static key vulnerabilities of WEP. The other options misrepresent WPA2's design or describe weaknesses of WEP itself.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A network engineer is concerned about VLAN hopping attacks using 802.1Q double-tagging on trunk links between switches. Which control most directly mitigates this specific attack technique?","o":["Enabling Dynamic Trunking Protocol (DTP) on all switch ports","Configuring an unused VLAN as the native VLAN on trunk ports and disabling automatic trunk negotiation","Enabling Spanning Tree PortFast on all access ports","Limiting the number of MAC addresses learned per switch port"],"c":1,"why":"Double-tagging attacks exploit the native VLAN being untagged on trunks; assigning an unused, dedicated VLAN as native and disabling DTP prevents the outer tag from being stripped and forwarded into another VLAN. Enabling DTP actually increases risk of switch spoofing, PortFast addresses STP convergence on edge ports, and MAC limiting addresses CAM table attacks, not tagging exploitation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security benefit of segmenting a network into multiple VLANs?","o":["It increases the physical distance between devices","It eliminates the need for firewalls entirely","It reduces broadcast traffic and limits the scope of a compromise to a single segment","It automatically encrypts all traffic between VLANs"],"c":2,"why":"VLANs logically separate broadcast domains, containing traffic and limiting lateral movement if one segment is compromised. VLANs do not provide encryption, do not affect physical distance, and do not replace firewalls, which are still needed for inter-VLAN traffic control.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements DNSSEC across its authoritative name servers. Which security risk does this control primarily address?","o":["DNS query content confidentiality from network eavesdroppers","DNS cache poisoning and response spoofing through cryptographic validation of records","DNS amplification-based distributed denial-of-service attacks","Unauthorized zone transfer disclosure to external hosts"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC digitally signs zone data, allowing resolvers to cryptographically validate that responses originated from the legitimate zone and were not altered in transit, directly countering cache poisoning and spoofing. It does not encrypt query contents (that requires DoT/DoH), does not inherently stop amplification DDoS, and zone transfer protection requires separate access controls like TSIG or ACLs.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"What is the key functional difference between an Intrusion Detection System (IDS) and an Intrusion Prevention System (IPS)?","o":["An IDS can block malicious traffic in real time, while an IPS can only alert administrators","An IPS can actively block or prevent malicious traffic, while an IDS only monitors and alerts","An IDS operates only on encrypted traffic, while an IPS cannot inspect encrypted traffic","There is no functional difference; the terms are interchangeable"],"c":1,"why":"An IPS sits in-line with traffic and can actively block malicious activity, whereas an IDS is typically passive, only detecting and alerting on suspicious activity without blocking it. The other options reverse the definitions or incorrectly claim no distinction exists.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect requires a firewall that relays TCP sessions between internal clients and external servers at the transport layer, terminating the client connection and establishing a separate connection to the destination, without inspecting or understanding application-layer protocol data. Which firewall type meets this requirement?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy firewall","Application-level proxy firewall"],"c":2,"why":"A circuit-level proxy (e.g., SOCKS-based) relays sessions at the transport layer, hiding internal topology by creating a separate outbound connection, without parsing application payloads. Application-level proxies inspect and understand application protocols, stateful inspection firewalls track connection state but do not relay/terminate sessions themselves, and packet filters make decisions purely on header fields without session relay.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network engineer is troubleshooting a device that forwards traffic based solely on destination IP addresses and maintains a routing table to determine the best path between networks. At which layer of the OSI model does this device primarily operate?","o":["Data Link Layer (Layer 2)","Network Layer (Layer 3)","Transport Layer (Layer 4)","Session Layer (Layer 5)"],"c":1,"why":"Routers make forwarding decisions based on logical (IP) addressing and routing tables, which is a Layer 3 function. Layer 2 devices (switches) use MAC addresses, Layer 4 deals with end-to-end connections/ports, and Layer 5 manages sessions.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization's web server is experiencing a flood of TCP SYN packets from spoofed source addresses, exhausting the connection table before the three-way handshake completes. Which mitigation technique is MOST effective against this specific attack?","o":["Implementing SYN cookies on the server","Enabling port security on the access switch","Deploying a reverse proxy with URL filtering","Increasing the MTU size on the network interface"],"c":0,"why":"SYN cookies allow the server to avoid allocating resources for a connection until the handshake completes, mitigating SYN flood attacks without maintaining state for half-open connections. Port security addresses MAC-based attacks, URL filtering doesn't address the transport-layer flood, and MTU size is unrelated.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise is implementing a zero trust network architecture using software-defined networking to enforce microsegmentation across its data center workloads. What is the primary security benefit of this approach?","o":["It enforces granular, identity- and context-based access policies between individual workloads regardless of their physical or network location","It eliminates the need for encryption of east-west traffic between segmented workloads","It replaces the need for host-based firewalls and endpoint controls entirely","It increases available network bandwidth through automated traffic engineering"],"c":0,"why":"Microsegmentation applies fine-grained, policy-based controls to traffic between individual workloads (east-west traffic), significantly limiting lateral movement even within the same subnet, which is the core zero trust benefit. It does not eliminate the need for encryption or host-based controls, and bandwidth optimization is not its security purpose.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company needs to establish a site-to-site connection between two branch offices over the public Internet, encrypting the entire original IP packet including headers to hide internal addressing from outside observers. Which IPsec mode should be implemented?","o":["Transport mode with ESP","Tunnel mode with ESP","Transport mode with AH","Tunnel mode with AH"],"c":1,"why":"Tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original IP packet (header and payload) inside a new IP packet, and ESP provides encryption plus authentication, concealing internal addressing—ideal for site-to-site VPNs. Transport mode only protects the payload, and AH alone does not provide confidentiality/encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A VoIP infrastructure is being targeted by an attacker who floods the SIP proxy server with a high volume of INVITE requests using spoofed source IP addresses, causing the server to exhaust resources tracking pending call setups. This attack is best classified as which of the following?","o":["ARP cache poisoning","Vishing","RTP media stream hijacking","SIP INVITE flood denial-of-service"],"c":3,"why":"A SIP INVITE flood is a signaling-layer DoS attack analogous to a TCP SYN flood, overwhelming the proxy's call-state resources with spoofed, unanswered session initiation requests. ARP poisoning operates at the data link layer, vishing is a social-engineering voice phishing technique, and RTP hijacking targets the media stream rather than session establishment signaling.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A penetration tester connects a laptop to an access port on a switch and sends double-tagged 802.1Q frames to reach a VLAN that should be isolated from the access port's native VLAN. What attack technique is being demonstrated?","o":["ARP poisoning","MAC flooding","VLAN hopping via double tagging","DHCP starvation"],"c":2,"why":"Double-tagging exploits how some switches process nested 802.1Q tags, allowing traffic to hop from a native VLAN to a normally restricted VLAN—this is VLAN hopping. ARP poisoning targets address resolution, MAC flooding overwhelms CAM tables, and DHCP starvation exhausts IP address leases.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which enhancement introduced in WPA3 directly addresses the vulnerability of offline dictionary attacks against the four-way handshake found in WPA2-Personal?","o":["Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) in CCMP mode","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","Temporal Key Integrity Protocol (TKIP)","Pre-Shared Key (PSK) rotation every 24 hours"],"c":1,"why":"SAE (based on the Dragonfly handshake) replaces the WPA2 PSK four-way handshake and is resistant to offline dictionary attacks because each authentication attempt requires interaction with the network. AES/CCMP is an encryption cipher, TKIP is a legacy WPA mechanism, and PSK rotation doesn't address the handshake vulnerability itself.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security architect wants a firewall that validates the legitimacy of a TCP session by verifying the three-way handshake sequence and tracking connection states, without inspecting application-layer payload content. Which firewall type BEST fits this requirement?","o":["Application-layer proxy firewall","Packet-filtering firewall","Circuit-level gateway (stateful inspection)","Web application firewall (WAF)"],"c":2,"why":"A stateful/circuit-level firewall tracks the state of connections (including handshake validity) at the transport layer without inspecting application payloads. Packet filtering firewalls are stateless, application proxies and WAFs inspect payload/application data.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A network administrator wants to segment traffic so that hosts in the HR department cannot directly communicate with hosts in the Engineering department, even though both are connected to the same physical switch. Which technology best achieves this?","o":["Spanning Tree Protocol","Virtual LAN (VLAN)","Address Resolution Protocol","Simple Network Management Protocol"],"c":1,"why":"VLANs logically segment a physical switch into separate broadcast domains, isolating traffic between departments. STP prevents loops, ARP resolves IP to MAC addresses, and SNMP is used for network management, none of which provide logical segmentation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Which technology should an organization deploy to protect against DNS cache poisoning by allowing resolvers to cryptographically verify the authenticity and integrity of DNS responses?","o":["DNS over HTTPS (DoH)","Split-horizon DNS","DNSSEC","Round-robin DNS load balancing"],"c":2,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to allow resolvers to verify that DNS responses are authentic and unaltered, directly mitigating cache poisoning. DoH encrypts the transport channel but doesn't authenticate response origin/integrity the same way, split-horizon DNS serves different views internally/externally, and round-robin DNS is a load-balancing technique unrelated to integrity.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol is primarily responsible for translating a domain name such as example.com into an IP address?","o":["DHCP","DNS","ARP","ICMP"],"c":1,"why":"DNS (Domain Name System) resolves human-readable domain names to IP addresses. DHCP assigns IP addresses, ARP resolves IP to MAC addresses on a local network, and ICMP is used for diagnostic messaging like ping.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is troubleshooting an IPsec site-to-site VPN that fails intermittently whenever traffic transits a NAT device between the two gateways. The tunnel is configured to use AH exclusively, with no ESP. What is the most likely root cause of the failure?","o":["AH does not support encryption, so the NAT device rejects the cleartext payload as a policy violation","AH's integrity check value is computed over the entire IP packet, including the source address in the header, so NAT's translation of that address invalidates the ICV at the receiver","AH cannot be negotiated in tunnel mode, causing the NAT device to silently drop all tunneled packets","AH requires IKE Phase 1 aggressive mode, which most NAT devices block by default"],"c":1,"why":"AH authenticates the entire IP packet, including header fields; when NAT rewrites the source IP address, the recalculated ICV no longer matches, causing verification failure. AH lacking encryption is true but irrelevant to the NAT-induced failure; AH does support tunnel mode; the failure is not tied to IKE negotiation mode.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company is migrating its voice traffic to a VoIP system over the corporate LAN. To protect the confidentiality of voice conversations in transit, which protocol should be implemented?","o":["Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP)","Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP)","Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) over TCP","H.323"],"c":1,"why":"SRTP adds encryption, message authentication, and integrity to RTP media streams, protecting voice call confidentiality. Plain RTP and H.323 do not inherently encrypt payload, and SIP over TCP only affects call signaling transport, not media encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to allow multiple internal hosts with private IP addresses to share a single public IP address when accessing the Internet. Which technology accomplishes this?","o":["Network Address Translation (NAT)","Virtual Private Network (VPN)","Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP)","Border Gateway Protocol (BGP)"],"c":0,"why":"NAT allows multiple private addresses to be translated to one or more public addresses, conserving IPv4 space. VPNs provide secure tunnels, DHCP assigns addresses, and BGP is a routing protocol between autonomous systems.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A wireless architect must select an EAP method that provides the strongest protection against a rogue access point performing an evil-twin attack, specifically ensuring no client credentials are exchanged until the network itself has been cryptographically verified.","o":["EAP-TLS, because it requires mutual certificate-based authentication before any credential exchange occurs","PEAP-MSCHAPv2, because the inner authentication is tunneled inside a TLS session","LEAP, because it uses a proprietary challenge-response mechanism resistant to spoofing","EAP-FAST, because it relies on a Protected Access Credential issued during provisioning"],"c":0,"why":"EAP-TLS mandates both client and server certificates, so the supplicant validates the authenticator's certificate before any authentication data is sent, defeating rogue APs. PEAP relies only on server-side certificate validation and is vulnerable if a client is misconfigured to trust any certificate; LEAP is a legacy protocol broken by offline dictionary attacks; EAP-FAST's initial PAC provisioning phase can itself be intercepted.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary security benefit of using WPA3 over WPA2 for wireless networks?","o":["It eliminates the need for a wireless access point","It uses stronger encryption and provides forward secrecy through improved key exchange","It allows unlimited SSID broadcasting range","It removes the need for any authentication method"],"c":1,"why":"WPA3 improves on WPA2 by using stronger encryption (e.g., 192-bit suite for Enterprise) and a more secure handshake (SAE) that provides forward secrecy. The other options misrepresent WPA3's function and do not relate to actual security improvements.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"During a penetration test, an attacker connected to a standard access port successfully injects double 802.1Q-tagged frames and reaches hosts on a VLAN they should not have access to. Which switch configuration change directly prevents this specific VLAN hopping technique?","o":["Enable Dynamic ARP Inspection on all access and trunk ports","Set the native VLAN on all trunk ports to an unused VLAN ID that is not assigned to any access port","Configure port security to limit each access port to a single learned MAC address","Enable BPDU Guard on all edge-facing switch ports"],"c":1,"why":"Double-tagging attacks exploit the fact that the outer tag matching the native VLAN gets stripped by the switch, allowing the inner tag to reach a different VLAN; assigning an unused, dedicated native VLAN on trunks breaks this assumption. ARP inspection mitigates ARP spoofing, port security mitigates MAC flooding, and BPDU Guard protects against STP manipulation—none address tag stripping.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A company wants to establish an encrypted tunnel between two office locations over the public Internet so that traffic between the sites is protected. Which technology is most appropriate?","o":["Site-to-site VPN","Network Address Translation","Spanning Tree Protocol","Simple Mail Transfer Protocol"],"c":0,"why":"A site-to-site VPN creates an encrypted tunnel between two networks over an untrusted medium like the Internet. NAT translates addresses, STP prevents switching loops, and SMTP is an email protocol—none provide encrypted site interconnection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company needs to establish an IPsec connection between two branch office gateways over the public Internet. The security requirement mandates confidentiality, integrity, and authentication of the payload, and it must also conceal the original source and destination IP addresses of the internal hosts from anyone observing the traffic on the Internet. Which IPsec configuration best meets these requirements?","o":["AH in tunnel mode","ESP in tunnel mode","ESP in transport mode","AH in transport mode"],"c":1,"why":"ESP provides confidentiality (encryption) plus integrity and authentication, and tunnel mode encapsulates the entire original IP packet (including headers) inside a new IP packet, hiding the original addresses. AH does not provide confidentiality, and transport mode leaves the original IP header exposed.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to guarantee that TLS sessions captured and stored today cannot be decrypted in the future even if the server's long-term RSA private key is later compromised. Which key exchange requirement should be mandated in the cipher suite policy?","o":["RSA key transport (RSA used to encrypt the session key)","Static Diffie-Hellman (DH_RSA) key exchange","Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (DHE or ECDHE) key exchange","Pre-shared key (PSK) exchange without ephemeral parameters"],"c":2,"why":"Ephemeral DH/ECDHE generates unique, session-specific key pairs that are discarded after use, providing perfect forward secrecy so a later compromise of the server's static private key cannot decrypt past sessions. RSA key transport and static DH both derive session keys from long-term keys, and plain PSK without ephemeral parameters offers no forward secrecy.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which network device operates at Layer 2 of the OSI model and forwards frames based on MAC addresses?","o":["Router","Switch","Firewall","Load Balancer"],"c":1,"why":"A switch forwards frames based on MAC addresses learned on its ports, operating at the Data Link Layer (Layer 2). Routers work at Layer 3 using IP addresses; firewalls and load balancers typically operate at higher layers or across multiple layers depending on type.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to inspect the payload of encrypted traffic between internal users and an external cloud application without installing agents on endpoints. Which architecture best supports this requirement?","o":["A network-based IPS operating in promiscuous mode on the core switch","A TLS-terminating forward proxy that re-encrypts traffic to the destination","A stateful firewall configured with deep packet inspection signatures","IPSec tunnel mode between the internal network and the cloud provider"],"c":1,"why":"A forward proxy that terminates and re-establishes TLS can decrypt, inspect, and re-encrypt traffic centrally without endpoint agents. IPS/DPI and stateful firewalls cannot see inside properly terminated TLS payloads, and IPSec tunnel mode only protects transport, it does not enable content inspection.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester on the internal voice VLAN captures unencrypted SIP INVITE messages and successfully hijacks a call session by modifying the Contact header in transit before it reaches the far-end proxy. Which control would have most directly prevented this specific attack?","o":["Enabling call admission control and QoS tagging on the voice VLAN","Deploying SRTP to encrypt the media stream between endpoints","Encrypting SIP signaling with TLS and enforcing mutual authentication between endpoints and the proxy","Segmenting voice traffic onto a dedicated VLAN with 802.1p priority tagging"],"c":2,"why":"The attack tampered with SIP signaling, so protecting integrity and confidentiality of signaling via TLS (SIPS) with mutual authentication is required; SRTP only protects the media stream, and VLAN segmentation or QoS controls do not prevent tampering with signaling messages by an attacker already present on that segment.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise is designing an 802.1X port-based network access control solution for its wired network and requires mutual authentication in which both the RADIUS server and the endpoint device each present and validate a digital certificate before network access is granted. Which EAP method satisfies this requirement?","o":["PEAP","EAP-TTLS","EAP-TLS","LEAP"],"c":2,"why":"EAP-TLS requires both the server and the client to have certificates, providing true mutual certificate-based authentication. PEAP and EAP-TTLS use a server-side certificate to build a TLS tunnel but typically authenticate the client via a non-certificate inner method (e.g., password), and LEAP relies on weak, password-based mutual authentication without certificates.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements IPSec in tunnel mode between two gateways to protect traffic traveling across the Internet. What does tunnel mode primarily provide compared to transport mode?","o":["Encryption of only the payload while leaving the original IP header exposed","Encryption and encapsulation of the entire original IP packet, including the header","Authentication without any encryption capability","Protection limited to Layer 2 traffic only"],"c":1,"why":"IPSec tunnel mode encrypts and encapsulates the entire original IP packet (including the header) inside a new IP packet, ideal for gateway-to-gateway communication. Transport mode only encrypts the payload, leaving the original header visible; the other options misstate IPSec's capabilities.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"During a network audit, an analyst notices that a switch port connected to a printer is placed in the same broadcast domain as finance workstations, despite having no business need for communication between them. Which control would most directly reduce the attack surface here?","o":["Implementing port security with MAC address limiting","Deploying VLANs to segment the printer from the finance subnet","Enabling Spanning Tree Protocol on the switch","Applying 802.1X authentication to the switch port"],"c":1,"why":"VLAN segmentation logically separates broadcast domains so devices with no business need to communicate are isolated, directly reducing lateral movement risk. Port security, STP, and 802.1X address device authentication and loop prevention, not logical segmentation between device groups.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"Which firewall architecture terminates each client connection completely and establishes an entirely separate connection to the destination server, enabling full parsing and validation of an application-layer protocol such as HTTP before any content is forwarded?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Circuit-level gateway","Stateful inspection firewall","Application-layer proxy firewall"],"c":3,"why":"An application-layer proxy breaks the connection into two segments and fully understands the application protocol, allowing deep content inspection and rewriting. Packet filters inspect only header fields, circuit-level gateways relay sessions without content awareness, and stateful inspection tracks connection state but does not fully parse application payloads.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester on an internal network is able to send crafted frames that reach hosts on a VLAN different from the one assigned to the tester's switch port, without having any prior access to a trunk port. The tester achieves this by embedding a frame with two 802.1Q tags, where the outer tag matches the native VLAN of the trunk. What attack technique is being used?","o":["MAC flooding","Switch spoofing via Dynamic Trunking Protocol","VLAN double tagging attack","ARP cache poisoning"],"c":2,"why":"A VLAN double tagging attack exploits switches that strip only the outer (native VLAN) tag on a trunk, forwarding the frame with its inner tag intact to another VLAN, effectively hopping VLANs from an access port. Switch spoofing requires negotiating a trunk via DTP, MAC flooding targets CAM table exhaustion, and ARP poisoning is unrelated to VLAN tagging.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company's security team wants to ensure that data confidentiality and integrity are protected for traffic traveling between two branch offices over the public Internet, and that the solution operates transparently at the network layer without requiring application changes. Which technology best meets this need?","o":["TLS 1.3 configured on all application servers","IPSec in tunnel mode between the site gateways","SSH port forwarding between branch routers","MPLS with traffic engineering enabled"],"c":1,"why":"IPSec tunnel mode encrypts and authenticates entire IP packets between gateways at the network layer, transparent to applications. TLS operates at the application/session layer and requires app support, SSH tunneling is not designed for site-to-site transparent protection, and MPLS provides traffic engineering but no inherent confidentiality.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An ISP wants to prevent both accidental and malicious announcement of IP prefixes it does not own by downstream networks, which could redirect global traffic through an unauthorized autonomous system. Which technology cryptographically validates the legitimate origin AS of a BGP route announcement?","o":["DNSSEC","Route Origin Authorization validated through RPKI","IPsec tunnel mode between BGP peers","BGP session authentication using MD5"],"c":1,"why":"RPKI-based Route Origin Authorizations cryptographically bind a prefix to its legitimate originating AS, allowing routers to reject invalid announcements. BGP MD5 only authenticates the peering session between two routers and does not validate route origin; IPsec secures the transport channel, not the routing data itself; DNSSEC secures DNS resolution and is unrelated to routing.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"In an 802.1X port-based network access control deployment, a laptop connects to a switch port and its EAP credentials are relayed by the switch to a centralized RADIUS server, which returns an accept or reject decision before the port is opened. What role does the switch perform in this exchange?","o":["Supplicant","Authenticator","Authentication server","Registration authority"],"c":1,"why":"In the 802.1X model, the switch acts as the Authenticator, controlling the port and relaying EAP messages between the supplicant (the laptop) and the authentication server (RADIUS), which makes the actual access decision. A registration authority is a PKI role unrelated to 802.1X.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A penetration tester successfully floods a target server with a high volume of TCP SYN packets using spoofed source addresses, causing the server's connection table to fill and legitimate connections to be dropped. Which category of attack is being demonstrated?","o":["Resource exhaustion denial of service","Session hijacking","ARP cache poisoning","Man-in-the-middle attack"],"c":0,"why":"A SYN flood consumes the server's half-open connection table resources, a classic resource exhaustion DoS. Session hijacking and MITM involve intercepting or taking over active sessions, and ARP poisoning manipulates local address resolution, none of which describe this scenario.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization is designing a wireless network for a hospital and needs an authentication method that supports mutual authentication between client and server using certificates, without transmitting user credentials over the air in a crackable form. Which EAP method best satisfies this requirement?","o":["EAP-MD5","LEAP","PEAP with MS-CHAPv2 only","EAP-TLS"],"c":3,"why":"EAP-TLS uses mutual certificate-based authentication for both client and server, eliminating credential transmission risk. EAP-MD5 and LEAP have known weaknesses in credential protection, and PEAP with MS-CHAPv2 alone only authenticates the server via certificate, not the client.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect implements DNSSEC on an organization's authoritative DNS servers to protect the integrity of zone data. Which statement best describes the actual security benefit and limitation of this implementation?","o":["DNSSEC encrypts DNS queries and responses, preventing eavesdroppers from viewing requested domain names","DNSSEC digitally signs DNS records to provide data origin authentication and integrity, but it does not provide confidentiality of DNS traffic","DNSSEC prevents all forms of DNS cache poisoning and eliminates the need for resolver-side validation","DNSSEC replaces the need for TLS certificate validation by cryptographically verifying the identity of web servers"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses digital signatures to let resolvers verify that DNS responses are authentic and unaltered, but the data itself remains unencrypted and visible in transit. It does not fully eliminate poisoning risks without proper validating resolvers, nor does it perform TLS-style server identity verification.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"At which layer of the OSI reference model do routers primarily operate to make forwarding decisions based on logical addressing?","o":["Data Link layer","Network layer","Transport layer","Session layer"],"c":1,"why":"Routers make forwarding decisions using IP (logical) addresses, which are processed at the Network layer (Layer 3). Data Link deals with MAC addresses (switches), Transport handles end-to-end connections (TCP/UDP), and Session manages dialog control, none of which involve routing decisions.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization migrates to a Software-Defined Networking (SDN) architecture in which network intelligence and forwarding decisions are centralized in an SDN controller that communicates with switches using a southbound API. From a security perspective, which risk is most directly introduced by this architectural change?","o":["Increased end-to-end encryption overhead on all data plane traffic","A compromised controller can grant an attacker centralized control over forwarding behavior across the entire network","SDN inherently disables the ability to implement network segmentation","Southbound APIs eliminate the need for authentication between control and data planes"],"c":1,"why":"Centralizing control logic in the SDN controller creates a high-value target; compromising it can allow an attacker to manipulate flow rules network-wide, making it a critical single point of failure/attack. SDN does not inherently add encryption overhead, disable segmentation, or remove the need for southbound authentication—those are implementation choices, not attributes of the SDN model itself.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is reviewing firewall rules and finds a rule permitting any source, any destination, on TCP port 3389 (RDP) at the network perimeter. Which risk does this rule primarily introduce?","o":["Exposure of a management protocol to brute-force and exploitation attempts from the Internet","Increased latency due to protocol overhead","Loss of data integrity due to lack of encryption on port 3389","Inability to perform network address translation on the segment"],"c":0,"why":"Allowing RDP from any source to any destination exposes a high-value remote management service directly to Internet-based brute-force and exploit attempts, a common initial access vector. RDP does support encryption, this rule does not affect NAT capability, and latency is not the primary security concern.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"A firewall that tracks the state of active connections and makes filtering decisions based on the context of traffic (such as whether a packet belongs to an established session) is best described as which type?","o":["Packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy only","Static packet filter"],"c":1,"why":"Stateful inspection firewalls maintain a state table of active connections and use that context to filter traffic, unlike simple packet filters which evaluate each packet independently based solely on static rules.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A company wants to ensure that if a web server's long-term RSA private key is compromised in the future, past recorded TLS sessions cannot be decrypted retroactively. Which cipher suite property must be present to achieve this?","o":["Use of RSA for key exchange combined with AES-256 for bulk encryption","Use of ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (DHE or ECDHE) key exchange to establish session keys","Use of SHA-256 instead of SHA-1 for the message authentication code","Use of a longer RSA key size, such as 4096 bits, for the certificate"],"c":1,"why":"Perfect Forward Secrecy requires that session keys be derived from ephemeral key exchange (DHE/ECDHE) rather than being tied to the server's static private key, so compromising that key later cannot expose past session keys. Static RSA key exchange, stronger hashing, or larger RSA key sizes do not provide forward secrecy.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An enterprise wants to prevent rogue devices from obtaining full network access when plugged into wired switch ports, requiring devices to be authenticated and possibly placed into a quarantine VLAN before being granted production access. Which technology should be implemented?","o":["802.1X port-based network access control","Dynamic ARP inspection","DHCP snooping","Private VLANs"],"c":0,"why":"802.1X provides port-based authentication, allowing switches to authenticate devices/users before granting network access, and can dynamically assign VLANs including quarantine. DHCP snooping and dynamic ARP inspection address specific spoofing attacks, and private VLANs restrict intra-VLAN communication but do not authenticate devices.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol suite is most commonly used to provide encryption and authentication for IP traffic in a site-to-site VPN?","o":["IPSec","SNMP","FTP","ARP"],"c":0,"why":"IPSec provides confidentiality, integrity, and authentication for IP packets and is the standard protocol suite for site-to-site VPNs. SNMP is for network management, FTP is for file transfer, and ARP resolves IP to MAC addresses—none provide VPN encryption.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A network engineer is troubleshooting an issue where a client application intermittently loses connectivity because two different hosts on the same subnet have been assigned the same IP address. At which OSI layer does the root cause of this addressing conflict primarily reside?","o":["Layer 2 - Data Link","Layer 3 - Network","Layer 4 - Transport","Layer 7 - Application"],"c":1,"why":"IP addressing and address conflicts are a Layer 3 (Network) function, since IP addresses operate at this layer for logical addressing and routing. Layer 2 deals with MAC addressing, Layer 4 handles end-to-end transport sessions, and Layer 7 concerns application data, none of which is where IP address conflicts originate.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization deploying an enterprise VoIP system wants to protect both call setup signaling and the actual voice media streams from interception on an untrusted network segment. Which combination of protocols should be implemented?","o":["H.323 with IPsec for signaling and RTP for media","SIP over TLS (SIPS) for signaling and SRTP for media","Plain SIP for signaling and RTP with VLAN segmentation for media","SIP with MD5 digest authentication for signaling and RTP over a VPN tunnel for media"],"c":1,"why":"SIPS encrypts SIP signaling using TLS, and SRTP provides encryption, integrity, and replay protection for the RTP media stream, directly addressing both signaling and media confidentiality. The other options either leave signaling or media unencrypted at the protocol level or rely on network-layer controls rather than protocol-native protections.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security team is redesigning perimeter defenses and wants publicly accessible servers to reside in a dedicated network segment isolated by two separate firewalls, ideally from different vendors, so that a vulnerability in one firewall's software does not automatically expose the internal network. Which firewall architecture does this describe?","o":["Dual-homed host architecture","Screened host architecture","Screened subnet (DMZ) architecture with defense-in-depth","Bastion host with a single packet-filtering firewall"],"c":2,"why":"A screened subnet architecture places a DMZ between two firewalls, and using different vendors for each firewall adds defense-in-depth against a single exploitable flaw. A dual-homed host relies on one multi-interfaced host without a separate DMZ, a screened host uses only one firewall paired with a bastion host, and a single packet-filtering firewall does not provide layered isolation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which wireless security protocol replaced WEP to address its weak encryption and key management flaws by introducing stronger encryption such as AES-CCMP?","o":["WPA2","Bluetooth pairing","SSID broadcasting","MAC filtering"],"c":0,"why":"WPA2 introduced AES-CCMP encryption to address the serious cryptographic weaknesses of WEP. Bluetooth pairing, SSID broadcasting, and MAC filtering are unrelated or weak controls that don't provide strong encryption for Wi-Fi traffic.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"Which service is responsible for resolving human-readable domain names, such as www.example.com, into IP addresses?","o":["DHCP","DNS","ARP","NAT"],"c":1,"why":"DNS (Domain Name System) translates domain names into IP addresses. DHCP assigns IP addresses to hosts, ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses, and NAT translates private to public IP addresses—none perform domain name resolution.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants multiple internal hosts with private IP addresses to share a single public IP address when accessing the Internet. Which technology accomplishes this?","o":["NAT","VLAN tagging","Spanning Tree Protocol","DNSSEC"],"c":0,"why":"Network Address Translation (NAT) allows multiple internal hosts to share one or more public IP addresses for outbound Internet access. VLAN tagging segments broadcast domains, Spanning Tree prevents Layer 2 loops, and DNSSEC secures DNS responses—none translate addresses.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security architect must deploy a site-to-site IPsec VPN between two offices, but the remote office's IPsec gateway sits behind a PAT (Port Address Translation) device that translates many internal hosts to a single public IP. Which configuration will provide both data confidentiality and reliable operation through the PAT device?","o":["AH in transport mode, since it authenticates the entire IP packet including the payload","ESP in tunnel mode with NAT Traversal (NAT-T) using UDP encapsulation on port 4500","AH in tunnel mode, since tunnel mode protects the original IP header from modification","ESP in transport mode without NAT-T, relying on the PAT device to preserve the original TCP/UDP ports"],"c":1,"why":"ESP in tunnel mode encrypts the entire original packet for confidentiality, and NAT-T wraps the ESP packet in a UDP header so PAT devices can translate and multiplex multiple internal hosts correctly despite ESP hiding the original transport-layer port numbers. AH fails through NAT/PAT in either mode because its integrity check (ICV) covers the IP header, which NAT/PAT devices alter, breaking the hash; ESP in transport mode without NAT-T also fails because PAT relies on visible transport-layer ports for translation, which ESP encrypts.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An organization must establish an IPSec VPN between two branch offices across the public Internet. The design requires that the entire original IP packet (including headers) be encrypted and authenticated, and the tunnel must successfully traverse a mid-path device performing Port Address Translation (PAT). Which configuration BEST satisfies these requirements?","o":["Authentication Header (AH) in transport mode","Authentication Header (AH) in tunnel mode","Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) in tunnel mode with NAT Traversal (NAT-T) enabled","ESP in transport mode combined with AH for integrity"],"c":2,"why":"ESP in tunnel mode encrypts and authenticates the entire original IP packet, and NAT-T (UDP encapsulation on port 4500) allows the ESP packet to survive address/port rewriting by a PAT device. AH is incompatible with NAT because it authenticates the outer IP header, including the source address that NAT modifies, breaking the integrity check; transport mode does not protect the original IP header.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"During a penetration test, an assessor plugs a laptop into an access port on a switch and crafts frames with two stacked 802.1Q VLAN tags: an outer tag matching the switch port's native (untagged) VLAN and an inner tag for a target VLAN. The assessor successfully receives traffic from the target VLAN without any Layer 3 device forwarding it. Which control would MOST effectively prevent this specific attack going forward?","o":["Implement port security to limit the number of MAC addresses learned per switch port","Explicitly assign an unused VLAN as the native VLAN on all trunk ports and disable it from carrying any user traffic","Enable Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) BPDU Guard on all access ports","Configure DHCP snooping on all VLANs to prevent rogue DHCP servers"],"c":1,"why":"This describes a VLAN double-tagging attack, which works because the outer tag matches the trunk's native VLAN and gets stripped by the first switch, exposing the inner tag to be forwarded onto the target VLAN; assigning an unused, non-user VLAN as native and disallowing tagged native traffic on trunks eliminates the vulnerable condition. Port security, BPDU Guard, and DHCP snooping address different threats (MAC flooding, STP manipulation, and rogue DHCP, respectively) and do not stop double-tagging VLAN hopping.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester on a switched network configures a host's NIC to send Ethernet frames with two stacked 802.1Q VLAN tags. The outer tag matches the switch port's native VLAN, and the inner tag specifies the target VLAN. Frames successfully reach hosts on the target VLAN despite the attacker's port being assigned to a different VLAN. Which control BEST prevents this specific attack?","o":["Enable port security to limit the number of MAC addresses per port","Assign the trunk ports' native VLAN to an unused VLAN ID and explicitly tag it, disabling auto-trunk negotiation","Enable Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) with BPDU guard on all access ports","Deploy private VLANs (PVLANs) on all access switches"],"c":1,"why":"This is a double-tagging VLAN hopping attack, which exploits switches that strip only the outer tag matching the native VLAN, exposing the inner tag to trunk forwarding logic. Moving the native VLAN off VLAN 1 to an unused ID and disabling native VLAN untagging closes this gap. Port security, STP/BPDU guard, and PVLANs address different threats (MAC flooding, topology attacks, and intra-VLAN isolation) and do not stop double-tagging.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An architect is comparing WPA2-Personal to WPA3-Personal for a wireless deployment. The key differentiator that specifically prevents offline dictionary attacks against captured handshake traffic is:","o":["WPA3's mandatory use of AES-256 instead of AES-128 for data encryption","WPA3's Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE), a Diffie-Hellman-based exchange requiring live interaction with the access point for each password guess","WPA3's use of a longer minimum passphrase length enforced by the access point","WPA3's disabling of open (unauthenticated) association entirely"],"c":1,"why":"SAE (Dragonfly handshake) derives a unique session key via an interactive Diffie-Hellman exchange, so an attacker cannot passively capture a handshake and brute-force it offline as with WPA2's 4-way handshake/PSK; each guess requires live protocol interaction, which is rate-limitable. Encryption strength and passphrase length do not address the offline-attack vector against the handshake itself.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization's network engineer is troubleshooting an application that requires reliable, ordered delivery of data with built-in flow control and error recovery between two hosts. At which OSI layer are these functions primarily implemented?","o":["Network layer","Transport layer","Session layer","Data Link layer"],"c":1,"why":"The Transport layer (Layer 4) provides end-to-end reliability, segmentation, sequencing, and flow control (e.g., via TCP). The Network layer handles routing/addressing, the Session layer manages dialogs, and the Data Link layer handles framing and MAC addressing, none of which provide these reliability services.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to log in using a smart card combined with a PIN. Which two authentication factor categories does this represent?","o":["Something you have and something you know","Something you are and something you know","Something you have and something you are","Something you know and something you know"],"c":0,"why":"A smart card is 'something you have' and a PIN is 'something you know.' It is not biometric (something you are), and using two different factor types (not two of the same type) is what makes this true multi-factor authentication.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A security team is redesigning perimeter defenses and wants to minimize the risk that a single firewall compromise grants an attacker a direct path from the Internet into the internal network. Which architecture provides the STRONGEST defense-in-depth against this scenario?","o":["A single three-legged firewall with separate interfaces for Internet, DMZ, and internal network","A screened subnet (DMZ) bounded by two firewalls, ideally from different vendors, with public-facing servers between them","A dual-homed host acting as the sole gateway between the Internet and internal network","A bastion host placed on the internal network with no firewall filtering"],"c":1,"why":"A screened subnet with two independent firewalls forces an attacker to defeat two separate control points (potentially from different vendors, reducing shared-vulnerability risk) before reaching the internal network. A single three-legged firewall represents one point of failure; a dual-homed host or unfiltered bastion host offers even weaker isolation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A company needs to establish an encrypted connection between two branch office gateways over the public Internet, ensuring the entire original IP packet, including its header, is protected. Which IPsec mode should be implemented?","o":["Transport mode","Tunnel mode","AH in transport mode only","ESP without authentication"],"c":1,"why":"Tunnel mode encapsulates and encrypts the entire original IP packet, including headers, making it ideal for gateway-to-gateway VPNs. Transport mode only protects the payload, leaving the original IP header exposed, which is unsuitable for site-to-site tunneling across public networks.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A CISO is briefed that the organization has deployed DNSSEC across its authoritative name servers. Which statement about the security benefit provided is accurate?","o":["DNSSEC encrypts DNS queries and responses, preventing eavesdroppers from viewing lookups","DNSSEC uses digital signatures and a chain of trust to verify the authenticity and integrity of DNS responses but does not provide confidentiality","DNSSEC replaces UDP-based DNS with a TLS-encrypted transport for all zone transfers","DNSSEC inherently mitigates DDoS attacks against DNS infrastructure by rate-limiting queries"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC adds cryptographic signatures (RRSIG, DNSKEY, DS records) that let resolvers validate that responses are authentic and unmodified, mitigating cache poisoning and spoofing—but it does not encrypt query/response content, so confidentiality is unaddressed (that is the role of DoH/DoT). It does not change the transport protocol for zone transfers or provide DDoS mitigation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A firewall administrator configures a device that maintains a table of active connections and automatically permits return traffic for an established session without requiring an explicit inbound rule. What type of firewall is being described?","o":["Static packet-filtering firewall","Stateful inspection firewall","Circuit-level proxy firewall","Application-layer gateway"],"c":1,"why":"A stateful inspection firewall tracks the state of active connections and dynamically allows associated return traffic. A static packet filter evaluates each packet independently with no session awareness, while proxy/application-layer firewalls operate differently by fully terminating and relaying sessions rather than simply tracking state tables.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company assigns access permissions to users based solely on their job function, such as 'Accountant' or 'HR Manager,' rather than assigning permissions individually. Which access control model is being used?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC grants permissions based on a user's assigned role rather than individual identity. DAC lets resource owners assign access, MAC uses security labels/clearances, and rule-based control relies on predefined if-then rules, none of which describe job-function-based grouping.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the primary benefit of implementing Single Sign-On (SSO) for end users?","o":["It eliminates the need for any authentication credentials","It requires users to authenticate once to access multiple independent systems","It automatically encrypts all data in transit between systems","It replaces the need for authorization controls entirely"],"c":1,"why":"SSO allows a user to authenticate once and gain access to multiple systems without re-entering credentials, improving usability. It does not eliminate credentials, provide encryption, or remove the need for separate authorization decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"During a VoIP security assessment, a tester on the same broadcast domain captures unencrypted RTP streams and reconstructs full audio conversations. Which control MOST directly remediates this specific finding?","o":["Implement Secure RTP (SRTP) to encrypt the media stream","Place all VoIP endpoints on a dedicated voice VLAN separate from data traffic","Require SIP signaling to use TLS instead of plaintext SIP","Deploy a Session Border Controller (SBC) at the network perimeter"],"c":0,"why":"The finding is eavesdropping on the media (RTP) payload itself, which SRTP directly remediates through encryption and authentication of the media stream. VLAN segmentation reduces broadcast exposure but does not prevent capture by a device already on that VLAN; securing SIP signaling with TLS protects call setup metadata, not the media; an SBC primarily manages perimeter signaling/media policy and NAT traversal, not payload confidentiality on the internal segment.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization requires employees to log in using a password plus a one-time code generated by a hardware token. Which authentication factor category does the hardware token represent?","o":["Something you know","Something you have","Something you are","Something you do"],"c":1,"why":"A hardware token is a physical device the user possesses, making it 'something you have.' Passwords are 'something you know,' biometrics are 'something you are,' and behavioral patterns are 'something you do.'","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"WPA3 was designed to address a specific weakness in WPA2-Personal where captured handshake traffic could be subjected to offline dictionary attacks to recover the pre-shared key. Which WPA3 feature directly mitigates this vulnerability?","o":["AES-256 encryption for all data frames","Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)","Mandatory use of 802.1X certificates","Extended Service Set roaming keys"],"c":1,"why":"SAE replaces the WPA2 four-way handshake with a Diffie-Hellman-based exchange that resists offline dictionary attacks even if traffic is captured. AES-256 alone doesn't fix the handshake weakness, 802.1X certificates apply to enterprise mode, and roaming keys address handoff, not offline PSK cracking.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a federated identity environment using SAML, which entity is responsible for authenticating the user and issuing an assertion to the service provider?","o":["The relying party","The identity provider (IdP)","The certificate authority","The resource owner"],"c":1,"why":"The Identity Provider (IdP) authenticates the user and generates a SAML assertion that the service provider (relying party) trusts. The relying party consumes the assertion rather than issuing it, and a CA issues certificates, not authentication assertions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise is implementing 802.1X port-based access control for WPA2-Enterprise wireless and wants the strongest available mutual authentication, where both the supplicant and the authentication server prove their identities using X.509 certificates, eliminating reliance on user password hashes during the handshake.","o":["EAP-MD5","LEAP","PEAP with MS-CHAPv2","EAP-TLS"],"c":3,"why":"EAP-TLS requires certificates on both the client and the RADIUS/authentication server, providing true mutual, certificate-based authentication without transmitting password hashes. EAP-MD5 and LEAP use weak, crackable challenge-response mechanisms; PEAP typically wraps MS-CHAPv2 (a password-hash-based method) inside a server-authenticated TLS tunnel, so the client side still relies on password hashes rather than certificates.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a Kerberos authentication exchange, what is the primary purpose of the Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT)?","o":["It encrypts all network traffic between client and server for the session","It allows the client to request service tickets from the KDC without re-entering credentials","It serves as the final authorization token granting access to a specific application server","It stores the user's long-term password hash for future authentication attempts"],"c":1,"why":"The TGT is issued after initial authentication and allows the client to obtain service tickets for specific resources without re-authenticating. It does not encrypt session traffic, is not the final access token (that's the service ticket), and does not store the password itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst notices that a workstation's ARP cache now maps the default gateway's IP address to an unauthorized device's MAC address, causing traffic to be silently redirected through the attacker's machine. Which attack does this describe?","o":["DNS cache poisoning","ARP spoofing","MAC flooding","BGP route hijacking"],"c":1,"why":"ARP spoofing involves sending forged ARP replies to associate an attacker's MAC address with a legitimate IP (like the gateway), enabling traffic interception. DNS poisoning targets name resolution, MAC flooding overwhelms switch CAM tables, and BGP hijacking manipulates Internet routing, none of which match the ARP cache symptom described.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee is terminated, which access management process should be performed IMMEDIATELY to reduce security risk?","o":["User provisioning","Account de-provisioning","Password rotation for all users","Access recertification for the entire department"],"c":1,"why":"De-provisioning promptly disables or removes the terminated employee's accounts and access rights, preventing unauthorized use. Provisioning creates new access, and the other options are broader periodic activities that do not address the immediate risk of an active terminated account.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D4","d":"hard","q":"A network engineer observes that hosts on an internal VLAN are receiving forged ARP replies, redirecting traffic intended for the default gateway to an attacker's workstation. Which combination of switch features BEST mitigates this attack at Layer 2?","o":["Enable DHCP snooping and Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI) on the switches","Deploy 802.1X port-based authentication on all access ports","Convert all client workstations to static IP addressing","Enable BPDU guard on all access switch ports"],"c":0,"why":"DHCP snooping builds a trusted binding table of IP-to-MAC-to-port mappings, which Dynamic ARP Inspection then uses to validate ARP packets and drop forged replies, directly countering ARP spoofing. 802.1X authenticates port access but does not validate ARP content; static IPs don't prevent forged ARP replies; BPDU guard protects against rogue STP switches, an unrelated attack vector.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"An organization places its guest Wi-Fi network on a separate VLAN from the corporate LAN. From a security perspective, what is the PRIMARY benefit of this segmentation?","o":["It encrypts all guest traffic automatically","It eliminates the need for a guest network firewall","It reduces the broadcast domain and limits lateral movement into corporate resources","It guarantees higher bandwidth for corporate users"],"c":2,"why":"VLAN segmentation confines broadcast traffic and, combined with access controls, prevents guest devices from directly reaching corporate systems, reducing lateral movement opportunities. VLANs do not provide encryption, do not remove the need for firewall rules between segments, and do not inherently guarantee bandwidth allocation.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to grant access based on a combination of user department, time of day, and resource sensitivity level, with rules that can be dynamically evaluated at request time. Which access control model best fits this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple attributes (user, environment, resource) dynamically via policy rules, making it ideal for context-aware decisions like time and sensitivity. RBAC is role-static, DAC relies on owner discretion, and MAC uses fixed security labels/clearances.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A biometric authentication system that incorrectly grants access to an unauthorized individual is exhibiting a high rate of which of the following?","o":["False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Enrollment failure rate"],"c":0,"why":"FAR measures how often an unauthorized user is incorrectly accepted. FRR measures legitimate users being wrongly denied, CER is the point where FAR and FRR intersect, and enrollment failure relates to inability to register a biometric sample, not access granting errors.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a SAML-based single sign-on implementation, which component is responsible for asserting a user's identity to a service provider after successful authentication?","o":["The relying party","The identity provider","The service provider's local directory","The user's browser cache"],"c":1,"why":"The Identity Provider (IdP) authenticates the user and issues a SAML assertion to the Service Provider (relying party), which trusts the assertion to grant access. The browser and local directory are not responsible for issuing the trust assertion.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"A security team is evaluating DNSSEC to improve the resilience of their name resolution infrastructure. Which statement BEST describes what DNSSEC actually provides?","o":["Encryption of DNS query and response payloads to ensure confidentiality","Digital signatures that provide data origin authentication and integrity for DNS records","Automatic blocking of malicious domains based on reputation feeds","Load balancing of DNS queries across multiple authoritative servers"],"c":1,"why":"DNSSEC uses public key cryptography to digitally sign DNS records, allowing resolvers to verify authenticity and detect tampering, but it does not encrypt DNS traffic. Confidentiality, reputation-based blocking, and load balancing are unrelated to DNSSEC's core function.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In the Kerberos authentication protocol, which component issues the session ticket a client uses to access a specific network service?","o":["The Key Distribution Center's Authentication Server","The Ticket Granting Service (TGS)","The client's local authentication cache","The application server itself"],"c":1,"why":"After initial authentication, the client presents its Ticket Granting Ticket to the Ticket Granting Service (TGS), which issues a service ticket for the specific resource. The Authentication Server only issues the initial TGT, and the application server validates rather than issues tickets.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During biometric system calibration, an administrator notices that lowering the sensitivity threshold reduces False Rejection Rate (FRR) but increases False Acceptance Rate (FAR). What is this tradeoff point called when FRR equals FAR?","o":["Type II error threshold","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Enrollment threshold","Throughput rate"],"c":1,"why":"The Crossover Error Rate is the point at which FAR and FRR are equal, and it is used as a key metric for comparing biometric system accuracy—the lower the CER, the more accurate the system. The other terms do not describe this specific balance point.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D4","d":"medium","q":"Before allowing a laptop to connect to the corporate network, a Network Access Control (NAC) solution checks the device's patch level, antivirus status, and disk encryption state. If the device fails the check, it is placed into a restricted remediation VLAN. What is the PRIMARY security purpose of this NAC implementation?","o":["To encrypt all traffic from non-compliant devices","To enforce endpoint compliance before granting network access","To provide intrusion detection for the internal network","To perform vulnerability scanning of external-facing servers"],"c":1,"why":"NAC evaluates endpoint posture (patches, AV, encryption) and enforces policy-based access, isolating non-compliant systems until remediated. It does not itself provide encryption, function as an IDS, or scan external servers, those are separate security functions.","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is an example of an administrative control used to enforce strong password practices in an organization?","o":["A password complexity policy requiring minimum length and character variety","An intrusion detection system monitoring login attempts","A biometric fingerprint scanner at the data center entrance","A firewall rule blocking external SSH access"],"c":0,"why":"A written password policy defining complexity and length requirements is an administrative (procedural) control. The other options are technical or physical controls, not administrative policy-based measures.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to enter a PIN and then insert a smart card to access a workstation. This is an example of which authentication concept?","o":["Multi-factor authentication","Single sign-on","Role-based access control","Mandatory access control"],"c":0,"why":"Combining something the user knows (PIN) with something the user has (smart card) uses two different authentication factor categories, which defines multi-factor authentication. SSO, RBAC, and MAC describe access management or authorization concepts, not authentication factor combinations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"Which practice is most critical to reduce the risk posed by orphaned accounts within an identity and access management program?","o":["Enforcing strong password complexity requirements for all accounts","Implementing multifactor authentication on privileged accounts","Establishing a formal deprovisioning process tied to HR termination events","Rotating shared service account credentials quarterly"],"c":2,"why":"Orphaned accounts result from employees leaving without their access being revoked, so a formal deprovisioning process integrated with HR offboarding directly addresses this risk. Password complexity, MFA, and credential rotation are valuable controls but do not ensure timely account removal.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In an access control model where permissions are assigned to job functions rather than to individual users, and users are granted access by being placed into these job function groups, which model is being used?","o":["Discretionary access control (DAC)","Role-based access control (RBAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)","Rule-based access control"],"c":1,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions to roles that correspond to job functions, and users inherit access by role membership, simplifying administration. DAC lets resource owners grant access, MAC uses security labels/clearances, and rule-based control uses predefined conditional rules.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An application uses OpenID Connect to authenticate users and OAuth 2.0 to authorize access to a separate API on the user's behalf. Which statement accurately distinguishes the two protocols in this scenario?","o":["OAuth 2.0 verifies the user's identity while OpenID Connect grants access tokens for API calls","OpenID Connect provides an identity token proving who the user is, while OAuth 2.0 provides access tokens defining what the application can do","Both protocols perform identical functions and are interchangeable in this design","OpenID Connect is used only for machine-to-machine authentication, not user authentication"],"c":1,"why":"OpenID Connect is built on top of OAuth 2.0 specifically to add an identity (ID) token for authentication, while OAuth 2.0's access tokens govern authorization to resources. The other options reverse or misstate the protocols' purposes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A security policy states that users should only be granted the minimum access necessary to perform their job duties. This principle is known as?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege","Defense in depth","Due diligence"],"c":1,"why":"Least privilege limits access rights to only what is needed for a role, reducing risk exposure. Separation of duties splits critical tasks among multiple people, defense in depth layers controls, and due diligence relates to reasonable care in decision-making.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution classifies data as Top Secret, Secret, and Confidential, and requires that users only access data at or below their assigned clearance level, with the system—not the data owner—enforcing this rule. Which access control model is being used?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Rule-Based Access Control","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)"],"c":2,"why":"MAC enforces access based on security labels and clearances at the system level, removing discretion from data owners, which matches this scenario. DAC relies on owner discretion, RBAC is based on job roles rather than clearance labels, and rule-based control uses generic if-then rules rather than clearance hierarchies.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is a primary security risk introduced by implementing single sign-on (SSO)?","o":["Users must remember multiple complex passwords","If credentials are compromised, an attacker gains access to all connected systems","It requires separate authentication for each application","It increases the number of passwords a user must manage"],"c":1,"why":"SSO centralizes authentication, so a single compromised credential can grant an attacker access to every integrated application, making credential protection critical. The other options describe the opposite of SSO's actual behavior, since SSO reduces the number of credentials and login prompts.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which authentication protocol relies on a trusted third party issuing time-stamped tickets to allow clients to prove their identity to network services without repeatedly sending passwords?","o":["Kerberos","RADIUS","OAuth","LDAP"],"c":0,"why":"Kerberos uses a Key Distribution Center to issue time-limited tickets, allowing mutual authentication without transmitting passwords repeatedly. RADIUS handles network access authentication/accounting, OAuth is an authorization framework for delegated access, and LDAP is a directory access protocol, not a ticket-based authentication system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A fingerprint scanner incorrectly grants access to an unauthorized individual whose fingerprint pattern was similar enough to an enrolled user. This type of error is known as?","o":["False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","Type I error"],"c":2,"why":"FAR measures the rate at which unauthorized users are incorrectly granted access, which matches this scenario. FRR (Type I error) is when authorized users are wrongly denied, and CER is the point where FAR and FRR intersect, not a specific error type itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee leaves an organization, which access management process ensures that all of the employee's system and application accounts are promptly disabled or removed?","o":["Provisioning","Federation","Deprovisioning","Authorization"],"c":2,"why":"Deprovisioning is the process of disabling or removing user accounts and access rights when they are no longer needed, such as at termination. Provisioning is the opposite process of creating access, federation links identities across organizations, and authorization determines what an active account can do.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company requires employees to log in using a smart card plus a PIN. Which combination of authentication factors does this represent?","o":["Something you have and something you know","Something you are and something you know","Something you have and something you are","Two instances of something you know"],"c":0,"why":"A smart card is 'something you have' and a PIN is 'something you know,' making this a true two-factor authentication scheme. Biometrics ('something you are') are not involved, and using two knowledge factors would not qualify as strong MFA.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A university allows students to use their university credentials to log into a partner online library service without creating a separate account. This capability is best described as?","o":["Identity federation","Role-based access control","Mandatory access control","Account provisioning"],"c":0,"why":"Identity federation allows a trusted identity provider's credentials to be used across multiple independent systems or organizations, exactly as described. RBAC and MAC are access control models unrelated to cross-domain trust, and provisioning refers to account creation, not credential reuse across systems.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to allow employees to authenticate once with their corporate identity provider and then access multiple cloud-based SaaS applications without re-entering credentials. Which technology BEST supports this requirement?","o":["Kerberos ticket-granting service","SAML-based federation","RADIUS authentication server","Discretionary access control lists"],"c":1,"why":"SAML federation enables a trusted identity provider to issue assertions that relying-party SaaS applications accept, enabling cross-domain single sign-on. Kerberos and RADIUS are typically used within a single trust domain/network, and DACLs govern authorization, not cross-domain authentication.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An employee logs into a corporate system using a password and then must also insert a smart card. Which authentication concept does this combination represent?","o":["Single sign-on","Multifactor authentication","Role-based access control","Federated identity"],"c":1,"why":"Combining a password (something you know) with a smart card (something you have) is multifactor authentication. SSO, RBAC, and federation are unrelated access control concepts, not authentication factor combinations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A hospital wants access decisions to be based on a combination of the user's department, the patient's care team assignment, time of day, and location of the request. Which access control model BEST fits this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes (department, team assignment, time, location) at the time of the request to make fine-grained access decisions. RBAC only considers role, MAC uses fixed security labels, and DAC leaves access decisions to resource owners.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which access control model assigns permissions to users based on their job function within an organization, simplifying administration for large groups of employees?","o":["Discretionary access control (DAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)","Role-based access control (RBAC)","Rule-based access control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC grants access based on organizational roles, making it efficient for managing permissions in large organizations. DAC relies on resource owners, MAC uses security labels/clearances, and rule-based control uses predefined conditions rather than job roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system is being tuned for a high-security data center. Administrators lower the sensitivity threshold to reduce the number of legitimate users who are rejected. What is the MOST likely consequence of this change?","o":["The False Rejection Rate (FRR) will increase","The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) will increase","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) will improve","Enrollment time for new users will increase"],"c":1,"why":"Lowering the sensitivity threshold makes it easier for legitimate users to be accepted (reducing FRR) but also makes it easier for impostors to be falsely accepted, increasing FAR. CER is a fixed point where FAR equals FRR and is a property of the system's overall accuracy, not something that improves simply by shifting the threshold.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that employees are granted access only to the specific information required to perform their current job duties, even if they hold a security clearance for higher classifications. Which principle does this describe?","o":["Separation of duties","Need-to-know","Least privilege","Defense in depth"],"c":1,"why":"Need-to-know restricts access to specific information required for a task, independent of clearance level. Least privilege is broader (minimum rights overall), separation of duties splits tasks among people, and defense in depth refers to layered security controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester compromises the NTLM password hash of the KRBTGT service account within an Active Directory domain. Using this hash, the tester crafts a Kerberos ticket-granting ticket that grants domain administrator privileges without ever authenticating to a domain controller with valid credentials. Which attack has been performed?","o":["Golden ticket attack","Silver ticket attack","Kerberoasting","Pass-the-hash attack"],"c":0,"why":"A golden ticket attack uses the compromised KRBTGT hash to forge fully valid TGTs for any account, granting persistent domain-wide access. A silver ticket forges only service tickets using a service account's hash; kerberoasting extracts crackable service account credentials via TGS requests; pass-the-hash authenticates directly with an NTLM hash without involving Kerberos ticket forgery.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During an access review, an auditor discovers that a former employee's account was disabled but never removed from several application-level access groups. Which control weakness does this MOST directly indicate?","o":["Inadequate separation of duties","Failure in the deprovisioning process during account termination","Improper implementation of role mining","Lack of multi-factor authentication enforcement"],"c":1,"why":"The scenario describes incomplete removal of access rights during offboarding, which is a deprovisioning failure in the identity lifecycle process. It is unrelated to separation of duties, role mining (used for designing roles), or MFA enforcement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A user authenticates once at a central identity provider and is then granted access to multiple independent web applications across different organizations without re-authenticating. Which technology enables this capability?","o":["Kerberos","Federated identity management","Role-based access control","Discretionary access control"],"c":1,"why":"Federated identity management (e.g., using SAML or OpenID Connect) allows trust relationships across organizational boundaries so a single authentication is honored by multiple external service providers. Kerberos is typically used within a single trusted domain, and RBAC/DAC are authorization models, not cross-domain authentication mechanisms.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a federated identity solution using SAML so that employees can access a third-party SaaS application with their corporate credentials. In this arrangement, which entity is responsible for authenticating the user and issuing the assertion?","o":["The Service Provider (SP)","The Identity Provider (IdP)","The Relying Party (RP)","The SaaS application's local user store"],"c":1,"why":"In SAML federation, the Identity Provider authenticates the user and issues a signed assertion to the Service Provider; the SP (relying party) consumes the assertion rather than authenticating the user itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following is the BEST justification for implementing session recording and just-in-time credential checkout for administrator accounts in a Privileged Access Management (PAM) solution?","o":["It eliminates the need for periodic access reviews","It reduces the standing exposure of privileged credentials and provides accountability for privileged actions","It replaces the need for network segmentation between administrative and production systems","It allows administrators to permanently reuse the same static password across systems"],"c":1,"why":"Just-in-time checkout limits how long privileged credentials remain active, reducing attack surface, while session recording provides auditability and accountability for privileged actions. PAM complements—rather than replaces—access reviews and network segmentation, and it discourages, not encourages, static password reuse.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a Kerberos authentication environment, what is the primary function of the Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT)?","o":["It encrypts all network traffic between client and server","It serves as proof of prior authentication so the client can request service tickets without re-entering credentials","It stores the user's password for future logins","It grants direct access to a specific application server"],"c":1,"why":"The TGT is issued by the Key Distribution Center after initial authentication and allows the client to request service tickets for various resources without re-authenticating. It does not encrypt all traffic, store passwords, or grant direct server access—that is the role of service tickets.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to enforce that users can only access resources based on labels such as 'Confidential' or 'Secret' and a corresponding clearance level, with the operating system enforcing the policy regardless of the resource owner's wishes. Which access control model best fits this requirement?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":2,"why":"MAC enforces access based on security labels and clearances, with the system (not the owner) controlling access decisions—ideal for classified environments. DAC lets owners decide, and RBAC/rule-based control are not centered on labels/clearances.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A developer is integrating a third-party mobile app so it can post updates to a user's social media account without ever seeing the user's social media password. Which protocol is designed for this delegated authorization scenario?","o":["OAuth 2.0","Kerberos","LDAP","RADIUS"],"c":0,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is specifically designed to grant a third-party application limited, delegated access to a resource on the user's behalf using access tokens, without exposing the user's actual credentials. Kerberos, LDAP, and RADIUS are authentication/directory protocols, not designed for this token-based delegated authorization model.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"Which statement correctly describes a key architectural difference between OAuth 2.0 and OpenID Connect (OIDC)?","o":["OAuth 2.0 issues access tokens for delegated resource authorization, while OIDC adds an ID token on top of OAuth 2.0 that conveys user authentication information.","OAuth 2.0 is XML-based while OIDC is JSON-based, which is why OIDC is preferred for federated identity.","OAuth 2.0 requires a SAML assertion to complete the authorization code redirect, whereas OIDC does not.","OIDC replaces the OAuth 2.0 access token with a Kerberos service ticket for API authentication."],"c":0,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is strictly an authorization framework producing access tokens for resource access; OIDC extends OAuth 2.0 by adding a signed ID token that provides authentication/identity claims. OAuth is JSON/REST based (not XML, that describes SAML), and neither protocol depends on SAML or Kerberos to function.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A biometric access control system is configured with a very strict matching threshold. Which outcome is most likely to increase as a result?","o":["False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Throughput rate"],"c":1,"why":"A stricter threshold makes the system less tolerant of variation, causing more legitimate users to be incorrectly rejected, increasing FRR. FAR would decrease under stricter settings, CER is the point where FAR and FRR are equal (not simply increased), and throughput generally decreases, not increases.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During a security audit, an organization discovers that several terminated employees' accounts remained active for weeks after their last day. Which control failure MOST directly caused this issue?","o":["Lack of multi-factor authentication","Inadequate deprovisioning process in the identity lifecycle","Weak password complexity requirements","Absence of role mining during RBAC design"],"c":1,"why":"Timely deprovisioning is a core identity lifecycle management control; its failure directly explains lingering active accounts. MFA, password complexity, and role mining are unrelated to account termination timing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During a Kerberos authentication exchange, a security analyst notices that a captured authenticator was replayed by an attacker several minutes after the original session. Which built-in Kerberos mechanism is specifically designed to detect and prevent this type of replay attack?","o":["Ticket-granting ticket (TGT) renewal intervals enforced by the KDC","Timestamps in the authenticator combined with a configured clock-skew tolerance on the KDC and services","Mutual TLS between the client and the Key Distribution Center","Salting of the user's password hash prior to pre-authentication"],"c":1,"why":"Kerberos authenticators include a timestamp; the KDC and target services reject authenticators that fall outside an allowed clock-skew window, making replayed authenticators detectable. TGT renewal, mutual TLS, and password salting address different concerns and do not directly prevent authenticator replay.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the MOST important reason for promptly disabling a user account when an employee is terminated?","o":["To free up software licenses for other employees","To reduce the risk of unauthorized access using valid credentials","To comply with password complexity requirements","To simplify the organization's directory structure"],"c":1,"why":"Prompt deprovisioning prevents a terminated employee (or anyone using their credentials) from accessing systems after employment ends, which is a critical security control. License management and directory simplification are administrative benefits, not the primary security rationale, and password complexity is unrelated to deprovisioning.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A Kerberos-based authentication system relies on which component to issue session tickets after a user's initial identity is verified?","o":["The Key Distribution Center's Ticket Granting Service (TGS)","The application server's local authentication module","The Authentication Server's password hash cache","The client's cached session key from a previous logon"],"c":0,"why":"After initial authentication (via the Authentication Service and issuance of a TGT), the Ticket Granting Service within the KDC issues service tickets for subsequent resource access. The other options are not the component responsible for ticket issuance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A mobile application needs to access a user's calendar data hosted by a third-party cloud service, but the application must never see or store the user's actual login credentials for that service. Which protocol is specifically designed to solve this delegated-authorization use case?","o":["SAML 2.0","Kerberos","OAuth 2.0","RADIUS"],"c":2,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is purpose-built for delegated authorization, issuing scoped access tokens to third-party applications without exposing the resource owner's credentials. SAML is primarily for federated authentication assertions, Kerberos is for internal ticket-based authentication, and RADIUS is for network access authentication.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a discretionary access control (DAC) model, who is primarily responsible for determining which users can access a particular resource?","o":["The system administrator, based on organizational policy","The owner of the resource","A centralized security committee","The operating system, based on classification labels"],"c":1,"why":"DAC allows the owner of a resource (such as a file) to decide who else may access it, at their discretion. Centralized administration and classification-based enforcement are characteristic of MAC, not DAC, and a security committee is not typically involved in day-to-day DAC decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system is tuned to minimize the chance of an unauthorized person being granted access, even if it means more legitimate users are occasionally rejected. This tuning primarily affects which metric?","o":["Increasing the False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","Decreasing the False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Increasing the False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Lowering the Crossover Error Rate (CER) to zero"],"c":2,"why":"Tightening sensitivity to reduce unauthorized acceptances (lower FAR) typically increases FRR, rejecting more legitimate users. CER can't be forced to zero, and the scenario describes a trade-off, not simultaneous reduction of both errors.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A healthcare organization requires that only clinicians currently assigned to a patient's care team, accessing from an organization-managed device, during their scheduled shift, can view that patient's record. Which access control model natively supports this requirement with the least additional custom logic?","o":["Role-based access control (RBAC)","Attribute-based access control (ABAC)","Discretionary access control (DAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)"],"c":1,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes simultaneously (role, relationship to patient, device compliance, time) to make dynamic access decisions. RBAC alone only considers role, DAC relies on owner discretion, and MAC uses static classification labels—none can natively incorporate all the contextual conditions described.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants an access control model where a resource can be granted or denied based on a real-time combination of the subject's department, the resource's sensitivity label, the time of day, and the requesting device's patch compliance status. Which access control model best supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple dynamic attributes (subject, object, environment) at request time to make fine-grained, context-aware decisions, exactly matching this scenario. RBAC only considers role assignment, DAC relies on owner discretion, and MAC uses static classification/clearance labels without this level of contextual flexibility.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A network administrator is configuring centralized authentication for network device management (routers and switches) and requires that authentication, authorization, and accounting be handled as separate, granular processes with encrypted communication of the entire packet body. Which protocol best meets this requirement?","o":["RADIUS","TACACS+","Kerberos","LDAP"],"c":1,"why":"TACACS+ separates AAA functions and encrypts the entire packet payload, making it well suited for device administration. RADIUS combines authentication/authorization and only encrypts the password field; Kerberos and LDAP are not AAA protocols for network device management.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric access control system is retuned to lower its acceptance threshold in order to reduce complaints from legitimate users being denied entry. What is the most likely security consequence of this change?","o":["The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) will increase, raising the risk of unauthorized individuals being granted access.","The False Rejection Rate (FRR) will increase, causing more legitimate users to be denied access.","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) will decrease, improving overall system accuracy.","Enrollment time will increase, reducing throughput at the sensor."],"c":0,"why":"Lowering the acceptance threshold makes the system more permissive, which increases FAR (more impostors accepted) while decreasing FRR—the opposite of option B. CER is a fixed point on the FAR/FRR curve characterizing overall system accuracy and is not simply lowered by a threshold change; enrollment time is unrelated to threshold tuning.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"In a SAML 2.0 web-based single sign-on federation, a user authenticates once at their home organization and is then granted access to a partner's SaaS application without re-entering credentials. Which component is responsible for issuing the signed assertion that the SaaS application trusts to grant access?","o":["The Service Provider (SP)","The Identity Provider (IdP)","The SAML metadata repository","The user's local browser session cache"],"c":1,"why":"The Identity Provider authenticates the user and issues the signed SAML assertion, which the Service Provider consumes to grant access. The SP relies on and validates the assertion rather than issuing it, and metadata repositories/browser caches merely support configuration and session storage, not assertion issuance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization is designing an authorization framework for a mobile app that needs to access a user's cloud storage account without ever handling the user's actual cloud storage password. Which framework is specifically designed for this delegated authorization use case?","o":["OAuth 2.0","SAML 2.0","Kerberos","RADIUS"],"c":0,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is designed for delegated authorization, allowing a third-party app to access resources on a user's behalf via scoped tokens without exposing credentials. SAML focuses on authentication/SSO assertions, and Kerberos/RADIUS are not designed for this delegated third-party access model.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements a privileged access management (PAM) solution requiring administrators to check out temporary, time-limited credentials from a vault before performing privileged tasks, with credentials automatically rotated after each use. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this approach?","o":["It eliminates the need for multifactor authentication on privileged accounts.","It reduces the attack surface by minimizing the duration and reuse of privileged credentials.","It guarantees non-repudiation without requiring session logging.","It replaces the need for role-based access control over administrative functions."],"c":1,"why":"Just-in-time credential checkout with automatic rotation limits how long and how often privileged credentials remain valid, reducing exposure to theft and reuse. It does not eliminate the need for MFA, does not by itself provide non-repudiation without logging, and works alongside—not instead of—RBAC.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A privileged access management (PAM) program introduces just-in-time (JIT) elevation, where administrators request temporary, time-bound elevated rights approved through a workflow rather than holding standing administrative privileges. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this approach?","o":["It eliminates the need for multifactor authentication on privileged accounts","It reduces the attack surface by minimizing the duration and scope of standing privileged access","It replaces the need for session recording on privileged sessions","It guarantees non-repudiation without requiring centralized logging"],"c":1,"why":"JIT elevation minimizes standing privilege, shrinking the window during which an attacker could exploit a privileged account, which is the core benefit of JIT/PAM. MFA and session recording remain complementary controls, not replaced by JIT, and non-repudiation still depends on proper logging.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing an access control system for a hospital where nurses need access to patient records only for patients currently assigned to their care team, and this assignment changes daily. Which access control approach BEST supports this dynamic requirement?","o":["Static Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) with roles defined by job title only","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC) using contextual attributes like care team assignment","Mandatory Access Control (MAC) using fixed classification labels","Discretionary Access Control (DAC) where each nurse grants access to peers"],"c":1,"why":"ABAC evaluates dynamic attributes (e.g., current care team assignment, time, location) to make real-time access decisions, fitting frequently changing relationships. Static RBAC lacks this granularity, MAC relies on fixed labels, and DAC is inappropriate for enforcing organizational policy consistently.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric access control vendor advertises that their fingerprint system has a Crossover Error Rate (CER) of 0.3%, compared to a competing product with a CER of 1.2%. What does this comparison indicate about system performance?","o":["The 0.3% CER system has a higher False Acceptance Rate than the 1.2% CER system","The 0.3% CER system is generally more accurate, since CER represents the point where FAR and FRR are equal and a lower value indicates better overall performance","The CER value only measures enrollment failure rates and says nothing about matching accuracy","A lower CER always means slower authentication response times regardless of matching accuracy"],"c":1,"why":"CER is the point at which False Acceptance Rate and False Rejection Rate intersect; a lower CER indicates a more accurate biometric system overall. It does not by itself indicate FAR being higher in the better system, measure enrollment failures, or correlate directly with authentication speed.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A web application generates a session ID before user authentication and continues using that same session ID after successful login. An attacker sends a victim a link containing a pre-set session ID; after the victim logs in, the attacker uses the same session ID to access the account. Which vulnerability does this describe?","o":["Session hijacking via packet sniffing","Session fixation","Cross-site request forgery (CSRF)","Session replay attack"],"c":1,"why":"Session fixation occurs when an attacker sets a known session identifier before authentication and reuses it afterward to gain access. Hijacking involves stealing an already-active session ID (e.g., via sniffing), CSRF forges requests using an existing authenticated session without needing the session ID itself, and replay involves resending previously captured legitimate messages.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An internal audit finds several active accounts belonging to employees who left the organization three months ago, still retaining VPN and application access. Which control failure MOST directly explains this finding, and what is the BEST remediation?","o":["Weak password policy; remediate by enforcing longer minimum password length","Lack of automated deprovisioning tied to the HR termination workflow; remediate by integrating identity governance with the HR system for timely account deactivation","Insufficient encryption of credential stores; remediate by upgrading to a hardware security module","Missing network segmentation; remediate by isolating the VPN concentrator in a separate VLAN"],"c":1,"why":"Orphaned accounts after termination point to a broken or missing automated deprovisioning process; integrating identity lifecycle management with HR events ensures timely deactivation. Password policy, encryption strength, and network segmentation do not address the root cause of accounts remaining active after termination.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During an access review, an auditor finds several employee accounts that retain access rights from their former job roles six months after transferring to new departments, in addition to newly granted access for their current roles. This finding directly results from a failure in which identity management process?","o":["Account provisioning","The 'mover' process of entitlement review and revocation during role change","Password policy enforcement","Federation trust configuration"],"c":1,"why":"The joiner-mover-leaver lifecycle requires that when a user's role changes ('mover'), prior entitlements no longer needed be revoked; failure to do so causes privilege creep. Provisioning refers to initial account creation (which already succeeded), and password policy or federation trust issues are unrelated to accumulated stale entitlements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A native mobile application implements the OAuth 2.0 Authorization Code flow to authenticate users and obtain access tokens. Security architects mandate the use of PKCE (Proof Key for Code Exchange) in this flow. What specific risk does PKCE mitigate?","o":["Brute-force guessing of user passwords during the authentication step","Interception and misuse of the authorization code by a malicious app on the same device, since public clients cannot securely store a client secret","Expiration of refresh tokens before the access token lifetime ends","Cross-site scripting attacks against the authorization server's login page"],"c":1,"why":"PKCE binds the authorization code to a dynamically generated code verifier, preventing a malicious app that intercepts the authorization code (e.g., via a shared redirect URI) from exchanging it for tokens, which is critical for public clients that cannot hold a confidential client secret. It does not address password brute-forcing, token expiration timing, or XSS on the authorization server itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A web application constructs LDAP search filters by directly concatenating unsanitized user input, such as building the filter (&(uid=<user_input>)(objectClass=person)). Which attack is this application most vulnerable to?","o":["LDAP injection, allowing an attacker to manipulate the search filter to bypass authentication or extract directory data","Pass-the-hash attack against the LDAP bind account","Kerberoasting of the LDAP service principal name","Man-in-the-middle attack due to unencrypted LDAP traffic"],"c":0,"why":"Concatenating unsanitized input into LDAP filter syntax is a classic LDAP injection vulnerability, analogous to SQL injection, allowing filter logic manipulation. The other options describe unrelated attack techniques not indicated by this specific coding flaw.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An employee logs into a corporate network using a smart card that generates a one-time PIN, in addition to a memorized PIN they enter manually. Which authentication factor category does the smart card represent?","o":["Something you know","Something you have","Something you are","Somewhere you are"],"c":1,"why":"A smart card is a physical token, making it 'something you have.' The memorized PIN is 'something you know.' Biometrics fall under 'something you are,' and location-based checks fall under 'somewhere you are,' neither of which applies to a smart card.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company wants to simplify permission management by assigning access rights based on employees' job functions rather than granting permissions to each user individually. Which access control model best fits this requirement?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions to roles that correspond to job functions, and users inherit permissions through role membership, simplifying administration. DAC relies on resource owners granting access, MAC uses security labels/clearances, and rule-based control uses predefined conditional rules rather than job roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a Kerberos authentication environment, what is the primary role of the Key Distribution Center (KDC)?","o":["To store user passwords in plaintext for verification","To issue and validate tickets used for authenticating clients to services","To encrypt all network traffic between clients and servers","To serve as the primary file server for the domain"],"c":1,"why":"The KDC issues ticket-granting tickets and service tickets that clients use to prove their identity to services without repeatedly sending credentials. It does not store plaintext passwords, encrypt general network traffic, or function as a file server.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A biometric access control system is configured with a very strict matching threshold to minimize the risk of unauthorized access. What is the MOST likely consequence of this configuration?","o":["A decrease in the False Acceptance Rate (FAR) and an increase in the False Rejection Rate (FRR)","An increase in both FAR and FRR simultaneously","A decrease in both FAR and FRR simultaneously","An increase in FAR and a decrease in FRR"],"c":0,"why":"Tightening the matching threshold makes the system less likely to accept an impostor (lower FAR) but more likely to reject legitimate users (higher FRR), since FAR and FRR typically have an inverse relationship. The other options misstate this well-known trade-off.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee is terminated from an organization, which of the following should occur FIRST as part of proper identity and access management practices?","o":["Archive the employee's personal files for future reference","Notify the employee's former manager via email","Disable or revoke the employee's access credentials immediately","Wait 30 days before removing any system access"],"c":2,"why":"Immediate revocation of access credentials upon termination is a critical control to prevent unauthorized access by a former employee. Archiving files, manager notification, or delaying access removal are secondary or inappropriate practices that increase security risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company wants its employees to use their existing corporate credentials to log into a third-party SaaS application without creating a separate account on that application. Which technology BEST supports this requirement?","o":["Federated identity management using SAML or OpenID Connect","Discretionary access control lists on the SaaS application","A shared local administrator account","Mandatory password rotation policies"],"c":0,"why":"Federated identity management allows users to authenticate with their home organization's credentials and access external services through trust relationships, commonly implemented with SAML or OpenID Connect. The other options do not address cross-domain authentication trust.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a Mandatory Access Control (MAC) model, access decisions are primarily based on which of the following?","o":["The discretion of the resource owner","Security labels and clearance levels assigned by a central authority","Group membership defined by department managers","Time-of-day restrictions configured by the user"],"c":1,"why":"MAC relies on centrally assigned security labels (e.g., classification levels) and user clearances to enforce access decisions, removing discretion from individual users. DAC involves owner discretion, while group membership and time restrictions are not defining characteristics of MAC.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to log in using a password AND a hardware token that generates a one-time code. This is an example of which authentication concept?","o":["Single-factor authentication using two credentials","Multifactor authentication combining something you know and something you have","Biometric authentication","Federated identity authentication"],"c":1,"why":"A password (something you know) plus a hardware token (something you have) represents two distinct factor categories, which is the definition of multifactor authentication. The other options misclassify the factor types or describe unrelated concepts.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to allow employees to log into a cloud-based expense reporting application using their corporate Active Directory credentials, without the cloud application ever seeing the user's password. Which technology best meets this requirement?","o":["SAML-based federated single sign-on","OAuth 2.0 client credentials grant","RADIUS authentication proxy","Kerberos ticket-granting service alone"],"c":0,"why":"SAML federation allows an identity provider (AD via a federation service) to issue signed assertions to a relying party (the cloud app), so the password never leaves the corporate domain. OAuth 2.0 is designed for authorization/delegated access to resources, not primarily for authenticating a user's identity to a relying party in this manner, RADIUS is typically used for network device authentication, and Kerberos alone does not extend trust across separate organizational/cloud boundaries without federation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"In a Kerberos-based authentication environment, an attacker who has compromised the krbtgt account's secret key can forge Ticket Granting Tickets (TGTs) that appear completely valid to the Key Distribution Center (KDC). What is this attack called, and why is it particularly dangerous?","o":["Pass-the-hash attack; it allows lateral movement using captured NTLM hashes without ever involving Kerberos","Golden ticket attack; because the krbtgt key is rarely rotated, forged TGTs can grant access to virtually any resource for an extended period until the key is changed","Kerberoasting; because service account password hashes extracted from service tickets can be cracked offline","Silver ticket attack; because it forges the TGT itself rather than a service ticket, granting unlimited access to any service"],"c":1,"why":"A golden ticket attack forges TGTs using the compromised krbtgt key, and because that key is infrequently rotated, the forged tickets remain valid and undetected for long periods. Pass-the-hash and Kerberoasting are distinct attacks not involving krbtgt compromise, and a silver ticket forges service tickets using a service account's key, not the krbtgt key.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In an access control model where permissions are assigned to job functions and users are granted access by being assigned to those functions, what is this model called?","o":["Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions to roles (job functions) rather than individuals, simplifying administration. MAC uses security labels/clearances, DAC lets resource owners grant access, and rule-based control relies on predefined conditional rules, not job roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A healthcare system needs to grant access to patient records based on a combination of the requester's role, the time of day, the patient's consent status, and whether the requester is on-site. Which access control model is best suited to this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple attributes (role, time, location, consent) dynamically at access time via policy rules, making it ideal for this multi-condition scenario. RBAC only considers role, DAC relies on resource owner discretion, and MAC uses fixed sensitivity labels rather than contextual attributes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing a SAML 2.0 federation between a corporate Identity Provider (IdP) and a cloud-based Service Provider (SP). Which control is MOST critical to prevent an attacker from tampering with attribute values inside a SAML assertion while it is in transit?","o":["Encrypting the SAML response using TLS at the transport layer","Digitally signing the SAML assertion using the IdP's private key","Setting a short assertion validity window using the NotOnOrAfter condition","Requiring the SP to validate the AudienceRestriction element"],"c":1,"why":"Digitally signing the assertion provides integrity protection, allowing the SP to detect any modification of attribute values. TLS protects data in transit between endpoints but does not prevent tampering if an endpoint or intermediary alters the assertion before signing verification; validity windows prevent replay, and audience restriction prevents misuse by unintended SPs, neither of which detects tampering.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a Kerberos authentication exchange, what is the primary purpose of including a timestamp in the authenticator sent to a service?","o":["To encrypt the session key using a stronger algorithm","To allow the KDC to issue a new ticket-granting ticket","To mitigate replay attacks by limiting the validity window of the request","To identify which realm the user belongs to"],"c":2,"why":"Timestamps in Kerberos authenticators let the service verify the request is recent and reject old, replayed authenticators, and clock synchronization enforces this window. Timestamps do not affect encryption strength, they are unrelated to TGT issuance, and realm identification is handled by principal naming, not timestamps.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company implements Single Sign-On (SSO) so employees authenticate once to access multiple applications. What is the PRIMARY security risk introduced by SSO?","o":["Users must remember multiple complex passwords","A compromised credential grants access to all connected systems","It eliminates the need for access reviews","It prevents the use of multifactor authentication"],"c":1,"why":"SSO's main risk is that a single compromised credential can expose every integrated system, increasing the impact of account compromise. SSO actually reduces password fatigue, does not eliminate access reviews, and can be combined with MFA.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization needs an access control model that can grant a contractor access to a project's financial documents only during business hours, only from corporate-managed devices, and only while the project's status field in the HR system reads 'Active.' Which access control model BEST supports this requirement natively?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple dynamic attributes (subject, environment, resource, time, device state) at access time, natively supporting this contextual policy. RBAC would require an explosion of roles to capture these conditions, DAC relies on owner discretion without contextual evaluation, and MAC relies on static sensitivity labels rather than dynamic contextual attributes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control vendor advertises that their fingerprint scanner has a lower Crossover Error Rate (CER) than a competitor's product. What does this indicate about the vendor's system?","o":["It has a higher False Acceptance Rate but lower False Rejection Rate","It is generally more accurate because FAR and FRR are lower and closer together at the crossover point","It requires a longer enrollment period to capture biometric templates","It uses a stronger hashing algorithm to store biometric templates"],"c":1,"why":"CER is the point where False Acceptance Rate equals False Rejection Rate; a lower CER means both error rates are minimized at that intersection, indicating higher overall accuracy. The other options describe unrelated system characteristics not indicated by CER.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a federated identity system using SAML, which component is responsible for authenticating the user and issuing an assertion to the service provider?","o":["The relying party","The identity provider (IdP)","The certificate authority","The resource server"],"c":1,"why":"The Identity Provider (IdP) authenticates the user and generates the SAML assertion that the service provider (relying party) trusts. The relying party consumes the assertion rather than issuing it, and a CA and resource server play different roles unrelated to SAML assertion issuance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During an access review, an auditor discovers several user accounts belonging to employees who left the company over six months ago, all of which still have active VPN and application access. Which control failure does this MOST directly indicate?","o":["Inadequate separation of duties","Failure in the identity deprovisioning process","Excessive use of privileged access management","Lack of multifactor authentication enforcement"],"c":1,"why":"Active accounts for terminated employees point to a breakdown in the deprovisioning stage of the identity lifecycle, where accounts should be disabled/removed upon termination. This is unrelated to separation of duties, PAM usage, or MFA enforcement, which address different risks.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric authentication system is tuned by adjusting its matching sensitivity threshold. As the threshold becomes stricter, the False Acceptance Rate (FAR) decreases while the False Rejection Rate (FRR) increases. What is the term for the point where the FAR and FRR curves intersect, and why is it significant?","o":["Type II error rate; it measures unauthorized acceptance independent of rejection rate","Crossover Error Rate (CER); it provides a single comparative metric of overall system accuracy, with a lower CER indicating better performance","Equal error margin; it defines the minimum acceptable biometric template enrollment time","Throughput rate; it measures how quickly the system processes authentication attempts under load"],"c":1,"why":"The Crossover Error Rate (CER) is the point where FAR equals FRR and is used as a standard benchmark for comparing biometric system accuracy across vendors—lower CER means better overall performance. Type II error rate refers only to false acceptance, not the intersection point, and the other options describe unrelated or fabricated metrics.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In the Kerberos authentication protocol, which component issues the ticket-granting ticket (TGT) to a user after initial authentication?","o":["The Key Distribution Center (KDC)","The service server","The client workstation","The relying party"],"c":0,"why":"The Key Distribution Center (KDC), specifically its Authentication Service, issues the TGT after verifying the user's credentials. The service server later grants service tickets, and the client and relying party do not issue TGTs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements Kerberos for network authentication. During testing, a security analyst discovers that a workstation's clock is 15 minutes ahead of the KDC's clock, and authentication attempts from that workstation are being rejected. Which security property of Kerberos is being enforced by this behavior?","o":["Mutual authentication between client and server","Symmetric encryption of the ticket-granting ticket","Protection against replay attacks via timestamp validation","Enforcement of the principle of least privilege"],"c":2,"why":"Kerberos relies on tightly synchronized clocks to validate authenticator timestamps and reject stale or replayed tickets; excessive clock skew causes valid requests to be rejected as potential replays. The other options describe legitimate Kerberos features but are not the mechanism being enforced by clock-skew checking.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing a solution to limit standing administrative access to critical servers, requiring administrators to request elevated privileges for a limited time window with approval and session recording. Which concept does this describe?","o":["Role mining","Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access management","Federated identity provisioning","Discretionary access control delegation"],"c":1,"why":"JIT privileged access management grants temporary, approved elevation of privileges only when needed, reducing the attack surface of standing admin rights, and typically includes session monitoring. Role mining is about discovering role structures, federated provisioning concerns cross-domain identity lifecycle, and DAC delegation is unrelated to time-bound elevation with approval workflows.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A biometric access control system incorrectly denies access to a legitimate, authorized user. This error is measured by which metric?","o":["False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Equal Error Rate (EER)"],"c":1,"why":"False Rejection Rate (FRR) measures how often legitimate users are incorrectly denied access. FAR measures the opposite error (unauthorized users accepted), and CER/EER represent the point where FAR and FRR are equal, not a single error type.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During a security assessment of a SAML-based SSO implementation, a tester successfully alters the NameID element inside a digitally signed SAML assertion without invalidating the signature, allowing impersonation of another user. Which attack technique was exploited?","o":["Cross-site request forgery (CSRF)","XML Signature Wrapping (XSW)","SAML assertion replay attack","OAuth access token substitution"],"c":1,"why":"XML Signature Wrapping exploits weaknesses in how XML signature validation is separated from the actual data processing logic, allowing an attacker to insert malicious content that is processed but not the content that was signed. CSRF, replay attacks, and OAuth token substitution involve different mechanisms and do not explain signature bypass via structural XML manipulation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization issues employees a smart card that must be inserted into a reader along with entry of a PIN to authenticate to workstations. Which authentication factor combination does this represent?","o":["Something you know and something you are","Something you have and something you know","Something you have and something you are","Two instances of something you know"],"c":1,"why":"The smart card is 'something you have' and the PIN is 'something you know,' making this a true two-factor authentication scheme. It does not involve biometrics ('something you are'), and it is not two instances of the same factor type.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"To reduce risk from standing privileged access, a security team implements a PAM solution that issues administrators temporary elevated credentials only when needed for a specific task, automatically revoking them after a defined period. Which security principle does this MOST directly implement?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege, via just-in-time (JIT) access provisioning","Defense in depth","Non-repudiation"],"c":1,"why":"JIT provisioning is a direct application of least privilege, minimizing the time window during which elevated privileges exist. Separation of duties divides tasks among multiple people, defense in depth layers multiple controls, and non-repudiation concerns proof of action, none of which describe time-limited privilege elevation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A hospital wants clinicians to access patient records only when they are physically on-site, using a hospital-issued device, and during their scheduled shift hours. Which access control model BEST supports this requirement?","o":["Role-based access control (RBAC)","Discretionary access control (DAC)","Attribute-based access control (ABAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple dynamic attributes (location, device identity, time) at the time of access request, making it ideal for context-dependent policies. RBAC grants access based solely on assigned roles without contextual attributes, DAC relies on owner discretion, and MAC uses static classification labels, none of which natively support this multi-attribute contextual decision.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee is terminated, which IAM practice is MOST important to perform promptly to reduce security risk?","o":["Resetting the employee's manager's password","Deprovisioning the employee's accounts and access rights","Rotating encryption keys organization-wide","Conducting a full penetration test"],"c":1,"why":"Prompt deprovisioning removes the terminated employee's access, preventing misuse of orphaned accounts. The other options are unrelated or disproportionate responses to a termination event.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company's access control policy states that the employee who processes vendor payments cannot also be the employee who approves new vendors in the system. This policy is an example of which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Need-to-know","Mandatory access control"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by a single individual, exactly as described. Least privilege concerns limiting access to only what's needed for a job function, need-to-know restricts access to specific information, and MAC is a labeling-based access control model, none of which describe splitting duties between roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester discovers that an internal web application builds LDAP search filters by directly concatenating unsanitized user input, such as a username field, into the filter string. Which attack is this application MOST vulnerable to, and what is an effective primary mitigation?","o":["Cross-site scripting; mitigated through output encoding of HTML responses","LDAP injection; mitigated through input validation and escaping of special LDAP filter characters","SQL injection; mitigated through the use of parameterized stored procedures","Kerberoasting; mitigated through enforcing strong service account passwords"],"c":1,"why":"Directly concatenating user input into LDAP filters allows attackers to inject special characters (e.g., *, (, )) to manipulate search logic—LDAP injection—mitigated by escaping special characters or using safe filter construction APIs. The other options describe unrelated attack classes and backends.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which access control model enforces access decisions based on security labels and clearance levels assigned by a central authority, rather than allowing resource owners to control access?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)"],"c":1,"why":"MAC uses centrally assigned labels and clearances (common in government/military systems) and does not allow owners discretion over access. DAC gives owners control, ABAC uses attributes/policies, and RBAC uses roles, none of which match the label/clearance description.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A financial firm terminates an employee for cause. The manager notifies HR the same day, but IT security does not disable the employee's accounts until three business days later due to a ticketing backlog. This scenario best illustrates a failure in which IAM process?","o":["Access recertification","Identity proofing","Timely deprovisioning","Federation trust establishment"],"c":2,"why":"Timely deprovisioning requires that access be revoked immediately upon termination to prevent unauthorized use of orphaned accounts; a multi-day delay represents a critical control failure in this process. Recertification concerns periodic access review, identity proofing concerns initial identity verification, and federation trust relates to cross-domain authentication agreements, none of which apply here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise uses federated SSO where a third-party SaaS provider is the Service Provider (SP) and the enterprise's AD FS instance is the Identity Provider (IdP). An employee is terminated and their AD account is immediately disabled, yet the employee retains access to the SaaS application for several more hours through an existing session. What is the MOST likely explanation?","o":["The SP never validated the IdP's signing certificate during the original authentication","The SP is honoring a previously issued long-lived session or token; disabling the account at the IdP prevents new authentications but does not automatically revoke existing SP-side sessions","The employee's account was moved to a disabled OU but retained a valid Kerberos TGT for the remainder of its lifetime","AD FS caches user credentials locally for 24 hours by default, allowing continued authentication"],"c":1,"why":"In federated SSO, authentication occurs once and results in a session/token at the SP; disabling the account at the IdP blocks future authentications but does not inherently terminate active sessions already established at the SP unless single logout or continuous access evaluation is implemented. The other options misattribute the cause to certificate validation, Kerberos TGT lifetime (irrelevant to a SAML/OIDC federation to a SaaS SP), or a nonexistent AD FS credential caching default.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A healthcare organization wants access decisions to be based on a combination of factors such as the user's department, the sensitivity of the patient record, the time of day, and whether the request originates from a hospital network. Which access control model BEST supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":1,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes (subject, object, environment) at access time, making it ideal for dynamic, multi-factor policy decisions. RBAC relies on static role assignments, MAC uses fixed classification labels, and DAC leaves access decisions to resource owners, none of which natively support the described multi-attribute logic.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During an access review, an auditor finds numerous 'orphaned accounts'—accounts still active in a critical application long after the associated employees left the organization. Which control failure is the MOST direct root cause of this finding?","o":["Lack of multi-factor authentication enforcement on the application","Absence of automated deprovisioning tied to termination events from the authoritative HR system within the identity lifecycle management process","Failure to implement role-based access control for the application","Insufficient password complexity requirements for application accounts"],"c":1,"why":"Orphaned accounts are a classic symptom of a broken joiner-mover-leaver process, specifically the lack of automated deprovisioning triggered by HR termination events. MFA, RBAC, and password complexity address different risks and would not by themselves prevent accounts from remaining active after termination.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An enterprise uses Kerberos for network authentication. Why do Kerberos implementations require closely synchronized clocks between clients, servers, and the Key Distribution Center (KDC)?","o":["To ensure ticket-granting tickets are encrypted using the strongest available cipher suite","To validate ticket timestamps and prevent replay attacks within an allowable time window","To enable the KDC to issue X.509 certificates for mutual authentication","To allow federated single sign-on across unrelated Kerberos realms"],"c":1,"why":"Kerberos tickets contain timestamps, and clock skew beyond the configured tolerance causes tickets to be rejected, which is a deliberate anti-replay control. Encryption strength, certificate issuance, and cross-realm federation are unrelated to the time-synchronization requirement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric vendor advertises that their fingerprint scanner has a Crossover Error Rate (CER) of 0.1%. What does this metric indicate about the system's performance?","o":["The point at which the False Acceptance Rate and False Rejection Rate are equal, representing overall accuracy","The percentage of authorized users who are falsely rejected during enrollment","The percentage of unauthorized users who are falsely accepted under the strictest sensitivity setting","The average time required to enroll a new biometric template"],"c":0,"why":"CER (also called the Equal Error Rate) is the threshold point where FAR and FRR intersect, and a lower CER indicates a more accurate biometric system overall. The other options describe FRR, FAR at a specific setting, or enrollment speed, none of which define the crossover point itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A user logs into a corporate system by inserting a smart card and entering a PIN. Which statement BEST describes why this qualifies as multi-factor authentication?","o":["It combines two independent knowledge factors, which strengthens the login process","It combines a possession factor (the card) with a knowledge factor (the PIN)","It combines two biometric factors captured from the same device","It relies on a single factor verified twice for redundancy"],"c":1,"why":"True multi-factor authentication requires factors from different categories; the smart card is something the user has, and the PIN is something the user knows. The other options either misclassify the factors or describe single-factor authentication.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY security risk introduced by implementing a Single Sign-On (SSO) solution across an enterprise?","o":["Increased likelihood of password reuse across multiple systems","Compromise of a single credential set grants an attacker access to all connected systems","Users are required to remember multiple complex passwords","Reduced visibility into user activity across integrated systems"],"c":1,"why":"SSO centralizes authentication, so a single compromised credential becomes a master key to every federated system, dramatically raising the impact of a breach. SSO actually reduces password reuse and the burden of remembering multiple passwords, and centralized logging typically improves, not reduces, visibility.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a SAML-based web SSO federation, after a user successfully authenticates, which entity generates and digitally signs the assertion that is presented to the service provider?","o":["The relying party","The identity provider (IdP)","The service provider (SP)","The attribute exchange broker"],"c":1,"why":"The identity provider authenticates the user and issues the signed SAML assertion consumed by the service provider (also called the relying party). The service provider/relying party consumes the assertion rather than issuing it, and there is no standard 'attribute exchange broker' role in basic SAML SSO.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing a privileged access management (PAM) solution for cloud infrastructure administrators. To minimize the attack surface associated with standing privileged accounts, which approach should be prioritized?","o":["Assigning permanent administrator roles protected by strong password policies","Implementing just-in-time (JIT) privileged access with time-bound elevation","Requiring multi-factor authentication only at initial login","Rotating shared administrator passwords on a monthly schedule"],"c":1,"why":"Just-in-time access grants elevated privileges only for the duration needed and automatically revokes them afterward, eliminating persistent standing privileges that attackers could exploit. Permanent roles, one-time MFA, and monthly password rotation all leave privileged access continuously available and do not address the standing-access risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"To reduce help-desk complaints about failed logins, an administrator lowers the sensitivity threshold on a fingerprint biometric system. What is the MOST likely security consequence of this change?","o":["Both the False Acceptance Rate (FAR) and False Rejection Rate (FRR) will decrease","The False Rejection Rate (FRR) will decrease while the False Acceptance Rate (FAR) will increase","The crossover error rate (CER) will improve, strengthening overall security","The system will require re-enrollment of all registered users"],"c":1,"why":"Lowering the matching threshold makes the system more lenient, reducing legitimate user rejections (FRR) but increasing the chance that impostors are falsely accepted (FAR), a classic biometric trade-off. CER measures the point where FAR and FRR are equal and is not automatically improved by this change; re-enrollment is not required.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester submits the string `*)(uid=*))(|(uid=*` into a web application's username field that is used to construct an LDAP search filter. The application returns all directory entries instead of a single user record. Which vulnerability does this demonstrate?","o":["LDAP injection due to improper input sanitization","A Kerberos golden ticket attack","SAML assertion tampering","Directory traversal attack"],"c":0,"why":"The crafted string manipulates LDAP filter syntax to alter query logic, a classic LDAP injection resulting from unsanitized input being directly embedded into the search filter. Golden ticket attacks target Kerberos TGTs, SAML tampering affects XML assertions, and directory traversal involves manipulating file system paths, none of which match this LDAP filter manipulation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization frequently discovers active accounts belonging to employees who left the company months earlier. Which control would MOST effectively address this identity lifecycle weakness?","o":["Requiring all employees to change passwords every 60 days","Conducting a manual access review once per year","Automating account deprovisioning triggered directly by HR termination events","Implementing single sign-on across all business applications"],"c":2,"why":"Automated deprovisioning tied to authoritative HR termination events immediately disables orphaned accounts, closing the gap between employee departure and access revocation. Periodic password changes, annual reviews, and SSO do not directly ensure timely account termination.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A user authenticates to a workstation and then leaves the desk unattended for an extended period without logging off. Which control is MOST effective at reducing the risk of an unauthorized person using the still-authenticated session?","o":["Enforcing a strong password complexity policy","Implementing an automatic idle session timeout with screen lock","Increasing the account lockout threshold after failed attempts","Requiring biometric enrollment for all users"],"c":1,"why":"An idle session timeout automatically locks or terminates an unattended authenticated session, directly mitigating unauthorized use. Password complexity, lockout thresholds, and biometric enrollment address different threats (guessing/brute force and initial authentication) but not an already-active unattended session.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to minimize the risk associated with standing administrative privileges on critical servers. Which approach BEST reduces this risk while still allowing administrators to perform necessary tasks?","o":["Assign all administrators to a single shared privileged account for simplicity","Grant permanent administrative rights to reduce delays in incident response","Implement just-in-time privileged access that grants time-limited, approval-based elevation","Disable multifactor authentication on administrative accounts to speed up routine tasks"],"c":2,"why":"Just-in-time privileged access grants elevated rights only when needed and automatically revokes them afterward, minimizing the window of exposure from standing privileges. Shared accounts destroy accountability, permanent rights increase risk, and disabling MFA weakens rather than strengthens security.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to log in using a password plus a one-time code generated by a mobile app. This is an example of which authentication concept?","o":["Single-factor authentication","Multi-factor authentication","Single sign-on","Role-based access control"],"c":1,"why":"Combining a password (something you know) with a one-time code from a device (something you have) uses two different factor types, which defines multi-factor authentication. The other options describe unrelated concepts.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which access control model assigns permissions to users based on their job function within an organization, simplifying administration by grouping similar access needs?","o":["Discretionary access control (DAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)","Role-based access control (RBAC)","Rule-based access control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC grants access based on predefined roles tied to job functions, reducing administrative overhead. DAC lets owners assign permissions, MAC uses security labels/clearances, and rule-based control uses if-then rules rather than roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company implements single sign-on (SSO) so employees can authenticate once and access multiple applications. What is a primary security risk introduced by SSO?","o":["Users must remember multiple complex passwords","If credentials are compromised, an attacker gains access to all connected applications","SSO eliminates the need for any authentication","SSO automatically enforces least privilege across all systems"],"c":1,"why":"SSO increases the impact of a single compromised credential set since it unlocks access to many systems, making strong authentication and monitoring essential. The other statements misrepresent how SSO functions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In biometric authentication systems, what does a high False Rejection Rate (FRR) indicate?","o":["Unauthorized users are frequently granted access","Authorized users are frequently denied access","The system has no crossover error rate","The biometric template is stored in an unencrypted format"],"c":1,"why":"FRR measures how often legitimate users are incorrectly rejected by the system, causing usability issues. A high False Acceptance Rate (FAR), not FRR, would indicate unauthorized users being granted access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which practice is MOST important to ensure when an employee is terminated, in order to maintain proper identity and access management?","o":["Archiving the employee's email for future reference","Promptly disabling or removing all of the employee's access accounts","Notifying the employee's team about the termination","Changing the organization's overall password policy"],"c":1,"why":"Timely deprovisioning of accounts prevents former employees from retaining unauthorized access, which is a core IAM control. The other actions may be reasonable HR steps but do not directly address access risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial services company wants to grant access to a shared reporting dashboard based on attributes such as the user's department, current project assignment, time of day, and the sensitivity level of the data being requested. Which access control model best supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":1,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple dynamic attributes (department, project, time, data sensitivity) at access time to make fine-grained decisions, which RBAC's static role assignments cannot easily accommodate. MAC relies on fixed security labels/clearances, and DAC relies on resource owner discretion, neither of which natively supports multi-attribute contextual decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A user logs into a cloud application using their corporate credentials via an identity provider, without the cloud application ever seeing the user's password. This scenario BEST describes which concept?","o":["Federated identity management","Mandatory access control","Discretionary access control","Rule-based access control"],"c":0,"why":"Federated identity management allows a trusted identity provider to authenticate users and pass assertions (e.g., via SAML) to service providers, so the application never handles the password directly. The other options are unrelated access control models.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements Kerberos for network authentication. During the authentication process, which component is responsible for issuing a Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT) to a user after successful initial authentication?","o":["The Ticket Granting Service (TGS)","The Authentication Server (AS)","The application server being accessed","The client workstation itself"],"c":1,"why":"The Authentication Server (AS), part of the Key Distribution Center (KDC), verifies the user's initial credentials and issues the TGT. The TGS later uses that TGT to issue service tickets for specific resources, and the application server and client are not responsible for issuing tickets.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"According to the principle of least privilege, users should be granted:","o":["The maximum access needed for any future role changes","Only the minimum access necessary to perform their current job functions","Full administrative access to reduce help desk tickets","Access equal to that of their direct supervisor"],"c":1,"why":"Least privilege restricts users to only the access required for their current tasks, minimizing the potential impact of misuse or compromise. The other options grant excessive, unnecessary access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to log in using a password AND a smart card. This is an example of which authentication concept?","o":["Single sign-on","Multifactor authentication","Role-based access control","Discretionary access control"],"c":1,"why":"Combining something you know (password) with something you have (smart card) uses two different factor types, which defines multifactor authentication. SSO refers to logging in once for multiple systems, and RBAC/DAC are authorization models, not authentication methods.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system is being tuned for optimal performance. At the point where the False Acceptance Rate (FAR) and False Rejection Rate (FRR) curves intersect, what is this point called, and what does it represent?","o":["Throughput rate; the speed at which the system processes users","Crossover Error Rate (CER); a measure of the system's overall accuracy","Enrollment rate; the percentage of users successfully enrolled","Type II error rate; the rate of unauthorized users being accepted"],"c":1,"why":"The Crossover Error Rate (CER) is the point where FAR equals FRR, and a lower CER indicates a more accurate biometric system; it is a standard metric for comparing biometric technologies. Throughput and enrollment rate measure different aspects of biometric performance, and Type II error alone only describes FAR.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In Role-Based Access Control (RBAC), access permissions are primarily assigned based on which of the following?","o":["The sensitivity label of the data object","The job function or role of the user","The discretion of the data owner","The physical location of the user"],"c":1,"why":"RBAC grants access based on a user's assigned role within the organization, simplifying administration. Sensitivity labels describe Mandatory Access Control (MAC), and owner discretion describes Discretionary Access Control (DAC).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During an audit, it is discovered that several employees who left the company six months ago still have active accounts with valid credentials. Which control failure does this scenario BEST illustrate?","o":["Lack of multifactor authentication","Inadequate account deprovisioning process","Failure to enforce least privilege","Absence of role-based access control"],"c":1,"why":"Timely deprovisioning upon termination is a core identity lifecycle control; its absence leaves orphaned accounts active for exploitation. MFA, least privilege, and RBAC address different aspects of access control and would not directly explain accounts remaining active after termination.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A user authenticates to a system using a smart card and a PIN. Which statement BEST describes this authentication approach?","o":["This is single-factor authentication because both elements are tied to the same physical card","This is true multifactor authentication because it combines something the user has with something the user knows","This is knowledge-based authentication only","This is risk-based authentication because the PIN adds contextual risk scoring"],"c":1,"why":"Multifactor authentication requires factors from at least two different categories; the smart card is 'something you have' and the PIN is 'something you know,' satisfying that requirement regardless of both being used together. It is not single-factor, purely knowledge-based, or risk-based since no contextual/behavioral scoring is involved.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary benefit of implementing Single Sign-On (SSO)?","o":["It eliminates the need for any authentication credentials","It allows a user to authenticate once and access multiple systems without re-authenticating","It automatically encrypts all network traffic","It replaces the need for access control lists"],"c":1,"why":"SSO improves usability and reduces password fatigue by allowing one authentication event to grant access to multiple connected systems. It does not eliminate credentials, encrypt traffic, or replace ACLs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In biometric authentication systems, the False Rejection Rate (FRR) measures which of the following?","o":["The percentage of unauthorized users incorrectly granted access","The percentage of authorized users incorrectly denied access","The time required to enroll a new user's biometric template","The likelihood that two users share identical biometric traits"],"c":1,"why":"FRR (Type I error) measures how often legitimate, authorized users are wrongly rejected by the system. The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) measures unauthorized users being wrongly accepted, which is the opposite error type.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to allow a mobile application to access a user's calendar data hosted by a third-party cloud provider without ever handling or storing the user's actual password. Which protocol is specifically designed for this delegated authorization scenario?","o":["Kerberos","RADIUS","OAuth 2.0","LDAP"],"c":2,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is designed for delegated authorization, allowing a client application to obtain limited access to a resource on behalf of a user via access tokens, without exposing the user's credentials to the client. Kerberos and RADIUS are authentication/AAA protocols not designed for this token-based delegation pattern, and LDAP is a directory access protocol.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language) is most commonly used to support which identity and access management function?","o":["Encrypting stored passwords in a database","Federated single sign-on across different organizations","Assigning discretionary permissions to file owners","Generating one-time passwords for MFA"],"c":1,"why":"SAML is an XML-based standard that enables identity federation, allowing a user authenticated by one organization (identity provider) to access resources at another organization (service provider) via SSO. It is not used for password encryption or OTP generation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization enforces a policy that no single employee can both initiate a wire transfer and approve it within the banking application. Which security principle does this policy exemplify?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Need to know"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties requires that critical tasks be divided among multiple individuals to prevent fraud or error by any single person, exactly as described. Least privilege limits access to only what's needed for a job function, defense in depth layers multiple controls, and need to know restricts information access based on necessity, none of which specifically address dividing conflicting duties.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements Kerberos for network authentication. A user successfully authenticates to the Key Distribution Center (KDC) and receives a ticket-granting ticket (TGT). What must the user present to the Ticket Granting Service (TGS) to obtain a service ticket for a specific application server?","o":["The user's plaintext password and the TGT","The TGT and an authenticator encrypted with the session key shared with the KDC","A digital certificate signed by the application server","The TGT alone, without any additional authenticator"],"c":1,"why":"Kerberos requires the client to present the TGT along with an authenticator (timestamp encrypted with the session key) to prove it is the legitimate ticket holder; presenting the TGT alone or a password would be replayable or insecure, and certificates are not part of standard Kerberos ticket exchange.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In the Kerberos authentication protocol, which component issues session tickets after a user has been initially authenticated?","o":["The Key Distribution Center's Ticket Granting Service","The client workstation","The application server directly","The X.509 certificate authority"],"c":0,"why":"After initial authentication, the Ticket Granting Service (TGS), part of the Key Distribution Center (KDC), issues service tickets for accessing specific resources. Kerberos does not rely on X.509 CAs, and the client does not issue its own tickets.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A healthcare company wants to grant access to patient records based on a combination of the requester's department, the patient's care team assignment, the time of day, and the sensitivity level of the record. Which access control model BEST supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple dynamic attributes (department, care team, time, sensitivity) at access time to make fine-grained decisions, unlike RBAC (static roles only), MAC (fixed labels/clearances), or DAC (owner discretion).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which access control model allows the owner of a resource to determine who else may access it and what permissions they receive?","o":["Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Rule-Based Access Control","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)"],"c":1,"why":"DAC grants the resource owner discretion to assign and modify access permissions for other users. MAC relies on centrally enforced classification labels, and ABAC/rule-based models use policies or attributes rather than owner discretion.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company uses a third-party identity provider (IdP) to authenticate employees to a cloud-based SaaS application using SAML. After the user authenticates to the IdP, what is sent to the service provider (SP) to grant access without requiring the user to log in again?","o":["A shared secret password stored at the SP","A digitally signed SAML assertion containing authentication and attribute statements","The user's Kerberos ticket-granting ticket","A one-time password generated by the SP"],"c":1,"why":"In SAML federation, the IdP issues a digitally signed assertion asserting the user's identity and attributes, which the SP trusts and uses to grant access; Kerberos tickets and OTPs are unrelated to SAML flows, and shared passwords defeat the purpose of federation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee is terminated, which access management practice is MOST important to perform promptly to reduce security risk?","o":["Updating the employee's job title in the HR system","Deprovisioning all of the employee's user accounts and access rights","Issuing a new password policy for remaining staff","Archiving the employee's email for legal hold"],"c":1,"why":"Prompt deprovisioning revokes all system access tied to the terminated employee's identity, closing an immediate security gap. Job title updates, new password policies, and email archiving are administrative or unrelated tasks that do not directly address the access risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system is being tuned for a high-security data center. Lowering the sensitivity threshold to reduce false rejections of authorized staff will most likely have which effect?","o":["Decrease the False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","Increase the False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","Increase the Crossover Error Rate (CER) only for unauthorized users","Have no effect on FAR or FRR"],"c":1,"why":"Reducing sensitivity to lower False Rejection Rate (FRR) typically increases False Acceptance Rate (FAR), since the system becomes more lenient and may accept unauthorized users; FAR and FRR are inversely related, and CER is a fixed point where they intersect, not user-specific.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During an identity lifecycle audit, an auditor discovers that several employees who transferred departments six months ago still retain access rights from their previous roles. Which IAM process failure BEST explains this finding?","o":["Inadequate identity proofing during onboarding","Lack of periodic access recertification and role-based deprovisioning","Absence of multifactor authentication enforcement","Weak password complexity requirements"],"c":1,"why":"Retained access after a role change indicates a failure in the access review/recertification process that should remove outdated entitlements when roles change; this is unrelated to identity proofing, MFA, or password strength.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is an example of a 'something you have' authentication factor?","o":["A fingerprint scan","A PIN code memorized by the user","A hardware token that generates one-time passcodes","The user's typing rhythm"],"c":2,"why":"A hardware token is a physical object the user possesses, making it a 'something you have' factor. Fingerprints and typing rhythm are 'something you are' (biometric) factors, and a PIN is 'something you know'.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A developer wants to allow a mobile application to access a user's cloud storage files on their behalf without ever handling the user's password. Which protocol is specifically designed to provide this delegated authorization capability?","o":["OpenID Connect (OIDC)","OAuth 2.0","Kerberos","RADIUS"],"c":1,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is designed for delegated authorization, allowing an application to obtain scoped access tokens without handling user credentials; OIDC adds authentication on top of OAuth, while Kerberos and RADIUS are not designed for this delegated access pattern.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In an access control model, users are granted permissions based on their job function within an organization rather than being assigned permissions individually. What is this model called?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions to roles that correspond to job functions, and users inherit permissions by being assigned to roles. DAC lets resource owners assign permissions individually, and MAC uses fixed labels/classifications set by a central authority.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that employees are granted only the minimum access necessary to perform their job duties. Which security principle does this describe?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege","Defense in depth","Due diligence"],"c":1,"why":"Least privilege means granting only the minimum access rights needed to perform a task, reducing risk exposure. Separation of duties splits critical tasks among multiple people, and defense in depth layers multiple controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A security administrator notices that Kerberos authentication for several workstations began failing intermittently after a recent network change. Investigation reveals that the workstations' clocks differ from the domain controller's clock by more than the configured maximum clock skew. What is the most likely underlying reason Kerberos authentication fails under these conditions?","o":["Kerberos tickets include encrypted timestamps to prevent replay attacks, and tickets outside the allowed skew are rejected as potentially replayed","Kerberos requires clock synchronization only for issuing the initial TGT, not for validating subsequent service tickets","Kerberos uses timestamps solely for audit logging purposes, so clock skew should not affect the authentication process","Kerberos relies on NTP to generate session encryption keys, and skew directly invalidates the cryptographic keys"],"c":0,"why":"Kerberos authenticators contain encrypted timestamps used to detect replay attacks; if skew exceeds the configured tolerance (commonly 5 minutes), the KDC or service rejects the ticket as potentially replayed. The other options misstate how timestamps are used throughout the protocol, not just at TGT issuance or for logging/key generation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution enforces a policy that all interactive user sessions on internal applications are automatically terminated after 15 minutes of inactivity. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this control?","o":["It reduces the risk of session hijacking or unauthorized use of an unattended authenticated session","It prevents brute-force password attacks against the login page","It ensures compliance with data retention requirements","It eliminates the need for multifactor authentication"],"c":0,"why":"Session timeouts reduce the window of opportunity for an attacker to hijack or misuse an unattended, still-authenticated session; it does not address brute-force login attempts, data retention, or replace the need for MFA.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary benefit of implementing Single Sign-On (SSO) for users accessing multiple applications?","o":["It eliminates the need for any authentication","It requires users to authenticate once and gain access to multiple systems without re-authenticating","It automatically encrypts all network traffic","It replaces the need for access control lists"],"c":1,"why":"SSO allows a user to authenticate once and gain access to multiple related but independent systems without repeated logins, improving usability. It does not eliminate authentication entirely, encrypt traffic, or remove the need for authorization mechanisms like ACLs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A mobile application needs to access a user's photos stored in a third-party cloud storage service, without ever handling or storing the user's storage-service credentials. Which protocol was specifically designed to address this delegated-authorization use case?","o":["SAML 2.0","OAuth 2.0","Kerberos","RADIUS"],"c":1,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is purpose-built for delegated authorization, issuing scoped, time-limited access tokens to third-party apps without exposing the resource owner's credentials. SAML is primarily for federated authentication/SSO assertions, Kerberos is for authentication within a trusted network realm, and RADIUS provides AAA services for network access, none of which match this delegation scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In the Kerberos authentication protocol, which component is responsible for issuing ticket-granting tickets (TGTs) to users after they successfully authenticate?","o":["The Ticket Granting Server (TGS)","The Key Distribution Center (KDC) Authentication Service","The application server","The client workstation"],"c":1,"why":"The Authentication Service, part of the Key Distribution Center (KDC), verifies the user's identity and issues the initial TGT. The TGS later uses the TGT to issue service tickets for specific resources, and the application server and client are not responsible for ticket issuance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a privileged access management (PAM) solution that grants administrators elevated rights to a production server only for a pre-approved, time-limited window tied to a specific change ticket. This approach is an example of which concept?","o":["Separation of duties","Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access","Mandatory vacation","Role mining"],"c":1,"why":"JIT privileged access grants elevated rights only when needed and for a limited duration, minimizing standing privileges; this scenario does not describe splitting duties among multiple people, rotating job assignments, or analyzing roles from access data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to grant access to a file based on a combination of factors: the requester's department, the sensitivity label of the file, the time of day, and whether the request originates from a managed corporate device. Which access control model is best suited to enforce this policy?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes of subject, object, and environment at access-decision time, making it ideal for dynamic, multi-factor policies. RBAC only considers role assignment, DAC relies on owner discretion, and MAC enforces fixed classification/clearance labels without environmental context like time or device posture.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During evaluation of two competing biometric authentication systems, an architect compares their Crossover Error Rate (CER). System A has a CER of 0.5%, and System B has a CER of 2%. What conclusion should the architect draw?","o":["System B is more accurate because it has a higher tolerance for enrollment variance","System A is more accurate because a lower CER indicates the point where FAR and FRR intersect at a lower overall error level","CER is irrelevant to accuracy; only the False Acceptance Rate should be compared","Both systems have identical accuracy because CER only measures enrollment throughput, not error rates"],"c":1,"why":"The Crossover Error Rate is the point at which False Acceptance Rate and False Rejection Rate are equal; a lower CER indicates a more accurate biometric system overall. Comparing FAR alone ignores FRR, and CER measures error balance, not throughput or enrollment tolerance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A biometric access control system incorrectly denies access to an authorized user who places their finger on the scanner. What is this error called?","o":["False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Type II error"],"c":1,"why":"FRR measures the rate at which legitimate, authorized users are incorrectly denied access. FAR measures unauthorized users being incorrectly granted access, CER is the point where FAR and FRR are equal, and 'Type II error' in biometrics actually refers to false acceptance, not rejection.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee is terminated, what is the MOST important identity and access management action that should be taken immediately?","o":["Change the employee's job title in the HR system","Disable or delete the employee's user accounts and access credentials","Notify the employee's former coworkers","Update the organization's org chart"],"c":1,"why":"Promptly disabling or deleting accounts prevents a terminated employee from retaining unauthorized access to systems and data, which is a critical security control. The other actions are administrative and do not directly mitigate the security risk of continued access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization uses SAML assertions to allow employees to authenticate once with their corporate identity provider and access a third-party cloud application without a separate login. What is this arrangement called?","o":["Mandatory Access Control","Federated identity management","Discretionary access control","Role mining"],"c":1,"why":"Federated identity management allows identity information to be shared and trusted across different organizations or domains, enabling SSO-like access to external services using assertions like SAML. MAC and DAC are access control models unrelated to cross-domain identity trust, and role mining is a technique for discovering roles from existing permissions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An internal audit finds several user accounts belonging to employees who left the organization more than six months ago still active in the directory with unchanged access rights. Which control failure most directly explains this finding?","o":["Lack of a formal periodic access review and re-certification process for all accounts","Absence of automated deprovisioning tied to HR termination events within the identity lifecycle management process","Failure to enforce password complexity requirements on privileged accounts","Insufficient multifactor authentication enrollment for terminated employees"],"c":1,"why":"The most direct cause is a broken joiner-mover-leaver process where termination in the HR system does not automatically trigger account disablement, leading to orphaned accounts. Access reviews are a compensating detective control but not the root cause; password complexity and MFA enrollment are unrelated to account termination.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A security team implements a Privileged Access Management (PAM) solution that requires administrators to check out unique, time-limited credentials for each session, records all privileged sessions, and automatically rotates shared account passwords after each use. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this approach compared to traditional shared administrator passwords?","o":["It eliminates the need for network segmentation between administrative and production systems","It reduces the value of stolen credentials by preventing reuse and provides accountability through session recording","It removes the requirement for administrators to authenticate before accessing privileged accounts","It guarantees compliance with least privilege without requiring any role definitions"],"c":1,"why":"Credential vaulting, rotation, and session recording limit the lifespan and reuse value of privileged credentials and create an audit trail tying actions to individuals, directly mitigating credential theft and insider risk. The other options overstate PAM's scope; it does not replace segmentation, authentication requirements, or formal least-privilege role design.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization's Kerberos-based SSO environment begins experiencing intermittent authentication failures across multiple workstations, even though credentials are correct and there are no network connectivity issues. Which of the following is the MOST likely root cause?","o":["The Key Distribution Center's ticket-granting ticket lifetime is set too high","Clock skew between client systems and the KDC exceeds the maximum allowed tolerance","The realm's cross-realm trust configuration is misconfigured","Users' service principal names contain invalid characters"],"c":1,"why":"Kerberos tickets contain timestamps used to prevent replay attacks; if client and KDC clocks drift beyond the configured tolerance (typically 5 minutes), valid credentials are rejected. Ticket lifetime, cross-realm trust, or SPN issues would produce different, more consistent failure patterns rather than intermittent time-related ones.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester submits the string '*)(uid=*))(|(uid=*' into a web application's username field that is used to build a directory search filter on the server side. The application returns unexpected results, potentially bypassing authentication. This is an example of which attack?","o":["Cross-site request forgery","LDAP injection","Kerberos golden ticket attack","Pass-the-hash attack"],"c":1,"why":"Injecting special LDAP filter syntax to manipulate a directory query is a classic LDAP injection attack, analogous to SQL injection but targeting directory services. CSRF, golden ticket, and pass-the-hash attacks involve entirely different mechanisms unrelated to manipulating search filter syntax.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A mobile application needs to authenticate users and obtain limited, delegated access to a user's calendar data hosted by a third-party API, without ever handling the user's password. Which combination of protocols BEST meets this requirement?","o":["SAML 2.0 alone","OAuth 2.0 authorization code flow combined with OpenID Connect","Kerberos with the S4U2Self extension","LDAP simple bind over TLS"],"c":1,"why":"OpenID Connect (built on OAuth 2.0) provides an ID token for authentication while OAuth 2.0's authorization code flow provides delegated, scoped access to the API without exposing the password. SAML is poorly suited to native mobile apps, Kerberos delegation is intended for intra-realm services, and LDAP bind would require direct credential handling.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An enterprise federates authentication for dozens of cloud SaaS applications to a single centralized Identity Provider (IdP) using SAML. From a risk-management perspective, what is the MOST significant architectural concern introduced by this design?","o":["SAML assertions cannot be digitally signed, making them inherently insecure for SSO","Compromise of the IdP could grant an attacker federated access to all connected service providers, making the IdP a high-value single point of failure","Federation prevents the use of multifactor authentication at the identity provider","SAML requires each service provider to store the user's password, increasing exposure"],"c":1,"why":"Centralizing authentication into a single IdP concentrates risk: a breach of the IdP can cascade into unauthorized access across every federated service provider. SAML assertions are typically signed and often encrypted (contradicting option A), federation is fully compatible with MFA at the IdP (contradicting C), and SPs in SAML federation do not store the user's password (contradicting D).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A financial services company must restrict access to customer records so that analysts can only view records for accounts in their assigned region, only during business hours, and only when connecting from a corporate-managed device. Which access control model BEST supports these requirements without creating an unmanageable number of static roles?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) with one role per region","Discretionary Access Control (DAC) delegated to data owners","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC) using policy rules","Mandatory Access Control (MAC) with hierarchical labels"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes (region, time, device posture) dynamically through policy rules, avoiding the role explosion that RBAC would require. DAC lacks centralized enforcement of contextual conditions, and MAC labels address confidentiality classification rather than dynamic contextual attributes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company requires employees to log in with a password and then answer a series of personal knowledge questions (e.g., mother's maiden name, first pet's name) before accessing payroll data. Which of the following best describes this authentication scheme?","o":["True multifactor authentication because two separate credentials are required","Single-factor authentication because both credentials are something the user knows","Two-factor authentication combining knowledge and possession factors","Risk-based authentication using adaptive step-up controls"],"c":1,"why":"Multifactor authentication requires credentials from different categories (knowledge, possession, inherence). A password and security questions are both 'something you know,' so this remains single-factor regardless of how many credentials are used.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"When comparing two biometric authentication systems, System A has a lower crossover error rate (CER) than System B. What does this indicate about System A's performance?","o":["System A requires less enrollment time than System B","System A has a lower storage requirement for biometric templates","System A provides a better balance between false acceptance and false rejection rates","System A is inherently more resistant to spoofing attacks"],"c":2,"why":"CER is the point at which the False Acceptance Rate and False Rejection Rate curves intersect; a lower CER indicates better overall accuracy and balance between these error types. It provides no information about enrollment time, template storage, or spoof resistance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A hospital wants to grant access to patient records based on a dynamic combination of the user's role, department, treating-physician relationship to the patient, and time of day. Which access control model BEST supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes simultaneously to make dynamic access decisions. RBAC only considers role, MAC relies on fixed security labels/clearances, and DAC leaves access decisions to the resource owner rather than policy attributes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"In a SAML 2.0 SP-initiated single sign-on flow, a user first attempts to access a protected resource at a service provider that has no active session for the user. Which sequence correctly reflects the order of events?","o":["The IdP issues an assertion, then the SP redirects the user to the IdP, then the user authenticates, then the SP grants access","The SP redirects the user to the IdP with an authentication request, the user authenticates at the IdP, the IdP posts a SAML assertion to the SP, and the SP validates the assertion and grants access","The user authenticates directly at the SP, the SP requests attribute release from the IdP, and the SP grants access","The SP issues a SAML assertion, the IdP validates the assertion, and the user then authenticates at the SP"],"c":1,"why":"In SP-initiated SSO, the SP redirects the unauthenticated user to the IdP with an AuthnRequest; after authentication, the IdP posts a signed assertion to the SP's Assertion Consumer Service, which validates it before granting access. The other sequences invert or misassign the roles of the SP and IdP in the trust relationship.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to log in using a smart card combined with a PIN. This is an example of which authentication approach?","o":["Single-factor authentication using two knowledge items","Multi-factor authentication combining something you have and something you know","Multi-factor authentication combining something you are and something you have","Risk-based authentication using contextual attributes"],"c":1,"why":"A smart card is 'something you have' and a PIN is 'something you know,' so combining them constitutes true multi-factor authentication. The other options misclassify the factor types or describe a different authentication model (risk-based) not used here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a SAML-based single sign-on (SSO) federation, which entity is responsible for authenticating the user and generating the assertion that the relying application consumes?","o":["Service provider","Identity provider","Policy enforcement point","Certificate authority"],"c":1,"why":"The identity provider (IdP) authenticates the user and issues the SAML assertion; the service provider trusts and consumes that assertion but does not perform the authentication itself. A PEP enforces access decisions, and a CA issues digital certificates, neither of which generates SAML assertions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is redesigning privileged access management to reduce the risk of standing administrative privileges being exploited. Which control provides the GREATEST reduction in risk?","o":["Requiring MFA for all administrator logins","Rotating shared administrator passwords every 30 days","Implementing just-in-time privilege elevation with time-bound, approved access requests","Logging all administrative session activity to a SIEM"],"c":2,"why":"Just-in-time elevation removes persistent standing privileges by granting access only for a limited, approved window, directly shrinking the attack surface associated with always-on admin rights. MFA, password rotation, and logging are valuable complementary controls but do not eliminate the underlying risk of continuously available privileged access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company assigns system access based on job function, so all members of the 'Accounts Payable' group automatically receive the same set of permissions. Which access control model is being used?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions to roles (job functions) rather than individuals, and users inherit access by being placed in that role. DAC lets owners assign access, MAC uses security labels/clearances, and rule-based control relies on if-then rules rather than job roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"What is the primary purpose of the Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT) in the Kerberos authentication protocol?","o":["It encrypts all network traffic between the client and application servers","It serves as proof of prior authentication, allowing the client to request service tickets without re-entering credentials","It stores the user's plaintext password for future logins","It acts as the shared session key between two application servers"],"c":1,"why":"After initial authentication with the Authentication Server, the client receives a TGT that it presents to the Ticket Granting Service to obtain service tickets without resubmitting credentials. Kerberos never transmits or stores plaintext passwords, and the TGT is not a network encryption mechanism or a server-to-server session key.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During an access recertification audit, an organization discovers several active accounts belonging to employees who left the company more than six months ago. Which control failure MOST directly explains this finding?","o":["Lack of integration between the HR system and the identity lifecycle management process","Absence of password complexity requirements for terminated accounts","Failure to enforce least privilege during initial account provisioning","Missing multifactor authentication on privileged accounts"],"c":0,"why":"Orphaned accounts typically result from a broken linkage between HR-driven termination events and automated deprovisioning workflows, so accounts are never disabled or removed. Password complexity, initial least-privilege provisioning, and MFA are unrelated to the failure to remove access upon termination.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A biometric fingerprint system is configured with a very strict matching threshold to minimize the chance of granting access to an unauthorized person. What is the most likely side effect of this configuration?","o":["The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) will decrease and the False Rejection Rate (FRR) will increase","The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) will increase and the False Rejection Rate (FRR) will decrease","Both FAR and FRR will decrease simultaneously","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) will improve while FRR remains unchanged"],"c":0,"why":"Tightening the matching threshold reduces false acceptances but increases false rejections, since legitimate users are more likely to be rejected. FAR and FRR have an inverse relationship, so they cannot both decrease, and CER is a fixed point where FAR=FRR, not something that 'improves' independently.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"When an employee is terminated for cause, which identity lifecycle practice BEST reduces organizational risk?","o":["Disable the account after 30 days to allow final payroll processing to complete","Immediately disable all access and revoke credentials as part of the termination process","Change the employee's password and leave the account active for audit purposes","Transfer the employee's access rights to their direct manager"],"c":1,"why":"Immediate revocation of access upon termination minimizes the window for misuse of credentials by a disgruntled or malicious former employee. Delaying disablement, merely changing the password, or transferring access to another user all leave exploitable access or accountability gaps.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A web application constructs LDAP search filters by directly concatenating user-supplied input from a login form. Which vulnerability does this MOST directly introduce, and what is the BEST remediation?","o":["Cross-site scripting; encode output displayed to users","LDAP injection; use input validation and proper escaping of special characters before constructing filters","Buffer overflow; enforce fixed-length input fields","Session fixation; regenerate session identifiers after login"],"c":1,"why":"Concatenating unsanitized input into LDAP filters allows attackers to manipulate filter logic, similar to SQL injection, resulting in LDAP injection; the remediation is proper escaping and validation of special characters (e.g., parentheses, asterisks, null bytes) or use of parameterized filter APIs. The other vulnerability/remediation pairs are unrelated to LDAP filter construction.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A system administrator is granted access only to the specific servers and commands required to perform backup operations, rather than full administrative rights across the network. This is an example of which security principle?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege","Defense in depth","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Least privilege means granting users only the access necessary to perform their job functions, exactly as described. Separation of duties involves splitting tasks among multiple people, defense in depth uses layered controls, and mandatory vacation is an administrative fraud-detection control—none apply here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"To mitigate the risk of session hijacking in a web application, which control is MOST effective?","o":["Enforcing complex password requirements at login","Regenerating the session identifier after successful authentication and transmitting cookies only over encrypted, secure channels","Implementing role-based access control for all authenticated users","Requiring biometric authentication at initial login"],"c":1,"why":"Regenerating session IDs post-authentication and protecting cookies with secure transmission directly addresses session fixation and hijacking. Strong passwords, RBAC, and biometrics improve authentication or authorization strength but do not protect an already-established session from being hijacked.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing an access control model for a hospital where access decisions must consider the patient's assigned doctor, the time of day, and whether the request originates from within the hospital network. Which access control model BEST fits these requirements?","o":["Discretionary access control (DAC)","Role-based access control (RBAC)","Attribute-based access control (ABAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes (relationship, time, location) to make dynamic access decisions, which fits this scenario. RBAC only considers role, DAC relies on owner discretion, and MAC uses fixed security labels/clearances, none of which natively support multi-attribute contextual decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system's False Acceptance Rate (FAR) and False Rejection Rate (FRR) intersect at a specific sensitivity threshold. This intersection point is known as the:","o":["Throughput rate","Crossover error rate (CER)","Enrollment threshold","Type II error boundary"],"c":1,"why":"The crossover error rate is the point where FAR equals FRR and is used as a standard metric to compare the accuracy of different biometric systems—a lower CER indicates better overall accuracy. Throughput measures processing speed, and the other terms are not standard measures of this intersection.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"In a Kerberos authentication exchange, after a client obtains a Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT) from the Authentication Service, it presents an authenticator to the Ticket Granting Service to request a service ticket. Which mechanism in this authenticator primarily protects the exchange against replay attacks?","o":["A nonce generated randomly for each request and cached indefinitely by the KDC","A timestamp encrypted with the session key, valid only within a short, synchronized time window","The lifetime value embedded in the TGT itself","Mutual authentication performed between the client and the Key Distribution Center"],"c":1,"why":"Kerberos authenticators include an encrypted timestamp that the KDC checks against a small allowable clock skew; a replayed authenticator falls outside this window and is rejected. TGT lifetime governs overall ticket validity but not replay of a single authenticator, and Kerberos does not rely on cached nonces or explicit mutual authentication steps for this specific protection.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A cloud-based HR application authenticates users by trusting assertions issued by the company's internal identity provider, eliminating the need for separate credentials on the HR system. Which technology model does this describe?","o":["Discretionary access control","Role mining","Federated identity management","Mandatory access control"],"c":2,"why":"Federated identity management allows a trusted identity provider to issue assertions (e.g., via SAML) that other service providers accept, enabling cross-domain SSO without duplicate credentials. The other options are unrelated access control models or identity governance activities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During a security assessment, an auditor discovers that terminated employees' accounts remain active in the directory for an average of 45 days after departure. Which control would MOST effectively address this finding?","o":["Implementing multifactor authentication for all users","Automating account deprovisioning tied to HR termination events","Increasing password complexity requirements","Enabling account lockout after failed login attempts"],"c":1,"why":"Automated deprovisioning linked to the HR system ensures accounts are disabled promptly upon termination, directly addressing the delay. MFA, password complexity, and lockout policies are unrelated controls that don't address the timely removal of access for departed employees.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"Which control is MOST important for reducing risk associated with shared administrative accounts in a privileged access management (PAM) program?","o":["Assigning a single complex password shared among all administrators","Implementing credential vaulting with automatic password rotation and session recording for each checkout","Allowing administrators to use their personal user accounts for elevated tasks","Disabling session logging to reduce storage overhead"],"c":1,"why":"Vaulting privileged credentials with automatic rotation and recording each checkout session ensures accountability and limits credential exposure over time. A shared static password provides no individual accountability, using personal accounts for privileged tasks blurs audit trails, and disabling logging removes critical forensic and oversight capability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee transfers to a new department, best practice for identity and access management requires which of the following actions?","o":["Leave existing access unchanged and add new permissions for the new role","Immediately disable the employee's account and issue a new one","Review and remove access no longer required while granting access needed for the new role","Grant the employee administrator rights to simplify future transfers"],"c":2,"why":"Proper access lifecycle management requires re-evaluating entitlements during a role change to remove unnecessary access and grant only what the new role requires, preventing privilege creep. Leaving old access, disabling the account entirely, or granting excessive admin rights all violate least privilege and proper provisioning practices.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system is being tuned. The administrator lowers the sensitivity threshold to reduce user complaints about failed scans. What is the MOST likely security consequence of this change?","o":["The False Rejection Rate (FRR) will increase","The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) will increase","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) will decrease","The enrollment time for new users will increase"],"c":1,"why":"Lowering the sensitivity threshold makes the system more permissive, increasing the likelihood that unauthorized individuals are incorrectly accepted (higher FAR), while FRR would decrease. CER is a fixed characteristic of the sensor/algorithm and doesn't decrease just from threshold tuning, and enrollment time is unaffected.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric access control system's sensitivity threshold is lowered to reduce user complaints about being denied entry. What is the most likely security consequence of this change?","o":["The False Rejection Rate (FRR) will increase while the False Acceptance Rate (FAR) decreases","The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) will increase while the False Rejection Rate (FRR) decreases","Both FAR and FRR will decrease simultaneously, improving the Crossover Error Rate","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) will improve, indicating stronger overall accuracy"],"c":1,"why":"Lowering the matching threshold makes the system more lenient, which reduces false rejections (fewer legitimate users denied) but increases false acceptances (more impostors admitted). FAR and FRR move inversely, not together, and a threshold change away from the crossover point worsens rather than improves the CER.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a policy requiring that database administrators check out a temporary, time-limited credential from a vault whenever they need elevated access, and the credential is automatically rotated after use. This is an example of which control?","o":["Just-in-time privileged access management","Discretionary access control","Role mining","Federated identity management"],"c":0,"why":"Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access management grants temporary elevated credentials on demand and rotates them afterward, reducing standing privilege risk. DAC concerns owner-granted permissions, role mining is an RBAC design technique, and federation deals with cross-domain identity assertions, none of which match this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a Kerberos authentication environment, what is the PRIMARY purpose of the Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT)?","o":["It encrypts all network traffic between client and server","It allows the client to request service tickets without re-entering credentials","It serves as the final authorization token for accessing a specific resource","It replaces the need for a Key Distribution Center"],"c":1,"why":"The TGT, issued by the Authentication Service after initial login, allows the client to request service tickets from the Ticket Granting Service without re-authenticating. It does not encrypt all traffic, is not the final resource-specific authorization (that's the service ticket), and the KDC is still required throughout the process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company's access review reveals that many employees have accumulated permissions from previous roles they no longer perform, creating excessive access rights. Which term BEST describes this issue?","o":["Privilege escalation","Separation of duties violation","Privilege creep","Least privilege enforcement"],"c":2,"why":"Privilege creep refers to the gradual accumulation of unnecessary access rights over time, typically due to role changes without corresponding access revocation. Privilege escalation involves gaining unauthorized higher access, separation of duties concerns conflicting duties held by one person, and least privilege enforcement is the opposite corrective control, not the problem itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A traditional web application with a confidential backend server needs to obtain an access token to call a protected API on behalf of a signed-in end user, without exposing the client secret to the browser. Which OAuth 2.0 grant type is most appropriate?","o":["Implicit grant","Client credentials grant","Authorization code grant","Resource owner password credentials grant"],"c":2,"why":"The authorization code grant allows the confidential server-side client to exchange an authorization code for tokens directly with the authorization server, keeping the client secret protected. Implicit grant exposes tokens in the browser and is deprecated, client credentials grant has no user context, and resource owner password credentials grant requires the app to handle raw user passwords, which is an anti-pattern.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial services firm wants to ensure that no single employee can both initiate and approve a wire transfer. Which access control principle is being enforced?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Mandatory vesting","Need to know"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties requires that critical tasks be divided among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by any single individual, exactly matching the wire transfer scenario. Least privilege limits the scope of access rather than dividing tasks, need to know restricts information access based on necessity, and mandatory vesting is not an access control concept.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"In an SP-initiated SAML SSO flow, after the Identity Provider (IdP) successfully authenticates the user, to which Service Provider (SP) endpoint is the SAML assertion typically delivered?","o":["The Single Logout (SLO) endpoint","The Artifact Resolution Service","The Assertion Consumer Service (ACS) URL","The SP's metadata publishing endpoint"],"c":2,"why":"The Assertion Consumer Service (ACS) is the specific SP endpoint designed to receive and process the SAML assertion (typically via HTTP POST) after IdP authentication. The SLO endpoint handles logout requests, the artifact resolution service is used only in the artifact binding to retrieve assertions by reference, and the metadata endpoint merely publishes configuration data, not runtime assertions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A multinational financial firm needs access decisions for a trading application to consider job role, current time of day, device compliance status, and the user's geographic location simultaneously, with policies that change frequently. Which access control model best supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)"],"c":3,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes (role, time, device posture, location) dynamically at request time, making it well suited for fine-grained, frequently changing policies. RBAC would require an unmanageable explosion of roles to capture every attribute combination, MAC relies on fixed sensitivity labels rather than contextual attributes, and DAC leaves access decisions to resource owners rather than centralized contextual policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A security team wants to reduce the risk of credential theft and lateral movement associated with domain administrator accounts that are typically logged in with standing privileges around the clock. Which control most directly addresses this risk?","o":["Enforcing multifactor authentication on all administrator logins","Rotating a shared administrator account password on a monthly schedule","Implementing just-in-time privileged access that grants time-bound elevation only when needed","Recording all privileged sessions for later audit review"],"c":2,"why":"Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access minimizes the attack surface by ensuring elevated rights exist only for the duration needed, directly eliminating standing privileges that attackers could hijack. MFA and session recording are valuable complementary controls but don't remove the standing privilege itself, and a shared rotated password actually increases risk by removing individual accountability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A custom web application authenticates users by performing an LDAP simple bind, directly concatenating user-supplied username and password values into the bind request and search filter without sanitization. What is the primary security risk this introduces?","o":["Buffer overflow in the LDAP client library due to oversized input","LDAP injection allowing an attacker to manipulate filter syntax and bypass authentication","Replay of a previously captured Kerberos ticket against the LDAP server","Session fixation due to predictable LDAP session identifiers"],"c":1,"why":"Unsanitized input concatenated into LDAP filters allows attackers to inject special characters (such as wildcards or boolean operators) to alter query logic and potentially bypass authentication, similar to SQL injection. Buffer overflow, Kerberos ticket replay, and session fixation are unrelated to the described input-handling flaw in LDAP filter construction.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization's HR system marks an employee as terminated, but the employee's network, VPN, and SaaS accounts remain active for several weeks before anyone notices. Which control would have MOST effectively prevented this exposure?","o":["A quarterly manual access recertification campaign","Password expiration policies requiring changes every 90 days","Automated deprovisioning workflows triggered directly by HR system termination events","Mandatory security awareness training on account handling for managers"],"c":2,"why":"Automated deprovisioning integrated with the authoritative HR system immediately disables access upon a termination event, closing the gap that manual, periodic, or awareness-based controls leave open due to their detective and delayed nature. Recertification campaigns and training may eventually catch the issue but do not prevent the extended window of exposure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is an example of the 'something you have' authentication factor?","o":["A four-digit PIN memorized by the user","A hardware token that generates one-time passcodes","A fingerprint scan","A user-created password"],"c":1,"why":"A hardware token is a physical item the user possesses, making it a 'something you have' factor. Passwords and PINs are 'something you know,' and a fingerprint is 'something you are.'","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company assigns system permissions to users based on their job function within the organization, such as 'HR Manager' or 'Accountant,' rather than assigning permissions to each individual user directly. This is an example of which access control model?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC) using time and location"],"c":1,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions based on organizational roles rather than individual identities. DAC lets resource owners grant access, MAC relies on classification labels, and ABAC uses multiple contextual attributes rather than simple job titles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An employee of Company A is able to log into a partner organization's (Company B) web application using their Company A corporate credentials, without Company B ever storing a separate password for that employee. This capability is best described as:","o":["Discretionary access control","Federated identity management","Mandatory access control","Rule-based access control"],"c":1,"why":"Federated identity management allows organizations to trust and accept authentication performed by another organization's identity provider, eliminating the need for duplicate credentials. The other options describe unrelated access control models.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which authentication factor category does a fingerprint scan represent?","o":["Something you know","Something you have","Something you are","Something you do"],"c":2,"why":"A fingerprint is a physical biometric characteristic, classifying it as 'something you are.' Passwords are 'something you know,' tokens are 'something you have,' and behavioral patterns like typing rhythm are 'something you do.'","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a Kerberos authentication environment, after a user successfully authenticates and receives a Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT), which component issues session tickets that allow the user to access specific network services?","o":["Certificate Authority (CA)","Ticket Granting Service (TGS)","Authentication Server (AS)","Directory Server"],"c":1,"why":"The TGS uses the valid TGT to issue service-specific session tickets. The AS handles initial authentication and TGT issuance, while a CA issues digital certificates, which is unrelated to Kerberos ticketing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee is terminated from an organization, which identity and access management process ensures that all of the employee's system access rights and accounts are promptly disabled or removed?","o":["Provisioning","Deprovisioning","Federation","Authorization"],"c":1,"why":"Deprovisioning is the process of removing access rights when they are no longer needed, such as at termination, reducing the risk of unauthorized access. Provisioning is the opposite process (granting access), and federation and authorization address different aspects of IAM.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An attacker has compromised the NTLM hash of the KRBTGT service account in an Active Directory domain. Which attack does this enable, and why is it considered especially severe compared to other Kerberos-based attacks?","o":["A golden ticket attack, allowing the attacker to forge Ticket Granting Tickets impersonating any user with any privilege level, remaining valid until the KRBTGT password is reset twice","A silver ticket attack, allowing forgery of service tickets limited to a single service account's access","A pass-the-hash attack, allowing NTLM authentication to file shares without the plaintext password","A Kerberoasting attack, allowing offline cracking of service account passwords extracted from TGS-REQ traffic"],"c":0,"why":"The KRBTGT account signs all TGTs; compromising its hash lets an attacker forge TGTs (golden tickets) for arbitrary users and privileges, and remediation requires resetting the KRBTGT password twice due to key history retention. Silver tickets, pass-the-hash, and Kerberoasting rely on different, more limited credential compromises.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants users to authenticate once and then access multiple related applications without re-entering credentials for each one. Which concept best describes this capability?","o":["Federation","Single sign-on (SSO)","Kerberos ticketing","Multi-factor authentication"],"c":1,"why":"SSO allows a user to authenticate once and gain access to multiple systems without repeated logins. Federation extends this across organizational boundaries, while Kerberos is one possible underlying protocol, not the general concept.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A biometric access control system incorrectly grants entry to an unauthorized individual because their fingerprint pattern was similar enough to a legitimately enrolled user's stored template. This outcome is best classified as:","o":["False Rejection Rate (FRR)","False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","Enrollment failure rate","Crossover Error Rate (CER)"],"c":1,"why":"FAR measures how often a biometric system incorrectly authenticates an unauthorized user, which matches this scenario. FRR is the opposite error (rejecting a legitimate user), and CER is the point where FAR and FRR are equal, not a single error event.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements federated SSO in which an Identity Provider issues an XML-based, digitally signed document containing authentication and attribute statements, which is then consumed by multiple independent web-based Service Providers to establish a session without requiring the user to re-authenticate. Which standard is being described?","o":["SAML 2.0","OAuth 2.0","RADIUS","Kerberos"],"c":0,"why":"SAML 2.0 uses XML-based, digitally signed assertions containing authentication and attribute statements exchanged between an IdP and SPs for browser-based SSO. OAuth 2.0 is an authorization framework using tokens (not XML assertions), RADIUS is for network access authentication, and Kerberos uses tickets, not XML assertions, and doesn't natively support cross-domain web federation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which biometric error occurs when an authorized user is incorrectly denied access by the system?","o":["False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Equal Error Rate (EER)"],"c":1,"why":"FRR measures how often legitimate users are wrongly rejected. FAR measures the opposite (unauthorized users wrongly accepted), and CER/EER represent the point where FAR and FRR are equal.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which security principle dictates that users should be granted only the minimum access rights necessary to perform their assigned job duties?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege","Defense in depth","Due diligence"],"c":1,"why":"Least privilege limits user access to only what is needed for their role, reducing the attack surface. Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people, and defense in depth and due diligence address different security concepts entirely.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A healthcare organization must grant access to patient records based on dynamic combinations of the requester's department, the patient's consent status, time of day, and the record's sensitivity label, and these combinations change frequently as policy evolves. Which access control model BEST supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC), because roles map cleanly to departments","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC), because policies can evaluate multiple dynamic attributes at request time","Discretionary Access Control (DAC), because record owners can grant access as needed","Mandatory Access Control (MAC), because sensitivity labels alone determine access"],"c":1,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual and dynamic attributes (department, consent, time, sensitivity) via policy rules, making it ideal for frequently changing, multi-factor access decisions. RBAC is too static for this granularity, DAC relies on owner discretion rather than policy, and MAC alone cannot incorporate consent or time-based conditions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security purpose of promptly disabling a user account after an employee is terminated?","o":["To comply with password complexity requirements","To prevent unauthorized access using valid credentials","To reduce the organization's software licensing costs","To enforce separation of duties among remaining staff"],"c":1,"why":"Timely deprovisioning prevents former employees from using still-valid credentials to access systems, a key identity lifecycle control. The other options are unrelated benefits, not the primary security rationale.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization requires employees to authenticate to the VPN using a smart card combined with a PIN entered on the card reader. Which statement best describes this authentication approach?","o":["It is single-factor authentication because both elements are used together as one login step","It is multifactor authentication because it combines something the user has with something the user knows","It is a form of single sign-on across multiple systems","It is biometric authentication because the smart card stores a unique identifier"],"c":1,"why":"The smart card represents 'something you have' and the PIN represents 'something you know'—two distinct factor categories, making this multifactor authentication. It is not SSO (no cross-system session sharing) and not biometric (no physiological trait is measured).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An online banking application requires a user to enter a password and then approve a push notification sent to their registered mobile device before granting access. This authentication process is an example of:","o":["Single-factor authentication","Two-factor authentication","Single sign-on","Discretionary access control"],"c":1,"why":"This combines a 'something you know' factor (password) with a 'something you have' factor (registered device), meeting the definition of two-factor authentication. It is not single-factor, single sign-on, or an access control model.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which access control model enforces access decisions based on labels such as 'Confidential' or 'Secret' assigned to both subjects and objects, with rules set by a central authority?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":1,"why":"MAC uses security labels and clearances enforced centrally, common in military/government systems. DAC lets owners decide access, and RBAC assigns permissions via job roles rather than sensitivity labels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"To reduce standing privilege risk for domain administrator accounts, a security team implements a solution where administrators must submit an elevation request, which upon approval grants time-limited membership in a privileged group that automatically expires after a defined window. This is an example of which control?","o":["Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access management","Role-based access control","Mandatory access control","Discretionary access control"],"c":0,"why":"JIT privileged access management grants temporary, approval-based elevation rather than persistent (standing) privileges, minimizing the attack surface. RBAC, MAC, and DAC describe access control models generally but do not specifically address time-bound, on-demand privilege elevation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial services firm wants to grant transaction approval rights only to users in the finance department, only during business hours, and only when connecting from an approved corporate subnet. Which access control model best supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes (department, time, location) dynamically to make access decisions, which RBAC (role only) and MAC (clearance labels only) cannot natively do; DAC relies on resource owner discretion rather than policy attributes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"In a Kerberos implementation, each authenticator sent by a client to a service includes a timestamp encrypted with the session key, and services reject authenticators that fall outside a small clock-skew window or that have already been seen. Which attack does this design primarily defend against?","o":["Replay of a captured ticket or authenticator","Offline brute-force guessing of the user's password","Man-in-the-middle substitution of the KDC's public key","Privilege escalation through forged service tickets"],"c":0,"why":"Timestamps combined with a rejection window and tracking of previously seen authenticators prevent an attacker from capturing and later replaying a valid authenticator. Kerberos password guessing is mitigated by pre-authentication, not timestamps; Kerberos uses symmetric keys (no PKI to MITM by default); and authenticator freshness does not address ticket forgery, which relies on key secrecy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A user must provide both a smart card and a PIN to log into a workstation. This is an example of which security concept?","o":["Single-factor authentication","Multi-factor authentication","Federated identity","Discretionary access control"],"c":1,"why":"Combining a smart card (something you have) with a PIN (something you know) constitutes multi-factor authentication, increasing assurance over a single factor. Federation and DAC are unrelated concepts.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric authentication system's FAR and FRR curves intersect at a threshold setting corresponding to a 2.5% Crossover Error Rate. If the acceptance threshold is lowered below this point (making the matching algorithm more lenient), what is the most likely effect?","o":["FAR decreases and FRR increases","FAR increases and FRR decreases","Both FAR and FRR decrease","Both FAR and FRR increase"],"c":1,"why":"Lowering the acceptance threshold makes the system more permissive, increasing the likelihood of accepting impostors (higher FAR) while reducing false rejections of legitimate users (lower FRR). The CER is the single point where FAR and FRR are equal; moving away from it in either direction trades one error type for the other rather than reducing or increasing both simultaneously.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A cloud-based SaaS application accepts authentication assertions issued by a corporate identity provider so that employees can log in without creating separate SaaS credentials. Which concept does this best illustrate?","o":["OAuth 2.0 delegated authorization","Federated single sign-on using SAML or OIDC assertions","Kerberos ticket delegation within a single realm","RADIUS-based network access control"],"c":1,"why":"Federated SSO uses trust between an identity provider and relying party (often via SAML or OIDC) so users authenticate once and access external services without separate credentials. OAuth handles authorization delegation (not primarily authentication), Kerberos operates within a single trusted realm, and RADIUS is used for network access authentication, not web federation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A photo-sharing site wants to let users grant a third-party printing service limited, revocable access to only their photo album, without ever sharing their site password with that third party. Which standard is purpose-built for this delegated authorization scenario?","o":["SAML 2.0","OAuth 2.0","Kerberos","RADIUS"],"c":1,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is designed specifically for delegated authorization, issuing scoped, revocable access tokens to third parties without exposing credentials. SAML is primarily for federated authentication/SSO assertions, Kerberos is for enterprise network authentication, and RADIUS is for network access authentication/accounting, none of which model third-party delegated resource access natively.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During a security assessment, a penetration tester successfully performs an anonymous LDAP bind against a corporate directory server and retrieves the full directory tree, including user email addresses and department attributes. Which remediation BEST addresses this finding?","o":["Disable anonymous bind and enforce authenticated access with least-privilege ACLs on directory attributes","Enable LDAP over SSL/TLS to encrypt directory traffic","Implement Kerberos pre-authentication for all directory clients","Rotate the KRBTGT account password to invalidate cached credentials"],"c":0,"why":"The root cause is that unauthenticated (anonymous) queries are permitted; disabling anonymous bind and enforcing authenticated, least-privilege access controls directly fixes this exposure. Encrypting the transport (TLS) protects data in transit but does not prevent unauthorized anonymous access, and Kerberos pre-authentication or KRBTGT rotation address unrelated authentication issues.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a Kerberos environment, why is it critical that all systems participating in authentication have synchronized clocks?","o":["To allow the Key Distribution Center to replicate its database across time zones","To validate ticket timestamps and prevent replay attacks using expired or reused tickets","To reduce encryption overhead during the TGT exchange","To enable load balancing between multiple ticket-granting servers"],"c":1,"why":"Kerberos tickets include timestamps with limited validity windows; clock skew beyond the allowed tolerance can cause valid tickets to be rejected or allow replay of intercepted tickets. The other options are not the purpose of time synchronization in Kerberos.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a system where a user's ability to access a file is determined by comparing attributes of the user (department, clearance, location) against attributes of the resource and environmental conditions (time of day, network zone) at the moment of the request. Which access control model is being used?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)"],"c":1,"why":"ABAC makes access decisions dynamically by evaluating subject, object, and environmental attributes against policy rules. RBAC relies on predefined roles, DAC relies on resource-owner discretion, and MAC relies on fixed security labels/clearances rather than flexible attribute combinations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A global enterprise wants an access control policy that grants access only when all of the following are simultaneously true: the requesting device passes a real-time patch-compliance check, the request originates from an approved geographic region, and the request occurs during defined business hours. Which access control model natively supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple dynamic attributes (device state, location, time) at request time via policy rules, making it well suited to this scenario. RBAC ties permissions to static roles and cannot easily incorporate real-time contextual attributes; MAC relies on fixed security labels/clearances; DAC leaves access decisions to resource owners without contextual policy logic.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements a system that evaluates contextual signals—geolocation, device fingerprint, and time-of-day—to dynamically determine whether a login attempt requires additional authentication factors beyond a password. This capability is best described as:","o":["Adaptive (risk-based) authentication","Multifactor authentication","Single sign-on","Federated identity management"],"c":0,"why":"Adaptive or risk-based authentication dynamically adjusts authentication requirements based on contextual risk signals. MFA simply requires multiple factors regardless of context, SSO addresses session reuse across applications, and federation addresses trust relationships between identity domains, none of which describe context-driven, dynamic step-up decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which principle states that users should be granted only the access rights necessary to perform their specific job duties?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege","Defense in depth","Need to know"],"c":1,"why":"Least privilege limits access rights to the minimum needed for a role, reducing risk of misuse. Separation of duties splits critical tasks among multiple people, and defense in depth refers to layered security controls generally.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to reduce the risk of credential replay and man-in-the-middle attacks during authentication over an untrusted network, without requiring users to memorize additional secrets. Which mechanism BEST meets this requirement?","o":["Static password with complexity requirements","One-time password (OTP) generated by a hardware token","Storing hashed passwords in a centralized directory","Increasing password history length to prevent reuse"],"c":1,"why":"An OTP token produces a new authentication value for each session, so a captured or replayed value is useless afterward, mitigating replay/MitM risk without adding memorized secrets. Static passwords, hashing at rest, and password history do not prevent live replay of a captured credential.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A native mobile application uses the OAuth 2.0 authorization code grant to obtain access tokens but, as a public client, cannot securely store a client secret. Which mechanism should be implemented to mitigate authorization code interception attacks?","o":["Proof Key for Code Exchange (PKCE)","Implicit grant flow","Client credentials grant","Resource owner password credentials grant"],"c":0,"why":"PKCE binds the authorization code to a dynamically generated code verifier/challenge pair, preventing an intercepted code from being exchanged by an attacker without the original verifier, making it the recommended mitigation for public clients. The implicit flow is deprecated and exposes tokens in the URL, while client credentials and password grants are unsuitable for delegated user authorization scenarios like this.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A federated identity architecture uses SAML assertions to allow employees to access a partner organization's cloud application. In this architecture, which entity is responsible for authenticating the user and issuing the assertion?","o":["Service Provider (SP)","Relying Party (RP)","Identity Provider (IdP)","Attribute Authority acting as the resource server"],"c":2,"why":"The Identity Provider authenticates the user and issues signed SAML assertions asserting identity and attributes; the Service Provider (relying party) trusts and consumes these assertions to grant access rather than performing authentication itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"Which practice most directly reduces the risk of orphaned user accounts remaining active after an employee leaves the organization?","o":["Enforcing periodic password rotation for all accounts","Implementing single sign-on across enterprise applications","Ensuring timely deprovisioning as part of the offboarding process","Conducting quarterly role-mining exercises"],"c":2,"why":"Orphaned accounts result from accounts not being disabled or removed when a user's employment ends; timely deprovisioning directly addresses this. Password rotation, SSO, and role mining are useful IAM practices but do not specifically prevent orphaned accounts from persisting.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system is tuned to minimize the chance that an unauthorized individual is granted access, even if this means some legitimate users are occasionally rejected. This tuning primarily affects which metric?","o":["Increasing the False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","Decreasing the False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Decreasing the False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","Lowering the Crossover Error Rate (CER) to zero"],"c":2,"why":"Tightening the sensitivity threshold to reduce unauthorized access lowers the False Acceptance Rate, typically at the cost of a higher False Rejection Rate. CER represents the point where FAR and FRR are equal and is a fixed system characteristic, not something adjusted for a single decision.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A government system classifies all data as Top Secret, Secret, or Confidential and enforces access strictly based on a user's security clearance and verified need-to-know, regardless of the data owner's preferences. This is an example of:","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":1,"why":"MAC enforces access based on fixed classification labels and clearance levels set by a central authority, removing discretion from the data owner—unlike DAC, where the owner controls permissions. RBAC is based on job roles, not classification labels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A security team wants to eliminate standing administrative access on production servers so that elevated privileges exist only for the exact duration needed to complete an approved, time-boxed task. Which control BEST achieves this goal?","o":["Separation of duties enforced through workflow approval","Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access provisioning","Static role-based access control with quarterly recertification","Mandatory access control with fixed security labels"],"c":1,"why":"JIT provisioning grants elevated rights only for the duration of an approved task and automatically revokes them afterward, removing standing privileged accounts. Separation of duties and RBAC with periodic recertification still leave standing access between reviews, and MAC labels govern classification-based access, not time-bound privilege elevation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During an access review, an auditor discovers that a former contractor's account remains active three months after contract termination, with unused but still-valid access rights to the finance system. Which IAM process failure MOST directly caused this finding?","o":["Inadequate account provisioning at onboarding","Lack of periodic entitlement review","Failure of automated deprovisioning tied to HR termination events","Absence of multi-factor authentication on the account"],"c":2,"why":"A timely deprovisioning process linked to termination events should have disabled the account immediately; its absence directly caused the lingering access. Provisioning issues occur at hiring, MFA absence relates to authentication strength, and periodic review is a compensating control that failed to catch this but is not the root process gap for termination handling.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During evaluation of a biometric authentication system, at what point is the Crossover Error Rate (CER) determined?","o":["The point where the False Acceptance Rate equals the False Rejection Rate","The threshold setting that produces the lowest False Rejection Rate regardless of False Acceptance Rate","The threshold setting that produces the lowest False Acceptance Rate regardless of False Rejection Rate","The point at which enrollment failures are highest across the user population"],"c":0,"why":"CER is the point on the sensitivity curve where FAR and FRR intersect; a lower CER indicates a more accurate biometric system overall. The other options describe extremes that favor one error type at the expense of the other, not the balanced crossover point.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric access control system is being tuned. As the sensitivity threshold is adjusted to lower the False Acceptance Rate (FAR), the False Rejection Rate (FRR) increases, and the point where the two curves intersect is recorded as a system quality benchmark. What is this intersection point called?","o":["Equal error margin","Crossover error rate (CER)","Type II error threshold","Sensitivity index"],"c":1,"why":"The crossover error rate (CER) is the point where FAR and FRR are equal, and it is the standard metric for comparing overall biometric system accuracy—the lower the CER, the better the system. 'Type II error' refers specifically to false acceptances, not the intersection point, and the other terms are not standard biometric benchmarks.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A web application uses session tokens to maintain authenticated state after login. Which practice BEST protects against session hijacking via token theft?","o":["Storing the session token in a persistent cookie with no expiration","Transmitting the session token only over HTTPS and setting it as HttpOnly and Secure","Embedding the session token in the URL for easy bookmarking","Using the same session token indefinitely across multiple logins"],"c":1,"why":"Marking cookies HttpOnly and Secure, combined with HTTPS transport, prevents client-side script access and network eavesdropping, reducing token theft risk. Persistent unexpiring cookies, URL embedding, and reusing tokens indefinitely all increase exposure and hijacking risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"Which control most directly mitigates online brute-force password guessing attacks against a login portal?","o":["Enforcing a minimum password length and complexity policy","Implementing account lockout after a defined number of failed login attempts","Requiring periodic password expiration every 90 days","Maintaining a password history to prevent reuse"],"c":1,"why":"Account lockout (or equivalent throttling/rate-limiting) directly limits the number of guesses an attacker can attempt in a given time, stopping brute-force attacks. Complexity, expiration, and history policies improve password strength or reduce reuse but do not stop repeated automated login attempts.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During a forensic investigation, an auditor must prove that a recorded privileged session transcript has not been altered since capture. Which control provides the STRONGEST assurance of this integrity?","o":["Storing session recordings in an encrypted password vault","Requiring multi-factor authentication before starting the privileged session","Generating a cryptographic hash of each recording at capture time and storing it in a tamper-evident, append-only log","Restricting playback of recordings to users holding the privileged administrator role"],"c":2,"why":"Cryptographic hashing combined with tamper-evident, append-only storage allows independent verification that a recording has not been modified after capture, directly supporting integrity assurance. Encryption protects confidentiality (not integrity proof), MFA controls who starts a session but not evidence integrity afterward, and restricting playback to admins is an access control, not an integrity control, and could even increase risk of undetected tampering by privileged insiders.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization is designing an access control model for a highly classified government system where users and objects both carry fixed sensitivity labels, and access decisions cannot be overridden by resource owners. Which access control model should be implemented?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Rule-Based Access Control with owner override"],"c":2,"why":"MAC enforces access based on fixed security labels and clearance levels set by a central authority, with no discretion given to resource owners, making it appropriate for highly classified environments. DAC explicitly allows owner discretion, RBAC assigns permissions via roles rather than labels, and rule-based access with owner override contradicts the non-discretionary requirement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A network engineer must select an AAA protocol for managing administrative access to routers and switches that (1) encrypts the entire packet payload, not just the password, and (2) allows granular, per-command authorization decisions separate from authentication. Which protocol meets both requirements?","o":["RADIUS","TACACS+","Kerberos","Diameter"],"c":1,"why":"TACACS+ encrypts the full packet body and separates authentication, authorization, and accounting, enabling per-command authorization control commonly used for network device administration. RADIUS encrypts only the password field within the packet and combines authentication and authorization in a single response; Kerberos is a ticket-based authentication protocol for network services, not device command authorization; Diameter is an AAA successor to RADIUS but does not provide TACACS+-style command-level authorization separation in standard network device implementations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the concept of 'least privilege' in access control?","o":["Users are granted the minimum level of access necessary to perform their job functions","Users are granted access based solely on their job title","Users are given full access and restricted only when a violation occurs","Access is granted equally to all users regardless of role"],"c":0,"why":"Least privilege means limiting access rights to only what is needed to perform authorized tasks, reducing risk. Granting access by title alone or giving full access by default violates this principle.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a system where access decisions are made by evaluating attributes of the subject (department, clearance), the object (classification, owner), and the environment (time of day, location) against a policy engine. Which access control model is being used?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":1,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple attributes of subjects, objects, and environment conditions via policy rules to make dynamic access decisions. RBAC relies on predefined roles, MAC uses fixed security labels/clearances set by a central authority, and DAC lets object owners grant access, none of which describe multi-attribute policy evaluation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A user enters a username and then provides a password to prove they are who they claim to be. Which two IAM concepts does this scenario illustrate, in order?","o":["Authorization, then accounting","Identification, then authentication","Authentication, then authorization","Accounting, then identification"],"c":1,"why":"Identification is claiming an identity (username), and authentication is proving that identity (password). Authorization and accounting occur after successful authentication, not during it.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company uses Kerberos for authentication in its Windows domain. A user reports that after their account password was changed by an administrator, they can still access resources using a previously issued ticket for another two hours. What does this scenario best illustrate?","o":["The Key Distribution Center (KDC) has been compromised","Ticket-Granting Tickets (TGTs) remain valid until their lifetime expires, independent of password changes","Kerberos does not support single sign-on","The user's account was not properly deprovisioned"],"c":1,"why":"Kerberos tickets are valid for their configured lifetime once issued; changing a password does not automatically invalidate outstanding tickets until they expire, which is a known operational characteristic, not a compromise or deprovisioning failure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In Role-Based Access Control (RBAC), how are permissions typically assigned to users?","o":["Permissions are assigned directly to each individual user account","Permissions are assigned to roles, and users are assigned to roles that match their job functions","Permissions are assigned based on the sensitivity label of the data owner","Permissions are randomly assigned to reduce predictability"],"c":1,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions to roles rather than individuals, simplifying administration as users are added to roles matching their responsibilities. Assigning directly to users describes DAC, and sensitivity labels describe MAC.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During a federation implementation using SAML 2.0, which component is responsible for authenticating the user and issuing an assertion to the relying application?","o":["Service Provider (SP)","Identity Provider (IdP)","Relying Party (RP) proxy","Attribute Authority Gateway"],"c":1,"why":"In SAML federation, the Identity Provider (IdP) authenticates the user and issues signed assertions to the Service Provider (SP), which consumes the assertion to grant access. The SP relies on the assertion rather than performing authentication itself; 'RP proxy' and 'Attribute Authority Gateway' are not standard SAML roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which authentication factor category does a fingerprint scan belong to?","o":["Something you know","Something you have","Something you are","Something you do"],"c":2,"why":"Biometric characteristics like fingerprints represent 'something you are.' Passwords are 'something you know,' and tokens are 'something you have.'","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Under a Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) model, how are permissions typically assigned to users?","o":["Directly to each individual user account","Based on the sensitivity label of the data","Through roles that correspond to job functions","By the resource owner on a case-by-case basis"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions to roles that map to job functions, and users are granted access by being assigned to the appropriate role, simplifying administration. Direct user assignment, sensitivity labels, and owner discretion describe other models (ad hoc, MAC, and DAC).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security team is evaluating a biometric access control system and finds that lowering the sensitivity threshold reduces employee complaints about being denied entry. What security trade-off is most likely occurring?","o":["The False Rejection Rate (FRR) is decreasing while the False Acceptance Rate (FAR) is increasing","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) is decreasing while overall accuracy improves","The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) is decreasing while the False Rejection Rate (FRR) increases","The enrollment time is increasing while throughput decreases"],"c":0,"why":"Lowering the sensitivity threshold makes the system more permissive, reducing false rejections (fewer legitimate users denied) but increasing false acceptances (more impostors accepted), a classic FRR/FAR trade-off. The CER is a fixed intersection point and does not simply decrease with threshold changes, and enrollment time is unrelated to threshold sensitivity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary benefit of implementing Single Sign-On (SSO) for end users?","o":["It eliminates the need for any authentication credentials","It requires users to authenticate once to gain access to multiple systems without re-entering credentials","It automatically encrypts all data transmitted between systems","It replaces the need for authorization controls entirely"],"c":1,"why":"SSO allows a user to authenticate once and access multiple related systems without repeated logins, improving usability. It does not eliminate authentication or remove the need for authorization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that when an employee is terminated, all system access is revoked promptly and consistently across cloud and on-premises applications. Which IAM process best addresses this requirement?","o":["Federated single sign-on (SSO)","Automated deprovisioning tied to the HR system of record","Just-in-time (JIT) access provisioning","Privileged access management (PAM) session recording"],"c":1,"why":"Automated deprovisioning triggered by HR status changes ensures timely, consistent access removal across all connected systems. SSO simplifies login but doesn't revoke access, JIT provisioning grants temporary access rather than revoking it, and PAM session recording is for monitoring privileged activity, not termination workflows.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization requires employees to use a smart card combined with a PIN to access sensitive systems. Which authentication concept does this combination best illustrate?","o":["Single sign-on","Multifactor authentication","Federated identity","Role-based access control"],"c":1,"why":"A smart card (something you have) plus a PIN (something you know) combines two distinct authentication factor types, which is the definition of multifactor authentication. SSO relates to session reuse, federation relates to cross-domain trust, and RBAC is an authorization model, not authentication.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial services firm requires that no single employee can both initiate and approve a wire transfer within the banking application. Which access control principle is being enforced?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Mandatory vacation","Need to know"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties (SoD) prevents any one individual from completing a sensitive transaction end-to-end, reducing fraud risk. Least privilege limits access to only what's needed, need to know restricts information access, and mandatory vacation is a detective control unrelated to transaction workflows.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization notices that its biometric fingerprint scanner occasionally allows unauthorized individuals to gain access. This is an example of which type of error?","o":["False Rejection Rate (FRR)","False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Equal Error Rate (EER)"],"c":1,"why":"A False Acceptance Rate error occurs when an unauthorized individual is incorrectly granted access. FRR is the opposite error (rejecting legitimate users), and CER/EER refer to the point where FAR and FRR are equal, not a specific error type.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Why is timely deprovisioning of user accounts considered a critical control in identity management?","o":["It improves network bandwidth utilization","It prevents former employees or unneeded accounts from retaining unauthorized access","It automatically updates password complexity rules","It reduces the need for encryption on stored data"],"c":1,"why":"Deprovisioning removes access rights when they are no longer needed (e.g., after termination), closing a common attack vector for unauthorized access. The other choices are unrelated to account lifecycle management.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to grant access decisions based on a combination of user department, time of day, and resource sensitivity classification, rather than fixed job titles. Which access control model best supports this requirement?","o":["Discretionary access control (DAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)","Role-based access control (RBAC)","Attribute-based access control (ABAC)"],"c":3,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple dynamic attributes (department, time, classification) to make fine-grained access decisions, unlike RBAC which relies on static role assignments. DAC leaves access decisions to resource owners, and MAC relies on fixed sensitivity labels and clearances rather than contextual attributes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A web application uses OAuth 2.0 to allow a third-party mobile app to access a user's photos stored on a cloud service without sharing the user's password. Which OAuth 2.0 component is issued to the mobile app to access the resource on the user's behalf?","o":["ID token","Access token","Refresh token secret key","SAML assertion"],"c":1,"why":"In OAuth 2.0, the access token is issued to the client application and presented to the resource server to access protected resources on the user's behalf. The ID token (used in OpenID Connect) conveys identity information rather than authorization, refresh tokens are used to obtain new access tokens rather than access resources directly, and SAML assertions belong to a different federation protocol.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee leaves an organization, what is the MOST important access management action to take promptly?","o":["Change the organization's firewall rules","Deprovision the employee's user accounts and access rights","Update the organization's disaster recovery plan","Reissue new badges to all remaining employees"],"c":1,"why":"Prompt deprovisioning of accounts and access rights prevents former employees from retaining unauthorized access, a critical IAM control. The other actions are unrelated to the immediate risk posed by a departing employee's credentials.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company allows employees to log into a partner organization's cloud application using their corporate credentials without creating a separate account. This capability is best described as:","o":["Role-based access control","Federated identity management","Discretionary access control","Privileged access management"],"c":1,"why":"Federated identity management allows users to authenticate using credentials from a trusted identity provider across organizational boundaries, avoiding duplicate accounts. RBAC, DAC, and PAM address different aspects of access control unrelated to cross-domain trust.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During a SAML-based single sign-on transaction, which entity is responsible for asserting a user's identity to the service provider?","o":["The relying party","The identity provider","The service provider","The resource owner"],"c":1,"why":"The identity provider (IdP) authenticates the user and issues a SAML assertion vouching for their identity to the service provider (relying party). The service provider consumes the assertion but does not generate it, and 'resource owner' is an OAuth term, not a SAML role.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing a password policy and wants to balance usability with resistance to offline brute-force attacks. Which combination of controls would most effectively achieve this goal?","o":["Short minimum length with frequent mandatory password changes every 30 days","Long minimum length with a salted, slow hashing algorithm and no forced periodic changes","Complex character requirements with passwords stored using reversible encryption","Long minimum length with passwords stored as unsalted SHA-1 hashes"],"c":1,"why":"Longer passwords combined with salted, computationally slow hashing (e.g., bcrypt/Argon2) significantly increase resistance to offline brute-force and rainbow table attacks; current guidance (e.g., NIST 800-63B) discourages frequent forced changes as they encourage weak, predictable passwords. Reversible encryption and unsalted fast hashes (SHA-1) are insecure storage practices.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a Kerberos authentication environment, what is the primary function of the Key Distribution Center (KDC)?","o":["To store user passwords in plaintext for quick retrieval","To issue tickets that allow authenticated users to access network services","To encrypt all data transmitted across the network","To serve as the final authority for authorization decisions on every resource"],"c":1,"why":"The KDC authenticates users and issues time-limited tickets (via the Authentication Service and Ticket-Granting Service) that permit access to network services without repeatedly sending credentials. It does not store plaintext passwords, encrypt all network data, or make per-resource authorization decisions itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which access control model relies on system-enforced labels (such as classification levels) rather than allowing resource owners to set permissions?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Rule-Based Access Control","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)"],"c":1,"why":"MAC uses centrally managed security labels and clearances enforced by the system, removing discretion from individual owners, which is characteristic of high-security environments. DAC gives owners control, while rule-based and role-based models use different assignment logic.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization's authentication failures spike after a domain controller's system clock drifts by 10 minutes from client workstations using Kerberos. Which of the following BEST explains why this causes Kerberos authentication failures?","o":["Kerberos tickets include timestamps to prevent replay attacks, and authentication fails when clock skew exceeds the maximum allowed tolerance","The KDC uses the system clock to generate session keys, and drift corrupts the key derivation function","Ticket-granting tickets expire immediately whenever any clock skew is detected, regardless of configured tolerance","Kerberos relies on the client clock to encrypt the service ticket, and drift prevents the server from decrypting it"],"c":0,"why":"Kerberos embeds timestamps in tickets/authenticators as an anti-replay mechanism, and the KDC/service rejects requests outside the configured clock skew tolerance (commonly 5 minutes); the other options misstate how keys and encryption actually work in the protocol.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A mobile app needs to obtain the user's verified identity (name, email) AND a token to call a third-party API on the user's behalf, without ever handling the user's password. Which combination of protocol and flow BEST satisfies this requirement?","o":["OAuth 2.0 Authorization Code flow alone, since access tokens inherently contain verified identity claims","SAML 2.0 with HTTP POST binding, extended to issue OAuth-compatible access tokens","OpenID Connect (OIDC) using the Authorization Code flow, which layers an ID token containing identity claims on top of OAuth 2.0 access tokens","Kerberos constrained delegation (S4U2Proxy) to obtain a service ticket representing the user's identity claims"],"c":2,"why":"OIDC is purpose-built to add an identity layer (the ID token) on top of OAuth 2.0's authorization framework, satisfying both authentication and delegated API access needs; plain OAuth tokens are opaque and not identity assertions, SAML is not natively designed for mobile/API delegation, and Kerberos delegation is an enterprise/on-prem mechanism unsuited to this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric system's sensitivity threshold is increased specifically to reduce false acceptances. Which outcome is the MOST likely direct consequence, and what does the Crossover Error Rate (CER) represent in this context?","o":["FRR decreases while FAR increases; CER is the point where FRR equals zero","FAR decreases while FRR increases; CER is the threshold at which FAR and FRR are equal, used to compare accuracy across biometric systems","Both FAR and FRR decrease simultaneously; CER represents the average of all threshold settings","FAR increases while FRR decreases; CER represents the maximum acceptable error tolerance defined by policy"],"c":1,"why":"Raising the threshold to be stricter reduces false acceptances (FAR) but increases false rejections (FRR), an inherent trade-off; CER is the specific point where these two curves intersect and is used as a standard metric for comparing biometric system accuracy, not a policy-defined tolerance or an average.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization discovers that several former employees still have active VPN accounts three months after termination. Which control failure is most directly responsible for this finding?","o":["Lack of multifactor authentication on the VPN","Inadequate account deprovisioning process","Absence of role-based access control","Failure to implement single sign-on"],"c":1,"why":"Active accounts for terminated employees indicate a breakdown in the deprovisioning step of the identity lifecycle, where HR termination events should trigger timely account disablement. MFA, RBAC, and SSO address different aspects of access management and would not by themselves prevent orphaned accounts.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A financial firm needs an access control model where a trader can access trading systems only during market hours, from a corporate-managed device, and only while their risk-training certification is current. Which access control model BEST supports this requirement natively?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC), by creating a new role for each unique combination of conditions","Mandatory Access Control (MAC), using sensitivity labels tied to time and device attributes","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC), which evaluates policies against subject, object, and environmental attributes at request time","Discretionary Access Control (DAC), allowing the trader's manager to grant access dynamically each morning"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC natively evaluates dynamic, contextual attributes (time, device posture, certification status) at access time; RBAC would require an unmanageable explosion of roles, MAC's labels aren't designed for time/device context, and DAC lacks the automated, policy-driven enforcement needed here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An application uses OAuth 2.0 to allow a third-party service to access a user's cloud storage files without sharing the user's password. What is the primary purpose of OAuth 2.0 in this scenario?","o":["To authenticate the user's identity to the third-party service","To authorize delegated access to specific resources on behalf of the user","To encrypt data in transit between the user and the storage provider","To provide a single set of credentials for multiple unrelated services"],"c":1,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is an authorization framework designed to grant delegated, scoped access to resources without exposing credentials; it does not itself authenticate identity (that is OpenID Connect's role) nor does it handle transport encryption or credential unification like SSO.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"In a SAML 2.0 federated SSO deployment, a Service Provider (SP) receives an assertion from an Identity Provider (IdP). Which validation step is MOST critical for preventing a replay attack using a previously captured, validly-signed assertion?","o":["Verifying the assertion's XML signature matches the IdP's public key","Checking the assertion's NotOnOrAfter condition and confirming the assertion ID has not been previously processed","Confirming the Subject NameID maps to an existing local user account","Validating that the assertion was transmitted over TLS 1.2 or higher"],"c":1,"why":"A signed assertion remains valid to replay within its time window unless the SP enforces the validity period and tracks assertion IDs to reject duplicates; signature verification confirms authenticity/integrity but does not by itself stop replay of a still-valid, correctly signed assertion, and NameID mapping/TLS address different concerns.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security team implements a solution that grants administrators temporary, time-limited elevated privileges only when needed, with all sessions logged and recorded. This approach is an example of which security practice?","o":["Separation of duties","Just-in-time privileged access management","Mandatory vacation policy","Discretionary access control"],"c":1,"why":"Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access management grants elevated rights only for the duration needed and logs activity, reducing the standing attack surface of privileged accounts. Separation of duties and mandatory vacation are unrelated administrative controls, and DAC concerns owner-granted permissions, not privilege elevation timing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An investment bank wants to prevent analysts who have accessed non-public information about Company A from also accessing information about Company A's direct competitors once assigned to a deal team, while still allowing flexible access before any assignment occurs. Which access control model BEST addresses this requirement?","o":["Bell-LaPadula model, using classification levels for each company's data","Biba integrity model, using integrity levels to separate competing datasets","Brewer-Nash model (Chinese Wall), which dynamically restricts access based on prior access history to prevent conflicts of interest","Clark-Wilson model, using well-formed transactions to enforce separation"],"c":2,"why":"The Brewer-Nash (Chinese Wall) model is specifically designed to dynamically restrict access based on a subject's access history to prevent conflicts of interest, exactly matching this scenario; Bell-LaPadula and Biba address confidentiality/integrity via static labels, and Clark-Wilson focuses on transaction integrity, not conflict-of-interest history.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester compromises a domain controller and extracts the NTLM hash of the krbtgt account within a Windows Active Directory domain. Which attack does this MOST directly enable?","o":["Pass-the-hash attack limited to a single workstation","A golden ticket attack allowing forged TGTs for any domain account","Kerberoasting to crack service account passwords offline","LLMNR poisoning to capture NTLMv2 credentials on the network"],"c":1,"why":"The krbtgt account's hash is used to sign Ticket Granting Tickets; possessing it allows an attacker to forge valid TGTs for any user (golden ticket), granting persistent domain-wide access. The other attacks do not require the krbtgt hash specifically.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A quarterly access review reveals several employees who transferred departments six months ago still retain access entitlements from their former roles. Which control would have MOST effectively prevented this accumulation of excessive privilege?","o":["Implementing mandatory annual security awareness training for all employees","Enforcing a formal offboarding process triggered only upon termination","Automating access recertification and entitlement revocation tied to HR transfer events within the joiner-mover-leaver (JML) process","Requiring multi-factor authentication for all privileged accounts"],"c":2,"why":"The gap is in the 'mover' stage of the identity lifecycle; automating entitlement review and revocation triggered by HR transfer events closes this gap directly, whereas awareness training, termination-only offboarding, and MFA do not address stale entitlements from internal role changes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A mobile application acts as a public OAuth 2.0 client (it cannot securely store a client secret) and uses the authorization code flow to obtain access tokens. Which control should be added to prevent authorization code interception attacks?","o":["Switch to the implicit grant flow for simplicity","Implement PKCE (Proof Key for Code Exchange)","Use the client credentials grant instead","Extend the access token lifetime to reduce reauthentication"],"c":1,"why":"PKCE binds the authorization code request to a dynamically generated verifier, preventing an intercepted code from being redeemed by an attacker. Implicit flow is deprecated and less secure, client credentials grant is meant for machine-to-machine auth, and longer token lifetimes increase risk rather than mitigate it.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A web application stores OAuth access and refresh tokens in browser localStorage for convenience. A penetration test discovers an XSS vulnerability that could allow an attacker to exfiltrate these tokens. Which remediation BEST reduces the risk of token theft leading to long-term account compromise?","o":["Increase the token signing key length from 2048 to 4096 bits","Store tokens in HttpOnly, Secure cookies and implement short-lived access tokens with refresh token rotation and sender-constrained (token-bound) credentials","Switch from OAuth 2.0 to SAML 2.0 for all session management","Encrypt the tokens client-side using a key stored in a JavaScript variable before placing them in localStorage"],"c":1,"why":"HttpOnly cookies are inaccessible to JavaScript (mitigating XSS token theft), while short-lived tokens, refresh rotation, and sender-constraining limit the damage if a token is somehow stolen; key length changes don't address exposure, switching to SAML doesn't solve client-side storage risk, and client-side encryption with a JS-accessible key provides no real protection against XSS.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A hospital requires that access to a patient's electronic record be granted only if the clinician's assigned department matches the patient's admitting department, the request occurs during the clinician's scheduled shift, and the request originates from a hospital-managed device. Which access control model BEST supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes (department match, time, device) dynamically at request time, which RBAC's static role assignments cannot express. MAC relies on fixed sensitivity labels, and DAC relies on resource-owner discretion, neither of which supports this contextual policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An administrator lowers the matching threshold on a fingerprint access control system after receiving complaints about failed authentications. Which outcome is the MOST likely direct result of this change?","o":["Decreased False Rejection Rate and increased False Acceptance Rate","Decreased False Acceptance Rate and increased False Rejection Rate","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) will decrease","Both FRR and FAR will decrease simultaneously"],"c":0,"why":"Lowering the threshold makes the system more lenient, reducing legitimate user rejections (FRR) but allowing more impostors through (FAR increases). CER is an intrinsic property of the sensor/algorithm at the point where FRR=FAR and isn't reduced by threshold tuning; FRR and FAR move inversely, not together.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An attacker intercepts a valid SAML assertion issued by an Identity Provider and successfully replays it in a separate browser session to impersonate the user at the Service Provider. Which combination of controls would MOST effectively prevent this?","o":["Encrypt the SAML assertion using the Service Provider's public key only","Transmit the assertion over unencrypted HTTP to simplify processing","Enforce short assertion validity windows, one-time-use tokens, and audience restriction","Increase the key length used to sign the assertion"],"c":2,"why":"Time-bound, single-use assertions with audience restriction render a captured assertion useless after first use or expiration, directly stopping replay. Encryption alone doesn't prevent replay of a still-valid token, removing TLS increases risk, and signature key length strengthens integrity but not replay resistance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a Mandatory Access Control (MAC) model, access to an object is primarily determined by:","o":["The role assigned to the user by the help desk","Security labels and clearances assigned by the system","The discretion of the object's owner","The size and location of the object"],"c":1,"why":"MAC enforces access based on classification labels and subject clearances set by a central authority, unlike DAC where the owner decides access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"To reduce risk from standing privileged accounts, a security architect implements a system where administrators must submit a request for elevated access that is granted only for a defined time window and automatically revoked afterward. Which concept does this describe?","o":["Role mining","Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access","Discretionary access delegation","Credential vaulting"],"c":1,"why":"JIT privileged access grants time-limited elevation only when needed, minimizing the window of exposure from standing privileges. Role mining is a discovery technique for defining roles, discretionary delegation is unrelated to time-bounding, and credential vaulting secures stored credentials but doesn't inherently time-limit their use.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"What is a primary benefit of implementing Single Sign-On (SSO) for end users?","o":["It eliminates the need for any authentication","It reduces the number of credentials users must remember and manage","It automatically enforces the principle of least privilege","It prevents all forms of replay attacks"],"c":1,"why":"SSO improves usability by letting users authenticate once to access multiple systems; it does not eliminate authentication, enforce least privilege, or inherently stop replay attacks.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A finance department policy mandates that the employee who initiates a wire transfer request can never be the same employee who approves it. Which security principle is being enforced?","o":["Least privilege","Need-to-know","Separation of duties","Defense in depth"],"c":2,"why":"Requiring different individuals to initiate and approve a transaction enforces separation of duties, preventing a single person from committing fraud unilaterally. Least privilege limits the scope of access, need-to-know limits information exposure, and defense in depth refers to layered controls generally, none of which specifically address this dual-control requirement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a SAML-based federated identity scenario, what is the purpose of the 'assertion' sent from the Identity Provider (IdP) to the Service Provider (SP)?","o":["It encrypts the user's password for long-term storage","It conveys authentication and attribute information about the user to the relying party","It defines firewall rules between the two domains","It automatically grants administrative access to the resource server"],"c":1,"why":"A SAML assertion is a statement from the IdP that vouches for the user's identity and attributes, allowing the SP to make an access decision; it is not related to firewall rules or password storage.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During an access certification review, an auditor finds multiple accounts belonging to employees who left the organization over six months ago, and these accounts remain active with valid credentials. What is the ROOT CAUSE of this finding?","o":["Lack of multi-factor authentication enforcement on the accounts","Inadequate deprovisioning within the identity lifecycle management process","Absence of role-based access control definitions","Failure to rotate service account passwords periodically"],"c":1,"why":"Orphaned active accounts result directly from a breakdown in the offboarding/deprovisioning step of identity lifecycle management. MFA, RBAC, and password rotation address different risk areas and would not by themselves prevent terminated employees' accounts from remaining active.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to swipe an access badge and then enter a PIN to enter the data center. This is an example of:","o":["Single-factor authentication","Two-factor authentication combining possession and knowledge factors","Biometric authentication","Role-based access control"],"c":1,"why":"The badge represents 'something you have' and the PIN represents 'something you know,' making this two-factor authentication; it is not biometric or an access control model.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security reason for promptly deprovisioning a user's accounts and access when they leave an organization?","o":["To reduce software licensing costs","To prevent the former employee from retaining unauthorized access to systems","To satisfy password complexity requirements","To allow the former employee to self-service password resets"],"c":1,"why":"Deprovisioning ensures that departing employees can no longer access organizational resources, closing a common attack vector; the other options are unrelated to the core security purpose.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In the Kerberos authentication protocol, what is the primary function of the Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT)?","o":["It authenticates the user directly to every individual service","It allows the user to request service tickets from the Ticket Granting Service without re-entering credentials","It encrypts all data transmitted between client and server","It permanently stores the user's password on the client machine"],"c":1,"why":"The TGT, issued by the Authentication Service, lets the client obtain service tickets from the TGS without re-authenticating; it does not directly authenticate to each service or store passwords.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which access control model assigns permissions based on a user's job function rather than assigning permissions to each individual user account?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-based access control tied to time of day"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC grants access based on roles that correspond to job functions, simplifying administration; DAC relies on owner discretion and MAC relies on security labels/clearances.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In Role-Based Access Control (RBAC), access permissions are primarily assigned based on:","o":["The sensitivity label of the data being accessed","The job function or role of the user within the organization","The discretion of the data owner for each individual user","The classification level of the requesting system"],"c":1,"why":"RBAC grants permissions according to organizational roles, simplifying administration compared to per-user assignments. Data sensitivity labels relate to MAC, and owner discretion describes DAC.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial services company wants to grant access to a sensitive application based on a combination of factors: the user's department, the time of day, the sensitivity classification of the data being accessed, and whether the connecting device is corporate-managed. Which access control model is best suited to enforce these dynamic, multi-factor policies?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":1,"why":"ABAC evaluates policies against multiple subject, object, and environmental attributes at access time, enabling fine-grained contextual decisions. RBAC only considers role assignment, MAC relies on fixed security labels and clearances, and DAC leaves access decisions to the resource owner, none of which natively support multi-attribute contextual rules.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a Kerberos authentication environment, after a user successfully proves their identity to the Authentication Service (AS) portion of the Key Distribution Center (KDC), what is issued to the user to allow them to subsequently request access to specific network services without re-entering their password?","o":["A service ticket for each resource immediately","A ticket-granting ticket (TGT)","A public key certificate","A one-time session password"],"c":1,"why":"The AS issues a TGT after successful authentication; this TGT is later presented to the Ticket-Granting Service (TGS) to obtain individual service tickets for specific resources. Service tickets are obtained using the TGT, not directly from initial authentication, and Kerberos does not use certificates or one-time passwords in its core protocol.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a SAML-based federated identity architecture, which entity is responsible for authenticating the end user's credentials and generating a digitally signed assertion that is then presented to a partner application to grant access?","o":["Service Provider (SP)","Identity Provider (IdP)","Certificate Authority (CA)","Policy Decision Point (PDP)"],"c":1,"why":"The IdP performs authentication and issues the signed SAML assertion consumed by the SP to grant access. The SP relies on the assertion rather than authenticating the user itself, the CA issues certificates rather than assertions, and a PDP is a generic access-control component, not a SAML-specific role.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During tuning of a biometric access control system, the point at which the False Acceptance Rate (FAR) and False Rejection Rate (FRR) curves intersect is used as a key metric. What does this intersection point represent, and how should it be interpreted?","o":["The enrollment failure rate; a higher value indicates more users successfully enrolled","The Crossover Error Rate (CER); a lower value indicates a more accurate biometric system","The throughput rate; a higher value indicates faster authentication processing","The Type I statistical error; it has no bearing on system accuracy"],"c":1,"why":"The CER (or Equal Error Rate) is the point where FAR equals FRR, and a lower CER indicates a more accurate and well-calibrated biometric system. Enrollment failure and throughput are separate performance metrics unrelated to this specific intersection, and the CER is directly tied to system accuracy, not merely a generic statistical error.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization's termination procedure states that a departing employee's manager submits an offboarding request to HR, which is then processed by IT within 48 hours. From a security best-practice perspective, what is the primary risk introduced by this workflow?","o":["The employee may be unable to access final paycheck information","The delay creates a window during which a terminated user retains active access to systems","HR may violate labor law by processing the request too quickly","The process fails to comply with password complexity requirements"],"c":1,"why":"Any delay between termination and account deactivation creates an exposure window where a disgruntled or compromised former employee could misuse still-active credentials; best practice is immediate, automated deprovisioning tied to the HR termination event. The other options are not meaningful security concerns related to account lifecycle management.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A user authenticates to a corporate VPN by inserting a smart card and then entering a PIN known only to them. How many authentication factors does this represent, and why?","o":["One factor, because both elements are entered through the same device","Two factors, because it combines something the user has with something the user knows","Three factors, because the smart card, PIN, and VPN client each count separately","One factor, because a PIN is considered equivalent to a password"],"c":1,"why":"A smart card is a possession factor (something you have) and a PIN is a knowledge factor (something you know), so together they constitute true two-factor authentication. Using a single device to present both elements does not collapse them into one factor, and the VPN client itself is not an authentication factor.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization's Kerberos authentication intermittently fails for users on a particular subnet, even though their credentials are correct and their tickets have not expired. Investigation reveals that workstations on that subnet are not synchronized with the domain's NTP source and their clocks differ from the KDC by more than 15 minutes. What is the MOST likely cause of the authentication failures?","o":["Kerberos authenticators are timestamped to prevent replay attacks, and the KDC rejects requests when clock skew exceeds the configured maximum tolerance","The workstations' service principal names (SPNs) have expired and must be re-registered in the directory","Kerberos requires all clients to use the same shared secret key as the KDC, and clock drift invalidates that key","The ticket-granting ticket (TGT) encryption type is incompatible with the domain controller's supported cipher suites"],"c":0,"why":"Kerberos relies on timestamped authenticators to prevent replay attacks; if client and KDC clocks differ beyond the allowed skew (commonly 5 minutes), the KDC rejects the authentication attempt as a potential replay. SPN expiration, shared-key mismatches, and cipher incompatibility are not caused by clock drift and would produce different, non-intermittent failures.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company implements single sign-on (SSO) so employees authenticate once to access multiple internal applications. Which of the following best describes the primary security concern introduced by this architecture, along with an appropriate mitigation?","o":["SSO increases password complexity requirements, so users should be trained on stronger passwords","Compromise of the user's single credential set grants an attacker access to all federated applications, so strong MFA should be enforced at the initial login","SSO eliminates the need for logging, so audit trails should be disabled to reduce storage costs","SSO requires each application to maintain a separate password, increasing administrative overhead"],"c":1,"why":"SSO consolidates authentication into a single point of trust, meaning a compromised credential can expose all connected applications; enforcing strong MFA at the initial authentication event mitigates this risk. SSO does not eliminate logging needs, does not increase password complexity requirements inherently, and reduces rather than increases per-application password administration.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is comparing IdP-initiated and SP-initiated SAML SSO flows for a new federation partnership. Which statement correctly identifies a security concern that is UNIQUE to IdP-initiated SSO?","o":["Because there is no preceding AuthnRequest from the SP, the SP has no request context to correlate with the incoming assertion, making it harder to detect replayed or injected assertions","IdP-initiated flows cannot digitally sign the SAML assertion, so message integrity cannot be verified","IdP-initiated flows transmit the assertion exclusively over unencrypted HTTP, unlike SP-initiated flows","IdP-initiated flows require the user to authenticate twice, once at the IdP and once at the SP"],"c":0,"why":"In IdP-initiated SSO, the flow begins without a corresponding SP AuthnRequest, so the SP cannot validate an InResponseTo value or request context, increasing exposure to assertion replay if other controls (audience restriction, short validity windows) aren't enforced. Signing, transport encryption, and double authentication are implementation choices, not inherent differences between the two flows.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to reduce the standing risk associated with administrator accounts that have permanent access to critical servers. Which privileged access management (PAM) approach best addresses this by granting elevated rights only for a limited, approved time window?","o":["Role mining to consolidate all admin roles into a single superuser account","Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access with time-bound approval workflows","Assigning all administrators the same shared service account for simplicity","Disabling account lockout policies for administrative accounts to prevent denial of service"],"c":1,"why":"JIT privileged access grants elevated permissions only when needed and automatically revokes them after a defined period, minimizing the attack surface of standing privileged accounts. Consolidating into a superuser account or sharing credentials increases risk and eliminates accountability, and disabling lockout policies weakens security rather than reducing standing privilege risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A mobile application acting as a public OAuth 2.0 client implements the authorization code flow with PKCE (Proof Key for Code Exchange) instead of the implicit flow. What is the PRIMARY security benefit PKCE provides in this scenario?","o":["It binds the authorization code to the client that initiated the request, preventing an attacker who intercepts the code from exchanging it for tokens without the original code_verifier","It encrypts the access token so that it cannot be read by the mobile OS or intercepting proxies","It removes the need for TLS between the client and the authorization server","It allows the client to safely store a static client secret embedded in the app binary"],"c":0,"why":"PKCE mitigates authorization code interception attacks against public clients (which cannot securely hold a client secret) by requiring the client to present a code_verifier matching the code_challenge sent at authorization time. PKCE does not encrypt tokens, does not replace TLS, and public clients should never rely on embedded static secrets.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the difference between identification and authentication?","o":["Identification grants access rights, while authentication assigns a username","Identification is the claim of an identity, while authentication is the process of proving that claim is valid","Identification and authentication are the same process performed twice for security","Authentication occurs before identification in every access control system"],"c":1,"why":"Identification is asserting who you are (e.g., entering a username), while authentication verifies that claim (e.g., entering a password). The other options misstate the relationship or reverse the correct order.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm wants access decisions for a sensitive trading application to consider the user's role, the device's patch/compliance status, the user's geolocation, and the time of day simultaneously, with policies that can be updated without reassigning user roles. Which access control model BEST satisfies this requirement?","o":["Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC), because it evaluates multiple contextual attributes dynamically at the time of the access request","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC), because roles can be nested to represent device and location combinations","Mandatory Access Control (MAC), because sensitivity labels inherently include contextual metadata","Discretionary Access Control (DAC), because resource owners can grant access based on any criteria they choose"],"c":0,"why":"ABAC evaluates policies against multiple runtime attributes (role, device posture, location, time) without requiring role explosion, making it the best fit for dynamic, context-aware decisions. RBAC would require an impractical number of roles to represent every attribute combination, MAC is centered on classification labels rather than contextual attributes, and DAC lacks centralized, consistent policy enforcement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization requires employees to enter a password and then a one-time numeric code generated by an authenticator app installed on their personal smartphone. What authentication factor category does the app-generated code represent?","o":["Something you know","Something you have","Something you are","Something you do"],"c":1,"why":"A code generated by an app tied to a specific registered device is a possession-based factor (something you have), similar to a hardware token. It is not knowledge-based, biometric, or behavioral.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to log in using a smart card and a PIN. This is an example of which authentication concept?","o":["Single-factor authentication using two credentials","Multi-factor authentication combining 'something you have' and 'something you know'","Federated identity management","Role-based access control"],"c":1,"why":"A smart card is 'something you have' and a PIN is 'something you know,' making this true multi-factor authentication. It is not federation or RBAC, which relate to identity sharing and permission assignment, not authentication factors.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An internal audit finds that an employee who has transferred between four departments over five years still retains access rights granted in each prior role, none of which were revoked during the transfers. Which control would MOST effectively prevent this type of privilege accumulation going forward?","o":["Mandatory periodic access recertification by resource/data owners tied to the mover process","Enforcing a stronger password complexity policy for all transferred employees","Implementing mandatory account lockout after failed login attempts","Requiring multi-factor authentication for all privileged accounts"],"c":0,"why":"Privilege creep from repeated internal transfers is best addressed by formal access recertification/attestation, where owners review and revoke access no longer needed as part of the joiner-mover-leaver process. Password policy, account lockout, and MFA address different threats (credential guessing/brute force) and do nothing to remove unnecessary standing access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a biometric access control system, which metric represents the rate at which unauthorized users are incorrectly granted access?","o":["False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","Equal Error Rate (EER)"],"c":2,"why":"FAR measures how often unauthorized individuals are incorrectly accepted. FRR is the opposite (rejecting authorized users), and CER/EER refer to the point where FAR and FRR are equal, not a specific error type.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial services company wants to make access decisions dynamically based on a combination of factors such as the user's job role, current location, time of day, and device compliance status. Which access control model best supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)"],"c":3,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes at the time of the access request to make fine-grained decisions. RBAC is limited to roles, DAC relies on resource-owner discretion, and MAC relies on fixed security labels/clearances.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"When evaluating two competing biometric authentication systems, an analyst plots False Acceptance Rate (FAR) and False Rejection Rate (FRR) against sensitivity threshold for each. Which statement about using the Crossover Error Rate (CER) to compare the systems is CORRECT?","o":["The CER is the point where FAR and FRR are equal, and a lower CER value indicates a more accurate overall biometric system","The CER is the average of FAR and FRR across all thresholds, and a higher CER indicates a more accurate system","The CER measures only enrollment failures and is unrelated to FAR or FRR","The CER is fixed by the biometric modality and cannot be changed by adjusting the sensitivity threshold"],"c":0,"why":"The Crossover (or Crossover Equal) Error Rate is the point at which FAR equals FRR; a lower CER represents a better-performing, more accurate biometric system overall. It is not an average across all thresholds, it is unrelated to enrollment failure rates, and it does vary with threshold and system design—CER identifies the optimal threshold, not a fixed modality constant.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which access control model assigns permissions based on a user's job function within an organization?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions according to roles tied to job functions, simplifying administration. DAC relies on resource owners' discretion, MAC uses security labels/clearances, and rule-based control uses predefined conditions rather than job roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a SAML-based single sign-on federation, which entity authenticates the user's credentials and issues a signed assertion confirming the user's identity to the requesting application?","o":["Service Provider","Identity Provider","Relying Party","Resource Server"],"c":1,"why":"The Identity Provider (IdP) performs the authentication and issues the SAML assertion. The Service Provider (also called the relying party) consumes the assertion but does not authenticate the user itself; a resource server is an OAuth concept, not SAML.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A company deploys enterprise-wide Single Sign-On (SSO) across 40 applications, replacing separate credentials for each. Security leadership raises a concern about the architecture. Which of the following BEST describes the primary new risk introduced by this SSO deployment if no compensating controls are added?","o":["Compromise of a single set of user credentials now grants an attacker access to all 40 connected applications instead of just one","Users will need to memorize more passwords than before, increasing the likelihood of weak password choices","SSO inherently disables the ability to enforce multi-factor authentication at any connected application","SSO prevents the organization from federating identities with external business partners"],"c":0,"why":"SSO consolidates authentication so a single compromised credential set becomes a master key to many systems, making the initial authentication event a high-value target and single point of compromise; this is why MFA and strong session controls are essential compensating controls. SSO reduces, not increases, password count, does not disable MFA, and is actually an enabler of federation rather than a barrier.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of a Single Sign-On (SSO) solution?","o":["To require multiple credentials for every application accessed","To allow a user to authenticate once and gain access to multiple systems without re-authenticating","To encrypt all network traffic between client and server","To enforce mandatory password changes across all systems"],"c":1,"why":"SSO enables a single authentication event to grant access to multiple connected systems, improving usability and reducing password fatigue. The other options describe unrelated security functions such as encryption or password policy enforcement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A network administrator is choosing between RADIUS and TACACS+ for authenticating administrative access to network infrastructure devices. Which statement accurately describes a key architectural difference between the two protocols?","o":["TACACS+ encrypts the entire packet payload and separates authentication, authorization, and accounting into distinct processes, whereas RADIUS encrypts only the password field and combines authentication and authorization","RADIUS encrypts the entire packet payload while TACACS+ only encrypts the password field, making RADIUS more suitable for command-level authorization","Both protocols encrypt only the password field, but TACACS+ uses UDP while RADIUS uses TCP for improved reliability","TACACS+ cannot perform accounting functions, so it must be paired with RADIUS in any AAA deployment"],"c":0,"why":"TACACS+ encrypts the full packet body and cleanly separates the AAA functions, allowing granular per-command authorization, while RADIUS encrypts only the password attribute and combines authentication with authorization in a single response—making TACACS+ generally preferred for device administration. The other options reverse these protocol characteristics or make an unfounded claim about TACACS+ lacking accounting capability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which protocol is commonly used to provide centralized authentication using a system of tickets to avoid transmitting passwords across the network?","o":["LDAP","RADIUS","Kerberos","OAuth"],"c":2,"why":"Kerberos uses a ticket-granting system with symmetric key cryptography to authenticate users without sending passwords over the network. LDAP is a directory access protocol, RADIUS is used for network access authentication, and OAuth is for authorization delegation, not ticket-based authentication.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester extracts the NTLM hash of the krbtgt service account from a compromised domain controller and uses it to forge Kerberos ticket-granting tickets that grant domain admin rights for any username, including accounts that don't exist in Active Directory. Which attack technique is being performed?","o":["Golden ticket attack","Pass-the-hash attack","Silver ticket attack","Kerberoasting"],"c":0,"why":"A golden ticket attack forges TGTs using the compromised krbtgt account's key, granting persistent, arbitrary domain access. Pass-the-hash authenticates directly with a captured NTLM hash rather than forging Kerberos tickets; a silver ticket forges a service ticket using a service account's key, limiting access to that service; Kerberoasting harvests service ticket hashes for offline password cracking, not ticket forgery.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In the Kerberos authentication protocol, what does a client present to the Ticket Granting Service (TGS) in order to obtain a service ticket for a specific resource?","o":["The Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT)","The user's plaintext password","The service's private key","The Key Distribution Center's master key"],"c":0,"why":"After initial authentication, the client receives a TGT from the Authentication Service and presents it to the TGS to request service tickets, avoiding repeated transmission of the password. The other options are never transmitted or used this way in Kerberos.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"During employee offboarding, which access management activity is MOST important to perform immediately to reduce security risk?","o":["Archiving the employee's email for compliance purposes","Disabling or removing the employee's user accounts and access rights","Updating the employee's job title in the HR system","Reassigning the employee's badge photo to a new hire"],"c":1,"why":"Promptly disabling or removing access prevents former employees from retaining unauthorized system access, which is a critical security control. The other actions are administrative tasks that do not directly mitigate the risk of unauthorized access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A cloud application configured as a SAML service provider (SP) begins rejecting all incoming SSO assertions from a trusted identity provider (IdP) with a 'signature validation failed' error, even though users authenticate successfully at the IdP. Federation worked correctly until the IdP's signing certificate was renewed. What is the MOST likely root cause?","o":["The SP's trust configuration still references the IdP's old signing certificate and was not updated after the certificate rotation","The system clocks between the IdP and SP have drifted beyond the allowed NotOnOrAfter tolerance","The NameID format sent by the IdP does not match the format expected by the SP's user attribute mapping","The SP is configured to require encrypted assertions, but the IdP is sending them in plaintext"],"c":0,"why":"A signature validation failure specifically points to the SP validating against an outdated certificate after the IdP rotated its signing key without updating the SP's trust anchor. Clock skew would produce an expired-assertion error, NameID mismatches cause identity mapping failures, and missing encryption produces decryption errors—none of which manifest as a signature mismatch.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An employee who transfers between departments over several years retains all previously granted access rights while accumulating new permissions for each new role, without any formal access review. This situation is best described as:","o":["Least privilege","Privilege creep","Separation of duties","Mandatory access review"],"c":1,"why":"Privilege creep (also called access aggregation) occurs when accumulated, unreviewed permissions exceed what is needed for the current role, violating least privilege. Separation of duties concerns dividing critical tasks, not accumulation of rights.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a federated identity environment using SAML, which entity is responsible for authenticating the user and issuing an assertion of identity?","o":["The Service Provider (SP)","The Relying Party","The Identity Provider (IdP)","The Resource Owner"],"c":2,"why":"In SAML federation, the Identity Provider authenticates the user and issues assertions that the Service Provider (relying party) trusts. The Service Provider consumes the assertion but does not perform the authentication itself, and 'Resource Owner' is a concept from OAuth, not SAML.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A data center restricts entry to the server room by requiring an employee to badge in at a locked door, which denies access to anyone without an authorized credential. This control is best classified as:","o":["Detective control","Corrective control","Preventive control","Compensating control"],"c":2,"why":"A locked door requiring authorization stops unauthorized access before it occurs, making it preventive. Detective controls identify incidents after the fact, corrective controls remediate after an incident, and compensating controls substitute for a primary control that cannot be implemented.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During tuning of a biometric authentication system, an administrator plots the False Acceptance Rate (FAR) and False Rejection Rate (FRR) against varying sensitivity thresholds. The point at which these two rates are equal is known as the:","o":["False Acceptance Rate","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","True Positive Rate","Enrollment Error Rate"],"c":1,"why":"The Crossover Error Rate (also called the Equal Error Rate) is the threshold point where FAR and FRR intersect, and it is commonly used as a key metric of biometric system accuracy. The other terms describe unrelated or single-sided metrics.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A mobile application needs to access a user's photos stored on a third-party cloud service without ever receiving or storing the user's password for that service. Which protocol is specifically designed to grant this kind of delegated, token-based access?","o":["SAML 2.0","Kerberos","OAuth 2.0","RADIUS"],"c":2,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is designed for delegated authorization, issuing scoped access tokens so applications can access resources on a user's behalf without handling credentials. SAML focuses on authentication/SSO assertions, Kerberos is for internal network authentication, and RADIUS is used for centralized network access authentication.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester gains SYSTEM-level access to a domain controller and extracts the password hash of a specific service account used by the Key Distribution Center. Using this hash, the tester can now forge Ticket Granting Tickets that appear valid for any user, including accounts that no longer exist, for years into the future. Which account's hash was compromised to enable this attack?","o":["The krbtgt service account","The built-in Administrator account","A user's Ticket Granting Service session key","A domain controller's machine account"],"c":0,"why":"The krbtgt account's hash is used by the KDC to sign all TGTs; compromising it enables a 'Golden Ticket' attack allowing forgery of arbitrary TGTs. The Administrator account hash only grants that user's rights, and TGS session keys and machine account hashes do not provide the same domain-wide ticket-forging capability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"In an OpenID Connect (OIDC) authorization code flow layered on OAuth 2.0, which token is specifically intended to let the client application authenticate the end user (confirm who they are), rather than authorize access to a protected API resource?","o":["ID token","Access token","Refresh token","Authorization code"],"c":0,"why":"The OIDC ID token is a signed JWT containing authentication claims (subject, issuer, auth time) meant for the client to verify user identity. The access token authorizes API calls, the refresh token obtains new access tokens without re-authentication, and the authorization code is a short-lived credential exchanged for tokens—none confirm user identity to the client directly.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements Kerberos for network authentication. A security analyst wants to understand how the protocol prevents replay attacks during the initial authentication exchange. Which mechanism primarily provides this protection?","o":["Time-stamped tickets with a limited validity window","Encryption of the entire session using a one-time pad","Mutual TLS certificate exchange between client and KDC","Use of a shared secret that changes with every login attempt"],"c":0,"why":"Kerberos tickets include timestamps and a short validity period, so a captured ticket becomes useless after expiration, mitigating replay attacks. The other options are not core Kerberos mechanisms.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A mobile application needs to access a user's photos stored in a third-party cloud storage API. The app should never see or store the user's cloud storage password, and the user should be able to grant the app a limited, revocable scope of access (e.g., 'read photos only'). Which protocol is specifically designed to solve this delegated-authorization problem?","o":["Kerberos","SAML 2.0","OAuth 2.0","RADIUS"],"c":2,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is an authorization framework designed to issue scoped, revocable access tokens without exposing the resource owner's credentials to the requesting application. SAML is primarily used for enterprise SSO assertions, Kerberos is a ticket-based authentication protocol for trusted network domains, and RADIUS is a network access AAA protocol; none provide delegated, scoped API authorization natively.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric vendor reports that a fingerprint scanner's False Acceptance Rate (FAR) equals its False Rejection Rate (FRR) at 2% when set to the crossover error rate (CER). The security team securing a nuclear facility control room wants to minimize the risk of an impostor gaining entry, and is willing to accept legitimate staff occasionally needing a second scan attempt. How should the matching threshold be adjusted relative to the CER?","o":["Increase the threshold above the CER point to lower FAR, accepting a higher FRR","Decrease the threshold below the CER point to lower FRR, accepting a higher FAR","Keep the threshold fixed at the CER, since it is universally optimal regardless of risk tolerance","Remove the biometric threshold entirely and rely solely on a PIN for equivalent assurance"],"c":0,"why":"Raising the threshold makes the match criteria stricter, which reduces false acceptances (impostors) at the cost of more false rejections (inconvenience)—appropriate for a high-security facility. Lowering the threshold does the opposite, favoring convenience over security; the CER is only a balanced reference point, not universally optimal for every risk profile; and removing the biometric control eliminates the intended security layer altogether.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A healthcare company wants access decisions to consider not just job role but also patient relationship, time of day, and location of the request. Which access control model best supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple attributes (role, relationship, time, location) dynamically to make fine-grained access decisions. RBAC relies only on role, DAC relies on owner discretion, and MAC relies on fixed security labels/clearances.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A hospital wants access decisions for its EHR system to dynamically factor in the requesting clinician's department, the patient's current consent status, time of day, and whether the connection originates from an approved network segment, without administrators having to predefine a role for every possible combination. Which access control model BEST supports this requirement?","o":["Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":0,"why":"ABAC evaluates policies against multiple contextual and subject/object attributes at request time, making it well-suited for dynamic, multi-factor decisions. RBAC would require an impractical explosion of roles to cover every attribute combination; MAC relies on fixed security labels/clearances rather than contextual attributes; DAC leaves access decisions to resource owners rather than centralized policy logic.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric access control vendor presents two fingerprint scanners for evaluation. Scanner A has a Crossover Error Rate (CER) of 0.3%, and Scanner B has a CER of 2.1%. Assuming all other factors (cost, speed, user acceptance) are equal, which statement is most accurate?","o":["Scanner B is more secure because a higher CER indicates stricter matching thresholds","Scanner A is more accurate overall because a lower CER indicates the point where FAR and FRR are more closely balanced at a lower error level","CER is irrelevant to accuracy since it only measures enrollment failures","Scanner B should be preferred because a higher CER reduces False Acceptance Rate specifically"],"c":1,"why":"CER (or Equal Error Rate) is the point at which False Acceptance Rate and False Rejection Rate curves intersect; a lower CER indicates a more accurate biometric system overall. CER does not measure enrollment failure rates, and a higher CER does not selectively favor FAR reduction—it indicates worse overall accuracy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a federated identity scenario using SAML, which entity is responsible for authenticating the user and issuing an assertion to the service the user is trying to access?","o":["The relying party","The service provider","The identity provider","The certificate authority"],"c":2,"why":"The Identity Provider (IdP) authenticates the user and issues a SAML assertion consumed by the Service Provider/relying party. The service provider and relying party are the same entity that trusts the assertion, and a CA is unrelated to SAML assertion issuance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization deploys a privileged access management (PAM) solution that grants administrators elevated credentials only for the duration of an approved task, after which the credentials are automatically revoked and rotated (just-in-time access). What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this model compared to maintaining standing privileged accounts?","o":["It reduces the attack surface and time window during which privileged credentials could be stolen or misused","It eliminates the need for multifactor authentication on privileged sessions","It removes the requirement to log or monitor privileged session activity","It guarantees non-repudiation of administrative actions without any additional controls"],"c":0,"why":"JIT access minimizes the duration that elevated credentials exist and are usable, shrinking the window for credential theft or abuse. It does not eliminate the need for MFA or logging—both remain best practice alongside JIT—and non-repudiation still requires proper session logging/attribution, not just short-lived credentials.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A healthcare organization needs an access control model where a nurse can view a patient's record only if the nurse is currently assigned to that patient's ward, it is during the nurse's scheduled shift, and the record is not flagged as psychiatric-sensitive. Which access control model most naturally supports this requirement without creating an unmanageable number of static roles?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)"],"c":1,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple dynamic attributes (subject, resource, environment, action) at access time, making it ideal for context-dependent policies like shift, ward assignment, and data sensitivity flags. RBAC would require an impractical explosion of roles to capture these combinations, DAC relies on owner discretion rather than policy attributes, and MAC uses static classification/clearance labels rather than contextual attributes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system is being tuned for a high-security data center. Administrators lower the sensitivity threshold to reduce user complaints about failed scans. What is the most likely security consequence of this change?","o":["The False Rejection Rate (FRR) will increase","The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) will increase","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) will decrease","Enrollment time for new users will increase"],"c":1,"why":"Lowering the sensitivity threshold makes the system more likely to accept an unauthorized user (higher FAR), trading security for convenience. FRR would decrease (fewer rejections), and CER is a fixed characteristic of the system's overall accuracy, not directly lowered by this tuning.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During an access certification review, an auditor finds several accounts belonging to employees who were terminated six months ago still have active VPN and application access. Which control failure MOST directly explains this finding?","o":["Lack of integration between the HR termination process and the identity lifecycle deprovisioning workflow","Absence of password complexity requirements on user accounts","Failure to enforce separation of duties among IT administrators","Missing multifactor authentication requirement on the VPN gateway"],"c":0,"why":"Active accounts persisting long after termination indicates the deprovisioning trigger from HR offboarding never fired or was not automated/integrated with IAM processes. Password complexity, separation of duties, and MFA are unrelated to whether an account is disabled upon termination.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A network administrator is designing centralized AAA for a large fleet of network devices (routers, switches, firewalls). The requirement is full encryption of the entire authentication, authorization, and accounting packet, plus the ability to authorize specific commands (e.g., allow 'show' commands but deny 'configure terminal') on a per-user basis. Which protocol best meets these requirements?","o":["RADIUS","TACACS+","Kerberos","LDAP over SSL"],"c":1,"why":"TACACS+ encrypts the entire AAA packet body and separates authentication, authorization, and accounting, allowing granular command-level authorization—commonly used for network device administration. RADIUS only encrypts the password field and combines authentication/authorization in a single response, Kerberos is not designed for device command authorization, and LDAPS is a directory access protocol, not an AAA protocol for command authorization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization following the Bell-LaPadula model wants to prevent a user with a lower clearance from reading data classified above their clearance level. Which property enforces this restriction?","o":["The Simple Security Property (no read up)","The *-Property (no write down)","The Discretionary Security Property","The Strong Star Property"],"c":0,"why":"The Simple Security Property ('no read up') prevents subjects from reading objects at a higher classification. The *-Property prevents writing down to lower classifications, not reading up; the Discretionary Security Property relates to DAC, and the Strong Star Property restricts both read and write to the same level.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A security assessment of a corporate LDAP directory reveals that it accepts anonymous (unauthenticated) binds, allowing any network client to query the full directory schema and user attributes without providing credentials. What is the MOST appropriate remediation?","o":["Disable anonymous binds and require authenticated LDAP connections using least-privilege service accounts, preferably over LDAPS","Enable LDAPS for encryption in transit but continue permitting anonymous binds for application compatibility","Relocate the directory server to a segmented VLAN without changing the bind configuration","Rotate the directory administrator account password on a more frequent schedule"],"c":0,"why":"The root cause is unauthenticated access to directory data; disabling anonymous binds and enforcing authenticated, least-privilege, encrypted connections directly addresses this exposure. Adding encryption alone (option B) still allows anonymous queries, network segmentation (option C) doesn't prevent access from within the segment, and password rotation (option D) is unrelated to the anonymous bind vulnerability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company is automating its joiner-mover-leaver process to reduce the risk of orphaned accounts. Which control provides the MOST direct mitigation for this specific risk?","o":["Enforcing multifactor authentication for all users","Conducting quarterly access certification reviews","Automatically disabling accounts upon HR-triggered termination events","Implementing role-based access control across all systems"],"c":2,"why":"Automated deprovisioning tied to HR termination events directly prevents orphaned accounts by ensuring timely account disablement. MFA and RBAC address different risks, and periodic reviews are a detective control that only catches orphaned accounts after the fact.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to log in using a password and a one-time code generated by a mobile app. Which authentication factor category does the one-time code represent?","o":["Something you know","Something you have","Something you are","Somewhere you are"],"c":1,"why":"A one-time code generated by a device (the phone/app) is based on possession of that device, making it 'something you have.' The password is 'something you know,' and biometrics would be 'something you are.'","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is evaluating Single Sign-On (SSO) for the enterprise. Which of the following is the MOST significant inherent risk introduced by SSO that must be mitigated through additional controls?","o":["Increased password complexity requirements for users","A compromised credential grants access to multiple systems","Reduced need for centralized identity governance","Inability to enforce role-based access control"],"c":1,"why":"SSO's main risk is that a single compromised credential can be leveraged to access every connected system, making strong authentication and monitoring essential. SSO does not reduce governance needs, does not prevent RBAC, and does not inherently increase password complexity requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which access control model assigns permissions to users based on their job function within an organization?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC grants access based on predefined roles tied to job functions, simplifying administration. DAC lets owners assign permissions, MAC uses security labels/clearances, and rule-based control uses if-then logic rather than job roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the security benefit of implementing Single Sign-On (SSO)?","o":["It eliminates the need for authentication entirely","It reduces the number of credentials users must manage, lowering password-related risks","It automatically encrypts all network traffic","It replaces the need for multi-factor authentication"],"c":1,"why":"SSO reduces credential fatigue and the number of passwords users must remember, decreasing risky behaviors like password reuse. SSO does not eliminate authentication, encrypt traffic, or replace MFA—it can and should be combined with MFA.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution wants to grant database administrators elevated privileges only for the duration of a specific maintenance task, with automatic expiration afterward. Which capability of a Privileged Access Management (PAM) solution best supports this requirement?","o":["Password vaulting for shared administrative accounts","Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access provisioning","Session recording and playback for audit purposes","Role mining to identify excessive entitlements"],"c":1,"why":"JIT provisioning grants temporary, time-limited elevated access that automatically expires, minimizing standing privilege exposure. Vaulting, session recording, and role mining are valuable PAM features but do not address time-bound privilege elevation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a Kerberos authentication system, what is the primary function of the Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT)?","o":["It encrypts all data transmitted between client and server","It allows the client to request service tickets without re-entering credentials","It serves as the final authorization for accessing a specific resource","It stores the user's password in plaintext for verification"],"c":1,"why":"The TGT is issued after initial authentication and allows the client to request service tickets from the Ticket Granting Service without re-authenticating. It does not encrypt all traffic, grant final resource access directly, or store passwords in plaintext.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A hospital wants to grant access to patient records based on a combination of the user's department, the patient's care team assignment, the time of day, and the location from which the request originates. Which access control model BEST supports this requirement?","o":["Discretionary access control (DAC)","Role-based access control (RBAC)","Attribute-based access control (ABAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple dynamic attributes (subject, object, environment) to make access decisions, which fits the multi-factor, contextual requirement described. RBAC only considers role, DAC relies on owner discretion, and MAC uses fixed security labels, none of which can natively incorporate time and location context.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An internal audit discovers dozens of active accounts belonging to employees who left the organization months ago, several of which still have VPN and privileged database access. Which control would MOST effectively prevent recurrence of this issue going forward?","o":["Requiring quarterly manual password resets for all accounts","Implementing automated deprovisioning triggered by HR system termination events","Increasing the minimum password complexity requirements","Enabling multi-factor authentication on all remote access accounts"],"c":1,"why":"Automated deprovisioning tied to authoritative HR lifecycle events (joiner-mover-leaver) ensures accounts are disabled immediately upon termination, directly addressing orphaned accounts. Password resets and complexity rules don't remove access for terminated users, and MFA strengthens authentication but does nothing to revoke access for accounts that should no longer exist.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"During employee offboarding, which IAM process is MOST critical to perform promptly to reduce security risk?","o":["Updating the employee's job title in the HR system","Deprovisioning the employee's accounts and access rights","Archiving the employee's email for compliance","Notifying the marketing department of the departure"],"c":1,"why":"Prompt deprovisioning of accounts and access prevents former employees from retaining unauthorized access, a major security risk. The other options, while administratively relevant, do not directly mitigate unauthorized access risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a Kerberos authentication exchange, after a client successfully authenticates to the Key Distribution Center (KDC), what does the client receive that it will present to the Ticket Granting Service to request access to a specific application server?","o":["A session key encrypted with the application server's public key","A ticket-granting ticket (TGT)","A digital certificate signed by the KDC","A one-time password derived from a shared secret"],"c":1,"why":"After initial authentication, the KDC's Authentication Service issues a TGT, which the client then presents to the Ticket Granting Service to obtain service tickets for specific resources. Kerberos uses symmetric keys, not public-key certificates or OTPs, in its core exchange.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization uses SAML to allow employees to log into a cloud-based application using their corporate credentials. What is this technology an example of?","o":["Federated identity management","Discretionary access control","Role mining","Password vaulting"],"c":0,"why":"SAML enables federated identity management, allowing identity assertions from one trusted domain (corporate) to authenticate users in another (cloud application). It is unrelated to DAC, role mining, or password vaulting, which serve different IAM purposes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A web application implements single sign-on across multiple subdomains. Researchers discover that an attacker can visit the login page, capture the pre-authentication session identifier issued by the server, trick a victim into authenticating using a crafted link containing that same identifier, and then use the identifier themselves to access the victim's authenticated session. Which control failure allowed this attack, and what is the correct remediation?","o":["Missing CSRF tokens; remediation is to add anti-CSRF tokens to all forms","Session fixation vulnerability; remediation is to regenerate the session identifier upon successful authentication","Weak password hashing; remediation is to upgrade to a stronger hashing algorithm","Missing HSTS header; remediation is to enforce strict transport security"],"c":1,"why":"This is a classic session fixation attack, where an attacker pre-sets a known session ID that the victim unknowingly authenticates under; the fix is to always issue a new session identifier after authentication succeeds. CSRF, password hashing, and HSTS address different vulnerability classes and would not prevent an attacker from reusing a known pre-authentication session ID.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements SAML-based federation so employees can log into a cloud HR application using their corporate credentials. In this architecture, which entity is responsible for authenticating the user and issuing the assertion?","o":["The service provider (SP)","The relying party","The identity provider (IdP)","The cloud access security broker (CASB)"],"c":2,"why":"In SAML federation, the Identity Provider authenticates the user and generates the signed assertion that is passed to the Service Provider (the cloud HR app), which trusts the assertion instead of authenticating the user itself. 'Relying party' is another term for the SP, and a CASB is a policy enforcement tool, not the assertion issuer.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system is being tuned. Security administrators lower the sensitivity threshold to reduce user complaints about being denied entry. What is the MOST likely security consequence of this change?","o":["The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) will increase","The False Rejection Rate (FRR) will increase","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) will improve","Enrollment time will increase"],"c":0,"why":"Lowering the sensitivity threshold makes the system more permissive, which reduces false rejections but increases the likelihood that unauthorized individuals are incorrectly accepted (higher FAR). CER is a fixed characteristic of the system at the point where FAR=FRR and doesn't 'improve' from threshold tuning alone; enrollment time is unrelated.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization's Kerberos-based authentication system is being reviewed for resilience against replay attacks. A penetration tester captures a valid service ticket and its accompanying authenticator sent by a client to a file server. Which built-in Kerberos mechanism is most directly responsible for preventing the tester from successfully replaying this captured authenticator to the file server at a later time?","o":["The KDC issues a new session key for every authentication request, invalidating old ones immediately","The authenticator contains a timestamp that the service checks against its cache of recently seen authenticators within an allowed clock skew window","The client and server exchange a Diffie-Hellman key agreement before every transaction","The ticket-granting ticket is digitally signed by the client's private key, preventing tampering"],"c":1,"why":"Kerberos authenticators include a timestamp; the service rejects authenticators with duplicate or stale timestamps within its clock-skew window and caches recently seen ones, which defeats replay. Session keys aren't reissued per-transaction, Kerberos doesn't use Diffie-Hellman for this purpose, and tickets are encrypted with the service's key, not signed with the client's private key.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During an audit, it is discovered that several employees who left the company six months ago still have active accounts with valid VPN access. Which identity and access management process failure is the PRIMARY cause of this finding?","o":["Inadequate access review and deprovisioning procedures","Lack of multifactor authentication on the VPN","Absence of a formal password policy","Failure to implement role-based access control"],"c":0,"why":"Active accounts for terminated employees indicate a breakdown in the deprovisioning/account lifecycle process, which should trigger timely account disablement upon termination. MFA, password policy, and RBAC are unrelated to the timely removal of access for departed employees.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A mobile application needs to authenticate a user via a third-party identity provider and also obtain a verifiable, standardized identity token (containing claims like subject and issuer) rather than just an access token for calling an API. Which protocol layered on top of another is specifically designed to provide this identity assertion capability?","o":["SAML 2.0 used independently of OAuth 2.0","OpenID Connect, built as an identity layer on top of OAuth 2.0","Kerberos extended with PKINIT pre-authentication","RADIUS with EAP-TLS"],"c":1,"why":"OpenID Connect extends OAuth 2.0 by adding an ID token (a signed JWT with identity claims), specifically solving the authentication gap that pure OAuth 2.0 (an authorization framework) does not address. SAML is a separate, older federation standard not built on OAuth; Kerberos and RADIUS are not web federation/token protocols for this use case.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution requires that users authenticate with a smart card and a PIN before accessing a trading system, and additionally verify a fingerprint at a secure workstation. This is an example of which authentication concept?","o":["Single sign-on (SSO)","Multifactor authentication using something you have, something you know, and something you are","Federated identity management","Role-based access control layered with mandatory access control"],"c":1,"why":"The smart card (something you have), PIN (something you know), and fingerprint (something you are) represent three distinct authentication factor categories, illustrating multifactor authentication. SSO refers to authenticating once for multiple systems, and federation involves trust across organizational boundaries, neither of which applies here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric access control vendor presents a comparison of two fingerprint scanners. Scanner A has a lower False Rejection Rate but a higher False Acceptance Rate at its default sensitivity setting than Scanner B. To fairly compare the intrinsic accuracy of the two scanners independent of a chosen sensitivity threshold, which metric should the security architect request?","o":["The False Acceptance Rate alone at maximum sensitivity","The False Rejection Rate alone at minimum sensitivity","The Crossover Error Rate, where FAR and FRR intersect","The average enrollment time per subject"],"c":2,"why":"The Crossover Error Rate (CER) is the point where FAR equals FRR, providing a single sensitivity-independent measure of a biometric system's overall accuracy, making it the standard basis for comparing devices. Looking at FAR or FRR alone at an arbitrary threshold doesn't allow fair comparison, and enrollment time measures usability, not accuracy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to minimize the risk associated with standing administrative privileges on critical servers. Administrators should only have elevated rights for the specific duration needed to perform a task, with all activity logged and access automatically revoked afterward. Which control BEST achieves this?","o":["Mandatory access control (MAC)","Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access management","Role-based access control (RBAC) with static role assignments","Discretionary access control (DAC)"],"c":1,"why":"JIT privileged access management grants temporary, time-limited elevated access only when needed and automatically revokes it afterward, directly addressing the risk of standing privileges. MAC, static RBAC, and DAC do not inherently provide time-bound, on-demand privilege elevation with automatic revocation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to swipe a badge and enter a PIN to access a secure data center. This is an example of which authentication concept?","o":["Single-factor authentication using two credentials","Multifactor authentication combining something you have and something you know","Mutual authentication between two systems","Single sign-on across multiple systems"],"c":1,"why":"The badge is 'something you have' and the PIN is 'something you know,' representing two distinct authentication factor categories, which is the definition of multifactor authentication. The other options mischaracterize the scenario (it is not single-factor, not system-to-system mutual authentication, and not SSO).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A developer is integrating a third-party mobile app so it can access a user's calendar data stored in a cloud service, without ever handling the user's cloud service password. Which protocol is specifically designed to provide this delegated authorization capability?","o":["Kerberos","LDAP","OAuth 2.0","RADIUS"],"c":2,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is designed for delegated authorization, allowing a third-party application to access a resource on behalf of a user via scoped access tokens, without exposing the user's credentials. Kerberos and RADIUS handle authentication/network access differently, and LDAP is a directory access protocol, not an authorization delegation framework.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) model, access rights are primarily assigned based on which of the following?","o":["The sensitivity label of the object being accessed","The job function or role of the user within the organization","The discretion of the data owner for each individual user","The classification level of the requesting subject"],"c":1,"why":"RBAC grants permissions according to organizational roles (e.g., 'HR Manager'), simplifying administration by assigning users to predefined roles. Labels and classification levels relate to Mandatory Access Control, and owner discretion describes DAC.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company implements a solution allowing employees to log in once and then access multiple cloud applications without re-entering credentials, using an identity provider that issues security assertions to service providers. What is this technology called?","o":["Kerberos ticketing","Federated Single Sign-On (SSO)","Role-based provisioning","Discretionary access control"],"c":1,"why":"Federated SSO uses a trusted identity provider to issue assertions (such as SAML tokens) that service providers accept, allowing one login to access multiple independent applications. Kerberos is a specific ticket-based protocol typically used within a single realm, not the general federated concept described here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A defense contractor implements a system where every file is assigned a classification label (e.g., Secret, Confidential) and every user is assigned a clearance level. Users cannot change these labels, and access decisions are made solely by comparing the subject's clearance to the object's classification per system-enforced rules, regardless of the object owner's wishes. Which access control model does this describe?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)"],"c":2,"why":"MAC enforces access based on fixed, system-assigned security labels and clearances that cannot be altered by object owners, consistent with models like Bell-LaPadula used in classified environments. DAC lets owners control access, RBAC assigns permissions via roles, and ABAC uses flexible attribute-based policies, none of which match the rigid, non-owner-controlled labeling described.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which authentication protocol relies on a trusted third-party Key Distribution Center (KDC) to issue time-stamped tickets to clients for accessing network services?","o":["RADIUS","LDAP","Kerberos","OAuth"],"c":2,"why":"Kerberos uses a KDC, which includes an Authentication Server and Ticket Granting Server, to issue time-sensitive tickets that prove identity without repeatedly transmitting passwords. RADIUS is used for centralized AAA for network access, LDAP is a directory access protocol, and OAuth is an authorization framework for delegated access, none of which use ticket-granting KDCs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During a SAML-based SSO implementation, a relying party (service provider) receives an XML response from the identity provider after a user authenticates. Which specific element within that response must the service provider validate to confirm that the user was actually authenticated by the identity provider (as opposed to merely receiving attribute information)?","o":["The <AttributeStatement> element","The <AuthnStatement> element within the <Assertion>","The <EntityDescriptor> in the IdP metadata","The <ArtifactResolve> request element"],"c":1,"why":"The <AuthnStatement> within a SAML Assertion specifically records that and how the subject was authenticated (including timestamp and authentication context), which the SP must validate to trust the authentication event. AttributeStatement conveys user attributes (not proof of authentication), EntityDescriptor is metadata about the IdP itself, and ArtifactResolve pertains to the artifact binding lookup mechanism, not authentication proof.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee is terminated, which identity and access management process ensures that all of the employee's accounts and access rights are promptly disabled?","o":["Provisioning","Authentication","Deprovisioning","Federation"],"c":2,"why":"Deprovisioning is the process of removing or disabling a user's accounts and access rights when they are no longer needed, such as upon termination, reducing the risk of orphaned accounts. Provisioning is the opposite process of granting access, authentication verifies identity, and federation relates to trust between identity domains.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution wants to reduce the risk of standing privileged accounts being compromised. They implement a system where administrators must submit a request with business justification, receive time-limited approval, and are granted elevated rights only for a defined window (e.g., 2 hours) before automatic revocation. This approach is best described as:","o":["Role-Based Access Control with static role assignment","Just-In-Time (JIT) privileged access provisioning","Discretionary access control delegation","Mandatory access control with temporal labels"],"c":1,"why":"JIT privileged access grants elevated rights only for a limited, approved time window rather than maintaining always-on (standing) privileges, directly matching the described workflow and significantly reducing the attack surface for privileged accounts. Static RBAC assigns persistent roles, DAC involves owner-based discretionary sharing, and MAC with temporal labels is not a standard recognized model for this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements Kerberos for network authentication. During the authentication process, which component is responsible for issuing a service ticket after validating a client's ticket-granting ticket (TGT)?","o":["The Key Distribution Center's Authentication Service (AS)","The Ticket Granting Service (TGS)","The client workstation's local security authority","The application server hosting the requested resource"],"c":1,"why":"The TGS validates the presented TGT and issues a service ticket for the specific resource; the AS only issues the initial TGT after verifying the user's credentials, and the client/server do not issue tickets themselves.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A biometric system is configured to be very strict in matching, resulting in some legitimate users being denied access. This outcome is best described as an increase in which metric?","o":["False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Equal Error Rate (EER)"],"c":1,"why":"False Rejection Rate measures how often legitimate, authorized users are incorrectly denied access, which increases as the system becomes stricter. FAR measures wrongly accepted impostors, and CER/EER are the point where FAR and FRR are equal, not a description of one-sided strictness.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An incident response team discovers that an attacker moved laterally across multiple Windows workstations using stolen NTLM password hashes without ever cracking the underlying passwords. Which combination of controls would MOST effectively mitigate this specific attack technique going forward?","o":["Enforce longer minimum password length and complexity requirements","Deploy multi-factor authentication on the initial VPN login only","Restrict/disable NTLM authentication where possible and enforce unique, randomized local administrator credentials (e.g., via LAPS)","Increase Kerberos ticket lifetime to reduce re-authentication frequency"],"c":2,"why":"Pass-the-hash attacks exploit reused local admin credentials and NTLM's vulnerability to hash reuse for authentication; disabling NTLM in favor of Kerberos and randomizing/rotating local admin passwords (LAPS) prevents the same hash from being valid across multiple machines. Password complexity doesn't stop hash reuse, MFA only at VPN login doesn't protect internal lateral movement via hashes, and longer Kerberos ticket lifetimes would not address the NTLM hash-reuse vector and could increase risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A hospital wants to grant clinicians access to patient records only when they are on-shift, assigned to that patient's unit, and using a hospital-issued device. Which access control model best supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes (time, location, device, assignment) at access time, enabling fine-grained dynamic decisions; RBAC only considers role, MAC relies on fixed security labels, and DAC leaves access decisions to resource owners without contextual enforcement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which access control model allows the data owner to determine who has access to a resource and what permissions they are granted?","o":["Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Rule-Based Access Control","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)"],"c":1,"why":"In DAC, the resource owner has discretion to grant or revoke access permissions to other users, commonly seen in file system permissions. MAC relies on centrally enforced labels rather than owner discretion, rule-based control uses predefined system rules, and ABAC grants access based on attributes rather than owner choice.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"To reduce the risk of brute-force password guessing attacks, which of the following controls is the MOST appropriate to implement?","o":["Account lockout after a defined number of failed login attempts","Requiring users to memorize their passwords instead of writing them down","Enforcing mandatory access control labels on all files","Implementing role-based access control for all applications"],"c":0,"why":"Account lockout policies temporarily disable an account after repeated failed login attempts, directly mitigating automated brute-force guessing attacks. The other options address different security concerns (data confidentiality labeling, role assignment, or general password hygiene) and do not directly stop repeated guessing attempts.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a SAML-based federated identity scenario, which entity is responsible for authenticating the user and issuing the assertion consumed by the relying application?","o":["The Service Provider (SP)","The Identity Provider (IdP)","The Relying Party's local directory","The federation's certificate authority"],"c":1,"why":"The Identity Provider authenticates the user and generates the SAML assertion; the Service Provider (relying party) consumes and validates that assertion but does not perform the authentication itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system is tuned so that its False Acceptance Rate (FAR) and False Rejection Rate (FRR) are equal. What is this point called, and what does it represent?","o":["The Crossover Error Rate (CER), indicating the overall accuracy and comparative quality of the biometric system","The enrollment threshold, indicating the minimum quality score for template creation","The Type I error boundary, indicating the maximum allowable false rejections","The throughput rate, indicating the number of authentications processed per minute"],"c":0,"why":"The Crossover Error Rate is the point where FAR equals FRR and is used to compare accuracy across biometric systems; a lower CER indicates better performance. The other terms do not describe this specific equilibrium point.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During an internal audit, it is discovered that several terminated employees still have active accounts on the ERP system three months after their last day. Which control failure does this MOST directly indicate?","o":["Inadequate password complexity enforcement","Lack of timely deprovisioning tied to the HR termination process","Failure to implement multi-factor authentication","Absence of role mining during RBAC design"],"c":1,"why":"Active accounts long after termination point to a breakdown in the deprovisioning process, typically caused by lack of integration between HR events and identity lifecycle management; the other options address unrelated controls (password strength, MFA, role design).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An application wants to allow a third-party service to access a user's cloud storage files for a limited time without ever handling the user's actual password. Which protocol is specifically designed for this delegated authorization use case?","o":["OAuth 2.0","LDAP","Kerberos","RADIUS"],"c":0,"why":"OAuth 2.0 is designed for delegated authorization, issuing scoped access tokens to third parties without exposing user credentials; LDAP and RADIUS handle directory lookups and network AAA respectively, and Kerberos is for mutual authentication within a trusted realm, not third-party delegation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to enter a PIN and then insert a smart card to access a workstation. Which authentication concept does this BEST illustrate?","o":["Single sign-on","Multifactor authentication","Federated identity","Role-based access control"],"c":1,"why":"Combining something you know (PIN) with something you have (smart card) is multifactor authentication. It is not SSO, federation, or RBAC, which relate to session sharing, cross-domain trust, and authorization respectively.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to reduce the risk associated with standing administrative privileges on critical servers. Which approach BEST achieves this by granting elevated access only for a limited, approved time window per task?","o":["Enforcing separation of duties across all administrative roles","Implementing just-in-time (JIT) privileged access with time-bound approval workflows","Requiring all administrators to use the same shared privileged account for accountability","Assigning permanent administrative rights but requiring MFA for login"],"c":1,"why":"JIT privileged access management grants elevated rights only when needed and automatically revokes them afterward, minimizing the attack surface of standing privileges; shared accounts harm accountability, permanent rights with MFA still leave standing privilege risk, and separation of duties addresses a different concern (fraud prevention, not privilege duration).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company assigns permissions to users based solely on their job function, such as 'Accountant' or 'HR Manager,' rather than assigning permissions to each individual user. This is an example of which access control model?","o":["Discretionary access control (DAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)","Role-based access control (RBAC)","Rule-based access control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions to roles that map to job functions, simplifying administration. DAC lets owners assign permissions individually, MAC uses security labels/clearances, and rule-based control uses if-then rules rather than job roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A file owner in a corporate file-sharing system can grant or revoke read/write permissions to other users at their own discretion. This is characteristic of which access control model?","o":["Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Rule-Based Access Control","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)"],"c":1,"why":"DAC allows the resource owner to determine and modify access permissions for others, which matches the scenario; MAC enforces access based on fixed labels set by a central authority, rule-based control relies on predefined system rules, and ABAC uses attribute evaluation rather than owner discretion.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is a primary security risk associated with implementing Single Sign-On (SSO)?","o":["Users must remember multiple complex passwords","A compromised credential can grant access to all connected systems","It significantly increases help desk password reset calls","It prevents centralized logging of user activity"],"c":1,"why":"SSO's main risk is that a single compromised credential can expose every integrated system, since one authentication event grants broad access. SSO actually reduces password fatigue, help desk calls, and can improve centralized logging.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm uses Kerberos for single sign-on across its internal network. During a security audit, testers demonstrate that a captured authenticator packet can be successfully resent to a service within a short window after interception, resulting in unauthorized session establishment. Which control most directly mitigates this specific weakness?","o":["Reducing the Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT) lifetime to a shorter duration","Enforcing tight clock synchronization between clients, the KDC, and application servers with a small allowable clock skew window","Encrypting Kerberos tickets with AES-256 instead of a weaker cipher","Requiring mutual authentication between the client and the application server"],"c":1,"why":"Kerberos replay protection relies on timestamps within the authenticator; a tightly synchronized clock with a minimal allowable skew window prevents captured authenticators from being reused after the valid window closes. Shortening TGT lifetime affects ticket renewal but not authenticator replay, stronger encryption doesn't address timing-based replay, and mutual authentication addresses impersonation of the server, not replay of a valid authenticator.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A business partner's employees need to access a company's cloud application using their own organization's credentials, without the company having to create separate accounts for them. Which technology BEST enables this?","o":["Kerberos","Federated identity management","Discretionary access control","Biometric authentication"],"c":1,"why":"Federated identity management (e.g., using SAML or OAuth) allows trusted external identity providers to authenticate users for a relying party without duplicate accounts. Kerberos is for single-domain authentication, DAC is an authorization model, and biometrics is an authentication factor, not a cross-domain trust mechanism.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester intercepts a SAML response from an Identity Provider and modifies it by inserting a forged assertion element while leaving the original, digitally signed assertion untouched elsewhere in the XML document. The Service Provider validates the signature successfully but processes the attacker's forged element, granting unauthorized access. What is this attack and its most effective mitigation?","o":["This is a SAML signature wrapping attack; mitigation requires validating that the element referenced by the signature is the exact element being processed by the application logic","This is a token replay attack; mitigation requires adding a nonce and short assertion validity window","This is a man-in-the-middle attack; mitigation requires enforcing TLS on all federation endpoints","This is a session fixation attack; mitigation requires regenerating the session identifier after authentication"],"c":0,"why":"XML signature wrapping exploits the gap between signature validation and the actual element processed by application logic; the fix is to strictly bind signature validation to the processed element (e.g., via correct XPath/ID referencing), not just checking signature validity anywhere in the document. The other attacks and mitigations are real but do not describe this specific flaw.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A biometric fingerprint system is being tuned for a high-security data center. Lowering the sensitivity threshold to reduce false rejections will MOST likely result in which outcome?","o":["A decrease in the False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","An increase in the False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","An increase in the Crossover Error Rate only","No change in system accuracy"],"c":1,"why":"Reducing sensitivity to lower false rejections (FRR) typically increases the chance that unauthorized users are incorrectly accepted, raising FAR. The two rates trade off against each other, so FAR does not decrease, and CER is a single point of comparison, not something that changes independently in this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A mobile application currently authenticates users via the OAuth 2.0 Implicit Grant flow. A security review flags that access tokens are exposed in the browser history and URL fragment, and the flow cannot be used with a client secret. What is the most appropriate remediation for a mobile/native application?","o":["Continue using the Implicit Grant flow but add token binding to the device","Switch to the Resource Owner Password Credentials Grant for simplicity","Migrate to the Authorization Code flow with Proof Key for Code Exchange (PKCE)","Switch to the Client Credentials Grant to eliminate user-facing tokens"],"c":2,"why":"Authorization Code flow with PKCE is the current best practice for public clients like mobile and single-page apps, eliminating token exposure in URLs and protecting against authorization code interception without requiring a client secret. Password Credentials Grant exposes user credentials directly to the app, Client Credentials Grant is for machine-to-machine (no user context), and token binding alone doesn't fix the fundamental exposure issues of implicit flow.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee is terminated, which access management practice is MOST important to perform immediately?","o":["Reassigning the employee's role to a new hire","Archiving the employee's email for legal hold","Disabling or revoking the employee's user accounts and access credentials","Updating the organization's password policy"],"c":2,"why":"Prompt deprovisioning—disabling accounts and revoking credentials—prevents unauthorized access by a terminated employee. Email archiving and role reassignment may occur later, and password policy updates are unrelated to individual offboarding.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric access control administrator lowers the sensitivity threshold to reduce user complaints about being falsely rejected, which simultaneously increases the rate of unauthorized users being falsely accepted. Which metric represents the point at which the False Rejection Rate equals the False Acceptance Rate, commonly used to compare the overall accuracy of competing biometric systems?","o":["Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Type I error rate","Enrollment failure rate","System throughput rate"],"c":0,"why":"The Crossover Error Rate is the point where FRR and FAR intersect and is a standard benchmark for comparing biometric system accuracy across vendors. Type I error is synonymous with FRR alone, not the intersection point, and enrollment failure/throughput measure operational usability rather than accuracy trade-offs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A government system uses classification labels such as 'Confidential,' 'Secret,' and 'Top Secret' to control access, and users cannot change these labels or override access decisions. Which access control model does this describe?","o":["Discretionary access control (DAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)","Attribute-based access control (ABAC)","Role-based access control (RBAC)"],"c":1,"why":"MAC enforces access based on fixed security labels/clearances set by a central authority, and users cannot alter them, which is typical of government/military systems. DAC allows owners to set permissions, ABAC uses dynamic attributes, and RBAC is based on job roles rather than classification labels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a system where a user must present a smart card and enter a PIN before being granted access to a workstation. This is an example of which authentication principle?","o":["Single sign-on","Multifactor authentication using something you have and something you know","Federated identity management","Role-based access control"],"c":1,"why":"The smart card is 'something you have' and the PIN is 'something you know,' combining two distinct factor categories to strengthen authentication. SSO relates to session reuse across systems, federation involves trust between organizations, and RBAC is an authorization model, not authentication.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A multinational corporation wants access to its financial systems to be dynamically restricted based on a combination of the user's job role, the compliance status of their device, the time of day, and their current geolocation, with decisions evaluated in real time at each access request. Which access control model natively supports this requirement with the least architectural modification?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC), because roles can be defined to inherently include contextual attributes","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC), because policies can evaluate multiple independent contextual attributes at the time of the access request","Mandatory Access Control (MAC), because sensitivity labels can be extended to encode time and location data","Discretionary Access Control (DAC), because resource owners can manually restrict access based on any criteria they choose"],"c":1,"why":"ABAC is purpose-built to evaluate multiple, independent, real-time attributes (subject, object, environment) in policy decisions, making it ideal for context-aware access. RBAC ties permissions to static roles and would require excessive role proliferation to capture this level of context, MAC's labels are designed for classification-based confidentiality controls not dynamic contextual attributes, and DAC relies on owner discretion rather than centrally enforced contextual policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During a Kerberos authentication exchange, a client receives a ticket-granting ticket (TGT) from the Key Distribution Center (KDC). What is the primary purpose of the TGT?","o":["To encrypt all subsequent application data exchanged between client and server","To allow the client to request service tickets from the ticket-granting service without re-entering credentials","To serve as the final authorization token used directly by application servers to grant access","To replace the need for a shared secret key between the client and the KDC"],"c":1,"why":"The TGT is presented to the ticket-granting service to obtain service tickets for specific resources, avoiding repeated password entry during the session. It is not used directly by application servers (that's the service ticket's role) and does not eliminate the need for shared secrets, which underpin the initial exchange.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An internal audit finds numerous active accounts belonging to employees terminated over 90 days ago, spread across 15 disparate systems that rely on manual deprovisioning tickets submitted by managers. What is the best long-term control to prevent recurrence of this finding?","o":["Increase the frequency of manual account reviews to weekly","Implement automated identity lifecycle management integrated with the HR system as the authoritative source, automatically triggering deprovisioning workflows upon a termination event","Require managers to submit termination tickets within 24 hours of an employee's departure","Enforce quarterly user access recertification campaigns across all systems"],"c":1,"why":"Integrating identity lifecycle management with an authoritative HR source and automating deprovisioning eliminates dependency on manual, error-prone processes across multiple systems, addressing the root cause. The other options are compensating manual controls that reduce but do not eliminate the risk of delayed or missed deprovisioning.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During an incident response investigation, analysts determine that an attacker who briefly compromised a single domain controller was later able to forge valid Kerberos Ticket Granting Tickets (TGTs) for any user in the domain, including Domain Admins, weeks after being evicted from the network and without needing any user's password. Which attack technique does this describe, and what secret material enables it?","o":["Golden ticket attack; exploits the domain's krbtgt account password hash","Pass-the-hash attack; exploits cached NTLM hashes in LSASS memory","Kerberoasting; exploits weak passwords on service accounts with SPNs","Silver ticket attack; exploits the password hash of a specific service account"],"c":0,"why":"A golden ticket is forged using the krbtgt account's hash, which signs all TGTs domain-wide, allowing the attacker to impersonate any account indefinitely until the krbtgt password is rotated (twice). Silver tickets are scoped to a single service account, Kerberoasting targets crackable service ticket hashes offline, and pass-the-hash uses NTLM hashes for direct authentication rather than TGT forgery.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A healthcare organization wants to grant access to patient records based on a combination of the requester's department, the patient's consent status, the time of day, and the sensitivity level of the record. Which access control model best supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple dynamic attributes (department, consent, time, sensitivity) at access time, making it ideal for complex, context-aware decisions. RBAC only considers role, MAC relies on fixed classification labels, and DAC leaves access decisions to resource owners without attribute evaluation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to eliminate standing (always-on) privileged access for database administrators while maintaining a complete audit trail of privileged actions and ensuring credentials are not reused indefinitely. Which solution best meets these requirements?","o":["Grant DBAs permanent local administrator rights but require password rotation every 90 days","Implement a Privileged Access Management (PAM) solution that provides just-in-time credential checkout, session recording, and automatic credential rotation after each use","Create a single shared administrative account with a strong password known to the DBA team","Require DBAs to send an email request before performing privileged tasks, without automated technical enforcement"],"c":1,"why":"A PAM solution with just-in-time checkout, session recording, and post-use credential rotation directly addresses standing access risk, accountability, and credential reuse. Permanent rights and shared accounts increase risk and reduce individual accountability, and an email-based request process lacks technical enforcement or reliable audit capability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A relying party (Service Provider) receives a SAML assertion from a trusted Identity Provider over TLS. Months later, a threat actor who had captured a copy of that original assertion (e.g., via a compromised proxy log) attempts to replay it to gain unauthorized access. Which SAML assertion control is specifically designed to prevent this replay?","o":["Encrypting the assertion using the SP's public key","Signing the assertion with the IdP's private key","NotOnOrAfter validity conditions combined with a OneTimeUse element","Requiring mutual TLS between the IdP and SP endpoints"],"c":2,"why":"Time-bound validity conditions and one-time-use restrictions prevent an old, previously consumed assertion from being accepted again. Signing provides integrity/authenticity (not replay protection), encryption provides confidentiality, and mutual TLS secures transport but does nothing once the assertion has already been captured and stored.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company wants employees to authenticate once with their corporate identity provider and then access a third-party SaaS application without re-entering credentials, while the SaaS provider trusts assertions issued by the corporate IdP. Which technology is most directly designed to fulfill this requirement?","o":["Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP)","Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML)","Kerberos","Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS)"],"c":1,"why":"SAML is an XML-based standard specifically designed for exchanging authentication and authorization assertions between an identity provider and a service provider, enabling federated SSO. LDAP is a directory access protocol, Kerberos is typically used within a single trusted realm, and RADIUS is primarily for network access authentication.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A web application authenticates users by directly concatenating user-supplied input into an LDAP search filter without sanitization. An attacker submits a username value of `*)(uid=*))(|(uid=*` and successfully bypasses authentication. What is this attack, and what is the most effective mitigation?","o":["This is an LDAP injection attack; mitigate by escaping LDAP special characters and using parameterized or programmatically constructed filters","This is a buffer overflow attack; mitigate by enforcing strict input length bounds checking","This is a SQL injection attack; mitigate by using parameterized stored procedures","This is a cross-site scripting attack; mitigate by encoding output rendered in the browser"],"c":0,"why":"Manipulating LDAP filter syntax via special characters like *, (, and | to alter query logic is a classic LDAP injection attack, mitigated by escaping special characters and building filters programmatically rather than through string concatenation. The other attack types and mitigations address unrelated vulnerability classes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A native mobile application implementing OAuth 2.0 uses the Authorization Code flow with Proof Key for Code Exchange (PKCE) instead of the classic Authorization Code flow without PKCE. What specific threat is PKCE primarily designed to mitigate for this type of public client?","o":["Authorization code interception by a malicious app registered on the same custom URI scheme","Cross-site request forgery against the token endpoint","Token substitution via an open redirect on the authorization server","Theft of long-lived refresh tokens via stored XSS in a web view"],"c":0,"why":"PKCE binds the authorization code to a dynamically generated code verifier so that even if a malicious app intercepts the redirect and steals the authorization code, it cannot exchange it for a token without the original verifier. The other threats are addressed by different controls (state parameter for CSRF, strict redirect URI validation, and secure storage/HttpOnly cookies, respectively).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system is configured to minimize the chance of unauthorized individuals being granted access, even if this means some legitimate users are occasionally rejected. This configuration prioritizes lowering which metric?","o":["False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Enrollment failure rate"],"c":0,"why":"Prioritizing security over convenience means tuning the system to reduce FAR (unauthorized users being incorrectly accepted), even though this typically increases FRR. CER represents the point where FAR and FRR are equal, and enrollment failure rate concerns registration issues, not ongoing authentication accuracy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A security team lowers the sensitivity threshold of a fingerprint-based physical access control system after receiving numerous complaints from employees about repeated failed scans. What is the most significant security consequence of this change?","o":["The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) increases, raising the likelihood that an unauthorized person is granted access","The False Rejection Rate (FRR) increases, causing more legitimate users to be denied access","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) decreases, improving the system's overall accuracy","Enrollment time increases because additional biometric samples must be captured"],"c":0,"why":"Lowering the matching threshold makes the system more lenient, which reduces false rejections but directly increases false acceptances, weakening security. CER is a fixed characteristic of the sensor/algorithm at the point where FAR=FRR and does not decrease as a result of threshold tuning; the other options describe the opposite effect.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization's identity governance process requires that when an employee changes roles internally, their previous access rights are automatically reviewed and removed if no longer needed, rather than simply accumulating new permissions. This practice is best described as preventing which condition?","o":["Privilege creep","Separation of duties violation","Credential stuffing","Session hijacking"],"c":0,"why":"Privilege creep occurs when users accumulate unnecessary access rights over time as roles change without proper deprovisioning; the described process directly mitigates this. Separation of duties concerns conflicting task assignments, while credential stuffing and session hijacking are unrelated attack techniques.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to enter a PIN and then insert a smart card to access a workstation. Which authentication category do these two factors represent, respectively?","o":["Something you know and something you have","Something you have and something you are","Something you know and something you know","Something you are and something you know"],"c":0,"why":"A PIN is 'something you know' and a smart card is 'something you have'; combining them is true multifactor authentication. The other pairings mislabel the factor types.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm needs access decisions that consider the requester's department, the sensitivity classification of the data, the time of day, and whether the requesting device is compliant with endpoint security policy. Which access control model is best suited to enforce this requirement, and why does role-based access control (RBAC) fall short here?","o":["Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC), because policies can evaluate multiple dynamic attributes at request time, whereas RBAC decisions are based solely on static role assignments","Mandatory Access Control (MAC), because sensitivity labels alone can encode time and device compliance","Discretionary Access Control (DAC), because resource owners can manually factor in all these conditions","RBAC enhanced with dynamic separation of duties, because roles can be redefined hourly to reflect device compliance"],"c":0,"why":"ABAC evaluates a policy against multiple contextual attributes (subject, object, environment) at access time, natively supporting conditions like time-of-day and device posture that static role membership in RBAC cannot express without creating an unmanageable number of roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security team implements a solution where administrators must request elevated privileges for a specific task, and the access is automatically granted for a limited time window before being revoked. This approach exemplifies which privileged access management concept?","o":["Discretionary access control","Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access","Mandatory vacation policy","Role mining"],"c":1,"why":"JIT privileged access grants elevated permissions only when needed and for a limited duration, reducing the attack surface associated with standing privileged accounts. DAC concerns owner-based access decisions, mandatory vacation is an operational control unrelated to access provisioning, and role mining is used to design RBAC structures.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A hospital assigns system permissions to users based solely on their job title, such as 'Nurse' or 'Pharmacist,' rather than granting access to each individual separately. Which access control model is being used?","o":["Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":1,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions to roles that are then assigned to users, matching job functions like 'Nurse.' MAC uses security labels/clearances, DAC lets owners grant access, and rule-based control uses if-then conditions rather than job roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A web application terminates a user's authenticated session after 15 minutes of inactivity and requires re-authentication to continue. What security objective does this control primarily support?","o":["Preventing SQL injection attacks","Reducing the risk of session hijacking on unattended or abandoned sessions","Enforcing separation of duties","Ensuring non-repudiation of transactions"],"c":1,"why":"Session timeouts limit the window during which an attacker could hijack or misuse an unattended authenticated session, directly reducing that risk. SQL injection is a code-level attack unrelated to session timeout, separation of duties concerns task division, and non-repudiation relates to proving action origin, not session expiration.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization follows a joiner-mover-leaver (JML) identity lifecycle process. Automated provisioning grants access correctly at hire, and deprovisioning removes access promptly at termination. However, an internal audit finds numerous employees who changed departments over the past two years still retain entitlements from their previous roles. Which control would most directly address this gap?","o":["Periodic access recertification/attestation performed by resource or data owners","Increasing the frequency of automated provisioning workflows at initial hire","Conducting an annual role-mining exercise to redesign the role catalog","Enforcing mandatory password rotation every 90 days for all accounts"],"c":0,"why":"Recurring access certification requires owners to actively review and confirm that existing entitlements are still appropriate, which catches accumulated 'access creep' from moves that automated hire/termination provisioning does not address. Role mining improves future role design but doesn't remove stale grants already assigned, and password rotation is unrelated to entitlement appropriateness.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company uses SAML to allow employees to log into a cloud-based expense reporting application using their corporate credentials without a separate login. What is this an example of?","o":["Federated identity management","Role-based access control","Mandatory access control","Kerberos ticket delegation"],"c":0,"why":"Federated identity management, often implemented with SAML, allows identities established in one domain (corporate) to be trusted and used in another (cloud app). RBAC and MAC are authorization models, not identity federation, and Kerberos is a different SSO protocol used mainly within Windows domains.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester discovers that a web application's login form builds an LDAP search filter by directly concatenating the user-supplied username, such as constructing (uid=<input>). By submitting a crafted value like *)(uid=*))(|(uid=*, the tester bypasses authentication entirely. What is the most effective remediation for this vulnerability?","o":["Properly validate and escape LDAP special characters in user input, or use parameterized LDAP query construction","Migrate all LDAP traffic to LDAPS to encrypt the bind request","Enforce an account lockout policy after a threshold of failed login attempts","Require mutual TLS client certificates for all directory service connections"],"c":0,"why":"This is an LDAP injection vulnerability caused by unsafe string concatenation of untrusted input into a search filter; the fix is input validation/escaping or parameterized filter construction, analogous to SQL injection defenses. Encryption, lockout policies, and mutual TLS do not prevent the filter logic itself from being manipulated.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A biometric fingerprint scanner is tuned to be extremely strict, rejecting many legitimate users to minimize the chance of letting in an impostor. This adjustment increases which metric?","o":["False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Throughput rate"],"c":1,"why":"Tightening sensitivity to reduce impostor acceptance increases the False Rejection Rate, since legitimate users are more often incorrectly denied. FAR would decrease, and CER is the point where FAR and FRR are equal, not a direct result of this change.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization deploys a Privileged Access Management (PAM) solution that requires administrators to check out privileged credentials from a vault for a limited, time-boxed session, after which the password is automatically rotated. Compared to standing, persistently assigned privileged accounts, what primary risk does this just-in-time approach mitigate?","o":["Reduces the attack window and value of stolen credentials by eliminating long-lived, reusable privileged passwords","Eliminates the need to enforce multi-factor authentication for privileged sessions","Removes the requirement to log or record privileged sessions for audit purposes","Automatically guarantees separation of duties across all privileged operations"],"c":0,"why":"Time-boxed checkout with automatic rotation drastically shortens how long a compromised privileged credential remains valid, directly reducing the value of credential theft compared to static, long-standing privileged accounts. It does not replace MFA, session logging, or separation-of-duties controls, which must still be implemented separately.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During an incident response investigation, analysts discover that an attacker obtained the password hash of the krbtgt service account in an Active Directory domain. Using this hash, the attacker forged Kerberos ticket-granting tickets that remained valid for years and granted access to any resource in the domain, even after user passwords were reset. Which attack technique does this describe?","o":["Golden Ticket attack","Pass-the-Hash attack","Silver Ticket attack","Kerberoasting"],"c":0,"why":"A Golden Ticket attack uses the compromised krbtgt hash to forge arbitrary TGTs, granting domain-wide access independent of user password changes. Pass-the-Hash reuses a user's NTLM hash for authentication rather than forging Kerberos tickets; a Silver Ticket forges only service tickets using a service account's hash, limiting scope to that service; Kerberoasting extracts and cracks service account password hashes from legitimately requested service tickets rather than forging tickets outright.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A security policy requires that the employee who initiates a wire transfer cannot also be the one who approves it. This is an example of which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Need to know"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties splits critical tasks between multiple people to prevent fraud or error by a single individual. Least privilege limits access to what's necessary, defense in depth layers controls, and need-to-know restricts information access based on job necessity, none of which specifically describe dividing a transaction into two roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A mobile application needs to authenticate a user via a third-party identity provider and also retrieve verified identity attributes such as the user's name and email address in a standardized token, in addition to obtaining an access token for calling a backend API. Which protocol layered on top of OAuth 2.0 is specifically designed to meet this identity assertion requirement?","o":["OpenID Connect (OIDC)","SAML 2.0","Kerberos","OAuth 2.0 alone"],"c":0,"why":"OpenID Connect adds an identity layer on top of OAuth 2.0, issuing an ID token containing verified user identity claims alongside the OAuth access token. SAML 2.0 is a separate XML-based federation standard not built on OAuth; OAuth 2.0 alone only handles delegated authorization and has no standardized identity assertion; Kerberos is a ticket-based protocol for internal network authentication, not web/mobile federation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee is terminated, which access management practice is MOST important to perform immediately to reduce security risk?","o":["Archiving the employee's email for legal purposes","Deprovisioning all of the employee's system and application access","Changing the organization's master encryption keys","Conducting a full security awareness training refresh"],"c":1,"why":"Prompt deprovisioning of accounts and access rights prevents a terminated employee from retaining unauthorized access, which is a critical IAM control. Email archiving may occur for compliance but doesn't address access risk, and key rotation or training are unrelated to immediate offboarding needs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A hospital wants to enforce that a physician can only access a specific patient's electronic health record if the physician is currently assigned to that patient's care team, is logged in during an active shift, and is connecting from an approved hospital subnet. Which access control model is best suited to enforce this policy?","o":["Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":0,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple dynamic attributes (assignment, time, network location) at access time, making it ideal for this contextual, multi-condition policy. RBAC grants access based solely on job role and cannot easily factor in shift time or network location; MAC relies on static security labels/clearances unrelated to these dynamic conditions; DAC lets resource owners grant access at their discretion, which does not scale to enforce consistent contextual rules across an organization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"Two biometric authentication systems are being evaluated. System A has a Crossover Error Rate (CER) of 3%, and System B has a CER of 7%. Both systems will be deployed at the same sensitivity threshold used to calculate these values. Which conclusion is correct?","o":["System A is more accurate because a lower CER indicates a better balance between false acceptances and false rejections","System B is more accurate because a higher CER means fewer false rejections overall","CER is irrelevant to accuracy and only measures enrollment time","The two systems are equally accurate because CER measures throughput, not error rates"],"c":0,"why":"CER is the point where the False Acceptance Rate equals the False Rejection Rate; a lower CER indicates a more accurate biometric system overall. A higher CER does not equate to fewer false rejections—it reflects a worse balance of both error types; CER directly measures accuracy, not enrollment time or throughput.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A web application authenticates users by building an LDAP search filter using unsanitized user input from the login form, such as: (&(uid=<input>)(userPassword=<input>)). A tester submits a username field containing \"*)(uid=*))(|(uid=*\" and successfully bypasses authentication. What is the underlying vulnerability being exploited?","o":["LDAP injection due to improper input sanitization in directory query construction","A Kerberos ticket replay vulnerability","A SAML assertion signature wrapping attack","Insufficient TLS configuration on the LDAP connection"],"c":0,"why":"The attacker is manipulating LDAP filter syntax through unsanitized input to alter query logic and bypass authentication—classic LDAP injection. This scenario involves no Kerberos tickets, SAML assertions, or TLS configuration; it is purely a query-construction/input-validation flaw in the directory search filter.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements SP-initiated SAML SSO. Security testing reveals that a captured, valid SAML assertion can be replayed by an attacker to gain unauthorized access to the service provider up to an hour after the original login. Which set of controls would most effectively mitigate this specific weakness?","o":["Enforce short assertion validity windows, one-time-use assertion IDs, and audience restriction checks at the SP","Increase the RSA key length used to sign the SAML assertion","Require the identity provider to use multifactor authentication for all users","Switch from SP-initiated to IdP-initiated SSO flow"],"c":0,"why":"Replay attacks are mitigated by enforcing tight time validity, tracking assertion IDs to prevent reuse, and validating the intended audience/recipient—these directly address the replay window issue. Increasing key length strengthens signature integrity but does not prevent replay of a validly signed assertion; requiring MFA at the IdP secures the initial login but not reuse of an already-issued assertion; switching SSO initiation flow does not inherently add replay protection.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution wants to minimize the risk posed by standing privileged accounts used by database administrators. They want administrators to request elevated access only when needed, have that access automatically time-limited, and have all privileged sessions recorded for audit. Which solution category best addresses these requirements?","o":["Privileged Access Management (PAM) with just-in-time access and session recording","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) with static role assignments","Mandatory multifactor authentication for all administrator logins","Network segmentation isolating the database servers"],"c":0,"why":"PAM solutions with just-in-time provisioning and session recording directly eliminate standing privilege and provide auditability of elevated sessions, matching all stated requirements. Static RBAC still grants persistent privileged roles rather than time-limited elevation; MFA strengthens authentication but does not limit privilege duration or record sessions; network segmentation limits lateral movement but does not address the standing-privilege or audit requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution issues employees a physical smart card that must be inserted into a reader along with a PIN to log in to workstations. The smart card itself represents which authentication factor?","o":["Something the user knows","Something the user has","Something the user is","Somewhere the user is"],"c":1,"why":"A smart card is a physical token the user possesses, making it a 'something you have' factor; the PIN paired with it is 'something you know.' Biometrics ('something you are') and location-based factors are unrelated to a physical card.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An employee transfers from the finance department to the marketing department. IT grants the new marketing-related access but fails to revoke the previously held finance system entitlements. Over several years of internal transfers, this employee accumulates access rights far beyond what any current role requires. What is this condition called, and which process failure primarily causes it?","o":["Privilege creep, caused by inadequate access review during the mover phase of the joiner-mover-leaver process","Privilege escalation, caused by a vulnerability in the authentication system","Separation of duties violation, caused by lack of dual control on financial transactions","Excessive least-privilege enforcement, caused by overly restrictive default role definitions"],"c":0,"why":"Privilege creep results from failing to revoke unneeded entitlements when a user's role changes (the 'mover' stage), leading to accumulated, unnecessary access over time. Privilege escalation refers to exploiting a flaw to gain unauthorized elevated access, not accumulated legitimate grants; a separation-of-duties violation concerns conflicting duties assigned to one person, not leftover access; the scenario describes excessive access, which is the opposite of least-privilege enforcement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"What is a primary security benefit of implementing Single Sign-On (SSO) for an organization's users?","o":["It eliminates the need for any authentication credentials","It reduces the number of passwords users must remember and manage","It automatically encrypts all network traffic","It grants users administrative access to all systems"],"c":1,"why":"SSO allows users to authenticate once and access multiple systems, reducing password fatigue and the number of credentials to manage. It does not eliminate authentication, encrypt traffic, or grant elevated privileges by itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a federated SSO solution using SAML so employees can access a cloud HR application with their corporate credentials. What is the primary responsibility of the Identity Provider (IdP) in this exchange?","o":["Consume the assertion and enforce authorization decisions for the HR application","Authenticate the user and issue a signed assertion asserting the user's identity to the service provider","Store and manage the HR application's business data","Act as the resource owner that approves each individual access request"],"c":1,"why":"The IdP is responsible for authenticating the user and generating a signed SAML assertion trusted by the service provider; consuming the assertion and enforcing authorization is the service provider's role, not the IdP's.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In the Kerberos authentication protocol, what is the primary function of the Key Distribution Center (KDC)?","o":["To store user passwords in plaintext for quick retrieval","To issue and manage tickets used for authenticating to services","To act as the final resource server that users access","To encrypt all data transmitted across the network"],"c":1,"why":"The KDC issues tickets (via the Authentication Service and Ticket Granting Service) that allow users to prove their identity to services without repeatedly sending credentials. It is not the resource server itself and does not store plaintext passwords.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company wants new hires to automatically receive the correct system permissions based solely on their job title (e.g., 'Accountant' or 'HR Analyst'), without administrators manually assigning individual rights. Which access control model best supports this requirement?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions to roles that correspond to job functions, and users inherit permissions by being assigned to a role. DAC relies on resource owner discretion, MAC uses security labels/clearances, and rule-based control relies on predefined conditional rules rather than job titles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"When an employee is terminated from an organization, what is the MOST important access management action to perform promptly?","o":["Reassign the employee's accounts to a coworker","Archive the employee's email for future reference","Disable or revoke the employee's access accounts and credentials","Change the organization's firewall rules"],"c":2,"why":"Prompt deprovisioning by disabling or revoking accounts prevents a terminated employee from retaining unauthorized access, which is a core IAM control. Reassigning accounts violates least privilege and accountability principles, and firewall changes are unrelated to individual deprovisioning.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An audit reveals that a former employee's VPN account remained active for three weeks after termination because IT was never notified by HR. Which control failure does this scenario best illustrate?","o":["Weak password complexity enforcement","Failure to integrate timely deprovisioning with the HR termination process","Absence of multifactor authentication on the VPN","Improper initial account provisioning at hire"],"c":1,"why":"The issue stems from the account not being disabled promptly after termination due to a broken HR-to-IT notification process, which is a deprovisioning failure. Password strength, MFA, and initial provisioning are unrelated to the delayed offboarding.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An attacker successfully compromises the krbtgt account's secret key on a Kerberos Key Distribution Center (KDC). What is the most significant risk created by this compromise?","o":["The attacker can forge Ticket Granting Tickets (golden tickets) that grant access to any resource in the realm without further authentication","The attacker can only decrypt service tickets for the single service that issued the compromised key","The attacker gains read-only access to the LDAP directory schema","The attacker must still know each user's password before impersonating them"],"c":0,"why":"The krbtgt account's key is used to encrypt and sign all TGTs; compromising it allows an attacker to forge arbitrary TGTs (a 'golden ticket') for any user or service, bypassing normal authentication entirely. The other options understate the scope of compromise, since the krbtgt key underlies the trust for the entire realm, not a single service or password.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a Kerberos authentication environment, after a user successfully authenticates to the Key Distribution Center (KDC) and receives a Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT), what does the TGT allow the user to do?","o":["Directly access any application server without further interaction with the KDC","Request service tickets from the Ticket Granting Service without re-entering credentials","Permanently bypass authentication for all future sessions","Serve as the master secret key shared between the KDC and all servers"],"c":1,"why":"The TGT is presented to the Ticket Granting Service to obtain service tickets for specific resources without re-authenticating, but it does not grant direct access to application servers itself. It is not a permanent bypass or a shared master key.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A mobile application using the OAuth 2.0 Authorization Code flow cannot securely store a client secret. Which additional mechanism should be implemented to protect against authorization code interception attacks?","o":["Proof Key for Code Exchange (PKCE)","Implicit grant flow instead of Authorization Code flow","A longer-lived refresh token","Client credentials grant with a shared secret"],"c":0,"why":"PKCE binds the authorization request to the token exchange using a dynamically generated code verifier/challenge, preventing an intercepted authorization code from being redeemed by an attacker. Implicit flow exposes tokens directly in the URL fragment (worse), longer refresh tokens increase risk, and client credentials grant is unsuitable for public clients without a secure secret.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which access control model relies on labels such as 'Confidential' or 'Secret' assigned to both subjects and objects, with access determined by a central authority rather than the resource owner?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":1,"why":"MAC uses security labels and clearances enforced by a central authority, common in classified/government systems. DAC allows resource owners to control access, while RBAC and rule-based models use roles or predefined rules instead of labels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements Kerberos for network authentication. During the authentication process, which component is responsible for issuing a service ticket after validating a user's Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT)?","o":["The Key Distribution Center's Authentication Service (AS)","The Ticket Granting Service (TGS)","The application server hosting the requested resource","The client workstation's local security authority"],"c":1,"why":"The TGS, a component of the KDC, validates the TGT and issues a service ticket for access to a specific resource; the AS only issues the initial TGT, and the application server and client are not involved in ticket issuance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"In a SAML 2.0 web browser SSO federation, which entity is responsible for authenticating the user's credentials and issuing the signed assertion consumed by the relying party?","o":["The Identity Provider (IdP)","The Service Provider (SP)","The Attribute Authority acting independently of the IdP","The user's local browser cache"],"c":0,"why":"The Identity Provider authenticates the subject and issues the SAML assertion; the Service Provider (relying party) consumes and validates that assertion but does not perform the authentication itself. Attribute authorities may supply additional attributes but are not the primary authenticator, and the browser is merely a transport mechanism.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In biometric authentication systems, what does the Crossover Error Rate (CER) represent?","o":["The point at which the False Acceptance Rate and False Rejection Rate are equal","The total number of enrollment failures during system setup","The maximum number of users a system can support","The average time required to authenticate a single user"],"c":0,"why":"The CER is the point where FAR and FRR intersect, and a lower CER indicates a more accurate biometric system. It has nothing to do with enrollment failures, user capacity, or authentication speed.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A network administrator is comparing RADIUS and TACACS+ for centralizing authentication of network device logins. Which statement correctly differentiates the two protocols?","o":["RADIUS encrypts the entire authentication packet, while TACACS+ encrypts only the password field","TACACS+ encrypts the entire packet payload, while RADIUS encrypts only the password field","Both protocols encrypt only the username field and leave the password in cleartext","Neither RADIUS nor TACACS+ provides any encryption of authentication data"],"c":1,"why":"TACACS+ encrypts the full body of the packet, providing stronger confidentiality, whereas RADIUS by default only encrypts the password field, leaving other attributes like username in cleartext. The other options misstate the actual encryption behavior of each protocol.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system is being tuned for a high-security data center. Security administrators lower the sensitivity threshold to reduce user complaints about failed logins. What is the most likely security consequence of this change?","o":["The False Rejection Rate (FRR) will increase, delaying legitimate users","The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) will increase, allowing more unauthorized access","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) will decrease, improving overall accuracy","The enrollment time for new users will increase significantly"],"c":1,"why":"Lowering the sensitivity threshold makes the system more permissive, which increases the False Acceptance Rate (unauthorized users accepted) while decreasing FRR, not the CER, which is a fixed point where FAR equals FRR for a given system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In a federated identity environment using SAML, what is the role of the Identity Provider (IdP)?","o":["It stores the resources that the user is trying to access","It authenticates the user and issues assertions about their identity to the service provider","It encrypts the user's data at rest within the service provider's database","It serves solely as a firewall between the user and the service provider"],"c":1,"why":"The Identity Provider authenticates users and issues signed assertions (tokens) that a Service Provider trusts to grant access, enabling federated SSO across organizations. The Service Provider, not the IdP, hosts the actual resources.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"When evaluating two competing biometric authentication systems, a security architect compares their Crossover Error Rate (CER). What does the CER represent?","o":["The point at which the False Rejection Rate and False Acceptance Rate are equal, used as a measure of overall system accuracy","The percentage of users who fail to enroll their biometric template successfully","The rate of false acceptances only, independent of false rejections","The average processing time required to authenticate a single user"],"c":0,"why":"CER (or Equal Error Rate) is the point where FRR and FAR intersect, and a lower CER indicates a more accurate biometric system overall. Enrollment failure rate, false-acceptance-only measures, and processing speed are separate metrics.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to implement an access control model where permissions are determined dynamically based on user department, time of day, resource sensitivity, and location. Which access control model best supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple attributes (subject, object, environment) in real time to make access decisions, unlike RBAC which relies solely on predefined roles, DAC which relies on owner discretion, and MAC which uses fixed security labels.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security manager reviews an internal process and finds that the same employee who requests new user accounts also has the authority to approve those requests and independently review the access logs. Which principle is being violated, and what change would best correct it?","o":["Least privilege; the employee's account should have fewer default permissions","Separation of duties; account approval and log review should be assigned to different individuals than the requester","Need-to-know; the employee should be restricted to viewing only relevant logs","Job rotation; the employee should be moved to a different department periodically"],"c":1,"why":"Having one person request, approve, and audit the same access violates separation of duties, which requires critical functions to be divided among multiple individuals to prevent fraud or error. Least privilege, need-to-know, and job rotation address different (though related) control objectives.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"In a SAML-based federated identity scenario, a user at Company A logs into a SaaS application hosted by Company B without re-entering credentials. Which statement correctly describes the roles involved?","o":["Company A is the Service Provider and Company B is the Identity Provider","Company A is the Identity Provider and Company B is the Service Provider","Both companies act as Identity Providers in a mutual trust relationship","Company B issues the SAML assertion after validating credentials with Company A's directory"],"c":1,"why":"Company A, which authenticates the user and issues the SAML assertion, is the Identity Provider (IdP); Company B, which consumes the assertion to grant access to its application, is the Service Provider (SP).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization assigns permissions to users based on their job function, such as 'Accountant' or 'HR Manager,' rather than assigning permissions to each individual user. Which access control model does this describe?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC assigns access rights based on organizational roles, simplifying administration. DAC lets resource owners grant access, MAC uses security labels/clearances, and rule-based control uses if-then rules rather than job roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An employee resigns and their last day is in two weeks. From an identity and access management perspective, what is the BEST practice for handling this employee's access during the notice period?","o":["Leave access unchanged until the last day to avoid disrupting current projects","Immediately disable all access and require re-provisioning if needed for transition tasks","Reduce access to only what is necessary for remaining duties and monitor activity closely","Grant temporary administrative access to allow the employee to document their work"],"c":2,"why":"Best practice during a notice period is to apply least privilege by scaling back access to only what's needed for remaining responsibilities while increasing monitoring, balancing security risk with business continuity; leaving access unchanged or granting elevated access increases insider threat risk, and full immediate disablement may disrupt legitimate transition work.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which statement best describes the primary purpose of Single Sign-On (SSO)?","o":["It encrypts all network traffic between the client and server","It allows a user to authenticate once and gain access to multiple independent systems without re-authenticating","It requires users to memorize a unique password for each application","It replaces the need for any authentication factor"],"c":1,"why":"SSO enables one authentication event to grant access across multiple systems, improving usability and reducing password fatigue. It does not encrypt traffic, does not require multiple passwords, and does not eliminate authentication entirely.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A user authenticates to a corporate VPN using a password combined with a one-time passcode generated by a hardware token. This is an example of which authentication concept?","o":["Single-factor authentication using two knowledge-based credentials","Multi-factor authentication combining something you know and something you have","Mutual authentication between client and server","Risk-based adaptive authentication"],"c":1,"why":"The password represents 'something you know' and the hardware token represents 'something you have,' satisfying the definition of multi-factor authentication; it is not single-factor, mutual authentication, or adaptive authentication based on risk signals.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In the Kerberos authentication protocol, what is the primary role of the Key Distribution Center (KDC)?","o":["To store user passwords in plaintext for quick retrieval","To issue tickets that allow authenticated users to access network services","To act as the final resource server that grants file access","To encrypt data at rest on the client workstation"],"c":1,"why":"The KDC issues tickets (via the Authentication Service and Ticket Granting Service) that let clients prove their identity to services without resending credentials. It does not store plaintext passwords, act as a resource server, or encrypt local data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security team implements a Privileged Access Management (PAM) solution for administrative accounts. Which capability provides the GREATEST reduction in risk from credential theft of shared administrative accounts?","o":["Enforcing complex password policies on shared admin accounts","Automatically rotating credentials after each privileged session and vaulting them","Requiring administrators to memorize passwords instead of writing them down","Assigning shared admin accounts to a single trusted employee"],"c":1,"why":"Automatic credential rotation and vaulting ensures that even if a credential is exposed, it becomes invalid after the session, minimizing the window for misuse; the other options do not address the core risk of static, reusable shared credentials.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company terminates an employee but forgets to disable their VPN and email accounts for several weeks. This scenario is a failure of which IAM process?","o":["Identity proofing","Account provisioning","Account deprovisioning","Password rotation"],"c":2,"why":"Deprovisioning is the process of removing access rights when a user leaves; failing to do so promptly creates a security risk. Provisioning is granting initial access, identity proofing verifies identity during onboarding, and password rotation is unrelated to termination.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An application uses OpenID Connect (OIDC) for user authentication and OAuth 2.0 for authorization to access a protected API. What is the primary distinction between the tokens issued by these two protocols?","o":["The access token proves user identity, while the ID token grants API access permissions","The ID token proves user identity, while the access token grants authorization to access resources","Both tokens serve identical purposes and are interchangeable in OIDC implementations","The refresh token replaces the need for both ID and access tokens in modern implementations"],"c":1,"why":"OIDC issues an ID token that contains identity claims about the authenticated user, while OAuth 2.0 issues an access token that authorizes access to protected resources/APIs; these tokens serve distinct purposes and are not interchangeable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A biometric fingerprint scanner incorrectly rejects an authorized employee's fingerprint, denying them access. Which metric does this error represent?","o":["False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Equal Error Rate (EER)"],"c":1,"why":"FRR measures the rate at which legitimate users are incorrectly denied access. FAR measures unauthorized users incorrectly granted access, and CER/EER refer to the point where FAR and FRR are equal, not a single rejection event.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which principle dictates that a user should be granted only the minimum access rights necessary to perform their job duties?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege","Defense in depth","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Least privilege limits access to only what is needed for the job function, reducing risk. Separation of duties splits critical tasks among multiple people, defense in depth layers security controls, and mandatory vacation is a fraud-detection administrative control.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants employees to use a single set of credentials to access both its internal HR system and a third-party SaaS payroll provider. Which technology is best suited to achieve this?","o":["A shared local administrator account","Federated identity management using SAML or OIDC","A static shared password stored in a spreadsheet","Disabling authentication on the SaaS provider"],"c":1,"why":"Federated identity management using standards like SAML or OIDC allows trusted identity assertions to be shared across organizational boundaries, enabling single credentials across internal and external systems. The other options are insecure practices, not legitimate IAM solutions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to grant access to a cloud file-sharing application based on attributes such as department, job title, clearance level, and time of day, without manually assigning roles for every possible combination. Which access control model BEST meets this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":1,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple attributes (subject, object, environment) in policy rules, allowing fine-grained, dynamic decisions without creating a role for every combination. RBAC would require explosion of roles, MAC relies on fixed sensitivity labels, and DAC relies on owner discretion, not attribute policies.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A security architect is designing a Kerberos-based authentication system for an enterprise network. Which component is responsible for issuing the initial ticket-granting ticket (TGT) to a user after successful authentication?","o":["The Ticket Granting Server (TGS)","The Key Distribution Center's Authentication Service (AS)","The application server the user wants to access","The client workstation itself"],"c":1,"why":"The Authentication Service (AS), part of the KDC, verifies the user's credentials and issues the TGT. The TGS later uses the TGT to issue service tickets, while the application server and client are not responsible for ticket issuance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric authentication system is tuned to minimize the rate at which unauthorized users are incorrectly granted access, even if this causes more legitimate users to be rejected. Which metric is being prioritized for reduction?","o":["False Acceptance Rate (FAR)","False Rejection Rate (FRR)","Crossover Error Rate (CER)","Equal Error Rate (EER)"],"c":0,"why":"FAR measures the rate of incorrectly accepting unauthorized users; minimizing it (even at the cost of higher FRR) is a security-focused tuning choice. FRR is the opposite metric, and CER/EER represent the point where FAR and FRR are equal, not a tuning priority.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester extracts the NTLM hash of the krbtgt account from a compromised domain controller. Using this hash, the tester can forge Kerberos tickets that remain valid until the krbtgt password is changed twice. What type of attack does this describe?","o":["Golden ticket attack","Silver ticket attack","Pass-the-hash attack","Kerberoasting attack"],"c":0,"why":"A golden ticket is forged using the krbtgt account's hash, allowing an attacker to create arbitrary TGTs for any user or group, persisting until krbtgt's password is rotated twice. Silver tickets forge service tickets using a service account hash, pass-the-hash reuses NTLM hashes without invoking Kerberos, and Kerberoasting targets service ticket hashes for offline cracking.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires employees to swipe a smart card and enter a PIN to log into workstations. This is an example of which authentication concept?","o":["Single-factor authentication using something you have","Multi-factor authentication combining something you have and something you know","Multi-factor authentication combining something you are and something you know","Single sign-on across multiple systems"],"c":1,"why":"A smart card is 'something you have' and a PIN is 'something you know', so combining them constitutes two-factor authentication. The other options misclassify the factors or describe an unrelated concept (SSO).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company federates identity with a SaaS vendor so employees can log in using their corporate credentials without re-entering a password. The SaaS provider trusts assertions issued by the company's identity provider. Which technology is MOST commonly used to implement this browser-based federation for enterprise SaaS single sign-on?","o":["Kerberos","RADIUS","SAML","TACACS+"],"c":2,"why":"SAML is the standard XML-based protocol for browser-based SSO federation between an identity provider and a service provider. Kerberos is used within a single trusted domain, and RADIUS/TACACS+ are primarily for network device and remote access authentication, not web SSO federation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"In a SAML 2.0 federated SSO deployment, which assertion element is primarily responsible for preventing an intercepted assertion from being replayed after its intended validity period?","o":["The Issuer element","The Conditions element with NotBefore/NotOnOrAfter attributes","The AudienceRestriction element","The SubjectConfirmation element"],"c":1,"why":"The Conditions element's NotBefore/NotOnOrAfter timestamps bound the assertion's validity window, mitigating replay attacks. AudienceRestriction limits which SP can consume the assertion, SubjectConfirmation binds it to a subject/method, and Issuer merely identifies the IdP—none of these limit the time window.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"Which term best describes the process of verifying that a user is who they claim to be, typically by presenting credentials such as a password?","o":["Identification","Authentication","Authorization","Accountability"],"c":1,"why":"Authentication is the verification of claimed identity via credentials. Identification is merely claiming an identity (e.g., a username), authorization determines access rights, and accountability tracks actions after access is granted.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During a security audit, an auditor discovers that a former employee's account was still active and had accessed company resources three weeks after termination. Which IAM process failure MOST directly caused this issue?","o":["Inadequate access review and deprovisioning process","Lack of multi-factor authentication","Weak password complexity requirements","Absence of a data classification policy"],"c":0,"why":"Failure to promptly disable or remove access upon termination is a deprovisioning failure, a core IAM lifecycle control. MFA, password complexity, and data classification are unrelated to whether the account itself should have been disabled.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A mobile application (a public client unable to securely store a client secret) needs to perform OAuth 2.0 authorization to access an API on behalf of a user. Which extension should be mandated to prevent authorization code interception attacks?","o":["Implicit grant flow","Client credentials grant","Proof Key for Code Exchange (PKCE)","Resource owner password credentials grant"],"c":2,"why":"PKCE binds the authorization request to the token exchange via a dynamically generated code verifier/challenge, protecting public clients from code interception without needing a client secret. Implicit flow exposes tokens in the URL fragment, client credentials is for machine-to-machine auth, and ROPC exposes user credentials directly to the client.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A company assigns access permissions to users based on their job function, such as 'Accountant' or 'HR Manager', rather than granting permissions to each individual user directly. Which access control model is being used?","o":["Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Rule-Based Access Control"],"c":2,"why":"RBAC assigns permissions to roles that correspond to job functions, and users inherit permissions through role membership. DAC lets resource owners grant access, MAC uses security labels/classifications, and rule-based control uses if-then rules rather than roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution requires that database administrators check out temporary, time-limited credentials from a vault whenever they need elevated access, rather than holding standing administrative rights. This approach BEST exemplifies which security concept?","o":["Separation of duties","Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access","Mandatory access control","Discretionary access control"],"c":1,"why":"JIT privileged access grants elevated permissions only for a limited time when needed, reducing the attack surface of standing privileges. Separation of duties splits tasks among individuals, and MAC/DAC describe how access is determined, not the temporal nature of privilege grants.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A healthcare organization needs to grant clinicians access to patient records only during their scheduled shift, only from hospital-owned devices, and only when connected to the internal network. Which access control model best supports this requirement without requiring a separate role for every combination of conditions?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes (time, device, network) at request time through policy rules, avoiding role explosion. RBAC would require a distinct role for every attribute combination, MAC relies on fixed classification labels, and DAC lets resource owners assign access without centralized contextual policy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"In biometric authentication systems, what does a False Rejection Rate (FRR) measure?","o":["The percentage of unauthorized users incorrectly granted access","The percentage of authorized users incorrectly denied access","The point at which FAR and FRR are equal","The average time required to enroll a new user's biometric template"],"c":1,"why":"FRR measures how often legitimate, authorized users are wrongly rejected by the biometric system. The percentage of unauthorized users wrongly accepted is the False Acceptance Rate (FAR), and the crossover point of FAR and FRR is the Crossover Error Rate (CER), not FRR itself.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a policy requiring that no single employee can both create a new vendor in the accounts payable system and approve payments to that vendor. Which access control principle does this policy enforce?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Need-to-know","Defense in depth"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties prevents a single individual from controlling an entire high-risk process, reducing fraud opportunity. Least privilege limits the amount of access granted, need-to-know limits access to information required for a task, and defense in depth refers to layered security controls, not task division.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A biometric authentication vendor reports that increasing the acceptance threshold (making the system stricter) to reduce the False Acceptance Rate (FAR) will have which effect on the system's overall performance?","o":["The False Rejection Rate (FRR) will increase","The False Rejection Rate (FRR) will decrease","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) will decrease","Both FAR and FRR will decrease simultaneously"],"c":0,"why":"FAR and FRR have an inverse relationship; tightening the threshold to lower false acceptances inevitably increases false rejections. CER is a fixed characteristic of the system's ROC curve at the point where FAR=FRR and is not changed by a single threshold adjustment, and FAR/FRR cannot both decrease from the same shift.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"easy","q":"A business partner uses SAML assertions to allow its employees to log into your company's cloud application using their home organization's credentials. This scenario best illustrates which concept?","o":["Federated identity management","Role-based access control","Discretionary access control","Kerberos ticket delegation"],"c":0,"why":"Federated identity management allows users to authenticate with a trusted third party (identity provider) and access resources at another organization (service provider) using standards like SAML. RBAC, DAC, and Kerberos are unrelated access/authentication mechanisms not specific to cross-organizational trust.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A web application uses OAuth 2.0 to allow a third-party service to access a user's photos stored on a cloud storage provider without sharing the user's password with the third party. Which artifact does the third-party application receive to gain this limited access?","o":["The user's hashed password","A Kerberos ticket-granting ticket","An access token","A SAML assertion signed by the user"],"c":2,"why":"OAuth 2.0 issues access tokens that grant limited, scoped access to resources without exposing credentials. Kerberos tickets and SAML assertions belong to different protocols, and the user's password is never shared under OAuth's delegated authorization model.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements just-in-time (JIT) account provisioning, where a federated identity provider automatically creates a local account on a service provider the first time a user authenticates via SSO. Which security risk is MOST directly introduced by this approach if not properly governed?","o":["Increased password reuse across systems","Orphaned accounts remaining active on the service provider after the user is terminated in the identity source","Excessive multi-factor authentication prompts","Inability to enforce the same password policy as the IdP"],"c":1,"why":"JIT provisioning creates accounts without centralized lifecycle tracking on the SP side, so if deprovisioning isn't explicitly wired to the same trigger (e.g., via SCIM), terminated users' local accounts can remain active. Password reuse and policy enforcement are largely irrelevant since authentication is federated, and MFA prompt frequency is unrelated to provisioning risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An administrator configures an LDAP client to authenticate to a directory server using a 'simple bind' operation over an unencrypted connection. What is the primary security weakness of this configuration?","o":["The directory schema cannot be extended","Replication between directory replicas will fail","The user's distinguished name and password are transmitted in cleartext","Anonymous access is automatically enabled for all users"],"c":2,"why":"Simple bind sends the DN and password in cleartext unless wrapped in TLS (LDAPS or StartTLS), exposing credentials to interception. Schema extensibility and replication are unrelated to the bind mechanism, and simple bind does not automatically enable anonymous access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a federated identity solution allowing employees to authenticate once at their corporate identity provider and access multiple partner SaaS applications without re-entering credentials. Which technology best describes the protocol most likely used to pass authentication assertions between the identity provider and the service providers?","o":["SAML","RADIUS","Kerberos","LDAP"],"c":0,"why":"SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language) is an XML-based standard specifically designed to exchange authentication and authorization assertions between identity providers and service providers in federated SSO. RADIUS and Kerberos are used for network/domain authentication, not cross-domain web federation, and LDAP is a directory access protocol, not an assertion exchange standard.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A privileged access management (PAM) solution vaults all administrative credentials, requires administrators to 'check out' a password for single use, automatically rotates it after check-in, and records the resulting session. What is the PRIMARY security benefit this design provides over standard shared local administrator accounts?","o":["It eliminates the need for multi-factor authentication on privileged accounts","It provides individual accountability and limits credential exposure for shared privileged accounts","It replaces the need for a centralized directory service","It automatically classifies data accessed during the session"],"c":1,"why":"Credential vaulting with checkout/rotation and session recording ties privileged use to an individual and minimizes the window a static shared password remains valid, directly addressing the accountability gap of shared admin accounts. It does not remove the need for MFA, replace directory services, or perform data classification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution wants to enforce access decisions based on attributes such as the user's department, the sensitivity label of the data, the time of day, and the requesting device's location. Which access control model best supports this requirement?","o":["Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)","Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"],"c":2,"why":"ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes (subject, object, environment) to make dynamic access decisions, which matches the scenario. RBAC only considers roles, MAC relies on fixed sensitivity labels and clearances without contextual attributes like time or location, and DAC leaves access decisions to resource owners rather than attribute policies.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"During an incident response investigation, a security team discovers that an attacker obtained the NTLM password hash of the krbtgt service account in an Active Directory domain. Which statement most accurately describes the impact and required remediation?","o":["The attacker can forge Kerberos Ticket Granting Tickets (Golden Tickets) with arbitrary lifetimes and group memberships; full remediation requires resetting the krbtgt password twice to invalidate both the current and prior key history.","The attacker can only forge individual service tickets for a single resource, limiting the blast radius to one application server.","Resetting the domain administrator account password will invalidate the attacker's ability to forge Kerberos tickets signed with the krbtgt key.","The compromise is self-limiting because forged tickets cannot exceed the domain's default 10-hour maximum ticket lifetime."],"c":0,"why":"The krbtgt account's key is used to sign TGTs, so its compromise allows creation of Golden Tickets that grant arbitrary, long-lived, and privileged access; because AD retains the previous krbtgt password in key history, a single reset is insufficient and the password must be reset twice to fully invalidate forged tickets. The other options misstate Kerberos ticket mechanics—krbtgt compromise enables TGT (not just service ticket) forgery, is unrelated to the domain admin account's own credentials, and attackers can set arbitrary ticket lifetimes in forged tickets, bypassing normal expiration.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements a SAML 2.0 federation so that employees can authenticate once at their corporate Identity Provider (IdP) and access a partner's SaaS application acting as the Service Provider (SP). Which statement correctly identifies how identity assertions are issued and how the trust relationship enabling the SP to accept them is established?","o":["The IdP issues digitally signed SAML assertions containing identity and attribute claims; trust is established through prior out-of-band exchange of metadata and public key certificates between the IdP and SP.","The SP generates its own assertions internally based on the user's browser cookies; trust is implicit because the SP owns the protected resource.","The user's browser digitally signs the assertion using a self-signed certificate generated at login; trust is based solely on the TLS session established with the SP.","An OAuth Attribute Authority encrypts the assertion using the resource owner's private key, and trust is granted dynamically through OAuth scope negotiation at request time."],"c":0,"why":"In SAML federation, the IdP is the authoritative issuer of signed assertions, and the SP validates them using trust established beforehand via exchanged metadata/certificates (federation trust setup), not at request time. The distractors incorrectly assign assertion issuance to the SP or the browser, and conflate OAuth's resource-owner/token-scope model with SAML's assertion-based architecture, which does not apply here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"During a security audit, an assessor finds that a terminated employee's account was still active 45 days after departure and had been used to log into the VPN. Which control failure is most directly responsible for this finding?","o":["Weak password complexity policy","Lack of multi-factor authentication","Inadequate deprovisioning process","Failure to implement least privilege"],"c":2,"why":"The core issue is that the account was not disabled/removed after termination, which is a deprovisioning failure in the identity lifecycle management process. Password complexity, MFA, and least privilege are unrelated to the account remaining active post-termination.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A company uses a centralized authentication system where a client obtains a ticket-granting ticket from an authentication server, then uses it to request service tickets for individual resources without re-entering credentials. This describes which authentication protocol?","o":["OAuth 2.0","Kerberos","TACACS+","OpenID Connect"],"c":1,"why":"Kerberos uses a Key Distribution Center to issue a ticket-granting ticket (TGT) followed by service tickets for individual resource access, exactly as described. OAuth 2.0 and OpenID Connect are web authorization/authentication frameworks using tokens rather than tickets, and TACACS+ is a network device AAA protocol, not a ticket-based system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to reduce the risk of a compromised administrator account being used to make unauthorized changes to critical systems. Which control provides the strongest mitigation by requiring a second authorized individual to approve sensitive administrative actions before execution?","o":["Mandatory vacation policy","Two-person integrity control","Separation of duties via job rotation","Single sign-on with adaptive authentication"],"c":1,"why":"Two-person integrity (dual control) requires two authorized individuals to jointly approve or perform a sensitive action, directly mitigating misuse of a single compromised privileged account. Mandatory vacation and job rotation are detective/preventive HR controls unrelated to real-time approval, and SSO with adaptive authentication strengthens login assurance but doesn't require a second approver for actions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A biometric access control system is being tuned to balance security and usability. Security management decides to lower the sensitivity threshold to reduce user complaints about repeated failed login attempts. What is the most likely security consequence of this change?","o":["The False Rejection Rate (FRR) will increase","The False Acceptance Rate (FAR) will increase","The Crossover Error Rate (CER) will decrease","Enrollment time will increase"],"c":1,"why":"Lowering the sensitivity threshold makes the system more permissive, increasing the likelihood that impostors are incorrectly accepted (higher FAR), while FRR decreases (fewer legitimate users rejected). CER is a fixed characteristic of the sensor/algorithm at the point where FAR=FRR and doesn't simply decrease from a threshold change, and enrollment time is unrelated to threshold sensitivity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"A web application allows users to log in using their existing Google account credentials to access a third-party service, with Google issuing an access token that the third-party application uses to retrieve limited profile information via an API. This scenario primarily illustrates which concept?","o":["Authentication via OAuth 2.0 authorization delegation","Single sign-on via Kerberos ticket delegation","Mandatory access control with attribute assertions","Directory federation via LDAP referrals"],"c":0,"why":"This describes OAuth 2.0, where the identity provider (Google) issues an access token allowing a third-party application limited, delegated access to specific resources/APIs without sharing credentials. Kerberos and LDAP are enterprise/directory protocols not used for this type of web API delegation, and MAC is unrelated to token-based delegation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to identify known weaknesses in its systems by comparing installed software versions against a database of published CVEs. Which security assessment activity best matches this description?","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Penetration testing","Security audit","Threat modeling"],"c":0,"why":"Vulnerability scanning compares system configurations and software versions against known vulnerability databases (e.g., CVE lists) to identify weaknesses. Penetration testing actively exploits vulnerabilities, an audit verifies compliance with standards, and threat modeling identifies potential threats during design, not existing known flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D5","d":"medium","q":"An organization's access review process discovers that many employees have accumulated access rights from previous roles they no longer perform, resulting in excessive combined privileges. Which term best describes this condition, and which process directly addresses it?","o":["Privilege creep; periodic access recertification","Least privilege violation; role mining","Segregation of duties failure; job rotation","Authorization sprawl; account provisioning"],"c":0,"why":"The accumulation of unnecessary access over time due to role changes without removal of old rights is known as privilege creep, and periodic access recertification (user access reviews) is the standard control to identify and remove such excess access. Role mining helps design roles but doesn't directly remove creep, and the other options mischaracterize the scenario or reference an unrelated remediation process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A penetration tester is given full knowledge of the target's network diagrams, source code, and credentials before testing begins. What type of test is this?","o":["Black-box test","Gray-box test","White-box test","Double-blind test"],"c":2,"why":"A white-box test provides the tester with complete internal knowledge of the system, simulating an insider or highly informed attacker. Black-box testing provides no prior knowledge, gray-box provides partial knowledge, and double-blind testing hides the test from both staff and testers regardless of information level.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An attacker steals a user's ticket-granting ticket (TGT) in a Kerberos-based single sign-on environment. The TGT has not yet expired. What is the MOST significant risk of this compromise?","o":["The attacker can decrypt all future network traffic because the TGT contains the domain master key","The attacker can impersonate the user to request service tickets from the ticket-granting service until the TGT expires, without needing the user's password","The attacker can mint new TGTs for arbitrary users because the TGT embeds the KDC's private key","The risk is negligible because each service ticket request forces the client to re-enter the user's password"],"c":1,"why":"A TGT is encrypted with the KDC's secret key and, once obtained, can be replayed to request service tickets (a pass-the-ticket attack) without further password entry until it expires. It does not contain the domain master key or the KDC's private key, and no password re-authentication occurs during service ticket issuance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary purpose of a security control self-assessment performed by internal staff rather than external auditors?","o":["To provide independent, legally binding certification of compliance","To allow the organization to identify and remediate weaknesses before formal external review","To replace the need for any external audits","To transfer liability for security failures to a third party"],"c":1,"why":"Self-assessments help organizations proactively find and fix gaps internally, improving readiness for external audits. They are not independent or legally binding, do not eliminate the need for external audits, and do not transfer liability.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to identify known vulnerabilities across all servers in a data center by comparing installed software versions against a database of published CVEs, without attempting to exploit any weaknesses. Which activity best describes this process?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability assessment","Security audit","Threat modeling"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs known weaknesses using scanning tools and CVE databases without exploitation. Penetration testing goes further by actively exploiting vulnerabilities; a security audit evaluates compliance with policy/standards; threat modeling identifies potential threats during design, not existing flaws in deployed systems.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A bank wants third-party budgeting apps to read customers' transaction data without ever handling the customers' bank credentials. The bank implements OAuth 2.0 with the authorization code grant. Which statement correctly describes this implementation?","o":["The third-party app collects the user's bank username and password and exchanges them directly for an access token","The user is redirected to the bank's authorization server, which authenticates the user and returns an authorization code that the app exchanges for an access token; the app never sees the bank credentials","OAuth 2.0 inherently proves the end user's identity to the third-party app, making a separate OpenID Connect layer unnecessary","The resulting access token is a permanent credential equivalent to the user's password and should be cached indefinitely by the app"],"c":1,"why":"The authorization code grant keeps credentials confined to the authorization server; the app only ever receives a code and later a token. OAuth 2.0 is an authorization framework, not an authentication protocol (OpenID Connect adds identity), and access tokens are scoped/time-limited, not permanent password equivalents.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a code review, a security analyst manually inspects source code line by line without executing the program to identify potential flaws such as buffer overflows. This is an example of which testing technique?","o":["Dynamic analysis","Static analysis","Fuzz testing","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Static analysis examines source code without executing it, looking for coding flaws. Dynamic analysis and fuzz testing involve executing the program, and regression testing verifies that changes have not broken existing functionality, not code inspection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During application security testing, an analyst examines the source code of a web application without executing it, using automated tools to flag insecure coding patterns such as unvalidated input handling. Which testing technique is being used?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source or binary code without executing the program, ideal for finding insecure coding patterns early. DAST tests a running application from the outside, fuzz testing sends malformed input to a running program, and IAST combines runtime and code analysis, none of which match static, non-executed code review.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A multinational firm needs access decisions that consider job role, current device compliance status, geolocation, and time of day simultaneously, and the number of possible role combinations is growing unmanageably under the current model. Which access control model BEST addresses this requirement?","o":["Role-based access control (RBAC)","Attribute-based access control (ABAC)","Discretionary access control (DAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)"],"c":1,"why":"ABAC evaluates policies against multiple contextual attributes dynamically, avoiding the 'role explosion' problem inherent in RBAC when many contextual factors must be combined. DAC relies on owner discretion and MAC on fixed sensitivity labels, neither of which natively supports multi-attribute contextual evaluation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security analyst runs an automated tool that compares a system's configuration and patch levels against a database of known weaknesses, producing a report of potential issues without attempting to exploit them. What activity was performed?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability assessment","Security audit","Social engineering test"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and reports potential weaknesses without exploitation. Penetration testing goes further by actively exploiting flaws; an audit verifies compliance with standards; social engineering targets human behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which type of test simulates real user transactions against a live production system to verify that critical functions are operating correctly, without the users' knowledge that a test is occurring?","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring","Penetration testing","Misuse case testing","Interface testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions are scripted, simulated actions run against production systems to continuously verify functionality and performance. Penetration testing seeks to exploit vulnerabilities, misuse case testing models abuse scenarios, and interface testing focuses on system-to-system communication, not simulated user behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A company evaluating a cloud service provider requests a report that includes the auditor's opinion on the design and operating effectiveness of security controls over a six-month period. Which report should the company request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3"],"c":2,"why":"SOC 2 Type II reports on the operating effectiveness of controls over a period of time (e.g., six months), addressing security, availability, and other trust criteria. SOC 2 Type I only assesses design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report without detailed testing results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a penetration test, the testing team is given full access to network diagrams, source code, and system credentials before beginning their assessment. What type of test is this?","o":["Black box testing","Gray box testing","White box testing","Blind testing"],"c":2,"why":"White box (also called clear box) testing provides testers with full internal knowledge of the target environment. Black box gives no prior information, gray box gives partial information, and blind testing means the target organization is unaware of the test.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A security team is concerned that standing privileged administrator accounts remain enabled and highly permissioned at all times, creating a persistent high-value target. Which control BEST reduces this exposure while still allowing administrators to perform necessary tasks?","o":["Increase the minimum password length and complexity requirements for privileged accounts","Implement just-in-time privileged access that grants time-bound elevation on request and automatically revokes it afterward","Rotate privileged account passwords every 90 days","Require multifactor authentication only at the administrator's first login of the day"],"c":1,"why":"Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access minimizes the window during which elevated rights exist, directly reducing the attack surface of standing privileges. Password complexity, periodic rotation, and one-time-per-day MFA do not eliminate the persistent availability of elevated rights between uses.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization requests a report from its cloud service provider that provides assurance over the provider's controls related to security, availability, and confidentiality for use by the organization's auditors. Which type of report is most appropriate?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","PCI DSS Attestation of Compliance","ISO 9001 certification"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the design and operating effectiveness of controls related to security, availability, confidentiality, processing integrity, and privacy over a period of time, making it ideal for auditor reliance. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, PCI DSS applies to payment card environments, and ISO 9001 relates to quality management, not security controls.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization's incident response team reviews firewall, IDS, and authentication logs weekly to identify anomalous patterns such as repeated failed logins followed by a successful one. This activity is an example of which security assessment technique?","o":["Log review and correlation","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Misuse case testing","Configuration management auditing"],"c":0,"why":"Log review and correlation involves analyzing recorded system and security events to detect suspicious patterns like brute-force attempts. Synthetic transactions simulate user activity to test system behavior, misuse case testing models attacker scenarios during design, and configuration auditing checks system settings against baselines, not log analysis.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An airport wants to speed passenger throughput at a biometric identity checkpoint by lowering the matching threshold, which reduces the False Rejection Rate (FRR). The security team objects. Which statement BEST explains the security team's concern?","o":["Lowering the threshold below the crossover error rate increases the False Acceptance Rate, allowing more impostors to be incorrectly matched as legitimate travelers","Lowering the threshold has no effect on the False Acceptance Rate because FRR and FAR are independent metrics","Lowering the threshold only affects enrollment time, not matching accuracy","The crossover error rate will decrease automatically whenever FRR decreases, improving overall security"],"c":0,"why":"FRR and FAR are inversely related around the crossover error rate (CER); reducing the threshold to lower FRR (convenience) necessarily raises FAR (security risk), allowing more impostors through. FRR and FAR are not independent, and CER is a fixed system characteristic, not something that automatically improves.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which type of code analysis technique examines source code for security flaws without actually executing the program?","o":["Dynamic analysis","Static analysis","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"Static analysis reviews source or compiled code without execution to find flaws like insecure functions or logic errors. Dynamic analysis and fuzzing require running code, and penetration testing is a broader exploitation-based assessment.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the MOST effective method for validating that a disaster recovery plan will function as intended during an actual disaster?","o":["Reviewing the plan documentation for completeness","Conducting a full-scale functional exercise involving actual failover","Interviewing IT staff about their understanding of the plan","Verifying that the plan has been updated within the last year"],"c":1,"why":"A full-scale functional exercise actually tests the plan's execution and reveals real gaps, providing the strongest validation. Document review, interviews, and update checks are useful but do not confirm the plan will actually work in practice.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A penetration tester is given full knowledge of the target application's source code, architecture diagrams, and network topology before beginning the engagement. This testing approach is best classified as which type?","o":["Black-box testing","Gray-box testing","White-box testing","Double-blind testing"],"c":2,"why":"White-box testing provides the tester with complete internal knowledge of the system, enabling thorough analysis of code and architecture. Black-box testing provides no internal knowledge, gray-box provides partial knowledge, and double-blind testing means neither the tester nor the defending team has advance notice, which is unrelated to information disclosure level.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A web application performs an anonymous LDAP bind and then builds a directory search filter by directly concatenating unsanitized user-supplied input for the username field. An attacker submits a crafted string containing wildcard and filter-manipulation characters and successfully bypasses the login logic. What is happening, and what is the BEST remediation?","o":["This is a buffer overflow attack; remediate by increasing the memory allocated to the input buffer","This is an LDAP injection attack exploiting an improperly constructed search filter; remediate by validating/escaping special characters and avoiding unauthenticated anonymous binds for sensitive queries","This is a Kerberos golden ticket attack; remediate by rotating the KRBTGT account password twice","This is a pass-the-hash attack; remediate by disabling LDAP in favor of NTLM authentication"],"c":1,"why":"Injecting LDAP filter metacharacters to alter search logic and bypass authentication is classic LDAP injection, remediated through input validation/escaping and restricting anonymous bind usage. The other options describe unrelated attack techniques (buffer overflow, golden ticket, pass-the-hash) that do not match this scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants an unbiased assessment of its security controls performed by a firm with no financial ties to the company being reviewed. Which type of audit best satisfies this requirement?","o":["Internal audit","Third-party (external) audit","Self-assessment","Management review"],"c":1,"why":"A third-party audit is conducted by an independent external firm, providing objectivity and reducing conflicts of interest. Internal audits and self-assessments are performed by organizational staff and may lack independence.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security tester intentionally submits malformed and unexpected input data to an application to observe how it handles errors and to uncover potential crashes or vulnerabilities. This technique is known as:","o":["Fuzz testing","Static code analysis","Baseline testing","Regression testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing involves feeding invalid, unexpected, or random data into an application to identify crashes, memory leaks, or security flaws. Static analysis examines code without execution, baseline testing compares performance to a known standard, and regression testing checks that changes haven't broken existing features.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An internal audit team performs an assessment of the organization's own security controls and reports findings directly to the CISO. A separate engagement is later conducted by an independent firm hired to validate compliance with a regulatory framework. What is the primary advantage of the independent firm's assessment over the internal audit?","o":["It is faster to complete because the firm is unfamiliar with the environment","It provides greater objectivity due to lack of organizational bias","It eliminates the need for management to review findings","It requires no scoping or planning phase"],"c":1,"why":"External/independent audits provide greater objectivity because the auditors have no vested interest in the organization's outcomes, reducing bias that internal auditors might have. Unfamiliarity typically slows an assessment rather than speeding it, and all audits still require scoping and management review of findings.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"A federated service provider is configured to accept unsolicited SAML assertions from its identity provider (IdP-initiated SSO) but does not validate assertion expiration (NotOnOrAfter) or track whether an assertion has already been consumed. What is the PRIMARY risk this introduces?","o":["Increased network latency due to an extra round trip to the identity provider","Inability of the service provider to enforce multifactor authentication at the identity provider","An attacker who captures a valid assertion could replay it to gain unauthorized access, potentially multiple times, since expiration and single-use are not enforced","The identity provider loses the ability to issue attribute-based claims to the service provider"],"c":2,"why":"Without enforcing assertion expiration and one-time use, a captured SAML assertion can be replayed for unauthorized access; this is the core replay risk in SSO. The other options are unrelated to assertion validation and are not consequences of missing replay protections.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A quality assurance team configures automated scripts that simulate real user actions—such as logging in, submitting a form, and logging out—on a production e-commerce site every 15 minutes to verify functionality and performance. This technique is known as which of the following?","o":["Synthetic transactions","Regression testing","Fuzz testing","Interface testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions use scripted, simulated user interactions to continuously monitor application availability and performance in production. Regression testing verifies that new changes haven't broken existing functionality after code changes, fuzz testing sends random/malformed input to find crashes, and interface testing focuses on validating data exchange between system components rather than simulating end-user behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D5","d":"hard","q":"An API architecture uses stateless JWT access tokens with a 24-hour expiration for authorization. The security team is concerned that a compromised token cannot be revoked before it naturally expires. Which control BEST addresses this weakness while preserving most of the scalability benefits of statelessness?","o":["Extend token expiration to seven days to reduce the frequency of reissuance","Store the JWT in browser local storage instead of an HttpOnly cookie to simplify access","Issue short-lived access tokens paired with a server-side, revocable refresh token, and check a revocation list for sensitive operations","Sign all tokens using a single symmetric key shared across every client application"],"c":2,"why":"Combining short-lived access tokens with revocable refresh tokens (and revocation checks for high-risk actions) limits the exposure window of a compromised token while retaining most stateless benefits. Extending expiration worsens the problem, storage location doesn't address revocation, and a shared symmetric key increases key-compromise risk across all clients.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/access_control"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A company deploys scripted transactions that mimic real user behavior on its e-commerce website every hour to verify the application is functioning correctly and available. What is this technique called?","o":["Fuzz testing","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Regression testing","Misuse case testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate user actions on a live system to proactively detect performance or availability issues. Fuzzing sends malformed input to find defects, regression testing verifies changes didn't break existing functionality, and misuse case testing models attacker behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution wants to test its disaster recovery plan by actually failing over live production systems to the alternate site and running business operations from there for a full day, with no fallback to the primary site during the test. Which type of DR test is being performed?","o":["Tabletop exercise","Simulation test","Parallel test","Full interruption test"],"c":3,"why":"A full interruption test involves actually shutting down primary operations and running the business entirely from the alternate site, representing the highest risk but most realistic DR test. A parallel test runs alternate site systems alongside (not instead of) production, a simulation test walks through a scenario without full failover, and a tabletop exercise is a discussion-based review without any technical failover.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which disaster recovery test type involves team members verbally walking through the recovery plan in a conference room without activating any actual systems?","o":["Full interruption test","Parallel test","Simulation test","Tabletop exercise"],"c":3,"why":"A tabletop exercise is a discussion-based walkthrough of the plan with no systems involved, making it low-risk and low-cost. Simulation tests involve more active role-play, parallel tests run alternate systems alongside production, and full interruption tests actually shut down primary operations.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Reviewing system and application logs after an incident to reconstruct the sequence of events is an example of which security assessment activity?","o":["Log review and analysis","Penetration testing","Threat modeling","Code review"],"c":0,"why":"Log review and analysis examines recorded system activity to detect anomalies or reconstruct events, which is essential for incident investigation. The other choices involve proactive testing or design-phase analysis, not post-event log examination.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which metric would best help a security manager measure the effectiveness of a vulnerability management program over time?","o":["Number of firewalls deployed","Average time to remediate identified vulnerabilities","Total employee headcount in IT","Number of security policies published"],"c":1,"why":"Average remediation time is a meaningful key performance indicator that reflects how efficiently identified risks are addressed. The other options are static counts unrelated to actual program effectiveness.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A CISO commissions a penetration test in which the testing team is given only the organization's name and public domain, and the internal security operations staff are deliberately not informed that a test will occur. The primary goal is to evaluate both the technical security posture and the SOC's ability to detect and respond to a real intrusion. Which type of engagement is this?","o":["Double-blind (zero-knowledge) penetration test","White-box penetration test","Gray-box vulnerability assessment","Compliance-driven internal audit"],"c":0,"why":"A double-blind test withholds knowledge from both the testers (black-box) and the defenders, allowing an authentic assessment of detection and incident response, not just exploitable vulnerabilities. White-box/gray-box tests give testers system knowledge, and a compliance audit checks controls against a standard rather than simulating an attack.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team is deciding between two testing approaches. One approach involves scanning systems to identify known weaknesses without exploiting them, producing a prioritized list of missing patches and misconfigurations. The other involves actively attempting to exploit weaknesses to determine real-world impact and simulate an attacker. Which pair of terms correctly describes these two approaches, respectively?","o":["Vulnerability assessment; penetration testing","Penetration testing; vulnerability assessment","Risk assessment; vulnerability assessment","Penetration testing; risk assessment"],"c":0,"why":"Vulnerability assessments identify and catalog weaknesses without exploitation, while penetration testing actively exploits vulnerabilities to demonstrate impact. The other pairings reverse or misapply these definitions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A prospective customer requires assurance that a cloud provider's security controls (access management, change control, monitoring) were not only suitably designed but also operated effectively and consistently over the preceding 12 months. Which report should the provider furnish?","o":["SOC 1 Type II report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 3 report"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of security-relevant controls over a period of time. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, SOC 2 Type I only assesses control design at a point in time, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary without the detailed testing results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A company is evaluating a cloud service provider (CSP) and wants independent assurance that the CSP's security controls were operating effectively over a six-month period, including evidence of testing performed by an independent auditor. Which document should the company request?","o":["SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 1 Type I report","A vendor-provided self-assessment questionnaire"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report covers the operating effectiveness of controls over a review period (not just a point in time) and is based on independent auditor testing, making it appropriate for ongoing assurance of security controls. Type I reports only assess design at a single point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and self-assessments lack independent verification.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security team must assess a third-party web application for which they have no source code access. They need to exercise the running application with crafted inputs to observe how it behaves under attack, including injection and authentication bypass attempts. Which testing methodology is most appropriate?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)","Manual secure code review"],"c":1,"why":"DAST tests the running application from the outside, black-box style, without needing source code, making it suitable here. SAST and manual code review require source access, and SCA only identifies vulnerable third-party components rather than testing runtime behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During the SDLC, a development team wants to identify insecure coding patterns, such as SQL injection vulnerabilities, by analyzing the application's source code without executing it. Which testing technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source code, bytecode, or binaries without executing the application, making it ideal for early detection of insecure coding patterns. DAST tests a running application, fuzz testing sends malformed input to a running system, and penetration testing simulates attacks against a live environment.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A tester captures legitimate protocol traffic between a client and server and then systematically flips bits, truncates fields, and inserts random byte sequences into the captured packets without any understanding of the underlying protocol specification, replaying the altered traffic to look for crashes. This technique is best classified as:","o":["Generation-based fuzzing","Mutation-based fuzzing","Model-based fuzzing","Static taint analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Mutation-based (dumb) fuzzing modifies existing valid inputs without protocol knowledge, exactly as described. Generation-based and model-based fuzzing require a formal understanding of the protocol/grammar to construct new inputs, and taint analysis is a static code-analysis technique unrelated to fuzzing input generation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants the earliest possible detection of anomalous behavior by privileged accounts, such as unusual login times or mass data exports. Which assessment approach best achieves this objective?","o":["Quarterly manual sampling of privileged-account logs","Annual third-party security audit","Real-time automated log correlation and alerting via a SIEM","Semiannual vulnerability scanning of privileged endpoints"],"c":2,"why":"Continuous, automated correlation of logs through a SIEM enables near real-time detection of anomalous privileged activity. Periodic manual sampling, annual audits, and semiannual scans introduce significant detection latency and can miss transient malicious activity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst notices that a SIEM has generated thousands of alerts overnight, most of which are false positives caused by a misconfigured rule. Which action would MOST effectively improve the long-term value of log review and correlation activities?","o":["Disable the SIEM's correlation engine until the issue is resolved","Increase the alert threshold for all rules across the environment","Tune the specific correlation rule and validate it against known-good and known-bad traffic","Instruct staff to ignore alerts generated during night shifts"],"c":2,"why":"Tuning the specific rule and validating it addresses the root cause of false positives while preserving detection capability. Disabling correlation, raising thresholds broadly, or ignoring alerts reduces visibility and increases risk of missing real incidents.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An assessor reviewing a penetration test report notices that the tester exercised only 40% of the application's identified functional paths, despite the scope requiring comprehensive testing. Which assessment technique should be used to identify and address this gap?","o":["Test coverage analysis","Misuse case testing","Interface testing","Regression testing"],"c":0,"why":"Test coverage analysis measures the extent to which test cases exercise code paths, functions, or requirements, helping identify untested areas. Misuse case testing focuses on abuse scenarios, interface testing focuses on data exchange points, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality—none directly measure overall coverage gaps.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A mid-sized organization's disaster recovery program has only completed tabletop exercises to date. Management now wants a more rigorous test that actually processes real transactions at the alternate site and compares results against production output, but without interrupting normal production operations. Which test type should be conducted next?","o":["Walkthrough test","Simulation test","Parallel test","Full interruption test"],"c":2,"why":"A parallel test processes actual transactions at the alternate site concurrently with production, validating recovery capability without disrupting live operations. A walkthrough is discussion-based, a simulation test rehearses response without full processing, and a full interruption test would shut down production, which the organization is not ready for.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization runs an automated tool that scans its network for known vulnerabilities and misconfigurations but does not attempt to exploit any of the findings. What type of security testing activity is this?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability assessment","Social engineering test","Red team exercise"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and reports known weaknesses without exploiting them. Penetration testing and red team exercises go further by actively exploiting vulnerabilities, and social engineering targets people, not systems.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to continuously verify that its customer-facing web application is available and performing critical transactions correctly, even during periods of low real user traffic. Which technique BEST supports this goal?","o":["Synthetic transactions","Fuzz testing","Code review","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate predefined user actions on a scheduled basis to proactively monitor availability and functionality, independent of actual user traffic. Fuzz testing looks for input-handling flaws, code review examines source code, and misuse case testing explores abuse scenarios—none provide continuous operational monitoring.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm hires an external team to emulate a sophisticated threat actor over several weeks, using social engineering, physical intrusion attempts, and multiple attack chains, with the explicit goal of measuring the blue team's detection and response capability rather than simply cataloging vulnerabilities. Which engagement type best describes this?","o":["Vulnerability assessment","Standard penetration test","Red team exercise","Regulatory compliance audit"],"c":2,"why":"A red team exercise emulates real adversary tactics, techniques, and procedures over an extended period to test detection and response, going beyond a standard penetration test's scope of finding and exploiting vulnerabilities. A vulnerability assessment only identifies weaknesses, and a compliance audit checks conformance to a standard, neither of which emulates adversary behavior against the SOC.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a code review, an analyst examines the application's source code line by line without executing the program to look for insecure coding patterns. This is an example of which testing technique?","o":["Dynamic analysis","Static analysis","Fuzz testing","Interface testing"],"c":1,"why":"Static analysis reviews source code without running it. Dynamic analysis and fuzz testing require executing the program, and interface testing focuses on interactions between components, not source code review.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A tester submits large volumes of randomly malformed and unexpected input to an application's input fields to observe crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions. Which testing technique is being used?","o":["Fuzz testing","Static analysis","Interface testing","Regression testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing involves feeding malformed or random input to software to uncover crashes, memory corruption, or unhandled exceptions, revealing input validation weaknesses. Static analysis examines code without execution, interface testing focuses on data exchange between components, and regression testing checks that changes haven't broken existing functionality.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During software test planning, the QA lead wants a code coverage metric that provides the strongest assurance that logic errors involving specific combinations of conditions will be caught, even though achieving full coverage is often impractical for complex code. Which metric is being described?","o":["Statement coverage","Branch (decision) coverage","Path coverage","Condition coverage"],"c":2,"why":"Path coverage requires testing every possible route through the code, including all combinations of branches, providing the most rigorous assurance but growing exponentially complex. Statement, branch, and condition coverage are less exhaustive, each testing progressively more logic but not every combined execution path.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to identify known vulnerabilities across all servers in a large data center by comparing installed software versions against a database of published CVEs, without attempting to exploit any weaknesses. Which testing activity best describes this approach?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability scanning","Security audit","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"Vulnerability scanning uses automated tools to compare system configurations and software versions against known vulnerability databases without exploitation. Penetration testing actively exploits weaknesses, an audit assesses compliance with standards, and fuzz testing sends malformed input to find defects.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A company wants an independent auditor's report that evaluates the design and operating effectiveness of its security controls over a period of several months for use by customers who rely on its cloud service. Which report type best fits this need?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","PCI DSS Attestation of Compliance","SOC 2 Type I report"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the design and operating effectiveness of controls over a period of time, which is exactly what is described. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, Type I reports only assess design at a point in time, and PCI DSS attestation is specific to payment card handling.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization's business continuity team wants to validate its disaster recovery plan with minimal disruption to production systems, focusing on discussion of roles, responsibilities, and decision points rather than actual failover. Which exercise type BEST meets this requirement?","o":["Full interruption test","Parallel test","Tabletop exercise","Simulation test"],"c":2,"why":"A tabletop exercise involves a discussion-based walkthrough of the plan without activating systems, making it low-risk and low-disruption. Parallel and simulation tests involve activating alternate systems to varying degrees, and a full interruption test actually shuts down production, both of which carry significantly more operational risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During application security testing, an assessor examines the source code line-by-line using automated tools to identify insecure coding patterns before the application is compiled or deployed. This technique is best classified as:","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source code, bytecode, or binaries without executing the application, making it ideal for early-stage code review. DAST tests a running application externally, IAST combines runtime instrumentation with SAST-like analysis, and fuzz testing sends random/malformed inputs to a running system.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A penetration tester is given full knowledge of the target's network diagrams, source code, and credentials before beginning the engagement. What type of test is this?","o":["Black box testing","Gray box testing","White box testing","Double-blind testing"],"c":2,"why":"White box testing provides the tester with complete internal knowledge of the target. Black box testing provides no internal information, gray box provides partial knowledge, and double-blind testing conceals the test from both the target's staff and sometimes the testers regarding scope details.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A financial services company needs an independent report on the design and operating effectiveness of its cloud provider's security controls over a six-month period to satisfy due diligence requirements for an ongoing vendor relationship. Which report should they request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates both the design and operating effectiveness of controls over a period of time (e.g., six months), which is needed for ongoing due diligence. Type I reports only assess design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report lacking detailed control testing information.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of reviewing system and security logs on a regular basis?","o":["To reduce the storage costs associated with log retention","To detect anomalous activity and potential security incidents","To satisfy backup requirements for disaster recovery","To automatically patch vulnerable systems"],"c":1,"why":"Log review is primarily performed to identify suspicious or anomalous activity that may indicate a security incident. It is not intended to reduce storage costs, fulfill backup requirements, or patch systems automatically.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A penetration tester is given full access to network diagrams, source code, and system credentials before beginning an assessment. This testing approach is best described as:","o":["Black box testing","Gray box testing","White box testing","Double-blind testing"],"c":2,"why":"White box (or clear box) testing provides the tester with complete internal knowledge of the system, including source code and architecture, allowing for thorough analysis. Black box testing provides no internal knowledge, gray box provides partial knowledge, and double-blind testing conceals the test from both the target's staff and often limits tester knowledge as well.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A QA team simulates real user transactions against a production e-commerce website at scheduled intervals to verify that checkout functionality continues to work correctly over time. What is this testing technique called?","o":["Fuzz testing","Synthetic transaction testing","Misuse case testing","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user activity against live systems to continuously verify functionality and performance. Fuzz testing injects malformed input, misuse case testing models attacker behavior, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality after a code change, not ongoing production monitoring.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization deploys scripted transactions that simulate real user behavior—such as logging in and completing a purchase—on its production e-commerce site every five minutes to detect performance degradation or functional failures. This technique is known as:","o":["Fuzz testing","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Misuse case testing","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transaction monitoring uses scripted, simulated user interactions to proactively test availability and performance of live systems. Fuzz testing injects malformed data to find crashes, misuse case testing models attacker behavior during design, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality, typically in non-production environments.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the difference between a security audit and a security assessment?","o":["An audit is always performed by internal staff, while an assessment is always performed by external parties","An audit measures compliance against a defined standard or policy, while an assessment evaluates overall security posture and provides recommendations","An audit only tests technical controls, while an assessment only tests administrative controls","There is no meaningful difference between the two terms"],"c":1,"why":"A security audit formally verifies compliance with a specific standard, policy, or regulation, whereas a security assessment more broadly evaluates security posture and offers improvement recommendations. The other statements incorrectly characterize who performs each activity or what controls each covers.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security tester submits large volumes of randomly generated, malformed, and unexpected input to an application's input fields to observe whether it crashes, leaks memory, or behaves unpredictably. This technique is called:","o":["Fuzz testing","Static code analysis","Misuse case testing","Interface testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing automatically generates invalid, unexpected, or random data as input to discover coding errors, crashes, and security vulnerabilities like buffer overflows. Static code analysis reviews source code without execution, misuse case testing models how an attacker might abuse a feature during design, and interface testing focuses on verifying correct data exchange between system components.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A tester sends large volumes of random, malformed, and unexpected input to an application's input fields to observe how the application handles the data and to identify potential crashes or vulnerabilities. This technique is known as what?","o":["Fuzz testing","Static code analysis","Interface testing","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing involves feeding random or malformed input to a program to discover vulnerabilities such as crashes or memory issues. Static code analysis examines source code without execution, interface testing checks interactions between components, and misuse case testing models how an attacker might misuse a feature rather than randomly generating input.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security program manager wants to measure how quickly the security operations team detects and contains security incidents over time to demonstrate improvement in the incident response process. Which type of metric would be most appropriate?","o":["Key Risk Indicator (KRI)","Key Performance Indicator (KPI)","Vulnerability density metric","Return on Security Investment (ROSI)"],"c":1,"why":"A KPI measures the effectiveness and efficiency of a process, such as mean time to detect (MTTD) and mean time to contain (MTTC), directly reflecting operational performance. A KRI signals potential future risk exposure rather than process performance, vulnerability density measures code quality, and ROSI calculates financial value of security spending.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A test plan requires reviewers to walk through documented attacker scenarios—such as an insider attempting to bypass approval workflows to authorize fraudulent payments—to ensure the application's design accounts for these threats before development begins. This activity is an example of:","o":["Interface testing","Misuse case testing","Regression testing","Vulnerability scanning"],"c":1,"why":"Misuse case testing (or abuse case testing) analyzes how a system could be intentionally misused by an attacker or malicious insider, typically performed during the design phase to inform secure requirements. Interface testing checks component interactions, regression testing verifies unchanged functionality after modifications, and vulnerability scanning identifies known technical weaknesses in deployed systems.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security team is defining the scope for an upcoming assessment. Management wants testers to identify and catalog all missing patches and misconfigurations across the environment using automated tools, without attempting to exploit any of the findings. Which activity best matches this requirement?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability assessment","Red team exercise","Security control assessment using NIST SP 800-53A test methods"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment uses automated scanning to identify and catalog weaknesses without exploitation. Penetration testing and red team exercises involve active exploitation to demonstrate impact, and an 800-53A control assessment evaluates control implementation against a baseline rather than scanning for missing patches.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization contracts a firm to conduct a double-blind penetration test. Which statement correctly describes a key characteristic of this test type compared to a standard (single-blind) penetration test?","o":["The testers are given full knowledge of the network architecture but the defenders are not informed of the test","Neither the testers nor the organization's internal security/incident response team are informed in advance, allowing evaluation of real-world detection and response","The test is conducted twice by two independent teams to cross-validate findings","The testers must obtain written authorization twice, once from IT and once from legal, before beginning"],"c":1,"why":"In a double-blind test, both the attackers (testers) and the defenders (blue team) are kept unaware of the exercise, which validates both attack technique effectiveness and the organization's actual detection/response capability. Option A describes a single-blind (zero-knowledge only for defenders) test, and C and D are fabricated procedural descriptions, not defining characteristics of double-blind testing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A development team wants to identify a SQL injection vulnerability that only manifests when unsanitized input reaches a database query during actual program execution, rather than being visible from analyzing the source code alone. Which testing approach is most appropriate?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Manual secure code review","Software composition analysis"],"c":1,"why":"DAST tests the running application by sending malicious inputs and observing actual behavior, making it effective at catching injection flaws that depend on runtime data flow. SAST and manual code review analyze source code without execution and may miss runtime-only issues, while software composition analysis focuses on identifying vulnerable third-party components, not injection logic.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A penetration testing team is hired to evaluate an organization's technical defenses while also assessing whether the internal security operations center (SOC) detects and responds to an active intrusion. Neither the testers nor the SOC analysts are given any advance notice or details about the engagement. Which type of test is being performed?","o":["Double-blind (zero-knowledge, two-sided) penetration test","White-box penetration test","Automated vulnerability scan","Tabletop exercise"],"c":0,"why":"A double-blind test withholds information from both the attackers and the defenders, providing a realistic measure of detection and incident response capability in addition to technical control effectiveness. White-box testing gives testers full knowledge, a vulnerability scan does not test human response, and a tabletop exercise is a discussion-based walkthrough, not an active technical test.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to identify known weaknesses in its systems by comparing installed software versions against a database of published vulnerabilities, without attempting to exploit any findings. Which activity best describes this?","o":["Vulnerability assessment","Penetration testing","Security audit","Threat modeling"],"c":0,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs known weaknesses using scanning tools without exploitation. Penetration testing goes further by actively exploiting findings; a security audit verifies compliance with policy/standards; threat modeling identifies potential threats during design, not existing flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A QA engineer feeds a target application massive volumes of randomly generated and malformed input to observe crashes, memory leaks, or unexpected behavior. Which limitation is most commonly associated with this testing technique?","o":["It cannot be automated and requires extensive manual test case design","It is effective at finding crashes but often provides little insight into the root cause or exploitability of the underlying vulnerability","It only works on compiled binaries and cannot test source code","It requires full knowledge of the internal application logic to generate effective test cases"],"c":1,"why":"Fuzz testing is highly automatable and requires no internal knowledge of the application, but while it excels at discovering crash conditions, it typically does not explain the root cause or confirm exploitability, requiring further analysis. The other options misstate fuzzing's automation level and knowledge requirements.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security team examines an application's source code line-by-line, without executing the program, to identify insecure coding patterns such as hardcoded credentials or SQL injection risks. This is an example of which testing technique?","o":["Dynamic application security testing (DAST)","Static application security testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source code without executing it, making it ideal for finding coding flaws early. DAST tests a running application; fuzz testing sends malformed input to a running program; penetration testing simulates real-world attacks against a live system.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During an application security assessment, a tester sends malformed, oversized, and unexpected input strings directly to an API's parameters without any knowledge of the underlying source code, looking for crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions. Which technique is being used?","o":["Fuzz testing","Static application security testing (SAST)","Interactive application security testing (IAST)","Regression testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing injects random, malformed, or boundary-violating input to trigger unexpected behavior without requiring source code access. SAST analyzes source/binary code without execution, IAST uses runtime instrumentation with code visibility, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality, not that inputs cause failures.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A cloud service provider offers its customers a SOC 2 Type II report. What does this report provide that a SOC 2 Type I report does not?","o":["Evidence that controls are suitably designed at a single point in time","An unqualified opinion on the financial statements of the service provider","Evidence of the operating effectiveness of controls over a defined period of time, typically six months to a year","A guarantee that no security incidents occurred during the reporting period"],"c":2,"why":"A Type II report tests operating effectiveness of controls over an observation period, while a Type I report only assesses design suitability at a specific point in time. SOC 2 does not address financial statements (that is SOC 1/SSAE 18 financial focus) and no audit report can guarantee zero incidents occurred.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to evaluate an internally developed web application without any prior knowledge of its source code, architecture, or credentials, simulating an external attacker's perspective. Which testing approach BEST describes this engagement?","o":["White-box testing","Gray-box testing","Black-box testing","Static application security testing (SAST)"],"c":2,"why":"Black-box testing simulates an external attacker with no internal knowledge of the system. White-box testing provides full internal knowledge (including source code), gray-box provides partial knowledge, and SAST is a code-analysis technique rather than a testing perspective.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization periodically runs scripted, simulated user actions—such as logging into a banking application and checking an account balance—to verify that the application is functioning correctly and available. What is this technique called?","o":["Misuse case testing","Synthetic transactions","Fuzz testing","Interface testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user activity to proactively monitor availability and performance of an application. Misuse case testing explores abuse scenarios; fuzz testing sends random/invalid input; interface testing verifies communication between system components.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization is evaluating a cloud service provider and needs assurance that the provider's security, availability, and confidentiality controls were not only suitably designed but also operated effectively over a continuous six-month period. Which report should the organization request?","o":["SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 3 report"],"c":0,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report tests operating effectiveness of controls over a defined period, whereas Type I only attests to the design of controls at a single point in time. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 provides a general-use summary without the detailed testing results needed here.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During a NIST SP 800-53A-based control assessment, an assessor reviews system configuration files, interviews the system administrator, and executes a script to verify that account lockout thresholds are enforced. This combination of activities represents the use of which assessment methods?","o":["Examine only","Interview and test only, since reviewing files is a form of interviewing","Examine, interview, and test, applied together to corroborate assessment findings","Test only, since automated verification is the authoritative method"],"c":2,"why":"NIST SP 800-53A defines three complementary assessment methods—examine (reviewing documents/configurations), interview (discussing with personnel), and test (exercising the mechanism)—and using all three together increases assurance and corroborates findings. Reviewing configuration files is examine, not interview, and relying on a single method reduces assurance compared to using multiple methods.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A company wants an independent auditor's report confirming that a cloud service provider's controls were suitably designed AND operated effectively over a period of time. Which report type should the company request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3 Type I","A vulnerability scan report"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the design and operating effectiveness of controls related to security, availability, and other Trust Services Criteria over a review period. Type I reports only assess design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and vulnerability scans don't provide assurance over control operation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During a security assessment, an analyst uses a tool that analyzes an application's source code for vulnerabilities without executing the program. Which testing methodology is being used?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source code or binaries without executing the application, identifying vulnerabilities like insecure coding patterns early in development. DAST tests a running application, fuzz testing sends malformed input to a running program, and IAST combines runtime monitoring with instrumentation during execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security team wants to proactively detect functional failures or performance degradation in a production e-commerce checkout process before real customers are affected. They configure automated scripts that periodically simulate a full purchase transaction end-to-end and alert on failures or latency thresholds. What is this technique called?","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring","Real user monitoring (RUM)","Fuzz testing","Log correlation analysis"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transaction monitoring uses scripted, predefined actions run at intervals against production to proactively detect issues before real users encounter them. Real user monitoring passively observes actual user sessions rather than simulating them, fuzz testing targets input handling for security flaws, and log correlation is reactive analysis of existing event data.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"To provide continuous assurance that a public-facing e-commerce checkout process remains functional and responsive between formal assessment cycles, a security team configures scripted transactions that simulate real user purchases at scheduled intervals and alert on failures or excessive latency. This technique is best described as which of the following?","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring","Fuzz testing","Misuse case testing","Interface testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions are scripted, simulated actions that continuously exercise application functionality to detect performance or availability issues in near real time. Fuzz testing sends malformed input to find defects, misuse case testing explores abuse scenarios, and interface testing validates data exchange between components—none of which describe scheduled simulated user transactions for ongoing monitoring.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to continuously verify that a critical e-commerce transaction path (login, add to cart, checkout) functions correctly and within acceptable performance thresholds, even during periods of low real user traffic. Which technique is MOST appropriate?","o":["Penetration testing","Synthetic transactions","Misuse case testing","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate user actions on a scheduled basis to proactively monitor availability and performance of critical business processes, independent of actual user traffic. Penetration testing assesses security weaknesses, misuse case testing explores abuse scenarios, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality after code changes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A SIEM platform establishes a baseline of normal login times, source locations, and data-transfer volumes for each user account over 30 days. It later generates an alert when an account's activity deviates significantly from its established baseline, even though no known attack signature matched. What detection method does this describe?","o":["Statistical anomaly-based (behavioral) detection","Signature-based detection","Misuse detection","Rule-based pattern matching against known indicators"],"c":0,"why":"Statistical anomaly-based detection flags deviations from an established behavioral baseline, catching previously unknown threats. Signature-based, misuse, and rule-based pattern matching all rely on comparison to known attack signatures or indicators, which would not trigger on a novel deviation with no matching pattern.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a disaster recovery test, participants gather in a conference room to walk through the recovery plan step-by-step, discussing roles and responsibilities without actually activating any systems. This is known as a:","o":["Parallel test","Full interruption test","Tabletop exercise","Simulation test"],"c":2,"why":"A tabletop exercise is a discussion-based walkthrough of the plan with no actual system activation. A simulation test involves acting out a scenario more actively; a parallel test activates alternate systems alongside production; a full interruption test shuts down primary operations entirely.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security analyst reviewing SIEM alert data notices that the security operations center is spending most of its time investigating alerts that turn out to be benign, while some true incidents are being missed. Which metric should the analyst prioritize improving through better correlation rules and tuning?","o":["Mean time to detect (MTTD)","False positive rate","Recovery time objective (RTO)","Number of total alerts generated per day"],"c":1,"why":"A high false positive rate directly causes analyst fatigue and missed true positives, so tuning correlation rules to reduce false positives addresses the root problem. MTTD measures detection speed rather than alert accuracy, RTO is a business continuity recovery metric, and simply reducing total alert volume without addressing accuracy could suppress true positives as well.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A CISSP is designing a security audit program and must decide who should perform an audit intended to provide the MOST objective assurance to external stakeholders such as regulators and business partners. Which audit type BEST meets this need?","o":["Internal audit performed by the IT department","Self-assessment performed by system owners","External audit performed by an independent third party","Internal audit performed by the security team"],"c":2,"why":"External audits conducted by independent third parties provide the highest level of objectivity and credibility to external stakeholders because the auditors have no organizational bias or conflict of interest. Internal audits and self-assessments, while valuable for internal improvement, lack the independence needed for external assurance.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During an authorized penetration test, the rules of engagement explicitly limit scope to a specific web application and prohibit any activity against the internal corporate network. While testing, the tester discovers a vulnerability in the web application that could allow pivoting into the excluded internal network. What should the tester do first?","o":["Stop before exploiting the pivot, document the finding, and immediately notify the designated point of contact for guidance","Exploit the vulnerability to fully demonstrate business impact on the internal network","Expand testing into the internal network since the vulnerability was discovered legitimately","Publicly disclose the finding to pressure the organization into fixing it quickly"],"c":0,"why":"Testers must strictly adhere to the authorized scope defined in the rules of engagement; discovering an out-of-scope path requires immediate reporting and written authorization before proceeding further. Exploiting or expanding scope without approval exceeds legal authorization, and public disclosure violates confidentiality and engagement terms.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which type of security assessment is typically performed by an independent third party to provide unbiased assurance to external stakeholders, such as regulators or customers, that controls meet a defined standard?","o":["Internal audit","External audit","Self-assessment","Configuration review"],"c":1,"why":"An external audit is conducted by an independent third party and provides unbiased assurance to outside stakeholders. Internal audits and self-assessments are performed by the organization's own staff and carry less independence; a configuration review is a narrower technical check, not a full audit.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A penetration tester is given only the target organization's public domain name and no internal network diagrams, credentials, or system documentation. Which type of testing approach is being used?","o":["White-box testing","Black-box testing","Gray-box testing","Crystal-box testing"],"c":1,"why":"Black-box testing simulates an external attacker with no prior knowledge of the target environment. White-box provides full internal knowledge, and gray-box provides partial knowledge; 'crystal-box' is not a standard testing term.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A vulnerability scan identifies a critical vulnerability in a legacy application that cannot be patched due to vendor discontinuation. The organization implements network segmentation and enhanced monitoring as compensating controls. What should happen NEXT in the vulnerability management lifecycle?","o":["Close the vulnerability finding since compensating controls are in place","Re-scan to remove the vulnerability from future reports","Document the residual risk and formally accept it through the risk management process","Immediately decommission the application without further action"],"c":2,"why":"When a vulnerability cannot be fully remediated, the residual risk introduced by compensating controls must be formally documented and accepted by appropriate risk owners through the risk management process. Simply closing the finding or removing it from reports ignores ongoing risk, and decommissioning may not be feasible or immediately necessary if compensating controls sufficiently reduce risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A CISO is explaining to executive management the fundamental difference between a vulnerability assessment and a penetration test on the same set of systems. Which statement best captures that difference?","o":["A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs potential weaknesses without exploiting them, while a penetration test actively exploits weaknesses to determine real-world business impact","A vulnerability assessment always requires source code access, while a penetration test never does","A vulnerability assessment is performed only by external third parties, while a penetration test is always performed internally","A vulnerability assessment tests availability controls only, while a penetration test tests confidentiality controls only"],"c":0,"why":"Vulnerability assessments enumerate and prioritize weaknesses using scanning and analysis without exploitation, whereas penetration tests go further by actively exploiting findings to validate exploitability and measure actual impact. The other statements misstate access requirements, performer roles, and control-type scope, none of which define the actual distinction.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"As part of an account management review, an auditor discovers several user accounts that have not been logged into for over six months but remain active with full privileges. What is the MOST appropriate immediate recommendation?","o":["Increase the password complexity requirements for all accounts","Disable or deactivate the inactive accounts and investigate their necessity","Grant the accounts additional privileges to improve usability","Ignore the finding since the accounts have not caused any incidents"],"c":1,"why":"Inactive accounts with standing privileges represent unnecessary attack surface and should be disabled and reviewed per the principle of least privilege. Increasing password complexity doesn't address the risk of unused accounts, granting more privileges worsens the exposure, and ignoring the finding leaves a security gap unaddressed.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which type of code analysis examines an application's source code for vulnerabilities without executing the program?","o":["Dynamic analysis","Static analysis","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"Static analysis reviews source code or binaries without running the program. Dynamic analysis and fuzz testing require the application to be executing, and penetration testing is a broader security exercise, not a code-review technique.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the primary purpose of conducting a tabletop exercise as part of security assessment activities?","o":["To physically test failover of production systems during a live outage","To validate incident response plans and team coordination through discussion-based scenarios without disrupting live systems","To perform automated vulnerability scanning against production networks","To measure code coverage of unit tests in the software development lifecycle"],"c":1,"why":"Tabletop exercises are discussion-based sessions where team members walk through simulated incident scenarios to validate plans, roles, and communication without impacting live systems. The other options describe live failover testing, vulnerability scanning, and software testing metrics, which are distinct assessment activities.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A quality assurance team is evaluating code coverage for a critical function containing multiple if/else decision branches. They want a metric that requires every possible outcome of each decision point (true and false) to be exercised at least once during testing, providing stronger assurance than simply executing every line of code once. Which coverage metric are they targeting?","o":["Branch (decision) coverage","Statement coverage","Path coverage","Condition/decision coverage combined with full path enumeration"],"c":0,"why":"Branch coverage requires that each decision point's possible outcomes (true/false) be tested at least once, which is stronger than statement coverage (which only requires each line to execute) but less exhaustive than full path coverage, which requires testing every possible route through the code, an impractical goal for complex logic.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to verify that its production web application correctly processes real-world user transactions on an ongoing basis. Which testing technique BEST accomplishes this?","o":["Synthetic transactions","Static code review","Vulnerability scanning","Log correlation"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user actions against a live system to continuously validate functionality and performance. The other options assess code, known vulnerabilities, or historical events rather than ongoing transaction behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An auditor reviewing system logs notices that critical authentication logs from a domain controller were automatically purged after 7 days due to default log rotation settings, despite a regulatory requirement to retain them for one year. What is the MOST significant issue this reveals?","o":["The domain controller has insufficient processing power for log analysis","The organization's log retention configuration does not align with compliance requirements","The logs were likely tampered with by an insider threat","The SIEM solution has failed to detect brute-force login attempts"],"c":1,"why":"The core issue is a misalignment between technical configuration (7-day rotation) and regulatory retention mandates (one year), which is a compliance and log management failure. There is no evidence presented of tampering, insider threat, or SIEM detection failure—those are unsupported assumptions not indicated by the scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a security assessment, an auditor sends structured questions to system owners asking them to describe their access control procedures. Which assessment technique is being used?","o":["Penetration testing","Log review","Questionnaire/interview","Vulnerability scanning"],"c":2,"why":"Questionnaires and interviews gather information directly from personnel about processes and controls. Penetration testing and vulnerability scanning are technical tests, and log review examines recorded system activity, not personnel input.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A software development team wants to verify that a newly added feature has not negatively impacted previously working functionality after a code change. Which type of testing should be performed?","o":["Regression testing","Penetration testing","Fuzz testing","Synthetic monitoring"],"c":0,"why":"Regression testing re-executes previously passed test cases after changes to confirm that existing functionality still works as expected. Penetration testing focuses on security vulnerabilities, fuzz testing sends random/malformed inputs to find crashes, and synthetic monitoring simulates user transactions for availability/performance rather than verifying code changes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of a vulnerability assessment?","o":["To exploit weaknesses and gain unauthorized access","To identify and prioritize known security weaknesses in systems","To simulate a real-world attacker's full attack chain","To evaluate employee awareness of phishing"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies, classifies, and prioritizes known weaknesses without actively exploiting them. Exploitation and full attack simulation describe penetration testing, and phishing awareness is a separate security awareness testing activity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A software team wants to test how their application handles unexpected, malformed, or random input data to uncover crashes or memory errors. Which technique should they use?","o":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Interface testing","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing feeds invalid or random data to an application to reveal crashes, memory leaks, or unexpected behavior. Regression testing checks for new defects after changes, interface testing validates data exchange between components, and misuse case testing focuses on abuse scenarios rather than malformed input specifically.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization is evaluating a cloud service provider's internal controls over security, availability, and confidentiality for use by customers and auditors. Which report should the provider supply?","o":["SOC 1 report","SOC 2 report","Penetration test report","Business impact analysis"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 report addresses controls relevant to security, availability, processing integrity, confidentiality, and privacy, making it appropriate for this evaluation. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and a penetration test report or BIA addresses different concerns.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"After deploying a patch to fix a security vulnerability, the security team re-runs previously passed test cases to ensure the fix did not break existing functionality. What is this activity called?","o":["Regression testing","Misuse case testing","Synthetic monitoring","Static analysis"],"c":0,"why":"Regression testing re-executes existing test cases after a change to confirm that previously working functionality still operates correctly. The other options describe unrelated testing methods focused on abuse cases, live transaction monitoring, or code review without execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A software security team wants to identify vulnerabilities in an application's source code before it is compiled, without executing the program. Which testing technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source, byte, or binary code without executing the application, making it ideal for early-stage code review. DAST and penetration testing require a running application, and fuzz testing injects malformed input at runtime rather than analyzing code structure.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to identify known vulnerabilities in its network devices without attempting to exploit them. Which testing activity best matches this requirement?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability assessment","Social engineering assessment","Red team exercise"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs known weaknesses using scanning tools without actively exploiting them. Penetration testing and red team exercises go further by attempting exploitation, and social engineering assessment targets human factors, not technical vulnerabilities.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a penetration test, the tester is given full knowledge of the target's source code, network diagrams, and credentials before testing begins. This is an example of which testing approach?","o":["Black box testing","White box testing","Gray box testing","Double-blind testing"],"c":1,"why":"White box testing provides the tester with complete knowledge of the environment, including source code and architecture. Black box testing provides no internal knowledge, gray box provides partial knowledge, and double-blind testing hides the test from both the tester's target and often internal staff monitoring.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of reviewing security logs on a regular basis?","o":["To satisfy regulatory retention requirements only","To detect anomalous activity and potential security incidents","To reduce the storage cost of log files","To generate compliance reports for auditors"],"c":1,"why":"The primary security purpose of log review is to identify suspicious or anomalous activity that may indicate a security incident. Retention, storage cost, and compliance reporting are secondary benefits, not the main security objective.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization hires a penetration testing firm and gives the testers full knowledge of the network architecture, source code, and credentials, but does not inform the internal SOC team that a test will occur. What best describes this testing approach?","o":["Double-blind test","White-box test","Gray-box test","Black-box test"],"c":1,"why":"White-box (full knowledge) testing gives testers complete internal information about the target. The scenario is not double-blind because only the SOC's awareness is hidden, not the testers' knowledge; gray-box implies partial knowledge, and black-box implies no internal information at all.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization requests a third-party attestation report from its cloud service provider to satisfy customers that security controls over availability and confidentiality have been operating effectively over the preceding twelve months, not merely designed correctly. Which report type should the provider furnish?","o":["SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 1 report focused on financial reporting controls","SOC 3 report intended for general public distribution"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report tests and reports on the operating effectiveness of controls over a period of time (typically 6-12 months), whereas Type I only assesses design suitability at a point in time; SOC 1 addresses controls relevant to financial reporting, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary lacking the detailed control testing results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A software development team wants to identify security flaws in application code before it is compiled and executed. Which technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic application security testing (DAST)","Static application security testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source code or binaries without executing the program, making it suitable for finding flaws before runtime. DAST and fuzz testing require the application to be running, and penetration testing typically occurs on a deployed system.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During a routine log review, a security analyst notices repeated failed login attempts from a single external IP address across multiple user accounts within a short time window. This pattern is most indicative of which activity?","o":["A password spraying attack","A distributed denial-of-service attack","A SQL injection attempt","A buffer overflow attack"],"c":0,"why":"Password spraying involves attempting a small number of common passwords across many accounts from a single source, producing exactly this log pattern. DoS attacks target availability rather than authentication, and SQL injection/buffer overflow attacks would appear in application or network logs, not authentication logs.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A CISO wants to measure both the external attack surface and the real-world detection and response capability of the internal security operations center. The engagement must ensure that the SOC has no advance knowledge that testing will occur, and the testers are given no internal documentation or credentials. Which engagement type meets these requirements?","o":["White-box test conducted with full network diagrams shared with the testing team","Single-blind test where testers receive no information but the SOC is notified beforehand","Double-blind test where neither the testers nor the SOC are given advance information","Gray-box test where testers are given limited architecture documentation only"],"c":2,"why":"A double-blind (zero-knowledge) test withholds information from both the attackers and the defenders, making it the only option that validates genuine detection and incident response performance; single-blind notifies the SOC in advance, and white-/gray-box tests provide the testing team internal knowledge, which is irrelevant to the SOC-awareness requirement.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A company evaluating a cloud service provider requests an independent report describing the design and operating effectiveness of the provider's security controls over a six-month period. Which report should the company request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of controls over an extended period (typically 6-12 months), which matches the requirement. Type I reports only assess design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report without detailed testing results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which type of test involves sending unexpected, malformed, or random data to an application to identify how it handles unexpected input?","o":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Interface testing","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing feeds malformed or random data into an application to uncover crashes, memory leaks, or unexpected behavior. Regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality, interface testing checks communication between components, and misuse case testing models attacker behavior conceptually rather than through random data injection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security team analyzes an application's source code line-by-line using an automated tool without executing the program, flagging a potential SQL injection vulnerability in a database query construction routine. This approach is best described as which testing technique, and what is its most significant limitation?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST); it cannot analyze code that is not exposed through a running interface","Static Application Security Testing (SAST); it often produces a high false-positive rate and cannot detect runtime or configuration-based issues","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST); it requires production traffic to generate findings","Fuzz testing; it can only be applied to compiled binaries rather than source code"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source or byte code without execution, making it effective for early-lifecycle detection of coding flaws like SQLi, but it commonly yields false positives and misses issues that only manifest at runtime (e.g., misconfigurations); DAST requires a running application, IAST requires instrumented runtime execution, and fuzzing targets running inputs, not static code review.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"To continuously validate that a critical e-commerce checkout process is functioning correctly from an end-user perspective, a security team configures automated scripts that simulate user transactions at regular intervals from multiple geographic locations. This technique is best described as:","o":["Interface testing","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Misuse case testing","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transaction monitoring uses scripted, simulated user interactions to proactively verify availability and performance of critical functions. Interface testing focuses on data exchange between components, misuse case testing explores abuse scenarios, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality rather than continuous monitoring.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An auditor reviews a company's access control policies, interviews staff, and inspects configuration settings to determine whether controls are operating as intended. This activity is best described as a:","o":["Vulnerability scan","Security audit","Penetration test","Threat model"],"c":1,"why":"A security audit involves systematic review of policies, procedures, and controls—often through documentation review, interviews, and inspection—to verify compliance and effectiveness. Vulnerability scans and penetration tests are technical testing activities, and threat modeling identifies potential threats rather than assessing control effectiveness.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A vulnerability researcher constructs malformed protocol messages by studying the target protocol's formal specification and building test cases from scratch that conform to, but deliberately violate, expected grammar rules, rather than modifying captured legitimate traffic. This fuzzing approach is known as:","o":["Mutation-based fuzzing","Generation-based fuzzing","Black-box regression testing","Boundary value analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Generation-based fuzzing builds inputs from a protocol or file format specification, allowing deeper protocol coverage than modifying existing samples; mutation-based fuzzing instead takes valid captured inputs and randomly alters them, and the other two options are unrelated testing techniques not specific to fuzzing methodology.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team runs an automated tool that scans network hosts for known CVEs and misconfigurations, producing a report of potential weaknesses without attempting to exploit them. Which activity does this describe?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability assessment","Red team exercise","Security audit"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs potential weaknesses using automated scanning without exploitation. Penetration testing goes further by actively exploiting findings, a red team exercise simulates a full adversarial campaign, and a security audit verifies compliance with policies/standards rather than scanning for technical flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security tester feeds an application large volumes of malformed, random, or unexpected input to observe crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions. This technique is known as:","o":["Fuzz testing","Static code analysis","Interface testing","Use case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing automatically generates invalid or random input to discover how software handles unexpected data, often revealing buffer overflows and crashes. Static analysis examines code without execution, interface testing focuses on component interactions, and use case testing validates expected functional behavior rather than abnormal input handling.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which metric would be MOST useful for measuring the effectiveness of a security awareness training program over time?","o":["Number of firewall rules changed per month","Percentage of employees who click on simulated phishing emails","Average CPU utilization of security appliances","Number of vulnerabilities patched per quarter"],"c":1,"why":"The click rate on simulated phishing emails directly measures user susceptibility to social engineering and the effectiveness of awareness training. The other metrics relate to unrelated technical or operational areas, not user security behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An e-commerce company wants to proactively detect degradation in checkout functionality on its production environment before real customers are affected, without waiting for actual user traffic to reveal problems. Which technique should be implemented?","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring using scripted simulated purchases run on a schedule","Real user monitoring (RUM) that passively observes actual customer sessions","Chaos engineering experiments that randomly terminate production services","Static code analysis integrated into the CI/CD pipeline"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions use scripted, repeatable simulated interactions executed against production systems on a schedule to proactively surface functional or performance issues before real users encounter them; RUM is passive and reactive, chaos engineering intentionally induces failures for resilience testing, and static code analysis examines code rather than live production behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants its developers to analyze application source code for insecure coding patterns (e.g., hardcoded credentials, SQL injection-prone constructs) before the application is compiled and deployed. Which testing technique best fits this requirement?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST) in production"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source code (or binaries) without executing the program, making it ideal for pre-deployment code review. DAST tests a running application externally, fuzzing sends malformed input to a running system, and IAST in production requires a live, deployed application—none analyze raw source code prior to compilation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An assessor designs test cases that specifically attempt to exploit an application in ways it was never intended to be used, such as submitting negative values into a quantity field or bypassing a multi-step workflow. This is an example of:","o":["Regression testing","Misuse case testing","Interface testing","Code review"],"c":1,"why":"Misuse case testing (negative testing) intentionally explores how a system responds to abuse or unintended use, complementing normal use case validation. Regression testing checks for unintended side effects of changes, interface testing examines data exchange points, and code review analyzes source code rather than runtime behavior under abuse.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to verify that its disaster recovery plan will function correctly without disrupting live production systems. Which test type is MOST appropriate?","o":["Full interruption test","Simulation test","Parallel test","Checklist review"],"c":2,"why":"A parallel test runs recovery operations at an alternate site alongside normal production, validating functionality without disrupting live systems. A full interruption test actually halts production, a simulation test is a walkthrough of scenarios without activating systems, and a checklist review is a basic documentation check rather than a functional test.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"To reduce alert fatigue caused by a high volume of alerts, an analyst raises the detection threshold on the organization's intrusion detection system, resulting in fewer alerts overall. What is the most likely unintended security consequence of this change?","o":["An increase in the false negative rate, allowing more actual attacks to go undetected","An increase in the mean time to detect for all alert categories uniformly","A decrease in the signal-to-noise ratio across all sensors","An increase in the number of true positive alerts generated per day"],"c":0,"why":"Raising the detection threshold reduces sensitivity, which lowers false positives but increases the likelihood that genuine malicious activity falls below the threshold and is missed (false negatives); the other options either misstate the direction of impact or are not the direct consequence of threshold tuning.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A penetration tester is given full knowledge of the target's network diagrams, source code, and credentials before beginning the engagement. This most closely describes which testing approach?","o":["Black-box testing","Gray-box testing","White-box testing","Double-blind testing"],"c":2,"why":"White-box testing provides the tester with complete internal knowledge of the system, simulating an insider or highly informed attacker. Black-box testing provides no prior knowledge, gray-box provides partial knowledge, and double-blind testing hides the exercise from the target organization's staff as well, which is unrelated to the tester's knowledge level.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A CISO wants to track how effectively the security assessment program identifies weaknesses before they lead to incidents. Which metric would be MOST useful for this purpose?","o":["Number of firewall rules changed per quarter","Mean time to detect (MTTD) vulnerabilities through internal testing versus external discovery","Total number of employees who completed security awareness training","Average CPU utilization during vulnerability scans"],"c":1,"why":"Comparing internally discovered vulnerabilities to those found externally (e.g., by attackers or third parties) directly measures the effectiveness of the assessment program at proactively identifying risk. The other metrics relate to operational or training activity but do not measure the assessment program's detection effectiveness.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"Management is evaluating two proposed security testing engagements and needs to correctly scope the statement of work. Which statement accurately differentiates a vulnerability assessment from a penetration test?","o":["A vulnerability assessment actively exploits identified weaknesses to demonstrate business impact, while a penetration test only catalogs and rates them","A penetration test actively exploits identified vulnerabilities to demonstrate the real-world extent of potential compromise, while a vulnerability assessment identifies and prioritizes weaknesses without exploitation","The two terms are interchangeable and differ only in the length of the final report","A vulnerability assessment always requires authenticated access, while a penetration test is always performed without any credentials"],"c":1,"why":"A penetration test goes beyond identification by actively exploiting vulnerabilities to prove impact and depth of compromise, whereas a vulnerability assessment focuses on discovering, cataloging, and risk-rating weaknesses without exploitation; the remaining options either reverse this distinction or introduce false absolute requirements about credentials.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A company evaluating a cloud service provider requests a report that includes an independent auditor's opinion on the operating effectiveness of security controls over a six-month review period. Which report should the company request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","ISO 27001 certificate"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of controls related to security, availability, and other trust criteria over a defined period, which is what's needed to assess ongoing control performance. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, Type I reports only assess design at a point in time (not operating effectiveness over time), and an ISO 27001 certificate confirms ISMS certification but doesn't provide the same detailed control-testing evidence.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During API security testing, a tester changes the numeric object identifier in an authenticated request's URL path from their own record ID to a sequentially adjacent ID and successfully retrieves another user's private data, despite having no authorization to view it. This finding indicates which class of vulnerability being validated by the test?","o":["Injection flaw due to improper input sanitization","Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA), also known as an Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR)","Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) due to missing anti-forgery tokens","Security misconfiguration from default credentials being left active"],"c":1,"why":"Manipulating an object reference to access another user's resource without proper server-side authorization checks is the hallmark of Broken Object Level Authorization/IDOR; it does not involve malicious input execution (injection), forged cross-site requests (CSRF), or default configuration settings (misconfiguration).","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A quarterly vulnerability scan against an externally facing legacy web application reports a critical SQL injection finding. Before opening a costly emergency change ticket, the security team wants to confirm the finding is a true positive and truly exploitable, without risking disruption to the live production environment. Which approach best achieves this goal?","o":["Immediately take the production application offline until a patch is available","Re-run the automated scanner with an updated signature database and accept the result if it repeats","Manually attempt crafted SQL injection payloads against a staging clone of the application that mirrors production configuration and data structure","Perform a full black-box penetration test directly against the live production instance"],"c":2,"why":"Manual exploitation attempts against a representative non-production clone validate true exploitability while protecting the live system; rescanning alone cannot confirm exploitability, testing live production risks outages, and taking the app offline is an overreaction before validation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of continuous log review and monitoring as part of a security assessment program?","o":["To replace the need for periodic penetration testing","To detect anomalous activity and policy violations in near real time","To satisfy annual compliance audit requirements only","To generate metrics for executive dashboards without operational use"],"c":1,"why":"Continuous log review's core security purpose is early detection of suspicious or anomalous activity, enabling timely response. It complements rather than replaces penetration testing, and while it may support compliance and reporting, those are secondary benefits, not the primary purpose.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A QA engineer sends large volumes of randomly generated, malformed, and unexpected input to an application's input fields to identify crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions. This technique is known as:","o":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing involves feeding random or malformed data into an application to uncover crashes, memory corruption, or unexpected behavior. Regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality, synthetic transactions simulate normal user behavior for performance monitoring, and misuse case testing focuses on modeling intentional abuse scenarios rather than random malformed input.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security team must assess a third-party compiled binary application for memory corruption vulnerabilities. The vendor will not provide source code. Which testing technique is most appropriate for identifying a buffer overflow under these constraints?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST) performed on decompiled pseudocode","Software Composition Analysis (SCA) to check for known vulnerable libraries","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST) that fuzzes the application's input interfaces at runtime","Manual secure code review focused on unsafe string handling functions"],"c":2,"why":"Dynamic testing/fuzzing exercises the running binary with malformed inputs and can reveal memory corruption without needing source code; SAST and manual code review require source, and SCA only flags known vulnerable components, not runtime memory errors.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During disaster recovery test planning, the team decides to actually shut down the primary production data center and fail over all operations to the alternate site to validate real-world recovery capability. This is an example of which type of DR test?","o":["Tabletop exercise","Simulation test","Parallel test","Full interruption test"],"c":3,"why":"A full interruption test involves actually stopping production operations at the primary site and shifting to the alternate site, representing the highest-risk and most realistic test. A tabletop exercise is discussion-based, a simulation test walks through a scenario without real failover, and a parallel test runs the alternate site alongside (not replacing) the primary site.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to simulate a realistic external attacker with zero prior knowledge of the network, while also ensuring the internal incident response and SOC teams are unaware a test is occurring, so their detection and response capabilities can be genuinely evaluated. Which type of penetration test best fits this requirement?","o":["White-box test with full network diagrams and credentials provided in advance","Gray-box test where the tester is given limited application-level credentials only","Double-blind (zero-knowledge) test in which neither the testers nor the defenders are informed of test details in advance","Announced black-box test where only the testing team lacks prior knowledge, but the SOC is notified of the test window"],"c":2,"why":"A double-blind test keeps both the attackers (testers) and defenders (SOC) uninformed, providing an authentic measure of detection and response; the other options either give the tester prior knowledge or forewarn the defenders, which invalidates the assessment of real-world detection capability.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security assessor wants to verify that a critical control—segregation of duties in the accounts payable process—is actually functioning as designed, rather than just confirming a policy document exists. Which assessment method provides the STRONGEST evidence of this?","o":["Reviewing the organization's written policy on segregation of duties","Interviewing the accounts payable manager about the process","Observing and testing actual transaction workflows and system access logs","Reviewing the organizational chart for the finance department"],"c":2,"why":"Directly observing and testing actual transactions and access logs provides empirical evidence that the control is operating effectively, not just documented. Policy review, interviews, and org charts only confirm intent or design, not actual operational effectiveness.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A company is selecting a cloud IaaS provider and must satisfy its external financial auditors that the provider's security controls (availability, confidentiality, and processing integrity) operated effectively over the preceding 12-month period, not just at a single point in time. Which report should the company request from the provider?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 3 report"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of Trust Services Criteria controls over an extended period, which is what the auditors need; Type I reports only assess design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary lacking the detailed testing evidence auditors require.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester captures live network traffic between a client and a proprietary industrial control protocol server, then randomly flips bits and alters field values within the captured packets before replaying them to the server to discover crash conditions. Which fuzzing technique is being used?","o":["Generation-based fuzzing","Mutation-based fuzzing","Model-based fuzzing derived from a formal protocol specification","Static taint-analysis fuzzing"],"c":1,"why":"Mutation-based (\"dumb\") fuzzing modifies existing valid captured inputs randomly to create malformed test cases; generation-based fuzzing builds inputs from a protocol grammar/model rather than mutating captured traffic, and taint analysis is a static code-tracing technique, not fuzzing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security manager wants a testing engagement that not only identifies weaknesses in an internet-facing application but also demonstrates the actual business impact by chaining vulnerabilities together to achieve data exfiltration. Which statement best distinguishes this engagement from a standard vulnerability assessment?","o":["A penetration test actively exploits identified weaknesses to prove real-world impact, whereas a vulnerability assessment only identifies, classifies, and prioritizes weaknesses without exploitation.","A vulnerability assessment always requires administrative credentials, while a penetration test is strictly performed with zero knowledge.","A penetration test is a passive review of configurations, while a vulnerability assessment involves active exploitation of systems.","Vulnerability assessments and penetration tests are functionally identical and differ only in the report template used."],"c":0,"why":"Penetration testing goes beyond identification by exploiting vulnerabilities to validate exploitability and business impact; vulnerability assessments stop at identification and risk-rating. The other options reverse or fabricate the distinction.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"Per NIST SP 800-53A assessment methodology, an assessor logs into a production access control system and actively attempts to access resources outside their authorized role to confirm that role-based access control enforcement functions as documented, rather than relying solely on policy documents or personnel statements. Which assessment method does this represent?","o":["Examine","Interview","Test","Trace"],"c":2,"why":"The \"Test\" method under SP 800-53A involves exercising one or more assessment objects (e.g., mechanisms, activities) under specified conditions to compare actual with expected behavior; \"Examine\" reviews documentation/artifacts, \"Interview\" gathers information from personnel, and \"Trace\" is not a defined 800-53A assessment method.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An application security team is evaluating two testing techniques: one analyzes the application's source code and binaries for insecure coding patterns before the application is ever executed, and the other interacts with the running application over HTTP without any visibility into the underlying code. Which pairing correctly matches these techniques to their capabilities?","o":["The first is DAST, which can pinpoint the exact vulnerable line of code; the second is SAST, which cannot see runtime behavior.","The first is SAST, which can pinpoint the exact vulnerable line of code but cannot detect runtime/configuration issues; the second is DAST, which detects runtime behavior but cannot map findings back to source code.","Both techniques are examples of IAST and produce identical results regardless of execution state.","The first is fuzz testing; the second is penetration testing, and both require full source code access."],"c":1,"why":"SAST (white-box) examines code/binaries statically and can locate exact vulnerable lines but misses runtime issues; DAST (black-box) tests the running application externally and finds runtime flaws but can't map to source location. The other options mismatch the definitions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An e-commerce company wants continuous assurance that its checkout workflow (login, add to cart, payment processing) remains functionally correct and available around the clock, even during periods of low real customer traffic overnight. Which monitoring technique should be implemented?","o":["Real user monitoring (RUM) that passively analyzes actual customer session data","Synthetic transaction monitoring that runs scripted end-to-end test transactions on a fixed schedule","Security information and event management (SIEM) log correlation across web server access logs","Threat hunting exercises performed quarterly by the security operations team"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions proactively simulate the full user workflow at regular intervals regardless of actual traffic volume, ensuring continuous functional and availability verification; RUM depends on real traffic (which may be absent overnight), SIEM log correlation is reactive/detective rather than proactive functional testing, and threat hunting addresses security investigation, not functional monitoring.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During scoping for an authorized penetration test, the client provides the testing team with a partial network diagram and limited internal credentials but withholds source code and full administrative access. This testing approach is best classified as:","o":["Black-box testing","White-box testing","Gray-box testing","Double-blind testing"],"c":2,"why":"Gray-box testing provides partial knowledge (some architecture/credentials) without full internal access or source code, simulating an insider or partially informed attacker. Black-box implies zero knowledge, white-box implies full knowledge, and double-blind refers to whether the defending team is aware of the test, not the tester's knowledge level.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During software security testing, a QA engineer designs test cases that ensure every possible outcome (true and false) of each conditional statement in the code has been executed at least once, in addition to covering every line. Which test coverage metric is being applied?","o":["Statement coverage","Branch (decision) coverage","Path coverage","Condition/decision coverage with multiple condition combinations (MC/DC)"],"c":1,"why":"Branch coverage specifically requires that each decision point's true and false outcomes are exercised, going beyond simple statement coverage; path coverage would require testing every possible route through the code (a much larger, often impractical set), and MC/DC additionally requires isolating the effect of each individual condition within compound decisions, which is not described here.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A customer requests assurance that a cloud provider's security controls were not only properly designed but also operated effectively over a six-month period. Which type of third-party assurance report satisfies this requirement?","o":["SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 1 Type I report","A vulnerability scan summary"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates both the design and the operating effectiveness of controls over a specified period (typically 6-12 months). SOC 2 Type I only assesses design at a single point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and a vulnerability scan is not an assurance/audit report.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A test engineer builds a fuzzing tool that constructs input packets strictly according to a documented protocol specification, systematically varying field values, lengths, and types based on that specification rather than mutating previously captured traffic. This approach is best described as:","o":["Mutation-based (dumb) fuzzing","Generation-based (smart) fuzzing","Regression testing","Passive vulnerability scanning"],"c":1,"why":"Generation-based fuzzing creates test cases from a model or specification of valid input structure, allowing more targeted and efficient coverage. Mutation-based fuzzing instead randomly alters existing valid samples without protocol awareness; the other options are unrelated testing types.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A penetration tester is given only the organization's public domain name and told to simulate an external attacker with no internal knowledge of network topology, credentials, or source code. This engagement is best described as which type of testing?","o":["White-box testing","Black-box testing","Gray-box testing","Crystal-box testing"],"c":1,"why":"Black-box testing simulates an attacker with no prior internal knowledge, relying solely on publicly available information. White-box provides full internal knowledge, and gray-box provides partial knowledge; 'crystal-box' is not a standard testing term.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"To continuously validate that a critical e-commerce checkout workflow remains available and functioning correctly from multiple geographic regions, a security team scripts automated transactions that simulate real user behavior at regular intervals and alert on failures or latency anomalies. This technique is known as:","o":["Log correlation analysis","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Misuse case testing","Static code analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transaction monitoring uses scripted, simulated user interactions to proactively test availability and performance of critical workflows. Log correlation reviews existing event data rather than generating test traffic, misuse case testing focuses on abuse scenarios during design, and static analysis examines source code, not live systems.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to identify vulnerabilities in a web application's source code before it is compiled and deployed, without executing the program. Which testing technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source or binary code for vulnerabilities without executing the application. DAST tests a running application, fuzz testing sends malformed input to a running system, and penetration testing exploits live systems—none of these examine code pre-execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization runs an automated tool that scans its network for known weaknesses, such as missing patches and misconfigurations, and produces a report listing them without attempting to exploit any of them. A separate team is later engaged to actively attempt to exploit these weaknesses to determine real-world impact. How are these two activities best distinguished?","o":["A vulnerability scan identifies and catalogs potential weaknesses without exploiting them, while a penetration test attempts to exploit vulnerabilities to demonstrate actual impact","A vulnerability scan exploits systems while a penetration test only produces a report of findings","Both activities are identical and interchangeable terms for the same process","A vulnerability scan requires written authorization while a penetration test does not"],"c":0,"why":"Vulnerability scanning is a passive, automated identification of potential issues, whereas penetration testing goes further by actively attempting exploitation to validate real-world risk; both require authorization, so option D is incorrect.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization is assessing a third-party REST API integration used to process payment data. Which testing focus would provide the MOST direct assurance against improper authorization allowing one authenticated user to access another user's payment records?","o":["Fuzzing the API's TLS handshake implementation","Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA) testing on API endpoints using different user tokens","Reviewing the API provider's SOC 2 Type I report","Performing a network-layer port scan against the API gateway"],"c":1,"why":"BOLA testing specifically verifies that authorization checks correctly restrict access to objects/records per authenticated identity, directly addressing horizontal privilege escalation risk. TLS fuzzing, a Type I audit report, and a port scan do not test object-level access control logic.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization runs an automated tool that scans its network and produces a report listing missing patches and misconfigured services, but does not attempt to exploit any of them. This activity is best classified as:","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability assessment","Red team exercise","Security audit"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs weaknesses without exploitation. Penetration testing and red team exercises actively exploit findings to demonstrate impact, and a security audit evaluates compliance against policies/standards rather than scanning for technical flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security analyst reviews an application's source code line by line, without compiling or running the program, to look for insecure coding patterns such as hardcoded credentials or improper input validation. Which testing technique does this describe?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source code without executing it, unlike DAST which tests a running application; fuzzing sends malformed input to a running system, and penetration testing involves active exploitation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A CISO wants a penetration test that also measures the effectiveness of the organization's SOC in detecting and responding to an active intrusion, ensuring the blue team's response is not influenced by advance knowledge of the test. Which rules-of-engagement model should be selected?","o":["Announced (white-box) testing with full disclosure to the SOC","Double-blind testing, where neither the SOC nor most staff are informed in advance","Blind testing, where only the target organization's management (not the testers) has full knowledge","Credentialed vulnerability scanning against production systems"],"c":1,"why":"Double-blind testing withholds knowledge from both the attacking team's target contacts (SOC/operations) and, to a degree, testers about defenses, providing a realistic measure of detection and response capability. Announced testing biases the SOC's behavior, blind testing (as defined) still informs the organization broadly, and vulnerability scanning doesn't test human/process detection at all.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A client requests a report from a cloud service provider that attests to the effectiveness of security controls over a six-month operating period, including evidence of consistent operation, rather than just a design assessment at a single point in time. Which report type satisfies this requirement?","o":["SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 1 Type I","ISO 27001 certificate"],"c":1,"why":"SOC 2 Type II evaluates control effectiveness over a period of time (e.g., 6-12 months), whereas Type I assesses control design at a single point in time. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and an ISO 27001 certificate confirms ISMS conformance but is not the same audit report type.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to identify known weaknesses in its systems by comparing installed software versions against a database of published vulnerabilities, without attempting to exploit any findings. Which security assessment technique BEST fits this description?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability scanning","Social engineering assessment","Red team exercise"],"c":1,"why":"Vulnerability scanning identifies and reports known weaknesses (e.g., missing patches) without exploitation. Penetration testing and red team exercises actively exploit findings, and social engineering targets human behavior, not software versions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Why do organizations regularly review system and security logs as part of an ongoing security assessment program?","o":["To reduce the amount of storage space consumed by log files","To detect anomalous activity and support timely incident investigation","To satisfy backup retention schedules for disaster recovery","To increase available network bandwidth for production systems"],"c":1,"why":"Log review is primarily performed to identify suspicious or anomalous behavior and provide evidence for investigations; the other options describe unrelated operational concerns, not the purpose of log review.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During disaster recovery test planning, management wants an exercise that requires no disruption to live production systems and involves stakeholders discussing their roles and responses to a simulated disaster scenario using the written DR plan. Which test type meets this requirement?","o":["Full interruption test","Parallel test","Simulation test","Tabletop exercise (structured walkthrough)"],"c":3,"why":"A tabletop exercise is a discussion-based review of the plan with no impact on production systems. A simulation test involves acting out response actions, a parallel test activates alternate systems alongside production, and a full interruption test actually takes down production systems.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a penetration test, the testing team is given full knowledge of the target's network diagrams, source code, and system credentials before testing begins. What type of test is this?","o":["Black box test","White box test","Gray box test","Double-blind test"],"c":1,"why":"A white box (or 'full knowledge') test provides testers complete internal information in advance. Black box testers have no prior knowledge, gray box testers have partial knowledge, and double-blind tests keep both testers and defenders unaware of the exercise.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A monitoring tool periodically executes scripted transactions that mimic typical user actions, such as logging in and submitting a form, against a production web application to verify it is functioning correctly and responding within expected time limits. What is this technique called?","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring","Static code analysis","Penetration testing","Log correlation"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions use scripted, simulated user interactions to proactively test availability and performance; the other options involve code review, active exploitation, or log analysis rather than simulated user behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"According to NIST SP 800-53A control assessment methodology, an assessor who reviews configuration files, policies, and architecture diagrams without interacting with personnel or executing the system is performing which assessment method?","o":["Interview","Examine","Test","Simulate"],"c":1,"why":"'Examine' involves reviewing, inspecting, or analyzing documentation and artifacts. 'Interview' involves discussions with personnel, 'Test' involves exercising the mechanism under controlled conditions, and 'Simulate' is not one of the three NIST SP 800-53A assessment methods (examine, interview, test).","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is a key advantage of static application security testing (SAST) over dynamic application security testing (DAST)?","o":["It can identify vulnerabilities in source code before the application is compiled or run","It tests the application in a live production environment","It requires no access to the application's source code","It can detect runtime configuration errors in the deployed environment"],"c":0,"why":"SAST examines source or binary code without executing the program, allowing vulnerabilities to be found early in development. DAST, by contrast, tests a running application and can catch runtime/configuration issues but requires the app to be executable, not source code access.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants independent, detailed assurance that a cloud service provider's security, availability, and confidentiality controls are both suitably designed and operating effectively over a period of time. Which report should the organization request?","o":["SOC 1 report","ISO 9001 certificate","SOC 2 Type II report","PCI DSS self-assessment questionnaire"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the design and operating effectiveness of controls over security, availability, and confidentiality over a review period; SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, ISO 9001 addresses quality management, and a PCI DSS SAQ is a self-assessment, not independent assurance.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security analyst regularly reviews system and application logs to identify unauthorized access attempts and unusual patterns of activity. This activity is an example of which security assessment practice?","o":["Penetration testing","Log review and analysis","Vulnerability scanning","Code review"],"c":1,"why":"Log review and analysis involves examining recorded system events to detect anomalies or security incidents. Penetration testing and vulnerability scanning are active testing techniques, and code review examines source code rather than log data.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution wants to continuously verify that its online banking application remains available and responsive from an end-user perspective, even when no real customers are actively logging complaints. Which technique is most appropriate?","o":["Synthetic transactions","Static code analysis","Misuse case testing","Regression testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user actions against a live production system to proactively monitor availability and performance. Static code analysis examines source code, misuse case testing models abuse scenarios during design, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality—none continuously monitor live production behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A tester sends large volumes of random, malformed, and unexpected input into an application's input fields to observe whether it crashes or behaves unpredictably. Which testing technique is being used?","o":["Fuzz testing","Static code review","Load testing","Interface usability testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzzing involves injecting random or malformed data to uncover crashes, memory issues, or unexpected behavior; static review examines code without execution, load testing measures performance under expected traffic, and usability testing evaluates user experience.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An e-commerce company uses automated scripts that simulate real user interactions—such as logging in and completing a purchase—on a regular schedule to verify that critical application functions remain available and correct. What is this technique called?","o":["Fuzz testing","Synthetic transactions","Misuse case testing","Interface testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user behavior on a scheduled basis to monitor availability and functional correctness. Fuzz testing sends malformed input to find defects, misuse case testing models attacker behavior, and interface testing focuses on API/UI boundaries rather than ongoing monitoring.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security operations team aggregates authentication logs, firewall logs, and IDS alerts into a single platform to correlate events and detect patterns indicative of a coordinated attack across multiple systems. This capability is best provided by:","o":["A vulnerability scanner","A Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system","A configuration management database (CMDB)","A data loss prevention (DLP) system"],"c":1,"why":"A SIEM centralizes log collection and correlates events across multiple sources to detect complex attack patterns. A vulnerability scanner identifies weaknesses, a CMDB tracks configuration items, and a DLP system focuses on preventing unauthorized data exfiltration rather than log correlation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During software testing, a report indicates that 85% of the application's source code lines were executed by the test suite. What metric does this percentage represent?","o":["Number of vulnerabilities discovered","Mean time to remediate defects","Code coverage","Defect density"],"c":2,"why":"Code coverage measures the proportion of source code exercised during testing, indicating how thoroughly the test suite examines the application; the other options measure unrelated aspects such as vulnerability counts or remediation timelines.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the primary purpose of an internal security audit compared to an external security audit?","o":["Internal audits are conducted by an independent third party to satisfy regulatory requirements","Internal audits are performed by the organization's own staff to assess compliance with internal policies and identify improvement areas","External audits are always less rigorous than internal audits","Internal audits replace the need for any external assessment"],"c":1,"why":"Internal audits are conducted by internal personnel to evaluate adherence to internal policies and controls, often as preparation for external audits. External audits, in contrast, are performed by independent third parties, often for regulatory or certification purposes, and are not inherently less rigorous.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An assessor reviews an organization's written policies, network diagrams, and system configuration files to evaluate control design, without interviewing staff or executing any technical tests. Which assessment method is being performed?","o":["Interview","Examine","Test","Vulnerability scanning"],"c":1,"why":"The 'examine' method involves reviewing documentation, artifacts, and configurations; 'interview' involves discussions with personnel, 'test' involves hands-on exercising of controls, and vulnerability scanning is a specific technical activity, not a general assessment method.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to identify vulnerabilities in a web application's source code before it is compiled, without executing the program. Which testing technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source code, bytecode, or binaries without executing the application, making it ideal for finding vulnerabilities early in development. DAST requires a running application, fuzzing sends malformed input to a running system, and penetration testing is a broader manual/automated exploitation exercise.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization is testing the boundaries between two software modules to ensure that data passed between them is correctly formatted and handled. What type of testing is being performed?","o":["Interface testing","Regression testing","Misuse case testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":0,"why":"Interface testing verifies that data exchanged between software components or modules is correctly formatted and processed at their boundaries. Regression testing checks that changes haven't broken existing functionality, misuse case testing models attacker abuse scenarios, and fuzz testing sends random/malformed input to find crashes or vulnerabilities.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During a penetration test, the testing team is given full knowledge of the target's network diagrams, source code, and credentials before beginning the engagement. This describes which type of test?","o":["Black-box testing","Gray-box testing","White-box testing","Double-blind testing"],"c":2,"why":"White-box (or clear-box) testing provides testers with complete internal knowledge of the environment, allowing for thorough analysis. Black-box testing provides no internal knowledge, gray-box provides partial knowledge, and double-blind testing hides the test from both testers and defenders.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A vulnerability management team runs two scans against the same set of servers: one using valid local administrator credentials supplied to the scanner, and one performed with no credentials from outside the network. The credentialed scan reports far more findings, including missing patches and misconfigured registry settings. Which statement BEST explains this difference?","o":["The credentialed scan can authenticate to the host and directly enumerate installed software, patch levels, and configuration settings, whereas the uncredentialed scan can only infer issues from externally observable network responses","The credentialed scan generates more network traffic, which triggers more false positives","The uncredentialed scan requires successful exploitation before it will report a finding, making it inherently less sensitive","Credentialed scans automatically bypass all firewall and IPS filtering, so more hosts are reachable"],"c":0,"why":"Credentialed scanning logs into the host and inspects local system state (patch databases, file versions, registry keys), yielding much deeper visibility than an uncredentialed scan that must infer vulnerabilities from network-exposed banners and behavior. The other options misstate how scanners operate.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants a third-party attestation that evaluates the design AND operating effectiveness of its cloud provider's security controls over a six-month period. Which report should the organization request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates both the design and operating effectiveness of controls over a specified period, providing assurance about ongoing control performance. Type I reports only assess design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report without detailed testing results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization is evaluating a cloud payroll provider and wants formal, independent assurance that the provider's security controls (not financial reporting controls) were suitably designed AND operated effectively over a six-month period. Which report should the organization request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 1 Type II","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II"],"c":3,"why":"SOC 2 addresses security/availability/confidentiality trust services criteria (not financial reporting, which is SOC 1), and a Type II report attests to operating effectiveness over a review period, whereas Type I only attests to design as of a point in time.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A QA engineer writes automated scripts that simulate real user transactions against a production e-commerce site every 15 minutes to detect performance degradation and availability issues before customers report them. This technique is best described as:","o":["Regression testing","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Misuse case testing","Interface testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user behavior on a live system to proactively detect performance or availability problems. Regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality, misuse case testing focuses on abuse scenarios, and interface testing validates data exchange between system components.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A monitoring team configures scripted transactions that log into a web application, perform a purchase, and log out every 15 minutes from multiple geographic locations, alerting if response times or error rates exceed thresholds—even when no real customers are actively using the site. What testing/monitoring technique is being described?","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring","Real user monitoring (RUM)","Fuzz testing","Regression testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions use scripted, simulated user activity to proactively detect availability and performance issues independent of actual traffic. RUM instead observes real user sessions; fuzzing and regression testing are unrelated to scripted availability checks.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following best differentiates a vulnerability assessment from a penetration test?","o":["A vulnerability assessment always requires administrative credentials, while a penetration test never does","A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs potential weaknesses, while a penetration test actively attempts to exploit them to demonstrate impact","A vulnerability assessment is performed only by external parties, while a penetration test is performed only internally","A vulnerability assessment tests physical security, while a penetration test tests only network security"],"c":1,"why":"Vulnerability assessments scan and enumerate potential weaknesses without exploitation, whereas penetration tests go further by actively exploiting vulnerabilities to prove real-world impact. The other options describe false or overly rigid distinctions not inherent to either methodology.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A static source code analysis tool found no issues in a web application, yet a later assessment discovered a SQL injection vulnerability that only appears when user input traverses several modules before reaching a dynamically constructed query. Which testing approach would have been MOST likely to detect this flaw?","o":["Dynamic application security testing (DAST) against the running application","A second, more thorough manual static code review","Fagan inspection of the design documents","Misuse case modeling during requirements analysis"],"c":0,"why":"DAST exercises the running application with actual malicious input and observes real behavior, making it effective at catching runtime data-flow issues that static analysis can miss when tainted data crosses multiple modules. The other options remain design/code-time activities that do not observe actual execution behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A software development team measures the percentage of code paths executed during automated testing to identify untested logic branches before release. This metric is known as:","o":["Code coverage analysis","Static analysis scoring","Attack surface analysis","Mutation testing"],"c":0,"why":"Code coverage analysis measures which lines, branches, or paths of code were exercised during testing, helping identify gaps in test suites. Static analysis scoring evaluates code quality without execution, attack surface analysis identifies exposed entry points, and mutation testing evaluates test suite quality by introducing deliberate code faults.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A QA report shows 100% statement coverage for a critical authorization module, yet a penetration tester finds an untested conditional branch that grants access when an exception is silently caught. Which coverage metric, if used instead, would have revealed this gap?","o":["Statement coverage","Branch (decision) coverage","Function coverage","Loop coverage"],"c":1,"why":"Statement coverage only confirms each line executed at least once; it does not guarantee both true and false outcomes of every decision were tested. Branch coverage specifically requires exercising all conditional outcomes, which would expose the untested exception-handling path.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security architect wants to verify that an API correctly validates input, handles authentication tokens, and returns appropriate error codes when interacting with a partner organization's system. Which type of testing is most appropriate?","o":["Interface testing","Regression testing","Misuse case testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":0,"why":"Interface testing validates that data exchange, authentication, and error handling between two systems or components function correctly according to specification. Regression testing checks for unintended side effects of changes, misuse case testing evaluates abuse scenarios, and fuzz testing sends random/malformed data to find crashes rather than validate normal interface behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization runs an automated tool that scans its network for known vulnerabilities, missing patches, and misconfigurations, then produces a report ranking findings by severity. What type of security assessment activity is this?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability assessment","Security audit","Risk assessment"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment uses automated tools to identify and rank known weaknesses without actively exploiting them. Penetration testing goes further by exploiting vulnerabilities, while audits and risk assessments are broader governance activities.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"Executive management wants a penetration test that evaluates not only the organization's technical defenses but also the incident response team's real-world detection and escalation capability, and does not want the IT and SOC staff informed in advance that a test is occurring. Which test type should be authorized?","o":["Blind test (testers have no prior knowledge, defenders are informed)","Double-blind test (neither testers nor defenders have prior knowledge)","Gray-box test with partial information shared with testers only","White-box test with full internal documentation provided to testers"],"c":1,"why":"A double-blind test keeps both the testing team and the defenders unaware, providing the most realistic evaluation of detection and response since staff cannot consciously or unconsciously prepare. A blind test still tips off defenders, and gray/white-box tests focus on tester knowledge of the environment, not defender awareness.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization's disaster recovery plan is evaluated by having key personnel walk through their responsibilities and discuss response actions during a simulated outage scenario, without actually activating any systems. This is an example of which DR test type?","o":["Full interruption test","Parallel test","Simulation (tabletop) test","Checklist test"],"c":2,"why":"A simulation or tabletop test involves personnel discussing and role-playing their responses to a scenario without executing actual recovery actions, making it lower-risk and useful for training. A full interruption test actually shuts down primary operations, a parallel test runs recovery systems alongside production, and a checklist test simply verifies that plan documents and resources are present and current.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a penetration test, the testers are given no prior knowledge of the target's internal network architecture, source code, or credentials and must discover everything on their own. What type of test is this?","o":["White-box testing","Gray-box testing","Black-box testing","Crystal-box testing"],"c":2,"why":"Black-box testing simulates an external attacker with zero prior knowledge of the environment. White-box provides full knowledge, and gray-box provides partial knowledge; 'crystal-box' is not a recognized testing term.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security team wants to assess the resilience of a proprietary network protocol implementation by automatically generating large volumes of malformed, unexpected, or randomly mutated packets and observing the target service for crashes, memory corruption, or hangs. Which technique are they using?","o":["Fuzz testing","Interface testing","Misuse case testing","Regression testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing feeds malformed or randomized input to software or protocol implementations to uncover crashes, memory corruption, and unhandled exceptions. Interface testing verifies functional interactions, misuse case testing models abuse scenarios at a design level, and regression testing confirms prior functionality still works after changes—none involve automated malformed-input generation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A penetration testing team is provided with network diagrams, IP address ranges, and full source code for a web application prior to testing. Which type of penetration test is being performed?","o":["Black-box testing","White-box testing","Gray-box testing","Double-blind testing"],"c":1,"why":"White-box testing provides the tester with complete internal knowledge of the target (source code, architecture, credentials), allowing thorough, efficient testing of internal logic. Black-box testing provides no internal information, gray-box provides partial information, and double-blind testing hides the test from both the target's staff and typically limits information to the tester as well.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team is engaged to test a web application without any prior knowledge of its source code, architecture, or internal design, simulating an external attacker. Which testing approach is being used?","o":["White-box testing","Gray-box testing","Black-box testing","Static analysis testing"],"c":2,"why":"Black-box testing is performed with no internal knowledge of the target, simulating an outside attacker's perspective. White-box testing uses full internal knowledge, gray-box uses partial knowledge, and static analysis examines source code directly rather than testing behavior externally.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization must comply with a payment card industry requirement mandating quarterly external checks of internet-facing systems for known CVEs, with automated severity scoring and minimal manual exploitation. Which activity best satisfies this specific requirement?","o":["Full-scope penetration test with social engineering","Automated vulnerability scanning","Red team engagement","Source code security review"],"c":1,"why":"Automated vulnerability scanning identifies and scores known vulnerabilities (e.g., via CVE/CVSS) without exploitation, matching the compliance requirement's scope and frequency. Penetration testing and red teaming involve active exploitation and are broader/less frequent, while code review does not address running production systems.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"Which testing technique analyzes an application's source code for security flaws such as SQL injection patterns or hardcoded credentials without executing the program?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source or compiled code without running it, identifying insecure coding patterns early in development. DAST tests a running application, fuzz testing sends malformed input to a running system, and penetration testing simulates real-world attacks against a live environment.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security analyst regularly reviews system and application logs to identify unauthorized access attempts, unusual user behavior, and policy violations. This activity is best classified as which type of security control?","o":["Preventive control","Detective control","Corrective control","Deterrent control"],"c":1,"why":"Log review is a detective control because it identifies and documents security events after they occur. It does not prevent, correct, or deter incidents itself.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security tester has access only to a compiled, running instance of a web application and no source code. The tester wants to identify vulnerabilities such as SQL injection by sending crafted inputs and observing application behavior at runtime. Which testing technique is MOST appropriate?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST) using instrumented code","Manual source code peer review"],"c":1,"why":"DAST tests a running application from the outside without requiring source code, making it ideal here. SAST and manual code review require source code access, and IAST requires instrumentation of the running code, which is not available in this black-box scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization runs an automated tool weekly that identifies missing patches, outdated software versions, and known CVEs across its network. This activity is best described as which type of security assessment?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability scanning","Security audit","Threat modeling"],"c":1,"why":"Vulnerability scanning uses automated tools to identify known weaknesses like missing patches and CVEs but does not attempt exploitation. Penetration testing actively exploits vulnerabilities, security audits assess compliance with policy/standards, and threat modeling identifies potential threats during design.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following testing techniques analyzes an application's source code without executing the program, in order to find coding flaws such as buffer overflows or insecure function calls?","o":["Dynamic analysis","Static analysis","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"Static analysis examines source or binary code without execution to identify flaws early in development. Dynamic analysis and fuzz testing require execution, and penetration testing targets running systems rather than source code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During fuzz testing of a file parser, the tester takes previously valid, well-formed input files and randomly flips bits, truncates sections, and alters byte values to create malformed test cases, rather than building inputs from a formal grammar of the file format. This approach is BEST described as which type of fuzzing?","o":["Generation-based fuzzing","Mutation-based fuzzing","Protocol-aware fuzzing","Model-based fuzzing"],"c":1,"why":"Mutation-based (dumb) fuzzing modifies existing valid samples randomly without understanding the underlying format. Generation-based and protocol-aware/model-based fuzzing construct inputs from a specification or grammar of the expected format, which is not the case here.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A company hires an independent CPA firm to evaluate its cloud service provider's controls over security, availability, and confidentiality, resulting in a report for customer assurance. This is an example of which type of audit?","o":["SOC 1 Type I audit","SOC 2 audit","PCI DSS self-assessment","ISO 27001 internal audit"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 audit specifically evaluates controls related to the Trust Services Criteria, including security, availability, and confidentiality, for service organizations. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, PCI DSS self-assessments are for payment card compliance, and internal ISO audits are conducted by the organization itself, not an independent third party.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A customer requests evidence that a cloud service provider's controls over security, availability, and confidentiality have been independently evaluated. Which document would best satisfy this request?","o":["A SOC 2 Type II report","A business impact analysis","A penetration test executive summary","A disaster recovery plan"],"c":0,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report provides an independent auditor's assessment of a service provider's controls over time regarding security, availability, and confidentiality. The other documents serve different purposes and are not independent third-party attestations of controls.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A cloud customer wants assurance that a SaaS provider's security controls related to confidentiality and availability have been operating effectively over the preceding twelve months, not just designed adequately at a single point in time. Which report should the customer request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 3 report summary letter"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates both the design and the operating effectiveness of controls over an extended period (typically 6-12 months), directly addressing the requirement. Type I reports only assess design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 is a high-level public summary lacking detailed testing results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During a security operations review, an analyst notices that thousands of daily log entries from firewalls, IDS, and servers are being aggregated and correlated to identify multi-stage attack patterns. Which technology is primarily responsible for this capability?","o":["Security Information and Event Management (SIEM)","Data Loss Prevention (DLP)","Intrusion Prevention System (IPS)","Network Access Control (NAC)"],"c":0,"why":"SIEM platforms aggregate and correlate log data from multiple sources to detect patterns indicative of attacks. DLP focuses on preventing data exfiltration, IPS blocks malicious traffic in real time, and NAC controls device access to the network—none of which perform cross-source log correlation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization is planning its annual disaster recovery test and wants to select the exercise that provides the MOST realistic validation of recovery capabilities while introducing the HIGHEST risk of disrupting live production operations.","o":["Structured walkthrough (tabletop) test","Simulation test","Parallel test","Full interruption test"],"c":3,"why":"A full interruption test actually shuts down primary operations and shifts fully to the recovery site, providing the most realistic validation but carrying the greatest operational risk. Tabletop and simulation tests are lower-risk discussion/scenario exercises, and parallel tests run recovery systems alongside (not instead of) production, reducing risk compared to full interruption.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization configures automated scripts to periodically simulate a user logging into a web application and completing a purchase, in order to verify the application is functioning correctly from an end-user perspective. This technique is known as:","o":["Fuzz testing","Synthetic transactions","Misuse case testing","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user actions on a system to proactively monitor availability and performance. Fuzz testing sends malformed input to find flaws, misuse case testing explores abuse scenarios, and regression testing verifies changes didn't break existing functionality.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"To continuously verify that a critical e-commerce checkout process is functioning correctly from a user's perspective, an organization scripts automated transactions that mimic real customer behavior and run at scheduled intervals. This technique is known as:","o":["Regression testing","Synthetic transactions","Fuzz testing","Misuse case testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions are scripted, simulated user interactions used to proactively monitor application availability and functionality. Regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality, fuzz testing injects malformed input to find flaws, and misuse case testing models attacker behavior rather than normal user transactions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"As part of a security assessment, an assessor sits down with system administrators and asks them to explain how access requests are approved and provisioned. This assessment technique is best described as:","o":["Log analysis","Interviewing","Vulnerability scanning","Code review"],"c":1,"why":"Interviewing personnel is a common assessment technique used to gather information about processes and controls directly from the people who perform them. The other options involve technical artifacts rather than direct conversation with staff.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security analyst reviewing centralized authentication logs notices that a database administrator account is being used to access financial reporting systems outside of normal business hours, a function typically performed by a separate application support account. This finding is MOST likely to be uncovered through which assessment technique?","o":["Vulnerability scanning of the database server","Log review and correlation for segregation-of-duties violations","Static code analysis of the reporting application","Penetration testing of network perimeter devices"],"c":1,"why":"Reviewing and correlating audit logs is the technique specifically designed to detect anomalous account usage patterns and segregation-of-duties violations. Vulnerability scanning and code analysis focus on technical flaws rather than usage patterns, and perimeter penetration testing would not reveal internal account misuse.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A QA team measures the percentage of application source code lines executed during a test suite run to determine testing thoroughness. This metric is called:","o":["Code coverage","Attack surface analysis","Interface testing","Mean time to detect"],"c":0,"why":"Code coverage measures the proportion of code exercised during testing, indicating how thoroughly the test suite validates the application. Attack surface analysis identifies exposed entry points, interface testing validates data exchange between components, and mean time to detect is an incident response metric, not a code-testing metric.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A company wants to continuously verify that its customer-facing e-commerce checkout process is functioning correctly from an end-user perspective, including third-party payment gateway integration, without waiting for actual customer transaction failures to be reported. Which technique BEST supports this goal?","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring","Passive network traffic analysis","Static application security testing","Annual third-party penetration testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user actions on a scheduled, automated basis to proactively detect functional or performance issues before real customers are affected. Passive traffic analysis and SAST do not exercise the live workflow end-to-end, and annual penetration testing is infrequent and focused on security flaws rather than continuous functional verification.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY reason organizations conduct periodic security control assessments rather than relying solely on the initial authorization to operate?","o":["To satisfy insurance requirements","To ensure controls remain effective as the environment and threats change over time","To reduce the frequency of employee security awareness training","To eliminate the need for incident response planning"],"c":1,"why":"Periodic assessments confirm that controls continue to operate effectively despite changes in systems, configurations, and the threat landscape. The other options are unrelated to the core purpose of ongoing security assessment.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to validate its disaster recovery plan without disrupting production systems, so it gathers stakeholders in a conference room to walk through the plan step-by-step, discussing roles and decisions for a simulated outage. This is an example of which DR test type?","o":["Full interruption test","Parallel test","Simulation test","Tabletop exercise"],"c":3,"why":"A tabletop exercise involves discussing the DR plan in a low-risk, discussion-based setting without activating actual recovery systems. A full interruption test actually shuts down production, a parallel test runs recovery systems alongside production, and a simulation test acts out a scenario more actively than a tabletop discussion but still stops short of full execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to identify exploitable weaknesses in a production web application by actually attempting to bypass authentication and escalate privileges, with prior written authorization and a defined scope. Which assessment technique best matches this description?","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Penetration testing","Static code analysis","Compliance audit"],"c":1,"why":"Penetration testing involves authorized, active exploitation attempts to validate real-world impact of weaknesses, unlike vulnerability scanning which only identifies potential issues without exploitation, and static analysis/compliance audits which don't involve active attack simulation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization integrates a tool into its CI/CD pipeline that analyzes application source code for insecure coding patterns before the code is compiled or deployed. Which testing methodology is being used?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source code or binaries without executing the application, making it suitable for early pipeline integration. DAST requires a running application, fuzz testing sends malformed inputs to a running system, and penetration testing is a broader manual exploitation activity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary difference between a vulnerability assessment and a penetration test?","o":["A vulnerability assessment exploits identified weaknesses, while a penetration test only reports them","A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs weaknesses, while a penetration test attempts to actively exploit them to demonstrate real-world impact","A penetration test is always fully automated, while a vulnerability assessment is always performed manually","A vulnerability assessment can only be performed by external auditors, while a penetration test can only be performed by internal staff"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment scans for and lists potential weaknesses, while a penetration test goes further by actively attempting to exploit them to prove and measure business impact. The other options misstate the roles or falsely restrict who can perform each activity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A company deploys scripted transactions that mimic real user behavior (e.g., logging in, searching, checking out) against a production e-commerce site at scheduled intervals to detect performance degradation or functional failures. What is this technique called?","o":["Synthetic transactions","Misuse case testing","Interface testing","Regression testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate typical user actions against live systems to proactively monitor availability and performance. Misuse case testing focuses on abuse scenarios, interface testing validates API/data exchange points, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A tester is given full access to source code, network diagrams, and system documentation before beginning a security test. This describes which testing approach?","o":["Black-box testing","Gray-box testing","White-box testing","Zero-knowledge testing"],"c":2,"why":"White-box (or full-knowledge) testing gives the tester complete internal knowledge of the system, including source code and architecture. Black-box and zero-knowledge testing involve no prior knowledge, and gray-box testing provides only partial information.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which security testing technique analyzes an application's source code for potential security flaws without actually executing the program?","o":["Dynamic application security testing (DAST)","Static application security testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source or binary code at rest to find flaws before runtime. DAST and fuzz testing require the application to be running, and penetration testing is a broader, more manual exploitation exercise.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization regularly reviews its firewall and system logs as part of its security assessment program. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this activity?","o":["To reduce data storage costs by identifying old logs","To detect anomalous activity and verify that security controls are operating effectively","To automatically remediate discovered vulnerabilities","To generate compliance certificates for auditors"],"c":1,"why":"Log review is a monitoring and assurance activity used to spot suspicious behavior and confirm controls are functioning as intended. It does not automatically fix vulnerabilities, reduce storage needs, or by itself produce compliance certificates.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During a security assessment, an analyst correlates firewall logs, IDS alerts, and authentication logs within a SIEM to identify a pattern indicating a multi-stage attack that no single log source revealed on its own. This activity primarily demonstrates the value of which security assessment practice?","o":["Log review and correlation","Code review","Synthetic monitoring","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Log review and correlation, especially via a SIEM, aggregates data from multiple sources to detect patterns invisible in isolated logs. The other options involve different techniques unrelated to aggregating and correlating log data across systems.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A customer wants assurance that a cloud provider's security, availability, and confidentiality controls are suitably designed AND operating effectively over a period of time. Which report should the customer request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","ISO 9001 certificate","A PCI DSS Attestation of Compliance only"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the design and operating effectiveness of Trust Services Criteria controls over a review period. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, ISO 9001 addresses quality management, and PCI DSS AOC covers only payment card data protection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A tester sends large volumes of randomly malformed and unexpected input to an application's input fields to observe whether it crashes, leaks memory, or behaves unpredictably. This technique is best described as:","o":["Fuzz testing","Interface testing","Misuse case testing","Static analysis"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing injects malformed or random data to reveal crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions. Interface testing verifies proper data exchange between components, misuse case testing evaluates specific abuse scenarios, and static analysis examines code without execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which technique involves simulating user actions against a live production application at scheduled intervals to verify availability and performance?","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring","Fuzz testing","Misuse case testing","Static code review"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions replicate typical user interactions to proactively test application health and performance. Fuzz testing sends malformed input to find crashes, misuse case testing explores abuse scenarios, and static code review examines source code, not live systems.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A regulator requires an organization to have its security controls evaluated by an independent firm with no operational ties to the organization, and the resulting report will be shared with external stakeholders for assurance purposes. This best describes which type of assessment?","o":["Internal audit","Self-assessment","Third-party (external) audit","Tabletop exercise"],"c":2,"why":"A third-party audit is conducted by an independent external entity, providing objective assurance to external stakeholders such as regulators or customers. Internal audits and self-assessments lack independence, and tabletop exercises are discussion-based DR/BC tests, not audits.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"In software security testing, what does 'test coverage' measure?","o":["The number of testers assigned to a project","The percentage of possible code paths, conditions, or requirements exercised by a set of tests","The total budget allocated for testing activities","The amount of time required to complete regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Test coverage quantifies how much of the application's logic or requirements have been exercised by tests, helping identify untested areas. Staffing, budget, and duration are project management metrics, not coverage measures.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which type of security testing is specifically designed to identify and exploit vulnerabilities to determine the real-world impact of a weakness, rather than simply listing potential flaws?","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Penetration testing","Code review","Security audit"],"c":1,"why":"Penetration testing actively attempts to exploit identified weaknesses to demonstrate real business impact. Vulnerability scanning only identifies and reports potential flaws without exploitation, while code review and audits assess different aspects of security posture.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution's external auditors require evidence that a SaaS payroll provider's internal controls over financial reporting operated effectively throughout the entire fiscal year, not just at a single point in time. Which report should the institution request from the SaaS provider?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 1 Type II","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 3"],"c":1,"why":"SOC 1 reports address controls relevant to financial reporting (ICFR); a Type II report evaluates operating effectiveness over a review period, whereas Type I only assesses design at a single point in time. SOC 2 addresses trust services criteria unrelated to financial statements, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary lacking detailed testing results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A QA team wants to verify that their test suite actually exercises all critical code paths, including error-handling branches, before releasing a new application version. Which testing metric would best help them assess this?","o":["Mean time to detect (MTTD)","Code coverage analysis","Recovery time objective (RTO)","Key risk indicator (KRI)"],"c":1,"why":"Code coverage analysis measures the percentage of code paths, branches, and statements executed by tests, directly addressing test completeness. MTTD and RTO relate to incident/recovery timing, and KRIs are risk management metrics, not test coverage measures.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which disaster recovery test type involves team members discussing their roles and responses to a simulated scenario without activating systems or relocating personnel?","o":["Full interruption test","Parallel test","Simulation test","Tabletop exercise"],"c":3,"why":"A tabletop exercise is a low-impact, discussion-based walkthrough of the plan with no actual system or facility activation. Simulation and parallel tests involve more active system engagement, and a full interruption test actually shifts operations to the recovery site.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A tester is given no prior knowledge of the target system's internal architecture, source code, or credentials before beginning an assessment. This describes which testing approach?","o":["White-box testing","Gray-box testing","Black-box testing","Crystal-box testing"],"c":2,"why":"Black-box testing simulates an external attacker with no internal knowledge of the system. White-box testing provides full internal knowledge, and gray-box testing provides partial knowledge; 'crystal-box' is not a standard testing term.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security tester is fuzzing a proprietary industrial control protocol for which no public specification exists. The tester has captured several hours of legitimate network traffic between a PLC and its controller. Which fuzzing approach is most appropriate given these constraints?","o":["Generation-based fuzzing using a formal protocol grammar","Mutation-based fuzzing derived from the captured traffic samples","Static analysis of the PLC firmware binary","Black-box penetration testing using default credential lists"],"c":1,"why":"Mutation (dumb) fuzzing perturbs previously captured valid inputs and does not require a protocol specification, making it well suited when no grammar or spec is available. Generation-based fuzzing requires a formal model of the protocol's structure, while static analysis and credential testing are not forms of protocol input fuzzing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization conducts a disaster recovery test in which the primary production environment is deliberately shut down and all operations are fully shifted to the alternate recovery site to validate real-world recovery capability. Which type of DR test is this?","o":["Tabletop exercise","Simulation test","Parallel test","Full interruption test"],"c":3,"why":"A full interruption test shuts down the primary site entirely and shifts operations to the alternate site, representing the highest-risk and most realistic DR test. A parallel test runs the alternate site alongside the still-active primary, simulations model a scenario discussion-based, and tabletop exercises are informal walkthroughs without actual system shutdown.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization hires an independent firm with no prior relationship to the company to evaluate its security controls and provide an objective opinion for regulatory compliance. This is an example of which type of assessment?","o":["Internal audit","Third-party audit","Self-assessment","Continuous monitoring"],"c":1,"why":"A third-party audit is conducted by an independent external organization to provide an unbiased evaluation, often required for regulatory or contractual compliance. Internal audits and self-assessments are performed by the organization's own staff, and continuous monitoring is an ongoing automated process rather than a discrete independent audit.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An assessor is engaged to test a production web application from the perspective of an external attacker, with no access to source code, application binaries, or internal architecture details. Which testing methodology best fits this engagement?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)"],"c":2,"why":"DAST tests a running application from the outside as a black box, matching an external attacker's perspective without needing source code. SAST requires source code, IAST requires an instrumentation agent embedded in the running application, and SCA analyzes third-party libraries/components rather than runtime application behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which testing technique involves running predefined, non-production transactions through a live production system to verify that it is functioning and performing correctly?","o":["Fuzz testing","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Static code analysis","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions are simulated, scripted transactions used to test system availability and performance in production without affecting real data. Fuzz testing sends malformed input to find defects, static analysis examines source code without execution, and penetration testing attempts exploitation rather than routine monitoring.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team needs to determine not just whether vulnerabilities exist on a web application but whether they can actually be exploited to gain unauthorized access to backend data. Which assessment technique is MOST appropriate to achieve this specific goal?","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Penetration testing","Static code analysis","Configuration review"],"c":1,"why":"Penetration testing actively attempts to exploit discovered weaknesses to prove real-world impact, whereas vulnerability scanning only identifies potential issues without validating exploitability. Static code analysis and configuration review examine code/settings but don't test live exploitation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"The CISO wants to realistically evaluate the detection and incident-response capabilities of the security operations center (SOC) without giving analysts any advance warning that could bias their behavior. The penetration testers will also be given no internal information about the environment. Which type of engagement best matches this objective?","o":["Blind (black-box) test","Double-blind test","White-box (crystal-box) test","Gray-box test"],"c":1,"why":"A double-blind test keeps both the testers (no prior knowledge of the environment) and the organization's own defenders unaware of the exercise, providing an unbiased assessment of real-world detection and response. A standard blind test still notifies defenders in advance, and white/gray-box designations relate only to how much internal knowledge the testers are given, not defender awareness.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A software development team uses an automated tool to examine application source code for security flaws without actually executing the program. This technique is known as:","o":["Dynamic analysis","Static analysis","Fuzz testing","Interface testing"],"c":1,"why":"Static analysis reviews source code directly without running the program, identifying issues like insecure coding patterns. Dynamic analysis and fuzz testing require code execution, and interface testing focuses on how components interact rather than code review.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to analyze an application's source code for insecure coding patterns, such as hardcoded credentials and unsafe function calls, before the application is compiled or deployed. Which testing approach should be used?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source code, bytecode, or binaries without executing the program, making it ideal for finding insecure patterns pre-deployment. DAST tests a running application, fuzzing sends random inputs to a running program, and penetration testing exploits live systems rather than reviewing code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During a 24-hour period, a network intrusion detection system generated 500 alerts, of which 450 were later confirmed as false positives and 50 as true positives. A post-incident forensic review determined that 70 actual attacks occurred during that period, meaning some attacks produced no alert at all. What is the false negative rate for this period?","o":["10%","20%","28.6%","40%"],"c":2,"why":"False negatives equal actual attacks not detected: 70 total attacks minus 50 true positives = 20 false negatives. False negative rate = FN / (FN + TP) = 20 / (20 + 50) = 28.6%. The other options result from miscalculating the numerator or denominator.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A company's customers require independent assurance that the company's cloud service has effective controls over security, availability, and confidentiality, and this assurance must come from a party with no financial interest in the outcome. Which type of audit best satisfies this requirement?","o":["Internal audit performed by the company's compliance department","Self-assessment questionnaire completed by IT staff","Third-party audit conducted by an independent CPA firm (e.g., SOC 2)","Management review during quarterly board meetings"],"c":2,"why":"A third-party audit by an independent firm provides objective, credible assurance to external stakeholders such as customers, which is exactly what SOC 2 reports provide. Internal audits and self-assessments lack independence, and board reviews are not formal audits with external assurance value.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During the requirements phase of a new online banking application, the security team develops diagrams showing how an attacker might exploit input fields to perform SQL injection, hijack sessions, or escalate privileges, in order to derive corresponding negative security requirements. Which technique is being applied?","o":["Use case modeling","Misuse case modeling","Data flow diagramming","Attack tree analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Misuse case modeling extends use-case diagrams to explicitly capture malicious actor interactions, driving negative/security requirements that later inform test cases. Use case modeling covers only intended functional behavior, DFDs model data movement rather than malicious intent, and attack trees use a different goal-decomposition notation distinct from use-case-based requirements work.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During a security review, an analyst aggregates and correlates log data from firewalls, IDS sensors, and authentication servers within a SIEM platform. What is the PRIMARY benefit of this correlation activity over reviewing each log source individually?","o":["It reduces the total storage space required for logs","It enables detection of multi-stage attack patterns that span multiple systems","It eliminates the need for log retention policies","It automatically remediates identified vulnerabilities"],"c":1,"why":"Correlating logs across multiple sources allows analysts to identify attack sequences (e.g., recon, exploitation, lateral movement) that would appear as isolated, low-severity events if reviewed separately. Correlation doesn't reduce storage, eliminate retention needs, or perform remediation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During disaster recovery testing, participants gather in a conference room to discuss and walk through their roles and responses to a simulated disaster scenario without activating any actual systems. This describes a:","o":["Full interruption test","Parallel test","Tabletop exercise","Simulation test"],"c":2,"why":"A tabletop exercise is a low-impact, discussion-based test where participants review procedures verbally without disrupting operations. Full interruption and parallel tests involve actual system activity, and a simulation test, while more active than a tabletop, typically involves practicing specific tasks rather than just discussion.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An API accepts an integer parameter 'quantity' that must be between 1 and 100 inclusive. To maximize defect detection with minimal test cases during interface testing, the tester submits the values -1, 0, 1, 50, 100, and 101. Which testing technique does this represent?","o":["Equivalence partitioning","Boundary value analysis","Fuzz testing","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Boundary value analysis targets values at and just outside the edges of valid input ranges (min-1, min, max, max+1), where defects most commonly occur. Equivalence partitioning would instead select one representative value per valid/invalid class rather than specifically targeting edges, fuzz testing uses random or malformed inputs without targeted boundaries, and regression testing re-executes existing test suites after changes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A web operations team wants continuous assurance that a critical online checkout process is functioning correctly from an end-user perspective, even during periods of low real traffic. Which technique BEST supports this goal?","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring","Passive network sniffing","Static code review","Interface testing during the SDLC only"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate scripted user actions at regular intervals, providing continuous, proactive validation of functionality and performance regardless of actual user traffic. Passive sniffing only observes existing traffic, static review doesn't test live behavior, and SDLC-phase testing isn't continuous in production.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the BEST reason for defining measurable security metrics, such as mean time to detect and mean time to remediate, as part of an assessment program?","o":["To satisfy auditors that documentation exists","To provide objective data for evaluating the effectiveness of security controls over time","To eliminate the need for penetration testing","To replace the need for a risk assessment"],"c":1,"why":"Measurable metrics allow an organization to objectively track and improve control effectiveness over time. Metrics do not replace testing or risk assessment activities, and satisfying auditors is a secondary benefit, not the primary purpose.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A tester submits large volumes of randomly generated, malformed, and unexpected input to an application's input fields to observe whether the application crashes or behaves unpredictably. This technique is known as:","o":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Interface testing","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing involves feeding random or malformed data into an application to uncover crashes, memory leaks, or unexpected behavior indicating vulnerabilities. Regression testing verifies prior functionality after changes, interface testing checks integration points, and misuse case testing models specific abuse scenarios rather than random input.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A company wants to proactively detect availability and performance degradation of its critical customer login workflow, including during off-peak hours when real user traffic is minimal or absent. Which monitoring approach should be implemented to meet this requirement?","o":["Real user monitoring (RUM)","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Log correlation via SIEM","Passive network traffic analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transaction monitoring executes scripted transactions at regular intervals regardless of actual user activity, ensuring continuous visibility even during low-traffic periods. RUM depends entirely on actual user sessions and yields no data when traffic is absent, while SIEM log correlation and passive traffic analysis are reactive/detective techniques rather than proactive availability checks.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A QA lead reports that automated tests execute every line of code in a module at least once, but many conditional branches (if/else paths) are never exercised. This indicates a gap in which testing metric?","o":["Statement coverage without adequate branch coverage","Mutation coverage","Path coverage exceeding statement coverage","Full requirements traceability"],"c":0,"why":"Executing every line at least once but missing conditional branches describes high statement coverage with low branch coverage, a common and important gap since untested branches can hide logic errors or vulnerabilities. The other options describe different or unrelated coverage concepts not matching the scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"Senior management asks the security team to provide a metric that indicates the LIKELIHOOD of a future security incident based on current threat and vulnerability trends, rather than a metric describing past performance. Which type of metric should be reported?","o":["Key Performance Indicator (KPI)","Key Risk Indicator (KRI)","Service Level Agreement (SLA) compliance rate","Mean Time to Detect (MTTD)"],"c":1,"why":"A Key Risk Indicator is forward-looking and signals potential future risk exposure based on trends, which matches management's request. KPIs and MTTD measure past operational performance, and SLA compliance measures adherence to contractual terms, not predictive risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A penetration testing engagement is structured so that the testers are given no prior information about the target environment, and the target organization's own IT and security staff are also not informed in advance that a test will occur. What type of penetration test is this?","o":["Double-blind test","Blind test","White-box test","Gray-box test"],"c":0,"why":"A double-blind test conceals the exercise from both the testing team (zero-knowledge) and the defenders, testing both attacker capability and real-world detection/response. A blind test only conceals information from the tester while staff are aware; white-box and gray-box tests provide the tester full or partial environmental knowledge, which contradicts the scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"Which testing technique identifies vulnerabilities such as SQL injection and reflected XSS by sending crafted HTTP requests to a running web application and analyzing the responses, without requiring access to the application's source code?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)","Manual secure code review"],"c":1,"why":"DAST is a black-box technique that exercises a running application externally to find exploitable runtime flaws. SAST and manual code review require source code access, and SCA identifies known-vulnerable third-party components rather than testing application behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which type of penetration test provides the testing team with no prior knowledge of the target organization's internal systems, network diagrams, or credentials before the engagement begins?","o":["White-box test","Black-box test","Gray-box test","Crystal-box test"],"c":1,"why":"A black-box test simulates an external attacker with zero internal knowledge, forcing testers to perform reconnaissance from scratch. White-box gives full knowledge, gray-box gives partial knowledge, and 'crystal-box' is not a standard testing term.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security team configures scripted, simulated user transactions to run against a production e-commerce site every five minutes, from multiple geographic locations, to detect performance degradation or functional failures before real customers report problems. This technique is best described as:","o":["Real user monitoring (RUM)","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Log correlation and review","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions use scripted, proactive probes to continuously validate availability and performance independent of actual user traffic. RUM passively observes real user sessions, log review is reactive analysis of recorded events, and regression testing validates that changes haven't broken existing functionality in a pre-production context.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to verify that its web application correctly handles unexpected or malformed input without crashing or exposing sensitive data. Which testing technique is BEST suited for this goal?","o":["Fuzz testing","Static code analysis","Log review","Synthetic transaction monitoring"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing feeds random, malformed, or unexpected input into an application to identify crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions. Static analysis examines source code without execution, log review analyzes historical events, and synthetic transactions simulate normal user behavior rather than abnormal input.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A cloud provider furnishes a customer with an attestation report describing the design and *operating effectiveness* of its security controls, based on evidence gathered by an independent auditor over a continuous six-month period. Which report type has the customer received?","o":["SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 1 report","SOC 3 report"],"c":1,"why":"SOC 2 Type II evaluates control operating effectiveness over an extended observation period, unlike Type I, which assesses control design at a single point in time. SOC 1 focuses on controls relevant to financial reporting, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report lacking the detailed testing results found in Type II.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A vulnerability scan flags a web server as running an outdated version of software with a known critical vulnerability. Upon manual verification, the security analyst confirms the software is actually current and the flagged issue does not exist. What is this result called?","o":["True positive","False positive","False negative","True negative"],"c":1,"why":"A false positive occurs when a scanner reports a vulnerability that does not actually exist. A true positive would be a correctly identified real vulnerability, and a false negative is a missed real vulnerability.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An automated scanner identifies open ports and cross-references software banner versions against a CVE database, producing a report with CVSS scores. A tester then manually confirms several findings and successfully exploits one flaw to extract data, demonstrating real-world business impact. Which statement correctly characterizes these two activities?","o":["Both activities are identical; CVSS scoring alone constitutes a penetration test","The automated scan is itself a penetration test because it identified vulnerabilities with severity ratings","The scan performed a vulnerability assessment identifying potential weaknesses, while manual exploitation constituted a penetration test validating actual exploitability","Once a CVSS score exceeds 7.0, manual exploitation is unnecessary because the score alone verifies exploitability"],"c":2,"why":"Vulnerability assessment/scanning identifies and rates potential weaknesses without proving exploitability, while penetration testing goes further by actively exploiting flaws to demonstrate real impact. CVSS scores are theoretical severity ratings, not proof of exploitability, and scanning alone does not equal a penetration test.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the primary purpose of a security audit conducted by an independent third party?","o":["To actively exploit vulnerabilities to demonstrate business impact","To provide an objective, unbiased assessment of compliance with policies, standards, or regulations","To train internal staff on incident response procedures","To perform routine patch management on production systems"],"c":1,"why":"Independent audits provide objective assurance that controls meet defined policies, standards, or regulatory requirements. Exploiting vulnerabilities describes penetration testing, not auditing, and audits are not focused on training or patching.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A tester takes a set of valid, well-formed input files accepted by an application and programmatically flips random bits and bytes within them, then feeds the altered files back into the application to observe crashes or unexpected behavior. This approach is an example of:","o":["Generation-based fuzzing","Mutation-based fuzzing","Static taint analysis","Boundary value analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Mutation-based (also called dumb) fuzzing derives test cases by randomly altering existing valid samples. Generation-based fuzzing instead builds inputs from a model of the protocol/format specification; static taint analysis traces data flow in source code, and boundary value analysis targets edge-case values rather than random mutation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"While testing a REST API, an assessor modifies the 'order_id' parameter in an authenticated request to a value belonging to a different customer and successfully retrieves that customer's order details, despite having no legitimate relationship to that record. This finding is most accurately classified as:","o":["Cross-site request forgery (CSRF)","Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA)","SQL injection","Session fixation"],"c":1,"why":"BOLA occurs when an API fails to verify that the authenticated caller is authorized to access the specific object referenced by an identifier, allowing horizontal privilege escalation. CSRF involves tricking a browser into submitting unwanted requests, SQL injection involves malicious query manipulation, and session fixation involves forcing a known session ID onto a victim—none of which match the described parameter-tampering scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a code review, a security analyst examines the application's source code line by line without executing the program, searching for insecure coding patterns such as hardcoded credentials. What type of testing is this?","o":["Dynamic analysis","Static analysis","Interactive analysis","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Static analysis examines source code without executing it, making it effective for finding issues like hardcoded secrets or insecure functions early in development. Dynamic analysis requires running the application, and regression testing verifies that changes didn't break existing functionality.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A dynamic test suite for a critical application achieves 100% statement coverage but only 60% branch (decision) coverage during a code coverage analysis. What does this result indicate to the security assessor?","o":["The test suite is fully adequate, since statement coverage is the accepted industry gold standard for completeness","Every line of code executed at least once, but many conditional logic paths were never exercised, so defects in untested branches may remain undetected","60% branch coverage implies that 40% of the application's statements were never executed by any test case","Branch coverage and statement coverage are two names for the same metric, calculated using different formulas"],"c":1,"why":"Statement coverage only confirms that each line ran at least once, while branch coverage measures whether both true and false outcomes of conditional logic were tested; achieving full statement coverage with partial branch coverage means many decision paths—and potential logic flaws—were never validated. The other options misstate the relationship between these distinct, non-equivalent metrics.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is an example of a synthetic transaction used in security assessment and testing?","o":["Reviewing firewall configuration files for misconfigurations","Simulating a user login and purchase flow on an e-commerce site to verify functionality and performance","Analyzing packet captures from a network intrusion","Interviewing employees about security awareness training"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions are scripted, simulated user interactions used to proactively test application availability, performance, and correct functioning. The other options describe configuration review, network forensics, and awareness assessment, not synthetic transactions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization's security team regularly reviews system and application logs to identify unauthorized access attempts and unusual account activity. This activity is an example of which type of security control assessment?","o":["Penetration testing","Log review and analysis","Vulnerability scanning","Misuse case testing"],"c":1,"why":"Log review and analysis involves examining recorded system events to detect anomalies, unauthorized access, or policy violations. Penetration testing actively attempts exploitation, vulnerability scanning checks for known weaknesses, and misuse case testing evaluates how systems respond to intentional abuse scenarios.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization runs an automated tool that scans its network for known vulnerabilities, missing patches, and misconfigurations, then produces a report ranking findings by severity. This activity is best described as a:","o":["Penetration test","Vulnerability assessment","Security audit","Risk assessment"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment uses automated scanning to identify known weaknesses without actively exploiting them. A penetration test goes further by attempting exploitation; an audit verifies compliance with standards; a risk assessment evaluates likelihood and impact of threats.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which metric would be MOST useful for measuring the effectiveness of a vulnerability management program over time?","o":["Total number of firewalls deployed","Average time to remediate identified critical vulnerabilities","Number of employees who completed security awareness training","Total storage capacity of the log management system"],"c":1,"why":"Mean time to remediate (MTTR) critical vulnerabilities is a key performance indicator that directly reflects how effectively an organization identifies and resolves security risks. The other metrics measure unrelated aspects such as infrastructure size, training completion, or storage capacity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a penetration test, the testing team is given no prior knowledge of the target's internal network architecture, source code, or credentials. This testing approach is known as:","o":["White box testing","Gray box testing","Black box testing","Crystal box testing"],"c":2,"why":"Black box testing simulates an external attacker with no inside knowledge. White box testing provides full internal knowledge, and gray box provides partial knowledge. 'Crystal box' is not a recognized testing term.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security analyst reviews firewall and authentication logs daily to identify unusual patterns, such as repeated failed login attempts from a foreign IP address. This activity primarily supports which security assessment function?","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Log review and monitoring","Penetration testing","Code review"],"c":1,"why":"Log review and monitoring involves analyzing system and security logs to detect anomalies and potential incidents. Vulnerability scanning targets weaknesses, penetration testing simulates attacks, and code review examines source code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary purpose of a third-party security audit conducted by an independent firm?","o":["To allow the organization to test its own incident response plan","To provide an unbiased evaluation of controls for stakeholders such as regulators or customers","To replace the need for internal vulnerability scanning","To train internal staff on secure coding practices"],"c":1,"why":"Third-party audits provide independent, objective assurance to external stakeholders about the effectiveness of controls. They do not replace scanning, train staff, or test incident response plans directly.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to identify vulnerabilities in a web application's source code by analyzing it line-by-line without executing the program. Which testing technique should they use?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":0,"why":"SAST analyzes source, byte, or binary code without executing the application, making it ideal for early-lifecycle code review. DAST tests a running application, fuzzing sends malformed input to a running system, and penetration testing is a broader exploitation-focused activity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A developer uses a tool that analyzes application source code for insecure coding patterns without executing the program. This technique is known as:","o":["Dynamic application security testing (DAST)","Static application security testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source code without running it, identifying insecure patterns early in development. DAST tests a running application, fuzz testing sends malformed input to running software, and penetration testing simulates real-world attacks.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A penetration testing team is provided with full network diagrams, application source code, and valid credentials before the engagement begins. This type of testing approach is best described as:","o":["Black box testing","White box testing","Gray box testing","Blind testing"],"c":1,"why":"White box (also called clear/crystal box) testing gives testers complete knowledge of the target environment, simulating an insider threat or thorough audit. Black box testing provides no internal knowledge, gray box provides partial knowledge, and blind testing means the target organization is unaware of the test.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An e-commerce company configures automated scripts that periodically simulate a customer completing a purchase to verify that the checkout process is functioning correctly from an external user's perspective. This technique is called:","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring","Misuse case testing","Interface testing","Regression testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user actions to proactively verify system availability and functionality. Misuse case testing focuses on abuse scenarios, interface testing checks data exchange between components, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During disaster recovery testing, an organization activates its alternate processing site and runs it concurrently with the live production environment to validate that systems function correctly, without disrupting normal operations. This describes which type of DR test?","o":["Tabletop exercise","Simulation test","Parallel test","Full interruption test"],"c":2,"why":"A parallel test runs the alternate site alongside production to validate functionality with no impact on live operations. A tabletop exercise is discussion-based, a simulation test walks through a scenario without activating systems, and a full interruption test actually shuts down production, which carries the highest risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a control assessment, an auditor interviews system administrators, examines configuration documentation, and tests firewall rules directly. This combination of methods reflects which assessment approach?","o":["Using only automated tools for efficiency","Applying multiple assessment methods (examine, interview, test) to gain assurance","Relying solely on vendor self-attestation","Performing only a paper-based compliance review"],"c":1,"why":"Combining examination, interviews, and testing (as in NIST SP 800-53A) provides more comprehensive assurance than relying on any single method alone. Self-attestation and paper-only reviews lack independent verification.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization runs automated tools every week to scan its network for known vulnerabilities such as missing patches, outdated software versions, and common misconfigurations. This activity is best classified as:","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability scanning","Red team exercise","Security audit"],"c":1,"why":"Vulnerability scanning uses automated tools to identify known weaknesses based on signatures or databases, typically without exploitation. Penetration testing and red team exercises involve active exploitation to demonstrate impact, and a security audit is a broader, often compliance-focused review process.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A company wants to evaluate its disaster recovery plan without disrupting live production systems, using a discussion-based session where team members walk through their roles and responses to a hypothetical outage. This is an example of a:","o":["Full interruption test","Parallel test","Tabletop exercise","Simulation test"],"c":2,"why":"A tabletop exercise is a low-cost, discussion-based review of the plan without operational disruption. A full interruption test actually shuts down production, a parallel test runs recovery systems alongside production, and a simulation test involves acting out a scenario more actively than a tabletop discussion.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"What is the PRIMARY benefit of aggregating log data from firewalls, servers, and endpoints into a centralized SIEM platform?","o":["It reduces the total storage required for log retention","It enables correlation of events across multiple sources to detect patterns indicating an attack","It automatically encrypts all collected log data at rest","It eliminates the need for individual system audit logging"],"c":1,"why":"Centralizing logs in a SIEM allows correlation engines to identify patterns and relationships across disparate sources that would be missed when reviewing logs individually. It does not inherently reduce storage needs, guarantee encryption, or eliminate the need for local logging on individual systems.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An e-commerce company configures automated scripts to simulate customer logins and checkout transactions every five minutes to continuously verify that the site is functioning and responsive from an end-user perspective. This technique is known as:","o":["Regression testing","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Interface testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transaction monitoring uses scripted, automated actions that mimic real user behavior to proactively verify functionality and performance. Regression testing re-verifies functionality after changes, interface testing focuses on data exchange between components, and fuzz testing sends malformed input to find defects.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A prospective customer wants assurance that a cloud service provider's security controls have operated effectively over a continuous 12-month period, not just that they were properly designed at a single point in time. Which report should the customer request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3 general use report"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates both the design and the operating effectiveness of controls over an extended period (typically 6-12 months), providing assurance of sustained effectiveness. Type I reports only assess design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 is a high-level summary lacking detailed testing results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security team wants to conduct a penetration test that evaluates both the attacker's ability to breach the network and the organization's Security Operations Center (SOC) ability to detect and respond, without the SOC being tipped off that a test is occurring. The testers themselves are given no internal architecture documentation. Which type of test best fits this scenario?","o":["Double-blind (zero-knowledge) test","Blind test with SOC notification","Targeted (white-box) test conducted with full knowledge by both parties","Gray-box test where testers have partial internal documentation"],"c":0,"why":"A double-blind test withholds knowledge from both the testers and the defenders, providing the most realistic assessment of both attack technique and detection/response capability. A standard blind test still notifies the defenders in advance, a targeted test shares full knowledge with both sides (reducing realism), and gray-box testing gives testers partial knowledge, which doesn't address the detection-capability objective.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"After deploying a patch to fix a critical vulnerability in a production application, the QA team re-executes the full suite of previously passed test cases to confirm the patch did not break existing functionality. This activity is best described as:","o":["Unit testing","Regression testing","User acceptance testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"Regression testing re-runs existing test cases after a change to ensure previously working functionality was not broken. Unit testing validates individual code components in isolation, acceptance testing confirms business requirements are met, and fuzz testing involves feeding random or malformed input to uncover defects.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An application security team is evaluating a testing technique that instruments the application's code while it runs under normal use (e.g., via automated functional test suites), allowing the tool to observe actual data flow and correlate a discovered vulnerability with the exact line of source code that caused it. Which technique is being described?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Runtime Application Self-Protection (RASP)"],"c":2,"why":"IAST uses instrumentation/agents inside the running application to combine the code-level visibility of static analysis with the real-execution context of dynamic analysis. SAST analyzes source code without execution, DAST tests the running application externally without code visibility, and RASP is a runtime defense/blocking mechanism rather than a testing methodology.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An automated vulnerability scanner flags a web server as vulnerable to a critical remote code execution CVE based on the version string returned in the HTTP response banner. Manual verification confirms the vendor backported the patch without updating the version banner, and the server is not actually exploitable. How should this finding be classified?","o":["True positive","False negative","False positive","Zero-day vulnerability"],"c":2,"why":"The scanner reported a vulnerability that does not actually exist, making this a false positive; this is a common limitation of banner/version-based scanning versus authenticated or exploit-based verification. A false negative would be a missed real vulnerability, a true positive would confirm an actual exploitable flaw, and a zero-day refers to an unpatched, previously unknown vulnerability, not a misreported patched one.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A company hires an external firm to perform a security assessment, providing only the organization's public domain name and no information about internal network architecture, credentials, or system diagrams. What type of penetration test is being performed?","o":["Black-box (zero-knowledge) test","White-box (full-knowledge) test","Gray-box (partial-knowledge) test","Red team exercise with insider collusion"],"c":0,"why":"A black-box test simulates an external attacker with no prior knowledge of internal systems. White-box testers receive full documentation, gray-box testers receive partial information, and a red team exercise typically involves broader objectives and may include insider cooperation, none of which match the scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"Which security testing technique analyzes an application's source code or binaries without executing the program, making it well suited for identifying vulnerabilities early in the SDLC before a working build exists?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Fuzz testing"],"c":0,"why":"SAST examines code or binaries at rest without execution, enabling detection early in the SDLC. DAST requires a running application, IAST instruments a running app combining static and dynamic data, and fuzzing sends malformed inputs to an executable build, none of which work without a running program.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A prospective client evaluating a cloud service provider requires assurance that the provider's security, availability, and confidentiality controls were not only appropriately designed but also operated effectively over a continuous six-month period, based on an independent auditor's testing of the controls during that window. Which report should the client request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 3 report"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of controls over an extended review period, whereas a Type I report only assesses control design at a single point in time. SOC 1 addresses controls relevant to financial reporting rather than the Trust Services Criteria, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report lacking the detailed testing results needed for this due-diligence decision.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"Which testing technique analyzes an application's source code for security flaws such as SQL injection patterns or insecure function calls without executing the program?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Fuzz testing","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST) during runtime"],"c":0,"why":"SAST examines source or binary code at rest without running the application. DAST tests a running application from the outside, fuzz testing feeds malformed input to a running program, and IAST instruments the application during execution, all requiring the program to run.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A fuzz testing tool creates malformed input test cases entirely from a formal grammar/model of a target protocol's specification, rather than modifying previously captured valid traffic samples. Which fuzzing approach is this?","o":["Mutation-based fuzzing","Generational (grammar-based) fuzzing","Dumb fuzzing","Protocol replay testing"],"c":1,"why":"Generational fuzzing constructs test cases from scratch using knowledge of the protocol's structure or grammar, typically achieving deeper, more targeted coverage than mutation-based approaches, which instead alter existing valid samples. Dumb fuzzing lacks structural knowledge of the input format, and protocol replay simply resends captured traffic unmodified rather than generating novel malformed inputs.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A CISO is evaluating a SaaS provider's security controls and needs assurance that the provider's controls were not only suitably designed but also operated effectively over a six-month period. Which report should the CISO request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 3 report"],"c":2,"why":"SOC 2 Type II tests both the design and operating effectiveness of controls over a defined period. SOC 1 addresses financial reporting controls, SOC 2 Type I only assesses design at a single point in time, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary lacking the detailed testing results needed.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security manager wants to identify known weaknesses across the network primarily by using automated tools that compare system configurations and software versions against a database of known CVEs. This activity is best described as a:","o":["Vulnerability assessment","Penetration test","Security audit","Qualitative risk assessment"],"c":0,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs known weaknesses using scanning tools and CVE databases. A penetration test goes further to exploit vulnerabilities, a security audit verifies compliance with policies/standards, and a risk assessment evaluates likelihood and impact rather than simply enumerating flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization implements automated scripts that periodically execute simulated user transactions (e.g., login, search, checkout) against a production e-commerce platform around the clock, comparing response times and results against expected baselines to detect failures before real customers are affected. This technique is best described as:","o":["Real user monitoring (RUM)","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Log correlation analysis","Canary deployment testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transaction monitoring uses scripted, simulated transactions to proactively test availability and performance independent of actual user traffic. Real user monitoring instead passively observes actual customer sessions, log correlation is a reactive/after-the-fact analysis technique, and canary deployment is a phased release strategy, not a continuous monitoring test.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A tester with no knowledge of a proprietary network protocol's specification wants to discover parsing vulnerabilities by taking captured valid traffic samples and randomly altering byte values before replaying them at the target service. This approach is best classified as which fuzzing technique?","o":["Generation-based (model-based) fuzzing","Mutation-based (dumb) fuzzing","Protocol-aware structured fuzzing","White-box symbolic fuzzing"],"c":1,"why":"Mutation-based fuzzing modifies existing valid samples without requiring knowledge of the underlying format, matching this scenario. Generation-based and protocol-aware fuzzing require a specification model, and symbolic fuzzing requires source-code-level path analysis, none of which apply here.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A customer requests assurance that a cloud service provider's security, availability, and confidentiality controls operated effectively throughout a 12-month period. Which report should the provider supply?","o":["SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 3 report","ISO 27001 certificate of registration"],"c":0,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of controls over a period of time against Trust Services Criteria. A SOC 1 Type I focuses on financial reporting controls at a point in time, a SOC 3 is a general-use summary lacking detail, and an ISO 27001 certificate attests to ISMS conformance but does not provide the same period-based control testing evidence.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During white-box code review, a tester wants to ensure that every decision point in the code (e.g., each if/else statement) has had both its true and false outcomes exercised at least once by the test suite. This is a description of which coverage criterion, and how does it differ from simply executing every line of code once?","o":["Statement coverage, which is stricter because it requires every line to execute regardless of decision outcomes","Branch coverage, which is stricter than statement coverage because it requires both outcomes of every decision to be exercised","Condition coverage, which is identical to statement coverage in practice","Path coverage, which requires far fewer test cases than branch coverage"],"c":1,"why":"Branch coverage requires that each decision point's true and false outcomes both be tested, which is a stronger criterion than statement coverage (which only requires each line to execute at least once, regardless of decision outcome). Condition coverage focuses on individual boolean sub-expressions rather than overall branch outcomes, and path coverage is far more exhaustive (testing every possible route through the code), requiring more, not fewer, test cases than branch coverage.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to identify known weaknesses in its systems by scanning for missing patches and misconfigurations, without attempting to exploit them. Which activity best describes this task?","o":["Vulnerability assessment","Penetration testing","Red team exercise","Security audit"],"c":0,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs known weaknesses without exploiting them. Penetration testing and red team exercises go further by actively exploiting vulnerabilities, and a security audit evaluates compliance with policies rather than scanning for technical flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A SIEM platform aggregates authentication logs and triggers an alert when it detects multiple failed login attempts for the same user account originating from geographically distant locations within a short time window. This capability is best described as:","o":["Log correlation and analysis","Log rotation and archival","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Static code review"],"c":0,"why":"Correlating events across multiple log sources to detect suspicious patterns is log correlation and analysis, a core SIEM function. Log rotation concerns storage management, synthetic transactions simulate user activity to test availability, and static code review examines source code, none of which describe cross-event pattern detection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution's disaster recovery test plan calls for actually shutting down primary processing systems and shifting all live production workloads to the alternate recovery site to fully validate that operations can continue, accepting the operational risk this entails. Which type of DR test is being performed?","o":["Tabletop exercise","Simulation test","Parallel test","Full interruption test"],"c":3,"why":"A full interruption test actually halts primary operations and fails over completely to the alternate site, making it the highest-risk but most conclusive validation of recovery capability. A parallel test runs the alternate site alongside the still-operating primary site without interrupting production, a simulation test walks through a disaster scenario without an actual failover, and a tabletop exercise is a discussion-based review involving no technical failover at all.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a security assessment, a tester examines an application's source code line by line to identify insecure coding patterns before the application is compiled or run. This technique is best described as:","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source or binary code without executing the program, making it ideal for early detection of coding flaws. DAST tests a running application, fuzz testing sends random/malformed input to a running system, and penetration testing actively exploits live systems.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A penetration tester is given full knowledge of the target's network diagrams, source code, and credentials before beginning the engagement. This type of testing approach is known as:","o":["Black box testing","Gray box testing","White box testing","Double-blind testing"],"c":2,"why":"White box testing provides the tester with complete knowledge of the environment, simulating an insider threat or thorough internal review. Black box testing provides no prior information, gray box provides partial information, and double-blind testing hides the test from staff as well as limiting tester knowledge.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During software testing, which metric measures the percentage of all possible decision branches (e.g., if/else paths) that have been exercised by the test suite?","o":["Branch coverage","Statement coverage","Function coverage","Mutation coverage"],"c":0,"why":"Branch coverage specifically measures whether each decision path has been tested. Statement coverage only tracks whether individual lines executed, function coverage tracks whether functions were called, and mutation coverage measures the test suite's ability to detect injected faults, not decision path execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A customer wants assurance not only that a service provider's controls are suitably designed, but also that those controls operated effectively over a defined period of time. Which type of report should the customer request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3 summary report"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates both the design and the operating effectiveness of controls over a period of time (typically 6-12 months), unlike Type I reports, which assess design only at a single point in time; SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary without detailed testing results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"Which type of disaster recovery test carries the greatest risk of impacting production operations because it involves shutting down the primary site and formally activating the secondary site?","o":["Full interruption test","Tabletop exercise","Simulation test","Parallel test"],"c":0,"why":"A full interruption test actually halts primary processing and fails over to the alternate site, creating real operational risk. A tabletop exercise is discussion-based, a simulation walks through a scenario without actual failover, and a parallel test runs the alternate site alongside (not instead of) production, minimizing risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security team configures automated scripts that periodically log into a web application and perform typical user actions, such as searching and checking out, to verify the application is functioning correctly from an end-user perspective. This technique is known as:","o":["Fuzz testing","Synthetic transactions","Misuse case testing","Interface testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user activity to proactively monitor application availability and performance. Fuzz testing sends malformed input to find crashes, misuse case testing focuses on how an attacker might abuse functionality, and interface testing validates data exchange between system components.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During a security assessment, a tester is given full knowledge of the target's network diagrams, source code, and credentials before beginning the engagement. This type of testing is best described as:","o":["Black-box testing","White-box testing","Gray-box testing","Double-blind testing"],"c":1,"why":"White-box testing provides the tester with complete internal knowledge of the system (source code, architecture, credentials) to allow thorough analysis. Black-box testing provides no internal knowledge, gray-box provides partial knowledge, and double-blind testing refers to withholding knowledge from both the tester and the defending team, not the amount of system detail given.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A SOC analyst notices the SIEM is generating an excessive number of alerts for a correlation rule designed to detect brute-force login attempts, most of which are traced to a legitimate scheduled batch job authenticating with service accounts. What is the MOST appropriate way to reduce false positives while preserving detection capability?","o":["Disable the brute-force correlation rule until further notice","Increase the global alert severity threshold across all rules","Create an exception baseline for the known service account behavior and refine the rule's thresholds","Stop ingesting authentication logs from the affected system"],"c":2,"why":"Tuning the rule with a documented exception for known-legitimate behavior reduces false positives while keeping detection logic intact. Disabling the rule or the log source creates blind spots, and raising the global threshold would suppress unrelated true positives across the environment.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"Which testing technique involves supplying invalid, unexpected, or randomly generated input to a program's interfaces to identify crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions?","o":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Interface (API) testing","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing automates the injection of malformed or random data to surface unhandled errors and vulnerabilities. Regression testing verifies that changes didn't break existing functionality, interface testing validates correct API behavior with expected inputs, and misuse case testing is a design-time threat modeling technique rather than dynamic input testing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP is evaluating tools to detect insecure coding patterns, hardcoded credentials, and potential SQL injection flaws by analyzing an application's source code without executing it. Which testing technique best fits this requirement?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Runtime Application Self-Protection (RASP)"],"c":0,"why":"SAST examines source or binary code without execution to find insecure patterns. DAST tests a running application, IAST instruments code during execution (a hybrid), and RASP is a runtime protection mechanism, not a testing technique.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which testing technique involves sending large amounts of random, malformed, or unexpected input to an application to identify crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions?","o":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Interface testing","Synthetic transaction monitoring"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing automatically generates malformed or random inputs to reveal how software handles unexpected data, often uncovering buffer overflows or crashes. Regression testing verifies that changes have not broken existing functionality, interface testing checks integration points, and synthetic transactions simulate normal user behavior rather than malformed input.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A vulnerability scan of a web application identifies an outdated library with a known CVE. A subsequent penetration test attempts to exploit this vulnerability to gain a reverse shell. What best distinguishes the penetration test from the vulnerability scan?","o":["The penetration test only identifies vulnerabilities without verifying exploitability","The vulnerability scan actively exploits weaknesses while the penetration test passively lists them","The penetration test actively attempts to exploit identified weaknesses to demonstrate real-world impact, while the scan only identifies potential weaknesses","Vulnerability scans require manual tester interaction while penetration tests are fully automated"],"c":2,"why":"Penetration testing goes beyond identification by actively attempting exploitation to demonstrate impact and validate risk, whereas vulnerability scanning is typically automated and only identifies potential weaknesses without exploiting them. The other options reverse or misstate these relationships.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"To proactively detect availability and performance issues before real customers are affected, a security team scripts a series of simulated login, search, and checkout actions that execute against the production e-commerce site every five minutes, 24/7. This technique is known as?","o":["Real user monitoring (RUM)","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Regression testing","Interface (API) fuzzing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transaction monitoring uses scripted, simulated user actions run on a schedule against production to proactively surface issues. RUM passively observes actual visitor traffic, regression testing verifies changes don't break prior functionality during development, and API fuzzing sends malformed inputs rather than scripted legitimate transactions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to conduct a penetration test that evaluates not only technical vulnerabilities but also the effectiveness of its Security Operations Center's detection and response capabilities, without informing SOC staff in advance. Which type of test should be performed?","o":["Double-blind (zero-knowledge) test","Single-blind (blind) test","White-box test","Announced test"],"c":0,"why":"A double-blind test keeps both testers and defenders uninformed, providing a realistic assessment of detection and response. A single-blind test notifies defenders, biasing their response; white-box testing gives testers full knowledge, not addressing defender blindness; an announced test alerts staff, defeating the purpose.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"Which code review technique involves examining source code line-by-line for security flaws WITHOUT executing the program?","o":["Dynamic analysis","Fuzzing","Static analysis","Fault injection"],"c":2,"why":"Static analysis examines source or compiled code without executing it, identifying issues like insecure coding patterns or hardcoded credentials. Dynamic analysis, fuzzing, and fault injection all involve executing the application to observe its behavior under various inputs or conditions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An auditor interviews IT staff, reviews change management tickets, and inspects firewall configuration exports to determine whether an organization's change control policy is being followed. This activity is an example of:","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability scanning","Security control assessment","Fuzz testing"],"c":2,"why":"A security control assessment evaluates whether implemented controls (like change management) are operating as intended, often through interviews, document review, and technical inspection. Penetration testing and vulnerability scanning are technical tests of systems, while fuzz testing targets application input handling.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization outsources payment card processing to a third-party service provider and wants the contractual ability to periodically verify the provider's security controls, either directly or through an independent assessor, throughout the life of the contract. Which contractual provision should be negotiated?","o":["Service level agreement (SLA)","Right-to-audit clause","Non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","Indemnification clause"],"c":1,"why":"A right-to-audit clause grants the customer, or its designated assessor, the contractual authority to examine the provider's controls. An SLA defines performance metrics, an NDA protects confidential information exchange, and an indemnification clause addresses liability allocation rather than audit access.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization hires an independent CPA firm to evaluate its financial reporting controls and issue an opinion for external stakeholders, including regulators and shareholders. This is an example of which type of audit?","o":["Internal audit","First-party audit","Third-party audit","Self-assessment audit"],"c":2,"why":"A third-party audit is performed by an independent external entity and is typically required for compliance or to provide assurance to external stakeholders such as regulators or shareholders. Internal and first-party audits are conducted by the organization's own staff, and a self-assessment lacks independent verification, making them less credible for external assurance purposes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A vulnerability scanner is reconfigured with highly sensitive detection thresholds specifically to minimize the risk of missing actual vulnerabilities. What is the most likely consequence of this configuration change?","o":["An increase in false positive results, requiring more analyst triage time","An increase in false negative results, reducing scan effectiveness","A decrease in scan completion time due to fewer signature checks","Elimination of the need for manual vulnerability validation"],"c":0,"why":"Increasing sensitivity to reduce false negatives typically raises the false positive rate, increasing analyst workload. It would not increase false negatives (the opposite is intended), scan time is not necessarily reduced, and manual validation remains necessary to confirm findings.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A vulnerability management program tracks several metrics. Which of the following is BEST classified as a Key Risk Indicator (KRI) rather than a Key Performance Indicator (KPI)?","o":["Average number of days required to remediate critical vulnerabilities","Number of vulnerability scans completed each quarter","Percentage of internet-facing systems with critical vulnerabilities open beyond the defined SLA window","Number of staff who completed secure coding training"],"c":2,"why":"A KRI provides a forward-looking indicator of current risk exposure, such as the proportion of critical, unpatched, internet-facing systems exceeding acceptable exposure windows. The other metrics measure program activity or efficiency, making them KPIs rather than KRIs.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team configures automated scripts that periodically simulate user login attempts and file downloads against a production e-commerce site to detect performance degradation or outages before customers report issues. This technique is known as:","o":["Misuse case testing","Synthetic transactions","Interface testing","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions involve scripted, simulated user actions performed against a live system to proactively monitor availability and performance. Misuse case testing focuses on how attackers might abuse functionality, interface testing validates data exchange between system components, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A customer requires assurance that a cloud service provider's security controls have operated effectively over the preceding 12 months, not just that they were suitably designed at a single point in time. Which report should the customer request?","o":["SOC 2 Type II","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 1 Type I","SOC 3"],"c":0,"why":"SOC 2 Type II reports on the operating effectiveness of controls over a review period (typically 6-12 months). Type I only assesses design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on controls relevant to financial reporting, and SOC 3 is a public-facing summary lacking detailed test results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A disaster recovery test involves relocating live production processing to an alternate site while the primary site remains operational, fully exercising alternate-site systems and personnel without disrupting normal business operations. This describes which type of DR test?","o":["Tabletop exercise","Simulation test","Parallel test","Full interruption test"],"c":2,"why":"A parallel test runs alternate-site systems alongside the still-operational primary site, validating recovery capability without disrupting production. A tabletop exercise is discussion-based only, a simulation test walks through a scenario without full system activation, and a full interruption test actually shuts down primary operations, which carries much higher risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"To proactively monitor the availability and performance of a production e-commerce application without affecting real customer data, a security team scripts automated transactions that simulate typical user behavior at regular intervals. Which technique is being used?","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring","Real user monitoring (RUM)","Regression testing","Interface testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate user actions against production systems to proactively monitor performance and availability. RUM observes actual live user traffic rather than simulated activity, regression testing verifies changes don't break existing functionality (typically pre-production), and interface testing validates data exchange between components, not ongoing availability monitoring.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A SOC analyst notices that a SIEM has correlated multiple failed login attempts from different source IPs against the same user account within a short time window, followed by a successful login. What security assessment activity does this scenario primarily represent?","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Log review and correlation for anomaly detection","Static code analysis","Synthetic transaction monitoring"],"c":1,"why":"This scenario describes reviewing and correlating log data across sources to detect anomalous patterns, such as a possible credential-stuffing or brute-force attack—a core function of log review within continuous security monitoring. Vulnerability scanning identifies weaknesses in systems, static analysis reviews source code, and synthetic transactions simulate user activity rather than analyzing actual log events.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A tester wants to generate malformed inputs based on a formal specification of a network protocol's message structure, rather than randomly altering previously captured valid packets. Which fuzzing approach is being used?","o":["Generation-based (intelligent) fuzzing","Mutation-based (dumb) fuzzing","Black-box penetration testing","Static code analysis"],"c":0,"why":"Generation-based fuzzing constructs test inputs from a protocol's formal specification or grammar, allowing deeper coverage of valid message structures. Mutation-based fuzzing instead randomly alters existing valid samples; black-box pentesting and static analysis are unrelated testing categories, not fuzzing methods.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"As part of a periodic access control assessment, an auditor compares the list of active employee accounts in the HR system against enabled accounts in Active Directory to identify accounts that should have been disabled after termination. This activity is best classified as:","o":["Penetration testing","Account management review","Code review","Misuse case testing"],"c":1,"why":"Account management review involves periodically verifying that user accounts and associated privileges remain appropriate, including identifying orphaned or improperly retained accounts after termination. Penetration testing and code review assess technical vulnerabilities rather than account lifecycle governance, and misuse case testing evaluates how functionality could be abused rather than reviewing account status.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During functional testing, a QA engineer only verifies that the application performs its intended functions correctly under expected inputs. Which additional testing approach should be incorporated to identify how the system behaves when a malicious actor intentionally submits invalid or hostile input?","o":["Misuse case (abuse case) testing","Regression testing","Unit testing","Acceptance testing"],"c":0,"why":"Misuse case testing models adversarial or hostile behavior to assess security-relevant responses to malicious input. Regression testing verifies changes don't break existing features, unit testing isolates individual code components, and acceptance testing confirms business requirements are met—none specifically address adversarial input by design.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A development team reports 100% statement coverage for their unit tests, meaning every line of code executed at least once during testing. A security architect is concerned this metric alone does not ensure thorough testing of conditional logic. Which additional coverage metric should be used to test both outcomes of every decision point?","o":["Branch (decision) coverage","Function coverage","Path coverage","Loop coverage"],"c":0,"why":"Branch coverage specifically verifies that both the true and false outcomes of every conditional statement are exercised, closing gaps left by statement coverage. Function coverage only confirms each function is called, path coverage is often impractically exhaustive for real systems, and loop coverage focuses narrowly on loop iteration counts rather than decision outcomes generally.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which type of penetration test provides the testing team with full knowledge of the target environment's architecture, source code, and credentials before testing begins?","o":["Black-box testing","White-box testing","Gray-box testing","Double-blind testing"],"c":1,"why":"White-box testing gives testers complete internal knowledge, allowing thorough and efficient testing. Black-box testing provides no internal information, gray-box provides partial information, and double-blind testing hides the test from both the testers' targets and often limits information given to testers.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to identify vulnerabilities in its web application source code before it is compiled and deployed. Which technique should be used?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Penetration testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source or binary code without executing it, making it suitable for pre-deployment code review. DAST and fuzz testing require a running application, and penetration testing typically occurs against a deployed system.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary purpose of a vulnerability scan compared to a penetration test?","o":["A vulnerability scan actively exploits weaknesses to demonstrate business impact","A vulnerability scan identifies and reports known weaknesses without exploiting them","A vulnerability scan requires the same skill level as a penetration test","A vulnerability scan is always performed after a penetration test"],"c":1,"why":"Vulnerability scans use automated tools to identify known weaknesses without attempting exploitation, whereas penetration tests go further by actively exploiting vulnerabilities to assess real-world impact. The other options misstate the relationship and scope of these two activities.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security team wants to verify that log data has not been altered since it was generated. Which control provides this assurance?","o":["Log rotation","Log normalization","Cryptographic hashing of log files","Centralized log aggregation"],"c":2,"why":"Cryptographic hashing creates a fingerprint that can detect any modification to log data, supporting integrity verification. Rotation, normalization, and aggregation help manage and standardize logs but do not verify integrity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which security assessment technique involves sending unexpected, malformed, or random data to an application to identify crashes or unexpected behavior?","o":["Fuzz testing","Code review","Misuse case testing","Interface testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing feeds invalid or random input to an application to uncover crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions. Code review examines source code, misuse case testing models attacker behavior scenarios, and interface testing focuses on validating data exchange points, none of which specifically involve random malformed input injection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization hires a security firm to test its network defenses. The testers are given no prior information about internal network architecture, IP ranges, or system configurations, and must simulate an external attacker with no insider knowledge. What type of testing approach is this?","o":["White-box testing","Black-box testing","Gray-box testing","Crystal-box testing"],"c":1,"why":"Black-box testing simulates an external attacker with no prior knowledge of the target environment, forcing testers to perform reconnaissance themselves. White-box provides full internal knowledge, gray-box provides partial knowledge, and 'crystal-box' is not a standard testing term.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team runs an automated tool weekly that scans hosts for missing patches, weak configurations, and known CVEs, producing a report ranked by severity. This activity is best described as which of the following?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability assessment","Security audit","Threat modeling"],"c":1,"why":"Vulnerability assessment uses automated scanning to identify and rank known weaknesses without exploiting them. Penetration testing goes further by actively exploiting vulnerabilities to demonstrate impact; a security audit evaluates compliance with policy/standards; threat modeling identifies potential threats during design.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A bank wants to evaluate the effectiveness of its perimeter security controls and, simultaneously, gauge how well its Security Operations Center (SOC) analysts detect and respond to a live intrusion. The engagement must not be disclosed to SOC staff in advance so that their reactions reflect real-world conditions. Which testing approach best satisfies these objectives?","o":["An announced black-box penetration test with the SOC notified 24 hours prior","An unannounced double-blind penetration test where neither the target system owners nor the SOC analysts are informed","A white-box test in which testers are given full source code and network diagrams","A gray-box test performed with partial documentation shared only with the testing team"],"c":1,"why":"A double-blind test keeps both the technical target and the defenders unaware of the exercise, allowing assessment of both control effectiveness and genuine SOC detection/response. Announcing the test or providing documentation to testers would bias results by alerting defenders or giving testers unrealistic insider knowledge.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An auditor performing a security control assessment interviews system administrators about how access reviews are conducted. This is an example of which assessment method?","o":["Testing","Examination","Interviewing","Automated scanning"],"c":2,"why":"Interviewing involves discussions with personnel to gather information about processes and controls, which is distinct from examining documentation (examination) or actively testing controls (testing). Automated scanning is a technical tool-based method, not a verbal exchange with staff.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During the software development lifecycle, a team wants to analyze application source code for insecure coding patterns, such as SQL injection risks, without executing the program. Which testing technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Interface testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source code or binaries for insecure patterns without running the application, making it ideal for early-lifecycle code review. DAST tests a running application, fuzz testing sends malformed input during execution, and interface testing focuses on data exchange points between components.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A tester is given full knowledge of the target's source code, network diagrams, and credentials before beginning a security test. This describes which type of testing approach?","o":["Black-box testing","Gray-box testing","White-box testing","Double-blind testing"],"c":2,"why":"White-box testing provides the tester with complete internal knowledge of the system, enabling thorough analysis. Black-box testing provides no internal knowledge; gray-box provides partial knowledge; double-blind testing hides the test from both the target's staff and sometimes the testers' full scope, not about knowledge level given to the tester.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During a security assessment, testers discover that a web application's authentication bypass vulnerability only manifests when the application is deployed behind a specific load-balancer configuration that improperly handles session tokens in a production-like environment. The flaw is not visible when reviewing the application's source code in isolation. Which testing methodology would most effectively have identified this vulnerability?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST) performed on the source code repository","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST) performed against a running instance in a representative environment","Manual peer code review of the authentication module","Software composition analysis of third-party libraries"],"c":1,"why":"DAST exercises the application at runtime within its actual deployment context, making it capable of surfacing environment- and configuration-dependent flaws like this session-handling issue. SAST and manual code review examine source code statically and would miss issues arising only from runtime infrastructure interactions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst reviewing centralized log data notices that a service account used only for automated backups authenticated interactively from an unusual geographic location at 3 a.m. This finding is most likely to be surfaced through which activity?","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Log review and analysis","Code review","Baseline configuration review"],"c":1,"why":"Log review and analysis (often supported by SIEM correlation) is designed to detect anomalous account behavior such as unexpected logins or usage patterns. Vulnerability scanning finds technical weaknesses, code review examines source code, and baseline configuration review checks system settings against approved standards, none of which would surface this behavioral anomaly.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which testing technique analyzes an application's source code for security flaws without executing the program?","o":["Dynamic application security testing (DAST)","Static application security testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source or compiled code without running it, identifying flaws like insecure functions or logic errors. DAST tests a running application; fuzz testing sends malformed input to a running program; penetration testing simulates real-world attacks against a live system.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A tester is evaluating a proprietary network protocol. Rather than capturing and mutating legitimate traffic samples, the tester writes a fuzzing engine that constructs entirely new packets from scratch based on the protocol's formal specification, deliberately generating edge cases and malformed field combinations not present in any observed traffic. This technique is best described as which type of fuzzing?","o":["Mutation-based (dumb) fuzzing","Generational (model-based) fuzzing","Random black-box fuzzing without protocol knowledge","Regression fuzzing using previously known crash inputs"],"c":1,"why":"Generational fuzzing builds test cases from a protocol model or specification, enabling coverage of edge cases beyond captured samples. Mutation fuzzing instead alters existing valid inputs, and the scenario explicitly avoids using captured traffic, ruling out mutation and random approaches.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A cloud service provider gives a customer a third-party audit report that describes the auditor's testing of controls over a six-month period and includes results of operating effectiveness, not just design. Which report type was most likely provided?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 3 report"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report covers the operating effectiveness of controls related to security, availability, or confidentiality over a period of time (e.g., six months), unlike Type I reports which assess design only at a point in time. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report without detailed testing results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization is selecting a cloud service provider and needs assurance that the provider's security controls have not only been properly designed but have also functioned effectively and consistently over the past twelve months. Which type of assurance report should the organization request from the provider's auditor?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 3 report with a point-in-time attestation"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates both the design and the operating effectiveness of controls over an extended period (typically 6-12 months), which directly addresses the requirement. Type I reports only assess control design at a single point in time, and SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls rather than security.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to identify and prioritize weaknesses in an organization's network by using automated tools that compare system configurations and patch levels against a database of known issues, without attempting to exploit them. Which activity best describes this approach?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability assessment","Red team exercise","Security audit"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment uses automated scanning to identify and rate potential weaknesses without exploitation. Penetration testing goes further by actively exploiting vulnerabilities; a red team exercise simulates real adversaries with broader objectives; a security audit verifies compliance with policies/standards, not just technical flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security analyst regularly reviews firewall, IDS, and authentication logs to identify unusual patterns such as repeated failed logins or unexpected outbound traffic. This activity primarily supports which security assessment function?","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Log review and analysis","Code review","Compliance auditing"],"c":1,"why":"Log review and analysis involves examining recorded system and network events to detect anomalies or indicators of compromise. Vulnerability scanning tests systems for known weaknesses; code review examines source code; compliance auditing verifies adherence to standards, none of which centers on ongoing log examination.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"To continuously validate that a critical e-commerce checkout process is functioning correctly from the customer's perspective, an organization configures automated scripts that simulate a full purchase transaction every 15 minutes and alert if failures occur. This technique is known as what?","o":["Fuzz testing","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Misuse case testing","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user activity on a scheduled basis to proactively verify system availability and functionality. Fuzz testing injects malformed input to find defects, misuse case testing models attacker behavior, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality after code modifications.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A customer wants assurance that a cloud service provider's internal controls over security, availability, and confidentiality are operating effectively over a period of time. Which type of report would best provide this assurance?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","Penetration test summary","Vulnerability scan report"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the design and operating effectiveness of controls related to security, availability, and confidentiality over a defined period, matching the requirement. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls; Type I only assesses design at a point in time; pen test and vulnerability scan reports address technical testing, not overall control assurance.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A company's customers require assurance that the organization's cloud service provider has effective controls over security, availability, and confidentiality operating consistently over a six-month period. Which type of report should the customer request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 3 report summary only"],"c":2,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the design AND operating effectiveness of controls over a period of time (e.g., six months), covering trust service criteria like security and availability. Type I only assesses design at a point in time; SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls; SOC 3 is a general-use summary lacking the detailed testing results needed here.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A company wants to continuously validate that its critical online transaction system is functioning correctly from an end-user perspective, even when no real user activity is occurring. Which technique should be implemented?","o":["Synthetic transactions","Log review","Static code analysis","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate user actions on a scheduled basis to proactively verify system availability and functionality. Log review is reactive and analyzes past activity, static code analysis examines source code rather than live system behavior, and misuse case testing focuses on abuse scenarios rather than routine functional monitoring.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"To proactively detect latent functional and security errors in a critical e-commerce checkout workflow before real customers encounter them, a security team configures automated scripts that periodically simulate complete user purchase transactions—including login, item selection, and payment—against the live production environment. What is this technique called?","o":["Real user monitoring (RUM)","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Passive network traffic analysis","Log correlation and SIEM alerting"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transaction monitoring uses scripted, simulated transactions to proactively validate system behavior and catch failures before real users are affected. RUM passively observes actual user sessions rather than generating simulated ones, and the other options do not involve actively exercising the application.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization deploys scripted transactions that mimic real user behavior, such as logging in and completing a purchase, to continuously monitor application performance and availability from an external perspective. This technique is known as:","o":["Synthetic transactions","Fuzz testing","Interface testing","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate typical user actions to proactively monitor system performance, availability, and functionality. Fuzz testing sends random/malformed input to find crashes; interface testing checks data exchange between components; misuse case testing models how an attacker might abuse functionality.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A QA engineer feeds a network protocol parser large volumes of randomly malformed and oversized packets to observe whether the application crashes, hangs, or exposes memory. Which testing technique is being applied?","o":["Fuzz testing","Static analysis","Misuse case testing","Interface testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing involves supplying invalid, unexpected, or random data to an application to uncover crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions, which is exactly the scenario described. Static analysis examines code without execution, misuse case testing models specific attacker scenarios, and interface testing focuses on data exchange correctness between components rather than malformed input handling.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An automated vulnerability scanner flags numerous findings as critical, but the security team knows from experience that many are false positives due to compensating controls not visible to the scanner (such as network segmentation or WAF rules). In a compliance-driven environment where remediation resources are limited, what is the best next step before assigning remediation priorities?","o":["Remediate all findings labeled critical regardless of context to satisfy compliance auditors","Suppress all findings with a history of being false positives in prior scans","Manually validate and correlate scan findings with compensating controls and exploitability before prioritizing remediation","Increase the scanning frequency to confirm findings through repeated automated detection"],"c":2,"why":"Manual validation and correlation with compensating controls ensures remediation effort is directed at genuinely exploitable risks, which is essential given known scanner limitations. Blindly remediating everything wastes resources, blanket suppression risks missing real vulnerabilities, and rescanning alone won't reveal context the scanner cannot see.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During test planning, a team documents specific ways an attacker might abuse a password reset feature, such as exploiting predictable security questions or intercepting reset tokens, and designs test cases around these abuse scenarios. This approach is best described as which of the following?","o":["Misuse case testing","Regression testing","Synthetic transaction testing","Static code analysis"],"c":0,"why":"Misuse case testing explicitly models how an attacker might abuse a feature and derives test cases from those abuse scenarios, complementing normal use-case testing. Regression testing checks for reintroduced defects after changes, synthetic transactions simulate normal user activity for monitoring, and static code analysis examines source code rather than functional abuse scenarios.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"According to security control assessment methodology, which of the following is an example of the 'examine' method of assessing a control, as opposed to 'test' or 'interview'?","o":["Reviewing firewall configuration files and change management documentation","Attempting to bypass the firewall using crafted packets","Asking the firewall administrator to describe the change process","Running an automated exploit against the firewall"],"c":0,"why":"The 'examine' method involves reviewing documents, configurations, and records to assess a control. Attempting to bypass the firewall or running an exploit is the 'test' method; asking the administrator to describe the process is the 'interview' method.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During application security testing, an assessor examines the source code line-by-line to identify insecure coding patterns such as unvalidated input handling, without executing the program. Which testing technique is being used?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source code or binaries without executing the application, making it ideal for detecting insecure coding patterns early. DAST tests a running application from the outside; fuzz testing sends malformed input to a running program; IAST combines runtime and code analysis, which is not what's described.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"Two microservices developed by separate teams communicate over an internal API. An assessor wants to verify that the receiving service properly validates and rejects malformed, oversized, or unexpected input sent across this trust boundary, rather than simply confirming that expected inputs produce correct outputs. Which testing activity best describes this focus?","o":["Unit testing of each microservice in isolation","Regression testing following the most recent code deployment","Interface (API) security testing focused on misuse cases at the trust boundary","Static code review of both services' source repositories"],"c":2,"why":"Interface testing that incorporates misuse cases specifically examines how a system handles unexpected, malicious, or malformed input at trust boundaries between components, which is the described objective. Unit testing typically validates intended functionality of a single component, regression testing verifies no new defects were introduced, and static review does not exercise live interactions between services.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During a scheduled penetration test, the assessment team is given zero information about the target environment, and the organization's own IT and security staff are not informed that a test is taking place. The goal is to evaluate both the technical controls and the effectiveness of the incident response process under realistic conditions. Which type of test is being described?","o":["Blind test, because the testers lack prior knowledge of the environment","Double-blind test, because neither the testers nor internal staff have knowledge of the assessment","White-box test, because full internal documentation was provided to the assessors","Gray-box test, because partial knowledge of the network architecture was shared"],"c":1,"why":"A double-blind test conceals the engagement from both the testers (who receive no environment details) and the organization's own staff (who are unaware testing is occurring), which uniquely allows evaluation of real-world detection and response capabilities. A blind test only conceals information from the testers; white-box and gray-box tests involve informed testers with full or partial knowledge, which is the opposite of the described scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A company wants to validate its disaster recovery plan without disrupting production systems or actually failing over to a backup site. Participants discuss their roles and walk through response steps for a simulated outage scenario. This is an example of a:","o":["Full interruption test","Parallel test","Tabletop exercise","Simulation test with live failover"],"c":2,"why":"A tabletop exercise involves participants discussing and walking through the plan in a low-risk, discussion-based format without impacting live systems. A full interruption test actually shuts down primary operations; a parallel test runs the backup system alongside production; a simulation with live failover would involve actual technical execution, which contradicts the scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst configures automated scripts that periodically simulate legitimate user transactions—such as logging in and completing a purchase—on a production e-commerce site to detect performance degradation or functional failures before real customers are affected. This technique is best described as:","o":["Misuse case testing","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Regression testing","Interface testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transaction monitoring uses scripted, simulated user interactions to proactively detect issues in production systems. Misuse case testing focuses on how attackers might abuse functionality; regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality; interface testing validates data exchange between system components, not ongoing production monitoring.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A CISO wants a single metric to present to the board that best reflects the ongoing efficiency and health of the vulnerability management remediation process, rather than simply the volume of vulnerabilities discovered. Which metric is most appropriate?","o":["Total number of vulnerabilities identified per scan cycle","Average CVSS score of all findings in the current inventory","Mean Time to Remediate (MTTR) for critical and high-severity vulnerabilities","Number of vulnerability scans completed per quarter"],"c":2,"why":"MTTR for high-severity findings directly measures how efficiently the organization closes its most significant exposures, which is the key indicator of program health. Raw vulnerability counts, average severity scores, and scan frequency describe scanning activity or exposure volume but do not measure remediation performance.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security team needs to identify SQL injection and cross-site scripting vulnerabilities in a third-party web application for which no source code is available. The application must be tested while running in a staging environment, sending crafted HTTP requests and observing responses. Which testing approach is most appropriate?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)","Manual secure code review"],"c":1,"why":"DAST tests an application externally while it is running, requiring no access to source code, making it ideal for black-box testing of injection and XSS flaws. SAST and manual code review both require source code access, and SCA is used to identify vulnerable third-party libraries/components rather than injection flaws through runtime interaction.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization is selecting a cloud service provider and requires assurance that the provider's security, availability, and confidentiality controls were not only properly designed but also operated effectively over a six-month period. Which report should the organization request from the provider?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 1 Type II report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report"],"c":3,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of controls related to the Trust Services Criteria (security, availability, confidentiality, etc.) over a defined period, which matches the requirement. SOC 1 reports focus on controls relevant to financial reporting, and any Type I report only assesses design suitability at a single point in time, not sustained operating effectiveness.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization deploys a Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system to aggregate logs from firewalls, IDS sensors, and servers, then applies correlation rules to detect a pattern of failed logins followed by a successful login from an unusual location. This process exemplifies which security assessment activity?","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Log review and analysis","Penetration testing","Code review"],"c":1,"why":"Log review and analysis, especially when automated through a SIEM with correlation rules, identifies suspicious patterns across multiple log sources. Vulnerability scanning checks for known weaknesses in systems, not log patterns; penetration testing actively exploits systems; code review examines application source code, unrelated to this scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A tester wants to evaluate a proprietary network protocol implementation by systematically crafting malformed packets based on the protocol's formal specification and grammar, rather than modifying previously captured legitimate traffic samples. Which fuzzing technique is being used?","o":["Mutation-based fuzzing","Generation-based fuzzing","Regression testing","Static binary analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Generation-based fuzzing constructs test inputs from a model or specification of the expected input format, allowing structured but invalid combinations to be produced. Mutation-based fuzzing instead modifies existing valid input samples; regression testing verifies prior functionality still works, and static binary analysis examines code without execution, neither of which involve crafting inputs from a specification.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A tester sends large volumes of randomly generated or malformed input data to a network protocol parser to observe whether it crashes, hangs, or exhibits unexpected behavior. This technique is known as:","o":["Fuzz testing","Boundary value analysis","Static analysis","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing involves feeding invalid, unexpected, or random data to software to identify crashes, memory leaks, or other vulnerabilities. Boundary value analysis is a functional testing technique focused on edge values of valid input ranges; static analysis examines code without execution; misuse case testing models attacker scenarios rather than random malformed input.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A federal agency operating under a Risk Management Framework wants to reduce the likelihood that its security posture drifts significantly between formal reauthorization assessments, which occur only every three years. The agency implements automated tools that continuously evaluate selected security controls and feed results into the organizational risk register. What is this practice called?","o":["Annual control self-assessment","Continuous monitoring program","Business continuity plan exercise","One-time vulnerability scan"],"c":1,"why":"Continuous monitoring provides ongoing, near-real-time visibility into control effectiveness and risk posture between formal assessment and authorization cycles, supporting an ongoing authorization decision. Annual self-assessments and one-time scans are point-in-time activities, and a BCP exercise tests continuity procedures rather than control effectiveness.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During a security audit, the auditor selects a sample of user access requests and traces each one through the approval workflow to verify that proper authorization was obtained before access was granted. This audit technique is best classified as:","o":["Compliance testing","Substantive testing","Vulnerability scanning","Penetration testing"],"c":0,"why":"Compliance testing verifies that controls are being followed as designed—here, tracing access requests through the approval process confirms adherence to the authorization policy. Substantive testing verifies the accuracy of data/transactions rather than process adherence; vulnerability scanning and penetration testing are technical assessments, not audit sampling techniques.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A disaster recovery team wants to validate their recovery procedures with minimal risk to production systems by having participants discuss and walk through their responsibilities and decision points in response to a simulated outage scenario, without actually activating any systems. This is an example of a:","o":["Full interruption test","Parallel test","Simulation test","Tabletop exercise"],"c":3,"why":"A tabletop exercise involves discussion-based walkthroughs of a scenario without operational activation, ideal for validating plans with minimal risk. A simulation test involves acting out response activities more actively; a parallel test runs recovery systems alongside production; a full interruption test actually shuts down production systems, both carrying much higher risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security operations team wants to proactively detect degradation in a critical e-commerce application's checkout process before actual customers experience failures. They configure automated scripts that simulate a user logging in, adding an item to a cart, and completing checkout every five minutes from multiple geographic locations. What testing technique does this describe?","o":["Real user monitoring","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Static code analysis","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transaction monitoring uses scripted, simulated user interactions to proactively test application availability and functionality, independent of actual customer traffic. Real user monitoring passively observes actual user sessions rather than generating simulated ones, and static code analysis and penetration testing do not involve scheduled functional simulation of business transactions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An analyst investigating a suspected breach notices that a failed login on a web server, followed by a successful VPN authentication from an unusual country, followed by an unusual database export, appear as three unrelated entries across three separate log sources. Only when these events are aggregated and analyzed together does a pattern indicating lateral movement become evident. What technique enabled this discovery?","o":["Log correlation analysis","Isolated single-source log review","Vulnerability assessment","Static application security testing"],"c":0,"why":"Log correlation analysis aggregates and cross-references events from multiple, disparate log sources to reveal patterns and relationships not visible when logs are reviewed in isolation, which is exactly what a SIEM-based correlation engine performs. Reviewing a single log source would miss the relationship across systems, and vulnerability assessment and SAST address weaknesses rather than event pattern detection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A test team is developing test cases not only for how a banking application should function for legitimate customers (e.g., transferring funds) but also for how a malicious actor might deliberately abuse the transfer feature to conduct fraud, such as exploiting race conditions to duplicate a transaction. What testing approach specifically addresses the second scenario?","o":["Use case testing","Misuse case testing","Unit testing","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Misuse case testing (or abuse case testing) explicitly models how an attacker might intentionally exploit or subvert a system's functionality, complementing use case testing which validates intended, legitimate behavior. Unit testing validates individual code components in isolation, and regression testing confirms that changes have not broken existing functionality, neither of which specifically models adversarial misuse.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization runs an automated tool weekly that compares system configurations against a database of known CVEs and misconfigurations, producing a list of unpatched software and weak settings. Which security testing technique is being described?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability scanning","Security audit","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"Vulnerability scanning uses automated tools to identify known weaknesses (unpatched software, misconfigurations) without actively exploiting them. Penetration testing goes further by attempting exploitation; an audit is a formal compliance review; fuzzing sends malformed input to find crashes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which statement best describes the primary difference between a vulnerability assessment and a penetration test?","o":["A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs potential weaknesses, while a penetration test actively attempts to exploit them to demonstrate real-world impact","A vulnerability assessment is always performed by an internal team, while a penetration test is always performed by an external vendor","A vulnerability assessment tests physical security, while a penetration test only tests network security","A vulnerability assessment requires management approval, while a penetration test does not"],"c":0,"why":"Vulnerability assessments enumerate and prioritize weaknesses without exploiting them, whereas penetration tests go further by exploiting vulnerabilities to prove impact. The other options describe incorrect or overly rigid distinctions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to evaluate a web application's source code for insecure coding patterns such as SQL injection vulnerabilities before the application is compiled and deployed. Which testing approach is most appropriate?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Penetration testing of the production environment"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source code (or binaries) for insecure patterns without executing the program, making it suitable for pre-deployment review. DAST tests a running application, IAST combines runtime instrumentation with analysis, and production penetration testing occurs after deployment.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"In a 'black-box' penetration test, what level of information is typically provided to the testing team before the engagement begins?","o":["Full network diagrams, source code, and administrative credentials","No prior knowledge of the internal systems, source code, or network architecture, simulating an external attacker","Partial knowledge, such as network diagrams but no credentials","Complete access to the source code but no network information"],"c":1,"why":"Black-box testing simulates an outside attacker with no internal knowledge, forcing testers to discover information on their own. Providing full or partial internal details describes white-box or gray-box testing instead.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A CISO wants independent assurance that a cloud service provider's controls are suitable for protecting customer financial data throughout the year, including evidence of control operation over time rather than a point-in-time snapshot. Which report should the CISO request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 2 Type I report","A vulnerability scan report from the provider"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the design AND operating effectiveness of controls over a period of time (e.g., 6-12 months), relevant to security/availability/confidentiality. Type I reports only assess design at a single point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and a vulnerability scan is not an assurance audit report.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which type of code analysis examines an application's source code for security flaws without executing the program?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Fuzz testing","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Penetration testing"],"c":2,"why":"SAST reviews source or binary code for vulnerabilities without running the application. DAST and fuzz testing require execution, and penetration testing typically targets running systems rather than raw code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During continuous monitoring, an analyst configures a system to automatically execute pre-defined business transactions against a production application at regular intervals to verify availability and performance from an end-user perspective. This technique is known as:","o":["Log correlation","Synthetic transactions","Misuse case testing","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user activity against a live system to proactively monitor availability, functionality, and performance. Log correlation analyzes existing log data, misuse case testing models attacker behavior, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security team wants to test a running web application by sending it various inputs and observing its behavior for vulnerabilities such as SQL injection. This is an example of which testing approach?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Code peer review","Threat modeling"],"c":1,"why":"DAST tests an application in its running state by interacting with it externally, which matches sending inputs and observing behavior. SAST analyzes source code without execution, and code review/threat modeling are performed differently.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A tester supplies large volumes of randomly malformed and unexpected input to a network protocol implementation to identify crashes, memory leaks, or unexpected behavior. This technique is best described as:","o":["Fuzz testing","Static code analysis","Interface testing","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing feeds invalid, unexpected, or random data to software to uncover crashes, memory corruption, or other flaws. Static analysis examines code without execution, interface testing focuses on data exchange between components, and misuse case testing models specific attacker scenarios rather than random input.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of regularly reviewing system and security logs?","o":["To satisfy storage retention requirements only","To identify anomalies, policy violations, or evidence of security incidents that may otherwise go unnoticed","To replace the need for intrusion detection systems","To generate reports solely for executive presentations"],"c":1,"why":"Log review helps detect suspicious activity, policy violations, and indicators of compromise that automated systems might miss. Retention compliance and executive reporting may be secondary benefits, but they are not the primary security purpose, and log review complements rather than replaces IDS.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security team runs an automated tool that scans network hosts for known missing patches and misconfigurations, then produces a report ranking issues by severity. This activity is best described as which type of assessment?","o":["Penetration test","Vulnerability assessment","Social engineering test","Business impact analysis"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment uses automated scanning to identify and rank known weaknesses without attempting exploitation. Penetration testing goes further to actively exploit findings, social engineering targets people, and a BIA analyzes impact of disruptions, not technical flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During a code review, a QA team measures the percentage of executable statements exercised by their test suite to determine testing thoroughness. Which metric are they calculating?","o":["Mean time to detect (MTTD)","Code coverage","Attack surface analysis","Defect density"],"c":1,"why":"Code coverage measures the proportion of source code executed during testing, indicating how thoroughly the test suite exercises the application. MTTD measures detection speed, attack surface analysis identifies exposed entry points, and defect density measures bugs per unit of code, not execution coverage.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Why might an organization engage an independent third-party firm to conduct a security audit rather than relying solely on internal staff?","o":["Third-party auditors are always less expensive than internal teams","Internal staff are legally prohibited from performing audits","An independent auditor provides objectivity and reduces potential bias or conflicts of interest in the assessment","Third-party audits do not require management approval"],"c":2,"why":"External auditors bring independence and objectivity, reducing bias that might occur when staff audit their own systems. Cost, legality, and approval requirements are not the defining reasons for using third-party auditors.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a penetration test, the testers are given no prior knowledge of the target's internal architecture, source code, or credentials and must discover everything on their own. What type of test is this?","o":["White box testing","Gray box testing","Black box testing","Crystal box testing"],"c":2,"why":"Black box testing simulates an external attacker with zero prior knowledge of the environment. White box testers have full internal knowledge, gray box testers have partial knowledge, and 'crystal box' is not a standard testing term.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security team must assess a compiled, closed-source third-party application for vulnerabilities such as buffer overflows and injection flaws while it is actively running in a QA environment. The vendor will not provide source code. Which testing technique is BEST suited to this scenario?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST) using decompiled binaries","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST) against the running application","Software Composition Analysis (SCA) of third-party libraries","Manual secure code review of the vendor's design documents"],"c":1,"why":"DAST tests an application from the outside while it executes, requiring no source code and capturing runtime behavior like memory corruption. SAST needs source or reliable decompiled code (impractical here), SCA only inventories known-vulnerable components, and design review doesn't test actual execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An internal audit team reviews access control logs, change management records, and incident response documentation to verify that an organization's ISO 27001-based ISMS is being implemented as designed. This activity is best classified as:","o":["A penetration test","A vulnerability assessment","An internal security audit","Synthetic transaction monitoring"],"c":2,"why":"Reviewing documentation, logs, and records to verify conformance with a management system standard (like ISO 27001) is a hallmark of an internal audit conducted by the organization's own personnel. Penetration tests and vulnerability assessments involve active technical testing, while synthetic transactions monitor live application performance.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization configures automated scripts to simulate user logins and transactions on its e-commerce site every 15 minutes to verify availability and performance. This technique is known as:","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring","Fuzz testing","Misuse case testing","Regression testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions use scripted, simulated user activity to proactively monitor system availability and performance. Fuzz testing targets input handling flaws, misuse case testing focuses on abuse scenarios, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A developer reviews application source code line by line, without executing the program, to identify insecure coding patterns such as hard-coded credentials. This technique is known as:","o":["Dynamic application security testing (DAST)","Static application security testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source code without running it, catching issues like insecure patterns early. DAST tests a running application, fuzzing sends malformed input to a running program, and penetration testing is a broader exploitation-focused exercise.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to identify weaknesses in its network by scanning systems for known vulnerabilities, but has not authorized any attempt to exploit those weaknesses. Which activity best describes this engagement?","o":["Penetration test","Vulnerability assessment","Red team exercise","Security audit"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs weaknesses without exploiting them. Penetration testing and red team exercises involve active exploitation, and a security audit evaluates compliance with policies/controls rather than scanning for technical flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A financial services customer is evaluating a cloud provider and requires evidence that the provider's security controls were both properly designed AND operated effectively over a continuous six-month period. Which report should the customer request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 3 report"],"c":2,"why":"SOC 2 Type II covers the trust services criteria (security, availability, etc.) and tests operating effectiveness over a period of time, unlike Type I which is a point-in-time design assessment. SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report without the detailed testing results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security manager wants to test whether help-desk staff would improperly reset a password for a caller who claims to be a senior executive but cannot provide standard identity verification. Which type of assessment technique should be used?","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Social engineering exercise","Static code analysis","Compliance audit"],"c":1,"why":"A social engineering exercise (e.g., pretext calling) directly tests human susceptibility to manipulation and policy adherence, which is the goal here. Vulnerability scanning and static code analysis assess technical systems, not human behavior, and a compliance audit reviews documentation/process adherence rather than actively testing staff response to deception.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a tabletop exercise used to test an organization's incident response plan, what best describes the activity that takes place?","o":["Actual systems are taken offline and real attack tools are used against production servers","Participants discuss and walk through hypothetical incident scenarios in a conference room setting without impacting live systems","Automated scanning tools are run against the network to identify vulnerabilities","Source code is reviewed line by line for security flaws"],"c":1,"why":"A tabletop exercise is a discussion-based walkthrough of a scenario, allowing teams to evaluate plans and roles without affecting live systems. Taking systems offline, scanning, or code review describe other, more technical or disruptive testing methods.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of regularly reviewing security audit logs?","o":["To satisfy storage capacity requirements","To detect unauthorized or anomalous activity that may indicate a security incident","To reduce the need for firewalls","To automatically patch vulnerable systems"],"c":1,"why":"Log review's main security value is identifying suspicious or unauthorized activity for timely response. Logs don't patch systems or replace firewalls, and storage capacity is an operational, not security, concern.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A development team wants to analyze application source code for insecure coding patterns before the application is compiled and run. Which technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Fuzz testing","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)"],"c":2,"why":"SAST examines source code without executing the program, making it suitable for pre-compilation review. DAST and fuzzing require a running application, and IAST instruments a running application during testing rather than analyzing raw source.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During a vulnerability assessment, a non-credentialed scan of a Windows server reports far fewer findings than a credentialed scan of the same host. What is the PRIMARY reason for this discrepancy?","o":["Non-credentialed scans only run during business hours, missing after-hours patches","Credentialed scans exploit vulnerabilities to confirm them, inflating the count","Non-credentialed scans can only enumerate network-exposed services and banners, while credentialed scans can inspect local patch levels, registry settings, and installed software","Non-credentialed scanners use outdated vulnerability signatures compared to credentialed scanners"],"c":2,"why":"Credentialed scans authenticate to the host and can query local configuration, patch state, and installed applications directly, revealing far more issues than a purely network-based, unauthenticated scan that is limited to what's visible externally. The other options misstate scanner behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization asks a vendor for a report describing the design of its controls at a single point in time, without testing their operating effectiveness. Which type of report is this?","o":["SOC 2 Type II","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 1 Type II","ISO 27001 certification audit"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type I report evaluates the design of controls at a specific point in time, whereas Type II tests operating effectiveness over a period. SOC 1 reports focus on financial controls, and ISO 27001 certification is a different audit framework.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A tester is given full knowledge of an organization's network diagrams, source code, and credentials before conducting a penetration test. What type of test is this?","o":["Black-box test","Gray-box test","White-box test","Double-blind test"],"c":2,"why":"White-box testing provides the tester with complete internal knowledge of the target environment. Black-box testing provides no prior knowledge, gray-box provides partial knowledge, and double-blind refers to neither the testers nor most staff being aware of the test's timing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A tester captures legitimate network packets from a proprietary protocol and writes a script that systematically flips bits, truncates fields, and injects random values into copies of these captured packets before replaying them at the parser to find crashes. This technique is an example of:","o":["Generation-based fuzzing","Mutation-based fuzzing","Symbolic execution","Fault injection via static taint analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Mutation-based (\"dumb\") fuzzing takes valid sample inputs and alters them to create malformed test cases, exactly as described. Generation-based fuzzing builds inputs from a protocol specification/grammar rather than mutating captured samples, and symbolic execution/taint analysis are code-analysis techniques, not input-mutation testing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A QA team automatically submits simulated user login attempts to a production web application every hour to verify continuous availability and correct functioning of the authentication service. This technique is called:","o":["Fuzz testing","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Misuse case testing","Regression testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user actions on live systems to verify functionality and performance continuously. Fuzzing sends malformed input to find crashes, misuse case testing explores abuse scenarios, and regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A company's customer requests evidence of the effectiveness of the company's security controls over a 12-month period, including operating effectiveness testing performed by an independent auditor. Which report would best satisfy this request?","o":["SOC 1 Type I report","SOC 2 Type II report","SOC 2 Type I report","A vulnerability scan report"],"c":1,"why":"A SOC 2 Type II report evaluates the operating effectiveness of security-related controls over a period of time (e.g., 12 months) by an independent auditor. Type I reports only assess design at a point in time, SOC 1 focuses on financial reporting controls, and a vulnerability scan does not provide independent assurance of control effectiveness.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to realistically evaluate its Security Operations Center's detection and incident response capability during an authorized penetration test. Which testing approach BEST achieves this by ensuring the SOC has no advance knowledge that a test is occurring?","o":["White-box (full knowledge) test","Single-blind (blind) test","Double-blind test","Gray-box test with rules of engagement shared with the SOC"],"c":2,"why":"In a double-blind test, neither the testers nor the defending SOC/incident response team have prior knowledge, providing the most realistic measure of detection and response. A single-blind test typically still informs some defenders in advance for safety, and white-box/gray-box tests share information that would bias the SOC's response.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Before conducting a security test, an assessor maps which test cases correspond to which functional requirements to ensure no requirement is left unverified. This activity is called:","o":["Test coverage analysis","Threat modeling","Code obfuscation","Configuration management"],"c":0,"why":"Test coverage analysis ensures that all requirements or code paths are addressed by test cases, reducing the risk of untested functionality. Threat modeling identifies potential threats, obfuscation hides code logic, and configuration management tracks system changes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst is correlating firewall, IDS, and authentication logs in a SIEM to identify a pattern of failed logins followed by a successful login from an unusual location. This activity is an example of:","o":["Synthetic transaction monitoring","Log review and correlation","Misuse case testing","Interface testing"],"c":1,"why":"Correlating multiple log sources to detect suspicious patterns is log review and correlation, a core security monitoring/assessment activity. Synthetic transactions simulate user activity proactively, misuse case testing evaluates how systems respond to abuse scenarios during design/testing, and interface testing validates data exchange between components.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During a security assessment, an auditor wants to verify that every security requirement in the system's specification has at least one corresponding test case, and that every test case maps back to a documented requirement. Which artifact is used to perform this verification?","o":["Requirements traceability matrix","Risk register","Configuration management database (CMDB)","Security Content Automation Protocol (SCAP) benchmark"],"c":0,"why":"A requirements traceability matrix explicitly cross-references requirements to test cases to confirm complete test coverage and eliminate gaps or orphaned tests. A risk register tracks identified risks, a CMDB tracks configuration items, and SCAP benchmarks define automated configuration/compliance checks, none of which map requirements to tests.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the purpose of a security assessment report delivered to senior management after a penetration test?","o":["To provide exploit code for internal red teams to reuse","To document findings, risk ratings, and remediation recommendations in a format management can use for decision-making","To replace the need for future vulnerability scans","To satisfy legal discovery requirements exclusively"],"c":1,"why":"The assessment report's core purpose is to communicate risks and remediation guidance to support informed management decisions. It is not meant to serve as reusable exploit code, eliminate future testing needs, or serve solely a legal discovery function.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A security team is contracted to perform a penetration test against a mid-size company's network. The scope requires that the internal security operations center (SOC) staff have no advance knowledge of the test, and the penetration testers are given no internal documentation, network diagrams, or credentials prior to starting. Which type of penetration test is being conducted?","o":["White-box test","Gray-box test","Double-blind (zero-knowledge) test","Black-box test with full disclosure to the SOC"],"c":2,"why":"A double-blind test conceals the engagement from both the testers (no internal info) and the defenders (no advance notice), testing both technical controls and real-world detection/response capability. White-box gives full information, gray-box gives partial information, and 'full disclosure to the SOC' contradicts the scenario since the SOC must remain unaware.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A SOC team's SIEM generates an overwhelming volume of alerts for internal administrative logins that are actually routine and expected, causing analysts to miss true incidents due to alert fatigue. Which action provides the BEST long-term resolution?","o":["Disable authentication logging for internal administrative accounts","Increase the retention period for raw logs to allow deeper forensic review later","Establish behavioral baselines for normal administrative activity and tune correlation rules/thresholds to alert only on deviations","Switch from a centralized SIEM to standalone host-based logging on each server"],"c":2,"why":"Baselining normal behavior and tuning correlation rules reduces false positives while preserving detection of true anomalies, addressing the root cause of alert fatigue. Disabling logging removes visibility, longer retention doesn't reduce noise, and decentralizing logging removes correlation capability entirely.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"To proactively verify that a web application's checkout process is functioning correctly at all hours without waiting for real customer complaints, an organization configures scripted transactions that mimic user behavior and run on a schedule. This is an example of:","o":["Synthetic transactions","Regression testing","Fuzz testing","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions use scripted, simulated user interactions to proactively monitor availability and functionality. Regression testing verifies that changes haven't broken existing functionality, fuzz testing injects malformed input to find flaws, and misuse case testing focuses on how a system handles malicious or abusive scenarios.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During the design and coding phase of a secure SDLC, a developer wants to identify potential injection flaws and insecure coding patterns directly within the application's source code before compilation, without executing the program. Which testing technique is most appropriate?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source or byte code without execution, making it ideal for early-SDLC review of unbuilt code. DAST and fuzz testing require a running application, and IAST requires instrumentation of a running app combined with code analysis, none of which fit the 'before compilation, without executing' constraint.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During test planning, a QA team creates test cases specifically designed to determine how the application behaves when an attacker attempts to bypass authentication using SQL injection. This testing approach is best described as:","o":["Misuse case testing","Interface testing","Test coverage analysis","Synthetic monitoring"],"c":0,"why":"Misuse case testing derives test scenarios from how a malicious actor might abuse the system, such as attempting SQL injection to bypass authentication. Interface testing focuses on data exchange between components, test coverage analysis measures how much of the code/requirements were tested, and synthetic monitoring simulates normal user behavior rather than attacks.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"To continuously validate that a production e-commerce checkout process is functioning correctly and securely without disrupting real customer transactions or exposing live customer data, a testing team scripts automated, scheduled transactions that mimic real user behavior end-to-end in the live environment. This technique is known as:","o":["Regression testing","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Chaos engineering","Interface (API) fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user activity against production systems on a scheduled basis to continuously validate functionality and performance without using live customer data. Regression testing validates changes against prior functionality (typically pre-production), chaos engineering intentionally injects failures to test resilience, and API fuzz testing targets malformed inputs rather than simulating normal transactions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm wants to proactively verify that its customer-facing online banking application is available and functioning correctly around the clock, even during periods of low real user traffic. The security team configures scripted actions that log in, check balances, and log out at scheduled intervals, then alerts if any step fails. Which testing technique does this describe?","o":["Real user monitoring (RUM)","Synthetic transaction monitoring","Passive vulnerability scanning","Log correlation analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Synthetic transaction monitoring uses scripted, simulated user actions run on a schedule to proactively verify functionality and availability independent of actual traffic. RUM only observes real user sessions, passive scanning identifies vulnerabilities rather than functional health, and log correlation is reactive analysis of existing events.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to validate its disaster recovery plan with minimal disruption to production systems, focusing on having stakeholders discuss their roles and responsibilities during a simulated incident without actually activating any systems. Which DR test type is being described?","o":["Parallel test","Full interruption test","Tabletop exercise","Simulation test"],"c":2,"why":"A tabletop exercise involves discussion-based walkthroughs of roles and responsibilities without activating systems, making it the least disruptive test type. A simulation test involves actually performing recovery actions, a parallel test runs recovery systems alongside production, and a full interruption test actually shuts down production, both of which carry far greater risk and disruption.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A CISO evaluating a cloud service provider (CSP) needs assurance that the CSP's security controls were not only suitably designed but also operated effectively over a six-month period. Which type of audit report should the CISO request from the CSP?","o":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 3"],"c":2,"why":"SOC 2 Type II reports test and attest to operating effectiveness of controls over a defined period, matching the requirement. SOC 2 Type I only evaluates design at a single point in time, SOC 1 focuses on controls relevant to financial reporting, and SOC 3 is a general-use summary report lacking the detailed testing results needed for due diligence.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A tester takes valid, well-formed sample application inputs (e.g., valid JSON API requests) captured from production traffic and then automatically applies random bit-flips, truncations, and value substitutions to generate thousands of malformed test cases, replaying them against the application to observe crashes or unexpected behavior. Which fuzzing approach is being used?","o":["Generation-based (model-based) fuzzing","Mutation-based fuzzing","Protocol-based fuzzing","Structure-aware grammar fuzzing"],"c":1,"why":"Mutation-based fuzzing starts with existing valid samples and randomly alters them to create test cases, exactly as described. Generation-based and grammar-aware fuzzing instead construct inputs from a specification or grammar model rather than mutating captured samples, and 'protocol-based' is not the defining characteristic of this specific technique.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"An auditor reviewing system logs for evidence of unauthorized access wants assurance that log entries have not been altered after being written, and that any modification attempt would be detectable. Which control BEST provides this assurance?","o":["Discretionary access control on the log directory","Periodic manual log review by administrators","Write-once storage combined with cryptographic hashing/chaining of log entries","Centralized log aggregation using syslog over UDP"],"c":2,"why":"Write-once media paired with cryptographic hash chaining prevents undetected alteration of stored logs, providing tamper-evidence and integrity assurance. DAC only restricts access but doesn't prevent authorized tampering, manual review doesn't ensure integrity, and syslog over UDP offers no integrity or delivery guarantees.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security team runs an automated tool that scans network hosts and compares open ports and services against a database of known vulnerabilities, producing a report of potential weaknesses without attempting to exploit them. What type of assessment is this?","o":["Penetration test","Vulnerability assessment","Social engineering test","Security audit"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and reports potential weaknesses using automated scanning without exploitation. A penetration test goes further by actively exploiting vulnerabilities; the other options involve different testing approaches unrelated to automated scanning.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"A QA team measures that 100% of the statements in a module have been executed during testing, yet a critical security vulnerability in an untested conditional branch was later discovered in production. What testing coverage metric, if achieved, would MOST likely have caught this defect?","o":["Statement coverage","Branch (decision) coverage","Function coverage","Line coverage"],"c":1,"why":"Branch coverage requires that both the true and false outcomes of every decision point be exercised, which would have forced testing of the vulnerable conditional path. Statement and line coverage only confirm that code lines executed at least once, without regard to which branch outcomes occurred, and function coverage merely confirms each function was invoked at least once.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"During a penetration test, the testing team is given no prior knowledge of the target's internal network architecture, source code, or credentials, simulating an external attacker's perspective. What testing approach is being used?","o":["White box testing","Gray box testing","Black box testing","Crystal box testing"],"c":2,"why":"Black box testing provides testers with no internal knowledge of the system, simulating an outside attacker. White box testing provides full internal knowledge, and gray box testing provides partial knowledge; 'crystal box' is not a standard testing term.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"hard","q":"During requirements analysis, a security architect works with the team to document specific ways a malicious actor might abuse the intended functionality of a new feature, such as using a password-reset feature to enumerate valid usernames. These abuse scenarios are then turned into specific test cases executed during QA. What testing technique is being used?","o":["Use case testing","Misuse case (abuse case) testing","Regression testing","Boundary value analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Misuse case (abuse case) testing explicitly models how a threat actor could exploit legitimate functionality for malicious purposes and derives test cases from those abuse scenarios. Use case testing validates intended functional behavior rather than abuse, regression testing verifies unchanged behavior after modifications, and boundary value analysis targets input range edges rather than intentional misuse scenarios.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A developer reviews application source code line by line using an automated tool to identify insecure coding patterns, such as hardcoded credentials or SQL injection vulnerabilities, without executing the program. This technique is best described as which of the following?","o":["Dynamic analysis","Fuzz testing","Static analysis","Penetration testing"],"c":2,"why":"Static analysis examines source code without executing it to find security flaws. Dynamic analysis and fuzz testing require running the application, and penetration testing involves active exploitation of a live system.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the primary purpose of reviewing system and application logs as part of a security assessment program?","o":["To generate compliance reports for auditors only","To detect anomalous activity, policy violations, and evidence of security incidents","To replace the need for vulnerability scanning","To automatically remediate identified vulnerabilities"],"c":1,"why":"Log review helps detect suspicious activity, policy violations, and signs of compromise that may not be caught by automated scans. Logs support but do not replace vulnerability scanning, and log review itself does not perform remediation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to continuously verify that a critical web application is functioning correctly from an end-user perspective by periodically simulating real user transactions, such as logging in and completing a purchase, and monitoring the results. This technique is known as which of the following?","o":["Synthetic transactions","Regression testing","Fuzz testing","Misuse case testing"],"c":0,"why":"Synthetic transactions simulate real user actions to monitor application availability and performance over time. Regression testing verifies that changes have not broken existing functionality, fuzz testing sends malformed input to find flaws, and misuse case testing models how attackers might abuse a system.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An independent accounting firm is hired to evaluate an organization's financial controls and provide an opinion for external stakeholders such as investors and regulators. This is an example of which type of audit?","o":["Internal audit","Third-party (external) audit","Self-assessment","Vulnerability assessment"],"c":1,"why":"A third-party or external audit is performed by an independent outside organization to provide an objective opinion for external stakeholders. Internal audits are conducted by staff within the organization, and a self-assessment is not independent; a vulnerability assessment focuses on technical weaknesses rather than financial controls.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"After a developer fixes a bug in a critical module, the QA team re-runs a suite of previously passed test cases to confirm that the fix did not introduce new defects elsewhere in the application. What type of testing is being performed?","o":["Unit testing","Regression testing","Acceptance testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"Regression testing re-executes existing test cases after changes to ensure that previously working functionality has not been broken. Unit testing focuses on individual components, acceptance testing validates business requirements, and fuzz testing involves feeding invalid or random input to find flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to identify known weaknesses in its externally facing web servers by comparing installed software versions against a database of known CVEs, without actively attempting to exploit any findings. Which activity best matches this description?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability assessment","Red team exercise","Social engineering assessment"],"c":1,"why":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and catalogs known weaknesses (e.g., via CVE matching) without exploitation. Penetration testing and red teaming go further by actively exploiting findings, and social engineering targets people, not software versions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to identify known vulnerabilities on its network devices by comparing installed software versions against a database of known weaknesses, without attempting to exploit any findings. Which activity best describes this process?","o":["Penetration testing","Vulnerability scanning","Social engineering assessment","Security control audit"],"c":1,"why":"Vulnerability scanning identifies known weaknesses via automated comparison against a vulnerability database without exploitation. Penetration testing goes further by actively exploiting findings, while the other options describe different assessment activities.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"A security testing team is hired to attack a company's network with zero prior knowledge of internal architecture, credentials, or source code, simulating an external attacker. Which testing approach is being used?","o":["White-box testing","Gray-box testing","Black-box testing","Static analysis testing"],"c":2,"why":"Black-box testing simulates an attacker with no internal knowledge of the target. White-box provides full knowledge (e.g., source code/architecture), and gray-box provides partial knowledge. Static analysis is a code review technique, not a pentest approach.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A CISSP is designing a security assessment program and wants to track a metric that indicates how quickly the organization identifies and responds to security incidents over time. Which of the following is the BEST example of such a metric?","o":["Number of firewalls deployed","Mean time to detect (MTTD) and mean time to respond (MTTR)","Total lines of code reviewed","Number of employees trained annually"],"c":1,"why":"MTTD and MTTR are key performance indicators that directly measure the speed of incident identification and response, which is central to assessing security program effectiveness. The other options measure resource counts or activity volume rather than detection and response speed.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"easy","q":"A security team runs an automated tool that analyzes an application's source code for insecure coding patterns before the application is compiled. What type of testing is being performed?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source code (white-box, pre-runtime) for vulnerabilities. DAST tests a running application from the outside, fuzz testing sends malformed input to a running program, and penetration testing simulates real-world attacks against a live system.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D6","d":"medium","q":"During the SDLC, a development team wants to scan application source code for insecure coding patterns before the application is compiled or run, allowing early remediation. Which technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source or binary code without executing the application, making it ideal for early-SDLC review. DAST and fuzzing require a running application, and penetration testing typically occurs later against a deployed system.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During an active security incident, which step should occur immediately after an incident has been identified and confirmed?","o":["Containment of the affected systems","Eradication of the root cause","Full forensic analysis of all logs","Notification of law enforcement"],"c":0,"why":"After identification, the incident response lifecycle moves to containment to limit damage and prevent spread before eradication and recovery occur; forensic analysis and law enforcement notification typically happen later or in parallel, not before containment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) should security requirements first be formally documented and incorporated into the project?","o":["Requirements analysis","Testing","Deployment","Maintenance"],"c":0,"why":"Security requirements should be identified as early as possible, during requirements analysis, so they can be designed in from the start. Adding them during testing or deployment is more costly and less effective, and maintenance occurs after the system is already in production.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"When collecting digital evidence from a compromised server, which data should an investigator collect FIRST according to the order of volatility?","o":["Contents of RAM","Data on hard disk drives","Backup tapes stored offsite","Printed system logs"],"c":0,"why":"RAM contents are the most volatile and can be lost when the system is powered down, so they must be collected first; disk data, backups, and printed logs are more persistent and can be collected later.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application allows users to enter data into a search field without restricting the type or format of characters entered. This lack of control makes the application most vulnerable to which type of attack?","o":["SQL injection","Denial of service via bandwidth exhaustion","Session fixation","ARP spoofing"],"c":0,"why":"Failing to validate or sanitize user input is the classic root cause of injection attacks such as SQL injection, where malicious input is interpreted as executable code. The other attacks target network protocols or session handling, not input validation flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A backup strategy captures only the files that have changed since the last full backup, and each subsequent backup grows larger until the next full backup. Which backup type is being described?","o":["Incremental backup","Differential backup","Mirror backup","Snapshot backup"],"c":1,"why":"A differential backup always references the last full backup, so its size grows each day; an incremental backup only captures changes since the last backup (full or incremental) and stays smaller, making the other options incorrect.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which type of security testing analyzes an application's source code for vulnerabilities without executing the program?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Penetration testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":0,"why":"SAST examines source or compiled code at rest to find flaws like insecure functions or logic errors. DAST and penetration testing require the application to be running, and fuzz testing involves feeding random or malformed input to a running program.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During a forensic investigation, an incident responder images a suspect's hard drive before analysis. What is the PRIMARY reason for creating and using a bit-for-bit forensic image rather than analyzing the original drive directly?","o":["It allows analysis to proceed faster than working with the original media","It preserves the original evidence in an unaltered state for legal admissibility","It automatically decrypts any encrypted files on the drive","It reduces the storage space required to retain the evidence"],"c":1,"why":"Working from a verified forensic image preserves the integrity and chain of custody of the original evidence, which is essential for admissibility in legal proceedings; the other options are not the primary justification and are largely inaccurate.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of a Change Advisory Board (CAB) in an organization's change management process?","o":["To execute approved changes in the production environment","To review, assess risk, and approve or reject proposed changes","To monitor systems for unauthorized configuration drift","To perform root cause analysis after an incident"],"c":1,"why":"The CAB's core function is to evaluate proposed changes for risk and business impact and formally approve or reject them; implementation, monitoring, and root cause analysis are separate operational activities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of using a version control (source code repository) system during software development?","o":["To track changes to code and allow rollback to previous versions","To automatically encrypt all application data at rest","To perform real-time vulnerability scanning of running code","To enforce network segmentation between development and production"],"c":0,"why":"Version control systems track history, manage concurrent changes, and allow reverting to earlier code states, supporting integrity and accountability. They do not encrypt data, scan for vulnerabilities, or manage network architecture.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization's incident response team has identified that a web server has been compromised and is actively being used to exfiltrate data. According to standard incident response methodology, what should the team do FIRST after detection and analysis, before eradication and recovery?","o":["Restore the server from a known-good backup","Notify law enforcement and regulatory bodies","Contain the incident by isolating the affected system from the network","Conduct a full root-cause analysis and write the final report"],"c":2,"why":"Containment limits further damage and data loss and must occur before eradication, recovery, or backup restoration; notification and root-cause reporting typically happen during or after containment, not as the first response step.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that only approved and tested code changes are moved into the production environment. Which practice BEST supports this goal?","o":["Formal change management with segregation of duties between developers and release approvers","Allowing developers to push code directly to production for faster releases","Disabling all logging in the production environment to improve performance","Using a single shared administrative account for all release activities"],"c":0,"why":"Change management with segregation of duties ensures changes are reviewed and approved by someone other than the developer, reducing the risk of unauthorized or untested code reaching production. The other options increase risk by removing oversight and accountability.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before deploying a critical security patch organization-wide, an administrator applies it to a small group of representative systems. What is the PRIMARY reason for this practice?","o":["To reduce the cost of purchasing the patch","To satisfy an audit requirement for documentation","To identify compatibility issues or system instability before wide deployment","To comply with vendor licensing restrictions"],"c":2,"why":"Testing patches on a limited set of systems helps detect unforeseen issues such as application incompatibility or system crashes before a broad rollout, minimizing operational disruption; the other options are not the primary driver for patch testing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company implements RAID 5 across its database servers to improve availability. Which statement BEST describes a limitation of this configuration?","o":["RAID 5 cannot survive the failure of any single disk in the array","RAID 5 provides no performance benefit over a single disk","RAID 5 requires an even number of disks to function","RAID 5 can tolerate only a single disk failure before data loss occurs"],"c":3,"why":"RAID 5 uses striping with a single parity block, allowing it to survive exactly one disk failure; a second simultaneous failure results in data loss. The other statements misrepresent RAID 5's actual capabilities and requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) should security requirements first be explicitly defined and documented?","o":["Design phase, once architecture diagrams are complete","Requirements analysis phase, alongside functional requirements","Testing phase, when vulnerabilities are typically discovered","Maintenance phase, after the system is deployed to production"],"c":1,"why":"Security requirements must be gathered early alongside functional requirements so they can drive design decisions; defining them later (design, testing, or maintenance) results in costly rework and security being treated as an afterthought.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"In a DevSecOps approach, security testing and controls are primarily integrated into which part of the development process?","o":["Continuously throughout the CI/CD pipeline, alongside development and operations","Only during a final security audit before major releases","Exclusively during the initial requirements gathering phase","Only after a security incident has occurred in production"],"c":0,"why":"DevSecOps embeds security practices continuously throughout development, integration, and deployment, enabling early detection of issues. Limiting security to a single phase or only reacting after incidents contradicts the continuous, shift-left philosophy of DevSecOps.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization needs to securely dispose of magnetic tape backups containing highly sensitive data before recycling the media. Which method provides the HIGHEST assurance that data cannot be recovered?","o":["Reformatting the tapes","Degaussing the tapes","Deleting the file index on the tapes","Relabeling the tapes for reuse"],"c":1,"why":"Degaussing exposes magnetic media to a strong magnetic field that disrupts the magnetic domains, effectively destroying data on magnetic tape; reformatting, deleting the index, or relabeling do not remove the underlying data and leave it recoverable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application accepts user-supplied data and builds SQL queries by concatenating strings. Which remediation provides the strongest protection against SQL injection?","o":["Rely solely on client-side JavaScript input validation","Use parameterized queries (prepared statements) with bound variables","Escape special characters only in the presentation layer","Deploy a signature-based web application firewall as the sole control"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data so user input can never alter query structure, addressing the root cause. Client-side validation is bypassable, presentation-layer escaping doesn't protect the database layer, and a WAF alone is a compensating control that can be evaded by novel payloads.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A company licenses critical software from a small vendor and is concerned the vendor might go out of business, leaving them without source code for maintenance. Which arrangement BEST addresses this risk?","o":["Software escrow agreement","Service level agreement (SLA)","Non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","End-user license agreement (EULA)"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow agreement places source code with a neutral third party who releases it to the licensee if the vendor fails to meet contractual obligations, such as going out of business. SLAs, NDAs, and EULAs address performance, confidentiality, or usage terms, not source code availability risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company implements a RAID configuration where data is written identically to two separate disks simultaneously. What is the PRIMARY benefit of this configuration?","o":["Increased storage capacity through striping","Fault tolerance through disk mirroring","Faster write performance through parity calculation","Reduced power consumption"],"c":1,"why":"This describes RAID 1 (mirroring), which duplicates data across disks to provide fault tolerance if one disk fails; it does not increase usable capacity, and parity-based performance gains describe other RAID levels like RAID 5.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A development team wants to analyze an application's source code for vulnerabilities such as buffer overflows and insecure function calls before the code is compiled or executed. Which testing technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing against a running instance","Black-box penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source, bytecode, or binary code without executing the program, making it suitable for early-stage code review. DAST, fuzzing, and penetration testing all require a running application and are performed later in the lifecycle.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A backup administrator wants to minimize both the storage required for daily backups and the restoration time in the event of data loss. Which backup strategy BEST balances these competing goals?","o":["Full backups every day","Full backup weekly with daily differential backups","Full backup weekly with daily incremental backups","Differential backups only, with no full backups"],"c":1,"why":"Differential backups capture all changes since the last full backup, so restoration only requires the full backup plus the most recent differential, reducing restore complexity while still saving storage compared to daily full backups; incremental backups require restoring the full backup plus every incremental in sequence, which increases restore time, and daily fulls waste storage.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security benefit of conducting peer code reviews before code is merged into the main branch?","o":["Identifying security flaws and coding errors early through independent examination","Eliminating the need for any further security testing later in the SDLC","Guaranteeing that the code is completely free of vulnerabilities","Replacing the need for a formal change management process"],"c":0,"why":"Peer code review provides an independent set of eyes to catch logic errors, insecure coding practices, and vulnerabilities early, complementing other testing methods. It does not guarantee complete freedom from vulnerabilities nor eliminate the need for further testing or change control.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"In disaster recovery planning, which metric defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss, measured in time, that an organization can tolerate following a disruptive event?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO measures the acceptable amount of data loss in time, indicating how far back backups or replication must reach; RTO addresses how quickly systems must be restored, while MTD and MTBF address downtime tolerance and reliability, not data loss.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An attacker tricks an authenticated user's browser into submitting an unwanted state-changing request to a web application on which the user is currently logged in. Which control is specifically designed to mitigate this type of attack?","o":["Strict input validation on all numeric fields","Anti-CSRF synchronizer tokens embedded in forms","Output encoding of HTML special characters","Enforcing short session idle timeouts"],"c":1,"why":"Cross-Site Request Forgery is mitigated by unpredictable, per-session tokens that verify the request originated from the legitimate application, not the attacker's site. Input validation and output encoding address injection/XSS, and session timeouts don't prevent CSRF during an active session.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A data center is decommissioning several solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained highly sensitive financial records. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate for ensuring the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Degaussing the drives with a strong magnetic field","Performing a single-pass format of the drive","Physical destruction of the drives via shredding or disintegration","Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory that is not affected by magnetic degaussing (which works on magnetic media), and wear-leveling can leave residual data after formatting or deletion; physical destruction is the recommended NIST 800-88 method for reliably sanitizing flash-based media.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company's Business Impact Analysis determines that its order-processing system can tolerate a maximum of 4 hours of downtime and no more than 15 minutes of data loss. Which pair of metrics BEST describes these requirements?","o":["MTTR of 4 hours and MTBF of 15 minutes","RTO of 4 hours and RPO of 15 minutes","RPO of 4 hours and RTO of 15 minutes","SLA of 4 hours and MTD of 15 minutes"],"c":1,"why":"Recovery Time Objective (RTO) defines the maximum acceptable downtime, and Recovery Point Objective (RPO) defines the maximum acceptable data loss window; MTTR/MTBF relate to repair and failure frequency, not these specific tolerances, and the RPO/RTO values are reversed in option C.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security operations center (SOC) analyst notices that a SIEM platform is generating a high volume of alerts for failed login attempts, but analysts are struggling to distinguish real attacks from benign anomalies. Which action would MOST effectively improve the SOC's detection capability going forward?","o":["Disable failed login alerting entirely to reduce noise","Increase the retention period for raw log data","Tune correlation rules and establish baselines to reduce false positives","Require all analysts to manually review every raw log entry daily"],"c":2,"why":"Tuning correlation rules and establishing behavioral baselines directly addresses alert fatigue by improving the signal-to-noise ratio; disabling alerting removes visibility, longer retention doesn't address false positives, and manual review of all logs is not scalable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization integrates automated security scanning tools directly into its CI/CD pipeline so that vulnerabilities are identified during the commit and build stages rather than after deployment. This practice is best described as which concept?","o":["Shifting security left","Waterfall development","Fagan inspection","Sandboxing"],"c":0,"why":"'Shifting left' means moving security activities earlier in the development pipeline to catch issues before they reach production, which is exactly what integrating scanners into CI/CD accomplishes. Waterfall is an SDLC model, Fagan inspection is a formal manual code review technique, and sandboxing is a runtime isolation control, none of which describe pipeline-integrated automated scanning.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP is called to a suspected compromise of a live Linux server. Multiple sources of potential evidence exist: RAM, CPU cache/registers, a mounted encrypted swap partition, and a remote syslog server that has been forwarding logs from this host for weeks. According to the order of volatility principle, which item should be imaged or captured FIRST?","o":["The remote syslog server's stored log files","The CPU cache and processor registers","The encrypted swap partition on local disk","The system's RAM contents"],"c":1,"why":"RFC 3227's order of volatility places CPU registers and cache as the most volatile data, lost within nanoseconds if not captured immediately; RAM is next, followed by disk-based data, with remote logs being the least volatile since they persist independently of the compromised host's state.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Which control best ensures that unauthorized modifications to application source code are prevented and that a complete audit trail of all changes is maintained?","o":["Software escrow agreement with a third party","A version control system enforcing access controls and change history","Code obfuscation prior to compilation","Digital rights management (DRM) applied to the compiled binary"],"c":1,"why":"A version control system with proper access controls restricts who can commit changes and logs every modification, providing both prevention and accountability. Software escrow protects against vendor failure, obfuscation deters reverse engineering, and DRM protects distributed binaries, none of which control or track source code changes during development.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During an incident response process, which phase involves determining the root cause and removing the threat from the environment before systems are restored?","o":["Detection","Eradication","Containment","Lessons learned"],"c":1,"why":"Eradication focuses on removing the root cause of an incident (e.g., malware, unauthorized access) from affected systems; containment limits spread, detection identifies the incident, and lessons learned occurs after recovery.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A storage architect must design a disk array that can survive the simultaneous failure of ANY two physical disks in the array while maximizing usable capacity relative to redundancy overhead, without relying on how disks are grouped into mirrored pairs. Which RAID level best satisfies this requirement?","o":["RAID 5","RAID 6","RAID 10","RAID 0"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 6 uses dual distributed parity, guaranteeing survival of any two simultaneous disk failures regardless of which disks fail. RAID 5 tolerates only one failure, RAID 0 offers no redundancy, and RAID 10 only survives two failures if they occur in different mirrored pairs, not any arbitrary two disks.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that a full backup taken on Sunday can be restored along with only the changes made since Sunday, minimizing the number of tapes needed for restoration compared to incremental backups. Which backup type should be used on the following days?","o":["Full backup","Differential backup","Incremental backup","Mirror backup"],"c":1,"why":"A differential backup captures all changes since the last full backup, so restoration only requires the full backup plus the most recent differential, unlike incremental backups which require the full backup plus every incremental since then.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization's applications rely heavily on numerous open-source libraries and third-party components. Which practice is most effective for identifying known vulnerabilities within these dependencies?","o":["Manual peer code review of application logic","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST) of the running application","Static Application Security Testing (SAST) of proprietary code only"],"c":1,"why":"SCA tools specifically inventory third-party and open-source components and cross-reference them against vulnerability databases to flag known CVEs. Manual review and SAST typically focus on proprietary code logic, and DAST tests runtime behavior rather than identifying specific vulnerable dependency versions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization's business impact analysis sets an RPO of 2 hours for its order-processing database. The current backup schedule performs a full backup nightly at midnight and incremental backups every 6 hours thereafter. A hardware failure occurs at 5:00 PM. What is the MOST accurate conclusion?","o":["The RPO is met because a backup exists from earlier that day","The RPO is violated because up to 5 hours of data could be lost, exceeding the 2-hour target","The RTO, not the RPO, has been violated in this scenario","The backup schedule satisfies the RPO because incrementals run four times daily"],"c":1,"why":"The last incremental ran at noon, meaning up to 5 hours of transactions (noon to 5 PM) could be lost—well beyond the 2-hour RPO target. RTO concerns restoration time, not data loss window, and having 'a' backup does not mean the loss window meets the defined objective.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary purpose of a chain of custody in handling digital evidence?","o":["To ensure evidence is encrypted during storage","To document who handled the evidence and when, preserving its integrity for legal proceedings","To determine the root cause of a security incident","To classify evidence based on sensitivity"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documents every person who handled evidence, when, and how, ensuring it has not been altered or tampered with, which is essential for admissibility in court; the other options describe unrelated security or forensic activities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During the requirements phase of a secure SDLC, a security architect creates a matrix that maps each defined security control to the specific business, regulatory, or contractual requirement it satisfies, and links each control forward to the test case that will verify it. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this artifact?","o":["To ensure security requirements remain traceable and verifiable from definition through testing","To calculate the total budget required for implementing all security controls","To determine which programming language is most suitable for the project","To replace the need for a formal risk assessment during design"],"c":0,"why":"A requirements traceability matrix ensures every security requirement is implemented, testable, and verified, preventing scope gaps; it is not a costing tool, a language-selection guide, or a substitute for risk assessment.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During litigation, opposing counsel challenges the admissibility of a forensic disk image, arguing it is not the original evidence. Which practice BEST supports the image's admissibility under the best evidence rule?","o":["Testimony from the investigator describing the imaging tool's reputation in the industry","A documented, unbroken chain of custody combined with a cryptographic hash matching the original media at the time of imaging","Storing the image on write-once media to prevent any possibility of future alteration","Having two independent examiners perform the imaging simultaneously"],"c":1,"why":"Courts generally accept a verified duplicate as an exception to the best evidence rule when chain of custody is documented and a cryptographic hash proves the image is an exact, unaltered copy of the original. Tool reputation, write-once storage, and dual examiners do not by themselves establish evidentiary integrity or authenticate the copy against the original.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization is designing a new software development lifecycle (SDLC) process and wants to minimize the cost of fixing security defects. During which SDLC phase should security requirements first be defined?","o":["Requirements and analysis","System testing","Deployment","Maintenance"],"c":0,"why":"Defining security requirements during the requirements/analysis phase is far less costly than discovering and fixing defects later; the other phases occur after design decisions have already been made, making remediation more expensive.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company implements a policy requiring that any modification to production systems be documented, reviewed, and approved before implementation. This is an example of which security operations practice?","o":["Configuration management","Change management","Patch management","Vulnerability management"],"c":1,"why":"Change management is the formal process of requesting, documenting, reviewing, and approving changes to production systems to minimize risk and ensure stability; configuration management focuses on maintaining known baselines, and patch/vulnerability management are more specific subsets.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A critical zero-day vulnerability is being actively exploited against a production system, and a vendor patch is available. The organization's standard change management process requires five business days of testing and CAB approval before deployment. What is the MOST appropriate course of action?","o":["Wait for the standard CAB approval cycle to avoid violating change management policy","Deploy the patch immediately through the emergency change process, then obtain retroactive CAB review and documentation","Deploy the patch without any change control since the threat is urgent and documentation can be skipped","Isolate the system from the network indefinitely instead of patching, until the next scheduled change window"],"c":1,"why":"Mature change management frameworks include an emergency change process specifically for situations like active exploitation, allowing expedited deployment while still requiring after-the-fact documentation and CAB review to maintain accountability and traceability. Skipping documentation entirely undermines governance, and waiting five days leaves the system exposed to an active exploit.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester exploits a stack-based buffer overflow and overwrites a return address with the location of injected shellcode placed on the stack. The exploit fails to execute the shellcode, yet the same tester later succeeds using a return-oriented programming (ROP) chain built entirely from existing executable code already loaded in memory. Which control most directly explains why the direct shellcode injection failed while the ROP chain succeeded?","o":["Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)","Data Execution Prevention (DEP) / NX bit enforcement","Stack canary (stack cookie) protection","Structured Exception Handler Overwrite Protection (SEHOP)"],"c":1,"why":"DEP/NX marks stack memory as non-executable, blocking direct injected shellcode, but it cannot stop ROP because ROP reuses already-executable code pages; a triggered stack canary would crash the process entirely rather than selectively block shellcode, ASLR concerns address predictability (and the ROP chain still working implies addresses were known), and SEHOP protects exception-handler chains, not shellcode execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which type of physical security control is a security guard performing a visual inspection of an employee's badge before allowing entry into a secure facility?","o":["Deterrent control","Detective control","Preventive control","Compensating control"],"c":2,"why":"Verifying identification before granting access is a preventive control because it stops unauthorized access before it occurs; detective controls identify events after they happen, and deterrent controls merely discourage attempts without direct verification.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application accepts user input directly into SQL queries, making it vulnerable to SQL injection. Which of the following is the MOST effective countermeasure?","o":["Encrypting the database at rest","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Limiting the length of input fields","Deploying a network firewall in front of the web server"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing attacker-supplied input from being interpreted as SQL commands. Encryption, input length limits, and network firewalls do not address the root cause of injection flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During an incident, analysts discover an APT actor has established a foothold on a segmented lab network that has no connectivity to production systems or sensitive data. The actor appears to be conducting reconnaissance but has not yet attempted lateral movement toward critical assets. What is the MOST appropriate immediate containment strategy?","o":["Immediately disconnect the entire corporate network from the internet to guarantee no data loss","Silently monitor and gather threat intelligence on the isolated segment while implementing additional segmentation controls, since business risk is currently low","Take no action until law enforcement arrives to avoid interfering with potential prosecution","Immediately terminate all active connections and power down the affected segment without further analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Because the compromised segment is already isolated from critical assets, continued controlled monitoring allows collection of threat intelligence and understanding of attacker TTPs without introducing business disruption; abrupt shutdown could destroy volatile evidence and alert the attacker prematurely. A full network disconnect is disproportionate given the contained blast radius, and waiting for law enforcement before taking any containment action is not required or advisable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A programming error allows an attacker to write data beyond the boundaries of an allocated memory buffer, potentially overwriting adjacent memory and executing arbitrary code. This describes which vulnerability?","o":["Cross-site scripting (XSS)","Race condition","Buffer overflow","SQL injection"],"c":2,"why":"A buffer overflow occurs when data exceeds the memory space allocated for it, corrupting adjacent memory. XSS involves injecting scripts into web pages, race conditions involve timing issues, and SQL injection targets database queries.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization's log management policy states that logs from critical servers must be reviewed daily and retained for one year. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this retention period?","o":["It reduces storage costs","It ensures logs are available for evidentiary purposes during investigations that may occur long after an incident","It satisfies encryption requirements","It automatically detects intrusions"],"c":1,"why":"Retaining logs for an extended period ensures they remain available for forensic investigation or compliance audits that may occur well after the events they record; log retention itself does not reduce costs, encrypt data, or detect intrusions automatically.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A data center housing sensitive servers requires a fire suppression system suitable for an occupied space that will not damage electronic equipment and will not pose an asphyxiation risk to personnel who may be present during discharge. Which system BEST meets these requirements?","o":["Carbon dioxide (CO2) total flooding system","Wet-pipe water sprinkler system","Dry chemical powder suppression system","Clean agent (e.g., FM-200 or Novec) gaseous suppression system"],"c":3,"why":"Clean agent systems extinguish fire via chemical reaction or heat absorption without leaving residue or damaging electronics, and are formulated to be safe for occupied spaces at design concentrations. CO2 displaces oxygen and is hazardous to occupants, water damages electronics, and dry chemical powder leaves corrosive residue harmful to equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which software testing technique analyzes an application's source code for security flaws WITHOUT executing the program?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Penetration testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source or compiled code without running it. DAST, penetration testing, and fuzz testing all require the application to be executed to observe its behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the MAIN purpose of conducting regular disaster recovery (DR) tabletop exercises?","o":["To physically test failover to a backup data center","To validate and improve the DR plan through discussion-based scenario walkthroughs without disrupting live systems","To perform full-scale system restoration","To calculate the recovery point objective"],"c":1,"why":"Tabletop exercises are discussion-based walkthroughs used to validate plans, identify gaps, and improve preparedness without impacting production systems, unlike full-scale or parallel tests that involve actual system failover.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A junior analyst is granted row-level access that permits viewing only one employee's salary record at a time, and the CEO's record is explicitly excluded from direct access. By issuing a series of otherwise authorized statistical queries (MIN, MAX, AVG, COUNT) against the full salary table, the analyst is able to mathematically deduce the CEO's exact salary. What is this attack called?","o":["Aggregation attack","Inference attack","Polyinstantiation bypass","Database shadowing"],"c":1,"why":"An inference attack occurs when a user deduces restricted information from patterns in permitted queries or statistics; aggregation involves combining many individually low-sensitivity data items to reveal a higher-sensitivity fact rather than deriving one hidden value via statistics, and polyinstantiation and database shadowing are unrelated multilevel-security concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During an internal investigation into a suspected data exfiltration, a security analyst images a suspect's hard drive before conducting analysis. What is the PRIMARY reason for creating this forensic image rather than analyzing the original drive directly?","o":["To comply with data retention regulations that mandate backups of all seized media","To preserve the original evidence in an unaltered state and maintain its integrity for legal proceedings","To reduce the time required to complete the forensic analysis","To allow the original drive to be returned to the employee more quickly"],"c":1,"why":"Working from a forensic copy preserves the original evidence from modification, ensuring integrity and admissibility (chain of custody). The other options are not the primary forensic rationale for imaging.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that previously stored classified data. The IT team proposes using a standard bulk degausser, as was done historically for magnetic hard disk drives. Why is this approach inadequate for SSDs, and what should be done instead?","o":["Degaussing is adequate for SSDs; no change is needed since the process is media-agnostic","SSDs use flash memory with no magnetic recording medium, so degaussing has no effect; cryptographic erasure or the vendor's secure erase/purge command per NIST SP 800-88 should be used instead","Physical incineration is the only NIST-approved method for any storage media, including SSDs","SSDs should simply be reformatted at the operating system level, which is equivalent to a purge-level sanitization"],"c":1,"why":"Degaussing relies on disrupting magnetic domains and is ineffective on flash-based SSDs, which store data electrically rather than magnetically. NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase (if the drive was encrypted) or vendor-supported secure erase/purge commands for proper sanitization; a standard OS-level format does not meet purge-level requirements and leaves recoverable data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A system administrator applies a vendor-released security update to fix a known vulnerability in an operating system. This activity is an example of which security operations process?","o":["Configuration management","Patch management","Change advisory review","Incident response"],"c":1,"why":"Patch management is the process of identifying, testing, and applying updates (patches) to remediate known vulnerabilities; configuration management maintains baseline settings, and incident response addresses active security events.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security operations center (SOC) analyst notices that a SIEM is generating thousands of low-priority alerts daily, causing analysts to routinely dismiss alerts without review. Which of the following actions would BEST address this problem?","o":["Increase log retention periods to capture more historical data for correlation","Disable logging for low-severity events to reduce alert volume","Tune correlation rules and thresholds to reduce false positives and prioritize high-fidelity alerts","Outsource all alert triage to a third-party managed security provider"],"c":2,"why":"Tuning correlation rules directly addresses alert fatigue by improving signal-to-noise ratio, which is a core SOC operations practice. Disabling logging removes visibility, increasing retention doesn't reduce alert volume, and outsourcing doesn't fix the underlying tuning problem.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A development team wants to track every change made to source code, allow rollback to previous versions, and support collaborative development. Which tool BEST supports this need?","o":["A version control system","A configuration management database (CMDB)","An intrusion detection system (IDS)","A data loss prevention (DLP) system"],"c":0,"why":"Version control systems (e.g., Git) track code changes, enable rollback, and support collaboration among developers. A CMDB tracks IT assets, while IDS and DLP are security monitoring tools unrelated to source code management.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A QA engineer intentionally introduces small, systematic changes into a compiled binary (e.g., flipping a comparison operator) and reruns the existing regression test suite against each mutated version to see whether any test detects the injected defect. Most mutants pass the suite undetected. What does this result indicate?","o":["The test suite has poor fault-detection effectiveness (weak mutation kill rate)","The application is highly resistant to fuzzing-based attacks","The project has reached a high CMMI maturity level","The code exhibits low cyclomatic complexity"],"c":0,"why":"This describes mutation testing, which measures test-suite quality by the percentage of injected defects (mutants) it catches; a low kill rate reveals weak tests, and the scenario says nothing about fuzzing resistance, process maturity, or code complexity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A database contains individual employee salary records that are each classified as unclassified, but a report combining all salaries reveals the total payroll budget, which is classified as confidential. This is an example of which database security issue?","o":["Inference","Aggregation","Polyinstantiation","Normalization"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining multiple low-sensitivity data items produces a higher-sensitivity result. Inference involves deducing sensitive information from indirect clues, polyinstantiation creates multiple versions of data for different security levels, and normalization is a database design technique unrelated to sensitivity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a RAID 5 configuration across five disks to support a critical database server. What is the PRIMARY benefit this configuration provides?","o":["Complete protection against data loss from a site-wide disaster","Fault tolerance allowing continued operation after a single disk failure, using distributed parity","Encryption of data at rest across all disks in the array","Doubling of read and write throughput compared to a single disk"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 5 stripes data with distributed parity, allowing the array to survive a single disk failure without data loss. It does not provide encryption, guaranteed performance doubling, or protection against site-wide disasters (which require offsite backup/DR strategies).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization's CI/CD pipeline resolves and downloads open-source dependencies by package name from a public registry during every automated build. An attacker publishes a malicious package under the exact same name as one of the organization's internal private packages, and the build system inadvertently pulls and executes the attacker's malicious code instead. Which control would MOST effectively prevent this specific attack?","o":["Running static application security testing (SAST) on the source code before each build","Digitally signing internal packages and configuring the package manager to prioritize a private, scoped internal registry over public sources","Running software composition analysis (SCA) after each release to identify vulnerable dependencies","Requiring mandatory peer code review for every pull request"],"c":1,"why":"This is a dependency-confusion attack, best mitigated by scoping/signing internal packages and forcing the package manager to resolve them from a trusted private registry first; SAST and SCA analyze code/known vulnerabilities but do not control which package source is resolved, and code review does not affect automated dependency resolution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A security tester sends large volumes of malformed, random, or unexpected input to an application to identify crashes or unhandled exceptions that could indicate vulnerabilities. This technique is known as:","o":["Regression testing","Fuzz testing","Unit testing","Code review"],"c":1,"why":"Fuzz testing feeds unexpected or malformed input to an application to uncover crashes or vulnerabilities. Regression testing verifies existing functionality after changes, unit testing checks individual code components, and code review is a manual inspection of source code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company's backup policy specifies full backups every Sunday and incremental backups every other day of the week. If a server fails on Thursday, which backups are required to fully restore the data?","o":["Only the most recent incremental backup from Wednesday","The Sunday full backup and the Sunday full backup only","The Sunday full backup plus all incremental backups from Monday through Wednesday, applied in sequence","The Sunday full backup and only the Wednesday incremental backup"],"c":2,"why":"Incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup (full or incremental), so restoration requires the full backup plus every incremental backup in sequence up to the point of failure. Skipping any incremental in the chain results in incomplete data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A DevSecOps team integrates automated security scanning into the earliest stages of the CI/CD pipeline rather than only testing before production release. This practice is best described as:","o":["Shifting security left","Security through obscurity","Defense in depth","Separation of duties"],"c":0,"why":"'Shifting left' means addressing security earlier in the development lifecycle to catch issues sooner and reduce cost. Security through obscurity relies on secrecy, defense in depth layers multiple controls, and separation of duties divides responsibilities among individuals.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A mobile banking API exposes the endpoint /api/accounts/{accountId}/balance. A tester, authenticated with their own valid session token, changes the accountId value in the request URL to another customer's account number and successfully retrieves that customer's balance data. Which vulnerability class does this represent?","o":["Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA)","Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)","Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)","Cross-site scripting via insecure direct object reference"],"c":0,"why":"BOLA occurs when an API authenticates a user correctly but fails to verify that the user is authorized to access the specific object referenced in the request; CSRF forges requests using a victim's session without their consent, SSRF tricks a server into making unintended internal requests, and option D is not a coherent, recognized vulnerability class.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"Before deploying a critical patch to a production ERP system, an organization requires the change to go through a formal change advisory board (CAB) review. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this requirement?","o":["To delay patch deployment until the vendor releases a newer version","To ensure the change is documented, assessed for risk and impact, and approved before implementation","To transfer liability for any system failure to the change requester","To satisfy an audit checklist item with no operational benefit"],"c":1,"why":"Change management processes like CAB review exist to formally assess risk, impact, and rollback plans before implementing changes, reducing the likelihood of unintended outages. The other options misrepresent the operational and risk-management purpose of change control.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A company licenses a mission-critical software application from a small vendor and is concerned that if the vendor ceases operations, the company will be left without the ability to maintain, patch, or troubleshoot the software's source code. Which contractual mechanism BEST mitigates this specific risk?","o":["Requiring the vendor to grant a perpetual license to the compiled application","Establishing a source code escrow agreement with a neutral third party, with defined release conditions","Negotiating a service level agreement (SLA) specifying uptime and response-time guarantees","Requiring the vendor to maintain cybersecurity liability insurance"],"c":1,"why":"Source code escrow places the source with a neutral third party who releases it to the licensee upon specified trigger events (e.g., vendor bankruptcy), directly addressing loss of vendor viability; a perpetual license, an SLA, and insurance do not provide access to the source code itself.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During a ransomware incident, the incident response team has identified and isolated the infected hosts, and is now restoring systems from clean backups. According to standard incident response phases, which phase are they CURRENTLY performing?","o":["Detection and analysis","Containment","Recovery","Post-incident activity (lessons learned)"],"c":2,"why":"Restoring systems from clean backups after isolation is part of the recovery phase, which focuses on returning systems to normal operation. Containment already occurred (isolation), and detection/lessons learned occur before and after recovery, respectively.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"During which phase of the software development lifecycle is threat modeling most effectively performed to maximize its value in reducing security defects?","o":["During the design phase, before coding begins","During the testing phase, after the code is complete","During deployment, immediately before production release","During maintenance, after the first security incident"],"c":0,"why":"Threat modeling during design allows architectural security flaws to be identified and mitigated before costly code is written; performing it later (testing, deployment, or maintenance) means flaws are found after resources have already been invested, making fixes more expensive and less effective.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A privileged system utility checks whether a file is owned by the calling user and, if so, opens that file with elevated privileges to perform a backup. An attacker exploits the narrow timing gap between the ownership check and the actual file open by swapping the file for a symbolic link pointing to a sensitive system file during that window. Which vulnerability class BEST describes this flaw?","o":["Time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","Integer overflow leading to memory corruption","Confused deputy problem via cross-site request forgery","Directory traversal through path canonicalization failure"],"c":0,"why":"TOCTOU describes exactly this pattern: a security check followed by a delayed action, exploited by altering the resource in the gap between check and use; the scenario involves no arithmetic overflow, no cross-site request, and no path traversal—only a timing-based substitution attack.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A business continuity plan specifies that the order management system must be restored within 4 hours of a disruption, and that no more than 30 minutes of transaction data can be lost. Which two metrics are being defined by these requirements, respectively?","o":["Mean time to repair (MTTR) and mean time between failures (MTBF)","Recovery time objective (RTO) and recovery point objective (RPO)","Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD) and service level agreement (SLA)","Recovery point objective (RPO) and recovery time objective (RTO)"],"c":1,"why":"The 4-hour restoration target is the RTO (time to restore service), and the 30-minute data loss tolerance is the RPO (maximum acceptable data loss measured in time). The other pairings either reverse the definitions or reference unrelated metrics.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application allows user-supplied input to be directly concatenated into SQL statements. Which remediation provides the strongest protection against SQL injection?","o":["Implementing client-side input validation using JavaScript","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements) with bound variables","Encoding all HTML output to prevent script execution","Increasing the length of the database administrator's password"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate SQL code from data, preventing attacker-supplied input from being interpreted as executable SQL regardless of content. Client-side validation can be bypassed, HTML encoding addresses XSS not SQLi, and password strength does not prevent injection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a policy requiring that the employee who initiates a wire transfer request cannot also be the person who approves and releases the payment. This control is an example of which security operations principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties splits critical functions between multiple people to prevent fraud or error by any single individual. Least privilege concerns minimal access rights, job rotation involves changing roles over time, and mandatory vacation forces time off to detect fraud, none of which describe this specific two-person control.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to identify vulnerabilities in a web application's source code without executing the program, in order to catch issues early in the build pipeline. Which testing technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source or binary code without executing it, making it suitable for early pipeline integration. DAST and penetration testing require a running application, and fuzz testing sends malformed input to a running program rather than analyzing static code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization experiences a malware outbreak. According to standard incident response methodology, which step should occur immediately after the incident has been detected and confirmed?","o":["Eradication","Containment","Lessons learned","Recovery"],"c":1,"why":"Containment limits the spread and damage of an incident immediately after detection/confirmation; eradication, recovery, and lessons learned occur later in the process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A backup administrator wants to minimize the time required to restore data while accepting longer nightly backup windows. Which backup strategy best meets this goal?","o":["Full backup every night","Incremental backup every night","Differential backup every night","Full backup weekly with daily incremental backups"],"c":0,"why":"A full backup every night allows restoration from a single backup set, minimizing restore time, though it requires the longest backup window; incremental and differential strategies reduce backup time but increase restore complexity and time.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which method provides the most reliable way to ensure data on a solid-state drive (SSD) cannot be recovered before disposal?","o":["Degaussing the drive","Physical destruction of the drive","Formatting the drive using the operating system","Deleting all files and emptying the recycle bin"],"c":1,"why":"Physical destruction is the most reliable sanitization method for SSDs since degaussing is ineffective on non-magnetic media and formatting/deletion do not remove data from flash memory cells.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before a patch is applied to a production server, which process should be followed to ensure the change is properly authorized, tested, and documented?","o":["Configuration management","Change management","Release management","Problem management"],"c":1,"why":"Change management governs the authorization, testing, and documentation of modifications to production systems; configuration management tracks system baselines, and release/problem management address different aspects of IT service operations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that only approved, tested code changes are promoted between development, staging, and production environments, with a clear audit trail of who approved each change. Which practice BEST supports this goal?","o":["Software configuration management with formal change control","Continuous deployment with automatic production pushes on every commit","Allowing developers direct write access to the production environment","Relying solely on developer unit testing before release"],"c":0,"why":"Software configuration management combined with formal change control provides version tracking, approval workflows, and auditability across environments. Automatic pushes on every commit or direct developer access to production bypass necessary review, and unit testing alone does not address change authorization or traceability.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) should security requirements first be formally identified and documented?","o":["Requirements gathering and analysis","Coding and implementation","User acceptance testing","Production deployment"],"c":0,"why":"Security requirements must be defined early, during requirements gathering, so they can be designed in from the start (a core secure SDLC principle). Identifying them during coding, testing, or after deployment is far more costly and often results in incomplete or bolted-on controls.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company wants to improve disk fault tolerance by allowing the system to continue operating even if one drive fails, without needing to restore from backup. Which technology best achieves this?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","Full backup rotation","Cold site failover"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 1 (mirroring) duplicates data across two drives, allowing continued operation if one drive fails; RAID 0 offers no redundancy, and backups/cold sites do not provide immediate fault tolerance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A company exposes a REST API to partner organizations for exchanging sensitive financial data. Which control provides the strongest assurance that each API request is both authenticated and authorized for the specific action requested?","o":["Requiring TLS encryption on all API endpoints","Issuing shared API keys embedded in client applications","Implementing OAuth 2.0 with scoped access tokens validated per request","Restricting API access by source IP address range"],"c":2,"why":"OAuth 2.0 with scoped tokens ties each request to a verified identity and limits actions to granted scopes, providing both authentication and fine-grained authorization. TLS only protects data in transit, shared keys don't identify individual users, and IP restrictions can be spoofed and don't address per-action authorization.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the BEST technique to mitigate SQL injection vulnerabilities in application code?","o":["Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Encrypting the database at rest","Implementing multi-factor authentication for users","Increasing input field character limits"],"c":0,"why":"Parameterized queries separate SQL code from data, preventing attacker-supplied input from altering query logic, which directly addresses the root cause of SQL injection. Encryption at rest, MFA, and character limits do not prevent the underlying injection flaw.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A company is licensing critical custom software from a small vendor and is concerned the vendor might go out of business, leaving the company unable to maintain the application. Which arrangement BEST addresses this risk?","o":["Purchasing an extended warranty from the vendor","Negotiating a software escrow agreement with a neutral third party","Requiring the vendor to sign a non-disclosure agreement","Increasing the frequency of vendor security audits"],"c":1,"why":"A software escrow agreement places source code and documentation with a neutral third party who releases it to the customer if the vendor fails to meet contractual obligations (e.g., goes out of business), ensuring continuity. Warranties, NDAs, and audits do not guarantee access to source code if the vendor ceases operations.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which principle ensures that employees are granted only the access necessary to perform their assigned job duties, reducing the risk of unauthorized data exposure?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Least privilege restricts access rights to only what is needed for a role; separation of duties divides responsibilities among multiple people, and job rotation/mandatory vacation are unrelated administrative controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A security analyst reviewing system logs notices repeated failed login attempts followed by a successful login from an unusual location. What is the analyst most likely detecting?","o":["A false positive from the antivirus system","A potential brute-force attack followed by account compromise","Normal user behavior during password reset","A scheduled system maintenance task"],"c":1,"why":"Repeated failed logins followed by success from an unusual location is a classic indicator of a brute-force attack leading to compromise, not benign or unrelated activity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A development team integrates automated security scanning tools directly into their CI/CD pipeline so that vulnerabilities are flagged with every code commit rather than only before major releases. This practice is best described as an example of which concept?","o":["Waterfall development methodology","Shifting security left in the development lifecycle","Security through obscurity","Segregation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"'Shifting left' means integrating security activities earlier and continuously throughout development rather than only at the end, which automated CI/CD scanning exemplifies. Waterfall is a sequential lifecycle model, security through obscurity relies on hiding design details, and segregation of duties is an access-control principle unrelated to this scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization needs a disaster recovery site that has power, networking, and hardware pre-installed and can be operational within a few hours, but does not have live data replication. This best describes which type of site?","o":["Hot site","Warm site","Cold site","Mobile site"],"c":1,"why":"A warm site has infrastructure like power and hardware ready but requires data restoration before full operation; a hot site has real-time data replication, and a cold site lacks pre-installed hardware.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to test its source code for security flaws without executing the program. Which testing method should be used?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Penetration testing","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing"],"c":2,"why":"SAST analyzes source code, bytecode, or binaries without executing the application, making it ideal for early detection of coding flaws. DAST, penetration testing, and fuzz testing all require the application to be running.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During a forensic investigation of a compromised server, an analyst must decide the order in which to collect evidence to preserve its integrity. According to the concept of order of volatility, which of the following should be collected FIRST?","o":["Contents of CPU cache and registers","Data stored on the local hard disk","Log files archived to backup tape","Network configuration documentation stored in a file share"],"c":0,"why":"CPU cache and registers hold the most volatile data and are lost almost instantly when power changes, so they must be captured first; disk data, archived logs, and static documentation are progressively less volatile and can be collected later.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A programmer fails to validate the length of user input before copying it into a fixed-size memory buffer, allowing data to overwrite adjacent memory. This is an example of which vulnerability?","o":["Race condition","Buffer overflow","Cross-site scripting","Privilege escalation via covert channel"],"c":1,"why":"A buffer overflow occurs when input exceeding the allocated buffer size overwrites adjacent memory, potentially corrupting data or enabling code execution. Race conditions involve timing issues, XSS involves script injection into web output, and covert channels involve unauthorized information leakage—none match this scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A ransomware infection is spreading across workstations in a single department. The incident response team has confirmed the scope is limited to that department's VLAN. What is the MOST appropriate immediate containment action?","o":["Isolate the affected VLAN from the rest of the network","Shut down the entire corporate network until the malware is identified","Delete all files with suspicious extensions on affected hosts","Wait for law enforcement to arrive before taking any action"],"c":0,"why":"Segment isolation limits further spread while preserving unaffected systems and evidence; shutting down the whole network is excessive and disruptive, deleting files destroys evidence, and waiting for law enforcement delays necessary containment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which tool is PRIMARILY used to track and manage changes to source code over time, including branching and merging by multiple developers?","o":["Version control system","Intrusion detection system","Configuration management database (CMDB)","Data loss prevention system"],"c":0,"why":"A version control system (e.g., Git, Subversion) tracks source code changes, supports branching/merging, and maintains history for collaborative development. An IDS monitors network/host activity, a CMDB tracks IT asset configurations broadly, and a DLP system prevents data exfiltration—none manage source code revisions directly.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization's Change Advisory Board (CAB) reviews a proposed emergency patch to a production database server. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this review?","o":["To assess the risk, impact, and rollback plan of the change before approval","To perform the actual technical installation of the patch","To assign the change to a specific system administrator","To document the change in the configuration management database only"],"c":0,"why":"The CAB's core function is risk and impact assessment, including verifying rollback procedures, prior to authorizing a change; it does not perform installation, assign tasks, or serve merely as a documentation repository.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A company licenses critical software from a small vendor and is concerned the vendor may go out of business, leaving the company without support or source code access. Which arrangement BEST addresses this risk?","o":["Software escrow agreement","Service level agreement (SLA)","Non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","Business associate agreement (BAA)"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow agreement places source code with a neutral third party, to be released to the licensee if the vendor fails to meet contractual obligations (such as going out of business), ensuring continuity. An SLA defines performance metrics, an NDA protects confidential information, and a BAA governs handling of protected health information—none guarantee source code access.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company performs a full backup every Sunday and wants to minimize daily backup time, accepting that restores may require multiple backup sets applied in sequence. Which backup strategy should they use?","o":["Full backup","Differential backup","Incremental backup","Mirror backup"],"c":2,"why":"Incremental backups capture only data changed since the last backup of any type, making daily backups fastest but requiring the full backup plus every incremental since to restore; differential only requires the full plus the latest differential, and full/mirror backups take longer daily.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which set of properties ensures that database transactions are processed reliably, such that a transaction either completes fully or not at all, and the database remains in a consistent state?","o":["CIA triad","OWASP Top Ten","ACID properties","STRIDE model"],"c":2,"why":"ACID (Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability) properties define reliable transaction processing in databases, ensuring all-or-nothing execution and consistency. The CIA triad addresses general information security goals, OWASP Top Ten lists common web vulnerabilities, and STRIDE is a threat modeling framework—none pertain to transaction reliability.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A storage administrator needs a RAID configuration that provides fault tolerance for a single disk failure while balancing cost and performance for a moderately write-intensive database. Which RAID level BEST meets this requirement?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 6 with no spare disks"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 5 stripes data with distributed parity, tolerating one disk failure with better storage efficiency than RAID 1 and better fault tolerance than RAID 0; RAID 6 without spares is more resilient but has higher parity overhead than needed here, making RAID 5 the balanced choice.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During live incident response on a running production server suspected of compromise, an analyst begins collecting evidence following the order of volatility to maximize the value of captured data before it is lost. Which item should be collected FIRST?","o":["Contents of RAM (physical memory)","CPU registers and processor cache","Data stored on locally attached hard disks","Backup tapes stored in an offsite vault"],"c":1,"why":"Per RFC 3227 and standard forensic methodology, CPU registers and cache are the most volatile data and decay in nanoseconds, so they must be captured before RAM, disk, or offline backups, which are progressively less volatile.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A security analyst discovers an actively running webshell on a production web server that is exfiltrating data to an external IP. The organization wants to stop the damage while preserving the possibility of forensic analysis and legal action. What is the BEST immediate action?","o":["Immediately power off the server to cut off attacker access","Isolate the server from the network (e.g., via VLAN or firewall block) while leaving it powered on","Format the disk and rebuild the server from a known-good image right away","Take no action until law enforcement arrives on site"],"c":1,"why":"Network isolation stops ongoing exfiltration while preserving volatile evidence (RAM, running processes, network connections) for later forensic capture. Powering off destroys volatile memory evidence, and rebuilding or waiting for law enforcement fails to contain the active threat in a timely manner.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"Before deploying a critical security patch to production servers, an organization requires the patch to be applied first in a staging environment that mirrors production. What is the PRIMARY reason for this step?","o":["To satisfy an audit checklist requirement with no functional purpose","To identify compatibility issues or unintended disruptions before production deployment","To reduce the time required to apply the patch in production","To avoid having to document the patch in the change management system"],"c":1,"why":"Testing in a representative staging environment validates that a patch does not break dependent applications or services before it affects production; the other options misstate the purpose or describe unrelated/incorrect benefits.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization has set a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 12 hours for a critical financial processing application. Business impact analysis determined that the Work Recovery Time (WRT) needed to validate data integrity and resume full business operations after systems are restored is 5 hours. To remain within the MTD, what is the MAXIMUM acceptable Recovery Time Objective (RTO) for restoring the underlying system?","o":["12 hours, since WRT is included within RTO by definition","7 hours, since MTD equals the sum of RTO and WRT","5 hours, since WRT and RTO must always be equal","17 hours, since WRT should be added on top of the MTD"],"c":1,"why":"MTD = RTO + WRT, so RTO = MTD - WRT = 12 - 5 = 7 hours. WRT is a separate downstream activity after technical restoration, not included in or equal to RTO, and cannot exceed the MTD boundary.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A business impact analysis determines that an order-processing system can tolerate at most 4 hours of downtime before causing unacceptable loss to the organization. This 4-hour value represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime is unrelated to this value","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":1,"why":"RTO defines the maximum acceptable time to restore a system after disruption; RPO instead measures acceptable data loss in time, and MTBF measures average time between failures, not recovery targets.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A production database becomes corrupted outside of the normal change window, threatening a critical business process. The on-call engineer has a tested fix ready to apply. According to change management best practices, what should occur?","o":["Bypass change management entirely since this is a genuine emergency and speed is the only priority","Apply the fix immediately under the organization's emergency change procedure, then submit full documentation for retroactive CAB review","Wait until the next scheduled Change Advisory Board meeting before implementing any fix","Only the CISO has authority to approve skipping the standard change control process"],"c":1,"why":"Mature change management programs include a defined emergency change process that allows immediate remediation followed by mandatory retroactive documentation and CAB review, preserving accountability without needless delay. Fully bypassing controls or waiting for a scheduled meeting either creates governance gaps or unacceptable delay.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A data center implements a physical access control where an employee must badge in, and the door will not permit a second person to pass through with the same badge swipe unless they also authenticate individually. This design is intended to prevent which threat?","o":["Piggybacking/tailgating into secure areas","Denial-of-service attacks on badge readers","Social engineering via phishing emails","Man-in-the-middle attacks on network traffic"],"c":0,"why":"This control, often implemented via a mantrap or anti-passback system, specifically prevents piggybacking/tailgating where an unauthorized person follows an authorized badge holder into a secure area; it has no relation to network-based attacks or phishing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A vulnerability scan identifies two issues: Vulnerability A, CVSS 9.8, on an isolated development server with no internet access and no known exploit code; Vulnerability B, CVSS 7.5, on an internet-facing production server, with threat intelligence confirming active exploitation in the wild. Given limited immediate patching resources, which vulnerability should be prioritized first?","o":["Vulnerability A, because a higher CVSS base score always indicates higher organizational risk","Vulnerability B, because active exploitation combined with internet exposure represents a more immediate and impactful risk despite the lower base score","Both should be patched simultaneously regardless of context since CVSS scores are the only valid prioritization criterion","Neither should be prioritized until a formal risk assessment committee convenes, regardless of exploitation status"],"c":1,"why":"Risk-based vulnerability management considers exploitability, exposure, and asset criticality, not just the base CVSS score. An actively exploited flaw on an exposed production asset poses far greater real-world risk than a theoretical high-severity flaw on an isolated, unexploited system.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to detect a low-and-slow credential-stuffing attack in which an adversary attempts a small number of authentication failures against many different systems over several days, staying below any single system's alerting threshold. Which SIEM capability is MOST critical to detecting this attack?","o":["Signature-based antivirus scanning on each endpoint","Real-time correlation of authentication events across multiple systems within a rolling time window","Long-term log retention solely for regulatory compliance reporting","Perimeter network packet capture without log aggregation from internal hosts"],"c":1,"why":"Cross-system correlation over time is what reveals a distributed, low-volume pattern invisible to any single host's logs or threshold-based alerts. Antivirus signatures, compliance-only retention, and perimeter-only capture do not correlate authentication attempts across multiple internal systems.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A company operates a 24/7 staffed data center and is selecting a fire suppression system for the server room. Which option BEST balances effective fire suppression with occupant safety and equipment protection?","o":["CO2 flooding system, due to its low cost and rapid fire suppression","Wet-pipe water sprinkler system, since water is inexpensive and widely available","Clean agent gaseous suppression system (e.g., FM-200/Novec), which suppresses fire without displacing breathable oxygen or damaging electronics","Dry chemical powder extinguishing system, due to its long shelf life"],"c":2,"why":"Clean agent systems extinguish fires via chemical reaction or heat absorption without depleting oxygen to unsafe levels or leaving damaging residue, making them appropriate for occupied data centers. CO2 displaces oxygen and is dangerous for humans, water damages electronics, and dry chemical powder leaves corrosive residue harmful to equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored regulated sensitive data. Following NIST SP 800-88 guidance, which sanitization approach is MOST appropriate?","o":["Degaussing the drives with a strong magnetic field, as used for traditional hard disk drives","Performing a full-disk cryptographic erase or vendor-supported secure erase command designed for SSD flash media","Deleting all files and emptying the recycle bin before repurposing the drives","Physically wiping the drive with a standard disk-wipe utility that overwrites sectors sequentially like on an HDD"],"c":1,"why":"SSDs use flash memory and wear-leveling, so magnetic degaussing has no effect and sector-based overwrite tools designed for HDDs cannot reliably reach all physical blocks; NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase or ATA/NVMe secure erase commands purpose-built for flash media. Simple file deletion leaves data recoverable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A software development team wants to minimize the cost of remediating security defects across the entire development lifecycle. Based on established software engineering economics, during which phase should security requirements first be formally identified and documented?","o":["Requirements and analysis phase","System testing phase","User acceptance testing phase","Operations and maintenance phase"],"c":0,"why":"Identifying security requirements during the requirements/analysis phase is the most cost-effective point, since defects found later (testing, UAT, or especially production) require significantly more rework and cost to fix. The other phases occur after design/coding decisions have already been made, making remediation far more expensive.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During threat modeling of a financial transaction API, a security architect determines that a valid, correctly signed transaction message contains no timestamp or nonce. An attacker who captures the message in transit could resend it unmodified multiple times, causing the server to process duplicate fund transfers even though the message itself was never altered. Under the STRIDE model, which threat category best describes this risk?","o":["Repudiation","Tampering","Spoofing","Denial of Service"],"c":1,"why":"Even though the message content is unmodified, replaying it to force unauthorized re-execution of a transaction violates the integrity of the system state, which STRIDE classifies as Tampering. Spoofing involves impersonating identity, Repudiation involves denying an action occurred, and Denial of Service involves degrading availability—none of which match a replay causing duplicate processing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During an incident response process, which of the following steps should occur immediately after an incident has been detected and confirmed?","o":["Eradication of the root cause","Containment of the affected systems","Recovery and return to normal operations","Post-incident review and lessons learned"],"c":1,"why":"After detection and confirmation, containment is the immediate priority to limit damage and prevent spread before eradication, recovery, and review occur.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to analyze an application's source code for vulnerabilities such as hardcoded credentials and unsafe function calls before the application is compiled or executed. Which testing technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source, byte, or binary code without executing the application, making it suitable for finding issues like hardcoded secrets early in development. DAST and penetration testing require a running application, and fuzz testing focuses on malformed input during execution rather than static code review.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An application security team is evaluating a Java web application built with numerous third-party libraries. They want a testing approach that instruments the running application with agents during normal functional QA execution, tracing actual data flow and library calls to pinpoint the exact vulnerable line of code with a low false-positive rate, without writing separate security test scripts. Which technique best fits this requirement?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Fuzz testing"],"c":2,"why":"IAST uses runtime instrumentation alongside functional tests to trace execution and data flow, giving precise, low-false-positive results tied to source location. SAST analyzes code without execution, DAST tests as an external black box with no code visibility, and fuzzing injects malformed input to find crashes but does not instrument internal execution paths.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the purpose of maintaining a chain of custody for digital evidence?","o":["To ensure evidence is encrypted during storage","To document who handled the evidence and when, preserving its integrity for legal proceedings","To reduce the size of evidence files for faster analysis","To determine which employees are authorized to access the incident response team"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documents every person who handled evidence and the actions taken, ensuring integrity and admissibility in court; the other options do not relate to evidentiary integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A financial analyst has access only to individual transaction records, each of which is classified at a low sensitivity level. By systematically querying and correlating many of these low-sensitivity records, the analyst is able to deduce a customer's overall net worth, which is classified as highly sensitive. This scenario best describes which type of database security concern?","o":["SQL injection","Aggregation attack","Buffer overflow","Cross-site scripting"],"c":1,"why":"An aggregation attack occurs when combining multiple pieces of individually low-sensitivity data produces a result that is more sensitive than any single piece, exactly as described. SQL injection and XSS are input-manipulation attacks, and a buffer overflow is a memory-corruption issue, none of which match this scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A web application lets users submit a URL, and the server fetches that URL to generate a link preview. An attacker submits 'http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/', and the server retrieves and displays the cloud instance's temporary IAM credentials. What type of attack is this?","o":["Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)","Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)","XML External Entity (XXE) injection","Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR)"],"c":1,"why":"SSRF occurs when an attacker manipulates a server into making unintended requests to internal or restricted resources, such as a cloud metadata service. CSRF forces a victim's browser to perform actions on an authenticated site, XXE abuses XML parsers to reach files or network resources via external entities, and IDOR involves unauthorized access to objects via predictable references—none of which involve the server itself being tricked into fetching an internal URL.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A backup strategy that copies only the data that has changed since the last full backup, and continues to grow in size each day until the next full backup, is known as which type of backup?","o":["Incremental backup","Differential backup","Full backup","Mirror backup"],"c":1,"why":"A differential backup captures all changes since the last full backup, growing larger each day, unlike an incremental backup which only captures changes since the last backup of any type (smaller, faster).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Which secure coding practice most directly prevents a buffer overflow vulnerability from occurring in the first place, rather than simply making successful exploitation more difficult?","o":["Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)","Enforcing strict bounds checking and input length validation before writing to a buffer","Enabling Data Execution Prevention (DEP)","Deploying a stack canary value"],"c":1,"why":"Bounds checking and input validation prevent data from ever being written beyond allocated memory, eliminating the root cause of the overflow. ASLR, DEP, and stack canaries are exploit-mitigation techniques that reduce the impact of an overflow but do not prevent the underlying memory corruption from happening.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An analyst has access only to aggregate department salary reports (no individual figures) and, by cross-referencing these with publicly available headcount and total payroll data, is able to mathematically deduce the exact salary of one named employee. What is this an example of?","o":["Aggregation","Inference","Polyinstantiation","Data diddling"],"c":1,"why":"Inference is deducing restricted information from available non-sensitive data through logical or statistical reasoning, which matches this scenario. Aggregation refers to combining multiple low-sensitivity data items to produce a single item of higher classification, polyinstantiation creates multiple record versions at different classification levels specifically to prevent inference, and data diddling is unauthorized alteration of data, none of which describe deduction from available reports.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During a live incident response on a compromised production server, the IR team has limited time before the system must be taken offline. According to the order of volatility principle, which type of evidence should be collected FIRST?","o":["Contents of system RAM (running processes, network connections)","Data stored on the local hard disk drive","Archived system logs stored on backup tape","Printed incident reports from the help desk"],"c":0,"why":"RAM contents are the most volatile and will be lost immediately upon power loss or reboot, so they must be captured first; disk data, archived logs, and paper records are progressively less volatile and can be preserved later without loss.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is reviewing a financial application that checks a user's file permissions before opening a file, but the file is opened only after a brief delay caused by additional validation logic. An attacker exploits the delay by swapping the target file with a symbolic link to a sensitive file after the permission check but before the open() call. Which vulnerability class does this describe, and what is the most effective mitigation?","o":["A race condition (TOCTOU); mitigate by using atomic file operations that combine the check and the access into a single system call","A buffer overflow; mitigate by validating input length before processing","An injection flaw; mitigate by using parameterized queries","A privilege escalation flaw; mitigate by enforcing least privilege on the service account"],"c":0,"why":"This is a classic Time-of-Check-to-Time-of-Use (TOCTOU) race condition, where the state of a resource changes between validation and use; the fix is to eliminate the window by using atomic operations (e.g., open with O_NOFOLLOW or combined check-and-open calls) rather than separate check/use steps. The other options describe unrelated vulnerability classes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements RAID 1 across its critical database servers. What is the primary security benefit provided by this configuration?","o":["Increased read/write performance through striping","Data redundancy through disk mirroring, protecting against a single disk failure","Reduced storage costs by combining multiple disks into one logical volume","Automatic encryption of data at rest"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 1 mirrors data across two disks, so if one disk fails the data remains available on the other; it does not primarily improve performance, reduce cost, or provide encryption.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization requires that every approved version of an application's source code, configuration files, and build scripts be recorded as a formal reference point before any new changes are introduced. This practice is an example of which software development security control?","o":["Regression testing","Configuration baselining","Static code analysis","Least privilege enforcement"],"c":1,"why":"Establishing a documented, approved reference point for code and configuration items is the definition of configuration baselining within configuration management, enabling rollback and change tracking. Regression testing verifies functionality after changes, static analysis scans code for flaws, and least privilege is an access control principle, none of which describe recording a reference baseline.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization's private npm registry hosts an internal package named 'acme-auth-utils' that has never been published publicly. The CI build tool is configured to check the public npm registry if a package isn't found locally first. An attacker publishes a malicious package with the identical name and a higher version number to the public registry. The next CI build automatically pulls and executes the attacker's package. What is this attack called?","o":["Typosquatting","Dependency confusion","Watering hole attack","Credential stuffing"],"c":1,"why":"Dependency confusion exploits package manager resolution logic so that a malicious public package with the same name (and higher version) is pulled instead of the intended private one. Typosquatting relies on similarly misspelled package names rather than identical ones, a watering hole attack compromises a site frequented by targets, and credential stuffing involves reusing stolen credentials—none match this build-resolution exploit.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A software security team has access only to a compiled, third-party binary with no source code, and they want to identify vulnerabilities that manifest only when the application is exercised with live inputs in a running environment. Which testing methodology is most appropriate?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)"],"c":1,"why":"DAST tests a running application from the outside (black-box) without requiring source code, making it ideal here. SAST and IAST require source code or instrumentation access, and SCA is used to identify vulnerable open-source components, not runtime behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A financial institution detects active ransomware encrypting files on a critical file server. The IR team must stop the spread while preserving forensic evidence for later analysis and potential legal action. What is the BEST containment action?","o":["Immediately power off the server to halt encryption","Isolate the server from the network while keeping it powered on, then capture volatile memory before further analysis","Delete all encrypted files and restore from the most recent backup right away","Wipe the disk and reinstall the operating system to eliminate the malware"],"c":1,"why":"Network isolation stops lateral spread/C2 communication while keeping the system powered on preserves volatile evidence (RAM, running processes) for forensic capture; powering off destroys volatile evidence, and deleting files or reimaging destroys evidence and eliminates root-cause analysis opportunities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of a formal change management process in IT operations?","o":["To eliminate the need for security testing before deployment","To ensure changes are reviewed, approved, tested, and documented before implementation to minimize unintended impact","To speed up deployment of emergency patches without review","To assign blame when a change causes an outage"],"c":1,"why":"Change management ensures changes are properly assessed, approved, and documented to reduce risk of unintended consequences; it does not eliminate testing, bypass review for speed, or serve a punitive purpose.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"To reduce the impact of buffer overflow vulnerabilities, a security engineer wants a control that randomizes the memory addresses of the stack, heap, and loaded libraries on each execution, making it difficult for an attacker to reliably predict where injected code or reusable code gadgets reside, even though the control does not prevent the overflow from occurring. Which control is being described?","o":["Stack canaries","Data Execution Prevention (DEP/NX)","Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)","Input validation"],"c":2,"why":"ASLR randomizes memory layout addresses on each execution, defeating an attacker's ability to reliably target specific addresses. DEP/NX marks memory regions non-executable but does not randomize addresses, stack canaries detect stack corruption via a sentinel value but don't affect address predictability, and input validation would prevent the overflow itself rather than mitigate exploitation of memory addresses.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A development team integrates automated vulnerability scanning tools directly into their continuous integration/continuous deployment (CI/CD) pipeline so that every code commit is scanned before it can be merged. This practice best exemplifies which DevSecOps principle?","o":["Segregation of duties","Shifting security left","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity"],"c":1,"why":"'Shifting left' means integrating security testing as early as possible in the development pipeline, which is exactly what automated scanning on every commit accomplishes. Segregation of duties concerns separating roles, defense in depth concerns layered controls, and security through obscurity relies on hiding design details, none of which describe this automation practice.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During an audit, a company discovers that a critical open-source library embedded in its flagship product has a known critical CVE, but the security team has no record of which products use this library or which version is deployed. What should the organization implement to prevent this gap going forward?","o":["A Web Application Firewall (WAF) in front of all production applications","A Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) process integrated into the build pipeline","Mandatory two-person code review for all commits","A bug bounty program covering all public-facing applications"],"c":1,"why":"An SBOM provides a complete, automatically generated inventory of all components and their versions used in a build, enabling rapid identification of affected products when a new CVE is disclosed. A WAF, code review, and bug bounty programs do not provide component-level visibility into the software supply chain.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application allows users to enter data into a search field, which is then used directly in a SQL query without modification. Which of the following is the MOST effective control to prevent SQL injection attacks against this application?","o":["Encrypting the database connection string","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Implementing a web application firewall as the only defense","Increasing the length limit on the input field"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, ensuring user input is never interpreted as executable SQL, which directly addresses the root cause of SQL injection. Encryption, WAFs alone, and input length limits do not reliably prevent injection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires that the employee who initiates a wire transfer request cannot also be the one who approves it. This control is an example of which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by a single individual; least privilege limits access rights, job rotation moves people between roles over time, and mandatory vacation forces time away from duties.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization determines that the Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) for its order-processing system is 8 hours. The technical recovery team's Recovery Time Objective (RTO) for restoring system functionality is 5 hours. What is the maximum Work Recovery Time (WRT) available to fully resume business operations without exceeding the MTD?","o":["3 hours","5 hours","8 hours","13 hours"],"c":0,"why":"MTD = RTO + WRT, so WRT = MTD - RTO = 8 - 5 = 3 hours; the other values either ignore the RTO already consumed or incorrectly sum the figures rather than subtracting.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A company licenses the source code of a critical business application from a small software vendor. Concerned that the vendor might go bankrupt or discontinue the product, the company negotiates a contractual arrangement requiring the vendor to deposit current source code, build scripts, and documentation with an independent third party, to be released to the company upon specific trigger events such as vendor insolvency. What is this arrangement called?","o":["Configuration management","Software escrow","Digital rights management (DRM)","Distributed version control"],"c":1,"why":"Software escrow is a contractual arrangement in which source code and supporting materials are held by a neutral third party and released to the licensee under defined trigger conditions. Configuration management governs internal change and version tracking, DRM protects copyrighted content from unauthorized use, and version control tracks code history but provides no independent third-party custody or contractual release conditions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A privileged process checks that a file is owned by the requesting user and then, a few milliseconds later, opens that file to perform an operation. An attacker exploits the small delay between the check and the actual file access to substitute a different file. What type of vulnerability is being exploited?","o":["Race condition (time-of-check to time-of-use)","SQL injection","Session fixation","Cross-site request forgery"],"c":0,"why":"This is a classic TOCTOU (time-of-check-to-time-of-use) race condition, where the attacker changes the resource state between validation and use. SQL injection, session fixation, and CSRF involve manipulating input, session tokens, or forged requests, not exploiting a timing gap in resource validation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A multi-level secure database must prevent low-clearance users from inferring the existence of classified records when they attempt to insert a record with a primary key that already exists at a higher classification level. Which database security technique directly addresses this?","o":["Database views restricting column access","Polyinstantiation, allowing multiple rows with the same key to exist at different classification levels","Referential integrity constraints","Two-phase commit protocols"],"c":1,"why":"Polyinstantiation allows the database to create a different, lower-classified version of a record with the same primary key so the low-clearance user's insert succeeds without revealing that a higher-classified record already exists. Views and referential integrity address access scoping and consistency, not inference from key collisions, and two-phase commit addresses transaction atomicity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) should security requirements ideally be first identified and documented?","o":["Testing phase","Requirements/analysis phase","Deployment phase","Maintenance phase"],"c":1,"why":"Security requirements should be defined during the requirements/analysis phase so they can be built into the design from the start, following the principle of 'security by design.' Addressing security later (testing, deployment, maintenance) is more costly and less effective.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company wants a disaster recovery site that has fully configured hardware, software, and near-real-time data replication, allowing failover within minutes to a few hours. Which type of recovery site best meets this requirement?","o":["Cold site","Warm site","Hot site","Reciprocal agreement site"],"c":2,"why":"A hot site is fully equipped and kept synchronized with production data, enabling rapid failover; cold sites have only basic infrastructure, warm sites have partial readiness with longer recovery time, and reciprocal agreements rely on another organization's facility.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A production system fails during off-hours and requires an emergency change to restore service before formal Change Advisory Board (CAB) review can occur. Which approach reflects a mature change management process?","o":["Emergency changes bypass all documentation since speed is critical to restoring service","The change is implemented immediately to restore service, then formally documented and reviewed retroactively by the CAB","Only the CISO may approve emergency changes, and no further review is required afterward","Emergency changes must go through the full standard CAB approval process before implementation, regardless of outage impact"],"c":1,"why":"Mature change management processes allow expedited emergency changes to restore service, followed by mandatory retroactive documentation and CAB review to ensure accountability and lessons learned; skipping documentation entirely or requiring full pre-approval during an outage is impractical and against best practice.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A company incorporates numerous open-source libraries into its commercial software product but has no formal process for tracking which versions are used or whether they contain known vulnerabilities. Which of the following would best address this gap?","o":["Implementing a Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) and continuous component vulnerability monitoring","Increasing the frequency of unit testing during development","Requiring mandatory code obfuscation before release","Adopting a waterfall development methodology"],"c":0,"why":"An SBOM provides an inventory of all third-party and open-source components, enabling ongoing tracking of versions and known vulnerabilities (e.g., via CVE feeds). Unit testing verifies functional correctness, code obfuscation hides code without addressing vulnerable dependencies, and a development methodology choice does not manage component risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A software organization has recently standardized its development processes so that every project team now follows the same documented lifecycle, templates, and review procedures across the enterprise. However, the organization has not yet implemented quantitative metrics to statistically manage process performance. According to the CMMI model, which maturity level does this organization most likely represent?","o":["Level 1 – Initial","Level 2 – Managed","Level 3 – Defined","Level 4 – Quantitatively Managed"],"c":2,"why":"Level 3 (Defined) is characterized by organization-wide standardized, documented processes applied consistently across projects, which matches the scenario. Level 1 is ad hoc and chaotic, Level 2 involves basic project-level management but processes may still vary between projects, and Level 4 adds statistical/quantitative control of process performance, which the organization has not yet achieved.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A developer writes code in C that calculates a buffer allocation size by multiplying a user-supplied count by a fixed record size, then allocates memory using that result without any bounds checking. Which secure coding flaw is most likely to result, and what is the best mitigation?","o":["Cross-site scripting; mitigate through output encoding","Integer overflow leading to undersized buffer allocation; mitigate by validating input ranges and using safe arithmetic functions that detect overflow","SQL injection; mitigate through parameterized queries","Use of a broken cryptographic algorithm; mitigate by adopting AES-256"],"c":1,"why":"Multiplying an unchecked, attacker-controlled value can overflow the integer type, wrapping to a small or negative number and causing an undersized allocation that leads to a subsequent buffer overflow; safe/checked arithmetic and input validation prevent this. The other options describe unrelated vulnerability categories that don't match the scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to identify vulnerabilities in application source code without executing the program. Which testing technique should be used?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source code or binaries without executing the application, identifying vulnerabilities like insecure coding patterns early. DAST, fuzzing, and penetration testing all involve testing a running application.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security operations benefit of deploying a Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system?","o":["It automatically patches vulnerable systems across the network","It aggregates and correlates log data from multiple sources to detect and alert on suspicious activity","It replaces the need for firewalls and intrusion prevention systems","It performs full disk encryption on all endpoints"],"c":1,"why":"A SIEM centralizes and correlates logs from various sources to identify patterns indicative of security incidents; it does not patch systems, replace network security devices, or perform encryption.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A vendor releases a critical security patch addressing an actively exploited zero-day vulnerability affecting a primary production system. Which approach BEST balances the risk of an untested patch against the risk of continued exploitation?","o":["Deploy the patch to representative test/staging systems mirroring production, validate functionality quickly, then expedite rollout to production with a documented rollback plan","Wait for the next scheduled quarterly patch cycle to ensure thorough regression testing","Deploy the patch immediately to all production systems without any testing, given the urgency of active exploitation","Delay patching indefinitely until the vendor guarantees zero side effects"],"c":0,"why":"Expedited but validated testing on representative systems, followed by controlled rollout with rollback capability, addresses both the urgency of active exploitation and the risk of destabilizing production; waiting for a routine cycle leaves systems exposed, and untested mass deployment risks unplanned outages.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A company licenses critical proprietary software from a small vendor and is concerned the vendor could go out of business, leaving the company without access to source code needed for continued maintenance. Which contractual control best addresses this risk?","o":["A service level agreement (SLA) specifying uptime guarantees","A software escrow agreement placing source code with a neutral third party, releasable upon defined trigger events","A right-to-audit clause allowing the company to inspect the vendor's development practices","A non-disclosure agreement (NDA) protecting the vendor's intellectual property"],"c":1,"why":"Software escrow specifically protects the licensee by ensuring source code (and often build/documentation materials) is held by a trusted third party and released if the vendor fails, is acquired, or otherwise cannot support the product. SLAs, audit rights, and NDAs address different risks and do not guarantee source code access.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the primary purpose of a version control (source code management) system in secure software development?","o":["To automatically encrypt all source code files at rest","To track changes to code over time and enable rollback to previous versions","To replace the need for code review before deployment","To perform automated penetration testing on committed code"],"c":1,"why":"Version control systems track changes, maintain history, and allow reverting to prior versions, supporting accountability and integrity of the codebase. It does not perform encryption, replace code review, or conduct penetration testing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A security analyst suspects a low-and-slow brute-force attack in which an attacker uses many different source IP addresses, each making only a few failed login attempts against a single target account over 24 hours, specifically to evade per-source-IP alerting thresholds. Which SIEM capability would MOST effectively detect this activity?","o":["Signature-based detection matching known attack tool strings","A correlation rule aggregating failed login events by target account across all source IPs within a rolling time window","Raising the per-IP failed login threshold to reduce noise","Real-time alerting triggered on any single failed login event"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregating failed authentication events by target account (rather than by source IP) across a time window reveals the cumulative attack pattern that individual per-IP thresholds miss; signature matching won't catch this behavioral pattern, and raising thresholds or alerting on single events either misses or floods with irrelevant data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to benchmark and improve the maturity of its secure software development practices specifically, comparing activities like threat modeling coverage, security testing integration, and governance across development teams, rather than assessing general process maturity across all engineering disciplines. Which model is purpose-built for this?","o":["CMMI (Capability Maturity Model Integration)","ISO 9001","BSIMM (Building Security In Maturity Model) or OWASP SAMM","ITIL Service Value Chain"],"c":2,"why":"BSIMM and OWASP SAMM are specifically designed to measure and mature software security practices such as threat modeling, secure testing, and governance activities within the SDLC. CMMI addresses general process maturity, ISO 9001 addresses quality management, and ITIL addresses IT service management, none of which are software-security-specific.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A software development team wants to ensure that changes to production code go through a formal, documented approval process before deployment. Which practice BEST supports this goal?","o":["Continuous deployment with no manual gates","Change management process with defined approval workflows","Allowing developers to push directly to production","Disabling logging to speed up releases"],"c":1,"why":"A formal change management process ensures changes are reviewed, approved, and documented before implementation, reducing risk of unauthorized or unstable changes. The other options bypass oversight and increase risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"Which fire suppression system is MOST appropriate for a manned data center housing sensitive electronic equipment, balancing effective fire suppression, occupant safety, and equipment protection?","o":["Wet pipe water sprinkler system","Carbon dioxide (CO2) total flooding system","Clean agent (e.g., FM-200/Novec) gaseous suppression system","Dry chemical powder extinguishing system"],"c":2,"why":"Clean agent gaseous systems suppress fire effectively without leaving residue or damaging electronics, and unlike CO2 they are safe for occupied spaces; water sprinklers damage equipment, and dry chemical powder leaves corrosive residue harmful to electronics.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A RESTful API endpoint allows authenticated users to update their own profile by submitting a JSON object with fields such as 'email' and 'bio'. A penetration tester discovers that submitting an additional field, 'isAdmin': true, in the request body actually elevates the user's privileges because the backend blindly binds all submitted JSON fields to the corresponding database object. Which vulnerability is being exploited, and what is the best remediation?","o":["Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF); remediate with anti-CSRF tokens","Mass assignment; remediate by using an explicit allow-list of bindable fields (DTOs) rather than binding all submitted fields directly to the model","Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR); remediate by validating object ownership on every request","Broken authentication; remediate by enforcing multi-factor authentication"],"c":1,"why":"This is a mass assignment vulnerability, where framework auto-binding allows attacker-supplied fields not intended to be user-editable (like 'isAdmin') to modify protected object properties; the fix is to explicitly whitelist which fields can be bound from user input (e.g., via DTOs) rather than binding the entire request body. CSRF, IDOR, and broken authentication describe different attack patterns unrelated to uncontrolled field binding.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY benefit of conducting peer code reviews during software development?","o":["It eliminates the need for functional testing","It allows developers to identify defects and security flaws before code is merged","It guarantees compliance with all regulatory requirements","It replaces the need for a quality assurance team"],"c":1,"why":"Peer code review helps catch bugs, logic errors, and security weaknesses early through human inspection, improving code quality before integration. It does not eliminate testing, guarantee compliance, or replace QA functions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday and incremental backups (capturing changes since the last backup, full or incremental) on each subsequent day. The server fails on Saturday afternoon, after Friday's incremental backup completed successfully but before Saturday's would run. To fully restore the server, which backups must be applied, and in what order?","o":["Only Friday's incremental backup","Sunday's full backup only","Sunday's full backup, followed sequentially by each incremental backup from Monday through Friday, in order","Sunday's full backup and Friday's incremental backup only, skipping Monday through Thursday"],"c":2,"why":"Incremental backups only capture changes since the previous backup, so full restoration requires the last full backup plus every subsequent incremental applied in sequence; unlike differential backups, skipping any incremental in the chain results in incomplete data recovery.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization adopts a DevSecOps approach by integrating automated security scanning into the earliest stages of its CI/CD pipeline. This practice is BEST described as an example of which concept?","o":["Security through obscurity","Shifting security left","Defense in depth only at the network layer","Segregation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"'Shifting left' refers to integrating security activities earlier in the development pipeline rather than only at the end, which is exactly what automated scanning early in CI/CD accomplishes. The other terms describe unrelated security concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Before incorporating a popular open-source library into a commercial application, which action BEST helps identify security risks associated with that component?","o":["Reviewing the library's marketing website for feature claims","Performing a software composition analysis (SCA) to check for known vulnerabilities","Assuming the library is safe because it is widely used","Renaming the library files to avoid detection by scanners"],"c":1,"why":"Software composition analysis scans third-party and open-source components against known vulnerability databases, helping identify risks such as outdated or vulnerable dependencies. Popularity alone does not guarantee security, and the other options provide no real risk assessment.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which phase of the incident response process focuses on limiting the scope and impact of an ongoing security incident before it can be fully removed from the environment?","o":["Containment","Eradication","Lessons learned","Detection"],"c":0,"why":"Containment is the phase where the incident's spread is limited (e.g., isolating affected systems) before eradication removes the root cause; eradication and lessons learned occur later, and detection occurs earlier in the process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) should security requirements be first formally defined and documented?","o":["Requirements/analysis phase, alongside functional requirements","Testing phase, after the code is written","Deployment phase, once the system is in production","Maintenance phase, in response to discovered vulnerabilities"],"c":0,"why":"Security requirements must be defined early, during requirements analysis, so they can be designed and built in from the start; addressing them later is more costly and often results in retrofitted, weaker controls.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During a ransomware outbreak, an incident response team disconnects infected workstations from the network and disables the affected file-share credentials before performing any remediation. Which phase of the incident response process does this action represent?","o":["Eradication","Containment","Lessons learned","Detection"],"c":1,"why":"Containment focuses on limiting the scope and impact of an incident (e.g., isolating hosts, disabling accounts) before removing the root cause. Eradication removes the malware itself, detection identifies the incident, and lessons learned occurs after recovery.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that any change to a production system is reviewed, approved, tested, and documented before implementation. Which process BEST accomplishes this goal?","o":["Configuration management","Change management","Patch management","Release management"],"c":1,"why":"Change management is the formal process for reviewing, approving, and documenting changes before implementation; configuration management tracks the baseline state, patch management addresses software updates specifically, and release management deals with deploying new versions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An application accepts user input directly into SQL statements without validation. Which control provides the most effective long-term protection against SQL injection?","o":["Increasing the length limit on input fields","Encrypting the database at rest","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements) with bound variables","Deploying a network intrusion detection system"],"c":2,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing attacker-supplied input from being interpreted as SQL commands; encryption at rest, field length limits, and NIDS do not address the root cause of injection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to analyze an application's source code for vulnerabilities before it is compiled and without executing the program. Which testing approach should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source, byte, or binary code without executing the application, identifying issues like insecure functions or logic flaws early; DAST, fuzzing, and pen testing all require a running application.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A forensic investigator seizes a hard drive from a compromised server and must ensure it can be used as evidence in court. Which practice is MOST critical to preserving the evidentiary value of the drive?","o":["Encrypting the drive image with AES-256 before analysis","Maintaining a documented chain of custody from seizure through analysis","Performing analysis only on weekends to avoid business disruption","Storing the original drive in a fireproof safe within the data center"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation proves the evidence was not altered or tampered with, which is essential for admissibility. Encryption and physical storage are good practices but do not by themselves establish evidentiary integrity, and analysis timing is irrelevant to legal admissibility.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"In software configuration management, what is the primary purpose of establishing a 'baseline' for a software release?","o":["To document known bugs for future patching","To create a fixed reference point of code and configuration for change control and rollback","To measure application performance under load","To define the encryption algorithms used in the application"],"c":1,"why":"A baseline is an approved, fixed snapshot of code/configuration used to track and control subsequent changes, enabling rollback if needed; the other options describe unrelated activities like bug tracking or performance testing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization's change management policy requires that all production changes follow a defined workflow. Which sequence correctly reflects a properly controlled change process?","o":["Implement change, test in production, document results, notify stakeholders","Submit request, assess impact and risk, obtain approval, test in non-production, schedule and implement, review outcome","Approve change verbally, implement immediately, document afterward if time permits","Test in production during business hours, roll back if issues occur, document only failures"],"c":1,"why":"A sound change management process requires formal request, risk assessment, approval, testing in a non-production environment, scheduled implementation, and post-implementation review. The other options skip critical controls like approval or testing, increasing risk to production systems.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to minimize the cost and impact of fixing security defects in a new application. At which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) should security requirements first be defined?","o":["During the requirements/planning phase, before design begins","During the coding phase, as developers write functions","During user acceptance testing, before deployment","During the maintenance phase, after the first patch cycle"],"c":0,"why":"Security requirements defined early in requirements/planning are far cheaper to address than defects discovered later; waiting until coding, testing, or maintenance dramatically increases remediation cost and risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A database allows users to query aggregate statistics but restricts access to individual records. An analyst is able to deduce a specific employee's salary by combining several allowed aggregate queries. What type of attack does this represent?","o":["SQL injection","Inference attack","Buffer overflow","Cross-site scripting"],"c":1,"why":"An inference attack occurs when a user deduces restricted information by correlating results from multiple permitted queries; this does not involve malicious code injection, memory corruption, or client-side scripting.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A backup administrator configures a schedule where a full backup runs every Sunday, and each subsequent day only the data that has changed since the LAST backup (whether full or incremental) is backed up. This describes which backup strategy?","o":["Differential backup","Incremental backup","Mirror backup","Snapshot backup"],"c":1,"why":"Incremental backups capture only changes since the most recent backup of any type, resulting in faster backups but requiring the full backup plus all incremental sets for restoration. Differential backups capture changes since the last FULL backup only, and mirror/snapshot describe different concepts entirely.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application accepts a username from a form field and inserts it directly into a SQL query string without any processing. Which secure coding technique BEST mitigates the resulting SQL injection risk?","o":["Increasing the database connection timeout","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Encrypting the database at rest","Disabling client-side JavaScript validation"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data so user input cannot alter the SQL statement's structure; timeouts, at-rest encryption, and client-side validation do not prevent injection because input is still concatenated into queries or can be bypassed.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During an active incident response, a forensic analyst must prioritize the collection of evidence from a compromised production server before it is powered down. Following the order of volatility, which item should be collected FIRST?","o":["Contents of CPU registers and cache memory","Data stored on the local hard disk","Configuration data stored in NVRAM","Archived log files stored on a backup tape"],"c":0,"why":"Order of volatility dictates collecting the most transient data first; CPU registers and cache are lost within nanoseconds of power loss or process changes, making them the highest priority. Disk data, NVRAM, and backups are progressively more persistent and can be collected later without loss.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Which programming practice is most effective at preventing buffer overflow vulnerabilities?","o":["Using strong password policies for application accounts","Performing input validation and bounds checking on all data written to memory buffers","Encrypting data before writing it to a buffer","Implementing role-based access control on the application"],"c":1,"why":"Buffer overflows occur when data exceeds allocated memory boundaries; validating input length and enforcing bounds checks prevents this, whereas encryption, RBAC, and password policies do not address memory-handling flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A business continuity plan states that the accounting system can tolerate a maximum of 4 hours of data loss in the event of a disruption. This requirement is best described as the:","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Service Level Agreement (SLA)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, dictating backup frequency. RTO and MTD relate to how quickly systems must be restored, not data loss tolerance, and an SLA is a contractual service commitment, not a continuity metric.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which backup strategy captures only the data that has changed since the last full backup, resulting in faster backups but longer restore times when combined with the full backup?","o":["Differential backup","Incremental backup","Full backup","Mirror backup"],"c":0,"why":"A differential backup captures all changes since the last full backup, so restore requires the full backup plus the most recent differential; incremental backups capture changes since the last backup of any type (faster but requiring multiple restores), and full/mirror backups copy everything.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization's business impact analysis establishes a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 8 hours for a critical order-processing system. The recovery team estimates the Work Recovery Time (WRT) needed to reconfigure and validate the system after restoration will be 3 hours. What is the maximum allowable Recovery Time Objective (RTO) the technical recovery team can target to stay within the MTD?","o":["8 hours","3 hours","5 hours","11 hours"],"c":2,"why":"MTD = RTO + WRT, so RTO = MTD - WRT = 8 - 3 = 5 hours. Using the full 8 hours as RTO would leave no time for WRT, and 11 hours exceeds the MTD entirely, violating business continuity requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which testing method analyzes an application's source code or binaries for vulnerabilities WITHOUT executing the program?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Penetration testing","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing"],"c":2,"why":"SAST examines source/binary code at rest to find flaws like insecure functions or logic errors. DAST, penetration testing, and fuzzing all require the application to be running.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is integrating a third-party open-source library into its application. Which practice best helps identify known vulnerabilities and license risks associated with that library?","o":["Conducting a software composition analysis (SCA)","Performing a full manual code review of the entire application","Relying solely on the vendor's marketing documentation","Encrypting the library's binary files before deployment"],"c":0,"why":"Software composition analysis specifically identifies open-source and third-party components, their known vulnerabilities, and license obligations; manual full-code review is impractical at scale, and vendor marketing or encryption do not reveal component risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security operations center deploys a tool that aggregates logs from firewalls, IDS sensors, and endpoint agents, then applies correlation rules to identify a coordinated attack pattern across multiple systems. This tool is best classified as a:","o":["Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system","Data Loss Prevention (DLP) system","Network Access Control (NAC) system","Intrusion Prevention System (IPS)"],"c":0,"why":"A SIEM aggregates and correlates log data from diverse sources to detect patterns indicative of an attack. DLP focuses on preventing data exfiltration, NAC controls device access to the network, and an IPS actively blocks malicious traffic rather than correlating logs across systems.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A critical zero-day vulnerability requires an emergency patch to be applied to a production database outside the normal change management schedule. The patch is applied immediately by the on-call engineer without prior Change Advisory Board (CAB) approval. What is the MOST appropriate next step to maintain proper change management governance?","o":["Roll back the patch immediately since it bypassed the approval process","Conduct a formal post-implementation review with the CAB to document and ratify the emergency change","Take no further action since the patch resolved the immediate security risk","Require the engineer to resubmit the same change through the standard change process next quarter"],"c":1,"why":"Emergency change procedures allow bypassing normal approval to address urgent risk, but the change must still be formally documented and reviewed by the CAB afterward to ensure accountability and proper record-keeping. Rolling back reintroduces the vulnerability, and ignoring the review or delaying documentation undermines change control integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A development team uses a system that tracks every change to source code, allows multiple developers to collaborate, and can revert files to prior states if a defect is introduced. What is this system called?","o":["A configuration management database (CMDB)","A version control system","An intrusion detection system (IDS)","A change advisory board (CAB)"],"c":1,"why":"A version control system (e.g., Git) manages source code history, collaboration, and rollback. A CMDB tracks IT assets, an IDS detects intrusions, and a CAB approves changes but does not manage code itself.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During evidence collection at a compromised server, which action is MOST important to preserve the integrity of digital evidence for potential legal proceedings?","o":["Immediately patching the vulnerability that was exploited","Maintaining a documented chain of custody for all evidence collected","Rebooting the system to check for persistence mechanisms","Deleting temporary files to reduce noise in the analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation proves evidence has not been altered or tampered with, which is essential for admissibility; patching, rebooting, or deleting files can destroy volatile evidence and compromise forensic integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"In a DevSecOps CI/CD pipeline, what is the primary benefit of embedding automated security testing gates directly into the build process?","o":["It eliminates the need for any manual security review","It allows vulnerabilities to be detected and remediated earlier and more cost-effectively, before production deployment","It guarantees compliance with all regulatory requirements automatically","It replaces the need for a separate incident response process"],"c":1,"why":"Embedding automated security checks (SAST, dependency scanning, etc.) into CI/CD shifts security left, catching issues earlier when they are cheaper to fix; it does not eliminate manual review, guarantee compliance, or remove the need for incident response.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization has limited staff to patch systems and must prioritize remediation efforts. Which approach BEST supports risk-based patch prioritization?","o":["Patch all systems in alphabetical order by hostname to ensure consistency","Patch only systems that have experienced downtime in the past month","Prioritize patches based on CVSS severity scores combined with asset criticality and exploitability","Apply patches strictly in the order vendors release them, regardless of system function"],"c":2,"why":"Risk-based prioritization considers vulnerability severity (e.g., CVSS), the criticality of the affected asset, and whether active exploits exist, ensuring the most dangerous exposures are addressed first. The other approaches ignore actual risk and could leave critical vulnerabilities unpatched.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A security analyst notices that log files on a critical server are being overwritten every 24 hours due to a small log size limit. What is the MOST significant security risk this presents?","o":["Increased disk space usage on the server","Reduced system performance during peak hours","Loss of evidence needed to investigate incidents that are discovered after 24 hours","Failure to comply with password complexity requirements"],"c":2,"why":"Short log retention means evidence of an incident may be overwritten before it's discovered, hindering investigation and forensics; the other options are unrelated to log rotation issues.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An attacker sends more data to an input field than the application's buffer was designed to hold, causing adjacent memory to be overwritten and potentially allowing arbitrary code execution. This describes which vulnerability?","o":["Cross-site scripting (XSS)","Buffer overflow","Race condition","Broken authentication"],"c":1,"why":"A buffer overflow occurs when input exceeds allocated memory space, corrupting adjacent memory. XSS involves injecting scripts into web pages, race conditions exploit timing between operations, and broken authentication relates to identity verification flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored highly sensitive financial data. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate for these devices?","o":["Degaussing the drives using a strong magnetic field","Performing a single-pass low-level format","Using the manufacturer's secure erase command or cryptographic erase, followed by verification","Physically wiping the drives with a damp cloth before recycling"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory and are not affected by magnetic degaussing, which only works on magnetic media like HDDs and tapes; secure erase or cryptographic erase commands designed for flash storage properly sanitize the data. A simple format or physical cleaning does not reliably remove data at the storage-cell level.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A storage array configured as RAID 5 experiences the simultaneous failure of two disks in the array. What is the MOST likely outcome?","o":["The array continues operating normally using distributed parity","The array automatically rebuilds using a hot spare with no data loss","All data in the array becomes unrecoverable due to insufficient parity","Only the data written after the first failure is lost"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 5 uses a single parity block per stripe and can tolerate only one disk failure; a second simultaneous failure destroys the ability to reconstruct data, resulting in total data loss for the array. RAID 6, which uses dual parity, would tolerate two failures, but this scenario specifies RAID 5.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Before integrating a free, publicly available open-source library into their commercial application, a development team should PRIMARILY evaluate which of the following?","o":["The library's font and color scheme for UI consistency","Known vulnerabilities, license terms, and maintenance status of the library","Whether the library was written in the same programming language as the main application","The number of downloads the library has received on public repositories"],"c":1,"why":"Software composition analysis focuses on identifying known vulnerabilities, license compliance risks, and whether a component is actively maintained, since unpatched or abandoned components introduce significant risk; download counts and language matching are far less relevant to security.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) in disaster recovery planning?","o":["The maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time","The maximum acceptable downtime before a system or process must be restored","The total cost of downtime for a critical business function","The frequency at which backups must be performed"],"c":1,"why":"RTO defines the maximum tolerable downtime before a system must be restored to avoid unacceptable business impact; data loss tolerance is measured by RPO, not RTO, and cost/backup frequency are separate metrics.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A software organization requires that any modification to production code must be documented, reviewed, tested, and formally approved before deployment. This process is an example of which security control?","o":["Configuration/change management","Separation of duties","Least privilege enforcement","Data classification"],"c":0,"why":"Change management ensures modifications are tracked, reviewed, and approved to maintain integrity and prevent unauthorized or untested changes. Separation of duties and least privilege address access control, not the change approval process; data classification concerns labeling sensitive information.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An employee is suspected of violating an internal acceptable use policy by accessing inappropriate content on a corporate laptop. HR wants to terminate the employee based on the investigation findings. Which standard of proof and investigative approach is MOST appropriate for this internal administrative investigation?","o":["Beyond a reasonable doubt, following strict criminal chain-of-custody procedures","Clear and convincing evidence, requiring law enforcement involvement","Preponderance of the evidence, following organizational policy and reasonable documentation practices","Probable cause, requiring a warrant before examining the laptop"],"c":2,"why":"Internal administrative investigations use the lower civil-style standard of preponderance of the evidence and are governed by organizational policy rather than criminal procedure. Beyond reasonable doubt and probable cause/warrant requirements apply to criminal proceedings, not internal HR actions, and clear and convincing evidence is a higher civil standard not typically required for employment decisions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before disposing of hard drives that contained sensitive customer data, which method provides the HIGHEST assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Reformatting the drive using the operating system's format utility","Deleting all files and emptying the recycle bin","Physical destruction of the drive (e.g., shredding or degaussing)","Moving the files to a different folder marked as archived"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction ensures data cannot be recovered by any means, which is critical for highly sensitive data; formatting, deleting, or moving files leaves the underlying data recoverable with forensic tools.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which security operations control is specifically designed to ensure that no single individual has complete control over a critical process, such as approving and executing a financial transaction?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by any single individual; least privilege limits access levels, job rotation moves people between roles over time, and mandatory vacation forces time away to help detect fraud.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"During code review, a developer notices that when an unexpected error occurs, the application defaults to granting the user full administrative access rather than denying access. Which secure design principle has been violated?","o":["Fail securely (fail closed)","Defense in depth","Economy of mechanism","Separation of duties"],"c":0,"why":"The principle of failing securely requires that when an error occurs, the system defaults to a safe, restrictive state rather than an open or privileged one. Defense in depth relates to layered controls, economy of mechanism to simplicity of design, and separation of duties to dividing critical tasks among individuals.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A data center housing sensitive research servers is being upgraded with a fire suppression system. The room is regularly occupied by staff. Which suppression approach provides the BEST balance of equipment protection and human safety?","o":["CO2 flooding system, since it rapidly extinguishes fires without leaving residue","A clean agent system such as FM-200, which extinguishes fire while maintaining breathable oxygen levels","A traditional wet-pipe water sprinkler system, since water is inexpensive and effective","Halon 1301, since it is still the industry standard for occupied data centers"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agents like FM-200 suppress fire through chemical reaction without significantly depleting oxygen, making them safe for occupied spaces while protecting electronic equipment. CO2 displaces oxygen and is lethal in occupied rooms, water damages electronics, and Halon has been phased out due to environmental regulations (Montreal Protocol).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained highly classified data. The IT team proposes using traditional degaussing equipment to sanitize the drives before disposal. Why is this approach INADEQUATE?","o":["Degaussing requires the drives to be reformatted first, which the team has not done","Degaussing works by disrupting magnetic fields, but SSDs use flash memory, which is not magnetic, so data may remain recoverable","Degaussing is only effective on drives larger than 1TB in capacity","Degaussing voids the manufacturer warranty, making it an inappropriate first step"],"c":1,"why":"Degaussing relies on magnetic disruption to erase data on magnetic media like HDDs; SSDs store data electrically in flash cells, so degaussing has no effect and data can remain recoverable. Per NIST SP 800-88 guidance, SSDs require cryptographic erase, secure firmware-based purge commands, or physical destruction instead.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A ransomware infection is actively spreading laterally across multiple network segments in an organization. The incident response team has identified the initial point of entry. What should be the team's IMMEDIATE priority before beginning eradication and recovery activities?","o":["Restore all affected systems from the most recent backup to minimize downtime","Isolate and contain infected systems and affected network segments to stop further spread","Conduct a full root-cause analysis to determine the attacker's identity and motive","Notify all customers and regulatory bodies of the breach within the first hour"],"c":1,"why":"Containment must occur immediately to stop the spread of an active threat before eradication and recovery, otherwise restoring systems or continuing operations risks re-infection. Root-cause analysis and breach notification are important but occur after containment, not as the immediate first step during an active spreading incident.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) is it most cost-effective to address security, and why?","o":["During requirements analysis, because security flaws are cheaper to fix before design and coding begin","During unit testing, because developers can immediately patch code they just wrote","During user acceptance testing, because business stakeholders can validate security controls directly","During deployment, because production environments provide the most realistic testing conditions"],"c":0,"why":"Addressing security requirements early (requirements phase) is far less costly than fixing defects after design, coding, or deployment, per established software engineering cost-of-defect studies. The other phases occur later in the lifecycle when remediation costs increase significantly.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application accepts user input directly into SQL query strings without validation, allowing attackers to manipulate database queries. Which control provides the MOST effective defense against this vulnerability?","o":["Encrypting the database at rest","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements) with bound variables","Implementing a web application firewall in blocking mode only","Increasing the complexity of database administrator passwords"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing attacker input from altering query structure, which directly addresses SQL injection. Encryption at rest, WAFs, and password complexity do not fix the underlying insecure query construction.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During a security investigation, an analyst removes a hard drive from a compromised server and documents who handled it, when, and why at each step. What security principle is being demonstrated?","o":["Chain of custody","Least privilege","Separation of duties","Due care"],"c":0,"why":"Chain of custody is the documented, chronological record of evidence handling that preserves its integrity for legal proceedings. Least privilege and separation of duties relate to access control, and due care is a general standard of diligence, not evidence handling.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to identify vulnerabilities in an application's source code before it is compiled and deployed, without executing the program. Which testing technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Penetration testing against the running application","Fuzz testing of the compiled binary"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source code (or bytecode) without execution, making it ideal for early detection of insecure coding patterns. DAST, penetration testing, and fuzzing all require a running application, which contradicts the requirement stated.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During an incident response, the team disconnects an infected workstation from the network to prevent malware from spreading to other systems. Which incident response phase does this action represent?","o":["Eradication","Containment","Lessons learned","Detection"],"c":1,"why":"Containment focuses on limiting the scope and impact of an incident, such as isolating an infected host. Eradication removes the root cause, detection identifies the incident, and lessons learned occurs after resolution.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company requires that any modification to a production server go through documented approval, testing, and a rollback plan before implementation. This process is an example of:","o":["Configuration management","Change management","Patch management","Release management"],"c":1,"why":"Change management governs the structured approval, testing, and documentation of modifications to systems to minimize risk. Configuration management tracks system states, patch management specifically addresses software updates, and release management deals with deploying new software versions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A backup strategy captures all data that has changed since the last full backup, regardless of any incremental backups performed since then. What type of backup is this?","o":["Incremental backup","Differential backup","Full backup","Mirror backup"],"c":1,"why":"A differential backup includes all changes since the last full backup, growing in size until the next full backup. An incremental backup only captures changes since the last backup of any type, and a full backup copies everything.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A database administrator notices that a user with access only to low-classification salary summary reports can repeatedly query the system and, by combining multiple non-sensitive queries, derive an individual employee's exact salary. This is an example of which attack?","o":["Data diddling","Aggregation attack","Buffer overflow","Salami attack"],"c":1,"why":"An aggregation attack occurs when combining multiple pieces of low-sensitivity data allows inference of higher-sensitivity information. Data diddling involves unauthorized data alteration, buffer overflow is a memory corruption issue, and a salami attack involves accumulating small unauthorized gains, none of which match this scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization's incident response team seizes a compromised workstation as evidence. Which of the following actions is MOST critical to maintaining the integrity of the evidence for potential legal proceedings?","o":["Encrypting the hard drive before transport to prevent unauthorized access","Documenting every individual who handles the evidence, along with the date, time, and purpose of access","Storing the evidence in a locked cabinet accessible only to general IT staff","Creating a working copy of the evidence on a shared network drive for team analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation proves the evidence was continuously controlled and unaltered, which is essential for admissibility in court. Encryption addresses confidentiality (not custody tracking), general IT access lacks individual accountability, and placing evidence on a network share risks unauthorized alteration and breaks custody.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization is decommissioning hard drives that contained highly classified data. Which method provides the highest assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive","Physical destruction of the drive","Overwriting the drive once with zeros"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction (e.g., shredding or pulverizing) provides the highest assurance of data unrecoverability, especially for highly classified data. Deletion, reformatting, and single-pass overwrites may leave data recoverable through forensic techniques.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During a project retrospective, the QA team confirms that a newly delivered software module was built exactly according to the approved design specification. However, business stakeholders reject the module because it does not address the organization's current needs, since the specification was based on requirements gathered over a year ago and the business process has since changed significantly. Which software assurance concept does this scenario best illustrate?","o":["The module passed verification but failed validation","The module passed validation but failed verification","The module failed both verification and validation","The module underwent regression testing but skipped unit testing"],"c":0,"why":"Verification answers 'did we build it right?' (conformance to specification), while validation answers 'did we build the right thing?' (meets actual business need). The module conformed to spec (verification passed) but no longer met the real business requirement (validation failed); it did not fail both, and the scenario has nothing to do with regression or unit testing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization has determined that its critical database application has a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 2 hours. Which backup strategy would BEST meet this requirement while balancing storage and processing overhead?","o":["A full backup performed daily at midnight","A weekly full backup with daily differential backups","A weekly full backup combined with continuous transaction log backups every 15 minutes","A snapshot taken once every 6 hours"],"c":2,"why":"Continuous transaction log backups every 15 minutes ensure data loss never exceeds the 2-hour RPO while avoiding the overhead of frequent full backups. Daily backups, daily differentials, and 6-hour snapshots all allow potential data loss exceeding 2 hours.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A legacy C application contains a classic stack-based buffer overflow. A penetration tester overflows a local buffer, overwrites the saved return address, and redirects execution into shellcode that was injected directly onto the stack. Which control would most directly prevent this specific exploitation technique from succeeding, even though the overflow itself still occurs?","o":["Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)","Data Execution Prevention / a non-executable stack (NX)","Stack canary values","Strict input length validation on all user-supplied fields"],"c":1,"why":"A non-executable stack (DEP/NX) prevents the CPU from executing any code located in the stack region, so even after the overflow and return-address overwrite occur, the injected shellcode cannot run. ASLR only makes addresses harder to predict, canaries detect corruption but don't stop execution of code elsewhere, and input validation would have prevented the overflow in the first place but is irrelevant once it has already occurred.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company requires a disaster recovery site that can become operational within 24-48 hours. The site includes partially configured hardware and network connectivity but requires data restoration and final configuration before supporting production workloads. Which type of alternate site does this describe?","o":["Hot site","Warm site","Cold site","Mobile site"],"c":1,"why":"A warm site has partially configured infrastructure requiring data restoration, achieving recovery in 24-48 hours—matching the scenario. A hot site is fully operational within hours, a cold site has only basic facilities requiring far longer setup, and a mobile site is a transportable unit typically used as a temporary alternative rather than this described configuration.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A database administrator who creates new user accounts is prohibited from also granting those accounts elevated permissions; a second administrator must approve and apply permission changes. This control is an example of:","o":["Job rotation","Separation of duties","Mandatory vacation","Dual control"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks between multiple people so no single individual has end-to-end control, reducing fraud and error risk. Dual control requires two people to perform the same action together, job rotation involves periodically changing roles, and mandatory vacation forces time away to detect fraud.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is adopting DevSecOps practices in its CI/CD pipeline. Which practice BEST exemplifies the 'shift-left' security principle?","o":["Running penetration tests only after the application has been deployed to production","Integrating automated static and dependency scanning into the build process before code merges to the main branch","Requiring the security team to manually review all code changes once per quarter","Waiting until user acceptance testing to evaluate application security controls"],"c":1,"why":"Shift-left security means moving security testing earlier in the development process; automating scans during the build/commit stage catches issues before they propagate. The other options delay security validation until much later stages, which contradicts the shift-left principle.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security team wants to detect a SQL injection flaw in a running web application by combining live traffic analysis with instrumentation agents embedded inside the application's runtime environment, without requiring access to the original source code. Which testing approach best fits this requirement?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Manual penetration testing only"],"c":2,"why":"IAST uses in-process instrumentation/agents combined with dynamic execution to observe actual code paths at runtime without needing source code, giving deeper insight than black-box DAST. SAST requires source code, and plain manual penetration testing does not use runtime instrumentation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization applies vendor-released security updates to its operating systems only after testing them in a staging environment to ensure they do not disrupt business applications. This practice is best described as:","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Patch management","Configuration management","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"Patch management involves identifying, testing, and deploying software updates to remediate vulnerabilities while minimizing operational disruption. Vulnerability scanning identifies weaknesses, configuration management tracks system settings, and penetration testing simulates attacks.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During a change management review, a critical security patch must be applied to a production system outside the normal change window due to an active exploit in the wild. Which process BEST describes the correct handling of this situation?","o":["Apply the patch immediately without documentation since it is an emergency","Follow the organization's emergency change process, including post-implementation review and documentation","Wait for the next scheduled Change Advisory Board (CAB) meeting to avoid violating change control","Delegate the decision to the system administrator without further approval or review"],"c":1,"why":"Mature change management includes a defined emergency change process that allows expedited action while still requiring documentation and after-the-fact review, preserving accountability. Skipping documentation, delaying critical patching, or bypassing all oversight each introduces unacceptable risk or control failures.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Which practice provides the strongest assurance of software integrity by ensuring that only approved, tracked changes are incorporated into a production codebase?","o":["Allowing developers to directly edit files on the production server for faster patching","Implementing a software configuration management (SCM) system with version control, change approval, and audit trails","Relying solely on developer code comments to document changes","Disabling logging on the build server to improve deployment speed"],"c":1,"why":"Software configuration management enforces controlled, auditable changes through version control and approval workflows, ensuring integrity and traceability. Direct production edits, relying on comments, and disabling logging all undermine control and accountability.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A database restricts direct access to the Salary field for standard analysts. An analyst instead queries for average salary and headcount by department, finds a department with exactly one employee, and thereby calculates that employee's exact salary from the reported average. This scenario is an example of which type of attack against database security?","o":["Aggregation attack","Inference attack","Polyinstantiation exploitation","SQL injection"],"c":1,"why":"This is an inference attack: the analyst deduces protected data (an individual salary) indirectly through logical/statistical reasoning over authorized query results. Aggregation refers to combining multiple lower-sensitivity data items to reconstruct a higher-sensitivity whole, not deriving a value through statistical math; polyinstantiation and SQL injection are unrelated concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A data center uses a small enclosed space with two interlocking doors, where only one door can be open at a time, to control entry into the server room. This is an example of which physical security control?","o":["Turnstile","Mantrap","Bollard","Security checkpoint"],"c":1,"why":"A mantrap is a small space with two interlocking doors that prevents more than one person from passing through at a time and stops tailgating. A turnstile controls foot traffic flow, a bollard prevents vehicle access, and a security checkpoint is a general inspection point, not this specific double-door design.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is integrating several open-source libraries into its commercial product. Which action provides the BEST way to manage the risk of vulnerable or malicious dependencies over time?","o":["Trusting that open-source projects with many contributors are inherently secure","Generating and maintaining a Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) and continuously monitoring components for known vulnerabilities","Avoiding all documentation of third-party components to reduce audit overhead","Compiling all open-source code once and never updating it after initial release"],"c":1,"why":"An SBOM combined with continuous vulnerability monitoring enables the organization to track dependencies and respond quickly to newly disclosed vulnerabilities, addressing supply-chain risk. The other options ignore ongoing risk management, which is essential given the dynamic nature of vulnerability disclosures.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A CI/CD build pipeline resolves package names against both an organization's private package repository and a public open-source registry. An attacker publishes a package under the same name as an internal, unpublished company package to the public registry with a higher version number. Due to misconfigured resolution order, the build system downloads and executes the attacker's malicious package instead of the internal one. What is this attack known as?","o":["Typosquatting","Dependency confusion","Watering hole attack","Supply chain SQL injection"],"c":1,"why":"Dependency confusion occurs when a build system is tricked into pulling a malicious public package instead of an intended internal package sharing the same name, often by exploiting version resolution logic. Typosquatting relies on similarly named (misspelled) packages, watering hole attacks target victims via compromised sites they visit, and there is no such standard concept as 'supply chain SQL injection.'","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A SOC analyst notices that a SIEM has generated thousands of alerts overnight, the vast majority of which are false positives. Which action would MOST effectively reduce alert fatigue while maintaining detection capability?","o":["Disable logging for the systems generating the most alerts","Tune correlation rules and alert thresholds based on the environment's established baseline behavior","Increase the number of analysts assigned to review alerts each shift","Configure the SIEM to log only critical-severity events going forward"],"c":1,"why":"Tuning correlation rules and thresholds to reflect normal baseline behavior reduces false positives without sacrificing visibility. Disabling logging or filtering out lower-severity events reduces detection capability, and adding more analysts treats the symptom rather than the root cause of poorly tuned rules.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A QA engineer feeds large volumes of malformed, random, or unexpected input into an application's input fields to observe crashes, memory leaks, or unexpected behavior. This testing technique is known as:","o":["Regression testing","Fuzz testing","Boundary value analysis","White-box testing"],"c":1,"why":"Fuzz testing involves feeding malformed or random data to an application to uncover crashes, memory corruption, or unhandled exceptions, often revealing security vulnerabilities. Regression testing verifies existing functionality after changes, boundary value analysis tests edge values of defined ranges, and white-box testing refers to testing with knowledge of internal code structure, none of which describe this scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A privileged setuid utility on a Unix system checks that a target file is owned by the invoking user and is not a symbolic link, then shortly afterward opens that same file path for writing. An attacker exploits the narrow timing window between the check and the open call to swap the file for a symlink pointing to /etc/passwd, allowing unauthorized modification of a protected system file. This vulnerability class is best described as?","o":["Time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","Buffer overflow","Directory traversal","Privilege escalation via SQL injection"],"c":0,"why":"This is a textbook TOCTOU race condition, where a security check and the subsequent use of the resource are separated in time, allowing the resource to be altered in between. There is no memory corruption (ruling out buffer overflow), no path manipulation to escape a directory (ruling out traversal), and no database query involved (ruling out SQL injection).","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization needs to securely dispose of solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained highly sensitive data. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate given the characteristics of SSD storage?","o":["Degaussing the drives","Overwriting the drives with a single pass of zeros","Cryptographic erasure combined with physical destruction","Performing a low-level format on the drives"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use wear-leveling and block remapping, making traditional overwriting unreliable, and they contain no magnetic media, making degaussing ineffective; cryptographic erasure of encrypted data followed by physical destruction reliably renders data unrecoverable. Low-level formatting also fails to guarantee removal of all remapped data blocks.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"Before deploying a critical security patch to production servers, what is the MOST important step in a mature patch management process?","o":["Notify end users of the upcoming change","Test the patch in a representative non-production environment","Schedule the patch deployment during an approved maintenance window","Obtain sign-off from the Change Advisory Board (CAB)"],"c":1,"why":"Testing in a representative environment verifies compatibility and stability, preventing the patch itself from causing outages or breaking dependent systems—the most direct technical risk. User notification, maintenance windows, and CAB approval are important governance and communication steps but do not validate the patch's technical impact.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A mobile banking REST API exposes an endpoint GET /api/accounts/{accountId}/transactions. The API correctly requires a valid authentication token for every request but does not verify that the account referenced by {accountId} actually belongs to the authenticated user, allowing any logged-in user to view another customer's transaction history simply by changing the ID value. This flaw is best classified as?","o":["Broken authentication","Broken object level authorization (Insecure Direct Object Reference)","Mass assignment vulnerability","Server-side request forgery (SSRF)"],"c":1,"why":"Authentication succeeds correctly here; the flaw is the missing authorization check that the requested object (account) belongs to the requesting subject, which is the definition of broken object level authorization / IDOR. Mass assignment involves unintended modification of object properties via unfiltered input fields, and SSRF involves tricking the server into making unintended requests to internal/external resources, neither of which applies here.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A data center houses sensitive electronic equipment and requires a fire suppression system that minimizes damage to hardware while suppressing fire quickly. Which type of system is MOST appropriate?","o":["Wet pipe sprinkler system","Dry pipe sprinkler system","Clean agent (gaseous) suppression system","Foam-based suppression system"],"c":2,"why":"Clean agent systems suppress fire by displacing oxygen or interrupting the combustion reaction without leaving residue or moisture, protecting sensitive electronics. Wet pipe, dry pipe, and foam systems all introduce liquid or residue that can damage electronic equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During contract negotiations for a critical proprietary application, the customer's legal and security teams insist on establishing a software escrow arrangement with an independent third party. What is the PRIMARY security benefit this arrangement provides to the customer?","o":["It guarantees the vendor will fix all future security vulnerabilities within contractual SLAs","It ensures the customer receives ongoing training and documentation updates from the vendor","It provides the customer conditional access to the application's source code if the vendor becomes unable to support the product, ensuring business continuity","It transfers full intellectual property ownership of the source code to the customer immediately upon contract signing"],"c":2,"why":"Software escrow places source code with a neutral third party and releases it to the customer only under defined trigger conditions (e.g., vendor bankruptcy or failure to support), protecting business continuity without altering day-to-day IP ownership. It does not guarantee vulnerability remediation, ongoing training, or immediate transfer of ownership at signing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During incident response on a live, compromised production server, a forensic analyst must collect evidence before the system is shut down. Which sequence correctly reflects the order of volatility, from most volatile (collect first) to least volatile (collect last)?","o":["Disk image, RAM contents, CPU registers/cache, archived log backups","CPU registers/cache, RAM contents and active network connections, local disk storage, archived backups/logs","Archived backups/logs, local disk storage, RAM contents, CPU registers/cache","RAM contents, archived backups/logs, CPU registers/cache, local disk storage"],"c":1,"why":"Forensic best practice (RFC 3227) dictates collecting the most transient data first: CPU registers/cache, then RAM and active network state, then disk, and finally archival/backup media, since each successive item persists longer and is at lower risk of loss. The other options invert or scramble this sequence, risking loss of the most fragile evidence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A software team follows a highly structured, formalized peer review process that includes six defined phases (planning, overview, preparation, inspection meeting, rework, and follow-up), assigns specific roles such as moderator, reader, and recorder, and uses defect checklists to drive the inspection meeting. Which review technique is being described?","o":["Fagan inspection","Structured walkthrough","Pair programming","Ad hoc peer review"],"c":0,"why":"Fagan inspection is the most formal, role-based, multi-phase code review methodology with defined entry/exit criteria and metrics. Walkthroughs are informal and author-led, pair programming is a continuous development practice rather than a discrete review, and ad hoc review lacks structure entirely.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A critical order-processing system has a documented Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 8 hours. The disaster recovery team has validated that systems can be technically restored (RTO) within 5 hours. Assuming the MTD formula MTD = RTO + WRT, what is the maximum allowable Work Recovery Time (WRT) to remain within the MTD?","o":["8 hours","5 hours","3 hours","13 hours"],"c":2,"why":"MTD equals RTO plus WRT (the time needed after systems are restored to verify data, reconfigure applications, and resume business functions). Since MTD is 8 hours and RTO consumes 5 hours, only 3 hours remain for WRT; exceeding this breaches the MTD. The other values either ignore the RTO already consumed or exceed the total MTD.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is evaluating exploit mitigation techniques for a legacy C application vulnerable to return-oriented programming (ROP) attacks, in which the attacker chains together existing executable code fragments already present in memory to bypass non-executable memory protections. Without modifying the application's source code, which control most directly disrupts this attack by making the locations of these code fragments unpredictable?","o":["Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)","Data Execution Prevention (DEP/NX)","Stack canaries","Strict input length validation"],"c":0,"why":"ROP attacks reuse existing executable code, so DEP/NX (which blocks execution of injected code in data segments) does not stop them; ASLR randomizes memory addresses, making it far harder for attackers to locate the gadgets needed to build a ROP chain. Stack canaries detect overflow of the current frame but don't prevent gadget reuse, and input validation requires source changes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A zero-day vulnerability is being actively exploited against a production application. The security team wants to deploy an emergency patch immediately, bypassing the normal change advisory board (CAB) schedule. Which action best reflects proper emergency change management practice?","o":["Apply the patch immediately with no documentation since the urgency justifies skipping process","Follow the organization's emergency change procedure: obtain expedited approval, document the change and rollback plan, implement it, and present it to the CAB for retroactive review","Wait for the next regularly scheduled CAB meeting before making any change, regardless of active exploitation","Deploy the patch directly to production without testing or a rollback plan since time is critical"],"c":1,"why":"Emergency change processes exist precisely for situations like active exploitation: they allow expedited approval and implementation while still requiring documentation, a rollback plan, and after-the-fact CAB review to maintain accountability and traceability. Skipping documentation, delaying indefinitely, or omitting testing/rollback planning all violate sound change management principles and increase risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization's software process is documented, standardized across all projects, and tailored consistently from an organization-wide standard process, but the organization has not yet established quantitative process performance baselines or statistical process control. According to the CMMI staged representation, which maturity level best describes this organization?","o":["Level 2 – Managed","Level 3 – Defined","Level 4 – Quantitatively Managed","Level 5 – Optimizing"],"c":1,"why":"Level 3 (Defined) is characterized by organization-wide standardized processes tailored per project, without yet using quantitative metrics for control, which is the hallmark of Level 4. Level 2 processes are managed at the project level but not standardized organization-wide, and Level 5 involves continuous process optimization based on quantitative feedback.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday night and a differential backup every other night of the week. The production server fails on Thursday morning before that night's backup runs. What is the minimum number of backup sets required to fully restore the system, and why?","o":["Four sets: the full backup plus the Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday differential backups, applied in order","Two sets: the full backup and only the most recent (Wednesday night) differential backup","One set: only the most recent differential backup, since differentials are self-contained","Seven sets: the full backup plus every differential backup made since the last full backup"],"c":1,"why":"A differential backup captures all changes since the last full backup, so restoration only requires the full backup plus the single most recent differential. This differs from incremental backups, which require the full backup plus every incremental in sequence. Restoring only a differential without the full backup, or applying multiple differentials sequentially, is unnecessary and reflects incremental (not differential) restore logic.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security team needs to test a web application that is already deployed in a staging environment. They do not have access to the source code but want to simulate an external attacker sending crafted HTTP requests to identify vulnerabilities such as SQL injection and reflected XSS in the running application. Which testing approach is most appropriate?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)"],"c":0,"why":"DAST is black-box testing performed against a running application without source code access, closely simulating external attacker behavior. SAST analyzes source/binary code directly, IAST requires runtime agents instrumented into the application (needing deployment access beyond black-box), and SCA identifies vulnerable third-party components rather than testing application logic.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A SOC detects an advanced persistent threat actor slowly exfiltrating data from a segmented internal network. Leadership wants to preserve evidence, understand the attacker's techniques, and avoid tipping off the adversary, while still limiting further damage. Which containment strategy is most appropriate?","o":["Immediately power off all affected hosts to stop the exfiltration as fast as possible","Isolate the affected network segment using controlled monitoring (e.g., a contained environment or network taps) to observe attacker behavior while restricting further outbound access","Take no containment action until the investigation is fully complete to avoid altering the environment","Notify the attacker's ISP immediately and wait for their response before taking any internal action"],"c":1,"why":"Controlled isolation with monitoring allows the organization to limit damage while preserving volatile evidence and gathering threat intelligence on attacker TTPs, which is standard practice for sophisticated intrusions. Immediately powering off systems destroys volatile memory evidence, taking no action allows continued data loss, and relying on an ISP is not a containment control within the organization's authority.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"In a multilevel secure database, a user cleared to the Secret level submits a query for a record that actually exists at the Top Secret classification level under the same primary key. To prevent the user from inferring the existence of the more sensitive record while still returning a plausible response appropriate to their clearance, the DBMS maintains multiple versions of the same record at different classification levels. What is this technique called?","o":["Polyinstantiation","Data aggregation","Inference attack mitigation via views","Content-dependent access control"],"c":0,"why":"Polyinstantiation is the deliberate creation of multiple record instances at different classification levels to prevent lower-cleared users from detecting higher-classified data. Aggregation refers to combining lower-sensitivity data to derive sensitive conclusions, and while views and content-dependent access control are related database security concepts, neither specifically describes maintaining multiple record versions to defeat inference.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A database server requires fault tolerance guaranteeing continued operation even if any two arbitrary disks in the array fail simultaneously. Which RAID level provides this guarantee?","o":["RAID 5, using single parity distributed across all disks","RAID 6, using dual distributed parity across all disks","RAID 10, using mirrored and striped disk pairs","RAID 0, using striping without parity or mirroring"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 6 uses dual parity, so it can tolerate the failure of any two disks in the array without data loss, regardless of which two fail. RAID 5 tolerates only a single disk failure; RAID 10 can survive two failures only if they are not both drives within the same mirrored pair, making it not a guaranteed protection; RAID 0 offers no fault tolerance at all.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A DevSecOps team wants to guarantee that build artifacts produced by their CI/CD pipeline cannot be tampered with as they pass through multiple automated stages (build, test, package, deploy) before reaching production, even if one intermediate stage is compromised. Which control provides the strongest assurance of artifact integrity across the entire pipeline?","o":["Cryptographically signing artifacts immediately after each verified build stage and validating signatures before each subsequent stage","Encrypting all artifacts at rest within the artifact repository","Applying role-based access control to restrict who can trigger pipeline stages","Requiring mandatory peer code review before merging to the main branch"],"c":0,"why":"Digital signatures with signature verification at each stage boundary provide cryptographic proof that an artifact has not been altered since it was signed, directly addressing tampering across pipeline stages. Encryption protects confidentiality but not integrity, RBAC reduces unauthorized access but doesn't detect tampering by an already-authorized compromised stage, and code review addresses source-level quality, not artifact integrity after the build process.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) should security requirements first be formally defined and documented?","o":["Requirements analysis","Testing","Deployment","Maintenance"],"c":0,"why":"Security requirements must be identified early, during requirements analysis, so they can be designed and built into the system from the start. Defining them during testing, deployment, or maintenance means security was not integrated into the design, leading to costly rework.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A web application accepts user-uploaded XML documents for processing. An attacker submits a crafted XML file that defines an external entity referencing a local system file path; when the parser resolves the entity, the contents of the local file are embedded into the application's response. Which vulnerability class does this attack exploit?","o":["XML External Entity (XXE) injection","Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)","XPath injection","Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)"],"c":0,"why":"XXE injection occurs when an XML parser processes attacker-defined external entities, allowing disclosure of local files or internal resources, exactly as described. SSRF involves the server being tricked into making unintended network requests (not specifically via XML entity parsing), XPath injection manipulates XPath query logic, and CSRF forces an authenticated user's browser to perform unwanted actions, none of which match this scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application accepts user-supplied text and directly incorporates it into a database query without any filtering. Which secure coding practice would BEST prevent an SQL injection attack in this scenario?","o":["Enforcing strong password complexity rules","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Encrypting the database at rest","Increasing the application's session timeout"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate SQL code from user input, preventing attackers from altering query logic. Password policy, encryption at rest, and session timeout do not address the root cause of injection vulnerabilities, which is unsanitized input concatenated into queries.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A company licenses a business-critical application from a small independent software vendor. To mitigate the risk of the vendor going out of business or discontinuing support, the licensing agreement requires the vendor to deposit the current source code, build environment configuration, and technical documentation with an independent third party, to be released to the licensee only if specific contractual trigger conditions occur. What is this arrangement called?","o":["Software escrow agreement","Service level agreement (SLA)","End-user license agreement (EULA) amendment","Business continuity plan (BCP) annex"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow agreement specifically addresses depositing source code and related materials with a neutral third party, released to the licensee upon defined trigger events such as vendor insolvency. An SLA defines service performance metrics, a EULA amendment modifies usage rights, and a BCP annex addresses organizational continuity planning, none of which describe the source code deposit mechanism.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During a forensic investigation, an administrator discovers a compromised server. Which action should be performed FIRST to preserve the integrity of evidence before any further analysis?","o":["Take a cryptographic hash of the volatile memory and disk images before analysis","Copy the log files to a USB drive for offline review","Power down the server immediately to prevent further compromise","Restore the server from the most recent backup to compare differences"],"c":0,"why":"Hashing captures a verifiable baseline of evidence integrity before any handling occurs, supporting chain of custody. Powering down loses volatile memory evidence, restoring from backup destroys the crime scene, and copying files without hashing first risks unverifiable evidence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization's incident response team has identified an active ransomware infection spreading across the network. Which action best represents the 'containment' phase of incident response?","o":["Isolating infected systems from the network to prevent further spread","Conducting a root cause analysis to determine the initial attack vector","Restoring affected systems from clean backups","Notifying regulatory bodies of the breach within required timelines"],"c":0,"why":"Containment focuses on limiting the scope and impact of an incident, such as network isolation. Root cause analysis is part of the identification/lessons-learned phase, restoration is recovery, and notification is a legal/compliance step, not containment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of using a version control (source code management) system during software development?","o":["To automatically encrypt all source code files","To track changes to code and allow rollback to previous versions","To replace the need for code review","To perform automated penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"Version control systems track history of changes, support collaboration, and allow reverting to earlier code states if a defect or vulnerability is introduced. They do not encrypt code, eliminate the need for review, or perform security testing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company wants a RAID configuration that provides fault tolerance against a single disk failure while maximizing usable storage efficiency, using at least four disks. Which RAID level BEST meets this requirement?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 10"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 5 uses distributed parity across disks, tolerating a single disk failure while using storage more efficiently than mirroring (RAID 1/10). RAID 0 offers no fault tolerance, and RAID 10 sacrifices more capacity for mirroring.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that no unauthorized modifications are made to production application code and that all changes are documented and approved. Which process BEST addresses this need?","o":["Risk assessment","Change management","Business impact analysis","Vulnerability scanning"],"c":1,"why":"Change management establishes formal procedures for requesting, reviewing, approving, and documenting changes to systems, ensuring accountability and reducing unauthorized modifications. Risk assessment, BIA, and vulnerability scanning serve different purposes and do not control the change approval process.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of a formal change management process in security operations?","o":["To ensure all changes are documented, tested, and approved before implementation to minimize unintended security impacts","To guarantee that only the IT help desk can make configuration changes","To eliminate the need for vulnerability scanning after updates","To reduce the frequency of software patching across the enterprise"],"c":0,"why":"Change management ensures changes are reviewed, tested, and approved to prevent unauthorized or disruptive modifications that could introduce vulnerabilities. It does not restrict all changes to help desk staff, eliminate scanning needs, or reduce patch frequency.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A programmer writes code that copies user input into a fixed-size memory array without checking the input length. This coding flaw could most likely lead to which type of vulnerability?","o":["Cross-site request forgery","Buffer overflow","Broken authentication","Insecure direct object reference"],"c":1,"why":"Failing to validate input length before copying it into a fixed-size buffer is the classic cause of a buffer overflow, potentially allowing memory corruption or code execution. The other options relate to different vulnerability classes not tied to unchecked memory copy operations.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday and an incremental backup every other day of the week. If a server fails on Thursday, how many backup sets must be restored to recover all data?","o":["Only the full backup from Sunday","The full backup plus all incremental backups from Monday through Wednesday","Only Wednesday's incremental backup","The full backup plus only Wednesday's incremental backup"],"c":1,"why":"Incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup (full or incremental), so all incremental sets since the last full backup must be restored in sequence along with the full backup. Restoring only the full backup or a single incremental would miss data changed on other days.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A development team wants to prevent SQL injection attacks in a web application that queries a relational database using user-supplied input. Which technique provides the STRONGEST protection against this vulnerability?","o":["Encoding all output displayed to the user","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements) with bound variables","Validating input length against a maximum character limit","Storing the database credentials in an encrypted configuration file"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate SQL code from data, ensuring user input is never interpreted as executable SQL, which directly addresses the root cause of injection. Output encoding prevents XSS, not SQLi; length limits alone don't stop malicious syntax; and credential encryption protects storage, not query construction.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"In a database security context, an attacker who is denied direct access to sensitive salary data instead queries the database using indirect, permitted queries and deduces the salary values from the results. This is an example of which attack?","o":["Aggregation","Inference","SQL injection","Buffer overflow"],"c":1,"why":"Inference occurs when a user deduces restricted information from data they are authorized to access, without directly querying the protected field. Aggregation involves combining multiple non-sensitive pieces to derive a sensitive whole, which is a related but distinct concept, and the other options are unrelated attack types.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of a software escrow agreement in a vendor relationship?","o":["It ensures the vendor's source code is available to the customer if the vendor goes out of business or fails to support the product","It guarantees the software will be free of all defects","It provides automatic patching of the software by a third party","It transfers all intellectual property rights to the customer"],"c":0,"why":"Software escrow protects the customer's business continuity by placing source code with a trusted third party, releasable under specified conditions like vendor bankruptcy. It does not guarantee defect-free code, provide patching services, or transfer IP ownership.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company's Business Continuity Plan states that the maximum acceptable amount of data loss for a critical database is 15 minutes. Which metric does this represent?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Service Delivery Objective (SDO)"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable data loss measured in time, dictating backup frequency. RTO refers to acceptable downtime before restoration, MTD is the total time a business function can be unavailable, and SDO relates to acceptable service levels during recovery, not data loss.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"During a secure code review, an assessor uses a tool that examines the application's source code without executing it, identifying potential vulnerabilities such as insecure API calls and hardcoded secrets. This is an example of which testing method?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source or binary code without execution to find flaws like hardcoded credentials. DAST tests a running application from the outside, fuzzing sends malformed input to a running program, and penetration testing simulates real-world attacks against a live system.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst configures a SIEM to correlate failed login attempts across multiple systems within a short time window and generate an alert. This capability is an example of which security operations function?","o":["Log rotation","Event correlation and analysis","Data loss prevention","Configuration baselining"],"c":1,"why":"Correlating multiple related events across systems to detect patterns like brute-force attacks is event correlation, a core SIEM function. Log rotation manages storage, DLP prevents data exfiltration, and configuration baselining defines secure system states, none of which involve cross-system event analysis.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is evaluating its software development processes against a framework that defines five progressive levels, from ad hoc practices to continuously optimized processes, to improve process maturity and predictability. Which model is being used?","o":["Capability Maturity Model Integration (CMMI)","Software Assurance Maturity Model (SAMM)","Waterfall methodology","ISO/IEC 27001"],"c":0,"why":"CMMI defines five maturity levels (Initial, Managed, Defined, Quantitatively Managed, Optimizing) to assess and improve organizational process maturity. SAMM focuses specifically on software security practices rather than general process maturity, Waterfall is a development lifecycle model, and ISO/IEC 27001 is an information security management standard.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"When designing fire suppression for a data center housing sensitive electronic equipment, which type of system is generally preferred to minimize damage to hardware while effectively suppressing fire?","o":["Wet pipe water sprinkler system","Clean agent gaseous suppression system","Dry chemical powder extinguishing system","Foam-based suppression system"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agent systems (e.g., FM-200, inert gases) suppress fire without leaving residue or conductive moisture, protecting sensitive electronics. Water, foam, and dry chemical systems can damage equipment through moisture, residue, or corrosion.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Two transactions attempt to update the same bank account balance simultaneously in a relational database. Without proper controls, one transaction could overwrite the other's update, causing an incorrect final balance. Which database property or mechanism is specifically designed to prevent this issue?","o":["Referential integrity","Database normalization","Locking (concurrency control)","Data dictionary enforcement"],"c":2,"why":"Locking mechanisms (e.g., row-level or table-level locks) enforce the isolation property of ACID transactions, preventing concurrent transactions from corrupting shared data. Referential integrity ensures valid foreign key relationships, normalization reduces redundancy, and a data dictionary documents schema metadata—none directly address concurrent update conflicts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A developer creates a base class called Shape with a method named calculateArea(). Subclasses such as Circle and Square each implement their own version of calculateArea() that behaves differently based on the object type, while the calling code invokes the method the same way regardless of the actual subclass. Which object-oriented concept does this describe?","o":["Encapsulation","Inheritance","Polymorphism","Abstraction"],"c":2,"why":"Polymorphism allows objects of different classes to respond differently to the same method call, as shown by each subclass implementing calculateArea() uniquely. Inheritance describes the subclass relationship itself, encapsulation refers to hiding internal state, and abstraction refers to simplifying complex reality into models—neither directly describes this varying method behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization is developing its incident response plan. Which of the following best represents the correct order of the standard incident response process?","o":["Detection, Response, Mitigation, Reporting, Recovery, Remediation, Lessons Learned","Preparation, Detection and Analysis, Containment, Eradication, Recovery, Lessons Learned","Containment, Eradication, Detection, Recovery, Reporting, Lessons Learned","Preparation, Containment, Detection, Eradication, Recovery, Reporting"],"c":1,"why":"The widely accepted incident response lifecycle is Preparation, Detection and Analysis, Containment, Eradication, Recovery, and Lessons Learned (post-incident activity). The other options reorder or omit key steps, which would leave gaps in the response process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A software vendor is providing a critical business application to a client but refuses to give the client direct access to the source code. The client is concerned about long-term supportability if the vendor goes out of business. Which arrangement BEST addresses this risk?","o":["Requiring the vendor to sign a non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","Establishing a software escrow agreement with a neutral third party","Purchasing an extended warranty on the software license","Implementing a service level agreement (SLA) with uptime guarantees"],"c":1,"why":"A software escrow agreement places source code with a trusted third party who will release it to the client under specified conditions (e.g., vendor bankruptcy), directly mitigating the supportability risk. An NDA protects confidentiality, a warranty covers defects, and an SLA addresses service performance—none guarantee access to source code if the vendor disappears.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A digital forensic investigator seizes a hard drive from a compromised server. Which practice is MOST important to ensure the evidence remains admissible in court?","o":["Encrypting the drive immediately after seizure","Maintaining a documented chain of custody from collection through analysis","Copying files directly onto the investigator's laptop for review","Allowing only senior management to handle the evidence"],"c":1,"why":"A properly documented chain of custody proves the evidence was handled and preserved without tampering, which is essential for admissibility. Encryption, informal copying, or restricting access to management do not address integrity and accountability of evidence handling.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a DevSecOps pipeline in which automated security testing tools scan code for vulnerabilities immediately after each code commit, before the build proceeds to the next stage. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this approach compared to testing only before production release?","o":["It eliminates the need for manual code reviews entirely","It ensures vulnerabilities are identified and remediated earlier when they are less costly to fix","It guarantees zero-day vulnerabilities will be detected before exploitation","It removes the need for a separate quality assurance testing phase"],"c":1,"why":"Shifting security testing earlier in the pipeline (\"shifting left\") allows vulnerabilities to be caught and fixed while code changes are small and context is fresh, significantly reducing remediation cost and effort. It does not eliminate manual review, guarantee detection of unknown zero-days, or replace QA testing, which serves different functional purposes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of implementing a Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system in security operations?","o":["To automatically patch vulnerable systems across the network","To centralize and correlate log data from multiple sources for real-time monitoring and analysis","To encrypt sensitive data at rest and in transit","To enforce role-based access control on production servers"],"c":1,"why":"A SIEM aggregates and correlates logs from various systems to detect anomalies and support incident detection and analysis. Patching, encryption, and access control are handled by other dedicated tools, not the SIEM's core function.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A legacy application written in C is found to be vulnerable to attacks where an attacker sends input longer than the allocated memory space for a variable, potentially allowing arbitrary code execution. Which secure development practice would MOST effectively prevent this class of vulnerability in future code?","o":["Implementing strict input length validation and using safe string-handling functions with bounds checking","Enabling verbose error logging for all input validation failures","Encrypting all data in transit between the client and server","Applying the principle of least privilege to the application's service account"],"c":0,"why":"Buffer overflows result from writing data beyond allocated memory boundaries; using bounds-checked functions and validating input length directly prevents this. Logging failures aids detection but not prevention, encryption protects data confidentiality in transit, and least privilege limits impact but does not stop the overflow from occurring.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Why is patch management considered a critical security operations activity?","o":["It ensures all users have the same software version for licensing purposes","It reduces the risk of exploitation by addressing known vulnerabilities in software and systems","It automatically generates security awareness training content","It replaces the need for a formal change management process"],"c":1,"why":"Patch management remediates known vulnerabilities before they can be exploited, reducing organizational risk. Licensing consistency and awareness training are unrelated benefits, and patching still requires change management, not a replacement for it.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before a change to a production firewall configuration can be implemented, an organization requires it to go through a Change Advisory Board (CAB). What is the PRIMARY benefit of this requirement?","o":["It guarantees the change will not cause any downtime","It ensures changes are reviewed for risk, impact, and business justification before implementation","It eliminates the need for rollback plans","It allows a single administrator to bypass testing requirements"],"c":1,"why":"A CAB reviews proposed changes to assess risk, business impact, and justification, helping prevent unauthorized or poorly planned changes. It does not guarantee zero downtime, eliminate rollback planning, or allow bypassing controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A forensic first responder arrives at a compromised server that is still powered on and connected to the network. Following RFC 3227 guidance on order of volatility, which item should be captured FIRST?","o":["Contents of RAM","CPU registers and processor cache","The current network connection/routing table","Temporary files stored on the local disk"],"c":1,"why":"CPU registers and cache are the most volatile data on a live system and are lost within nanoseconds if not captured immediately; RAM, network state tables, and temp files are progressively less volatile and can be captured afterward.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday and an incremental backup every other day of the week. If a system fails on Thursday, which backups are needed to fully restore the system?","o":["Only Thursday's incremental backup","Sunday's full backup and Thursday's incremental backup only","Sunday's full backup and all incremental backups from Monday through Wednesday","Only Sunday's full backup"],"c":2,"why":"Incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup (full or incremental), so restoring requires the last full backup plus every incremental backup made since then, in sequence. Skipping intermediate incrementals or relying on a single backup would result in data loss.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A Business Impact Analysis establishes a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 24 hours for a critical order-processing system. The disaster recovery plan specifies a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 16 hours to bring the system back online and a Work Recovery Time (WRT) of 6 hours to validate data integrity and resume normal processing. Based on this plan, what is the total downtime and does it satisfy the MTD requirement?","o":["16 hours total; it satisfies the MTD","22 hours total; it satisfies the MTD","22 hours total; it exceeds the MTD and must be revised","30 hours total; it exceeds the MTD and must be revised"],"c":1,"why":"Total downtime equals RTO plus WRT (16+6=22 hours), which is within the 24-hour MTD, so the plan is acceptable. The other options either miscalculate the sum or incorrectly conclude the MTD is violated.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization is decommissioning several solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained highly sensitive data. Which method is MOST appropriate for ensuring the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Degaussing the drives","Performing a single-pass quick format","Physical destruction (e.g., shredding or disintegration) of the drives","Deleting all files and emptying the recycle bin"],"c":2,"why":"Because SSDs use flash memory and wear-leveling, degaussing (effective only on magnetic media) and simple deletion or formatting do not reliably sanitize data; physical destruction is the recommended method for ensuring unrecoverable data on SSDs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization is redesigning its secure SDLC and wants to maximize the cost-effectiveness of vulnerability remediation. Research shows that defects found and fixed early are dramatically cheaper to correct than those found after deployment. Which practice provides the greatest return by identifying design-level security flaws before any code is written?","o":["Performing static application security testing (SAST) on the first code commit","Conducting threat modeling during the requirements and design phase","Running dynamic application security testing (DAST) against a staging environment","Performing a penetration test immediately before production release"],"c":1,"why":"Threat modeling during design identifies architectural flaws (e.g., missing authentication boundaries) before code exists, when remediation is cheapest. SAST, DAST, and pre-release pen testing all occur after code is written, so they find and fix flaws later and at higher cost.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A storage architect must select a RAID configuration for a database cluster that must remain fully operational even if any two disks fail simultaneously, without relying on a specific mirrored pair relationship. Which RAID level BEST meets this requirement?","o":["RAID 5","RAID 6","RAID 10","RAID 0+1"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 6 uses dual distributed parity, guaranteeing survival of ANY two simultaneous disk failures. RAID 5 tolerates only one failure, and RAID 10/0+1 can only guarantee survival of two failures if they occur in different mirrored pairs, not any arbitrary two disks.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company requires that the employee who initiates a wire transfer request cannot be the same person who approves it. This control is an example of which security operations principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by a single individual. Least privilege limits access rights, job rotation shifts personnel between roles over time, and mandatory vacation forces time away to help detect fraud, none of which describe splitting transaction initiation from approval.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A hospital database allows clinical staff to query patient age ranges and separately query diagnosis codes, neither of which is individually classified as sensitive. However, an analyst discovers that by combining multiple authorized queries, they can reliably identify a specific patient's diagnosis. This is an example of which security issue, and what is the most effective countermeasure?","o":["SQL injection; use parameterized queries to prevent the combination of statements","An aggregation attack; implement context- and content-dependent access controls that restrict combinable query results","A covert channel; implement mandatory access control labels on all database rows","A race condition; enforce atomic transactions on all read queries"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining multiple low-sensitivity data elements produces a higher-sensitivity result; the fix is controlling query combinations (e.g., limiting result set correlation), not injection defenses, MAC labeling alone, or transaction atomicity, which address unrelated problems.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During an internal investigation, a digital forensic examiner creates a bit-for-bit image of a suspect's hard drive, generates a cryptographic hash of both the original and the image, and stores the original drive in a locked evidence room. Two days later, it is discovered that a manager accessed the evidence room alone and unsupervised, without signing the evidence log. What is the MOST significant consequence of this event?","o":["The hash values are automatically invalidated and must be regenerated","The chain of custody has been broken, potentially making the evidence inadmissible","The evidence remains valid as long as the working copy hash matches the original","No impact occurs since the manager did not alter the drive"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody requires an unbroken, documented record of who accessed evidence and when; unsupervised, undocumented access creates reasonable doubt about tampering regardless of whether the hash later matches, undermining admissibility. Hash values would only change if the data itself were altered, not merely by unauthorized access.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A privileged utility checks whether a file is owned by the invoking user and then, in a separate subsequent operation, opens that file with elevated privileges. A local attacker exploits the timing gap between the check and the open to substitute a symbolic link pointing to a sensitive system file. What vulnerability class does this describe?","o":["Integer overflow leading to privilege escalation","Time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","Buffer overflow via unchecked input length","Improper input validation resulting in path traversal"],"c":1,"why":"TOCTOU race conditions exploit the gap between validating a resource's state and acting on it, exactly as described here. Buffer overflow, integer overflow, and path traversal involve different mechanisms (memory corruption or unsanitized path input), not a timing gap between check and use.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A critical zero-day vulnerability is actively being exploited in the wild, and the vendor has released an emergency patch. The normal change advisory board (CAB) does not meet for another five days. According to change management best practices, what is the MOST appropriate course of action?","o":["Apply the patch immediately without any documentation since time is critical","Wait for the next scheduled CAB meeting to maintain process integrity","Invoke the emergency change process: test if feasible, apply the patch, document the change, and obtain retroactive CAB approval","Deny the patch until a full regression test cycle is completed, regardless of exploitation risk"],"c":2,"why":"Mature change management processes include an emergency/expedited change path that allows rapid remediation of active threats while still requiring documentation and after-the-fact governance review. Skipping documentation entirely or waiting for a scheduled meeting both leave the organization exposed or non-compliant with change control principles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security team wants to test a web application using an approach that instruments the running application with an agent, observes actual code execution paths as test cases run, and correlates runtime behavior with source code locations to pinpoint vulnerabilities with fewer false positives than pure black-box testing. Which testing methodology is being described?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing with random input generation","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)"],"c":2,"why":"IAST uses instrumentation/agents inside the running application to map observed runtime behavior back to source code, reducing false positives versus black-box DAST or pure fuzzing. SAST analyzes source code without execution, and DAST tests externally without code-level visibility.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a set of solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained highly sensitive data. Which sanitization approach is MOST appropriate given the characteristics of flash-based storage?","o":["Degaussing the drives to eliminate residual magnetic fields","A single-pass overwrite using a standard disk-wipe utility designed for HDDs","Cryptographic erase of the drive's encryption keys, followed by physical destruction if required by policy","Performing a full-format operation through the operating system"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory with wear-leveling, making traditional overwrite techniques unreliable since data may reside in reallocated blocks inaccessible to standard wipe tools; degaussing is ineffective because SSDs are not magnetic media. NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase and/or physical destruction for reliable SSD sanitization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An API endpoint GET /api/invoices/{invoiceId} returns invoice details after validating that the requester holds a valid session token. A tester with a legitimate low-privilege account changes {invoiceId} to a sequential number belonging to another customer and successfully retrieves that customer's invoice, even though authentication succeeded normally. What is the underlying vulnerability?","o":["Broken authentication due to weak session token generation","Broken object level authorization (BOLA), also known as an insecure direct object reference","Cross-site request forgery (CSRF) allowing unauthorized state changes","Server-side request forgery (SSRF) exposing internal resources"],"c":1,"why":"The API correctly authenticates the user but fails to verify the authenticated user is authorized to access that specific object, the hallmark of BOLA/IDOR. Authentication itself isn't broken, no forged request is being made by another user's browser (ruling out CSRF), and no internal server request is being triggered (ruling out SSRF).","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday night and a differential backup every other night of the week. On Thursday morning, the primary storage array fails and all data must be restored from backup, with the most recent available backup being Wednesday night's differential. How many backup sets must be restored, and in what order, to recover the data?","o":["Only Wednesday night's differential backup, since it contains all changes","The full Sunday backup followed by Wednesday night's differential backup","The full Sunday backup followed by every differential backup from Monday through Wednesday, in sequence","Monday's, Tuesday's, and Wednesday's differential backups only, without the full backup"],"c":1,"why":"Differential backups always capture all changes since the LAST FULL backup, so only the full backup plus the most recent differential are needed for restoration. This is a key distinction from incremental backups, which would require restoring the full backup plus every incremental in sequence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application allows users to enter search terms that are directly concatenated into SQL queries. Which of the following controls BEST prevents SQL injection attacks against this application?","o":["Using parameterized queries (prepared statements) to separate SQL code from user input","Increasing the session timeout value for authenticated users","Enabling verbose error messages to assist with debugging","Storing user passwords in plaintext for faster database lookups"],"c":0,"why":"Parameterized queries ensure user input is treated strictly as data, not executable code, which directly prevents SQL injection. Session timeouts, verbose errors, and plaintext passwords are unrelated or actively harmful security practices.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A software vendor wants to ensure that build artifacts distributed to customers have not been tampered with between the build server and the customer's deployment pipeline, and that customers can cryptographically verify the artifact originated from the vendor. Which control best achieves this?","o":["Storing build artifacts in a version control system with commit history","Applying a cryptographic digital signature to each release artifact, verified before deployment","Encrypting the artifact with a symmetric key shared out-of-band with customers","Publishing a SHA-1 hash of the artifact alongside the download link"],"c":1,"why":"Digital signing binds the artifact to the vendor's private key, providing both integrity verification and authenticity of origin when verified against the vendor's public key. Version control history doesn't protect distributed artifacts, symmetric encryption provides confidentiality but not authenticated origin, and a published hash alone (especially weak SHA-1) only detects accidental corruption, not deliberate substitution by an attacker who can also alter the published hash.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) should security requirements first be defined to minimize overall cost and risk?","o":["Requirements/analysis phase","Deployment phase","Maintenance phase","Disposal phase"],"c":0,"why":"Defining security requirements early, during requirements/analysis, is far less costly than retrofitting security later; addressing security only at deployment, maintenance, or disposal significantly increases cost and risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A legacy application allocates a memory block for a session object containing a user's cleartext credentials, then frees the block without zeroing its contents when the session ends. A subsequent process on the same system allocates memory and, due to allocator behavior, receives the same physical memory region, exposing the previous user's credentials. What secure coding principle was violated?","o":["Least privilege, because the process should not have had memory access rights","Object reuse protection, requiring memory to be sanitized before reallocation","Fail-secure design, requiring the application to halt on any memory allocation error","Defense in depth, requiring multiple independent memory protection layers"],"c":1,"why":"Object reuse controls require that memory (or storage) be cleared before being reassigned to a new subject/process to prevent residual data disclosure; failing to zero the freed block is a direct violation. Least privilege concerns access rights (not memory scrubbing), fail-secure concerns error handling, and defense in depth is a general layered strategy, not the specific control that was missing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes a buffer overflow vulnerability?","o":["Writing data beyond the boundaries of allocated memory, potentially overwriting adjacent memory","Encrypting sensitive data using a deprecated cryptographic algorithm","Failing to properly validate a user's authentication credentials","Using an outdated version of the TLS protocol for data in transit"],"c":0,"why":"A buffer overflow occurs when a program writes more data to a buffer than it can hold, corrupting adjacent memory and potentially allowing code execution. The other options describe unrelated cryptographic or authentication issues.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During an active malware outbreak, a security analyst confirms that a worm is spreading laterally across the internal network. According to standard incident response methodology, what should be the analyst's IMMEDIATE priority?","o":["Isolate affected systems from the network to stop further spread","Perform a full forensic disk image of every infected host","Notify law enforcement and regulatory bodies","Restore infected systems from the most recent backup"],"c":0,"why":"Containment (isolating affected systems) must occur immediately to stop the spread before eradication, recovery, or detailed forensics/notification, which happen in later phases.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A development team's CI/CD pipeline automatically pulls open-source packages by name from a public package registry during every build. An attacker publishes a malicious package to the public registry using the exact same name as an internal private package the company uses, and the build system pulls the attacker's version instead, executing malicious code during the build. What attack technique is this, and what is the best mitigation?","o":["Typosquatting; train developers to carefully check package names before installation","Dependency confusion; configure the package manager to prioritize a private registry and use scoped package names or hash pinning","Cross-site scripting; sanitize all output rendered in the build logs","Man-in-the-middle attack; enforce TLS for all registry connections"],"c":1,"why":"Dependency confusion exploits ambiguity between internal and public package namespaces with identical names; the fix is registry prioritization, scoping, and integrity pinning (e.g., hash/lockfile verification), not TLS (which doesn't prevent pulling the wrong legitimate-looking package), XSS mitigation (irrelevant to build dependencies), or relying solely on manual name-checking, which doesn't scale and doesn't address the root namespace collision.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which type of security testing examines an application's source code or binary for vulnerabilities WITHOUT executing the program?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Penetration testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":0,"why":"SAST analyzes code at rest (source or binary) without execution. DAST, penetration testing, and fuzzing all require the application to be running to identify vulnerabilities.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is redesigning its software development lifecycle to reduce the cost of fixing security defects. At which phase should security requirements first be formally defined and incorporated into the project?","o":["During the requirements/analysis phase, before design begins","During unit testing, once code modules are complete","During user acceptance testing, prior to production release","During the maintenance phase, after the first patch cycle"],"c":0,"why":"Security requirements should be identified as early as possible (requirements/analysis phase) because defects found later in the lifecycle are exponentially more costly to fix; the other phases occur too late to prevent design flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An investigator collecting a compromised laptop for a legal case documents every person who handled the device, along with dates, times, and the purpose of each transfer. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this practice?","o":["To ensure the evidence is encrypted during transport","To establish and preserve the chain of custody so the evidence remains admissible in court","To satisfy backup and retention requirements for the organization","To ensure only law enforcement personnel are permitted to examine the device"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation proves the integrity and handling history of evidence, which is essential for admissibility; encryption and backup are unrelated goals, and non-law-enforcement personnel (e.g., forensic examiners) routinely and legitimately handle evidence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Why is it considered a security best practice to maintain separate development, test, and production environments?","o":["To prevent untested code and unauthorized access from affecting live production systems and data","To allow developers unrestricted administrative access to production servers","To eliminate the need for formal change management approval","To speed up deployments by bypassing security testing"],"c":0,"why":"Separating environments protects production data and systems from untested changes and reduces the risk of unauthorized access. The other options describe practices that increase, not decrease, security risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application accepts user input directly into SQL query strings, making it vulnerable to injection attacks. Which remediation provides the strongest protection against SQL injection?","o":["Encrypting the database connection string","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements) with bound variables","Implementing a web application firewall in blocking mode only","Increasing the length limit on input fields"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing attacker-supplied input from being interpreted as SQL commands. Encryption, WAFs, and field length limits are supplementary controls but do not eliminate the injection vulnerability at its root.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A backup administrator implements a strategy where only files that have changed since the LAST backup of any type (full or incremental) are backed up each night. A full restore therefore requires the last full backup plus every incremental backup taken since. Which backup type is being described?","o":["Incremental backup","Differential backup","Full backup","Snapshot backup"],"c":0,"why":"Incremental backups capture changes since the last backup of any kind, requiring the full backup plus all subsequent incrementals for restore; differential backups only require the full plus the latest differential, and full/snapshot backups don't fit this restore chain description.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to identify vulnerabilities in an application's source code before it is compiled and deployed, without executing the program. Which testing approach best meets this need?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing against a running instance","Penetration testing of the production environment"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source or binary code without execution, making it suitable for pre-deployment code review. DAST, fuzzing, and penetration testing all require a running application and are therefore performed later in the lifecycle.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A business continuity plan states that after a disruption, the organization can tolerate losing at most 15 minutes of transaction data, while systems must be restored to operation within 4 hours. Which metric defines the 15-minute value?","o":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Work Recovery Time (WRT)"],"c":0,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, whereas RTO defines how quickly systems must be restored; MTD and WRT relate to overall downtime tolerance and post-restoration recovery activities, not data loss.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"In object-oriented programming, which principle enhances security by restricting direct access to an object's internal data and exposing only defined interfaces (methods)?","o":["Encapsulation","Polymorphism","Inheritance","Multithreading"],"c":0,"why":"Encapsulation hides internal object state and only allows interaction through controlled methods, reducing the attack surface. Polymorphism and inheritance relate to code reuse and behavior, not access restriction; multithreading concerns concurrent execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A database administrator notices that a user with access only to individual, low-sensitivity fields in a table is able to combine multiple authorized queries to deduce classified information not directly accessible to them. This is an example of which database security issue?","o":["Aggregation","SQL injection","Polyinstantiation","Data remanence"],"c":0,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining multiple pieces of non-sensitive data results in access to sensitive information. Inference is similar but involves deducing information logically rather than combining query results directly; SQL injection, polyinstantiation, and data remanence describe unrelated concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A critical zero-day vulnerability requires a patch to be applied to production servers outside the normal change management cycle. The security team applies the patch immediately to prevent exploitation. What should occur NEXT to align with sound change management practice?","o":["Submit the change for formal emergency-change documentation and retroactive review by the Change Advisory Board","Skip documentation since the change was made under emergency conditions","Wait for the next scheduled Change Advisory Board meeting before applying any further changes","Permanently bypass change management for all future security patches"],"c":0,"why":"Emergency changes should still be documented and reviewed retroactively to maintain accountability and process integrity; skipping documentation or abandoning change management entirely undermines governance, and delaying critical patching for a scheduled CAB meeting would leave the organization exposed.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A development team wants to ensure that changes to source code are tracked, that unauthorized modifications are prevented, and that previous versions can be restored if needed. Which practice best supports these goals?","o":["Code obfuscation","Software configuration management with a version control system","Static analysis integrated into the IDE","Runtime application self-protection (RASP)"],"c":1,"why":"Software configuration management, implemented through version control systems, tracks changes, enforces access controls on code repositories, and allows rollback to prior versions. Obfuscation, static analysis, and RASP address different security concerns unrelated to change tracking and rollback.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"When incorporating third-party open-source libraries into a software product, which of the following is the MOST important security practice?","o":["Regularly scanning for known vulnerabilities and tracking library versions","Assuming the code is secure because it has been publicly reviewed","Disabling all logging generated by third-party components","Avoiding review of library documentation to speed up development"],"c":0,"why":"Open-source components can contain known vulnerabilities that must be actively tracked and patched; assuming inherent security, disabling logging, or skipping documentation review all increase risk rather than mitigate it.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization deploys a SIEM to aggregate logs from firewalls, servers, and endpoint agents into a single platform. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this centralized approach?","o":["It enables correlation of events across multiple systems to detect patterns indicative of an attack","It removes the need to maintain logging on individual host systems","It automatically guarantees compliance with all applicable regulations","It eliminates the need for a log retention policy"],"c":0,"why":"Centralized logging's key value is correlating events across disparate sources to identify multi-stage attacks; it does not eliminate the need for host-level logging, guarantee compliance, or remove retention requirements.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization exposes a REST API to external partners for retrieving customer records. Which control is MOST important for preventing unauthorized parties from accessing another customer's data through the API?","o":["Rate limiting on API calls","Object-level authorization checks on every request","TLS encryption for all API traffic","API versioning to deprecate older endpoints"],"c":1,"why":"Broken object-level authorization (BOLA) is a leading API vulnerability; without per-request authorization checks tied to the requesting user's permissions, an authenticated user could access another user's records by manipulating identifiers. Rate limiting, TLS, and versioning address availability, confidentiality-in-transit, and lifecycle management, but not access control to specific objects.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A user without direct access to classified salary data is able to determine an individual's salary range by combining several pieces of unclassified data he does have access to. This is an example of which database security issue?","o":["Polyinstantiation","Aggregation","Normalization","Referential integrity"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining multiple low-sensitivity data elements reveals higher-sensitivity information. Polyinstantiation involves creating multiple versions of data at different classification levels, while normalization and referential integrity relate to database design, not confidentiality breaches.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to prevent unauthorized individuals from following an authorized employee into a secure data center (piggybacking/tailgating). Which physical control BEST addresses this specific risk?","o":["A mantrap with interlocking doors that admits only one person at a time","A badge reader mounted at the entrance","Closed-circuit television (CCTV) monitoring the entrance","A security guard posted at the main lobby desk"],"c":0,"why":"A mantrap physically enforces single-person entry, directly preventing piggybacking; badge readers and CCTV can be defeated by someone following an authorized person through an open door, and a lobby guard provides deterrence but not a reliable physical barrier.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A legacy C application does not perform bounds checking when copying user-supplied input into a fixed-size stack buffer. Which vulnerability class does this weakness represent?","o":["Cross-site request forgery","Race condition (TOCTOU)","Buffer overflow","Insecure deserialization"],"c":2,"why":"Failing to validate the length of input before copying it into a fixed-size buffer is the classic cause of buffer overflow vulnerabilities, potentially allowing memory corruption or code execution. CSRF, TOCTOU races, and deserialization flaws involve different mechanisms unrelated to buffer bounds.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"Before deploying a critical security patch to production database servers, what is the BEST first step for the operations team to take?","o":["Test the patch in a non-production environment to validate compatibility and stability","Deploy the patch immediately to all production servers to minimize exposure time","Wait until the next scheduled quarterly maintenance window regardless of the vulnerability's severity","Disable the rollback plan to simplify and speed up the deployment process"],"c":0,"why":"Testing in a non-production environment first reduces the risk of the patch causing outages or compatibility issues in production; deploying untested patches immediately, delaying critical patches unnecessarily, or removing rollback options all increase operational risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization implementing a CI/CD pipeline wants to prevent vulnerable open-source components from being introduced into production builds. Which control should be integrated directly into the automated pipeline?","o":["Annual manual code review by the security team","Software composition analysis (SCA) scanning during the build stage","Post-deployment penetration testing only","Requiring developers to sign a secure coding policy acknowledgment"],"c":1,"why":"Software composition analysis tools automatically scan dependencies for known vulnerabilities and license issues as part of the automated build, catching problems before deployment. Annual reviews, post-deployment testing, and policy acknowledgments are not integrated, continuous controls within the pipeline itself.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that evidence collected from a compromised server can be used in legal proceedings. Which concept ensures that the evidence has not been altered from the time it was collected until it is presented in court?","o":["Chain of custody","Due diligence","Separation of duties","Least privilege"],"c":0,"why":"Chain of custody documents who handled evidence, when, and how, proving its integrity for legal admissibility. Due diligence relates to reasonable care, separation of duties prevents fraud, and least privilege limits access rights—none address evidence integrity tracking.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which backup type copies only the files that have changed since the last full backup, and does NOT reset the archive bit, resulting in cumulative growth over time?","o":["Full backup","Differential backup","Incremental backup","Mirror backup"],"c":1,"why":"A differential backup captures all changes since the last full backup and does not clear the archive bit, so each differential grows larger over time. Incremental backups reset the archive bit and only capture changes since the last backup of any type; full backups copy everything; mirror backups are exact real-time copies.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A security analyst notices that a critical patch was applied directly to a production server without testing or documentation. Which security operations process was most likely bypassed?","o":["Configuration management","Change management","Vulnerability management","Asset management"],"c":1,"why":"Change management ensures that modifications to systems—including patches—are reviewed, tested, approved, and documented before implementation. Configuration management tracks baseline settings, vulnerability management identifies weaknesses, and asset management tracks inventory, none of which specifically govern the approval process for changes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the primary purpose of a Recovery Time Objective (RTO)?","o":["The maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time","The maximum tolerable length of time a system can be down after a disruption","The minimum staffing level required during a disaster","The total cost of downtime for a critical business function"],"c":1,"why":"RTO defines the maximum acceptable downtime before a system or process must be restored to avoid unacceptable business impact. Data loss tolerance is defined by the Recovery Point Objective (RPO), not RTO; the other options describe unrelated metrics.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements a security operations center (SOC) practice where multiple log sources—firewalls, IDS, servers—are aggregated into a single platform for correlation and alerting. What is this platform commonly called?","o":["Intrusion Prevention System (IPS)","Security Information and Event Management (SIEM)","Data Loss Prevention (DLP)","Network Access Control (NAC)"],"c":1,"why":"A SIEM aggregates and correlates log data from multiple sources to detect and alert on security events. An IPS blocks malicious traffic, DLP prevents data exfiltration, and NAC controls device access to the network—none perform centralized log correlation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which physical security control is specifically designed to prevent a vehicle from ramming through a facility's perimeter at high speed?","o":["Bollards","Turnstiles","Mantrap","Security guard post"],"c":0,"why":"Bollards are sturdy, short vertical posts installed to block vehicle access while allowing pedestrian movement. Turnstiles and mantraps control pedestrian flow, and a guard post alone does not physically stop a vehicle.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During a disaster recovery test, an organization fully shuts down its primary site and executes complete failover operations at the backup site, including real transactions. Which type of DR test is this?","o":["Tabletop exercise","Walkthrough test","Simulation test","Full interruption test"],"c":3,"why":"A full interruption test involves completely shutting down the primary site and switching all operations to the backup site, the most realistic and highest-risk test type. Tabletop and walkthrough tests are discussion-based, and simulation tests mimic a disaster without an actual shutdown of production systems.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application accepts user input directly into a SQL query string without any sanitization, allowing an attacker to alter the query's logic. Which control is MOST effective at preventing this type of attack?","o":["Enabling verbose error messages for debugging","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Increasing database connection timeout values","Encrypting the database at rest"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate SQL code from data, preventing attacker-supplied input from being interpreted as executable SQL commands. Verbose errors, timeout settings, and encryption at rest do not address the root cause of SQL injection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A security team reviews an application's source code line-by-line using an automated tool, without executing the program, to identify potential vulnerabilities. Which testing technique is being used?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Penetration testing","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing"],"c":2,"why":"SAST analyzes source or binary code without execution, making it ideal for early-stage code review. DAST, fuzzing, and penetration testing all involve executing or interacting with a running application.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An administrator configures a system so that critical patches are automatically tested in a staging environment before being deployed to production servers. This practice primarily supports which security operations goal?","o":["Reducing the risk of system instability from untested updates","Eliminating the need for a change management process","Ensuring compliance with data retention policies","Preventing unauthorized physical access to servers"],"c":0,"why":"Testing patches in staging before production deployment reduces the risk that an update will cause outages or conflicts in the live environment. It does not eliminate change management (rather it supports it), and it is unrelated to data retention or physical access controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An attacker injects a malicious script into a comment field of a website, which then executes in the browsers of other users who view that page. What type of vulnerability is this?","o":["Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)","Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)","SQL injection","Buffer overflow"],"c":0,"why":"XSS occurs when untrusted input is rendered by a victim's browser as executable script, exactly as described. CSRF tricks a user's browser into making unwanted requests, SQL injection targets databases, and buffer overflow is a memory-based flaw, none of which match this scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"During which phase of the software development lifecycle should security requirements first be formally documented alongside functional requirements?","o":["Requirements analysis","Coding/implementation","Unit testing","Deployment"],"c":0,"why":"Security requirements must be captured during requirements analysis so they are treated as first-class requirements and drive design decisions; addressing security only during coding, testing, or deployment leads to costly rework and gaps because architectural choices are already fixed.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A programmer writes a function that copies user-supplied input into a fixed-size memory buffer without checking the input length. What vulnerability does this MOST likely introduce?","o":["Race condition","Buffer overflow","Cross-site request forgery","Insecure deserialization"],"c":1,"why":"Failing to validate input length before copying it into a fixed-size buffer is the classic cause of a buffer overflow, which can corrupt memory and potentially allow code execution. The other options involve unrelated flaw types not caused by unchecked buffer copy operations.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application accepts user input directly into SQL statements without validation, allowing an attacker to manipulate query logic. Which control BEST mitigates this vulnerability?","o":["Implementing a Web Application Firewall in blocking mode only","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Encrypting the database at rest","Increasing the length limit on input fields"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing user input from altering SQL query structure, which directly addresses SQL injection. A WAF can help detect attacks but is not a substitute for secure coding, encryption at rest doesn't stop injection, and field length limits don't prevent malicious syntax.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization licensing critical third-party software wants assurance that it can access the vendor's source code if the vendor goes out of business. Which arrangement BEST addresses this concern?","o":["Software escrow agreement","Service level agreement (SLA)","Non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","Business associate agreement (BAA)"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow agreement places source code with a neutral third party who releases it to the licensee under specified conditions, such as vendor bankruptcy. SLAs address performance metrics, NDAs protect confidential information, and BAAs apply to HIPAA-covered relationships — none provide source code access guarantees.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During an active incident response, a security analyst discovers that a compromised web server is actively exfiltrating customer data to an external IP address. The incident response team has already identified the affected system and gathered initial evidence. What should the team do NEXT, before removing the malware and restoring the system?","o":["Contain the affected system by isolating it from the network","Notify all customers whose data may have been exposed","Rebuild the server from a known-good backup image","Perform root cause analysis to determine the initial attack vector"],"c":0,"why":"Containment must occur before eradication and recovery to stop ongoing damage (data exfiltration); notification, rebuilding, and root cause analysis are later phases of the incident response lifecycle that should follow containment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to analyze an application's source code for vulnerabilities before the application is compiled and executed. Which testing methodology should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Fuzz testing","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Penetration testing"],"c":2,"why":"SAST examines source or byte code without executing the program, making it suitable for pre-compilation analysis. DAST and penetration testing require a running application, and fuzzing sends malformed input to a running program rather than analyzing source code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of a formal change management process in software development?","o":["To increase the speed of code deployment regardless of risk","To ensure changes are reviewed, approved, tested, and documented before implementation","To eliminate the need for version control systems","To grant developers unrestricted access to production systems"],"c":1,"why":"Change management ensures changes are properly evaluated, authorized, tested, and tracked to reduce risk of unintended impact. It does not aim to bypass controls, remove version control, or grant unrestricted access, which would increase risk rather than manage it.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A forensic investigator is collecting evidence from a live, running server suspected of being compromised. According to the order of volatility, which piece of evidence should be collected FIRST?","o":["Contents of RAM and running processes","Data on the local hard drive","Log files stored on a remote syslog server","Backup tapes stored in an offsite vault"],"c":0,"why":"The order of volatility dictates that the most transient data—such as RAM contents and running processes—be collected first, as it is lost when the system is powered off; disk data, remote logs, and offsite backups are comparatively more persistent.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which secure design principle is BEST demonstrated when a database application account is granted only the specific permissions needed to read and write to a single table, rather than full administrative rights?","o":["Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Least privilege","Security through obscurity"],"c":2,"why":"Least privilege means granting only the minimum access necessary to perform a required function, exactly as described. Separation of duties involves dividing tasks among multiple people, defense in depth layers multiple controls, and security through obscurity relies on secrecy of design rather than access restriction.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization's business impact analysis determines that a critical order-processing application can tolerate at most 4 hours of downtime and no more than 30 minutes of data loss. Which pair of metrics does this describe, respectively?","o":["RTO of 4 hours; RPO of 30 minutes","MTD of 4 hours; MTTR of 30 minutes","RPO of 4 hours; RTO of 30 minutes","WRT of 4 hours; RTO of 30 minutes"],"c":0,"why":"Recovery Time Objective (RTO) is the maximum acceptable downtime, and Recovery Point Objective (RPO) is the maximum acceptable data loss measured in time; the other option orderings reverse or misapply these definitions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A backup administrator wants to minimize both the storage space required for daily backups and the restore time in the event of a failure. The current strategy uses a full backup every Sunday and incremental backups Monday through Saturday. What is a key disadvantage of this incremental approach compared to a differential strategy?","o":["Restoring requires the full backup plus every incremental backup since the last full backup, increasing restore time","Incremental backups require significantly more storage than differential backups","Incremental backups cannot be automated or scheduled","Incremental backups reset the archive bit on all files regardless of whether they changed"],"c":0,"why":"Incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup (full or incremental), so restoration requires applying the full backup plus every subsequent incremental in sequence, lengthening restore time; differential backups only require the full plus the latest differential, and incrementals actually use less storage than differentials over time.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A change management process requires that all production changes be approved by a Change Control Board (CCB) before implementation. A developer needs to deploy an emergency security patch to fix an actively exploited zero-day vulnerability, and there is no time to convene the full CCB. What is the BEST course of action?","o":["Follow the organization's documented emergency change procedure, then present the change to the CCB for retroactive review","Deploy the patch without any approval since the vulnerability is actively being exploited","Wait until the next scheduled CCB meeting to obtain proper approval before deploying","Deploy the patch and document it as a standard change in the next change log"],"c":0,"why":"Mature change management processes include an emergency change procedure that allows expedited deployment with abbreviated approval, followed by formal retroactive review; bypassing approval entirely, delaying critical patching, or mislabeling it as routine all violate proper change control governance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During an active security incident, a forensic analyst arrives at a compromised production server that cannot be taken offline immediately. Following the standard order of volatility for live evidence collection, which sequence should the analyst use to capture evidence?","o":["Disk image, RAM dump, CPU cache/registers, network connection state","CPU cache/registers, RAM contents, network connection state (ARP/routing tables), disk data","Network connection state, disk data, RAM contents, CPU cache/registers","RAM contents, disk data, CPU cache/registers, network connection state"],"c":1,"why":"The order of volatility principle requires collecting the most transient data first—CPU registers/cache, then RAM, then network state, then disk—because volatile data is lost quickly or during shutdown, while disk data persists longest.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A software vendor's internal audit finds that each project team follows written development procedures, but the specific practices, templates, and quality metrics differ significantly from team to team, and no organization-wide process performance data is collected. According to the Capability Maturity Model Integration (CMMI), this organization is best characterized as operating at which maturity level?","o":["Level 2 - Managed","Level 3 - Defined","Level 4 - Quantitatively Managed","Level 1 - Initial"],"c":0,"why":"Level 2 (Managed) means basic project-level processes exist and are followed, but they are not yet standardized across the organization, which explains the inconsistency between teams. Level 3 (Defined) requires an organization-wide standard process tailored consistently by all projects, and Level 4 requires quantitative process metrics, neither of which exist here; Level 1 implies no defined process at all, which contradicts the written procedures described.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization is decommissioning a set of solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained highly sensitive government data. Which media sanitization method is MOST appropriate for ensuring the data is unrecoverable on this type of storage media?","o":["Cryptographic erase combined with vendor-specified secure erase commands, followed by physical destruction","Degaussing the drives using a strong magnetic field","Overwriting the drives once with a single pass of zeros","Reformatting the drives using the operating system's quick format utility"],"c":0,"why":"SSDs use flash memory and wear-leveling, making magnetic degaussing ineffective and simple overwriting unreliable since data may reside in reallocated blocks; NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase/vendor secure erase with physical destruction for high-sensitivity data on SSDs, while quick format does not remove underlying data at all.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A ransomware variant is propagating laterally across multiple network segments via SMB. The incident response team has confirmed the infection but has not yet completed forensic imaging of affected hosts. Which action best balances containment with evidence preservation?","o":["Immediately power off all infected hosts to stop the spread","Isolate the affected network segments via VLAN/firewall rules while keeping infected hosts powered on for live analysis","Wait until forensic images of every infected host are completed before taking any containment action","Deploy an updated antivirus signature enterprise-wide and monitor for further spread before isolating"],"c":1,"why":"Network-level isolation halts propagation while preserving volatile memory evidence on running hosts; powering off destroys RAM evidence, delaying containment allows continued spread, and signatures alone don't stop lateral movement already underway.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A storage administrator configures a RAID array using four disks, striping data with parity distributed across all disks, allowing the array to survive the failure of any single disk without data loss. Which RAID level is being described?","o":["RAID 5","RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 10"],"c":0,"why":"RAID 5 uses striping with distributed parity across all disks, tolerating a single disk failure; RAID 0 offers no redundancy, RAID 1 uses mirroring rather than parity striping, and RAID 10 combines mirroring and striping but is described differently than parity-based fault tolerance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A penetration test reveals that a web application builds SQL statements by directly concatenating user-supplied form data into query strings, allowing attackers to alter query logic. Which remediation provides the strongest and most reliable mitigation against this class of vulnerability?","o":["Enforcing strict maximum input length limits on all form fields","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements) that separate code from data","Adding client-side JavaScript validation to reject suspicious characters","Blacklisting known dangerous characters such as apostrophes and semicolons"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries structurally separate SQL code from user data so injected input can never alter query logic, addressing the root cause. Length limits, client-side validation, and blacklisting are all bypassable and do not prevent the underlying mixing of code and data.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A trading platform's RPO is defined as 1 hour. Backups run every 4 hours at 00:00, 04:00, 08:00, 12:00, 16:00, and 20:00. A database server fails at 14:30. Based on this scenario, what is the data-loss exposure and RPO compliance status?","o":["30 minutes of data at risk; RPO met","2.5 hours of data at risk; RPO not met","4 hours of data at risk; RPO met","1 hour of data at risk; RPO not met"],"c":1,"why":"The last successful backup occurred at 12:00; failure at 14:30 means 2.5 hours of unbacked-up data exists, exceeding the 1-hour RPO threshold, so the RPO is violated.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security tester repeatedly submits large volumes of malformed, random, and boundary-violating input to an application's network interface without any access to or knowledge of its source code, monitoring the application for crashes, hangs, or memory corruption. This testing technique is best described as:","o":["Black-box fuzz testing","White-box static code analysis","Mutation testing of unit test suites","Structural statement coverage testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing feeds unexpected or malformed input to a target and observes behavior; performing this without knowledge of internal code is the defining characteristic of black-box fuzzing. Static analysis examines source code, mutation testing evaluates test suite quality by altering code, and coverage testing measures which code paths execute during testing—none match the described black-box, input-driven approach.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company wants to validate its disaster recovery plan without disrupting live production systems or incurring significant cost, while still actively exercising the recovery procedures and communication flow among team members. Which disaster recovery test type BEST meets this objective?","o":["Simulation test","Full interruption test","Parallel test","Checklist review"],"c":0,"why":"A simulation test walks the team through a realistic disaster scenario and exercises response procedures and communication without actually failing over production systems, balancing thoroughness with low risk and cost; a full interruption test disrupts live operations, a parallel test requires standing up actual recovery systems at higher cost, and a checklist review is passive and does not actively exercise procedures.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A zero-day vulnerability actively being exploited in the wild requires an out-of-cycle patch on a production system. The organization's normal change management process requires a two-week CAB review cycle. Which approach best reflects mature change management practice?","o":["Bypass change management entirely since the risk of exploitation outweighs process concerns","Apply the patch through an expedited emergency change process, with abbreviated testing, documented risk acceptance, and retroactive CAB review","Delay the patch until the next scheduled CAB meeting to maintain process integrity","Apply the patch silently without notifying stakeholders to avoid delays"],"c":1,"why":"Emergency change procedures allow rapid remediation of critical risk while preserving documentation, approval, and after-the-fact review; skipping process entirely or delaying to a formal CAB both introduce unacceptable exposure or process failure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A user has legitimate access to a department's total budget figures and to the department's headcount figures, but not to individual salary data. By correlating these two authorized data sets over several reporting periods, the user is able to closely estimate an individual employee's salary. This scenario best illustrates which database security concern?","o":["Inference attack","Aggregation attack","Polyinstantiation","Data remanence"],"c":0,"why":"An inference attack occurs when a user deduces restricted information by correlating multiple pieces of data they are authorized to access, exactly as described. Aggregation involves combining many individually low-sensitivity records of the same type to reveal a collectively sensitive whole, which is a different mechanism; polyinstantiation and data remanence are unrelated concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that any change to production source code can be traced to a specific approved request, with the ability to roll back to a known-good version if a defect is introduced. Which practice BEST supports this goal?","o":["Code obfuscation","Software configuration management with version control","Just-in-time compilation","Static code analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Software configuration management (including version control, baselining, and change tracking) provides traceability of changes and rollback capability. Obfuscation protects intellectual property, JIT compilation is a runtime optimization, and static analysis finds vulnerabilities but doesn't manage change history.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A SOC's SIEM generates hundreds of alerts daily for a correlation rule matching failed login attempts followed by a successful login within 5 minutes. Analysis shows 95% of these alerts are legitimate users who mistyped their passwords. What is the best action to improve detection efficacy?","o":["Disable the correlation rule since it generates excessive noise","Increase the failed-login threshold and add contextual conditions (e.g., geolocation anomaly, off-hours access) to the rule","Instruct analysts to ignore alerts matching this rule","Hire additional analysts to review every alert manually without changing rule logic"],"c":1,"why":"Tuning the rule with additional context reduces false positives while preserving genuine brute-force/account-compromise detection; disabling or ignoring the rule creates blind spots, and adding staff without tuning fails to address the root cause.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A development organization heavily relies on third-party open-source libraries across its product portfolio. To effectively manage the ongoing risk of newly disclosed vulnerabilities in these components throughout the software lifecycle, which practice is MOST effective?","o":["Maintaining a Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) and continuously monitoring components against vulnerability feeds","Requiring developers to manually re-review all open-source source code before each release","Blocking all outbound internet access from development environments","Running static analysis tools only against the organization's proprietary code"],"c":0,"why":"An SBOM combined with continuous monitoring provides visibility into exactly which components and versions are in use, enabling rapid identification and remediation when new CVEs are disclosed. Manual code review of all open-source code is impractical at scale, blocking internet access does not address vulnerability tracking, and analyzing only proprietary code ignores third-party component risk entirely.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security assessment of a CI/CD pipeline finds that database credentials used by automated deployment scripts are stored in plaintext within the pipeline's configuration repository, accessible to all developers with repo access. Which remediation BEST addresses this finding while preserving deployment automation?","o":["Integrate a secrets management/vault solution that injects credentials at runtime","Require a developer to manually type credentials during each deployment","Move the credentials into environment variables defined in the same repository","Encrypt the entire repository using a key shared among all developers"],"c":0,"why":"A secrets management/vault solution stores credentials securely and injects them dynamically at deploy time, eliminating plaintext exposure while keeping the pipeline fully automated. Manual entry breaks automation; environment variables in the same repo and repository-wide encryption with a shared key still expose the secret to anyone with repository or key access.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of SSDs that contained sensitive financial records. Due to wear-leveling and over-provisioning, standard multi-pass overwrite techniques cannot reliably sanitize all data blocks. Per NIST SP 800-88 guidance, which approach is most appropriate?","o":["Perform a single-pass zero-fill overwrite using standard disk utilities","Use cryptographic erase (if data was encrypted) or physically destroy the drives; overwrite alone is not a reliable Purge method for SSDs","Perform a low-level format using the operating system's disk management tool","Degauss the SSDs using a standard magnetic degausser"],"c":1,"why":"NIST SP 800-88 notes overwriting is unreliable on flash media due to wear-leveling; cryptographic erase or physical destruction are the recommended Purge/Destroy methods, whereas degaussing is ineffective on non-magnetic SSDs and a single overwrite/format may miss remapped blocks.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday at midnight and an incremental backup every night, Monday through Saturday. A file server fails on Friday afternoon; the most recent successful backup was Thursday night's incremental. To fully restore the server, which backup sets must be applied, and in what order?","o":["Only Thursday night's incremental backup","The Sunday full backup, followed sequentially by the Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday incremental backups","The Sunday full backup only","The Sunday full backup and the Thursday incremental backup only, skipping Monday through Wednesday"],"c":1,"why":"Incremental backups capture only changes since the last backup of any type, so full restoration requires the full backup plus every incremental in sequence; omitting intermediate incrementals or restoring only the latest one would leave out changed data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A researcher exploits a stack-based buffer overflow by overwriting a function's return address to redirect execution into attacker-supplied shellcode placed on the stack. Which operating system control is SPECIFICALLY designed to prevent the CPU from executing code located in non-executable memory regions such as the stack?","o":["Data Execution Prevention (DEP) / NX bit","Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)","Stack canaries","Control Flow Guard (CFG)"],"c":0,"why":"DEP/NX marks memory regions like the stack as non-executable, directly blocking execution of injected shellcode regardless of where it resides. ASLR randomizes memory addresses to make exploitation harder but doesn't prevent execution once an address is found; stack canaries detect overflow corruption before return but don't block execution of code elsewhere; CFG restricts indirect control-flow transfers rather than marking memory non-executable.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A mobile application uses a third-party REST API to retrieve user account data. Which mechanism provides the BEST way to ensure the API only grants access to resources the authenticated user has explicitly authorized, without sharing the user's credentials with the mobile app?","o":["Basic authentication over HTTPS","OAuth 2.0 authorization framework","Storing the user's password in the app's local keychain","IP address whitelisting"],"c":1,"why":"OAuth 2.0 allows delegated, scoped access via tokens without the client app ever handling the user's actual credentials. Basic auth and storing passwords require credential sharing/storage, and IP whitelisting does not address per-user authorization at all.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A storage engineer configures RAID 6 across eight 2TB disks in an array. Which statement correctly describes the resulting fault tolerance and usable capacity?","o":["The array tolerates failure of any two disks simultaneously and provides approximately 12TB of usable capacity","The array tolerates failure of any one disk and provides approximately 14TB of usable capacity","The array tolerates failure of any two disks simultaneously and provides approximately 16TB of usable capacity","The array tolerates failure of any three disks simultaneously and provides approximately 10TB of usable capacity"],"c":0,"why":"RAID 6 uses dual distributed parity, tolerating two simultaneous disk failures, and reserves two disks' worth of capacity for parity: (8-2) × 2TB = 12TB usable; the other options misstate the fault tolerance level or miscalculate usable capacity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization adopts a DevSecOps model and wants to identify vulnerabilities as early as possible in a continuous integration/continuous delivery (CI/CD) pipeline. Which practice BEST reflects the 'shift left' security principle?","o":["Running a full penetration test only after production deployment","Integrating automated SAST/SCA scans into the build pipeline before code merges","Performing an annual third-party security audit","Waiting until user acceptance testing to review security requirements"],"c":1,"why":"Shift left means moving security testing earlier in the pipeline, so integrating automated static analysis and software composition analysis at build/commit time catches issues before they progress further. The other options push detection later in the lifecycle, contradicting the shift-left principle.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During a Common Criteria evaluation of a multilevel secure system, evaluators discover that a high-security-level process can intentionally modulate its CPU utilization in a detectable pattern, allowing a low-security-level process monitoring system performance counters to receive signaled information despite no formal data path existing between the two levels. This is best classified as a:","o":["Covert channel","Side-channel attack on cryptographic keys","Time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","Object reuse vulnerability"],"c":0,"why":"A covert channel is an unintended communication path that allows information to flow between security levels in violation of policy by exploiting a shared resource like CPU timing, exactly as described. Side-channel attacks typically target leakage of cryptographic secrets through physical characteristics, TOCTOU involves a race between validation and use of a resource, and object reuse concerns residual data in reallocated memory—none match this intentional cross-level signaling scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A software vendor wants to give customers visibility into all open-source and third-party components embedded in a delivered application, including their versions, to support vulnerability management. Which artifact should the vendor provide?","o":["A digital signature of the compiled binary","A Software Bill of Materials (SBOM)","A code coverage report","A non-disclosure agreement"],"c":1,"why":"An SBOM is a formal, machine-readable inventory of all components and dependencies used in software, enabling customers to track known vulnerabilities in third-party/open-source code. A digital signature verifies binary integrity but lists no components, code coverage measures test thoroughness, and an NDA is a legal document unrelated to component inventory.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During an incident response process, which of the following activities occurs FIRST after a potential security incident is suspected?","o":["Eradication of the root cause","Detection and identification of the event","Recovery of affected systems","Lessons learned review"],"c":1,"why":"The incident response lifecycle begins with detection and identification to confirm an event has occurred; eradication, recovery, and lessons learned all follow only after the incident has been properly identified and contained.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization seizes a laptop as part of an internal investigation. Which practice is MOST important to ensure the evidence remains admissible in legal proceedings?","o":["Encrypting the hard drive before analysis","Maintaining a documented chain of custody","Running antivirus scans on the evidence","Restoring the laptop to its original owner quickly"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation proves who handled evidence and when, preserving its integrity and admissibility; encryption, antivirus scans, or returning the device do not establish evidentiary integrity and could alter the evidence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which RAID level provides fault tolerance by writing identical copies of data to two separate disks simultaneously?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 6"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 1 (mirroring) duplicates data across two disks for redundancy. RAID 0 offers no fault tolerance (striping only), while RAID 5 and 6 use parity across multiple disks rather than full mirroring.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company performs a full backup every Sunday and wants to minimize daily backup time while accepting longer restore times. Which backup strategy BEST meets this goal?","o":["Daily differential backups","Daily incremental backups","Daily full backups","Continuous data protection"],"c":1,"why":"Incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup (full or incremental), making daily backups fastest, though restoration requires applying multiple incremental sets sequentially. Differential backups grow larger each day, and daily full backups take the most time.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A system administrator is granted access only to the specific servers and functions required for their job duties, and nothing more. This is an example of which security principle?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege","Defense in depth","Job rotation"],"c":1,"why":"Least privilege restricts access rights to the minimum necessary to perform job functions. Separation of duties divides tasks among multiple people, defense in depth layers controls, and job rotation moves personnel between roles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A programmer writes code that copies user-supplied data into a fixed-size memory buffer without checking the length of the input. What type of vulnerability does this create?","o":["Race condition","Buffer overflow","Cross-site request forgery","Insecure direct object reference"],"c":1,"why":"Failing to validate the length of input before copying it into a fixed-size buffer is the classic cause of a buffer overflow, which can corrupt memory and potentially allow code execution. The other options involve different mechanisms unrelated to buffer size handling.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"To reduce the risk of fraud, an organization requires that the employee who initiates a purchase order cannot also approve the payment for that order. This control is an example of which concept?","o":["Least privilege","Mandatory vacation","Separation of duties","Dual control"],"c":2,"why":"Separation of duties splits critical tasks between different individuals to prevent a single person from committing and concealing fraud. Least privilege limits access levels, mandatory vacation forces time off to detect fraud, and dual control requires two people to jointly perform one action rather than dividing sequential steps.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An attacker enters ' OR '1'='1 into a web application's login field and successfully bypasses authentication. Which security control would have MOST effectively prevented this outcome?","o":["Strong password hashing","Parameterized queries/input validation","Network firewall rules","Full disk encryption"],"c":1,"why":"This is a classic SQL injection attack; using parameterized queries and validating input prevents user data from being interpreted as SQL commands. Password hashing, firewalls, and disk encryption do not address injection flaws in application logic.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which document is PRIMARILY concerned with restoring critical business functions at an alternate location after a disruptive event, as opposed to restoring IT systems specifically?","o":["Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)","Business Continuity Plan (BCP)","Incident Response Plan (IRP)","Configuration Management Plan"],"c":1,"why":"The BCP focuses on maintaining or resuming overall business operations after a disruption, whereas the DRP focuses specifically on restoring IT infrastructure and systems; IRP addresses security incident handling, and configuration management concerns system change control.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which testing approach involves analyzing an application's source code for security flaws without executing the program?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Penetration testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source or binary code without running the application, identifying issues like insecure coding patterns. DAST and penetration testing require execution, and fuzz testing feeds random input to a running program.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before disposing of old hard drives that contained sensitive customer data, which method provides the MOST assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive with a quick format","Physically destroying the drive through shredding or degaussing","Moving the files to a hidden folder"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction (shredding, degaussing, or incineration) ensures data cannot be recovered from the media. Deleting files, quick formatting, or hiding files leave data recoverable through forensic tools.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of using a source code version control system in a secure software development environment?","o":["To automatically encrypt all source code files","To track changes, enable rollback, and maintain accountability for code modifications","To perform automated penetration testing on committed code","To replace the need for code review"],"c":1,"why":"Version control systems track who changed what and when, allowing rollback to previous versions and supporting audit trails and accountability. They do not perform encryption, penetration testing, or eliminate the need for code review.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A software architect designs a module so that each component only has access to the specific data and functions it needs to perform its task, and nothing more. This design approach reflects which security principle?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity"],"c":1,"why":"Least privilege means granting only the minimum access necessary to perform a function, which matches the scenario described. Separation of duties involves dividing tasks among different people, defense in depth uses layered controls, and security through obscurity relies on secrecy of design rather than access restriction.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During an active network intrusion, an incident responder has limited time to collect evidence before the affected system must be taken offline. According to standard forensic principles regarding order of volatility, which of the following should be collected FIRST?","o":["Contents of RAM and active network connection state","Log files stored on a hardened, remote syslog server","A full forensic disk image of the affected system","Backup tapes stored in an offsite vault"],"c":0,"why":"RAM contents and active network state are the most volatile and will be lost the moment the system is powered down or the connection is terminated; disk images, remote logs, and offsite backups persist and can be collected later without loss.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A security tester feeds an application large amounts of random, malformed, or unexpected input to observe how the program handles it and to uncover crashes or vulnerabilities. This technique is known as:","o":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Static analysis","Unit testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing (fuzzing) involves supplying invalid, unexpected, or random data to a program to discover flaws such as crashes or memory corruption. Regression and unit testing focus on verifying expected functionality, and static analysis examines code without execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A financial application performs a full backup every Sunday at midnight and incremental backups every 4 hours thereafter (12am, 4am, 8am, 12pm, 4pm, 8pm). A ransomware attack encrypts the production database at 3:15 PM on Wednesday. The organization's BCP defines a maximum tolerable RPO of 4 hours for this system. Based on the backup schedule, what is the actual outcome?","o":["Only 15 minutes of data would be lost, far exceeding the RPO requirement","Approximately 3 hours 15 minutes of data would be lost, which meets the 4-hour RPO requirement","Approximately 7 hours 15 minutes of data would be lost, failing to meet the RPO requirement","Zero data loss occurs because incremental backups run continuously"],"c":1,"why":"The last incremental backup before the attack ran at 12:00 PM Wednesday, so data from 12:00 PM to 3:15 PM (about 3h15m) would be lost, which is within the 4-hour RPO. The other options misapply the backup schedule timing.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is transitioning from a traditional Waterfall development model to an Agile/DevOps approach and wants to ensure security is not deprioritized in the faster release cycles. Which practice best supports this goal?","o":["Deferring all security testing until the final release candidate build to avoid slowing down sprints","Embedding automated security testing (SAST/DAST) directly into the CI/CD pipeline so vulnerabilities are identified with each build","Requiring a full manual penetration test before every sprint release regardless of code changes","Removing security requirements from user stories and handling them as a separate parallel project"],"c":1,"why":"Integrating automated security testing into CI/CD (DevSecOps) provides continuous, scalable security feedback without blocking rapid release cycles. Deferring testing to the end, requiring full manual pentests every sprint, or separating security from requirements all undermine the speed benefits of Agile/DevOps or delay defect detection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An application allows any authenticated user to view another user's account details simply by changing an ID number in the URL, with no server-side authorization check. This is an example of which vulnerability category?","o":["Broken access control","Security misconfiguration","Cryptographic failure","Insufficient logging and monitoring"],"c":0,"why":"Allowing a user to access another user's data by manipulating an identifier without proper authorization checks is a classic broken access control flaw. The other categories involve configuration errors, weak cryptography, or lack of audit trails, none of which describe this specific access issue.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application accepts a username field and passes it directly into a SQL query string without modification. An attacker enters a crafted string that alters the query's logic to bypass authentication. Which secure coding control would MOST effectively prevent this specific vulnerability?","o":["Implementing output encoding on all HTTP responses","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements) for all database access","Enforcing strong password complexity requirements","Enabling verbose error messages to help developers debug the query"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing attacker input from altering SQL query structure, which directly addresses SQL injection. Output encoding mitigates XSS, not SQLi; password complexity doesn't stop injection; verbose errors actually aid attackers rather than prevent the attack.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A security architect requires a RAID configuration that guarantees continued data availability even if ANY two disks fail simultaneously, regardless of which two disks are affected. Which RAID level should be selected?","o":["RAID 5","RAID 6","RAID 10","RAID 1"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 6 uses dual distributed parity, guaranteeing tolerance of any two simultaneous disk failures. RAID 5 tolerates only one failure, RAID 1 (a simple two-disk mirror) tolerates only one, and RAID 10 only survives a two-disk failure if both failed disks are not from the same mirrored pair, so it cannot guarantee survival of ANY two-disk failure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"During a security assessment, a tool analyzes an application's compiled binary and source code without executing it, flagging a buffer overflow risk in a specific function. What type of testing was performed?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source or binary code without execution (white-box, at rest) to identify vulnerabilities like buffer overflows. DAST tests a running application; fuzzing sends malformed input during execution; penetration testing simulates real attacks against a live system, none of which match 'without executing it.'","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization's Change Advisory Board (CAB) normally requires five business days of review before production changes are approved. A critical zero-day vulnerability is being actively exploited and requires patching within hours. Which approach BEST reflects sound change management practice?","o":["Bypass change management entirely because the patch is urgent and security-related","Follow an expedited emergency change procedure that still requires documentation, a backout plan, and post-implementation review","Wait for the standard five-day CAB cycle to avoid violating policy","Allow the security team to apply the patch without any change record since they hold administrative rights"],"c":1,"why":"Mature change management frameworks include a defined emergency change process that preserves accountability and rollback capability while allowing speed; skipping documentation entirely or waiting the full cycle both introduce unacceptable risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During an active APT intrusion, responders discover that an attacker is exfiltrating data through a compromised server. Immediately disconnecting the server would stop the exfiltration but would alert the attacker and destroy volatile evidence in memory and active sessions. What is the MOST appropriate containment approach?","o":["Immediately power off the server to halt all attacker activity","Take no action until law enforcement arrives, to avoid contaminating evidence","Move the server to a monitored, isolated network segment while capturing live forensic data, allowing continued observation without full data loss","Publicly disclose the breach immediately, before any containment action, to satisfy notification laws"],"c":2,"why":"Controlled, monitored isolation preserves volatile evidence and intelligence-gathering opportunities while limiting further damage; powering off destroys volatile data, inaction allows continued exfiltration, and premature public disclosure before containment is procedurally and often legally inappropriate.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A developer writes code that first checks whether a file exists and is writable by the current user, then—several instructions later—opens that file for writing. A penetration tester is able to swap the file for a symbolic link pointing to a sensitive system file in the interval between the check and the open call, causing the sensitive file to be overwritten. Which vulnerability class does this describe?","o":["Time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","Buffer overflow","SQL injection","Cross-site request forgery (CSRF)"],"c":0,"why":"TOCTOU race conditions exploit the gap between a security check and the action that relies on it, allowing substitution of the resource in that window. Buffer overflow, SQL injection, and CSRF involve entirely different mechanisms (memory corruption, malicious query input, and forged web requests, respectively) and do not match this timing-based attack.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During an incident response effort, a security team has successfully isolated an infected host from the network to prevent further spread of malware. According to standard incident response methodology, which phase should the team perform NEXT?","o":["Eradication","Detection and analysis","Lessons learned/post-incident review","Recovery"],"c":0,"why":"After containment, the team must eradicate the root cause (e.g., remove malware, close the vulnerability) before moving to recovery. Detection occurs earlier, and lessons learned occurs after recovery is complete.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A backup administrator performs a full backup every Sunday and a differential backup every day thereafter. On Thursday morning, the production server fails and must be restored. Which backup sets must be restored, and in what order?","o":["The full backup only, since differentials are cumulative and self-contained","The full backup plus every differential backup from Monday through Wednesday, applied sequentially","The full backup plus only the most recent (Wednesday) differential backup","The full backup plus the Monday incremental, followed by the Tuesday and Wednesday differentials"],"c":2,"why":"Differential backups capture all changes since the last full backup, so restoration requires only the full backup and the single most recent differential. Restoring multiple differentials or mixing incremental terminology is unnecessary and reflects a misunderstanding of how differential backups work.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A multilevel secure database contains a row for a classified project budget at the Secret classification level, keyed on project ID 4521. An unclassified user attempts to insert a row using the same project ID with benign dummy data. To prevent the unclassified user from inferring that a classified record already exists under that key, the DBMS allows both rows to coexist, returning only the row appropriate to the querying user's clearance. What technique is being used?","o":["Polyinstantiation","Database normalization","Data aggregation","Referential integrity enforcement"],"c":0,"why":"Polyinstantiation permits multiple rows with the same primary key at different classification levels specifically to prevent lower-cleared users from inferring the existence of higher-classified data. Normalization is a schema design technique, aggregation describes combining low-sensitivity data to derive high-sensitivity conclusions (the opposite concern), and referential integrity concerns foreign key consistency, not classification separation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A forensic investigator collects a hard drive from a compromised server as evidence in a potential criminal case. Which practice is MOST important for ensuring the evidence will be admissible in legal proceedings?","o":["Encrypting the drive contents before beginning analysis","Maintaining a detailed chain of custody documenting every individual who handled or transferred the evidence","Performing all forensic analysis only during normal business hours","Storing the drive in a RAID array for redundancy"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody proves the evidence has not been altered or tampered with from collection to presentation in court, which is essential for admissibility. Encryption, timing of analysis, and storage redundancy do not establish evidentiary integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning SSDs that contained classified data. The standard sanitization procedure calls for degaussing followed by physical inspection. A storage engineer objects to this approach. What is the technical basis for the objection, and what should be done instead?","o":["Degaussing is ineffective on SSDs because they store data electronically in flash cells rather than magnetically; cryptographic erase or vendor ATA Sanitize/Secure Erase commands with verification should be used instead","Degaussing is effective but must be performed twice on SSDs to ensure completeness","SSDs can never be sanitized and must always be physically destroyed regardless of data sensitivity","Degaussing works correctly on SSDs only if the drive remains powered on during the process"],"c":0,"why":"SSDs use non-magnetic flash memory, so degaussing has no effect on stored data; NIST SP 800-88 guidance recommends cryptographic erasure or vendor sanitize commands with verification. Physical destruction is one valid option but is not always mandatory, and the other statements misstate how degaussing works.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A database administrator notices that a user with access only to summary-level sales reports can, through repeated legitimate queries, deduce confidential individual salary figures that they are not authorized to view directly. This is an example of which database security issue?","o":["SQL injection","Aggregation attack","Buffer overflow","Cross-site request forgery"],"c":1,"why":"An aggregation attack occurs when combining multiple non-sensitive data elements or queries allows inference of sensitive information the user isn't authorized to access directly. SQL injection involves malicious query manipulation, buffer overflow is a memory corruption issue, and CSRF is a web session attack—none describe deriving sensitive data from authorized aggregate queries.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security team must assess a production-like web application for injection and session-management flaws. The team has no access to source code, cannot install any runtime agents or instrumentation on the application server, and must test the application as an external user would interact with it. Which testing technique is most appropriate?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)"],"c":1,"why":"DAST performs black-box testing against a running application without requiring source code or instrumentation, matching the stated constraints. SAST requires source code, IAST requires an instrumented agent inside the running application, and SCA identifies vulnerable third-party components rather than testing application logic for injection flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday and a differential backup every other day of the week. If the server fails on Thursday morning before that day's backup runs, which backups are required to fully restore the system?","o":["Sunday's full backup and Wednesday's differential backup","Sunday's full backup only","Sunday's full backup plus Monday's, Tuesday's, and Wednesday's differential backups","Wednesday's differential backup only"],"c":0,"why":"A differential backup captures all changes since the last full backup, so restoring requires only the most recent full backup and the latest differential (Wednesday's). Incremental backups, not differential, would require all intervening backups.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A defense attorney challenges the admissibility of a forensic disk image, arguing it is not the original hard drive. Under evidentiary principles commonly applied to digital forensics (analogous to the best evidence rule), which is the STRONGEST argument for admitting the image?","o":["The best evidence rule does not apply to any form of digital evidence","A forensic duplicate created with proper procedure and verified by a cryptographic hash matching the original is treated as an accurate, reliable representation and is admissible in place of the original","The image is admissible only if the original hard drive has since been destroyed and is therefore unavailable","Digital images are inherently hearsay and require live witness testimony describing the contents of every file"],"c":1,"why":"Courts widely accept properly created and hash-verified forensic duplicates as legally equivalent to the original under duplicate-evidence provisions; the best evidence rule does apply conceptually to digital evidence, availability of the original is not a prerequisite, and hash-verified images are not automatically hearsay.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that changes to application source code are tracked, that unauthorized modifications can be detected, and that previous stable versions can be restored if a deployment fails. Which control BEST supports these objectives?","o":["Code obfuscation","Version control system with audit logging and rollback capability","Static code analysis performed once at project completion","Encrypting the source code repository at rest only"],"c":1,"why":"A version control system with audit trails and rollback provides traceability, integrity verification, and recovery for source code changes. Obfuscation hides code logic but doesn't track changes; one-time static analysis doesn't provide ongoing change control; encryption at rest protects confidentiality but not versioning or rollback.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company's disaster recovery plan specifies a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 4 hours for its financial database. Which statement BEST reflects the meaning of this RPO?","o":["The system must be fully restored and operational within 4 hours of a disruption","The organization can tolerate losing up to approximately 4 hours' worth of data","Backup media must be tested for integrity every 4 hours","The maximum allowable system downtime is 4 hours"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, dictating backup frequency. Statements about restoration time and downtime describe the Recovery Time Objective (RTO), not RPO.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"Following a widely publicized breach involving a vulnerable open-source logging library embedded in thousands of commercial products, an organization needs to quickly determine which of its internally developed applications include the affected component and identify the exact version in use. Which artifact would most directly support this analysis?","o":["Software Bill of Materials (SBOM)","Service Level Agreement (SLA)","End User License Agreement (EULA)","Network topology diagram"],"c":0,"why":"An SBOM enumerates all components and dependencies, including versions, within a piece of software, enabling rapid identification of affected applications. An SLA and EULA are contractual/legal documents unrelated to component inventory, and a network topology diagram describes infrastructure connectivity, not embedded software components.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A company is building a public-facing REST API that will allow third-party applications to access user data on behalf of users. Which approach BEST ensures that the API grants access only to the specific resources a user has authorized, without exposing the user's actual credentials to the third-party application?","o":["Basic HTTP authentication with the user's username and password sent on every request","OAuth 2.0 authorization framework using scoped access tokens","A shared static API key embedded in the third-party application's code","IP address whitelisting of the third-party application's servers"],"c":1,"why":"OAuth 2.0 allows delegated, scoped access via tokens without exposing the resource owner's credentials to the third party, aligning with least privilege. Basic auth exposes credentials directly, static API keys don't provide user-specific consent or granularity, and IP whitelisting doesn't address user-level authorization at all.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During deployment of a critical security patch to address an actively exploited vulnerability, the IT team bypasses the normal Change Advisory Board (CAB) review process to remediate quickly. Which control BEST balances rapid remediation with accountability?","o":["Requiring emergency changes to be documented and formally reviewed retroactively by the CAB","Disabling the change management process entirely during active security incidents","Allowing all future patches to bypass CAB review to speed up operations","Permitting any employee to approve emergency changes without documentation"],"c":0,"why":"Emergency change procedures allow rapid action while still requiring after-the-fact documentation and CAB review to maintain accountability and traceability. Eliminating change management or allowing undocumented approvals removes necessary oversight.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A development team's CI/CD pipeline currently stores a third-party API key as a base64-encoded string embedded in the Dockerfile, which is committed to a private Git repository. A security architect determines this practice is inadequate. Which remediation best addresses the risk while preserving pipeline automation?","o":["Encrypt the API key with AES-256 before base64-encoding it into the Dockerfile","Store the API key in a dedicated secrets management service that injects it into the container at runtime via environment variables","Move the API key into a separate configuration file within the same private repository","Require a developer to manually type the API key each time the pipeline executes"],"c":1,"why":"A secrets management service provides encryption at rest, access control, rotation, and audit logging while keeping automation intact. Base64 encoding is trivially reversible and not encryption if the key itself isn't properly protected in transit/storage; moving the secret to another file in the same repo still exposes it to anyone with repo access; and manual entry breaks automation and does not scale securely.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A software development team incorporates numerous open-source libraries into their application. Management is concerned about inheriting unknown vulnerabilities and unpatched components from these dependencies. Which practice would MOST directly address this risk?","o":["Conducting Software Composition Analysis (SCA) to inventory and monitor third-party components for known vulnerabilities","Increasing the frequency of unit testing performed by developers","Applying full disk encryption to development workstations","Requiring developers to sign a code of ethics agreement"],"c":0,"why":"SCA tools identify and track open-source and third-party components, mapping them against known vulnerability databases (e.g., CVE) to manage supply-chain risk. Unit testing validates functional correctness rather than dependency vulnerabilities, disk encryption protects data at rest on endpoints, and ethics agreements don't provide technical vulnerability detection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization needs to decommission several solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored highly sensitive data. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate according to NIST SP 800-88 guidelines?","o":["Degaussing the drives","Cryptographic erase or physical destruction","Performing a low-level format","Deleting files and emptying the recycle bin"],"c":1,"why":"SSDs are not magnetic media, so degaussing is ineffective; NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase, purge techniques, or physical destruction for flash-based media. Formatting or simple deletion does not remove data from underlying flash cells.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"Review the following C function:\n\n```c\nvoid process(char *input, unsigned int len) {\n    char *buffer = malloc(len + 1);\n    if (buffer == NULL) return;\n    memcpy(buffer, input, len);\n    buffer[len] = '\\0';\n}\n```\n\nAn attacker supplies a value of len equal to 0xFFFFFFFF (UINT_MAX) along with a large input buffer. Which vulnerability does this code most likely introduce?","o":["Integer overflow leading to a heap buffer overflow","Reflected cross-site scripting (XSS)","Insecure deserialization","SQL injection"],"c":0,"why":"When len equals UINT_MAX, the expression len + 1 wraps around to 0, causing malloc(0) to allocate a minimal buffer; the subsequent memcpy then copies len (a huge value) bytes into that tiny buffer, producing a severe heap buffer overflow. XSS, insecure deserialization, and SQL injection are unrelated to integer arithmetic and memory allocation sizing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An application's CI/CD pipeline automatically deploys code to production immediately after a developer pushes a commit that passes unit tests, with no additional review or approval step. From a secure software development perspective, what is the PRIMARY risk of this configuration?","o":["Unit tests will run more slowly due to lack of parallelization","Malicious or flawed code could reach production without independent security review or segregation of duties","The development team will be unable to use version control effectively","Encryption keys used in the pipeline will automatically expire"],"c":1,"why":"Automatic deployment without independent code review, security testing gates, or approval violates segregation of duties and allows insecure or malicious code to reach production unchecked. The other options are unrelated technical side effects not tied to the core risk of unreviewed automatic deployment.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A database administrator needs a storage configuration that provides fault tolerance against a single disk failure while balancing cost and performance more efficiently than full disk mirroring. Which RAID level BEST meets this requirement?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 10"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 5 uses striping with distributed parity, tolerating a single disk failure while requiring less storage overhead than mirroring (RAID 1) or RAID 10. RAID 0 offers no fault tolerance, and RAID 1/10 have higher storage overhead.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A mobile banking application calls the endpoint GET /api/accounts/12345/balance to retrieve the authenticated user's account balance. A researcher discovers that by changing the URL to GET /api/accounts/12346/balance while still authenticated as the original user, they can view a different customer's balance because the server never verifies that the requested account belongs to the caller. Per the OWASP API Security Top 10, which vulnerability class does this represent?","o":["Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA/IDOR)","Mass assignment","Security misconfiguration","Broken authentication"],"c":0,"why":"BOLA (also known as Insecure Direct Object Reference) occurs when an API exposes object identifiers without enforcing per-object access control, exactly as shown. Mass assignment involves unintended binding of client-supplied fields to internal objects, security misconfiguration refers to broader infrastructure/settings issues, and broken authentication concerns failures in verifying identity rather than authorizing access to a specific object once authenticated.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A SOC analyst notices, via SIEM correlation, multiple failed login attempts using different usernames but the same few passwords across many different systems within a short time window. This activity is MOST indicative of which type of attack?","o":["Password spraying","SQL injection","Cross-site scripting","Man-in-the-middle attack"],"c":0,"why":"Password spraying involves trying a small set of common passwords against many accounts/systems to avoid lockout thresholds, producing this exact pattern. The other attacks target different vectors (injection flaws, client-side scripts, or traffic interception) and would not present as widespread failed logins.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A hospital licenses a proprietary electronic health records system from a small startup vendor. The hospital's risk management team is concerned about continuity of care if the vendor becomes insolvent or is acquired and discontinues the product, leaving the hospital without the ability to maintain or modify the software. Which contractual arrangement best mitigates this specific risk?","o":["Software escrow agreement","Service Level Agreement (SLA)","Non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","Perpetual software license"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow agreement deposits the source code with a neutral third party, to be released to the customer under defined trigger conditions such as vendor bankruptcy, ensuring continuity of the application. An SLA addresses performance metrics, an NDA addresses confidentiality of information, and a perpetual license grants ongoing usage rights but does not guarantee access to source code or ongoing maintainability if the vendor disappears.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During an incident response process, which of the following steps occurs immediately after an incident has been detected and validated as a true positive?","o":["Eradication of the root cause","Containment of the affected systems","Recovery and restoration of normal operations","Lessons learned review"],"c":1,"why":"After detection and validation, the immediate priority is containment to limit damage and prevent spread; eradication, recovery, and lessons learned occur later in the incident response lifecycle.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A security analyst collects a hard drive as evidence during an investigation. Which practice BEST ensures the evidence remains legally admissible in court?","o":["Encrypting the drive before storage","Maintaining a documented chain of custody","Making the drive read-only using the operating system","Storing the drive in the analyst's personal locker"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation tracks who handled evidence, when, and how, which is essential for admissibility. Encryption and read-only settings don't establish handling history, and personal storage undermines evidentiary integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to reduce the risk of unauthorized or untested modifications to production systems. Which process BEST addresses this concern?","o":["Configuration management","Change management","Patch management","Vulnerability management"],"c":1,"why":"Change management establishes formal approval, testing, and documentation for modifications to reduce unauthorized or disruptive changes. Configuration management maintains baselines, patch management applies fixes, and vulnerability management identifies weaknesses—none directly control the approval process for changes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) are functional and security requirements first formally documented before any code is written?","o":["Requirements analysis","Design","Implementation/Coding","Testing"],"c":0,"why":"Requirements analysis is the phase where business, functional, and security requirements are gathered and documented, forming the basis for later design and coding. Design occurs after requirements are defined, and coding/testing come even later in the SDLC.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which backup strategy provides the FASTEST restoration time when recovering from a total system failure, assuming daily backups are performed?","o":["Full backup only","Full backup plus incremental backups","Full backup plus differential backups","Differential backups only"],"c":0,"why":"A full backup allows complete restoration from a single backup set, minimizing restoration time. Incremental and differential strategies require restoring the full backup plus multiple additional backups, increasing recovery time.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application allows users to enter search terms that are directly concatenated into a SQL query without sanitization. Which vulnerability does this create?","o":["Cross-site request forgery","Buffer overflow","SQL injection","Race condition"],"c":2,"why":"Directly concatenating unsanitized user input into a SQL query allows attackers to inject malicious SQL commands, which is the classic SQL injection vulnerability. The other options involve different attack mechanisms unrelated to unsanitized query construction.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which type of software testing analyzes source code for security flaws without actually executing the program?","o":["Dynamic application security testing (DAST)","Static application security testing (SAST)","Penetration testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"Static application security testing examines source or binary code for vulnerabilities without running the application. DAST and penetration testing both involve executing the running application, and fuzz testing feeds malformed input to a running program to observe behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A file-processing service checks whether a user has permission to write to a specific file, and then, in a separate subsequent operation, opens that file for writing. A local attacker discovers that by replacing the target file with a symbolic link to a sensitive system file between the permission check and the write operation, they can cause the service to overwrite the sensitive file. What class of vulnerability does this scenario describe?","o":["Time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","SQL injection","Stack-based buffer overflow","Integer overflow"],"c":0,"why":"This is the classic TOCTOU pattern: a security check (permission validation) and the subsequent use (file open) are separated in time, allowing an attacker to alter the referenced resource in between. SQL injection, buffer overflow, and integer overflow involve entirely different mechanisms (malicious input parsing or arithmetic/memory errors), not a check/use timing gap.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company needs to ensure that hard drives being decommissioned cannot have their data recovered, even using advanced forensic tools. Which method BEST achieves this?","o":["Reformatting the drive","Deleting all files and emptying the recycle bin","Physical destruction of the drive","Overwriting the drive once with zeros"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction (e.g., shredding, degaussing for magnetic media) provides the highest assurance that data cannot be recovered. Reformatting and deletion leave data recoverable, and a single overwrite pass may not meet stringent security requirements for highly sensitive data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that all changes to application source code are tracked, that developers cannot overwrite each other's work unnoticed, and that prior versions can be restored if needed. Which practice best supports this goal?","o":["Code obfuscation","Version control system","Static code analysis","Load balancing"],"c":1,"why":"A version control system tracks changes, manages concurrent edits, and allows rollback to prior versions, directly addressing the stated goals. The other options relate to protecting code from reverse engineering, finding vulnerabilities, or distributing network traffic, not change tracking.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which RAID level provides fault tolerance by mirroring data across two disks, allowing continued operation if one disk fails?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 6"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 1 mirrors data across two disks, providing redundancy if one fails. RAID 0 offers no fault tolerance, while RAID 5 and RAID 6 use parity striping across multiple disks rather than direct mirroring.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During a forensic investigation, an administrator removes a hard drive from a compromised server and creates a bit-for-bit image before analysis. What is the PRIMARY reason for working from the image rather than the original drive?","o":["To preserve the original evidence in its unaltered state for legal admissibility","To reduce the time required to complete the investigation","To allow multiple investigators to work on the original simultaneously","To comply with vendor warranty requirements on the drive"],"c":0,"why":"Working from a verified forensic image preserves the integrity and chain of custody of the original evidence, which is essential for admissibility in legal proceedings. The other options are not the primary forensic justification for imaging.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A company licenses critical software from a small vendor and is concerned the vendor might go out of business, leaving them without access to the source code needed for maintenance. Which arrangement best mitigates this risk?","o":["Software escrow agreement","Service level agreement","Non-disclosure agreement","Right-to-audit clause"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow agreement places the source code with a neutral third party who releases it to the customer if the vendor fails to meet specified obligations, such as going out of business. SLAs, NDAs, and audit clauses address different concerns like performance guarantees, confidentiality, and audit rights, not source code access continuity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"In business continuity planning, which metric represents the MAXIMUM acceptable amount of data loss, measured in time, following a disruptive event?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable data loss measured in time (e.g., data since the last backup). RTO measures acceptable downtime for restoring services, MTD is the total time a business can tolerate disruption, and MTBF measures average time between hardware failures.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security team wants to detect vulnerabilities by instrumenting the application with agents that monitor code execution paths, data flow, and library calls while QA testers exercise the application through its normal functional test suite. This approach combines knowledge of the underlying source code with live runtime behavior. Which testing technique is being described?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Runtime Application Self-Protection (RASP)"],"c":2,"why":"IAST uses instrumentation inside a running application during functional testing to correlate code-level context with dynamic behavior, bridging SAST and DAST. SAST analyzes source/binaries without execution, DAST tests a running app externally without code visibility, and RASP is a production-time protective control rather than a testing technique.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization's incident response team has just confirmed that a server was compromised via an unpatched vulnerability and has isolated the affected system from the network. Which incident response phase should the team perform NEXT?","o":["Eradication of the malware and root cause","Post-incident lessons-learned review","Detection and analysis of the initial alert","Notification of law enforcement"],"c":0,"why":"After containment (isolating the system), the next standard phase is eradication—removing the malware and closing the vulnerability that caused the compromise. Detection/analysis already occurred, lessons-learned happens after recovery, and law enforcement notification is situational, not the mandatory next step.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which set of properties ensures that a database transaction is processed reliably, either completing fully or not at all, and that the database remains in a valid state afterward?","o":["CIA triad","ACID properties","STRIDE model","RBAC model"],"c":1,"why":"ACID (Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability) properties define reliable transaction processing in databases. The CIA triad concerns confidentiality, integrity, and availability of information generally; STRIDE is a threat modeling framework; RBAC is an access control model, neither related to transaction reliability.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the primary purpose of security event logging and monitoring in daily operations?","o":["To enforce least privilege on user accounts","To detect anomalous or unauthorized activity in a timely manner","To encrypt data in transit between systems","To automatically patch vulnerable systems"],"c":1,"why":"Logging and monitoring are primarily used to detect suspicious or unauthorized activity so it can be investigated and addressed. Least privilege, encryption, and patching are separate security controls not directly tied to log monitoring's core purpose.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization's internal build system pulls a package named 'corp-auth-utils' from a public package repository during a CI build because the internal private repository was temporarily misconfigured. An attacker had previously published a malicious package with the identical name and a higher version number to the public repository, and it was silently installed into the build, executing attacker code. What is this attack technique called?","o":["Typosquatting","Dependency confusion","Watering hole attack","Cross-site request forgery"],"c":1,"why":"Dependency confusion occurs when a build system is tricked into resolving an internal package name against a public repository, pulling an attacker-controlled package with the same name and a higher version instead of the intended private one. Typosquatting relies on similarly-named (not identical) packages, watering hole attacks target victims via compromised sites they visit, and CSRF is unrelated to package resolution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company implements RAID 5 across its database servers to improve availability. Which statement BEST describes the security/availability trade-off of this configuration?","o":["RAID 5 protects against single-disk failure through parity striping but does not replace offsite backups for disaster recovery","RAID 5 eliminates the need for backups because data is fully duplicated across all disks","RAID 5 provides encryption of data at rest in addition to fault tolerance","RAID 5 protects against multi-site disasters by distributing data across geographic locations"],"c":0,"why":"RAID 5 uses parity to tolerate a single disk failure, improving availability, but it does not protect against data corruption, deletion, ransomware, or site-wide disasters, so backups remain necessary. The other options misstate RAID 5's capabilities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A developer adds code to strip out or encode special characters such as < and > from user input before displaying it back on a web page. This practice primarily defends against which type of attack?","o":["Cross-site scripting (XSS)","Denial of service","Privilege escalation","ARP spoofing"],"c":0,"why":"Encoding or stripping special characters like < and > prevents browsers from interpreting injected script tags, which directly mitigates cross-site scripting attacks. The other attacks are not primarily addressed by output encoding of HTML special characters.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A multi-level secure database must prevent a low-clearance user from inferring the existence of a classified record when that user attempts to insert a row with a primary key that already exists at a higher classification level. The system instead silently creates a separate row visible only to the low-clearance user, using the same key value. What database security technique does this describe?","o":["Polyinstantiation","Data normalization","Referential integrity enforcement","Aggregation control"],"c":0,"why":"Polyinstantiation allows multiple rows with the same primary key at different classification levels so that lower-level users cannot infer the existence of higher-level data through key collision errors. Normalization and referential integrity are data-modeling/consistency concepts unrelated to classification, and aggregation control addresses combining low-sensitivity data to infer high-sensitivity conclusions, not key collisions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization's Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) for its order-processing system is 10 hours. The DR plan specifies an RTO of 6 hours and a Work Recovery Time (WRT) of 3 hours. During an actual outage, the technical recovery team brought the system back online in 7 hours, and data validation/reconciliation before returning to production took an additional 2 hours, for a total outage of 9 hours. Which statement BEST describes the outcome?","o":["The organization met its MTD because total downtime (9 hours) remained under the 10-hour threshold, even though the RTO target was exceeded","The organization failed to meet its recovery objectives because the RTO of 6 hours was exceeded","The organization failed because WRT exceeded its planned value of 3 hours","The outcome is unacceptable because RPO was not addressed in the recovery"],"c":0,"why":"MTD is the ultimate boundary combining RTO and WRT; as long as total downtime stays within MTD, the recovery is considered successful overall even if an individual sub-metric like RTO was exceeded. WRT was actually under its target (2h vs 3h), and RPO relates to data loss, not downtime, so it is irrelevant here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A backup administrator wants to minimize both the daily backup window and the number of tapes needed to restore data after a failure, while accepting a moderate increase in storage use. Which backup strategy BEST meets this requirement?","o":["Full backup every night","Differential backup each night after a weekly full backup","Incremental backup each night after a weekly full backup","Snapshot-only backup with no full backups"],"c":1,"why":"Differential backups capture all changes since the last full backup, making restores faster (only two sets needed: full + latest differential) at the cost of larger backup size compared to incrementals, which require the full plus every incremental since. A nightly full backup maximizes window and storage.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester successfully exploits a buffer overflow but finds that chaining together small existing code fragments (return-oriented programming) to build a working exploit is unreliable because the memory addresses of loaded libraries change on every execution of the vulnerable process. Which OS-level defense mechanism is most directly responsible for this difficulty?","o":["Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)","Data Execution Prevention (DEP)","Stack canaries","Input validation routines"],"c":0,"why":"ASLR randomizes the base addresses of loaded modules and the stack/heap on each execution, making it difficult for ROP chains to reliably locate reusable code gadgets. DEP prevents execution of injected code in data regions but does not randomize addresses, stack canaries detect stack corruption rather than address predictability, and input validation is a coding practice, not an OS memory protection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of a formal change management process in security operations?","o":["To ensure that all modifications to production systems are authorized, tested, and documented to minimize unintended security impact","To eliminate the need for security testing prior to deployment","To transfer accountability for system changes to the change advisory board","To guarantee that all changes are implemented immediately upon request"],"c":0,"why":"Change management ensures changes are reviewed, approved, tested, and documented to control risk and maintain system integrity. It does not eliminate testing, immediately implement all requests, or shift accountability away from system owners.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During a security review of a CI/CD pipeline, an assessor finds that database credentials used by automated deployment scripts are stored as plaintext environment variables defined directly in the CI configuration file, which is stored in the same source repository as the application code. What is the BEST remediation?","o":["Move the credentials into a separate configuration file with restricted repository access","Base64-encode the credentials before committing them to the CI configuration file","Integrate the pipeline with a centralized secrets management service that injects credentials at runtime and are never persisted in the repository","Rotate the credentials monthly while keeping them in the CI configuration file"],"c":2,"why":"A secrets management service (e.g., a vault) that dynamically injects credentials at deploy/run time eliminates persistent storage of secrets in source control entirely, addressing the root cause. Restricting file access or encoding still leaves secrets recoverable in version history, and rotation alone does not prevent exposure of the current credential in the repository.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is updating its SDLC methodology to reduce the cost of fixing security defects. At which phase should formal security requirements first be documented and approved?","o":["Requirements analysis","Design","System testing","Maintenance/operations"],"c":0,"why":"Security requirements must be defined during the requirements phase so they can drive design decisions and be validated throughout development; addressing them later (design, testing, or maintenance) is far more costly and often results in retrofitted, weaker controls.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst reviewing SIEM alerts notices repeated failed login attempts from a single external IP against multiple user accounts within a short time frame. This pattern is MOST indicative of which type of attack?","o":["Password spraying","SQL injection","Man-in-the-middle attack","Session fixation"],"c":0,"why":"Password spraying involves attempting a small set of common passwords against many accounts from a single source, producing the described pattern. SQL injection, MitM, and session fixation involve different attack vectors not reflected in this log pattern.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An internal audit reveals that standard users of an application can modify or delete entries in the application's activity log after performing sensitive transactions, effectively allowing them to later deny having performed those actions. Using the STRIDE threat model, which threat category does this scenario primarily represent, and what is the most appropriate mitigation?","o":["Tampering; mitigated by strict input validation on all log entries","Repudiation; mitigated by cryptographically signing and write-protecting log entries","Information Disclosure; mitigated by encrypting the log storage at rest","Elevation of Privilege; mitigated by enforcing role-based access control on application functions"],"c":1,"why":"The core issue is that users can deny performing actions because the system cannot prove log integrity — this is the Repudiation category in STRIDE, best mitigated through non-repudiation controls like digital signatures and immutable/write-once logging. Tampering mitigation (input validation) doesn't address the ability to alter logs after the fact, encryption at rest protects confidentiality but not integrity/non-repudiation, and RBAC controls initial access, not the ability to deny actions already taken.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application accepts user input to build SQL queries dynamically, and the team wants to eliminate SQL injection risk at the code level. Which control is most effective?","o":["Restricting the maximum length of input fields","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements) with bound variables","Relying on client-side JavaScript validation","Encrypting the database at rest"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data so user input can never be interpreted as SQL commands, directly addressing the root cause of injection. Length limits and client-side validation are easily bypassed, and encryption at rest does not prevent injection at all.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization's disaster recovery plan specifies a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 4 hours for its financial database. Which backup strategy would BEST support this requirement?","o":["Weekly full backups only","Continuous or near-continuous transaction log backups performed at least every 4 hours","Monthly full backups with no interim backups","Manual backups performed at the administrator's discretion"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable data loss measured in time; a 4-hour RPO requires backups (such as transaction log shipping) frequent enough to ensure no more than 4 hours of data is lost. Weekly, monthly, or discretionary backups would result in far greater potential data loss.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A company depends on a critical proprietary application from a small vendor with no in-house development staff. The company is concerned that if the vendor goes out of business, they will be unable to maintain or fix the software. Which contractual control BEST mitigates this specific business continuity risk?","o":["Requiring a service level agreement (SLA) with defined uptime guarantees","Establishing a source code escrow agreement with a neutral third party","Conducting an annual software license compliance audit","Requiring the vendor to carry cyber liability insurance"],"c":1,"why":"A source code escrow agreement ensures that if the vendor becomes unable to support the software (e.g., bankruptcy), the source code is released to the customer so internal or third-party developers can maintain it. SLAs address performance during normal operation, license audits address compliance not continuity, and liability insurance compensates for damages but does not provide access to the code needed to maintain the software.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A first responder arrives at a live, still-running server believed to be compromised. To preserve the most forensically significant data before it is lost, which sequence correctly follows the order of volatility from MOST volatile to LEAST volatile?","o":["CPU registers/cache → RAM → network state (routing tables, ARP cache, active connections) → running processes → local disk → archival backups","RAM → CPU registers/cache → local disk → network state → archival backups","Local disk → RAM → CPU registers/cache → network state → archival backups","Network state → RAM → CPU registers/cache → local disk → archival backups"],"c":0,"why":"Per RFC 3227 order-of-volatility guidance, CPU registers and cache change fastest and must be captured first, followed by RAM, then transient network/process state, then disk, with archival media being least volatile. The other sequences misplace disk or network state ahead of more volatile memory-resident data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team needs to assess a production web application for vulnerabilities without access to its source code, by sending crafted HTTP requests and observing responses. Which testing approach are they using?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Software composition analysis","Unit testing"],"c":1,"why":"DAST tests a running application from the outside, like an attacker would, without needing source code, making it ideal here. SAST requires source/binary code analysis, software composition analysis inventories third-party components, and unit testing is done by developers on isolated code modules.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization requires that the employee who initiates a wire transfer request cannot also be the person who approves and releases the payment. This control is an example of which security principle?","o":["Separation of duties","Least privilege","Defense in depth","Job rotation"],"c":0,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical functions among multiple people so no single individual can complete a sensitive transaction alone, reducing fraud risk. Least privilege limits access scope, defense in depth layers controls, and job rotation periodically changes roles—none of which directly describe this dual-control scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A critical zero-day vulnerability is being actively exploited against a production system. The standard change window is five days away. Which approach BEST balances the need for rapid remediation with proper change control governance?","o":["Invoke the emergency change procedure to deploy the patch immediately, then submit full documentation to the Change Advisory Board for retrospective review and approval","Wait for the next scheduled CAB meeting before applying any patch to preserve process integrity","Deploy the patch immediately without any change record, since emergencies are exempt from documentation requirements","Require full regression testing in the production environment before deploying the patch, regardless of active exploitation"],"c":0,"why":"Mature change management processes include a defined emergency change path that permits immediate action while still requiring after-the-fact documentation and CAB review for accountability. Waiting for the next CAB meeting leaves the system exposed, skipping documentation breaks auditability, and testing in production is not required by an emergency-change process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A clerk is authorized to view individual employee department codes and individual bonus percentages, but not salaries. By combining several of these authorized queries, the clerk is able to deduce an individual employee's exact salary. This is best described as:","o":["An aggregation attack","An inference attack","A SQL injection attack","A covert channel"],"c":1,"why":"Inference occurs when a user derives sensitive information from patterns in data they are authorized to access, even though they never directly queried the restricted field. Aggregation refers to combining multiple low-sensitivity records to produce a higher-sensitivity summary, which is a related but distinct concept; SQL injection and covert channels do not apply here.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A vulnerability scan returns two findings: CVE-1 has a CVSS base score of 9.8 and affects an isolated test server with no internet connectivity or sensitive data. CVE-2 has a CVSS base score of 7.5, affects an internet-facing payment gateway, and has a known exploit actively being used in the wild. Which vulnerability should be remediated FIRST, and why?","o":["CVE-2, because exploitability, exposure, and asset criticality make its actual risk higher despite the lower base CVSS score","CVE-1, because CVSS base score alone should always determine remediation priority","Both should be remediated simultaneously regardless of context, since CVSS scores dictate priority by policy","CVE-1, because critical severity ratings must always be patched before high severity ratings"],"c":0,"why":"Risk-based vulnerability management considers exploitability, exposure, and business criticality, not just the base CVSS score; an actively exploited flaw on an internet-facing, high-value asset represents greater actual risk than a higher-scored flaw on an isolated, low-value system. Prioritizing purely by CVSS ignores real-world context and asset value.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A development team establishes a software configuration management (SCM) baseline immediately before a major release. What is the primary security benefit of this practice?","o":["It guarantees the code is free of vulnerabilities","It provides a known reference point to detect unauthorized or unexpected changes","It automatically encrypts source code repositories","It eliminates the need for code review"],"c":1,"why":"A baseline creates a documented, approved snapshot of the codebase and configuration so that any later deviation can be identified and investigated, supporting integrity and change control. It does not guarantee vulnerability-free code, does not provide encryption, and does not replace code review.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A financial services organization requires a highly transactional database platform to survive the simultaneous failure of ANY two disks in the array without data loss, while accepting some reduction in write throughput compared to mirroring solutions. Which RAID level BEST satisfies this requirement?","o":["RAID 6, because dual distributed parity guarantees recovery from any two concurrent disk failures","RAID 10, because striped mirrors always provide the fastest writes and equivalent fault tolerance to RAID 6","RAID 5, because single parity provides sufficient protection for transactional workloads","RAID 0, because striping maximizes performance and is acceptable given the redundancy requirement"],"c":0,"why":"RAID 6 uses two independent parity blocks, guaranteeing tolerance of any two simultaneous disk failures, at the cost of write performance due to dual parity calculations. RAID 10 offers better write performance but only survives two failures if they occur in different mirror pairs, not any arbitrary two disks; RAID 5 tolerates only one failure, and RAID 0 offers no redundancy at all.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A DevSecOps team integrates automated static analysis and dependency scanning into the pipeline immediately after each code commit, rather than waiting until pre-release testing. This practice is best described as:","o":["Shifting security left","Continuous deployment","Blue-green deployment","Security through obscurity"],"c":0,"why":"'Shifting left' means moving security activities earlier in the development lifecycle so defects are caught and remediated sooner and at lower cost. Continuous deployment and blue-green deployment refer to release strategies, not the timing of security testing, and security through obscurity is an anti-pattern unrelated to this practice.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday and a differential backup every other day of the week. A server fails on Friday morning, before that day's differential backup runs. Which backup sets are required to fully restore the server, and in what order?","o":["The Sunday full backup, followed by Thursday's differential backup (the most recent one), applied in that order","The Sunday full backup, followed by every differential backup from Monday through Thursday, applied in chronological order","Only Thursday's differential backup, since differentials are self-contained","The Sunday full backup only, since differentials are not needed for restoration"],"c":0,"why":"Differential backups capture all changes since the last full backup, so only the full backup plus the single most recent differential are needed to restore fully. Incremental backups, by contrast, would require every incremental since the last full backup applied in sequence, which is the trade-off being tested here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A QA engineer writes a tool that automatically generates malformed, random, and boundary-violating inputs to feed into an application's input fields to observe crashes or unexpected behavior. This technique is known as:","o":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Interface testing","Acceptance testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing (fuzzing) specifically involves injecting invalid or random data to uncover crashes, memory issues, or unhandled exceptions. Regression testing verifies existing functionality after changes, interface testing focuses on data exchange between components, and acceptance testing validates business requirements—none involve deliberately malformed input generation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A company wants to validate that its alternate processing site can actually execute live production transactions correctly, without risking any disruption to the primary production environment during the test. Which disaster recovery test type is MOST appropriate?","o":["Parallel test, in which the alternate site processes live data simultaneously with, but independently of, the primary site","Full interruption test, in which primary operations are shut down and processing is switched entirely to the alternate site","Tabletop exercise, in which stakeholders discuss the recovery plan around a conference table","Structured walkthrough, in which the plan is reviewed step by step without any live systems involved"],"c":0,"why":"A parallel test allows the alternate site to process real production data concurrently with the primary site, validating technical functionality without interrupting live operations. A full interruption test achieves realism but at the cost of production disruption, while tabletop exercises and walkthroughs are discussion-based and do not validate actual technical failover.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A multilevel secure database must allow a Secret-cleared user and a Top-Secret-cleared user to insert data using the same primary key without creating a covert channel or revealing the existence of the higher-classification record. Which technique addresses this requirement?","o":["Database normalization","Referential integrity constraints","Polyinstantiation","Data masking"],"c":2,"why":"Polyinstantiation allows multiple rows with the same key to exist at different classification levels, preventing lower-cleared users from inferring the existence of higher-classified data. Normalization and referential integrity address data structure and consistency, not classification-based access, and data masking obscures values rather than allowing multiple classified instances of the same record.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"Security analysts suspect an insider with valid credentials is exfiltrating sensitive files to personal cloud storage during off-hours. The team wants the strongest detection capability while ensuring any logs collected remain suitable as evidence in a potential legal proceeding. Which approach BEST achieves both goals?","o":["Deploy user and entity behavior analytics (UEBA) correlating DLP, proxy, and authentication logs, and write the resulting logs to write-once, read-many (WORM) storage","Block all outbound traffic to known cloud storage domains at the perimeter firewall","Require managerial approval for all employee logins that occur outside normal business hours","Increase password complexity requirements for all privileged accounts across the environment"],"c":0,"why":"UEBA correlation across multiple log sources provides behavioral detection of anomalous exfiltration activity, while WORM storage preserves log integrity and non-repudiation for chain-of-custody purposes. The other options are preventive controls that do not provide detection or investigative evidentiary value for an ongoing suspected insider threat.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During an incident response process, which phase focuses on limiting the scope and magnitude of an incident to prevent it from spreading further?","o":["Containment","Eradication","Lessons Learned","Detection"],"c":0,"why":"Containment aims to isolate affected systems and stop the incident from spreading. Eradication removes the root cause after containment, detection identifies the incident, and lessons learned occurs after recovery.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An attacker enters ' OR '1'='1 into a web application login field and successfully bypasses authentication. What type of vulnerability does this exploit?","o":["Cross-site scripting (XSS)","SQL injection","Buffer overflow","Session fixation"],"c":1,"why":"This is a classic SQL injection where unsanitized input alters the intended SQL query logic; XSS involves injecting scripts into pages viewed by other users, buffer overflow involves memory corruption, and session fixation involves forcing a known session ID.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An investigator collects a hard drive from a compromised server as evidence. Which practice is MOST important to ensure the evidence remains admissible in legal proceedings?","o":["Encrypting the drive before analysis","Maintaining a documented chain of custody","Making the analysis on the original drive only","Storing the drive in the investigator's personal office"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documents who handled evidence, when, and how, which is essential to prove integrity and admissibility in court. Analyzing on the original drive risks altering evidence, and personal storage or encryption alone do not establish legal admissibility.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A programmer writes a function that copies user-supplied input into a fixed-size array without checking the input length. What vulnerability does this most likely introduce?","o":["Race condition","Buffer overflow","Cross-site request forgery","Insecure direct object reference"],"c":1,"why":"Copying input without length validation into a fixed-size buffer can overwrite adjacent memory, causing a buffer overflow; the other options involve timing issues, forged requests, or improper access control, not memory corruption from unchecked input size.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A backup strategy captures all changes made since the last full backup, growing larger each day until the next full backup. Which backup type is this?","o":["Differential backup","Incremental backup","Full backup","Mirror backup"],"c":0,"why":"A differential backup always backs up all changes since the last full backup, so it grows daily. An incremental backup only captures changes since the last backup (full or incremental), making it smaller and requiring the clear flag reset each time.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A security tester sends large volumes of random, malformed, and unexpected input to an application's input fields to see if it crashes or behaves unexpectedly. This is an example of which testing method?","o":["Regression testing","Fuzz testing","Unit testing","Acceptance testing"],"c":1,"why":"Fuzz testing involves feeding invalid or random data to discover crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions. Regression testing verifies existing functionality after changes, unit testing checks individual code modules, and acceptance testing validates business requirements.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A file-processing utility checks whether a file is owned by the invoking user, and then, in a separate subsequent operation, opens that file for writing. An attacker replaces the file with a symbolic link to a sensitive system file between the check and the open call. Which vulnerability class does this describe, and what is the most effective mitigation?","o":["A time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition, mitigated by performing the check and use as a single atomic operation","An integer overflow, mitigated by using bounds-checked data types","A SQL injection flaw, mitigated by parameterized queries","A cross-site request forgery, mitigated by anti-CSRF tokens"],"c":0,"why":"The scenario is a classic TOCTOU race condition where state can change between the check and the use; atomic operations (e.g., opening with exclusive flags tied to ownership verification) close the window. The other options describe unrelated vulnerability classes that don't match a check/use timing gap.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security team must assess a production e-commerce API for which they have no source code access and cannot install instrumentation agents on the running service. They need to identify vulnerabilities by sending crafted requests and observing responses. Which testing approach is most appropriate?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)"],"c":1,"why":"DAST tests a running application from the outside via crafted inputs without needing source code or instrumentation, matching the black-box constraint. SAST requires source code, IAST requires runtime agents, and SCA analyzes third-party component inventories rather than probing live behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization regularly applies vendor-released updates to fix known vulnerabilities in its software. This activity is best described as part of which security operations process?","o":["Configuration management","Patch management","Vulnerability assessment","Incident response"],"c":1,"why":"Patch management specifically involves the identification, testing, and deployment of vendor fixes for known vulnerabilities. Vulnerability assessment identifies weaknesses but does not remediate them, and configuration management deals with system baselines and settings broadly.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Why is a version control (source code repository) system important in secure software development?","o":["It automatically encrypts all application data at rest","It tracks changes to code, enabling accountability, rollback, and review of modifications","It eliminates the need for code review","It replaces the need for a formal change management process"],"c":1,"why":"Version control provides an auditable history of who changed what and when, supporting accountability and the ability to revert problematic changes; it does not encrypt data, and it complements rather than replaces code review or change management.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company implements RAID 1 across its critical database servers. What is the PRIMARY security/operational benefit of this configuration?","o":["Increased storage capacity through striping","Data redundancy through disk mirroring","Faster backup and restore times","Reduced need for offsite backups"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 1 mirrors data across two disks, providing redundancy if one disk fails. It does not increase capacity (that's striping/RAID 0) and does not eliminate the need for offsite backups, which protect against site-level disasters.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A database contains individual salary records that are not classified as sensitive, but a user who queries and combines many of these records can determine the overall payroll budget, which IS considered sensitive. This is an example of which database security concern?","o":["Inference","Aggregation","Polyinstantiation","Normalization"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining non-sensitive pieces of data results in sensitive information; inference is deriving sensitive information from indirect clues without directly combining records. Polyinstantiation and normalization are unrelated database concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization determines that its order-processing system can tolerate a maximum of 4 hours of data loss in the event of a disaster. This value represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, dictating backup frequency. RTO defines how quickly a system must be restored, while MTD is the total tolerable downtime and MTBF relates to hardware reliability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"In object-oriented programming, which concept restricts direct access to an object's internal data and requires interaction through defined methods, thereby improving security by controlling how data is modified?","o":["Inheritance","Polymorphism","Encapsulation","Abstraction"],"c":2,"why":"Encapsulation bundles data with the methods that operate on it and hides internal state, limiting direct manipulation. Inheritance relates to deriving classes, polymorphism allows different implementations of the same interface, and abstraction hides complexity but is not specifically about restricting direct data access.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"To reduce the risk of a single administrator being able to both create and approve financial transactions in a system, an organization implements which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacations"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by any single individual. Least privilege limits access rights generally, job rotation moves people between roles over time, and mandatory vacations help detect fraud but don't directly split duties.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is redesigning its software development lifecycle (SDLC) to reduce the cost and impact of security defects. At which phase should security requirements first be formally defined and documented?","o":["During the requirements analysis phase, before design begins","During the testing phase, so defects can be identified before release","During the deployment phase, so production controls can be configured","During the maintenance phase, once user feedback is available"],"c":0,"why":"Security requirements defined during requirements analysis allow security to be designed in from the start, which is far cheaper than remediating defects found later. Testing, deployment, and maintenance occur too late to shape secure design decisions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application accepts user input directly in SQL query strings, making it vulnerable to SQL injection. Which remediation BEST addresses the root cause of this vulnerability?","o":["Encrypt the database connection string","Use parameterized queries (prepared statements) for all database access","Increase input field length limits to prevent buffer overflows","Implement a web application firewall as the sole control"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing attacker-supplied input from being interpreted as SQL commands, addressing the root cause. Encryption, field length limits, and a WAF alone do not fix the underlying injection flaw.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A file permission check is performed, and shortly afterward the file is opened and modified by a privileged process. An attacker manages to swap the file with a malicious one in the interval between the check and the use. This is an example of which type of vulnerability?","o":["Buffer overflow","Time-of-check/time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","Cross-site scripting","SQL injection"],"c":1,"why":"A TOCTOU race condition occurs when a resource's state changes between the time it is validated and the time it is used. Buffer overflow, XSS, and SQL injection involve different attack mechanisms unrelated to this timing gap.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A software team adopts a DevSecOps pipeline that automatically runs static analysis and dependency scanning on every code commit before merging. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this approach compared to traditional periodic security reviews?","o":["It eliminates the need for manual penetration testing entirely","It shifts security testing earlier and provides continuous, rapid feedback to developers","It guarantees that no vulnerabilities will exist in production code","It removes the need for a formal change management process"],"c":1,"why":"Integrating automated security testing into the CI/CD pipeline (\"shifting left\") gives developers immediate feedback and catches issues earlier and more frequently than periodic reviews. It does not eliminate penetration testing, guarantee zero vulnerabilities, or remove change management requirements.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company's disaster recovery plan states that after a system outage, the organization can tolerate losing no more than 4 hours of transaction data. This requirement defines which of the following?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Service Level Agreement (SLA)"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, dictating backup frequency. RTO measures how quickly systems must be restored, MTD is the maximum time a business function can be down before severe impact, and an SLA is a contractual performance commitment, none of which describe acceptable data loss.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During incident response on a live, compromised server that must remain running for evidence collection, which of the following data sources should be collected FIRST according to the order of volatility?","o":["Hard drive contents","CPU registers and cache memory","System log files stored on disk","Offsite backup tapes"],"c":1,"why":"The order of volatility dictates collecting the most transient data first; CPU registers and cache change constantly and are lost immediately on power-down or process changes. Disk contents, log files, and backup tapes are far more persistent and can be captured later without loss of evidentiary value.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A company outsources development of a mission-critical application to a third-party vendor. The contract requires that if the vendor goes out of business or fails to meet support obligations, the client will receive access to the current source code and build materials. Which control does this describe?","o":["A non-disclosure agreement","Software escrow","A service level agreement","A code signing certificate"],"c":1,"why":"Software escrow places source code and related materials with a neutral third party for release under specified conditions (e.g., vendor insolvency), protecting the client's continuity. NDAs protect confidentiality, SLAs define performance metrics, and code signing verifies authenticity/integrity of released binaries, none of which addresses source code continuity risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday. To minimize the number of media sets required during restoration after a failure on Thursday, even at the cost of longer nightly backup times, which backup strategy should be used for the intervening days?","o":["Incremental backup","Differential backup","Snapshot-only backup","Mirror backup with no full backup"],"c":1,"why":"Differential backups capture all changes since the last full backup, so restoration requires only the full backup plus the most recent differential (two sets total). Incremental backups require the full backup plus every incremental since, increasing restore complexity, while the other options don't fit the described full-backup schedule.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A legacy C application does not validate the length of user-supplied input before copying it into a fixed-size stack buffer, allowing an attacker to overwrite adjacent memory and execute arbitrary code. Which combination of controls would MOST effectively mitigate this class of vulnerability?","o":["Input bounds checking combined with stack canaries and address space layout randomization (ASLR)","Strong encryption of the application's binary at rest","Implementing role-based access control on the application server","Using a signed digital certificate for the application executable"],"c":0,"why":"Bounds checking prevents overflows at the source, while stack canaries and ASLR are compensating memory-protection controls that make exploitation harder even if an overflow occurs. Encryption at rest, RBAC, and code signing do not address the underlying memory corruption issue.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During a STRIDE-based threat modeling session for a financial transaction system, the team identifies a threat where a user could later deny having authorized a wire transfer. Which control category most directly addresses this specific threat?","o":["Encryption of data at rest to prevent unauthorized disclosure","Digital signatures and detailed audit logging to establish non-repudiation","Input validation to prevent tampering with transaction amounts","Rate limiting to prevent denial of service"],"c":1,"why":"The threat described is Repudiation in STRIDE, which is countered by non-repudiation controls such as digital signatures and immutable audit logs tying an action to an identity. The other options correspond to different STRIDE categories (Disclosure, Tampering, and Denial of Service) and do not address repudiation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A critical security patch must be applied immediately to production systems due to active exploitation in the wild, making it impractical to wait for the next Change Advisory Board (CAB) meeting. What is the BEST approach to maintain change management integrity?","o":["Apply the patch without any documentation since the situation is urgent","Follow the organization's emergency change procedure, applying the patch and obtaining retroactive approval and documentation","Wait for the next scheduled CAB meeting before taking any action","Apply the patch only after completing full regression testing in the production environment"],"c":1,"why":"A well-defined emergency change process allows urgent changes to be implemented quickly while still requiring documentation and after-the-fact approval, preserving accountability. Skipping documentation entirely, delaying until a scheduled meeting, or requiring full production regression testing before an emergency patch would leave systems exposed and undermine both security and governance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A development organization wants to ensure that only code from verified, authorized developers is deployed to production, and that any unauthorized tampering with a build artifact after compilation can be detected. Which practice BEST achieves this goal?","o":["Storing all source code in a private repository with access logging only","Applying digital signatures to build artifacts and verifying them before deployment","Requiring developers to use strong passwords for repository access","Performing quarterly code reviews of the production codebase"],"c":1,"why":"Digitally signing build artifacts provides both authentication of origin and integrity verification, allowing tampering to be detected before deployment. Repository logging, password policy, and periodic reviews do not provide cryptographic assurance of artifact integrity at deployment time.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization plans to reuse a solid-state drive (SSD) at a lower classification level within the same facility. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate given the characteristics of SSD media?","o":["Degaussing the drive","Overwriting the drive once with a pattern of zeros","Using the drive's built-in cryptographic erase or vendor-specified secure erase function","Physically labeling the drive as sanitized and placing it in secure storage"],"c":2,"why":"Because SSDs use flash memory rather than magnetic storage and employ wear-leveling, degaussing is ineffective and simple overwrite passes may miss reallocated blocks; NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase or vendor secure-erase commands as the reliable purge method. Labeling alone provides no actual sanitization.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security engineer is fuzz testing a proprietary binary network protocol for which no specification is publicly available and only a small set of captured legitimate traffic samples exist. Which fuzzing approach is most suitable for maximizing coverage of the protocol's structure?","o":["Generation-based fuzzing using a formally defined grammar of the protocol","Mutation-based fuzzing that randomly alters bytes in the captured legitimate samples","Static code review of the protocol handler's source code","Manual black-box penetration testing using only documented API calls"],"c":1,"why":"Without a known specification, mutation-based fuzzing that perturbs valid captured samples is the practical approach because it doesn't require a formal grammar. Generation-based fuzzing needs a defined grammar (unavailable here), static review requires source code, and manual testing using only documented calls would miss protocol edge cases fuzzing is meant to find.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to test a proprietary binary application for input-handling vulnerabilities without access to source code, by feeding it large volumes of malformed and unexpected input to observe crashes or abnormal behavior. Which testing technique are they using?","o":["Static application security testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Code review via manual walkthrough","Interface testing using mock objects"],"c":1,"why":"Fuzz testing automatically generates malformed or random input to a running application to uncover crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions without needing source code. SAST requires source/binary code analysis of structure, manual code review needs source access, and mock-object interface testing is used for isolating components, not vulnerability discovery via malformed input.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"To maintain proper separation of duties within an organization's security operations, who should be primarily responsible for reviewing audit logs that record the activities of system administrators?","o":["The same system administrators whose activities are being logged","An independent security or audit function separate from the administrators","The help desk team handling user support tickets","The end users of the systems being administered"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties requires that log review of privileged activity be performed by a party independent of those being monitored, preventing administrators from concealing their own misuse. Having administrators review their own logs, or assigning review to unrelated roles like help desk or end users, defeats the purpose of oversight.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A legacy C application is vulnerable to a stack-based buffer overflow. The organization enables Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR), stack canaries, and Data Execution Prevention (DEP)/NX simultaneously. An attacker attempting a classic return-to-libc exploit finds the attack significantly harder to execute reliably. Which of these controls contributes MOST directly to defeating return-to-libc style attacks specifically?","o":["Stack canaries, because they detect any overflow before the return address is reached","ASLR, because it randomizes the location of libraries, making it difficult to predict addresses to jump to","DEP/NX, because it prevents any code from being loaded into memory","Input validation at the application layer, because it stops malformed input before it reaches the stack"],"c":1,"why":"Return-to-libc attacks rely on jumping to known addresses of existing library functions; ASLR randomizes those addresses each run, directly undermining the attacker's ability to reliably target them. Stack canaries detect corruption but don't stop the attacker from redirecting execution once bypassed, DEP/NX prevents executing injected code but not reuse of existing legitimate code, and generic input validation doesn't specifically counter address-prediction-based exploitation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A data center architect designs a load-balanced server cluster so that if any single server fails, the remaining servers can absorb the full production workload without performance degradation. This design principle is best described as:","o":["Failback configuration","Simple load balancing","N+1 redundancy","Active-passive clustering"],"c":2,"why":"N+1 redundancy specifically means provisioning one additional unit of capacity beyond what is minimally required, so the loss of any single component does not impact overall service capacity. Load balancing alone doesn't guarantee spare capacity, failback refers to returning to a primary system after failover, and active-passive clustering typically leaves standby resources idle rather than sharing load.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"Before deploying a newly released vendor security patch to production servers, an organization should FIRST:","o":["Deploy the patch directly to all production servers to minimize the exposure window","Test the patch in a non-production environment that closely mirrors production","Wait 90 days to see if other organizations report problems before acting","Disable the affected service entirely until the patch can be manually reviewed line by line"],"c":1,"why":"Standard patch management practice requires testing patches in a representative non-production environment to identify compatibility or stability issues before production rollout. Deploying directly to production risks outages, waiting 90 days leaves known vulnerabilities exposed, and disabling services is often operationally infeasible and unnecessary if proper testing is performed.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During live forensic triage of a compromised production server that cannot be taken offline, an investigator identifies four potential evidence sources that must be prioritized: the contents of physical RAM, the system's ARP cache, a swap file on local disk, and archived log files stored on a network share. Following the standard order of volatility (as described in RFC 3227), which source should be captured first?","o":["The contents of physical RAM","The ARP cache","The swap file on disk","The archived log files on the network share"],"c":1,"why":"The order of volatility ranks CPU registers/cache highest, followed by routing tables, ARP cache, and process tables, then RAM, then temporary file systems (swap), then disk, then remote/archived logs. The ARP cache is more volatile than RAM and must be captured before it, making the other options incorrect in sequence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A SOC detects indicators of an advanced persistent threat (APT) actor that has established lateral movement across multiple network segments using a compromised service account. Full scope of the intrusion is not yet known. Which containment approach best balances the need to limit damage with the need to preserve evidence and fully understand the attacker's foothold?","o":["Immediately disable the compromised account and isolate all affected hosts from the network","Continue covert monitoring and log collection to map the full extent of the intrusion, then execute a coordinated eradication once scope is understood","Immediately reimage all systems suspected of compromise to eliminate the threat","Notify law enforcement and take no further internal action until they provide direction"],"c":1,"why":"With sophisticated APT actors, premature overt action (disabling accounts, isolating hosts, reimaging) can tip off the adversary, causing them to accelerate exfiltration, destroy evidence, or pivot to undiscovered footholds; best practice is covert observation to fully map the intrusion before a coordinated takedown. Waiting solely on law enforcement guidance unnecessarily delays necessary internal containment planning.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A BIA for an order-processing system establishes a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 24 hours, an RTO of 10 hours, a Work Recovery Time (WRT) of 6 hours, and a required RPO of 2 hours. Current backups are performed every 4 hours. Which statement correctly evaluates this recovery plan?","o":["The plan is fully compliant because RTO plus WRT (16 hours) is within the 24-hour MTD","The backup schedule fails to meet the RPO requirement; backups must occur at least every 2 hours to limit data loss to the required amount","The RPO is irrelevant as long as the MTD is satisfied","The RPO can be safely extended to 4 hours since that matches the current backup interval"],"c":1,"why":"RPO measures maximum tolerable data loss and is governed by backup frequency, independent of the downtime metrics (RTO/WRT/MTD). With backups every 4 hours, up to 4 hours of data could be lost, exceeding the 2-hour RPO requirement, so backup frequency must increase; downtime metrics being satisfied does not address data-loss exposure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm depends on a mission-critical application developed by a small third-party vendor. The firm's risk committee is concerned that if the vendor goes out of business or stops supporting the product, the firm will have no way to maintain or modify the application. Which contractual control BEST addresses this specific risk?","o":["A source code escrow agreement with a neutral third party","A service level agreement guaranteeing 99.9% uptime","A right-to-audit clause in the vendor contract","An indemnification clause covering financial losses from vendor failure"],"c":0,"why":"Source code escrow ensures the firm can obtain and maintain the source code if the vendor becomes unable to support the product; SLAs, audit rights, and indemnification address performance or financial recourse but do not provide continued access to the code itself.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A zero-day vulnerability is being actively exploited in the wild, and a patch must be deployed immediately, but the organization's Change Advisory Board (CAB) does not meet again for five days. What is the most appropriate action consistent with mature change management practices?","o":["Deploy the patch immediately without following any change process, since the situation is an emergency","Invoke the organization's emergency change procedure, obtaining abbreviated approval from a designated emergency change authority and completing a post-implementation review","Wait until the next scheduled CAB meeting to preserve process integrity, accepting the exposure risk in the interim","Deploy the patch immediately and simply log it retroactively as a standard, pre-approved change"],"c":1,"why":"Mature change management programs include a defined emergency change process that allows abbreviated approval by a designated authority while still requiring documentation and a post-implementation review, preserving control integrity without unacceptable delay. Bypassing process entirely, waiting for the full CAB cycle, or mislabeling the change afterward all create governance and audit gaps.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is evaluating memory protection mechanisms to defend a legacy C application against return-oriented programming (ROP) attacks, in which an attacker chains together existing code fragments (gadgets) already present in memory to bypass DEP/NX protections. Which control is MOST effective specifically against this technique?","o":["Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR) alone","Stack canaries","Control Flow Integrity (CFI)","Data Execution Prevention (DEP/NX)"],"c":2,"why":"CFI validates that indirect branches and returns go only to legitimate, expected targets, directly disrupting the gadget-chaining technique ROP relies on. ASLR only raises the difficulty of locating gadgets, stack canaries detect certain overflow-based corruption but not gadget reuse, and DEP/NX is what ROP was specifically designed to bypass.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During an incident response, a technician must collect volatile evidence from a live, compromised production server before it is powered down for forensic imaging. According to the standard order of volatility, which artifact should be captured FIRST?","o":["Contents of physical RAM","CPU registers and cache contents","Current network connection state (netstat output)","List of currently running processes"],"c":1,"why":"CPU registers and cache are the most volatile and change or disappear within nanoseconds to seconds, so they must be captured before RAM, process lists, or network state, which persist slightly longer but are still highly volatile.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning self-encrypting solid-state drives (SEDs) that stored top-secret data and must sanitize them in accordance with NIST SP 800-88 guidance. Which method is most appropriate?","o":["Degaussing the drives using a high-powered magnetic field","Cryptographic erase by destroying the encryption key, followed by verification of the sanitization outcome","A single-pass overwrite of the entire drive with zeros","Performing a quick format of the drive's file system"],"c":1,"why":"SSDs are flash-based and unaffected by magnetic degaussing; NIST SP 800-88 recognizes cryptographic erase (destroying the key on a self-encrypting drive) as an effective purge method when verified. Overwrite methods are unreliable on SSDs due to wear-leveling and block remapping, and a quick format does not remove underlying data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A development team needs to test a running web application to identify vulnerabilities such as injection flaws and insecure data flows with high accuracy, by instrumenting the application code so that analysis occurs from within the application during execution, combining knowledge of both the code structure and runtime behavior. Which testing approach BEST fits this description?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)"],"c":2,"why":"IAST uses instrumentation agents within the running application to combine code-level visibility with runtime behavior, reducing false positives compared to black-box DAST and avoiding the source-only limitations of SAST. SCA focuses on identifying known-vulnerable third-party components, not runtime behavior analysis.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization performs a full backup nightly at 00:00 and an incremental backup every 6 hours at 06:00, 12:00, and 18:00. A server failure occurs at 22:00, corrupting all local data. The business has defined an RPO of 4 hours for this system. What is the actual maximum data loss window, and does it satisfy the stated RPO?","o":["6 hours of data loss; RPO is not met","4 hours of data loss; RPO is exactly met","8 hours of data loss; RPO is not met","2 hours of data loss; the organization exceeds the RPO requirement"],"c":1,"why":"The most recent backup before the 22:00 failure was the 18:00 incremental, so only 4 hours of data (18:00-22:00) is at risk, which exactly meets the 4-hour RPO; the other answers miscalculate the time gap.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During an incident response process, an analyst confirms that unusual outbound traffic from a server is indeed malicious activity rather than a false alarm. Which phase of the incident response lifecycle does this represent?","o":["Detection and analysis","Containment","Eradication","Post-incident recovery"],"c":0,"why":"Detection and analysis involves confirming and validating that an event is a genuine security incident before response actions like containment or eradication begin.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An analyst with 'confidential' clearance is permitted to query a database containing individually unclassified employee records. By running a series of legitimate, individually authorized queries and combining the results, the analyst is able to deduce a 'secret'-level fact about a reorganization. Which database security issue does this scenario illustrate?","o":["Polyinstantiation","Aggregation","SQL injection","Inference through indirect deduction from metadata"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining multiple pieces of individually low-sensitivity data produces a result of higher sensitivity than any single piece. Inference typically involves deducing sensitive information from indirect or contextual clues rather than direct combination of authorized query results; polyinstantiation and SQL injection are unrelated concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During an active security incident causing significant business impact, an emergency configuration change is needed on a production firewall. Which approach best reflects proper change management practice under these conditions?","o":["Bypass change management entirely since the security team has authority to act unilaterally during incidents","Implement the change immediately using an expedited emergency-change approval, then submit full documentation and a retrospective review to the Change Advisory Board afterward","Delay the change until the next regularly scheduled CAB meeting to avoid any unauthorized changes","Require the change to go through full standard testing in a staging environment before implementation, regardless of urgency"],"c":1,"why":"Emergency change procedures allow expedited approval to act quickly while still requiring after-the-fact documentation and CAB review to maintain accountability and control; skipping change management entirely or delaying critical action are both inappropriate.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A backup strategy captures all data that has changed since the last full backup, regardless of any incremental backups taken in between. Which backup type is being described?","o":["Incremental backup","Differential backup","Full backup","Mirror backup"],"c":1,"why":"A differential backup always references the last full backup and grows larger each day, whereas an incremental backup only captures changes since the last backup of any type (full or incremental).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A financial services company implements RAID 5 across four 2TB disks to protect a critical database and requires the array to tolerate any two simultaneous disk failures without data loss. Does the current RAID 5 configuration meet this requirement?","o":["Yes, RAID 5's distributed parity allows recovery from any two simultaneous disk failures","No; RAID 5 tolerates only a single disk failure at a time, so RAID 6 (dual parity) or a properly configured RAID 1+0 array would be needed to meet the requirement","Yes, as long as a hot spare disk is configured, RAID 5 becomes functionally equivalent to RAID 6","No; the only way to achieve this level of fault tolerance is to migrate to RAID 0 with additional mirrored copies"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 5 uses single parity and can survive only one disk failure at a time; a second failure during rebuild causes data loss. RAID 6 adds a second parity block enabling tolerance of two simultaneous failures, and RAID 1+0 can also meet this depending on mirror layout. A hot spare shortens rebuild time but does not provide true dual-failure fault tolerance, and RAID 0 provides no fault tolerance at all.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) should security requirements first be identified and documented?","o":["Requirements analysis","Testing","Deployment","Maintenance"],"c":0,"why":"Security requirements must be defined at the requirements analysis phase so they can guide design and implementation; identifying them later (testing, deployment, maintenance) is far more costly and often results in incomplete coverage.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A microservices-based application requires that internal services authenticate to one another without human interaction, and each service call must be authenticated, encrypted in transit, and independently verifiable without relying on a shared long-lived secret embedded in code. Which combination of controls BEST satisfies these requirements?","o":["Hardcoded API keys distributed via configuration files and TLS 1.2 for transport","Mutual TLS (mTLS) between services combined with short-lived OAuth 2.0 client credentials tokens","Basic authentication over HTTPS with credentials rotated quarterly","A shared symmetric secret stored in an environment variable on each service"],"c":1,"why":"mTLS provides mutual, certificate-based authentication and encryption between services, while short-lived OAuth 2.0 tokens issued via the client credentials grant limit exposure if compromised and avoid embedding long-lived secrets in code. The other options rely on static, long-lived, or weak credential mechanisms unsuitable for machine-to-machine authentication at scale.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A company receives a formal litigation hold notice naming several employees whose email may be relevant to pending litigation. The company's standard retention policy automatically purges email after 90 days. What is the correct action?","o":["Continue the normal 90-day purge cycle since litigation has not yet formally begun","Issue a legal hold suspending deletion of all potentially relevant data for the named individuals, overriding the standard retention schedule until counsel releases the hold","Immediately delete any emails that could be damaging to the company's position before the hold takes effect","Forward only the specific emails requested by opposing counsel to outside counsel and continue routine deletion of everything else"],"c":1,"why":"A litigation hold legally requires preservation of potentially relevant data and overrides normal retention/destruction schedules; failing to do so, or destroying evidence, can result in spoliation sanctions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before a production firewall rule change is implemented, an organization requires documentation, testing, approval by a change advisory board, and a rollback plan. This process is an example of which security operations practice?","o":["Configuration management","Change management","Patch management","Release management"],"c":1,"why":"Change management ensures that modifications to production systems are reviewed, approved, tested, and reversible to minimize disruption and risk; configuration management instead focuses on maintaining and tracking baseline system states.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An employee is suspected of leaking proprietary source code. The organization plans to pursue both internal disciplinary action and a criminal referral to law enforcement. Which statement correctly contrasts the standards of proof applicable to these parallel investigation paths?","o":["Both administrative and criminal investigations require proof beyond a reasonable doubt","Administrative investigations require only a preponderance of the evidence, while criminal prosecution requires proof beyond a reasonable doubt","Civil investigations require the highest standard of proof, exceeding even criminal cases","All investigation types—administrative, civil, and criminal—apply the identical 'clear and convincing evidence' standard"],"c":1,"why":"Internal/administrative investigations typically apply the lower preponderance-of-the-evidence standard (more likely than not), while criminal prosecutions require the much higher beyond-a-reasonable-doubt standard; civil cases generally use preponderance or, in some cases, clear and convincing evidence—never exceeding the criminal standard, and the standards are not uniform across investigation types as the other options claim.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application allows user input to be directly concatenated into SQL query strings without validation. Which type of attack is this application most vulnerable to?","o":["Cross-site scripting","SQL injection","Buffer overflow","Session hijacking"],"c":1,"why":"Directly embedding unvalidated user input into SQL statements is the classic cause of SQL injection, allowing attackers to manipulate queries. XSS involves script injection into web pages, buffer overflow involves memory handling, and session hijacking involves stealing session tokens — none relate to unsanitized SQL concatenation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During a security review, an organization discovers that an internal package name used in its private build system was never published to the public package repository. An attacker registered a public package with the identical name, and the build pipeline inadvertently pulled the malicious public package instead of the internal one, resulting in compromised build artifacts. Which supply chain risk does this scenario describe?","o":["Typosquatting","Dependency confusion","A watering hole attack","Code signing certificate compromise"],"c":1,"why":"Dependency confusion occurs when a package manager resolves an internal, unpublished package name to a malicious public package of the same name due to misconfigured repository precedence. Typosquatting relies on similarly misspelled names rather than identical names, and the other options describe unrelated attack types.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"Which disaster recovery test type activates and runs live operations at the alternate processing site while the primary site continues normal production simultaneously, without cutting over live business traffic?","o":["Tabletop exercise","Simulation test","Parallel test","Full interruption test"],"c":2,"why":"A parallel test operates the alternate site concurrently with the primary to validate recovery capability without disrupting live operations; a full interruption actually shifts production, and tabletop/simulation exercises are discussion-based or scripted walkthroughs without live system activation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An investigator collects a hard drive from a compromised system and must ensure it remains admissible in court. Which practice is MOST critical to preserving the integrity of this evidence?","o":["Encrypting the drive before storage","Maintaining a documented chain of custody","Copying the drive using standard file copy tools","Allowing multiple analysts to independently examine the original drive"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documents who handled evidence, when, and how, proving it was not altered or tampered with; the other options either risk evidence integrity or fail to address legal admissibility.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A SOC's SIEM generates excessive false-positive alerts from a correlation rule that flags any account with more than three failed logins within five minutes, causing significant analyst alert fatigue. A separate regulatory requirement mandates retaining security-relevant logs for one year. Which action best addresses the alert fatigue while preserving detection efficacy and regulatory compliance?","o":["Disable the failed-login correlation rule entirely to eliminate the noise","Refine the correlation rule to incorporate additional context—such as geolocation anomalies, account privilege level, and time-of-day patterns—rather than relying on a simple failure count threshold","Reduce log retention to 30 days to decrease SIEM processing load and free resources for rule tuning","Redirect all failed-login logs to an unmonitored archive so they no longer clutter the primary SIEM dashboard"],"c":1,"why":"Improving correlation logic with contextual enrichment increases detection fidelity and reduces false positives without eliminating visibility into a legitimate attack vector. Disabling the rule creates a blind spot, shortening retention below the one-year regulatory requirement creates a compliance violation, and diverting logs to an unmonitored archive defeats real-time detection entirely.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which type of application security testing analyzes source code for vulnerabilities without executing the program?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source or compiled code in a non-runtime state to find flaws. DAST and penetration testing require the application to be running, and fuzz testing sends random/malformed input to a running application rather than analyzing static code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A privileged system utility checks whether a user has permission to write to a file, and shortly afterward performs the write operation. An attacker exploits the small time gap between the permission check and the actual write by replacing the target file with a symbolic link to a sensitive system file. Which vulnerability class does this scenario represent?","o":["Time-of-check to time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","Buffer overflow","Cross-site request forgery","Improper input validation"],"c":0,"why":"This is a classic TOCTOU race condition, where the state of a resource changes between the validation (check) and the operation (use), allowing an attacker to substitute the resource. Buffer overflow, CSRF, and generic input validation issues do not describe this timing-based substitution attack.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) containing sensitive data. Security policy requires assurance that the data cannot be recovered. Why is cryptographic erasure generally preferred over simple overwrite-based sanitization for SSD media?","o":["SSDs use magnetic platters that retain residual data even after multiple overwrite passes","Wear-leveling and block remapping in SSD firmware can prevent overwrite commands from reaching every physical block that once held data, whereas destroying the encryption key renders all stored ciphertext permanently unreadable","Cryptographic erasure physically destroys the NAND flash chips, which is required for compliance with data destruction standards","Overwriting is always faster and more thorough than degaussing when applied to SSD media"],"c":1,"why":"SSD wear-leveling means logical overwrite commands may not touch every physical location where data resided, making overwrite unreliable; if data was encrypted at rest, destroying the key achieves effective sanitization regardless of physical remnants. SSDs are non-magnetic, so degaussing is ineffective, and cryptographic erasure does not physically destroy hardware.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company wants to improve disk fault tolerance so that a single drive failure does not cause data loss, while also maintaining good read performance. Which RAID level provides this using striping with parity across at least three disks?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 10"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 5 stripes data with distributed parity across three or more disks, allowing recovery from a single disk failure; RAID 0 offers no redundancy, RAID 1 uses mirroring rather than parity, and RAID 10 requires more disks for the same fault tolerance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of a version control system in a secure software development environment?","o":["To encrypt source code files at rest","To track and manage changes to code, enabling rollback and accountability","To automatically patch known vulnerabilities in code","To compile code into an executable binary"],"c":1,"why":"Version control systems track changes, maintain history, and support accountability and rollback, which are essential for change management and auditing. They do not perform encryption, automatic patching, or compilation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A SOC analyst aggressively tunes SIEM correlation rules to eliminate a high volume of benign alerts flagged as false positives. What is the primary security risk introduced by overly aggressive alert tuning?","o":["An increase in false negatives, potentially causing genuine attacks to go undetected","Higher long-term storage costs due to retaining more raw log data","A violation of the principle of least privilege across monitored systems","A decrease in mean time to detect (MTTD) for real incidents"],"c":0,"why":"Overly broad suppression of alerts to reduce noise risks filtering out true positives along with false ones, increasing false negatives and the chance that real attacks are missed; the other options are unrelated or describe the opposite effect.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which activity is a core part of an effective patch management program?","o":["Applying all vendor patches immediately to production without testing","Testing patches in a non-production environment before deployment","Disabling automatic vulnerability scanning after patches are applied","Removing all patch management logs after successful deployment"],"c":1,"why":"Testing patches before production deployment reduces the risk of introducing instability; the other options either bypass necessary controls or remove valuable audit information.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A DevOps team wants to ensure that only build artifacts produced by the authorized CI/CD pipeline are deployed to production, and that any tampering after the build stage is detectable before deployment. Which practice BEST achieves this goal?","o":["Storing all artifacts in a private container registry with access control lists","Digitally signing build artifacts using a private key held in a hardware security module, with signature verification prior to deployment","Encrypting artifacts at rest using AES-256 in the artifact repository","Requiring peer code review approval before merging to the main branch"],"c":1,"why":"Digital signing with a securely stored private key, combined with signature verification before deployment, provides both authenticity (confirms the pipeline produced the artifact) and integrity (detects tampering). Encryption at rest and access controls protect confidentiality and access but do not verify authenticity or detect post-build tampering, and code review addresses source code quality rather than build artifact integrity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"Which statement correctly contrasts the burden of proof between criminal and civil investigations arising from the same computer intrusion incident?","o":["Both criminal and civil cases require proof beyond a reasonable doubt, but criminal cases carry harsher penalties","Criminal investigations require proof beyond a reasonable doubt, while civil investigations use the lower standard of a preponderance of the evidence","Civil investigations require proof beyond a reasonable doubt because they often involve significant monetary damages","Administrative investigations always require the same burden of proof as criminal investigations because both can result in termination of employment"],"c":1,"why":"Criminal law demands proof beyond a reasonable doubt due to the severity of potential penalties, whereas civil litigation only requires a preponderance of the evidence (more likely than not); administrative investigations typically use an even lower internal standard, not the criminal standard.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization's plan focuses specifically on restoring IT systems and data after a disruptive event, while a separate plan addresses how the entire business will continue critical operations during the disruption. What is the plan focused on restoring IT systems called?","o":["Business continuity plan (BCP)","Disaster recovery plan (DRP)","Continuity of operations plan (COOP)","Business impact analysis (BIA)"],"c":1,"why":"A DRP specifically addresses recovery of IT infrastructure and data, while the BCP addresses broader organizational continuity of business functions; a BIA is an analysis tool, not a recovery plan.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During a forensic investigation of a compromised database server, an analyst collects a disk image and transfers it to a secure evidence locker. Each transfer, handler, and timestamp is logged on an accompanying form. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this documentation?","o":["To ensure evidence integrity and admissibility in legal proceedings by tracking who handled the evidence and when","To reduce the overall time required to complete the incident response process","To assign personal liability to the employee who caused the incident","To satisfy vendor service-level agreement reporting requirements"],"c":0,"why":"Chain of custody documentation proves evidence has not been altered or tampered with, which is essential for legal admissibility; the other options are not the purpose of this control.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"To reduce the risk of a single employee committing undetected fraud, an organization requires that no one person can both request and approve a financial transaction. This is an example of which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacations"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent any one individual from having enough control to commit fraud undetected; least privilege limits access rights, job rotation changes roles periodically, and mandatory vacations force absence to reveal irregularities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During a ransomware incident, the response team has isolated infected hosts from the network and confirmed the malware can no longer spread. They now begin removing the malicious payload, closing the exploited vulnerability, and rebuilding affected systems from known-good images. Which incident response phase does this describe?","o":["Detection","Containment","Eradication","Lessons Learned"],"c":2,"why":"Eradication involves removing the root cause of the incident (malware, vulnerabilities) after containment has stopped the spread; containment already occurred, and detection and lessons learned happen at different stages.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization licenses proprietary software from a small vendor and is concerned the vendor could go out of business, leaving them without access to source code for critical maintenance. Which control best addresses this risk?","o":["Software escrow agreement","Digital rights management","Code signing certificate","Configuration management database"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow agreement places source code with a neutral third party, to be released to the licensee if the vendor fails to meet contractual obligations such as going out of business. The other options address different concerns like licensing enforcement, code authenticity, and asset tracking.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"In a DevSecOps model, integrating automated security testing early and throughout the CI/CD pipeline is best described as which concept?","o":["Shifting security left","Security through obscurity","Defense in depth","Least privilege"],"c":0,"why":"\"Shifting left\" means moving security activities earlier in the development pipeline rather than only at the end. Defense in depth and least privilege are general security principles unrelated to pipeline timing, and security through obscurity is a discouraged practice of relying on secrecy rather than sound controls.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A program fails to properly check the size of user-supplied input before copying it into a fixed-length memory buffer, allowing an attacker to overwrite adjacent memory and potentially execute arbitrary code. What type of vulnerability is this?","o":["Race condition","Buffer overflow","Cross-site request forgery","Broken access control"],"c":1,"why":"A buffer overflow occurs when input exceeding the allocated buffer size overwrites adjacent memory, which can lead to code execution. Race conditions involve timing between events, CSRF tricks a user's browser into unwanted actions, and broken access control relates to improper authorization enforcement.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A storage administrator needs a RAID configuration that provides fault tolerance through data mirroring, without using striping, and can survive the failure of one disk in each mirrored pair with the simplest rebuild process. Which RAID level best fits this requirement?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 6"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 1 mirrors data across two disks with no striping, providing simple redundancy at the cost of 50% usable capacity; RAID 0 offers no fault tolerance, and RAID 5/6 use striping with parity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday night and a differential backup every other night of the week. A server fails on Thursday morning before that night's backup runs. Which backups are required to fully restore the server?","o":["Sunday's full backup and Wednesday night's differential backup","Sunday's full backup only","All differential backups from Monday through Wednesday plus Sunday's full backup","Only the most recent differential backup, without the full backup"],"c":0,"why":"Differential backups capture all changes since the last full backup, so restoration only requires the full backup plus the most recent differential; incremental backups, not differentials, would require all backups in sequence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A critical zero-day vulnerability is being actively exploited in the wild, and a vendor patch is available. The organization's standard change process normally requires a two-week Change Advisory Board (CAB) review cycle. What is the BEST course of action?","o":["Wait for the next scheduled CAB meeting to maintain process consistency","Deploy the patch immediately without any documentation to save time","Use an emergency change procedure to apply the patch with expedited approval, followed by retroactive documentation and review","Delay patching until the next quarterly maintenance window"],"c":2,"why":"Mature change management programs include an emergency change process for urgent security risks, allowing expedited approval while still requiring documentation and post-implementation review; bypassing documentation entirely or waiting weeks would leave the organization exposed.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A business continuity plan specifies a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 4 hours and a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 2 hours for a critical application. What does this mean for the organization?","o":["The organization can tolerate losing up to 4 hours of data and must restore the application within 2 hours of a disruption","The organization must restore the application within 4 hours and can tolerate losing up to 2 hours of data","Backups must occur every 2 hours and disaster recovery tests every 4 hours","RPO and RTO are interchangeable terms describing the same recovery metric"],"c":0,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable data loss measured in time, while RTO defines the maximum acceptable downtime; the other options misstate or conflate the definitions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of SSDs that previously stored highly sensitive data. Traditional degaussing will not work on this media type. What is the MOST appropriate sanitization approach?","o":["Perform a standard degaussing procedure as with magnetic media","Use cryptographic erase along with vendor-approved secure erase commands, followed by physical destruction if required by policy","Perform a quick format of the drive before disposal","Delete all files and empty the recycle bin"],"c":1,"why":"SSDs use flash memory, not magnetic storage, so degaussing is ineffective; cryptographic erase and vendor secure-erase commands, combined with physical destruction for highly sensitive data, are the appropriate NIST-aligned sanitization methods. Quick format and file deletion do not remove underlying data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security team implements a SIEM that aggregates and correlates logs from firewalls, endpoint detection tools, and authentication servers. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this correlation capability?","o":["It reduces the total amount of log storage required across the organization","It enables detection of complex, multi-stage attacks that would not be visible when examining any single log source in isolation","It eliminates the need for a formal log retention policy","It automatically remediates vulnerabilities identified in the correlated logs"],"c":1,"why":"Correlating events across multiple sources allows analysts to identify attack patterns spanning several systems, such as a phishing login followed by lateral movement, which a single log source would not reveal; SIEMs do not reduce storage needs, eliminate retention requirements, or auto-remediate vulnerabilities.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that critical system logs cannot be altered or deleted by an administrator after they are written, in order to preserve evidence integrity. Which control BEST achieves this?","o":["Write-once, read-many (WORM) storage for log files","Requiring administrators to use strong passwords","Encrypting logs with a symmetric key","Storing logs on the same server that generates them"],"c":0,"why":"WORM storage physically or logically prevents modification or deletion of written data, protecting log integrity. Strong passwords and encryption do not prevent an authorized administrator from altering logs, and local storage on the source server increases risk of tampering.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During which phase of the incident response process does an organization primarily focus on removing malware and closing the vulnerability that allowed the incident to occur?","o":["Detection","Eradication","Containment","Lessons Learned"],"c":1,"why":"Eradication involves removing the root cause, such as malware or unauthorized access, from affected systems. Detection identifies the incident, containment limits its spread, and lessons learned occurs after recovery to improve future response.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which backup strategy provides the FASTEST restoration time when recovering from a total system failure, at the cost of requiring the most storage space?","o":["Differential backup","Incremental backup","Full backup performed daily","Full backup performed weekly with daily incrementals"],"c":2,"why":"Daily full backups allow restoration from a single, complete backup set, minimizing restoration time, though they consume the most storage. Incremental and differential backups require combining multiple backup sets, increasing restoration complexity and time.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An application accepts user input directly into a SQL query string without any filtering, allowing an attacker to manipulate the query. Which secure coding practice most directly mitigates this vulnerability?","o":["Enabling verbose error messages","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Increasing database connection timeout","Encrypting the database at rest"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing attacker-supplied input from altering the SQL command structure; error messages, timeouts, and encryption at rest do not prevent SQL injection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization implements a formal process requiring that all modifications to production systems be documented, reviewed, tested, and approved before implementation. This process is an example of which security operations practice?","o":["Configuration management","Change management","Patch management","Release management"],"c":1,"why":"Change management is the formal process for reviewing, approving, and documenting changes to reduce risk and unintended impact. Configuration management tracks system baselines, patch management specifically addresses software updates, and release management deals with deploying new software versions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A development team wants to eliminate SQL injection vulnerabilities in a web application that dynamically builds queries based on user input. Which control provides the MOST effective mitigation?","o":["Client-side JavaScript input validation before form submission","Parameterized queries (prepared statements) that separate SQL code from data","Signature-based detection rules on a web application firewall","Stored procedures that concatenate user input into dynamic SQL strings"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries treat user input strictly as data, never as executable code, which structurally prevents injection. Client-side validation is easily bypassed, a WAF is a compensating control that can miss novel payloads, and stored procedures using dynamic SQL concatenation remain vulnerable.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A security team analyzes an application's source code line-by-line using automated tools without executing the program. What type of testing is being performed?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Penetration testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source, byte, or binary code without executing the application, unlike DAST which tests a running application; penetration and fuzz testing also involve execution or active exploitation attempts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of conducting regular vulnerability scans on production systems?","o":["To exploit vulnerabilities and confirm business impact","To identify known weaknesses before attackers can exploit them","To replace the need for penetration testing entirely","To determine root cause after a security incident has occurred"],"c":1,"why":"Vulnerability scanning proactively identifies known security weaknesses so they can be remediated before exploitation. It does not attempt exploitation (that is penetration testing), does not replace pen testing, and is not primarily a post-incident forensic activity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security tester has access only to a compiled, deployed web application and no source code. The tester interacts with the running application, sending crafted requests and observing responses to identify vulnerabilities. Which testing methodology is being used?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Manual secure code review","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)"],"c":1,"why":"DAST tests an application in its running state via its exposed interfaces without needing source code, ideal for black-box scenarios. SAST and manual code review require source access, and SCA identifies known vulnerabilities in third-party components rather than testing runtime behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following best describes the primary purpose of a software configuration management (SCM) system in a development environment?","o":["Encrypting source code repositories","Tracking and controlling changes to code and related artifacts throughout development","Performing automated malware scanning of production servers","Managing user access to the corporate network"],"c":1,"why":"SCM systems (e.g., version control) track changes, maintain version history, and support rollback and auditability of code and configuration items; encryption, malware scanning, and network access control are separate security functions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company wants to ensure that no single employee can both initiate and approve a wire transfer, reducing the risk of fraud. Which security principle is being applied?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent any one individual from committing fraud unilaterally. Least privilege limits access rights generally, job rotation moves staff between roles over time, and mandatory vacation forces time off to help detect fraud.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A retail company's database allows regional managers to view individual store sales figures, which are considered low sensitivity. However, a manager runs a query that sums all store figures company-wide and derives the total corporate revenue, a figure classified as confidential and normally restricted to executives. What type of security issue does this illustrate?","o":["Inference attack","Aggregation attack","Polyinstantiation","Data remanence"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining multiple low-sensitivity data elements produces a result that is more sensitive than any individual piece, exactly as shown by deriving total revenue from individual store data. Inference involves deducing sensitive facts through logical reasoning from unrelated data rather than direct combination, and the other options are unrelated database security concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application allows an attacker to inject malicious JavaScript into a page viewed by other users, causing their browsers to execute the script. This is an example of which vulnerability?","o":["Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)","Buffer overflow","Race condition","Privilege escalation"],"c":0,"why":"XSS occurs when untrusted input is rendered in a web page and executed by victims' browsers; buffer overflows, race conditions, and privilege escalation involve different mechanisms unrelated to script injection into web content.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before disposing of old hard drives that once stored sensitive customer data, which method provides the HIGHEST assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive with a quick format","Physical destruction (e.g., shredding or degaussing)","Moving the files to a different folder and renaming them"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction, such as shredding or degaussing, ensures data cannot be recovered by any means. Deleting files, quick formatting, or renaming files only remove pointers to the data, leaving the underlying information recoverable with forensic tools.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Within a secure SDLC, a Change Control Board (CCB) is established primarily to accomplish which function?","o":["Formally review, approve, and document proposed changes to production code to maintain integrity and traceability","Execute penetration tests against the final release candidate before deployment","Negotiate licensing terms for third-party open-source libraries","Perform obfuscation of source code prior to compiling the release build"],"c":0,"why":"The CCB's role in configuration/change management is to ensure changes are authorized, documented, and traceable, preserving system integrity and accountability. Penetration testing, licensing negotiation, and code obfuscation are separate activities handled by different roles or teams.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A database user with limited query permissions is able to deduce classified salary information by combining the results of several authorized, low-sensitivity queries. This scenario best describes which type of attack?","o":["Aggregation attack","SQL injection","Cross-site request forgery","Buffer overflow"],"c":0,"why":"Aggregation (and the related inference attack) occurs when combining multiple pieces of non-sensitive data reveals sensitive information; the other options describe unrelated attack techniques involving code injection, forged requests, or memory manipulation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization's data center uses a suppression system that removes oxygen or interrupts the chemical reaction of fire without damaging sensitive electronic equipment. Which type of fire suppression system is being described?","o":["Wet pipe sprinkler system","Clean agent (gaseous) suppression system","Dry pipe sprinkler system","Deluge sprinkler system"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agent systems use gases like FM-200 or inert gases to suppress fire without leaving residue or causing water damage to electronics. Wet pipe, dry pipe, and deluge systems all use water, which poses a risk to sensitive equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A project team is developing a large, complex, high-risk system where requirements are expected to evolve and risk must be reassessed continuously throughout development. Which SDLC model is BEST suited to this scenario?","o":["Waterfall model","Spiral model","Pure Agile Scrum with no risk gates","V-model"],"c":1,"why":"The Spiral model explicitly incorporates iterative risk analysis at each cycle, making it well suited for large, high-risk projects with evolving requirements. Waterfall is rigid and sequential, the V-model emphasizes verification/validation pairing rather than risk iteration, and Agile without risk gates lacks the formal risk assessment loop needed here.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A software security team wants to identify design-level flaws (such as missing authentication on a data flow between two trust boundaries) before any code is written. At which phase of the secure SDLC should this activity be performed to maximize its cost-effectiveness?","o":["During the requirements phase, using automated static analysis tools","During the design phase, using threat modeling techniques such as data flow diagrams and STRIDE","During the testing phase, using dynamic application security testing (DAST)","During the maintenance phase, using penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"Threat modeling during design identifies architectural flaws like missing trust-boundary controls before code exists, when remediation is cheapest. Static/dynamic analysis and penetration testing operate on code or running systems and occur later, at higher remediation cost.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary security benefit of conducting formal peer code reviews before merging code into the main branch?","o":["It eliminates the need for further testing","It guarantees compliance with all regulatory requirements","It helps identify security flaws, logic errors, and coding standard violations early","It replaces the need for a change management process"],"c":2,"why":"Peer code review helps catch defects, insecure coding practices, and logic errors before they reach production, complementing (not replacing) testing, compliance efforts, and change management processes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization's electronic door control system is designed so that if it loses power or communication with the access control server, the doors automatically lock rather than unlock, even though this could complicate emergency egress. This design decision reflects which security principle?","o":["Fail open","Fail secure","Least privilege","Defense in depth"],"c":1,"why":"Fail secure ensures the system defaults to a protective (locked) state upon failure, prioritizing confidentiality/access control over availability. Fail open would default to unlocked, and least privilege and defense in depth describe unrelated access and layering concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization integrates automated security scanning and threat modeling into the earliest stages of its agile development pipeline rather than waiting until after deployment. This practice is best described as which of the following?","o":["Shift-left security (DevSecOps)","Waterfall methodology","Change advisory board review","Regression testing"],"c":0,"why":"Shift-left security, a core DevSecOps principle, moves security activities earlier in the development process to find and fix issues sooner and more cheaply; waterfall, change advisory boards, and regression testing describe different processes not focused on early integration of security.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A legacy web application concatenates user input directly into SQL query strings. Developers propose three fixes: (1) escaping special characters, (2) deploying a web application firewall, and (3) rewriting queries to use parameterized statements/prepared statements. Which approach provides the strongest primary defense against SQL injection, and why?","o":["The web application firewall, because it can be updated with new signatures without changing application code","Escaping special characters, because it directly neutralizes malicious input at the point of entry","Parameterized statements, because they separate the SQL command structure from user-supplied data so input can never be interpreted as executable code","All three provide equal protection, so the choice should be based solely on implementation cost"],"c":2,"why":"Parameterized queries send data separately from the command structure, so injected input cannot alter query logic regardless of encoding tricks. WAFs and escaping are compensating/defense-in-depth controls that can be bypassed by encoding variations or logic flaws and should not be the primary control.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A software team wants to automatically identify known vulnerabilities and outdated versions in the open-source libraries bundled with their application. Which tool or technique is specifically designed for this purpose?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Runtime Application Self-Protection (RASP)"],"c":1,"why":"SCA scans an application's dependencies against databases of known vulnerabilities (e.g., CVEs) to flag risky third-party or open-source components. SAST analyzes custom source code for flaws, IAST combines runtime and code analysis for the application under test itself, and RASP provides runtime protection rather than dependency inventory analysis.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security architect needs to test a third-party web application for injection and authentication flaws, but the organization has no access to the application's source code and cannot deploy instrumentation agents inside the runtime. Which testing methodology is most appropriate?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST), because it analyzes code structure without execution","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST), because it combines runtime instrumentation with code analysis","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST), because it tests the running application externally by simulating attacks against exposed interfaces","Software Composition Analysis (SCA), because it inventories open-source components for known vulnerabilities"],"c":2,"why":"DAST operates as a black-box technique against the running application through its exposed interfaces, requiring no source code or internal instrumentation. SAST needs source code, IAST needs runtime agents/instrumentation, and SCA only identifies vulnerable dependencies rather than testing application logic.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"During QA, testers feed an application large volumes of malformed, random, and unexpected input data to observe whether it crashes, leaks memory, or behaves unpredictably. Which testing technique is being described?","o":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Unit testing","Boundary value analysis"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing involves supplying invalid, unexpected, or random data to an application to uncover crashes, memory issues, and unhandled exceptions. Regression testing verifies prior functionality still works after changes, unit testing validates individual code components, and boundary value analysis targets edge-case inputs rather than random malformed data.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A hospital database allows clinicians to view individual patient records but restricts access to reports summarizing rare-disease case counts by zip code, because a user with legitimate access to many individual records could deduce the same sensitive summary information without ever being granted access to the aggregate report. This scenario is an example of which security concern?","o":["A covert channel exploitation","An inference attack","A time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) vulnerability","A privilege escalation attack"],"c":1,"why":"Inference occurs when a subject deduces restricted information by combining pieces of data they are authorized to access. This is not a covert channel (which involves out-of-band signaling), a TOCTOU race condition, or privilege escalation, none of which describe deducing hidden aggregate facts from permitted individual records.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During an internal fraud investigation, a security analyst images a suspect's hard drive for evidence. Which action is MOST important to ensure the evidence remains admissible in a subsequent legal proceeding?","o":["Encrypting the forensic image with a strong algorithm before storage","Maintaining a documented chain of custody from collection through analysis","Using the fastest available imaging tool to minimize system downtime","Storing the original drive in the analyst's personal locked office"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation proves the evidence was not altered or tampered with, which is essential for admissibility. Encryption, speed, and informal storage do not establish evidentiary integrity or an unbroken custody record.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization detects an active ransomware infection spreading across multiple workstations. According to standard incident response methodology, what should the response team do IMMEDIATELY after detection and analysis confirm the incident?","o":["Begin eradication by wiping and reimaging all affected systems","Contain the incident by isolating affected systems from the network","Notify law enforcement and regulatory bodies","Conduct a full root cause analysis and lessons-learned review"],"c":1,"why":"Containment limits the spread of damage and is the priority immediately following detection/analysis, before eradication or recovery. Notification and lessons-learned occur later in the process, and eradication before containment risks further spread.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A file-processing utility running with elevated privileges checks whether a file is owned by the calling user and, if so, proceeds to open and modify it in a separate subsequent operation. A local attacker is able to replace the file with a symbolic link to a sensitive system file between the check and the open operation. What vulnerability class does this describe, and what is the most effective mitigation?","o":["A buffer overflow; mitigate by using bounds-checked memory functions","A time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition; mitigate by performing the check and the action as a single atomic operation","A SQL injection flaw; mitigate by using parameterized queries","An insecure deserialization flaw; mitigate by validating object types before deserialization"],"c":1,"why":"This is a classic TOCTOU race condition where the state of a resource can change between validation and use; the correct fix is to make the check-then-act sequence atomic (e.g., using file descriptors instead of paths, or OS-level atomic operations). The other options describe unrelated vulnerability classes that don't match the scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A storage administrator needs a RAID configuration that provides fault tolerance while maximizing usable storage capacity, using the fewest number of disks, and can survive the failure of exactly one drive. Which RAID level BEST meets these requirements?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 6"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 5 uses distributed parity across disks, tolerating a single drive failure while using less overhead than RAID 1 (mirroring, 50% capacity loss) and requiring fewer disks than RAID 6 (which tolerates two failures). RAID 0 offers no fault tolerance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A development team uses inheritance extensively, and a subclass overrides a parent class's method that performs an authorization check, replacing it with a version that always returns 'authorized.' Because polymorphism allows the subclass instance to be used wherever the parent class is expected, this override goes undetected during integration. Which secure coding principle was most directly violated?","o":["Fail-safe defaults, because the override should have denied access by default","The Liskov Substitution Principle in a security context, since the subclass altered the expected security-relevant behavior of the parent class in a way that breaks callers' security assumptions","Least privilege, because the subclass was granted more privilege than necessary","Separation of duties, because a single class should not perform both authorization and business logic"],"c":1,"why":"The core issue is that substituting the subclass violates the caller's reasonable expectation of consistent security behavior (a security-relevant Liskov substitution violation), enabling silent authorization bypass. While fail-safe defaults is a related concept, the specific defect described is an object-oriented design/behavioral substitution flaw, not a configuration default, privilege assignment, or duty separation issue.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During live incident response on a compromised production server that cannot be taken offline immediately, a forensic analyst must collect volatile evidence before it is lost. Which of the following represents the CORRECT order of volatility for collecting this evidence, from MOST volatile to LEAST volatile?","o":["CPU registers and cache, RAM contents, network connections/ARP cache, local disk storage, archival backup media","Local disk storage, RAM contents, network connections/ARP cache, CPU registers and cache, archival backup media","Archival backup media, local disk storage, RAM contents, network connections/ARP cache, CPU registers and cache","RAM contents, local disk storage, CPU registers and cache, network connections/ARP cache, archival backup media"],"c":0,"why":"Order of volatility dictates collecting the most transient data first: CPU registers/cache, then RAM, then network state, then disk, then archival media. The other orderings collect highly volatile data (registers, RAM, network state) too late, risking permanent loss of critical evidence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A backup administrator wants to minimize the time required to restore data after a failure while also minimizing daily backup storage and processing time. The environment already performs weekly full backups. Which backup strategy BEST balances these competing goals?","o":["Daily incremental backups, requiring the full backup plus all incrementals to restore","Daily differential backups, requiring the full backup plus only the latest differential to restore","Daily full backups every day of the week","Continuous data protection with no periodic full backups"],"c":1,"why":"Differential backups capture all changes since the last full backup, so restoration only requires the full backup plus the most recent differential, speeding recovery compared to incremental chains. Daily full backups consume excessive storage/time, and incrementals require restoring multiple sets sequentially.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis determines that a critical order-processing system has a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 8 hours. The disaster recovery plan states that the technical restoration of the system (RTO) must be completed within 5 hours of the outage. Based on this, what is the maximum allowable Work Recovery Time (WRT) to ensure the organization stays within the MTD?","o":["8 hours","5 hours","3 hours","13 hours"],"c":2,"why":"WRT is the time remaining after systems are technically restored (RTO) to fully verify and resume business operations, calculated as MTD minus RTO (8 - 5 = 3 hours). 8 hours ignores the RTO already consumed, 5 hours confuses WRT with RTO, and 13 hours incorrectly adds the values instead of subtracting.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A developer implements encryption for stored credit card data using AES in ECB (Electronic Codebook) mode with a key hardcoded into the application binary. A security review flags multiple issues. Which of the following is the MOST significant flaw from a cryptographic design perspective, independent of the hardcoded key issue?","o":["ECB mode encrypts identical plaintext blocks into identical ciphertext blocks, revealing patterns in the underlying structured data","AES is a deprecated algorithm and should be replaced with DES for compliance","AES requires a hardware security module and cannot be implemented in software","ECB mode requires an initialization vector, and omitting it caused the vulnerability"],"c":0,"why":"ECB mode's lack of chaining means identical plaintext blocks always produce identical ciphertext, leaking structural patterns (a well-known cryptographic weakness distinct from key management); AES is not deprecated, does not require an HSM, and ECB mode does not use an IV at all, making the last option factually incorrect.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A change advisory board (CAB) is reviewing a proposed emergency change to patch a critical vulnerability being actively exploited. Which of the following BEST reflects proper change management practice in this scenario?","o":["Bypass the change management process entirely since the vulnerability is actively exploited","Apply the patch immediately without testing to reduce exposure time, then document it after the fact","Use an expedited emergency change process that still includes risk assessment, approval, and documentation","Wait for the next scheduled monthly CAB meeting to review and approve the change"],"c":2,"why":"Emergency change procedures allow expedited handling of urgent changes while still requiring risk assessment, appropriate approval, and documentation to maintain control and accountability. Skipping the process entirely or acting without any review introduces uncontrolled risk, while waiting for a scheduled meeting is inappropriate given active exploitation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A storage architect must design a RAID array that can survive the simultaneous failure of any two drives in the set while using less raw storage overhead than a fully mirrored solution. Which RAID level BEST meets this requirement?","o":["RAID 5","RAID 6","RAID 10","RAID 0"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 6 uses dual distributed parity, allowing the array to tolerate any two simultaneous drive failures with less overhead than RAID 10's full mirroring. RAID 5 tolerates only a single failure, RAID 10 can only guarantee survival of two failures if they occur in different mirrored pairs, and RAID 0 offers no fault tolerance at all.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security operations center (SOC) analyst configures a SIEM to correlate failed login attempts across multiple systems from a single source IP within a short time window. This is an example of which security operations capability?","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Event correlation for anomaly detection","Data loss prevention","Configuration management"],"c":1,"why":"Correlating events across multiple sources to identify patterns like distributed failed logins is a core SIEM function used for anomaly and attack detection. Vulnerability scanning, DLP, and configuration management address different operational concerns.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An investigator seizes a hard drive as evidence and later creates a forensic image for analysis using a write blocker. Which action provides the STRONGEST assurance that the original evidence was not altered and best supports admissibility of the evidence in court?","o":["Recording the drive's make, model, and serial number on the chain-of-custody form","Calculating a cryptographic hash of the original drive before imaging, hashing the resulting image, and confirming both hashes match","Storing the original drive in a locked evidence room accessible only to the lead investigator","Ensuring that only one examiner handles the evidence for the duration of the case"],"c":1,"why":"Matching cryptographic hashes of the original media and the forensic image provides mathematical proof that the image is an exact, unaltered copy, which is the strongest technical control for integrity and admissibility. Documentation, restricted storage access, and single-examiner handling support chain of custody but do not themselves prove the data was not altered.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization's business continuity plan testing schedule calls for an exercise where participants discuss their roles and responses to a hypothetical disaster scenario in a conference room, without activating any actual systems or facilities. Which type of BCP test is being described?","o":["Full interruption test","Parallel test","Simulation test","Tabletop exercise"],"c":3,"why":"A tabletop exercise involves discussion-based walkthroughs of roles and procedures without activating systems. A simulation test involves more active role-play with mock scenarios, a parallel test activates alternate systems alongside production, and a full interruption test actually shuts down primary operations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During a critical production outage, a system administrator applies an emergency configuration change to restore service without obtaining prior approval from the Change Advisory Board (CAB). Within a mature change management process, which of the following is the BEST way to handle this situation afterward?","o":["Immediately revert the change until formal CAB approval is obtained, even though the outage will resume","Take no further action since the change successfully resolved the outage","Document the change thoroughly and submit it for expedited retrospective review and formal approval by the CAB as soon as possible","Automatically discipline the administrator for bypassing the standard change management process"],"c":2,"why":"Mature change management processes include a defined emergency change procedure that permits urgent action to restore service, followed by mandatory documentation and retrospective CAB review to ensure accountability and process integrity. Reverting a working fix would cause unnecessary downtime, taking no action bypasses governance entirely, and automatic discipline is not part of a properly designed emergency change process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"Prior to disposing of decommissioned hard drives that once stored highly sensitive financial records, which method provides the HIGHEST assurance that data cannot be recovered?","o":["Deleting all files and emptying the recycle bin","Performing a quick format of the drive","Physical destruction of the drive via shredding or degaussing","Overwriting the drive once with random data"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction (shredding, degaussing, or incineration) provides the highest assurance of data irrecoverability for highly sensitive data, especially for drives being fully decommissioned. Deletion and quick formatting leave data recoverable, and a single overwrite pass offers less assurance than physical destruction for highly sensitive information.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is designing fire suppression for a data center that is routinely occupied by staff during normal operations. Which suppression method provides effective fire suppression while remaining safe for use in occupied spaces, avoiding the ozone-depletion issues of older agents?","o":["Halon 1301 total flooding system","CO2 total flooding system","FM-200 (HFC-227ea) clean agent system","Wet-pipe water sprinkler system"],"c":2,"why":"FM-200 is a clean agent that suppresses fire by removing heat without displacing breathable oxygen or depleting ozone, making it suitable for occupied data centers. Halon is banned due to ozone depletion, CO2 displaces oxygen and is dangerous for occupied spaces, and wet-pipe sprinklers risk water damage to electronic equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday night, followed by daily incremental backups (backing up only data changed since the last backup, whether full or incremental) each subsequent night. A server failure occurs Friday morning, before that day's backup job runs. How many backup sets must be restored, in order, to fully recover the server?","o":["1 (only the most recent incremental)","2 (the full backup and Thursday's incremental)","5 (the full backup plus Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday incrementals)","6 (the full backup plus incrementals from Monday through Friday)"],"c":2,"why":"Because incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup of any type, restoring requires the last full backup (Sunday) plus every incremental made since, in sequence (Monday–Thursday) — five sets total, since Friday's backup never ran. Restoring only the full or only the last incremental would omit intervening changes, and there is no Friday incremental to restore.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"Per NIST SP 800-88 media sanitization guidelines, which method is MOST appropriate for sanitizing a solid-state drive (SSD) prior to disposal, given that traditional degaussing and simple overwriting are unreliable on flash-based media?","o":["Degaussing the SSD using a high-powered magnetic field","Performing a single logical overwrite pass across the drive's addressable space","Using the drive's built-in cryptographic erase or ATA/NVMe Secure Erase command, followed by verification","Reformatting the drive using the operating system's quick format utility"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use wear-leveling and over-provisioning, so logical overwrites may not reach all physical blocks, and degaussing is ineffective since flash memory is not magnetic; built-in cryptographic erase or Secure Erase commands sanitize at the controller level and are the NIST-recommended approach, followed by verification. Degaussing, single-pass overwrite, and quick format are all recognized as insufficient for reliably sanitizing SSD data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During the incident response process, which phase involves isolating affected systems to prevent further damage while preserving evidence for later analysis?","o":["Detection","Containment","Eradication","Lessons Learned"],"c":1,"why":"Containment focuses on limiting the scope and impact of an incident, such as isolating affected systems, while preserving evidence. Detection identifies the incident, eradication removes the root cause, and lessons learned occurs after recovery.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that evidence collected from a compromised server can be used in legal proceedings. Which practice is MOST important to maintain the integrity of this evidence?","o":["Encrypting the evidence before storage","Maintaining a documented chain of custody","Storing the evidence on a network share for easy access","Allowing only the system administrator to view the evidence"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation tracks who handled evidence, when, and how, which is essential for admissibility in court. Encryption and access restrictions help protect confidentiality but do not by themselves establish an unbroken record of evidence handling.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company performs a full backup every Sunday and wants to minimize the time required for daily backups while accepting a longer restore process. Which backup type should they use for Monday through Saturday?","o":["Differential backup","Incremental backup","Full backup","Mirror backup"],"c":1,"why":"Incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup (full or incremental), making daily backup jobs fast, though restoration requires applying the full backup plus all incrementals in sequence. Differential backups grow larger each day since they capture all changes since the last full backup, increasing daily backup time compared to incremental.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An administrator discovers that a critical vulnerability has been publicly disclosed for software used throughout the organization. What should be the FIRST step in addressing this through the patch management process?","o":["Immediately apply the patch to all production systems","Assess the vulnerability's risk and applicability to the organization's environment","Disable the affected software on all systems until a patch is available","Notify all employees about the vulnerability via email"],"c":1,"why":"Patch management begins with risk assessment to determine the vulnerability's relevance, severity, and potential impact before deciding on remediation actions. Immediately patching without testing or assessment can cause unplanned outages, and disabling software or mass notification are premature without understanding the actual risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A software development organization wants to ensure that security defects are identified and remediated at the lowest possible cost. At which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) should security requirements first be formally defined?","o":["During the requirements and planning phase, before design begins","During the testing phase, after code has been written","During the design phase, once the architecture has been chosen","During the maintenance phase, as vulnerabilities are discovered in production"],"c":0,"why":"Defining security requirements during requirements/planning is the most cost-effective point to address security, since flaws found later (design, testing, maintenance) are exponentially more expensive to fix and may require rework of already-completed phases.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A programmer writes code that copies user-supplied input into a fixed-size stack array without checking the input length. This coding flaw is most likely to result in which vulnerability?","o":["Race condition","Buffer overflow","Cross-site request forgery","Directory traversal"],"c":1,"why":"Copying unchecked input into a fixed-size buffer is the classic cause of a buffer overflow, which can corrupt memory or allow code execution; the other options involve different root causes unrelated to buffer size handling.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team needs to review an application's source code for insecure coding patterns, such as hardcoded credentials and improper input handling, without executing the application. Which testing technique should they use?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Manual penetration testing against a running instance"],"c":0,"why":"SAST analyzes source, byte, or binary code without executing the program, making it ideal for finding coding flaws early. DAST and IAST require the application to be running, and penetration testing targets a live system rather than raw source code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Which operating system security mechanism specifically helps mitigate exploitation of stack-based buffer overflow vulnerabilities by making the memory locations of executable code and data unpredictable to an attacker?","o":["Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)","Parameterized queries","Multi-factor authentication","Data masking"],"c":0,"why":"ASLR randomizes the memory addresses used by a process, making it difficult for an attacker to reliably predict where injected shellcode will reside after a buffer overflow. Parameterized queries address SQL injection, MFA addresses authentication, and data masking protects sensitive data at rest/display—none relate to memory address predictability.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"When decommissioning hard drives that contained sensitive customer data, which method provides the HIGHEST assurance that the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive using a quick format","Physical destruction of the drive (e.g., shredding or degaussing)","Moving the files to a different folder and renaming them"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction, such as shredding or degaussing, ensures data cannot be recovered by any means and is the highest assurance method for sensitive data disposal. Deleting files, quick formatting, or renaming files leaves the underlying data recoverable through forensic tools.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which secure coding practice is MOST effective at preventing SQL injection attacks?","o":["Encrypting the database at rest","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Increasing the length of session tokens","Disabling client-side JavaScript"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate SQL code from user data, preventing injected input from being interpreted as commands; encryption, session token length, and disabling JavaScript do not address the injection vulnerability itself.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application accepts user input directly into SQL statements without sanitization, allowing attackers to manipulate database queries. What is the most effective primary control to prevent this class of vulnerability?","o":["Using parameterized queries or prepared statements","Encrypting the database at rest","Deploying a network intrusion detection system","Disabling verbose error messages returned to users"],"c":0,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing user input from being interpreted as executable SQL, directly addressing SQL injection at its root cause. Encryption, IDS, and error message suppression are useful defense-in-depth measures but do not prevent the injection itself.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A security team examines an application's source code line-by-line, without executing the program, to identify potential vulnerabilities. This technique is known as:","o":["Dynamic analysis","Fuzz testing","Static analysis","Penetration testing"],"c":2,"why":"Static analysis reviews source or compiled code without execution; dynamic analysis, fuzzing, and penetration testing all involve running the application to observe its behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A database allows analysts to run statistical queries (e.g., average salary by department) but restricts access to individual employee records. An analyst notices that one department has only a single employee, and by querying the average salary for that department, they are able to determine that individual's exact salary. This is an example of what type of attack?","o":["Inference attack","Aggregation attack","SQL injection","Data remanence exposure"],"c":0,"why":"This is an inference attack, where sensitive individual-level information is deduced from permitted aggregate/statistical queries through logical reasoning. Aggregation refers to combining multiple low-sensitivity data elements to create a higher-sensitivity dataset, not deducing a single value from a statistical function; SQL injection and data remanence are unrelated concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of a source code repository with version control in a secure development process?","o":["To automatically encrypt all application data","To track changes, enable rollback, and maintain accountability for code modifications","To replace the need for code review","To perform automated penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"Version control systems maintain a history of changes, support rollback, and provide accountability for who changed what code; they do not perform encryption, replace code review, or conduct penetration testing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to prevent developers from accidentally committing API keys and passwords into the source code repository as part of its CI/CD pipeline. Which control would be most effective at addressing this risk?","o":["Automated secret-scanning pre-commit or pre-merge hooks integrated into the pipeline","Manual peer code review conducted once per quarter","Installing endpoint antivirus software on developer workstations","Restricting repository access to a single network segment"],"c":0,"why":"Automated secret-scanning integrated directly into the commit/merge workflow catches hardcoded secrets before they ever enter the repository, providing timely and consistent enforcement. Quarterly manual reviews are too infrequent, and antivirus or network segmentation controls do not address credential leakage in code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A company licenses critical software from a small vendor and is concerned the vendor may go out of business, leaving them without support or source code access. Which arrangement BEST addresses this risk?","o":["Software escrow agreement","Non-disclosure agreement","Service level agreement","Business associate agreement"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow agreement places source code with a trusted third party to be released if the vendor fails to meet obligations (e.g., goes out of business); the other agreements address confidentiality, performance metrics, or regulatory data handling, not source code continuity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During an incident response engagement, an analyst discovers that a compromised web server is actively exfiltrating customer data to an external IP address. According to standard incident response methodology, what should the team do FIRST before eradicating the malware?","o":["Isolate or contain the affected system to stop further data loss","Restore the server from the last known good backup","Notify all customers whose data may have been affected","Patch the vulnerability that was exploited"],"c":0,"why":"Containment must occur before eradication and recovery to stop ongoing damage and preserve evidence; restoring, notifying, or patching prematurely could destroy evidence or allow continued exfiltration while other steps are performed.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A quality assurance engineer wants to discover unknown vulnerabilities in a compiled application by automatically feeding it large volumes of malformed, unexpected, or random input and monitoring for crashes or unexpected behavior. Which testing technique is being described?","o":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Static code analysis","Unit testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing (fuzzing) involves injecting malformed or random data into an application's inputs to uncover crashes, memory leaks, and other unexpected behavior indicative of vulnerabilities. Regression and unit testing verify known functionality against expected behavior, and static analysis examines code without execution or malformed input.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A forensic analyst arrives at a running, compromised production server that must be preserved for evidence. Following the standard order of volatility for live evidence collection, which data source should be captured first, before any other?","o":["Contents of RAM","CPU registers and cache","The running process list from the operating system","Contents of the page/swap file on disk"],"c":1,"why":"CPU registers and cache are the most volatile data on a live system and are lost the instant power state changes or the CPU executes further instructions, so they must be captured first per RFC 3227 order of volatility; RAM, process lists, and swap files are less volatile and can be captured afterward.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A developer writes code that first checks whether a user has permission to access a file, then—several instructions later—opens the file for writing. A penetration tester is able to substitute a symbolic link pointing to a sensitive system file between the check and the open call, gaining unauthorized write access. Which class of vulnerability does this represent?","o":["Time-of-check to time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","Stack-based buffer overflow","Blind SQL injection","Integer overflow leading to heap corruption"],"c":0,"why":"The vulnerability arises from a timing gap between validation and use of a resource, allowing the resource to be swapped—this is the definition of a TOCTOU race condition, not a memory corruption or injection flaw.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A database allows users to query aggregate sales totals by region but not individual customer records. An analyst discovers that by combining several allowed aggregate queries, they can deduce a specific customer's purchase amount. This is an example of:","o":["An inference attack","A covert channel","A salami attack","A polyinstantiation failure"],"c":0,"why":"An inference attack occurs when a user deduces restricted information by combining multiple pieces of authorized, less-sensitive data; the other terms describe unrelated concepts such as hidden communication channels or duplicate data records for different classification levels.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A forensic investigator seizes a laptop as evidence in a fraud investigation. Which practice is MOST critical to ensure the evidence remains admissible in court?","o":["Encrypting the hard drive before analysis to protect confidentiality","Maintaining a documented chain of custody from seizure through presentation","Performing analysis only on the original physical drive to preserve authenticity","Allowing multiple investigators to independently analyze the original media"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documents who handled evidence, when, and why, which is essential for admissibility; analysis should be done on a forensic copy (not the original) to preserve integrity, and encrypting or allowing multiple people to handle the original drive would risk altering the evidence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Before deploying a security patch to a production application, an organization requires that the change be formally documented, reviewed for impact, tested in a non-production environment, approved by a change advisory board, and accompanied by a rollback plan. Which process is responsible for enforcing these requirements?","o":["Change management","Configuration management","Patch inventory tracking","Version control system logging"],"c":0,"why":"Change management governs the formal process of proposing, evaluating, approving, testing, and implementing changes—including rollback planning—to production systems. Configuration management tracks and maintains system baselines and versions but does not itself govern the approval workflow, and patch inventory or version control logging are supporting records rather than the governing process.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A CISSP is leading incident response for a ransomware outbreak that is actively encrypting file shares across several network segments. Preserving forensic evidence for a potential criminal prosecution is a stated priority. Which containment action best balances stopping the spread with preserving forensic value?","o":["Immediately power off all affected servers to stop the encryption process","Isolate the infected network segments (e.g., via quarantine VLAN or ACL) while leaving affected systems powered on","Delete the ransomware executable from each infected host as soon as it is identified","Restore all affected systems from the most recent backup immediately, without further analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Network-layer isolation halts lateral spread while preserving volatile memory that may contain encryption keys or attacker artifacts; powering off destroys RAM-resident evidence, deleting the malware destroys artifacts needed for analysis, and restoring immediately forfeits the opportunity to determine root cause and scope.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A legacy financial application builds SQL statements by concatenating user-supplied account numbers directly into calls to stored procedures. A code review finds that input length limits and single-quote escaping are already in place, yet penetration testers still achieve injection using numeric-only payloads. What is the most effective remediation?","o":["Increase the maximum input length restriction to reduce payload space","Replace dynamic string concatenation with parameterized queries using bound variables","Escape additional special characters such as semicolons and hyphens","Move the stored procedure logic into client-side JavaScript validation"],"c":1,"why":"Escaping and length limits are incomplete and bypassable defenses; parameterized queries/prepared statements separate code from data at the driver level, eliminating injection regardless of input content. The other options are partial, brittle mitigations that attackers can still circumvent.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"In a DevSecOps model, embedding automated security testing tools directly into the continuous integration/continuous deployment (CI/CD) pipeline is primarily intended to:","o":["Eliminate the need for manual code reviews entirely","Shift security testing earlier and make it a continuous part of development","Replace the requirements-gathering phase","Ensure compliance audits are no longer required"],"c":1,"why":"Embedding security tools in CI/CD reflects 'shifting security left,' catching issues earlier and continuously rather than only at the end; it supplements, not eliminates, manual review, requirements gathering, or compliance audits.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday and wants to minimize the time required to restore data after a failure, even though this increases daily backup storage and time. Which backup strategy should be used for the remaining days of the week?","o":["Incremental backups, which only capture changes since the last backup of any type","Differential backups, which capture all changes since the last full backup","Mirror backups, which continuously replicate data changes in real time","Snapshot backups, which only preserve metadata pointers to unchanged blocks"],"c":1,"why":"Differential backups only require the full backup plus the single most recent differential to restore, making restoration faster than incremental (which requires the full plus every incremental since), at the cost of larger and longer daily backups.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis established a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 4 hours for a critical ERP database. The current process performs only a single full backup nightly at midnight, with no other backup activity during the day. A catastrophic failure occurs at 3:00 p.m. What does this scenario demonstrate?","o":["The Recovery Time Objective (RTO) has been exceeded because recovery will take longer than 4 hours","The backup strategy fails to meet the RPO because as much as 15 hours of data could be lost","The Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) has been violated because the outage duration exceeds acceptable limits","The backup strategy meets the RPO because a backup exists within the last 24 hours"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable data loss measured in time; with only a nightly backup, up to 15 hours of transactions could be lost, far exceeding the 4-hour RPO. RTO and MTD relate to downtime duration, not data loss, and were not addressed by the scenario.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"In a multilevel statistical database, analysts with 'Confidential' clearance can query individual sales records, none of which are individually sensitive. However, by running a series of overlapping SUM and COUNT queries, an analyst is able to deduce a 'Secret'-level aggregate revenue figure for a classified defense program. Which control is MOST directly designed to prevent this outcome?","o":["Row-level mandatory access control labeling on each record","Polyinstantiation of the affected records at multiple classification levels","Inference controls, such as restricting minimum query set size and monitoring for correlated queries","Transparent data encryption applied to the database at rest"],"c":2,"why":"This scenario describes an inference/aggregation attack against a statistical database; the specific countermeasure is inference control (query set size restrictions, noise addition, audit of query patterns). Row labeling and polyinstantiation address direct access and covert-channel writes, not statistical inference, and encryption at rest does not stop authorized query-based inference.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A change advisory board (CAB) is reviewing a proposed emergency change to patch a critical zero-day vulnerability. The system owner argues that normal change management procedures should be bypassed entirely due to the urgency. What is the BEST response?","o":["Approve the request and skip documentation to save time given the emergency","Deny the change until the next scheduled change window regardless of risk","Follow the organization's emergency change process, which still requires expedited approval, testing where feasible, and after-the-fact documentation","Allow the system owner to implement the change without any CAB involvement since they own the system"],"c":2,"why":"Emergency changes still follow an abbreviated but defined process with expedited approval and retrospective documentation to maintain accountability and rollback capability; completely bypassing change management or delaying critical patching creates unacceptable risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A critical zero-day vulnerability is being actively exploited against an organization's internet-facing application, and the vendor has released an emergency patch. According to change management best practices, what should the organization do?","o":["Wait for the next scheduled Change Advisory Board meeting to review and approve the patch before deployment","Deploy the patch immediately through an emergency change process, then present it to the CAB for retroactive review and documentation","Deploy the patch without any documentation because the situation is time-critical","Deploy the patch during the next standard maintenance window to minimize business disruption"],"c":1,"why":"Emergency change procedures exist precisely for active-exploit scenarios, allowing rapid deployment followed by required retroactive documentation and CAB review; waiting for a scheduled meeting or maintenance window leaves the system exploitable, and skipping documentation violates change management controls.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A software vendor wants to proactively identify known vulnerabilities in the open-source libraries bundled into its product before each release, and to respond quickly when a new CVE is disclosed for a dependency already in production. Which practice BEST supports this goal?","o":["Rely on vendor attestations that all third-party code has been reviewed for security","Generate and maintain a Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) and correlate it against vulnerability feeds using software composition analysis (SCA) tools","Perform an annual manual code review of the entire third-party codebase","Conduct dynamic penetration testing only against the compiled release binary"],"c":1,"why":"An SBOM provides an inventory of components and versions, and SCA tooling automatically cross-references that inventory against vulnerability databases, enabling continuous and rapid identification of newly disclosed issues. Attestations and periodic manual review or black-box testing do not scale and cannot promptly surface newly published CVEs in specific dependency versions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A database administrator wants a RAID configuration that provides both fault tolerance and can survive the failure of any two disks simultaneously, while maximizing usable storage compared to full mirroring. Which RAID level BEST meets this requirement?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 5","RAID 6","RAID 1"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 6 uses dual distributed parity, allowing it to tolerate the failure of two disks simultaneously while using less overhead than mirroring (RAID 1); RAID 5 only tolerates one disk failure, RAID 0 offers no fault tolerance, and RAID 1 has significant storage overhead.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday at midnight and daily incremental backups Monday through Saturday. A total system failure occurs on Friday at noon, before that day's incremental backup has run. How many backup sets are required to fully restore the system to its most recent recoverable state?","o":["1 (the full backup only)","2 (the full backup and the most recent incremental)","5 (the full backup plus each incremental from Monday through Thursday)","6 (the full backup plus each incremental including Friday)"],"c":2,"why":"Incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup of any type, so restoration requires the full backup plus every subsequent incremental in sequence (Mon-Thu); Friday's incremental never ran, so it cannot be included, and a single incremental alone is insufficient because incrementals are not cumulative like differentials.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security team has access to a compiled third-party binary with no source code or documentation. They want to uncover unknown memory-corruption vulnerabilities by systematically feeding malformed and boundary-case inputs to the application and observing crashes prior to release. Which testing technique is MOST appropriate?","o":["Fuzz testing","Static application security testing (SAST)","Formal mathematical verification","Manual peer code review"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing is a dynamic, black-box technique well suited to discovering unknown vulnerabilities (like buffer overflows) in binaries without source access. SAST and manual review require source code, and formal verification requires a specification and is impractical for compiled third-party binaries.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization is selecting a disaster recovery site and needs the facility to be operational within minutes to a few hours of a disaster, with servers, network connectivity, and near-real-time data replication already in place, but at a lower cost than maintaining a fully redundant live environment. Which site type BEST fits this requirement?","o":["Cold site","Warm site","Hot site","Reciprocal agreement site"],"c":2,"why":"A hot site has fully configured hardware, network connectivity, and near-real-time replicated data, enabling recovery within minutes to hours; a warm site requires additional setup time, a cold site has only basic infrastructure, and reciprocal agreements are informal arrangements with uncertain readiness.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored highly classified data. Which sanitization method is most appropriate given the internal architecture of SSDs?","o":["Degaussing the drives using a high-powered magnetic field","Overwriting the drives three times using a legacy DoD 5220.22-M pattern","Performing a cryptographic erase of the self-encrypting drives, followed by verification","Physically wiping the drives with a standard consumer disk-wipe utility"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory with wear leveling and over-provisioning, so magnetic degaussing has no effect and overwrite patterns cannot reliably reach all physical blocks; cryptographic erase (destroying the encryption key on a self-encrypting drive) is the NIST SP 800-88 recommended method, and consumer wipe utilities cannot guarantee access to spare/reserved flash areas.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During a post-incident review, an organization discovers that a developer had committed a cloud provider API key directly into a Git repository months earlier; the key was later found and abused by an attacker. Which control would have MOST effectively prevented this exposure before the code was ever merged?","o":["Automated secrets-scanning integrated into pre-commit hooks and the CI/CD pipeline","Deploying a web application firewall in front of the production environment","Requiring annual security awareness training for all developers","Applying binary code obfuscation to the compiled release"],"c":0,"why":"Automated secrets detection at commit time and within the pipeline blocks credentials from ever entering version control, addressing the root cause. A WAF, training, and obfuscation are downstream or indirect controls that would not have stopped the key from being committed in the first place.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security operations center (SOC) analyst notices that a SIEM is generating an overwhelming number of alerts, many of which are false positives, causing analysts to miss genuine threats. Which action would MOST effectively address this problem?","o":["Disable logging for the noisiest low-priority systems to reduce alert volume","Tune correlation rules and alert thresholds based on the organization's environment and threat intelligence","Increase the number of analysts on shift to review every alert manually","Switch to a different SIEM product with a larger vendor rule set"],"c":1,"why":"Tuning correlation rules, thresholds, and whitelisting based on environmental context and threat intelligence reduces false positives while preserving detection of true threats; disabling logging creates blind spots, adding staff doesn't scale, and simply changing products doesn't fix untuned rules.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A data center housing critical, always-on servers requires an automatic fire suppression system that will not damage electronic equipment and is safe for personnel who may be present during activation. Which suppression agent is most appropriate for a new installation?","o":["A water-based wet-pipe sprinkler system","A carbon dioxide (CO2) total-flooding system","A clean agent system such as FM-200 or Inergen","A Halon 1301 total-flooding system"],"c":2,"why":"Clean agents like FM-200 and Inergen suppress fire without damaging electronics and are formulated to be used safely in occupied spaces; water damages electronic equipment, CO2 displaces oxygen and poses asphyxiation risk to occupants, and Halon production has been banned under the Montreal Protocol, making it unsuitable for new installations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization assesses its software development practices and finds that each project team follows its own ad hoc process with inconsistent documentation, though most projects manage to complete on schedule. To achieve a level where processes are standardized, documented, and tailored consistently from an organization-wide set of defined procedures, which CMMI maturity level must the organization reach?","o":["Level 1 – Initial","Level 2 – Managed","Level 3 – Defined","Level 5 – Optimizing"],"c":2,"why":"CMMI Level 3 (Defined) is characterized by organization-wide standard processes that projects tailor consistently, with documented, proactive process management. Level 2 involves basic project-level management without organizational standardization, and Level 5 involves continuous quantitative process improvement, which goes beyond simple standardization.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization is decommissioning hard drives that contained highly sensitive government data. The drives will not be reused and must be rendered completely unrecoverable per NIST SP 800-88 guidelines. Which method is MOST appropriate?","o":["Reformatting the drives using the operating system's quick format utility","Overwriting the drives once with random data using a standard file deletion tool","Physical destruction of the drives, such as shredding or degaussing followed by incineration","Deleting all files and emptying the recycle bin on each drive"],"c":2,"why":"For highly sensitive data on media that won't be reused, NIST SP 800-88 recommends destruction (physical methods like shredding or degaussing) to ensure data is completely unrecoverable; quick formatting, single overwrites, or simple file deletion leave data recoverable through forensic techniques.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A security analyst notices that an employee's badge access log shows entry into the building at 8:00 a.m., while a VPN log shows a successful login using the same account from an overseas IP address at 8:05 a.m. Which security operations capability made this anomaly detectable?","o":["Vulnerability scanning","Log correlation across disparate data sources via a SIEM","Signature-based intrusion prevention system matching","Heuristic analysis performed by antivirus software"],"c":1,"why":"Detecting an 'impossible travel' anomaly requires correlating events from unrelated systems (physical access control and VPN logs) under a single account and timeline, a core SIEM function; vulnerability scanning, IPS signatures, and antivirus heuristics operate on different data and would not identify this cross-domain behavioral anomaly.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A researcher demonstrates a stack-based buffer overflow against a compiled application by overwriting local variables to eventually overwrite the return address on the stack. Which specific compiler-level mitigation is designed to detect this exact corruption and abort execution before the function returns?","o":["Stack canary (guard value) checks","Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)","Data Execution Prevention (DEP/NX)","Strict input length validation at the API boundary"],"c":0,"why":"Stack canaries place a known guard value between buffers and control data; if overwritten, the check fails before the return instruction executes, directly detecting this attack. ASLR and DEP make exploitation harder by randomizing addresses or blocking code execution in data regions but do not detect the overflow itself, and input validation is an upstream preventive control rather than the runtime detection mechanism being asked about.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A software development team is evaluating SDLC models for a large, high-risk project where requirements are not fully understood and technical risks must be continuously assessed and mitigated before committing further resources. Which SDLC model is BEST suited for this scenario?","o":["Waterfall model","Spiral model","Rapid Application Development (RAD)","Big Bang model"],"c":1,"why":"The Spiral model explicitly incorporates iterative risk analysis at each cycle before proceeding, making it ideal for high-risk, poorly understood requirements. Waterfall is rigid and sequential, RAD focuses on speed over risk analysis, and Big Bang has no formal planning or risk management.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A code review reveals that a function copies user-supplied input into a fixed-length stack buffer using strcpy() without validating the input length. Which vulnerability class does this MOST directly introduce?","o":["Cross-site request forgery","Buffer overflow","SQL injection","Insecure deserialization"],"c":1,"why":"Copying unvalidated input into a fixed-size buffer without bounds checking is the classic root cause of a buffer overflow, potentially allowing memory corruption or code execution. CSRF, SQL injection, and insecure deserialization involve different attack vectors unrelated to unchecked buffer copying.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application constructs SQL queries by concatenating user input directly into query strings. Which remediation provides the STRONGEST protection against SQL injection?","o":["Restricting the maximum length of user input fields","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Deploying a web application firewall as the sole control","Manually escaping single quotes in the application code"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, ensuring user input is never interpreted as executable SQL, which is the most robust defense. Length restrictions, manual escaping, and WAFs alone can be bypassed and are considered secondary or compensating controls, not primary fixes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to test an application for security flaws both before and after deployment. Which statement correctly distinguishes Static Application Security Testing (SAST) from Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)?","o":["SAST executes the running application to find flaws, while DAST reviews source code without execution","SAST analyzes source or binary code without executing it, while DAST tests the application in a running state","SAST and DAST both require full access to source code to function","SAST can only be performed after deployment, while DAST is performed only during development"],"c":1,"why":"SAST (white-box) examines code/binaries without running the application, detecting issues early in development, whereas DAST (black-box) tests the application while it is executing, simulating real attacks. The other options reverse or misstate these definitions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A company licenses critical business software from a small vendor and is concerned about continuity if the vendor goes bankrupt or discontinues support. Which arrangement BEST addresses this risk?","o":["Requiring the vendor to purchase cyber liability insurance","Establishing a software escrow agreement for the source code","Negotiating a longer software license term","Requiring the vendor to provide quarterly financial statements"],"c":1,"why":"A software escrow agreement places source code with a neutral third party, releasing it to the customer under agreed conditions (e.g., vendor bankruptcy), ensuring business continuity. Insurance, longer licenses, and financial reporting do not guarantee continued access to or support of the software itself.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Two concurrent database transactions access the same record: one updates a value but has not yet committed, while the other reads the uncommitted value. If the first transaction rolls back, the second transaction has read data that never officially existed. Which concurrency control issue does this describe?","o":["Deadlock","Dirty read","Lost update","Phantom read"],"c":1,"why":"A dirty read occurs when a transaction reads uncommitted data from another transaction that is later rolled back. A lost update involves overwriting changes, a phantom read involves new rows appearing between queries, and a deadlock is a resource contention stalemate, none of which match this scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) is it MOST cost-effective to begin addressing security requirements?","o":["During the requirements and design phase, before coding begins","During the testing phase, just before deployment","During the maintenance phase, after the system is in production","During the disposal phase, when the system is retired"],"c":0,"why":"Integrating security into requirements and design ('shift left') catches issues early when they are cheapest to fix. Addressing security later in testing, maintenance, or disposal costs significantly more to remediate and may require rework of already-built components.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to discover unknown vulnerabilities in a compiled application by automatically feeding it large volumes of malformed, unexpected, or random input and monitoring for crashes or abnormal behavior. Which testing technique are they using?","o":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Boundary value analysis","Static code analysis"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing automatically generates malformed or random inputs to uncover unhandled exceptions, crashes, or vulnerabilities in running software. Regression testing verifies existing functionality after changes, boundary value analysis targets edge-case inputs manually, and static analysis examines code without execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the correct order of steps in the incident response process, according to standard security operations practice?","o":["Detection, Response, Mitigation, Reporting, Recovery, Remediation, Lessons Learned","Recovery, Detection, Response, Reporting, Mitigation, Lessons Learned","Response, Detection, Recovery, Reporting, Mitigation, Lessons Learned","Reporting, Detection, Mitigation, Response, Recovery, Lessons Learned"],"c":0,"why":"The standard incident response lifecycle begins with detecting the event, then responding and mitigating its impact, reporting to stakeholders, recovering systems, remediating root cause, and capturing lessons learned. The other orderings place recovery or reporting before detection/response, which is illogical.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An application accepts user input and directly concatenates it into a SQL query string. Which technique is the MOST effective defense against SQL injection in this scenario?","o":["Using parameterized queries (prepared statements) with bound variables","Increasing the length limit on the input field","Encrypting the database connection with TLS","Storing the database credentials in a configuration file"],"c":0,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing attacker-supplied input from being interpreted as SQL commands. Encrypting the connection, adjusting field length, or securing credential storage do not prevent injection because the underlying query construction remains vulnerable.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A development team is integrating numerous open-source libraries into a new application and wants to identify known vulnerabilities and license compliance issues in these third-party components. Which practice should they implement?","o":["Software Composition Analysis (SCA)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Code coverage analysis","Penetration testing of the production environment"],"c":0,"why":"Software Composition Analysis specifically scans and inventories third-party and open-source components to identify known vulnerabilities (e.g., via CVE databases) and license obligations. DAST tests running application behavior, code coverage measures test thoroughness, and penetration testing assesses overall system security rather than component-level dependency risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During an internal investigation, an administrator seizes a hard drive believed to contain evidence of misconduct. Which practice is MOST important to preserve the evidentiary value of the drive?","o":["Immediately analyzing the original drive with forensic software to save time","Maintaining a documented chain of custody showing everyone who handled the evidence and when","Storing the drive in a locked cabinet without any documentation","Copying files from the drive to a shared network folder for team review"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation proves the evidence was properly controlled and not tampered with, which is essential for admissibility. Working directly on the original drive or copying files casually can alter or contaminate evidence, and undocumented storage fails to prove integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A security team wants to analyze an application's source code for vulnerabilities without executing the program. Which testing approach should they use?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":0,"why":"SAST examines source code, bytecode, or binaries without executing the application, making it ideal for early-stage code review. DAST, fuzzing, and penetration testing all require the application to be running.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company performs a full backup every Sunday and wants a backup strategy that minimizes the time needed to restore data after a failure occurring on a Thursday, even though it will require more storage than incremental backups. Which backup type should be used on the other days?","o":["Incremental backup","Differential backup","Mirror backup only","Snapshot backup with no full backup"],"c":1,"why":"Differential backups capture all changes since the last full backup, so restoration only requires the full backup plus the most recent differential, speeding recovery at the cost of larger backup size compared to incremental backups, which only capture changes since the last backup of any type.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of using a version control system (such as Git) in secure software development?","o":["To track and manage changes to source code, enabling accountability and rollback to previous known-good states","To automatically remove all vulnerabilities from submitted code","To encrypt source code so it cannot be read by unauthorized developers","To replace the need for code review and testing"],"c":0,"why":"Version control systems track changes over time, providing accountability, collaboration history, and the ability to roll back to a prior stable version if a defect or vulnerability is introduced. They do not automatically fix vulnerabilities, encrypt code, or eliminate the need for review/testing.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to improve disk fault tolerance by striping data with parity across multiple disks so that if one disk fails, data can still be reconstructed. Which RAID level BEST describes this configuration?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 10 without parity"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 5 stripes data with distributed parity across disks, allowing reconstruction of data if a single disk fails. RAID 0 offers no redundancy, RAID 1 uses mirroring rather than parity striping, and 'RAID 10 without parity' is not an accurate description of any standard RAID level.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"In database security, which term describes the situation where a user combines multiple pieces of non-sensitive information to deduce sensitive information they are not authorized to know?","o":["Inference","Aggregation","Polyinstantiation","Normalization"],"c":0,"why":"Inference occurs when a user deduces restricted information by reasoning from available, lower-sensitivity data. Aggregation refers to combining individual data elements to form a more sensitive collection (a related but distinct concept), while polyinstantiation and normalization are unrelated database concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which media sanitization method is generally considered the MOST effective for ensuring data on a solid-state drive (SSD) cannot be recovered, especially when the drive will be reused within the organization?","o":["Degaussing the drive","Deleting files and emptying the recycle bin","Using a vendor-supported cryptographic erase or secure purge command","Reformatting the drive using a quick format"],"c":2,"why":"Because SSDs use flash memory rather than magnetic storage, degaussing is ineffective, and simple deletion or quick formatting leaves data recoverable. Cryptographic erase or vendor-supported secure purge commands are designed specifically for SSDs and reliably render data unrecoverable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires that all proposed modifications to production application code be documented, reviewed, tested, and formally approved before deployment. This process is an example of which security practice?","o":["Change management","Configuration management baseline","Incident response","Business continuity planning"],"c":0,"why":"Change management ensures that modifications are reviewed, tested, and approved before implementation, reducing the risk of unauthorized or disruptive changes. Configuration management baselining documents system state, incident response handles security events, and business continuity planning addresses disruption recovery—none of which describe the approval process for code changes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A hospital's business continuity plan focuses on keeping critical patient-care functions running during a disruption, while a separate plan details how to restore the data center's servers and network after a hurricane. Which of the following BEST describes the second plan?","o":["Business continuity plan (BCP)","Disaster recovery plan (DRP)","Business impact analysis (BIA)","Incident response plan (IRP)"],"c":1,"why":"A disaster recovery plan specifically addresses restoring IT infrastructure and systems after a disruptive event, whereas the BCP addresses maintaining overall business operations. A BIA identifies critical functions and impact but is not itself a recovery plan, and an IRP focuses on handling security incidents.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"To reduce the risk of a single employee committing fraud undetected, an organization requires that the person who initiates a wire transfer cannot also be the person who approves it. This is an example of which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties divides critical tasks among multiple people so no single individual can complete a sensitive process alone, reducing fraud risk. Least privilege limits access rights, job rotation moves staff between roles over time, and mandatory vacation forces time away to help detect fraud, none of which directly describe splitting transaction initiation and approval.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"When designing an API that allows third-party applications to access user data, which principle dictates that each API consumer should only be granted the minimum permissions necessary to perform its specific function?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity"],"c":0,"why":"Least privilege ensures that each API client or consumer receives only the access rights needed for its intended function, limiting potential damage from compromise or misuse. Separation of duties involves dividing tasks among multiple parties, defense in depth layers multiple controls, and security through obscurity relies on hiding implementation details rather than restricting access.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization detects that ransomware is actively encrypting files on several workstations connected to the corporate network. According to standard incident response methodology, what should the incident response team do immediately after confirming the incident (identification phase)?","o":["Isolate the affected systems from the network to contain the spread","Restore all affected systems from the most recent backup","Perform a full forensic disk image of every affected workstation","Notify law enforcement and regulatory bodies of the breach"],"c":0,"why":"Containment is the next step after identification and takes priority to stop further damage; restoration, deep forensic imaging, and external notification are appropriate later steps in eradication, recovery, and post-incident phases.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A forensic investigator is collecting evidence from a live, running server suspected of being compromised. Per the order-of-volatility principle, which data source should be collected FIRST?","o":["Contents of CPU registers and cache","Contents of the local hard disk","Remote syslog server entries","Backup tapes stored offsite"],"c":0,"why":"CPU registers and cache are the most volatile and will be lost almost immediately if not captured first; disk contents, remote logs, and backup tapes are progressively less volatile and can be collected afterward.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A forensic investigator uses a hardware write blocker to create a bit-for-bit image of a suspect drive. The SHA-256 hash calculated from the completed image does not match the hash calculated from the original drive before imaging began. Which action BEST preserves the evidentiary integrity of the investigation?","o":["Discard the original hash value and adopt the new image's hash as the baseline going forward","Assume a hash collision occurred and proceed with analysis of the image as acquired","Document the discrepancy, verify the integrity and function of the write blocker and imaging tool, and re-acquire the image while maintaining full chain-of-custody documentation","Use the mismatched image for analysis since SHA-256 collisions are statistically common enough to disregard"],"c":2,"why":"A hash mismatch indicates the acquisition may not be a faithful copy, so proper procedure requires documenting the anomaly, validating tools, and re-imaging to maintain defensibility. SHA-256 collisions are not practically common, and using an unverified image or arbitrarily changing the baseline hash would destroy the chain of custody.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A system administrator must apply an emergency patch to remediate a vulnerability that is actively being exploited in the wild, and there is no time to wait for the next scheduled Change Advisory Board (CAB) meeting. Which action BEST maintains the integrity of the change management process while addressing the urgency?","o":["Apply the patch immediately and document it for expedited, retroactive CAB review and approval","Skip formal change management entirely since the situation is an emergency","Wait until the next regularly scheduled CAB meeting before applying the patch","Apply the patch only after obtaining informal verbal approval from a single manager, with no documentation"],"c":0,"why":"Emergency change procedures allow rapid implementation followed by prompt documentation and retroactive review, preserving accountability and traceability; bypassing the process entirely or delaying critical patching both create unacceptable risk or process gaps.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A financial firm's business continuity plan specifies a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 15 minutes for its trading database. The database currently relies solely on a full backup taken nightly at midnight, with no other backup mechanism. A server crash occurs at 14:30, requiring restoration from the previous night's backup. Which statement correctly evaluates this situation?","o":["The RPO is met because the Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 4 hours was not exceeded during restoration","The RPO is violated because up to 14.5 hours of transaction data will be lost, far exceeding the 15-minute target","The RPO is not applicable in this scenario since the Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) was not exceeded","The RPO is satisfied because the nightly backup completed successfully without errors"],"c":1,"why":"RPO measures acceptable data loss, not restoration time or backup success; with only nightly full backups, up to 14.5 hours of data would be lost, violating a 15-minute RPO. The other options confuse RPO with RTO/MTD or backup completion status.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company performs a full backup every Sunday night and a differential backup every other night of the week. On Thursday morning, the server's primary disk fails and must be restored. Which backups are required to fully restore the system, and in what combination?","o":["The Sunday full backup plus only the most recent (Wednesday night) differential backup","The Sunday full backup plus every differential backup taken since Sunday","Only the Wednesday night differential backup","The Sunday full backup plus the Thursday incremental backup"],"c":0,"why":"A differential backup captures all changes since the last full backup, so only the full backup plus the single most recent differential are needed; incremental backups (which capture changes since the last backup of any type) would require all increments, but that is not the scheme described here.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A storage administrator must design a disk array that can tolerate the simultaneous failure of any two disks while maximizing usable capacity relative to a mirrored solution. Which RAID level should be selected?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 5","RAID 6","RAID 10"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 6 uses dual distributed parity, allowing survival of two simultaneous disk failures with better capacity efficiency than RAID 10's mirroring. RAID 0 offers no redundancy, RAID 5 tolerates only a single disk failure, and RAID 10 sacrifices more capacity to mirroring.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A data center is designing a storage array that must remain fully operational even if any two disks fail simultaneously. Which RAID level should be implemented to meet this requirement?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 6"],"c":3,"why":"RAID 6 uses dual distributed parity, allowing the array to survive the simultaneous failure of two disks; RAID 0 offers no redundancy, RAID 1 only mirrors and typically tolerates a single disk failure, and RAID 5 tolerates only one disk failure.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning solid-state drives (SSDs) that previously stored Top Secret data. Per NIST SP 800-88 guidance, which sanitization approach is MOST appropriate given the sensitivity of the data and the characteristics of flash-based media?","o":["Degauss the drives using a high-powered magnetic degausser","Overwrite the drives once with zeros using standard disk-wipe software","Physically destroy the drives (e.g., shredding or disintegration), since wear leveling makes logical overwriting unreliable for ensuring complete data removal","Perform a low-level format and reissue the drives for internal reuse"],"c":2,"why":"NIST SP 800-88 recognizes that degaussing is ineffective on non-magnetic flash media and that wear leveling can leave remnant data inaccessible to standard overwrite tools, making physical destruction the appropriate 'Destroy' method for highly sensitive data. Formatting or single-pass overwriting does not guarantee purge-level assurance on SSDs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A business continuity plan states that the maximum tolerable data loss for a critical database is 4 hours, and the system must be brought back online within 8 hours of a disruption. Which of the following correctly identifies the RPO and RTO for this system?","o":["RPO = 4 hours, RTO = 8 hours","RPO = 8 hours, RTO = 4 hours","RPO = RTO = 4 hours","RPO = RTO = 8 hours"],"c":0,"why":"Recovery Point Objective (RPO) defines the maximum acceptable data loss measured in time, and Recovery Time Objective (RTO) defines the maximum acceptable downtime; here these map directly to 4 hours and 8 hours respectively, not the reverse or equal values.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During a critical production outage, an engineer bypasses the Change Advisory Board (CAB) and applies an untested hotfix directly to a production system to restore service. Which statement BEST reflects sound change management practice in this situation?","o":["This is a policy violation regardless of circumstances and must never occur under any change management framework","This is acceptable only if a formal emergency change process is followed, including post-implementation documentation and retroactive CAB review","Emergency changes are exempt from documentation requirements because speed is the priority","Configuration management processes automatically supersede change management procedures during emergencies"],"c":1,"why":"Mature change management frameworks include a defined emergency change process that allows expedited action while still requiring retroactive review, approval, and documentation to maintain control and auditability. Blanket prohibition, skipping documentation, or conflating configuration management with change management are all incorrect characterizations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm's development team currently performs all security testing during final QA, just before production release. Which change best exemplifies the 'shift-left' security principle and would most reduce the cost of fixing defects?","o":["Increase the frequency and depth of penetration testing conducted during the QA phase","Perform threat modeling and secure design review during the requirements and design phases","Deploy a web application firewall in front of the production environment","Require code signing certificates for all release builds"],"c":1,"why":"Shift-left means moving security activities earlier in the SDLC (requirements/design), where threat modeling catches design flaws that are far cheaper to fix than defects found in QA or production. The other options address later stages (testing, runtime protection, integrity verification) rather than moving activities earlier.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A legacy application written in C cannot be rewritten in a memory-safe language in the short term. Which combination of platform-level mitigations would most effectively reduce the exploitability of stack-based buffer overflow vulnerabilities without modifying application source code?","o":["Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR), stack canaries, and Data Execution Prevention (DEP/NX)","Strict input length validation implemented only at the database layer","Full-disk encryption combined with TLS for all network traffic","Digitally signing the compiled binary before deployment"],"c":0,"why":"ASLR, stack canaries, and DEP/NX are OS/compiler-level exploit mitigations that make buffer overflow exploitation significantly harder without requiring source changes. Database-layer validation doesn't address memory corruption, and encryption or code signing protect confidentiality/integrity rather than runtime memory safety.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During an active ransomware outbreak spreading via SMB across network segments, incident responders must choose a containment strategy. Which approach BEST balances stopping further spread with preserving forensic evidence?","o":["Immediately power off all affected systems to halt encryption activity","Isolate affected systems from the network via segmentation or VLAN reconfiguration while keeping systems powered on to allow volatile memory forensics","Delay any containment action until a complete eradication and recovery plan is formally approved","Restore all affected systems from backup immediately without isolating currently infected hosts"],"c":1,"why":"Network isolation while keeping systems running preserves volatile evidence (memory, active connections) for analysis while stopping lateral spread; powering off systems destroys volatile evidence, delaying containment allows continued damage, and restoring without isolation risks immediate reinfection.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A data analyst has authorized access to individual, de-identified patient records for research purposes but is not permitted to see identifying information. By cross-referencing the results of several authorized queries with publicly available demographic data, the analyst deduces the identity of a specific patient. This scenario is best described as which type of attack?","o":["Aggregation attack","Inference attack","Polyinstantiation exploit","SQL injection"],"c":1,"why":"Inference occurs when a subject deduces restricted information by correlating accessible data with other available knowledge, without directly accessing the protected field. Aggregation instead refers to combining many individually low-sensitivity data elements that together become sensitive; polyinstantiation and SQL injection are unrelated to this deduction-based scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is updating its Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) methodology to better integrate security. During which phase should security requirements be formally identified and documented, based on business and regulatory needs?","o":["Design phase, after the architecture has been drafted","Requirements/analysis phase, before design begins","Testing phase, once code has been written","Maintenance phase, after deployment"],"c":1,"why":"Security requirements must be captured during requirements analysis so they can drive design decisions; defining them later (design, testing, or maintenance) results in costly rework and gaps because architecture and code would already be built without them in mind.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday night and an incremental backup every subsequent night (Monday through Saturday). The server fails on Friday morning before that day's backup runs. How many backup sets must be restored, in order, to recover the system to its state as of Thursday night?","o":["Two backup sets: the full backup and Thursday's incremental","Five backup sets: the full backup plus the Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday incrementals","One backup set: only the most recent incremental","Four backup sets: only the incrementals from Monday through Thursday"],"c":1,"why":"Incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup of any type, so restoring requires the full backup plus every incremental in sequence up to the desired recovery point—five sets total. Differential backups would only require the full plus the latest differential, which is a common point of confusion reflected in the distractors.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During a security audit of a software development environment, auditors find that developers can push code changes directly to the production environment without any independent review, testing sign-off, or approval record. Which software configuration management control is most critically absent?","o":["Static application security testing integrated into the IDE","A formal change control process requiring independent review and approval before promotion to production","Automated code obfuscation prior to compilation","An incident response plan for production outages"],"c":1,"why":"The described weakness is the lack of segregation of duties and an approval workflow (change control board) before code reaches production. SAST, obfuscation, and IR plans address vulnerability detection, reverse-engineering resistance, and post-incident handling respectively, not unauthorized/unreviewed promotion of code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application accepts user-supplied data and inserts it directly into SQL queries using string concatenation. Which remediation provides the strongest structural defense against SQL injection?","o":["Rely on input validation using a blacklist of known malicious characters","Use parameterized queries (prepared statements) to separate code from data","Deploy a web application firewall in front of the application","HTML-encode all output returned to the browser"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries ensure user input is always treated as data, not executable SQL, eliminating the injection vector at the code level. Blacklisting is easily bypassed, a WAF is only a compensating control, and output encoding addresses XSS, not SQL injection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is upgrading fire suppression for its data center and must select a system that minimizes equipment damage, provides effective suppression, and complies with environmental regulations restricting ozone-depleting substances. Which system BEST meets these requirements?","o":["A Halon 1301 total-flooding system","A wet-pipe water sprinkler system","A clean agent system using FM-200 (HFC-227ea)","A CO2 total-flooding system designed for use in occupied spaces"],"c":2,"why":"Clean agents like FM-200 suppress fire effectively, leave no residue, and are not ozone-depleting, making them suitable for occupied data centers. Halon is restricted due to ozone depletion, water sprinklers risk damaging electronic equipment, and high-concentration CO2 flooding poses asphyxiation risk in occupied spaces.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security team must assess a closed-source, third-party binary application for vulnerabilities related to malformed or unexpected input handling, and no source code is available. Which testing technique is most appropriate?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Manual secure code review","Software composition analysis (SCA)"],"c":1,"why":"Fuzz testing is a dynamic technique that feeds malformed or random input to a running application and does not require source code, making it ideal here. SAST and manual code review require source access, and SCA identifies known-vulnerable components rather than input-handling flaws.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to analyze an application's source code for vulnerabilities such as hardcoded credentials and insecure API calls without executing the application. Which testing technique should they use?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source, byte, or binary code without running the application, making it well suited to find issues like hardcoded secrets early in development. DAST, fuzzing, and penetration testing all require the application to be running.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A REST API exposes an endpoint '/api/users/{id}/invoices' that returns invoice data for the specified user ID. Testing reveals that any authenticated user can retrieve another user's invoices simply by changing the {id} value in the URL, regardless of account ownership. This vulnerability is best categorized as:","o":["Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA)","Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)","Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)","Security misconfiguration"],"c":0,"why":"BOLA occurs when an API fails to verify that the authenticated user is authorized to access the specific object referenced by an identifier, exactly as described. CSRF tricks a browser into performing unwanted actions, SSRF causes the server to make unintended requests, and generic misconfiguration doesn't specifically describe this authorization flaw.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A legacy C application crashes when a user enters a string longer than the allocated memory buffer, allowing an attacker to potentially execute arbitrary code. What is the root cause of this vulnerability?","o":["Insufficient session timeout configuration","Lack of proper bounds checking on input length","Use of outdated encryption algorithms","Absence of centralized logging"],"c":1,"why":"This describes a classic buffer overflow, caused by the program writing more data into a buffer than it can hold because input length was not validated against the buffer size. Session timeouts, encryption, and logging are unrelated to this memory corruption issue.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"In an object-oriented application, a subclass overrides a security-critical method inherited from a base class that enforces an access control check, and the override omits the check, allowing bypass. Which secure design practice would best prevent this specific risk?","o":["Marking the security-critical method as final/sealed so it cannot be overridden","Using dynamic (late) binding for all methods to increase flexibility","Increasing the use of multiple inheritance across the class hierarchy","Making all class members public to simplify testing"],"c":0,"why":"Declaring the security-critical method final (or sealed) prevents subclasses from overriding and removing the enforced check, directly addressing the root cause. Dynamic binding and multiple inheritance increase flexibility but also increase attack surface for this exact issue, and making members public violates encapsulation and would worsen security.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that only reviewed and formally approved code changes are promoted from a development environment into production. Which control most directly achieves this goal?","o":["Maintaining source code in a version control system","A formal change management process incorporating segregation of duties and approval gates","Performing unit testing on all new code","Conducting periodic code reviews after deployment"],"c":1,"why":"A change management process with segregation of duties and approvals ensures changes are authorized before reaching production. Version control tracks changes but doesn't enforce authorization, unit testing checks functionality rather than approval, and post-deployment reviews occur too late to prevent unauthorized releases.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization depends on a business-critical application built by a small third-party vendor. Leadership is concerned the vendor could go out of business, leaving the organization unable to maintain or modify the application. Which contractual arrangement best addresses this risk?","o":["A software escrow agreement requiring source code and build materials to be held by a neutral third party","A standard service level agreement (SLA) specifying uptime guarantees","A right-to-audit clause allowing periodic security assessments of the vendor","A perpetual license granting unlimited use of the compiled application"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow agreement ensures that source code and build/deployment materials are released to the customer under defined trigger conditions, such as vendor bankruptcy, preserving business continuity. SLAs and audit rights address service quality and security assurance but not code availability, and a perpetual license to the compiled binary alone doesn't provide access to source code needed for maintenance.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is evaluating testing tools for a critical financial application. She wants a technique that instruments the application code with sensors while it runs under real user or automated interaction, allowing it to see both the data flow (like dynamic testing) and the actual source code path executed (like static testing) in order to reduce false positives common to black-box scanning. Which testing approach best fits this requirement?","o":["Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST) run against the compiled binary","Fuzz testing with random input generation","Manual black-box penetration testing"],"c":0,"why":"IAST uses instrumentation/agents inside the running application to correlate runtime behavior with source code execution paths, combining strengths of SAST and DAST and reducing false positives. SAST alone cannot see runtime data flow, fuzzing is random and lacks code visibility, and manual black-box testing has no code-level insight.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During a software configuration management audit, an assessor discovers that developers can push code directly to the production branch without any peer review, and there is no record linking a given production binary back to the exact source commit, test results, and approval that produced it. Which control gap is most directly responsible for this finding?","o":["Lack of a formal change and release management process with build traceability","Absence of static code analysis in the IDE","Failure to encrypt the source code repository at rest","Insufficient input validation in the application code"],"c":0,"why":"The scenario describes missing traceability between source, build, and release artifacts and lack of review gates—core failures of change/release management and configuration management, not a code-level or encryption issue. SAST, encryption at rest, and input validation address different problems entirely.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A database administrator notices that a user with access only to aggregate sales totals per region is able to repeatedly query slightly different aggregate combinations and, by comparing the results, deduce the exact salary of a specific named employee, even though that employee's individual record is never directly returned. This is best classified as which type of attack?","o":["SQL injection","Inference attack via aggregation","Broken object-level authorization","Cross-site request forgery"],"c":1,"why":"Deriving restricted data by combining multiple permitted aggregate queries is a classic inference attack enabled by weak aggregation controls, not an injection flaw, an API authorization flaw, or a web session forgery issue.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A database contains individual employee records that are not classified as sensitive. An analyst notices that by querying salary bands for all employees except one, they can deduce the exact salary of the excluded employee. What type of attack does this represent?","o":["Aggregation attack","Inference attack","SQL injection attack","Polyinstantiation"],"c":1,"why":"This is an inference attack, where an individual deduces sensitive information (a specific salary) by reasoning from non-sensitive data. An aggregation attack instead involves combining many low-sensitivity records to produce a single high-sensitivity result; SQL injection and polyinstantiation are unrelated concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A mobile banking API allows an authenticated user to retrieve their own account statement via GET /accounts/{accountId}/statement. A penetration tester finds that by simply changing the accountId value in the URL to another customer's account number, they can retrieve that customer's statement without any additional authorization check on the server. Which vulnerability class does this represent?","o":["Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA)","Insecure Direct Object Reference in a legacy monolith only","Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)","Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)"],"c":0,"why":"This is the API-specific manifestation of authorization failure where object ownership is not verified server-side—known in API security as Broken Object Level Authorization. It is not XSS or SSRF, and while related to classic IDOR, the API context and OWASP API Top 10 terminology make BOLA the precise, current classification.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An attacker submits a web form input of ' OR '1'='1 into a login field, hoping to bypass authentication. Which type of attack is being attempted?","o":["Cross-site scripting (XSS)","SQL injection","Buffer overflow","Session hijacking"],"c":1,"why":"The classic ' OR '1'='1 payload is used to manipulate SQL queries and is the hallmark of a SQL injection attack; XSS involves script injection into pages, buffer overflow involves memory corruption, and session hijacking targets active sessions, not query logic.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A development team wants to identify open-source libraries used in their application that have known published vulnerabilities (CVEs) so they can prioritize patching. Which practice best supports this goal?","o":["Software Composition Analysis (SCA)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Code style linting","Manual license review only"],"c":0,"why":"SCA tools scan an application's dependencies to identify open-source and third-party components and cross-reference them against vulnerability databases. DAST tests running applications for behavior-based flaws, linting checks code style, and license review alone does not address security vulnerabilities.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization adopting a secure SDLC wants to identify design-level security flaws, such as trust boundary violations and missing authentication on a new microservice architecture, before any code is written. At which phase should this activity be performed, and what is the primary technique used?","o":["Requirements phase, using data classification only","Design phase, using threat modeling (e.g., STRIDE/DFD analysis)","Testing phase, using dynamic application security testing","Maintenance phase, using patch management review"],"c":1,"why":"Threat modeling during the design phase identifies architectural flaws like trust boundary violations before implementation, which is far more cost-effective than finding them via testing or after deployment. Data classification and patch management address different lifecycle concerns, and DAST requires a running application, which doesn't exist yet.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which secure coding practice is MOST effective at preventing SQL injection vulnerabilities?","o":["Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Encrypting the database at rest","Implementing strong password policies","Enabling verbose error messages for debugging"],"c":0,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing attacker input from altering query structure; encryption at rest, password policies, and verbose errors do not address injection flaws and verbose errors can even aid attackers.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"During a security review of a REST API, a tester changes the numeric ID in the URL (e.g., /orders/1005) to a different value and successfully retrieves another customer's order data, even though they are not authorized to view it. Which vulnerability class does this best represent?","o":["Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA)","SQL injection","Security misconfiguration","Improper rate limiting"],"c":0,"why":"BOLA occurs when an API fails to properly verify that the authenticated user is authorized to access the specific object referenced by an identifier, exactly as shown here. This is not SQL injection (no malicious query input), misconfiguration (no server setting error), or rate limiting (unrelated to authorization checks).","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A CI/CD pipeline automatically pulls an open-source package by name from a public package repository during every build. An attacker publishes a malicious package under the exact same name to a public repository with a higher version number than the internal private package the build was intended to use, causing the pipeline to fetch and execute the attacker's code. This supply chain attack is best described as which of the following?","o":["Typosquatting","Dependency confusion","Man-in-the-middle attack on TLS","Cross-site scripting via a compromised dependency"],"c":1,"why":"Dependency confusion occurs when a build system is tricked into resolving a package name to a malicious public package instead of the intended internal one, typically by version or namespace ambiguity—distinct from typosquatting, which relies on misspelled names, and unrelated to TLS interception or XSS.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of performing static application security testing (SAST) on source code?","o":["To test the application's performance under heavy load","To identify vulnerabilities by analyzing source code without executing it","To simulate a live attack against a running application","To verify compliance with license agreements"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source or binary code without execution to find vulnerabilities early; dynamic testing (DAST) tests running applications, and load testing and license compliance are unrelated to SAST's purpose.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A digital forensic investigator removes a hard drive from a compromised server as evidence. Which practice BEST ensures the evidence will remain admissible in a legal proceeding?","o":["Encrypting the hard drive immediately after removal","Maintaining a detailed chain of custody documenting everyone who handled the evidence and when","Creating a working copy of the drive for the IT department to review","Storing the original drive in a locked drawer at the investigator's desk"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation proves the evidence was not altered or mishandled, which is essential for admissibility. Encryption, copying for IT, or informal storage do not establish this unbroken accountability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A legacy C application is found to be vulnerable to a classic stack-based buffer overflow that an attacker could exploit for arbitrary code execution. Which combination of operating system and compiler-level controls would most effectively mitigate exploitation even if the vulnerable code itself is not immediately patched?","o":["Input length validation performed only at the presentation layer","Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR) combined with Data Execution Prevention (DEP) and stack canaries","Enabling verbose error logging to detect the overflow attempt","Migrating the database layer to use parameterized queries"],"c":1,"why":"ASLR, DEP, and stack canaries are runtime/compiler mitigations specifically designed to make memory corruption exploits like stack overflows unreliable or detectable, providing defense-in-depth while the root cause is fixed. Presentation-layer validation doesn't stop native memory corruption, logging doesn't prevent exploitation, and parameterized queries address SQL injection, not buffer overflows.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A software development team stores all source code changes in a centralized repository that tracks revisions, allows rollback, and records who made each change. This practice is an example of which control?","o":["Configuration management / version control","Least privilege enforcement","Data loss prevention (DLP)","Separation of duties"],"c":0,"why":"Tracking, storing, and controlling changes to code with rollback and audit capability describes version control, a key configuration management practice; it is not inherently about privilege limits, data leakage prevention, or duty separation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which security operations principle requires that no single individual has complete control over a critical process, such as both initiating and approving a financial transaction?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties splits critical tasks among multiple people to reduce the risk of fraud or error. Least privilege limits access scope, job rotation moves staff between roles, and mandatory vacation is a detective control, not a preventive split of duties.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A development team encrypts sensitive configuration files using AES in ECB (Electronic Codebook) mode. A security reviewer notes that identical plaintext blocks always produce identical ciphertext blocks, allowing an analyst to detect repeating patterns and potentially infer structure of the encrypted data even without breaking the key. What is the most appropriate remediation?","o":["Increase the AES key size from 128 to 256 bits","Switch to an authenticated mode such as AES-GCM or use CBC/CTR with a unique IV per encryption","Apply the encryption twice using ECB mode for defense-in-depth","Replace AES with a proprietary in-house cipher algorithm"],"c":1,"why":"The pattern-leakage problem is inherent to ECB mode's lack of chaining/randomization; the fix is to use a mode with proper IV/nonce usage and ideally authentication (e.g., GCM), not simply a larger key or double ECB encryption, which does not address the mode weakness. Custom proprietary ciphers violate the principle of using vetted, standard cryptography.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which type of software testing involves executing a running application to discover vulnerabilities such as improper input handling, without access to the source code?","o":["Dynamic application security testing (DAST)","Static application security testing (SAST)","Unit testing","Code review"],"c":0,"why":"DAST tests a running application from the outside (black-box) to find runtime vulnerabilities; SAST examines source code, unit testing verifies individual code components, and code review is a manual source inspection technique.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An administrator wants to minimize restore time after a data loss event and is willing to use more backup storage to achieve this. When combined with periodic full backups, which backup type BEST meets this goal?","o":["Incremental backup","Differential backup","Transaction log backup only","Bit-level mirroring without versioning"],"c":1,"why":"A differential backup captures all changes since the last full backup, so restoration only requires the full backup plus the latest differential, which is faster than incremental backups that require the full backup plus every incremental since. It also uses more storage than incremental backups, matching the stated trade-off.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A first responder arrives at a compromised production server that is still powered on and connected to the network. Following the principle of order of volatility, which item should be collected FIRST before the system is powered down or disconnected?","o":["Log files archived on backup tape","The contents of volatile memory (RAM)","Data stored on the local hard drive","Configuration files stored in the system's BIOS/firmware settings"],"c":1,"why":"RAM contents (including running processes, open network connections, and encryption keys) are the most volatile and will be lost immediately upon power-down, so they must be captured first; disk data, archived logs, and firmware settings are comparatively persistent and can be collected afterward.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"In relational database security, which property ensures that a transaction is either fully completed or fully rolled back, leaving the database in a consistent state?","o":["Atomicity","Isolation","Durability","Normalization"],"c":0,"why":"Atomicity, one of the ACID properties, guarantees all-or-nothing transaction completion; isolation concerns concurrent transaction visibility, durability ensures committed data persists, and normalization is a design technique unrelated to transaction integrity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following correctly represents the FIRST two phases of a standard incident response process, in order?","o":["Containment, then Eradication","Detection, then Response","Preparation, then Detection/Identification","Recovery, then Lessons Learned"],"c":2,"why":"Preparation establishes tools, training, and procedures before an incident occurs, followed by detection/identification when an event is discovered. Containment/eradication and recovery/lessons learned occur later in the process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Why is input validation considered a fundamental secure coding practice?","o":["It improves application performance by reducing code size","It ensures that only expected, well-formed data is processed, reducing exposure to injection and overflow attacks","It replaces the need for encryption of sensitive data","It guarantees compliance with all regulatory requirements"],"c":1,"why":"Input validation restricts data to expected formats and values, mitigating injection, overflow, and other attacks that rely on malformed input; it does not primarily affect performance, replace encryption, or guarantee regulatory compliance.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A financial firm's business impact analysis establishes a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 4 hours for its transaction database. The current backup schedule performs a single full backup nightly at 2:00 a.m. A disk failure occurs at 1:00 p.m. the following day. What deficiency does this incident most directly expose?","o":["The Recovery Time Objective (RTO) has been exceeded because restoration will take too long","The RPO has been violated because up to 11 hours of transaction data will be unrecoverable, exceeding the 4-hour threshold","The organization violated the 3-2-1 backup rule by maintaining only one backup copy","The disk failure indicates that RAID redundancy, not the backup schedule, was inadequate"],"c":1,"why":"RPO measures maximum tolerable data loss measured backward from the incident; since the last backup was 11 hours prior, this far exceeds the 4-hour RPO. RTO concerns restoration time, not data loss, and the scenario gives no information about RAID configuration or number of backup copies.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which security operations activity is PRIMARILY concerned with ensuring that all modifications to production systems are formally requested, reviewed, approved, and documented before implementation?","o":["Configuration management","Change management","Patch management","Release management"],"c":1,"why":"Change management governs the approval workflow and documentation for any modification to systems. Configuration management tracks baseline states, patch management addresses vulnerability remediation, and release management focuses on deployment scheduling and packaging.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During a forensic investigation of a compromised server, an analyst must decide the order in which to collect volatile data before shutting down the system. According to the concept of order of volatility, which of the following should be collected FIRST?","o":["CPU cache and registers","Contents of RAM","Data on local hard disk","Archived log files on backup tape"],"c":0,"why":"Order of volatility dictates collecting the most transient data first; CPU cache/registers change constantly and are lost immediately on power-down, making them the highest priority, more volatile than RAM, disk, or archived backups.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A data center requires a fire suppression system that will not damage sensitive electronic equipment and is safe to activate in occupied spaces. Which system is MOST appropriate?","o":["Wet pipe water sprinkler system","Clean agent gaseous suppression system","CO2 flooding system","Dry chemical powder system"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agent systems suppress fire without leaving residue or moisture that damages electronics and are formulated to be safe for occupied areas. Water damages equipment, CO2 displaces oxygen and endangers occupants, and dry chemical leaves corrosive residue.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A database server requires very high write performance and must tolerate the failure of a single drive without incurring the performance penalty associated with parity calculations. Storage capacity efficiency is a lower priority than write speed. Which RAID level BEST meets these requirements?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 6"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 1 (mirroring) provides fault tolerance for a single drive failure with no parity computation overhead, preserving write performance at the cost of storage efficiency. RAID 0 has no redundancy, and RAID 5/6 incur parity calculation overhead that reduces write performance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company's Recovery Point Objective (RPO) for its financial database is 4 hours, and its Recovery Time Objective (RTO) is 8 hours. Which backup strategy would BEST satisfy the RPO requirement?","o":["Full backup performed once every 24 hours","Differential backup performed once every 12 hours","Transaction log backups performed every 3 hours","Annual full backup with monthly incremental backups"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable data loss measured in time; transaction log backups every 3 hours ensure that no more than 3 hours of data would be lost, satisfying the 4-hour RPO. The other options all risk losing more data than the RPO allows.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before deploying a critical security patch to production servers, what is the MOST important step an organization should take?","o":["Send an email notification to all end users","Test the patch in a non-production environment first","Schedule the deployment for a weekend","Back up the patch management server itself"],"c":1,"why":"Testing patches in a staging or lab environment first identifies compatibility issues or failures before they affect production. User notification and scheduling are useful but secondary, and backing up the patch server has no bearing on patch impact to production systems.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization's customer support system is important but not mission-critical, and has an RTO of 24 hours. The disaster recovery budget precludes maintaining a fully mirrored, always-on facility. Which alternate site strategy BEST balances the RTO requirement against cost?","o":["Cold site","Warm site","Hot site","Reciprocal agreement with an untested business partner"],"c":1,"why":"A warm site is partially equipped and can typically be activated within roughly 12–24 hours, fitting the 24-hour RTO at moderate cost. A cold site would take too long to activate, a hot site exceeds the budget for this non-mission-critical system, and an untested reciprocal agreement carries unacceptable uncertainty for meeting a defined RTO.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization wants to ensure that emergency changes made outside the normal change management process are still properly documented and reviewed. Which control BEST addresses this requirement?","o":["Requiring a Change Advisory Board (CAB) to pre-approve all changes before implementation","Mandating retroactive review and approval of emergency changes within a defined timeframe after implementation","Disabling the ability to make emergency changes to production systems","Requiring all changes, including emergency ones, to go through the full standard change request lifecycle before implementation"],"c":1,"why":"Emergency changes must sometimes bypass normal pre-approval due to urgency, but a retroactive review ensures accountability and proper documentation after the fact. Pre-approval (A, D) defeats the purpose of an emergency change, and disabling emergency changes (C) is impractical and risky.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization needs a disaster recovery site with fully configured hardware and near real-time data replication so that operations can resume within minutes to a few hours. Which type of alternate site BEST meets this requirement?","o":["Cold site","Warm site","Hot site","Mobile site"],"c":2,"why":"A hot site maintains fully operational infrastructure and continuously replicated data, enabling very rapid failover. Cold sites require hardware installation, warm sites need partial setup and data restoration, and mobile sites are temporary and variable in readiness.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst notices that a SIEM is generating an overwhelming number of alerts, many of which are false positives, causing analyst fatigue. Which action would MOST effectively address this issue?","o":["Increase the retention period for log storage","Tune correlation rules and adjust alert thresholds based on baseline behavior","Disable logging for low-risk systems to reduce volume","Switch from a SIEM to a simple log aggregator"],"c":1,"why":"Tuning correlation rules and thresholds based on established baselines reduces false positives while preserving detection capability. Increasing retention or disabling logging does not address alert quality, and removing the SIEM eliminates correlation and analytic capability entirely.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"Shortly after receiving a credible threat of litigation related to a data breach, an organization's legal counsel issues a litigation hold notice covering all systems involved in the incident. Which action would MOST directly violate the organization's legal hold obligations?","o":["Suspending automatic log rotation on the affected systems for the duration of the investigation","Allowing routine 30-day log rotation to continue, overwriting potentially relevant evidence","Restricting system access to a designated forensic response team","Creating verified forensic images of the affected systems for offline analysis"],"c":1,"why":"Allowing scheduled deletion or overwriting of potentially relevant data after a litigation hold has been issued constitutes spoliation of evidence and directly violates the hold; suspending rotation, restricting access, and imaging systems are all proper preservation actions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization is selecting a fire suppression system for a data center housing sensitive electronic equipment. Which of the following is generally considered MOST appropriate?","o":["Wet pipe sprinkler system using water","Clean agent gaseous suppression system (e.g., FM-200)","Carbon dioxide flooding system for occupied spaces","Foam-based suppression system"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agent gaseous systems suppress fire without leaving residue or damaging electronics, making them ideal for data centers. Water and foam risk equipment damage, and CO2 systems are dangerous for occupied spaces due to asphyxiation risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A SOC analyst finds that a correlation rule intended to detect brute-force login attempts is generating excessive false positives because a legitimate load-testing tool repeatedly authenticates during business hours from a known source IP. Which response BEST addresses the issue while preserving detection capability?","o":["Disable the brute-force correlation rule entirely to eliminate the noise","Increase the alert threshold and add a scoped exception for the known source IP during scheduled testing windows","Instruct SOC analysts to ignore all alerts generated by this correlation rule going forward","Exclude the load-testing tool's logs from SIEM ingestion so they no longer trigger the rule"],"c":1,"why":"Tuning the threshold and adding a time- and source-scoped exception addresses the specific false-positive source while keeping the rule effective against genuine brute-force attempts; disabling the rule, blanket-ignoring alerts, or excluding logs entirely would create detection blind spots.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During an internal investigation, a security team seizes a suspect's laptop. Which practice is MOST important to preserve the integrity and admissibility of the evidence?","o":["Immediately analyzing the original drive to save time","Creating a forensically sound bit-for-bit image and maintaining a documented chain of custody","Copying only the files relevant to the investigation onto a USB drive","Allowing the suspect's manager to review the laptop contents before forensic imaging"],"c":1,"why":"A forensically sound image preserves the original evidence unaltered while allowing analysis on a copy, and a documented chain of custody ensures the evidence's integrity is provable in legal proceedings. Direct analysis, partial copying, or unauthorized access could compromise or spoil evidence integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning several solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained top-secret classified data. Per NIST SP 800-88 guidance, which sanitization approach is MOST appropriate for this media type?","o":["Degaussing the drives with a high-coercivity magnetic field","Cryptographic erase combined with verified physical destruction of the media","A single-pass overwrite with zeros using a standard disk-wipe utility","Low-level formatting followed by re-partitioning of the drives"],"c":1,"why":"SSDs use flash memory rather than magnetic storage, so degaussing has no effect, and wear-leveling/reallocated blocks make simple overwrite or formatting unreliable for complete data removal. NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase and/or physical destruction for high-sensitivity data on flash media.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During active exploitation of a zero-day vulnerability, a security team must deploy an emergency patch to production servers outside the normal weekly change window. Which action is MOST consistent with a mature change management process?","o":["Deploy the patch immediately without documentation, since speed is critical, and update records once the crisis subsides","Wait for the next scheduled Change Advisory Board (CAB) meeting to formally approve the deployment","Follow the organization's emergency change procedure, obtaining expedited approval from a designated emergency change authority, then complete full documentation and CAB review after deployment","Bypass change management entirely, since security patches are inherently exempt from IT governance processes"],"c":2,"why":"Mature change management includes a defined emergency change process that allows rapid, authorized action while preserving accountability through expedited approval and mandatory retrospective documentation/review; deploying with no approval or documentation, waiting for a scheduled CAB, or treating security patches as exempt all undermine control and traceability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application accepts user input directly into SQL queries built through string concatenation. Which remediation provides the strongest protection against SQL injection?","o":["Encrypting the database connection string","Limiting the length of input fields","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Deploying a network intrusion detection system"],"c":2,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing user input from being interpreted as SQL commands regardless of content or length; length limits, encrypted connections, and NIDS do not address the root cause of injection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company's business continuity plan identifies that its order-processing application can tolerate no more than 2 hours of downtime before causing unacceptable business impact. This value represents which of the following?","o":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)","Service Level Agreement (SLA) threshold"],"c":1,"why":"Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) represents the longest period a business function can be unavailable before causing unacceptable harm. RPO relates to data loss tolerance, MTBF relates to failure frequency, and SLA thresholds are contractual metrics, not continuity planning measures.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to identify vulnerabilities that only appear when the application is running in its actual deployment environment, such as issues caused by misconfigured web server headers or runtime authentication flows. Which testing technique is most appropriate?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Manual code review","Software composition analysis"],"c":1,"why":"DAST exercises the running application to find runtime and environment-dependent issues, whereas SAST and manual code review analyze source code without execution and would miss configuration-dependent flaws; SCA focuses on identifying known vulnerable components.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security operations team wants to reduce the risk of a single administrator being able to both create and approve changes to critical firewall rules. Which principle BEST addresses this concern?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Defense in depth","Job rotation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties ensures that no single individual has control over an entire critical process, reducing the risk of unilateral, unauthorized changes. Least privilege limits access scope but not necessarily role separation, defense in depth refers to layered controls, and job rotation addresses long-term exposure to fraud rather than concurrent authority.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A database allows a user to run multiple queries, each returning individually unclassified data elements. By combining the results, the user is able to derive a classified summary that no single query revealed. This is an example of which database security issue?","o":["Inference attack","Aggregation attack","SQL injection","Polyinstantiation"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining multiple low-sensitivity data elements produces a result of higher sensitivity; inference involves deducing sensitive information through logical reasoning about patterns rather than direct combination of query results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization requires that all proposed code changes be reviewed and formally approved before being merged into the production branch. Which control best describes this practice?","o":["Change control board approval","Static code analysis","Regression testing","Code signing"],"c":0,"why":"A change control/configuration control board provides formal governance and approval for changes before deployment, ensuring proper review; static analysis, regression testing, and code signing are technical activities, not approval governance processes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"In a DevSecOps model, security testing tools are integrated directly into the CI/CD pipeline so that vulnerabilities are identified during the build process rather than after deployment. This practice is best described as:","o":["Shifting security left","Defense in depth","Security through obscurity","Separation of duties"],"c":0,"why":"'Shifting left' means moving security activities earlier into the development lifecycle to catch issues sooner and reduce remediation cost; the other terms describe unrelated security concepts such as layered controls or role separation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A company licensing critical software from a small vendor is concerned the vendor may go out of business, leaving the company without support or the ability to maintain the application. Which arrangement best mitigates this risk?","o":["Software escrow agreement","Service level agreement (SLA)","Non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","Right-to-audit clause"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow agreement places source code with a neutral third party, released to the customer if the vendor fails to meet contractual obligations such as going out of business; SLAs, NDAs, and audit clauses address performance, confidentiality, and oversight, not source code continuity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization defines the maximum amount of data loss it can tolerate, measured in time, before an outage causes unacceptable harm to the business. Which metric describes this?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)"],"c":1,"why":"RPO measures the acceptable amount of data loss in time (i.e., how far back you must restore data from backups). RTO measures how quickly systems must be restored, MTBF measures reliability, and MTD is the total time a business process can be down.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A mobile banking API allows a user to retrieve account details by submitting an account ID in the request. A tester discovers that changing the ID value returns another customer's account data, even though the requesting user is not authorized for that account. This is most accurately classified as which vulnerability?","o":["Broken object level authorization","Cross-site request forgery","Insecure direct object encryption","Improper session termination"],"c":0,"why":"Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA) occurs when an API fails to verify that the authenticated user is authorized to access the specific object referenced, a leading OWASP API security risk; the other options describe unrelated vulnerability classes.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A backup administrator wants to minimize the time required to restore data after a failure while accepting slightly longer backup windows each night. Which backup strategy best supports this goal, assuming a full backup is taken weekly?","o":["Incremental backups every night, which only capture changes since the last backup of any type","Differential backups every night, which capture all changes since the last full backup","Performing only full backups every night","Snapshotting the system state without backing up data"],"c":1,"why":"Differential backups grow larger over the week but only require the last full backup plus the most recent differential to restore, making restoration faster than incremental (which requires the full backup plus every incremental since). Full backups nightly would be safest for restore time but not what the question is testing, and snapshots alone are not a backup strategy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An attacker enters ' OR '1'='1' into a web application's login field and successfully bypasses authentication. Which secure coding practice would BEST prevent this type of attack?","o":["Enabling verbose error messages for debugging","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Encrypting the database at rest","Implementing a longer password policy"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing SQL injection by ensuring user input is treated strictly as data. Encryption at rest and password policy do not address injection flaws, and verbose errors would actually help an attacker.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During an investigation, an analyst documents every person who handled a piece of digital evidence, along with the date, time, and purpose of each transfer. What is this documentation called?","o":["Chain of custody","Data classification log","Incident response plan","Configuration management record"],"c":0,"why":"Chain of custody records the handling, transfer, and storage of evidence to preserve its integrity and admissibility in legal proceedings. The other terms relate to unrelated processes (classifying data, planning incident response, or tracking configuration changes).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A vulnerability allows an attacker to inject malicious JavaScript into a web page that is later executed in the browser of another user viewing that page. This is an example of which vulnerability class?","o":["Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)","Buffer overflow","Race condition","Privilege escalation"],"c":0,"why":"XSS occurs when unsanitized user input is reflected or stored and later executed as script in another user's browser. Buffer overflows, race conditions, and privilege escalation are unrelated vulnerability categories.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST illustrates the security operations principle of separation of duties?","o":["Requiring the same administrator to both approve and implement firewall rule changes for efficiency","Requiring one employee to initiate a wire transfer and a different employee to approve it","Granting all employees administrative rights to reduce help desk tickets","Allowing a single security analyst to review and delete all audit logs without oversight"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties splits critical tasks between two or more people so no single individual can complete a sensitive process alone, reducing fraud and error risk, as shown by requiring separate initiators and approvers for a transfer. The other options concentrate power in a single person, which is the opposite of this control.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which type of software security testing analyzes an application's source code for vulnerabilities WITHOUT executing the program?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Penetration testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source or compiled code without running it, identifying issues like insecure functions or logic flaws early. DAST, penetration testing, and fuzzing all require the application to be running.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before a proposed modification to production systems is implemented, a Change Advisory Board (CAB) reviews the request. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this review?","o":["To assign blame if the change causes an outage","To ensure the change is properly evaluated for risk, tested, and approved before implementation","To bypass the need for testing since the CAB approval replaces it","To automatically implement the change without further documentation"],"c":1,"why":"The CAB's primary role is to assess risk, impact, and readiness of proposed changes and formally approve them before they move into production, supporting a controlled change management process. It is not meant to assign blame, replace testing, or skip documentation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security architect is choosing a programming language for new embedded firmware after previous incidents involving stack corruption and dangling pointers led to remote code execution. Which language characteristic would most directly reduce the risk of these vulnerability classes?","o":["Strong typing with automatic implicit type conversion between primitives","Memory-safe design that enforces bounds checking and automatic memory management","Support for object-oriented inheritance and polymorphism","Just-in-time compilation for improved runtime performance"],"c":1,"why":"Buffer overflows and use-after-free defects stem from unchecked memory access; a memory-safe language enforces bounds checking and manages allocation/deallocation, eliminating this vulnerability class at the language level. Implicit type conversion, OOP features, and JIT compilation do not address memory-safety issues and can even introduce their own risks.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Why is it a best practice to maintain strict separation between development, test, and production environments?","o":["To reduce the number of servers an organization must purchase","To prevent untested or insecure code changes from directly affecting live production systems","To allow developers unrestricted access to live customer data for testing","To eliminate the need for change management approval"],"c":1,"why":"Environment separation ensures changes are validated before reaching production, reducing the risk of introducing defects, malicious code, or unauthorized access into live systems; it does not reduce hardware needs or bypass change control.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization receives a vendor patch that addresses a critical vulnerability. Before deploying it to production servers, what is the MOST appropriate first step?","o":["Deploy the patch immediately to all production servers to close the vulnerability as fast as possible","Test the patch in a non-production environment to verify compatibility and stability","Wait for the next scheduled quarterly patch cycle regardless of severity","Disable the vulnerable service permanently instead of patching"],"c":1,"why":"Best practice is to test patches in a non-production environment first to identify compatibility or stability issues before wide deployment, balancing urgency with risk. Immediate blind deployment or waiting for an unrelated schedule ignores risk management, and disabling the service may not be feasible or necessary.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A hospital database allows clinicians to query patient records at the 'Confidential' level, but auditors discover that a user without access to a patient's HIV status was still able to insert a diagnosis record, causing two conflicting rows to exist for the same patient at different classification levels. This is an example of which database security technique being applied?","o":["Aggregation control","Polyinstantiation","Content-dependent access control","Database normalization"],"c":1,"why":"Polyinstantiation deliberately creates multiple versions of the same record at different classification levels so that a lower-cleared subject cannot infer the existence of higher-classified data. Aggregation control addresses combining non-sensitive data to derive sensitive conclusions, content-dependent access control restricts access based on data value, and normalization is a data-integrity design technique unrelated to multilevel security.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A development team uses a version control system that tracks every change to source code, allows rollback to prior versions, and requires peer approval before merging changes. This practice is an example of:","o":["Software configuration management","Data remanence control","Business continuity planning","Least privilege enforcement"],"c":0,"why":"Software configuration management (SCM) governs versioning, change tracking, and controlled integration of code changes. The other options relate to unrelated security domains (data disposal, continuity, access control).","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A data center houses sensitive electrical equipment and computer hardware. Which fire suppression method is MOST appropriate for this environment to minimize damage to the equipment?","o":["Water sprinkler system","Clean agent (gaseous) suppression system","Foam-based suppression system","Wet chemical suppression system"],"c":1,"why":"Clean agent gaseous suppression systems extinguish fires without leaving residue or conducting electricity, making them ideal for data centers with sensitive electronics. Water, foam, and wet chemical systems can damage equipment and pose electrical hazards.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A development team wants to identify vulnerabilities in a web application by instrumenting the running application's code so that both the internal execution paths and the external HTTP requests/responses can be correlated in real time during QA testing. Which testing approach does this describe?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Fuzz testing"],"c":2,"why":"IAST uses instrumentation inside the running application to observe internal code execution while correlating it with external inputs/outputs, combining strengths of SAST and DAST. SAST analyzes source/binary code without execution, DAST tests the running application externally without code visibility, and fuzz testing sends malformed inputs without instrumented correlation of internal execution paths.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company's incident response team has confirmed that a web server has been compromised and is actively being used to exfiltrate data. Following the six-phase incident response process, what should the team do next before eradicating the malware?","o":["Contain the affected system by isolating it from the network","Restore the system from the most recent known-good backup","Notify all customers whose data may have been affected","Conduct a full forensic disk image for law enforcement"],"c":0,"why":"Containment must occur immediately after detection/analysis to stop ongoing damage (e.g., data exfiltration) before eradication and recovery steps are taken; restoring, notifying, or imaging are later or parallel activities that don't stop the active compromise.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During incident response, which of the following represents the CORRECT general order of phases?","o":["Eradication, Detection, Containment, Recovery","Detection, Containment, Eradication, Recovery","Containment, Detection, Recovery, Eradication","Recovery, Containment, Detection, Eradication"],"c":1,"why":"The standard incident response lifecycle progresses from detecting the incident, containing it to limit damage, eradicating the root cause, and then recovering normal operations. The other sequences place phases out of logical order, such as attempting eradication or recovery before the incident is even detected or contained.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A first responder arrives at a workstation that is still powered on and appears to be actively communicating with an external IP address during a suspected data exfiltration incident. Digital evidence must later be admissible in court. Which order of evidence collection best reflects the correct order of volatility for this live system?","o":["Hard disk contents, then swap/page file, then RAM, then CPU cache and registers","CPU cache and registers, then RAM, then swap/page file, then hard disk contents","Network logs from the perimeter firewall, then RAM, then hard disk contents, then CPU registers","Hard disk contents, then CPU cache and registers, then RAM, then swap/page file"],"c":1,"why":"The order of volatility principle dictates collecting the most transient data first: CPU registers/cache, then RAM, then swap, then persistent disk storage, since disk contents are the least likely to change or disappear if collection is delayed. The other sequences collect disk data too early, risking loss of volatile evidence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization discovers that a widely used open-source library embedded in its flagship product contained a backdoor inserted by a compromised maintainer account. Which control would have provided the organization with the earliest and most direct visibility into this risk?","o":["Conducting periodic penetration tests against the production application","Maintaining a Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) with continuous vulnerability and provenance monitoring","Requiring developers to sign a secure coding policy acknowledgment annually","Implementing network-based intrusion detection at the perimeter"],"c":1,"why":"An SBOM with continuous monitoring provides visibility into all third-party and open-source components, their versions, and known issues, enabling early detection of compromised dependencies. Penetration testing and IDS are reactive/production-focused, and policy acknowledgments do not provide technical visibility into supply chain components.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During a forensic investigation, an analyst removes a hard drive from a suspect workstation. Which practice is MOST important to preserve the evidentiary value of the drive for potential legal proceedings?","o":["Encrypting the drive image before analysis","Maintaining a documented chain of custody from collection through analysis","Analyzing the original drive directly to save time","Storing the drive in a locked cabinet only after analysis is complete"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation proves the evidence was handled properly and wasn't tampered with, which is essential for admissibility; analyzing the original drive (rather than a forensic copy) can alter or damage evidence, and encryption/late storage don't address custody integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During an active incident, a security analyst discovers a compromised endpoint that is currently exfiltrating sensitive data to an external server. The organization intends to pursue legal action against the attacker. What is the BEST immediate containment action?","o":["Immediately power off the machine to stop the data loss and prevent further compromise","Disconnect the host from the network (e.g., via port shutdown or VLAN quarantine) while leaving it powered on, then begin volatile memory capture","Allow the exfiltration to continue while forensic imaging of the disk is completed, to avoid tipping off the attacker","Reimage the machine from a known-good backup to restore service as quickly as possible"],"c":1,"why":"Isolating the host preserves volatile evidence (RAM, running processes, network state) for forensic capture while immediately stopping further data loss. Powering off destroys volatile evidence; letting exfiltration continue causes unnecessary harm; reimaging destroys all evidence before analysis.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A database allows users to query individually low-sensitivity records, but by combining multiple query results a user can deduce classified information they are not authorized to know. This risk is known as:","o":["Aggregation","Polyinstantiation","Normalization","Data diddling"],"c":0,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining non-sensitive data elements reveals sensitive information. Polyinstantiation creates multiple versions of data for different security levels, normalization is a database design technique, and data diddling refers to unauthorized data alteration.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A developer is remediating a SQL injection vulnerability in a legacy application. Management insists that adding input validation on the web form is sufficient. What is the primary weakness of relying solely on input validation to prevent SQL injection?","o":["Input validation cannot be applied to numeric fields, only text fields","Input validation occurs only during initial page load and not on subsequent postbacks","Input validation can be bypassed by attackers who craft inputs that pass validation rules but still alter query logic when concatenated into SQL statements","Input validation requires client-side JavaScript, which increases page load time"],"c":2,"why":"Input validation is a defense-in-depth measure but does not change how untrusted data is structurally separated from SQL command logic; attackers can craft syntactically valid input that still manipulates the query. Parameterized queries/prepared statements address the root cause by separating code from data. The other options are factually incorrect or irrelevant to the security weakness.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution determines that it can tolerate losing no more than 15 minutes of transaction data in the event of a disaster. This requirement is best expressed as which metric?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Service Delivery Objective (SDO)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, directly matching the 15-minute tolerance; RTO measures how quickly systems must be restored, and MTD/SDO relate to downtime tolerance and service capacity, not data loss.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization's BCP policy mandates a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 4 hours for its order-processing database. Currently, full backups run every Sunday at midnight and no other backups occur during the week. A hardware failure destroys the database at 3:00 PM on Wednesday. Which statement BEST describes the situation and the appropriate remediation?","o":["The current backup scheme meets the RPO because a full backup exists; no changes are needed","The actual potential data loss (over 3 days) far exceeds the 4-hour RPO; backup frequency must be increased or replication implemented to close the gap","The RTO, not the RPO, has been violated, so backup frequency is irrelevant","Since RPO only applies to disaster declarations and this is a hardware failure, the metric does not apply"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the maximum tolerable data loss measured in time; with only weekly full backups, actual exposure is days, not hours, violating the 4-hour RPO. The fix is more frequent backups or continuous replication—RTO concerns recovery time, not data loss, and RPO applies to any data-loss event, not just formal disasters.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization plans to incorporate a popular open-source library into its commercial software product. Which of the following is the MOST important security consideration before adoption?","o":["Verifying the library has an attractive user interface","Confirming the library's license permits commercial redistribution and reviewing it for known vulnerabilities","Ensuring the library was written in the same programming language as the main application","Selecting the library with the newest release date regardless of maintenance history"],"c":1,"why":"Before adopting third-party/open-source code, organizations must assess licensing compatibility and known vulnerabilities (e.g., via CVE databases) to manage legal and security risk; UI appearance, matching language, and recency alone do not address these risks.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester notices that a multi-level secure system's response time to a query varies measurably depending on whether a higher-classified process is concurrently accessing a shared resource, allowing the tester to infer the existence of classified activity. This is an example of which type of covert channel?","o":["Storage channel","Timing channel","Overt channel","Side channel in cryptographic key exchange"],"c":1,"why":"A timing covert channel conveys information through variations in the timing of system events or resource access rather than through data storage locations. A storage channel would involve writing to a shared storage location that another process reads; 'overt channel' is not a covert channel type; and this scenario is not specifically about cryptographic key exchange.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization performs a full backup every Sunday and incremental backups every other day of the week. If the server fails on Thursday, which backups are needed to fully restore the data?","o":["Only Wednesday's incremental backup","Sunday's full backup plus Wednesday's incremental backup only","Sunday's full backup plus every incremental backup from Monday through Wednesday","Sunday's full backup and Thursday's incremental backup only"],"c":2,"why":"Incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup (full or incremental), so restoring requires the full backup plus every incremental in sequence up to the failure point; skipping any incremental would leave gaps in the restored data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A company performs a full backup every Sunday and incremental backups every other night of the week. On Thursday morning, the production server fails and must be restored to its state as of Wednesday night. Which backups must be restored, and in what order, to achieve a complete and correct recovery?","o":["Only Wednesday night's incremental backup, since it contains all changes","The full Sunday backup, followed by Monday's, Tuesday's, and Wednesday's incremental backups, applied in chronological order","The full Sunday backup and only the most recent (Wednesday) incremental backup","Wednesday's incremental backup followed by the full Sunday backup"],"c":1,"why":"Incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup of any type, so full restoration requires the last full backup plus every subsequent incremental applied in the correct chronological sequence. Restoring only the latest incremental or skipping intermediate increments would omit changes captured in earlier incrementals.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During a secure design review, an architect notes that Module A directly manipulates internal data structures of Module B and relies on B's specific implementation details rather than a defined interface. From a software security perspective, what is the most significant risk this design introduces?","o":["Increased cohesion within Module A, making it harder to test in isolation","Tight coupling, which increases the attack surface and causes changes in Module B to unpredictably affect the security posture of Module A","Improved encapsulation, which reduces maintainability but has no security impact","Reduced abstraction, which only affects code readability and has no bearing on security"],"c":1,"why":"Tight coupling between modules means that vulnerabilities, changes, or flaws in one module's internals can directly and unpredictably affect dependent modules, complicating security analysis and increasing the effective attack surface. High cohesion is generally desirable, and encapsulation/abstraction violations here are the actual problem, not improvements as the other options suggest.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A critical production system requires an urgent configuration change to remediate an actively exploited vulnerability. The organization's standard change management process normally requires two weeks of testing and CAB approval. What is the MOST appropriate action?","o":["Bypass change management entirely since the vulnerability is critical","Follow the emergency change process, which allows expedited approval with post-implementation review","Wait for the next scheduled CAB meeting to maintain process integrity","Implement the change silently without documentation to save time"],"c":1,"why":"A well-designed change management process includes an emergency change procedure for urgent situations, allowing expedited approval while still maintaining documentation and after-the-fact review; bypassing the process or acting without documentation undermines accountability and auditability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A critical zero-day vulnerability is actively being exploited in the wild, and a vendor patch is available. The organization's normal change management process requires two weeks of testing and CAB approval before production deployment. What is the BEST course of action?","o":["Bypass change management entirely and deploy the patch immediately without documentation, since speed is critical","Wait for the next scheduled CAB meeting to maintain process integrity, even though this delays remediation by up to two weeks","Invoke the organization's emergency change management procedure to deploy the patch expeditiously, with documentation and retroactive CAB review/approval","Perform the full two-week testing cycle as normal, since untested patches pose greater risk than the vulnerability itself"],"c":2,"why":"A mature change management program includes an emergency change process that allows expedited deployment for critical risks while still requiring documentation and after-the-fact approval, preserving accountability and change control. Bypassing all controls or waiting weeks are both unacceptable extremes given active exploitation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A DevSecOps team is integrating security into a CI/CD pipeline for a new microservices application. To align with a 'shift-left' security philosophy, at which point should threat modeling (e.g., using STRIDE) primarily be performed?","o":["After deployment, during the production monitoring phase","During the design phase, before code is written, based on data flow diagrams of the proposed architecture","Immediately before the final production release, as part of the change advisory board review","During user acceptance testing, once functional requirements are validated"],"c":1,"why":"Shift-left security emphasizes identifying threats as early as possible; threat modeling during the design phase, using data flow diagrams to apply frameworks like STRIDE, allows architectural flaws to be addressed before costly code is written. Performing it post-deployment, pre-release, or during UAT delays discovery until after significant investment and increases remediation cost and risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained highly sensitive data. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate given the characteristics of SSD storage?","o":["Degaussing the drives with a strong magnetic field","Overwriting the drives once with zeros using a standard disk-wipe utility","Using the manufacturer's secure erase command or cryptographic erase, followed by physical destruction if required","Reformatting the drive using the operating system's quick format option"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory and wear-leveling, making magnetic degaussing ineffective and simple overwrites unreliable due to inaccessible remapped blocks; secure erase/cryptographic erase commands (or physical destruction for high sensitivity) properly account for SSD architecture, unlike quick formatting which leaves data recoverable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) should security requirements first be formally documented and agreed upon with stakeholders?","o":["Requirements analysis","Design","Coding/implementation","User acceptance testing"],"c":0,"why":"Security requirements must be captured during requirements analysis so they can drive design and coding decisions; addressing them later (design, coding, or testing) is more costly and often results in incomplete or retrofitted controls.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization must sanitize a set of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored classified data before reissuing the drives for a lower-classification use within the same facility. Which method is MOST appropriate and effective per current media sanitization best practices?","o":["Degauss the drives using a strong magnetic field to erase the data","Perform a single-pass overwrite of the entire logical address space using standard OS tools","Use the drive's built-in cryptographic erase or ATA/NVMe Secure Erase/Sanitize command, verifying successful completion","Perform a quick format of the file system and reformat with a new partition table"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory with wear-leveling and over-provisioned blocks, making degaussing (a magnetic technique) ineffective and standard overwrites unreliable since not all physical blocks are addressable. NIST SP 800-88 recommends using the device's built-in cryptographic erase or sanitize command as the effective method; a quick format does not remove underlying data at all.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A database administrator wants to implement a storage solution that provides fault tolerance against a single disk failure while maximizing usable storage capacity across multiple disks. Which RAID level BEST meets this requirement?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 6 with dual parity across only two disks"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 5 uses striping with distributed parity across multiple disks, tolerating a single disk failure while offering better storage efficiency than mirroring (RAID 1); RAID 0 has no fault tolerance, and RAID 6 with only two disks is not a valid configuration since it requires a minimum of four disks.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security architect wants to identify vulnerabilities in a web application's source code before it is compiled, without executing the program. Which testing technique should be used?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source or binary code without executing it, making it ideal for finding coding flaws pre-compilation. DAST, fuzzing, and penetration testing all require a running application to exercise inputs and observe behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During disaster recovery testing, an organization activates its alternate processing site and runs live production transactions simultaneously at both the primary and alternate sites to validate that the alternate site can handle full production load, without interrupting the primary site's operations. This describes which type of DR test?","o":["Tabletop (structured walk-through) test","Simulation test","Parallel test","Full interruption test"],"c":2,"why":"A parallel test runs actual production operations at both the primary and alternate sites concurrently to validate alternate-site capability without risking business operations. A full interruption test actually halts primary operations, a tabletop is discussion-based only, and a simulation test does not involve full live processing at the alternate site.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst configures a SIEM to generate an alert whenever more than 10 failed login attempts occur from a single source IP within one minute, followed by a successful login. This is an example of which security operations capability?","o":["Log rotation and archival","Signature-based antivirus detection","Event correlation to detect potential brute-force attacks","Network access control (NAC) enforcement"],"c":2,"why":"Correlating multiple related events (repeated failures followed by success) across a time window is a classic SIEM correlation rule used to detect brute-force login attempts; this is not log rotation, antivirus signature matching, or NAC, which serve different functions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A database administrator notices that a user without direct access to classified salary data can deduce approximate salary ranges by correlating job titles, department budgets, and publicly available data. This is an example of which database security issue?","o":["Aggregation","Inference","Polyinstantiation","SQL injection"],"c":1,"why":"Inference occurs when a user deduces restricted information by combining lower-sensitivity data points. Aggregation involves combining multiple low-sensitivity records to produce a higher-sensitivity result directly from the database, not through logical deduction; polyinstantiation and SQL injection are unrelated concepts.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A data center houses both server racks (requiring strict access control) and serves as an emergency egress path in case of fire. Which door lock configuration BEST balances security and life-safety requirements for this space?","o":["Fail-secure locks on all doors, ensuring the room remains locked and secure even during a power failure or fire alarm","Fail-safe locks on doors along the egress path, which unlock automatically during a power failure or fire alarm to allow evacuation, combined with monitored access control during normal operations","Mechanical deadbolts with no electronic access control, to eliminate dependency on power","Fail-secure locks on egress doors, overridden manually by security staff during an emergency"],"c":1,"why":"Life safety always takes precedence over asset security; fail-safe locks unlock during power loss or fire alarm activation to permit evacuation while still providing controlled access during normal operations. Fail-secure locks on egress paths could trap personnel during an emergency, violating life-safety codes, and manual override introduces unacceptable delay and risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization licenses a critical application from a third-party vendor and wants assurance that it can continue maintaining the software if the vendor goes out of business. Which control best addresses this concern?","o":["Software escrow agreement","Non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","Service Level Agreement (SLA)","Code signing certificate"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow agreement places source code with a neutral third party, releasing it to the customer if the vendor fails to meet contractual obligations (e.g., bankruptcy). NDAs and SLAs govern confidentiality and performance, not code continuity, and code signing verifies integrity/authenticity, not business continuity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Which practice best exemplifies the DevSecOps principle of 'shifting security left' in the software development pipeline?","o":["Running a final penetration test just before production release","Integrating automated security scanning tools into the CI/CD pipeline during code commits","Conducting a security audit annually after deployment","Requiring security sign-off only at the change advisory board meeting"],"c":1,"why":"Shifting left means embedding security testing early and continuously in development, such as automated scans at commit time, so flaws are caught before they propagate. The other options represent security checks performed late in or after the lifecycle, which is what shifting left aims to avoid.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A development team incorporates numerous open-source libraries into their application. Which tool or process is specifically designed to identify known vulnerabilities and license risks in these third-party components?","o":["Software Composition Analysis (SCA)","Static code analysis","Threat modeling","Code obfuscation"],"c":0,"why":"SCA tools scan dependencies to identify known vulnerabilities (e.g., CVEs) and licensing issues in third-party and open-source components. Static code analysis examines the organization's own source code, threat modeling identifies design-level threats, and obfuscation protects code from reverse engineering.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is evaluating its software development processes against a framework that measures organizational process maturity from ad hoc to optimized levels. Which model is being used?","o":["Capability Maturity Model Integration (CMMI)","ISO/IEC 27001","OWASP Top 10","NIST Risk Management Framework (RMF)"],"c":0,"why":"CMMI specifically assesses and improves organizational process maturity across defined levels (from Initial to Optimizing). ISO 27001 is an ISMS certification standard, OWASP Top 10 lists common web vulnerabilities, and RMF is a risk management lifecycle framework, none of which measure process maturity levels.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A programmer writes code that fails to validate the length of user input before copying it into a fixed-size memory buffer, allowing an attacker to overwrite adjacent memory and execute arbitrary code. This vulnerability is best classified as which type of flaw?","o":["Race condition","Buffer overflow","Cross-site request forgery","Time-of-check to time-of-use (TOCTOU)"],"c":1,"why":"A buffer overflow results from writing data beyond the bounds of an allocated buffer due to inadequate input length validation, potentially allowing code execution. Race conditions and TOCTOU involve timing between checks and actions, and CSRF is a web-based attack forcing unauthorized actions via a victim's browser.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An investigator collects a hard drive from a compromised server as evidence. Which practice is MOST important to ensure the evidence remains admissible in court?","o":["Encrypting the drive before storage","Maintaining a documented chain of custody","Analyzing the drive on the original system","Storing the drive in a locked cabinet only"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documents who handled evidence, when, and how, proving it was not altered or tampered with, which is essential for admissibility. Encryption and storage alone do not prove integrity of handling, and analysis should be done on a forensic copy, not the original.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company wants a RAID configuration that provides both fault tolerance and improved read performance by striping data with parity across multiple disks, tolerating the failure of a single disk. Which RAID level BEST meets this requirement?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 6 without parity"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 5 stripes data with distributed parity across disks, allowing recovery from a single disk failure while improving read performance. RAID 0 offers no fault tolerance, RAID 1 mirrors without striping, and 'RAID 6 without parity' is not a valid configuration since RAID 6 relies on dual parity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"During which phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) should security requirements first be formally documented and incorporated into the project plan?","o":["Requirements analysis","Design","Implementation/coding","Testing"],"c":0,"why":"Security requirements must be defined during requirements analysis so they can drive design and implementation decisions; addressing security later (design, coding, or testing) is more costly and often results in incomplete coverage.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application accepts user input directly into SQL query strings without any validation or parameterization. Which type of attack is this application MOST vulnerable to?","o":["Cross-site request forgery","SQL injection","Buffer overflow","Session fixation"],"c":1,"why":"Concatenating unvalidated user input directly into SQL statements allows attackers to inject malicious SQL commands, which is the classic SQL injection vulnerability; the other attacks target different mechanisms such as session handling or memory management.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization runs an automated tool that scans an application's source code for security vulnerabilities without executing the program. What type of testing is this?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Penetration testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source or binary code for vulnerabilities without running the application, whereas DAST, penetration testing, and fuzz testing all involve exercising the running application to observe its behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A programmer writes code that copies user-supplied input into a fixed-size memory buffer without checking the input length. This coding flaw could MOST likely lead to which vulnerability?","o":["Cross-site scripting","Buffer overflow","Race condition","Insecure deserialization"],"c":1,"why":"Copying data into a fixed-size buffer without length checks can overwrite adjacent memory, which is the definition of a buffer overflow; the other options involve different root causes such as improper output encoding or timing issues.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization defines that after a disaster, a critical database must be restored to a state no older than 15 minutes prior to the outage. Which metric does this requirement describe?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Service Level Agreement (SLA)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, i.e., how far back data must be recoverable. RTO measures how quickly a system must be restored, MTD is the maximum downtime tolerable, and SLA is a broader service agreement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A development team wants to ensure that all changes to application source code are tracked, that multiple developers can work concurrently without overwriting each other's work, and that previous versions can be restored if needed. Which tool or process BEST supports these goals?","o":["A version control (source code management) system","A configuration management database (CMDB)","An intrusion detection system","A load balancer"],"c":0,"why":"Version control systems like Git track changes, manage concurrent edits, and allow rollback to prior versions of source code; a CMDB tracks IT asset configurations, while IDS and load balancers serve unrelated operational functions.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Which media sanitization method is generally considered the MOST effective for ensuring data cannot be recovered from a solid-state drive (SSD) that will be reused?","o":["Degaussing","Manufacturer-supported secure erase/cryptographic erase followed by verification","Deleting files through the operating system","Formatting the drive using a quick format"],"c":1,"why":"SSDs use flash memory and are not affected by degaussing (which works on magnetic media); vendor-supported secure erase or cryptographic erase, combined with verification, is the recommended NIST-aligned method for SSD sanitization. Deleting files or quick formatting leaves data recoverable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires that no single employee can both initiate and approve a financial transaction within the ERP system. This control is an example of which security principle?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Job rotation","Mandatory vacation"],"c":1,"why":"Separation of duties splits critical tasks among multiple people to prevent fraud or error by a single individual. Least privilege limits access scope, job rotation cycles employees through roles, and mandatory vacation forces time away to help detect fraud.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of input validation in secure software development?","o":["Ensuring that data received by an application conforms to expected format, type, and range before processing","Encrypting all data transmitted between client and server","Logging all user actions for later forensic review","Restricting network access to the application server"],"c":0,"why":"Input validation checks that data meets expected criteria before it is processed, preventing malformed or malicious input from causing errors or vulnerabilities; encryption, logging, and network restrictions address confidentiality, accountability, and access control, not input correctness.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During a forensic investigation of a compromised database server, an investigator seizes the physical drive as evidence. Which of the following procedures BEST preserves the evidentiary integrity of the drive for subsequent legal proceedings?","o":["Boot the original drive in a lab environment to confirm it contains the expected data, then generate a cryptographic hash before storage","Attach the drive using a hardware write-blocker, create a bit-for-bit forensic image, calculate a cryptographic hash of both the original and the image, and document every individual who handles the evidence","Copy the relevant log files and database tables to a separate USB drive for analysis, then place the original drive in a locked evidence room","Use built-in operating system copy utilities to duplicate the drive's contents onto a network share for the forensic team to review remotely"],"c":1,"why":"A write-blocker prevents any modification to the original media, and hashing plus a documented chain of custody ensures the image's authenticity and integrity can be proven in court. Booting the original drive, using OS copy tools, or selectively copying files can alter timestamps/metadata and breaks forensic soundness and chain of custody.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A web application checks whether a user has permission to write to a specific file, and then, in a separate subsequent step, opens that file for writing. An attacker exploits the delay between these two operations by replacing the target file with a symbolic link to a sensitive system file after the permission check completes but before the write occurs. Which vulnerability class does this describe?","o":["Time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","Buffer overflow due to unchecked input length","SQL injection via unsanitized file path parameter","Integer overflow in file size calculation"],"c":0,"why":"TOCTOU race conditions occur when a security check and the corresponding action are separated in time, allowing an attacker to alter the state of the resource in between; this is exactly the symlink-swap scenario described. The other options involve unrelated flaws (input length validation, injection, or arithmetic overflow) that do not depend on a timing gap between check and use.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization's Recovery Point Objective (RPO) for its order-processing database is 15 minutes. The current backup strategy consists of a full backup every Sunday at midnight and incremental backups every 4 hours during business hours only (08:00-18:00). Which conclusion is correct regarding this strategy?","o":["The strategy meets the RPO because incremental backups occur multiple times per day","The strategy fails to meet the RPO; a technology such as continuous data replication or transaction log shipping is needed to limit data loss to 15 minutes","The strategy fails to meet the RPO, but simply increasing the frequency of full backups to twice daily would resolve the gap","The RPO is irrelevant here because RPO only applies to full backups, not incremental backups"],"c":1,"why":"With backups only every 4 hours (and none outside business hours), potential data loss far exceeds 15 minutes, so near-continuous mechanisms like replication or log shipping are required. More frequent full backups alone don't close a multi-hour gap, and RPO applies to the overall recovery point regardless of backup type.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A database analyst who is not authorized to view individual salary records is able to determine an employee's exact salary by combining the results of several queries against average salary by department, headcount, and total payroll. Which control is MOST effective at preventing this type of attack?","o":["Encrypting the salary column at rest with a strong algorithm","Enforcing query set size restrictions and result perturbation/cell suppression on aggregate queries","Requiring stronger password complexity for the analyst's account","Normalizing the database schema to a higher normal form"],"c":1,"why":"This is a classic inference attack via aggregation; the correct mitigation is limiting the size/specificity of query results, suppressing small cell counts, or adding noise so exact values cannot be derived. Encryption at rest, password policy, and normalization do not address the logical inference problem created by combining legitimate aggregate query results.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A critical production application fails at 2:00 AM, and the on-call engineer needs to apply an unscheduled configuration change to restore service immediately. According to formal change management best practices, which approach is MOST appropriate?","o":["Apply the change immediately without approval since production is down, and skip documentation since the outage requires speed over process","Apply the change immediately under emergency change authority from a designated approver, then present the change to the Change Advisory Board for retrospective review, including a tested backout plan and full documentation","Wait until the next scheduled Change Advisory Board meeting to obtain approval before applying any change, even during the outage","Apply the change immediately, then only document it if the change causes additional problems later"],"c":1,"why":"Mature change management processes include an emergency change procedure that permits rapid action under a designated authority while still requiring retrospective CAB review, a backout plan, and documentation. Skipping approval and documentation entirely, or waiting for a scheduled CAB meeting, are inappropriate for genuine emergencies.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A system uses a full backup every Sunday night and a differential backup every other night of the week. The system fails on Thursday morning, and administrators need to restore data to its state as of Wednesday night. Which backup sets must be restored, and in what manner?","o":["The full backup from Sunday, followed by every differential backup from Monday through Wednesday, restored in chronological order","Only the full backup from Sunday, since differential backups are not needed for a Thursday failure","The full backup from Sunday and only the Wednesday differential backup, since each differential backup contains all changes since the last full backup","The differential backup from Wednesday alone, since it is cumulative and includes the full backup data"],"c":2,"why":"Differential backups capture all changes since the last full backup, so only the most recent differential plus the original full backup are needed to restore. This differs from incremental backups, which require restoring every incremental set in sequence since the last full backup.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A development team is building a new financial transaction system. During which SDLC phase should the team define abuse/misuse cases (e.g., 'attacker attempts to replay a transaction') alongside normal use cases?","o":["Design phase, after the architecture has been finalized","Requirements/analysis phase, in parallel with functional requirements","Testing phase, immediately before user acceptance testing","Maintenance phase, after the first production incident"],"c":1,"why":"Abuse and misuse cases should be elicited during requirements analysis alongside functional use cases so that security requirements shape the architecture from the start; waiting until design, testing, or maintenance means security requirements are bolted on late, increasing cost and residual risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security analyst discovers that a workstation is actively transmitting sensitive data to an external IP address associated with known exfiltration activity. To stop the data loss while preserving the best forensic evidence, what is the BEST immediate action?","o":["Power off the workstation immediately to halt all network traffic","Disconnect the network cable or disable the network adapter while leaving the system powered on","Allow the transmission to continue until the end of the business day to avoid disrupting the user","Reimage the workstation from the last known-good backup"],"c":1,"why":"Disabling network connectivity stops the exfiltration while preserving volatile memory (running processes, open connections) for forensic analysis. Powering off destroys volatile evidence, waiting allows continued data loss, and reimaging destroys evidence entirely.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm requires storage redundancy capable of surviving the simultaneous failure of any two disks in an array while maximizing usable storage capacity compared to full mirroring. Which RAID configuration BEST meets this requirement?","o":["RAID 1 (mirroring)","RAID 5 (striping with single parity)","RAID 6 (striping with dual parity)","RAID 0 (striping without redundancy)"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 6 uses dual parity, allowing the array to survive two simultaneous disk failures while providing better usable capacity than full mirroring (RAID 1). RAID 5 tolerates only a single disk failure, and RAID 0 provides no fault tolerance at all.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to ensure that no code reaches the production branch of its source repository without having been reviewed and that the commit history cannot be silently altered after review. Which combination of controls BEST achieves this?","o":["Nightly full backups of the repository combined with antivirus scanning of the build server","Branch protection rules requiring mandatory peer code review plus cryptographically signed commits","Storing the repository on an air-gapped server with no network access","Requiring developers to change their passwords every 30 days"],"c":1,"why":"Branch protection with mandatory review enforces process integrity, and signed commits provide cryptographic assurance of authorship and prevent undetected tampering with history. Backups/antivirus, air-gapping, and password rotation do not enforce review gating or detect history tampering.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During a disaster recovery exercise, the organization fully activates its alternate processing site, and live production transactions are simultaneously processed at both the primary and alternate sites to validate real-world performance, while the primary site continues normal operations. Which type of DR test is being performed?","o":["Tabletop exercise","Simulation test","Parallel test","Full interruption test"],"c":2,"why":"A parallel test runs actual production workloads at the alternate site alongside the primary site without disrupting normal operations, validating real capability. A full interruption test would shut down the primary site entirely, a tabletop exercise is discussion-based only, and a simulation test uses scenario walkthroughs rather than live transaction processing at both sites.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"When digital evidence is seized during an internal investigation, which factor is MOST critical to maintaining a valid chain of custody?","o":["Encrypting the evidence file with a strong algorithm","Documenting who handled the evidence, when, and for what purpose at every transfer","Storing the evidence in a locked cabinet accessible only to the investigator","Calculating a cryptographic hash of the evidence only after the investigation concludes"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody is defined by a continuous, documented record of possession and handling; without it, evidence integrity and admissibility can be challenged. Encryption, storage security, and end-of-investigation hashing are good practices but do not by themselves establish custody.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A stateless REST API currently authenticates users via a session cookie, and the application has been found vulnerable to cross-site request forgery (CSRF). Which change to the authentication mechanism would MOST directly reduce the CSRF risk without reintroducing server-side session state?","o":["Continue using the cookie but set it to HttpOnly only","Move to bearer token authentication passed in the Authorization header instead of a cookie","Switch to HTTP Basic authentication over TLS","Set the cookie's SameSite attribute to None to allow cross-origin use"],"c":1,"why":"Bearer tokens sent explicitly in an Authorization header are not automatically attached by the browser to cross-site requests the way cookies are, which removes the core mechanism CSRF relies on. HttpOnly only protects against script access (not CSRF), Basic auth still relies on browser-cached credentials sent automatically, and SameSite=None would actually worsen CSRF exposure.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is redesigning its SDLC to reduce the cost of fixing security defects. During which phase should security requirements be defined to achieve the greatest cost savings over the life of the project?","o":["Requirements and analysis phase","System testing phase","User acceptance testing phase","Post-deployment maintenance phase"],"c":0,"why":"Defining security requirements early (requirements/analysis) is far cheaper than fixing defects found later, since flaws found in testing or production require costly rework, retesting, and possible redesign.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization's change management policy requires Change Advisory Board (CAB) approval before any production change. During a critical outage, an on-call engineer applies a fix without prior approval to restore service. What should occur next according to sound change management practice?","o":["Nothing further is needed, since emergency situations are exempt from all change control","The change should be documented and submitted through an emergency/retroactive review process for formal approval as soon as possible","The engineer should be disciplined for bypassing the CAB regardless of the circumstances","The change must be reversed immediately, regardless of business impact, until CAB approval is obtained"],"c":1,"why":"Mature change management processes include an emergency change procedure that allows rapid action followed by retroactive documentation and approval, preserving accountability without exempting changes from oversight entirely. Ignoring the process, automatic discipline, or blind reversal are not standard practice.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An incident responder arrives at a compromised server that is still powered on and connected to the network. Following the principle of order of volatility, which of the following actions should be performed FIRST to preserve the most valuable, time-sensitive evidence?","o":["Power down the server and remove the hard drive for imaging","Capture the contents of volatile memory (RAM) and CPU cache/registers before they are lost","Make a forensic image of the hard disk to preserve file system evidence","Export historical log files from the centralized SIEM for the past 30 days"],"c":1,"why":"Order of volatility dictates that the most transient data—CPU registers, cache, and RAM—must be captured first, as this data is lost immediately upon power-off. Disk imaging, log exports, and shutting down the system are all lower priority since that data persists longer or is unaffected by delayed collection.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security tester has no access to source code for a proprietary binary and wants to discover unknown input-handling vulnerabilities by automatically generating large volumes of malformed and unexpected input to the application's interfaces. Which testing technique is being used?","o":["Static application security testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing (dynamic, black-box)","Formal verification using mathematical proofs","Manual secure code review"],"c":1,"why":"Fuzzing is a black-box dynamic technique that feeds malformed/random input to an application to surface crashes or unexpected behavior without needing source code. SAST and manual review require source access, and formal verification uses mathematical proofs rather than input generation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company performs a full backup every Sunday night. To minimize daily backup time while still being able to restore using only the full backup plus a single additional backup set, which backup strategy should be used for the remaining days?","o":["Incremental backups","Differential backups","Full backups every day","Snapshot-only backups"],"c":1,"why":"Differential backups capture all changes since the last full backup, so restoration only requires the full backup plus the most recent differential. Incremental backups require the full backup plus every incremental since, and daily full backups take the most time to run, contradicting the goal.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that previously stored highly sensitive data and must ensure the data is unrecoverable before disposal. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate for this media type?","o":["Degaussing the drives with a high-powered magnetic degausser","Performing a single-pass overwrite using traditional disk-wiping software designed for magnetic hard drives","Using the SSD's built-in cryptographic erase feature (if supported) or following NIST SP 800-88 purge guidance specific to flash-based media, followed by verification","Physically labeling the drives as \"sanitized\" and storing them in a locked cabinet pending eventual disposal"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory, not magnetic platters, so degaussing is ineffective, and traditional overwrite tools may not reach all physical blocks due to wear-leveling; NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase or vendor-specific purge/sanitize commands for flash media, followed by verification. Labeling without actual sanitization does not remove data risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A CI/CD pipeline currently has API keys and database credentials hardcoded as plaintext environment variables in the build scripts stored in the repository. Which remediation BEST addresses the underlying risk?","o":["Base64-encode the credentials before committing them to the repository","Integrate a secrets management vault that injects short-lived, dynamically generated credentials at pipeline runtime","Move the credentials into a separate configuration file within the same repository","Restrict repository read access to the DevOps team only"],"c":1,"why":"A secrets vault with short-lived, dynamically generated credentials eliminates long-lived static secrets from source control entirely and limits exposure if leaked. Base64 encoding provides no real protection, moving to another file still commits secrets to version history, and restricting access does not eliminate the risk of hardcoded long-lived secrets.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team needs to assess a running web application for vulnerabilities without access to its source code, simulating attacks against the live, deployed system to observe actual responses. Which testing methodology best fits this scenario?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Manual source code review"],"c":1,"why":"DAST is a black-box technique that tests a running application externally without needing source code. SAST and code review require source access, and IAST requires internal instrumentation of the running code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An operating system reallocates a memory segment previously used by Process A to Process B without clearing its contents first, allowing Process B to potentially read residual sensitive data left by Process A. Which security principle, if properly implemented, would have prevented this?","o":["Object reuse control requiring sanitization of memory before reallocation","Principle of least privilege applied to process scheduling","Mandatory access control labeling of memory pages","Application of the Bell-LaPadula confidentiality model to process memory"],"c":0,"why":"Object reuse controls specifically require that storage objects (memory, disk blocks) be cleared/sanitized before being reassigned to a new subject to prevent data leakage through residual content. Least privilege, MAC labeling, and Bell-LaPadula govern access decisions, not the clearing of reused storage objects.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A business impact analysis states that after a disruption, the organization can tolerate losing no more than 15 minutes of transaction data. This requirement defines which metric, and which technology would BEST support meeting it?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO); supported by a cold site","Recovery Point Objective (RPO); supported by synchronous replication or frequent log shipping","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD); supported by daily tape backups","RTO; supported by weekly full backups"],"c":1,"why":"Data loss tolerance is defined by RPO, and achieving a 15-minute RPO requires near-real-time replication or frequent transaction log shipping rather than infrequent backups. RTO measures downtime tolerance, not data loss, so the other options mismatch the metric or use inadequate technology.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Developers are updating a legacy application that builds SQL statements by concatenating user-supplied input directly into query strings. Which remediation most effectively eliminates the underlying SQL injection risk?","o":["Add client-side JavaScript input validation","Replace dynamic query concatenation with parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Deploy a web application firewall in front of the application","Encode all output displayed to the user"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data so user input cannot alter query structure, directly addressing the root cause. Client-side validation and WAFs can be bypassed, and output encoding addresses XSS, not SQL injection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"Before deploying a critical security patch to production servers, what is the BEST practice for an organization to follow?","o":["Deploy the patch immediately to all production servers to minimize the exposure window","Test the patch in a representative non-production environment, then deploy through the standard change management process","Wait 90 days after release to ensure the patch has stabilized before testing","Apply the patch only to internet-facing servers and skip internal systems"],"c":1,"why":"Testing patches in an environment that mirrors production, followed by controlled deployment through change management, balances risk reduction with stability. Immediate mass deployment risks unforeseen issues, arbitrary waiting periods leave systems exposed, and skipping internal systems ignores lateral-movement risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A user who is authenticated to their online banking site visits an unrelated malicious website in another browser tab. That site silently submits a hidden form to the banking site, using the user's existing session cookie, and transfers funds without the user's knowledge or consent. What attack technique does this describe?","o":["Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)","Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)","Session fixation","SQL injection"],"c":1,"why":"CSRF exploits the trust a site has in an authenticated user's browser by forcing it to submit unwanted requests using existing session credentials. XSS involves injecting scripts into a trusted site, and session fixation involves forcing a known session ID before authentication.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization needs to sanitize solid-state drives (SSDs) before disposal. Due to wear-leveling, traditional overwrite methods may not reliably erase all data. Which approach is MOST appropriate for these drives?","o":["Degaussing the drives with a strong magnetic field","Performing multiple passes of random-data overwrites","Cryptographic erase (destroying the encryption key) combined with vendor-supported secure erase, or physical destruction","Deleting all files and performing a quick format"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use non-magnetic flash memory, so degaussing is ineffective, and wear-leveling makes overwrite-based sanitization unreliable; cryptographic erase or vendor secure-erase commands (or physical destruction) are recommended by NIST SP 800-88 for flash media. Deleting/formatting only removes file pointers, leaving data recoverable.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"In a multilevel secure database, two records share the same primary key but exist at different classification levels; a low-clearance user querying the key sees a cover record, while a high-clearance user sees the sensitive real record. What database security technique is being used?","o":["Aggregation","Inference","Polyinstantiation","Data normalization"],"c":2,"why":"Polyinstantiation allows multiple rows with the same key at different sensitivity levels to prevent lower-cleared users from inferring the existence of higher-classified data. Aggregation and inference describe how sensitive conclusions can be derived from combined or indirect data, not the mitigation technique itself.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A database administrator needs a RAID configuration that provides fault tolerance against a single disk failure using parity, while minimizing the number of disks required. Which RAID level BEST meets this requirement?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 1","RAID 5","RAID 10"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 5 uses distributed parity across a minimum of three disks, tolerating a single disk failure with less storage overhead than mirroring-based solutions. RAID 0 offers no fault tolerance, RAID 1 mirrors data without parity and has higher overhead per capacity, and RAID 10 requires more disks than RAID 5 for equivalent fault tolerance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"After a critical vulnerability is discovered in a widely used open-source logging library, an organization struggles to determine which of its applications use the affected component and version. Which artifact, if maintained proactively, would have allowed rapid identification of affected systems?","o":["Software Bill of Materials (SBOM)","Configuration Management Database (CMDB) for hardware assets","Application source code repository","Change management log"],"c":0,"why":"An SBOM lists all components, libraries, and their versions used in software, enabling rapid identification of systems affected by a vulnerable dependency. A hardware CMDB, source repository, and change log do not provide this component-level dependency inventory.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A development team wants to reduce the risk that a single rogue or compromised developer could introduce malicious code into production through the CI/CD pipeline. Which control most directly addresses this risk?","o":["Requiring mandatory peer code review and approval before merging to the main branch","Encrypting all code repositories at rest","Increasing the frequency of automated dependency scanning","Implementing role-based access control on the production database"],"c":0,"why":"Mandatory peer review enforces separation of duties, ensuring no single individual can unilaterally introduce code into production. Encryption at rest, dependency scanning, and database RBAC address different risks and do not prevent a single actor from pushing unreviewed code.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A software architect is evaluating two module designs and wants to select the one that minimizes the security impact of future code changes, so that modifying one module is unlikely to require changes in unrelated modules. Which design characteristics should be prioritized?","o":["High coupling and low cohesion","Low coupling and high cohesion","High coupling and high cohesion","Low coupling and low cohesion"],"c":1,"why":"Low coupling minimizes interdependencies between modules, and high cohesion ensures each module has a single, well-defined purpose, together limiting the ripple effect of changes and reducing the attack surface introduced by modifications. The other combinations increase interdependency or unrelated functionality within modules, raising risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During an active security incident, the response team disconnects the affected server from the network to prevent further spread of malware. Which incident response phase does this action represent?","o":["Detection","Containment","Eradication","Recovery"],"c":1,"why":"Containment focuses on limiting the scope and impact of an incident, such as isolating an infected system from the network; detection is identifying that an incident occurred, eradication removes the root cause, and recovery restores normal operations.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization wants to ensure that digital evidence collected during an investigation remains admissible in court. Which practice is MOST important for preserving the integrity of that evidence?","o":["Encrypting the evidence with a strong algorithm","Maintaining a documented chain of custody","Storing the evidence on a redundant RAID array","Compressing the evidence to save storage space"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documents who handled the evidence, when, and how, proving it was not altered or tampered with; encryption, RAID storage, and compression do not address the legal requirement of demonstrating unbroken custody and integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application allows users to enter data that is directly concatenated into SQL queries without validation. Which secure coding practice would BEST mitigate the risk of SQL injection?","o":["Use of parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Increasing the database connection timeout","Encrypting the database at rest","Implementing role-based access control on the web server"],"c":0,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data, preventing attacker-supplied input from altering query logic. Encryption at rest, timeouts, and RBAC do not address the injection vulnerability itself.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An attacker injects malicious JavaScript into a comment field of a website, which then executes in the browsers of other users who view the page. This is an example of which vulnerability?","o":["Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)","SQL Injection","Buffer Overflow","Race Condition"],"c":0,"why":"XSS occurs when untrusted input is rendered as executable script in another user's browser. SQL injection targets databases, buffer overflow targets memory, and a race condition involves timing of concurrent operations.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of using a source code version control system in a secure development environment?","o":["To track and manage changes to code, enabling accountability and rollback if defects or malicious changes are introduced","To automatically encrypt all source code files at rest","To perform automated penetration testing on committed code","To replace the need for code review before deployment"],"c":0,"why":"Version control systems provide change tracking, accountability, and the ability to revert problematic changes. They do not perform encryption, penetration testing, or eliminate the need for code review.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization relies on a third-party vendor for a critical software application. To protect against the vendor going out of business or failing to maintain the code, which arrangement should the organization establish?","o":["Software escrow agreement","Service level agreement only","Non-disclosure agreement","Business associate agreement"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow agreement ensures a copy of the source code is held by a neutral third party and released to the customer under specified conditions, such as vendor bankruptcy. SLAs, NDAs, and BAAs address performance, confidentiality, and healthcare data handling, respectively, not source code access continuity.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During an active incident response, a security analyst discovers that a compromised web server is actively exfiltrating data to an external IP address. The organization's priority is to stop the ongoing damage while preserving evidence for later analysis. Which action best reflects the appropriate next step in the incident response process?","o":["Immediately power off the server to halt all activity","Isolate the server from the network while keeping it powered on","Rebuild the server from a known-good backup","Notify law enforcement before taking any technical action"],"c":1,"why":"Isolating the host (e.g., via network segmentation) stops further exfiltration while preserving volatile memory and system state for forensic analysis; powering off destroys volatile evidence, rebuilding skips containment/analysis, and law enforcement notification is not the immediate technical containment step.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A database contains individually unclassified pieces of information, but when a user queries and combines several fields together, the result reveals sensitive information the user is not authorized to know. This is an example of which database security issue?","o":["Aggregation","Normalization","Polyinstantiation","Referential integrity violation"],"c":0,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining multiple low-sensitivity data elements produces a higher-sensitivity result. Normalization refers to database design efficiency, polyinstantiation creates multiple views of data at different classification levels, and referential integrity concerns relationships between tables, not information disclosure.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An investigator collects a hard drive from a suspect workstation as part of a corporate fraud investigation. To ensure the evidence remains admissible in court, which control is MOST critical to maintain throughout the investigation?","o":["Encrypting the drive image with a strong algorithm","Maintaining an unbroken chain of custody documentation","Storing the drive in a locked evidence room only","Using write-blocking hardware during imaging"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation proves the evidence was not altered or tampered with from collection through presentation, which is essential for admissibility; write-blocking and secure storage support integrity but chain of custody is the overarching requirement courts rely on.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company performs a full backup every Sunday and an incremental backup every other day of the week. If a server fails on Thursday, how many backup sets are needed to fully restore the data?","o":["Only the Thursday incremental backup","Only the Sunday full backup","The Sunday full backup plus all incremental backups through Thursday","The Sunday full backup plus only the Wednesday incremental backup"],"c":2,"why":"Incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup (full or incremental), so a full restore requires the last full backup plus every incremental backup made since then; using only one incremental or skipping days would omit needed data.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company's disaster recovery plan specifies that the order-processing system must be restored within 4 hours of an outage, and no more than 15 minutes of transaction data can be lost. What do these two values represent, respectively?","o":["Mean Time to Repair (MTTR) and Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO) and Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) and Service Level Agreement (SLA)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO) and Recovery Time Objective (RTO)"],"c":1,"why":"RTO defines the maximum acceptable time to restore a system (4 hours), while RPO defines the maximum acceptable data loss measured in time (15 minutes); MTTR/MTBF relate to reliability metrics, and MTD/SLA are different concepts entirely.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During incident response, a first responder must collect volatile data from a compromised production server before it is powered down. Per standard forensic guidance (e.g., RFC 3227), which order of evidence collection BEST preserves the most volatile and perishable data first?","o":["Disk files, then RAM, then CPU cache/registers, then network state","CPU cache/registers, RAM, network state/routing tables, temporary file systems, disk, remote logs, archival media","Archival backups, disk images, RAM, CPU registers","Network state, disk, RAM, CPU registers, archival media"],"c":1,"why":"The order of volatility principle dictates collecting the most transient data (CPU registers/cache, then RAM, then network state) before less volatile data like disk and archival media, since volatile data is lost first if not captured immediately. The other options reverse or scramble this order, risking loss of critical short-lived evidence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before a new firewall rule is implemented in production, it must be reviewed and approved by a change advisory board. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this change management control?","o":["To assign blame if the change causes an outage","To ensure changes are evaluated for risk and business impact before implementation","To satisfy audit documentation requirements only","To delay changes so administrators have more time to test personally"],"c":1,"why":"Change management exists to formally assess and control the risk and impact of changes before they occur, reducing the chance of unintended outages or security gaps; it is not primarily about assigning blame, pure documentation, or intentional delay.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A system administrator wants to deploy a critical security patch to production servers. Which of the following BEST demonstrates adherence to a formal change management process?","o":["Applying the patch immediately to all servers since it addresses a critical vulnerability","Testing the patch in a staging environment, obtaining change advisory board approval, then scheduling deployment","Deploying the patch to a single production server first without prior testing to observe results","Waiting until the next scheduled quarterly maintenance window regardless of severity"],"c":1,"why":"Proper change management requires testing, documented approval (e.g., via a CAB), and scheduled deployment to minimize unintended impact, even for urgent patches (which may use an expedited but still documented process); skipping testing/approval or arbitrary delay both violate change control principles.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is redesigning its software development lifecycle to reduce the cost of fixing security defects. At which phase should security requirements first be formally defined and documented?","o":["During the requirements analysis phase, before design begins","During unit testing, once code modules are available for review","During the maintenance phase, after user feedback identifies issues","During deployment, when the production environment is configured"],"c":0,"why":"Defining security requirements during requirements analysis allows them to drive design and coding decisions, which is far cheaper than retrofitting security later; waiting until testing, maintenance, or deployment means defects are found and fixed at much higher cost and risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A business impact analysis determines that the Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) for a critical order-processing application is 6 hours. During a disaster recovery test, the team successfully restores the application with a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 15 minutes, but the actual Recovery Time Objective (RTO) achieved is 8 hours. What is the MOST significant concern raised by this test result?","o":["The RPO of 15 minutes is too aggressive and will increase backup infrastructure costs unnecessarily","The achieved RTO exceeds the MTD, meaning the recovery capability does not meet the business's continuity requirements even though data loss is minimal","The RPO exceeds the MTD, which is a critical planning failure","MTD becomes irrelevant once a specific RTO target is defined, so no further action is needed"],"c":1,"why":"MTD represents the absolute maximum time the business can tolerate an outage; since the achieved RTO (8 hours) exceeds the MTD (6 hours), the recovery plan fails to meet business continuity requirements regardless of how good the RPO is. The other options misstate the relationship between RPO, RTO, and MTD or dismiss a genuine planning gap.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company's disaster recovery plan states that after a disruption, no more than 4 hours of data loss is acceptable. Which metric does this 4-hour value represent?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, dictating backup frequency; RTO is about how quickly systems must be restored, MTD is the total downtime an organization can tolerate, and MTBF measures average time between failures of a component.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization is decommissioning solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained highly classified data. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate given the physical characteristics of SSD storage?","o":["Overwriting the drive once with zeros using standard disk-wipe software","Degaussing the drive using a strong magnetic field","Physical destruction (e.g., shredding or disintegration) following vendor/NIST guidance","Performing a quick format of the drive's file system"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory with wear-leveling and over-provisioning, making software overwriting unreliable for complete sanitization, and degaussing is ineffective on non-magnetic media; physical destruction per NIST SP 800-88 guidelines ensures data cannot be recovered from highly classified SSDs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A web application allows users to search a product database by entering a product name into a text field. An attacker enters a string containing SQL commands and successfully extracts data from unrelated tables. Which control provides the most effective mitigation against this specific vulnerability?","o":["Encrypting the database connection string with strong cryptography","Implementing parameterized queries (prepared statements) for all database access","Increasing the length limit validation on the input field","Enabling verbose error messages to help developers diagnose the issue"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate SQL code from user-supplied data, preventing injected input from being interpreted as executable commands, which directly addresses SQL injection. Encryption, length limits, and verbose errors do not prevent the input from being parsed as SQL.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A financial database supporting a high-volume, write-intensive transaction system requires both strong fault tolerance and high write performance. Read performance is secondary. Which RAID configuration BEST meets these requirements?","o":["RAID 0 for maximum throughput with no redundancy overhead","RAID 5, since parity striping provides both redundancy and acceptable write performance","RAID 10 (mirrored and striped), since it avoids parity-calculation overhead while providing redundancy and strong write performance","RAID 6, since dual parity provides the highest possible fault tolerance for any workload"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 10 combines mirroring and striping, avoiding the parity write penalty inherent in RAID 5/6, making it best suited for write-intensive workloads needing fault tolerance. RAID 0 offers no redundancy, and RAID 5/6 incur significant write performance penalties due to parity calculations, especially under heavy random writes.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization's vulnerability scanner identifies a critical, actively exploited vulnerability on several production servers for which the vendor has released an official patch. What is the BEST immediate next step?","o":["Wait for the next scheduled quarterly patch cycle","Test the patch in a non-production environment and expedite deployment through change management","Ignore the vulnerability since it has not yet caused an incident","Disable the vulnerability scanner to stop generating alerts"],"c":1,"why":"Critical, actively exploited vulnerabilities warrant expedited but still controlled remediation—testing to avoid breaking production, then deploying quickly through an accelerated change process; waiting for a routine cycle, ignoring the issue, or disabling the scanner all leave the organization exposed.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security operations center (SOC) analyst notices that a SIEM is generating thousands of low-priority alerts daily, causing analysts to overlook genuine threats. Which approach would MOST effectively address this problem?","o":["Disabling logging for the noisiest low-value sources","Tuning correlation rules and adjusting alert thresholds based on risk and context","Increasing the number of analysts to review every alert manually","Switching to a different SIEM vendor with a larger alert database"],"c":1,"why":"Tuning correlation rules and thresholds reduces false positives and prioritizes meaningful alerts, directly addressing alert fatigue; disabling logging creates blind spots, adding staff doesn't scale, and changing vendors doesn't solve a tuning/process problem.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A security team wants to identify vulnerabilities in a web application's source code before it is compiled, without executing the application. Which testing approach best meets this requirement?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing against a running instance","Penetration testing of the production environment"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source or binary code without executing the program, making it suitable for pre-compilation review. DAST, fuzzing, and penetration testing all require the application to be running, which does not meet the stated requirement.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A forensic investigator is imaging a suspect's hard drive for use in potential litigation. Which practice BEST ensures the evidentiary integrity and admissibility of the resulting forensic image?","o":["Copy files directly from the original drive using the operating system's standard copy function to save time","Use a write-blocker during imaging and generate cryptographic hashes of the original drive and the image before and after acquisition","Image the drive only after installing forensic analysis tools directly onto the original media","Rely on the investigator's contemporaneous notes alone, since hashing is only necessary for network-based evidence"],"c":1,"why":"A write-blocker prevents any modification to the original evidence during acquisition, and matching cryptographic hashes before/after imaging proves the image is an exact, unaltered copy, both essential for admissibility. Copying via the OS or installing tools on original media risks altering timestamps/metadata, undermining evidentiary integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A Security Operations Center (SOC) analyst notices a spike in failed login attempts followed by a successful login from an unusual geographic location. Which security operations function MOST directly enabled this detection?","o":["Configuration management","Continuous monitoring and log analysis","Physical access control","Software escrow"],"c":1,"why":"Continuous monitoring and correlation of log data (often via a SIEM) allows analysts to detect anomalous patterns like brute-force attempts followed by anomalous logins; configuration management, physical access control, and software escrow do not provide this detection capability.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"During a code review, a security architect notices that developers routinely commit directly to the main branch of the source repository without any peer review or automated checks. Which practice would BEST address the risk this introduces?","o":["Requiring all commits to be encrypted before storage","Implementing branch protection rules requiring pull requests and mandatory code review before merge","Increasing the retention period of repository backups","Restricting repository access to a single administrator account"],"c":1,"why":"Branch protection with mandatory pull requests and peer review ensures changes are validated before integration, catching defects and malicious code early. Encryption, backup retention, and single-admin access do not address the lack of review and quality control in the commit process.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During an active investigation, analysts discover command-and-control (C2) traffic originating from an internal server communicating with an external IP address, indicating an ongoing advanced persistent threat (APT) compromise. Immediately blocking the traffic risks alerting the attacker, who may destroy further evidence or activate destructive payloads. What is the BEST immediate course of action?","o":["Immediately block the C2 traffic at the perimeter firewall to stop further data exfiltration","Shut down the affected server immediately to contain the threat, then begin forensic analysis","Continue covert monitoring of the traffic while preserving logs and gathering threat intelligence, coordinating closely with legal and management before taking overt action","Notify the end user of the affected system so they can change their password and disconnect the machine themselves"],"c":2,"why":"Covert monitoring allows the organization to gather intelligence on attacker TTPs, scope the compromise, and preserve evidence before tipping off the adversary, which is standard practice for sophisticated intrusions under proper authorization. Immediate blocking, shutdown, or user notification could alert the attacker prematurely, causing evidence destruction or lateral movement to accelerate.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before disposing of old hard drives that contained sensitive customer data, an organization wants to ensure the data cannot be recovered by any means, including advanced forensic techniques. Which method BEST achieves this goal?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive using a quick format","Physical destruction of the drive (e.g., shredding or degaussing)","Moving the files to a hidden folder"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction methods like shredding or degaussing render data unrecoverable even with advanced forensic tools, whereas deleting files, quick formatting, or hiding folders leave data recoverable with common forensic techniques.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A financial institution performs full backups every Sunday and wants to minimize both backup storage requirements and restore time for a Wednesday outage. Which backup strategy achieves this balance MOST effectively?","o":["Differential backups every day, capturing all changes since the last full backup","Incremental backups every day, capturing only changes since the previous backup","Full backups every day to ensure the fastest possible restore","Snapshot-only backups with no full backup baseline"],"c":0,"why":"Differential backups require restoring only the last full backup plus the most recent differential, offering faster restores than incrementals (which require the full backup plus every incremental in sequence) while using less storage than daily full backups; snapshots without a full baseline are not a complete backup strategy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A critical zero-day vulnerability is being actively exploited in the wild, and a vendor-supplied patch must be deployed immediately to production systems, bypassing the normal Change Advisory Board (CAB) review cycle. Which practice BEST reflects proper emergency change management?","o":["Apply the patch immediately without documentation, since emergency changes are exempt from change management processes","Apply the patch immediately under emergency change procedures, then conduct a retrospective CAB review and formally document the change and its justification","Delay patch deployment until the next scheduled CAB meeting regardless of the exploit's severity","Allow each system owner to independently decide whether to apply the patch, without central tracking"],"c":1,"why":"Emergency change management processes allow expedited implementation for urgent risks but still require retrospective review and documentation to maintain accountability, traceability, and lessons-learned analysis. Skipping documentation entirely, delaying for a scheduled meeting during active exploitation, or decentralizing decision-making undermine control and governance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A data center's fire suppression system is being upgraded. Given the presence of sensitive electronic equipment, which suppression method is MOST appropriate to minimize equipment damage while effectively extinguishing fires?","o":["Water sprinkler systems (wet pipe)","Carbon dioxide (CO2) flooding systems","Clean agent gaseous suppression (e.g., FM-200 or similar)","Foam-based suppression systems"],"c":2,"why":"Clean agent gaseous systems extinguish fires without leaving residue or damaging electronics and are safer for occupied spaces than CO2, which displaces oxygen and poses asphyxiation risk; water and foam systems can cause significant damage to electronic equipment.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored highly classified data. Which sanitization approach is MOST appropriate according to NIST SP 800-88 guidelines, given the known limitations of traditional methods on flash-based media?","o":["Degaussing, since it is effective on any magnetic or electronic storage media","A single-pass overwrite with zeros, which is sufficient for all storage media types","Cryptographic erase combined with physical destruction, since wear-leveling and overprovisioning can leave residual data inaccessible to standard overwrite or degaussing methods","A low-level format performed through the operating system's disk utility"],"c":2,"why":"NIST SP 800-88 recognizes that SSDs use wear-leveling and overprovisioning, making traditional overwriting unreliable and degaussing ineffective since SSDs are not magnetic media; cryptographic erase plus physical destruction is recommended for high-sensitivity data. Overwriting, degaussing, and OS-level formatting cannot reliably sanitize all physical storage cells on SSDs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A security team deploys a honeypot on the network. An attacker who had already been observed attempting unauthorized scanning and exploitation against the production network is subsequently redirected to the honeypot, where they continue their attack. From a legal defensibility standpoint, why does this scenario represent enticement rather than entrapment?","o":["Because honeypots are illegal in all jurisdictions, so the distinction is irrelevant","Because the attacker had already demonstrated independent criminal intent and action before interacting with the honeypot, rather than being induced to commit a crime they otherwise would not have attempted","Because entrapment only applies to law enforcement agencies, never to private organizations, regardless of attacker intent","Because a warrant was obtained prior to deploying the honeypot, which is the sole factor separating entrapment from enticement"],"c":1,"why":"Enticement is legally distinguished from entrapment by the fact that the attacker independently formed and acted on criminal intent before any inducement by the defender; redirecting an already-attacking party to a honeypot does not create new criminal intent. Warrants are not required for honeypot deployment on one's own network, and the entrapment/enticement distinction applies broadly, not only to law enforcement.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"In a multilevel secure (MLS) database, a user cleared only for the Unclassified level attempts to insert a new row using a primary key value that already belongs to an existing Secret-level row. The DBMS silently creates a second row with the same key value but marks it Unclassified, rather than rejecting the insert or revealing that the Secret row exists. Which security technique does this describe, and what does it primarily prevent?","o":["Polyinstantiation; it prevents a covert/inference channel that would reveal the existence of higher-classified data through a primary key collision.","Database aggregation control; it prevents combining lower-classified data to derive a higher-classified aggregate value.","View-based access control; it enforces need-to-know by exposing filtered views per clearance level.","Content-dependent access control; it grants access based on data values rather than key structure."],"c":0,"why":"Polyinstantiation allows multiple rows with the same key at different classification levels so that a lower-cleared user's insert doesn't fail or leak the presence of a higher-classified record, closing a covert channel. Aggregation, views, and content-dependent control address different problems and don't explain the duplicate-key behavior described.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security team wants to detect a SQL injection flaw that only becomes exploitable once the application is executing against its live database during automated functional regression tests. They also want the tool to pinpoint the exact vulnerable line of source code without a separate manual code review. Which testing approach best satisfies both requirements?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Manual penetration testing"],"c":2,"why":"IAST uses runtime instrumentation/agents embedded in the running application, so it observes actual execution (like DAST) while correlating findings back to exact source lines (like SAST). Pure DAST is black-box and can't cite source lines; pure SAST has no runtime context; manual pen testing doesn't automatically map to source code at scale.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A mobile banking application exposes a REST API endpoint that allows a user to retrieve account details by supplying an account ID in the URL. A tester discovers that by simply changing the account ID value, they can view other customers' account data without additional authorization checks. This vulnerability is best classified as which type of flaw?","o":["Broken object-level authorization","Insecure cryptographic storage","Cross-site request forgery","Security misconfiguration in the web server"],"c":0,"why":"Broken object-level authorization occurs when an API fails to verify that the requesting user is authorized to access the specific object referenced by an identifier, allowing horizontal privilege escalation. The other options describe unrelated vulnerability classes not indicated by this scenario.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization's internal build system pulls a package named 'auth-utils' from a public package repository because the internal private registry was misconfigured with lower priority. An attacker had already published a malicious package with the same name and a higher version number to the public repository. The build unknowingly incorporated the malicious package. Which control would most directly mitigate this dependency confusion attack?","o":["Increase logging verbosity on the build server to detect anomalies after the fact.","Enforce package signing and scope all internal package names to a trusted private registry, giving it explicit priority over public sources, combined with lockfile version pinning.","Require two-person code review for all pull requests.","Run container image vulnerability scans after the build completes."],"c":1,"why":"Dependency confusion exploits ambiguous package resolution between private and public registries; scoping/namespacing packages, prioritizing the trusted private source, and pinning verified versions/hashes prevent the wrong package from being fetched. Logging, code review, and post-build scanning are detective, not preventive, and don't address the resolution flaw itself.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A CISO wants to benchmark the organization's software security practices against industry norms and create a roadmap for improving processes such as threat modeling, secure coding standards, and security testing maturity across development teams. Which of the following would be MOST useful for this purpose?","o":["A software composition analysis (SCA) tool report","The Software Assurance Maturity Model (SAMM)","A single penetration test report from the last release","The organization's incident response plan"],"c":1,"why":"SAMM (and similarly BSIMM) is specifically designed to assess and benchmark an organization's software security practices and guide maturity improvement across the SDLC. SCA reports, a single pen test, and an incident response plan provide point-in-time or unrelated information, not a maturity framework.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During a secure code review, an architect finds that Module A directly manipulates Module B's internal data structures and repeatedly calls several of Module B's private helper functions to perform multiple unrelated tasks. From a secure software design standpoint, what does this design most likely indicate, and what is the recommended remediation?","o":["High coupling and low cohesion; refactor to increase cohesion within modules and reduce coupling between them via well-defined interfaces.","Low coupling and high cohesion; no remediation is needed since encapsulation is preserved.","High cohesion and low coupling; increase coupling further to improve code reuse.","Low cohesion and low coupling; introduce shared global variables to simplify inter-module communication."],"c":0,"why":"Direct manipulation of another module's internals and reliance on unrelated helper functions is a classic symptom of high coupling and low cohesion, which enlarges attack surface and complicates isolated security testing. The other options mischaracterize the symptoms or recommend changes that would worsen security and maintainability.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization is adopting continuous integration/continuous deployment (CI/CD) pipelines and wants to ensure that security vulnerabilities in third-party open-source libraries are identified automatically before code is merged. Which tool type should be integrated into the pipeline to BEST meet this need?","o":["Software composition analysis (SCA)","Web application firewall (WAF)","Network intrusion detection system (NIDS)","Data loss prevention (DLP) solution"],"c":0,"why":"SCA tools scan dependencies and open-source components for known vulnerabilities and license issues, directly addressing risks from third-party libraries in the build pipeline. A WAF, NIDS, and DLP protect running systems or data flows, not source dependencies during build.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization's software engineering process group reports that all major development processes are formally documented and tailored per project (organization-defined), and the organization has begun collecting detailed process performance metrics and applying statistical process control to reduce variation in cycle time and defect rates. It has not yet implemented systematic, organization-wide process innovation. According to the CMMI model, which maturity level best describes this organization?","o":["Level 2 – Managed","Level 3 – Defined","Level 4 – Quantitatively Managed","Level 5 – Optimizing"],"c":2,"why":"Level 4 (Quantitatively Managed) is characterized by statistical/quantitative control of process performance, which this scenario explicitly describes. Level 3 involves standardized, tailored processes without the statistical control described; Level 5 requires continuous, proactive process improvement/innovation, which is explicitly absent here.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A penetration tester overflows a stack-based buffer in a legacy C application and overwrites the return address to redirect execution to injected shellcode placed on the stack. Which memory-protection control, when properly enabled at the OS/CPU level, would prevent this specific exploit from executing, regardless of where the attacker places the shellcode in memory?","o":["Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)","Data Execution Prevention (DEP)/NX bit","Stack canary/cookie value","Structured Exception Handler Overwrite Protection (SEHOP)"],"c":1,"why":"DEP/NX marks data regions like the stack as non-executable, so the CPU refuses to execute injected shellcode there no matter its address. ASLR only randomizes locations (bypassable via leaks/brute force, not a hard execution block); stack canaries detect overflow before return but don't prevent execution of code already placed elsewhere; SEHOP protects exception handler chains, not generic shellcode execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A file-handling routine first calls stat() to verify that a target log file is owned by the current user with safe permissions, then later calls open() on the same file path to write data. An attacker exploits the interval between these calls by replacing the file with a symbolic link to a sensitive system file. Which secure coding practice would best eliminate this vulnerability class?","o":["Reduce the interval between the check and the use to shrink the race window.","Combine the check and use into a single atomic operation (e.g., open with O_NOFOLLOW/O_EXCL) rather than performing separate check-then-act calls.","Encrypt the log file at rest to prevent tampering.","Run the log-writing process with reduced privileges."],"c":1,"why":"This is a TOCTOU (time-of-check-to-time-of-use) race condition; the only reliable fix is eliminating the gap by using atomic operations that check and act in one step. Shrinking the window reduces but doesn't eliminate risk; encryption doesn't stop the symlink substitution; privilege reduction limits impact but doesn't fix the underlying race.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A newly disclosed critical vulnerability affects a specific version of a widely used open-source logging library. The security team must rapidly determine which of the organization's several hundred applications include this library, even as a transitive (nested) dependency, without manually inspecting each codebase. Which practice, if already implemented, would most efficiently enable this determination?","o":["Static code analysis results from the most recent release cycle.","Maintaining an accurate, automatically generated Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) for each application.","Annual third-party penetration testing reports.","A centralized secrets management vault."],"c":1,"why":"An SBOM inventories all direct and transitive components in each application, enabling rapid, automated searches for a specific vulnerable library version across the portfolio. SAST results, pen test reports, and secrets vaults don't provide a comprehensive, queryable inventory of software components.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application accepts user-supplied data and directly concatenates it into a SQL query string without any filtering. This design most directly exposes the application to which type of attack?","o":["Cross-site request forgery","SQL injection","Buffer overflow","Session fixation"],"c":1,"why":"Directly embedding unsanitized user input into SQL statements is the classic root cause of SQL injection; the other attacks target different mechanisms such as request forgery, memory handling, or session tokens, not query construction.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which secure coding practice is most effective at preventing injection attacks such as SQL injection and command injection?","o":["Input validation and parameterized queries","Code obfuscation","Increasing server memory allocation","Disabling error messages to users"],"c":0,"why":"Validating input and using parameterized queries (or prepared statements) ensures untrusted data cannot alter command structure, directly preventing injection. Obfuscation, memory allocation, and hiding error messages do not address the root cause.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization detects unusual network traffic indicating a possible compromise. According to standard incident response methodology, what should the team do immediately after detecting and confirming the incident, before eradication begins?","o":["Contain the affected systems to prevent further damage or spread","Restore all systems from the most recent backup","Notify law enforcement and regulatory agencies","Conduct a full root-cause analysis and lessons-learned review"],"c":0,"why":"Containment follows detection/identification in the incident response lifecycle to limit damage before eradication and recovery occur. Restoration, notification, and lessons-learned happen at later stages of the process.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of using a version control system during software development?","o":["To automatically encrypt source code at rest","To track and manage changes to source code over time, enabling rollback and collaboration","To perform dynamic testing of the application","To compile source code into executable binaries"],"c":1,"why":"Version control systems track history of code changes, support collaboration, and allow reverting to prior states; they are not primarily encryption tools, testing tools, or compilers.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A security analyst wants to correlate log data from firewalls, servers, and endpoint agents in real time to identify potential attack patterns across the enterprise. Which technology best supports this goal?","o":["A Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system","A host-based intrusion prevention system (HIPS)","A vulnerability scanner","A configuration management database (CMDB)"],"c":0,"why":"A SIEM aggregates and correlates log and event data from multiple sources for centralized analysis and alerting. HIPS protects individual hosts, a vulnerability scanner finds weaknesses, and a CMDB tracks configuration items, none of which correlate multi-source logs.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before a proposed modification to a production system is implemented, it must be reviewed and approved by a designated group to assess risk and business impact. What is this group commonly called?","o":["Change Advisory Board (CAB)","Incident Response Team (IRT)","Configuration Control Board for Disaster Recovery","Security Operations Center (SOC) staff"],"c":0,"why":"The Change Advisory Board reviews, evaluates, and approves proposed changes as part of formal change management. The IRT handles incidents, and the SOC monitors operations, but neither approves change requests.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which type of software testing analyzes source code for vulnerabilities without executing the program?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Penetration testing","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing"],"c":2,"why":"SAST examines source or compiled code without running it, identifying issues like insecure functions or logic flaws. DAST, penetration testing, and fuzzing all involve executing the running application.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"An organization requires that all changes to production application code go through documented approval, testing, and rollback planning before deployment. This practice is an example of which security control?","o":["Data loss prevention","Change management","Identity federation","Network segmentation"],"c":1,"why":"Change management processes formally control, document, and approve modifications to systems and code to reduce risk of unauthorized or untested changes; the other options address unrelated security domains.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A backup strategy captures only the data that has changed since the last full backup, regardless of any incremental backups taken in between. What type of backup is this?","o":["Differential backup","Incremental backup","Full backup","Snapshot backup"],"c":0,"why":"A differential backup always backs up changes since the last full backup, resulting in larger backups over time but simpler restoration. Incremental backups only capture changes since the last backup of any type, making them smaller but requiring more files to restore.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Before integrating a third-party open-source library into an application, which action best supports secure software development practices?","o":["Assume the library is secure because it is widely used","Review the library for known vulnerabilities and verify its provenance and licensing","Disable all logging to improve performance","Skip code review since the source code is not written in-house"],"c":1,"why":"Vetting third-party components for known vulnerabilities, integrity, and licensing is essential to secure development, since popularity alone does not guarantee security; disabling logging or skipping review increases risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which practice best exemplifies the principle of 'least privilege' when designing an application's access control model?","o":["Granting all authenticated users administrative rights for convenience","Assigning users only the minimum permissions necessary to perform their job functions","Allowing all users to bypass authentication for internal tools","Granting broad default permissions and restricting access only when issues arise"],"c":1,"why":"Least privilege means users receive only the access needed to perform their tasks, minimizing potential damage from compromised accounts. Granting broad or default access contradicts this principle and increases risk.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During business continuity planning, a company determines that the order-processing system must be restored within 4 hours of an outage to avoid unacceptable business impact. This 4-hour figure represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":0,"why":"RTO defines the target time within which a system must be restored after a disruption. RPO relates to acceptable data loss, MTD is the absolute maximum downtime before severe damage occurs, and MTBF measures reliability, not recovery targets.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization is decommissioning old magnetic tape backups that contain sensitive data. Which method is most appropriate for ensuring the data cannot be recovered?","o":["Degaussing the tapes with a strong magnetic field","Deleting the file index on the tapes","Reformatting the tapes using standard software","Physically relabeling the tapes as \"empty\""],"c":0,"why":"Degaussing uses a strong magnetic field to disrupt the magnetic domains on tape media, effectively destroying the data. Deleting an index or reformatting leaves recoverable data, and relabeling does nothing to the actual content.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During a forensic investigation, an analyst documents every person who handled a piece of digital evidence, along with the time, date, and purpose of each transfer. What principle is being followed?","o":["Chain of custody","Least privilege","Separation of duties","Data remanence control"],"c":0,"why":"Chain of custody documents the handling of evidence to preserve its integrity and admissibility in legal proceedings. Least privilege and separation of duties are access control principles, and data remanence control relates to residual data after deletion.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization detects that an internal file server has been compromised by malware that is actively exfiltrating data. According to standard incident response methodology, what should the response team do immediately after confirming the compromise, before eradicating the malware or restoring the system?","o":["Contain the affected system to prevent further damage or spread","Perform root cause analysis and write the final incident report","Restore the system from the most recent backup","Notify all employees company-wide about the incident"],"c":0,"why":"Containment must occur immediately after detection/analysis to stop further damage before eradication and recovery; jumping to restoration or reporting before containment risks reinfection or loss of evidence, and mass notification is not an immediate technical priority.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Before deploying a newly released vendor patch to production servers, an organization first applies it to a limited set of non-production systems to check for compatibility issues. What best describes this practice?","o":["Patch testing in a controlled environment prior to broader rollout","Emergency change management bypassing normal review","Zero-day vulnerability exploitation testing","Configuration baseline enforcement"],"c":0,"why":"Testing patches in a non-production environment first helps identify compatibility or stability issues before wide deployment, reducing operational risk. The other options describe unrelated or opposite practices, such as bypassing review or testing exploits.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During incident response to a suspected server compromise, the team must collect forensic evidence before remediation begins. Which sequence of evidence collection correctly follows the principle of order of volatility, from MOST volatile to LEAST volatile?","o":["CPU registers and cache; routing tables/ARP cache/process tables; RAM contents; temporary file systems; disk data; remote logs and archival media","Disk data; RAM contents; CPU registers and cache; remote logs; archival backups","RAM contents; disk data; CPU registers and cache; archival backups; remote logs","Remote logs; disk data; RAM contents; CPU registers and cache; archival backups"],"c":0,"why":"Per RFC 3227 and standard forensic practice, evidence should be collected starting with the most volatile artifacts (registers/cache), then kernel/network state, RAM, temporary storage, disk, and finally remote logs and archival media which persist longest. The other orderings collect volatile data too late, risking loss of critical evidence.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A forensic investigator seizes a laptop as evidence in a suspected fraud case. Which practice is MOST critical to ensuring the evidence remains admissible in court?","o":["Encrypting the hard drive before analysis to protect confidentiality","Maintaining a documented chain of custody showing who handled the evidence and when","Analyzing the original drive directly to preserve the exact state of the data","Storing the laptop in the investigator's personal office for convenience"],"c":1,"why":"Chain of custody documentation proves evidence integrity and handling history, which courts require for admissibility. Analyzing the original drive directly (rather than a forensic image) risks altering evidence, and improper storage undermines integrity.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A workstation on the finance VLAN begins encrypting files rapidly, indicating active ransomware. The incident handler wants to stop the spread while preserving maximum forensic value. Which action is MOST appropriate as the FIRST containment step?","o":["Immediately power off the workstation to stop the encryption process","Disconnect the workstation from the network (e.g., disable the switch port) while leaving it powered on","Run a full antivirus scan on the live system before taking any other action","Wait until the incident response team completes a formal risk assessment before touching the system"],"c":1,"why":"Isolating the host from the network halts lateral spread while preserving volatile memory for forensic analysis; powering off destroys RAM-based evidence and may trigger destructive payloads, scanning a live infected system risks altering artifacts, and delaying containment allows continued spread.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During a threat modeling exercise using STRIDE, a security architect identifies a scenario where an attacker intercepts a firmware update package in transit and alters its binary contents before the device installs it, causing the device to execute attacker-controlled code. Which STRIDE category best classifies this threat?","o":["Repudiation","Tampering","Information Disclosure","Elevation of Privilege"],"c":1,"why":"Tampering refers to unauthorized modification of data or code, which matches the alteration of the firmware package. Repudiation deals with denying an action, Information Disclosure with unauthorized data exposure, and Elevation of Privilege with gaining unauthorized access rights—none of which describe modifying the update's contents.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization implements a formal change management process requiring all production changes to be reviewed by a Change Advisory Board (CAB) before implementation. What is the PRIMARY security benefit of this process?","o":["It guarantees that all changes will improve system performance","It eliminates the need for post-implementation testing","It reduces the risk of unauthorized or poorly vetted changes disrupting operations or introducing vulnerabilities","It replaces the need for a configuration management database"],"c":2,"why":"Change management's core purpose is risk reduction by ensuring changes are reviewed, tested, and approved before deployment, preventing unauthorized or harmful changes; it does not guarantee performance gains, eliminate testing needs, or replace CMDB functions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An application accepts user input directly into SQL query strings, making it vulnerable to SQL injection. Which remediation provides the strongest protection against this vulnerability?","o":["Encrypting the database at rest","Using parameterized queries (prepared statements)","Implementing a web application firewall only","Increasing input field character limits"],"c":1,"why":"Parameterized queries separate code from data so user input cannot alter query logic, directly addressing the root cause of SQL injection. Encryption at rest protects stored data but not query logic, a WAF is a compensating control that can be bypassed, and limiting field length does not prevent malicious syntax within the allowed length.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A business continuity plan specifies a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 4 hours for an order-processing database. The current backup schedule performs snapshots every 6 hours. Which statement BEST describes this situation?","o":["The RPO is being met because backups occur regularly throughout the day","The backup schedule fails to meet the RPO; in a worst-case failure, up to 6 hours of data could be lost, exceeding the 4-hour tolerance","The RPO should simply be redefined to match the Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of the system","RPO only applies to full system recovery, not to database transactions, so the backup schedule is irrelevant"],"c":1,"why":"RPO defines the maximum tolerable data loss measured in time; a 6-hour backup interval exceeds a 4-hour RPO, meaning more frequent backups or replication are needed. RPO and RTO measure different concepts and are not interchangeable, and RPO is directly tied to backup/replication frequency for the data in question.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company's business continuity plan states that after a disruption, critical order-processing systems must be restored within 4 hours, and no more than 15 minutes of transaction data can be lost. Which metric defines the 15-minute value?","o":["Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":2,"why":"RPO defines the acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, dictating backup frequency. RTO defines the time to restore operations (the 4-hour figure), MTD is the overall tolerable outage duration, and MTBF relates to hardware reliability, not data loss.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"During a code review, an analyst notes that a C program copies user-supplied input into a fixed-size stack buffer without checking the input length. Which vulnerability class does this represent?","o":["Race condition (TOCTOU)","Integer overflow","Buffer overflow","Cross-site request forgery"],"c":2,"why":"Copying unchecked input into a fixed-size buffer can overwrite adjacent memory, which is the classic definition of a buffer overflow. TOCTOU involves timing between check and use, integer overflow involves numeric wraparound, and CSRF is a web-specific attack unrelated to memory handling.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security team must assess a vendor-supplied web application for vulnerabilities. They have no access to source code, cannot install runtime agents on the vendor's servers, but can send crafted HTTP requests to the running application and observe its responses, including error messages and behavior under malformed input. Which testing methodology is most appropriate for this constraint?","o":["Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)"],"c":1,"why":"DAST is a black-box technique that tests a running application externally by sending inputs and analyzing outputs, requiring no source code or internal instrumentation. SAST requires source code access, IAST requires instrumentation agents inside the running application, and SCA analyzes third-party components/libraries rather than runtime behavior.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A critical zero-day vulnerability requires an emergency patch to production systems outside the normal change window. Which practice BEST reflects a properly governed emergency change management process?","o":["The system administrator applies the patch immediately without documentation, since speed is critical during an emergency","The patch is applied after abbreviated approval from a designated emergency change authority, with documentation, testing where feasible, and formal Change Advisory Board (CAB) review after the fact","The change is delayed until the next scheduled CAB meeting to maintain process integrity","The vendor applies the patch directly, bypassing all internal change control since it originates externally"],"c":1,"why":"Emergency change processes still require authorization and documentation, just on an accelerated timeline, followed by formal after-the-fact review; skipping documentation or delaying critical patches both introduce unacceptable risk, and external vendor access must still go through internal change control.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A database administrator configures nightly backups such that each backup captures only the data that has changed since the LAST FULL backup, regardless of any backups taken in between. Restoring the database requires the last full backup plus only the most recent of these backups. Which backup type is being described?","o":["Incremental backup","Differential backup","Full backup","Snapshot backup"],"c":1,"why":"Differential backups capture changes since the last full backup, so only the last full and the most recent differential are needed for restoration. Incremental backups capture changes since the last backup of any type, requiring the full backup plus every incremental since then.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A software organization wants to formally assess and improve the maturity of its development processes, moving from ad hoc practices toward defined, measured, and optimized processes. Which model is specifically designed for this purpose?","o":["ITIL","CMMI","COBIT","TOGAF"],"c":1,"why":"CMMI (Capability Maturity Model Integration) provides staged or continuous maturity levels specifically for improving software/process development capability. ITIL focuses on IT service management, COBIT on IT governance, and TOGAF on enterprise architecture.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization's log retention policy automatically purges security logs after 90 days. Legal counsel has just issued a litigation hold notice indicating logs from a specific server are relevant to pending litigation, and those logs are scheduled for automatic deletion in five days. What should the security team do?","o":["Allow the automatic deletion to proceed, since the retention policy was approved by management before the litigation hold","Suspend the automatic deletion process for the affected logs and preserve them until the legal hold is lifted, overriding the standard retention schedule","Delete the logs early to avoid the appearance of tampering once litigation formally begins","Encrypt the logs and continue with scheduled deletion, since encrypted data does not require preservation"],"c":1,"why":"A litigation hold legally supersedes routine retention/destruction schedules; failing to preserve relevant evidence constitutes spoliation and can result in legal sanctions. The other options all result in destruction of evidence subject to the hold.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An employee with authorized access to view individual employee salary records issues a series of legitimate queries and mathematically combines the results to calculate the organization's total payroll budget, a figure classified at a higher sensitivity level than any single salary. Which database security issue does this scenario illustrate?","o":["Inference attack","Aggregation attack","Polyinstantiation","SQL injection"],"c":1,"why":"Aggregation occurs when combining multiple pieces of individually low-sensitivity data produces a result that should be classified higher. Inference involves deducing restricted information indirectly without directly querying it; polyinstantiation involves creating multiple record versions at different classification levels; SQL injection is a code injection attack, not a data classification issue.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A security team deploys a SIEM solution that ingests logs from firewalls, IDS sensors, and endpoint agents. What is the PRIMARY operational advantage this provides over reviewing each log source independently?","o":["It eliminates the need for endpoint detection agents","It automatically patches vulnerabilities identified in the logs","It correlates events across multiple sources to identify attack patterns that a single log source would not reveal","It guarantees compliance with all regulatory logging requirements"],"c":2,"why":"SIEM's core value is correlation of disparate log sources to detect multi-stage or distributed attacks that would be missed reviewing sources in isolation. It does not patch vulnerabilities, replace endpoint agents, or automatically ensure regulatory compliance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization needs to securely decommission a set of solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained classified data. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate, given the limitations of traditional techniques on flash-based media?","o":["Degaussing the drives with a high-powered magnetic field","Performing a single-pass overwrite using a standard formatting utility","Using the manufacturer's ATA Secure Erase or cryptographic erase command with verification, per NIST SP 800-88 guidance, or physical destruction if erase cannot be verified","Deleting all files and emptying the recycle bin"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory rather than magnetic media, so degaussing has no effect; wear-leveling can leave overwritten data recoverable via simple formatting; NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic/secure erase with verification, or physical destruction as a fallback, for flash-based storage.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A file-processing application first checks whether the invoking user has write permission to a specified file path, and shortly afterward opens that path for writing. An attacker exploits the delay between these two operations by replacing the target file with a symbolic link pointing to a sensitive system file, causing the application to overwrite it with attacker-controlled data. What vulnerability class does this describe?","o":["Buffer overflow","Time-of-check to time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition","Cross-site request forgery","Integer overflow"],"c":1,"why":"TOCTOU vulnerabilities occur when a security check and the subsequent use of the resource are separated in time, allowing an attacker to alter the resource's state in between. Buffer/integer overflows involve memory corruption from unchecked input size or arithmetic, and CSRF is a web attack forcing unwanted actions in an authenticated session—none match this timing-based file substitution attack.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that contained highly sensitive data. Which sanitization method is MOST appropriate and effective for this media type?","o":["Degaussing the drives with a strong magnetic field","Performing a single-pass overwrite of the entire drive","Using the manufacturer's cryptographic erase function or secure erase command designed for SSDs","Formatting the drive using the operating system's quick format utility"],"c":2,"why":"SSDs use flash memory unaffected by magnetic fields, making degaussing ineffective; wear-leveling also makes simple overwrites unreliable for full sanitization. Cryptographic erase or vendor-specific secure erase commands are the recommended methods for SSDs, per NIST SP 800-88 guidance.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A company performs a full backup every Sunday and differential backups every other night. On Thursday, the primary storage array fails. To restore the system to the most recent recoverable point using this differential backup strategy, which backups are required?","o":["The full backup from Sunday plus every differential backup from Monday through Wednesday, applied in sequence","The full backup from Sunday plus only the most recent differential backup (Wednesday night's)","Only the most recent differential backup, since it contains all changes since the full backup","Every incremental backup since the last full backup, applied in reverse chronological order"],"c":1,"why":"A differential backup captures all changes since the last full backup, so restoration requires only the full backup plus the latest differential. Incremental backups (not used here) would require the full backup plus every incremental in sequence, and a differential alone lacks the full baseline needed for restoration.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A development team designs a public REST API that requires clients to include a static API key as a parameter directly in the URL query string (e.g., https://api.example.com/data?apikey=XYZ123). During a security review, this design is flagged as high risk. What is the PRIMARY concern with this approach?","o":["The API key will expire too quickly, causing frequent authentication failures","URL query strings are commonly logged by web servers, proxies, and browser history, exposing the key to unauthorized parties","REST APIs cannot support any form of authentication in the URL","Query string parameters are automatically encrypted by HTTPS, making this method insecure"],"c":1,"why":"URLs, including query strings, are routinely recorded in server logs, proxy logs, browser history, and referrer headers, creating multiple avenues for credential leakage. Key expiration is unrelated to this design flaw, REST APIs can support various authentication methods, and while HTTPS encrypts the transport, it does not prevent logging of the URL at endpoints after decryption.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A company implements RAID 5 across five disks in a storage array to improve availability. What happens if two disks in the array fail simultaneously?","o":["The array continues operating normally with no data loss","Data is lost because RAID 5 can only tolerate a single disk failure","The array automatically rebuilds using distributed parity across all five disks","Performance decreases but all data remains fully accessible"],"c":1,"why":"RAID 5 uses single parity striping, tolerating only one disk failure at a time; a second simultaneous failure causes data loss because there is insufficient parity information to reconstruct the data. RAID 6 or mirrored configurations would be needed to survive two simultaneous failures.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"In a DevSecOps pipeline, security controls such as static code scanning and dependency checking are integrated as early as possible in the development lifecycle. This practice is best described as:","o":["Security by obscurity","Shift-left security","Defense in depth","Separation of duties"],"c":1,"why":"Shift-left security means moving security testing and controls earlier in the SDLC to catch issues before they become costly to fix. Security by obscurity relies on hiding design details, defense in depth uses layered controls, and separation of duties divides responsibilities to prevent fraud—neither describes early-lifecycle integration.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization wants to ensure that software updates pushed to thousands of endpoint devices are verifiably authentic and have not been altered since being released by the vendor, even if the update is distributed through an untrusted content delivery network. Which control best addresses this requirement?","o":["File integrity monitoring on the endpoint after installation","Digital code signing of the update package by the vendor","Mandatory access control on the update repository","Network-based intrusion detection at the CDN edge"],"c":1,"why":"Digital code signing uses the vendor's private key to cryptographically sign the package, allowing endpoints to verify authenticity and integrity before installation regardless of the distribution channel's trustworthiness. File integrity monitoring detects changes only after the fact, MAC on the repository doesn't protect the package once it leaves that repository, and IDS at the CDN edge does not verify code authenticity end-to-end.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A data center's server room door is equipped with an electronic lock tied to the building's fire alarm system, and the room also serves as a fire egress path. Which lock configuration is MOST appropriate, balancing security and life safety requirements?","o":["Fail-secure, so the door remains locked during a power failure to protect sensitive equipment","Fail-safe, so the door automatically unlocks during a power failure or fire alarm activation to allow safe evacuation","A manual deadbolt with no electronic integration, to avoid dependency on the fire alarm system","Fail-secure, but with a manual key override available only to the facilities manager"],"c":1,"why":"Life safety and fire codes require egress paths to unlock automatically upon power loss or fire alarm activation (fail-safe) so occupants can evacuate safely; fail-secure configurations that keep egress doors locked during emergencies violate life-safety requirements regardless of the security benefit.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"Two virtual machines belonging to different security domains share the same physical hypervisor. Despite having no authorized network connection or shared file system, security researchers discover that one VM can leak classified data to the other by deliberately modulating its CPU cache access patterns in a specific timing sequence that the second VM monitors and decodes. What does this scenario best describe?","o":["A covert channel","A side-channel attack via power analysis","A man-in-the-middle attack","A denial-of-service attack"],"c":0,"why":"A covert channel is an unintended communication path that violates security policy by allowing information transfer between subjects not authorized to communicate, and using cache timing to deliberately encode and transmit data is a classic covert timing channel. Side-channel power analysis targets cryptographic key extraction from power consumption, not deliberate two-party communication; MITM requires interception of legitimate traffic; and DoS aims to disrupt availability, not exfiltrate data.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A company is licensing critical software from a small vendor and is concerned the vendor could go out of business, leaving the company without support or source code. Which contractual arrangement best mitigates this risk?","o":["Service level agreement (SLA)","Software escrow agreement","Non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","Right-to-audit clause"],"c":1,"why":"A software escrow agreement places source code with a neutral third party, to be released to the licensee if the vendor fails to meet contractual obligations (e.g., bankruptcy), directly addressing business continuity risk. An SLA defines performance metrics, an NDA protects confidential information, and a right-to-audit clause allows inspection but does not guarantee code access.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"An organization uses object-oriented programming and wants to ensure that internal implementation details of a class are hidden from external code, exposing only defined interfaces. Which OOP concept enforces this?","o":["Polymorphism","Inheritance","Encapsulation","Abstraction layering"],"c":2,"why":"Encapsulation bundles data and methods within a class while restricting direct access to internal state, exposing only well-defined interfaces—supporting secure design by limiting unintended access. Polymorphism allows objects to be treated as instances of a common superclass, inheritance allows classes to derive properties from parent classes, and 'abstraction layering' is not a standard OOP encapsulation mechanism.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A multi-level secure database must allow a low-clearance user to insert a record with the same primary key as an existing high-classification record, without the low-clearance user being able to detect the existence of the high-classification version, while both records remain independently accessible to users at their respective clearance levels. Which database security technique enables this?","o":["Polyinstantiation","Database normalization","View-based access control alone","Data masking"],"c":0,"why":"Polyinstantiation allows multiple instances of a record with the same key to exist at different classification levels, preventing lower-level users from inferring the existence of higher-level data through key collisions or update conflicts. Normalization addresses data redundancy and integrity, not classification; view-based access control alone would typically prevent the insert due to key conflicts rather than allowing coexisting instances; data masking obscures values but does not resolve the multi-instance key conflict.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm is designing a secure SDLC and wants to catch vulnerabilities as early as possible while code is still being written, with full visibility into source code structure and logic paths. Which testing technique should be integrated directly into the developer's IDE and CI pipeline for this purpose?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing against a running instance","Penetration testing during the deployment phase"],"c":1,"why":"SAST analyzes source, bytecode, or binary code without executing it, allowing early detection of flaws like injection points during coding. DAST and fuzzing require a running application, and penetration testing typically occurs later, closer to deployment, not during coding.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A developer implements a function that checks whether a file exists and is owned by the requesting user, then later opens that file for writing based on the earlier check. An attacker is able to replace the file with a symbolic link to a sensitive system file between the check and the open operation. This is an example of which vulnerability class?","o":["Race condition (TOCTOU)","Buffer overflow","SQL injection","Cross-site request forgery"],"c":0,"why":"This is a classic Time-of-Check-to-Time-of-Use (TOCTOU) race condition, where the state of a resource changes between validation and use. It has no relation to buffer overflows, injection, or CSRF, which involve entirely different attack mechanics.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"During a code review, a security architect finds that a web application concatenates user input directly into a SQL query string without any sanitization, but the application does use a web application firewall (WAF) to filter known attack patterns. Which statement best describes the residual risk?","o":["The risk is fully mitigated because the WAF blocks all injection attempts","The risk remains significant because WAFs rely on signature/pattern matching and can be bypassed by novel or obfuscated payloads","The risk is eliminated because parameterized queries are unnecessary once a WAF is in place","The risk only applies to stored procedures, not inline SQL concatenation"],"c":1,"why":"WAFs provide a compensating control but are pattern-based and can be evaded through encoding, obfuscation, or novel payloads; the root cause (unsanitized concatenation) remains exploitable. Parameterized queries or prepared statements are still required as the primary defense.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization detects unusual outbound traffic from a server and confirms it is compromised. According to standard incident response methodology, what is the NEXT phase after detection and identification?","o":["Containment","Eradication","Lessons learned","Recovery"],"c":0,"why":"After identifying an incident, the next step is containment to limit damage and prevent spread before eradicating the root cause and moving to recovery. Eradication and recovery occur later, and lessons learned is the final post-incident phase.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization uses a database that returns aggregate salary statistics (e.g., average salary) for query results as small as two employees, allowing an attacker to derive an individual's exact salary by comparing consecutive aggregate queries. Which security concept does this scenario best illustrate?","o":["Polyinstantiation","Inference attack via aggregation","SQL injection through blind boolean queries","Covert channel exploitation"],"c":1,"why":"This describes an inference attack, where sensitive individual data is deduced from permitted aggregate queries, a classic database security concern requiring query result minimum set sizes. Polyinstantiation and covert channels are unrelated database confidentiality mechanisms, and no injection is occurring here.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"During a forensic investigation, an analyst documents who collected each piece of digital evidence, when, and how it was stored and transferred. What principle is being followed?","o":["Least privilege","Separation of duties","Chain of custody","Due diligence"],"c":2,"why":"Chain of custody tracks the handling of evidence from collection to presentation to ensure integrity and admissibility. The other terms relate to access control and organizational governance, not evidence handling.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web application accepts user input for a search field without validating or sanitizing it, allowing an attacker to alter the intended SQL query. Which type of vulnerability does this describe?","o":["Cross-site request forgery","Buffer overflow","SQL injection","Race condition"],"c":2,"why":"SQL injection occurs when unsanitized user input is inserted into a database query, allowing attackers to manipulate query logic; the other options involve different mechanisms (forged requests, memory overflow, or timing issues) unrelated to query manipulation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A software company distributes a proprietary application to enterprise clients and wants to ensure that if the vendor goes out of business, clients can still obtain the source code to maintain the software themselves. Which arrangement best addresses this requirement?","o":["Software escrow agreement with a neutral third party","Perpetual software license with no maintenance clause","Open-sourcing the code under a permissive license immediately","Digital rights management (DRM) embedded in the binary"],"c":0,"why":"A software escrow arrangement places source code with a trusted third party who releases it to licensees under predefined conditions like vendor insolvency, protecting business continuity. The other options either don't address vendor failure or are unrelated to continuity of source access.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A backup strategy captures only the files that have changed since the LAST FULL backup, regardless of any backups taken in between. Which backup type is this?","o":["Incremental backup","Differential backup","Full backup","Snapshot backup"],"c":1,"why":"A differential backup always backs up changes since the last full backup, growing larger each day, whereas an incremental backup only captures changes since the last backup of any type (full or incremental).","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A security team evaluating a microservices architecture is concerned that a compromised internal service could impersonate other services when making API calls, since traffic is only encrypted with TLS at the perimeter gateway. Which control would BEST address this specific concern?","o":["Implementing mutual TLS (mTLS) with service identity verification between all internal services","Increasing TLS certificate key length from 2048-bit to 4096-bit at the gateway only","Enabling HTTP compression on internal API responses","Applying rate limiting on the external API gateway"],"c":0,"why":"Mutual TLS requires both client and server services to present and validate certificates, ensuring internal service-to-service authentication and preventing impersonation—perimeter-only TLS does not protect east-west traffic. Key length increases, compression, and rate limiting don't address service identity verification.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which type of software security testing analyzes an application's source code without executing the program?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Penetration testing","Fuzz testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST examines source or binary code at rest to find flaws before runtime, whereas DAST, penetration testing, and fuzz testing all require the application to be running and exercised with inputs.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of a Change Advisory Board (CAB) in an IT change management process?","o":["To perform the technical implementation of approved changes","To review, assess risk, and approve or reject proposed changes before implementation","To conduct post-incident forensic analysis","To manage user account provisioning requests"],"c":1,"why":"The CAB's role is governance—evaluating risk, impact, and business justification for proposed changes and approving or rejecting them. Implementation is performed by technical teams, not the CAB.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"A CI/CD pipeline automatically pulls open-source dependencies during every build without version pinning or integrity verification. Which attack technique does this practice make the organization MOST vulnerable to?","o":["Dependency confusion / supply chain substitution attack","Cross-site scripting via reflected input","Session fixation during authentication","Business logic abuse through parameter tampering"],"c":0,"why":"Without version pinning and integrity checks (e.g., checksums, signed packages), an attacker can publish a malicious package with a similar name or higher version number that the build system unknowingly pulls—a dependency confusion/supply chain attack. The other options are application-layer runtime attacks unrelated to build-time dependency resolution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"In database security, an inference attack occurs when a user derives sensitive information without directly accessing it. Which scenario best illustrates inference?","o":["A user combines several unclassified reports to deduce a classified fact","A user exploits a buffer overflow to gain root access","A user intercepts network traffic to capture plaintext credentials","A user is granted excessive permissions by a misconfigured access control list"],"c":0,"why":"Inference involves deducing restricted information from a combination of lower-sensitivity data; the other options describe unrelated attack types such as memory exploitation, sniffing, or authorization misconfiguration.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"An organization's business continuity plan states that the order-processing system must be restored within 4 hours of an outage. This 4-hour value represents which metric?","o":["Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)","Recovery Time Objective (RTO)","Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"],"c":2,"why":"RTO is the target time within which a system must be restored after a disruption. RPO refers to acceptable data loss measured in time, MTD is the absolute maximum outage before severe harm, and MTBF measures reliability, not recovery.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which activity is a core component of software configuration management (SCM) that helps ensure only approved code changes are released?","o":["Load balancing","Change control and approval processes","Data classification","Business impact analysis"],"c":1,"why":"SCM relies on formal change control to review, approve, and track modifications to code and configurations before release; the other choices relate to availability, data governance, or continuity planning, not code change oversight.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"hard","q":"An organization is migrating legacy virtual machine-based applications to containers and wants to ensure that even if an attacker compromises a running container, they cannot persist changes or escalate privileges into the underlying host through writable layers. Which design principle should be enforced?","o":["Running all containers with root privileges for administrative simplicity","Using immutable, read-only container filesystems with no persistent writable layer at runtime","Mounting the host's Docker socket into every container for orchestration visibility","Disabling container image scanning to reduce build pipeline latency"],"c":1,"why":"Immutable, read-only filesystems prevent attackers from writing persistent malicious changes inside a compromised container, limiting impact and forcing redeployment from a known-good image. Running as root, mounting the Docker socket, and disabling scanning all significantly increase attack surface and risk of host compromise.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A company is decommissioning hard drives that contained highly sensitive data and wants to ensure the data cannot be recovered by any means before the drives are recycled. Which method provides the HIGHEST assurance of data destruction?","o":["Deleting the files and emptying the recycle bin","Reformatting the drive","Physical destruction (e.g., shredding or pulverizing)","Overwriting the drive once with zeros"],"c":2,"why":"Physical destruction renders the media completely unusable and unreadable, providing the highest assurance for highly sensitive data. Deletion, reformatting, and single-pass overwriting may leave residual data recoverable through forensic techniques.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"A web page allows attackers to inject malicious client-side scripts that execute in the browsers of other users viewing the page. This is an example of which vulnerability?","o":["Cross-site scripting (XSS)","Directory traversal","Session fixation","Command injection"],"c":0,"why":"XSS involves injecting malicious scripts that execute in victims' browsers, typically due to improper output encoding; the other options involve file path manipulation, session identifier abuse, or OS command execution rather than client-side script injection.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D8","d":"easy","q":"Which testing technique involves sending large volumes of random, malformed, or unexpected input to an application to identify crashes or unexpected behavior?","o":["Regression testing","Fuzz testing","Unit testing","White-box testing"],"c":1,"why":"Fuzz testing feeds invalid or random data into an application to discover crashes, memory leaks, or security flaws; regression testing verifies existing functionality, unit testing checks individual components, and white-box testing refers to code-aware testing with knowledge of internal structure, not random input generation.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"Why do organizations implement centralized log collection and correlation (e.g., via a SIEM) as part of security operations?","o":["To reduce the need for network firewalls","To automatically patch vulnerable systems","To aggregate and correlate events from multiple sources for faster detection of security incidents","To encrypt data at rest across all servers"],"c":2,"why":"Centralized logging and correlation allow analysts to detect patterns and incidents across many systems that would be missed if logs were reviewed in isolation. It does not replace firewalls, patching, or encryption functions.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"easy","q":"A data center uses a small enclosed space with two interlocking doors, where only one door can be open at a time, to control physical entry. What is this control called?","o":["Turnstile","Mantrap","Bollard","Faraday cage"],"c":1,"why":"A mantrap is a physical access control with two interlocking doors that prevents piggybacking by allowing only one door open at a time. Turnstiles allow one-at-a-time passage but lack the dual-door design, bollards prevent vehicle intrusion, and a Faraday cage blocks electromagnetic signals.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"During live forensic response on a compromised production server that cannot be powered off, an incident handler must decide the order in which volatile evidence is collected to minimize loss of data. Per the order of volatility principle, which type of data should be captured FIRST?","o":["Contents of CPU registers and cache","Contents of RAM and running process list","Data stored on locally attached hard drives","Data stored on network-attached backup archives"],"c":0,"why":"The order of volatility ranks CPU registers and cache as the most volatile data, lost within nanoseconds if not captured immediately, followed by RAM, then disk, then archival backups, which are the least volatile and can be collected last.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization's BIA identifies a Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) of 10 hours for its ERP system. The recovery team estimates that once the technical system is restored, an additional 3 hours will be required to reload transactions, validate data integrity, and return the application to full production use (work recovery time). Based on this, what is the maximum Recovery Time Objective (RTO) the disaster recovery plan should target for technical restoration?","o":["13 hours","10 hours","7 hours","3 hours"],"c":2,"why":"MTD equals RTO plus WRT (MTD = RTO + WRT). Solving for RTO gives 10 - 3 = 7 hours. Using the full 10 hours as RTO or ignoring WRT would exceed the MTD once work recovery time is added.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A financial services firm is designing a storage array for a mission-critical transaction database. The requirement states the array must remain fully operational even if any two disks fail simultaneously, while providing better storage efficiency than full mirroring. Which RAID level BEST meets this requirement?","o":["RAID 0","RAID 5","RAID 6","RAID 1"],"c":2,"why":"RAID 6 uses dual distributed parity, allowing the array to survive two simultaneous disk failures while using less overhead than mirroring (RAID 1). RAID 5 tolerates only one failure, and RAID 0 offers no redundancy.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"In an Agile development environment, at what point should security requirements ideally first be introduced to minimize costly rework later in the project?","o":["During the sprint retrospective after each release","As part of the product backlog and user stories before sprint planning begins","After user acceptance testing is complete","Only during the final security audit before production release"],"c":1,"why":"Embedding security requirements into user stories before sprint planning ('shift-left') allows developers to design and code securely from the start; addressing security only in retrospectives, after UAT, or at final audit means defects are found too late, increasing remediation cost.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During live forensic evidence collection from a compromised server that must remain operational, an investigator is prioritizing data acquisition based on the order of volatility. Which of the following should be collected FIRST?","o":["Contents of the hard disk file system","CPU cache and register contents","Log files stored on a remote syslog server","Backup tapes stored offsite"],"c":1,"why":"CPU cache/register contents are the most volatile and will be lost almost immediately if not captured first; disk contents, remote logs, and offsite backups are comparatively persistent and can be collected later without loss.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Which testing technique analyzes an application's source or byte code without executing the program, and is commonly used to detect coding flaws such as unvalidated input or insecure function calls?","o":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Penetration testing"],"c":1,"why":"SAST inspects code at rest (source/byte code) to find vulnerabilities before execution. DAST tests a running application, fuzzing sends malformed input to a running program, and penetration testing simulates real-world attacks against a live system—none of these examine code without execution.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An administrator applies an emergency security patch to a production database server outside normal maintenance windows due to an active exploit being used in the wild. No prior Change Advisory Board (CAB) approval was obtained. Which action BEST reflects adherence to a mature change management process?","o":["No further action is required since the patch resolved an active security incident.","The change should be reversed immediately since it bypassed CAB approval.","The emergency change should be documented and submitted for retroactive CAB review and approval.","Future emergency changes should be prohibited to prevent unauthorized modifications."],"c":2,"why":"Mature change management processes include an emergency change track that allows immediate action during active incidents but requires the change be documented and formally reviewed/approved after the fact to maintain accountability and traceability. Reversing a fix that resolved an active exploit, or banning emergency changes outright, would increase risk.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"An organization's disaster recovery plan specifies a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 4 hours for a critical transactional database. Which backup strategy would BEST satisfy this requirement?","o":["A full backup performed once per week","Incremental backups performed every 4 hours between weekly full backups","A full backup performed once per month","Backups performed only after major application releases"],"c":1,"why":"An RPO of 4 hours means no more than 4 hours of data can be lost, requiring backups at least that frequently; weekly, monthly, or release-based backups would allow far more data loss than the RPO permits.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"A user without direct access to salary records is able to determine an employee's approximate salary by cross-referencing that employee's job title with a published report of average departmental salaries. This scenario best illustrates which security concern?","o":["Aggregation","Inference","Polyinstantiation","Data remanence"],"c":1,"why":"Inference occurs when a user logically deduces sensitive information from a combination of non-sensitive data sources, as shown here. Aggregation refers to combining multiple low-sensitivity records of the same type to produce a higher-sensitivity dataset, not deducing new facts through reasoning.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"An organization is decommissioning a batch of solid-state drives (SSDs) that stored classified data. Security staff plan to use the traditional multi-pass overwrite technique used for magnetic hard drives. Which statement BEST describes why this approach is inadequate for SSDs and what should be done instead?","o":["Overwriting is equally effective on SSDs, so no additional action is needed.","SSD wear-leveling and block remapping can leave data remnants untouched by overwrite; cryptographic erase or physical destruction should be used instead.","SSDs cannot be sanitized under any circumstances and must remain in service indefinitely.","Degaussing is the recommended sanitization method for SSDs."],"c":1,"why":"SSD controllers use wear-leveling and remap logical-to-physical blocks, so overwrite commands may not touch all physical locations holding data remnants; NIST SP 800-88 recommends cryptographic erase or physical destruction for flash media. Degaussing is ineffective because SSDs are not magnetic media.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"A backup administrator wants to minimize restore time after a failure and is willing to accept progressively longer nightly backup windows as the week goes on. Which backup strategy best achieves this goal?","o":["Weekly full backups with daily incremental backups","Weekly full backups with daily differential backups","Daily full backups only","Continuous full backups with no incremental or differential backups"],"c":1,"why":"Differential backups capture all changes since the last full backup, so restoration only requires the full backup plus the most recent differential (faster restore), though each differential grows larger over the week; incremental backups keep nightly backups small but require restoring the full backup plus every incremental since, which lengthens restore time.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Which software testing method involves feeding an application large volumes of random, malformed, or boundary-violating input to uncover crashes, memory leaks, or unhandled exceptions?","o":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Static code analysis","Interface testing"],"c":0,"why":"Fuzz testing automatically generates malformed or random inputs to reveal how the application handles unexpected data, exposing crashes or memory issues. Regression testing verifies existing functionality after changes, static analysis reviews code without execution, and interface testing focuses on communication between components rather than malformed input.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"},{"dom":"D7","d":"hard","q":"A security team deploys a honeypot on an internal network segment to observe attacker behavior. Which of the following practices would create the GREATEST legal risk of entrapment or liability for the organization?","o":["Placing the honeypot on an isolated VLAN with no path to production systems","Actively advertising the honeypot as containing valuable data specifically to lure an already-suspected employee into committing an unauthorized act","Logging all interactions with the honeypot for later analysis","Configuring the honeypot to mimic a real production server's banner"],"c":1,"why":"Passive enticement (making a system merely attractive) is generally legal, but actively targeting and inducing a specific suspected individual to commit an act they otherwise would not have committed can constitute entrapment, creating significant legal exposure. Isolation, logging, and banner mimicry are standard, low-risk honeypot practices.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D7","d":"medium","q":"During a change management review, the process requires that the person who submits a change request cannot also be the person who approves it for production deployment. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this control?","o":["To speed up the approval process for urgent changes","To enforce segregation of duties and reduce the risk of unauthorized or malicious changes","To eliminate the need for change testing prior to deployment","To reduce the amount of documentation required for the change"],"c":1,"why":"Separating requester and approver roles is a segregation-of-duties control that prevents a single individual from unilaterally introducing unauthorized changes; it does not speed approvals, remove testing requirements, or reduce documentation.","link":"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/61/r2/final"},{"dom":"D8","d":"medium","q":"Which practice best ensures that every change to an application's source code is traceable to a specific developer, documented, and reversible if a defect is discovered post-deployment?","o":["Establishing a formal code review board","Using a version control system with mandatory commit messages and branching/merge policies","Conducting quarterly penetration tests","Digitally signing compiled binaries before release"],"c":1,"why":"A version control system with enforced commit and branching policies provides an auditable history of who changed what and when, and enables rollback. Code review boards and penetration tests improve quality/security but do not inherently provide change traceability or rollback capability, and signing binaries only verifies integrity, not change history.","link":"https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/"}];})(typeof window!=="undefined"?window:globalThis);
